HP:0005579.definition: Any impairment of reabsorption of chloride by the kidney.

HP:0005580.name: Duplication of renal pelvis
HP:0005580.definition: A duplication of the renal pelvis.

HP:0005583.name: Tubular basement membrane disintegration
HP:0005583.definition: DIsruption and breaking up of the basement membrane of the tubules of the kidney.

HP:0005584.name: Renal cell carcinoma
HP:0005584.definition: A type of carcinoma of the kidney with origin in the epithelium of the proximal convoluted renal tubule.

HP:0005588.name: Patchy palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0005588.definition: A focal type of palmoplantar keratoderma in which only certain areas of the palms and soles are affected.

HP:0005592.name: Giant melanosomes in melanocytes
HP:0005592.definition: The presence of large spherical melanosomes (1 to 6 micrometer in diameter) in the cytoplasm of melanocytes.

HP:0005593.name: Macular hypopigmented whorls, streaks, and patches

HP:0005597.name: Congenital alopecia totalis
HP:0005597.definition: Loss of all scalp hair with congenital onset.

HP:0005598.name: Facial telangiectasia in butterfly midface distribution
HP:0005598.definition: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin in a butterfly midface distribution.

HP:0005600.name: Congenital giant melanocytic nevus
HP:0005600.definition: The giant congenital nevus is greater than 8 cm in size, pigmented and often hairy. A giant congenital nevus is smaller in infants and children, but it usually continues to grow with the child.

HP:0005605.name: Large cafe-au-lait macules with irregular margins
HP:0005605.definition: Large hypermelanotic macules with jagged borders.

HP:0005608.name: Bilobate gallbladder
HP:0005608.definition: The presence of a bilobed gallbladder, related to a duplication of the gallbladder primordium.

HP:0005613.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the femur
HP:0005613.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the femur.

HP:0005616.name: Accelerated skeletal maturation
HP:0005616.definition: An abnormally increased rate of skeletal maturation. Accelerated skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

HP:0005619.name: Thoracolumbar kyphosis
HP:0005619.definition: Hyperconvexity of the thoracolumbar spine producing a rounded or humped appearance.

HP:0005620.name: Hypermobility of interphalangeal joints
HP:0005620.definition: The ability of the interphalangeal joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

HP:0005621.name: Trapezoidal vertebral body
HP:0005621.definition: An anomalous trapezoidal appearance of a vertebral body. A trapezoid is a four-sided shape that has two sides that are parallel and two sides that are not parallel. In this case, the two lateral sides of the vertebra are parallel, and the top and the bottom are slanted with respect to each other such that the vertebra is shorter in the front or back than on the other side.

HP:0005622.name: Broad long bones
HP:0005622.definition: Increased cross-section (diameter) of the long bones. Note that widening may primarily affect specific regions of long bones (e.g., diaphysis or metaphysis), but this should be coded separately.

HP:0005623.name: Absent ossification of calvaria
HP:0005623.definition: Acalvaria is an extremely rare congenital malformation characterized by an absence of flat bones of skull, dura mater, and associated muscles in the presence of normal cranial contents and facial bones.

HP:0005626.name: Posterior fusion of lumbosacral vertebrae
HP:0005626.definition: Bony fusion of the posterior part of the L5 vertebral body with the sacrum.

HP:0005627.name: Type D brachydactyly
HP:0005627.definition: This type of brachydactyly is characterized by short and broad terminal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes.

HP:0005638.name: Decreased anterioposterior diameter of lumbar vertebral bodies

HP:0005639.name: Hyperextensible hand joints
HP:0005639.definition: The ability of the joints of the hand to move beyond their normal range of motion.

HP:0005645.name: Intervertebral disk calcification
HP:0005645.definition: The presence of abnormal calcium deposition of the intervertebral disk.

HP:0005648.name: Bilateral ulnar hypoplasia
HP:0005648.definition: Underdevelopment of the ulna on both sides.

HP:0005650.name: 2-5 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0005650.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the second to the fifth fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0005652.name: Cortical sclerosis
HP:0005652.definition: Sclerosis (abnormal hardening) of cortical bone, characterized by increased radiodensity.

HP:0005655.name: Multiple digital exostoses
HP:0005655.definition: Multiple exostoses originating in the fingers and toes.

HP:0005656.name: Positional foot deformity
HP:0005656.definition: A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the muscle and soft tissue. In contrast if the bones of the foot are affected the term structural foot deformity applies.

HP:0005661.name: Salmonella osteomyelitis
HP:0005661.definition: Osteomyelitis caused by infection with the bacteria, salmonella.

HP:0005665.name: Massively thickened long bone cortices
HP:0005665.definition: Extreme thickening of the cortex of long bones.

HP:0005667.name: Os odontoideum
HP:0005667.definition: Separation of the odontoid process from the body of the axis.

HP:0005671.name: Bilateral intracerebral calcifications
HP:0005671.definition: Deposition of calcium salts on both sides of the cerebrum.

HP:0005679.name: Dupuytren contracture
HP:0005679.definition: An abnormality of the hand resulting from contracture of the palmar fascia with a fixed flexion deformity of the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints and the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints.

HP:0005680.name: Tongue-like lumbar vertebral deformities
HP:0005680.definition: A tongue-like protusion from the anterior aspect of lumbar vertebral bodies.

HP:0005684.name: Distal arthrogryposis
HP:0005684.definition: An inherited primary limb malformation disorder characterized by congenital contractures of two or more different body areas and without primary neurologic and/or muscle disease that affects limb function.

HP:0005686.name: Patchy osteosclerosis
HP:0005686.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0005688.name: Dysplastic distal thumb phalanges with a central hole

HP:0005694.name: Partial fusion of proximal row of carpal bones

HP:0005696.name: Postaxial polydactyly type A
HP:0005696.definition: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand with a complete extra finger and extra metacarpal.

HP:0005700.name: Increased bone density with cystic changes

HP:0005707.name: Bilateral triphalangeal thumbs
HP:0005707.definition: A bilateral form of triphalangeal thumb.

HP:0005720.name: Shortening of all metacarpals
HP:0005720.definition: Abnormal reduction in length of all metacarpal bones.

HP:0005722.name: Hyperextensible thumb
HP:0005722.definition: The ability of the thumb joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

HP:0005725.name: Nonopposable triphalangeal thumb
HP:0005725.definition: A form of triphalangeal thumb that cannot be placed opposite the fingers of the same hand.

HP:0005731.name: Cortical irregularity
HP:0005731.definition: An abnormal irregularity of cortical bone.

HP:0005733.name: Spinal stenosis with reduced interpedicular distance
HP:0005733.definition: An abnormal narrowing of the spinal canal related to a reduction in the interpedicular distance (i.e., the distance measured between the pedicles on frontal [coronal] imaging).

HP:0005739.name: Posterior subluxation of radial head
HP:0005739.definition: Partial dislocation of the head of the radius in the posterior direction.

HP:0005743.name: Avascular necrosis of the capital femoral epiphysis
HP:0005743.definition: Avascular necrosis of the proximal epiphysis of the femur occurring in growing children and caused by an interruption of the blood supply to the head of the femur close to the hip joint. The necrosis is characteristically associated with flattening of the femoral head, for which reason the term coxa plana has been used to refer to this feature in the medical literature.

HP:0005744.name: obsolete Generalized osteoporosis with pathologic fractures

HP:0005746.name: Osteosclerosis of the base of the skull
HP:0005746.definition: An increase in bone density affecting the basicranium (base of the skull).

HP:0005750.name: Lower-limb joint contracture
HP:0005750.definition: A limitation in the passive range of motion of a joint of the lower limb resulting from loss of elasticity in the periarticular tissues owing to structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules or skin.

HP:0005756.name: Neonatal epiphyseal stippling
HP:0005756.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more epiphyses during the neonatal period.

HP:0005758.name: Basilar impression
HP:0005758.definition: Abnormal elevation of the floor of the posterior fossa including occipital condyles and foramen magnum.

HP:0005759.name: Small flat posterior fossa
HP:0005759.definition: An abnormally small and flat configuration of the posterior cranial fossa.

HP:0005768.name: 2-4 toe cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0005768.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the toes 2, 3, and 4.

HP:0005769.name: Fifth finger distal phalanx clinodactyly
HP:0005769.definition: Bending or curvature of the distal phalanx of little finger in the radial direction (i.e., towards the 4th finger).

HP:0005772.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tibia
HP:0005772.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the tibia.

HP:0005773.name: Short forearm
HP:0005773.definition: Underdevelopment of both forearm bones, the ulna and the radius, resulting in a shortened forearm.

HP:0005780.name: Absent fourth finger distal interphalangeal crease
HP:0005780.definition: Absence of the distal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fourth finger.

HP:0005787.name: Lumbar platyspondyly
HP:0005787.definition: A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance between the vertebral endplates affecting the lumbar spine.

HP:0005789.name: Generalized osteosclerosis
HP:0005789.definition: An abnormal increase of bone mineral density with generalized involvement of the skeleton.

HP:0005791.name: Cortical thickening of long bone diaphyses
HP:0005791.definition: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the diaphyseal region of long bones.

HP:0005793.name: Shortening of all distal phalanges of the toes
HP:0005793.definition: Abnormally short distal phalanx of toe of all toes.

HP:0005798.name: Posterior radial head dislocation
HP:0005798.definition: A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an posterior direction.

HP:0005815.name: Supernumerary ribs
HP:0005815.definition: The presence of more than 12 rib pairs.

HP:0005817.name: Postaxial polysyndactyly of foot
HP:0005817.definition: Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the foot on the lateral side (i.e., on the side of the little toe).

HP:0005819.name: Short middle phalanx of finger
HP:0005819.definition: Short (hypoplastic) middle phalanx of finger, affecting one or more fingers.

HP:0005824.name: Clinodactyly of the 2nd toe
HP:0005824.definition: Bending or curvature of a second toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

HP:0005830.name: Flexion contracture of toe
HP:0005830.definition: One or more bent (flexed) toe joints that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0005832.name: Dysharmonic delayed bone age
HP:0005832.definition: A type of dysharmonic skeletal maturation in which there is a delay in skeletal maturation whose degree differs markedly in different bones.

HP:0005833.name: obsolete Joint swelling onset late infancy

HP:0005837.name: obsolete Joint dislocations in young adult

HP:0005841.name: Calcific stippling of infantile cartilaginous skeleton

HP:0005844.name: Rounded middle phalanx of finger
HP:0005844.definition: An abnormally round shape of the middle phalanx of the finger.

HP:0005849.name: Diffuse cerebral calcification
HP:0005849.definition: Generalized deposition of calcium salts within the cerebrum.

HP:0005855.name: Multiple prenatal fractures
HP:0005855.definition: The presence of bone fractures in the prenatal period that are diagnosed at birth or before.

HP:0005856.name: Ulnar radial head dislocation
HP:0005856.definition: A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint in an ulnar direction.

HP:0005863.name: Type E brachydactyly
HP:0005863.definition: In type E brachydactyly, shortening of the fingers is mainly in the metacarpals and metatarsals.

HP:0005864.name: Pseudoarthrosis
HP:0005864.definition: A pathologic entity characterized by a developmental defect in a long bone leading to bending and pathologic fracture, with inability to form a normal bony callus with subsequent fibrous nonunion, leading to the pseudarthrosis (or "false joint").

HP:0000414.name: Bulbous nose
HP:0000414.definition: Increased volume and globular shape of the anteroinferior aspect of the nose.

HP:0000415.name: Abnormal choanae morphology
HP:0000415.definition: Abnormality of the choanae (the posterior nasal apertures).

HP:0000418.name: Narrow nasal ridge
HP:0000418.definition: Decreased width of the nasal ridge.

HP:0000419.name: Abnormal nasal septum morphology
HP:0000419.definition: An abnormality of the nasal septum.

HP:0000420.name: Short nasal septum
HP:0000420.definition: Reduced superior to inferior length of the nasal septum.

HP:0000421.name: Epistaxis
HP:0000421.definition: Epistaxis, or nosebleed, refers to a hemorrhage localized in the nose.

HP:0000422.name: Abnormal nasal bridge morphology
HP:0000422.definition: Abnormality of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose. It lies between the glabella and the inferior boundary of the nasal bone, and extends laterally to the inner canthi.

HP:0000426.name: Prominent nasal bridge
HP:0000426.definition: Anterior positioning of the nasal root in comparison to the usual positioning for age.

HP:0000429.name: Abnormal morphology of the nasal alae
HP:0000429.definition: An abnormality of the Ala of nose.

HP:0000430.name: Underdeveloped nasal alae
HP:0000430.definition: Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi.

HP:0000431.name: Wide nasal bridge
HP:0000431.definition: Increased breadth of the nasal bridge (and with it, the nasal root).

HP:0000436.name: Abnormal nasal tip morphology
HP:0000436.definition: An abnormality of the nasal tip.

HP:0000437.name: Depressed nasal tip
HP:0000437.definition: Decreased distance from the nasal tip to the nasal base.

HP:0000444.name: Convex nasal ridge
HP:0000444.definition: Nasal ridge curving anteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip. The nose appears often also prominent, and the columella low.

HP:0000445.name: Wide nose
HP:0000445.definition: Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae.

HP:0000446.name: Narrow nasal bridge
HP:0000446.definition: Decreased width of the bony bridge of the nose.

HP:0000448.name: Prominent nose
HP:0000448.definition: Distance between subnasale and pronasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased anterior protrusion of the nasal tip.

HP:0000452.name: Choanal stenosis
HP:0000452.definition: Abnormal narrowing of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture).

HP:0000453.name: Choanal atresia
HP:0000453.definition: Absence or abnormal closure of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture). Most embryologists believe that posterior choanal atresia results from a failure of rupture between the 35th and 38th day of fetal life of the partition which separates the bucconasal or buccopharyngeal membranes. The resultant choanal atresia may be unilateral or bilateral, bony or membranous, complete or incomplete. In over 90 per cent of cases the obstruction is bony, while in the remainder it is membranous. The bony type of atresia is commonly located 1-2 mm. anterior to the posterior edge of the hard palate, and the osseous septum varies in thickness from 1 to 10 mm. In the membranous form of choanal atresia the obstruction usually occurs further posteriorly. In approximately one third of cases the atresia is bilateral.

HP:0000455.name: Broad nasal tip
HP:0000455.definition: Increase in width of the nasal tip.

HP:0000456.name: Bifid nasal tip
HP:0000456.definition: A splitting of the nasal tip. Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal tip.

HP:0000457.name: Depressed nasal ridge
HP:0000457.definition: Lack of prominence of the nose resulting from a posteriorly-placed nasal ridge.

HP:0000458.name: Anosmia
HP:0000458.definition: An inability to perceive odors. This is a general term describing inability to smell arising in any part of the process of smelling from absorption of odorants into the nasal mucous overlying the olfactory epithelium, diffusion to the cilia, binding to olfactory receptor sites, generation of action potentials in olfactory neurons, and perception of a smell.

HP:0000460.name: Narrow nose
HP:0000460.definition: Interalar distance more than 2 SD below the mean for age, or alternatively, an apparently decreased width of the nasal base and alae.

HP:0000463.name: Anteverted nares
HP:0000463.definition: Anteriorly-facing nostrils viewed with the head in the Frankfurt horizontal and the eyes of the observer level with the eyes of the subject. This gives the appearance of an upturned nose (upturned nasal tip).

HP:0000465.name: Webbed neck
HP:0000465.definition: Pterygium colli is a congenital skin fold that runs along the sides of the neck down to the shoulders. It involves an ectopic fibrotic facial band superficial to the trapezius muscle. Excess hair-bearing skin is also present and extends down the cervical region well beyond the normal hairline.

HP:0000467.name: Neck muscle weakness
HP:0000467.definition: Decreased strength of the neck musculature.

HP:0000468.name: Increased adipose tissue around the neck
HP:0000468.definition: An increased amount of subcutaneous fat tissue around the neck.

HP:0000471.name: Gastrointestinal angiodysplasia
HP:0000471.definition: Dysplasia affecting the vasculature of the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0000472.name: Long neck
HP:0000472.definition: Increased inferior-superior length of the neck.

HP:0000473.name: Torticollis
HP:0000473.definition: Involuntary contractions of the neck musculature resulting in an abnormal posture of or abnormal movements of the head.

HP:0000474.name: Thickened nuchal skin fold
HP:0000474.definition: A thickening of the skin thickness in the posterior aspect of the fetal neck. A nuchal fold (NF) measurement is obtained in a transverse section of the fetal head at the level of the cavum septum pellucidum and thalami, angled posteriorly to include the cerebellum. The measurement is taken from the outer edge of the occiput bone to the outer skin limit directly in the midline. An NF measurement greater than 5 mm at 14 to 17+6 weeks of gestation, or 6 mm at 18 to 28 weeks has been associated with a markedly increased risk for Down syndrome.

HP:0000475.name: Broad neck
HP:0000475.definition: Increased side-to-side width of the neck.

HP:0000476.name: Cystic hygroma
HP:0000476.definition: A cystic lymphatic lesion of the neck.

HP:0000478.name: Abnormality of the eye
HP:0000478.definition: Any abnormality of the eye, including location, spacing, and intraocular abnormalities.

HP:0000479.name: Abnormal retinal morphology
HP:0000479.definition: A structural abnormality of the retina.

HP:0000480.name: Retinal coloboma
HP:0000480.definition: A notch or cleft of the retina.

HP:0000481.name: Abnormal cornea morphology
HP:0000481.definition: Any abnormality of the cornea, which is the transparent tissue at the front of the eye that covers the iris, pupil, and anterior chamber.

HP:0000482.name: Microcornea
HP:0000482.definition: A congenital abnormality of the cornea in which the cornea and the anterior segment of the eye are smaller than normal. The horizontal diameter of the cornea does not reach 10 mm even in adulthood.

HP:0000483.name: Astigmatism
HP:0000483.definition: A type of refraction error associated with abnormal curvatures on the anterior and/or posterior surface of the cornea.

HP:0000484.name: Hyperopic astigmatism
HP:0000484.definition: A form of astigmatism in which one meridian is hyperopic while the one at a right angle to it has no refractive error.

HP:0000485.name: Megalocornea
HP:0000485.definition: An enlargement of the cornea with normal clarity and function. Megalocornea is diagnosed with a horizontal corneal diameter of 12 mm or more at birth or 13 mm or more after two years of age.

HP:0000486.name: Strabismus
HP:0000486.definition: A misalignment of the eyes so that the visual axes deviate from bifoveal fixation. The classification of strabismus may be based on a number of features including the relative position of the eyes, whether the deviation is latent or manifest, intermittent or constant, concomitant or otherwise and according to the age of onset and the relevance of any associated refractive error.

HP:0000488.name: Retinopathy
HP:0000488.definition: Any noninflammatory disease of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality.

HP:0000489.name: obsolete Abnormality of globe location or size

HP:0000490.name: Deeply set eye
HP:0000490.definition: An eye that is more deeply recessed into the plane of the face than is typical.

HP:0000493.name: Abnormal foveal morphology
HP:0000493.definition: An abnormality of the fovea centralis, the central area of the macula that mediates central, high resolution vision and contains the largest concentration of cone cells in the retina.

HP:0000494.name: Downslanted palpebral fissures
HP:0000494.definition: The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations below the mean.

HP:0000495.name: Recurrent corneal erosions
HP:0000495.definition: The presence of recurrent corneal epithelial erosions. Although most corneal epithelial defects heal quickly, some may show recurrent ulcerations.

HP:0000496.name: Abnormality of eye movement
HP:0000496.definition: An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eye movements or their control.

HP:0000497.name: Globe retraction and deviation on abduction

HP:0000501.name: Glaucoma
HP:0000501.definition: Glaucoma refers loss of retinal ganglion cells in a characteristic pattern of optic neuropathy usually associated with increased intraocular pressure.

HP:0000503.name: Tortuosity of conjunctival vessels
HP:0000503.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the conjunctival blood vessels.

HP:0000505.name: Visual impairment
HP:0000505.definition: Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery.

HP:0000506.name: Telecanthus
HP:0000506.definition: Distance between the inner canthi more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparently increased distance between the inner canthi.

HP:0000508.name: Ptosis
HP:0000508.definition: The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective).

HP:0000510.name: Rod-cone dystrophy
HP:0000510.definition: An inherited retinal disease subtype in which the rod photoreceptors appear to be more severely affected than the cone photoreceptors. Typical presentation is with nyctalopia (due to rod dysfunction) followed by loss of mid-peripheral field of vision, which gradually extends and leaves many patients with a small central island of vision due to the preservation of macular cones.

HP:0000511.name: Vertical supranuclear gaze palsy
HP:0000511.definition: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a vertical direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

HP:0000512.name: Abnormal electroretinogram
HP:0000512.definition: Any abnormality of the electrical responses of various cell types in the retina as measured by electroretinography.

HP:0000514.name: Slow saccadic eye movements
HP:0000514.definition: An abnormally slow velocity of the saccadic eye movements.

HP:0000518.name: Cataract
HP:0000518.definition: A cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the crystalline lens of the eye or in its capsule.

HP:0000519.name: Developmental cataract
HP:0000519.definition: A cataract that occurs congenitally as the result of a developmental defect, in contrast to the majority of cataracts that occur in adulthood as the result of degenerative changes of the lens.

HP:0000520.name: Proptosis
HP:0000520.definition: An eye that is protruding anterior to the plane of the face to a greater extent than is typical.

HP:0000523.name: Subcapsular cataract
HP:0000523.definition: A cataract that affects the region of the lens directly beneath the capsule of the lens.

HP:0000524.name: Conjunctival telangiectasia
HP:0000524.definition: The presence of small (ca. 0.5-1.0 mm) dilated blood vessels near the surface of the mucous membranes of the conjunctiva.

HP:0000525.name: Abnormality iris morphology
HP:0000525.definition: An abnormality of the iris, which is the pigmented muscular tissue between the cornea and the lens, that is perforated by an opening called the pupil.

HP:0000526.name: Aniridia
HP:0000526.definition: Abnormality of the iris characterized by, typically bilateral, complete or partial iris hypoplasia. The phenotype ranges from mild defects of anterior iris stroma only to almost complete absence of the iris.

HP:0000527.name: Long eyelashes
HP:0000527.definition: Mid upper eyelash length >10 mm or increased length of the eyelashes (subjective).

HP:0000528.name: Anophthalmia
HP:0000528.definition: Absence of the globe or eyeball.

HP:0000529.name: Progressive visual loss
HP:0000529.definition: A reduction of previously attained ability to see.

HP:0000532.name: Abnormal chorioretinal morphology
HP:0000532.definition: An abnormality of the choroid and retina.

HP:0000533.name: Chorioretinal atrophy
HP:0000533.definition: Atrophy of the choroid and retinal layers of the fundus.

HP:0000537.name: Epicanthus inversus
HP:0000537.definition: A fold of skin starting at or just below the medial aspect of the lower lid and arching upward to cover, extend in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.

HP:0000538.name: Pseudopapilledema
HP:0000538.definition: Apparent optic disc swelling in the absence of increased intracranial pressure.

HP:0000539.name: Abnormality of refraction
HP:0000539.definition: An abnormality in the process of focusing of light by the eye in order to produce a sharp image on the retina.

HP:0000540.name: Hypermetropia
HP:0000540.definition: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects in the distance clearly, while objects nearby appear blurry.

HP:0000541.name: Retinal detachment
HP:0000541.definition: Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium.

HP:0000542.name: Impaired ocular adduction
HP:0000542.definition: Reduced ability to move the eye in the direction of the nose.

HP:0000543.name: Optic disc pallor
HP:0000543.definition: A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disc (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression.

HP:0000544.name: External ophthalmoplegia
HP:0000544.definition: Paralysis of the external ocular muscles.

HP:0000545.name: Myopia
HP:0000545.definition: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects nearby clearly, while objects in the distance appear blurry.

HP:0000546.name: Retinal degeneration
HP:0000546.definition: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells.

HP:0000549.name: Abnormal conjugate eye movement
HP:0000549.definition: Any deviation from the normal motor coordination of the eyes that allows for bilateral fixation on a single object.

HP:0000550.name: Undetectable electroretinogram
HP:0000550.definition: Lack of any response to stimulation upon electroretinography.

HP:0000551.name: Color vision defect
HP:0000551.definition: An anomaly in the ability to discriminate between or recognize colors.

HP:0000552.name: Tritanomaly
HP:0000552.definition: Difficulty distinguishing between yellow and blue, possible related to dysfunction of the S photopigment.

HP:0000553.name: Abnormal uvea morphology
HP:0000553.definition: An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball.

HP:0000554.name: Uveitis
HP:0000554.definition: Inflammation of one or all portions of the uveal tract.

HP:0000555.name: Leukocoria
HP:0000555.definition: An abnormal white reflection from the pupil rather than the usual black reflection.

HP:0000556.name: Retinal dystrophy
HP:0000556.definition: Retinal dystrophy is an abnormality of the retina associated with a hereditary process. Retinal dystrophies are defined by their predominantly monogenic inheritance and they are frequently associated with loss or dysfunction of photoreceptor cells as a primary or secondary event.

HP:0000557.name: Buphthalmos
HP:0000557.definition: Diffusely large eye (with megalocornea) associated with glaucoma.

HP:0000558.name: Rieger anomaly
HP:0000558.definition: A congenital malformation of the anterior segment characterized by iridicorneal malformation, glaucoma, iris stroma hypoplasia, posterior embryotoxon, and corneal opacities.

HP:0000563.name: Keratoconus
HP:0000563.definition: A cone-shaped deformity of the cornea characterized by the presence of corneal distortion secondary to thinning of the apex.

HP:0000564.name: Lacrimal duct atresia
HP:0000564.definition: A developmental disorder of the lacrimal drainage system that most often affects the lacrimal ostium and resulting in non-opening of the nasolacrimal duct. It usually results from a non-canalization of the nasolacrimal duct.

HP:0000565.name: Esotropia
HP:0000565.definition: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes turned inward ('crossed') to a relatively severe degree, usually defined as 10 diopters or more.

HP:0000567.name: Chorioretinal coloboma
HP:0000567.definition: Absence of a region of the retina, retinal pigment epithelium, and choroid.

HP:0000568.name: Microphthalmia
HP:0000568.definition: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one or both eyes.

HP:0000570.name: Abnormal saccadic eye movements
HP:0000570.definition: An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impairment of fast (saccadic) eye movements.

HP:0000571.name: Hypometric saccades
HP:0000571.definition: Saccadic undershoot, i.e., a saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.

HP:0000572.name: Visual loss
HP:0000572.definition: Loss of visual acuity (implying that vision was better at a certain time point in life). Otherwise the term reduced visual acuity should be used (or a subclass of that).

HP:0000574.name: Thick eyebrow
HP:0000574.definition: Increased density/number and/or increased diameter of eyebrow hairs.

HP:0000575.name: Scotoma
HP:0000575.definition: A regional and pathological increase of the light detection threshold in any region of the visual field surrounded by a field of normal or relatively well-preserved vision.

HP:0000576.name: Centrocecal scotoma
HP:0000576.definition: A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) located between the central point of fixation and the blind spot with a roughly horizontal oval shape.

HP:0000577.name: Exotropia
HP:0000577.definition: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward.

HP:0000580.name: Pigmentary retinopathy
HP:0000580.definition: An abnormality of the retina characterized by pigment deposition. It is typically associated with migration and proliferation of macrophages or retinal pigment epithelial cells into the retina; melanin from these cells causes the pigmentary changes. Pigmentary retinopathy is a common final pathway of many retinal conditions and is often associated with visual loss.

HP:0000581.name: Blepharophimosis
HP:0000581.definition: A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures.

HP:0000582.name: Upslanted palpebral fissure
HP:0000582.definition: The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, the inclination of the palpebral fissure is greater than typical for age.

HP:0000585.name: Band keratopathy
HP:0000585.definition: An abnormality of the cornea characterized by the deposition of calcium in a band across the central cornea, leading to decreased vision, foreign body sensation, and ocular irritation.

HP:0000586.name: Shallow orbits
HP:0000586.definition: Reduced depth of the orbits associated with prominent-appearing ocular globes.

HP:0000588.name: Optic disc coloboma
HP:0000588.definition: A cleft of the optic nerve that extends inferiorly.

HP:0000589.name: Coloboma
HP:0000589.definition: A developmental defect characterized by a cleft of some portion of the eye or ocular adnexa.

HP:0000590.name: Progressive external ophthalmoplegia
HP:0000590.definition: Initial bilateral ptosis followed by limitation of eye movements in all directions and slowing of saccades.

HP:0000592.name: Blue sclerae
HP:0000592.definition: An abnormal bluish coloration of the sclera.

HP:0000593.name: Abnormal anterior chamber morphology
HP:0000593.definition: Abnormality of the anterior chamber, which is the space in the eye that is behind the cornea and in front of the iris.

HP:0000594.name: Shallow anterior chamber
HP:0000594.definition: Reduced depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is decreased.

HP:0000597.name: Ophthalmoparesis
HP:0000597.definition: Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.

HP:0000599.name: Abnormality of the frontal hairline
HP:0000599.definition: An anomaly in the placement or shape of the hairline (trichion) on the forehead, that is, the border between skin on the forehead that has head hair and that does not.

HP:0000600.name: Abnormality of the pharynx
HP:0000600.definition: An anomaly of the pharynx, i.e., of the tubular structure extending from the base of the skull superiorly to the esophageal inlet inferiorly.

HP:0000601.name: Hypotelorism
HP:0000601.definition: Interpupillary distance less than 2 SD below the mean (alternatively, the appearance of an decreased interpupillary distance or closely spaced eyes).

HP:0000602.name: Ophthalmoplegia
HP:0000602.definition: Paralysis of one or more extraocular muscles that are responsible for eye movements.

HP:0000603.name: Central scotoma
HP:0000603.definition: An area of depressed vision located at the point of fixation and that interferes with central vision.

HP:0000605.name: Supranuclear gaze palsy
HP:0000605.definition: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a particular direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

HP:0000606.name: Abnormality of the periorbital region
HP:0000606.definition: An abnormality of the region situated around the orbit of the eye.

HP:0000608.name: Macular degeneration
HP:0000608.definition: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells of the macula lutea.

HP:0000610.name: Abnormal choroid morphology
HP:0000610.definition: Any structural abnormality of the choroid.

HP:0000613.name: Photophobia
HP:0000613.definition: Excessive sensitivity to light with the sensation of discomfort or pain in the eyes due to exposure to bright light.

HP:0000614.name: Abnormal nasolacrimal system morphology
HP:0000614.definition: An abnormality of the nasolacrimal drainage system, which serves as a conduit for tear flow from the external eye to the nasal cavity.

HP:0000617.name: Abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit
HP:0000617.definition: An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impaired smooth-pursuit eye movements.

HP:0000618.name: Blindness
HP:0000618.definition: Blindness is the condition of lacking visual perception defined as a profound reduction in visual perception. On the 6m visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 3/60. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 20/400. On the decimal visual acuity scale, blindness is defined as less than 0.05. Blindness is typically characterized by a visual field of no greater than 10 degrees in radius around central fixation.

HP:0000619.name: Impaired convergence
HP:0000619.definition: Reduced ability to turn the eyes inward in order to focus on a nearby object.

HP:0000621.name: Entropion
HP:0000621.definition: An abnormal inversion (turning inward) of the eyelid (usually the lower) towards the globe. Entropion is usually acquired as a result of involutional or cicatricial processes but may occasionally be congenital.

HP:0000622.name: Blurred vision
HP:0000622.definition: Lack of sharpness of vision resulting in the inability to see fine detail.

HP:0000623.name: Supranuclear ophthalmoplegia
HP:0000623.definition: A vertical gaze palsy with inability to direct the gaze of the eyes downwards.

HP:0000625.name: Eyelid coloboma
HP:0000625.definition: A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower or upper eyelid.

HP:0000627.name: Posterior embryotoxon
HP:0000627.definition: A posterior embryotoxon is the presence of a prominent and anteriorly displaced line of Schwalbe.

HP:0000631.name: Retinal arterial tortuosity
HP:0000631.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal artery.

HP:0000633.name: Decreased lacrimation
HP:0000633.definition: Abnormally decreased lacrimation, that is, reduced tear production.

HP:0000634.name: Impaired ocular abduction
HP:0000634.definition: An impaired ability of the eye to move in the outward direction (towards the side of the head).

HP:0000635.name: Blue irides
HP:0000635.definition: A markedly blue coloration of the iris.

HP:0000636.name: Upper eyelid coloboma
HP:0000636.definition: A short discontinuity of the margin of the upper eyelid.

HP:0000637.name: Long palpebral fissure
HP:0000637.definition: Distance between medial and lateral canthi is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, apparently increased length of the palpebral fissures.

HP:0000639.name: Nystagmus
HP:0000639.definition: Rhythmic, involuntary oscillations of one or both eyes related to abnormality in fixation, conjugate gaze, or vestibular mechanisms.

HP:0000640.name: Gaze-evoked nystagmus
HP:0000640.definition: Nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.

HP:0000641.name: Dysmetric saccades
HP:0000641.definition: The controller signal for saccadic eye movements has two components: the pulse that moves the eye rapidly from one point to the next, and the step that holds the eye in the new position. When both the pulse and the step are not the correct size, a dysmetric refixation eye movement results.

HP:0000642.name: Red-green dyschromatopsia
HP:0000642.definition: Difficulty with discriminating red and green hues.

HP:0000643.name: Blepharospasm
HP:0000643.definition: A focal dystonia that affects the muscles of the eyelids and brow, associated with involuntary recurrent spasm of both eyelids.

HP:0000646.name: Amblyopia
HP:0000646.definition: Reduced visual acuity that is uncorrectable by lenses in the absence of detectable anatomic defects in the eye or visual pathways.

HP:0000647.name: Sclerocornea
HP:0000647.definition: A congenital anomaly in which a part or the whole of the cornea acquires the characteristics of sclera, resulting in clouding of the cornea.

HP:0000648.name: Optic atrophy
HP:0000648.definition: Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy.

HP:0000649.name: Abnormality of visual evoked potentials
HP:0000649.definition: An anomaly of visually evoked potentials (VEP), which are electrical potentials, initiated by brief visual stimuli, which are recorded from the scalp overlying the visual cortex.

HP:0000650.name: Abnormal amplitude of pattern reversal visual evoked potentials

HP:0000651.name: Diplopia
HP:0000651.definition: Diplopia is a condition in which a single object is perceived as two images, it is also known as double vision.

HP:0000652.name: Lower eyelid coloboma
HP:0000652.definition: A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower eyelid.

HP:0000654.name: Decreased light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram amplitude
HP:0000654.definition: Decreased amplitude of eletrical response upon electroretinography.

HP:0000656.name: Ectropion
HP:0000656.definition: An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin.

HP:0000657.name: Oculomotor apraxia
HP:0000657.definition: Ocular motor apraxia is a deficiency in voluntary, horizontal, lateral, fast eye movements (saccades) with retention of slow pursuit movements. The inability to follow objects visually is often compensated by head movements. There may be decreased smooth pursuit, and cancelation of the vestibulo-ocular reflex.

HP:0000659.name: Peters anomaly
HP:0000659.definition: A form of anterior segment dysgenesis in which abnormal cleavage of the anterior chamber occurs. Peters anomaly is characterized by central, paracentral, or complete corneal opacity.

HP:0000660.name: Lipemia retinalis
HP:0000660.definition: A creamy appearance of the retinal blood vessels that occurs when the concentration of lipids in the blood are extremely increased, with pale pink to milky white retinal vessels and altered pale reflexes from choroidal vasculature.

HP:0000662.name: Nyctalopia
HP:0000662.definition: Inability to see well at night or in poor light.

HP:0000664.name: Synophrys
HP:0000664.definition: Meeting of the medial eyebrows in the midline.

HP:0000666.name: Horizontal nystagmus
HP:0000666.definition: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements.

HP:0000667.name: Phthisis bulbi
HP:0000667.definition: Atrophy of the eyeball with blindness and decreased intraocular pressure due to end-stage intraocular disease.

HP:0000668.name: Hypodontia
HP:0000668.definition: The absence of five or less teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop.

HP:0000670.name: Carious teeth
HP:0000670.definition: Caries is a multifactorial bacterial infection affecting the structure of the tooth. This term has been used to describe the presence of more than expected dental caries.

HP:0000674.name: Anodontia
HP:0000674.definition: The absence of all teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop.

HP:0000675.name: Macrodontia of permanent maxillary central incisor
HP:0000675.definition: Increased size of the maxillary central secondary incisor tooth.

HP:0000676.name: Abnormality of the incisor
HP:0000676.definition: An abnormality of the Incisor tooth.

HP:0000677.name: Oligodontia
HP:0000677.definition: The absence of six or more teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop.

HP:0000678.name: Dental crowding
HP:0000678.definition: Changes in alignment of teeth in the dental arch

HP:0000679.name: Taurodontia
HP:0000679.definition: Increased volume of dental pulp of permanent molar characterized by a crown body-root ratio equal or larger than 1:1 or an elongated pulp chambers and apical displacement of the bifurcation or trifurcation of the roots.

HP:0000680.name: Delayed eruption of primary teeth
HP:0000680.definition: Delayed tooth eruption affecting the primary dentition.

HP:0000682.name: Abnormal dental enamel morphology
HP:0000682.definition: An abnormality of the dental enamel.

HP:0000683.name: Grayish enamel
HP:0000683.definition: A gray discoloration of the dental enamel.

HP:0000684.name: Delayed eruption of teeth
HP:0000684.definition: Delayed tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD beyond the mean eruption age.

HP:0000687.name: Widely spaced teeth
HP:0000687.definition: Increased spaces (diastemata) between most of the teeth in the same dental arch.

HP:0000689.name: Dental malocclusion
HP:0000689.definition: Dental malocclusion refers to an abnormality of the occlusion, or alignment, of the teeth and the way the upper and lower teeth fit together, resulting in overcrowding of teeth or in abnormal bite patterns.

HP:0000690.name: Agenesis of maxillary lateral incisor
HP:0000690.definition: Agenesis of one or more maxillary lateral incisor, comprising the maxillary lateral primary incisor and maxillary lateral secondary incisor.

HP:0000691.name: Microdontia
HP:0000691.definition: Decreased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD below mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased maximum width of tooth.

HP:0000692.name: Tooth malposition
HP:0000692.definition: Abnormal alignment, positioning, or spacing of the teeth, i.e., misaligned teeth.

HP:0000694.name: Odontodysplasia
HP:0000694.definition: The diagnosis odontodysplasia requires clinical and radiological exams, in which unusually large pulp chambers and large pulp room chambers with thin enamel and dentin are visible. It may affect either a single tooth or several teeth. The term regional odontodysplasia is used if several teeth are affected. It affects the deciduous and permanent dentitions in the maxilla, the mandible or both, although the maxilla is more frequently involved. A type of dental dysplasia occurring in dentinogenesis imperfecta in which the pulp chambers are enlarged and there is a reduced amount of coronal dentin.

HP:0000695.name: Natal tooth
HP:0000695.definition: A tooth present at birth or erupting within the first month of life.

HP:0000696.name: Delayed eruption of permanent teeth
HP:0000696.definition: Delayed tooth eruption affecting the secondary dentition.

HP:0000698.name: Conical tooth
HP:0000698.definition: An abnormal conical form of the teeth, that is, a tooth whose sides converge or taper together incisally.

HP:0000699.name: Diastema
HP:0000699.definition: Increased space between two adjacent teeth in the same dental arch.

HP:0006355.name: Agenesis of mandibular central incisor
HP:0006355.definition: Agenesis of lower secondary incisor or lower primary incisor.

HP:0006357.name: Premature loss of permanent teeth
HP:0006357.definition: Premature loss of the permanent teeth.

HP:0006358.name: Shovel-shaped maxillary central incisors
HP:0006358.definition: A tooth with a crown with marked lingual or palatal marginal ridges causing scooped lingual or palatal surfaces.

HP:0006367.name: Crumpled long bones
HP:0006367.definition: An crumpled radiographic appearance of the long bones, as if the long bone had been crushed together producing irregularities. This feature is the result of multiple fractures and repeated rounds of ineffective healing, as can be seen for instance in severe forms of osteogenesis imperfecta.

HP:0006369.name: Irregular patellae
HP:0006369.definition: An alteration of the normally relatively smooth margins of the kneecap in radiographic images leading to an irregular contour.

HP:0006370.name: Distal ulnar epiphyseal stippling
HP:0006370.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the distal epiphysis of the ulna.

HP:0006371.name: Broad long bone diaphyses
HP:0006371.definition: Increased width of the diaphysis of long bones.

HP:0006375.name: Dumbbell-shaped femur
HP:0006375.definition: The femur is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.

HP:0006380.name: Knee flexion contracture
HP:0006380.definition: A type of knee joint contracture in which the knee is in a fixed bent (flexed) configuration such that it cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0006381.name: Rudimentary fibula
HP:0006381.definition: Absent or nearly absent fibula. (Does not include aplastic)

HP:0006383.name: Progressive bowing of long bones
HP:0006383.definition: Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.

HP:0006384.name: Club-shaped distal femur
HP:0006384.definition: An abnormal conformation of the femur that becomes gradually enlarged towards the distal end. This feature affects the distal femoral metaphysis and epiphysis.

HP:0006385.name: Short lower limbs
HP:0006385.definition: Shortening of the legs related to developmental hypoplasia of the bones of the leg.

HP:0006386.name: Hypoplastic distal radial epiphyses
HP:0006386.definition: Underdevelopment of the distal epiphysis of the radius.

HP:0006387.name: Wide distal femoral metaphysis
HP:0006387.definition: Increased width of the distal part of the shaft (metaphysis) of the femur.

HP:0006389.name: Limited knee flexion
HP:0006389.definition: Reduced ability to flex (bend) the knee joint.

HP:0006390.name: Anterior tibial bowing
HP:0006390.definition: An abnormal anterior bending or curvature of the tibia.

HP:0006391.name: Overtubulated long bones
HP:0006391.definition: Overconstriction, or narrowness of the diaphysis and metaphysis of long bones.

HP:0006392.name: Increased density of long bones
HP:0006392.definition: An abnormal increase in the bone density of the long bones.

HP:0006394.name: Limited pronation/supination of forearm
HP:0006394.definition: A limitation of the ability to place the forearm in a position such that the palm faces anteriorly (supination) and to place the forearm in a position such that the palm faces posteriorly (pronation).

HP:0006398.name: Flat distal femoral epiphysis
HP:0006398.definition: An abnormal flattening of the distal epiphysis of femur.

HP:0006406.name: Club-shaped proximal femur
HP:0006406.definition: An abnormal conformation of the femur that becomes gradually enlarged towards the proximal end. This feature affects the proximal femoral metaphysis and epiphysis.

HP:0006407.name: Irregular distal femoral epiphysis
HP:0006407.definition: Anomaly of the contour of the Distal epiphysis of femur such that its normally smooth appearance is irregular.

HP:0006409.name: Progressive leg bowing
HP:0006409.definition: Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of the leg.

HP:0006414.name: Distal tibial bowing
HP:0006414.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature of the distal portion of the tibia.

HP:0006415.name: Cortically dense long tubular bones
HP:0006415.definition: Increased density of the compact bone of long bone.

HP:0006420.name: Asymmetric radial dysplasia
HP:0006420.definition: The presence of asymmetric developmental dysplasia of the radius.

HP:0006423.name: Peg-like central prominence of distal tibial metaphyses

HP:0006429.name: Broad femoral neck
HP:0006429.definition: An abnormally wide femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

HP:0006431.name: Abnormal proximal femoral metaphysis morphology
HP:0006431.definition: An anomaly of the metaphysis of the proximal femur (close to the hip).

HP:0006433.name: Radial dysplasia
HP:0006433.definition: Radial dysplasia, also known as radial longitudinal deficiency, includes radial clubhand and is a disfiguring, and potentially disabling, congenital limb anomaly. The entire upper limb may be involved, although the defect is most evident in the forearm and hand. Affected children suffer a variable degree of hypoplasia or absence of the preaxial skeleton and soft tissues, in particular the thumb, radius, and dorsoradial soft tissues. The hand is usually radially deviated and subluxated off the distal aspect of the ulna, the ulna may be shortened and have a bow-shaped deformity, and there is no true wrist (radiocarpal) joint in Bayne2 type-III and IV radial dysplasia.

HP:0006434.name: Hypoplasia of proximal radius
HP:0006434.definition: Proximal radial shortening owing to a congenital defect of development.

HP:0006437.name: Disproportionate prominence of the femoral medial condyle

HP:0006438.name: Enlargement of the distal femoral epiphysis
HP:0006438.definition: An abnormal enlargement of the distal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0006439.name: Radioulnar dislocation
HP:0006439.definition: A dislocation is a separation of the radius and ulna bones where they normally meet. The radioulnar joints are two locations, proximal and distal, in which the radius and ulna articulate in the forearm. Both can dislocate.

HP:0006440.name: Increased density of long bone diaphyses

HP:0006442.name: Hypoplasia of proximal fibula
HP:0006442.definition: Underdevelopment or shortening of the end of the fibula (calf bone) nearest the knee.

HP:0006450.name: Multicentric ossification of proximal femoral epiphyses

HP:0006453.name: Lateral displacement of the femoral head
HP:0006453.definition: A developmental anomaly with lateral displacement of the femoral head.

HP:0006454.name: Delayed patellar ossification
HP:0006454.definition: Formation of bone in the patella later than normal.

HP:0006456.name: Irregular proximal tibial epiphyses
HP:0006456.definition: Anomaly of the contour of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia such that its normally smooth appearance is irregular.

HP:0006459.name: Dorsal subluxation of ulna
HP:0006459.definition: Partial dislocation of the ulna in the dorsal direction.

HP:0006461.name: Proximal femoral epiphysiolysis
HP:0006461.definition: Slipped capital femoral epiphysis is defined as a posterior and inferior slippage of the proximal epiphysis of the femur onto the metaphysis (femoral neck), occurring through the physeal plate during the early adolescent growth spurt.

HP:0006462.name: Generalized bone demineralization
HP:0006462.definition: A generalized decrease in bone mineral density.

HP:0006465.name: Periosteal thickening of long tubular bones
HP:0006465.definition: Thickening of the periosteum of long bone.

HP:0006467.name: Limited shoulder movement
HP:0006467.definition: A limitation of the range of movement of the shoulder joint.

HP:0006470.name: Thin long bone diaphyses
HP:0006470.definition: Decreased width of the diaphysis of long bones.

HP:0006473.name: Anterior bowing of long bones
HP:0006473.definition: An abnormal anterior curvature of a long bone.

HP:0006476.name: Abnormality of the pancreatic islet cells
HP:0006476.definition: An abnormality of the islet of Langerhans, i.e., of the regions of the pancreas that contain its endocrine cells. These are the alpha cells, which produce glucagon, the beta cells, which produce insulin and amylin, the delta cells, which produce somatostatin, the PP cells, which produce pancreatic polypeptide, and the epsilon cells, which produce ghrelin.

HP:0006477.name: Abnormal alveolar ridge morphology
HP:0006477.definition: Any abnormality of the alveolar ridges (on the upper or lower jaws). The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth.

HP:0006479.name: Abnormal dental pulp morphology
HP:0006479.definition: An abnormality of the dental pulp.

HP:0006480.name: Premature loss of teeth
HP:0006480.definition: Exfoliation of a tooth more than 2 SD earlier than the normal age for the deciduous teeth and not related to traume or neglect. Exfoliation of a permanent tooth is per se abnormal.

HP:0006481.name: Abnormality of primary teeth
HP:0006481.definition: Any abnormality of the primary tooth.

HP:0006482.name: Abnormal dental morphology
HP:0006482.definition: An abnormality of the morphology of the tooth.

HP:0006483.name: Abnormal number of teeth
HP:0006483.definition: The presence of an altered number of of teeth.

HP:0006486.name: Abnormal dental root morphology
HP:0006486.definition: An abnormality of the dental root.

HP:0006487.name: Bowing of the long bones
HP:0006487.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.

HP:0006488.name: Bowing of the arm
HP:0006488.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature affecting a long bone of the arm.

HP:0006489.name: Abnormal femoral metaphysis morphology
HP:0006489.definition: An anomaly of the femoral metaphysis.

HP:0006492.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fibula
HP:0006492.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the fibula.

HP:0006493.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the lower limbs
HP:0006493.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the lower limbs.

HP:0006494.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the feet

HP:0006495.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ulna
HP:0006495.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the ulna.

HP:0006496.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the upper limbs
HP:0006496.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the upper limbs.

HP:0006498.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the patella
HP:0006498.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the patella.

HP:0006499.name: Abnormal femoral epiphysis morphology
HP:0006499.definition: An anomaly of a growth plate of a femur.

HP:0006500.name: Abnormal lower limb epiphysis morphology
HP:0006500.definition: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or both legs.

HP:0006502.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the carpal bones
HP:0006502.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the carpal bones.

HP:0006503.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving forearm bones
HP:0006503.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of one or more forearm bones.

HP:0006504.name: obsolete Anomaly of the limb diaphyses morphology

HP:0006505.name: Abnormal limb epiphysis morphology
HP:0006505.definition: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of a limb.

HP:0006507.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the humerus
HP:0006507.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the humerus.

HP:0006509.name: Diverticulosis of trachea
HP:0006509.definition: Tracheal diverticula are blind-ended outpouchings arising from the trachea. They are usually an incidental finding. Occasionally they can mimic pneumomediastinum. Tracheal diverticula are either congenital or acquired, in the latter case the most common causes are prolonged increased intraluminal pressure, e.g. chronic cough, COPD, tracheomalacia, and iatrogenic (e.g. post-surgical).

HP:0006510.name: Chronic pulmonary obstruction
HP:0006510.definition: An anomaly that is characterized progressive airflow obstruction that is only partly reversible, inflammation in the airways, and systemic effects or comorbities.

HP:0006511.name: Laryngeal stridor
HP:0006511.definition: An abnormal high-pitched noisy sound, occurring during inhalation or exhalation caused by the incomplete obstruction in the throat.

HP:0006516.name: Hypersensitivity pneumonitis
HP:0006516.definition: Hypersensitivity pneumonitis involves inhalation of an antigen. This leads to an exaggerated immune response and a following inflammation of the alveoli within the lungs. The main feature of chronic hypersensitivity pneumonitis on lung biopsies is expansion of the interstitium by lymphocytes accompanied by an occasional multinucleated giant cell or loose granuloma. After exposure to the provoking antigen, following symptoms can be seen: fever, chills, malaise, cough, hemoptysis, chest tightness, dyspnea, rash, swelling and headache and can be completely reversible, based on the duration of the illness, categorized as acute (HP:0011009), subacute (HP:0011011), and chronic (HP:0011010).

HP:0006517.name: Intraalveolar phospholipid accumulation
HP:0006517.definition: Accumulation of amorphous PAS-positive material in the space between alveolar macrophages, sometimes as condensed form (oval bodies) are typically found in alveolar proteinosis.

HP:0006518.name: Pulmonary venous occlusion
HP:0006518.definition: Substantial narrowing or blockage of small pulmonary veins as a result of disorganized smooth muscle hypertrophy and collagen matrix deposition.

HP:0006521.name: Pulmonary lymphangiectasia
HP:0006521.definition: Abnormal dilatation of the pulmonary lymphatic vessels. Lymphatic fluid in the lung is derived from normal leakage of fluid out of the blood capillaries in the lung. In pulmonary lymphangiectasia, the pulmonary lymphatics are not properly connected and become dilated with fluid.

HP:0006527.name: Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia
HP:0006527.definition: Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonitis is a benign lymphoproliferative disorder of the lung that is characterized by the presence of a dense, predominantly lymphocytic interstitial infiltrate (lymphocytes, plasma cells, other elements of the lymphoreticular system) that expands the alveolar septa.

HP:0006528.name: Chronic lung disease
HP:0006528.definition: According to the definitions of the American and British Thoracic Societies, including pulmonary functional tests, X-rays, and CT scans for items such as fibrosis, bronchiectasis, bullae, emphysema, nodular or lymphomatous abnormalities.

HP:0006529.name: Abnormal pulmonary lymphatics
HP:0006529.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary lymphatic chain.

HP:0006530.name: Abnormal pulmonary interstitial morphology
HP:0006530.definition: Abnormality of the lung parenchyma extending to the pulmonary interstitium and leading to diffuse pulmonary fibrosis.

HP:0006532.name: Recurrent pneumonia
HP:0006532.definition: An increased susceptibility to pneumonia as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of pneumonia.

HP:0006535.name: Recurrent intrapulmonary hemorrhage
HP:0006535.definition: A recurrent hemorrhage occurring within the lung.

HP:0006536.name: Airway obstruction
HP:0006536.definition: Obstruction of conducting airways of the lung.

HP:0006538.name: Recurrent bronchopulmonary infections
HP:0006538.definition: An increased susceptibility to bronchopulmonary infections as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchopulmonary infections.

HP:0006541.name: obsolete Chronic obstructive airway disease from birth

HP:0006544.name: Extrapulmonary lobar sequestration
HP:0006544.definition: A type of pulmonary sequestration that is completely enclosed in its own pleural sac, occurring above, within, or below the diaphragm, and without communication with the tracheobronchial tree.

HP:0006548.name: Pulmonary arteriovenous malformation
HP:0006548.definition: Pulmonary arteriovenous malformation, a condition most commonly associated with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia, is an abnormal communication between the pulmonary artery and pulmonary vein without an intervening capillary communication. HRCT images usually show a coarse spidery appearance of the peripheral vascular markings in the lungs. More specific findings are obtained in the pulmonary angiogram where the normally invisible capillary phase is replaced by irregular vascular channels bridging the peripheral branches of pulmonary arteries and veins.

HP:0006554.name: Acute hepatic failure
HP:0006554.definition: Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as acute if there is onset of encephalopathy within 8 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver.

HP:0006555.name: Diffuse hepatic steatosis
HP:0006555.definition: A diffuse form of hepatic steatosis.

HP:0006558.name: Decreased mitochondrial complex III activity in liver tissue
HP:0006558.definition: Decreased activity of complex III of the mitochondrion in the liver.

HP:0006559.name: Hepatic calcification
HP:0006559.definition: The presence of abnormal calcium deposition in the liver.

HP:0006560.name: Biliary hyperplasia
HP:0006560.definition: Hyperplasia of the biliary tree, as manifested by increased size of bile ducts, dilated lumen, and histologically by an increased number of epithelial cells or hyperplasia.

HP:0006562.name: Viral hepatitis
HP:0006562.definition: Inflammation of the liver due to infection with a virus.

HP:0006563.name: Malformation of the hepatic ductal plate

HP:0006564.name: Fluctuating hepatomegaly
HP:0006564.definition: Intermittently increased size of the liver.

HP:0006565.name: Increased hepatocellular lipid droplets
HP:0006565.definition: An abnormal increase in the amount of intracellular lipid droplets in hepatocytes.

HP:0006568.name: Increased hepatic glycogen content
HP:0006568.definition: An increase in the amount of glycogen stored in hepatocytes compared to normal.

HP:0006571.name: Reduced number of intrahepatic bile ducts
HP:0006571.definition: The presence of reduced numbers of intrahepatic bile duct than normal.

HP:0006573.name: Acute hepatic steatosis
HP:0006573.definition: An acute form of hepatic steatosis.

HP:0006577.name: Macronodular cirrhosis
HP:0006577.definition: A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of large regenerative nodules.

HP:0006579.name: Prolonged neonatal jaundice
HP:0006579.definition: Neonatal jaundice refers to a yellowing of the skin and other tissues of a newborn infant as a result of increased concentrations of bilirubin in the blood. Neonatal jaundice affects over half of all newborns to some extent in the first week of life. Prolonged neonatal jaundice is said to be present if the jaundice persists for longer than 14 days in term infants and 21 days in preterm infants.

HP:0006580.name: Portal fibrosis
HP:0006580.definition: Fibroblast proliferation and fiber expansion from the portal areas to the lobule.

HP:0006581.name: Depletion of mitochondrial DNA in liver
HP:0006581.definition: An abnormal reduction in the number of mitochondria in hepatocytes.

HP:0006582.name: Reye syndrome-like episodes
HP:0006582.definition: Repeated occurrences of acute noninflammatory encephalopathy and fatty degenerative liver failure.

HP:0006585.name: Congenital pseudoarthrosis of the clavicle
HP:0006585.definition: The two portions of the clavicle (corresponding to the two primary ossification centers of the clavicle) are connected by a fibrous bridge that is contiguous with the periosteum, and a synovial membrane develops, resulting in a clavicle with a bipartite appearance radiographically. Congenital pseudarthrosis of the clavicle generally presents as a painless mass or swelling over the clavicle.

HP:0006587.name: Straight clavicles
HP:0006587.definition: An abnormally straight configuration of the clavicle, a tubular bone which normally is doubly curved .

HP:0006591.name: Absent glenoid fossa
HP:0006591.definition: Lack of development of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

HP:0006595.name: Scapulohumeral synostosis
HP:0006595.definition: Bony fusion between the humerus and scapula, leading to an impairment in mobility of the affected shoulder joint.

HP:0006597.name: Diaphragmatic paralysis
HP:0006597.definition: The presence of a paralyzed diaphragm.

HP:0006598.name: Irregular ossification at anterior rib ends

HP:0006606.name: Irregular chondrocostal junctions
HP:0006606.definition: Irregular surface of the normally relatively smooth border between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.

HP:0006607.name: Precocious costochondral ossification
HP:0006607.definition: Early ossification of the costochondral junction, which is the joint between the ribs and costal cartilage in the front of the rib cage.

HP:0006608.name: Midclavicular hypoplasia
HP:0006608.definition: Underdevelopment of the middle portion of the clavicle.

HP:0006610.name: Wide intermamillary distance
HP:0006610.definition: A larger than usual distance between the left and right nipple.

HP:0006611.name: Decreased number of sternal ossification centers
HP:0006611.definition: A less than normal number of sternal ossification centers. The sternum is initially formed from bilateral sternal plates that chondrify and begin to fuse with ribs at 10 weeks gestational age. Ossification starts in the manubrium and upper part of the sternal body at the 6th month, in the middle of the sternal body at the 7th month, in the lower part of the body during the 1st postnatal year and in the xiphoid process between years 5 and 18. The number of ossification centers vary up to six, and it is the ossification centers that are visualized by prenatal ultrasound. This term describes a reduction in the number of ossification centers compared with age-related norms.

HP:0006615.name: Absent in utero rib ossification
HP:0006615.definition: Lack of formation and mineralization of the ribs in utero.

HP:0006619.name: Anterior rib punctate calcifications
HP:0006619.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in point-like foci within the anterior portion of one or more ribs.

HP:0006623.name: Costochondral joint sclerosis
HP:0006623.definition: Abnormal increase in density of the tissue at the costochondral junctions.

HP:0006625.name: Multifocal breast carcinoma
HP:0006625.definition: Breast carcinoma that is bilateral or otherwise multifocal.

HP:0006628.name: Absent sternal ossification
HP:0006628.definition: Lack of formation of mineralized bony tissue of the sternum.

HP:0006633.name: Glenoid fossa hypoplasia
HP:0006633.definition: Underdevelopment of the glenoid fossa, which is the cavity in the lateral part of the scapula which articulates with the head of the humerus.

HP:0006634.name: Osteosclerosis of ribs
HP:0006634.definition: Osteosclerosis of ribs (increased density related to increased bone mass).

HP:0006638.name: Midclavicular aplasia
HP:0006638.definition: Developmental defect resulting in congenital absence of the middle portion of the clavicle.

HP:0006640.name: Multiple rib fractures
HP:0006640.definition: More than one fracture of the ribs. Callus formation around multiple rib fractures can produce a row of multiple rounded expansions (beadlike prominences) giving the appearance of beaded ribs. Note that rachitic rosary would have one bead per rib (a swelling at the costochondral junction), while beaded ribs in the context of multiple rib fractures have multiple beads (fractures) along the same rib.

HP:0006645.name: Thin clavicles
HP:0006645.definition: Abnormally reduced diameter (cross section) of the clavicles.

HP:0006646.name: Costal cartilage calcification
HP:0006646.definition: Calcification of the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage found at the anterior ends of the ribs which serve to prolong the ribs forward and contribute to the elasticity of the walls of the thorax.

HP:0006649.name: Costochondral pain
HP:0006649.definition: Chest wall pain in the area of the costochondral junctions.

HP:0006650.name: Thickening of the lateral border of the scapula

HP:0006660.name: Aplastic clavicle
HP:0006660.definition: Absence of the clavicles as a developmental defect.

HP:0006665.name: Coat hanger sign of ribs
HP:0006665.definition: An abnormal morphology of the ribs consisting of shorted, abnormally curved ribs. On posteroanterior chest radiography, the ribs show a curvature resembling that of a coat hanger (clothes hanger).

HP:0006677.name: Prolonged QRS complex
HP:0006677.definition: Increased time for the complex comprised of the Q wave, R wave, and S wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).. In adults, normal values are 0.06 - 0.10 sec.

HP:0006679.name: Granulomatous coronary arteritis
HP:0006679.definition: Inflammation of the coronary arteries involving a granulomatous response, i.e., a non-specific inflammatory response involving granulomas, defined as a compact organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes including epithelioid and giant cells.

HP:0006682.name: Premature ventricular contraction
HP:0006682.definition: Premature ventricular contractions (PVC) or ventricular extrasystoles are premature contractions of the heart that arise in response to an impulse in the ventricles rather than the normal impulse from the sinoatrial (SA) node.

HP:0006683.name: Abnormal ventricular filling
HP:0006683.definition: An abnormality of filling of a ventricle with blood during diastole.

HP:0006684.name: Ventricular preexcitation with multiple accessory pathways
HP:0006684.definition: A form of ventricular preexcitation due to the presence of multiple accessory pathways for cardiac conduction.

HP:0006685.name: Endocardial fibrosis
HP:0006685.definition: The presence of excessive connective tissue in the endocardium.

HP:0006687.name: Aortic tortuosity
HP:0006687.definition: Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the aorta.

HP:0006689.name: Bacterial endocarditis
HP:0006689.definition: A bacterial infection of the endocardium, the inner layer of the heart, which usually involves the heart valves.

HP:0006691.name: Pulmonic valve myxoma
HP:0006691.definition: A benign tumor of connective tissue containing mucous or gelatinous material (myxoma) localized in the pumonic valve.

HP:0006692.name: Short chordae tendineae of the tricuspid valve
HP:0006692.definition: Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the tricuspid valve.

HP:0006694.name: Early progressive calcific cardiac valvular disease

HP:0006695.name: Atrioventricular canal defect
HP:0006695.definition: A defect of the atrioventricular septum of the heart.

HP:0006698.name: Dilatation of the ventricular cavity
HP:0006698.definition: A localized outpouching of ventricular cavity that is generally associated with dyskinesia and paradoxical expansion during systole.

HP:0006699.name: Premature atrial contractions
HP:0006699.definition: A type of cardiac arrhythmia with premature atrial contractions or beats caused by signals originating from ectopic atrial sites.

HP:0006702.name: Coronary artery dissection
HP:0006702.definition: Acute occurrence of a dissection (tear within the tunica intima and entry of blood into the tunica media) of a coronary artery.

HP:0006704.name: Abnormal coronary artery morphology
HP:0006704.definition: Any structural abnormality of the coronary arteries.

HP:0006705.name: Abnormal atrioventricular valve morphology
HP:0006705.definition: An abnormality of an atrioventricular valve.

HP:0006707.name: Abnormality of the hepatic vasculature
HP:0006707.definition: An abnormality of the hepatic vasculature.

HP:0006710.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the clavicles
HP:0006710.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones).

HP:0006711.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the thorax

HP:0006721.name: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia
HP:0006721.definition: A form of acute leukemia characterized by excess lympoblasts.

HP:0006725.name: Pancreatic adenocarcinoma
HP:0006725.definition: The presence of an adenocarcinoma of the pancreas.

HP:0006727.name: T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemias
HP:0006727.definition: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia of T-cell origin. It comprises about 15% of childhood cases and 25% of adult cases. It is more common in males than females.

HP:0006729.name: Retroperitoneal paraganglioma
HP:0006729.definition: A paraganglioma (previously referred to as chemodectoma) located in the retroperitoneal space. Paragangliomas (also known as extra-adrenal pheochromocytomas) are rare tumors that arise from extra-adrenal chromaffin cells. Paragangliomas are characterized by secretions of excessive catecholamines, including epinephrine, norepinephrine and dopamine, which may lead to clinical symptoms, including episodic hypertension, tachycardia and diaphoresis. However, between 40 and 50% of paragangliomas are non-functional.

HP:0006731.name: Follicular thyroid carcinoma
HP:0006731.definition: The presence of an follicular adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland.

HP:0006732.name: Papillary renal cell carcinoma type 2
HP:0006732.definition: A type of papillary renal cell carcinoma in which the papillae are covered by large eosinophilic cells with pleomorphic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and nuclear pseudostratification.

HP:0006733.name: Acute megakaryocytic leukemia
HP:0006733.definition: A rare subtype of acute myeloid leukemia evolving from primitive megakaryoblasts.

HP:0006735.name: Renal cortical adenoma
HP:0006735.definition: The presence of an adenoma in the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0006737.name: Extraadrenal pheochromocytoma
HP:0006737.definition: Pheochromocytoma not originating from the adrenal medulla but from another source such as from chromaffin cells in or about sympathetic ganglia.

HP:0006739.name: Squamous cell carcinoma of the skin
HP:0006739.definition: Squamous cell carcinoma of the skin is a malignant tumor of squamous epithelium.

HP:0006740.name: Transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder
HP:0006740.definition: The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder with origin in a transitional epithelial cell.

HP:0006744.name: Adrenocortical carcinoma
HP:0006744.definition: A malignant neoplasm of the adrenal cortex that may produce hormones such as cortisol, aldosterone, estrogen, or testosterone.

HP:0006748.name: Adrenal pheochromocytoma
HP:0006748.definition: Pheochromocytoma originating from the adrenal medulla.

HP:0006751.name: Paraspinal neurofibroma
HP:0006751.definition: A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized adjacent to the spine.

HP:0006753.name: Neoplasm of the stomach
HP:0006753.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the stomach.

HP:0006755.name: Cutaneous leiomyosarcoma
HP:0006755.definition: The presence of leiomyosarcoma of the skin.

HP:0006758.name: Malignant genitourinary tract tumor
HP:0006758.definition: The presence of a malignant neoplasm of the genital system.

HP:0006762.name: Renal pelvic carcinoma
HP:0006762.definition: The presence of a carcinoma in the renal pelvis.

HP:0006765.name: Chondrosarcoma
HP:0006765.definition: A slowly growing malignant neoplasm derived from cartilage cells.

HP:0006766.name: Papillary renal cell carcinoma
HP:0006766.definition: The presence of renal cell carcinoma in the renal papilla.

HP:0006767.name: Pituitary prolactin cell adenoma
HP:0006767.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma originating in prolactin secreting cells. This kind of adenoma is characterized by overproduction of prolactin, and may cause loss of menstrual periods and breast milk production in women.

HP:0006770.name: Clear cell renal cell carcinoma
HP:0006770.definition: A subtype of renal cell carcinoma thought to originate from mature renal tubular cells in the proximal tubule of the nehpron.

HP:0006771.name: Duodenal adenocarcinoma
