HP:0006771.definition: A malignant epithelial tumor with a glandular organization that originates in the duodenum.

HP:0006772.name: Renal angiomyolipoma
HP:0006772.definition: A benign renal neoplasm composed of fat, vascular, and smooth muscle elements.

HP:0006774.name: Ovarian papillary adenocarcinoma
HP:0006774.definition: The presence of a papillary adenocarcinoma of the ovary.

HP:0006775.name: Multiple myeloma
HP:0006775.definition: A malignant plasma cell tumor growing within soft tissue or within the skeleton.

HP:0006778.name: Benign genitourinary tract neoplasm
HP:0006778.definition: A non-malignant neoplasm of the genitourinary system.

HP:0006780.name: Parathyroid carcinoma
HP:0006780.definition: A malignancy of the parathyroid glands. Parathyroid carcinoma usually secretes parathyroid hormone, leading to hyperparathyroidism.

HP:0006781.name: Hurthle cell thyroid adenoma
HP:0006781.definition: A kind of thyroid adenoma characterized by the presence of oxyphil cells.

HP:0006785.name: Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy
HP:0006785.definition: Muscular dystrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle (the hips and shoulders).

HP:0006794.name: Loss of ability to walk in first decade

HP:0006802.name: Abnormal anterior horn cell morphology
HP:0006802.definition: Any anomaly of the anterior horn cell.

HP:0006803.name: Vivid hallucination
HP:0006803.definition: Perceptual experiences that are vivid, intense, and sensory in nature occur in the absence of corresponding stimuli from the external environment.

HP:0006808.name: Cerebral hypomyelination
HP:0006808.definition: Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the white matter of the central nervous system.

HP:0006812.name: White mater abnormalities in the posterior periventricular region

HP:0006813.name: Focal hemiclonic seizure
HP:0006813.definition: A type of focal clonic seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking rapidly involves one side of the body at seizure onset.

HP:0006817.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis
HP:0006817.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0006818.name: 4-layered lissencephaly
HP:0006818.definition: A form of lissencephaly in which the cortex is thickened and has four more or less disorganized layers rather than six normal layers resulting from incomplete neuronal migration during brain development. At neuropathological examination, a 4-layered cortex consists of an upper molecular layer, a second thin cellular layer containing pyramidal neurons usually observed in layer V, a third pale poorly cellular layer and a fourth thick deep layer made up of neurons which had failed to migrate. Radiologocally would manifest as agyria or pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm.

HP:0006821.name: Frontal polymicrogyria
HP:0006821.definition: A type of polymicrogyria with a gradient of severity (anterior more severe than posterior) extending from frontal poles posteriorly to precentral gyrus and inferiorly to frontal operculum.

HP:0006825.name: Pallor of dorsal columns of the spinal cord
HP:0006825.definition: An abnormally pale appearance of the dorsal portion of the gray substance of the spinal cord. This finding can be observed by histological examination.

HP:0006829.name: Severe muscular hypotonia
HP:0006829.definition: A severe degree of muscular hypotonia characterized by markedly reduced muscle tone.

HP:0006830.name: obsolete Severe neonatal hypotonia in males

HP:0006834.name: Developmental stagnation at onset of seizures
HP:0006834.definition: A cessation of the development of a child in the areas of motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and/or emotional skills, following the onset of epilepsy.

HP:0006837.name: Congenital Horner syndrome
HP:0006837.definition: A type of Horner syndrome with congenital onset.

HP:0006844.name: Absent patellar reflexes
HP:0006844.definition: Absence of the knee jerk reflex, which can normally be elicited by tapping the patellar tendon with a reflex hammer just below the patella.

HP:0006849.name: Hypodysplasia of the corpus callosum
HP:0006849.definition: Developmental defect characterized by a small and malformed corpus callosum.

HP:0006850.name: Hypoplasia of the ventral pons
HP:0006850.definition: Underdevelopment of the ventral portion of the pons.

HP:0006851.name: Symmetric spinal nerve root neurofibromas
HP:0006851.definition: Multiple neurofibromas of the spinal nerve roots with a symmetric distribution.

HP:0006852.name: Episodic generalized hypotonia
HP:0006852.definition: The occurrence of repeated episodes of generalized muscular hypotonia.

HP:0006855.name: Cerebellar vermis atrophy
HP:0006855.definition: Wasting (atrophy) of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0006858.name: Impaired distal proprioception
HP:0006858.definition: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position occurring at distal joints.

HP:0006863.name: Severe expressive language delay
HP:0006863.definition: A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

HP:0006865.name: Sensorimotor polyneuropathy affecting arms more than legs

HP:0006870.name: Lobar holoprosencephaly
HP:0006870.definition: A type of holoprosencephaly in which most of the right and left cerebral hemispheres and lateral ventricles are separated but the most rostral aspect of the telencephalon, the frontal lobes, are fused, especially ventrally.

HP:0006873.name: Symmetrical progressive peripheral demyelination
HP:0006873.definition: A symmetric and progressive loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0006879.name: Pontocerebellar atrophy
HP:0006879.definition: Atrophy affecting the pons and the cerebellum.

HP:0006881.name: Diffuse peripheral demyelination
HP:0006881.definition: A diffuse loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0006886.name: Impaired distal vibration sensation
HP:0006886.definition: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the distal portions of the limbs.

HP:0006887.name: Intellectual disability, progressive
HP:0006887.definition: The term progressive intellectual disability should be used if intelligence decreases/deteriorates over time.

HP:0006889.name: Intellectual disability, borderline
HP:0006889.definition: Borderline intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 70-85.

HP:0006892.name: Frontotemporal cerebral atrophy
HP:0006892.definition: Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the frontotemporal cerebrum.

HP:0006896.name: Hypnopompic hallucination
HP:0006896.definition: Brief hallucinations that occur as you wake up in the morning, in a state that falls somewhere between dreaming and being fully awake.

HP:0006897.name: Abducens palsy
HP:0006897.definition: Malfunction of the abducens nerve as manifested by impairment of the ability of the affected eye to be moved outward. Patients who develop abducens nerve palsy often present with binocular horizontal diplopia, which is a double vision when looking at objects side by side. There will be a notable weakness of the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle leading to a deficit in of eye abduction on the affected side. Some patients may present with a constant head turning movement to maintain binocular fusion and to lessen the degree of diplopia.

HP:0006906.name: Congenital intracerebral calcification
HP:0006906.definition: The presence of calcium deposition within brain structures that is present already at the time of birth.

HP:0006916.name: Intraaxonal accumulation of curvilinear autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
HP:0006916.definition: Curvilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material within axons.

HP:0006919.name: obsolete Abnormal aggressive, impulsive or violent behavior

HP:0006921.name: Axial muscle stiffness
HP:0006921.definition: Stiffness (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) of the axial musculature.

HP:0006927.name: Unilateral polymicrogyria
HP:0006927.definition: Excessive number of small gyri (convolutions) on the surface of one side of the brain.

HP:0006929.name: Hypoglycemic encephalopathy
HP:0006929.definition: Brain damage related to a lowering of blood glucose below a critical level (around 30 mg/dl), which may lead to confusion, lethargy and delirium followed by seizures and coma. Prolonged hypoglycemia may lead to irreversible brain damage.

HP:0006930.name: Frontoparietal cortical dysplasia
HP:0006930.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the cortex of frontal lobe and the cortex of parietal lobe.

HP:0006931.name: Pericallosal lipoma
HP:0006931.definition: Pericallosal lipomas are congenital soft masses of adipose cells encapsulated by a thin layer of fibrous tissue, appearing adjacent to the corpus callosum of the brain.

HP:0006932.name: Transient psychotic episodes
HP:0006932.definition: Relatively short-lived periods of psychosis are characterized by the sudden onset of severe disturbances in perception, thinking, and behavior. These episodes typically last for a brief duration, generally ranging from a few days to a few weeks, and are often triggered by a significant stressor or traumatic event.

HP:0006934.name: Congenital nystagmus
HP:0006934.definition: Nystagmus dating from or present at birth.

HP:0006937.name: Impaired distal tactile sensation
HP:0006937.definition: A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation) on the skin of the distal limbs. This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.

HP:0006938.name: Impaired vibration sensation at ankles
HP:0006938.definition: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration at the ankles. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to the malleoli of the ankles.

HP:0006944.name: Abolished vibration sense
HP:0006944.definition: A complete loss of the ability to perceive vibration.

HP:0006946.name: Recurrent meningitis
HP:0006946.definition: An increased susceptibility to meningitis as manifested by a medical history of recurrent episodes of meningitis.

HP:0006955.name: Olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia
HP:0006955.definition: Hypoplasia of the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.

HP:0006957.name: obsolete Loss of ability to walk

HP:0006958.name: Abnormal auditory evoked potentials
HP:0006958.definition: An abnormality of the auditory evoked potentials, which are used to trace the signal generated by a sound, from the cochlear nerve, through the lateral lemniscus, to the medial geniculate nucleus, and to the cortex.

HP:0006959.name: Proximal spinal muscular atrophy
HP:0006959.definition: Proximal spinal muscular atrophy, i.e., muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.

HP:0006960.name: Choroid plexus calcification
HP:0006960.definition: The presence of calcium deposition in the choroid plexus.

HP:0006962.name: Gait instability, worse in the dark

HP:0006970.name: Periventricular leukomalacia
HP:0006970.definition: Periventricular leukomalacia is characterized by diffuse injury of deep cerebral white matter, accompanied in its most severe form by focal necrosis. The neuropathologic hallmarks of PVL are microglial activation and focal and diffuse periventricular depletion of premyelinating oligodendroglia.

HP:0006976.name: Necrotizing encephalopathy
HP:0006976.definition: A type of encephalopathy (brain disease, damage, or malfunction accompanied by an altered mental state) that is characterized by evidence of necrosis of brain tissue.

HP:0006977.name: Deficit in grammar
HP:0006977.definition: Deficit in grammar, including syntax and morphology.

HP:0006979.name: Sleep-wake cycle disturbance
HP:0006979.definition: Any abnormality of an individual's circadian rhythm that affects the timing of sleeping and being awake is referred to as a sleep-wake disorder.

HP:0006980.name: Progressive leukoencephalopathy
HP:0006980.definition: Leukoencephalopathy that gets more severe with time.

HP:0006984.name: obsolete Distal sensory loss of all modalities

HP:0006988.name: Alobar holoprosencephaly
HP:0006988.definition: A type of holoprosencephaly characterized by the presence of a single ventricle and no separation of the cerebral hemisphere. The single midline ventricle is often greatly enlarged.

HP:0006989.name: Dysplastic corpus callosum
HP:0006989.definition: Dysplasia and dysgenesis of the corpus callosum are nonspecific descriptions that imply defective development of the corpus callosum. The term dysplasia is applied when the morphology of the corpus callosum is altered as a congenital trait. For instance, the corpus callosum may be hump-shaped, kinked, or a striped corpus callosum that lacks an anatomically distinct genu and splenium.

HP:0006990.name: Myelin-dependent gliosis
HP:0006990.definition: A type of gliosis that occurs in the vicinity of injured neurons.

HP:0006999.name: Basal ganglia gliosis
HP:0006999.definition: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the basal ganglia.

HP:0007001.name: Loss of Purkinje cells in the cerebellar vermis

HP:0007002.name: Motor axonal neuropathy
HP:0007002.definition: Progressive impairment of function of motor axons with muscle weakness, atrophy, and cramps. The deficits are length-dependent, meaning that muscles innervated by the longest nerves are affected first, so that for instance the arms are affected at a later age than the onset of deficits involving the lower leg.

HP:0007007.name: Cavitation of the basal ganglia
HP:0007007.definition: The formation of small cavities in the tissue of the basal ganglia.

HP:0007010.name: Poor fine motor coordination
HP:0007010.definition: An abnormality of the ability (skills) to perform a precise movement of small muscles with the intent to perform a specific act. Fine motor skills are required to mediate movements of the wrists, hands, fingers, feet, and toes.

HP:0007011.name: Fourth cranial nerve palsy
HP:0007011.definition: Paralysis of the fourth cranial (trochlear) nerve manifested as weakness of the superior oblique muscle which causes vertical diplopia that is maximal when the affected eye is adducted and directed inferiorly.

HP:0007015.name: Poor gross motor coordination
HP:0007015.definition: An abnormality of the ability (skills) to perform a precise movement of large muscles with the intent to perform a specific act. Gross motor skills are required to mediate movements of the arms, legs, and other large body parts.

HP:0007018.name: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder
HP:0007018.definition: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) manifests at age 2-3 years or by first grade at the latest. The main symptoms are distractibility, impulsivity, hyperactivity, and often trouble organizing tasks and projects, difficulty going to sleep, and social problems from being aggressive, loud, or impatient.

HP:0007023.name: Antenatal intracerebral hemorrhage
HP:0007023.definition: Cerebral hemorrhage that occurs before birth.

HP:0007024.name: Pseudobulbar paralysis
HP:0007024.definition: Bilateral impairment of the function of the cranial nerves 9-12, which control musculature involved in eating, swallowing, and speech. Pseudobulbar paralysis is characterized clinically by dysarthria, dysphonia, and dysphagia with bifacial paralysis, and may be accompanied by Pseudobulbar behavioral symptoms such as enforced crying and laughing.

HP:0007027.name: Poorly formed metencephalon
HP:0007027.definition: A morphological abnormality of the metencephalon.

HP:0007029.name: Cerebral berry aneurysm
HP:0007029.definition: A small, sac-like aneurysm (outpouching) of a cerebral blood vessel.

HP:0007033.name: Cerebellar dysplasia
HP:0007033.definition: Cerebellar dysplasia (abnormal growth or development) is defined by abnormal cerebellar foliation, white matter arborization, and gray-white matter junction. Cerebellar dysplasia is a neuroimaging finding that describes abnormalities of both the cerebellar cortex and white matter and is associated with variable neurodevelopmental outcome. Dysplasia may globally involve the cerebellum or affect only one cerebellar hemisphere. In addition, cerebellar dysplasia may be associated with cortical/subcortical cysts.

HP:0007035.name: Anterior encephalocele
HP:0007035.definition: A type of congenital malformation in which brain tissue protrudes through a defect in the anterior (front) part of the skull.

HP:0007039.name: Symmetric T2-signal increase with T1-signal decrease in the putamen
HP:0007039.definition: A symmetric magnetic resonance imaing (MRI) abnormality of the basal ganglia characterized by an increase of signal intensity in T2-weighted images and a corresponding signal decrease on T1-weighted images.

HP:0007041.name: Chronic lymphocytic meningitis
HP:0007041.definition: Meningitis that persists for more than 4 weeks, and lymphocytes are present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0007047.name: Atrophy of the dentate nucleus
HP:0007047.definition: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of dentate nucleus.

HP:0007048.name: Large basal ganglia
HP:0007048.definition: Increased size of the basal ganglia.

HP:0007054.name: Proximal hyperreflexia
HP:0007054.definition: Hyperactive stretch reflexes of muscles that move proximal joints (elbow, knee).

HP:0007058.name: Generalized cerebral atrophy/hypoplasia
HP:0007058.definition: Generalized atrophy or hypoplasia of the cerebrum.

HP:0007063.name: Aplasia of the inferior half of the cerebellar vermis

HP:0007064.name: Progressive language deterioration
HP:0007064.definition: Progressive loss of previously present language abilities.

HP:0007065.name: Disorganization of the anterior cerebellar vermis

HP:0007066.name: Proximal limb muscle stiffness
HP:0007066.definition: Stiffness of the limbs (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) occurring in the proximal limb muscle.

HP:0007067.name: Distal peripheral sensory neuropathy
HP:0007067.definition: Peripheral sensory neuropathy affecting primarily distal sensation.

HP:0007068.name: Inferior cerebellar vermis hypoplasia
HP:0007068.definition: Underdevelopment of the inferior portion of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0007074.name: Thick corpus callosum
HP:0007074.definition: Increased vertical dimension of the corpus callosum. This feature can be visualized by sagittal sections on magnetic resonance tomography imaging of the brain.

HP:0007076.name: Extrapyramidal muscular rigidity
HP:0007076.definition: Muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).

HP:0007078.name: Decreased amplitude of sensory action potentials
HP:0007078.definition: A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.

HP:0007082.name: Dilated third ventricle
HP:0007082.definition: An increase in size of the third ventricle.

HP:0007089.name: Facial-lingual fasciculations
HP:0007089.definition: Fasciculations affecting the tongue muscle and the musculature of the face.

HP:0007098.name: Paroxysmal choreoathetosis
HP:0007098.definition: Episodes of choreoathetosis that can occur following triggers such as quick voluntary movements.

HP:0007099.name: Chiari type I malformation
HP:0007099.definition: Arnold-Chiari type I malformation refers to a relatively mild degree of herniation of the posteroinferior region of the cerebellum (the cerebellar tonsils) into the cervical canal with little or no displacement of the fourth ventricle. It is characterized by one or both pointed (not rounded) cerebellar tonsils that project 5 mm below the foramen magnum, measured by a line drawn from the basion to the opisthion (McRae Line)

HP:0007103.name: Hypointensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
HP:0007103.definition: A darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

HP:0007105.name: Infantile encephalopathy
HP:0007105.definition: Encephalopathy with onset in the infantile period.

HP:0007107.name: Segmental peripheral demyelination
HP:0007107.definition: A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers from segments of the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0007108.name: Demyelinating peripheral neuropathy
HP:0007108.definition: Demyelinating neuropathy is characterized by slow nerve conduction velocities with reduced amplitudes of sensory/motor nerve conduction and prolonged distal latencies.

HP:0007115.name: Naso-orbital encephalocele
HP:0007115.definition: A type of encephalocele that occurs along the medial orbit wall at the level of the frontal process of the maxilla and the ethmoid-lacrimal bone junction.

HP:0007123.name: Subcortical dementia
HP:0007123.definition: A particular type of dementia characterized by a pattern of mental defects consisting prominently of forgetfulness, slowness of thought processes, and personality or mood change.

HP:0007126.name: Proximal amyotrophy
HP:0007126.definition: Amyotrophy (muscular atrophy) affecting the proximal musculature.

HP:0007131.name: Acute demyelinating polyneuropathy
HP:0007131.definition: Acute progressive areflexic weakness and mild sensory changes resulting from myelin breakdown and axonal degeneration.

HP:0007132.name: Pallidal degeneration
HP:0007132.definition: Neurodegeneration involving the globus pallidus,a part of the basal ganglia that is involved in the regulation of voluntary movement.

HP:0007149.name: Distal upper limb amyotrophy
HP:0007149.definition: Muscular atrophy of distal arm muscles.

HP:0007156.name: Asymmetric limb muscle stiffness
HP:0007156.definition: Stiffness of the limbs (a condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm) occurring in an asymmetric pattern.

HP:0007158.name: Progressive extrapyramidal muscular rigidity
HP:0007158.definition: A progressive degree of muscular rigidity (continuous contraction of muscles with constant resistance to passive movement).

HP:0007159.name: Fluctuations in consciousness
HP:0007159.definition: Changes in one's level of awareness and responsiveness to their environment.

HP:0007162.name: Diffuse demyelination of the cerebral white matter
HP:0007162.definition: A diffuse loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

HP:0007163.name: obsolete Corticospinal tract disease in lower limbs

HP:0007165.name: Periventricular heterotopia
HP:0007165.definition: A form of gray matter heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is typically located periventricularly, also sometimes called subependymal heterotopia. Periventricular means beside the ventricles. This is by far the most common location for heterotopia. Subependymal heterotopia present in a wide array of variations. There can be a small single node or a large number of nodes, can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, can be small or large, single or multiple, and can form a small node or a large wavy or curved mass.

HP:0007166.name: Paroxysmal dyskinesia
HP:0007166.definition: Episodic bouts of involuntary movements with dystonic, choreic, ballistic movements, or a combination thereof. There is no loss of consciousness during the attacks.

HP:0007179.name: Absent smooth pursuit
HP:0007179.definition: A complete lack of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion.

HP:0007181.name: Interosseus muscle atrophy
HP:0007181.definition: Atrophy of the interosseus muscles (including the palmar interossei that lie on the anterior aspect of the metacarpals, the dorsal interosseus muscles of the hand, which lie between the intercarpals, the plantar interosseus muscles, which lie underneath the metatarsal bones, and the dorsal interossei, which are located between the metatarsal bones.

HP:0007182.name: Peripheral hypomyelination
HP:0007182.definition: Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0007183.name: Focal T2 hyperintense basal ganglia lesion
HP:0007183.definition: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.

HP:0007185.name: Loss of consciousness
HP:0007185.definition: Loss of alertness and orientation to place and time.

HP:0007187.name: Focal lissencephaly
HP:0007187.definition: A congenital absence of the convolutions of the cerebral cortex and a poorly formed sylvian fissure that affects a particular part of the cortex.

HP:0007188.name: Congenital facial diplegia
HP:0007188.definition: Facial diplegia (that is, bilateral facial palsy) with congenital onset.

HP:0007190.name: Neuronal loss in the cerebral cortex

HP:0007193.name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure on awakening
HP:0007193.definition: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure of either generalized or focal onset occurring on or soon after wakening (typically within 90 minutes of waking, regardless of the time of day).

HP:0007200.name: Episodic hypersomnia
HP:0007200.definition: Recurrent episodes of severe hypersomnia are accompanied by cognitive and behavioral disturbances, including confusion, derealization, apathy, compulsive eating, and hypersexuality.

HP:0007201.name: Cerebral artery atherosclerosis
HP:0007201.definition: The formation of the formation of fibrofatty lesions in the wall of an artery located in the brain.

HP:0007206.name: Hemimegalencephaly
HP:0007206.definition: Enlargement of all or parts of one cerebral hemisphere.

HP:0007207.name: Photosensitive tonic-clonic seizure
HP:0007207.definition: Generalized-onset tonic-clonic seizures that are provoked by flashing or flickering light.

HP:0007208.name: Irregular myelin loops
HP:0007208.definition: Presence of irregular redundant loops of focally folded myelin in a peripheral nerve.

HP:0007209.name: Facial paralysis
HP:0007209.definition: Complete loss of ability to move facial muscles innervated by the facial nerve (i.e., the seventh cranial nerve).

HP:0007210.name: Lower limb amyotrophy
HP:0007210.definition: Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb.

HP:0007215.name: Periodic hyperkalemic paralysis
HP:0007215.definition: Episodes of muscle weakness associated with elevated levels of potassium in the blood.

HP:0007229.name: Intracerebral periventricular calcifications
HP:0007229.definition: The presence of calcium deposition in the cerebral white matter surrounding the cerebral ventricles.

HP:0007230.name: Decreased distal sensory nerve action potential
HP:0007230.definition: A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential in distal nerve segments. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.

HP:0007232.name: Spinocerebellar tract disease in lower limbs

HP:0007233.name: Clusters of axonal regeneration
HP:0007233.definition: Groups of small caliber axons in peripheral nerve biospies indicative of axonal regeneration.

HP:0007240.name: Progressive gait ataxia
HP:0007240.definition: A type of gait ataxia displaying progression of clinical severity.

HP:0007249.name: Decreased number of small peripheral myelinated nerve fibers

HP:0007250.name: Recurrent external ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007250.definition: Alternating and recurrent weakness of the external ocular muscles.

HP:0007256.name: Abnormal pyramidal sign
HP:0007256.definition: Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract.

HP:0007258.name: Severe demyelination of the white matter
HP:0007258.definition: A severe loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

HP:0007260.name: Type II lissencephaly
HP:0007260.definition: A form of lissencephaly characterized by an uneven cortical surface with a so called 'cobblestone' appearace. There are no distinguishable cortical layers.

HP:0007262.name: Symmetric peripheral demyelination
HP:0007262.definition: A symmetric loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0007263.name: Spinocerebellar atrophy
HP:0007263.definition: Atrophy affecting the cerebellum and the spinocerebellar tracts of the spinal cord.

HP:0007266.name: Cerebral dysmyelination
HP:0007266.definition: Defective structure and function of myelin sheaths of the white matter of the brain.

HP:0007267.name: Chronic axonal neuropathy
HP:0007267.definition: An abnormality characterized by chronic impairment of the normal functioning of the axons.

HP:0007269.name: Spinal muscular atrophy
HP:0007269.definition: Muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.

HP:0007270.name: Atypical absence seizure
HP:0007270.definition: An atypical absence seizure is a type of generalized non-motor (absence) seizure characterized by interruption of ongoing activities and reduced responsiveness. In comparison to a typical absence seizure, changes in tone may be more pronounced, onset and/or cessation may be less abrupt, and the duration of the ictus and post-ictal recovery may be longer. Although not always available, an EEG often demonstrates slow (<3 Hz), irregular, generalized spike-wave activity.

HP:0007274.name: Recurrent bacterial meningitis
HP:0007274.definition: An increased susceptibility to bacterial meningitis as manifested by a medical history of recurrent episodes of bacterial meningitis.

HP:0007277.name: Paucity of anterior horn motor neurons

HP:0007281.name: Developmental stagnation
HP:0007281.definition: A cessation of the development of a child in the areas of motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and/or emotional skills.

HP:0007285.name: Facial palsy secondary to cranial hyperostosis
HP:0007285.definition: Paralysis of the facial nerves on the basis of overgrowth of the cranial bones causing impingement upon the seventh cranial nerve.

HP:0007286.name: Horizontal jerk nystagmus
HP:0007286.definition: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements, in which the movement in one direction is faster than in the other.

HP:0007289.name: Limb fasciculations
HP:0007289.definition: Fasciculations affecting the musculature of the arms and legs.

HP:0007291.name: Posterior fossa cyst
HP:0007291.definition: A discrete posterior fossa cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) collection that does not communicate directly with the fourth ventricle.

HP:0007301.name: Oromotor apraxia
HP:0007301.definition: Oral-motor apraxia is the inability to volitionally sequence oral movements of the speech structure for nonspeech tasks in the absence of neuromuscular deficits such as paralysis or muscle weakness. Oral-motor apraxia is diagnosed when, despite intact sensory motor function an individual is unable to use these effector systems under voluntary control.

HP:0007302.name: Bipolar affective disorder
HP:0007302.definition: Bipolar disorder is an illness of mood characterized by alternating episodes of elevated and depressed moods, which are interspersed with euthymic periods.

HP:0007305.name: CNS demyelination
HP:0007305.definition: A loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

HP:0007307.name: Rapid neurologic deterioration
HP:0007307.definition: Loss of neurological function in a time frame that is considered relatively quick, for instance, loss of a develomental milestone or substantial exacerbation of neurological complications such as seizures or feeding difficulties within a few months.

HP:0007321.name: Deep white matter hypodensities
HP:0007321.definition: Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the deep cerebral white matter.

HP:0007325.name: Generalized dystonia
HP:0007325.definition: A type of dystonia that affects all or most of the body.

HP:0007328.name: Impaired pain sensation
HP:0007328.definition: Reduced ability to perceive painful stimuli.

HP:0007330.name: Frontoethmoidal encephalocele
HP:0007330.definition: A type of anterior encephalocele in which there is a protrusion of the contents of the skull through a breach at the point where the frontal and ethmoidal bones meet. Frontoethmoidal encephalocele can be divided further into three distinct categories: nasofrontal, nasoethmoidal, and nasoorbital.

HP:0007332.name: Focal hemifacial clonic seizure
HP:0007332.definition: Focal seizure characterized at onset by clonic movements affecting half of the face.

HP:0007333.name: Hypoplasia of the frontal lobes
HP:0007333.definition: Underdevelopment of the frontal lobe of the cerebrum.

HP:0007334.name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with focal onset
HP:0007334.definition: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with focal onset is a focal-onset seizure which progresses into a bilateral tonic-clonic phase.

HP:0007335.name: Recurrent encephalopathy
HP:0007335.definition: Recurrent episodes of brain dysfunction that may be triggered by factors such as metabolic disturbances or infections.

HP:0007338.name: Hypermetric saccades
HP:0007338.definition: A saccade that overshoots the target with the dynamic saccade.

HP:0007340.name: Lower limb muscle weakness
HP:0007340.definition: Weakness of the muscles of the legs.

HP:0007341.name: Diffuse swelling of cerebral white matter

HP:0007343.name: Abnormal morphology of the limbic system
HP:0007343.definition: Any structural anomaly of the limbic system, a set of midline structures surrounding the brainstem of the mammalian brain, originally described anatomically, e.g., hippocampal formation, amygdala, hypothalamus, cingulate cortex. Although the original designation was anatomical, the limbic system has come to be associated with the system in the brain subserving emotional functions. As such, it is very poorly defined and doesn't correspond closely to the anatomical meaning any longer. [BirnLex].

HP:0007350.name: Upper limb hyperreflexia
HP:0007350.definition: Increased intensity of the a reflex in the arm.

HP:0007351.name: Upper limb postural tremor
HP:0007351.definition: A type of tremors that is triggered by holding an arm in a fixed position.

HP:0007359.name: Focal-onset seizure
HP:0007359.definition: A focal-onset seizure is a type of seizure originating within networks limited to one hemisphere. They may be discretely localized or more widely distributed, and may originate in subcortical structures.

HP:0007361.name: Abnormal pons morphology
HP:0007361.definition: A structural abnormality of the pons.

HP:0007367.name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system

HP:0007369.name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the cerebrum
HP:0007369.definition: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebrum, also known as the telencephalon, the largest and most highly developed part of the human brain.

HP:0007370.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the corpus callosum
HP:0007370.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.

HP:0007371.name: Corpus callosum atrophy
HP:0007371.definition: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the corpus callosum.

HP:0007375.name: Abnormal septum pellucidum morphology
HP:0007375.definition: An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.

HP:0007376.name: Abnormal choroid plexus morphology
HP:0007376.definition: An abnormality of the choroid plexus, which is the area in the cerebral ventricles in which cerebrospinal fluid is produced by modified ependymal cells.

HP:0007377.name: Abnormality of somatosensory evoked potentials
HP:0007377.definition: An abnormality of somatosensory evoked potentials (SSEP), i.e., of the electrical signals of sensation going from the body to the brain in response to a defined stimulus. Recording electrodes are placed over the scalp, spine, and peripheral nerves proximal to the stimulation site. Clinical studies generally use electrical stimulation of peripheral nerves to elicit potentials. SSEP testing determines whether peripheral sensory nerves are able to transmit sensory information like pain, temperature, and touch to the brain. Abnormal SSEPs can result from dysfunction at the level of the peripheral nerve, plexus, spinal root, spinal cord, brain stem, thalamocortical projections, or primary somatosensory cortex.

HP:0007378.name: Neoplasm of the gastrointestinal tract
HP:0007378.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0007379.name: Neoplasm of the genitourinary tract
HP:0007379.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genitourinary system.

HP:0007380.name: Facial telangiectasia
HP:0007380.definition: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin of the face.

HP:0007385.name: Aplasia cutis congenita of scalp
HP:0007385.definition: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp.

HP:0007395.name: Postnatal-onset ichthyosiform erythroderma
HP:0007395.definition: A type of ichthyosiform erythroderma with postnatal onset.

HP:0007396.name: Early cutaneous photosensitivity
HP:0007396.definition: Photosensitivity of the skin occurring early in life.

HP:0007397.name: Axillary apocrine gland hypoplasia
HP:0007397.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the apocrine sweat glands in the region of the axilla.

HP:0007401.name: Macular atrophy
HP:0007401.definition: Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the macula, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.

HP:0007402.name: Areas of hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation that do not follow Blaschko lines

HP:0007404.name: Nonepidermolytic palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007404.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles charactersized by hyperkeratosis of the stratum corneum with no evidence of epidermolysis characteristic of epidermolytic hyperkeratosis.

HP:0007407.name: Excessive skin wrinkling on dorsum of hands and fingers

HP:0007408.name: Tegumentary leishmaniasis susceptibility
HP:0007408.definition: Increased susceptibility to infection by the protozan parasite of the genus Leishmania.

HP:0007409.name: obsolete Absence of subcutaneous fat over entire body except buttocks, hips, and thighs

HP:0007410.name: Palmoplantar hyperhidrosis
HP:0007410.definition: An abnormally increased perspiration on palms and soles.

HP:0007413.name: Nevus flammeus of the forehead
HP:0007413.definition: Naevus flammeus localized in the skin of the forehead.

HP:0007414.name: Neonatal wrinkled skin of hands and feet

HP:0007417.name: Discoid lupus rash
HP:0007417.definition: Cutaneous lesion that develops as a dry, scaly, red patch that evolves to an indurated and hyperpigmented plaque with adherent scale. Scarring may result in central white patches (loss of pigmentation) and skin atrophy.

HP:0007420.name: Spontaneous hematomas
HP:0007420.definition: Spontaneous development of hematomas (hematoma) or bruises without significant trauma.

HP:0007421.name: Telangiectases of the cheeks
HP:0007421.definition: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin of the cheeks.

HP:0007428.name: Telangiectasia of the oral mucosa
HP:0007428.definition: Telangiectasia (that is, the presence of small dilated superficial blood vessels) of the oral mucosa.

HP:0007429.name: Few cafe-au-lait spots
HP:0007429.definition: The presence of two to five cafe-au-lait macules.

HP:0007430.name: Generalized edema
HP:0007430.definition: Generalized abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body.

HP:0007431.name: Congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma
HP:0007431.definition: An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin with congenital onset.

HP:0007434.name: Plaque-like facial hemangioma
HP:0007434.definition: Hemangioma is a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells. This term refers to facial hemangiomas that have a plaque-like morphology.

HP:0007437.name: Multiple cutaneous leiomyomas
HP:0007437.definition: The presence of multiple leiomyomas of the skin.

HP:0007438.name: Mottled pigmentation of the trunk and proximal extremities

HP:0007443.name: Partial albinism
HP:0007443.definition: Absence of melanin pigment in various areas, which is found at birth and is permanent. The lesions are known as leucoderma and are often found on the face, trunk, or limbs.

HP:0007446.name: Palmoplantar blistering
HP:0007446.definition: A type of blistering that affects the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.

HP:0007447.name: Diffuse palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007447.definition: Diffuse abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles.

HP:0007450.name: Increased groin pigmentation with raindrop depigmentation

HP:0007451.name: Ipsilateral lack of facial sweating
HP:0007451.definition: Inability to sweat on the same side of the face that is affected by ptosis and miosis. This is a feature of Horner syndrome.

HP:0007453.name: Flexural lichenification
HP:0007453.definition: Lichenification affecting primarily flexural areas of the skin.

HP:0007460.name: Autoamputation of digits
HP:0007460.definition: The spontaneous detachment of a digit (finger or toe) from the body due to long standing pathology.

HP:0007462.name: Bitot spots of the conjunctiva
HP:0007462.definition: Keratinization of the bulbar conjunctiva near the limbus (corneoscleral junction), resulting in a raised spot.

HP:0007464.name: Sparse facial hair
HP:0007464.definition: Reduced number or density of facial hair.

HP:0007465.name: Honeycomb palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007465.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles with an honeycomb pattern.

HP:0007468.name: Perifollicular hyperkeratosis
HP:0007468.definition: Increased amount of keratin (visible as white scales) surrounding hair follicles.

HP:0007469.name: Palmoplantar cutis gyrata
HP:0007469.definition: Cutis gyrata of palms and soles.

HP:0007470.name: Periarticular subcutaneous nodules
HP:0007470.definition: Subcutaneous nodules that are located in the vicinity of joints.

HP:0007471.name: Axillary and groin hyperpigmentation and hypopigmentation

HP:0007475.name: Congenital bullous ichthyosiform erythroderma
HP:0007475.definition: An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin that presents at birth or shortly thereafter with generalized erythema, blistering, erosions, and peeling. In the subsequent months, erythema and blistering improves but patients go on to develop hyperkeratotic scaling that is especially prominent along the joint flexures, neck, hands and feet.

HP:0007477.name: Abnormal dermatoglyphics
HP:0007477.definition: An abnormality of dermatoglyphs (fingerprints), which are present on fingers, palms, toes, and soles.

HP:0007479.name: Congenital nonbullous ichthyosiform erythroderma
HP:0007479.definition: The term collodion baby applies to newborns who appear to have an extra layer of skin (known as a collodion membrane) that has a collodion-like quality. It is a descriptive term, not a specific diagnosis or disorder (as such, it is a syndrome). Affected babies are born in a collodion membrane, a shiny waxy outer layer to the skin. This is shed 10-14 days after birth, revealing the main symptom of the disease, extensive scaling of the skin caused by hyperkeratosis. With increasing age, the scaling tends to be concentrated around joints in areas such as the groin, the armpits, the inside of the elbow and the neck. The scales often tile the skin and may resemble fish scales.

HP:0007480.name: Decreased sweating due to autonomic dysfunction

HP:0007489.name: Diffuse telangiectasia
HP:0007489.definition: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) with a diffuse localization.

HP:0007490.name: Linear arrays of macular hyperkeratoses in flexural areas

HP:0007494.name: Discrete 2 to 5-mm hyper- and hypopigmented macules

HP:0007497.name: Focal friction-related palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007497.definition: Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot in areas exposed to friction.

HP:0007499.name: Recurrent staphylococcal infections
HP:0007499.definition: Increased susceptibility to staphylococcal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of staphylococcal infections.

HP:0007500.name: Decreased number of sweat glands
HP:0007500.definition: The presence of fewer than normal sweat glands.

HP:0007501.name: Streaks of hyperkeratosis along each finger onto the palm

HP:0007502.name: Follicular hyperkeratosis
HP:0007502.definition: A skin condition characterized by excessive development of keratin in hair follicles, resulting in rough, cone-shaped, elevated papules resulting from closure of hair follicles with a white plug of sebum.

HP:0007506.name: Congenital absence of skin of limbs

HP:0007508.name: Punctate palmar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007508.definition: Tiny bumps of thickened skin (hyperkeratosis) on the palms of the hands.

HP:0007514.name: Edema of the dorsum of hands
HP:0007514.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the hands.

HP:0007516.name: Redundant skin on fingers
HP:0007516.definition: Loose and sagging skin of the fingers.

HP:0007517.name: Palmoplantar cutis laxa
HP:0007517.definition: Loose, wrinkled skin of hands and feet.

HP:0007519.name: obsolete Lack of subcutaneous fatty tissue

HP:0007525.name: Yellow subcutaneous tissue covered by thin, scaly skin

HP:0007534.name: Congenital posterior occipital alopecia
HP:0007534.definition: Loss of hair in the occipital region of the scalp with congenital onset.

HP:0007536.name: Aplasia cutis congenita of midline scalp vertex

HP:0007537.name: Severe photosensitivity
HP:0007537.definition: A severe degree of photosensitivity of the skin.

HP:0007541.name: Frontal cutaneous lipoma
HP:0007541.definition: Presence of a cutaneous lipoma on the forehead.

HP:0007542.name: Absent pigmentation of the ventral chest
HP:0007542.definition: Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the anterior chest.

HP:0007544.name: Piebald skin depigmentation
HP:0007544.definition: Congenital large depigmented (white) macule of irergular rhomboid shape. Piebald skin depigmentation generally presents with multiple such macules in the affected individual. There may be smaller (5-15mm), discrete, skin-colored and hyperpigmented macules interspersed within the depigmented macules.

HP:0007545.name: Congenital palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007545.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin on the palms and soles that is present at birth.

HP:0007548.name: obsolete Palmoplantar keratosis with erythema and scale

HP:0007549.name: Desquamation of skin soon after birth

HP:0007554.name: Confetti hypopigmentation pattern of lower leg skin

HP:0007556.name: Plantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0007556.definition: Hyperkeratosis affecting the sole of the foot.

HP:0007561.name: obsolete Telangiectases in sun-exposed and nonexposed skin

HP:0007565.name: Multiple cafe-au-lait spots
HP:0007565.definition: The presence of six or more cafe-au-lait spots.

HP:0007569.name: Generalized seborrheic dermatitis
HP:0007569.definition: Seborrheic dermatitis that is not localized to any one particular region.

HP:0007570.name: Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans
HP:0007570.definition: Hyperkeratosis lenticularis perstans (HLP), also known as Flegel disease, is a keratinization abnormality characterized by small, asymptomatic erythematous papules that leave characteristic punctate bleeding when they become detached. The lesions generally occur symmetrically along the top of the foot and on the legs, appearing more rarely on the arms, forearms, palms, and soles, and even on the oral mucosa.

HP:0007573.name: Late onset atopic dermatitis
HP:0007573.definition: A form of atopic dermatitis with onset in adulthood characterized by atopic red face, chronic lichenified eczema on the trunk, subacute or psoriasiform dermatitis.

HP:0007576.name: Palmar neurofibroma
HP:0007576.definition: A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the palm of the hand.

HP:0007588.name: Reticular hyperpigmentation
HP:0007588.definition: Increased pigmentation of the skin with a netlike (reticular) pattern.

HP:0007589.name: Aplasia cutis congenita on trunk or limbs
HP:0007589.definition: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the trunk or the limbs.

HP:0007590.name: Aplasia cutis congenita over posterior parietal area

HP:0007592.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the eccrine sweat glands
HP:0007592.definition: Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the eccrine sweat glands.

HP:0007596.name: Painful subcutaneous lipomas
HP:0007596.definition: The presence of multiple subcutaneous lipoma that cause pain.

HP:0007598.name: Bilateral single transverse palmar creases
HP:0007598.definition: The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease on both hands.

HP:0005866.name: Opposable triphalangeal thumb
HP:0005866.definition: A form of triphalangeal thumb that can be placed opposite the fingers of the same hand.

HP:0005868.name: Metaphyseal enchondromatosis
HP:0005868.definition: An enchondroma is a benign growth of cartilage that develops within the medullary cavity of bone. Enchondromatosis refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas, and this term refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas within the medulla of metaphyseal bone. Radiographically an enchondroma presents a an oval, linear, or pyramidal osteolytic (radiolucent) lesion with well defined margins.

HP:0005871.name: Metaphyseal chondrodysplasia
HP:0005871.definition: An abnormality of skeletal development characterized by a disturbance of the metaphysis and its histological structure with relatively normal epiphyses and vertebrae.

HP:0005872.name: Brachytelomesophalangy
HP:0005872.definition: Disproportionately short middle and distal phalanges compared to the hand/foot.

HP:0005873.name: Polysyndactyly of hallux
HP:0005873.definition: Combined syndactyly and polydactyly of the great toe.

HP:0005878.name: Enlarged sagittal diameter of the cervical canal

HP:0005879.name: Congenital finger flexion contractures
HP:0005879.definition: Multiple bent (flexed) finger joints that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0005880.name: Metacarpophalangeal synostosis
HP:0005880.definition: Fusion of a metacarpal bone with the proximal phalanx of the finger distal to it across the corresponding metacarpophalangeal joint.

HP:0005885.name: Absent ossification of cervical vertebral bodies
HP:0005885.definition: A lack of bone mineralization of one or more body of cervical vertebra.

HP:0005886.name: Aphalangy of the hands
HP:0005886.definition: Absence of a digit or of one or more phalanges of a finger.

HP:0005890.name: Hyperostosis cranialis interna
HP:0005890.definition: Bony overgrowth of the internal (endosteal) surface of the calvaria and the base of skull.

HP:0005891.name: Progressive forearm bowing
HP:0005891.definition: Progressive bending or abnormal curvature of the forearm skeleton.

HP:0005892.name: Proximal tibial and fibular fusion
HP:0005892.definition: A developmental defect characterized by the abnormal fusion of the proximal tibia and fibula.

HP:0005894.name: Double first metacarpals
HP:0005894.definition: Duplication of the metacarpal I bones.

HP:0005895.name: Radial deviation of thumb terminal phalanx

HP:0005900.name: Fifth metacarpal with ulnar notch
HP:0005900.definition: Presence of an angular or V -shaped indentation on the ulnar side of the fifth metacarpal bone (i.e., on the sides towards the fifth finger).

HP:0005905.name: Abnormal cervical curvature
HP:0005905.definition: The presence of an abnormal curvature of the cervical vertebral column.

HP:0005906.name: Delayed pneumatization of the mastoid process
HP:0005906.definition: An abnormally reduced degree of pneumatization (i.e., formation of air cells) in the mastoid process with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0005910.name: Rhomboid or triangular shaped 5th finger middle phalanx
HP:0005910.definition: Rhomboid or triangular shaped 5th (little) finger middle phalanx.

HP:0005914.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the metacarpal bones
HP:0005914.definition: Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the metacarpal bones.

HP:0005916.name: Abnormal metacarpal morphology
HP:0005916.definition: Any abnormal shape or structure of the metacarpal bones.

HP:0005917.name: Supernumerary metacarpal bones
HP:0005917.definition: The presence of more than the normal number of metacarpal bones.

HP:0005918.name: Abnormal finger phalanx morphology
HP:0005918.definition: Abnormalities affecting the phalanx of finger.

HP:0005920.name: Abnormal epiphysis morphology of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0005920.definition: Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand. Note that this includes the epiphysis of the 1st metacarpal. In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5 (whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits).

HP:0005921.name: obsolete Abnormal ossification of hand bones

HP:0005922.name: Abnormal hand morphology
HP:0005922.definition: Any structural anomaly of the hand.

HP:0005924.name: Abnormal hand epiphysis morphology
HP:0005924.definition: Any abnormality of the epiphyses of the phalanges or metacarpal bones.

HP:0005926.name: Abnormal hand cortical bone morphology
HP:0005926.definition: An anomaly of the outer shell (cortex) of a hand bone.

HP:0005927.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving bones of the hand
HP:0005927.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the bones of the hand.

HP:0005930.name: Abnormal epiphysis morphology
HP:0005930.definition: An anomaly of epiphysis, which is the expanded articular end of a long bone that developes from a secondary ossification center, and which during the period of growth is either entirely cartilaginous or is separated from the shaft by a cartilaginous disk.

HP:0005932.name: Abnormal renal corticomedullary differentiation
HP:0005932.definition: An abnormality of corticomedullary differentiation (CMD) on diagnostic imaging such as magnetic resonance imaging, computer tomography, or sonography. CMD is a difference in the visualization of cortex and medulla.

HP:0005938.name: Abnormal respiratory motile cilium morphology
HP:0005938.definition: Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the motile cilium.

HP:0005942.name: Desquamative interstitial pneumonitis
HP:0005942.definition: Diffuse filling of the distal airspaces of the lungs, the alveoli, with macrophages. Desquamative interstitial pneumonitis (DIP) is characterized additionally by thickened alveolar septa and by a sparse inflammatory infiltrate that often includes plasma cells and occasional eosinophils. The alveoli are lined by plump cuboidal pneumocytes. Lymphoid aggregates may be present.

HP:0005944.name: Bilateral lung agenesis
HP:0005944.definition: Bilateral lack of development of the lungs.

HP:0005945.name: Laryngeal obstruction
HP:0005945.definition: Blockage of the upper airway at the level of the larynx often accompanied by respiratory distress.

HP:0005946.name: Ventilator dependence with inability to wean

HP:0005947.name: Decreased sensitivity to hypoxemia
HP:0005947.definition: Reduced tendency to respond to a reduced concentration of oxygen in the blood by increasing respiration.

HP:0005948.name: Multiple pulmonary cysts
HP:0005948.definition: The presence of multiple lung cysts.

HP:0005949.name: Apneic episodes in infancy
HP:0005949.definition: Recurrent episodes of apnea occurring during infancy.

HP:0005950.name: Laryngeal web
HP:0005950.definition: A membrane-like structure that extends across the laryngeal lumen close to the level of the vocal cords.

HP:0005956.name: Anteroposteriorly shortened larynx
HP:0005956.definition: Abnormal shortening of the larynx in the anteroposterior (front to back) axis.

HP:0005961.name: Hypoargininemia
HP:0005961.definition: A decreased concentration of arginine in the blood.

HP:0005968.name: Temperature instability
HP:0005968.definition: Disordered thermoregulation characterized by an impaired ability to maintain a balance between heat production and heat loss, with resulting instability of body temperature.

HP:0005972.name: Respiratory acidosis
HP:0005972.definition: Acidosis because of respiratory retention of carbon dioxide.

HP:0005973.name: Fructose intolerance
HP:0005973.definition: Reduced intestinal absorption of fructose. Breath testing after ingestion of fructose has been widely adopted as a standard method of identifying fructose malabsorption and intolerance. A dose of 25 g of fructose dissolved in a 10% solution is generally accepted as the appropriate dose of fructose for clinical use of H2 and CH4 breath testing. High levels of hydrogen in exhaled breath subsequent hours indicate fructose intolerance. Presence of malabsorption and reproduction of symptoms during a breath test provides the best objective evidence and symptom correlation for fructose intolerance.

HP:0005978.name: Type II diabetes mellitus
HP:0005978.definition: A type of diabetes mellitus initially characterized by insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia and subsequently by glucose interolerance and hyperglycemia.

HP:0005979.name: Metabolic ketoacidosis
HP:0005979.definition: A metabolic acidosis due to accumulation of ketone bodies generally observed in the setting of poor nutritional intake.

HP:0005987.name: Multinodular goiter
HP:0005987.definition: Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to multiple nodules in the thyroid gland.

HP:0005988.name: Congenital muscular torticollis
HP:0005988.definition: A congenital form of torticollis resulting from shortening of the sternocleidomastoid muscle and leading to a limited range of motion in both rotation and lateral bending.

HP:0005989.name: Redundant neck skin
HP:0005989.definition: Excess skin around the neck, often lying in horizontal folds.

HP:0005990.name: Thyroid hypoplasia
HP:0005990.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the thyroid gland.

HP:0005991.name: Limited neck flexion
HP:0005991.definition: Reduced ability to lower the chin towards the chest by bending the neck.

HP:0005994.name: Nodular goiter
HP:0005994.definition: Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to one or more nodules in the thyroid gland.

HP:0005995.name: Decreased adipose tissue around neck
HP:0005995.definition: Reduced amount of adipose tissue in the region of the neck.

HP:0005999.name: Ureteral atresia
HP:0005999.definition: A developmental defect defined by the failure of the formation of the lumen (tube) of the ureter.

HP:0006000.name: Ureteral obstruction
HP:0006000.definition: Obstruction of the flow of urine through the ureter.

HP:0006006.name: Hypotrophy of the small hand muscles

HP:0006009.name: Broad phalanx
HP:0006009.definition: Increased side-to-side width of one or more phalanges of the fingers or toes.

HP:0006011.name: Cuboidal metacarpal
HP:0006011.definition: Severely shortened metacarpal with a cuboidal appearance.

HP:0006016.name: Delayed phalangeal epiphyseal ossification
HP:0006016.definition: Delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more phalanx.

HP:0006028.name: Metaphyseal cupping of metacarpals
HP:0006028.definition: Metaphyseal cupping affecting the metacarpal bones.

HP:0006042.name: Y-shaped metacarpals
HP:0006042.definition: Y-shaped metacarpals are the result of a partial fusion of two metacarpal bones, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Y-shaped metacarpals may be seen in combination with polydactyly.

HP:0006048.name: Distal widening of metacarpals
HP:0006048.definition: Abnormal increase in width of the distal region of the metacarpal bones.

HP:0006059.name: Cone-shaped metacarpal epiphyses
HP:0006059.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpal bones, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphyses are located at the distal ends of the metacarpal bones.

HP:0006067.name: Multiple carpal ossification centers
HP:0006067.definition: A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more long bones.

HP:0006070.name: Metacarpophalangeal joint contracture
HP:0006070.definition: A chronic loss of joint motion in metacarpophalangeal joints due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.

HP:0006077.name: Absent proximal finger flexion creases
HP:0006077.definition: Absence of the proximal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.

HP:0006092.name: Malaligned carpal bone
HP:0006092.definition: Malalignement of carpal bone angles either with respect to each other, to the corresponding metacarpals or with respect to the wrist (radius and ulna).

HP:0006097.name: 3-4 finger osseus syndactyly
HP:0006097.definition: Fusion of the third (middle) and fourth (ring) finger, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual finger bones.

HP:0006099.name: Metacarpophalangeal joint hyperextensibility
HP:0006099.definition: Increased mobility of one ore more metacarpophalangeal joint.

HP:0006101.name: Finger syndactyly
HP:0006101.definition: Webbing or fusion of the fingers, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

HP:0006107.name: Fingerpad telangiectases
HP:0006107.definition: Telangiectasia (small dilated blood vessels) located in the fingerpads at the tips of the fingers.

HP:0006108.name: Tapered metacarpals
HP:0006108.definition: Metacarpal that becomes thinner toward the distal end.

HP:0006109.name: Absent phalangeal crease
HP:0006109.definition: Absence of one or more interphalangeal creases (i.e., of the transverse lines in the skin between the phalanges of the fingers).

HP:0006110.name: Shortening of all middle phalanges of the fingers
HP:0006110.definition: Short, hypoplastic middle phalanx of finger, affecting all fingers.

HP:0006112.name: Expanded phalanges with widened medullary cavities

HP:0006114.name: Multiple palmar creases
HP:0006114.definition: The presence of multiple creases on the palm of the hand (more than the normal three major creases (distal transverse crease, proximal transverse crease, and thenar crease).

HP:0006118.name: Shortening of all distal phalanges of the fingers
HP:0006118.definition: Hypoplasia of all of the distal phalanx of finger.

HP:0006119.name: Proximal tapering of metacarpals
HP:0006119.definition: Some or all of the metacarpal bones (i.e., metacarpal II to V) have a pointed proximal appearance.

HP:0006121.name: Acral ulceration
HP:0006121.definition: A type of digital ulcer that manifests as an open sore on the surface of the skin at the tip of a finger or toe.

HP:0006127.name: Long proximal phalanx of finger
HP:0006127.definition: Increased length of the proximal phalanx of finger.

HP:0006129.name: Drumstick terminal phalanges
HP:0006129.definition: Rounding and broadening of the tufts of the distal phalanges.

HP:0006134.name: Enlarged metacarpal epiphyses
HP:0006134.definition: Abnormally large size of one or more growth plates (epiphyses) of the metacarpal bones (i.e., the tubular bones of the hand between the carpus and the phalanges).

HP:0006140.name: Premature fusion of phalangeal epiphyses
HP:0006140.definition: Fusion of the epiphysis and metaphysis of one or more phalanges prior to the normal age or stage of growth.

HP:0006143.name: Abnormal finger flexion crease
HP:0006143.definition: Anomalous flexion crease (i.e., a transverse line that crosses the skin of a finger).

HP:0006144.name: Shortening of all proximal phalanges of the fingers
HP:0006144.definition: Congenital hypoplasia of proximal phalanx of finger or all fingers.

HP:0006145.name: Central Y-shaped metacarpal
HP:0006145.definition: A central Y-shaped metacarpal is the result of a partial fusion of two central metacarpals (i.e., metacarpals 2-4) of the hand, with the two arms of the Y pointing in the distal direction. Central Y-shaped metacarpals may be seen as a result of a central polydactyly with partial fusion of the duplicated metacarpal.

HP:0006146.name: Broad metacarpal epiphyses
HP:0006146.definition: Increased side-to-side width of the metacarpal epiphyses.

HP:0006150.name: Swan neck-like deformities of the fingers
HP:0006150.definition: A swan neck deformity describes a finger with a hyperextended PIP joint and a flexed DIP joint. The most common cause for a swan neck-like deformity is a disruption of the end of the extensor tendon. Conditions that loosen the PIP joint and allow it to hyperextend, for example conditions that weaken the volar plate, can produce a swan neck deformity of the finger. One example is rheumatoid arthritis. Another cause are conditions that tighten up the small (intrinsic) muscles of the hand and fingers, for example hand trauma or nerve disorders, such as cerebral palsy, Parkinson's disease, or stroke.

HP:0006152.name: Proximal symphalangism of hands
HP:0006152.definition: The term proximal symphalangism refers to a bony fusion of the middle and proximal phalanges of the digits of the hand, in other words the proximal interphalangeal joint (PIJ) is missing which can be seen either on x-rays or as an absence of the proximal interphalangeal finger creases.

HP:0006155.name: Long phalanx of finger
HP:0006155.definition: Increased length of multiple or a single phalanx of finger.

HP:0006156.name: Ulnar deviation of thumb
HP:0006156.definition: Bending or curvature of a thumb towards the ulnar side (towards the ring finger).

HP:0006159.name: Mesoaxial hand polydactyly
HP:0006159.definition: The presence of a supernumerary finger (not a thumb) involving the third or fourth metacarpal with associated osseous syndactyly.

HP:0006160.name: Irregular metacarpals
HP:0006160.definition: Irregular morphology of one or more metacarpal bones.

HP:0006161.name: Short metacarpals with rounded proximal ends

HP:0006162.name: Soft tissue swelling of interphalangeal joints

HP:0006170.name: Chess-pawn distal phalanges
HP:0006170.definition: A morphological abnormality of distal phalanges such that they have the appearance of chess pawns.

HP:0006172.name: Flattened, squared-off epiphyses of tubular bones

HP:0006174.name: Metacarpal diaphyseal endosteal sclerosis
HP:0006174.definition: Increase in bone density in the diaphyseal (shaft) region of a metacarpal bone.

HP:0006176.name: Two carpal ossification centers present at birth

HP:0006184.name: Decreased palmar creases
HP:0006184.definition: Poorly defined or shallow palmar creases.

HP:0006191.name: Deep palmar crease
HP:0006191.definition: Excessively deep creases of the palm.

HP:0006192.name: Tapered phalanx of finger
HP:0006192.definition: Phalanges of the fingers becoming thinner toward the distal end.

HP:0006193.name: Thimble-shaped middle phalanges of hand
HP:0006193.definition: The middle phalanx of finger resembles a thimble, a small metal cap to protect the finger while sewing that has a broad (proximal) base and narrower top, whereby both base and top are flat.

HP:0006203.name: Decreased movement range in interphalangeal joints

HP:0006205.name: Irregular phalanges
HP:0006205.definition: Alteration of the normally smooth radiographic contour of phalanges producing an irregular appearance.

HP:0006206.name: Hypersegmentation of proximal phalanx of second finger
HP:0006206.definition: Presence of an additional phalanx-like bone, producing an extra, wedge-shaped bone at the base of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0006208.name: Metaphyseal cupping of proximal phalanges
HP:0006208.definition: Metaphyseal cupping affecting the proximal phalanges.

HP:0006213.name: Thin proximal phalanges with broad epiphyses of the hand

HP:0006216.name: Single interphalangeal crease of fifth finger
HP:0006216.definition: Presence of only one (instead of two, as normal) interphalangeal crease of the fifth finger.

HP:0006217.name: Limited mobility of proximal interphalangeal joint

HP:0006224.name: Tapering pointed ends of distal finger phalanges
HP:0006224.definition: A reduction in diameter of the distal phalanx of finger towards the distal end such that the tip of the phalanx comes to a point (this feature can be observed on radiograms).

HP:0006226.name: Osteoarthritis of the first carpometacarpal joint

HP:0006232.name: Expanded metacarpals with widened medullary cavities

HP:0006233.name: Osteoarthritis of the distal interphalangeal joint

HP:0006234.name: Osteolysis involving tarsal bones
HP:0006234.definition: An increased resorption of bone matrix by osteoclasts leading to bony defects involving the tarsal bones.

HP:0006236.name: Slender metacarpals
HP:0006236.definition: Decreased width of the metacarpal bones (that is, reduced diameter).

HP:0006239.name: Shortening of all middle phalanges of the toes
HP:0006239.definition: Abnormal shortening of all middle phalanges of toes.

HP:0006248.name: Limited wrist movement
HP:0006248.definition: An abnormal limitation of the mobility of the wrist.

HP:0006254.name: Elevated circulating alpha-fetoprotein concentration
HP:0006254.definition: Concentration of alpha-fetoprotein in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0006261.name: Abnormal phalangeal joint morphology of the hand

HP:0006263.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0006263.definition: Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the proximal, middle, and distal phalanges of the 2nd finger.

HP:0006268.name: Fluctuating splenomegaly
HP:0006268.definition: Intermittently increased size of the spleen.

HP:0006273.name: Pancreatic lymphangiectasis
HP:0006273.definition: The presence of lymphangiectasis in the pancreas.

HP:0006274.name: Reduced pancreatic beta cells
HP:0006274.definition: Reduced number of beta cells in the pancreatic islets of Langerhans.

HP:0006278.name: Ectopic pancreatic tissue
HP:0006278.definition: The presence of pancreatic tissue outside the normal pancreas, in many cases along the foregut and proximal midgut.

HP:0006282.name: Generalized hypoplasia of dental enamel
HP:0006282.definition: A generalized form of developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.

HP:0006283.name: Multiple unerupted teeth
HP:0006283.definition: The presence of multiple embedded tooth germs which have failed to erupt.

HP:0006285.name: Enamel hypomineralization
HP:0006285.definition: A decreased amount of enamel mineralization. Hypomineralized enamel has a brown discoloration and brittle aspect.

HP:0006288.name: Advanced eruption of teeth
HP:0006288.definition: Premature tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD earlier than the mean eruption age.

HP:0006289.name: Agenesis of central incisor
HP:0006289.definition: Agenesis of one or more central incisors, i.e., of lower secondary incisor, lower primary incisor, upper secondary incisor, or of upper central primary incisor.

HP:0006290.name: Discolored lateral incisors
HP:0006290.definition: The presence of discolored lateral incisors.

HP:0006291.name: Marked delay in eruption of permanent teeth

HP:0006293.name: Agenesis of maxillary central incisor
HP:0006293.definition: Agenesis of upper secondary incisor or of upper central primary incisor.

HP:0006297.name: Enamel hypoplasia
HP:0006297.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.

HP:0006298.name: Prolonged bleeding after dental extraction
HP:0006298.definition: Prolonged bleeding post dental extraction sufficient to require medical intervention.

HP:0006302.name: Dagger-shaped pulp calcifications
HP:0006302.definition: Dagger-shaped calcifications in the dental pulp.

HP:0006313.name: Widely spaced primary teeth
HP:0006313.definition: Increased space between the primary teeth. Note this phenotype should be distinguished from increased space due purely to microdontia.

HP:0006315.name: Solitary median maxillary central incisor
HP:0006315.definition: A single maxillary central incisor positioned in the midline with morphological symmetry of the crown and bordered by lateral incisors.

HP:0006316.name: Irregularly spaced teeth
HP:0006316.definition: Irregular distribution of the teeth along the dental arch, i.e., and irregular spatial pattern of teeth.

HP:0006323.name: Premature loss of primary teeth
HP:0006323.definition: Loss of the primary (also known as deciduous) teeth before the usual age.

HP:0006329.name: Alveolar process hypoplasia
HP:0006329.definition: Underdevelopment of the alveolar process (also known as alveolar bone).

HP:0006332.name: Supernumerary maxillary incisor
HP:0006332.definition: The presence of a supernumerary, i.e., extra, maxillary incisor, either the primary maxillary incisor or the permanent maxillary incisor.

HP:0006333.name: Crowded maxillary incisors
HP:0006333.definition: A type of dental misalignment with crowded central incisors, i.e., of maxillary secondary incisor, or of maxillary central primary incisor.

HP:0006334.name: Hypoplasia of the primary teeth
HP:0006334.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the primary teeth.

HP:0006335.name: Persistence of primary teeth
HP:0006335.definition: Persistence of the primary teeth beyond the age by which they normally are shed and replaced by the permanent teeth.

HP:0006336.name: Short dental root
HP:0006336.definition: Tooth root length more than 2 SD below mean, or subjectively apparently decreased tooth root length.

HP:0006337.name: Premature eruption of permanent teeth
HP:0006337.definition: Premature tooth eruption of the permanent dentition.

HP:0006338.name: Malformation of mandibular premolar
HP:0006338.definition: An abnormality of the morphology of secondary premolar tooth.

HP:0006339.name: Conical mandibular incisor
HP:0006339.definition: An abnormal conical morphology of the primary or permanent mandibular incisors.

HP:0006342.name: Peg-shaped maxillary lateral incisors
HP:0006342.definition: A tooth crown with its mesial and distal sides converging or tapering toward the incisal edge causing severe reduction of mesiodistal diameter

HP:0006344.name: Abnormal primary molar morphology
HP:0006344.definition: An abnormality of morphology of primary molar.

HP:0006346.name: Screwdriver-shaped incisors
HP:0006346.definition: An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth in which the tooth is shaped like a screwdriver blade, i.e., having a rhomboid shape.

HP:0006347.name: Microdontia of primary teeth
HP:0006347.definition: Decreased size of the primary teeth.

HP:0006349.name: Agenesis of permanent teeth
HP:0006349.definition: A congenital defect characterized by the absence of one or more permanent teeth, including oligodontia, hypodontia, and adontia of the of permanent teeth.

HP:0006350.name: Pulp obliteration
HP:0006350.definition: Mineralized substance filling the entire dental pulp space.

HP:0006352.name: Failure of eruption of permanent teeth
HP:0006352.definition: Lack of tooth eruption of the secondary dentition.

HP:0006353.name: Hypoplasia of the tooth germ
HP:0006353.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the tooth germ, i.e., of the structure that forms in odontogenesis that will develop into a tooth.

HP:0008419.name: Intervertebral disk degeneration
HP:0008419.definition: The presence of degenerative changes of intervertebral disk.

HP:0008420.name: Punctate vertebral calcifications
HP:0008420.definition: The presence of punctiform calcification of the bone of the vertebral bodies.

HP:0008422.name: Vertebral wedging
HP:0008422.definition: An abnormal shape of the vertebral bodies whereby the vertebral bodies are thick on one side and taper to a thin edge at the other.

HP:0008423.name: Spinal dysplasia
HP:0008423.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the vertebral column.

HP:0008428.name: Vertebral clefting
HP:0008428.definition: Schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.

HP:0008430.name: Anterior beaking of lumbar vertebrae
HP:0008430.definition: Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies of the lumbar spine.

HP:0008432.name: Anterior wedging of L1
HP:0008432.definition: An abnormality of the shape of the lumbar vertebra L1 such that it is wedge-shaped (narrow towards the front).

HP:0008435.name: Absent in utero ossification of vertebral bodies

HP:0008438.name: Vertebral arch anomaly
HP:0008438.definition: A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.

HP:0008439.name: Lumbar hemivertebrae
HP:0008439.definition: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the lumbar spine.

HP:0008440.name: C1-C2 vertebral abnormality
HP:0008440.definition: Any abnormality of the atlas and the axis.

HP:0008441.name: Herniation of intervertebral nuclei
HP:0008441.definition: The presence of one or more herniated nucleus pulposus of intervertebral disk.

HP:0008442.name: Vertebral hyperostosis
HP:0008442.definition: Excessive growth of the bones of the vertebral bodies.

HP:0008443.name: Neuropathic spinal arthropathy
HP:0008443.definition: A progressive disorder of vertebral joint degeneration that occurs in the setting of any condition characterized by decreased afferent innervation, involving loss of deep pain and proprioceptive sensation in the vertebral column. Patients most commonly present with symptoms of lower back pain, sitting imbalance, progressive spinal deformity (usually kyphosis), and an audible clicking sound on changing postures.

HP:0001644.name: Dilated cardiomyopathy
HP:0001644.definition: Dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is defined by the presence of left ventricular dilatation and left ventricular systolic dysfunction in the absence of abnormal loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) or coronary artery disease sufficient to cause global systolic impairment. Right ventricular dilation and dysfunction may be present but are not necessary for the diagnosis.

HP:0001645.name: Sudden cardiac death
HP:0001645.definition: The heart suddenly and unexpectedly stops beating resulting in death within a short time period (generally within 1 h of symptom onset).

HP:0001646.name: Abnormal aortic valve morphology
HP:0001646.definition: Any abnormality of the aortic valve.

HP:0001647.name: Bicuspid aortic valve
HP:0001647.definition: The presence of an aortic valve with two instead of the normal three cusps (flaps). Bicuspid aortic valvue is a malformation of a commissure (small space between the attachment of each cusp to the aortic wall) and the adjacent parts of the two corresponding cusps forming a raphe (the fused area of the two underdeveloped cusps turning into a malformed commissure between both cusps; the raphe is a fibrous ridge that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps).

HP:0001648.name: Cor pulmonale
HP:0001648.definition: Right-sided heart failure resulting from chronic hypertension in the pulmonary arteries and right ventricle.

HP:0001649.name: Tachycardia
