HP:0002280.definition: Increase in size of the cisterna magna, one of three principal openings in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid and pia mater, located between the cerebellum and the dorsal surface of the medulla oblongata.

HP:0002282.name: Gray matter heterotopia
HP:0002282.definition: Heterotopia or neuronal heterotopia are macroscopic clusters of misplaced neurons (gray matter), most often situated along the ventricular walls or within the subcortical white matter.

HP:0002283.name: Global brain atrophy
HP:0002283.definition: Unlocalized atrophy of the brain with decreased total brain matter volume and increased ventricular size.

HP:0002286.name: Fair hair
HP:0002286.definition: A lesser degree of hair pigmentation than would otherwise be expected.

HP:0002289.name: Alopecia universalis
HP:0002289.definition: Loss of all hair on the entire body.

HP:0002290.name: Poliosis
HP:0002290.definition: Circumscribed depigmentation of the hair of the head or the eyelashes.

HP:0002292.name: Frontal balding
HP:0002292.definition: Absence of hair in the anterior midline and/or parietal areas.

HP:0002296.name: Progressive hypotrichosis
HP:0002296.definition: Progressively reduced or lacking hair growth.

HP:0002299.name: Brittle hair
HP:0002299.definition: Fragile, easily breakable hair, i.e., with reduced tensile strength.

HP:0002300.name: Mutism
HP:0002300.definition: Complete lack of speech or verbal communication in a person despite attempts to engage in conversation. Mutism as a phenomena assumes the individual has previous capacity for speech and in the pediatric population it assumes that the person is past the age of typical language development.

HP:0002301.name: Hemiplegia
HP:0002301.definition: Paralysis (complete loss of muscle function) in the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.

HP:0002304.name: Akinesia
HP:0002304.definition: Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily.

HP:0002305.name: Athetosis
HP:0002305.definition: A slow, continuous, involuntary writhing movement that prevents maintenance of a stable posture. Athetosis involves continuous smooth movements that appear random and are not composed of recognizable sub-movements or movement fragments. In contrast to chorea, in athetosis, the same regions of the body are repeatedly involved. Athetosis may worsen with attempts at movement of posture, but athetosis can also occur at rest.

HP:0002307.name: Drooling
HP:0002307.definition: Habitual flow of saliva out of the mouth.

HP:0002308.name: Chiari malformation
HP:0002308.definition: Chiari malformation consists of a downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils and the medulla through the foramen magnum, sometimes causing hydrocephalus as a result of obstruction of CSF outflow.

HP:0002312.name: Clumsiness
HP:0002312.definition: Lack of physical coordination resulting in an abnormal tendency to drop items or bump into objects.

HP:0002313.name: Spastic paraparesis
HP:0002313.definition: Partial loss of the ability to move the lower limbs accompanied by spasticity of the lower limbs.

HP:0002314.name: Degeneration of the lateral corticospinal tracts
HP:0002314.definition: Deterioration of the tissues of the lateral corticospinal tracts.

HP:0002315.name: Headache
HP:0002315.definition: Cephalgia, or pain sensed in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.

HP:0002318.name: Cervical myelopathy
HP:0002318.definition: A collection of pathologic conditions that result from progressive spinal cord dysfunction secondary to cord compression in the cervical spine.

HP:0002321.name: Vertigo
HP:0002321.definition: An abnormal sensation of spinning while the body is actually stationary.

HP:0002322.name: Resting tremor
HP:0002322.definition: A resting tremor occurs when muscles are at rest and becomes less noticeable or disappears when the affected muscles are moved. Resting tremors are often slow and coarse.

HP:0002323.name: Anencephaly
HP:0002323.definition: Anencephaly is a developmental anomaly characterized by a fetus that has no calvarium, with a lack of most or all of the fetus' brain tissue. Anencephaly belongs to a collective group known as neural tube defects (NTD) and is a result of the neural tube failing to close in its rostral end during fetal development.

HP:0002324.name: Hydranencephaly
HP:0002324.definition: A defect of development of the brain characterized by replacement of greater portions of the cerebral hemispheres and the corpus striatum by cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and glial tissue.

HP:0000775.name: Abnormality of the diaphragm
HP:0000775.definition: Any abnormality of the diaphragm, the sheet of skeletal muscle that separates the thoracic cavity from the abdominal cavity.

HP:0000776.name: Congenital diaphragmatic hernia
HP:0000776.definition: The presence of a hernia of the diaphragm present at birth.

HP:0000777.name: Abnormal thymus morphology
HP:0000777.definition: Abnormality of the thymus, an organ located in the upper anterior portion of the chest cavity just behind the sternum and whose main function is to provide an environment for T lymphocyte maturation.

HP:0000782.name: Abnormal scapula morphology
HP:0000782.definition: Any abnormality of the scapula, also known as the shoulder blade.

HP:0000787.name: Nephrolithiasis
HP:0000787.definition: The presence of calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

HP:0000790.name: Hematuria
HP:0000790.definition: The presence of blood in the urine. Hematuria may be gross hematuria (visible to the naked eye) or microscopic hematuria (detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine).

HP:0000791.name: Uric acid nephrolithiasis
HP:0000791.definition: The presence of uric acid-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

HP:0000793.name: Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis
HP:0000793.definition: A type of glomerulonephritis characterized by diffuse mesangial cell proliferation and the thickening of capillary walls due to subendothelial extension of the mesangium. The term membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis is often employed to denote a general pattern of glomerular injury seen in a variety of disease processes that share a common pathogenetic mechanism, rather than to describe a single disease entity

HP:0000794.name: IgA deposition in the glomerulus
HP:0000794.definition: The presence of immunoglobulin A deposits in the glomerulus.

HP:0000795.name: Abnormality of the urethra
HP:0000795.definition: An abnormality of the urethra, i.e., of the tube which connects the urinary bladder to the outside of the body.

HP:0000796.name: Urethral obstruction
HP:0000796.definition: Obstruction of the flow of urine through the urethra.

HP:0000798.name: Oligozoospermia
HP:0000798.definition: Reduced count of spermatozoa in the semen, defined as a sperm count below 20 million per milliliter semen.

HP:0000799.name: Renal steatosis
HP:0000799.definition: Abnormal fat accumulation in the kidneys.

HP:0000802.name: Impotence
HP:0000802.definition: Inability to develop or maintain an erection of the penis.

HP:0000803.name: Renal cortical cysts
HP:0000803.definition: Cysts of the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0000804.name: Xanthine nephrolithiasis
HP:0000804.definition: The presence of xanthine-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

HP:0000805.name: Enuresis
HP:0000805.definition: Lack of the ability to control the urinary bladder leading to involuntary urination at an age where control of the bladder should already be possible.

HP:0000807.name: Glanular hypospadias
HP:0000807.definition: A type of hypospadias in which the urethral meatus is located at the head of the penis, but not all the way at the tip.

HP:0000808.name: Penoscrotal hypospadias
HP:0000808.definition: A severe form of hypospadias in which the urethral opening is located at the junction of the penis and scrotum.

HP:0000809.name: Urinary tract atresia
HP:0000809.definition: Congenital absence of the normal opening of a structure of the urinary tract.

HP:0000811.name: Abnormal external genitalia morphology
HP:0000811.definition: A structural anomaly of the external genitalia.

HP:0000812.name: Abnormal internal genitalia
HP:0000812.definition: An anomaly of the adnexa, uterus, and vagina (in female) or seminal tract and prostate (in male).

HP:0000813.name: Bicornuate uterus
HP:0000813.definition: The presence of a bicornuate uterus.

HP:0000815.name: Hypergonadotropic hypogonadism
HP:0000815.definition: Reduced function of the gonads (testes in males or ovaries in females) associated with excess pituitary gonadotropin secretion and resulting in delayed sexual development and growth delay.

HP:0000816.name: Abnormality of Krebs cycle metabolism
HP:0000816.definition: An abnormality of the tricarboxylic acid cycle.

HP:0000817.name: Reduced eye contact
HP:0000817.definition: A reduced frequency or duration of eye contact.

HP:0000818.name: Abnormality of the endocrine system
HP:0000818.definition: An abnormality of the endocrine system.

HP:0000819.name: Diabetes mellitus
HP:0000819.definition: A group of abnormalities characterized by hyperglycemia and glucose intolerance.

HP:0000820.name: Abnormality of the thyroid gland
HP:0000820.definition: An abnormality of the thyroid gland.

HP:0000822.name: Hypertension
HP:0000822.definition: The presence of chronic increased pressure in the systemic arterial system.

HP:0000823.name: Delayed puberty
HP:0000823.definition: Passing the age when puberty normally occurs with no physical or hormonal signs of the onset of puberty.

HP:0000824.name: Decreased response to growth hormone stimulation test
HP:0000824.definition: Insufficient responses to growth hormone (GH) provocation tests. GH deficiency is defined as a serum peak GH concentration less than 10 ng/mL on provocation with a combination of at least two separate stimulation tests.

HP:0000825.name: Hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia
HP:0000825.definition: An increased concentration of insulin combined with a decreased concentration of glucose in the blood.

HP:0000826.name: Precocious puberty
HP:0000826.definition: The onset of secondary sexual characteristics before a normal age. Although it is difficult to define normal age ranges because of the marked variation with which puberty begins in normal children, precocious puberty can be defined as the onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls or 9 years in boys.

HP:0000828.name: Abnormality of the parathyroid gland
HP:0000828.definition: An abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0000829.name: Hypoparathyroidism
HP:0000829.definition: A condition caused by a deficiency of parathyroid hormone characterized by hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia.

HP:0000830.name: Anterior hypopituitarism
HP:0000830.definition: A condition of reduced function of the anterior pituitary gland characterized by decreased secretion of one or more of the pituitary hormones growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, prolactin, luteinizing hormone, and follicle-stimulating hormone.

HP:0000831.name: Insulin-resistant diabetes mellitus
HP:0000831.definition: A type of diabetes mellitus related not to lack of insulin but rather to lack of response to insulin on the part of the target tissues of insulin such as muscle, fat, and liver cells. This type of diabetes is typically associated with increases both in blood glucose concentrations as well as in fasting and postprandial serum insulin levels.

HP:0000832.name: Primary hypothyroidism
HP:0000832.definition: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in the thyroid gland.

HP:0000834.name: Abnormality of the adrenal glands
HP:0000834.definition: Abnormality of the adrenal glands, i.e., of the endocrine glands located at the top of the kindneys.

HP:0000835.name: Adrenal hypoplasia
HP:0000835.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal glands.

HP:0000836.name: Hyperthyroidism
HP:0000836.definition: An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3).

HP:0000837.name: Increased circulating gonadotropin level
HP:0000837.definition: Overproduction of gonadotropins (FSH, LH) by the anterior pituitary gland.

HP:0000839.name: Pituitary dwarfism
HP:0000839.definition: A type of reduced stature with normal proportions related to dysfunction of the pituitary gland related to either an isolated defect in the secretion of growth hormone or to panhypopituitarism, i.e., a deficit of all the anterior pituitary hormones.

HP:0000840.name: Adrenogenital syndrome
HP:0000840.definition: Adrenogenital syndrome is also known as congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which results from disorders of steroid hormone production in the adrenal glands leading to a deficiency of cortisol. The pituitary gland reacts by increased secretion of corticotropin, which in turn causes the adrenal glands to overproduce certain intermediary hormones which have testosterone-like effects.

HP:0000841.name: Hyperactive renin-angiotensin system
HP:0000841.definition: An abnormally increased activity of the renin-angiotensin system, causing hypertension by a combination of volume excess and vasoconstrictor mechanisms.

HP:0000842.name: Hyperinsulinemia
HP:0000842.definition: An increased concentration of insulin in the blood.

HP:0000843.name: Hyperparathyroidism
HP:0000843.definition: Excessive production of parathyroid hormone (PTH) by the parathyroid glands.

HP:0000845.name: Elevated circulating growth hormone concentration
HP:0000845.definition: Acromegaly is a condition resulting from overproduction of growth hormone by the pituitary gland in persons with closed epiphyses, and consists chiefly in the enlargement of the distal parts of the body. The circumference of the skull increases, the nose becomes broad, the tongue becomes enlarged, the facial features become coarsened, the mandible grows excessively, and the teeth become separated. The fingers and toes grow chiefly in thickness.

HP:0000846.name: Adrenal insufficiency
HP:0000846.definition: Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands.

HP:0000847.name: Abnormality of renin-angiotensin system
HP:0000847.definition: An abnormality of the renin-angiotensin system.

HP:0000848.name: Increased circulating renin concentration
HP:0000848.definition: An increased level of renin in the blood.

HP:0000851.name: Congenital hypothyroidism
HP:0000851.definition: A type of hypothyroidism with congenital onset.

HP:0000852.name: Pseudohypoparathyroidism
HP:0000852.definition: A condition characterized by resistance to the action of parathyroid hormone, in which there is hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia, and (appropriately) high levels of parathyroid hormone.

HP:0000853.name: Goiter
HP:0000853.definition: An enlargement of the thyroid gland.

HP:0000854.name: Thyroid adenoma
HP:0000854.definition: The presence of a adenoma of the thyroid gland.

HP:0000855.name: Insulin resistance
HP:0000855.definition: Increased resistance towards insulin, that is, diminished effectiveness of insulin in reducing blood glucose levels.

HP:0000858.name: Irregular menstruation
HP:0000858.definition: Abnormally high variation in the amount of time between periods.

HP:0000859.name: Increased circulating aldosterone concentration
HP:0000859.definition: Overproduction of the mineralocorticoid aldosterone by the adrenal cortex.

HP:0000860.name: Parathyroid hypoplasia
HP:0000860.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0000863.name: Central diabetes insipidus
HP:0000863.definition: A form of diabetes insipidus related to a failure of vasopressin (AVP) release from the hypothalamus.

HP:0000864.name: Abnormality of the hypothalamus-pituitary axis
HP:0000864.definition: Abnormality of the pituitary gland (also known as hypophysis), which is an endocrine gland that protrudes from the bottom of the hypothalamus at the base of the brain. The pituitary gland secretes the hormones ACTH, TSH, PRL, GH, endorphins, FSH, LH, oxytocin, and antidiuretic hormone. The secretion of hormones from the anterior pituitary is under the strict control of hypothalamic hormones, and the posterior pituitary is essentially an extension of the hypothalamus, so that hypothalamus and pituitary gland may be regarded as a functional unit.

HP:0000867.name: Secondary hyperparathyroidism
HP:0000867.definition: Secondary hyperparathyroidism refers to the production of higher than normal levels of parathyroid hormone in the presence of hypocalcemia.

HP:0000870.name: Increased circulating prolactin concentration
HP:0000870.definition: The presence of abnormally increased levels of prolactin in the blood. Prolactin is a peptide hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland that plays a role in breast development and lactation during pregnancy.

HP:0000871.name: Panhypopituitarism
HP:0000871.definition: A pituitary functional deficit affecting all the anterior pituitary hormones (growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, and prolactin).

HP:0000872.name: Hashimoto thyroiditis
HP:0000872.definition: A chronic, autoimmune type of thyroiditis associated with hypothyroidism.

HP:0000873.name: Diabetes insipidus
HP:0000873.definition: A state of excessive water intake and hypotonic (dilute) polyuria. Diabetes insipidus may be due to failure of vasopressin (AVP) release (central or neurogenic diabetes insipidus) or to a failure of the kidney to respond to AVP (nephrogenic diabetes insipidus).

HP:0000876.name: Oligomenorrhea
HP:0000876.definition: Infrequent menses (less than 6 per year or more than 35 days between cycles).

HP:0000878.name: 11 pairs of ribs
HP:0000878.definition: Presence of only 11 pairs of ribs.

HP:0000879.name: Short sternum
HP:0000879.definition: Decreased inferosuperior length of the sternum.

HP:0000888.name: Horizontal ribs
HP:0000888.definition: A horizontal (flat) conformation of the ribs, the long curved bones that form the rib cage and normally progressively oblique (slanted) from ribs 1 through 9, then less slanted through rib 12.

HP:0000889.name: Abnormal clavicle morphology
HP:0000889.definition: Any abnormality of the clavicles (collar bones).

HP:0000892.name: Bifid ribs
HP:0000892.definition: A bifid rib refers to cleavage of the sternal end of a rib, usually unilateral. Bifid ribs are usually asymptomatic, and are often discovered incidentally by chest x-ray.

HP:0000893.name: Bulging of the costochondral junction
HP:0000893.definition: Abnormal outward curving (protuberance) of the junction of ribs and costal cartilage.

HP:0000895.name: Lateral clavicle hook
HP:0000895.definition: An excessive upward convexity of the lateral clavicle.

HP:0000896.name: Rib exostoses
HP:0000896.definition: Multiple circumscribed bony excrescences located in the ribs.

HP:0000897.name: Rachitic rosary
HP:0000897.definition: A row of beadlike prominences at the junction of a rib and its cartilage (i.e., enlarged costochondral joints), resembling a rosary. Note that rachitic rosary would have one bead per rib (a swelling at the costochondral junction), while beaded ribs in the context of multiple rib fractures have multiple beads (fractures) along the same rib.

HP:0000902.name: Rib fusion
HP:0000902.definition: Complete or partial merging of adjacent ribs.

HP:0000904.name: Flaring of rib cage
HP:0000904.definition: The presence of wide, concave anterior rib ends.

HP:0000905.name: Progressive clavicular acroosteolysis
HP:0000905.definition: Progressive bone resorption in the distal part of the clavicle.

HP:0000911.name: Flat glenoid fossa
HP:0000911.definition: Abnormally flat configuration of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

HP:0000912.name: Sprengel anomaly
HP:0000912.definition: A congenital skeletal deformity characterized by the elevation of one scapula (thus, one scapula is located superior to the other).

HP:0000913.name: Posterior rib fusion
HP:0000913.definition: Complete or partial merging of the posterior part of adjacent ribs.

HP:0000915.name: Pectus excavatum of inferior sternum
HP:0000915.definition: Pectus excavatum (defect of the chest wall characterized by depression of the sternum) affecting primarily the inferior region of the sternum.

HP:0000916.name: Broad clavicles
HP:0000916.definition: Increased width (cross-sectional diameter) of the clavicles.

HP:0000917.name: Superior pectus carinatum
HP:0000917.definition: Pectus carinatum affecting primarily the superior part of the sternum.

HP:0000918.name: Scapular exostoses
HP:0000918.definition: The presence of multiple exostoses on the scapula. An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage.

HP:0000919.name: Abnormality of the costochondral junction
HP:0000919.definition: Any anomaly of the costochondral junction. The costochondral junctions are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.

HP:0000920.name: Enlargement of the costochondral junction
HP:0000920.definition: Abnormally increased size of the costochondral junctions, which are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum.

HP:0000921.name: Missing ribs
HP:0000921.definition: A developmental anomaly with absence of one or more ribs.

HP:0000924.name: Abnormality of the skeletal system
HP:0000924.definition: An abnormality of the skeletal system.

HP:0000925.name: Abnormality of the vertebral column
HP:0000925.definition: Any abnormality of the vertebral column.

HP:0000926.name: Platyspondyly
HP:0000926.definition: A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance between the vertebral endplates.

HP:0000927.name: Abnormality of skeletal maturation
HP:0000927.definition: The bones of the skeleton undergo a series of characteristic changes in size, shape, and calcification from fetal life until puberty. An abnormality of this process can include delayed or accelerated skeletal maturation, or deviation of some, but not all bones from the expected patterns of maturation.

HP:0000929.name: Abnormal skull morphology
HP:0000929.definition: An abnormality of the skull, the bony framework of the head which is comprised of the neurocranium (with eight cranial bones) and the viscerocranium (facial skeleton) that comprises fourteen facial bones with the mandible as its largest bone.

HP:0000930.name: Elevated imprint of the transverse sinuses

HP:0000931.name: Thinning and bulging of the posterior fossa bones

HP:0000932.name: Abnormal posterior cranial fossa morphology
HP:0000932.definition: An abnormality of the fossa cranii posterior (the posterior fossa), which is made up primarily of the occipital bone and which surrounds to the foramen magnum.

HP:0000933.name: Posterior fossa cyst at the fourth ventricle

HP:0000934.name: Chondrocalcinosis
HP:0000934.definition: Radiographic evidence of articular calcification that represent calcium pyrophosphate depositions in soft tissue surrounding joints and at the insertions of tendons near joints (Entheses/Sharpey fibers) .

HP:0000935.name: Thickened cortex of long bones
HP:0000935.definition: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of long bones.

HP:0000938.name: Osteopenia
HP:0000938.definition: Osteopenia is a term to define bone density that is not normal but also not as low as osteoporosis. By definition from the World Health Organization osteopenia is defined by bone densitometry as a T score -1 to -2.5.

HP:0000939.name: Osteoporosis
HP:0000939.definition: Osteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disease characterized by low bone density and microarchitectural deterioration of bone tissue with a consequent increase in bone fragility. According to the WHO criteria, osteoporosis is defined as a BMD that lies 2.5 standard deviations or more below the average value for young healthy adults (a T-score below -2.5 SD).

HP:0000940.name: Abnormal diaphysis morphology
HP:0000940.definition: An abnormality of the structure or form of the diaphysis, i.e., of the main or mid-section (shaft) of a long bone.

HP:0000944.name: Abnormal metaphysis morphology
HP:0000944.definition: An abnormality of one or more metaphysis, i.e., of the somewhat wider portion of a long bone that is adjacent to the epiphyseal growth plate and grows during childhood.

HP:0000947.name: Dumbbell-shaped long bone
HP:0000947.definition: An abnormal appearance of the long bones with resemblance to a dumbbell, a short bar with a weight at each end. That is, the long bone is shortened and displays flaring (widening) of the metaphyses.

HP:0000952.name: Jaundice
HP:0000952.definition: Yellow pigmentation of the skin due to bilirubin, which in turn is the result of increased bilirubin concentration in the bloodstream.

HP:0000953.name: Hyperpigmentation of the skin
HP:0000953.definition: A darkening of the skin related to an increase in melanin production and deposition.

HP:0000954.name: Single transverse palmar crease
HP:0000954.definition: The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease.

HP:0000956.name: Acanthosis nigricans
HP:0000956.definition: A dermatosis characterized by thickened, hyperpigmented plaques, typically on the intertriginous surfaces and neck.

HP:0000957.name: Cafe-au-lait spot
HP:0000957.definition: Cafe-au-lait spots are hyperpigmented lesions that can vary in color from light brown to dark brown with smooth borders and having a size of 1.5 cm or more in adults and 0.5 cm or more in children.

HP:0000958.name: Dry skin
HP:0000958.definition: Skin characterized by the lack of natural or normal moisture.

HP:0000960.name: Sacral dimple
HP:0000960.definition: A cutaneous indentation resulting from tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) of the intergluteal cleft.

HP:0000961.name: Cyanosis
HP:0000961.definition: Bluish discoloration of the skin and mucosa due to poor circulation or inadequate oxygenation of arterial or capillary blood.

HP:0000962.name: Hyperkeratosis
HP:0000962.definition: Hyperkeratosis is thickening of the epidermis involving the outer layer of the skin, the stratum corneum, which is composed of large, polyhedral, plate-like envelopes filled with keratin which are the dead cells that have migrated up from the stratum granulosum.

HP:0000963.name: Thin skin
HP:0000963.definition: Reduction in thickness of the skin, generally associated with a loss of suppleness and elasticity of the skin.

HP:0000964.name: Eczematoid dermatitis
HP:0000964.definition: Eczema is a form of dermatitis that is characterized by scaly, pruritic, erythematous lesions located on flexural surfaces.

HP:0000965.name: Cutis marmorata
HP:0000965.definition: A reticular discoloration of the skin with cyanotic (reddish-blue appearing) areas surrounding pale central areas due to dilation of capillary blood vessels and stagnation of blood within the vessels. Cutis marmorata generally occurs on the legs, arms and trunk and is often more severe in cold weather.

HP:0000967.name: Petechiae
HP:0000967.definition: Petechiae are pinpoint-sized reddish/purple spots, resembling a rash, that appear just under the skin or a mucous membrane when capillaries have ruptured and some superficial bleeding into the skin has happened. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to developing petechiae.

HP:0000968.name: Ectodermal dysplasia
HP:0000968.definition: Ectodermal dysplasia is a group of conditions in which there is abnormal development of the skin, hair, nails, teeth, or sweat glands.

HP:0000969.name: Edema
HP:0000969.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body.

HP:0000971.name: Abnormal sweat gland morphology
HP:0000971.definition: Any structural abnormality of the sweat gland.

HP:0000972.name: Palmoplantar hyperkeratosis
HP:0000972.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.

HP:0000973.name: Cutis laxa
HP:0000973.definition: Wrinkled, redundant, inelastic and sagging skin.

HP:0007609.name: Hypoproteinemic edema
HP:0007609.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body because of decreased osmotic pressure of plasma (hypoproteinemia).

HP:0007613.name: Spinous keratoses of palms and soles

HP:0007616.name: Nevus flammeus nuchae
HP:0007616.definition: Naevus flammeus localized in the skin of the neck. This is one of the most common birthmarks and present in approximately 25% of all newborns.

HP:0007618.name: Subcutaneous calcification
HP:0007618.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in subcutaneous tissue (i.e., the the lowermost layer of the integument).

HP:0007620.name: Cutaneous leiomyoma
HP:0007620.definition: The presence of leiomyoma of the skin.

HP:0007633.name: Bilateral microphthalmos
HP:0007633.definition: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of both eyes.

HP:0007634.name: Nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy
HP:0007634.definition: An acute condition characterized by sudden visual loss (usually discovered in the morning), optic disc edema at onset, optic disc-related visual field defects. Nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy can be associated with flame hemorrhages on the swollen disk or nearby neuroretinal layer, and sometimes with nearby cotton-wool exudates.

HP:0007641.name: Dyschromatopsia
HP:0007641.definition: A form of colorblindness in which only two of the three fundamental colors can be distinguished due to a lack of one of the retinal cone pigments.

HP:0007642.name: Congenital stationary night blindness
HP:0007642.definition: A nonprogressive (i.e., stationary) form of difficulties with night blindness with congenital onset.

HP:0007643.name: Peripheral tractional retinal detachment
HP:0007643.definition: Tractional retinal detachment at the periphery of the retina.

HP:0007646.name: Absent lower eyelashes
HP:0007646.definition: Lack of eyelashes on the lower lid.

HP:0007647.name: Congenital extraocular muscle anomaly
HP:0007647.definition: Congenital abnormality of the extraocular muscles.

HP:0007648.name: Punctate cataract
HP:0007648.definition: A type of cataract with punctate opacities of the lens.

HP:0007649.name: Congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium
HP:0007649.definition: Sharply demarcated, congenital hyperpigmentation of the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0007655.name: Eversion of lateral third of lower eyelids

HP:0007656.name: Lacrimal gland aplasia
HP:0007656.definition: A congenital defect of development characterized by absence of the lacrimal gland.

HP:0007657.name: Diffuse nuclear cataract
HP:0007657.definition: Opacity of the entire lens nucleus.

HP:0007659.name: obsolete Decreased retinal pigmentation with dispersion

HP:0007667.name: Peripheral cystoid retinal degeneration
HP:0007667.definition: Degenerative changes of the peripheral retina consisting of close-packed tiny cystic spaces at the outer plexiform/inner nuclear retinal level. The degeneration is very common in adult eyes and starts adjacent to the ora serrata and extends circumferentially and posteriorly.

HP:0007670.name: Abnormal vestibulo-ocular reflex
HP:0007670.definition: An abnormality of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR). The VOR attempts to keep the image stable on the retina. Ideally passive or active head movements in one direction are compensated for by eye movements of equal magnitude.

HP:0007677.name: Vitelliform-like macular lesions
HP:0007677.definition: Vitelliform maculopathy is a sharply demarcated lesion caused by the accumulation of material, often lipofuscin in the subretinal space underlying the macula.

HP:0007678.name: Lacrimal duct stenosis
HP:0007678.definition: Narrowing of a tear duct (lacrimal duct).

HP:0007686.name: Abnormal pupillary function
HP:0007686.definition: A functional abnormality of the pupil.

HP:0007688.name: Undetectable light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
HP:0007688.definition: Absence of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

HP:0007695.name: Abnormal pupillary light reflex
HP:0007695.definition: An abnormality of the reflex that controls the diameter of the pupil, in response to the intensity of light that falls on the retina of the eye.

HP:0007700.name: Ocular anterior segment dysgenesis
HP:0007700.definition: Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin.

HP:0007704.name: Paroxysmal involuntary eye movements
HP:0007704.definition: Sudden-onset episode of abnormal, involuntary eye movements.

HP:0007707.name: Congenital aphakia
HP:0007707.definition: Absence of the crystalline lens of the eye as a result of a developmental defect.

HP:0007709.name: Band-shaped corneal dystrophy
HP:0007709.definition: A type of genetically determined disease of the cornea with corneal lesions with a band-like shape.

HP:0007716.name: Uveal melanoma
HP:0007716.definition: A malignant melanoma originating within the eye. The tumor originates from the melanocytes in the uvea (which comprises the iris, ciliary body, and choroid).

HP:0007717.name: Chronic irritative conjunctivitis
HP:0007717.definition: A chronic irritative conjunctivitis, which commonly presents with general irritation and redness of the eyes, with a burning, dry, or foreign-body sensation of the eyes.

HP:0007720.name: Flat cornea
HP:0007720.definition: Cornea plana is an abnormally flat shape of the cornea such that the normal protrusion of the cornea from the sclera is missing. The reduced corneal curvature can lead to hyperopia, and a hazy corneal limbus and arcus lipoides may develop at an early age.

HP:0007721.name: Saccular conjunctival dilatations
HP:0007721.definition: Presence of multiple dilatations (sac-like outpouchings) in the blood vessels of the conjunctiva.

HP:0007722.name: Retinal pigment epithelial atrophy
HP:0007722.definition: Atrophy (loss or wasting) of the retinal pigment epithelium observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.

HP:0007727.name: Opacification of the corneal epithelium
HP:0007727.definition: Lack of transparency of the corneal epithelium.

HP:0007728.name: Congenital miosis
HP:0007728.definition: Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil of congenital onset.

HP:0007730.name: Iris hypopigmentation
HP:0007730.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation of the iris.

HP:0007731.name: Chorioretinal dysplasia
HP:0007731.definition: Abnormal development of the choroid and retina.

HP:0007737.name: Bone spicule pigmentation of the retina
HP:0007737.definition: Pigment migration into the retina in a bone-spicule configuration (resembling the nucleated cells within the lacuna of bone).

HP:0007754.name: Macular dystrophy
HP:0007754.definition: Macular dystrophy is a nonspecific term for premature retinal cell aging and cell death, generally confied to the macula in which no clear extrinsic cause is evident.

HP:0007756.name: obsolete Slitlike anterior chamber angles in children

HP:0007759.name: Opacification of the corneal stroma
HP:0007759.definition: Reduced transparency of the stroma of cornea.

HP:0007761.name: Pericentral scotoma
HP:0007761.definition: A scotoma (area of diminished vision within the visual field) that surrounds the central fixation point.

HP:0007763.name: Retinal telangiectasia
HP:0007763.definition: Dilatation of small blood vessels of the retina.

HP:0007765.name: Deep anterior chamber
HP:0007765.definition: Increased depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is increased.

HP:0007766.name: Optic disc hypoplasia
HP:0007766.definition: Underdevelopment of the optic disc, that is of the optic nerve head, where ganglion cell axons exit the eye to form the optic nerve.

HP:0007768.name: Central retinal vessel vascular tortuosity
HP:0007768.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of retinal blood vessels (arteries, arterioles, veins, venules).

HP:0007772.name: Impaired smooth pursuit
HP:0007772.definition: An impairment of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion.

HP:0007773.name: Vitreoretinopathy
HP:0007773.definition: Ocular abnormality characterized by premature degeneration of the vitreous and the retina that may be associated with increased risk of retinal detachment.

HP:0007777.name: Chorioretinal scar
HP:0007777.definition: Fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound (i.e., a scar) located in the choroid and retina or the eye.

HP:0007778.name: Posterior retinal neovascularization
HP:0007778.definition: A type of retinal neovascularization that affects the posterior pole of the retina.

HP:0007780.name: Cortical pulverulent cataract
HP:0007780.definition: A type of cataract characterized by punctate, dust-like opacities within the cortical region of the lens.

HP:0007783.name: obsolete Butterfly retinal pigment epithelial dystrophy

HP:0007787.name: Posterior subcapsular cataract
HP:0007787.definition: A type of cataract affecting the posterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the Lens capsule.

HP:0007791.name: Patchy atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium
HP:0007791.definition: Wasting (atrophy) of the retinal pigment epithelium present in small, isolated areas.

HP:0007793.name: Granular macular appearance
HP:0007793.definition: Mottled (spotted or blotched with different shades) pigmentary abnormality of the macula lutea.

HP:0007795.name: Anterior cortical cataract
HP:0007795.definition: A cataract that affects the anterior part of the cortex of the lens.

HP:0007799.name: Conjunctival whitish salt-like deposits
HP:0007799.definition: The presence of whitish deposits in the conjunctiva resembling salt. May be related to calcinosis.

HP:0007800.name: Increased axial length of the globe
HP:0007800.definition: Abnormal largeness of the eye with an axial length > 2.5 standard deviations from population mean.

HP:0007802.name: Granular corneal dystrophy
HP:0007802.definition: The presence of central, fine, whitish granular lesions in the stroma of the cornea. This type of corneal dystrophy is usually asymptomatic and begins in childhood and shows a slow progression. Later in the course, the corneal epithelium and Bowman's layer may be affected. Histologically, the cornea shows a uniform deposition of hyaline material.

HP:0007803.name: Monochromacy
HP:0007803.definition: Complete color blindness, a complete inability to distinguish colors. Affected persons cannot perceive colors, but only shades of gray.

HP:0007811.name: Horizontal pendular nystagmus
HP:0007811.definition: Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements of equal velocity.

HP:0007812.name: Herpetiform corneal ulceration
HP:0007812.definition: The presence of one or more dendritic corneal epithelial ulcers characterized by a treelike branching linear pattern with feathery edges and terminal bulbs. Herpetiform corneal ulcers can be identified by fluorescein staining.

HP:0007813.name: Nongranulomatous uveitis
HP:0007813.definition: A form of uveitis that is not associated with the formation of granulomas.

HP:0007814.name: Retinal pigment epithelial mottling
HP:0007814.definition: Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium, i.e., localized or generalized fundal pigment granularity associated with processes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0007815.name: Abnormal distribution of retinal arterioles and venules

HP:0007817.name: Horizontal supranuclear gaze palsy
HP:0007817.definition: A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a horizontal direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal.

HP:0007818.name: Central heterochromia
HP:0007818.definition: The presence of distinct colors in the central (pupillary) zone of the iris than in the mid-peripheral (ciliary) zone.

HP:0007819.name: Presenile cataracts
HP:0007819.definition: Presenile cataract is a kind of cataract that occurs in early adulthood, that is, at an age that is younger than usual.

HP:0007820.name: Lacrimal punctal atresia
HP:0007820.definition: Congenital absence or closure of the opening of the lacrimal punctum.

HP:0007824.name: Total ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007824.definition: Paralysis of both the extrinsic and intrinsic ocular muscles.

HP:0007825.name: obsolete Cataracts develop in second or third decade

HP:0007830.name: Adult-onset night blindness
HP:0007830.definition: Inability to see well at night or in poor light with onset in adulthood.

HP:0007831.name: Nonprogressive restrictive external ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007831.definition: Nonprogressive restriction of movement of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.

HP:0007834.name: Progressive cataract
HP:0007834.definition: A kind of cataract that progresses with age.

HP:0007840.name: Long upper eyelashes
HP:0007840.definition: Increased length of the upper eyelashes.

HP:0007841.name: Amyloid deposition in the vitreous humor
HP:0007841.definition: Deposition of hyaline extracellular material (amyloid) into the vitreous humor, which can manifest as vitreous opacities and reduced visual acuity.

HP:0007856.name: Punctate opacification of the cornea
HP:0007856.definition: Punctate opacification (reduced transparency) of the corneal stroma.

HP:0007858.name: Chorioretinal lacunae
HP:0007858.definition: Punched out lesions in the pigmented layer of the retina.

HP:0007859.name: Congenital horizontal nystagmus
HP:0007859.definition: Horizontal nystagmus dating from or present at birth.

HP:0007862.name: Retinal calcification
HP:0007862.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in the retina.

HP:0007867.name: Restrictive partial external ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007867.definition: Fibrosis of only some of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position.

HP:0007872.name: Choroidal hemangioma
HP:0007872.definition: The presence of multiple hemangiomas in the choroid. These are generally reddish or orange or can have increased pigmentation maiking them difficult to distinguish from choroidal melanomas.

HP:0007874.name: Almond-shaped palpebral fissure
HP:0007874.definition: A shape created by an acute downward arching of the upper eyelid and upward arching of the lower eyelid, toward the medial canthus, which gives the outline of the palpebral fissures the configuration of an almond. Thus, the maximum distance between the fissures is offset from, and medial to, the center point.

HP:0007879.name: Allergic conjunctivitis
HP:0007879.definition: Allergic Conjunctivitis is an allergic inflammation of the conjunctiva.

HP:0007885.name: Slowed horizontal saccades
HP:0007885.definition: An abnormally slow velocity of horizontal saccadic eye movements.

HP:0007886.name: Absent extraocular muscles
HP:0007886.definition: Congenital absence of the extraocular muscles.

HP:0007889.name: Iridescent posterior subcapsular cataract
HP:0007889.definition: A type of posterior subcapsular cataract characterized by an iridescent color.

HP:0007894.name: Hypopigmentation of the fundus
HP:0007894.definition: Reduced pigmentation of the fundus, typically generalized. Fundoscopy may reveal a low level pigment in both RPE and choroid with clear visibility of choroidal vessels (pale/albinoid) or low pigment level in the RPE with deep pigment in choroid so that visible choroidal vessels are separated by deeply pigmented zones (tesselated/tigroid).

HP:0007899.name: Retinal nonattachment
HP:0007899.definition: Failure of attachment of the retina during development.

HP:0007902.name: Vitreous hemorrhage
HP:0007902.definition: Bleeding within the vitreous compartment of the eye.

HP:0007903.name: Paravenous chorioretinal atrophy
HP:0007903.definition: Chorioretinal atrophy along the retinal veins.

HP:0007906.name: Ocular hypertension
HP:0007906.definition: Intraocular pressure that is 2 standard deviations above the population mean.

HP:0007913.name: Reticular retinal dystrophy
HP:0007913.definition: A type of of patterned retinal dystrophy that shows a reticular pattern of pigmentation.

HP:0007915.name: Polymorphous posterior corneal dystrophy
HP:0007915.definition: This corneal dystrophy affects the posterior limiting membrane of the cornea and is characterized by polymorphous plaques of calcium deposits in the deep stromal layers of the cornea, and occasionally by vesicular lesions of the endothelium and edema of the deep corneal stroma.

HP:0007916.name: obsolete Small anterior lens surface opacities

HP:0007917.name: Tractional retinal detachment
HP:0007917.definition: A type of retinal detachment arising due to a combination of contracting retinal membranes, abnormal vitreoretinal adhesions, and vitreous changes. It is usually seen in the context of diseases that induce a fibrovascular response, e.g. diabetes.

HP:0007925.name: Lacrimal duct aplasia
HP:0007925.definition: A congenital defect resulting in absence of the lacrimal duct.

HP:0007928.name: Abnormal flash visual evoked potentials
HP:0007928.definition: Anomaly of the visual evoked potentials elicited by a flash stimulus, generally a flash of light subtending an angle of at least 20 degrees of the visual field and presented in a dimly lit room.

HP:0007929.name: Peripheral retinal detachment
HP:0007929.definition: Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium occurring near the outer limit (periphery) of the retina.

HP:0007932.name: Bilateral congenital mydriasis
HP:0007932.definition: Congenital abnormal dilation of the pupil on both sides.

HP:0007933.name: Broad lateral eyebrow
HP:0007933.definition: Regional increase in the width (height) of the lateral eyebrow.

HP:0007936.name: Restrictive external ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007936.definition: Fibrosis of the external ocular muscles such that the eyes of affected individuals are partially or completely fixed in a strabismic position. Residual eye movements are significantly limited.

HP:0007937.name: Reticular pigmentary degeneration
HP:0007937.definition: A type of retinal reticular pigmentation that forms a polygonal, netlike arrangement of hyperpigmented lines forming geometric patterns in the fundus.

HP:0007939.name: Blue cone monochromacy
HP:0007939.definition: A form of monochromacy in which vision is derived from the remaining preserved blue (S) cones and rod photoreceptors.

HP:0007941.name: Limited extraocular movements
HP:0007941.definition: Limited mobility of the eye within its socket.

HP:0007942.name: Internal ophthalmoplegia
HP:0007942.definition: Paralysis of the iris and ciliary apparatus.

HP:0007943.name: Congenital stapes ankylosis
HP:0007943.definition: A form of stapes ankylosis with congenital onset.

HP:0007946.name: Unilateral narrow palpebral fissure
HP:0007946.definition: A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures on one side only.

HP:0007947.name: Pericentral retinitis pigmentosa
HP:0007947.definition: A subtype of retinitis pigmentosa in which, instead of the pathology starting in the mid-periphery like typical retinitis pigmentosa, the disease starts in the near periphery closer to the vascular arcades and tends to spare the far periphery.

HP:0007948.name: Dense posterior cortical cataract
HP:0007948.definition: A type of posterior cortical cataract characterized by dense lenticular opacities.

HP:0007950.name: Peripapillary chorioretinal atrophy
HP:0007950.definition: Chorioretinal atrophy concentrated around the optic papilla (i.e., the optic nerve head).

HP:0007958.name: Optic atrophy from cranial nerve compression

HP:0007963.name: Pattern dystrophy of the retina
HP:0007963.definition: A spectrum of fundoscopic appearances characterized by the development of a variety of patterns of deposits predominantly in the macular area. The deposits are typically bilateral, relatively symmetrical, yellow/white and associated with changes at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium. With time, retinal atrophy may occur. A number of pattern dystrophy subtypes have been described including butterfly-shaped dystrophy, reticular dystrophy (net-like pattern) and fundus pulverulentus (granular, mottled pigmentation).

HP:0007968.name: Remnants of the hyaloid vascular system
HP:0007968.definition: Persistence of the hyaloid artery, which is the embryonic artery that runs from the optic disc to the posterior lens capsule may persist; the site of attachment may form an opacity. The hyaloid artery is a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and usually regresses completely before birth. This features results from a failure of regression of the hyaloid vessel, which supplies the primary vitreous during embryogenesis and normally regresses in the third trimester of pregnancy, leading to a particular form of posterior cataract.

HP:0007971.name: Lamellar cataract
HP:0007971.definition: A congenital cataract in which opacity is limited to layers of the lens external to the nucleus (i.e., the perinuclear region), i.e., between the nuclear and cortical layers of the lens.

HP:0007973.name: Retinal dysplasia
HP:0007973.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the retina.

HP:0007975.name: Hypometric horizontal saccades
HP:0007975.definition: Saccadic undershoot of horizontal saccadic eye movements, i.e., a horizontal saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object.

HP:0007976.name: Cerulean cataract
HP:0007976.definition: Cerulean cataracts are a kind of congenital cataract having peripheral bluish and white opacifications in concentric layers with occasional central lesions arranged radially. Although the opacities may be observed during fetal development and childhood, usually visual acuity is only mildly reduced until adulthood, when lens extraction is generally necessary.

HP:0007979.name: Gaze-evoked horizontal nystagmus
HP:0007979.definition: Horizontal nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.

HP:0007981.name: obsolete Concentric narrowing of visual field

HP:0007984.name: Electronegative electroretinogram
HP:0007984.definition: A dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram in which the b-wave that is of markedly lower amplitude than the associated a-wave (source: Holder GE., Inherited Chorioretinal Dystrophies: A Textbook and Atlas; 2014; p.17; ISBN 978-3-540-69466-3).

HP:0007985.name: Retinal arteriolar occlusion
HP:0007985.definition: Blockage of retinal arteriole, generally associated with interruption of blood flow and oxygen delivery to affected regions of the retina.

HP:0007988.name: Macular hypopigmentation
HP:0007988.definition: Decreased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.

HP:0007989.name: Intraretinal exudate
HP:0007989.definition: Retinal exudate within the retinal tissue itself.

HP:0007990.name: Hypoplastic iris stroma
HP:0007990.definition: Underdevelopment of the stroma of iris.

HP:0007993.name: Malformed lacrimal duct
HP:0007993.definition: Congenital malformation of the lacrimal duct associated with incomplete development of the bony nasolacrimal canal or craniofacial anomalies.

HP:0007994.name: Peripheral visual field loss
HP:0007994.definition: Loss of peripheral vision with retention of central vision, resulting in a constricted circular tunnel-like field of vision.

HP:0008000.name: Decreased corneal reflex
HP:0008000.definition: An abnormally reduced response to stimulation of the cornea (by touch, foreign body, blowing air). The corneal reflex (also known as the blink reflex, normally results in an involuntary blinking of the eyelids.

HP:0008001.name: Foveal hyperpigmentation
HP:0008001.definition: Increased amount of pigmentation in the fovea centralis.

HP:0008002.name: Abnormality of macular pigmentation
HP:0008002.definition: Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation.

HP:0008011.name: Peripheral opacification of the cornea
HP:0008011.definition: Reduced transparency of the peripheral region of the cornea.

HP:0008014.name: Central fundal arteriolar microaneurysms
HP:0008014.definition: Microscopic aneurysms of the retinal arterioles near the central part of the fundus, visible as small round dark red dots on the retinal surface (not arising from visible vessels) that are by definition less than the diameter of the major optic veins as they cross the optic disc.

HP:0008017.name: obsolete Depigmented lesions of the retinal pigment epithelium

HP:0008019.name: Superior lens subluxation
HP:0008019.definition: Partial dislocation of the lens in a superior direction.

HP:0008028.name: Cystoid macular degeneration
HP:0008028.definition: A form of macular degeneration characterized by the presence of multiple cysts in the macula.

HP:0008031.name: Posterior Y-sutural cataract
HP:0008031.definition: A type of sutural cataract in which the opacity follows the posterior Y suture.

HP:0008035.name: Retinitis pigmentosa inversa
HP:0008035.definition: Retinitis pigmentosa inversa is form of retinal degeneration characterized by areas of retinal/chorioretinal degeneration with pigment migration in the macular area (in contrast to retinitis pigmentosa which, at early disease stages, predominantly affects the retinal periphery).

HP:0008037.name: Absent anterior chamber of the eye
HP:0008037.definition: Absence of the anterior chamber of the eye owing to a developmental defect.

HP:0008038.name: Aplastic/hypoplastic lacrimal glands
HP:0008038.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the lacrimal gland.

HP:0008043.name: Retinal arteriolar constriction
HP:0008043.definition: Decreased retinal arteriolar diameters, which may decrease blood flow and slow oxygen delivery to regions of the retina.

HP:0008046.name: Abnormal retinal vascular morphology
HP:0008046.definition: A structural abnormality of retinal vasculature.

HP:0008047.name: Abnormality of the vasculature of the eye

HP:0008048.name: Abnormal line of Schwalbe morphology
HP:0008048.definition: An abnormality of the line of Schwalbe.

HP:0008049.name: Abnormality of the extraocular muscles
HP:0008049.definition: An abnormality of an extraocular muscle.

HP:0008050.name: Abnormality of the palpebral fissures
HP:0008050.definition: An anomaly of the space between the medial and lateral canthi of the two open eyelids.

HP:0008051.name: obsolete Abnormality of the retinal pigment epithelium

HP:0008052.name: Retinal fold
HP:0008052.definition: A wrinkle of retinal tissue projecting outward from the surface of the retina and visible as a line on fundoscopy.

HP:0008053.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the iris
HP:0008053.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the iris.

HP:0008054.name: Abnormal morphology of the conjunctival vasculature
HP:0008054.definition: Any abnormality of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva.

HP:0008055.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the uvea
HP:0008055.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the uvea, the pigmented middle layer of the eye consisting of the iris and ciliary body together with the choroid.

HP:0008060.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fovea
HP:0008060.definition: Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.

HP:0008062.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the anterior segment of the eye
HP:0008062.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior segment of the eye.

HP:0008063.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the lens
HP:0008063.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the lens.

HP:0008064.name: Ichthyosis
HP:0008064.definition: An abnormality of the skin characterized the presence of excessive amounts of dry surface scales on the skin resulting from an abnormality of keratinization.

HP:0008066.name: Abnormal blistering of the skin
HP:0008066.definition: The presence of one or more bullae on the skin, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls.

HP:0008069.name: Neoplasm of the skin
HP:0008069.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the skin.

HP:0008071.name: Maternal hypertension
HP:0008071.definition: Increased blood pressure during a pregnancy.

HP:0008072.name: Maternal virilization in pregnancy
HP:0008072.definition: Virilization (deepening of voice, facial hirsutism and scalp hair loss) with onset during pregnancy (usually towards the end of the first trimester) and regression several months post-partum.

HP:0008073.name: Low maternal circulating estriol concentration
HP:0008073.definition: An abnormally low concentration of serum conjugated estriol as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

HP:0008076.name: Osteoporotic tarsals
HP:0008076.definition: Reduction in bone mineral density affecting any or all of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

HP:0008079.name: Absent fifth metatarsal
HP:0008079.definition: A developmental abnormality characterized by the absence of the fifth metatarsal bone.

HP:0008080.name: Hallux varus
HP:0008080.definition: Medial deviation of the great toe owing to a deformity of the great toe joint causing the hallux to deviate medially.

HP:0008081.name: Pes valgus
HP:0008081.definition: An outward deviation of the foot at the talocalcaneal or subtalar joint.

HP:0008087.name: Nonossified fifth metatarsal
HP:0008087.definition: The presence of a fifth metatarsal bone that has not undergone ossification at an age when ossification is usually visible.

HP:0008089.name: Abnormality of the fifth metatarsal bone
HP:0008089.definition: An anomaly of the fifth metatarsal bone.

HP:0008094.name: Widely spaced toes
HP:0008094.definition: An overall widening of the spaces between the digits.

HP:0008096.name: Medially deviated second toe
HP:0008096.definition: Medial deviation of the second toe.

HP:0008102.name: Expanded metatarsals with widened medullary cavities

HP:0008103.name: Delayed tarsal ossification
HP:0008103.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

HP:0008107.name: Plantar crease between first and second toes
HP:0008107.definition: The presence of unusually deep creases (ridges/wrinkles) on the skin of sole of foot located between the first and second toe.

HP:0008108.name: Advanced tarsal ossification
HP:0008108.definition: Precocious (accelerated) maturation and calcification of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

HP:0008112.name: Plantar flexion contracture
HP:0008112.definition: A type of contracture in which the plantar flexion muscles are contracted.

HP:0008114.name: Metatarsal diaphyseal endosteal sclerosis
HP:0008114.definition: Osteosclerosis of the endosteal surface of the diaphyses (shafts) of the metatarsal bones.

HP:0008115.name: Clinodactyly of the 3rd toe
HP:0008115.definition: Bending or curvature of a third toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

HP:0008116.name: Flexion limitation of toes
HP:0008116.definition: Limitation of the ability to bend the toes.

HP:0008122.name: Calcaneonavicular fusion
HP:0008122.definition: Synostosis of the calcaneus with the navicular bone.

HP:0008124.name: Talipes calcaneovarus
HP:0008124.definition: A congenital deformity characterized by a dorsiflexed, inverted, and adducted foot, i.e., a combination of talipes calcaneus and talipes varus.

HP:0008127.name: Bipartite calcaneus
HP:0008127.definition: A two-part calcaneus, a finding that probably results from delayed coalescence of two primary calcaneal centers of ossification.

HP:0008131.name: Tarsal stippling
HP:0008131.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more tarsal bones.

HP:0008132.name: Medial rotation of the medial malleolus
HP:0008132.definition: Hindfoot valgus (posterior part of the foot turns outward) in combination with forefoot abduction (front part of the foot (the forefoot) is angled outwards away from the midline of the body, relative to the hindfoot) and lowering of the midfoot.

HP:0008134.name: Irregular tarsal ossification
HP:0008134.definition: Defective ossification in an irregular pattern of the seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

HP:0008138.name: Equinus calcaneus
HP:0008138.definition: Abnormal plantar flexion of the calcaneus relative to the longitudinal axis of the tibia. This results in the angle between the long axis of the tibia and the long axis of the heel bone (calcaneus) being greater than 90 degrees.

HP:0008142.name: Delayed calcaneal ossification
HP:0008142.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of the calcaneus.

HP:0008148.name: Impaired epinephrine-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0008148.definition: Abnormal response to epinephrine as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of epinephrine.

HP:0008150.name: Elevated serum transaminases during infections
HP:0008150.definition: Elevations of the levels of SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) that occur during infections.

HP:0008151.name: Prolonged prothrombin time
HP:0008151.definition: Increased time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.

HP:0008153.name: Periodic hypokalemic paresis
HP:0008153.definition: Episodes of muscle weakness associated with reduced levels of potassium in the blood.

HP:0008155.name: Mucopolysacchariduria
HP:0008155.definition: Excessive amounts of mucopolysaccharide in the urine.

HP:0008158.name: Hyperapobetalipoproteinemia
HP:0008158.definition: Hyperapobetalipoproteinemia is defined as the combination of a normal low density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol in the face of an increased LDL apolipoprotein B (apoB) protein.

HP:0008160.name: 3-hydroxydicarboxylic aciduria
HP:0008160.definition: The concentration of 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0008161.name: Absent leukocyte alkaline phosphatase
HP:0008161.definition: Alkaline phosphatase levels measured within leukocytes is below detectable levels.

HP:0008162.name: Asymptomatic hyperammonemia
HP:0008162.definition: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood not associated with symptoms such as encephalopathy.

HP:0008163.name: Decreased circulating cortisol level
HP:0008163.definition: Abnormally reduced concentration of cortisol in the blood.

HP:0008165.name: obsolete Decreased helper T cell proportion

HP:0008166.name: Decreased beta-galactosidase activity
HP:0008166.definition: Abnormally decreased rate of beta-galactosidase activity. Beta-galactosidase activity can be measured in leukocyte, fibroblast, or plasma.

HP:0008167.name: Very long chain fatty acid accumulation

HP:0008169.name: Reduced factor VII activity
HP:0008169.definition: Reduced activity of coagulation factor VII. Factor VII is part of the extrinsic coagulation pathway, which is initiated at the site of injury in response to the release of tissue factor (fIII). Tissue factor and activated factor VII catalyze the activation of factor X.

HP:0008179.name: Decreased Arden ratio of electrooculogram
HP:0008179.definition: An abnormal reduction in the Arden ratio, which is the ratio between the light peak and the dark trough of the smoothed (physiologic) EOG record.

HP:0008181.name: Abetalipoproteinemia
HP:0008181.definition: An absence of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0008185.name: Precocious puberty in males
HP:0008185.definition: The onset of puberty before the age of 9 years in boys.

HP:0008186.name: Adrenocortical cytomegaly
HP:0008186.definition: The presence of large polyhedral cells with eosinophilic granular cytoplasm and enlarged nuclei in the adrenal cortex.

HP:0008187.name: Absence of secondary sex characteristics
HP:0008187.definition: No secondary sexual characteristics are present at puberty.

HP:0008188.name: Thyroid dysgenesis
HP:0008188.definition: Thyroid dysgenesis is a descriptive term that should be avoided if more precise information is available. However, the HPO keeps retains this term because it is commonly used in the medical literature. In humans, the process of thyroid morphogenesis occurs from the 3rd to 16th week of gestation. Alterations occurring during this period may result in a thyroid gland that is absent (thyroid agenesis or athyreosis), hypoplastic (thyroid hypoplasia), or located in an unusual position (thyroid ectopy). All these entities are grouped under the term thyroid dysgenesis.

HP:0008191.name: Thyroid agenesis
HP:0008191.definition: The congenital absence of the thyroid gland.

HP:0008194.name: Multiple pancreatic beta-cell adenomas
HP:0008194.definition: The presence of multiple pancreatic islet cell adenomas.

HP:0008198.name: Congenital hypoparathyroidism
HP:0008198.definition: Deficiency of parathyroid hormone with congenital onset.

HP:0008200.name: Primary hyperparathyroidism
HP:0008200.definition: A type of hyperparathyroidism caused by a primary abnormality of the parathyroid glands (e.g., adenoma, carcinoma, hyperplasia). Primary hyperparathyroidism is associated with hyercalcemia.

HP:0008202.name: Reduced circulating prolactin concentration
HP:0008202.definition: A reduced level of prolactin in the blood circulation. Prolactin is a protein hormone that is secreted by lactotrophs in the anterior pituitary and that stimulates mammary gland development and milk production.

HP:0008204.name: Precocious puberty with Sertoli cell tumor

HP:0008205.name: Insulin-dependent but ketosis-resistant diabetes
HP:0008205.definition: Ketosis-resistant diabetes is a synonym for type II diabetes. This term thus refers to a form of type II diabetes in which patients are dependent on insulin.

HP:0008207.name: Primary adrenal insufficiency
HP:0008207.definition: Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands as a result of a primary defect in the glands themselves.

HP:0008209.name: Premature ovarian insufficiency
HP:0008209.definition: Amenorrhea due to loss of ovarian function before the age of 40. Primary ovarian insuficiency (POI) is a state of female hypergonadotropic hypogonadism. It can manifest as primary amenorrhea with onset before menarche or secondary amenorrhea.

HP:0008213.name: Gonadotropin deficiency
HP:0008213.definition: A reduced ability to secrete gonadotropins, which are protein hormones secreted by gonadotrope cells of the anterior pituitary gland, including the hormones follitropin (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).

HP:0008214.name: Decreased serum estradiol
HP:0008214.definition: A reduction below normal concentration of estradiol in the circulation.

HP:0008216.name: Adrenal gland dysgenesis
HP:0008216.definition: Abnormal development of the adrenal gland.

HP:0008223.name: Compensated hypothyroidism
HP:0008223.definition: Condition associated with a raised serum concentration of thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) but a normal serum free thyroxine (FT4).

HP:0008227.name: Pituitary resistance to thyroid hormone
HP:0008227.definition: A condition in which the pituitary gland is partially resistant to thyroid hormone, so that it continues to secrete thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) until the blood level of thyroid hormone rises higher than normal.

HP:0008229.name: Thyroid lymphangiectasia
HP:0008229.definition: The presence of lymphangiectasis of the thyroid gland.

HP:0008232.name: Elevated circulating follicle stimulating hormone level
HP:0008232.definition: An elevated concentration of follicle-stimulating hormone in the blood.

HP:0008233.name: Decreased circulating progesterone
HP:0008233.definition: An reduced concentration of progesterone in the blood.

HP:0008237.name: Hypothalamic hypothyroidism
HP:0008237.definition: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyrotropin-releasing hormone activity.

HP:0008239.name: Adrenal medullary hypoplasia
HP:0008239.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal medulla.

HP:0008242.name: Pseudohypoaldosteronism
HP:0008242.definition: A state of renal tubular unresponsiveness or resistance to the action of aldosterone.

HP:0008244.name: Congenital adrenal hypoplasia
HP:0008244.definition: A type of adrenal hypoplasia with congenital onset.

HP:0008444.name: Posterior wedging of vertebral bodies
HP:0008444.definition: An abnormality of the shape of vertebrae, such that they are wedge-shaped (narrow towards the back).

HP:0008445.name: Cervical spinal canal stenosis
HP:0008445.definition: An abnormal narrowing of the cervical spinal canal.

HP:0008450.name: Narrow vertebral interpedicular distance
HP:0008450.definition: A reduction of the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces.

HP:0008454.name: Lumbar kyphosis
HP:0008454.definition: Over curvature of the lumbar region.

HP:0008455.name: Dysplastic sacrum
HP:0008455.definition: A developmental defect of the sacrum characterized by partial or disordered development of the sacrum in which portions of the sacrum, which normally is formed by fusion of five sacral vertebrae S1-S5, fail to form or fail to form normally.

HP:0008456.name: C2-C3 subluxation
HP:0008456.definition: A partial dislocation of the intervertebral joint between the second and third cervical vertebrae.

HP:0008457.name: Caudal interpedicular narrowing
HP:0008457.definition: Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column. Note that normally, the interpedicular distances get progressively wider as one proceeds down the spine.

HP:0008458.name: Progressive congenital scoliosis
HP:0008458.definition: A progressive form of scoliosis with congenital onset.

HP:0008459.name: Cervical vertebral agenesis
HP:0008459.definition: Agenesis of one or more vertebrae of the cervical vertebral column.

HP:0008464.name: Absent spinous processes of lower thoracic and lumbar vertebrae

HP:0008465.name: Absent vertebra
HP:0008465.definition: A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies.

HP:0008467.name: Thoracic hemivertebrae
HP:0008467.definition: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the thoracic spine.

HP:0008468.name: Abnormal sacral segmentation
HP:0008468.definition: An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation of sacral vertebrae during development.

HP:0008469.name: Cervical vertebral dysplasia
HP:0008469.definition: Dysplasia of the cervical vertebral column.

HP:0008470.name: Lower thoracic interpediculate narrowness
HP:0008470.definition: A reduction of the distance between the lower thoracic vertebral pedicles.

HP:0008473.name: Narrow anterio-posterior vertebral body diameter
HP:0008473.definition: An abnormal reduction of the anterioposterior diameter of the vertebral body.

HP:0008477.name: Poorly ossified cervical vertebrae
HP:0008477.definition: Decreased ossification of the cervical vertebral bodies, i.e., of the Cervical vertebrae set.

HP:0008480.name: Cervical spondylosis
HP:0008480.definition: Arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the cervical vertebral column.

HP:0008483.name: Cervical vertebral bodies with decreased anteroposterior diameter

HP:0008484.name: Thoracolumbar interpediculate narrowness
HP:0008484.definition: A reduction of the distance between thoracolumbar vertebral pedicles.

HP:0008486.name: Lumbar interpedicular narrowing
HP:0008486.definition: Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between lumbar vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column.

HP:0008489.name: Spondylolisthesis at L5-S1
HP:0008489.definition: Complete bilateral fractures of the pars interarticularis resulting in the anterior slippage of the fifth lumbar vertebral body (L5) onto the sacrum (level S1).

HP:0008491.name: Premature anterior fontanel closure
HP:0008491.definition: Early closure (ossification) of the anterior fontanelle, which generally undergoes closure around the 18th month of life.

HP:0008494.name: Inferior lens subluxation
HP:0008494.definition: Partial displacement of the lens in the inferior direction.

HP:0008499.name: High hypermetropia
HP:0008499.definition: A severe form of hypermetropia with over +5.00 diopters.

HP:0008501.name: obsolete Median cleft lip and palate

HP:0008504.name: Moderate sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008504.definition: The presence of a moderate form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

HP:0008511.name: Central posterior corneal opacity
HP:0008511.definition: Reduced transparency of the central posterior portion of the corneal stroma.

HP:0008513.name: Bilateral conductive hearing impairment
HP:0008513.definition: A bilateral type of conductive hearing impairment.

HP:0008516.name: Abnormality of the vertebral spinous processes

HP:0008517.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the sacrum
HP:0008517.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the sacral bone.

HP:0008519.name: Abnormal coccyx morphology
HP:0008519.definition: Any structural abnormality of the coccyx.

HP:0008523.name: Posterior helix pit
HP:0008523.definition: Permanent indentation on the posteromedial aspect of the helix that may be sharply or indistinctly delineated.

HP:0008527.name: Congenital sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008527.definition: A type of hearing impairment caused by an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve with congenital onset.

HP:0008528.name: Long hairs growing from helix of pinna

HP:0008529.name: Absence of acoustic reflex
HP:0008529.definition: Absence of the acoustic reflex, an involuntary contraction of the stapedius muscle that occurs in response to high-intensity sound stimuli.

HP:0008537.name: Cleft at the superior portion of the pinna

HP:0008542.name: Low-frequency hearing loss
HP:0008542.definition: A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the low frequencies of sound (125 Hz to 1000 Hz).

HP:0008544.name: Abnormally folded helix
HP:0008544.definition: Any structural anomaly of the border of the helix, which usually forms a rolled rim but is highly variable in shape.

HP:0008554.name: Cochlear malformation
HP:0008554.definition: The presence of a malformed cochlea.

HP:0008555.name: Absent vestibular function
HP:0008555.definition: Complete lack of functioning of the vestibular apparatus.

HP:0008568.name: Vestibular areflexia
HP:0008568.definition: Vestibular areflexia can be measured as the absence of the caloric nystagmus response in electronystagmography.

HP:0008569.name: Microtia, second degree
HP:0008569.definition: Median longitudinal length of the ear more than two standard deviations below the mean in the presence of some, but not all, parts of the normal ear.

HP:0008573.name: Low-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008573.definition: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects primarily the lower frequencies.

HP:0008577.name: Underfolded helix
HP:0008577.definition: Underdevelopment of the helix that either affects the entire helix, or is localized.

HP:0008583.name: Underfolded superior helices
HP:0008583.definition: A condition in which the superior portion of the helix is folded over to a lesser degree than normal.

HP:0008587.name: Mild neurosensory hearing impairment
HP:0008587.definition: The presence of a mild form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

HP:0008588.name: Slit-like opening of the exterior auditory meatus
HP:0008588.definition: A type of stenosis of the external auditory meatus in which the opening of the external auditory meatus appears as a vertical slit.

HP:0008589.name: Hypoplastic helices
HP:0008589.definition: Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna.

HP:0008591.name: Congenital conductive hearing impairment
HP:0008591.definition: A type of conductive deafness with congenital onset.

HP:0008593.name: Prominent antitragus
HP:0008593.definition: Increased anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

HP:0008596.name: Postlingual sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008596.definition: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with onset after the acquisition of speech.

HP:0008598.name: Mild conductive hearing impairment
HP:0008598.definition: A mild form of conductive hearing impairment.

HP:0008606.name: Supraauricular pit
HP:0008606.definition: Benign congenital lesion of the supraauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

HP:0008607.name: Progressive conductive hearing impairment
HP:0008607.definition: A progressive type of conductive deafness.

HP:0008609.name: Abnormal middle ear morphology
HP:0008609.definition: An abnormality of the morphology or structure of the middle ear.

HP:0008610.name: Infantile sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008610.definition: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with infantile onset.

HP:0008615.name: Adult onset sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008615.definition: The presence of sensorineural deafness with late onset.

HP:0008619.name: Bilateral sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008619.definition: A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects both ears.

HP:0008625.name: Severe sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0008625.definition: A severe form of sensorineural hearing impairment.

HP:0008628.name: Abnormal stapes morphology
HP:0008628.definition: An abnormality of the stapes, a stirrup-shaped ossicle in the middle ear.

HP:0008629.name: Pulsatile tinnitus
HP:0008629.definition: Pulsatile tinnitus is generally classified a kind of objective tinnitus, meaning that it is not only audible to the patient but also to the examiner on auscultation of the auditory canal and/or of surrounding structures with use of an auscultation tube or stethoscope. Usually, pulsatile tinnitus is heard as a lower pitched thumping or booming, a rougher blowing sound which is coincidental with respiration, or as a clicking, higher pitched rhythmic sensation.

HP:0008631.name: Ureteral dysgenesis
