HP:0008631.definition: A developmental anomaly of the ureter.

HP:0008633.name: Agonadism
HP:0008633.definition: Absence of sex glands (gonads are the organs that produce gametes; testis in males and ovary in females).

HP:0008635.name: Urinary bladder wall hypertrophy
HP:0008635.definition: Increase in thickness of the wall of the urinary bladder. This finding may be seen in conditions such as bladder outlet obstruction and may be accompanied by increased trabeculation of the bladder wall musculature.

HP:0008643.name: Nephroblastomatosis
HP:0008643.definition: Presence of persistent islands of renal blastema in the postnatal kidney. Nephroblastomatosis represents a complex abnormality of nephrogenesis and has been defined as the persistence of metanephricblastema into infancy and childhood.

HP:0008651.name: Uric acid urolithiasis independent of gout

HP:0008652.name: Autonomic erectile dysfunction
HP:0008652.definition: Impotence (inability to develop or maintain an erection) resulting from abnormal functioning of the autonomic nervous system.

HP:0008653.name: Crescentic glomerulonephritis
HP:0008653.definition: A type of extracapillary glomerulonephritis characterized by the formation of crescent-like cellular proliferation.

HP:0008655.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the fallopian tube
HP:0008655.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.

HP:0008659.name: Multiple small medullary renal cysts
HP:0008659.definition: The presence of many cysts in the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0008660.name: Renotubular dysgenesis
HP:0008660.definition: A developmental defect characterized by absence or poor development of proximal renal tubules.

HP:0008668.name: Gonadal dysgenesis, male
HP:0008668.definition: Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to an unassigned sex differentiation.

HP:0008669.name: Abnormal spermatogenesis
HP:0008669.definition: Incomplete maturation or aberrant formation of the male gametes.

HP:0008672.name: Calcium oxalate nephrolithiasis
HP:0008672.definition: The presence of calcium- and oxalate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.

HP:0008676.name: Congenital megaureter
HP:0008676.definition: A developmental disturbance with extreme ureteral dilatation.

HP:0008677.name: Congenital nephrotic syndrome
HP:0008677.definition: Nephrotic syndrome with onset within the first three months of life.

HP:0008678.name: Renal hypoplasia/aplasia
HP:0008678.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the kidney.

HP:0008682.name: Renal tubular epithelial necrosis
HP:0008682.definition: Coagulative necrosis of tubular epithelial cells, defined as cells with increased cytoplasmic eosinophilia and nucleus that has a condensed chromatin pattern with fuzzy nuclear contour or has barely visible nuclear basophilic staining. The extent of cortical tubular necrosis is scoredsemiquantitatively as none, mild (less than 25% tubules with necrosis), moderate (25-50 percent), and severe (over 50%).

HP:0008683.name: Enlarged labia minora
HP:0008683.definition: Increase in size of the folds of skin between the outer labia.

HP:0008684.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the uterus
HP:0008684.definition: Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the uterus.

HP:0008689.name: Bilateral cryptorchidism
HP:0008689.definition: Absence of both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.

HP:0008691.name: Solitary bladder diverticulum
HP:0008691.definition: Presence of a single diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.

HP:0008696.name: Renal hamartoma
HP:0008696.definition: A disordered proliferation of mature tissues that are native to the kidneys.

HP:0008697.name: Hypoplasia of the fallopian tube
HP:0008697.definition: Developmental hypoplasia of the fallopian tube.

HP:0008703.name: Gonadal calcification
HP:0008703.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in gonadal tissue.

HP:0008708.name: Partial development of the penile shaft
HP:0008708.definition: A congenital condition of the external male genitalia in which the shaft of the penis fails to fully develop.

HP:0008711.name: Benign prostatic hyperplasia
HP:0008711.definition: The presence of non-malignant hyperplasia of the prostate.

HP:0008716.name: Urethrovaginal fistula
HP:0008716.definition: The presence of a fistula between the vagina and the urethra.

HP:0008717.name: Unilateral renal atrophy
HP:0008717.definition: A unilateral form of atrophy of the kidney.

HP:0008718.name: Unilateral renal dysplasia
HP:0008718.definition: A unilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.

HP:0008722.name: Urethral diverticulum
HP:0008722.definition: The presence of a diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urethra.

HP:0008723.name: Gonadal dysgenesis with female appearance, male
HP:0008723.definition: Unusual gonadal development in a person with a 46,XY male karyotype, leading to a more female sex differentiation.

HP:0008730.name: Female external genitalia in individual with 46,XY karyotype
HP:0008730.definition: The presence of female external genitalia in a person with a male karyotype.

HP:0008732.name: Renal hypophosphatemia
HP:0008732.definition: Renal hypophosphatemia is defined as reduced serum phosphate (e.g., below 0.70 mmol/l) and an inappropriately high renal phosphate excretion.

HP:0008734.name: Decreased testicular size
HP:0008734.definition: Reduced volume of the testicle (the male gonad).

HP:0008738.name: Partially duplicated kidney
HP:0008738.definition: The presence of a partially duplicated kidney.

HP:0008740.name: Longitudinal vaginal septum
HP:0008740.definition: The presence of a longitudinal vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication.

HP:0008743.name: Coronal hypospadias
HP:0008743.definition: A mild form of hypospadias in which the urethra opens just under the corona glandis, that is, where the head of the penis meets the shaft.

HP:0008744.name: Abnormal aryepiglottic fold morphology
HP:0008744.definition: An abnormality of the aryepiglottic fold.

HP:0008747.name: Cartilaginous ossification of larynx
HP:0008747.definition: Ossification affecting the set of cartilages of larynx.

HP:0008750.name: Laryngeal atresia
HP:0008750.definition: Congenital absence of the lumen of the larynx. Laryngeal atresia is a rare condition. If the laryngeal opening fails to develop, fluid secreted by the lungs cannot be expelled. In a fetus with laryngeal atresia, the lungs are either normal or hyperplastic, not hypoplastic. Mortality is reported as 100%. At obstetric US examination, views of the fetal neck demonstrate a dilated trachea filled with trapped fluid. Views of the fetal chest show enlarged, hyperechoic lungs, with dilated fluid-filled bronchi. Fetal ascites is usually present.

HP:0008751.name: Laryngeal cleft
HP:0008751.definition: Presence of a gap in the posterior laryngotracheal wall with a continuity between the larynx and the esophagus.

HP:0008752.name: Laryngeal cartilage malformation
HP:0008752.definition: A malformation of the laryngeal cartilage.

HP:0008754.name: Laryngeal calcification
HP:0008754.definition: Calcification (abnormal deposits of calcium) in the laryngeal tissues.

HP:0008756.name: Bowing of the vocal cords
HP:0008756.definition: Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the vocal folds.

HP:0008757.name: Unilateral vocal cord paralysis
HP:0008757.definition: A loss of the ability to move the vocal fold on one side.

HP:0008760.name: Violent behavior
HP:0008760.definition: Conduct and/or behavior, both verbal and non-verbal, including but not limited to verbal and/or physical aggression, attacks, threats, harassment, intimidation, and other disruptive behaviors in any form or through any medium, that cause or have the potential to cause a reasonable person to fear physical harm from any individual(s) or group(s) towards any person(s) or property. This is commonly defined as a violent act characterized by the use of physical force, anger, or sudden intense activity.

HP:0008763.name: No social interaction
HP:0008763.definition: Lack of intentional participation in interactions with another person.

HP:0008765.name: Auditory hallucination
HP:0008765.definition: Perception of sounds without auditory stimulus.

HP:0008767.name: Self-mutilation of tongue and lips due to involuntary movements
HP:0008767.definition: Uncontrolled movements result in tissue damage to the tongue and lips.

HP:0008768.name: Abnormal sexual behavior
HP:0008768.definition: A deviation of sexual behaviors from the personal norms of the individual in the context of socially and culturally recognized patterns of human sexual behaviors.

HP:0008770.name: Obsessive-compulsive trait
HP:0008770.definition: The presence of one or more obsessive-compulsive personality traits. Obsessions refer to persistent intrusive thoughts, and compulsions to intrusive behaviors, which the affected person experiences as involuntary, senseless, or repugnant.

HP:0008771.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ear
HP:0008771.definition: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ear.

HP:0008772.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the external ear
HP:0008772.definition: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the external ear.

HP:0008773.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle ear
HP:0008773.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the middle ear.

HP:0008774.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the inner ear
HP:0008774.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the inner ear.

HP:0008776.name: Abnormal renal artery morphology
HP:0008776.definition: Any structural abnormality of the renal artery.

HP:0008777.name: Abnormal vocal cord morphology
HP:0008777.definition: An abnormality of the vocal cord.

HP:0008783.name: Wide proximal femoral metaphysis
HP:0008783.definition: Increased width of the proximal part of the shaft (metaphysis) of the femur.

HP:0008784.name: Wide capital femoral epiphyses
HP:0008784.definition: Abnormally wide morphology of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0008785.name: Delayed ossification of pubic rami
HP:0008785.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of the rami (branches) of the pubic bone.

HP:0008786.name: Iliac crest serration
HP:0008786.definition: Irregularities of the iliac crest that produce the appearance of a lace border around it.

HP:0008788.name: Delayed pubic bone ossification
HP:0008788.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of the pubic bone.

HP:0008789.name: Cone-shaped capital femoral epiphysis
HP:0008789.definition: A cone-shaped deformity of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0008794.name: Dysplastic iliac wing
HP:0008794.definition: A general term that describes a congenital defect in the iliac wing resulting from abnormal development.

HP:0008796.name: Femoral retroversion
HP:0008796.definition: An abnormal backward rotation of the hip relative to the knee such that the hips are externally rotated with the foot pointed outward instead of straight ahead (out-toeing).

HP:0008797.name: Early ossification of capital femoral epiphyses
HP:0008797.definition: Developmental acceleration of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0008798.name: Widened greater sciatic notch
HP:0008798.definition: The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a increase in the lateral dimension of the notch.

HP:0008800.name: Limited hip movement
HP:0008800.definition: A decreased ability to move the femur at the hip joint associated with a decreased range of motion of the hip.

HP:0008804.name: Broad femoral head
HP:0008804.definition: Increased width of the femoral head.

HP:0008807.name: Acetabular dysplasia
HP:0008807.definition: A smaller than normal acetabulum that has insufficient femoral head coverage leading to abnormal hip joint contact pressures, instability and pain.

HP:0008808.name: High iliac wing
HP:0008808.definition: Increased height of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally).

HP:0008817.name: Aplastic pubic bone
HP:0008817.definition: A developmental defect characterized by lack of development of the pubis bone.

HP:0008818.name: Large iliac wing
HP:0008818.definition: Increased size of the ilium ala.

HP:0008819.name: Narrow femoral neck
HP:0008819.definition: An abnormally reduced diameter of the femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

HP:0008820.name: Absent ossification of capital femoral epiphysis
HP:0008820.definition: Lack of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0008822.name: Hypoplastic ischiopubic ramus
HP:0008822.definition: Underdevelopment of the ischiopubic ramus, which is comprised of the inferior pubic ramus and the inferior ramus of the ischium.

HP:0008823.name: Inferior pubic ramus hypoplasia
HP:0008823.definition: Underdevelopment of the lower branch of the pubis bone (inferior pubic ramus).

HP:0008824.name: Hypoplastic iliac body
HP:0008824.definition: Underdevelopment of the body of ilium.

HP:0008826.name: obsolete Dislocation of the femoral head

HP:0008828.name: Delayed proximal femoral epiphyseal ossification
HP:0008828.definition: Developmental delay of ossification of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0008829.name: Delayed femoral head ossification
HP:0008829.definition: Delayed ossification of the femoral head.

HP:0008830.name: Hypoplastic pubic ramus
HP:0008830.definition: Underdevelopment of a ramus (branch) of the pubic bone.

HP:0008835.name: Multicentric femoral head ossification
HP:0008835.definition: There is normally one ossification center in the head of the femur. This term applies if there are multiple such centers.

HP:0008845.name: Mesomelic short stature
HP:0008845.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by disproportionate shortening of the medial parts of the extremities (forearm or lower leg).

HP:0008846.name: Severe intrauterine growth retardation
HP:0008846.definition: Intrauterine growth retardation that is 4 or more standard deviations below average, corrected for sex and gestational age.

HP:0008848.name: Moderately short stature
HP:0008848.definition: A moderate degree of short stature, more than -3 SD but not more than -4 SD from mean corrected for age and sex.

HP:0008850.name: Severe postnatal growth retardation
HP:0008850.definition: Severely slow or limited growth after birth, being four standard deviations or more below age- and sex-related norms.

HP:0008855.name: Moderate postnatal growth retardation
HP:0008855.definition: A moderate degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between three and four standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.

HP:0008857.name: Neonatal short-trunk short stature
HP:0008857.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with congenital onset recognizable at birth.

HP:0008866.name: Failure to thrive secondary to recurrent infections
HP:0008866.definition: Insufficient weight gain or inappropriate weight loss for a child, that is attributed to an endogenous recurrent infections.

HP:0008872.name: Feeding difficulties in infancy
HP:0008872.definition: Impaired feeding performance of an infant as manifested by difficulties such as weak and ineffective sucking, brief bursts of sucking, and falling asleep during sucking. There may be difficulties with chewing or maintaining attention.

HP:0008873.name: Disproportionate short-limb short stature
HP:0008873.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short limbs but an average-sized trunk.

HP:0008883.name: Mild intrauterine growth retardation
HP:0008883.definition: Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 2 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 3 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

HP:0008887.name: Adipose tissue loss
HP:0008887.definition: A reduction in the amount of adipose tissue (fat) compared with the amount previously present in an individual.

HP:0008897.name: Postnatal growth retardation
HP:0008897.definition: Slow or limited growth after birth.

HP:0008905.name: Rhizomelia
HP:0008905.definition: Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of limbs (i.e. the femur and humerus).

HP:0008915.name: Childhood-onset truncal obesity
HP:0008915.definition: Truncal obesity with onset during childhood, defined as between 2 and 10 years of age.

HP:0008921.name: Neonatal short-limb short stature
HP:0008921.definition: A type of short-limbed dwarfism that is manifest beginning in the neonatal period.

HP:0008922.name: Childhood-onset short-trunk short stature
HP:0008922.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in childhood.

HP:0008935.name: Generalized neonatal hypotonia
HP:0008935.definition: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature.

HP:0008936.name: Axial hypotonia
HP:0008936.definition: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk.

HP:0008944.name: Distal lower limb amyotrophy
HP:0008944.definition: Muscular atrophy of distal leg muscles.

HP:0008945.name: Loss of ability to walk in early childhood

HP:0008946.name: Pelvic girdle amyotrophy
HP:0008946.definition: Atrophy of the muscles of the pelvic girdle (also known as hip girdle), i.e., the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, the adductors, the psoas major and the iliacus muscle.

HP:0008947.name: Floppy infant
HP:0008947.definition: Floppiness/hypotonia is defined as reduced resistance to passive movement of joints. Physical examination of floppy/hypotonic infants shows head lag, lack of shoulder and elbow muscle contraction on traction response, inability to tighten the shoulder girdle muscles (or slipping through) when held under the axillae, scarf sign (when the arm is pulled to the opposite side, the arm wraps around the neck with the elbow crossing midline), hyperdorsiflexion of the feet, easy apposition of the thumb against the forearm, feet touching the cheek with ease and without discomfort, frog leg position, and inverted U sign on ventral suspension (head, arms, and legs hanging down without elbow or knee flexion and the trunk rounded in a dome shape).

HP:0008948.name: Proximal upper limb amyotrophy
HP:0008948.definition: Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the arms.

HP:0008952.name: Shoulder muscle hypoplasia
HP:0008952.definition: Underdevelopment of muscles of the shoulder.

HP:0008954.name: Intrinsic hand muscle atrophy
HP:0008954.definition: Atrophy of the intrinsic muscle groups of the hand, comprising the thenar and hypothenar muscles; the interossei muscles; and the lumbrical muscles.

HP:0008955.name: Progressive distal muscular atrophy
HP:0008955.definition: Progressive muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities.

HP:0008956.name: Proximal lower limb amyotrophy
HP:0008956.definition: Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the legs, i.e., of the thigh.

HP:0008959.name: Distal upper limb muscle weakness
HP:0008959.definition: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the arms.

HP:0008962.name: Calf muscle hypoplasia
HP:0008962.definition: Underdevelopment of the muscuklature of the calf.

HP:0008963.name: Tibialis muscle weakness
HP:0008963.definition: Muscle weakness affecting the tibialis anterior muscle.

HP:0008964.name: Nonprogressive muscular atrophy
HP:0008964.definition: Muscular atrophy that does not display a progression in severity with time.

HP:0008967.name: Exercise-induced muscle stiffness
HP:0008967.definition: A type of muscle stiffness that occurs following physical exertion.

HP:0008968.name: Muscle hypertrophy of the lower extremities
HP:0008968.definition: Muscle hypertrophy primarily affecting the legs.

HP:0008972.name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
HP:0008972.definition: Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.

HP:0008981.name: Calf muscle hypertrophy
HP:0008981.definition: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the calf muscles.

HP:0008984.name: Neck muscle hypoplasia
HP:0008984.definition: Underdevelopment of muscles of the neck.

HP:0008985.name: Increased intramuscular fat
HP:0008985.definition: An abnormal increase in the amount of intramuscular fat tissue.

HP:0008986.name: Agenesis of the diaphragm
HP:0008986.definition: Congenital lack, i.e., aplasia of the diaphragm.

HP:0008988.name: Pelvic girdle muscle atrophy
HP:0008988.definition: Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles that attach to the pelvic girdle (the gluteal muscles, the lateral rotators, adductor magnus, adductor brevis, adductor longus, pectineus, and gracilis muscles).

HP:0008991.name: Exercise-induced leg cramps
HP:0008991.definition: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles of the leg brought on by physical exertion.

HP:0008993.name: Increased intraabdominal fat
HP:0008993.definition: An abnormal increase in the amount of intraabdominal fat tissue.

HP:0008994.name: Proximal muscle weakness in lower limbs
HP:0008994.definition: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the legs.

HP:0008997.name: Proximal muscle weakness in upper limbs
HP:0008997.definition: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the arms.

HP:0009002.name: Loss of truncal subcutaneous adipose tissue
HP:0009002.definition: Loss (reduction of previously present) of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the region of the trunk.

HP:0009003.name: Increased subcutaneous truncal adipose tissue
HP:0009003.definition: The presence of an abnormally increased amount of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the trunk of the body.

HP:0009005.name: Weakness of the intrinsic hand muscles

HP:0009011.name: Hypoplasia of serratus anterior muscle
HP:0009011.definition: Underdevelopment of the serratus anterior muscle, which is involved in abduction, upward Rotation, and elevation of the scapula.

HP:0009016.name: Upper limb muscle hypoplasia
HP:0009016.definition: Underdevelopment of muscles of the arm.

HP:0009017.name: Loss of gluteal subcutaneous adipose tissue
HP:0009017.definition: Loss (reduction of previously present) of subcutaneous adipose tissue in the gluteal region.

HP:0009019.name: Progressive loss of facial adipose tissue

HP:0009020.name: Exercise-induced muscle fatigue
HP:0009020.definition: An abnormally increased tendency towards muscle fatigue induced by physical exercise.

HP:0009023.name: Abdominal wall muscle weakness
HP:0009023.definition: Decreased strength of the abdominal musculature.

HP:0009025.name: Increased connective tissue
HP:0009025.definition: The presence of an abnormally increased amount of connective tissue.

HP:0009026.name: Hypoplasia of latissimus dorsi muscle
HP:0009026.definition: Underdevelopment of the latissimus dorsi muscle, which is involved in adduction, extension, internal rotation, and transverse extension of the shoulder and assists in movement of the scapula.

HP:0009027.name: Foot dorsiflexor weakness
HP:0009027.definition: Weakness of the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot, that is, of the movement of the toes towards the shin. The foot dorsiflexors include the tibialis anterior, the extensor hallucis longus, the extensor digitorum longus, and the peroneus tertius muscles.

HP:0009028.name: Generalized weakness of limb muscles
HP:0009028.definition: Generalized weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.

HP:0009031.name: Amyotrophy of ankle musculature
HP:0009031.definition: Atrophy of the muscles of the ankle.

HP:0009049.name: Peroneal muscle atrophy
HP:0009049.definition: Atrophy of the peroneous muscles, peroneus longus (also known as Fibularis longus), Peroneus brevis (also known as fibularis brevis, and Peroneus tertius (also known as fibularis tertius).

HP:0009050.name: Quadriceps muscle atrophy
HP:0009050.definition: Muscular atrophy involving the quadriceps muscle.

HP:0009051.name: Increased muscle glycogen content
HP:0009051.definition: An increased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.

HP:0009053.name: Distal lower limb muscle weakness
HP:0009053.definition: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.

HP:0009055.name: Generalized limb muscle atrophy
HP:0009055.definition: Generalized (unlocalized) atrophy affecting muscles of the limbs in both proximal and distal locations.

HP:0009056.name: Loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue from upper limbs

HP:0009058.name: Increased muscle lipid content
HP:0009058.definition: An abnormal accumulation of lipids in skeletal muscle.

HP:0009060.name: Scapular muscle atrophy
HP:0009060.definition: Atrophy of the muscles that are responsible for moving the scapula, which are the levator scapulae, the infraspinatus muscle, the teres major, the teres minor, and the supraspinatus muscle.

HP:0009063.name: Progressive distal muscle weakness
HP:0009063.definition: Progressively reduced strength of the distal musculature.

HP:0009064.name: Generalized lipodystrophy
HP:0009064.definition: Generalized degenerative changes of the fat tissue.

HP:0009067.name: Progressive spinal muscular atrophy
HP:0009067.definition: Progressive spinal muscular atrophy, i.e., muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.

HP:0009071.name: Inflammatory myopathy
HP:0009071.definition: Chronic muscle inflammation accompanied by muscle weakness.

HP:0009072.name: Decreased Achilles reflex
HP:0009072.definition: Decreased intensity of the Achilles reflex (also known as the ankle jerk reflex), which can be elicited by tapping the tendon is tapped while the foot is dorsiflexed.

HP:0009073.name: Progressive proximal muscle weakness
HP:0009073.definition: Lack of strength of the proximal muscles that becomes progressively more severe.

HP:0009077.name: Weakness of long finger extensor muscles

HP:0009084.name: Midline notch of upper alveolar ridge

HP:0009085.name: Alveolar ridge overgrowth
HP:0009085.definition: Increased width of the alveolar ridges.

HP:0009088.name: Speech articulation difficulties
HP:0009088.definition: Impairment in the physical production of speech sounds.

HP:0009098.name: Chronic oral candidiasis
HP:0009098.definition: Chronic accumulation and overgrowth of the fungus Candida albicans on the mucous membranes of the mouth, generally manifested as associated with creamy white lesions on the tongue or inner cheeks, occasionally spreading to the gums, tonsils, palate or oropharynx.

HP:0009099.name: Median cleft palate
HP:0009099.definition: Cleft palate of the midline of the palate.

HP:0009101.name: Submucous cleft lip
HP:0009101.definition: A cleft of the lip with overlying mucous membrane.

HP:0009102.name: Anterior open-bite malocclusion
HP:0009102.definition: Anterior open bite is a malocclusion characterized by a gap between the anterior teeth (incisors), that is, by a deficiency in the normal vertical overlap between antagonist incisal edges when the posterior teeth are in occlusion.

HP:0009104.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the pubic bone
HP:0009104.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the pubic bone.

HP:0009105.name: Abnormal ossification of the pubic bone
HP:0009105.definition: Abnormal ossification (bone tissue formation) affecting the pubic bone, also known as the pubis.

HP:0009106.name: Abnormal pelvis bone ossification
HP:0009106.definition: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of any bone of the bony pelvis.

HP:0009107.name: Abnormal ossification involving the femoral head and neck

HP:0009108.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the femoral head and neck

HP:0009109.name: Denervation of the diaphragm
HP:0009109.definition: Interruption of the innervation of the diaphragm.

HP:0009110.name: Diaphragmatic eventration
HP:0009110.definition: A congenital failure of muscular development of part or all of one or both hemidiaphragms, resulting in superior displacement of abdominal viscera and altered lung development.

HP:0009112.name: Aplasia of the left hemidiaphragm
HP:0009112.definition: Congenital absence of the left half of the diaphragm.

HP:0009113.name: Diaphragmatic weakness
HP:0009113.definition: A decrease in the strength of the diaphragm.

HP:0009115.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving the skeleton
HP:0009115.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of one or more components of the skeleton.

HP:0009116.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the skull

HP:0009117.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the maxilla
HP:0009117.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the maxilla.

HP:0009118.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the mandible
HP:0009118.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the mandible.

HP:0009119.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the frontal sinuses
HP:0009119.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of frontal sinus.

HP:0009120.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the sinuses
HP:0009120.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of a cranial sinus or sinuses.

HP:0009121.name: Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
HP:0009121.definition: An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.

HP:0009122.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia affecting bones of the axial skeleton
HP:0009122.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of bones of the axial skeleton.

HP:0009123.name: Mixed hypo- and hyperpigmentation of the skin

HP:0009124.name: Abnormal adipose tissue morphology
HP:0009124.definition: An abnormality of adipose tissue, which is loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes.

HP:0009125.name: Lipodystrophy
HP:0009125.definition: Degenerative changes of the fat tissue.

HP:0009126.name: Increased adipose tissue
HP:0009126.definition: An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell).

HP:0009127.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the limbs

HP:0009128.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the musculature of the extremities

HP:0009129.name: Upper limb amyotrophy
HP:0009129.definition: Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the upper limbs.

HP:0009130.name: Hand muscle atrophy
HP:0009130.definition: Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the hand.

HP:0009131.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the thorax
HP:0009131.definition: A disease or lesion affecting the muscles of the thorax.

HP:0009132.name: Abnormal tarsal bone mineral density
HP:0009132.definition: This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density of the tarsal bones, which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone.

HP:0009134.name: Osteolysis involving bones of the feet

HP:0009136.name: Duplication involving bones of the feet

HP:0009138.name: Synostosis involving bones of the lower limbs
HP:0009138.definition: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones lower limbs.

HP:0009139.name: Osteolysis involving bones of the lower limbs

HP:0009140.name: Synostosis involving bones of the feet

HP:0009141.name: Depletion of mitochondrial DNA in muscle tissue

HP:0009142.name: Duplication of bones involving the upper extremities

HP:0009144.name: Supernumerary bones of the axial skeleton

HP:0009145.name: Abnormal cerebral artery morphology
HP:0009145.definition: Any structural anomaly of a cerebral artery. The cerebral arteries comprise three main pairs of arteries and their branches, which supply the cerebrum of the brain. These are the anterior cerebral artery, the middle cerebral artery, and the posterior cerebral artery.

HP:0009147.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009147.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009148.name: Small epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009148.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009149.name: Triangular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009149.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the little finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.

HP:0002480.name: Hepatic encephalopathy
HP:0002480.definition: Central nervous system dysfunction in association with liver failure and characterized clinically (depending on degree of severity) by lethargy, confusion, nystagmus, decorticate posturing, spasticity, and bilateral Babinski reflexes.

HP:0002486.name: Myotonia
HP:0002486.definition: An involuntary and painless delay in the relaxation of skeletal muscle following contraction or electrical stimulation.

HP:0002487.name: Hyperkinetic movements
HP:0002487.definition: Motor hyperactivity with excessive movement of muscles of the body as a whole.

HP:0002488.name: Acute leukemia
HP:0002488.definition: A clonal (malignant) hematopoietic disorder with an acute onset, affecting the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. The malignant cells show minimal differentiation and are called blasts, either myeloid blasts (myeloblasts) or lymphoid blasts (lymphoblasts).

HP:0002490.name: Increased CSF lactate
HP:0002490.definition: Increased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0002491.name: Spasticity of facial muscles
HP:0002491.definition: Spasticity of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve.

HP:0002492.name: Abnormal corticospinal tract morphology
HP:0002492.definition: Abnormality of the corticospinal tract, which is the chief element of the pyramidal system (the principle motor tract) and is the only direct connection between the cerebrum and the spinal cord.

HP:0002493.name: Upper motor neuron dysfunction
HP:0002493.definition: A functional anomaly of the upper motor neuron. The upper motor neurons are neurons of the primary motor cortex which project to the brainstem and spinal chord via the corticonuclear, corticobulbar and corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts. They are involved in control of voluntary movements. Dysfunction leads to weakness, impairment of fine motor movements, spasticity, hyperreflexia and abnormal pyramidal signs.

HP:0002494.name: Abnormal rapid eye movement sleep
HP:0002494.definition: Abnormality of REM Sleep are phases of REM sleep are characterized by desynchronized EEG patterns, increases in heart rate and blood pressure, sympathetic activation, and a profound loss of muscle tone except for the eye and middle-ear muscles. There are also phases of rapid eye movements.

HP:0002495.name: Impaired vibratory sensation
HP:0002495.definition: A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration. Clinically, this is usually tested with a tuning fork which vibrates at 128 Hz and is applied to bony prominences such as the malleoli at the ankles or the metacarpal-phalangeal joints. There is a slow decay of vibration from the tuning fork. The degree of vibratory sense loss can be crudely estimated by counting the number of seconds that the examiner can perceive the vibration longer than the patient.

HP:0002500.name: Abnormal cerebral white matter morphology
HP:0002500.definition: An abnormality of the cerebral white matter.

HP:0002504.name: Calcification of the small brain vessels
HP:0002504.definition: Deposition of calcium salts within small blood vessels of the brain.

HP:0002505.name: Loss of ambulation
HP:0002505.definition: Inability to walk in a person who previous had the ability to walk.

HP:0002506.name: Diffuse cerebral atrophy
HP:0002506.definition: Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebrum.

HP:0002507.name: Semilobar holoprosencephaly
HP:0002507.definition: A type of holoprosencephaly in which the left and right frontal and parietal lobes are fused and the interhemispheric fissure is only present posteriorly.

HP:0002508.name: Brainstem dysplasia
HP:0002508.definition: A developmental structural anomaly of the stalk-like part of the brain that comprises the midbrain (aka mesencephalon), the pons (aka pons Varolii), and the medulla oblongata, and connects the cerebral hemispheres with the cervical spinal cord.

HP:0002510.name: Spastic tetraplegia
HP:0002510.definition: Spastic paralysis affecting all four limbs.

HP:0002511.name: Alzheimer disease
HP:0002511.definition: A degenerative disease of the brain characterized by the insidious onset of dementia. Impairment of memory, judgment, attention span, and problem solving skills are followed by severe apraxia and a global loss of cognitive abilities. The condition primarily occurs after age 60, and is marked pathologically by severe cortical atrophy and the triad of senile plaques, neurofibrillary tangles, and neuropil threads.

HP:0002514.name: Cerebral calcification
HP:0002514.definition: The presence of calcium deposition within the cerebrum.

HP:0002515.name: Waddling gait
HP:0002515.definition: Weakness of the hip girdle and upper thigh muscles, for instance in myopathies, leads to an instability of the pelvis on standing and walking. If the muscles extending the hip joint are affected, the posture in that joint becomes flexed and lumbar lordosis increases. The patients usually have difficulties standing up from a sitting position. Due to weakness in the gluteus medius muscle, the hip on the side of the swinging leg drops with each step (referred to as Trendelenburg sign). The gait appears waddling. The patients frequently attempt to counteract the dropping of the hip on the swinging side by bending the trunk towards the side which is in the stance phase (in the German language literature this is referred to as Duchenne sign). Similar gait patterns can be caused by orthopedic conditions when the origin and the insertion site of the gluteus medius muscle are closer to each other than normal, for instance due to a posttraumatic elevation of the trochanter or pseudarthrosis of the femoral neck.

HP:0002516.name: Increased intracranial pressure
HP:0002516.definition: An increase of the pressure inside the cranium (skull) and thereby in the brain tissue and cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0002518.name: Abnormal periventricular white matter morphology
HP:0002518.definition: A structural abnormality of the myelinated axons (white matter) located near the cerebral ventricles.

HP:0002519.name: Hypnagogic hallucination
HP:0002519.definition: Hypnagogic hallucinations are brief hallucinations that occur as you are falling asleep.

HP:0002521.name: Hypsarrhythmia
HP:0002521.definition: Hypsarrhythmia is abnormal interictal high amplitude waves and a background of irregular spikes. There is continuous (during wakefulness), high-amplitude (>200 Hz), generalized polymorphic slowing with no organized background and multifocal spikes demonstrated by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0002522.name: Areflexia of lower limbs
HP:0002522.definition: Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the lower limbs.

HP:0002524.name: Cataplexy
HP:0002524.definition: A sudden and transient episode of bilateral loss of muscle tone, often triggered by emotions.

HP:0002526.name: Deficit in nonword repetition
HP:0002526.definition: Impaired ability to repeat non-word sounds. Nonword repetition (NWR) is a measure of short-term phonological memory.

HP:0002528.name: Granulovacuolar degeneration
HP:0002528.definition: Electron-dense granules within double membrane-bound cytoplasmic vacuoles.

HP:0002529.name: Neuronal loss in central nervous system

HP:0002530.name: Axial dystonia
HP:0002530.definition: A type of dystonia that affects the midline muscles, i.e., the chest, abdominal, and back muscles.

HP:0002533.name: Abnormal posturing
HP:0002533.definition: Involuntary flexion or extension of the arms and legs.

HP:0002536.name: Abnormal cortical gyration
HP:0002536.definition: An abnormality of the gyri (i.e., the ridges) of the cerebral cortex of the brain.

HP:0002538.name: Abnormal cerebral cortex morphology
HP:0002538.definition: Any structural abnormality of the cerebral cortex.

HP:0002539.name: Cortical dysplasia
HP:0002539.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the cerebral cortex.

HP:0002542.name: Olivopontocerebellar atrophy
HP:0002542.definition: Neuronal degeneration in the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.

HP:0002544.name: Retrocollis
HP:0002544.definition: A form of torticollis in which the head is drawn back, either due to a permanent contractures of neck extensor muscles, or to a spasmodic contracture.

HP:0002545.name: Patchy demyelination of subcortical white matter
HP:0002545.definition: Patchy loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

HP:0002548.name: Parkinsonism with favorable response to dopaminergic medication
HP:0002548.definition: Parkinsonism is a clinical syndrome that is a feature of a number of different diseases, including Parkinson disease itself, other neurodegenerative diseases such as progressive supranuclear palsy, and as a side-effect of some neuroleptic medications. Some but not all individuals with Parkinsonism show responsiveness to dopaminergic medication defined as a substantial reduction of amelioration of the component signs of Parkinsonism (including mainly tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and postural instability) upon administration of dopaminergic medication.

HP:0002549.name: Deficit in phonologic short-term memory
HP:0002549.definition: Impaired ability to repeat non-word sounds. The test for nonword repetition involves the repetition of nonsensical words of increasing length and complexity and is regarded as a measure of phonological (speech sound) processing and short-term memory

HP:0002553.name: Highly arched eyebrow
HP:0002553.definition: Increased height of the central portion of the eyebrow, forming a crescent, semicircular, or inverted U shape.

HP:0002558.name: Supernumerary nipple
HP:0002558.definition: Presence of more than two nipples.

HP:0002561.name: Absent nipple
HP:0002561.definition: Congenital failure to develop, and absence of, the nipple.

HP:0002562.name: Low-set nipples
HP:0002562.definition: Placement of the nipples at a lower than normal location.

HP:0002563.name: Constrictive pericarditis
HP:0002563.definition: Presence of a thickened, fibrotic pericardium that forms a non-compliant shell around the heart, and resulting from chronic inflammation of the pericardium.

HP:0002564.name: obsolete Malformation of the heart and great vessels

HP:0002566.name: Intestinal malrotation
HP:0002566.definition: An abnormality of the intestinal rotation and fixation that normally occurs during the development of the gut. This can lead to volvulus, or twisting of the intestine that causes obstruction and necrosis.

HP:0002570.name: Steatorrhea
HP:0002570.definition: Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats.

HP:0002571.name: Achalasia
HP:0002571.definition: A disorder of esophageal motility characterized by the inability of the lower esophageal sphincter to relax during swallowing and by inadequate or lacking peristalsis in the lower half of the body of the esophagus.

HP:0002573.name: Hematochezia
HP:0002573.definition: The passage of fresh (red) blood per anus, usually in or with stools. Most rectal bleeding comes from the colon, rectum, or anus.

HP:0002574.name: Episodic abdominal pain
HP:0002574.definition: An intermittent form of abdominal pain.

HP:0002575.name: Tracheoesophageal fistula
HP:0002575.definition: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the esophagus and the trachea.

HP:0002576.name: Intussusception
HP:0002576.definition: An abnormality of the intestine in which part of the intestine invaginates (telescopes) into another part of the intestine.

HP:0002578.name: Gastroparesis
HP:0002578.definition: Decreased strength of the muscle layer of stomach, which leads to a decreased ability to empty the contents of the stomach despite the absence of obstruction.

HP:0002579.name: Gastrointestinal dysmotility
HP:0002579.definition: Abnormal intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis, related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

HP:0002580.name: Volvulus
HP:0002580.definition: Abnormal twisting of a portion of intestine around itself or around a stalk of mesentery tissue.

HP:0002582.name: Atrophic gastritis
HP:0002582.definition: Atrophic gastritis (AG) is a histopathological entity that is characterized by chronic inflammation of the gastric mucosa with loss of gastric glandular cells and replacement by intestinal-type epithelium, pyloric-type glands, and fibrous tissue.

HP:0002583.name: Colitis
HP:0002583.definition: Colitis refers to an inflammation of the colon and is often used to describe an inflammation of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum). Colitides may be acute and self-limited or chronic, and broadly fit into the category of digestive diseases.

HP:0002587.name: Projectile vomiting
HP:0002587.definition: Vomiting that ejects the gastric contents with great force.

HP:0002588.name: Duodenal ulcer
HP:0002588.definition: An erosion of the mucous membrane in a portion of the duodenum.

HP:0002591.name: Polyphagia
HP:0002591.definition: A neurological anomaly with gross overeating associated with an abnormally strong desire or need to eat.

HP:0002592.name: Gastric ulcer
HP:0002592.definition: An ulcer, that is, an erosion of an area of the gastric mucous membrane.

HP:0002593.name: Intestinal lymphangiectasia
HP:0002593.definition: Angiectasia of lymph vessels (i.e., dilatation of lymphatic vessels) in the intestines.

HP:0002595.name: Ileus
HP:0002595.definition: Acute obstruction of the intestines preventing passage of the contents of the intestines.

HP:0002599.name: Head titubation
HP:0002599.definition: A head tremor of moderate speed (3 to 4 Hz) in the anterior-posterior direction.

HP:0002600.name: Hyporeflexia of lower limbs
HP:0002600.definition: Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in the lower limbs. Reflexes are elicited by stretching the tendon of a muscle, e.g., by tapping.

HP:0002601.name: Paresis of extensor muscles of the big toe

HP:0002605.name: Hepatic necrosis
HP:0002605.definition: The presence of cell death (necrosis) affecting the liver.

HP:0002607.name: Bowel incontinence
HP:0002607.definition: Involuntary fecal soiling in adults and children who have usually already been toilet trained.

HP:0002608.name: Celiac disease
HP:0002608.definition: Celiac disease (CD) is an autoimmune condition affecting the small intestine, triggered by the ingestion of gluten, the protein fraction of wheat, barley, and rye. Clinical manifestations of CD are highly variable and include both gastrointestinal and non-gastrointestinal features. The hallmark of CD is an immune-mediated enteropathy. This term is included because the occurrence of CD is seen as a feature of a number of other diseases.

HP:0002612.name: Congenital hepatic fibrosis
HP:0002612.definition: The presence of fibrosis of that part of the liver with congenital onset.

HP:0002613.name: Biliary cirrhosis
HP:0002613.definition: Progressive destruction of the small-to-medium bile ducts of the intrahepatic biliary tree, which leads to progressive cholestasis and often end-stage liver disease.

HP:0002614.name: Hepatic periportal necrosis
HP:0002614.definition: A type of hepatic necrosis that is concentrated around the necrosis of hepatocytes localized around the intrahepatic branch of portal vein.

HP:0002616.name: Aortic root aneurysm
HP:0002616.definition: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic root.

HP:0002617.name: Vascular dilatation
HP:0002617.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of an artery, vein or the heart.

HP:0002621.name: Atherosclerosis
HP:0002621.definition: A condition characterized by patchy atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques which develop in the walls of medium-sized and large arteries and can lead to arterial stenosis with reduced or blocked blood flow.

HP:0002623.name: Overriding aorta
HP:0002623.definition: An overriding aorta is a congenital heart defect where the aorta is positioned directly over a ventricular septal defect, instead of over the left ventricle. The result is that the aorta receives some blood from the right ventricle, which reduces the amount of oxygen in the blood. It is one of the four conditions of the Tetralogy of Fallot. The aortic root can be displaced toward the front (anteriorly) or directly above the septal defect, but it is always abnormally located to the right of the root of the pulmonary artery. The degree of override is quite variable, with 5-95% of the valve being connected to the right ventricle.

HP:0002625.name: Deep venous thrombosis
HP:0002625.definition: Formation of a blot clot in a deep vein. The clot often blocks blood flow, causing swelling and pain. The deep veins of the leg are most often affected.

HP:0002626.name: Venous varicosities of celiac and mesenteric vessels
HP:0002626.definition: Elongated and tortuous mesenteric veins, which comprise the inferior mesenteric vein and the superior mesenteric vein.

HP:0002627.name: Right aortic arch with mirror image branching
HP:0002627.definition: The aortic arch crosses the right mainstem bronchus and not the left mainstem bronchus, but does not result in the creation of a vascular ring. The first branch is the left brachiocephalic artery which divides into the left carotid artery and left subclavian artery, the second branch is the right carotid artery, the third branch is the right subclavian artery.

HP:0002629.name: Gastrointestinal arteriovenous malformation
HP:0002629.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0002630.name: Fat malabsorption
HP:0002630.definition: Abnormality of the absorption of fat from the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0002634.name: Arteriosclerosis
HP:0002634.definition: Sclerosis (hardening) of the arteries with increased thickness of the wall of arteries as well as increased stiffness and a loss of elasticity.

HP:0002635.name: Type IV atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0002635.definition: In type IV atherosclerotic lesions a dense accumulation of extracellular lipid occupies an extensive but well-defined region of the intima. This type of extracellular lipid accumulation is known as the lipid core. A fibrous tissue increase is not a feature, and complications such as defects of the lesion surface and thrombosis are not present. The type IV lesion is also known as atheroma. Type IV is the first lesion considered advanced in this classification because of the severe intimal disorganization caused by the lipid core. The characteristic core appears to develop from an increase and the consequent confluence of the small isolated pools of extracellular lipid that characterize type III lesions. The increase in lipid is believed to result from continued insudation from the plasma. Type IV lesions, when they first appear in younger people, are found in the same locations as adaptive intimal thickenings of the eccentric type. Thus, atheroma is, at least initially, an eccentric lesion.

HP:0002636.name: Dilatation of an abdominal artery
HP:0002636.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in an artery that originates from the abdominal aorta.

HP:0002637.name: Cerebral ischemia
HP:0002637.definition: Restriction of arterial blood supply to the brain associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the tissue.

HP:0002638.name: Superficial thrombophlebitis
HP:0002638.definition: Inflammation of a superficial vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein).

HP:0002639.name: Budd-Chiari syndrome
HP:0002639.definition: Budd-Chiari syndrome (BCS) is caused by obstruction of hepatic venous outflow at any level from the small hepatic veins to the junction of the inferior vena cava (IVC) with the right atrium, 1 and occurs in 1/100,000 of the general population worldwide. The most common presentation is with ascites, but can range from fulminant hepatic failure (FHF) to asymptomatic forms. Obstruction of hepatic venous outflow is mainly caused by primary intravascular thrombosis, which can occur suddenly or be repeated over time, accompanied by some revascularization, accounting for the variable parenchymal hepatic damage and histologic presentation. Budd-Chiari syndrome is thus a disease, but since it occurs as a manifestation of several other diseases, this term is kept for the present for convenience.

HP:0002640.name: Hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma
HP:0002640.definition: A type of hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma.

HP:0002642.name: Arteriovenous fistulas of celiac and mesenteric vessels

HP:0002644.name: Abnormal pelvic girdle bone morphology
HP:0002644.definition: An abnormality of the bony pelvic girdle, which is a ring of bones connecting the vertebral column to the femurs.

HP:0002645.name: Wormian bones
HP:0002645.definition: The presence of extra bones within a cranial suture. Wormian bones are irregular isolated bones which appear in addition to the usual centers of ossification of the cranium.

HP:0002647.name: Aortic dissection
HP:0002647.definition: Aortic dissection refers to a tear in the intimal layer of the aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers of the aorta.

HP:0002650.name: Scoliosis
HP:0002650.definition: The presence of an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine.

HP:0002652.name: Skeletal dysplasia
HP:0002652.definition: A general term describing features characterized by abnormal development of bones and connective tissues.

HP:0002653.name: Bone pain
HP:0002653.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to bone.

HP:0002655.name: Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia
HP:0002655.definition: A disorder of bone growth affecting the vertebrae and the ends of the long bones (epiphyses).

HP:0002659.name: Increased susceptibility to fractures
HP:0002659.definition: An abnormally increased tendency to fractures of bones caused by an abnormal reduction in bone strength that is generally associated with an increased risk of fracture.

HP:0002661.name: Painless fractures due to injury
HP:0002661.definition: An increased tendency to fractures following trauma, with fractures occurring without pain.

HP:0002664.name: Neoplasm
HP:0002664.definition: An organ or organ-system abnormality that consists of uncontrolled autonomous cell-proliferation which can occur in any part of the body as a benign or malignant neoplasm (tumor).

HP:0002665.name: Lymphoma
HP:0002665.definition: A cancer originating in lymphocytes and presenting as a solid tumor of lymhpoid cells.

HP:0002666.name: Pheochromocytoma
HP:0002666.definition: Pheochromocytomas (also known as chromaffin tumors) produce, store, and secrete catecholamines. Pheochromocytomas usually originate from the adrenal medulla but may also develop from chromaffin cells in or about sympathetic ganglia. A common symptom of pheochromocytoma is hypertension owing to release of catecholamines.

HP:0002667.name: Nephroblastoma
HP:0002667.definition: The presence of a nephroblastoma, which is a neoplasm of the kidney that primarily affects children.

HP:0002668.name: Paraganglioma
HP:0002668.definition: A carotid body tumor (also called paraganglionoma or chemodectoma) is a tumor found in the upper neck at the branching of the carotid artery. They arise from the chemoreceptor organ (paraganglion) located in the adventitia of the carotid artery bifurcation.

HP:0002669.name: Osteosarcoma
HP:0002669.definition: A malignant bone tumor that usually develops during adolescence and usually affects the long bones including the tibia, femur, and humerus. The typical symptoms of osteosarcoma comprise bone pain, fracture, limitation of motion, and tenderness or swelling at the site of the tumor.

HP:0002671.name: Basal cell carcinoma
HP:0002671.definition: The presence of a basal cell carcinoma of the skin.

HP:0002673.name: Coxa valga
HP:0002673.definition: Coxa valga is a deformity of the hip in which the angle between the femoral shaft and the femoral neck is increased compared to age-adjusted values (about 150 degrees in newborns gradually reducing to 120-130 degrees in adults).

HP:0002676.name: Cloverleaf skull
HP:0002676.definition: Trilobar skull configuration when viewed from the front or behind.

HP:0002677.name: Small foramen magnum
HP:0002677.definition: An abnormal narrowing of the foramen magnum.

HP:0002679.name: Abnormal sella turcica morphology
HP:0002679.definition: Abnormality of the sella turcica, a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone at the base of the human skull.

HP:0002680.name: J-shaped sella turcica
HP:0002680.definition: A deformity of the sella turcica whereby the sella extends further anterior than normal such that the anterior clinoid process appears to overhang it, giving the appearance of the letter J on imaging of the skull.

HP:0002683.name: Abnormal calvaria morphology
HP:0002683.definition: Abnormality of the morphology (structure) of the calvaria (skullcap), that is, of that part of the skull that is made up of the superior portions of the frontal bone, occipital bone, and parietal bones and covers the cranial cavity that contains the brain.

HP:0002684.name: Thickened calvaria
HP:0002684.definition: The presence of an abnormally thick calvaria.

HP:0002686.name: Pregnancy history
HP:0002686.definition: Medical history of maternal diseases, exposures, or other relevant findings during the pregnancy of which the index person was the product.

HP:0002687.name: Abnormality of frontal sinus
HP:0002687.definition: An abnormality of the frontal sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The frontal sinus is located within the frontal bone.

HP:0002690.name: Large sella turcica
HP:0002690.definition: An abnormal enlargement of the sella turcica.

HP:0002691.name: Platybasia
HP:0002691.definition: A developmental malformation of the occipital bone and upper end of the cervical spine, in which the latter appears to have pushed the floor of the occipital bone upward such that there is an abnormal flattening of the skull base.

HP:0002693.name: Abnormal skull base morphology
HP:0002693.definition: An abnormality of the base of the skull, which forms the floor of the cranial cavity and separates the brain from other facial structures. The skull base is made up of five bones: the ethmoid, sphenoid, occipital, paired frontal, and paired parietal bones, and is subdivided into 3 regions: the anterior, middle, and posterior cranial fossae. The petro-occipital fissure subdivides the middle cranial fossa into 1 central component and 2 lateral components.

HP:0002694.name: Sclerosis of skull base
HP:0002694.definition: Increased bone density of the skull base without significant changes in bony contour.

HP:0002695.name: obsolete Symmetrical, oval parietal bone defects

HP:0002696.name: Abnormal parietal bone morphology
HP:0002696.definition: Any abnormality of the parietal bone of the skull.

HP:0002697.name: Parietal foramina
HP:0002697.definition: The presence of symmetrical and circular openings (foramina) in the parietal bone ranging in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters wide.

HP:0002699.name: Abnormal foramen magnum morphology
HP:0002699.definition: Any abnormality of the foramen magnum.

HP:0002700.name: Large foramen magnum
HP:0002700.definition: An abnormal increase in the size of the foramen magnum.

HP:0002703.name: Abnormality of skull ossification
HP:0002703.definition: An abnormality of the process of ossification of the skull.

HP:0002705.name: High, narrow palate
HP:0002705.definition: The presence of a high and narrow palate.

HP:0002707.name: Palate telangiectasia
HP:0002707.definition: The presence of small (ca. 0.5-1.0 mm) dilated blood vessels near the surface of the mucous membranes of the palate.

HP:0002708.name: Prominent median palatal raphe
HP:0002708.definition: Unusual prominence of the median palatal raphe, which is the ridge formed by the fusion of the two plates of the skull that form the hard palate.

HP:0002710.name: Commissural lip pit
HP:0002710.definition: A depression located at an oral commissure.

HP:0002711.name: Exaggerated median tongue furrow
HP:0002711.definition: Increased depth of the median tongue furrow.

HP:0002714.name: Downturned corners of mouth
HP:0002714.definition: A morphological abnormality of the mouth in which the angle of the mouth is downturned. The oral commissures are positioned inferior to the midline labial fissure.

HP:0002715.name: Abnormality of the immune system
HP:0002715.definition: An abnormality of the immune system.

HP:0002718.name: Recurrent bacterial infections
HP:0002718.definition: Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of bacterial infection.

HP:0002721.name: Immunodeficiency
HP:0002721.definition: Failure of the immune system to protect the body adequately from infection, due to the absence or insufficiency of some component process or substance.

HP:0002722.name: Recurrent abscess formation
HP:0002722.definition: An increased susceptibility to abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent abscesses.

HP:0002723.name: Absence of bactericidal oxidative respiratory burst in phagocytes
HP:0002723.definition: An absence of the phase of elevated metabolic activity, during which oxygen consumption increases, that occurs in neutrophils, monocytes, and macrophages shortly after phagocytosing material. An enhanced uptake of oxygen leads to the production, by an NADH dependent system, of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), superoxide anions and hydroxyl radicals, which play a part in microbiocidal activity.

HP:0002724.name: Recurrent Aspergillus infections
HP:0002724.definition: An increased susceptibility to Aspergillus infections, as manifested by a history of recurrent episodes of Aspergillus infections.

HP:0002725.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus
HP:0002725.definition: A chronic, relapsing, inflammatory, and often febrile multisystemic disorder of connective tissue, characterized principally by involvement of the skin, joints, kidneys, and serosal membranes.

HP:0002726.name: Recurrent Staphylococcus aureus infections
HP:0002726.definition: Increased susceptibility to Staphylococcus aureus infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Staphylococcus aureus infection.

HP:0002728.name: Chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis
HP:0002728.definition: Recurrent or persistent superficial Candida infections of the skin, mucous membranes, and nails.

HP:0002729.name: Follicular hyperplasia
HP:0002729.definition: Lymphadenopathy (enlargement of lymph nodes) owing to hyperplasia of follicular (germinal) centers.

HP:0002730.name: Chronic noninfectious lymphadenopathy
HP:0002730.definition: A chronic form of lymphadenopathy that is not related to infection.

HP:0002731.name: Decreased T cell apoptosis
HP:0002731.definition: Abnormal decrease of apoptosis by peripheral blood T cells in an in vitro culture, compared to a healthy control sample. May be either spontaneous, induced by UV, X-ray, FasL or other agens. Commonly measured by surface expression of phosphatidyl serine labelled by Annexin V, but other methods such as staning of cleaved Caspases may be used by different laboratories.

HP:0002740.name: Recurrent E. coli infections
HP:0002740.definition: Increased susceptibility to infections with Escherichia coli, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection with this agent.

HP:0002741.name: Recurrent Serratia marcescens infections
HP:0002741.definition: Increased susceptibility to Serratia marcescens infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Serratia marcescens infection.

HP:0002742.name: Recurrent Klebsiella infections
HP:0002742.definition: Increased susceptibility to Klebsiella infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Klebsiella infection.

HP:0002743.name: Recurrent enteroviral infections
HP:0002743.definition: Increased susceptibility to enteroviral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of enteroviral infection.

HP:0002744.name: obsolete Bilateral cleft lip and palate

HP:0002745.name: Oral leukoplakia
HP:0002745.definition: A thickened white patch on the oral mucosa that cannot be rubbed off.

HP:0002747.name: Respiratory insufficiency due to muscle weakness

HP:0002748.name: Rickets
HP:0002748.definition: Rickets is divided into two major categories including calcipenic and phosphopenic. Hypophosphatemia is described as a common manifestation of both categories. Hypophosphatemic rickets is the most common type of rickets that is characterized by low levels of serum phosphate, resistance to ultraviolet radiation or vitamin D intake. There are several issues involved in hypophosphatemic rickets such as calcium, vitamin D, phosphorus deficiencies. Moreover, other disorder can be associated with its occurrence such as absorption defects due to pancreatic, intestinal, gastric, and renal disorders and hepatobiliary disease. Symptoms are usually seen in childhood and can be varied in severity. Severe forms may be linked to bowing of the legs, poor bone growth, and short stature as well as joint and bone pain. Hypophosphatemic rickets are associated with renal excretion of phosphate, hypophosphatemia, and mineral defects in bones. The familial type of the disease is the most common type of rickets.

HP:0002749.name: Osteomalacia
HP:0002749.definition: Osteomalacia is a general term for bone weakness owing to a defect in mineralization of the protein framework known as osteoid. This defective mineralization is mainly caused by lack in vitamin D. Osteomalacia in children is known as rickets.

HP:0002750.name: Delayed skeletal maturation
HP:0002750.definition: A decreased rate of skeletal maturation. Delayed skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body.

HP:0002751.name: Kyphoscoliosis
HP:0002751.definition: An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane.

HP:0002753.name: Thin bony cortex
HP:0002753.definition: Abnormal thinning of the cortical region of bones.

HP:0002754.name: Osteomyelitis
HP:0002754.definition: Osteomyelitis is an inflammatory process accompanied by bone destruction and caused by an infecting microorganism.

HP:0002756.name: Pathologic fracture
HP:0002756.definition: A pathologic fracture occurs when a bone breaks in an area that is weakened secondarily to another disease process such as tumor, infection, and certain inherited bone disorders. A pathologic fracture can occur without a degree of trauma required to cause fracture in healthy bone.

HP:0002757.name: Recurrent fractures
HP:0002757.definition: The repeated occurrence of bone fractures (implying an abnormally increased tendency for fracture).

HP:0002758.name: Osteoarthritis
HP:0002758.definition: Degeneration (wear and tear) of articular cartilage, i.e., of the joint surface. Joint degeneration may be accompanied by osteophytes (bone overgrowth), narrowing of the joint space, regions of sclerosis at the joint surface, or joint deformity.

HP:0002761.name: Generalized joint hypermobility
HP:0002761.definition: Joint hypermobility (ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion) affecting many or all joints of the body. In individuals with Joint hypermobility at multiple sites (usually five or more), the term generalized joint hypermobility is preferred.

HP:0002762.name: Multiple exostoses
HP:0002762.definition: Presence of more than one exostosis. An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.

HP:0002764.name: Stippled chondral calcification
HP:0002764.definition: Punctate (speckled, dot-like) deposition of calcium of calcium salts in the articular cartilage (cartilage located in joints).

HP:0002778.name: Abnormal tracheal morphology
HP:0002778.definition: A structural anomaly of the trachea.

HP:0002780.name: Bronchomalacia
HP:0002780.definition: Weakness or softness of the cartilage in the walls of the bronchial tubes.

HP:0002781.name: Upper airway obstruction
HP:0002781.definition: Increased resistance to the passage of air in the upper airway.

HP:0002783.name: Recurrent lower respiratory tract infections
HP:0002783.definition: An increased susceptibility to lower respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent lower respiratory tract infections.

HP:0002786.name: Tracheobronchomalacia
HP:0002786.definition: Weakness of the cartilage in the trachea and the bronchi, resulting in a floppy (non-rigid) airway. Affected persons may have difficulties to maintain patency of the airways.

HP:0002787.name: Tracheal calcification
HP:0002787.definition: Calcification (abnormal deposits of calcium) in the tracheal tissues.

HP:0002788.name: Recurrent upper respiratory tract infections
HP:0002788.definition: An increased susceptibility to upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent upper respiratory tract infections (running ears - otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).

HP:0002791.name: Hypoventilation
HP:0002791.definition: A reduction in the amount of air transported into the pulmonary alveoli by breathing, leading to hypercapnia (increase in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide).

HP:0002792.name: Reduced vital capacity
HP:0002792.definition: An abnormal reduction on the vital capacity, which is defined as the total lung capacity (volume of air in the lungs at maximal inflation) less the residual volume (i.e., volume of air in the lungs following maximal exhalation) of the lung.

HP:0002793.name: Abnormal pattern of respiration
HP:0002793.definition: An anomaly of the rhythm or depth of breathing.

HP:0002795.name: Abnormal respiratory system physiology
HP:0002795.definition: Abnormal function of the respiratory system.

HP:0002797.name: Osteolysis
HP:0002797.definition: Osteolysis refers to the destruction of bone through bone resorption with removal or loss of calcium.

HP:0002803.name: Congenital contracture
HP:0002803.definition: One or more flexion contractures (a bent joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively) that are present at birth.

HP:0002804.name: Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita
HP:0002804.definition: Multiple congenital contractures in different body areas.

HP:0002808.name: Kyphosis
HP:0002808.definition: Exaggerated anterior convexity of the thoracic vertebral column.

HP:0002812.name: Coxa vara
HP:0002812.definition: Coxa vara includes all forms of decrease of the femoral neck shaft angle (the angle between the neck and the shaft of the femur) to less than 120 degrees.

HP:0002813.name: Abnormal limb bone morphology
HP:0002813.definition: Any abnormality of bones of the arms or legs.

HP:0002815.name: Abnormality of the knee
HP:0002815.definition: An abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.

HP:0002816.name: Genu recurvatum
HP:0002816.definition: An abnormally increased extension of the knee joint, so that the knee can bend backwards.

HP:0002823.name: Abnormal femur morphology
HP:0002823.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the femur.

HP:0002825.name: Caudal appendage
HP:0002825.definition: The presence of a tail-like skin appendage located adjacent to the sacrum.

HP:0002826.name: Halberd-shaped pelvis
HP:0002826.definition: An anomalous radiographic appearance of the developing pelvis, in which the greater ischiadic noth (incisura ischiadica major) is shallow and the pelvis takes on the appearance said to resemble a halberd (a weapon especially of the 15th and 16th centuries consisting typically of a battle-ax and pike mounted on a handle).

HP:0002827.name: Hip dislocation
HP:0002827.definition: Displacement of the femur from its normal location in the hip joint.

HP:0002832.name: Calcific stippling
HP:0002832.definition: An abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) pattern of calcifications in soft tissues within or surrounding bones (as observed on radiographs).

HP:0002833.name: Cystic angiomatosis of bone
HP:0002833.definition: Disseminated multifocal hemangiomatous or lymphangiomatous lesions of the skeleton. The lesions are lytic, well-defined, round or oval lesions within the medullary cavity, and they have an intact cortex, and manifest variable peripheral sclerosis and may exhibit endosteal scalloping.

HP:0002835.name: Aspiration
HP:0002835.definition: Inspiration of a foreign object into the airway.

HP:0002836.name: Bladder exstrophy
HP:0002836.definition: Eversion of the posterior bladder wall through the congenitally absent lower anterior abdominal wall and anterior bladder wall.

HP:0002837.name: Recurrent bronchitis
HP:0002837.definition: An increased susceptibility to bronchitis as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchitis.

HP:0002839.name: Urinary bladder sphincter dysfunction
HP:0002839.definition: Abnormal function of a sphincter of the urinary bladder.

HP:0002841.name: Recurrent fungal infections
HP:0002841.definition: Increased susceptibility to fungal infections, as manifested by multiple episodes of fungal infection.

HP:0002842.name: Recurrent Burkholderia cepacia infections
HP:0002842.definition: Increased susceptibility to infections with Burkholderia cepacia, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection with this agent.

HP:0002843.name: Abnormal T cell morphology
HP:0002843.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of total or subset T cell count. T cells are commonly characterized as CD3+ lymphocytes, or their subpopulations, in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group, measured ex vivo. These may include both TCR alpha/beta and gamma/delta T cells.

HP:0002845.name: obsolete Increased proportion of peripheral CD3+ T cells

HP:0002846.name: Abnormal B cell morphology
HP:0002846.definition: A structural abnormality of B cells.

HP:0002847.name: Impaired memory B cell generation
HP:0002847.definition: Impaired production of memory cells, the B cells that persist for years or an entire lifetime and which confer rapid and enhanced response to secondary challenge.

HP:0002848.name: Decreased specific anti-polysaccharide antibody level
HP:0002848.definition: The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against bacterial polysaccharides.

HP:0002849.name: Absence of lymph node germinal center
HP:0002849.definition: Absence of germinal centers in lymph nodes. Germinal centers are the parts of lymph nodes in which B lymphocytes proliferate, differentiate, mutate through somatic hypermutation and class switch during antibody responses.

HP:0002850.name: Decreased circulating total IgM
HP:0002850.definition: An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) in blood.

HP:0002851.name: Elevated double-negative T cell proportion
HP:0002851.definition: Abnormal increase of double negative (DN) CD3+CD4-CD8- T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0002853.name: Increased HLA DR+ CD4+ T cell proportion
HP:0002853.definition: Abnormal increase of the activated HLA-DR+ CD4+ T cell subpopulation, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0002857.name: Genu valgum
HP:0002857.definition: The legs angle inward, such that the knees are close together and the ankles far apart.

HP:0002858.name: Meningioma
HP:0002858.definition: The presence of a meningioma, i.e., a benign tumor originating from the dura mater or arachnoid mater.

HP:0002860.name: Squamous cell carcinoma
HP:0002860.definition: The presence of squamous cell carcinoma of the skin.

HP:0002861.name: Melanoma
HP:0002861.definition: The presence of a melanoma, a malignant cancer originating from pigment producing melanocytes. Melanoma can originate from the skin or the pigmented layers of the eye (the uvea).

HP:0002862.name: Bladder carcinoma
HP:0002862.definition: The presence of a carcinoma of the urinary bladder.

HP:0002863.name: Myelodysplasia
HP:0002863.definition: Clonal hematopoietic stem cell disorders characterized by dysplasia (ineffective production) in one or more hematopoietic cell lineages, leading to anemia and cytopenia.

HP:0002865.name: Medullary thyroid carcinoma
HP:0002865.definition: The presence of a medullary carcinoma of the thyroid gland.

HP:0002867.name: Abnormal ilium morphology
HP:0002867.definition: An abnormality of the ilium, the largest and uppermost bone of the pelvis.

HP:0002868.name: Narrow iliac wing
HP:0002868.definition: Decreased width of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally).

HP:0002869.name: Flared iliac wing
HP:0002869.definition: Widening of the ilium ala, that is of the wing of the ilium, combined with external rotation, leading to a flared appearance of the iliac wing.

HP:0002870.name: Obstructive sleep apnea
HP:0002870.definition: Obstructive Sleep Apnea is a condition characterized by the obstruction of the airway and pauses in breathing during sleep, which occur multiple times throughout the night. It is related to the relaxation of muscle tone that typically happens during sleep, leading to a partial collapse of the soft tissues in the airway and causing airflow obstruction.

HP:0002871.name: Central apnea
HP:0002871.definition: Apnea resulting from depression of the respiratory centers in the medulla oblongata. There is a lack of respiratory effort rather than obstruction of airflow.

HP:0002872.name: Apneic episodes precipitated by illness, fatigue, stress
HP:0002872.definition: Recurrent episodes of apnea that are precipitated by factors such as illness, fatigue, or stress.

HP:0002875.name: Exertional dyspnea
HP:0002875.definition: Perceived difficulty to breathe that occurs with exercise or exertion and improves with rest.

HP:0002877.name: Nocturnal hypoventilation
HP:0002877.definition: An abnormal reduction in alveolar ventilation occurring during sleep. This is characterized by a rise in arterial carbon dioxide.

HP:0002878.name: Respiratory failure
HP:0002878.definition: A severe form of respiratory insufficiency characterized by inadequate gas exchange such that the levels of oxygen or carbon dioxide cannot be maintained within normal limits.

HP:0002879.name: Anisospondyly
HP:0002879.definition: Abnormally increased variability of the size of the vertebral bodies.

HP:0002882.name: Sudden episodic apnea
HP:0002882.definition: Recurrent bouts of sudden, severe apnea that may be life-threatening.

HP:0002883.name: Hyperventilation
