HP:0005227.definition: Presence of multiple adenomatous polyps in the colon.

HP:0005232.name: Pancreatic dysplasia
HP:0005232.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the pancreas.

HP:0005233.name: Hypoplasia of the gallbladder
HP:0005233.definition: The presence of a hypoplastic gallbladder.

HP:0005235.name: Jejunal atresia
HP:0005235.definition: A developmental defect resulting in abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the jejunum.

HP:0005236.name: Chronic calcifying pancreatitis
HP:0005236.definition: A form of chronic pancreatitis that is characterized by calcification.

HP:0005237.name: Degenerative liver disease
HP:0005237.definition: The presence of degenerative changes of the liver.

HP:0005241.name: Total intestinal aganglionosis
HP:0005241.definition: A congenital defect characterized by the lack of ganglion cells in the entire intestine, i.e., the aganglionic segment comprises the entire large and small bowel.

HP:0005242.name: Extrahepatic biliary duct atresia
HP:0005242.definition: Atresia in the extrahepatic bile duct.

HP:0005243.name: Partial abdominal muscle agenesis
HP:0005243.definition: Failure to form of portions of the abdominal musculature.

HP:0005246.name: Giant hypertrophic gastritis
HP:0005246.definition: A type of gastritis characterized by excessive proliferation of the gastric mucosa and diffuse thickening of the gastric mucosal folds.

HP:0005247.name: Hypoplasia of the abdominal wall musculature

HP:0005248.name: Intrahepatic biliary atresia
HP:0005248.definition: Atresia in the intrahepatic bile duct.

HP:0009389.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the 5th finger
HP:0009389.definition: A secondary ossification center in the fifth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009390.name: Small epiphyses of the 5th finger
HP:0009390.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009391.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 5th finger
HP:0009391.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 5th finger.

HP:0009392.name: Triangular epiphyses of the 5th finger
HP:0009392.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 5th finger of the hand.

HP:0002894.name: Neoplasm of the pancreas
HP:0002894.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the pancreas.

HP:0002895.name: Papillary thyroid carcinoma
HP:0002895.definition: The presence of a papillary adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland.

HP:0002896.name: Neoplasm of the liver
HP:0002896.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the liver.

HP:0002897.name: Parathyroid adenoma
HP:0002897.definition: A benign tumor of the parathyroid gland that can cause hyperparathyroidism.

HP:0002900.name: Hypokalemia
HP:0002900.definition: An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood.

HP:0002901.name: Hypocalcemia
HP:0002901.definition: An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the blood.

HP:0002902.name: Hyponatremia
HP:0002902.definition: An abnormally decreased sodium concentration in the blood.

HP:0002904.name: Hyperbilirubinemia
HP:0002904.definition: An increased amount of bilirubin in the blood.

HP:0002905.name: Hyperphosphatemia
HP:0002905.definition: An abnormally increased phosphate concentration in the blood.

HP:0002907.name: Microscopic hematuria
HP:0002907.definition: Microscopic hematuria detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine.

HP:0002909.name: Generalized aminoaciduria
HP:0002909.definition: An increased concentration of all types of amino acid in the urine.

HP:0002910.name: Elevated circulating hepatic transaminase concentration
HP:0002910.definition: Elevations of the levels of SGOT and SGPT in the serum. SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) are transaminases primarily found in the liver and heart and are released into the bloodstream as the result of liver or heart damage. SGOT and SGPT are used clinically mainly as markers of liver damage.

HP:0002912.name: Methylmalonic acidemia
HP:0002912.definition: Increased concentration of methylmalonic acid in the blood.

HP:0002913.name: Myoglobinuria
HP:0002913.definition: Presence of myoglobin in the urine.

HP:0002914.name: Hyperchloriduria
HP:0002914.definition: An increased concentration of chloride in the urine.

HP:0002917.name: Hypomagnesemia
HP:0002917.definition: An abnormally decreased magnesium concentration in the blood.

HP:0002918.name: Hypermagnesemia
HP:0002918.definition: An abnormally increased magnesium concentration in the blood.

HP:0002919.name: Ketonuria
HP:0002919.definition: High levels of ketone bodies (acetoacetic acid, beta-hydroxybutyric acid, and acetone) in the urine. Ketone bodies are insignificant in the blood and urine of normal individuals in the postprandial or overnight-fasted state.

HP:0002920.name: Decreased circulating ACTH concentration
HP:0002920.definition: The concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), is below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.

HP:0002921.name: Abnormal cerebrospinal fluid morphology
HP:0002921.definition: An abnormality of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0002922.name: Increased CSF protein concentration
HP:0002922.definition: Increased concentration of protein in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0002923.name: Rheumatoid factor positive
HP:0002923.definition: The presence in the serum of an autoantibody directed against the Fc portion of IgG.

HP:0002925.name: Elevated circulating thyroid-stimulating hormone concentration
HP:0002925.definition: Increased concentration of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) in the blood circulation.

HP:0002926.name: Abnormality of thyroid physiology
HP:0002926.definition: An abnormal functionality of the thyroid gland.

HP:0002927.name: Histidinuria
HP:0002927.definition: An increased concentration of histidine in the urine.

HP:0002928.name: Decreased activity of the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex

HP:0002930.name: Impaired sensitivity to thyroid hormone
HP:0002930.definition: Reduced sensitivity of end organs to thyroid hormone characterized by elevated serum levels of free thyroid hormone with nonsuppressed thyroid stimulating hormone.

HP:0002932.name: Aldehyde oxidase deficiency
HP:0002932.definition: A reduction in aldehyde oxidase level.

HP:0002933.name: Ventral hernia
HP:0002933.definition: Ventral hernia refers to a condition in which abdominal contents protrude through a weakened portion of the abdominal wall.

HP:0002936.name: Distal sensory impairment
HP:0002936.definition: An abnormal reduction in sensation in the distal portions of the extremities.

HP:0002937.name: Hemivertebrae
HP:0002937.definition: Absence of one half of the vertebral body.

HP:0002938.name: Lumbar hyperlordosis
HP:0002938.definition: An abnormal accentuation of the inward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region.

HP:0002942.name: Thoracic kyphosis
HP:0002942.definition: Over curvature of the thoracic region, leading to a round back or if sever to a hump.

HP:0002945.name: Intervertebral space narrowing
HP:0002945.definition: Decreased height of the intervertebral disk.

HP:0002947.name: Cervical kyphosis
HP:0002947.definition: Exaggerated convexity of the cervical vertebral column, causing the cervical spine to bow outwards and take on a rounded appearance.

HP:0002948.name: Vertebral fusion
HP:0002948.definition: A developmental defect leading to the union of two adjacent vertebrae.

HP:0002949.name: Fused cervical vertebrae
HP:0002949.definition: A congenital anomaly characterized by a joining (fusion) of two or more cervical vertebral bodies with one another.

HP:0002951.name: Partial absence of cerebellar vermis
HP:0002951.definition: Congenital absence of a part of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0002955.name: Granulomatosis
HP:0002955.definition: A granulomatous inflammation leading to multiple granuloma formation, which is a specific type of inflammation. A granuloma is a focal compact collection of inflammatory cells, mononuclear cells predominating, usually as a result of the persistence of a non-degradable product and of active cell mediated hypersensitivity.

HP:0002958.name: Immune dysregulation
HP:0002958.definition: Altered immune function characterized by lymphoid proliferation, immune activation, and excessive autoreactivity often leading to autoimmune/inflammatory complications.

HP:0002959.name: Impaired Ig class switch recombination
HP:0002959.definition: An impairment of the class-switch recombination process that normally leads B lymphocytes to produce IgG, IgA, or IgE.

HP:0002960.name: Autoimmunity
HP:0002960.definition: The occurrence of an immune reaction against the organism's own cells or tissues.

HP:0002961.name: Dysgammaglobulinemia
HP:0002961.definition: Selective deficiency of one or more, but not all, classes of immunoglobulins.

HP:0002963.name: Abnormal delayed hypersensitivity skin test
HP:0002963.definition: Delay in cutaneous immune reaction to specific antigens mediated not by antibodies but by cells. The delayed hypersensitivity test is an immune function test measuring the presence of activated T cells that recognize a specific antigen and is performed by injecting a small amount of the antigen into the skin. The area of the injection is examined 48-72 hours thereafter.

HP:0002965.name: Cutaneous anergy
HP:0002965.definition: Inability to react to a delayed hypersensitivity skin test.

HP:0002967.name: Cubitus valgus
HP:0002967.definition: Abnormal positioning in which the elbows are turned out.

HP:0002970.name: Genu varum
HP:0002970.definition: A positional abnormality marked by outward bowing of the legs in which the knees stay wide apart when a person stands with the feet and ankles together.

HP:0002971.name: Absent microvilli on the surface of peripheral blood lymphocytes
HP:0002971.definition: Absence of the fingerlike protrusive, actin-dependent structures found on the surface of peripheral blood lymphocytes.

HP:0002972.name: Reduced delayed hypersensitivity
HP:0002972.definition: Decreased ability to react to a delayed hypersensitivity skin test.

HP:0002973.name: Abnormal forearm morphology
HP:0002973.definition: An abnormality of the lower arm.

HP:0002974.name: Radioulnar synostosis
HP:0002974.definition: An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the radius and the ulna.

HP:0002977.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the central nervous system
HP:0002977.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of tissue in the central nervous system.

HP:0002979.name: Bowing of the legs
HP:0002979.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature affecting a long bone of the leg.

HP:0002981.name: Abnormality of the calf
HP:0002981.definition: An abnormality of the calf, i.e. of the posterior part of the lower leg.

HP:0002982.name: Tibial bowing
HP:0002982.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature of the tibia.

HP:0002983.name: Micromelia
HP:0002983.definition: The presence of abnormally small extremities.

HP:0002986.name: Radial bowing
HP:0002986.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature of the radius.

HP:0002987.name: Elbow flexion contracture
HP:0002987.definition: An elbow contracture that limits the ability of the elbow joint to be extended (straightened), meaning that the elbow is fixed in an flexed (bent) position.

HP:0002991.name: Abnormal fibula morphology
HP:0002991.definition: An anomaly of the calf bone (fibula), one of the two bones of the calf.

HP:0002999.name: Patellar dislocation
HP:0002999.definition: The kneecap normally is located within the groove termed trochlea on the distal femur and can slide up and down in it. Patellar dislocation occurs if the patella fully dislocates out of the groove.

HP:0003002.name: Breast carcinoma
HP:0003002.definition: The presence of a carcinoma of the breast.

HP:0003005.name: Ganglioneuroma
HP:0003005.definition: A benign neoplasm that usually arises from the sympathetic trunk in the mediastinum, representing a tumor of the sympathetic nerve fibers arising from neural crest cells.

HP:0003006.name: Neuroblastoma
HP:0003006.definition: Neuroblastoma is a solid tumor that originate in neural crest cells of the sympathetic nervous system. Most neuroblastomas originate in the abdomen, and most abdominal neuroblastomas originate in the adrenal gland. Neuroblastomas can also originate in the thorax, usually in the posterior mediastinum.

HP:0003010.name: Prolonged bleeding time
HP:0003010.definition: Prolongation of the time taken for a standardized skin cut of fixed depth and length to stop bleeding.

HP:0003011.name: Abnormality of the musculature
HP:0003011.definition: Abnormality originating in one or more muscles, i.e., of the set of muscles of body.

HP:0003013.name: Bulging epiphyses
HP:0003013.definition: A morphological abnormality of epiphyses whereby they are abnormally outwardly curving (protuberant).

HP:0003015.name: Flared metaphysis
HP:0003015.definition: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of one or more long bones.

HP:0003016.name: Metaphyseal widening
HP:0003016.definition: Abnormal widening of the metaphyseal regions of long bones.

HP:0003019.name: Abnormality of the wrist
HP:0003019.definition: Abnormality of the wrist, the structure connecting the hand and the forearm.

HP:0003021.name: Metaphyseal cupping
HP:0003021.definition: Metaphyseal cupping refers to an inward bulging of the metaphyseal profile giving the metaphysis a cup-like appearance.

HP:0003023.name: Bowing of limbs due to multiple fractures
HP:0003023.definition: Curvature of the shafts of the long bones due to multiple fractures.

HP:0003025.name: Metaphyseal irregularity
HP:0003025.definition: Irregularity of the normally smooth surface of the metaphyses.

HP:0003026.name: Short long bone
HP:0003026.definition: One or more abnormally short long bone.

HP:0003027.name: Mesomelia
HP:0003027.definition: Shortening of the middle parts of the limbs (forearm and lower leg) in relation to the upper and terminal segments.

HP:0003028.name: Abnormality of the ankle
HP:0003028.definition: An anomaly of the joint that connects the foot with the leg.

HP:0003031.name: Ulnar bowing
HP:0003031.definition: Bending of the diaphysis (shaft) of the ulna.

HP:0003034.name: Diaphyseal sclerosis
HP:0003034.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more diaphyses. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0003037.name: Enlarged joints
HP:0003037.definition: Increase in size of one or more joints.

HP:0003041.name: Humeroradial synostosis
HP:0003041.definition: An abnormal osseous union (fusion) between the radius and the humerus.

HP:0003042.name: Elbow dislocation
HP:0003042.definition: Dislocation of the distal humerus out of the elbow joint, where the radius, ulna, and humerus meet.

HP:0003043.name: Abnormal shoulder morphology
HP:0003043.definition: An abnormality of the shoulder, which is defined as the structures surrounding the shoulder joint where the humerus attaches to the scapula.

HP:0003044.name: Shoulder flexion contracture
HP:0003044.definition: Chronic reduction in active and passive mobility of the shoulder joint due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement.

HP:0003048.name: Radial head subluxation
HP:0003048.definition: Partial dislocation of the head of the radius.

HP:0003051.name: Enlarged metaphyses
HP:0003051.definition: Abnormal increase in size of one or more metaphyses.

HP:0003066.name: Limited knee extension
HP:0003066.definition: Reduced ability to extend (straighten) the knee joint.

HP:0003067.name: Madelung deformity
HP:0003067.definition: An anomaly related to partial closure, or failure of development of the ulnar side of the distal radial growth plate, which results in an arrest of epiphyseal growth of the medial and volar portions of the distal radius. This leads to shortening of the radius and relative overgrowth of the ulna.

HP:0003072.name: Hypercalcemia
HP:0003072.definition: An abnormally increased calcium concentration in the blood.

HP:0003073.name: Hypoalbuminemia
HP:0003073.definition: Reduction in the concentration of albumin in the blood.

HP:0003074.name: Hyperglycemia
HP:0003074.definition: An increased concentration of glucose in the blood.

HP:0003075.name: Hypoproteinemia
HP:0003075.definition: A decreased concentration of protein in the blood.

HP:0003076.name: Glycosuria
HP:0003076.definition: An increased concentration of glucose in the urine.

HP:0003077.name: Hyperlipidemia
HP:0003077.definition: An elevated lipid concentration in the blood.

HP:0003079.name: Defective DNA repair after ultraviolet radiation damage

HP:0003080.name: Hydroxyprolinuria
HP:0003080.definition: An increased concentration of 4-hydroxy-L-proline in the urine.

HP:0003081.name: Increased urinary potassium
HP:0003081.definition: An increased concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.

HP:0003083.name: Dislocated radial head
HP:0003083.definition: A dislocation of the head of the radius from its socket in the elbow joint.

HP:0003084.name: Recurrent long bone fractures
HP:0003084.definition: An increased tendency to fractures of the long bones (Mainly, the femur, tibia, fibula, humerus, radius, and ulna).

HP:0003090.name: Hypoplasia of the capital femoral epiphysis
HP:0003090.definition: Underdevelopment of the proximal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:0003091.name: Trophic limb changes
HP:0003091.definition: Trophic changes occurring in a limb.

HP:0003093.name: Limited hip extension
HP:0003093.definition: Limitation of the extension of the hip, i.e., decreased ability to straighten the hip joint and thereby increase the angle between torso and thigh; moving the thigh or top of the pelvis backward.

HP:0003097.name: Short femur
HP:0003097.definition: An abnormal shortening of the femur.

HP:0003099.name: Fibular overgrowth
HP:0003099.definition: Relatively increased growth of the fibula compared to that of the tibia.

HP:0003100.name: Slender long bone
HP:0003100.definition: Reduced diameter of a long bone.

HP:0003102.name: Increased carrying angle
HP:0003102.definition: An abnormal increase in the carrying angle, which is the angle he long axis of the extended forearm as it lies lateral to the long axis of the arm.

HP:0003103.name: Abnormal cortical bone morphology
HP:0003103.definition: An abnormality of compact bone (also known as cortical bone), which forms the dense surface of bones.

HP:0003105.name: Protuberances at ends of long bones
HP:0003105.definition: The presence of multiple protuberances (bulges, or knobs) at the ends of the long bones.

HP:0003106.name: Subperiosteal bone resorption
HP:0003106.definition: Loss of bone mass occurring beneath the periosteum (the periosteum is the connective-tissue membrane that surrounds all bones except at the articular surfaces). This process may create a serrated and lace-like appearance in periosteal cortical bone.

HP:0003107.name: Abnormal circulating cholesterol concentration
HP:0003107.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of cholesterol in the blood circulation.

HP:0003108.name: Hyperglycinuria
HP:0003108.definition: An increased concentration of glycine in the urine.

HP:0003109.name: Hyperphosphaturia
HP:0003109.definition: An increased excretion of phosphates in the urine.

HP:0003110.name: Abnormality of urine homeostasis
HP:0003110.definition: An abnormality of the composition of urine or the levels of its components.

HP:0003111.name: Abnormal blood ion concentration
HP:0003111.definition: Abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of a monoatomic ion.

HP:0003112.name: Abnormal circulating amino acid concentration
HP:0003112.definition: The presence of an abnormal decrease or increase of one or more amino acids in the blood circulation.

HP:0003113.name: Hypochloremia
HP:0003113.definition: An abnormally decreased chloride concentration in the blood.

HP:0003117.name: Abnormal circulating hormone concentration
HP:0003117.definition: Concentration of a hormone in the blood circulation outside of normal limits.

HP:0003118.name: Increased circulating cortisol level
HP:0003118.definition: Overproduction of the hormone of cortisol by the adrenal cortex, resulting in a characteristic combination of clinical symptoms termed Cushing syndrome, with truncal obesity, a round, full face, striae atrophicae and acne, muscle weakness, and other features.

HP:0003119.name: Abnormal circulating lipid concentration
HP:0003119.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a lipid in the blood circulation.

HP:0003121.name: Limb joint contracture
HP:0003121.definition: A contracture (chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin) that prevent normal movement of one or more joints of the limbs.

HP:0003124.name: Hypercholesterolemia
HP:0003124.definition: An increased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0003125.name: Reduced factor VIII activity
HP:0003125.definition: Reduced activity of coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.

HP:0003126.name: Low-molecular-weight proteinuria
HP:0003126.definition: Excretion in urine of proteins of a size smaller than albumin (molecular weight 69 kD).

HP:0003127.name: Hypocalciuria
HP:0003127.definition: An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the urine.

HP:0003128.name: Lactic acidosis
HP:0003128.definition: An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids.

HP:0003130.name: Abnormal peripheral myelination
HP:0003130.definition: An abnormality of the myelination of motor and sensory peripheral nerves. These are axons for motor nerves and dendrites for sensory nerves in the strict anatomic sense.

HP:0003131.name: Cystinuria
HP:0003131.definition: An increased concentration of cystine in the urine.

HP:0003133.name: Abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts
HP:0003133.definition: An abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts, a set of axonal fibers originating in the spinal cord and terminating in the ipsilateral cerebellum. The spinocerebellar tract convey information to the cerebellum about limb and joint position (proprioception). They comprise the ventral spinocerebellar tract, the anterior spinocerebellar tract, and the posterior spinocerebellar tract.

HP:0003134.name: Abnormality of peripheral nerve conduction
HP:0003134.definition: An abnormality of the conduction of electrical impulses by peripheral (motor or sensory) nerves. This finding is elicited by a nerve conduction study (NCS).

HP:0003137.name: Prolinuria
HP:0003137.definition: Level of proline in the urine anove the upper limit of normal.

HP:0003138.name: Increased blood urea nitrogen
HP:0003138.definition: An increased amount of nitrogen in the form of urea in the blood.

HP:0003139.name: Panhypogammaglobulinemia
HP:0003139.definition: A reduction in the circulating levels of all the major classes of immunoglobulin. is characterized by profound decreases in all classes of immunoglobulin with an absence of circulating B lymphocytes.

HP:0003140.name: T-wave inversion in the right precordial leads

HP:0003141.name: Increased LDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0003141.definition: An elevated concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0003144.name: Increased serum serotonin
HP:0003144.definition: A increased concentration of serotonin in the blood.

HP:0003145.name: Decreased circulating adenosylcobalamin concentration
HP:0003145.definition: The concentration of adenosylcobalam in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal. Adenosylcobalamin is one of the active forms of vitamin B12.

HP:0003146.name: Hypocholesterolemia
HP:0003146.definition: An decreased concentration of cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0003149.name: Hyperuricosuria
HP:0003149.definition: An abnormally high level of uric acid in the urine.

HP:0003150.name: Glutaric aciduria
HP:0003150.definition: The concentration of glutaric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0003153.name: Cystathioninuria
HP:0003153.definition: An elevated urinary concentration of cystathionine.

HP:0003154.name: Increased circulating ACTH level
HP:0003154.definition: An abnormal increased in the concentration of corticotropin, also known as adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), in the blood.

HP:0003155.name: Elevated circulating alkaline phosphatase concentration
HP:0003155.definition: Abnormally increased serum levels of alkaline phosphatase activity.

HP:0003158.name: Hyposthenuria
HP:0003158.definition: An abnormally low urinary specific gravity, i.e., reduced concentration of solutes in the urine.

HP:0003159.name: Hyperoxaluria
HP:0003159.definition: Increased excretion of oxalates in the urine.

HP:0003160.name: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin
HP:0003160.definition: Glycosylated transferrin concentrations can be measured in serum as a marker of N-linked glycosylation fidelity. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II. These terms are retained for historical reasons but for new annotations the precise glycosylation defect should be recorded.

HP:0003161.name: 4-Hydroxyphenylpyruvic aciduria
HP:0003161.definition: Increased relative concentration of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid in the urine.

HP:0003163.name: Elevated urinary delta-aminolevulinic acid
HP:0003163.definition: An increased concentration of 5-aminolevulinic acid (CHEBI:17549) in the urine.

HP:0003165.name: Elevated circulating parathyroid hormone level
HP:0003165.definition: An abnormal increased concentration of parathyroid hormone.

HP:0003166.name: Increased urinary taurine
HP:0003166.definition: Increased concentration of taurine in the urine.

HP:0003167.name: Carnosinuria
HP:0003167.definition: An increased concentration of carnosine in the urine.

HP:0003168.name: Dibasicaminoaciduria
HP:0003168.definition: An increased level of a dibasic amino acid in the urine. Dibasic amino acids are usually referred to simply as basic aminoacids because they contain basic side chains at neutral pH. These are arginine (Arg), lysine (Lys), and histidine (His).

HP:0003170.name: Abnormal acetabulum morphology
HP:0003170.definition: An abnormality of the acetabulum, i.e., the Acetabular part of hip bone, which together with the head of the femur forms the hip joint.

HP:0003172.name: Abnormal pubic bone morphology
HP:0003172.definition: An anomaly of the the pubic bone, i.e., of the ventral and anterior of the three principal components (pubis, ilium, ischium) of the hip bone.

HP:0003173.name: Hypoplastic pubic bone
HP:0003173.definition: Underdevelopment of the pubis, which together with the ilium and the ischium, is one of the three bones that make up the hip bone.

HP:0003174.name: Abnormal ischium morphology
HP:0003174.definition: An anomaly of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

HP:0003175.name: Hypoplastic ischia
HP:0003175.definition: Underdevelopment of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

HP:0003177.name: Squared iliac bones
HP:0003177.definition: A shift from the normally round (convex) appearance of the iliac wing towards a square-like appearance.

HP:0003179.name: Protrusio acetabuli
HP:0003179.definition: Intrapelvic bulging of the medial acetabular wall.

HP:0003180.name: Flat acetabular roof
HP:0003180.definition: Flattening of the superior part of the acetabulum, which is a cup-shaped cavity at the base of the hipbone into which the ball-shaped head of the femur fits. The acetabular roof thereby appears horizontal rather than arched, as it normally does.

HP:0003183.name: Wide pubic symphysis
HP:0003183.definition: Abnormally increased width of the pubic symphysis is the midline cartilaginous joint uniting the superior rami of the left and right pubic bones.

HP:0003184.name: Decreased hip abduction
HP:0003184.definition: Reduced ability to move the femur outward to the side.

HP:0003185.name: Short greater sciatic notch
HP:0003185.definition: The sacroiliac joint in the bony pelvis connects the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments. The notch is located directly superior to the joint. This term refers to a reduction in the height of the notch.

HP:0003186.name: Inverted nipples
HP:0003186.definition: The presence of nipples that instead of pointing outward are retracted inwards.

HP:0003189.name: Long nose
HP:0003189.definition: Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased length from the nasal root to the nasal base.

HP:0003191.name: Cleft ala nasi
HP:0003191.definition: The presence of a notch in the margin of the ala nasi.

HP:0003193.name: Allergic rhinitis
HP:0003193.definition: It is characterized by one or more symptoms including sneezing, itching, nasal congestion, and rhinorrhea.

HP:0003194.name: Short nasal bridge
HP:0003194.definition: Decreased superior-inferior length of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose.

HP:0003196.name: Short nose
HP:0003196.definition: Distance from nasion to subnasale more than two standard deviations below the mean, or alternatively, an apparently decreased length from the nasal root to the nasal tip.

HP:0003198.name: Myopathy
HP:0003198.definition: A disorder of muscle unrelated to impairment of innervation or neuromuscular junction.

HP:0003200.name: Ragged-red muscle fibers
HP:0003200.definition: An abnormal appearance of muscle fibers observed on muscle biopsy. Ragged red fibers can be visualized with Gomori trichrome staining as irregular and intensely red subsarcolemmal zones, whereas the normal myofibrils are green. The margins of affect fibers appear red and ragged. The ragged-red is due to the accumulation of abnormal mitochondria below the plasma membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to the appearance of a red rim and speckled sarcoplasm.

HP:0003201.name: Rhabdomyolysis
HP:0003201.definition: Breakdown of muscle fibers that leads to the release of muscle fiber contents (myoglobin) into the bloodstream.

HP:0003202.name: Skeletal muscle atrophy
HP:0003202.definition: The presence of skeletal muscular atrophy (which is also known as amyotrophy).

HP:0003203.name: Decreased neutrophil oxidative burst
HP:0003203.definition: Abnormal decrease of neutrophil oxidative burst, commonly measured through oxidation of dihydrorhodamine (DHR) using flow cytometry or through nitroblue tetrazolium test (NBT) using optical microscopy, upon stimulation with phorbol-12-myristate-13-acetate (PMA), E. coli or other ligands.

HP:0003204.name: Intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
HP:0003204.definition: The intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent storage material.

HP:0003205.name: Curvilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
HP:0003205.definition: An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a curved pattern.

HP:0003207.name: Arterial calcification
HP:0003207.definition: Pathological deposition of calcium salts in one or more arteries.

HP:0003208.name: Fingerprint intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
HP:0003208.definition: An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a trabecular or fingerprint-like pattern.

HP:0003209.name: Decreased pyruvate carboxylase activity
HP:0003209.definition: A decreased rate of pyruvate carboxylase activity.

HP:0003210.name: Decreased methylmalonyl-CoA mutase activity
HP:0003210.definition: An abnormality of Krebs cycle metabolism that is characterized by a decreased rate of methylmalonyl-CoA mutase activity.

HP:0003212.name: Increased circulating IgE concentration
HP:0003212.definition: An abnormally increased overall level of immunoglobulin E in blood.

HP:0003213.name: Deficient excision of UV-induced pyrimidine dimers in DNA

HP:0003214.name: Prolonged G2 phase of cell cycle

HP:0003215.name: Dicarboxylic aciduria
HP:0003215.definition: An increased concentration of dicarboxylic acid in the urine.

HP:0003217.name: Hyperglutaminemia
HP:0003217.definition: An increased concentration of glutamine in the blood.

HP:0003218.name: Oroticaciduria
HP:0003218.definition: An increased concentration of orotic acid in the urine.

HP:0003219.name: Ethylmalonic aciduria
HP:0003219.definition: The concentration of ethylmalonic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0003220.name: Abnormality of chromosome stability
HP:0003220.definition: A type of chromosomal aberration characterized by reduced resistance of chromosomes to change or deterioration.

HP:0003221.name: Chromosomal breakage induced by crosslinking agents
HP:0003221.definition: Increased amount of chromosomal breaks in cultured blood lymphocytes or other cells induced by treatment with DNA cross-linking agents such as diepoxybutane and mitomycin C.

HP:0003223.name: Decreased circulating methylcobalamin concentration
HP:0003223.definition: The concentration of methylcobalamin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal. Methylcobalamin is a form of vitamin B12.

HP:0003224.name: Increased cellular sensitivity to UV light

HP:0003225.name: Reduced coagulation factor V activity
HP:0003225.definition: Decreased activity of coagulation factor V.

HP:0003226.name: Rectilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
HP:0003226.definition: An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a straight or rectilinear pattern.

HP:0003228.name: Hypernatremia
HP:0003228.definition: An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the blood.

HP:0003231.name: Hypertyrosinemia
HP:0003231.definition: An increased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.

HP:0003233.name: Decreased HDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0003233.definition: An decreased concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0003234.name: Decreased circulating carnitine concentration
HP:0003234.definition: Concentration of carnitine in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0003235.name: Hypermethioninemia
HP:0003235.definition: An increased concentration of methionine in the blood.

HP:0003236.name: Elevated circulating creatine kinase concentration
HP:0003236.definition: An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase (CK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy.

HP:0003237.name: Increased circulating IgG concentration
HP:0003237.definition: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin G in blood.

HP:0003239.name: Phosphoethanolaminuria
HP:0003239.definition: An increased level of phosphoethanolamine (synonym: O-phosphoethanolamine) in the urine.

HP:0003240.name: Increased phosphoribosylpyrophosphate synthetase level
HP:0003240.definition: Abnormally elevated level of the enzyme phosphoribosyl pyrophosphatesynthetase, which catalyzes the synthesis of PP-ribose-P from ATP and ribose-5-phosphate.

HP:0003241.name: External genital hypoplasia
HP:0003241.definition: Underdevelopment of part or all of the external reproductive organs.

HP:0003244.name: Penile hypospadias
HP:0003244.definition: Location of the urethral opening on the inferior aspect of the penis.

HP:0003246.name: Prominent scrotal raphe
HP:0003246.definition: Increased size of the ridge of tissue that extends along the midline of the scrotum.

HP:0003248.name: Gonadal tissue inappropriate for external genitalia or chromosomal sex

HP:0003254.name: Abnormality of DNA repair
HP:0003254.definition: An abnormality of the process of DNA repair, that is, of the process of restoring DNA after damage.

HP:0003256.name: Abnormality of the coagulation cascade
HP:0003256.definition: An abnormality of the coagulation cascade, which is comprised of the contact activation pathway (also known as the intrinsic pathway) and the tissue factor pathway (also known as the extrinsic pathway) as well as cofactors and regulators.

HP:0002329.name: Drowsiness
HP:0002329.definition: Abnormal feeling of sleepiness or difficulty staying awake.

HP:0002330.name: Paroxysmal drowsiness
HP:0002330.definition: A neurological disorder marked by a sudden recurrent uncontrollable compulsion to sleep

HP:0002331.name: Recurrent paroxysmal headache
HP:0002331.definition: Repeated episodes of headache with rapid onset, reaching a peak within minutes and of short duration (less than one hour) with pain that is throbbing, pulsating, or bursting in quality.

HP:0002332.name: Lack of peer relationships
HP:0002332.definition: The state of not having relationships with peers outside of school or organized activity appropriate to developmental level. This may be caused by behavioral or physical barriers.

HP:0002333.name: Motor deterioration
HP:0002333.definition: Loss of previously present motor (i.e., movement) abilities.

HP:0002334.name: Abnormal cerebellar vermis morphology
HP:0002334.definition: An anomaly of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0002335.name: Agenesis of cerebellar vermis
HP:0002335.definition: Congenital absence of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0002339.name: Abnormal caudate nucleus morphology
HP:0002339.definition: Any structural abnormality of the caudate nucleus.

HP:0002341.name: Cervical cord compression
HP:0002341.definition: Compression of the spinal cord in the cervical region, generally manifested by paresthesias and numbness, weakness, difficulty walking, abnormalities of coordination, and neck pain or stiffness.

HP:0002342.name: Intellectual disability, moderate
HP:0002342.definition: Moderate mental retardation is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 35-49.

HP:0002343.name: Normal pressure hydrocephalus
HP:0002343.definition: A form of hydrocephalus characterized by enlarged cerebral ventricles and normal cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) pressure upon lumbar puncture.

HP:0002345.name: Action tremor
HP:0002345.definition: A tremor present when the limbs are active, either when outstretched in a certain position or throughout a voluntary movement.

HP:0002346.name: Head tremor
HP:0002346.definition: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting head movement.

HP:0002349.name: Focal aware seizure
HP:0002349.definition: A type of focal-onset seizure in which awareness is preserved. Awareness during a seizure is defined as the patient being fully aware of themself and their environment throughout the seizure, even if immobile.

HP:0002352.name: Leukoencephalopathy
HP:0002352.definition: This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells.

HP:0002353.name: EEG abnormality
HP:0002353.definition: Abnormality observed by electroencephalogram (EEG), which is used to record of the brain's spontaneous electrical activity from multiple electrodes placed on the scalp.

HP:0002354.name: Memory impairment
HP:0002354.definition: An impairment of memory as manifested by a reduced ability to remember things such as dates and names, and increased forgetfulness.

HP:0002356.name: Writer's cramp
HP:0002356.definition: A focal dystonia of the fingers, hand, and/or forearm that appears when the affected person attempts to do a task that requires fine motor movements such as writing or playing a musical instrument.

HP:0002360.name: Sleep abnormality
HP:0002360.definition: An abnormal pattern in the quality, quantity, or characteristics of sleep.

HP:0002361.name: Psychomotor deterioration
HP:0002361.definition: Loss of previously present mental and motor abilities.

HP:0002362.name: Shuffling gait
HP:0002362.definition: A type of gait (walking) characterized by by dragging one's feet along or without lifting the feet fully from the ground.

HP:0002366.name: Abnormal lower motor neuron morphology
HP:0002366.definition: Any structural anomaly of the lower motor neuron.

HP:0002367.name: Visual hallucination
HP:0002367.definition: Visual perception in the absence of a visual stimulus.

HP:0002372.name: Normal interictal EEG
HP:0002372.definition: Lack of observable abnormal electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns in an individual with a history of seizures. About half of individuals with epilepsy show interictal epileptiform discharges upon the first investigation. The yield can be increased by repeated studies, sleep studies, or by ambulatory EEG recordings over 24 hours. Normal interictal EEG is a sign that can be useful in the differential diagnosis.

HP:0002373.name: Febrile seizure (within the age range of 3 months to 6 years)
HP:0002373.definition: A febrile seizure is any type of seizure (most often a generalized tonic-clonic seizure) occurring with fever (at least 38 degrees Celsius) but in the absence of central nervous system infection, severe metabolic disturbance or other alternative precipitant in children between the ages of 3 months and 6 years.

HP:0002375.name: Hypokinesia
HP:0002375.definition: Abnormally diminished motor activity. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.

HP:0002376.name: Developmental regression
HP:0002376.definition: Loss of developmental skills, as manifested by loss of developmental milestones.

HP:0002378.name: Hand tremor
HP:0002378.definition: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the hand.

HP:0002380.name: Fasciculations
HP:0002380.definition: Fasciculations are observed as small, local, involuntary muscle contractions (twitching) visible under the skin. Fasciculations result from increased irritability of an axon (which in turn is often a manifestation of disease of a motor neuron). This leads to sporadic discharges of all the muscle fibers controlled by the axon in isolation from other motor units.

HP:0002381.name: Aphasia
HP:0002381.definition: An acquired language impairment of some or all of the abilities to produce or comprehend speech and to read or write.

HP:0002383.name: Infectious encephalitis
HP:0002383.definition: A disorder of the brain caused by an infectious agent that presents with fever, headache, and an altered level of consciousness. There may also be focal or multifocal neurologic deficits, and focal or generalized seizure activity.

HP:0002384.name: Focal impaired awareness seizure
HP:0002384.definition: Focal impaired awareness seizure (or focal seizure with impaired or lost awareness) is a type of focal-onset seizure characterized by some degree (which may be partial) of impairment of the person's awareness of themselves or their surroundings at any point during the seizure.

HP:0002385.name: Paraparesis
HP:0002385.definition: Weakness or partial paralysis in the lower limbs.

HP:0002389.name: Cavum septum pellucidum
HP:0002389.definition: If the two laminae of the septum pellucidum are not fused then a fluid-filled space or cavum is present. The cavum septum pellucidum is present at birth but usually obliterates by the age of 3 to 6 months. It is up to 1cm in width and the walls are parallel. It is an enclosed space and is not part of the ventricular system or connected with the subarachnoid space.

HP:0002392.name: EEG with polyspike wave complexes
HP:0002392.definition: The presence of complexes of repetitive spikes and waves in EEG.

HP:0002395.name: Lower limb hyperreflexia
HP:0002395.definition: Increased intensity of the a reflex in the leg.

HP:0002396.name: Cogwheel rigidity
HP:0002396.definition: A type of rigidity in which a muscle responds with cogwheellike jerks to the use of constant force in bending the limb (i.e., it gives way in little, repeated jerks when the muscle is passively stretched).

HP:0002401.name: Stroke-like episode
HP:0002401.definition: No consensus exists on what a stroke-like episode is, but these episodes can be functionally defined as a new neurological deficit, occurring with or without the context of seizures, which last longer than 24 hours.

HP:0002403.name: Positive Romberg sign
HP:0002403.definition: The patient stands with the feet placed together and balance and is asked to close his or her eyes. A loss of balance upon eye closure is a positive Romberg sign and is interpreted as indicating a deficit in proprioception.

HP:0002404.name: Thickened superior cerebellar peduncle
HP:0002404.definition: Increased width of the superior cerebellar peduncle.

HP:0002406.name: Limb dysmetria
HP:0002406.definition: A type of dysmetria involving the limbs.

HP:0002408.name: Cerebral arteriovenous malformation
HP:0002408.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the brain.

HP:0002410.name: Aqueductal stenosis
HP:0002410.definition: Stenosis of the cerebral aqueduct (also known as the mesencephalic duct, aqueductus mesencephali, or aqueduct of Sylvius), which connects the third cerebral ventricle in the diencephalon to the fourth ventricle, which is between the pons and cerebellum.

HP:0002411.name: Myokymia
HP:0002411.definition: Myokymia consists of involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions that spread across the affected striated muscle.

HP:0002414.name: Spina bifida
HP:0002414.definition: Incomplete closure of the embryonic neural tube, whereby some vertebral arches remain unfused and open. The mildest form is spina bifida occulta, followed by meningocele and meningomyelocele.

HP:0002415.name: Leukodystrophy
HP:0002415.definition: Leukodystrophy refers to deterioration of white matter of the brain resulting from degeneration of myelin sheaths in the CNS. Their basic defect is directly related to the synthesis and maintenance of myelin membranes. Symmetric white matter involvement at MRI is a typical finding in patients with leukodystrophies.

HP:0002416.name: Subependymal cysts
HP:0002416.definition: Cerebral cysts, usually located in the wall of the caudate nucleus or in the caudothalamic groove. They are found in up to 5.2% of all neonates, using transfontanellar ultrasound in the first days of life.

HP:0002418.name: Abnormal midbrain morphology
HP:0002418.definition: An abnormality of the midbrain, which has as its parts the tectum, cerebral peduncle, midbrain tegmentum and cerebral aqueduct.

HP:0002419.name: Molar tooth sign on MRI
HP:0002419.definition: An abnormal appearance of the midbrain in axial magnetic resonance imaging in which the elongated superior cerebellar peduncles give the midbrain an appearance reminiscent of a molar or wisdom tooth.

HP:0002421.name: Poor head control
HP:0002421.definition: Difficulty to maintain correct position of the head while standing or sitting. Infant head lag is observed when the head seems to flop around or lags posteriorly behind the trunk. Several articles have maintained that head lag should be absent by age 3 to 4 months.

HP:0002423.name: Long-tract sign
HP:0002423.definition: Long-tract signs refer to symptoms that are attributable to the involvement of the long fiber tracts in the spinal cord, which connect the spinal cord to the brain and mediate spinal and motor functions. These include spasticity, hyperreflexia, and abnormal reflexes such as Babinski or Hoffman's sign. If possible, it is preferable to use the precise HPO terms for these abnormalities.

HP:0002425.name: Anarthria
HP:0002425.definition: A defect in the motor ability that enables speech.

HP:0002427.name: Expressive aphasia
HP:0002427.definition: Impairment of expressive language and relative preservation of receptive language abilities. That is, the patient understands language (speech, writing) but cannot express it.

HP:0002435.name: Meningocele
HP:0002435.definition: Protrusion of the meninges through a defect of the skull or vertebral column.

HP:0002436.name: Occipital meningocele
HP:0002436.definition: A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull in the occipital region.

HP:0002442.name: Dyscalculia
HP:0002442.definition: A specific learning disability involving mathematics and arithmetic.

HP:0002444.name: Hypothalamic hamartoma
HP:0002444.definition: The presence of a hamartoma of the hypothalamus.

HP:0002445.name: Tetraplegia
HP:0002445.definition: Paralysis of all four limbs, and trunk of the body below the level of an associated injury to the spinal cord. The etiology of quadriplegia is similar to that of paraplegia except that the lesion is in the cervical spinal cord rather than in the thoracic or lumbar segments of the spinal cord.

HP:0002446.name: Astrocytosis
HP:0002446.definition: Proliferation of astrocytes in the area of a lesion of the central nervous system.

HP:0002450.name: Abnormal motor neuron morphology
HP:0002450.definition: Any structural anomaly that affects the motor neuron.

HP:0002451.name: Limb dystonia
HP:0002451.definition: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the limbs.

HP:0002453.name: Abnormal globus pallidus morphology
HP:0002453.definition: An abnormality of the globus pallidus.

HP:0002454.name: Eye of the tiger anomaly of globus pallidus
HP:0002454.definition: The presence, on T2-weighted magnetic resonance imaging, of markedly low signal intensity of the globus pallidus that surrounds a central region of high signal intensity in the anteromedial globus pallidus, producing an eye-of-the-tiger appearance. The sign is thought to represent iron accumulation in the globus pallidus.

HP:0002460.name: Distal muscle weakness
HP:0002460.definition: Reduced strength of the musculature of the distal extremities.

HP:0002461.name: Cerebellar dentate nucleus calcification
HP:0002461.definition: Pathological deposition of calcium salts in the dentate nucleus of the cerebellum.

HP:0002463.name: Language impairment
HP:0002463.definition: Language impairment is a deficit in comprehension or production of language that includes reduced vocabulary, limited sentence structure, or impairments in written or spoken communication. Language abilities are substantially and quantifiably below age expectations.

HP:0002464.name: Spastic dysarthria
HP:0002464.definition: A type of dysarthria related to bilateral damage of the upper motor neuron tracts of the pyramidal and extra- pyramidal tracts. Speech of affected individuals is slow, effortful, and has a harsh vocal quality.

HP:0002472.name: Small cerebral cortex
HP:0002472.definition: Reduced size of the cerebral cortex.

HP:0002474.name: Expressive language delay
HP:0002474.definition: A delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

HP:0002475.name: Myelomeningocele
HP:0002475.definition: Protrusion of the meninges and portions of the spinal cord through a defect of the vertebral column.

HP:0002476.name: Primitive reflex
HP:0002476.definition: The primitive reflexes are a group of behavioral motor responses which are found in normal early development, are subsequently inhibited, but may be released from inhibition by cerebral, usually frontal, damage. They are thus part of a broader group of reflexes which reflect release phenomena, such as exaggerated stretch reflexes and extensor plantars. They do however involve more complex motor responses than such simple stretch reflexes, and are often a normal feature in the neonate or infant.

HP:0010060.name: Bullet-shaped hallux phalanx
HP:0010060.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010061.name: Curved hallux phalanx
HP:0010061.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the big toe.

HP:0010062.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the hallux

HP:0010063.name: Patchy sclerosis of hallux phalanx
HP:0010063.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more phalanges of the big toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010064.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the hallux

HP:0010065.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the hallux

HP:0010066.name: Duplication of phalanx of hallux
HP:0010066.definition: Partial or complete duplication of one or more phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010067.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010067.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010068.name: Broad first metatarsal
HP:0010068.definition: Increased side-to-side width of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010069.name: Bullet-shaped 1st metatarsal
HP:0010069.definition: An abnormal morphology of the firstmetatarsal bone, which is short and wide and tapers distally, and lacks the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010070.name: Curved 1st metatarsal
HP:0010070.definition: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a proximal phalanx of the 1st metatarsal bone.

HP:0010071.name: Osteolytic defects of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010071.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the first metatarsal.

HP:0010075.name: Duplication of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010075.definition: A developmental defect consisting in the duplication of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010076.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010077.name: Broad distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010077.definition: An increase in width of the distal phalanx of the big toe.

HP:0010078.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010078.definition: An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010079.name: Curved distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010079.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of the distal phalanx of the big toe.

HP:0010080.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010081.name: Patchy sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010082.name: Symphalangism affecting the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010083.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010084.name: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010085.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010086.name: Broad proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010086.definition: Increased width of proximal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010087.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010087.definition: An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the big toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010088.name: Curved proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010088.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the big toe.

HP:0010089.name: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010090.name: Patchy sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010091.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010092.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010093.name: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010093.definition: Partial or complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010094.name: Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010094.definition: Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010095.name: Partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010095.definition: Partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010096.name: Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010097.name: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010098.name: Complete duplication of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010098.definition: A developmental defect consisting in the complete duplication of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010099.name: Partial duplication of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010099.definition: A developmental defect consisting in the duplication of part of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010100.name: Complete duplication of hallux phalanx
HP:0010100.definition: Complete duplication of one or more phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010101.name: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the hallux

HP:0010102.name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010103.name: Short distal phalanx of hallux
HP:0010103.definition: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the distal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010104.name: Absent first metatarsal
HP:0010104.definition: A developmental defect characterized by the absence of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010106.name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010107.name: Short proximal phalanx of hallux
HP:0010107.definition: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010110.name: Aplasia of the phalanges of the hallux

HP:0010111.name: Short phalanx of hallux
HP:0010111.definition: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of a phalanx of big toe.

HP:0010112.name: Mesoaxial foot polydactyly
HP:0010112.definition: The presence of a supernumerary toe (not a hallux) involving the third or fourth metatarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.

HP:0010113.name: Absent hallux epiphysis
HP:0010113.definition: Failure to form (agenesis) of one or more epiphyses of the big toe.

HP:0010117.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the hallux

HP:0010122.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the hallux
HP:0010122.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the hallux.

HP:0010124.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010125.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010125.definition: In contrast to the metatarsals 2-5, the first metatarsal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, whereas the proximal phalanx of the big toe is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits. This term applies to abnormalities of the epiphysis of the first metatarsal bone.

HP:0010126.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010126.definition: In contrast to the metatarsals 2-5, the first metatarsal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, whereas the proximal phalanx of the big toe is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits. This term applies to abnormalities affecting the proximal phalanx of the hallux.

HP:0010127.name: Absent epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010127.definition: Failure to form (agenesis) of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux.

HP:0010128.name: Bracket epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010128.definition: The epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux surrounds the diaphysis, having a bracket-like form.

HP:0010129.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010130.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010131.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010132.name: Irregular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010133.name: Ivory epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010134.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010134.definition: A pseudoepiphysis (an accessory epiphysis that does not significantly contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone) located in the proximal phalanx of the big toe.

HP:0010135.name: Small epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010136.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010136.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the proximal phalanx of the hallux.

HP:0010137.name: Triangular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010138.name: Absent epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010138.definition: Failure to form (agenesis) of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux.

HP:0010139.name: Bracket epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010139.definition: The epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux surrounds the diaphysis, having a bracket-like form.

HP:0010140.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010141.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010142.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010143.name: Irregular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010144.name: Ivory epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010145.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010146.name: Small epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010147.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux
HP:0010147.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of the hallux.

HP:0010148.name: Triangular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0010149.name: Absent epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010149.definition: Failure to form (agenesis) of the epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal.

HP:0010150.name: Bracket epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010150.definition: The epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal surrounds the diaphysis, having a bracket-like form.

HP:0010151.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010151.definition: A conical (cone-shaped) appearance of the epiphysis of the first metatarsal of the foot.

HP:0010153.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal

HP:0010155.name: Ivory epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal
HP:0010155.definition: The epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal appears hard and dense like ivory. An ivory epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0010158.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the 1st metatarsal

HP:0010162.name: Absent epiphyses of the toes
HP:0010162.definition: Absence of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the toes.

HP:0010166.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the toes

HP:0010171.name: Epiphyseal stippling of toe phalanges
HP:0010171.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of phalanges of the toes.

HP:0010173.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the toes

HP:0010174.name: Broad phalanx of the toes
HP:0010174.definition: Increased width of phalanx of one or more toes.

HP:0010175.name: Bullet-shaped toe phalanx
HP:0010175.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010176.name: Curved toe phalanx
HP:0010176.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more toe phalanges.

HP:0010177.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the toes

HP:0010178.name: Patchy sclerosis of toe phalanx
HP:0010178.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the foot.

HP:0010179.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the toes

HP:0010180.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the toes

HP:0010181.name: Duplication of phalanx of toe
HP:0010181.definition: Partial/complete duplication of one or more phalanx of toe.

HP:0010182.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010183.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010184.name: Abnormality of toe proximal phalanx
HP:0010184.definition: A morphological anomaly of one or more proximal phalanges of one or more toes.

HP:0010185.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the toes
HP:0010185.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges of the toes.

HP:0010186.name: Broad distal phalanx of the toes
HP:0010186.definition: Increased width of the distal phalanx of toe of one or more toes.

HP:0010187.name: Bullet-shaped distal toe phalanx
HP:0010187.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more distal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010188.name: Curved distal toe phalanx
HP:0010188.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more distal toe phalanges.

HP:0010189.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010190.name: Patchy sclerosis of distal toe phalanx
HP:0010190.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the distal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010191.name: Symphalangism affecting the distal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010192.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010193.name: Duplication of distal phalanx of toe
HP:0010193.definition: A partial or complete duplication of one or more distal phalanx of toe.

HP:0010194.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010195.name: Broad middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010196.name: Bullet-shaped middle toe phalanx
HP:0010196.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more middle phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010197.name: Curved middle toe phalanx
HP:0010197.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more middle toe phalanges.

HP:0010198.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010199.name: Patchy sclerosis of middle toe phalanx
HP:0010199.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010200.name: Symphalangism affecting the middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010201.name: Triangular shaped middle phalanges of the toes

HP:0010202.name: Duplication of middle phalanx of toe
HP:0010202.definition: Partial or complete duplication of a middle phalanx of toe.

HP:0010203.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of proximal toe phalanx
HP:0010203.definition: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the toe.

HP:0010204.name: Broad proximal phalanx of toe
HP:0010204.definition: An increase in width of one ore more proximal toe phalanges.

HP:0010205.name: Bullet-shaped proximal toe phalanx
HP:0010205.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010206.name: Curved proximal toe phalanx
HP:0010206.definition: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a proximal phalanx of one or more toes.

HP:0010207.name: Osteolytic defect of the proximal toe phalanx
HP:0010207.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal toe phalanx.

HP:0010208.name: Patchy sclerosis of proximal toe phalanx
HP:0010208.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010209.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010210.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanges of the toes

HP:0010211.name: Duplication of proximal phalanx of toe
HP:0010211.definition: Partial/complete duplication of a proximal phalanx of toe.

HP:0000700.name: Periapical bone loss
HP:0000700.definition: Radiolucency (reflecting a reduction in the bony substance) around the apex (the tip of the dental root).

HP:0000705.name: Amelogenesis imperfecta
HP:0000705.definition: A developmental dysplasia of the dental enamel.

HP:0000706.name: Eruption failure
HP:0000706.definition: A tooth which does not erupt within the teeth eruption timeline and after the loss of eruption potential.

HP:0000707.name: Abnormality of the nervous system
HP:0000707.definition: An abnormality of the nervous system.

HP:0000708.name: Atypical behavior
HP:0000708.definition: Atypical behavior is an abnormality in a person's actions that can be controlled or modulated by the will of the individual. While abnormal behaviors can be difficult to control, they are distinct from other abnormal actions that cannot be affected by the individual's will.

HP:0000709.name: Psychosis
HP:0000709.definition: A condition characterized by changes in personality and thought patterns, often accompanied by hallucinations and delusional beliefs, is known as psychosis.

HP:0000710.name: Hyperorality
HP:0000710.definition: Hyperorality is a condition characterized by an excessive preoccupation with oral sensations and behaviors, such as chewing, sucking, biting, swallowing, and excessive mouthing of objects.

HP:0000711.name: Restlessness
HP:0000711.definition: A state of unease is characterized by diffuse motor activity or motion, which is subject to limited control, nonproductive, or disorganized behavior.

HP:0000712.name: Emotional lability
HP:0000712.definition: Unstable emotional experiences and frequent mood changes; emotions that are easily aroused, intense, and/or disproportionate to events and circumstances.

HP:0000713.name: Agitation
HP:0000713.definition: A state of excessive motor activity that is associated with mental distress or a feeling of substantial unease or inner tension. Distinguished from restlessness by the increased level of emotional distress and negative intensity of the experience. Agitation has a significant level of physical activity that is typically threatening to the self or others.

HP:0000716.name: Depression
HP:0000716.definition: Frequently experiencing feelings of being down, miserable, and/or hopeless; struggling to recover from these moods; having a pessimistic outlook on the future; feeling a pervasive sense of shame; having a low self-worth; experiencing thoughts of suicide and engaging in suicidal behavior.

HP:0000717.name: Autism
HP:0000717.definition: Autism is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by impaired social interaction and communication, and by restricted and repetitive behavior. Autism begins in childhood. It is marked by the presence of markedly abnormal or impaired development in social interaction and communication and a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Manifestations of the disorder vary greatly depending on the developmental level and chronological age of the individual (DSM-IV).

HP:0000718.name: Aggressive behavior
HP:0000718.definition: Behavior or an act aimed at harming a person, animal, or physical property (e.g., acts of physical violence; shouting, swearing, and using harsh language; slashing someone's tires).

HP:0000719.name: Inappropriate behavior
HP:0000719.definition: An explicit or perceived action, demonstration, conduct, or language (verbal and written) that is contrary to generally accepted norms, rules, procedures, or unacceptable within the context in which it is carried out. Inappropriate behaviors could take place in a sexual or social context and could be aggressive, violent, impulsive, intimidating, or threatening in nature.

HP:0000722.name: Compulsive behaviors
HP:0000722.definition: Behavior that consists of repetitive acts, characterized by the feeling that one "has to" perform them, while being aware that these acts are not in line with one's overall goal.

HP:0000723.name: Restrictive behavior
HP:0000723.definition: Behavior characterized by an abnormal limitation to a few interests and activities.

HP:0000725.name: Psychotic episodes
HP:0000725.definition: Periods of time during which an individual experiences significant disturbances in their thoughts, perceptions, emotions, and behavior, resulting in a loss of touch with reality. These episodes are hallmark features of psychotic disorders such as schizophrenia, schizoaffective disorder, and certain forms of bipolar disorder.

HP:0000726.name: Dementia
HP:0000726.definition: A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior.

HP:0000728.name: Impaired ability to form peer relationships
HP:0000728.definition: Difficulty to establish relations with others in a comparable social group (peers) that may be manifested in pehnomena such as not being able to initiative a conversation, understand social cues, or to discuss shared interests. This feature is associated with poor integration within a community or group.

HP:0000729.name: Autistic behavior
HP:0000729.definition: Persistent deficits in social interaction and communication and interaction as well as a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest as well as repetitive patterns of behavior.

HP:0000732.name: Inflexible adherence to routines
HP:0000732.definition: A need to strictly adhere to repetitive routines or patterns of behavior which are created by the environment. One becomes upset or distressed when their routines are disrupted or altered.

HP:0000733.name: Motor stereotypy
HP:0000733.definition: Use of the same abnormal action in response to certain triggers or at random. They may be used as a way to regulate one's internal state but must otherwise have no apparent functional purpose.

HP:0000734.name: Disinhibition
HP:0000734.definition: Reduced ability to control, or a failure to resist a temptation, urge, or impulse. Examples include disregard for social conventions, general impulsivity, and poor risk assessment.

HP:0000736.name: Short attention span
HP:0000736.definition: Reduced attention span characterized by distractibility and impulsivity.

HP:0000737.name: Irritability
HP:0000737.definition: A proneness to anger, i.e., a tendency to become easily bothered or annoyed.

HP:0000738.name: Hallucinations
HP:0000738.definition: Perceptions in a conscious and awake state that, in the absence of external stimuli, have qualities of real perception. These perceptions are vivid, substantial, and located in external objective space.

HP:0000739.name: Anxiety
HP:0000739.definition: Intense feelings of nervousness, tension, or panic often arise in response to interpersonal stresses. There is worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities. Individuals may feel fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty, and they may also have fears of falling apart or losing control.

HP:0000740.name: Episodic paroxysmal anxiety
HP:0000740.definition: Recurrent attacks of severe anxiety, which occur without restriction to any particular situation or set of circumstances, are therefore unpredictable.

HP:0000741.name: Apathy
HP:0000741.definition: Apathy is a quantitative reduction of interest, motivation and the initiation and persistence of goal-directed behavior, where often the accompanying emotions, thoughts, and social interactions are also diminished. The individual is typically non-reactive to provocations, positive or negative, and appears to not care. Distinguished from lethargy which involves lack of physical or mental energy.

HP:0000742.name: Self-mutilation
HP:0000742.definition: Deliberate harm to one's body resulting in tissue damage, without a conscious intent to die.

HP:0000743.name: Frontal release signs
HP:0000743.definition: Primitive reflexes traditionally held to be a sign of disorders that affect the frontal lobes.

HP:0000744.name: Low frustration tolerance
HP:0000744.definition: The feeling of frustration can be defined as an emotional reaction that occurs when a desired goal is not achieved. Frustration intolerance is defined as an age-inappropriate response to frustration, characterized by crying or temper tantrums in children, or aggressive or other undesirable behaviors.

HP:0000745.name: Abnormal diminished volition
HP:0000745.definition: A reduction in willful and motivated goal-directed behavior that is considered the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action.

HP:0000746.name: Delusion
HP:0000746.definition: A delusion is a fixed false belief held despite evidence to the contrary. The term delusion broadly encompasses all false judgments that possess the following external characteristics to a significant, albeit unspecified, extent: (1) they are held with an exceptional level of conviction, accompanied by an unparalleled subjective certainty; (2) there is an inability to consider alternative experiences or compelling counter-arguments; (3) the content of the belief is impossible.

HP:0000748.name: Inappropriate laughter
HP:0000748.definition: Laughing that may be excessive and/or inappropriate in context (e.g., laughing at a funeral while others are crying).

HP:0000750.name: Delayed speech and language development
HP:0000750.definition: A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.

HP:0000751.name: Personality changes
HP:0000751.definition: An abnormal shift in patterns of thinking, acting, or feeling.

HP:0000752.name: Hyperactivity
HP:0000752.definition: Hyperactivity is a condition characterized by constant and unusually high levels of activity, even in situations where it is deemed inappropriate.

HP:0000756.name: Agoraphobia
HP:0000756.definition: A type of anxiety disorder characterized by the avoidance of public places, especially where crowds gather.

HP:0000757.name: Lack of insight
HP:0000757.definition: Lack of insight (Anosognosia) is a neurological condition in which an individual is unaware of his or her own neurological deficit or psychiatric condition. Anosognosia can be associated with mental illness, dementia, and structural brain lesions and can affect an individual's conscious awareness of deficits involving judgment, emotions, memory, executive function, language skills, and motor ability.

HP:0000758.name: Abnormal nonverbal communicative behavior
HP:0000758.definition: Abnormalities in eye contact, communicative facial expressions, gesture use, or the use of others' bodies to communicate convey shared meanings within a culture that replace or supplement verbal communication.

HP:0000759.name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system morphology
