HP:0000759.definition: A structural abnormality of the peripheral nervous system, which is composed of the nerves that lead to or branch off from the central nervous system. This includes the cranial nerves (olfactory and optic nerves are technically part of the central nervous system).

HP:0000762.name: Decreased nerve conduction velocity
HP:0000762.definition: A reduction in the speed at which electrical signals propagate along the axon of a neuron.

HP:0000763.name: Sensory neuropathy
HP:0000763.definition: Peripheral neuropathy affecting the sensory nerves.

HP:0000765.name: Abnormal thorax morphology
HP:0000765.definition: Any abnormality of the thorax (the region of the body formed by the sternum, the thoracic vertebrae and the ribs).

HP:0000766.name: Abnormal sternum morphology
HP:0000766.definition: An anomaly of the sternum, also known as the breastbone.

HP:0000767.name: Pectus excavatum
HP:0000767.definition: A defect of the chest wall characterized by a depression of the sternum, giving the chest ("pectus") a caved-in ("excavatum") appearance.

HP:0000768.name: Pectus carinatum
HP:0000768.definition: A deformity of the chest caused by overgrowth of the ribs and characterized by protrusion of the sternum.

HP:0000771.name: Gynecomastia
HP:0000771.definition: Abnormal development of large mammary glands in males resulting in breast enlargement.

HP:0000774.name: Narrow chest
HP:0000774.definition: Reduced width of the chest from side to side, associated with a reduced distance from the sternal notch to the tip of the shoulder.

HP:0010705.name: 4-5 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0010705.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the fourth (ring) to the fifth (little) finger that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0010706.name: 1-3 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0010706.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the thumb to the middle finger that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0010707.name: 1-4 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0010707.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the thumb to the ring finger that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0010708.name: 1-5 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0010708.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the thumb to the little finger that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints (complete syndactyly of all fingers of the hand).

HP:0010709.name: 2-4 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0010709.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the second (index) to the fourth (ring) finger that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0010710.name: 3-5 finger syndactyly
HP:0010710.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the middle to little fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0010711.name: 1-2 toe syndactyly
HP:0010711.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes one and two.

HP:0010712.name: 1-4 toe syndactyly
HP:0010712.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to four.

HP:0010713.name: 1-5 toe syndactyly
HP:0010713.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to five (complete syndactyly of all toes of the foot).

HP:0010714.name: 2-4 toe syndactyly
HP:0010714.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to four.

HP:0010715.name: 2-5 toe syndactyly
HP:0010715.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to five.

HP:0010716.name: 3-5 toe syndactyly
HP:0010716.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes three to five.

HP:0010717.name: Osseous syndactyly of toes
HP:0010717.definition: Webbing or fusion of the toes, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual bones of the toes. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a tibial-fibular axis. Fusions of bones of the toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

HP:0010719.name: Abnormality of hair texture
HP:0010719.definition: An abnormality of the texture of the hair.

HP:0010720.name: Abnormal hair pattern
HP:0010720.definition: An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.

HP:0010721.name: Abnormal hair whorl
HP:0010721.definition: An abnormal hair whorl (that is, a patch of hair growing in the opposite direction of the rest of the hair).

HP:0010722.name: Asymmetry of the ears
HP:0010722.definition: An asymmetriy, i.e., difference in size, shape or position between the left and right ear.

HP:0010724.name: Advanced pneumatization of the mastoid process
HP:0010724.definition: An abnormally advanced degree of pneumatization (i.e., formation of air cells) in the mastoid process with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0010726.name: Prominent corneal nerve fibers
HP:0010726.definition: Abnormal prominence of the corneal nerve fibers.

HP:0010727.name: Spontaneous rupture of the globe
HP:0010727.definition: Rupture of the eyeball not due to trauma.

HP:0010728.name: Aplasia of the retina
HP:0010728.definition: A developmental defect characterized by absence of the retina.

HP:0010729.name: Cherry red spot of the macula
HP:0010729.definition: Pallor of the perifoveal macula of the retina with appearance of a small circular reddish choroid shape as seen through the fovea centralis due to relative transparency of the macula.

HP:0010730.name: Double eyebrow
HP:0010730.definition: This may present as a partial or complete duplication of the eyebrows.

HP:0010731.name: Extension of eyebrows towards upper eyelid
HP:0010731.definition: The eyebrows extend towards - or even all the way down to - the margin of the upper eyelid.

HP:0010732.name: Nodular changes affecting the eyelids
HP:0010732.definition: Nodular changes affecting the eyelids may have many different causes such as cystic lesions (chalaziae, hordeolae), lipogranulomas, melanomas, infectious diseases (Molluscum contagiosum) and many more.

HP:0010733.name: Naevus flammeus of the eyelid
HP:0010733.definition: Naevus flammeus localized in the skin of the eyelid.

HP:0010734.name: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones
HP:0010734.definition: Tumor-like growths that consist of replacement of the medullary bone with fibrous tissue, causing the expansion and weakening of the areas of bone involved. Especially when involving the skull or facial bones, the lesions can cause externally visible deformities. The skull is often, but not necessarily, affected, and any other bone or bones may be involved. Fibrous dysplasia can either effect isolated bones (Monostotic fibrous dysplasia) or also generalized all bones of the body (Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia).

HP:0010735.name: Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia
HP:0010735.definition: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in many bones throughout of the body. Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia is a cardinal feature of McCune-Albright syndrome.

HP:0010736.name: Monostotic fibrous dysplasia
HP:0010736.definition: Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in only one bone.

HP:0010739.name: Osteopoikilosis
HP:0010739.definition: Osteopoikilosis is a benign, asymptomatic sclerotic dysplasia of the bones. It affects both male and female and may be seen at any age. Radiographically sclerotic circular or ovoid lesions are usually symmetrically distributed in a periarticular location. Lesions can increase or decrease in size and number in serial radiographs or even disappear and do not have increased bone radiotracer uptake.

HP:0010740.name: Osteopathia striata
HP:0010740.definition: A lamellar pattern visible on radiographs and mainly localized at the metaphyses of the long tubular bones. Pathologic-anatomical studies revealed that these benign signs on x-rays are the result of a juvenile metaphyseal bone necrosis. Calcifications in the necrotic marrow lead to this lamellar or lattice-like appearance.

HP:0010741.name: Pedal edema
HP:0010741.definition: An abnormal accumulation of excess fluid in the lower extremity resulting in swelling of the feet and extending upward to the lower leg.

HP:0010742.name: Edema of the upper limbs
HP:0010742.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin of the arms.

HP:0010743.name: Short metatarsal
HP:0010743.definition: Diminished length of a metatarsal bone, with resultant proximal displacement of the associated toe.

HP:0010744.name: Absent metatarsal bone
HP:0010744.definition: A developmental abnormality characterized by the absence (aplasia) of a metatarsal bone.

HP:0010745.name: Aplasia of the phalanges of the toes
HP:0010745.definition: Absence of a digit or of one or more phalanges of a toe.

HP:0010746.name: Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the toes

HP:0010747.name: Medial flaring of the eyebrow
HP:0010747.definition: An abnormal distribution of eyebrow hair growth in the medial direction.

HP:0010748.name: Ectopic lacrimal punctum
HP:0010748.definition: Positioning of a lacrimal punctum other than at the medial margins of the eyelid.

HP:0010749.name: Blepharochalasis
HP:0010749.definition: Blepharochalasis is characterized by recurrent, non-painful, nonerythematous episodes of eyelid edema. It has been divided into hypertrophic and atrophic forms. In the hypertrophic form recurrent edema results in orbital fat herniation through a weakened orbital septum. Most patients who have blepharochalasis present in an atrophic condition with atrophy of redundant eyelid skin and superior nasal fat pads.

HP:0010750.name: Dermatochalasis
HP:0010750.definition: Loss of elasticity of the upper and lower eyelids causing the skin to sag and bulge.

HP:0010751.name: Dimple chin
HP:0010751.definition: A persistent midline depression of the skin over the fat pad of the chin.

HP:0010752.name: Cleft mandible
HP:0010752.definition: Midline deficiency of the mandible and some or all overlying tissues.

HP:0010754.name: Abnormality of the temporomandibular joint
HP:0010754.definition: An anomaly of the temporomandibular joint.

HP:0010755.name: Asymmetry of the maxilla
HP:0010755.definition: Asymmetry between the left and right sides of the maxilla.

HP:0010756.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the premaxilla
HP:0010756.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the premaxilla.

HP:0010757.name: Aplasia of the premaxilla
HP:0010757.definition: Absence of the premaxilla, which is the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla.

HP:0010758.name: Abnormality of the premaxilla
HP:0010758.definition: An abnormality of the premaxilla, the most anterior part of the maxilla that usually bears the central and lateral incisors and includes the anterior nasal spine and inferior aspect of the piriform rim. The premaxilla contains the bone and teeth of the primary palate.

HP:0010759.name: Prominence of the premaxilla
HP:0010759.definition: Prominent positioning of the premaxilla in relation to the rest of the maxilla, the facial skeleton, or mandible. Not necessarily caused by an increase in size (hypertrophy of) the premaxilla.

HP:0010760.name: Absent toe
HP:0010760.definition: Aplasia of a toe. That is, absence of all phalanges of a non-hallux digit of the foot and the associated soft tissues.

HP:0010762.name: Chordoma
HP:0010762.definition: A chordoma is a tumor that arises from embryonic remnants of the notochord along the length of the neuraxis. Chordomas generally occur in the sacrum, intracranially at the clivus, or along the spinal axis.

HP:0010763.name: Low insertion of columella
HP:0010763.definition: Insertion of the posterior columella below the nasal base.

HP:0010765.name: Palmar hyperkeratosis
HP:0010765.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin localized to the palm of the hand.

HP:0010766.name: Ectopic calcification
HP:0010766.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in a tissue or location in which calcification does not normally occur.

HP:0010767.name: Sacrococcygeal pilonidal abnormality
HP:0010767.definition: The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.

HP:0010769.name: Pilonidal sinus
HP:0010769.definition: A sinus in the coccygeal region (the region of the intergluteal cleft). A pilonidal sinus often contains hair and skin debris.

HP:0010771.name: Pilonidal abscess
HP:0010771.definition: A hair-containing cyst or sinus usually in the coccygeal region.

HP:0010772.name: Anomalous pulmonary venous return
HP:0010772.definition: A developmental defect characterized by abnormal connection of one or more pulmonary veins to the superior or inferior vena cava, the right atrium, or the coronary sinus, resulting in a left-to-right shunt of oxygenated blood.

HP:0010773.name: Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return
HP:0010773.definition: A form of anomalous pulmonary venous return in which not all pulmonary veins drain abnormally. Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return frequently involves one or both of the veins from one lung.

HP:0010774.name: Cor triatriatum
HP:0010774.definition: The presence of an additional membrane in the left or right cardiac atrium which results in the subdivision of the affected atrium (and thus in total three atria, whence the name).

HP:0010775.name: Vascular ring
HP:0010775.definition: A developmental defect of the aortic arch system in which the trachea and esophagus are completely encircled by connected segments of the aortic arch and its branches. This occurs if the normal process of regression and persistence of the bilateral embryonic aortic arches fails.

HP:0010776.name: Tracheobronchmegaly
HP:0010776.definition: Marked widening of the trachea and major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.

HP:0010777.name: Bronchomegaly
HP:0010777.definition: Marked widening of the major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.

HP:0010779.name: Large pelvis bone
HP:0010779.definition: The presence of an abnormally large pelvis.

HP:0010780.name: Hyperacusis
HP:0010780.definition: Over-sensitivity to certain frequency ranges of sound.

HP:0010781.name: Skin dimple
HP:0010781.definition: Skin dimples are cutaneous indentations that are the result of tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) causing an indentation.

HP:0010782.name: Shoulder dimple
HP:0010782.definition: A subtype of skin dimples occurring in the shoulder region.

HP:0010783.name: Erythema
HP:0010783.definition: Redness of the skin, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

HP:0010784.name: Uterine neoplasm
HP:0010784.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterus.

HP:0010785.name: Gonadal neoplasm
HP:0010785.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a gonad.

HP:0010786.name: Urinary tract neoplasm
HP:0010786.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary system.

HP:0010787.name: Genital neoplasm
HP:0010787.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genital system.

HP:0010788.name: Testicular neoplasm
HP:0010788.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis.

HP:0010790.name: Hypoplasia of the Leydig cells
HP:0010790.definition: Underdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

HP:0010791.name: Hyperplasia of the Leydig cells
HP:0010791.definition: Hypertrophy or overdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

HP:0010793.name: Bifid nail
HP:0010793.definition: A digit with two nails, with at least some soft tissue between them.

HP:0010794.name: Impaired visuospatial constructive cognition
HP:0010794.definition: Reduced ability affecting mainly visuospatial cognition which may be tested using pattern construction (for example by Differential Ability Scales, which test a person's strengths and weaknesses across a range of intellectual abilities).

HP:0010797.name: Hemangioblastoma
HP:0010797.definition: A hemangioblastoma is a benign vascular neoplasm that arises almost exclusively in the central nervous system. Hemangioblastomas consist of a tightly packed cluster of small blood vessels forming a mass of up to 1 or 2 cm in diameter.

HP:0010798.name: Lip freckle
HP:0010798.definition: Increased focal pigmentation of the vermilion of the lips.

HP:0010799.name: Pinealoma
HP:0010799.definition: A neoplasm of the pineal gland.

HP:0010800.name: Absent cupid's bow
HP:0010800.definition: Lack of paramedian peaks and median notch of the upper lip vermilion.

HP:0010801.name: Underdeveloped nasolabial fold
HP:0010801.definition: Reduced bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion or commissure).

HP:0010802.name: Perioral hyperpigmentation
HP:0010802.definition: Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the skin surrounding the vermilion of the lips.

HP:0010803.name: Everted upper lip vermilion
HP:0010803.definition: Inner aspect of the upper lip vermilion (normally apposing the teeth) visible in a frontal view, i.e., the presence of an everted upper lip.

HP:0010804.name: Tented upper lip vermilion
HP:0010804.definition: Triangular appearance of the oral aperture with the apex in the midpoint of the upper vermilion and the lower vermilion forming the base.

HP:0010805.name: Upturned corners of mouth
HP:0010805.definition: Oral commissures positioned superior to the midline labial fissure.

HP:0010806.name: U-Shaped upper lip vermilion
HP:0010806.definition: Gentle upward curve of the upper lip vermilion such that the center is placed well superior to the commissures.

HP:0010807.name: Open bite
HP:0010807.definition: Visible space between the dental arches in occlusion.

HP:0010808.name: Protruding tongue
HP:0010808.definition: Tongue extending beyond the alveolar ridges or teeth at rest.

HP:0010809.name: Broad uvula
HP:0010809.definition: Increased width of the uvula (subjective finding).

HP:0010813.name: Abnormal number of hair whorls
HP:0010813.definition: More than two clockwise hair whorls.

HP:0010814.name: Abnormal position of hair whorl
HP:0010814.definition: Hair growth from a single point on the scalp in any location other than lateral to the midline and close to the vertex of the skull.

HP:0010815.name: Nevus sebaceous
HP:0010815.definition: A congenital, hairless plaque consisting of overgrown epidermis, sebaceous glands, hair follicles, apocrine glands and connective tissue. They are a variant of epidermal naevi. Sebaceous naevi most often appear on the scalp, but they may also arise on the face, neck or forehead. At birth, a sevaceous nevus typically appears as a solitary, smooth, yellow-orange hairless patch. Sebaceous naevi become more pronounced around adolescence, often appearing bumpy, warty or scaly.

HP:0010816.name: Epidermal nevus
HP:0010816.definition: Epidermal naevi are due to an overgrowth of the epidermis and may be present at birth (50%) or develop during childhood.

HP:0010817.name: Linear nevus sebaceous
HP:0010817.definition: A type of nevus sebaceous with a linear form, raised borders and yellowish color.

HP:0010818.name: Generalized tonic seizure
HP:0010818.definition: A generalized tonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterized by bilateral limb stiffening or elevation, often with neck stiffening without a subsequent clonic phase. The tonic activity can be a sustained abnormal posture, either in extension or flexion, sometimes accompanied by tremor of the extremities.

HP:0010819.name: Atonic seizure
HP:0010819.definition: Atonic seizure is a type of motor seizure characterized by a sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting about 1 to 2 seconds, involving head, trunk, jaw, or limb musculature.

HP:0010820.name: Focal emotional seizure with crying
HP:0010820.definition: Focal emotional seizure with crying (dacrystic) is characterized by the presence of stereotyped crying, this may be accompanied by lacrimation, sad facial expression and sobbing. The subjective emotion of sadness may or may not be present.

HP:0010821.name: Focal emotional seizure with laughing
HP:0010821.definition: Focal emotional seizure with laughing (gelastic) is characterized by bursts of laughter or giggling, usually without appropriate related emotion of happiness, and described as 'mirthless'.

HP:0010822.name: Scintillating scotoma
HP:0010822.definition: A scintillating scotoma is a common visual aura that can precede a migraine, whereby a spot of flickering light near the center of the visual fields occurs. The spot prevents vision, and is thus termed scotoma. The scotoma can extend into one or more shimmering arcs of white or colored flashing lights.

HP:0010823.name: Ridged cranial sutures
HP:0010823.definition: An overlap of the bony plates of the skull in an infant, with or without early closure.

HP:0010824.name: Abnormal fifth cranial nerve morphology
HP:0010824.definition: Any structural abnormality of the fifth cranial nerve.

HP:0010825.name: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve
HP:0010825.definition: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve.

HP:0010826.name: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve
HP:0010826.definition: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve.

HP:0010827.name: Abnormal seventh cranial physiology
HP:0010827.definition: Abnormality of the seventh cranial nerve sometimes also referred to as the facial nerve.

HP:0010828.name: Hemifacial spasm
HP:0010828.definition: Intermittent clonic or tonic contraction of muscles supplied by facial nerve. Muscles are relaxed in between contractions.

HP:0010829.name: Impaired temperature sensation
HP:0010829.definition: A reduced ability to discriminate between different temperatures.

HP:0010830.name: Impaired tactile sensation
HP:0010830.definition: A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation). This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.

HP:0010831.name: Impaired proprioception
HP:0010831.definition: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.

HP:0010832.name: Abnormality of pain sensation
HP:0010832.definition: Pain is an unpleasant sensation that can range from mild, localized discomfort to agony, whereby the physical part of pain results from nerve stimulation and is often accompanied by an emotional component. This term groups abnormalities in pain sensation presumed to result from abnormalities related to the specific nerve fibers that carry the pain impulses to the brain.

HP:0010833.name: Spontaneous pain sensation
HP:0010833.definition: Spontaneous pain is a kind of neuropathic pain which occurs without an identifiable trigger.

HP:0010834.name: Trophic changes related to pain
HP:0010834.definition: Trophic changes is a term used to describe abnormalities in the area of pain that include primarily wasting away of the skin, tissues, or muscle, thinning of the bones, and changes in how the hair or nails grow, including thickening or thinning of hair or brittle nails.

HP:0010835.name: Dissociated sensory loss
HP:0010835.definition: A pattern of sensory loss with selective loss of touch sensation and proprioception without loss of pain and temperature, or vice-versa.

HP:0010837.name: Decreased circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
HP:0010837.definition: Decreased concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood.

HP:0010838.name: High nonceruloplasmin-bound serum copper
HP:0010838.definition: An increased concentration of non ceruloplasmin bound copper in the blood.

HP:0010839.name: Increased urinary copper concentration
HP:0010839.definition: An increased concentration of copper in the urine.

HP:0010841.name: Multifocal epileptiform discharges
HP:0010841.definition: An abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG) and being identified at multiple locations (foci).

HP:0010843.name: EEG with focal slow activity
HP:0010843.definition: Focal (localized) slow activity reflects focal dysfunction, not diffuse dysfunction (i.e., encephalopathy).

HP:0010844.name: EEG with multifocal slow activity
HP:0010844.definition: Multifocal slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0010845.name: EEG with generalized slow activity
HP:0010845.definition: Diffuse slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0000974.name: Hyperextensible skin
HP:0000974.definition: A condition in which the skin can be stretched beyond normal, and then returns to its initial position.

HP:0000975.name: Hyperhidrosis
HP:0000975.definition: Abnormal excessive perspiration (sweating) despite the lack of appropriate stimuli like hot and humid weather.

HP:0000977.name: Soft skin
HP:0000977.definition: Subjective impression of increased softness upon palpation of the skin.

HP:0000978.name: Bruising susceptibility
HP:0000978.definition: An ecchymosis (bruise) refers to the skin discoloration caused by the escape of blood into the tissues from ruptured blood vessels. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to bruising. The corresponding phenotypic abnormality is generally elicited on medical history as a report of frequent ecchymoses or bruising without adequate trauma.

HP:0000979.name: Purpura
HP:0000979.definition: Purpura (from Latin: purpura, meaning purple) is the appearance of red or purple discolorations on the skin that do not blanch on applying pressure. They are caused by bleeding underneath the skin. This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to developing purpura. Purpura are larger than petechiae.

HP:0000982.name: Palmoplantar keratoderma
HP:0000982.definition: Abnormal thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.

HP:0000988.name: Skin rash
HP:0000988.definition: A red eruption of the skin.

HP:0000989.name: Pruritus
HP:0000989.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased disposition to experience pruritus.

HP:0000991.name: Xanthomatosis
HP:0000991.definition: The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.

HP:0000992.name: Cutaneous photosensitivity
HP:0000992.definition: An increased sensitivity of the skin to light. Photosensitivity may result in a rash upon exposure to the sun (which is known as photodermatosis). Photosensitivity can be diagnosed by phototests in which light is shone on small areas of skin.

HP:0000993.name: Molluscoid pseudotumors
HP:0000993.definition: Bluish-grey, spongy nodules associated with scars over pressure points and easily traumatized areas like the elbows and knees.

HP:0000995.name: Melanocytic nevus
HP:0000995.definition: A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.

HP:0000996.name: Facial capillary hemangioma
HP:0000996.definition: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells with small endothelial spaces, occurring in the face.

HP:0000997.name: Axillary freckling
HP:0000997.definition: The presence in the axillary region (armpit) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.

HP:0000998.name: Hypertrichosis
HP:0000998.definition: Hypertrichosis is increased hair growth that is abnormal in quantity or location.

HP:0000999.name: Pyoderma
HP:0000999.definition: Any manifestation of a skin disease associated with the production of pus.

HP:0001000.name: Abnormality of skin pigmentation
HP:0001000.definition: An abnormality of the pigmentation of the skin.

HP:0001003.name: Multiple lentigines
HP:0001003.definition: Presence of an unusually high number of lentigines (singular: lentigo), which are flat, tan to brown oval spots.

HP:0001004.name: Lymphedema
HP:0001004.definition: Localized fluid retention and tissue swelling caused by a compromised lymphatic system.

HP:0001007.name: Hirsutism
HP:0001007.definition: Abnormally increased hair growth referring to a male pattern of body hair (androgenic hair).

HP:0001009.name: Telangiectasia
HP:0001009.definition: Telangiectasias refer to small dilated blood vessels located near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes, measuring between 0.5 and 1 millimeter in diameter. Telangiectasia are located especially on the tongue, lips, palate, fingers, face, conjunctiva, trunk, nail beds, and fingertips.

HP:0001010.name: Hypopigmentation of the skin
HP:0001010.definition: A reduction of skin color related to a decrease in melanin production and deposition.

HP:0001012.name: Multiple lipomas
HP:0001012.definition: The presence of multiple lipomas (a type of benign tissue made of fatty tissue).

HP:0001013.name: Eruptive xanthomas
HP:0001013.definition: Eruptive xanthomas are yellow-orange-to-red-brown papules that are often surrounded by an erythematous halo. They appear in crops on the buttocks, extensor surfaces of the extremities, and flexural creases. Acutely, variable amounts of pruritus and pain occur.

HP:0001014.name: Angiokeratoma
HP:0001014.definition: Angiokeratomas are hyperkeratotic papules that are characterized histologically by superficial ectatic (i.e., dilated) blood vessels with epidermal proliferation. Clinically, angiokeratoma presents as a small, raised, dark-red spot.

HP:0001015.name: Prominent superficial veins
HP:0001015.definition: A condition in which superficial veins (i.e., veins just under the skin) are more conspicuous or noticeable than normal.

HP:0001017.name: Anemic pallor
HP:0001017.definition: A type of pallor that is secondary to the presence of anemia.

HP:0001018.name: Abnormal palmar dermatoglyphics
HP:0001018.definition: An abnormality of the dermatoglyphs, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of palm of hand.

HP:0001019.name: Erythroderma
HP:0001019.definition: An inflammatory exfoliative dermatosis involving nearly all of the surface of the skin. Erythroderma develops suddenly. A patchy erythema may generalize and spread to affect most of the skin. Scaling may appear in 2-6 days and be accompanied by hot, red, dry skin, malaise, and fever.

HP:0001022.name: Albinism
HP:0001022.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of skin, hair and eye (iris and retina).

HP:0001024.name: Skin dimple over apex of long bone angulation

HP:0001025.name: Urticaria
HP:0001025.definition: Raised, well-circumscribed areas of erythema and edema involving the dermis and epidermis. Urticaria is intensely pruritic, and blanches completely with pressure.

HP:0001027.name: Soft, doughy skin
HP:0001027.definition: A skin texture that is unusually soft (and may feel silky), and has a malleable consistency resembling that of dough.

HP:0001028.name: Hemangioma
HP:0001028.definition: A hemangioma is a benign tumor characterized by blood-filled spaces lined by benign endothelial cells. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma (in contrast to a hemangioma with small endothelial spaces, which is called capillary hemangioma).

HP:0001029.name: Poikiloderma
HP:0001029.definition: Poikiloderma refers to a patch of skin with (1) reticulated hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation, (2) wrinkling secondary to epidermal atrophy, and (3) telangiectasias.

HP:0001030.name: Fragile skin
HP:0001030.definition: Skin that splits easily with minimal injury.

HP:0001032.name: Absent distal interphalangeal creases
HP:0001032.definition: Absence of the distal interphalangeal flexion creases of the fingers.

HP:0001034.name: Hypermelanotic macule
HP:0001034.definition: A hyperpigmented circumscribed area of change in normal skin color without elevation or depression of any size.

HP:0001036.name: Parakeratosis
HP:0001036.definition: Abnormal formation of the keratinocytes of the epidermis characterized by persistence of nuclei, incomplete formation of keratin, and moistness and swelling of the keratinocytes.

HP:0001041.name: Facial erythema
HP:0001041.definition: Redness of the skin of the face, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

HP:0001046.name: Intermittent jaundice
HP:0001046.definition: Jaundice that is sometimes present, sometimes not.

HP:0001047.name: Atopic dermatitis
HP:0001047.definition: Atopic dermatitis (AD) or atopic eczema is an itchy, inflammatory skin condition with a predilection for the skin flexures. It is characterized by poorly defined erythema with edema, vesicles, and weeping in the acute stage and skin thickening (lichenification) in the chronic stage.

HP:0001048.name: Cavernous hemangioma
HP:0001048.definition: The presence of a cavernous hemangioma. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma.

HP:0001049.name: Absent dorsal skin creases over affected joints

HP:0001051.name: Seborrheic dermatitis
HP:0001051.definition: Seborrheic dermatitis is a form of eczema which is closely related to dandruff. It causes dry or greasy peeling of the scalp, eyebrows, and face, and sometimes trunk.

HP:0001052.name: Nevus flammeus
HP:0001052.definition: A congenital vascular malformation consisting of superficial and deep dilated capillaries in the skin which produce a reddish to purplish discolouration of the skin.

HP:0001055.name: Erysipelas
HP:0001055.definition: Increased susceptibility to erysipelas, as manifested by a medical history of repeated episodes of erysipelas, which is a superficial infection of the skin, typically involving the lymphatic system.

HP:0001056.name: Milia
HP:0001056.definition: Presence of multiple small cysts containing keratin (skin protein) and presenting as tiny pearly-white bumps just under the surface of the skin.

HP:0001057.name: Aplasia cutis congenita
HP:0001057.definition: A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin in multiple or solitary non-inflammatory, well-demarcated, oval or circular ulcers with a diameter of about 1 to 2 cm. Aplasia cutis congenita most commonly occurs on the scalp, but may present in the face, trunk, or limbs.

HP:0001058.name: Poor wound healing
HP:0001058.definition: A reduced ability to heal cutaneous wounds.

HP:0001059.name: Pterygium
HP:0001059.definition: Pterygia are 'winglike' triangular membranes occurring in the neck, eyes, knees, elbows, ankles or digits.

HP:0001060.name: Axillary pterygium
HP:0001060.definition: Presence of a cutaneous membrane (flap) in the armpit.

HP:0001061.name: Acne
HP:0001061.definition: A skin condition in which there is an increase in sebum secretion by the pilosebaceous apparatus associated with open comedones (blackheads), closed comedones (whiteheads), and pustular nodules (papules, pustules, and cysts).

HP:0001062.name: Atypical nevus
HP:0001062.definition: A large pigmented lesion measuring 5-15 mm in diameter with irregular, notched, and ill defined border and with color that may range from tan to dark brown to pink.

HP:0001063.name: Acrocyanosis
HP:0001063.definition: Bluish discoloration of the skin of the hands or feet.

HP:0001065.name: Striae distensae
HP:0001065.definition: Thinned, erythematous, depressed bands of atrophic skin. Initially, striae appear as flattened and thinned, pinkish linear regions of the skin. Striae tend to enlarge in length and become reddish or purplish. Later, striae tend to appear as white, depressed bands that are parallel to the lines of skin tension. Striae distensae occur most often in areas that have been subject to distension such as the lower back, buttocks, thighs, breast, abdomen, and shoulders.

HP:0001067.name: Neurofibroma
HP:0001067.definition: A benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor that generally appears as a soft, skin-colored papule or small subcutaneous nodule. Individuals with neurofibromatosis can have numerous neurofibromas.

HP:0001069.name: Episodic hyperhidrosis
HP:0001069.definition: Intermittent episodes of abnormally increased perspiration.

HP:0001071.name: Angiokeratoma corporis diffusum
HP:0001071.definition: Angiokeratoma corporis diffusum (ACD) is typically characterized by innumerable small red to black papules which occur in clusters and are situated symmetrically in the bathing trunks area. The number of lesions and the extension of the body increase steadily with time so that generalization and mucosal involvement are common. The single lesion begins with a minute reddish papule which enlarges to up to 10 mm in diameter, becomes dark red to black with a discrete keratotic overgrowth. Histologically, the papules are characterized by superficial dilated capillaries in papillary dermis with epidermal proliferation.

HP:0001074.name: Atypical nevi in non-sun exposed areas

HP:0001075.name: Atrophic scars
HP:0001075.definition: Scars that form a depression compared to the level of the surrounding skin because of damage to the collagen, fat or other tissues below the skin.

HP:0001080.name: Biliary tract abnormality
HP:0001080.definition: An abnormality of the biliary tree.

HP:0001081.name: Cholelithiasis
HP:0001081.definition: Hard, pebble-like deposits that form within the gallbladder.

HP:0001082.name: Cholecystitis
HP:0001082.definition: The presence of inflammatory changes in the gallbladder.

HP:0001083.name: Ectopia lentis
HP:0001083.definition: Dislocation or malposition of the crystalline lens of the eye. A partial displacement (or dislocation) of the lens is described as a subluxation of the lens, while a complete displacement is termed luxation of the lens. A complete displacement occurs if the lens is completely outside the patellar fossa of the lens, either in the anterior chamber, in the vitreous, or directly on the retina. If the lens is partially displaced but still contained within the lens space, then it is termed subluxation.

HP:0001084.name: Corneal arcus
HP:0001084.definition: A hazy, grayish-white ring about 2 mm in width located close to but separated from the limbus (the corneoscleral junction). Corneal arcus generally occurs bilaterally, and is related to lipid deposition in the cornea. Corneal arcus can occur in elderly persons as a part of the aging process but may be associated with hypercholesterolemia in people under the age of 50 years.

HP:0001085.name: Papilledema
HP:0001085.definition: Papilledema refers to edema (swelling) of the optic disc secondary to any factor which increases cerebral spinal fluid pressure.

HP:0001087.name: Developmental glaucoma
HP:0001087.definition: Glaucoma which forms during the early years of a child's life is called developmental or congenital glaucoma.

HP:0001088.name: Brushfield spots
HP:0001088.definition: The presence of whitish spots in a ring-like arrangement at the periphery of the iris.

HP:0001090.name: Abnormally large globe
HP:0001090.definition: Diffusely large eye (with megalocornea) without glaucoma.

HP:0001092.name: Absent lacrimal punctum
HP:0001092.definition: No identifiable superior and/or inferior lacrimal punctum.

HP:0001093.name: Optic nerve dysplasia
HP:0001093.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the optic nerve.

HP:0001094.name: Iridocyclitis
HP:0001094.definition: A type of anterior uveitis, in which there is Inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body.

HP:0001096.name: Keratoconjunctivitis
HP:0001096.definition: Inflammation of the cornea and conjunctiva.

HP:0001097.name: Keratoconjunctivitis sicca
HP:0001097.definition: Dryness of the eye related to deficiency of the tear film components (aqueous, mucin, or lipid), lid surface abnormalities, or epithelial abnormalities. Keratoconjunctivitis sicca often results in a scratchy or sandy sensation (foreign body sensation) in the eyes, and may also be associated with itching, inability to produce tears, photosensitivity, redness, pain, and difficulty in moving the eyelids.

HP:0001098.name: Abnormal fundus morphology
HP:0001098.definition: Any structural abnormality of the fundus of the eye.

HP:0001100.name: Heterochromia iridis
HP:0001100.definition: Heterochromia iridis is a difference in the color of the iris in the two eyes.

HP:0001102.name: Angioid streaks of the fundus
HP:0001102.definition: Irregular lines in the deep retina that are typically configured in a radiating fashion and emanate from the optic disc. Angioid streaks are crack-like dehiscences in abnormally thickened and calcified Bruch's membrane, resulting in atrophy of the overlying retinal pigment epithelium. They may be associated with a number of endocrine, metabolic, and connective tissue abnormalities but are frequently idiopathic.

HP:0001103.name: Abnormal macular morphology
HP:0001103.definition: A structural abnormality of the macula lutea, which is an oval-shaped highly pigmented yellow spot near the center of the retina.

HP:0001105.name: Retinal atrophy
HP:0001105.definition: Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the fundus, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.

HP:0001106.name: Periorbital hyperpigmentation
HP:0001106.definition: Increased pigmentation of the skin in the region surrounding the orbit of the eye.

HP:0001107.name: Ocular albinism
HP:0001107.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of the iris and retina.

HP:0001112.name: Leber optic atrophy
HP:0001112.definition: Degeneration of retinal ganglion cells and their axons.

HP:0001114.name: Xanthelasma
HP:0001114.definition: The presence of xanthomata in the skin of the eyelid.

HP:0001115.name: Posterior polar cataract
HP:0001115.definition: A polar cataract that affects the posterior pole of the lens.

HP:0001116.name: Macular coloboma
HP:0001116.definition: A congenital defect of the macula distinct from coloboma associated with optic fissure closure defects. Macular coloboma is characterized by a sharply defined, rather large defect in the central area of the fundus that is oval or round, and coarsely pigmented.

HP:0001117.name: Sudden loss of visual acuity
HP:0001117.definition: Severe loss of visual acuity within hours or days. This is characteristic of Leber hereditary optic neuropathy.

HP:0001118.name: Juvenile cataract
HP:0001118.definition: A type of cataract that is not apparent at birth but that arises in childhood or adolescence.

HP:0001119.name: Keratoglobus
HP:0001119.definition: Limbus-to-limbus corneal thinning, often greatest in the periphery, with globular protrusion of the cornea.

HP:0001120.name: Abnormality of corneal size
HP:0001120.definition: Any abnormality of the size or morphology of the cornea.

HP:0001125.name: Transient unilateral blurring of vision
HP:0001125.definition: Transient blurring of vision associated with the aura phase of migraine.

HP:0001126.name: Cryptophthalmos
HP:0001126.definition: Cryptophthalmos is a condition of total absence of eyelids and the skin of forehead is continuous with that of cheek, in which the eyeball is completely concealed by the skin, which is stretched over the orbital cavity.

HP:0001128.name: Trichiasis
HP:0001128.definition: Inversion and rubbing of the eyelashes against the globe of the eye.

HP:0001131.name: Corneal dystrophy
HP:0001131.definition: The term corneal dystrophy embraces a heterogenous group of bilateral genetically determined non-inflammatory corneal diseases that are restricted to the cornea.

HP:0001132.name: Lens subluxation
HP:0001132.definition: Partial dislocation of the lens of the eye.

HP:0001133.name: Constriction of peripheral visual field
HP:0001133.definition: An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye.

HP:0001134.name: Anterior polar cataract
HP:0001134.definition: A polar cataract that affects the anterior pole of the lens.

HP:0001136.name: Retinal arteriolar tortuosity
HP:0001136.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal arterioles.

HP:0001137.name: Alternating esotropia
HP:0001137.definition: Esotropia in which either eye may be used for fixation.

HP:0001140.name: Limbal dermoid
HP:0001140.definition: A benign tumor typically found at the junction of the cornea and sclera (limbal epibullar dermoid).

HP:0001141.name: Severely reduced visual acuity
HP:0001141.definition: Severe reduction of the ability to see. On the 6m visual acuity scale, severe reduction is defined as less than 6/60 but at least 3/60. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, severe reduction is defined as less than 20/200 but at least 20/400. On the decimal visual acuity scale, severe reduction is defined as less than 0.1 but at least 0.05.

HP:0001142.name: Lenticonus
HP:0001142.definition: A conical projection of the anterior or posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

HP:0001144.name: Orbital cyst
HP:0001144.definition: Presence of a cyst in the region of the periorbital tissues. Orbital cysts can be derived from epithelial or glandular tissue within or surrounding the orbit (lacrimal glands, salivary glands, conjunctival, oral, nasal, or sinus epithelium).

HP:0001147.name: Retinal exudate
HP:0001147.definition: Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.

HP:0001149.name: Lattice corneal dystrophy
HP:0001149.definition: The presence of fine, branching linear opacities in Bowman's layer in the central area that may spread to the periphery in the clinical course. The deep corneal stroma may be involved but the process does not reach Descemet's membrane. Recurrent corneal erosion may occur. Histologic examination reveals amyloid deposits in the collagen fibers of the cornea.

HP:0001151.name: Impaired horizontal smooth pursuit
HP:0001151.definition: An abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit characterized by an impairment of the ability to track horizontally moving objects.

HP:0001152.name: Saccadic smooth pursuit
HP:0001152.definition: An abnormality of tracking eye movements in which smooth pursuit is interrupted by an abnormally high number of saccadic movements.

HP:0001153.name: Septate vagina
HP:0001153.definition: The presence of a vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication. The septum is longitudinal in the majority of cases.

HP:0001155.name: Abnormality of the hand
HP:0001155.definition: An abnormality affecting one or both hands.

HP:0001156.name: Brachydactyly
HP:0001156.definition: Digits that appear disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot. The word brachydactyly is used here to describe a series distinct patterns of shortened digits (brachydactyly types A-E). This is the sense used here.

HP:0001159.name: Syndactyly
HP:0001159.definition: Webbing or fusion of the fingers or toes, involving soft parts only or including bone structure. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a radio-ulnar axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers or toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "symphalangism".

HP:0001161.name: Hand polydactyly
HP:0001161.definition: A kind of polydactyly characterized by the presence of a supernumerary finger or fingers.

HP:0001162.name: Postaxial hand polydactyly
HP:0001162.definition: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand (that is, on the side with the fifth finger).

HP:0001163.name: obsolete Abnormality of the metacarpal bones

HP:0001166.name: Arachnodactyly
HP:0001166.definition: Abnormally long and slender fingers (spider fingers).

HP:0001169.name: Broad palm
HP:0001169.definition: For children from birth to 4 years of age the palm width is more than 2 SD above the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is above the 95th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately wide for the length.

HP:0001171.name: Split hand
HP:0001171.definition: A condition in which middle parts of the hand (fingers and metacarpals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic middle fingers over absent middle fingers as far as oligo- or monodactyl hands.

HP:0001172.name: Abnormal thumb morphology
HP:0001172.definition: An abnormal structure of the first digit of the hand.

HP:0001177.name: Preaxial hand polydactyly
HP:0001177.definition: Supernumerary digits located at the radial side of the hand. Polydactyly (supernumerary digits) involving the thumb occurs in many distinct forms of high variability and severity. Ranging from fleshy nubbins over varying degrees of partial duplication/splitting to completely duplicated or even triplicated thumbs or preaxial (on the radial side of the hand) supernumerary digits.

HP:0001178.name: Ulnar claw
HP:0001178.definition: An abnormal hand position characterized by hyperextension of the fourth and fifth fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints of the same fingers such that they are curled towards the palm.

HP:0001181.name: Adducted thumb
HP:0001181.definition: In the resting position, the tip of the thumb is on, or near, the palm, close to the base of the fourth or fifth finger.

HP:0001182.name: Tapered finger
HP:0001182.definition: The gradual reduction in girth of the finger from proximal to distal.

HP:0001187.name: Hyperextensibility of the finger joints
HP:0001187.definition: The ability of the finger joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

HP:0001188.name: Hand clenching
HP:0001188.definition: An abnormal hand posture in which the hands are clenched to fists. All digits held completely flexed at the metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints. In prenatal sonography of the fetal clenched hand, the index finger overlaps a clenched fist formed by the other digits. The proximal interphalangeal articulation of the index finger is flexed and ulnarly deviated, and the thumb is adducted.

HP:0001191.name: Abnormal carpal morphology
HP:0001191.definition: An abnormality affecting the carpal bones of the wrist (scaphoid, lunate, triquetral, pisiform, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, hamate).

HP:0001193.name: Ulnar deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand

HP:0001194.name: Abnormalities of placenta or umbilical cord
HP:0001194.definition: An abnormality of the placenta (the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall) or of the umbilical cord (the cord that connects the fetus to the placenta).

HP:0001195.name: Single umbilical artery
HP:0001195.definition: Single umbilical artery (SUA) is the absence of one of the two umbilical arteries surrounding the fetal bladder and in the fetal umbilical cord.

HP:0001196.name: Short umbilical cord
HP:0001196.definition: Decreased length of the umbilical cord.

HP:0001197.name: Abnormality of prenatal development or birth
HP:0001197.definition: An abnormality of the fetus or the birth of the fetus, excluding structural abnormalities.

HP:0001199.name: Triphalangeal thumb
HP:0001199.definition: A thumb with three phalanges in a single, proximo-distal axis. Thus, this term applies if the thumb has an accessory phalanx, leading to a digit like appearance of the thumb.

HP:0001204.name: Distal symphalangism of hands
HP:0001204.definition: The term distal symphalangism refers to a bony fusion of the distal and middle phalanges of the digits of the hand, in other words the distal interphalangeal joint (DIJ) is missing which can be seen either on x-rays or as an absence of the distal interphalangeal finger creases.

HP:0001211.name: Abnormal fingertip morphology
HP:0001211.definition: An abnormal structure of the tip (end) of a finger.

HP:0001212.name: Prominent fingertip pads
HP:0001212.definition: A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips. The term "persistent fetal fingertip pads" is often used as a synonym, but should better not be used because it implies knowledge of history of the patient which often does not exist.

HP:0001215.name: Camptodactyly of 2nd-5th fingers
HP:0001215.definition: The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the second to fifth fingers cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.

HP:0001216.name: Delayed ossification of carpal bones
HP:0001216.definition: Ossification of carpal bones occurs later than age-adjusted norms.

HP:0001217.name: Clubbing
HP:0001217.definition: Broadening of the soft tissues (non-edematous swelling of soft tissues) of the digital tips in all dimensions associated with an increased longitudinal and lateral curvature of the nails.

HP:0001218.name: Autoamputation
HP:0001218.definition: Auto-amputation is the spontaneous detachment of an appendage from the body due to long standing pathology.

HP:0001220.name: Interphalangeal joint contracture of finger
HP:0001220.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion in an interphalangeal joint of a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0001223.name: Pointed proximal second through fifth metacarpals
HP:0001223.definition: All of the metacarpal bones of the hand have a pointed proximal appearance.

HP:0001226.name: obsolete Acral ulceration and osteomyelitis leading to autoamputation of digits

HP:0001227.name: Abnormality of the thenar eminence
HP:0001227.definition: An abnormality of the thenar eminence, i.e., of the muscle on the palm of the human hand just beneath the thumb.

HP:0001232.name: Nail bed telangiectasia
HP:0001232.definition: Telangiectases in the area of the nails.

HP:0001233.name: 2-3 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0001233.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the second to the third fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0001234.name: Hitchhiker thumb
HP:0001234.definition: With the hand relaxed and the thumb in the plane of the palm, the axis of the thumb forms an angle of at least 90 degrees with the long axis of the hand.

HP:0001238.name: Slender finger
HP:0001238.definition: Fingers that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.

HP:0001239.name: Wrist flexion contracture
HP:0001239.definition: A chronic loss of wrist joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevent normal movement of the joints of the wrist.

HP:0001245.name: Small thenar eminence
HP:0001245.definition: Underdevelopment of the thenar eminence with reduced palmar soft tissue mass surrounding the base of the thumb.

HP:0001248.name: Short tubular bones of the hand
HP:0001248.definition: Decreased length of the tubular bones of the hand, that is, the phalanges and metacarpals.

HP:0001249.name: Intellectual disability
HP:0001249.definition: Intellectual disability, previously referred to as mental retardation, is characterized by subnormal intellectual functioning that occurs during the developmental period. It is defined by an IQ score below 70.

HP:0001250.name: Seizure
HP:0001250.definition: A seizure is an intermittent abnormality of nervous system physiology characterized by a transient occurrence of signs and/or symptoms due to abnormal excessive or synchronous neuronal activity in the brain.

HP:0001251.name: Ataxia
HP:0001251.definition: Cerebellar ataxia refers to ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum. This causes a variety of elementary neurological deficits including asynergy (lack of coordination between muscles, limbs and joints), dysmetria (lack of ability to judge distances that can lead to under- or overshoot in grasping movements), and dysdiadochokinesia (inability to perform rapid movements requiring antagonizing muscle groups to be switched on and off repeatedly).

HP:0001252.name: Hypotonia
HP:0001252.definition: Hypotonia is an abnormally low muscle tone (the amount of tension or resistance to movement in a muscle). Even when relaxed, muscles have a continuous and passive partial contraction which provides some resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia thus manifests as diminished resistance to passive stretching. Hypotonia is not the same as muscle weakness, although the two conditions can co-exist.

HP:0001254.name: Lethargy
HP:0001254.definition: A state of fatigue, either physical or mental slowness and sluggishness, with difficulties in initiating or performing simple tasks. Distinguished from apathy which implies indifference and a lack of desire or interest in the task. A person with lethargy may have the desire, but not the energy to engage in personal or socially relevant tasks.

HP:0001256.name: Intellectual disability, mild
HP:0001256.definition: Mild intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 50-69.

HP:0001257.name: Spasticity
HP:0001257.definition: A motor disorder characterized by a velocity-dependent increase in tonic stretch reflexes with increased muscle tone, exaggerated (hyperexcitable) tendon reflexes.

HP:0001258.name: Spastic paraplegia
HP:0001258.definition: Complete loss of the ability to move the lower limbs accompanied by spasticity of the lower limbs.

HP:0001259.name: Coma
HP:0001259.definition: The complete absence of wakefulness and consciousness, which is evident through a lack of response to any form of external stimuli.

HP:0001260.name: Dysarthria
HP:0001260.definition: Dysarthric speech is a general description referring to a neurological speech disorder characterized by poor articulation. Depending on the involved neurological structures, dysarthria may be further classified as spastic, flaccid, ataxic, hyperkinetic and hypokinetic, or mixed.

HP:0001262.name: Excessive daytime somnolence
HP:0001262.definition: A state of abnormally strong desire for sleep during the daytime.

HP:0001263.name: Global developmental delay
HP:0001263.definition: A delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child, including motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and emotional skills. This term should only be used to describe children younger than five years of age.

HP:0001264.name: Spastic diplegia
HP:0001264.definition: Spasticity (neuromuscular hypertonia) primarily in the muscles of the legs, hips, and pelvis.

HP:0001265.name: Hyporeflexia
HP:0001265.definition: Reduction of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.

HP:0001266.name: Choreoathetosis
HP:0001266.definition: Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements).

HP:0001268.name: Mental deterioration
HP:0001268.definition: Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults.

HP:0001269.name: Hemiparesis
HP:0001269.definition: Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength.

HP:0001270.name: Motor delay
HP:0001270.definition: A type of Developmental delay characterized by a delay in acquiring motor skills.

HP:0010212.name: Flexion contracture of the hallux
HP:0010212.definition: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the first (big) toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010213.name: Contracture of the tarsometatarsal joint of the hallux
HP:0010213.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion in the tarsometatarsal joint of the hallux due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The tarsometatarsal joints of the feet are also called Lisfranc's joints.

HP:0010214.name: Contracture of the interphalangeal joint of the hallux
HP:0010214.definition: The interphalangeal joint of the big toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010215.name: Contractures of the metatarsophalangeal joint of the hallux
HP:0010215.definition: The joint between the first metatarsal and the proximal phalanx of the first (big) toe cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010219.name: Structural foot deformity
HP:0010219.definition: A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the bones of the foot (as well as muscle and soft tissue). In contrast if only the muscle and soft tissue are affected the term positional foot deformity applies.

HP:0010220.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the 2nd metacarpal
HP:0010220.definition: Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the second metacarpal bone.

HP:0010222.name: Abnormal 3rd metacarpal epiphysis morphology
HP:0010222.definition: Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the third metacarpal bone.

HP:0010223.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the 3rd metacarpal
HP:0010223.definition: The normal epiphysis of the third metacarpal is localized at the distal end of the metacarpal bone. This term applies if an accessory epiphysis, located at the proximal end of the metacarpal bone, is present.

HP:0010224.name: Abnormal 4th metacarpal epiphysis morphology
HP:0010224.definition: Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the 4th metacarpal bone.

HP:0010225.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the 4th metacarpal
HP:0010225.definition: The normal epiphysis of the fourth metacarpal is localized at the distal end of the metacarpal bone. This term applies if an accessory epiphysis, located at the proximal end of the metacarpal bone, is present.

HP:0010226.name: Abnormal 5th metacarpal epiphysis morphology
HP:0010226.definition: Any abnormality of the epiphysis of the fifth metacarpal bone.

HP:0010227.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the 5th metacarpal
HP:0010227.definition: The normal epiphysis of the fifth metacarpal is localized at the distal end of the metacarpal bone. This term applies if an accessory epiphysis, located at the proximal end of the metacarpal bone, is present.

HP:0010228.name: Absent epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010228.definition: Absence of one or more epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers.

HP:0010229.name: Bracket epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010229.definition: Bracket epiphysis refers to an abnormality in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0010230.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010230.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the fingers of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

HP:0010231.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010231.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0010232.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010232.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers.

HP:0010233.name: Irregular epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010233.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers.

HP:0010234.name: Ivory epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010234.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0010235.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010235.definition: A secondary ossification center in the phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0010236.name: Small epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010236.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0010237.name: Epiphyseal stippling of finger phalanges
HP:0010237.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of phalanges of the fingers.

HP:0010238.name: Triangular epiphyses of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0010238.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the fingers of the hand.

HP:0010239.name: Aplasia of the middle phalanx of the hand
HP:0010239.definition: Absence of one or more middle phalanx of a finger.

HP:0010241.name: Short proximal phalanx of finger
HP:0010241.definition: Congenital hypoplasia of one or more proximal phalanx of finger.

HP:0010242.name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010243.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the distal phalanx of finger
HP:0010243.definition: Any anomaly of distal epiphysis of phalanx of finger.

HP:0010244.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010245.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010246.name: Absent epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010247.name: Bracket epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010247.definition: An abnormality of the distal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0010248.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010249.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010250.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010251.name: Irregular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010252.name: Ivory epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010252.definition: Distal epiphyses of the hand are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0010253.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010253.definition: A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0010254.name: Small epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010255.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010256.name: Triangular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010257.name: Absent epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010258.name: Bracket epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
HP:0010258.definition: An abnormality of the middle phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0010259.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010260.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010261.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
HP:0010261.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand.

HP:0010262.name: Irregular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010263.name: Ivory epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
HP:0010263.definition: Epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0010264.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
HP:0010264.definition: A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0010265.name: Small epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010266.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010267.name: Triangular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0010268.name: Absent epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010269.name: Bracket epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010269.definition: An abnormality of the proximal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0010270.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010271.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010272.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010273.name: Irregular epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010274.name: Ivory epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010274.definition: Epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0010275.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
HP:0010275.definition: A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0010276.name: Small epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010277.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010278.name: Triangular epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0010280.name: Stomatitis
HP:0010280.definition: Stomatitis is an inflammation of the mucous membranes of any of the structures in the mouth.

HP:0010281.name: Cleft lower lip
HP:0010281.definition: A gap in the lower lip.

HP:0010282.name: Thin lower lip vermilion
HP:0010282.definition: Height of the vermilion of the medial part of the lower lip more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective).

HP:0010284.name: Intra-oral hyperpigmentation
HP:0010284.definition: Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the mucosa of the mouth.

HP:0010285.name: Oral synechia
HP:0010285.definition: Fibrous band between the mucosal surfaces of the upper and lower alveolar ridges.

HP:0010286.name: Abnormal salivary gland morphology
HP:0010286.definition: Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva.

HP:0010287.name: Abnormality of the submandibular glands
HP:0010287.definition: Any abnormality of the submandibular glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth, superior to the digastric muscles.

HP:0010288.name: Abnormality of the sublingual glands
HP:0010288.definition: Any abnormality of the sublingual glands, which are the salivary glands that are located beneath the floor of the mouth anterior to the submandibular glands.

HP:0010289.name: Cleft maxillary alveolar ridge
HP:0010289.definition: A gap (cleft) affecting one of the alveolar ridges, which are the protuberances in the mouth that contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth. An alveolar cleft can affect all structures of the alveolar ridge, including the gingiva, other mucosa, periosteum, alveolar bone, and teeth. Alveolar cleft occurs in response to divergence from normal development during frontonasal prominence growth, contact, and fusion. The most common alveolar portion of the cleft is located between the lateral incisor and the canine.

HP:0010290.name: Short hard palate
HP:0010290.definition: Distance between the labial point of the incisive papilla to the midline junction of the hard and soft palate more than 2 SD below the mean (objective) or apparently decreased length of the hard palate (subjective).

HP:0010291.name: Prominent palatine ridges
HP:0010291.definition: Increased size and/or number of soft tissue folds on the palatal side of the maxillary alveolar ridge.

HP:0010293.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the uvula
HP:0010293.definition: Underdevelopment or absence of the uvula.

HP:0010294.name: Palate fistula
HP:0010294.definition: A fistula which connects the oral cavity and the pharyngeal area via the aspects of the soft palate.

HP:0010295.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tongue
HP:0010295.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the tongue.

HP:0010296.name: Ankyloglossia
HP:0010296.definition: Short or anteriorly attached lingual frenulum, associated with limited mobility of the tongue.

HP:0010297.name: Bifid tongue
HP:0010297.definition: Tongue with a median apical indentation or fork.

HP:0010298.name: Smooth tongue
HP:0010298.definition: Glossy appearance of the entire tongue surface.

HP:0010300.name: Abnormally low-pitched voice
HP:0010300.definition: A persistent (minutes to hours) abnormal decrease in the pitch of the voice for the context or social situation or significantly different from the baseline of the individual.

HP:0010301.name: Spinal dysraphism
HP:0010301.definition: A heterogeneous group of congenital spinal anomalies that result from defective closure of the neural tube early in fetal life.

HP:0010302.name: Spinal cord tumor
HP:0010302.definition: A neoplasm affecting the spinal cord.

HP:0010303.name: Abnormal spinal meningeal morphology
HP:0010303.definition: Any abnormality of the spinal meninges, the system of membranes (dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater) which envelops the spinal cord.

HP:0010304.name: Spinal meningeal diverticulum
HP:0010304.definition: An outpouching of the spinal meninges.

HP:0010306.name: Short thorax
HP:0010306.definition: Reduced inferior to superior extent of the thorax.

HP:0010307.name: Stridor
HP:0010307.definition: Stridor is a high pitched sound resulting from turbulent air flow in the upper airway.

HP:0010308.name: Asternia
HP:0010308.definition: The congenital absence of the sternum.

HP:0010309.name: Bifid sternum
HP:0010309.definition: The sternal cleft is a rare congenital anomaly resulting from a fusion failure of the sternum.

HP:0010310.name: Chylothorax
HP:0010310.definition: Accumulation of excessive amounts of lymphatic fluid (chyle) in the pleural cavity.

HP:0010311.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the breasts
HP:0010311.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the breasts.

HP:0010313.name: Breast hypertrophy
HP:0010313.definition: The presence of hypertrophy of the breast.

HP:0010315.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the diaphragm
HP:0010315.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the diaphragm.

HP:0010316.name: Ebstein anomaly of the tricuspid valve
HP:0010316.definition: Ebstein's anomaly refers to an abnormally placed and deformed tricuspid valve characterized by apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid valve leaflets, leading to atrialization of the right ventricle with a variable degree of malformation and displacement of the anterior leaflet.

HP:0010318.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the abdominal wall musculature
HP:0010318.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the abdominal musculature.

HP:0010319.name: Abnormal second toe morphology
HP:0010319.definition: An anomaly of the second toe.

HP:0010320.name: Abnormal third toe morphology
HP:0010320.definition: An anomaly of the third toe.

HP:0010321.name: Abnormal fourth toe morphology
HP:0010321.definition: An anomaly of the fourth toe.

HP:0010322.name: Abnormal fifth toe morphology
HP:0010322.definition: An anomaly of the little toe.

HP:0010323.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 2nd toe

HP:0010324.name: Abnormal morphology of phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010324.definition: An anomaly of a phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010327.name: Flexion contracture of the 2nd toe
HP:0010327.definition: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the second toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010329.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 3rd toe

HP:0010330.name: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 3rd toe

HP:0010333.name: Flexion contracture of 3rd toe
HP:0010333.definition: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the third toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010335.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 4th toe

HP:0010336.name: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 4th toe

HP:0010339.name: Flexion contracture of the 4th toe
HP:0010339.definition: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the fourth toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010341.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 5th toe

HP:0010342.name: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 5th toe

HP:0010345.name: Flexion contracture of the 5th toe
HP:0010345.definition: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the fifth toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

HP:0010347.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe

HP:0010349.name: Bullet-shaped 2nd toe phalanx
HP:0010349.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010350.name: Curved 2nd toe phalanx
HP:0010350.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the second toe.

HP:0010351.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 2nd toe

HP:0010352.name: Patchy sclerosis of 2nd toe phalanx
HP:0010352.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the second toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010353.name: Second toe symphalangism
HP:0010353.definition: Fusion of the interphalangeal joints of the 2nd toe.

HP:0010354.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 2nd toe

HP:0010355.name: Duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
HP:0010355.definition: Partial or complete duplication of a phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010356.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010357.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010358.name: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010359.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd toe

HP:0010361.name: Bullet-shaped 3rd toe phalanx
HP:0010361.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the third toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010362.name: Curved 3rd toe phalanx
HP:0010362.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the third toe.

HP:0010363.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 3rd toe

HP:0010364.name: Patchy sclerosis of 3rd toe phalanx
HP:0010364.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010365.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the 3rd toe

HP:0010366.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd toe

HP:0010367.name: Duplication of phalanx of the 3rd toe
HP:0010367.definition: Partial or complete duplication of phalanx of third toe.

HP:0010368.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe

HP:0010369.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe

HP:0010370.name: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe
HP:0010370.definition: An anomaly of the proximal phalanx of third toe.
