HP:0010371.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 4th toe

HP:0010373.name: Bullet-shaped 4th toe phalanx
HP:0010373.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the fourth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010374.name: Curved 4th toe phalanx
HP:0010374.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the fourth toe.

HP:0010375.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 4th toe

HP:0010376.name: Patchy sclerosis of 4th toe phalanx
HP:0010376.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fourth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010377.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the 4th toe

HP:0010378.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 4th toe

HP:0010379.name: Duplication of phalanx of the 4th toe
HP:0010379.definition: Partial or complete duplication of phalanx of fourth toe.

HP:0010380.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0010381.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0010382.name: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0010383.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 5th toe

HP:0010385.name: Bullet-shaped 5th toe phalanx
HP:0010385.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the fifth toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010386.name: Curved 5th toe phalanx
HP:0010386.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more phalanges of the fifth toe.

HP:0010387.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 5th toe

HP:0010388.name: Patchy sclerosis of 5th toe phalanx
HP:0010388.definition: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fifth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

HP:0010389.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the 5th toe

HP:0010390.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 5th toe

HP:0010391.name: Duplication of the phalanges of the 5th toe
HP:0010391.definition: Partial or complete duplication of one or more phalanx of little toe.

HP:0010392.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0010393.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0010394.name: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0010395.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010395.definition: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe.

HP:0010396.name: Broad proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010397.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010397.definition: An abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010398.name: Curved proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010398.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe.

HP:0010399.name: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010400.name: Patchy sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010401.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010402.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010403.name: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010403.definition: Partial or complete duplication of proximal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010404.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010405.name: Broad middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010406.name: Bullet-shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010406.definition: An abnormal morphology of the middle phalanx of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010407.name: Curved middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010407.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe.

HP:0010408.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010409.name: Patchy sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010410.name: Symphalangism affecting the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010411.name: Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010412.name: Duplication of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010412.definition: Partial or complete duplication of middle phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010413.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010414.name: Broad distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010415.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010415.definition: An abnormal morphology of the distal phalanx of the second toe, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0010416.name: Curved distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010416.definition: A deviation from the normal straight form of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe.

HP:0010417.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010418.name: Patchy sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010419.name: Symphalangism affecting the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010420.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010421.name: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010421.definition: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010422.name: Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010422.definition: Complete duplication of proximal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010423.name: Partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010423.definition: Partial duplication of proximal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010424.name: Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010424.definition: Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010425.name: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010425.definition: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010426.name: Complete duplication of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010426.definition: Complete duplication of middle phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010427.name: Partial duplication of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010427.definition: Partial duplication of middle phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010428.name: Partial duplication of phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010428.definition: Partial duplication of a phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010429.name: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
HP:0010429.definition: Complete duplication of a phalanx of second toe.

HP:0010430.name: Aplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe

HP:0010431.name: Short phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010431.definition: Reduced length of one or more phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

HP:0010432.name: Absent distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010432.definition: Absence of distal phalanx of the second toe as a result of developmental aplasia.

HP:0010433.name: Short distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010433.definition: Reduced length of the distal phalanx of the second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

HP:0010434.name: Aplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010435.name: Short middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010435.definition: Reduced length of the middle phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

HP:0010436.name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0010437.name: Short proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0010437.definition: Reduced length of the proximal phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

HP:0010438.name: Abnormal ventricular septum morphology
HP:0010438.definition: A structural abnormality of the interventricular septum.

HP:0010440.name: Ectopic accessory toe-like appendage
HP:0010440.definition: In contrast to forms of polydactyly where the supernumerary digit (this can either be a rudimentary or a completely 'normal' digit) is either located postaxial (on the fibular side of the foot, next top the little toe), preaxial (on the tibial side of the foot, next to the big toe) or mesoaxial (somewhere central, between big and little toe), a supernumerary digit may also be placed ectopically, meaning anywhere else except post-,meso- or preaxial. In the literature this is sometimes referred to as Disorganisation-like Syndrome (OMIM223200).

HP:0010441.name: Ectopic accessory finger-like appendage
HP:0010441.definition: In contrast to forms of polydactyly where the supernumerary digit (this can either be a rudimentary or a completely 'normal' digit) is either located postaxial (on the ulnar side of the hand, next to the little finger), preaxial (on the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb) or mesoaxial (somewhere central, between thumb and little finger), a supernumerary digit may also be placed ectopically, meaning anywhere else except post-,meso- or preaxial. In the literature this is sometimes referred to as Disorganisation-like Syndrome (OMIM223200).

HP:0010442.name: Polydactyly
HP:0010442.definition: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of supernumerary fingers or toes.

HP:0010443.name: Bifid femur
HP:0010443.definition: A bifid or bifurcated appearance of the femur as seen on x-rays, possible appearing as a more or less severe bowing of the upper leg. Might be associated with hip dysplasia on the affected side.

HP:0010444.name: Pulmonic regurgitation
HP:0010444.definition: The retrograde (backwards) flow of blood through the pulmonary valve into the right ventricle during diastole.

HP:0010445.name: Primum atrial septal defect
HP:0010445.definition: An ostium primum atrial septal defect is located in the most anterior and inferior aspect of the atrial septum. The ostium primum refers to an anterior and inferior opening (ostium) within the septum primum, which divides the rudimentary atrium during fetal development. The ostium primum is normally sealed by fusion of the superior and inferior endocardial cushions around 5 weeks' gestation. Ostium primum defects result from a failure of the fusion of the embryologic endocardial cushion and septum primum.

HP:0010446.name: Tricuspid stenosis
HP:0010446.definition: A narrowing of the orifice of the tricuspid valve of the heart.

HP:0010447.name: Anal fistula
HP:0010447.definition: An abnormal connection between the epithelialised surface of the anal canal and the perianal skin.

HP:0010448.name: Colonic atresia
HP:0010448.definition: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the colon. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the colon.

HP:0010450.name: Esophageal stenosis
HP:0010450.definition: An abnormal narrowing of the lumen of the esophagus.

HP:0010451.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the spleen
HP:0010451.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the spleen.

HP:0010452.name: Ectopia of the spleen
HP:0010452.definition: An abnormal (non-anatomic) location of the spleen.

HP:0010453.name: Pelvic bone asymmetry
HP:0010453.definition: Pelvic asymmetry refers to asymmetric positioning of landmarks on the two sides of the pelvis and may have a structural or functional etiology.

HP:0010454.name: Acetabular spurs
HP:0010454.definition: The presence of osteophytes (bone spurs), i.e., of bony projections originating from the acetabulum.

HP:0010455.name: Steep acetabular roof
HP:0010455.definition: An exaggeration of the normal arched form of the acetabular roof such that it takes on a steep appearance.

HP:0010456.name: Abnormal greater sciatic notch morphology
HP:0010456.definition: An abnormality of the sacrosciatic notch, i.e., the deep indentation in the posterior border of the hip bone at the point of union of the ilium and ischium.

HP:0010457.name: obsolete Widening of the sacrosciatic notch

HP:0010458.name: Female pseudohermaphroditism
HP:0010458.definition: Hermaphroditism refers to a discrepancy between the morphology of the gonads and that of the external genitalia. In female pseudohermaphroditism, the genotype is female (XX) and the gonads are ovaries, but the external genitalia are virilized.

HP:0010459.name: True hermaphroditism
HP:0010459.definition: The presence of both ovarian and testicular tissues either in the same or in opposite gonads. Affected persons have ambiguous genitalia and may have 46,XX or 46,XY karyotypes or 46,XX/XY mosaicism.

HP:0010460.name: Abnormality of the female genitalia
HP:0010460.definition: Abnormality of the female genital system.

HP:0010461.name: Abnormality of the male genitalia
HP:0010461.definition: Abnormality of the male genital system.

HP:0010462.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ovary
HP:0010462.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ovary.

HP:0010463.name: Aplasia of the ovary
HP:0010463.definition: Aplasia, that is failure to develop, of the ovary.

HP:0010464.name: Streak ovary
HP:0010464.definition: A developmental disorder characterized by the progressive loss of primordial germ cells in the developing ovaries of an embryo, leading to hypoplastic ovaries composed of wavy connective tissue with occasional clumps of granulosa cells, and frequently mesonephric or hilar cells.

HP:0010465.name: Precocious puberty in females
HP:0010465.definition: The onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls.

HP:0010468.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the testes
HP:0010468.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the testes.

HP:0010469.name: Absent testis
HP:0010469.definition: Testis not palpable in the scrotum or inguinal canal.

HP:0010470.name: Supernumerary testes
HP:0010470.definition: The presence of more than two testes.

HP:0010471.name: Oligosacchariduria
HP:0010471.definition: Increased urinary excretion of oligosaccharides (low molecular weight carbohydrate chains composed of at least three monosaccharide subunits), derived from a partial degradation of glycoproteins.

HP:0010472.name: Abnormal circulating porphyrin concentration
HP:0010472.definition: An abnormality in the synthesis or catabolism of heme. Heme is composed of ferrous iron and protoporphyrin IX and is an essential molecule as the prosthetic group of hemeproteins such as hemoglobin, myoglobin, mitochondrial and microsomal cytochromes.

HP:0010473.name: Porphyrinuria
HP:0010473.definition: Abnormally increased excretion of porphyrins in the urine.

HP:0010474.name: Bladder stones
HP:0010474.definition: Buildups of minerals that form in the urinary bladder.

HP:0010475.name: Cloacal exstrophy
HP:0010475.definition: Cloacal exstrophy is a severe anterior abdominal wall defect in which the two hemibladders are visible and are separated by a midline intestinal plate, an omphalocele, and an imperforate anus.

HP:0010476.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the bladder
HP:0010476.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.

HP:0010479.name: Patent urachus
HP:0010479.definition: Persistence of the urachal canal resulting in a canal between the bladder and the umbilicus.

HP:0010480.name: Urethral fistula
HP:0010480.definition: The presence of an abnormal connection between the urethra and another organ or the skin.

HP:0010481.name: Urethral valve
HP:0010481.definition: The presence of an abnormal membrane obstructing the urethra.

HP:0010482.name: Acromelia of the upper limbs
HP:0010482.definition: Shortening of the arms predominantly affecting terminal parts of the arm in relation to the upper and middle limb segments.

HP:0010483.name: Amniotic constriction rings of arms
HP:0010483.definition: Amniotic constriction rings affecting the arms.

HP:0010484.name: Hypertrophy of the upper limb
HP:0010484.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the upper limbs (due to an increase of the size of cells).

HP:0010485.name: Hyperextensibility at elbow
HP:0010485.definition: The ability of the elbow joint to move beyond its normal range of motion.

HP:0010486.name: Abnormality of the hypothenar eminence
HP:0010486.definition: An abnormality of the hypothenar eminence, i.e., of the muscles on the ulnar side of the palm of the hand (i.e., on the side of the little finger).

HP:0010487.name: Small hypothenar eminence
HP:0010487.definition: Reduced muscle mass on the ulnar side of the palm, that is, reduction in size of the hypothenar eminence.

HP:0010488.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the palmar creases
HP:0010488.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the palmar creases.

HP:0010489.name: Absent palmar crease
HP:0010489.definition: The absence of the major creases of the palm (distal transverse crease, proximal transverse crease, or thenar crease).

HP:0010490.name: Abnormality of the palmar creases
HP:0010490.definition: An abnormality of the creases of the skin of palm of hand.

HP:0010491.name: Digital constriction ring
HP:0010491.definition: A narrow segment of significantly reduced circumference of a digit.

HP:0010492.name: Osseous finger syndactyly
HP:0010492.definition: Webbing or fusion of the fingers, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual finger bones.

HP:0010493.name: Long metacarpals
HP:0010493.definition: An abnormally increased length of the metacarpal bones.

HP:0010494.name: Acromelia of the lower limbs
HP:0010494.definition: Shortening of the legs predominantly affecting terminal parts of the leg in relation to the upper and middle arm segments.

HP:0010495.name: Amniotic constriction rings of legs
HP:0010495.definition: Amniotic constriction rings affecting the legs.

HP:0010496.name: Hypertrophy of the lower limb
HP:0010496.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the lower limbs (due to an increase of the size of cells).

HP:0010497.name: Sirenomelia
HP:0010497.definition: A developmental defect in which the legs are fused together.

HP:0008245.name: Pituitary hypothyroidism
HP:0008245.definition: A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion.

HP:0008247.name: Euthyroid hyperthyroxinemia
HP:0008247.definition: Increased levels of thyroxine without evidence of clinical thyroid disease.

HP:0008251.name: Congenital goiter
HP:0008251.definition: An enlargement of the thyroid gland with congenital onset.

HP:0008256.name: Adrenocortical adenoma
HP:0008256.definition: Adrenocortical adenomas are benign tumors of the adrenal cortex.

HP:0008258.name: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia
HP:0008258.definition: A type of adrenal hyperplasia with congenital onset.

HP:0008259.name: Adrenocorticotropin receptor defect
HP:0008259.definition: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in the ACTH receptor.

HP:0008261.name: Pancreatic islet cell adenoma
HP:0008261.definition: The presence of an adenoma of the pancreas with origin in a pancreatic B cell.

HP:0008263.name: Thyroid defect in oxidation and organification of iodide

HP:0008264.name: Neutrophil inclusion bodies
HP:0008264.definition: The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neutrophils. Cytoplasmic neutrophil inclusions (oval, basophilic) are also known as Doehle bodies.

HP:0008269.name: Increased red cell hemolysis by shear stress

HP:0008271.name: Abnormal cartilage collagen
HP:0008271.definition: Abnormal morphology of collagen fibers in cartilage. In cartilage, collagen II, actually a collagen II:IX:XI heterofibril, is by far the most important type of collagen. A number of abnormalities may be appreciated by electron micrography or biochemical investigations, including sparse collagen fibers in the cartilage matrix.

HP:0008277.name: Abnormal blood zinc concentration
HP:0008277.definition: An abnormality of zinc ion homeostasis.

HP:0008281.name: Acute hyperammonemia
HP:0008281.definition: An increased concentration of ammonia in the blood with sudden onset.

HP:0008282.name: Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia
HP:0008282.definition: An increased amount of unconjugated (indirect) bilurubin in the blood.

HP:0008283.name: Fasting hyperinsulinemia
HP:0008283.definition: An increased concentration of insulin in the blood in the fasting state, i.e., not as the response to food intake.

HP:0008290.name: Partial complement factor H deficiency
HP:0008290.definition: A partial reduction in level of the complement component Factor H in circulation.

HP:0008291.name: Pituitary corticotropic cell adenoma
HP:0008291.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH).

HP:0008293.name: Long-chain dicarboxylic aciduria
HP:0008293.definition: An increase in the level of long-chain dicarboxylic acid in the urine.

HP:0008297.name: Transient hyperphenylalaninemia
HP:0008297.definition: A condition of not having consistently high levels of phenylalanine in the blood but of experiencing temporary hyperphenylalaninemia following ingestion of large quantities of phenylalanine (for instance, following an oral loading test with phenylalanine).

HP:0008301.name: Dermatan sulfate excretion in urine
HP:0008301.definition: An increased concentration of dermatan sulfate in the urine.

HP:0008303.name: Olivary degeneration
HP:0008303.definition: Degeneration of the olivary bodies, prominent oval structures in the medulla oblongata.

HP:0008305.name: Exercise-induced myoglobinuria
HP:0008305.definition: Presence of myoglobin in the urine following exercise.

HP:0008309.name: Medium chain dicarboxylic aciduria
HP:0008309.definition: An increase in the level of medium chain dicarboxylic acid in the urine.

HP:0008311.name: Spinal cord posterior columns myelin loss

HP:0008314.name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex II
HP:0008314.definition: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex II, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

HP:0008315.name: Decreased plasma free carnitine
HP:0008315.definition: A decreased concentration of free (unbound) carnitine in the blood.

HP:0008316.name: Abnormal mitochondria in muscle tissue
HP:0008316.definition: An abnormality of the mitochondria in muscle tissue.

HP:0008318.name: Elevated leukocyte alkaline phosphatase
HP:0008318.definition: Increased alkaline phosphatase measured within leukocytes.

HP:0008320.name: Impaired collagen-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0008320.definition: Abnormal response to collagen or collagen-mimetics as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition collagen or collagen-mimetics.

HP:0008321.name: Reduced factor X activity
HP:0008321.definition: Reduced activity of coagulation factor X. The extrinsic and intrinsic pathways converge at factor X (fX). The extrinsic pathway activates fX by means of d factor VII with its cofactor, tissue factor. The intrinsic pathway activates fX by means of the tenase complex (Ca2+ and factors VIIIa, IXa and X) on the surface of activated platelets. Factor Xa in turn activates prothrombin (factor II) to thrombin (factor IIa).

HP:0008322.name: Abnormal mitochondrial morphology
HP:0008322.definition: Any structural anomaly of the mitochondria.

HP:0008323.name: Abnormal light- and dark-adapted electroretinogram
HP:0008323.definition: An abnormality of the combined rod-and-cone response on electroretinogram.

HP:0008326.name: Reduced circulating vitamin B6 circulating
HP:0008326.definition: An abnormally decreased concentration of vitamin B6 in the blood circulation.

HP:0008327.name: Microscopic nephrocalcinosis
HP:0008327.definition: The presence of microscopic crystalline calcium precipitates in the form of oxalate and/or phosphate in the renal parenchyma.

HP:0008330.name: Reduced von Willebrand factor activity
HP:0008330.definition: Decreased activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.

HP:0008338.name: Partial functional complement factor D deficiency
HP:0008338.definition: A partial reduction in level of the complement component Factor D in circulation.

HP:0008339.name: Diaminoaciduria
HP:0008339.definition: An increased urine level of any amino acid carrying two amino groups (Asparagine, glutamine and lysine, cystine, ornithine).

HP:0008341.name: Distal renal tubular acidosis
HP:0008341.definition: A type of renal tubular acidosis characterized by a failure of acid secretion by the alpha intercalated cells of the cortical collecting duct of the distal nephron. The urine cannot be acidified below a pH of 5.3, associated with acidemia and hypokalemia.

HP:0008344.name: Elevated circulating branched chain amino acid concentration
HP:0008344.definition: Concentration of a branched chain amino acid in the blood above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0008345.name: Hypoplasia of the iris dilator muscle

HP:0008347.name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex IV
HP:0008347.definition: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex IV, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

HP:0008348.name: Decreased circulating IgG2 concentration
HP:0008348.definition: A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG2 subclass in the blood circulation.

HP:0008352.name: Impaired platelet adhesion
HP:0008352.definition: An abnormality of adhesion of thrombocytes. Normally, platelets adhere to collagen in the vascular subendothelium within seconds of injury via a receptor made up of glycoprotein Ia and IIa and GPVI and to vWF via receptor GPIb/IX/V. The adherent platelets then release granules that lead to platelet activation and aggregation.

HP:0008353.name: Neutral hyperaminoaciduria
HP:0008353.definition: The presence of an abnormally increased concentration of neutral amino acids in the urine. The neutral amino acids are tryptophan, alanine, asparagine, glutamine, histidine, isoleucine, leucine, phenylalanine, serine, threonine, tyrosine and valine.

HP:0008354.name: Factor X activation deficiency
HP:0008354.definition: Reduced ability to transform factor X into its activated form factor Xa.

HP:0008357.name: Reduced factor XIII activity
HP:0008357.definition: Decreased activity of coagulation factor XIII (also known as fibrin stabilizing factor). Activated Factor XIII cross-links fibrin polymers solidifying the clot.

HP:0008358.name: Hyperprolinemia
HP:0008358.definition: An increased concentration of proline in the blood.

HP:0008360.name: Neonatal hypoproteinemia
HP:0008360.definition: A neonatal decreased concentration of proteins in the blood.

HP:0008362.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the hallux
HP:0008362.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the big toe.

HP:0008363.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tarsal bones
HP:0008363.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the tarsal bones.

HP:0008364.name: Abnormality of the calcaneus
HP:0008364.definition: An abnormality of the calcaneus, also known as the heel bone, one of the or heel bone, one of the components of the tarsus of the foot which make up the heel.

HP:0008366.name: Foot joint contracture
HP:0008366.definition: Contractures of one or more joints of the feet meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0008368.name: Tarsal synostosis
HP:0008368.definition: Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the tarsus (calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, cuneiiform bones).

HP:0008369.name: Abnormal tarsal ossification
HP:0008369.definition: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of any of the tarsal bones, seven bones of the foot comprising the calcaneus, talus, cuboid, navicular, and the cuneiform bones.

HP:0008371.name: Abnormal metatarsal ossification
HP:0008371.definition: Any abnormal process of ossification of the metatarsal bones, which normally are each ossified from two centers: one for the body, and one for the head (metatarsal II,III,IV, and V) and one for the body and one for the base (metatarsal I). The ossification process begins in the center of the body about the ninth week, and extends toward either extremity. The center for the base of the first metatarsal appears about the third year, and the centers for the heads of the other bones between the fifth and eighth years. They join the bodies between the eighteenth and twentieth years.

HP:0008372.name: Abnormal circulating vitamin A concentration
HP:0008372.definition: Concentration of vitamin A in the blood circulation outside limits of normal.

HP:0008383.name: Slow-growing nails
HP:0008383.definition: Nails whose growth is slower than normal.

HP:0008386.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nails
HP:0008386.definition: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the nail.

HP:0008390.name: Recurrent loss of toenails and fingernails
HP:0008390.definition: Repeated loss, or shedding, of the nails of the fingers and toes.

HP:0008391.name: Dystrophic fingernails
HP:0008391.definition: The presence of misshapen or partially destroyed nail plates, often with accumulation of soft, yellow keratin between the dystrophic nail plate and nail bed, resulting in elevation of the nail plate.

HP:0008392.name: Subungual hyperkeratosis
HP:0008392.definition: A thickening of the stratum corneum in the region beneath the nails.

HP:0008393.name: Congenital curved nail of fourth toe

HP:0008396.name: Chronic monilial nail infection
HP:0008396.definition: Chronic infection of the nails by Candida species.

HP:0008398.name: Hypoplastic fifth fingernail
HP:0008398.definition: A nail of the fifth finger that is diminished in length and width, i.e., underdeveloped nail of little finger.

HP:0008399.name: Circumungual hyperkeratosis
HP:0008399.definition: A thickening of the stratum corneum, the outer layer of the skin, in the region surrounding the nails.

HP:0008400.name: Onycholysis of distal fingernails
HP:0008400.definition: Detachment of the distal fingernails from the nail bed.

HP:0008402.name: Ridged fingernail
HP:0008402.definition: Longitudinal, linear prominences in the fingernail plate.

HP:0008404.name: Nail dystrophy
HP:0008404.definition: Onychodystrophy (nail dystrophy) refers to nail changes apart from changes of the color (nail dyschromia) and involves partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate.

HP:0011338.name: Abnormality of mouth shape
HP:0011338.definition: An abnormality of the outline, configuration, or contour of the mouth.

HP:0011339.name: Abnormality of upper lip vermillion
HP:0011339.definition: An abnormality of the vermilion border, the sharp demarcation between the lip (red colored) and the adjacent normal skin.

HP:0011340.name: Incomplete cleft of the upper lip
HP:0011340.definition: Cleft of the upper lip that does not go all the way from the bottom of the upper lip until the nasal cavity.

HP:0011341.name: Long upper lip
HP:0011341.definition: Increased width of the upper lip.

HP:0011342.name: Mild global developmental delay
HP:0011342.definition: A mild delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

HP:0011343.name: Moderate global developmental delay
HP:0011343.definition: A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

HP:0011344.name: Severe global developmental delay
HP:0011344.definition: A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

HP:0011345.name: Moderate expressive language delay
HP:0011345.definition: A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

HP:0011346.name: Mild expressive language delay
HP:0011346.definition: A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

HP:0011347.name: Abnormality of ocular abduction
HP:0011347.definition: An abnormality involving the movement of the eye outwards.

HP:0011348.name: Abnormal sixth cranial nerve morphology
HP:0011348.definition: Any structural abnormality of the abducens nerve.

HP:0011350.name: Mild receptive language delay
HP:0011350.definition: A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

HP:0011351.name: Moderate receptive language delay
HP:0011351.definition: A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

HP:0011352.name: Severe receptive language delay
HP:0011352.definition: A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

HP:0011353.name: Arterial intimal fibrosis
HP:0011353.definition: Formation of excess fibrous connective tissue in the tunica intima (innermost layer) of arteries.

HP:0011354.name: Generalized abnormality of skin
HP:0011354.definition: An abnormality of the skin that is not localized to any one particular region.

HP:0011355.name: Localized skin lesion
HP:0011355.definition: A lesion of the skin that is located in a specific region rather than being generalized.

HP:0011356.name: Regional abnormality of skin
HP:0011356.definition: An abnormality of the skin that is restricted to a particular body region.

HP:0011359.name: Dry hair
HP:0011359.definition: Hair that lacks the luster (shine or gleam) of normal hair.

HP:0011360.name: Acquired abnormal hair pattern
HP:0011360.definition: An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth that is acquired during the course of life.

HP:0011361.name: Congenital abnormal hair pattern
HP:0011361.definition: A congenital abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.

HP:0011363.name: Abnormality of hair growth rate
HP:0011363.definition: Hair whose growth rate deviates from the norm.

HP:0011365.name: Patchy hypopigmentation of hair
HP:0011365.definition: Reduced pigmentation of hair in patches.

HP:0011368.name: Epidermal thickening
HP:0011368.definition: Thickening of the epidermal layer of the skin.

HP:0011369.name: Mongolian blue spot
HP:0011369.definition: Congenital deep dermal melanosis in the sacral area.

HP:0011370.name: Recurrent cutaneous fungal infections
HP:0011370.definition: Increased susceptibility to cutaneous fungal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of cutaneous fungal infections.

HP:0011371.name: Recurrent viral skin infections
HP:0011371.definition: Increased susceptibility to viral skin infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral skin infections.

HP:0011372.name: Aplasia of the inner ear
HP:0011372.definition: Absence of the inner ear due to a developmental defect.

HP:0011373.name: Incomplete partition of the cochlea
HP:0011373.definition: Incomplete formation of the cochlear partition. The scala vestibuli and scala tympani separated by the cochlear partition, except in the apical turn where the two scalae are in continuity via the helicotrema.

HP:0011374.name: Incomplete partition of the cochlea type I
HP:0011374.definition: Incomplete partition I is also known as cystic cochleovestibular malformation, where the cochlea has no bony modiolus, resulting in an empty cystic cochlea. This is accompanied by a dilated cystic vestibule with developmental arrest at the fifth week of gestation.

HP:0011375.name: Cochlear aplasia
HP:0011375.definition: Absence of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.

HP:0011376.name: Abnormal morphology of the vestibule of the inner ear
HP:0011376.definition: A morphological abnormality of the vestibule, the central part of the osseous labyrinth that is situated medial to the tympanic cavity, behind the cochlea, and in front of the semicircular canals.

HP:0011377.name: Aplasia of the vestibule
HP:0011377.definition: Complete absence of the vestibule of the inner ear.

HP:0011378.name: Hypoplasia of the vestibule of the inner ear
HP:0011378.definition: Underdevelopment of the vestibule of the inner ear.

HP:0011379.name: Dilated vestibule of the inner ear
HP:0011379.definition: Dilatation of the vestibule of the inner ear.

HP:0011380.name: Abnormal semicircular canal morphology
HP:0011380.definition: An abnormality of the morphology of the semicircular canal.

HP:0011383.name: Enlarged semicircular canal
HP:0011383.definition: Increased size of the semicircular canal.

HP:0011384.name: Abnormality of the internal auditory canal
HP:0011384.definition: An abnormality of the Internal acoustic meatus, i.e., of the canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone through which the cranial nerve VII and cranial nerve VIII traverse.

HP:0011385.name: Absent internal auditory canal
HP:0011385.definition: Aplasia of the internal auditory canal.

HP:0011386.name: Narrow internal auditory canal
HP:0011386.definition: Reduction in diameter of the internal auditory canal.

HP:0011387.name: Enlarged vestibular aqueduct
HP:0011387.definition: Increased size of the vestibular aqueduct.

HP:0011388.name: Enlarged cochlear aqueduct
HP:0011388.definition: Increased size of the cochlear duct, i.e., of a duct that communicates between the perilymphatic space and the subarachnoid space, and transmits a vein from the cochlea to join the internal jugular.

HP:0011389.name: Functional abnormality of the inner ear
HP:0011389.definition: An abnormality of the function of the inner ear.

HP:0011390.name: Abnormal inner ear morphology
HP:0011390.definition: A structural anomaly of the internal part of the ear.

HP:0011395.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cochlea
HP:0011395.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.

HP:0011396.name: Abnormality of the cochlear nerve
HP:0011396.definition: Any anomaly of the cohclear nerve, which is the part of the vestibulocochlear nerve that is responsible for transmitting auditory signals from the inner ear to the cochlear nuclei within the brainstem and ultimately to the primary auditory cortex within the temporal lobe.

HP:0011397.name: Abnormality of the dorsal column of the spinal cord
HP:0011397.definition: An abnormality of the dorsal columns, i.e., of the dorsal portion of the gray substance of the spinal cord. The dorsal column consists of the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus and itself is part of the dorsal funiculus.

HP:0011399.name: Tibialis anterior muscle atrophy
HP:0011399.definition: Wasting of the tibialis anterior muscle.

HP:0011400.name: Abnormal CNS myelination
HP:0011400.definition: An abnormality of myelination of nerves in the central nervous system.

HP:0011401.name: Delayed peripheral myelination
HP:0011401.definition: Delayed myelination in the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0011403.name: Abnormal umbilical cord blood vessel morphology

HP:0011404.name: Lethal short-trunk short stature
HP:0011404.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs that is lethal at birth.

HP:0011406.name: Infancy onset short-trunk short stature
HP:0011406.definition: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in infancy.

HP:0011408.name: Moderate intrauterine growth retardation
HP:0011408.definition: Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 3 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 4 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

HP:0011409.name: Abnormal placental membrane morphology
HP:0011409.definition: Structural anomaly of the fetal membranes (also known as the amniochorionic or placental membranes), which comprise a vital intrauterine compartment, where they perform mechanical, immune, and endocrine functions to promote growth of the fetus and protection from environmental adversity. Amniochorionic membranes anatomically consist of a single layer of cuboidal amnion epithelial cells, chorionic trophoblasts, and scattered fibroblasts connected by a layer of type IV collagen-rich extracellular matrix.

HP:0011410.name: Caesarean section
HP:0011410.definition: Delivery of a fetus through surgical incisions made through the abdominal wall (laparotomy) and the uterine wall (hysterotomy).

HP:0011412.name: Ventouse delivery
HP:0011412.definition: Delivery of newborn by means of a ventouse, a vacuum device used to assist the delivery of a baby when the second stage of labor has not progressed adequately.

HP:0011413.name: Shoulder dystocia
HP:0011413.definition: Shoulder dystocia occurs when the fetal anterior shoulder impacts against the maternal symphysis following delivery of the vertex.

HP:0011414.name: Hydropic placenta
HP:0011414.definition: An abnormality of the placenta in which there are numerous cystic spaces within the placenta as well as placental enlargement.

HP:0011417.name: Long umbilical cord
HP:0011417.definition: Increased length of the umbilical cord.

HP:0011418.name: Abnormal insertion of umbilical cord
HP:0011418.definition: Anomalous location of the insertion of umbilical cord in the placenta. Normally, the insertion is at least two centimers distant from the edge of the placenta.

HP:0011419.name: Placental abruption
HP:0011419.definition: Separation of the placenta from the uterus wall before delivery.

HP:0011420.name: Age of death
HP:0011420.definition: The age group when the cessation of life happens.

HP:0011421.name: Death in adolescence
HP:0011421.definition: Death during adolescence, the period between childhood and adulthood (roughly between the ages of 10 and 16 years).

HP:0011422.name: Abnormal blood chloride concentration
HP:0011422.definition: An abnormality of chloride homeostasis or concentration in the body.

HP:0011423.name: Hyperchloremia
HP:0011423.definition: An abnormally increased chloride concentration in the blood.

HP:0011424.name: Increased serum zinc
HP:0011424.definition: An increased concentration of zinc in the blood.

HP:0011425.name: Fetal ultrasound soft marker
HP:0011425.definition: An finding upon obstetric ultrasound examination performed at around 16 to 20 weeks of gestation that is abnormal but not clearly identifiable as a fetal anatomic malformation or growth restriction. Such findings are known as soft markers since they are associated with increased risk for fetal aneuploidy or other disorders.

HP:0011426.name: Fetal choroid plexus cysts
HP:0011426.definition: Fetal choroid plexus cysts (CPCs) are sonographically discrete, small cysts found in the choroid plexus within the lateral cerebral ventricles of the developing fetus at 14 to 24 weeks gestation. Imaging of the choroid plexus is performed in the transverse plane of the fetal head at the same level that the lateral cerebral ventricle is evaluated. The choroid plexus should be inspected bilaterally for the presence of cysts. The size of CPCs is not of clinical relevance (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011427.name: Enlarged fetal cisterna magna
HP:0011427.definition: The cisterna magna is measured on a transaxial view of the fetal head angled 15 degrees caudal to the canthomeatal line. The anterior/posterior diameter is taken between the inferior/posterior surface of the vermis of the cerebellum to the inner surface of the cranium. An enlarged cisternal magna is defined by an anterior/posterior diameter of 10 mm or more (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011428.name: Short fetal femur length
HP:0011428.definition: A short femur length is defined as either a measurement below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or a measurement that is less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The femur should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011429.name: Short fetal humerus length
HP:0011429.definition: A short humerus length is defined as a length below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or as a measurement less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The humerus should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011430.name: Hypoplasia of fetal nasal bone
HP:0011430.definition: On prenatal ultrasound, the nasal bone is a thin echogenic line within the bridge of the fetal nose. The fetus is imaged facing the transducer with the fetal face strictly in the midline. The angle of insonation is 90 degrees, with the longitudinal axis of the nasal bone as the reference line. Calibres are placed at each end of the nasal bone. Absence of the nasal bone or measurements below 2.5th percentile are considered significant (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011431.name: Fetal fifth finger clinodactyly
HP:0011431.definition: Fifth finger clinodactyly is defined by a hypoplastic or absent mid-phalanx of the fifth digit. Ultrasound identification of the fetal hand must first be undertaken and then appropriate magnification accomplished. The evaluation requires stretching of the 5 fingers. The diagnosis is established when the middle phalanx of the fifth finger is markedly smaller than normal or absent, which often causes the finger to be curved inward (PMID:16100637).

HP:0011432.name: Elevated maternal circulating alpha-fetoprotein concentration
HP:0011432.definition: Increase in the levels of maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein levels during pregnancy.

HP:0011433.name: High maternal circulating chorionic gonadotropin concentration
HP:0011433.definition: An abnormally high concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

HP:0011434.name: Low maternal circulating chorionic gonadotropin concentration
HP:0011434.definition: An abnormally low concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

HP:0011435.name: Low maternal circulating PAPP-A concentration
HP:0011435.definition: An abnormally low concentration of serum PAPP-A (pregnancy associated plasma protein A), as compared to normal values for gestational-age.

HP:0011436.name: Abnormal maternal serum screening
HP:0011436.definition: An abnormally elevated or decreased level of a maternal serum marker analytes used in screening for aneuploidy.

HP:0011437.name: Maternal autoimmune disease
HP:0011437.definition: A medical history of a fetus or child born to a mother with an autoimmune disease.

HP:0011438.name: Maternal teratogenic exposure
HP:0011438.definition: A medical history of exposure of the mother of a child or fetus to a teratogenic substance during pregnancy.

HP:0011440.name: Alcohol-induced rhabdomyolysis
HP:0011440.definition: Rhabdomyolysis induced by intake of alcohol.

HP:0011441.name: Abnormal medulla oblongata morphology
HP:0011441.definition: An abnormality of the medulla oblongata, the lower half of the brainstem.

HP:0011442.name: Abnormal central motor function
HP:0011442.definition: An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.

HP:0011444.name: Decorticate rigidity
HP:0011444.definition: A type of rigidity in which the arms are in flexion and adduction and the legs are extended. This signifies a lesion in the cerebral white matter, internal capsules, or thalamus.

HP:0011445.name: Athetoid cerebral palsy
HP:0011445.definition: A type of cerebral palsy characterized by slow, involuntary muscle movement and mixed muscle tone.

HP:0011448.name: Ankle clonus
HP:0011448.definition: Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Ankle clonus is tested by rapidly flexing the foot upward.

HP:0011449.name: Knee clonus
HP:0011449.definition: Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Knee clonus can be tested by rapidly pushing the patella towards the toes.

HP:0011450.name: Unusual CNS infection
HP:0011450.definition: A type of infection of the central nervous system that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

HP:0011451.name: Primary microcephaly
HP:0011451.definition: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender at birth.

HP:0011452.name: Functional abnormality of the middle ear
HP:0011452.definition: An abnormality of the function of the middle ear.

HP:0011453.name: Abnormal incus morphology
HP:0011453.definition: An abnormality of the incus, an ossicle in the middle ear.

HP:0011454.name: Abnormal malleus morphology
HP:0011454.definition: An abnormality of the malleus, an ossicle in the middle ear.

HP:0011457.name: Loss of eyelashes
HP:0011457.definition: This term refers to the loss of eyelashes that were previously present.

HP:0011458.name: Abdominal symptom
HP:0011458.definition: A subjective manifestation of disease localized to the abdomen.

HP:0011459.name: Esophageal carcinoma
HP:0011459.definition: The presence of a carcinoma of the esophagus.

HP:0011460.name: Embryonal onset
HP:0011460.definition: Onset of disease at up to 8 weeks following fertilization (corresponding to 10 weeks of gestation).

HP:0011461.name: Fetal onset
HP:0011461.definition: Onset prior to birth but after 8 weeks of embryonic development (corresponding to a gestational age of 10 weeks).

HP:0011462.name: Young adult onset
HP:0011462.definition: Onset of disease at the age of between 16 and 40 years.

HP:0011463.name: Childhood onset
HP:0011463.definition: Onset of disease at the age of between 1 and 5 years.

HP:0011464.name: Aganglionosis of the small intestine
HP:0011464.definition: A lack of intestinal ganglion cells (i.e., an aganglionic section of bowel) affecting the small intestine.

HP:0011465.name: Duodenal aganglionosis
HP:0011465.definition: A lack of intestinal ganglion cells (i.e., an aganglionic section of bowel) affecting the duodenum.

HP:0011466.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the gallbladder
HP:0011466.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the gallbladder.

HP:0011467.name: Absent gallbladder
HP:0011467.definition: A developmental defect in which the gallbladder fails to form.

HP:0011468.name: Facial tics
HP:0011468.definition: Sudden, repetitive, nonrhythmic motor movements (spasms), involving the eyes and muscles of the face.

HP:0011469.name: Nasal regurgitation
HP:0011469.definition: Regurgitation of milk through the nose.

HP:0011470.name: Nasogastric tube feeding in infancy
HP:0011470.definition: Feeding problem necessitating nasogastric tube feeding.

HP:0011471.name: Gastrostomy tube feeding in infancy
HP:0011471.definition: Feeding problem necessitating gastrostomy tube feeding.

HP:0011473.name: Villous atrophy
HP:0011473.definition: The enteric villi are atrophic or absent.

HP:0011474.name: Childhood onset sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0011474.definition: Sensorineural hearing impairment with childhood onset.

HP:0011475.name: Persistent stapedial artery
HP:0011475.definition: Persistence of the stapedial artery, which normally regresses during embryonic life.

HP:0011476.name: Profound sensorineural hearing impairment
HP:0011476.definition: Complete loss of hearing related to a sensorineural defect.

HP:0011477.name: Upbeat nystagmus
HP:0011477.definition: In primary position, the eyes drift slowly downward and then spontaneously beat upward. Upward gaze accentuates the nystagmus. The associated oscillopsias are often very irritating, but the symptoms are usually transient.

HP:0011478.name: True anophthalmia
HP:0011478.definition: Absence of globe, optic nerve, chiasm and optic tracts. No evidence of ocular tissue on MRI scan or examination.

HP:0011479.name: Abnormal lacrimal punctum morphology
HP:0011479.definition: An abnormality of the lacrimal punctum, an opening on the eyelid close to the medial canthus that drains tears from the conjunctival sac into the lacrimal duct in the same eyelid.

HP:0011480.name: Unilateral microphthalmos
HP:0011480.definition: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one eye.

HP:0011481.name: Abnormal lacrimal duct morphology
HP:0011481.definition: An abnormality of the lacrimal duct, a duct that drain tears from the conjunctiva, via the lacrimal puncta, into the lacrimal sac.

HP:0011482.name: Abnormal lacrimal gland morphology
HP:0011482.definition: Abnormality of the lacrimal gland, i.e., of the almond-shaped gland that secretes the aqueous layer of the tear film for each eye.

HP:0011483.name: Anterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
HP:0011483.definition: Adhesions between the iris and the cornea.

HP:0011484.name: Posterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
HP:0011484.definition: Adhesions between the iris and the lens.

HP:0011485.name: Corneolenticular adhesion
HP:0011485.definition: Developmental abnormality in which the lens and cornea are not separated.

HP:0011486.name: Abnormal corneal thickness
HP:0011486.definition: An abnormal anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.

HP:0011487.name: Increased corneal thickness
HP:0011487.definition: A increased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.

HP:0011488.name: Abnormal corneal endothelium morphology
HP:0011488.definition: Abnormality of the corneal endothelium, that is, the single layer of cells on the inner surface of the cornea.

HP:0011490.name: Abnormal Descemet membrane morphology
HP:0011490.definition: Abnormality of Descemet's membrane, which is the basement membrane of the corneal endothelium.

HP:0011491.name: Reduced number of corneal endothelial cells
HP:0011491.definition: A reduction in the number of corneal endothelial cells.

HP:0011492.name: Abnormal corneal stroma morphology
HP:0011492.definition: An abnormality of the stroma of cornea, also known as the substantia propria of cornea.

HP:0011493.name: Central opacification of the cornea
HP:0011493.definition: Reduced transparency of the central portion of the corneal stroma.

HP:0011494.name: Generalized opacification of the cornea
HP:0011494.definition: Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.

HP:0011495.name: Abnormal corneal epithelium morphology
HP:0011495.definition: Abnormality of the corneal epithelium, that is of the epithelial tissue that covers the front of the cornea.

HP:0011496.name: Corneal neovascularization
HP:0011496.definition: Ingrowth of new blood vessels into the cornea.

HP:0011497.name: Rubeosis iridis
HP:0011497.definition: Formation of new blood vessels on the iris. The new vessels do not display the typical radially symmertic growth pattern of normal iris blood vessels, but rather appear disorganized. Rubeosis usually starts from the pupillary border with tiny tufts of dilated capillaries or red spots that can only be appreciated with high magnification.

HP:0011501.name: Anterior lenticonus
HP:0011501.definition: A conical projection of the anterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

HP:0011502.name: Posterior lenticonus
HP:0011502.definition: A conical projection of the posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.

HP:0011504.name: Bull's eye maculopathy
HP:0011504.definition: Progressive maculopathy characterized by concentric regions of hyper- and hypo-pigmentation.

HP:0011505.name: Cystoid macular edema
HP:0011505.definition: Cystoid macular edema (CME) is any type of macular edema that involves cyst formation.

HP:0011506.name: Choroidal neovascularization
HP:0011506.definition: Choroidal neovascularization (CNV) is the creation of new blood vessels in the choroid layer of the eye.

HP:0011507.name: Macular flecks
HP:0011507.definition: Pale often indistinct lesions of the macula.

HP:0011508.name: Macular hole
HP:0011508.definition: A macular hole is a small break in the macula, located in the center of the retina.

HP:0011509.name: Macular hyperpigmentation
HP:0011509.definition: Increased amount of pigmentation in the macula lutea.

HP:0011510.name: Drusen
HP:0011510.definition: Drusen (singular, 'druse') are tiny yellow or white accumulations of extracellular material (lipofuscin) that build up in Bruch's membrane of the eye.

HP:0011511.name: Macular schisis
HP:0011511.definition: Splitting of the retina in the macular region.

HP:0011513.name: Retinal cavernous hemangioma
HP:0011513.definition: A benign tumor of the retina that appears as a grouping of blood-filled saccules within the inner retinal layers or on the surface of the optic disc. Retinal cavernous angioma are described as having a 'cluster of grapes' appearance.

HP:0011514.name: Abnormality of binocular vision
HP:0011514.definition: An abnormality of binocular vision, that is of the ability to synthesize the visual inputs from both eyes to a single image with perception of depth.

HP:0011515.name: Abnormal stereopsis
HP:0011515.definition: Inability to make fine depth discriminations from parallax provided by the two eyes' different positions on the head.

HP:0011516.name: Achromatopsia
HP:0011516.definition: A condition where the retina contains no functional cone cells, so that in addition to the absence of color discrimination, vision in lights of normal intensity is difficult.

HP:0011517.name: Cone monochromacy
HP:0011517.definition: The condition of having both rods and cones, but only a single kind of cone. Affected individuals have good pattern vision in daylight, but cannot distinguish between colors.

HP:0011518.name: Dichromacy
HP:0011518.definition: Individuals affected by dichromacy possess only two types of cones, instead of three.

HP:0011519.name: Anomalous trichromacy
HP:0011519.definition: Individuals with anomalous trichromacy possess three types of cones, but one of the three types of cones has an abnormal spectral sensitivity compared to normal cones.

HP:0011520.name: Deuteranomaly
HP:0011520.definition: A type of anomalous trichromacy associated with abnormal M photopigment, such that the absorption spectrum is shifted toward L wavelengths. Affected individuals have difficulties distinguishing between red and green.

HP:0011521.name: Deuteranopia
HP:0011521.definition: Complete lack of the M photopigment, which is replaced with the L photopigment. Affected individuals tend to confuse red and green.

HP:0011522.name: Protanopia
HP:0011522.definition: Blue and green cones only; no functional red cones.

HP:0011523.name: Iris cyst
HP:0011523.definition: An iris cyst is composed of a single cell layer of epithelium and is filled with fluid.

HP:0011524.name: Iris melanoma
HP:0011524.definition: Malignant tumor of melanocytes affecting the iris.

HP:0011525.name: Iris nevus
HP:0011525.definition: A benign brown pigmented area over the iris representing proliferation of melanocyte cells in the stromal layer of the iris. An iris nevus can be flat or occasionally slightly elevated.

HP:0011526.name: Abnormality of lens shape
HP:0011526.definition: An abnormal shape of the lens.

HP:0011527.name: Lentiglobus
HP:0011527.definition: Exaggerated curvature of the lens of the eye, producing an anterior or posterior spherical bulging.

HP:0011528.name: Solitary congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium
HP:0011528.definition: Sharply demarcated hyperpigmentation which is congenital found in around 3-5% of the population and of no functional significance.

HP:0011529.name: Multiple bilateral congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium
HP:0011529.definition: Sharply demarcated hyperpigmentation which is congenital.

HP:0011530.name: Retinal hole
HP:0011530.definition: A small break in the retina.

HP:0011531.name: Vitritis
HP:0011531.definition: Inflammation of the vitreous body, characterized by the presence of inflammatory cells and protein exudate in the vitreous cavity.

HP:0011532.name: Subretinal exudate
HP:0011532.definition: A type of retinal exudate located in the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0011533.name: Snowflake vitreoretinal degeneration
HP:0011533.definition: The appearance of yellow/white crystalline-like (hence the name) spots in the retina and thickening of the peripheral part of the vitreous.

HP:0011534.name: Abnormal spatial orientation of the cardiac segments
HP:0011534.definition: Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the cardiac segments to other components of the heart.

HP:0011535.name: Abnormal atrial arrangement
HP:0011535.definition: Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the atria to other components of the heart.

HP:0011536.name: Right atrial isomerism
HP:0011536.definition: Right atrial isomerism is characterized by bilateral triangular, morphologically right atrial, appendages, both joining the atrial chamber along a broad front with internal terminal crest.

HP:0011537.name: Left atrial isomerism
HP:0011537.definition: In left atrial isomerism there is a bilateral small finger-shaped morphologically left atrial appendage joining the atrial chamber along a narrow front without an internal terminal crest.

HP:0011538.name: Atrial situs inversus
HP:0011538.definition: Mirror image atrial arrangement, with morphologic right atrium on the left hand side and morphologic left atrium on the right hand side.

HP:0011539.name: Atrial situs ambiguous
HP:0011539.definition: Common atrium without defining morphologic features.

HP:0011540.name: Congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries
HP:0011540.definition: The essence of the lesion is the combination of discordant atrioventricular and ventriculo-arterial connections. Thus, the morphologically right atrium is connected to a morphologically left ventricle across the mitral valve, with the left ventricle then connected to the pulmonary trunk. The morphologically left atrium is connected to the morphologically right ventricle across the tricuspid valve, with the morphologically right ventricle connected to the aorta.

HP:0011541.name: Criss-cross atrioventricular valves
HP:0011541.definition: Crossing of the inflow streams of the two ventricles, due to an apparent twisting of the heart about its long axis.

HP:0011542.name: Criss-cross atrioventricular valves with superior-inferior ventricles
HP:0011542.definition: Criss-cross atrioventricular valves with a rare cardiac malformation characterized by the two ventricles lying one above the other instead of side by side.

HP:0011543.name: Superior-inferior ventricles without criss-cross atrioventricular valves

HP:0011545.name: Abnormal connection of the cardiac segments
HP:0011545.definition: A deviance in the normal connections between two cardiac segments.

HP:0011546.name: Abnormal atrioventricular connection
HP:0011546.definition: An abnormality of the circulatory connection between atria and ventricles.

HP:0011547.name: Absent left sided atrioventricular connection
HP:0011547.definition: A defect where there is no connection between the left atrium and left ventricle.

HP:0011548.name: Absent right sided atrioventricular connection
HP:0011548.definition: A defect where there is no connection between the right atrium and right ventricle.

HP:0011549.name: Univentricular heart with absent left sided atrioventricular connection

HP:0011550.name: Biventricular heart with straddling right sided atrioventricular valve and absent left sided atrioventricular connection

HP:0011551.name: Right sided atrium to left ventricle and absent left sided atrioventricular connection

HP:0011552.name: Ambiguous atrioventricular connection
HP:0011552.definition: With left or right cardiac isomerism in a biventricular, the atrioventricular connections are perforce ambiguous, in that one of the connections is concordant (e.g., right-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic right ventricle) and one of the connections is discordant (e.g., left-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic left ventricle).

HP:0011553.name: Discordant atrioventricular connection
HP:0011553.definition: Connection of the right atrium to the left ventricle and of the left atrium to the right ventricle in a biventricular heart.

HP:0011554.name: Double inlet atrioventricular connection
HP:0011554.definition: The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve.

HP:0011555.name: Double inlet left ventricle
HP:0011555.definition: The condition in which both atria are joined to the left ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually there is a hypoplastic right ventricle, which may be on the opposite side of the heart as usual.

HP:0011556.name: Double inlet right ventricle
HP:0011556.definition: The condition in which both atria are joined to the right ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually, the left ventricle is hypoplastic.

HP:0011557.name: Double inlet to single ventricle of indeterminate morphology
HP:0011557.definition: The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. The morphology of this ventricle does not allow one to determine if it corresponds to the left or right ventricle.

HP:0011558.name: Double inlet to single ventricle with common atrioventricular orifice

HP:0011559.name: Double inlet to single ventricle with two atrioventricular valves

HP:0011560.name: Mitral atresia
HP:0011560.definition: A congenital defect with failure to open of the mitral valve orifice.

HP:0011561.name: Overriding atrioventricular valve
HP:0011561.definition: An atrioventricular valve that empties into both ventricles. The valve overrides the interventricular septum above a ventricular septum defect.

HP:0011562.name: Straddling atrioventricular valve
HP:0011562.definition: Anomalous insertion of the chordae tendinae or papillary muscles into the contralateral ventricle in the presence of a ventricular septum defect.

HP:0011563.name: Abnormal ventriculoarterial connection
HP:0011563.definition: An abnormality of the circulatory connection between the ventricles and the pulmonary artery and aorta.

HP:0011564.name: Mitral valve arcade
HP:0011564.definition: Anomalous mitral valve arcade is diagnosed based on the following features (1) An adequately sized mitral valve orifice; (2) short, thick, and poorly differentiated chordae with direct union of the papillary muscles to the anterior leaflet; (3) narrow or nearly nonexistent spaces between the abnormal chordae; and (4) greater differentiation of the chordae attached to the posterior papillary muscle.

HP:0011565.name: Common atrium
HP:0011565.definition: Complete absence of the interatrial septum with common atrioventricular valve and two atrioventricular connections.

HP:0011566.name: Cor triatriatum dexter
HP:0011566.definition: A congenital anomaly with partitioning of the right atrium to form a triatrial heart caused by persistence of the right valve of the sinus venosus. Typically, the right atrial partition is due to exaggerated fetal eustachian and thebesian valves, which together form an incomplete septum across the lower part of the atrium. This septum may range from a reticulum to a substantial sheet of tissue.

HP:0010498.name: Bipartite patella
HP:0010498.definition: A developmental defect that occurs if the two halves of the patella fail to fuse in early childhood.

HP:0010499.name: Patellar subluxation
HP:0010499.definition: The kneecap normally is located within the groove termed trochlea on the distal femur and can slide up and down in it. Patellar subluxation refers to an unstable kneecap that does not slide centrally within its groove, i.e., a partial dislocation of the patella.

HP:0010500.name: Hyperextensibility of the knee
HP:0010500.definition: The ability of the knee joint to extend beyond its normal range of motion (the lower leg is moved beyond a straight position with respect to the thigh).

HP:0010501.name: Limitation of knee mobility
HP:0010501.definition: An abnormal limitation of knee joint mobility.

HP:0010502.name: Fibular bowing
HP:0010502.definition: A bending or abnormal curvature of the fibula.

HP:0010503.name: Fibular duplication
HP:0010503.definition: Duplication of the fibula. This may occur as a part of diplopodia (accessory tarsal or metatarsal bone). Diplopodia with double fibula is an extremely rare condition.

HP:0010504.name: Increased length of the tibia
HP:0010504.definition: An abnormal increase in the length of the tibia.

HP:0010505.name: Limitation of movement at ankles
HP:0010505.definition: An abnormal limitation of the mobility of the ankle joint.

HP:0010506.name: Abnormal plantar dermatoglyphics
HP:0010506.definition: An abnormality of dermatoglyphs on the toes and soles, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of sole of foot.

HP:0010507.name: Foot asymmetry
HP:0010507.definition: A difference in size or shape between the left and right foot.

HP:0010508.name: Metatarsus valgus
HP:0010508.definition: A condition in which the anterior part of the foot rotates outward away from the midline of the body and the heel remains straight.

HP:0010510.name: Hypermobility of toe joints
HP:0010510.definition: An ability of the toe joints to move beyond their normal range of motion.

HP:0010511.name: Long toe
HP:0010511.definition: Toes that appear disproportionately long compared to the foot.

HP:0010513.name: Pituitary calcification
HP:0010513.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in the pituitary gland.

HP:0010514.name: Hyperpituitarism
HP:0010514.definition: Hypersecretion of one or more pituitary hormones. This can occur in conditions in which deficiency in the target organ leads to decreased hormonal feedback, or as a primary condition most usually in connection with a pituitary adenoma.

HP:0010515.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thymus
HP:0010515.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the thymus.

HP:0010517.name: Ectopic thymus tissue
HP:0010517.definition: The presence of ectopic thymus tissue. Normally, cells of the ventral bud of the third pharyngeal pouch detach and migrate in the eighth gestational week caudally and medially towards the location of the mature thyroid. They migrate further retrosternally into the superior mediastinum. There are two main ways ectopic thymus tissue can develop. Either cells detach along the descensus path and proliferate, thereby forming accessory thymus tissue, or the entire gland fails to descend.

HP:0010518.name: Thyroglossal cyst
HP:0010518.definition: An abnormality of the thyroid gland owing to the presence of a fibrous cyst resulting from the persistence of the thyroglossal duct.

HP:0010519.name: Increased fetal movement
HP:0010519.definition: An abnormal increase in quantity or strength of fetal movements.

HP:0010521.name: Gait apraxia
HP:0010521.definition: Gait apraxia affecting the ability to make walking movements with the legs.

HP:0010522.name: Dyslexia
HP:0010522.definition: A learning disorder characterized primarily by difficulties in learning to read and spell. Dyslectic children also exhibit a tendency to read words from right to left and to confuse letters such as b and d whose orientation is important for their identification. Children with dyslexia appear to be impaired in phonemic skills (the ability to associate visual symbols with the sounds they represent).

HP:0010523.name: Alexia
HP:0010523.definition: An acquired type of sensory aphasia where damage to the brain leads to the loss of the ability to read.

HP:0010524.name: Disturbed sensory perception
HP:0010524.definition: Alteration or impairment in the processing or interpretation of sensory information can lead to abnormal perceptions or experiences.

HP:0010525.name: Finger agnosia
HP:0010525.definition: The examiner identified the inability to name, move, or touch specific fingers.

HP:0010526.name: Dysgraphia
HP:0010526.definition: A writing disability in the absence of motor or sensory deficits of the upper extremities, resulting in an impairment in the ability to write regardless of the ability to read and not due to intellectual impairment.

HP:0010527.name: Astereognosis
HP:0010527.definition: Tactile agnosia refers to the inability to recognize objects by touch, while the inability to discriminate shape and size by touch is also a related condition.

HP:0010528.name: Prosopagnosia
HP:0010528.definition: Inability to recognize faces of familiar persons.

HP:0010529.name: Echolalia
HP:0010529.definition: Echolalia is the automatic imitative repetition of sounds, words, or phrases in the absence of explicit awareness. The repeated words or phrases are typically odd or used in a non-social manner. These can be words or phrases that the affected individual has heard or invented.

HP:0010530.name: Palatal tremor
HP:0010530.definition: Palatal tremor (PT) is an involuntary, rhythmic and oscillatory movement of the soft palate. PT is a rare type of tremor involving the soft palate. It can be unilateral or bilateral.

HP:0010531.name: Spinal myoclonus
HP:0010531.definition: Spinal myoclonus is generally due to a tumor, infection, injury, or degenerative process of the spinal cord, and is characterized by involuntary rhythmic muscle contractions, usually at a rate of more than one per second. Myoclonus occurs synchronously in several muscles and can be increased in severity and frequency by fatigue or stress, but is usually unaffected by sensory stimuli. Spinal myoclonus ceases during sleep or anesthesia.

HP:0010533.name: Spasmus nutans
HP:0010533.definition: The combination of pendular nystagmus, head nodding, and torticollis.

HP:0010534.name: Transient global amnesia
HP:0010534.definition: A paroxysmal, transient loss of memory function with preservation of immediate recall and remote memory but with a severe impairment of memory for recent events and ability to retain new information.

HP:0010535.name: Sleep apnea
HP:0010535.definition: An intermittent cessation of airflow at the mouth and nose during sleep is known as sleep apnea. Apneas that last at least 10 seconds are considered significant, but individuals with sleep apnea may experience apneas lasting from 20 seconds up to 2 or 3 minutes. Patients may have up to 15 events per hour of sleep.

HP:0010536.name: Central sleep apnea
HP:0010536.definition: Sleep apnea results from a temporary loss of the central drive to the muscles responsible for breathing.

HP:0010537.name: Wide cranial sutures
HP:0010537.definition: An abnormally increased width of the cranial sutures for age-related norms (generally resulting from delayed closure).

HP:0010539.name: Thin calvarium
HP:0010539.definition: The presence of an abnormally thin calvarium.

HP:0010540.name: Advanced pneumatization of cranial sinuses
HP:0010540.definition: A degree of pneumatization that is increased compared to age-related norms.

HP:0010541.name: Cutis gyrata of scalp
HP:0010541.definition: The presence of convoluted folds and furrows formed from thickened skin of the scalp, resembling cerebriform pattern. The scalp has convoluted and elevated folds, 1 to 2 cm in thickness. The convolutions generally cannot be flattened by traction.

HP:0010542.name: Vestibular nystagmus
HP:0010542.definition: Nystagmus due to disturbance of the vestibular system; eye movements are rhythmic, with slow and fast components.

HP:0010543.name: Opsoclonus
HP:0010543.definition: Bursts of large-amplitude multidirectional saccades without intersaccadic interval

HP:0010544.name: Vertical nystagmus
HP:0010544.definition: Vertical nystagmus may present with either up-beating or down-beating eye movements or both. When present in the straight-ahead position of gaze it is referred to as upbeat nystagmus or downbeat nystagmus.

HP:0010545.name: Downbeat nystagmus
HP:0010545.definition: Downbeat nystagmus is a type of fixation nystagmus with the fast phase beating in a downward direction. It generally increases when looking to the side and down and when lying prone.

HP:0010546.name: Muscle fibrillation
HP:0010546.definition: Fine, rapid twitching of individual muscle fibers with little or no movement of the muscle as a whole as ascertained by electromyography (EMG). If a motor neuron or its axon is destroyed, the muscle fibers it innervates undergo denervation atrophy. This leads to hypersensitivity of individual muscle fibers to acetyl choline so that they may contract spontaneously. Isolated activity of individual muscle fibers is generally so fine it cannot be seen through the intact skin, although it can be recorded as a short-duration spike in the EMG.

HP:0010547.name: Muscle flaccidity
HP:0010547.definition: A type of paralysis in which a muscle becomes soft and yields to passive stretching, which results from loss of all or practically all peripheral motor nerves that innervated the muscle. Muscle tone is reduced and the affected muscles undergo extreme atrophy within months of the loss of innervation.

HP:0010548.name: Percussion myotonia
HP:0010548.definition: A localized myotonic contraction in a muscle in reaction to percussion (tapping with the examiner's finger, a rubber percussion hammer, or a similar object).

HP:0010549.name: Weakness due to upper motor neuron dysfunction
HP:0010549.definition: Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Paralysis due to lesions of the principle motor tracts is related to a lesion in the corticospinal, corticobulbar or brainstem descending (subcorticospinal) neurons.

HP:0010550.name: Paraplegia
HP:0010550.definition: Severe or complete weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities.

HP:0010551.name: Paraplegia/paraparesis
HP:0010551.definition: Weakness of both lower extremities with sparing of the upper extremities. Paraplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas paraparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength.

HP:0010553.name: Oculogyric crisis
HP:0010553.definition: An acute dystonic reaction with blepharospasm, periorbital twitches, and protracted fixed staring episodes. There may be a maximal upward deviation of the eyes in the sustained fashion. Oculogyric crisis can be triggered by a number of factors including neuroleptic medications.

HP:0010554.name: Cutaneous finger syndactyly
HP:0010554.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints, or a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two fingers that lies significantly distal to the flexion crease that overlies the metacarpophalangeal joint of the adjacent fingers.

HP:0010557.name: Overlapping fingers
HP:0010557.definition: A finger resting on the dorsal surface of an adjacent digit when the hand is at rest.

HP:0010558.name: Abnormality of the clivus
HP:0010558.definition: An abnormality of the clivus, which is the inclined bony region of the posterior cranial fossa located between the sella turcica and the foramen magnum.

HP:0010559.name: Vertical clivus
HP:0010559.definition: An abnormal vertical orientation of the clivus (which normally forms a kind of slope from the sella turcica down to the region of the foramen magnum).

HP:0010560.name: Undulate clavicles
HP:0010560.definition: An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the clavicles.

HP:0010561.name: Undulate ribs
HP:0010561.definition: An abnormally wavy surface or edge of the ribs.

HP:0010564.name: Bifid epiglottis
HP:0010564.definition: A midline anterior-posterior cleft of the epiglottis that involves at least two-thirds of the epiglottic leaf.
