HP:0012668.name: Vasovagal syncope
HP:0012668.definition: A vasovagal episode or vasovagal syncope is the most common form of reflex syncope. Reflex syncope is a general term used to describe types of syncope resulting from a failure in autoregulation of blood pressure, and ultimately, in cerebral perfusion pressure resulting in transient loss of consciousness. The mechanisms responsible for this are complex and involve both depression of cardiac output as well as a decrease in vascular tone.

HP:0012669.name: Carotid sinus syncope
HP:0012669.definition: An exaggerated response to carotid sinus baroreceptor stimulation resulting in syncope from transient diminished cerebral perfusion.

HP:0012670.name: Orthostatic syncope
HP:0012670.definition: Syncope following a quick change in position from lying down to standing.

HP:0012671.name: Abulia
HP:0012671.definition: Abulia is characterized by difficulty in initiating and sustaining spontaneous movements; the person often appears frozen but will move hesitantly on request. There are frequently substantial reductions in emotional responsiveness, spontaneous speech, and social interaction. The individual appears to be content to remain still and inactive with minimal movement, but moves or reacts hesitantly in response to interactions.

HP:0012672.name: Akinetic mutism
HP:0012672.definition: The combined absence of spontaneous movement (akinesia) and speech (mutism). There may be eye movements consistent with visual tracking and the person may remember the events occurring at the time of the experience of stupor.

HP:0012673.name: Aplasia of the upper vagina
HP:0012673.definition: A failure to develop of the upper vagina.

HP:0012674.name: Aplasia of the lower vagina
HP:0012674.definition: A failure to develop of the lower part of the vagina.

HP:0012675.name: Iron accumulation in brain
HP:0012675.definition: An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in brain tissue.

HP:0012676.name: Copper accumulation in brain
HP:0012676.definition: An anomalous build up of copper (Cu) in the brain.

HP:0012677.name: obsolete Iron accumulation in globus pallidus

HP:0012678.name: Iron accumulation in substantia nigra
HP:0012678.definition: An anomalous build up of iron (Fe) in the substantia nigra.

HP:0012679.name: Widened interpedicular distance
HP:0012679.definition: An increase in the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces.

HP:0012680.name: Abnormality of the pineal gland
HP:0012680.definition: An anomaly of the pineal gland,a small endocrine gland in the brain that produces melatonin.

HP:0012681.name: Abnormal pineal morphology
HP:0012681.definition: A structural abnormality of the pineal gland.

HP:0012682.name: Pineal gland calcification
HP:0012682.definition: Accumulation of calcium salts in the pineal gland.

HP:0012683.name: Pineal cyst
HP:0012683.definition: A glial uniloculated or multiloculated fluid-filled sac that either reside within or completely replace the pineal gland.

HP:0012684.name: Abnormal pineal volume
HP:0012684.definition: An abnormal increase or decrease in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.

HP:0012685.name: Decreased pineal volume
HP:0012685.definition: An abnormal reduction in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.

HP:0012686.name: Increased pineal volume
HP:0012686.definition: An abnormal elevation in the quantity of three-dimensional space taken up by the pineal gland.

HP:0012687.name: Agenesis of pineal gland
HP:0012687.definition: Failure to develop of the pineal gland, defined clinically as the absence of the pineal gland with no indication of the pineal gland even having been present.

HP:0012688.name: Abnormality of pineal physiology
HP:0012688.definition: A functional abnormality of the pineal gland.

HP:0012689.name: Abnormal pineal melatonin secretion
HP:0012689.definition: An anomaly in the amount or timing of melatonin secretion by the pineal gland. Note that melatonin is also synthesized by multiple tissues outside of the pineal gland.

HP:0012690.name: T2 hypointense thalamus
HP:0012690.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting the entire thalamus.

HP:0012691.name: Focal T2 hypointense thalamic lesion
HP:0012691.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the thalamus.

HP:0012692.name: Focal T2 hyperintense thalamic lesion
HP:0012692.definition: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the thalamus.

HP:0012693.name: Abnormal thalamic size
HP:0012693.definition: Deviation from the normal range of size of the thalamus.

HP:0012694.name: Enlarged thalamic volume
HP:0012694.definition: An increase in the quantity of space occupied by the thalamus.

HP:0012695.name: Decreased thalamic volume
HP:0012695.definition: A reduction in the quantity of space occupied by the thalamus.

HP:0012696.name: Abnormal thalamic MRI signal intensity
HP:0012696.definition: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the thalamus.

HP:0012697.name: Small basal ganglia
HP:0012697.definition: Decreased size of the basal ganglia.

HP:0012698.name: Cerebellar gliosis
HP:0012698.definition: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the cerebellum.

HP:0012699.name: Anomaly of lower limb diaphyses
HP:0012699.definition: A structural abnormality of a diaphysis of the leg.

HP:0012700.name: Abnormal large intestine physiology
HP:0012700.definition: A functional anomaly of the large intestine.

HP:0012701.name: Bowel urgency
HP:0012701.definition: A sudden, irresistible need to have a bowel movement.

HP:0012702.name: Tenesmus
HP:0012702.definition: A repeated, painful urge to defecate without excreting stool.

HP:0012703.name: Abnormal subarachnoid space morphology
HP:0012703.definition: Abnormality in the space in the meninges beneath the arachnoid membrane and above the pia mater that contains the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0012704.name: Widened subarachnoid space
HP:0012704.definition: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater.

HP:0012705.name: Abnormal metabolic brain imaging by MRS
HP:0012705.definition: An anomaly of metabolism in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0012706.name: Elevated brain choline level by MRS
HP:0012706.definition: An increase in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0012707.name: Elevated brain lactate level by MRS
HP:0012707.definition: An increase in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0012708.name: Reduced brain N-acetyl aspartate level by MRS
HP:0012708.definition: A decrease in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0012709.name: Abnormal brain choline/creatine ratio by MRS
HP:0012709.definition: A deviation from normal in the ratio of choline to creatine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0012710.name: Ingrown nail
HP:0012710.definition: Excessive growth of a nail laterally into the nail fold.

HP:0012711.name: Delayed ossification of vertebral epiphysis
HP:0012711.definition: A delay in the process of formation and maturation of the epiphysis of one or more vertebrae.

HP:0012712.name: Mild hearing impairment
HP:0012712.definition: The presence of a mild form of hearing impairment.

HP:0012713.name: Moderate hearing impairment
HP:0012713.definition: The presence of a moderate form of hearing impairment.

HP:0012714.name: Severe hearing impairment
HP:0012714.definition: A severe form of hearing impairment.

HP:0012715.name: Profound hearing impairment
HP:0012715.definition: A profound (essentially complete) form of hearing impairment.

HP:0012716.name: Moderate conductive hearing impairment
HP:0012716.definition: The presence of a moderate form of conductive hearing impairment.

HP:0012717.name: Severe conductive hearing impairment
HP:0012717.definition: A severe form of conductive hearing impairment.

HP:0012718.name: Abnormal gastrointestinal tract morphology
HP:0012718.definition: Abnormal structure of the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0012719.name: Functional abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract
HP:0012719.definition: Abnormal functionality of the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0012720.name: Neoplasm of the nose
HP:0012720.definition: Tumor (An abnormal mass of tissue resulting from abnormally dividing cells) of the nasal cavity.

HP:0012721.name: Venous malformation
HP:0012721.definition: A vascular malformation resulting from a developmental error of venous tissue composed of dysmorphic channels lined by flattened endothelium and exhibiting slow turnover. A venous malformation may present as a blue patch on the skin ranging to a soft blue mass. Venous malformations are easily compressible and usually swell in thewhen venous pressure increases (e.g., when held in a dependent position or when a child cries). They may be relatively localized or quite extensive within an anatomic region.

HP:0012722.name: Heart block
HP:0012722.definition: Impaired conduction of cardiac impulse occurring anywhere along the conduction pathway.

HP:0012723.name: Sinoatrial block
HP:0012723.definition: Disturbance in the atrial activation that is caused by transient failure of impulse conduction from the sinoatrial node to the cardiac atria.

HP:0012724.name: Upper eyelid edema
HP:0012724.definition: Edema in the region of the upper eyelid.

HP:0012725.name: Cutaneous syndactyly
HP:0012725.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints, or a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits that lies significantly distal to the flexion crease that overlies the metacarpophalangeal or metatarsophalangeal joint of the adjacent digits.

HP:0012726.name: Episodic hypokalemia
HP:0012726.definition: An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood occurring periodically with a return to normal between the episodes.

HP:0012727.name: Thoracic aortic aneurysm
HP:0012727.definition: An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the thoracic aorta.

HP:0012728.name: Fusiform descending thoracic aortic aneurysm
HP:0012728.definition: A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the descending thoracic aorta that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall

HP:0012729.name: Saccular descending thoracic aortic aneurysm
HP:0012729.definition: An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the descending thoracic aorta that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall

HP:0012730.name: Aglossia
HP:0012730.definition: Absence of the tongue owing to a developmental abnormality.

HP:0012731.name: Ectopic anterior pituitary gland
HP:0012731.definition: Abnormal anatomic location of the anterior pituitary gland.

HP:0012732.name: Anorectal anomaly
HP:0012732.definition: An abnormality of the anus or rectum.

HP:0012733.name: Macule
HP:0012733.definition: A flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin.

HP:0012734.name: Ketotic hypoglycemia
HP:0012734.definition: Low blood glucose is accompanied by elevated levels of ketone bodies in the body.

HP:0012735.name: Cough
HP:0012735.definition: A sudden, audible expulsion of air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation.

HP:0012736.name: Profound global developmental delay
HP:0012736.definition: A profound delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.

HP:0012737.name: Small intestinal polyp
HP:0012737.definition: A discrete abnormal tissue mass that protrudes into the lumen of the small intestine and is attached to the intestinal wall either by a stalk, pedunculus, or a broad base.

HP:0012739.name: Agenesis of the small intestine
HP:0012739.definition: Failure to develop of the small intestine.

HP:0012740.name: Papilloma
HP:0012740.definition: A tumor of the skin or mucous membrane with finger-like projections.

HP:0012741.name: Unilateral cryptorchidism
HP:0012741.definition: Absence of a testis from the scrotum on one side owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.

HP:0012742.name: Thin fingernail
HP:0012742.definition: Fingernail that appears thin when viewed on end.

HP:0012743.name: Abdominal obesity
HP:0012743.definition: Excessive fat around the stomach and abdomen.

HP:0012744.name: Femoral aplasia
HP:0012744.definition: Failure of the femur to develop.

HP:0012745.name: Short palpebral fissure
HP:0012745.definition: Distance between the medial and lateral canthi is more than 2 SD below the mean for age (objective); or, apparently reduced length of the palpebral fissures.

HP:0012746.name: Thin toenail
HP:0012746.definition: Toenail that appears thin when viewed on end.

HP:0012747.name: Abnormal brainstem MRI signal intensity
HP:0012747.definition: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem.

HP:0012748.name: Focal T2 hyperintense brainstem lesion
HP:0012748.definition: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

HP:0012749.name: Focal T2 hypointense brainstem lesion
HP:0012749.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

HP:0012750.name: T2 hypointense brainstem
HP:0012750.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting the entire brainstem.

HP:0012751.name: Abnormal basal ganglia MRI signal intensity
HP:0012751.definition: A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia.

HP:0012752.name: Focal T2 hypointense basal ganglia lesion
HP:0012752.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.

HP:0012753.name: T2 hypointense basal ganglia
HP:0012753.definition: A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting all of the basal ganglia.

HP:0012754.name: CNS hypermyelination
HP:0012754.definition: Increased amount of myelin in the central nervous system.

HP:0012755.name: Enlarged brainstem
HP:0012755.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the brainstem.

HP:0012756.name: CSF polymorphonuclear pleocytosis
HP:0012756.definition: An increased polymorphonuclear cell count in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0012757.name: Abnormal neuron morphology
HP:0012757.definition: A structural anomaly of a neuron. Neurons are electrically excitable cells that transmit signals throughout the body. Neurons employ both electrical and chemical components in the transmission of information. Neurons are connected to other neurons at synapses and connected to effector organs or cells at neuroeffector junctions.

HP:0012758.name: Neurodevelopmental delay
HP:0012758.definition: Neurodevelopmental delay (NDD) refers to delays in the maturation of the brain and central nervous system; infants and young children with NDD may experience delays in the development of one or more skills including gross motor abilities, fine-motor coordination, language abilities and ability to solve increasingly complex problems.

HP:0012759.name: Neurodevelopmental abnormality
HP:0012759.definition: A deviation from normal of the neurological development of a child, which may include any or all of the aspects of the development of personal, social, gross or fine motor, and cognitive abilities.

HP:0012760.name: Reduced social responsiveness
HP:0012760.definition: A reduced ability to participate in the back-and-forth flow of social interaction appropriate to culture and developmental level, which is normally characterized by an influence of the behavior of one person on the behavior of another person. This results in difficulty interacting with others through emotional, physical, or verbal communication.

HP:0012761.name: Absent mastoid
HP:0012761.definition: A developmental anomaly in which the mastoid process fails to form and is thus found to be congenitally absent.

HP:0012762.name: Cerebral white matter atrophy
HP:0012762.definition: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebral white matter.

HP:0012763.name: Paroxysmal dyspnea
HP:0012763.definition: A sudden attack of dyspnea that occurs while the affected person is at rest.

HP:0012764.name: Orthopnea
HP:0012764.definition: A sensation of breathlessness in the recumbent position, relieved by sitting or standing.

HP:0012765.name: Widened cerebellar subarachnoid space
HP:0012765.definition: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebellum.

HP:0012766.name: Widened cerebral subarachnoid space
HP:0012766.definition: An increase in size of the anatomic space between the arachnoid membrane and pia mater in the region surrounding the cerebrum.

HP:0012767.name: Abnormal placental size
HP:0012767.definition: A deviation from normal size of the placenta.

HP:0012769.name: Abnormal arm span
HP:0012769.definition: A deviation from normal of the length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle)

HP:0012770.name: Reduced arm span
HP:0012770.definition: Decreased length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle).

HP:0012771.name: Increased arm span
HP:0012771.definition: Increased length of the arm span (length from one end of an individual's arms measured at the fingertips to the other when raised parallel to the ground at shoulder height at a one-hundred eighty degree angle).

HP:0012772.name: Abnormal upper to lower segment ratio
HP:0012772.definition: A deviation from normal of the relation between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis.

HP:0012773.name: Reduced upper to lower segment ratio
HP:0012773.definition: Decreased ratio between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis. Consider the term Disproportionate tall stature (HP:0001519) if tall stature is also present.

HP:0012774.name: Increased upper to lower segment ratio
HP:0012774.definition: Elevated ratio between the upper and the lower segment of the body, where the lower segment is defined as the length between the top of pubic symphysis to floor, and the upper segment is defined as the top of head to top of pubic symphysis.

HP:0012775.name: Stellate iris
HP:0012775.definition: A lacy pattern or iris pigmentation that resembles the spokes of a bicycle wheel.

HP:0012776.name: Abnormal ciliary body morphology
HP:0012776.definition: A structural anomaly of the ciliary body.

HP:0012777.name: Retinal neoplasm
HP:0012777.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the retina.

HP:0012778.name: Retinal astrocytic hamartoma
HP:0012778.definition: A glial tumor of the retinal nerve fiber layer arising from a retinal astrocyte.

HP:0012779.name: Transient hearing impairment
HP:0012779.definition: Hearing loss that occurs acutely and resolves completely.

HP:0012780.name: Neoplasm of the ear
HP:0012780.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ear.

HP:0012781.name: Mid-frequency hearing loss
HP:0012781.definition: A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the middle frequencies of sound (1000 Hz to 3000 Hz).

HP:0012782.name: Perilobar nephrogenic rest
HP:0012782.definition: A type of nephrogenic rest associated with multiple lesions in the periphery of the renal lobe.

HP:0012783.name: Intralobar nephrogenic rest
HP:0012783.definition: A type of nephrogenic rest usually representing single lesions within the renal lobe, renal sinus, or calyceal walls.

HP:0012784.name: Perinephritis
HP:0012784.definition: Inflammation of the connective and adipose tissues surrounding the kidney.

HP:0012785.name: Flexion contracture of finger
HP:0012785.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion in a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0012786.name: Recurrent cystitis
HP:0012786.definition: Repeated infections of the urinary bladder.

HP:0012788.name: Reticulate pigmentation of oral mucosa
HP:0012788.definition: A net-like pattern of increased pigmentation of the oral cavity.

HP:0012790.name: Abnormal intramembranous ossification
HP:0012790.definition: An anomaly in the process of intramembranous ossification by which flat bones (cranial bones of the skull, i.e., the frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal bones, and the clavicles) are formed.

HP:0012791.name: Abnormal humeral ossification
HP:0012791.definition: An anomaly of the process of formation of bone in the humerus.

HP:0012792.name: Absent ossification of thoracic vertebral bodies
HP:0012792.definition: A lack of bone mineralization of one or more body of thoracic vertebra.

HP:0012793.name: Kinked brainstem
HP:0012793.definition: A kinked appearance of the brainstem, i.e., an exaggerated flexure.

HP:0012794.name: Periventricular white matter hypodensities
HP:0012794.definition: Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

HP:0012795.name: Abnormal optic disc morphology
HP:0012795.definition: A morphological abnormality of the optic disc, i.e., of the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.

HP:0012796.name: Increased cup-to-disc ratio
HP:0012796.definition: An elevation in the ratio of the diameter of the cup of the optic disc to the total diameter of the disk. The optic disc has an orange-pink rim with a pale center (the cup) that does not contain neuroretinal tissue. An increase in this ratio therefore may indicate a decrease in the quantity of healthy neuroretinal cells.

HP:0012797.name: Lymphatic vessel neoplasm
HP:0012797.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from the lymphatic vessels.

HP:0012798.name: Pulmonary lymphangiomyomatosis
HP:0012798.definition: Infiltration of smooth muscle-like cells in lymph vessels as well as the lung (pleura, alveolar septa, bronchi, pulmonary vessels and lymphatics as well as lymph nodes, especially in posterior mediastinum and retroperitoneum). Focal emphysema can develop because of airway narrowing, and the thoracic duct may be obliterated. Pulmonary lymphangiomyomatosis may lead to multiple small cysts with a hamartomatous proliferation of smooth muscle in their walls.

HP:0012799.name: Unilateral facial palsy
HP:0012799.definition: One-sided weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure.

HP:0012800.name: Accessory cranial suture
HP:0012800.definition: A cranial suture that is in addition to canonical membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.

HP:0012801.name: Narrow jaw
HP:0012801.definition: Bigonial distance (lower facial width) more than 2 standard deviations below the mean (objective); or an apparently decreased width of the lower jaw (mandible) when viewed from the front (subjective).

HP:0012802.name: Broad jaw
HP:0012802.definition: Bigonial distance (lower facial width) more than 2 SD above the mean (objective); or an apparently increased width of the lower jaw (mandible) when viewed from the front (subjective).

HP:0012803.name: Anisometropia
HP:0012803.definition: Inequality of refractive power of the two eyes.

HP:0012804.name: Corneal ulceration
HP:0012804.definition: Disruption of the epithelial layer of the cornea with involvement of the underlying stroma.

HP:0012805.name: Iris transillumination defect
HP:0012805.definition: Transmission of light through the iris as visualized upon slit lamp examination or infrared iris transillumination videography. The light passes through defects in the pigmentation of the iris.

HP:0012806.name: Proboscis
HP:0012806.definition: A fleshy, tube-like structure usually located in the midline of the face or just to one side of the midline.

HP:0012807.name: High insertion of columella
HP:0012807.definition: Insertion of the posterior columella superior to the nasal base.

HP:0012808.name: Abnormal nasal base norphology
HP:0012808.definition: An anomaly of the nasal base, which can be conceived of as an imaginary line between the most lateral points of the external inferior attachments of the alae nasi to the face.

HP:0012809.name: Narrow nasal base
HP:0012809.definition: Decreased distance between the attachments of the alae nasi to the face.

HP:0012810.name: Wide nasal base
HP:0012810.definition: Increased distance between the attachments of the alae nasi to the face.

HP:0012811.name: Wide nasal ridge
HP:0012811.definition: Increased width of the nasal ridge.

HP:0012812.name: Fullness of paranasal tissue
HP:0012812.definition: Increased bulk of tissue alongside the nose. The fullness can be caused by both bony and soft tissues.

HP:0012813.name: Unilateral breast hypoplasia
HP:0012813.definition: Underdevelopment of the breast on one side only.

HP:0012814.name: Bilateral breast hypoplasia
HP:0012814.definition: Underdevelopment of the breast on both sides.

HP:0012815.name: Hypoplastic female external genitalia
HP:0012815.definition: Underdevelopment of part or all of the female external reproductive organs (which include the mons pubis, labia majora, labia minora, Bartholin glands, and clitoris).

HP:0012816.name: Right ventricular noncompaction cardiomyopathy
HP:0012816.definition: A predominantly right ventricular variant of isolated noncompaction cardiomyopathy.

HP:0012817.name: Noncompaction cardiomyopathy
HP:0012817.definition: A type of cardiomyopathy characterized anatomically by deep trabeculations in the ventricular wall, which define recesses communicating with the main ventricular chamber.

HP:0012818.name: Biventricular noncompaction cardiomyopathy
HP:0012818.definition: Noncompaction cardiomyopathy that affects both ventricles.

HP:0012820.name: Bilateral vocal cord paralysis
HP:0012820.definition: A loss of the ability to move the vocal fold on both sides.

HP:0012821.name: Unilateral vocal cord paresis
HP:0012821.definition: Decreased strength of the vocal fold on one side.

HP:0012822.name: Bilateral vocal cord paresis
HP:0012822.definition: Decreased strength of the vocal fold on both sides.

HP:0012823.name: Clinical modifier
HP:0012823.definition: This subontology is designed to provide terms to characterize and specify the phenotypic abnormalities defined in the Phenotypic abnormality subontology, with respect to severity, laterality, age of onset, and other aspects.

HP:0012824.name: Severity
HP:0012824.definition: The intensity or degree of a manifestation.

HP:0012825.name: Mild
HP:0012825.definition: Having a relatively minor degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between two and three standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

HP:0012826.name: Moderate
HP:0012826.definition: Having a medium degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between three and four standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

HP:0012827.name: Borderline
HP:0012827.definition: Having a minor degree of severity that is considered to be on the boundary between the normal and the abnormal ranges. For quantitative traits, a deviation of that is less than two standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

HP:0012828.name: Severe
HP:0012828.definition: Having a high degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of between four and five standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

HP:0012829.name: Profound
HP:0012829.definition: Having an extremely high degree of severity. For quantitative traits, a deviation of more than five standard deviations from the appropriate population mean.

HP:0012830.name: Position
HP:0012830.definition: The anatomical localization of the specified phenotypic abnormality.

HP:0012831.name: Laterality
HP:0012831.definition: The localization with respect to the side of the body of the specified phenotypic abnormality.

HP:0012832.name: Bilateral
HP:0012832.definition: Being present on both sides of the body.

HP:0012833.name: Unilateral
HP:0012833.definition: Being present on only the left or only the right side of the body.

HP:0012834.name: Right
HP:0012834.definition: Being located on the right side of the body.

HP:0012835.name: Left
HP:0012835.definition: Being located on the left side of the body.

HP:0012836.name: Spatial pattern
HP:0012836.definition: The pattern by which a phenotype affects one or more regions of the body.

HP:0012837.name: Generalized
HP:0012837.definition: Affecting all regions without specificity of distribution.

HP:0009393.name: Absent epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009393.definition: Absence of one or more epiphyses of the 4th finger.

HP:0009394.name: Bracket epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009394.definition: An abnormality of the fourth finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009395.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009395.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

HP:0009396.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009396.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009397.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009397.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger.

HP:0009398.name: Irregular epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009398.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 4th finger.

HP:0009399.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009399.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 4th finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009400.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009400.definition: A secondary ossification center in the fourth finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009401.name: Small epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009401.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 4th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009402.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009402.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 4th finger.

HP:0009403.name: Triangular epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009403.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 4th finger of the hand.

HP:0009404.name: Broad phalanges of the 4th finger
HP:0009404.definition: Increased width of the phalanges of the 4th finger.

HP:0009405.name: Bullet-shaped phalanges of the 4th finger
HP:0009405.definition: A fourth finger with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009406.name: Patchy sclerosis of 4th finger phalanx
HP:0009406.definition: Uneven increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fourth (ring) finger.

HP:0009407.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 4th finger
HP:0009407.definition: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 4th finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009408.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 4th finger

HP:0009410.name: Absent epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009410.definition: Absence of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009411.name: Bracket epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009411.definition: An abnormality of the third finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009412.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009412.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

HP:0009413.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009413.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009414.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009414.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009415.name: Irregular epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009415.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009416.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009416.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009417.name: Pseudoepiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009417.definition: A secondary ossification center in the third finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009418.name: Small epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009418.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009419.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009419.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009420.name: Triangular epiphyses of the 3rd finger
HP:0009420.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger of the hand.

HP:0009421.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0009422.name: Broad distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009422.definition: Increased width of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009423.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009423.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger is affected.

HP:0009424.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009424.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009425.name: Patchy sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009425.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the third finger.

HP:0009426.name: Distal/middle symphalangism of 3rd finger
HP:0009426.definition: Fusion of the terminal/distal and middle phalanges of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009427.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009427.definition: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009428.name: Curved distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009428.definition: Curved appearance of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009429.name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009429.definition: Absence of the distal phalanx of the middle (3rd) finger.

HP:0009430.name: Broad middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009430.definition: Increased width of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009431.name: Bullet-shaped middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009431.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger is affected.

HP:0009432.name: Curved middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009432.definition: Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger.

HP:0009433.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009433.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009434.name: Patchy sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009434.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the middle phalanx of the third finger.

HP:0009435.name: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of 3rd finger
HP:0009435.definition: Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger with another bone.

HP:0009436.name: Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009436.definition: Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009437.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0009438.name: Absent middle phalanx of 3rd finger
HP:0009438.definition: Absence of the middle phalanx of the middle (3rd) finger.

HP:0009439.name: Short middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009439.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the middle phalanx of the third finger.

HP:0009440.name: Broad phalanges of the 3rd finger
HP:0009440.definition: Increased width of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009441.name: Bullet-shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger
HP:0009441.definition: A third finger with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009442.name: Curved phalanges of the 3rd finger
HP:0009442.definition: Curved appearance of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009443.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 3rd finger
HP:0009443.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009444.name: Patchy sclerosis of 3rd finger phalanx
HP:0009444.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third finger.

HP:0009445.name: Symphalangism of the 3rd finger
HP:0009445.definition: Fusion of two or more bones of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009446.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger
HP:0009446.definition: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009447.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd finger

HP:0009448.name: obsolete Aplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd finger

HP:0009449.name: obsolete Hypoplastic/small phalanges of the 3rd finger

HP:0009450.name: Broad proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009450.definition: Increased width of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009451.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009451.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger is affected.

HP:0009452.name: Curved proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009452.definition: Curved appearance of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009453.name: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009453.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009454.name: Patchy sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009454.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.

HP:0009455.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009455.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with another bone.

HP:0009456.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009456.definition: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 3rd (middle) finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009457.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0009458.name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009458.definition: Absence of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009459.name: Short proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
HP:0009459.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.

HP:0009462.name: Radial deviation of the 3rd finger
HP:0009462.definition: Displacement of the 3rd finger towards the radial side (i.e., towards the thumb).

HP:0009463.name: Ulnar deviation of the 3rd finger
HP:0009463.definition: Displacement of the 3rd finger towards the ulnar side (i.e., towards the ring finger).

HP:0009464.name: Ulnar deviation of the 2nd finger
HP:0009464.definition: Displacement of the 2nd (index) finger towards the ulnar side.

HP:0009465.name: Ulnar deviation of finger
HP:0009465.definition: Bending or curvature of a finger toward the ulnar side (i.e., away from the thumb). The deviation is at the metacarpal-phalangeal joint, and this finding is distinct from clinodactyly.

HP:0009466.name: Radial deviation of finger
HP:0009466.definition: Bending or curvature of a finger toward the radial side (i.e., towards the thumb). The deviation is at the metacarpal-phalangeal joint, and this finding is distinct from clinodactyly.

HP:0009467.name: Radial deviation of the 2nd finger
HP:0009467.definition: Displacement of the 2nd finger towards the radial side.

HP:0009468.name: Deviation of the 2nd finger
HP:0009468.definition: Displacement of the 2nd finger from its normal position.

HP:0009469.name: Contracture of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger
HP:0009469.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009470.name: Contracture of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 3rd finger
HP:0009470.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009471.name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger
HP:0009471.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 3rd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009473.name: Joint contracture of the hand
HP:0009473.definition: Contractures of one ore more joints of the hands meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009477.name: Proximal/middle symphalangism of 4th finger
HP:0009477.definition: Fusion of the proximal and middle phalanges of the 4th finger.

HP:0009478.name: Symphalangism of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger with the 4th metacarpal
HP:0009478.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger with the 4th metacarpal.

HP:0009482.name: Proximal/middle symphalangism of 3rd finger
HP:0009482.definition: Fusion of the proximal and middle phalanges of the 3rd finger.

HP:0009483.name: Symphalangism of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with the 3rd metacarpal
HP:0009483.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with the 3rd metacarpal.

HP:0009484.name: Deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
HP:0009484.definition: Displacement of the hand or of fingers of the hand from their normal position.

HP:0009485.name: Radial deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand

HP:0009486.name: Radial deviation of the hand
HP:0009486.definition: An abnormal position of the hand in which the wrist is bent toward the radius (i.e., toward the thumb).

HP:0009487.name: Ulnar deviation of the hand
HP:0009487.definition: Divergence of the longitudinal axis of the hand at the wrist in a posterior (ulnar) direction (i.e., towards the little finger).

HP:0009488.name: Absent epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009488.definition: Absence of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009489.name: Bracket epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009489.definition: An abnormality of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009490.name: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009490.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

HP:0009491.name: Enlarged epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009491.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009492.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009492.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009493.name: Irregular epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009493.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009494.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009494.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009495.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the 2nd finger
HP:0009495.definition: A secondary ossification center in the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009496.name: Small epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009496.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009497.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009497.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009498.name: Triangular epiphyses of the 2nd finger
HP:0009498.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger of the hand.

HP:0009499.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009500.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009501.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009502.name: Absent epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009502.definition: Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009503.name: Bracket epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009503.definition: An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009504.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009504.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

HP:0009505.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009505.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009506.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009506.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009507.name: Irregular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009507.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009508.name: Ivory epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009508.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009509.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009509.definition: A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009510.name: Small epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009510.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009511.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009511.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009512.name: Triangular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009512.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.

HP:0009513.name: Absent epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009514.name: Bracket epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009514.definition: An abnormality of the middle phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009515.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009516.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009517.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009518.name: Irregular epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009519.name: Ivory epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009520.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009520.definition: A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009521.name: Small epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009522.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009523.name: Triangular epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009524.name: Absent epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009525.name: Bracket epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009525.definition: An abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009526.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009527.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009528.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009529.name: Irregular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009530.name: Ivory epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009531.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009531.definition: A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanx of the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

HP:0009532.name: Small epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009533.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009534.name: Triangular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009536.name: Short 2nd finger
HP:0009536.definition: Hypoplasia of the second finger, also known as the index finger.

HP:0009537.name: Flexion contracture of the 2nd finger
HP:0009537.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion in the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 2nd finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

HP:0009538.name: Contracture of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger
HP:0009538.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the distal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009539.name: Contracture of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 2nd finger
HP:0009539.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009540.name: Contracture of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger
HP:0009540.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0009541.name: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 2nd finger
HP:0009541.definition: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 2nd (index) finger.

HP:0009542.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009543.name: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009544.name: Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009546.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 2nd finger
HP:0009546.definition: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009548.name: Bullet-shaped phalanges of the 2nd finger
HP:0009548.definition: A second finger with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009550.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 2nd finger

HP:0009551.name: Patchy sclerosis of 2nd finger phalanx
HP:0009551.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009552.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd finger

HP:0009553.name: Abnormality of the hairline
HP:0009553.definition: The hairline refers to the outline of hair of the head. An abnormality of the hairline can refer to an unusually low or high border between areas of the scalp with and without hair or to abnormal projections of scalp hair.

HP:0009554.name: Preauricular hair displacement
HP:0009554.definition: An tongue-like extension of hair towards the cheeks, in which hair growth extends in front of the ear to the lateral cheekbones.

HP:0009557.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009558.name: Broad distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009558.definition: Increased width of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009559.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009559.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.

HP:0009560.name: Curved distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009560.definition: Curved appearance of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009561.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009561.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009562.name: Patchy sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009562.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009563.name: Distal/middle symphalangism of 2nd finger
HP:0009563.definition: Fusion of the terminal/distal and middle phalanges of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009564.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009564.definition: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009565.name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009566.name: Short distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009566.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the distal phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009568.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009569.name: Broad middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009569.definition: Increased width of the middle phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009570.name: Bullet-shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009570.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.

HP:0009571.name: Curved middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009571.definition: Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009572.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009572.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009573.name: Patchy sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009573.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the middle phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009574.name: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of 2nd finger
HP:0009574.definition: Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.

HP:0009575.name: Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009575.definition: Triangular shaped middle phalanx of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009576.name: Absent middle phalanx of 2nd finger
HP:0009576.definition: Absence of the middle phalanx of the index (2nd) finger.

HP:0009577.name: Short middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009577.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the middle phalanx of the second finger, also known as the index finger.

HP:0009579.name: Proximal/middle symphalangism of the 2nd finger
HP:0009579.definition: Fusion of the proximal and middle phalanges of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009580.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0009581.name: Broad proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009581.definition: Increased width of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009582.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009582.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger is affected.

HP:0009583.name: Curved proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009583.definition: Curved appearance of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009584.name: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009584.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009585.name: Patchy sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009585.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009586.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009586.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.

HP:0009587.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009587.definition: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009588.name: Vestibular schwannoma
HP:0009588.definition: A vestibular schwannoma (also known as acoustic neuroma, acoustic neurinoma, or acoustic neurilemoma) is a benign, usually slow-growing tumor that develops from the VIIIth cranial nerve supplying the inner ear.

HP:0009591.name: Abnormal vestibulocochlear nerve morphology
HP:0009591.definition: Any structural anomaly of the vestibulocochlear nerve. The vestibulocochlear nerve consists of the vestibular and cochlear nerves, also known as cranial nerve eight (CN VIII). Each nerve has distinct nuclei within the brainstem. The vestibular nerve is primarily responsible for maintaining body balance and eye movements, while the cochlear nerve is responsible for hearing.

HP:0009592.name: Astrocytoma
HP:0009592.definition: Astrocytoma is a neoplasm of the central nervous system derived from astrocytes. Astrocytes are a type of glial cell, and thus astrocytoma is a subtype of glioma.

HP:0009593.name: Peripheral schwannoma
HP:0009593.definition: The presence of a peripheral schwannoma.

HP:0009594.name: Retinal hamartoma
HP:0009594.definition: A hamartoma (a benign, focal malformation consisting of a disorganized mixture of cells and tissues) of the retina.

HP:0009596.name: Aplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009596.definition: Absence of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger.

HP:0009597.name: Short proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
HP:0009597.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the proximal phalanx of the second finger.

HP:0009598.name: Symphalangism of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger with the 2nd metacarpal
HP:0009598.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger with the 2nd metacarpal.

HP:0009599.name: Abnormality of thumb epiphysis
HP:0009599.definition: Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the proximal, and distal phalanges of the thumb and/or the 1st metacarpal.

HP:0009600.name: Thumb contracture
HP:0009600.definition: Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the thumb joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin. The term camptodactyly is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

HP:0009602.name: Abnormality of thumb phalanx
HP:0009602.definition: A structural anomaly of one or more phalanges of the thumb.

HP:0009603.name: Deviation of the thumb
HP:0009603.definition: Displacement of the thumb from its normal position.

HP:0009606.name: Complete duplication of distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009606.definition: Complete duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. On x-ray two separate bones appear side to side.

HP:0009608.name: Complete duplication of proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009608.definition: Complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. On x-ray two separate bones appear side to side. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009609.name: Duplication of the 1st metacarpal
HP:0009609.definition: Partail or complete duplication of the first metacarpal bone.

HP:0009611.name: Bifid distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009611.definition: Partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx) to a partially fused appearance of the two bones.

HP:0009612.name: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009612.definition: Complete or partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side.

HP:0009613.name: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009613.definition: Complete or partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009614.name: Bifid proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009614.definition: This term applies if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is partially duplicated. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx) to a partially fused appearance of the two bones. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009615.name: Complete duplication of the first metacarpal
HP:0009615.definition: Complete duplication of the first metacarpal bone.

HP:0009616.name: Bifid first metacarpal
HP:0009616.definition: Partial duplication of the first metacarpal bone.

HP:0009617.name: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009617.definition: Any anomaly of the distal phalanx of thumb.

HP:0009618.name: Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009618.definition: An anomaly of the shape or form of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009620.name: obsolete Radial deviation of the thumb

HP:0009621.name: obsolete Ulnar deviation of the thumb

HP:0009622.name: Distally placed thumb
HP:0009622.definition: Insertion of thumb at a more distal location than normal.

HP:0009624.name: Carpometacarpal thumb joint contracture
HP:0009624.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the carpometacarpal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is formed by the first metacarpal and the trapezial bone and is also called Articulatio carpometacarpalis pollicis, carpometacarpal articulation of thumb, carpometacarpal joint of thumb or first carpometacarpal articulation. Seldom referred to as thumb saddle joint.

HP:0009625.name: Metacarpophalangeal thumb joint contracture
HP:0009625.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the metacarpophalangeal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is also called Articulatio metacarpophalangealis pollicis.

HP:0009626.name: Interphalangeal thumb joint contracture
HP:0009626.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. This joint is also called Articulatio interphalangealis pollicis.

HP:0009629.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009629.definition: This term applies if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is either small/hypoplastic or absent. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009630.name: Broad proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009630.definition: Increased width of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009631.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009631.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the proximal phalanx of the thumb is affected.

HP:0009632.name: Curved proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009632.definition: A deviation from the normal straight shape of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009633.name: Osteolytic defect of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009633.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009634.name: Patchy sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009634.definition: An uneven increase in bone density of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009635.name: Synostosis of thumb phalanx
HP:0009635.definition: Fusion of a phalanx of the thumb with another bone.

HP:0009636.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009636.definition: Triangular shaped proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009637.name: Absent proximal phalanx of thumb
HP:0009637.definition: Absence of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009638.name: Short proximal phalanx of thumb
HP:0009638.definition: Hypoplastic (short) proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009640.name: Synostosis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with the 1st metacarpal
HP:0009640.definition: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with the 1st metacarpal.

HP:0009641.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the thumb

HP:0009642.name: Broad distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009642.definition: Increased width of the distal phalanx of thumb.

HP:0009643.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009643.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the distal phalanx of the thumb is affected.

HP:0009644.name: Curved distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009644.definition: A deviation from the normal straight shape of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009645.name: Osteolytic defect of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009645.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009646.name: Patchy sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009646.definition: An uneven increase in bone density of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009648.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009648.definition: Triangular shaped distal phalanx of the thumb. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

HP:0009649.name: Aplasia of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009649.definition: Absence of the distal/terminal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009650.name: Short distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009650.definition: Hypoplastic (short) distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009652.name: Bullet-shaped thumb phalanx
HP:0009652.definition: An abnormal morphology of one or more phalanges of the thumb, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009653.name: Curved thumb phalanx
HP:0009653.definition: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a thumb phalanx.

HP:0009654.name: Osteolytic defect of thumb phalanx
HP:0009654.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of one or more phalanges of the thumb.

HP:0009655.name: Patchy sclerosis of thumb phalanx
HP:0009655.definition: An uneven increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the thumb.

HP:0009656.name: Symphalangism of the thumb
HP:0009656.definition: Congenital fusion (ankylosis) of the interphalangeal joint of the thumb.

HP:0009657.name: Triangular shaped thumb phalanx
HP:0009657.definition: Abnormal shape of one or more phalanges of the thumb such that affected phalanges resemble a triangle.

HP:0009658.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the thumb

HP:0009659.name: Partial absence of thumb
HP:0009659.definition: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a thumb.

HP:0009662.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009662.definition: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb. This epiphysis is located on the proximal end of the phalanx.

HP:0009663.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009663.definition: This term applies if the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb, which is located at the proximal end of the phalanx, does not appear in concordance with gender and age dependant norms as seen on x-rays. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009664.name: Absent epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009664.definition: Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009665.name: Bracket epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009665.definition: An abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the thumb in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009666.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009666.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009667.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009667.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009668.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009668.definition: Epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.

HP:0009669.name: Irregular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009669.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009670.name: Ivory epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009670.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009671.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009671.definition: A pseudoepiphysis (which is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis) of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009672.name: Small epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009672.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009673.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009673.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009674.name: Triangular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009674.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009675.name: Absent epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009675.definition: Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009676.name: Bracket epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
