HP:0009676.definition: An abnormality of the distal phalanx of the thumb in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009677.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009677.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

HP:0009678.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009678.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009679.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009679.definition: Epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.

HP:0009680.name: Irregular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009680.definition: Uneven radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009681.name: Ivory epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009681.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009682.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009682.definition: A pseudoepiphysis (which is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis) of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009683.name: Small epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009683.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the distal phalanx of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009684.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009684.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0009685.name: Triangular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0009685.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the thumb of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.

HP:0009686.name: Absent epiphyses of the thumb
HP:0009686.definition: Absence of one or more epiphyses of the thumb.

HP:0009687.name: Bracket epiphyses of the thumb
HP:0009687.definition: An abnormality of the thumb in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

HP:0009688.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the thumb
HP:0009688.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the thumb, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

HP:0009689.name: Enlarged thumb epiphysis
HP:0009689.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009690.name: Fragmentation of thumb epiphysis
HP:0009690.definition: Epiphysis of the thumb having multiple bony fragments.

HP:0009691.name: Irregular thumb epiphysis
HP:0009691.definition: Uneven radiographic opacity of the one or more epiphyses of the thumb.

HP:0009692.name: Ivory epiphysis of the thumb
HP:0009692.definition: Sclerosis of one or more of the epiphyses of the thumb, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009693.name: Pseudoepiphysis of the thumb
HP:0009693.definition: A pseudoepiphysis (which is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis) of one or more phalanges of the thumb.

HP:0009694.name: Small thumb epiphysis
HP:0009694.definition: Abnormally small size of one or more of the epiphyses of the thumb with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009695.name: Stippling of thumb epiphysis
HP:0009695.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more of the epiphyses of the thumb.

HP:0009697.name: Contracture of the distal interphalangeal joint of the fingers
HP:0009697.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion in one or more distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers.

HP:0009699.name: Osteolytic defects of the hand bones

HP:0009700.name: Finger symphalangism
HP:0009700.definition: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the fingers. The synonymous term "symphalangism of the hand" may be translated as fusions of bones of varying digree, that involve at least one phalangeal bone of the hand. If bony fusions are referred to as "Symphalangism" the fusion occurs in a proximo-distal axis. Fusions of bones of the fingers in a radio-ulnar axis are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly.

HP:0009701.name: Metacarpal synostosis
HP:0009701.definition: Fusion involving two or more metacarpal bones (A synostosis of the first metacarpal and the proximal phalanx of the thumb can also be observed, note that the first metacarpal bone corresponds to a proximal phalanx).

HP:0009702.name: Carpal synostosis
HP:0009702.definition: Synostosis (bony fusion) involving one or more bones of the carpus (scaphoid, lunate, triquetrum, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, hamate, pisiform).

HP:0009703.name: Synostosis involving the 1st metacarpal
HP:0009703.definition: Fusion of the 1st metacarpal with another bone. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2 to 5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

HP:0009704.name: Chronic CSF lymphocytosis
HP:0009704.definition: Chronic cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) lymphocytosis is defined as the finding, in at least two serial CSF examinations, of more than 5 cells per cubic millimeter.

HP:0009709.name: Increased CSF interferon alpha
HP:0009709.definition: Increased concentration of interferon alpha in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0009710.name: Chilblains
HP:0009710.definition: Chilblains, also called perniosis, are an inflammatory skin condition related to an abnormal vascular response to the cold. We are unaware of a reliable estimate of incidence. It typically presents as tender, pruritic red or bluish lesions located symmetrically on the dorsal aspect of the fingers, toes, ears and nose. Less commonly, reports describe involvement of the thighs and buttocks. The lesions present hours after exposure to cold and usually resolve spontaneously in one to three weeks.

HP:0009711.name: Retinal capillary hemangioma
HP:0009711.definition: A benign vascular tumor of the retina without any neoplastic characteristics.

HP:0009713.name: Spinal hemangioblastoma
HP:0009713.definition: A hemangioblastoma of the spinal cord.

HP:0009715.name: Papillary cystadenoma of the epididymis
HP:0009715.definition: A cystadenoma, an epithelial tumor, that originates within the head of the epididymis.

HP:0009716.name: Subependymal nodules
HP:0009716.definition: Small nodular masses which originate in the subependymal region of the lateral ventricles and protrude into the ventricular cavity. They may represent subependymal hamartomas of tuberous sclerosis.

HP:0009717.name: Cortical tubers
HP:0009717.definition: Cortical tubers in the brain are hamartomatous lesions typically located at the gray-white matter interface, commonly in the frontal and parietal lobes. Cortical tubers are composed of abnormal glial and neural cells, and the size, number, and location vary among patients.

HP:0009718.name: Subependymal giant-cell astrocytoma
HP:0009718.definition: A demarcated, largely intraventricular tumor in the region of the foramen of Monro composed of spindle to large plump or ganglion-like cells with eosinophilic to amphophilic cytoplasm and somewhat pleomorphic nuclei with occasional prominent nucleoli. These tumors are almost always associated with tuberous sclerosis.

HP:0009719.name: Hypomelanotic macule
HP:0009719.definition: Hypomelanotic macules ("ash leaf spots") are white or lighter patches of skin that may appear anywhere on the body and are caused by a lack of melanin. White ash leaf-shaped macules are considered to be characteristic of tuberous sclerosis.

HP:0009720.name: Adenoma sebaceum
HP:0009720.definition: The presence of a sebaceous adenoma with origin in the sebum secreting cells of the skin.

HP:0009721.name: Shagreen patch
HP:0009721.definition: A plaque representing a connective-tissue nevus. Connective tissue naevi are uncommon skin lesions that occur when the deeper layers of the skin do not develop correctly or the components of these layers occur in the wrong proportion. Shagreen patches are oval-shaped and nevoid, skin-colored or occasionally pigmented, smooth or crinkled. The word shagreen refers to a type of roughened untanned leather.

HP:0009722.name: Dental enamel pits
HP:0009722.definition: The presence of small depressions in the dental enamel.

HP:0009723.name: Abnormal subungual morphology
HP:0009723.definition: A lesion located beneath a fingernail or toenail.

HP:0009724.name: Subungual fibromas
HP:0009724.definition: The presence of fibromata beneath finger or toenails.

HP:0009725.name: Bladder neoplasm
HP:0009725.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary bladder.

HP:0009726.name: Renal neoplasm
HP:0009726.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the kidney.

HP:0009727.name: Achromatic retinal patches
HP:0009727.definition: Areas of the retina lacking pigmentation. Punched out areas of chorioretinal hypopigmentation less than 1 disk diameter in size and tending to be located in the midperiphery of the retina.

HP:0009728.name: Neoplasm of striated muscle
HP:0009728.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumor) originating in striated muscle, either skeletal muscle or cardiac muscle.

HP:0009729.name: Cardiac rhabdomyoma
HP:0009729.definition: A benign tumor of cardiac striated muscle.

HP:0009730.name: Rhabdomyoma
HP:0009730.definition: A benign tumor of striated muscle.

HP:0009731.name: Cerebral hamartoma
HP:0009731.definition: The presence of a hamartoma of the cerebrum.

HP:0009732.name: Plexiform neurofibroma
HP:0009732.definition: A neurofibroma in which Schwann cells proliferate inside the nerve sheath, producing an irregularly thickened, distorted, tortuous structure.

HP:0009733.name: Glioma
HP:0009733.definition: The presence of a glioma, which is a neoplasm of the central nervous system originating from a glial cell (astrocytes or oligodendrocytes).

HP:0009734.name: Optic nerve glioma
HP:0009734.definition: A glioma originating in the optic nerve or optic chiasm.

HP:0009735.name: Spinal neurofibroma
HP:0009735.definition: A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the spine.

HP:0009736.name: Tibial pseudarthrosis
HP:0009736.definition: Pseudarthrosis, or "false joint" of the tibia is the result of a developmental failure in the tibia progressing to spontaneous fracture and subsequent fibrous nonunion. The fracture is rarely present at birth but commonly develops during the first 18 months of life.

HP:0009737.name: Lisch nodules
HP:0009737.definition: The presence of pigmented, oval and dome-shaped raised hamartomatous nevi of the iris..

HP:0009741.name: Nephrosclerosis
HP:0009741.definition: Nephrosclerosis refers to thickening or scarring ("sclerosis") resulting from damage to the renal arterioles, also referred to as arteriosclerosis of the kidney arteries.

HP:0009742.name: Stiff shoulders
HP:0009742.definition: Shoulder joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in shoulders when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity.

HP:0009744.name: Abnormal spinal dura mater morphology
HP:0009744.definition: An abnormality of the spinal dura mater, which is the outermost of the three layers of the meninges surrounding the spinal cord.

HP:0009745.name: Spinal arachnoid cyst
HP:0009745.definition: Presence of arachnoid cysts of the spinal canal extradurally in the epidural space.

HP:0009746.name: Thick nasal septum
HP:0009746.definition: Abnormally increased thickness of the nasal septum.

HP:0009747.name: Lumbosacral hirsutism
HP:0009747.definition: Abnormally increased hair growth in the lumbosacral region.

HP:0009748.name: Large earlobe
HP:0009748.definition: Increased volume of the earlobe, that is, abnormally prominent ear lobules.

HP:0009751.name: Aplasia of the pectoralis major muscle
HP:0009751.definition: Absence of the pectoralis major muscle.

HP:0009752.name: Cleft in skull base
HP:0009752.definition: A bony defect in the skull base.

HP:0009754.name: Fibrous syngnathia
HP:0009754.definition: Complete or nearly complete soft tissue fusion of the alveolar ridges.

HP:0009755.name: Ankyloblepharon
HP:0009755.definition: Partial fusion of the upper and lower eyelid margins by single or multiple bands of tissue.

HP:0009756.name: Popliteal pterygium
HP:0009756.definition: A pterygium (or pterygia) occurring in the popliteal region (the back of the knee).

HP:0009757.name: Intercrural pterygium
HP:0009757.definition: A pterygium (or pterygia) in the intercrural (groin) region.

HP:0009758.name: Pyramidal skinfold extending from the base to the top of the nails
HP:0009758.definition: Pyramidal skinfold extending from the base to the top of the nails is a rare and distinctive anomaly seen in popliteal pterygia syndrome.

HP:0009760.name: Antecubital pterygium
HP:0009760.definition: Pterygium affecting the elbow. This is a cutaneous web that can lead to severe flexion contracture of the elbow joint. Antecubital pterygium can be unilateral, bilateral, symmetric, or asysmmetric.

HP:0009761.name: Anterior clefting of vertebral bodies
HP:0009761.definition: Anterior schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies.

HP:0009762.name: Facial wrinkling
HP:0009762.definition: Excessive wrinkling of the skin of the face.

HP:0009763.name: Limb pain
HP:0009763.definition: Chronic pain in the limbs with no clear focal etiology.

HP:0009765.name: Low hanging columella
HP:0009765.definition: Columella extending inferior to the level of the nasal base, when viewed from the side.

HP:0009767.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0009767.definition: Small or missing phalangeal bones of the fingers of the hand.

HP:0009768.name: Broad phalanges of the hand
HP:0009768.definition: Increased width of the phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009769.name: Bullet-shaped phalanges of the hand
HP:0009769.definition: The presence of short and wide phalanges which taper distally ("bullet shaped").

HP:0009771.name: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0009771.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009772.name: Patchy sclerosis of finger phalanx
HP:0009772.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009773.name: Symphalangism affecting the phalanges of the hand
HP:0009773.definition: Fusion of two or more phalangeal bones of the hand.

HP:0009774.name: Triangular shaped phalanges of the hand

HP:0009775.name: Amniotic constriction ring
HP:0009775.definition: Annular constrictions around the digits, limbs, or trunk, occurring congenitally (sometimes causing intrauterine autoamputation) and also associated with a wide variety of disorders. Constrictive amniotic bands are the result of primary amniotic rupture, which can lead to entanglement of fetal tissue (especially limbs) in fibrous amniotic strands.

HP:0009776.name: Adactyly
HP:0009776.definition: The absence of all phalanges of all the digits of a limb and the associated soft tissues.

HP:0009777.name: Absent thumb
HP:0009777.definition: Absent thumb, i.e., the absence of both phalanges of a thumb and the associated soft tissues.

HP:0009778.name: Short thumb
HP:0009778.definition: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the thumb.

HP:0009779.name: 3-4 toe syndactyly
HP:0009779.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes three and four.

HP:0009780.name: Iliac horns
HP:0009780.definition: Horn-like malformations of the iliac crests with symmetrical bilateral central posterior iliac processes. A characteristic finding in the Nail-Patella syndrome. Iliac horns are visible on X-ray and may be palpable, but are asymptomatic.

HP:0009781.name: Lester's sign
HP:0009781.definition: A zone of darker pigmentation around the central part of the iris with a roughly cloverleaf or flower shape.

HP:0009782.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the biceps
HP:0009782.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the biceps muscle.

HP:0009784.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the triceps
HP:0009784.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the triceps muscle.

HP:0009786.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the musculature of the thigh
HP:0009786.definition: Absence or underdevelopment involving the musculature of the thigh.

HP:0009787.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the quadriceps
HP:0009787.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the quadriceps muscle.

HP:0009789.name: Perianal abscess
HP:0009789.definition: The presence of an abscess located around the anus.

HP:0009790.name: Hemisacrum
HP:0009790.definition: A hemisacral defect involving the sacral vertebrae S2 to S5. In hemisacrum, the first sacral vertebra is intact and there is agenesis involving only S2-S5.

HP:0009791.name: Bifid sacrum
HP:0009791.definition: Presence of a bifid sacral bone.

HP:0009793.name: Presacral teratoma
HP:0009793.definition: A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma located anterior to the sacrum and entirely inside the body (Altman type IV).

HP:0009794.name: Branchial anomaly
HP:0009794.definition: Congenital developmental defect arising from the primitive branchial apparatus.

HP:0009795.name: Branchial fistula
HP:0009795.definition: A congenital fistula in the neck resulting from incomplete closure of a branchial cleft.

HP:0009796.name: Branchial cyst
HP:0009796.definition: A branchial cyst is a remnant of embryonic development resulting from a failure of obliteration of a branchial cleft and consists of a subcutaneous cystic mass. Cysts are located anterior or posterior to the ear or in the submandibular region.

HP:0009797.name: Cholesteatoma
HP:0009797.definition: Cholesteatoma is a benign but potentially destructive growth consisting of keratinizing epithelium located in the middle ear and/or mastoid process. In cholesteatoma, a skin cyst grows into the middle ear and mastoid. The cyst is not cancerous but can erode tissue and cause destruction of the ear.

HP:0009798.name: Euthyroid goiter
HP:0009798.definition: A goiter that is not associated with functional thyroid abnormalities.

HP:0009799.name: Supernumerary spleens
HP:0009799.definition: The presence of two or more accessory spleens.

HP:0009800.name: Maternal diabetes
HP:0009800.definition: Maternal diabetes can either be a gestational, mostly type 2 diabetes, or a type 1 diabetes. Essential is the resulting maternal hyperglycemia as a non-specific teratogen, imposing the same risk of congenital malformations to pregnant women with both type 1 and type2 diabetes.

HP:0009802.name: Aplasia of the phalanges of the hand
HP:0009802.definition: Absence of one or more of the phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009803.name: Short phalanx of finger
HP:0009803.definition: Short (hypoplastic) phalanx of finger, affecting one or more phalanges.

HP:0009804.name: Tooth agenesis
HP:0009804.definition: The absence of one or more teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop

HP:0009805.name: Low-output congestive heart failure
HP:0009805.definition: A form of heart failure characterized by reduced cardiac output. This may be seen in patients with heart failure owing to ischemic heart disease, hypertension, cardiomyopathy, and other causes.

HP:0009806.name: Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus
HP:0009806.definition: A form of diabetes insipidus caused by failure of the kidneys to respond to vasopressin (AVP).

HP:0009808.name: Anomaly of the upper limb diaphyses
HP:0009808.definition: A structural abnormality of a diaphysis of the arm.

HP:0009809.name: Abnormal upper limb metaphysis morphology
HP:0009809.definition: An anomaly of one or more metaphyses of the arms.

HP:0009811.name: Abnormality of the elbow
HP:0009811.definition: An anomaly of the joint that connects the upper and the lower arm.

HP:0009812.name: Amelia involving the upper limbs
HP:0009812.definition: Amelia of one or both upper limbs.

HP:0009813.name: Upper limb phocomelia
HP:0009813.definition: Missing or malformed long bones of the upper limbs with the distal parts (the hands) connected to the variably shortened or even absent upper extremity, leading to a flipper-like appearance, as opposed to other forms of limb malformations were either the whole limb is missing (such as amelia), or the distal part of a limb is absent (peromelia).

HP:0009814.name: Upper limb peromelia
HP:0009814.definition: Peromelia affecting only the upper limbs. That is, the distal parts of the arm are missing leading to stump formation.

HP:0009815.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the extremities
HP:0009815.definition: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the extremities.

HP:0009816.name: Lower limb undergrowth
HP:0009816.definition: Leg shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the lower extremity.

HP:0009817.name: Aplasia involving bones of the lower limbs

HP:0009818.name: Amelia involving the lower limbs
HP:0009818.definition: Complete or near-complete absence of a leg.

HP:0009819.name: Lower limb phocomelia
HP:0009819.definition: Phocomelia affecting only the lower limbs.

HP:0009820.name: Lower limb peromelia
HP:0009820.definition: Peromelia affecting only the lower limbs. That is, the distal parts of the leg are missing leading to stump formation.

HP:0009821.name: Forearm undergrowth
HP:0009821.definition: Forearm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the forearm.

HP:0009823.name: Aplasia involving bones of the upper limbs

HP:0009824.name: Upper limb undergrowth
HP:0009824.definition: Arm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the upper extremity.

HP:0009825.name: Aplasia involving bones of the extremities

HP:0009826.name: Limb undergrowth
HP:0009826.definition: Limb shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the extremities.

HP:0009827.name: Amelia
HP:0009827.definition: Congenital absence (aplasia) of one or more limbs.

HP:0009828.name: Peromelia
HP:0009828.definition: The distal parts of the limbs are missing leading to a stump formation.

HP:0009829.name: Phocomelia
HP:0009829.definition: Missing or malformed long bones of the extremities with the distal parts (such as hands and/or feet) connected to the variably shortened or even absent extremity, leading to a flipper-like appearance, as opposed to other forms of limb malformations were either the hole limb is missing (such as amelia), or the distal part of a limb is absent (peromelia).

HP:0009830.name: Peripheral neuropathy
HP:0009830.definition: Peripheral neuropathy is a general term for any disorder of the peripheral nervous system. The main clinical features used to classify peripheral neuropathy are distribution, type (mainly demyelinating versus mainly axonal), duration, and course.

HP:0009831.name: Mononeuropathy
HP:0009831.definition: A focal lesion of a single peripheral nerve. Damage to a sensory nerve is accompanied by sensory impairment of all modalities in the affected anatomic distribution.

HP:0009832.name: Abnormal distal phalanx morphology of finger
HP:0009832.definition: Any anomaly of distal phalanx of finger.

HP:0009833.name: Abnormal middle phalanx morphology of the hand
HP:0009833.definition: An anomaly of middle phalanx of finger.

HP:0009834.name: Abnormal proximal phalanx morphology of the hand

HP:0009835.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the hand
HP:0009835.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the distal phalanges.

HP:0009836.name: Broad distal phalanx of finger
HP:0009836.definition: Abnormally wide (broad) distal phalanx of finger.

HP:0009837.name: Bullet-shaped distal phalanges of the hand
HP:0009837.definition: Short and wide distal phalanges that taper distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009838.name: Curved distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009839.name: Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009840.name: Patchy sclerosis of distal phalanx of finger
HP:0009840.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009843.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0009844.name: Broad middle phalanx of finger
HP:0009844.definition: Increased width of the middle phalanx of finger.

HP:0009845.name: Bullet-shaped middle phalanges of the hand
HP:0009845.definition: Any of the middle phalanges with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009846.name: Curved middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0009847.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0009848.name: Patchy sclerosis of middle phalanx of finger
HP:0009848.definition: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009849.name: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of finger
HP:0009849.definition: Fusion of a middle phalanx of a finger with another bone.

HP:0009850.name: Triangular shaped middle phalanges of the hand

HP:0009851.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009852.name: Broad proximal phalanges of the hand
HP:0009852.definition: Increased width of the proximal phalanges of the finger.

HP:0009853.name: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanges of the hand
HP:0009853.definition: Short and wide proximal phalanges that taper distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

HP:0009854.name: Curved proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009855.name: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009856.name: Patchy sclerosis of proximal phalanx of finger
HP:0009856.definition: Uneven increase in bone density of the proximal phalanges of the hand.

HP:0009857.name: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009858.name: Triangular shaped proximal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009875.name: Triangular shaped distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009878.name: Cerebellar ataxia associated with quadrupedal gait
HP:0009878.definition: The presence of cerebellar signs and symptoms such as lack of balance associated with quadrupedal gait (locomotion on all four extremities with a 'bear-like' gait with the legs held straight).

HP:0009879.name: Simplified gyral pattern
HP:0009879.definition: An abnormality of the cerebral cortex with fewer gyri but with normal cortical thickness. This pattern is usually often associated with congenital microcephaly.

HP:0009880.name: Broad distal phalanges of all fingers
HP:0009880.definition: Abnormally wide (broad) distal phalanx of finger of all fingers.

HP:0009881.name: Aplasia of the distal phalanges of the hand

HP:0009882.name: Short distal phalanx of finger
HP:0009882.definition: Short distance from the end of the finger to the most distal interphalangeal crease or the distal interphalangeal joint flexion point. That is, hypoplasia of one or more of the distal phalanx of finger.

HP:0009883.name: Duplication of the distal phalanx of hand
HP:0009883.definition: This term applies if one or more of the distal phalanges of the hand are either partially duplicated, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance of the phalanges, or completely duplicated.

HP:0009884.name: Tapered distal phalanges of finger
HP:0009884.definition: A reduction in diameter of the distal phalanx of finger towards the distal end.

HP:0009886.name: Trichorrhexis nodosa
HP:0009886.definition: Trichorrhexis nodosa is the formation of nodes along the hair shaft through which breakage readily occurs. It is thus a focal defect in the hair fiber that is characterized by thickening or weak points (nodes) that cause the hair to break off easily. The result is defective, abnormally fragile hair.

HP:0009888.name: Abnormality of secondary sexual hair
HP:0009888.definition: Abnormality of the growth of secondary sexual hair, which normally ensues during puberty. In males, secondary sexual hair usually comprises body hair, including underarm, abdominal, chest, and pubic hair. In females, secondary sexual hair usually comprises a lesser degree of body hair, most prominently underarm and pubic hair.

HP:0009889.name: Localized hirsutism
HP:0009889.definition: Abnormally increased hair growth with a localized distribution.

HP:0009890.name: High anterior hairline
HP:0009890.definition: Distance between the hairline (trichion) and the glabella (the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose), in the midline, more than two SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between the hairline and the glabella.

HP:0009891.name: Underdeveloped supraorbital ridges
HP:0009891.definition: Flatness of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.

HP:0009892.name: Anotia
HP:0009892.definition: Complete absence of any auricular structures.

HP:0009893.name: Telangiectasia of the ear
HP:0009893.definition: The presence of telangiectasia of the ear.

HP:0009894.name: Thickened ears
HP:0009894.definition: Increased thickness of the external ear.

HP:0012838.name: Localized
HP:0012838.definition: Being confined or restricted to a particular location.

HP:0012839.name: Distal
HP:0012839.definition: Localized away from the central point of the body.

HP:0012840.name: Proximal
HP:0012840.definition: Localized close to the central point of the body.

HP:0012841.name: Retinal vascular tortuosity
HP:0012841.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal blood vessels.

HP:0012842.name: Skin appendage neoplasm
HP:0012842.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the hair follicles, sebaceous glands, or sweat glands.

HP:0012843.name: Hair follicle neoplasm
HP:0012843.definition: An uncontrolled autonomous cell-proliferation originating in a hair follicle, which is an epidermal adnexal structures responsible for hair growth.

HP:0012844.name: Trichilemmoma
HP:0012844.definition: A benign tumor originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.

HP:0012845.name: Single trichilemmoma
HP:0012845.definition: Presence of a unitary trichilemmoma, a benign tumor originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.

HP:0012846.name: Multiple trichilemmomata
HP:0012846.definition: Presence of multiple trichilemmomata, a benign tumor originating from the outer root sheath of the hair follicle.

HP:0012847.name: Epilepsia partialis continua
HP:0012847.definition: Epilepsia partialis continua (also called Kojevnikov's or Kozhevnikov's epilepsia) is a type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repeated stereotyped simple motor manifestations such as jerks, typically of a limb or the face, recurring every few seconds or minutes for extended periods (days or years).

HP:0012848.name: Small intestinal stenosis
HP:0012848.definition: The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the small intestine.

HP:0012850.name: Small intestinal dysmotility
HP:0012850.definition: Abnormal small intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

HP:0012851.name: Colonic stenosis
HP:0012851.definition: A narrowing of a segment of colon whereby bowel continuity is maintained.

HP:0012852.name: Hepatic bridging fibrosis
HP:0012852.definition: Hepatic fibrosis that reaches from a portal area to another portal area.

HP:0012853.name: Scrotal hypospadias
HP:0012853.definition: Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the scrotum.

HP:0012854.name: Midshaft hypospadias
HP:0012854.definition: Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the middle of the inferior shaft of the penis.

HP:0012855.name: Scrotal hyperpigmentation
HP:0012855.definition: Increased pigmentation (skin color) of the scrotum.

HP:0012856.name: Abnormal scrotal rugation
HP:0012856.definition: Anomaly of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.

HP:0012857.name: Increased scrotal rugation
HP:0012857.definition: Increased number or density of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.

HP:0012858.name: Decreased scrotal rugation
HP:0012858.definition: Decreased number or density of the folded ridges (wrinkles) of skin of the scrotum.

HP:0012859.name: Esophageal leukoplakia
HP:0012859.definition: A white patch or plaque occurring on the surface of the esophageal mucous membranes that cannot be rubbed off and cannot be characterized clinically as any other disease.

HP:0012860.name: Testicular fibrosis
HP:0012860.definition: Formation of excess connective tissue in the testicle.

HP:0012861.name: Ovotestis
HP:0012861.definition: A gonad that contains both ovarian follicles and testicular tubular elements.

HP:0012862.name: Abnormal germ cell morphology
HP:0012862.definition: Any structural anomaly of a reproductive cell.

HP:0012863.name: Abnormal male germ cell morphology
HP:0012863.definition: A structural anomaly of a male reproductive cell.

HP:0012865.name: Abnormal sperm head morphology
HP:0012865.definition: A structural abnormality of the sperm head.

HP:0012866.name: Abnormal sperm neck morphology
HP:0012866.definition: A structural abnormality of the sperm neck.

HP:0012867.name: Abnormal sperm mid-piece morphology
HP:0012867.definition: A structural abnormality of the sperm mid-piece.

HP:0012868.name: Abnormal sperm tail morphology
HP:0012868.definition: A structural abnormality of the sperm tail.

HP:0012869.name: Acephalic spermatozoa
HP:0012869.definition: Spermatozoa with very small cranial ends devoid of any nuclear material, that is, lacking a typical sperm head.

HP:0012870.name: Vanishing testis
HP:0012870.definition: A condition which is considered to be due to the subsequent atrophy and disappearance in fetal life of an initially normal testis. In the presence of spermatic cord structures is evidence of the presence of the testis in early intrauterine life. When associated with a blind-ending spermatic cord, this entity is named as his absence of a testis in an otherwise normal 46XY male is usually unilateral and is assumed to be a consequence of intrauterine or perinatal torsion or infarction.

HP:0012871.name: Varicocele
HP:0012871.definition: A varicocele is a widening of the veins along the spermatic cord, leading to enlarged, twisted veins in the scrotum, and manifested clinically by a painless testicle lump, scrotal swelling, or bulge in the scrotum.

HP:0012872.name: Abnormal vas deferens morphology
HP:0012872.definition: A structural anomaly of the secretory duct of the testicle that carries spermatozoa from the epididymis to the prostatic urethra where it terminates to form ejaculatory duct.

HP:0012873.name: Absent vas deferens
HP:0012873.definition: Aplasia (congenital absence) of the vas deferens.

HP:0012874.name: Abnormal male reproductive system physiology
HP:0012874.definition: An abnormal functionality of the male genital system.

HP:0012875.name: Abnormal ejaculation
HP:0012875.definition: Abnormality in the process of ejection of semen (usually carrying sperm) from the male reproductive tract.

HP:0012876.name: Premature ejaculation
HP:0012876.definition: The emission of semen and seminal fluid during the act of preparation for sexual intercourse, i.e. before there is penetration, or shortly after penetration.

HP:0012877.name: Retrograde ejaculation
HP:0012877.definition: The emission of semen and seminal fluid into the bladder instead of through the penis during orgasm.

HP:0012878.name: Retarded ejaculation
HP:0012878.definition: Difficulty of a male in achieving orgasm.

HP:0012880.name: Abnormal labia minora morphology
HP:0012880.definition: An anomaly of the labia minora, the folds of skin between the outer labia.

HP:0012881.name: Abnormal labia majora morphology
HP:0012881.definition: An anomaly of the outer labia.

HP:0012883.name: Fallopian tube cyst
HP:0012883.definition: A fluid filled sac located in the Fallopian tube.

HP:0012884.name: Fallopian tube torsion
HP:0012884.definition: A twisting of the Fallopian tube. Sudden onset with sharp, colicky pelvic pain associated with nausea, vomiting, bowel, and bladder symptoms is the usual presentation.

HP:0012885.name: Fallopian tube duplication
HP:0012885.definition: The presence of a supernumerary Fallopian tube.

HP:0012886.name: Hemorrhagic ovarian cyst
HP:0012886.definition: An abdominal mass formed by bleeding into a follicular ovarian cyst or corpus luteum cyst.

HP:0012887.name: Ovarian serous cystadenoma
HP:0012887.definition: A cystic tumor of the ovary, containing thin, clear, yellow serous fluid and varying amounts of solid tissue.

HP:0012888.name: Abnormal uterine cervix morphology
HP:0012888.definition: An anomaly of the neck of the uterus (lower part of the uterus), called the uterine cervix.

HP:0012889.name: Cervical endometriosis
HP:0012889.definition: Abnormal growth of endometrial cells (which are normally limited to the uterus) within the cervix.

HP:0012891.name: High posterior hairline
HP:0012891.definition: Hair on the neck extends less inferiorly than usual.

HP:0012892.name: Facial muscle hypertrophy
HP:0012892.definition: Hypertrophy of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

HP:0012893.name: Neck muscle hypertrophy
HP:0012893.definition: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the muscles of the neck.

HP:0012894.name: Paraspinal muscle hypertrophy
HP:0012894.definition: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the paraspinal muscles.

HP:0012895.name: Scapular muscle hypertrophy
HP:0012895.definition: Muscle hypertrophy affecting the scapular muscles.

HP:0012896.name: Abnormal motor evoked potentials
HP:0012896.definition: An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs). MEPs are measured following single-pulse or repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation and can be used for the assessment of the excitability of the motor cortex and the integrity of conduction along the central and peripheral motor pathways.

HP:0012897.name: Abnormal upper-limb motor evoked potentials
HP:0012897.definition: An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs) in the arm.

HP:0012898.name: Abnormal lower-limb motor evoked potentials
HP:0012898.definition: An anomaly identified by motor evoked potentials (MEPs) in the leg.

HP:0012899.name: Handgrip myotonia
HP:0012899.definition: Difficulty releasing one's grip associated with prolonged first handgrip relaxation times.

HP:0012900.name: Myotonia of the face
HP:0012900.definition: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the face.

HP:0012901.name: Myotonia of the jaw
HP:0012901.definition: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the jaw.

HP:0012902.name: Myotonia of the lower limb
HP:0012902.definition: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the leg.

HP:0012903.name: Myotonia of the upper limb
HP:0012903.definition: Slowed relaxation of muscles in the arm.

HP:0012904.name: Cold-sensitive myotonia
HP:0012904.definition: An involuntary and painless delay in the relaxation of skeletal muscle following contraction or electrical stimulation that is induced by exposure to cold.

HP:0012905.name: Euryblepharon
HP:0012905.definition: Euryblepharon is a congenital eyelid anomaly characterized by horizontal enlargement of the palpebral fissure. The eyelid is shortened vertically compared with the horizontal dimension, with associated lateral canthal malpositioning and lateral ectropion abnormally wide lid opening.

HP:0020001.name: Clinical anophthalmos
HP:0020001.definition: Congenital anophthalmos is a rare ocular anomaly in which histologically detectable eyeball structures are absent due to poor development of the primary optic nerve vesicle. However, with appropriate imaging or intraoperatively, rudimentary remains of this structure can usually be detected. Therefore, the term clinical congenital anophthalmos seems more appropriate and denotes a phenotypic range between microphthalmos and anophthalmos.

HP:0020002.name: Ileal stricture
HP:0020002.definition: A pathological narrowing of the ileum that is caused by the development of a ring of scar tissue that constricts the ileal lumen.

HP:0020006.name: Ciliary body coloboma
HP:0020006.definition: A coloboma of the ciliary body.

HP:0020034.name: Diffuse
HP:0020034.definition: A spatial pattern that is spread out, i.e., not localized.

HP:0020035.name: Lower limb dysmetria
HP:0020035.definition: A lack of coordination of leg movement manifested by undershoot or overshoot of the intended position of the leg.

HP:0020036.name: Upper limb dysmetria
HP:0020036.definition: A lack of coordination of arm movement manifested by undershoot or overshoot of the intended position of the arm.

HP:0020037.name: Astasia
HP:0020037.definition: A postural abnormality characterized by the inability to stand without external support despite having sufficient muscle strength.

HP:0020038.name: Vertebrobasilar dolichoectasia
HP:0020038.definition: Elongation, dilatation, and/or tortuosity of the vertebrobasilar segment. The definition of VBD includes: (i) diameter of basilar or vertebral artery over 4.5 mm; or (ii) deviation of any portion more than 10 mm from the shortest expected course; and (iii) length of basilar artery over 29.5 mm or length of intracranial vertebral artery over 23.5 mm.

HP:0020041.name: Double elevator palsy
HP:0020041.definition: A type of incomitant strabismus in which both elevator muscles (i.e., the inferior oblique and superior rectus muscles) of the same eye are weak leading to restricted elevation and hypotropia.

HP:0020042.name: Double depressor palsy
HP:0020042.definition: An ocular movement abnormality characterized by simultaneous weakness of the inferior rectus muscle and superior oblique muscle of the same eye.

HP:0020043.name: Vertical incomitant strabismus
HP:0020043.definition: A type of incomitant strabismus in which the angle of deviation varies as the patient's gaze shifts upwards and/or downwards.

HP:0020045.name: Esodeviation
HP:0020045.definition: A manifest or latent ocular deviation in which one or both eyes tends to deviate nasally.

HP:0020046.name: Accommodative esotropia
HP:0020046.definition: A form of esotropia (convergent deviation of the eyes) associated with activation of the accommodative reflex.

HP:0020047.name: Abnormal myeloid cell morphology
HP:0020047.definition: Any structural anomaly of a cell of the monocyte, granulocyte, mast cell, megakaryocyte, or erythroid lineage.

HP:0020048.name: Reduced bone-marrow pro-B cell count
HP:0020048.definition: A reduction in the numbers of pro-B cells (defined by coexpression of CD34 and CD19). Earlier B-cell precursors are defined by expressing surface CD34 and cytoplasmic TdT in the absence of CD19.

HP:0020049.name: Exodeviation
HP:0020049.definition: A manifest or latent ocular deviation in which one or both eyes tends to deviate temporally.

HP:0020050.name: Anti-granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor antibody positivity
HP:0020050.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor.

HP:0020054.name: Abnormal erythrocyte physiology
HP:0020054.definition: Any functional abnormality of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).

HP:0020058.name: Abnormal red blood cell count
HP:0020058.definition: Any deviation from the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.

HP:0020059.name: Increased red blood cell count
HP:0020059.definition: An abnormal elevation above the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.

HP:0020060.name: Decreased red blood cell count
HP:0020060.definition: An abnormal reduction below the normal number of red blood cells per volume in the circulation.

HP:0020061.name: Abnormal hemoglobin concentration
HP:0020061.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of hemoglobin in the blood.

HP:0020062.name: Decreased hemoglobin concentration
HP:0020062.definition: An abnormal reduction below normal hemoglobin concentration in the circulation.

HP:0020064.name: Abnormal total eosinophil count
HP:0020064.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of absolute number of eosinophils in the blood, per microlitre, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0020071.name: Viremia
HP:0020071.definition: The presence of virus in the blood.

HP:0020072.name: Persistent EBV viremia
HP:0020072.definition: Persistent presence of Epstein-Barr virus in the blood.

HP:0020073.name: Hypopigmented macule
HP:0020073.definition: A white or lighter patch of skin that may appear anywhere on the body and are caused by decreased skin pigmentation.

HP:0020074.name: Crystalluria
HP:0020074.definition: The presence of crystals in the urine.

HP:0020075.name: Leucine crystalluria
HP:0020075.definition: The presence of leucine crystals in the urine.

HP:0020076.name: Wrist ganglion
HP:0020076.definition: A benign soft tissue tumor of the wrist usually found in the dorsal aspect of the wrist and communicate with the joint via a pedicle. This pedicle usually originates not only at the scapholunate ligament, but also may arise from a number of other sites over the dorsal aspect of the wrist capsule.

HP:0020077.name: Carnitinuria
HP:0020077.definition: An elevated level of carnitine in the urine.

HP:0020078.name: Alaninuria
HP:0020078.definition: An increased level of alanine in the urine.

HP:0020079.name: Beta-alaninuria
HP:0020079.definition: The amount of beta-alanine in the urine, when normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0020080.name: Erythrocyte inclusion bodies
HP:0020080.definition: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of substances in red blood cells.

HP:0020081.name: Pappenheimer bodies
HP:0020081.definition: A type of erythrocyte inclusion characterized by basophilic stippling of erythrocytes, that is, by numerous very small coarse or fine blue granules within the cytoplasm with the additional stipulation that the stippled particles are due to iron granules (demonstrable by the Prussian blue stain).

HP:0020082.name: Heinz bodies
HP:0020082.definition: A type of erythrocyte inclusion composed of denatured hemoglobin.

HP:0020083.name: Furuncle
HP:0020083.definition: An infection of a hair follicle that extends subcutaneously, forming an abscess.

HP:0020084.name: Carbuncle
HP:0020084.definition: A pustular lesion of the skin emerging from group of infected hair follicles, characterized by a deep location and dissecting through tissue planes. A carbuncle is larger and deeper than a furuncle.

HP:0020085.name: Infection following live vaccination
HP:0020085.definition: An infection resulting from live attenuated vaccines (LAV), that is, a vaccine prepared from living viruses or bacteria that have been weakened under laboratory conditions. LAV vaccines will replicate in a vaccinated individual and produce an immune response but usually cause mild or no disease. are derived from disease-causing pathogens.

HP:0020086.name: BCGitis
HP:0020086.definition: Local or regional infection with Bacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination.

HP:0020087.name: BCGosis
HP:0020087.definition: Distant, or disseminated infection with Bacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination associated with failure to contain thebacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination leading to spread of BCG to many sites in the body. The tuberculosis vaccine BCG contains live attenuated Mycobacterium bovis.

HP:0020088.name: Post-vaccination measles
HP:0020088.definition: Infection with the measles virus of the live-attenuated vaccine. This is an extremely rare event and may indicate immunocompromise in some cases.

HP:0020089.name: Post-vaccination rubella
HP:0020089.definition: Infection with the rubella virus of the live-attenuated vaccine.

HP:0020090.name: Post-vaccination polio
HP:0020090.definition: Infection with live attenuated polio vaccine following vaccination. This is an extremely rare event that may indicate immunocompromise.

HP:0020091.name: Post-vaccination rotavirus infection
HP:0020091.definition: Infection with live attenuated rotavirus vaccine following vaccination.

HP:0020093.name: Recurrent deep organ abscess formation
HP:0020093.definition: Repeated episodes of the formation of abscesses in organs. An abscess is a circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the parenchyma or an organ.

HP:0020095.name: Prolonged need of intravenous antibiotic therapy
HP:0020095.definition: Clinical assessment of a requirement to treat with intravenous antibiotics over an unusually prolonged period of time.

HP:0020096.name: Recurrent streptococcal infections
HP:0020096.definition: Increased susceptibility to streptococcal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of streptococcal infections.

HP:0020097.name: Infection due to encapsulated bacteria
HP:0020097.definition: An infection by an encapsulated bacterial agent. Isolates which cause invasive disease are usually surrounded by a polysaccharide capsule, which is a major virulence factor and the key antigen in protective protein-polysaccharide conjugate vaccines.

HP:0020099.name: Severe norovirus infection
HP:0020099.definition: An unusually severe course of infection with Human norovirus, previously known as Norwalk virus. Norovirus, an RNA virus of the family Caliciviridae, is a human enteric pathogen. Norovirus infection-associated illness may also be more prolonged and severe in immunocompromised individuals and may be associated with remarkably persistent viral excretion in some of these individuals.

HP:0020100.name: Unusual fungal infection
HP:0020100.definition: An unusual fungal infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection by a fungal agent.

HP:0020101.name: Invasive fungal infection
HP:0020101.definition: Fungal infection characterized by invasion of host tissues.

HP:0020102.name: Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia
HP:0020102.definition: An opportunistic disease caused by invasion of unicellular fungus Pneumocystis jirovecii. Transmission of P. jirovecii cysts takes place through the airborne route, and usually, its presence in lungs is asymptomatic. However, people with impaired immunity, especially those with CD4+ T cell count below 200/microliter, are still at risk of the development of Pneumocystis pneumonia due to P. jirovecii invasion. Symptoms induced by this disease are not specific: progressive dyspnea, non-productive cough, low-grade fever, arterial partial pressure of oxygen below 65 mmHg, and chest radiographs demonstrating bilateral, interstitial shadowing.

HP:0020103.name: Invasive pulmonary aspergillosis
HP:0020103.definition: Infection of the lungs with aspergillus. In the respiratory mucosa, the spores may germinate into hyphae, which in turn can invade the mucosa leading to invasive pulmonary aspergillosis.

HP:0020104.name: Unusual protozoan infection
HP:0020104.definition: An unusual protozoan infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection by a protozoal agent.

HP:0020105.name: Severe toxoplasmosis
HP:0020105.definition: Toxoplasmosis is a widespread parasitic infection that is frequently asymptomatic in immunocompetent patients. However, this obligate intracellular protozoan parasite can evade the immune system and persist for the life of its host in cyst form, predominantly in the brain, retina, and muscles. Reactivation of latent cysts may occur when the immune system fails to maintain cytokine pressure, which mainly relies on gamma interferon (IFN-gamma). Toxoplasmosis is a life-threatening infection in immunocompromised patients (ICPs).

HP:0020106.name: Severe giardiasis
HP:0020106.definition: An unusually severe infection due to Giardia lamblia, also called Giardia duodenalis or Giardia intestinalis, which is a protozoan parasite of the small intestine that causes extensive morbidity worldwide.

HP:0020107.name: Unusual helminthic infection
HP:0020107.definition: An unusual helminthic infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection by a worm (helminth).

HP:0020108.name: Unusual parasitic infection
HP:0020108.definition: An unusual parasitic infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection by a parasite.

HP:0020110.name: Bone fracture
HP:0020110.definition: A partial or complete breakage of the continuity of a bone.

HP:0020111.name: Abnormal regulatory T cell proportion
HP:0020111.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the regulatory (Treg) CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized by the CD127lowCD25hi phenotype, with the optional additional positivity for FoxP3, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0020112.name: Increased proportion of regulatory T cells
HP:0020112.definition: Abnormal increase of the regulatory (Treg) CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized by the CD127lowCD25hi phenotype, with the optional additional positivity for FoxP3, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0020113.name: Decreased proportion of regulatory T cells
HP:0020113.definition: Abnormal decrease of the regulatory (Treg) CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized by the CD127lowCD25hi phenotype, with the optional additional positivity for FoxP3, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0020114.name: Persistent human papillomavirus infection
HP:0020114.definition: Human papillomaviruses (HPVs) are small oncogenic viruses. HPV has been shown to cause a variety of lesions and malignancies, which predominantly affect the anogenital region. Low-risk, non-oncogenic HPV types are associated with anogenital warts and recurrent respiratory papillomatosis while high-risk, oncogenic types are associated with cervical, penile, anal, vaginal, vulvar, and oropharyngeal cancers. Infection with anogenital HPV is usually asymptomatic and resolves spontaneously without consequences in the immunocompetent host. When disease does occur, the most common manifestation is genital warts, which may be small papules, or flat, smooth or pedunculated lesions. This resolution of HPV lesions is not generally seen in the immunosuppressed, resulting in severe, persistent and extensive manifestations of HPV disease.

HP:0020117.name: Hypoplastic dermoepidermal hemidesmosomes
HP:0020117.definition: Underdeveloped hemidesmosomes at the dermoepidermal junction. Hemidesmosomes are the specialized junctional complexes, that contribute to the attachment of epithelial cells to the underlying basement membrane in stratified and other complex epithelia, such as the skin.

HP:0020118.name: Radial artery aplasia
HP:0020118.definition: Congenital absence of the radial artery.

HP:0020119.name: Abnormal retinal nerve fiber layer morphology
HP:0020119.definition: A structural abnormality of the retinal nerve fiber layer

HP:0020120.name: Retinal nerve fiber edema
HP:0020120.definition: Swelling (edema) of the retinal nerve fibers.

HP:0020121.name: Conception by assisted reproductive technology
HP:0020121.definition: A history of conception by an assisted reproductive technology such as in vitro fertilization (IVF), intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI), and cryopreservation.

HP:0020122.name: Bite cells
HP:0020122.definition: Red blood cells that appear to have parts of them bitten away.

HP:0020123.name: Tympanosclerosis
HP:0020123.definition: A stiffening of the tympanic membrane due to calcification, typically presents as white plaque-like lesions, involving discrete regions of the tympanic membrane and/or middle ear.

HP:0020125.name: Spontaneous conjunctival filtering bleb
HP:0020125.definition: Avascular cystic elevations of the superior conjunctiva not related to ocular surgery or trauma.

HP:0020126.name: Prostate mass
HP:0020126.definition: A lump detected in the prostate. In this context, mass is a general term for a lump or growth that may be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes, or an immune reaction.

HP:0020127.name: Periarticular soft-tissue mass
HP:0020127.definition: A lump detected in the region that surrounds a joint. In this context, mass is a general term for a lump or growth that may be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes, or an immune reaction.

HP:0020128.name: Aplasia of the olfactory tract
HP:0020128.definition: Aplasia (congenital absence) of the olfactory tract, which causes anosmia, a complete loss of the sense of smell.

HP:0020129.name: Abnormal urine protein level
HP:0020129.definition: Any deviation of the concentration of one or more proteins in the urine.

HP:0020130.name: Increased urinary neutrophil gelatinase-associated lipocalin
HP:0020130.definition: An increased concentration of neutrophil gelatinase-associated lipocalin in the urine (there is no generally accepted threshold, but some studies choose a threshold of above 150 nanogram per milliliter).

HP:0020131.name: Abnormal tubular basement membrane morphology
HP:0020131.definition: Abnormal structure of the basement membrane of the renal tubulus.

HP:0020132.name: Thickening of the tubular basement membrane
HP:0020132.definition: Increase in thickness of the basement membrane of the tubulus of the kidney.

HP:0020133.name: Podocyte hypertrophy
HP:0020133.definition: Increased visceral epithelial cell size, with or without cytoplasmic protein droplets.

HP:0020134.name: Increased urine neutrophil count
HP:0020134.definition: Abnormally increased count of neutrophils in urine.

HP:0020135.name: Myofibromatosis
HP:0020135.definition: A mesenchymal neoplasm characterized by solitary or multiple nodules involving the skin, striated muscles, bones and, sometimes, viscera. It usually appears as a subcutaneous nodule, but can also appear as an ulcer, pedunculated lesion, or similar to a hemangioma. Histology shows well-circumscribed tapered cell lobes, resembling smooth muscle cells. At its center, perivascular round cells (hemangiopericitoides) are usually observed, giving a biphasic appearance.

HP:0020136.name: Anticardiolipin IgG antibody positivity
HP:0020136.definition: The presence of circulating IgG autoantibodies to cardiolipin.

HP:0020137.name: Anticardiolipin IgM antibody positivity
HP:0020137.definition: The presence of circulating IgM autoantibodies to cardiolipin.

HP:0020138.name: History of recent animal bite
HP:0020138.definition: Medical history of a recent bite injury due to an animal.

HP:0020139.name: History of recent insect bite
HP:0020139.definition: Medical history of a recent bite injury due to an insect.

HP:0020140.name: History of recent tick bite
HP:0020140.definition: Medical history of a recent bite injury due to a tick.

HP:0020141.name: Blood pressure substantially higher in legs than arms
HP:0020141.definition: An abnormal blood pressure discrepancy between the upper and lower extremities with the blood pressure measured in the legs being much higher than the blood pressure measure in the arms. In healthy individuals, ankle systolic blood pressures are only slightly higher than the systolic blood pressure measured in the arm.

HP:0020142.name: Blood pressure substantially higher in arms than legs
HP:0020142.definition: An abnormal blood pressure discrepancy between the upper and lower extremities with the blood pressure measured in the arms being much higher than the blood pressure measure in the legs. In healthy individuals, ankle systolic blood pressures are only slightly higher than the systolic blood pressure measured in the arm.

HP:0020143.name: Tracheal duplication cyst
HP:0020143.definition: A cyst in the trachea, whose wall is made up by tissue similar to the bronchial tree, including cartilage and smooth muscle, and is lined by secretory respiratory epithelium composed of cuboid or columnar ciliated epithelium.

HP:0020144.name: Calcium phosphate crystalluria
HP:0020144.definition: The presence of calcium phosphate crystals in the urine.

HP:0020145.name: Calcium oxalate crystalluria
HP:0020145.definition: The presence of calcium oxalate crystals in the urine.

HP:0020146.name: Calcium carbonate crystalluria
HP:0020146.definition: The presence of calcium carbonate crystals in the urine.

HP:0020147.name: 2-Methylbutyryl glycinuria
HP:0020147.definition: Increased concentration of 2-methylbutyryl glycine in the urine.

HP:0020148.name: Increased circulating mead acid level
HP:0020148.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration od mead acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0020149.name: Elevated circulating succinate
HP:0020149.definition: An increase concentration of succinate in the blood circulation.

HP:0020150.name: Elevated urinary uromodulin level
HP:0020150.definition: The concentration of uromodulin (also known as Tamm Horsfall protein) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0020151.name: Anti-dsDNA antibody positivity
HP:0020151.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against double-stranded DNA.

HP:0020152.name: Distal joint hypermobility
HP:0020152.definition: Lack of stability of a distal joint (e.g., finger).

HP:0020153.name: Positive blood 1,3 beta glucan test
HP:0020153.definition: Beta-1,3-glucan is a major constituent of all of the characterized fungal cell walls, making up between 30-80 percent of the mass of the wall. It is a biomarker of fungal infections such as invasive pulmonary aspergillosis.

HP:0020154.name: Nevus comedonicus
HP:0020154.definition: A type of epidermal nevus characterized by closely arranged, dilated follicular openings with keratinous plugs resembling classical comedones.

HP:0020155.name: Abnormal oocyte morphology
HP:0020155.definition: An abnormal structure of the female germ cell (egg cell).

HP:0020156.name: Abnormal zona pellucida morphology
HP:0020156.definition: Abnormal structure of the oocyte extracellular matrix region known as the zona pellucida.

HP:0020157.name: Thin zona pellucida
HP:0020157.definition: Reduced thickness of the zona pellucida.

HP:0020158.name: Increased circulating adrenic acid concentration
HP:0020158.definition: An increased concentration of adrenic acid (also known as cis-7,10,13,16-Docosatetraenoic acid) in the blood circulation.

HP:0020159.name: Reduced response to gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0020159.definition: Failure of the gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) stimulation test to induce an appropriate increased in luteinizing hormone (LH), follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) levels.

HP:0020161.name: Branch retinal artery occlusion
HP:0020161.definition: Blockage of a branch of the retinal artery. This can cause loss of a section of visual field.

HP:0020163.name: Cilioretinal artery occlusion
HP:0020163.definition: Blockage of the cilioretinal artery. The central retinal artery supplies the inner retina and the surface of the optic nerve. In some individuals, the cilioretinal artery, a branch of the ciliary circulation, may supply a portion of the retina including the macula. In cilioretinal artery occlusion, vision loss results from cell death in the inner retinal layers (mainly ganglion cells) despite relative sparing of the outer layers.

HP:0020164.name: Ophthalmic artery occlusion
HP:0020164.definition: A partial or complete obstruction of the ophthalmic artery (branch of the internal carotid artery) that may lead to severe ischemia of the affected globe and associated ocular tissues. It can present with a similar picture to central retinal artery occlusion; however, profound choroidal ischaemia also occurs.

HP:0020165.name: Branch retinal vein occlusion
HP:0020165.definition: Blockage of a branch of the retinal vein. It may present with sudden-onset of painless vision loss or visual field defect correlating to the area of perfusion of the obstructed vessels.

HP:0020166.name: Central retinal vein occlusion
HP:0020166.definition: Central retinal vein occlusion is an occlusion of the main retinal vein posterior to the lamina cribrosa of the optic nerve and is typically caused by thrombosis.

HP:0020167.name: Hemiretinal vein occlusion
HP:0020167.definition: A variant of central retinal vein occlusions that involves the superior or inferior half of the retina.

HP:0020169.name: Abnormal drug response
HP:0020169.definition: An anomalous response to a medication related to individual variation in metabolic or immune response to drugs varying from potentially from potentially life-threatening adverse drug reactions to alteration of therapeutic efficacy.

HP:0020170.name: Increased blood drug concentration
HP:0020170.definition: High plasma concentration of a drug as compared to previously measured thresholds given the expected concentration for the applied dosage regime.

HP:0020171.name: Decreased blood drug concentration
HP:0020171.definition: Low plasma concentration of a drug as compared to previously measured thresholds given the expected concentration for the applied dosage regime.

HP:0020172.name: Adverse drug response
HP:0020172.definition: An unpleasant or harmful reaction resulting from treatment with a drug.

HP:0020173.name: Reduced drug efficacy
HP:0020173.definition: Decreased response to a drug intervention in comparison to the expected response.

HP:0020174.name: Refractory drug response
HP:0020174.definition: Absent or significantly reduced efficacy of drug intervention characterized by lack of measurable benefit or deterioration of disease course.

HP:0020175.name: Reduced circulating cholinesterase activity
HP:0020175.definition: Activity or concentration of cholinesterase in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0020176.name: Cholesterol crystalluria
HP:0020176.definition: The presence of cholesterol crystals in the urine.

HP:0020177.name: Abnormal CD8-positive TEMRA T cell proportion
HP:0020177.definition: An abnormal proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta effector memory RA TEMRA T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CD45RA-positive, CD45RO-negative, and CCR7-negative.

HP:0020178.name: Abnormal dendritic cell count
HP:0020178.definition: A deviation from the normal count of dendritic cells in the peripheral blood circulation. Dendritic cells are of hematopoietic origin, typically resident in particular tissues, specialized in the uptake, processing, and transport of antigens to lymph nodes for the purpose of stimulating an immune response via T cell activation. These cells are lineage negative (CD3-negative, CD19-negative, CD34-negative, and CD56-negative).

HP:0020179.name: Abnormal circulating haptoglobin concentration
HP:0020179.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of haptoglobin in the blood circulation.

HP:0020180.name: Elevated haptoglobin level
HP:0020180.definition: An abnormally high concentration of haptoglobin in the blood circulation. Haptoglobin is an acute-phase reactant whose levels can become elevated in the presence of infection and inflammation.

HP:0020181.name: Reduced haptoglobin level
HP:0020181.definition: An abnormally low concentration of haptoglobin in the blood circulation. Decreased haptoglobin in conjunction with increased reticulocyte count and anemia may indicate hemolysis. Decreased haptoglobin levels can also occur in the absence of hemolysis, due to cirrhosis of the liver, disseminated ovarian carcinomatosis, pulmonary sarcoidosis, and elevated estrogen state.

HP:0020182.name: Abnormal circulating A-type atrial natriuretic peptide concentration
HP:0020182.definition: A measurable change in circulating levels of Atrial natriuretic peptide hormone, a protein which plays an important role in the regulation of body fluid volume and blood pressure.

HP:0020183.name: Increased circulating A-type natriuretic peptide concentration
HP:0020183.definition: A measurable elevation in circulating levels of Atrial natriuretic peptide hormone, a protein which plays an important role in the regulation of body fluid volume and blood pressure.

HP:0020184.name: Decreased circulating A-type natriuretic peptide concentration
HP:0020184.definition: A measurable reduction in circulating levels of Atrial natriuretic peptide hormone, a protein which plays an important role in the regulation of body fluid volume and blood pressure.

HP:0020185.name: Superior cerebellar dysplasia
HP:0020185.definition: Abnormal morphological development of the superior part of the cerebellum.

HP:0020186.name: Multilobulated spleen
HP:0020186.definition: The fetal spleen is lobulated, and these lobules normally disappear before the birth. Lobulation of the spleen may persist into adult life and be typically seen along the medial part of the spleen. A persisting lobule results in a variation in shape of the spleen.

HP:0020187.name: Thick pachygyria
HP:0020187.definition: Pachygyria with a very thick cerebral cortex measuring 10-20 mm. Note that cortical thickness cannot be measured reliably on scans done between 3 and 24 months of age.

HP:0020188.name: Anterior predominant pachygyria with 5-10 mm cortical thickness
HP:0020188.definition: Pachygyria with cortical thickness between 5 and 10 mm with and a posterior predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically over 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Posterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.

HP:0020189.name: Posterior predominant thick cortex pachygyria
HP:0020189.definition: Pachygyria with cortical thickness above 10 mm with and a posterior predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Posterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.

HP:0020190.name: Perisylvian predominant thick cortex pachygyria
HP:0020190.definition: Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and a perisylvian predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Perisylvian predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.

HP:0020191.name: Anterior predominant thick cortex pachygyria
HP:0020191.definition: Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and an anterior predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Anterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe over the frontal and temporal lobes.

HP:0020192.name: Pachygyria with 5-10 mm cortical thickness
HP:0020192.definition: Pachygyria with a mildly thickened cerebral cortex measuring 5-10 mm. Note that cortical thickness cannot be measured reliably on scans done between 3 and 24 months of age.

HP:0020193.name: Prolonged reptilase time
HP:0020193.definition: An abnormally increased duration of the reptilase time. Reptilase time is a functional plasma clotting assay, which is based on the enzymatic activity of batroxobin. By specifically cleaving fibrinogen A from fibrinogen, batroxobin leads to the formation of a stable fibrin clot. The time, starting from the addition of batroxobin to the plasma sample, until clot formation is the reptilase time and is given in seconds.

HP:0020194.name: IgA heavy chain paraproteinemia
HP:0020194.definition: An abnormal IgA heavy chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0020195.name: IgG heavy chain paraproteinemia
HP:0020195.definition: An abnormal IgG heavy chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0020196.name: IgM heavy chain paraproteinemia
HP:0020196.definition: An abnormal IgM heavy chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0020197.name: Increased circulating arachidonic acid concentration
HP:0020197.definition: An increased circulation of arachidonic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0020198.name: Abnormal circulating 18-hydroxycorticosterone level
HP:0020198.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of 18-Hydroxycorticosterone level in the blood circulation.

HP:0020199.name: Decreased circulating 18-hydroxycortisone level
HP:0020199.definition: A subnormal concentration of 18-Hydroxycorticosterone level in the blood circulation.

HP:0020200.name: Increased circulating 18-hydroxycortisone level
HP:0020200.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of 18-Hydroxycorticosterone level in the blood circulation.

HP:0020201.name: Abnormal sarcomere morphology
HP:0020201.definition: Any structural anomaly of the sarcomere, which is unit of a myofibril in a muscle cell, composed of an array of overlapping thick and thin filaments between two adjacent Z disks.

HP:0020202.name: Abnormal Z disk morphology
HP:0020202.definition: Any structural anomaly of the Z disk, which is the platelike region of a muscle sarcomere to which the plus ends of actin filaments are attached.

HP:0020203.name: Z-band streaming
HP:0020203.definition: Streaming or smearing of the Z band, which is then no longer confined to a narrow zone which bisects the I band. The Z disk may extend across the I band or the entire sarcomere in a zigzag manner. Focal thickening, smudging, and blurring of the Z band takes place concurrently. Myofibrillar disorganization is a frequent but not invariable accompanying change.

HP:0020204.name: Tubulointerstitial bacterial infiltration
HP:0020204.definition: Tubulointerstitial infiltration of bacteria identified on routine and/or special (Brown-Hopps) stains.

HP:0020205.name: Tubulointerstitial fungal infiltration
HP:0020205.definition: Tubulointerstitial infiltration of yeast or hyphal-microrganisms identified on routine and/or special (PAS, silver) stains.

HP:0020206.name: Simple ear
HP:0020206.definition: The pinna has fewer folds and grooves than usual.

HP:0020208.name: Eating-induced seizure
HP:0020208.definition: A seizure precipitated by aspects of anticipating food, eating itself, or the post-prandial period.

HP:0020209.name: Hot water-induced seizure
HP:0020209.definition: A seizure precipitated by pouring cupfuls of very hot water (40 to 50 degrees Celsius) in rapid succession over the head. Bathing in this manner is the most common trigger.

HP:0020210.name: Praxis-induced seizure
HP:0020210.definition: A seizure precipitated by complex, cognition-guided tasks often involving visuomotor coordination and decision-making.

HP:0020211.name: Proprioceptive-induced seizure
HP:0020211.definition: A seizure precipitated by movement or a change in posture.

HP:0020213.name: Somatosensory-induced seizure
HP:0020213.definition: A somatosensory reflex seizure is a seizure precipitated by somatic stimulation of a specific part of the body in the absence of startle or surprise.

HP:0020214.name: Startle-induced seizure
HP:0020214.definition: Startle-induced seizures are triggered by multiple and non-specific stimuli (auditory, somatosensory, and rarely visual) and are characterized by their sudden unexpected nature. Sudden noise rather than pure sound is the most effective acoustic stimulus.

HP:0020215.name: Thinking-induced seizure
HP:0020215.definition: Seizures induced by thinking and decision-making.

HP:0020216.name: Visually-induced seizure
HP:0020216.definition: Seizures evoked by visual stimuli. This includes clinical seizures induced by strobe lighting, television and other screens, flickering environmental lighting and self-induction by causing a strobe effect.

HP:0020217.name: Focal aware motor seizure
HP:0020217.definition: A type of focal motor seizure in which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

HP:0020218.name: Focal aware atonic seizure
HP:0020218.definition: A type of focal atonic seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0020219.name: Motor seizure
HP:0020219.definition: A motor seizure is a type of seizure that is characterized at onset by involvement of the skeletal musculature. The motor event could consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.

HP:0020220.name: Focal atonic seizure
HP:0020220.definition: A focal seizure characterized at onset by sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic activity, typically lasting more than 500 ms but less than 2 seconds. It may involve the head, trunk, jaw or limb musculature.

HP:0020221.name: Clonic seizure
HP:0020221.definition: A clonic seizure is a type of motor seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking, that is regularly repetitive.

HP:0020222.name: Hypohomocysteinemia
HP:0020222.definition: A decreased concentration of homocysteine in the blood.

HP:0020223.name: Dermal sinus tract
HP:0020223.definition: A dermal sinus tract is an abnormality present at birth over the dorsal midline where an abnormal epithelialized connection from the skin tracks inwards towards the spine, most commonly seen in the lumbosacral region.

HP:0020224.name: Mammary duct ectasia
HP:0020224.definition: A non-proliferative inflammatory disorder of the large duct (milk duct) of the breast; as such, it affects nipple and areola complex. The condition is characterized by focal dilatation of the lactiferous duct system is due to endoluminal changes, as well as the loss of duct wall elastin, leading to abnormally dilated and tortuous lactiferous ducts with associated periductal inflammation and fibrosis. Mammary duct ectasia may present with nipple discharge or palpable mass.

HP:0020225.name: Breast abscess
HP:0020225.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the breast.

HP:0020226.name: Nipple tenderness
HP:0020226.definition: Pain or discomfort produced by touching the nipple.

HP:0020227.name: Floating gallbladder
HP:0020227.definition: An abnormal configuration in which the gallbladder is pedunculated, hanging free of the liver, and attached only by the cystic mesentery,

HP:0020228.name: Biospecimen phenotypic feature
