HP:0020228.definition: A phenotypic abnormality obvserved in a biospecimen such as a biopsy or an extirpated tumor or tissue.

HP:0020229.name: Abnormal lymph-node biospecimen
HP:0020229.definition: Any abnormal phenotypic feature observed in a biospecimen derived from a lymph node, generally obtained by lymph node biopsy (removal of lymph node tissue for microscopic examination).

HP:0020230.name: Abnormal lymph-node tissue architecture
HP:0020230.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality of the architecture of the tissue of a lymph node.

HP:0020231.name: Abnormal lymph-node cellular finding
HP:0020231.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality within cells located in a lymph node.

HP:0020233.name: Abnormal lymph-node cellular antigen expression
HP:0020233.definition: Abnormal expression of an antigen (marker) by cells located in a lymph node.

HP:0020234.name: Altered lymph-node tissue architecture
HP:0020234.definition: An alteration that affects multiple components of the architecture of a lymph node.

HP:0020235.name: Effaced lymph-node architecture
HP:0020235.definition: Effacement of architecture typically refers to a cellular infiltrate destroying the normal follicular architecture of a lymph node. This effacement may result in sheets of cells that do not form clear architecture (seen in many lymphomas) or may lead to replacement of the normal architecture by atypical architecture, for example effacement of normal lymph node architecture (including normal follicles and patent lymph node sinuses) by many abnormal follicles in follicular lymphoma.

HP:0020236.name: Vaguely nodular lymph-node architecture
HP:0020236.definition: In contrast to normal lymph node architecture or that of follicular lymphoma, where follicles are typically distinct and readily identifiable on H&E stained biopsy sections, the cells within an atypical lymph node may show what appear to groups of cells forming vague nodules but not forming clear follicles.

HP:0020237.name: Lymph-node capsular invasion by lymphocytes
HP:0020237.definition: Migration of substantial numbers of lymphocytes into the capsule of a lymph node.

HP:0020238.name: Lymph-node extracapsular extension by lymph-node lymphocytes
HP:0020238.definition: Migration of lymphocytes into the soft tissues surrounding the lymph node.

HP:0020239.name: Increased lymph-node epithelioid histiocyte count
HP:0020239.definition: Number of epithelioid histiocytes (histiocytes are tissue-resident macrophages) located within a lymph node above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0020240.name: Scattered lymph node individual epithelioid histiocytes
HP:0020240.definition: Many individual (not clustered) epithelioid histiocytes throughout at least part of a lymph node.

HP:0020241.name: Clustered lymph node epithelioid histiocytes
HP:0020241.definition: Formation of clusters (group of cells positioned near each other) of epithelioid histiocytes within a lymph node.

HP:0020242.name: Abnormal lymph-node follicle architecture
HP:0020242.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality of the architecture of follicles of a lymph node.

HP:0020243.name: Floral-pattern lymph node follicles
HP:0020243.definition: Atypical lymph node follicles that have mantle zone cells invaginating/infiltrating into the follicle centers, which is said to confer a flower-like appearance.

HP:0020244.name: Colonization of follicles by lymphoma cells
HP:0020244.definition: In contrast to follicular lymphoma, which typically is a lymphoma that forms follicles or potentially completely replaces normal follicles, some lymphomas (most commonly marginal zone lymphoma) can infiltrate normal follicles so both normal lymphocytes and the infiltrating lymphoma cells are present. This is called colonization of follicles by the lymphoma cells.

HP:0020245.name: Crowded lymph-node follicles
HP:0020245.definition: Reduction in the average distance between adjacent lymph node follicles.

HP:0020246.name: Lymph-node follicular lysis
HP:0020246.definition: An abnormal morphology of hyperplastic lymph node follicles characterized by distortion of the follicular architecture by tongues and clusters of dark blue mantle cells impinging on and invading the reactive germinal center (Mostly T cells and mantle-zone B cells).

HP:0020247.name: Non-polarized lymph node germinal centers
HP:0020247.definition: A loss of the typical polarization of the architecture of a lymph node germinal center.

HP:0020248.name: Irregularly shaped lymph node germinal centers
HP:0020248.definition: A deviation from the typically fairly round or oval form of a lymph node germinal center.

HP:0020249.name: Abnormal lymph-node marginal or mantle zone morphology
HP:0020249.definition: An abnormality of the structure of the mantle or marginal zone of a lymph node.

HP:0020250.name: Abnormal lymph node marginal zone morphology

HP:0020251.name: Abnormal lymph node mantle zone morphology

HP:0020253.name: Lymph node with expanded mantle zones
HP:0020253.definition: Enlargement of the typical outer ring of small lymphocytes (mantle zone) surrounding a germinal center of a lymph node.

HP:0020254.name: Lymph node with poorly defined germinal center borders
HP:0020254.definition: Reduced demarcation of the border between germinal centers and mantle zones. This border is typically seen as a crisp line on hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained lymph node sections.

HP:0020255.name: Abnormal lymph-node germinal center morphology
HP:0020255.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality of germinal centers of a lymph node.

HP:0020257.name: Mantle zone pattern
HP:0020257.definition: This refers to an architectural pattern of infiltration where atypical lymphocytes surround germinal centers, often expanding the mantle zones but without effacing architecture.

HP:0020258.name: Germinal centers with absent marginal zones

HP:0020261.name: Poorly defined primary lymph-node follicles
HP:0020261.definition: Lack of the typical easily recognized delineation of primary follicles within lymph nodes.

HP:0020262.name: Progressive transformation of germinal centers
HP:0020262.definition: This is a condition sometimes seen in a subset of germinal centers of reactive lymph nodes where germinal centers become enlarged and infiltrated by benign mantle zone cells and some T cells.

HP:0020263.name: Absent germinal center tingible body macrophages
HP:0020263.definition: Lack of observable tingible body macrophages (TBMs) in germinal centers (GCs) of secondary lymphoid follicles. TBMs represent unique, large phagocytic cells that reside and are a subset of mononuclear phagocytes.

HP:0020264.name: Lack of germinal center mitotic figures
HP:0020264.definition: Absence of extreme paucity of mitotic figures in a lymph node germinal center.

HP:0020265.name: Non-polarized mantle zones
HP:0020265.definition: Lack of the typical polarization of the outer ring of small lymphocytes (mantle zone) surrounding a germinal center of a lymph node.

HP:0020266.name: Hyalinized lymph-node vessels
HP:0020266.definition: Hyalinized means to become clear/translucent such as collagen becoming more pale staining (collagen is typically quite eosinophilic, meaning attracted to the pink/red dye eosin); however, with regard to vessels in the lymph node, hyalinization is often used to describe vessel walls that appear markedly thickened or surrounded by eosinophilic material such as collagen, not necessarily translucent appearing.

HP:0020267.name: Lymph-node follicular sclerosis
HP:0020267.definition: Collagen deposition, typically with decreased cellularity, within lymph-node follicles.

HP:0020268.name: Compressed lymph-node sinuses
HP:0020268.definition: Loss of the typical patency (openness) of lymph node sinuses.

HP:0020269.name: Lymph-node proliferation centers
HP:0020269.definition: Proliferation centers are a finding specific to chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma where regions (typically relatively small, comparable to the size of a lymph node follicle) appear more pale on H&E stained sections (though they may become enlarged to merge together). These areas contain increased numbers of enlarged lymphoma cells with nucleoli (prolymphocytes and paraimmunoblasts) and show a higher proliferation rate (readily visualized with a Ki-67 immunohistochemical stain) than surrounding lymphoma cells. They can be mistaken as vague follicle formation and are therefore sometimes referred to as pseudofollicles.

HP:0020270.name: Cytologic atypia in mantle cells
HP:0020270.definition: Lymphocytes in the mantle zones of lymph node secondary follicles show cellular atypia such as enlarged size, increased cytoplasm, atypical distribution of chromatin, or irregular nuclear contours.

HP:0020271.name: Increased lymph-node eosinophils
HP:0020271.definition: Eosinophils count within a lymph node above normal limits.

HP:0020272.name: Increased lymph-node plasma cells
HP:0020272.definition: Number of plasma cells per lymph node above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0020273.name: High lymph node non-germinal center mitotic activity
HP:0020273.definition: Increased numbers of mitotic figures outside of germinal centers.

HP:0020274.name: Lymph-node lymphocyte monocytoid morphology
HP:0020274.definition: Lymphocytes that show morphologic features resembling monocytes, such as increased cytoplasm and slightly enlarged nuclei that are more irregular than most lymph node lymphocytes.

HP:0020275.name: Reduced lymph node lymphocyte morphological variability
HP:0020275.definition: Decreased morphological variability of lymph node lymphocytes as compared to the typically somewhat heterogeneous morphology of populations of benign lymph node lymphocytes.

HP:0020276.name: Increased large lymphocytes in lymph node
HP:0020276.definition: An increased number of large lymphocytes within a lymph node compared to a normal non-reactive lymph node.

HP:0020277.name: Hodgkin morphology cells
HP:0020277.definition: Hodgkin cells are typically large and often show very large nucleoli and sometimes binucleation or multinucleation. Reed-Sternberg cells are a type of Hodgkin cell that is binucleated with very large nucleoli that stains slightly red on H&E stained sections (often said to mimic owl eyes). Other Hodgkin cell morphologies include cells that are dying with dark basophilic (blue) nuclei that appear somewhat smudged (mummified cells) and cells with a large space around or adjacent to the nuclei and retracted cytoplasm after tissue fixation (lacunar cells). Hodgkin cells are characteristic of Hodgkin lymphoma, however several non-Hodgkin lymphomas and noN-neoplastic conditions are known to sometimes show a few similar morphology cells.

HP:0020279.name: Irregular lymph-node lymphocyte nuclei
HP:0020279.definition: Lymph node lymphocyte nuclei that are more irregular than the typical round to slightly oval shapes of the majority of lymph node lymphocytes.

HP:0020280.name: Lymph-node Dutcher bodies
HP:0020280.definition: Dutcher bodies are collections of immunoglobulin protein that overlie or invaginate into the nucleus of plasma cells. These nuclear pseudoinclusions can occasionally be seen in reactive states and may be increased in specific neoplastic conditions.

HP:0020281.name: Finely dispersed lymph node lymphocyte chromatin
HP:0020281.definition: Nuclei of lymphocytes with less dense, evenly distributed chromatin than the normal densely packed, often clumped chromatin of mature lymphocytes.

HP:0020282.name: Abnormal lymph-node lymphocyte chromatin
HP:0020282.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality of the chromatin (complex of DNA and protein which comprises chromosomes) of lymphocytes that are located within a lymph node.

HP:0020283.name: Clumping of lymph node lymphocyte chromatin
HP:0020283.definition: Nuclei of lymphocytes show multiple small densely packed areas of chromatin that appear as relatively evenly spaced clumps of basophilic (blue) staining within the nuclei on Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stained sections.

HP:0020284.name: Abnormal lymph-node lymphocyte cytoplasm morphology
HP:0020284.definition: Any phenotypic abnormality of the cytoplasm (material located within the cell membrane but excluding the nucleus) of lymphocytes that are located within a lymph node.

HP:0020285.name: Decreased lymph node lymphocyte cytoplasm
HP:0020285.definition: The amount of cytoplasm in lymphocytes is even less than the relatively little cytoplasm found in the majority of lymphocytes within lymph nodes.

HP:0020286.name: Increased lymph node lymphocyte cytoplasm
HP:0020286.definition: Increased amount of cytoplasm compared to the majority of lymphocytes in a benign lymph node.

HP:0020287.name: Abnormal level of lymph-node cellular CD19 expression
HP:0020287.definition: Detection of an abnormal level of CD19 on the cell(s) of interest in a lymph node with the use of anti-CD19 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0020288.name: Abnormal lymph-node cellular B-cell marker expression
HP:0020288.definition: Abnormal expression of an antigen (marker) that is normally expressed by B lymphocytes.

HP:0020289.name: Abnormal level of lymph-node cellular CD20 expression
HP:0020289.definition: Detection of abnormal levels of CD20 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD20 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0020290.name: CD79a expression
HP:0020290.definition: Detection of the presence of CD79a on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD79a antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0020291.name: Increased lymph-node cellular CD20 expression
HP:0020291.definition: Increased levels of CD20 expression compared to normal B cells.

HP:0020292.name: Decreased lymph-node cellular CD20 expression
HP:0020292.definition: Decreased levels of CD20 expression compared to normal B cells.

HP:0020293.name: Decreased lymph-node cellular CD19 expression
HP:0020293.definition: Decreased levels of CD19 expression compared to normal B cells.

HP:0020294.name: Increased lymph-node cellular CD19 expression
HP:0020294.definition: Increased levels of CD19 expression compared to normal B cells.

HP:0020295.name: PAX5 expression
HP:0020295.definition: Detection of the presence of PAX5 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-PAX5 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry).

HP:0020296.name: Germinal center B-lymphocyte BCL2 expression
HP:0020296.definition: Positive staining for BCL2 apoptosis regulator protein in lymph-node germinal center B cells.

HP:0025002.name: Abnormal cecum morphology
HP:0025002.definition: A structural anomaly of the cecum, which is the proximal blind pouch of the ascending colon, is located at the ileocecal junction in the right iliac fossa.

HP:0025004.name: Hallux rigidus
HP:0025004.definition: Osteoarthritis of the metatarsophalangeal joint of the first toe.

HP:0025005.name: Thickening of glomerular capillary wall
HP:0025005.definition: Widening of the wall of capillary blood vessels in the glomerulus. This feature may be produced by deposits and other changes affecting either subepithelial and subendothelial regions or the glomerular basement membrane itself.

HP:0025006.name: Abnormal glomerular capillary morphology
HP:0025006.definition: A structural anomaly of the capillary blood vessels in the renal glomerulus.

HP:0025007.name: Ectopic fovea
HP:0025007.definition: An abnormal anatomic position of the fovea, the small, central pit composed of closely packed cones that is located in the macula of the retina.

HP:0025008.name: Tracheal tug on inspiration
HP:0025008.definition: Downward movement of the trachea during inspiration due to downward traction on the tracheobronchial tree.

HP:0025009.name: Forward slanting upper incisors
HP:0025009.definition: The upper incisors deviate from the normal angle of being roughly parallel to the surface of the face and instead slant outwards.

HP:0025010.name: Foveal atrophy
HP:0025010.definition: Partial or complete loss of foveal tissue that was once present.

HP:0025011.name: Pyriform aperture stenosis
HP:0025011.definition: Narrowing of the anterior nasal aperture (piriform or pyriform aperture), which is a pear-shaped opening in the skull that forms the bony inlet of the nose.

HP:0025012.name: Status cribrosum
HP:0025012.definition: Diffusely widened perivascular spaces in the basal ganglia, affecting especially the corpus striatum. Status cribrosum is usually symmetrical, with the perivascular spaces showing CSF signal and without diffusion restriction. The word cribriform means sievelike, with multiple perforations.

HP:0025013.name: Decerebrate rigidity
HP:0025013.definition: A type of rigidity that is manifested by an exaggerated extensor posture of all extremities.

HP:0025014.name: Subcutaneous spheroids
HP:0025014.definition: Small, hard cyst-like nodules, freely moveable in the subcutis over the bony prominences of the legs and arms, which have an outer calcified layer with a translucent core on x-ray.

HP:0025016.name: Abnormal capillary morphology
HP:0025016.definition: A structural anomaly of the tiny blood vessels that connect arterioles with venules and whose walls act as semipermeable membranes that mediate the diffusion of fluids and gases between the blood circulation and body tissues.

HP:0025017.name: Capillary fragility
HP:0025017.definition: Reduced resistance to rupture of capillary blood vessels. Capillary fragility may manifest as a bleeding diathesis with spontaneous ecchymoses (bruises).

HP:0025018.name: Abnormal capillary physiology
HP:0025018.definition: A functional anomaly of the tiny blood vessels that connect arterioles with venules and whose walls act as semipermeable membranes that mediate the diffusion of fluids and gases between the blood circulation and body tissues.

HP:0025019.name: Arterial rupture
HP:0025019.definition: Sudden breakage of an artery leading to leakage of blood from the circulation.

HP:0025020.name: Elevated prostate-specific antigen level
HP:0025020.definition: An increased concentration of prostate specific antigen (PSA) in the circulation.

HP:0025021.name: Abnormal erythrocyte sedimentation rate
HP:0025021.definition: A deviation from normal range of the erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. An elevation may indicate inflammation or may be caused by any condition that elevates fibrinogen. A decreased ESR may be seen in polycythemia or in certain blood diseases in which red blood cells have an irregular or smaller shape that causes slower settling.

HP:0025022.name: Decreased erythrocyte sedimentation rate
HP:0025022.definition: A reduced erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). The ESR is a test that measures the distance that erythrocytes have fallen after one hour in a vertical column of anticoagulated blood under the influence of gravity. The ESR is a nonspecific finding. A decreased ESR may be seen in polycythemia or in certain blood diseases in which red blood cells have an irregular or smaller shape that causes slower settling.

HP:0025023.name: Rectal atresia
HP:0025023.definition: A developmental defect resulting in complete obliteration of the lumen of the rectum. That is, there is an abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the rectum.

HP:0025024.name: Megarectum
HP:0025024.definition: An abnormal dilation of the rectum. There is a large filled rectum as a result of underlying innervation or muscular abnormalities, which remains after disimpaction of the rectum.

HP:0025025.name: Rectovestibular fistula
HP:0025025.definition: A congenital malformation characterized by an abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the vulval vestibule, at the lower aspect of the vaginal opening.

HP:0025026.name: H-type rectovestibular fistula
HP:0025026.definition: Rectovestibular fistula with a normal anus is known as H-type fistula or double termination of the alimentary tract.

HP:0025027.name: Osteoma cutis
HP:0025027.definition: The term osteoma refers to the anomalous presence of ossification (bone formation) in the interior of the dermis or epidermis. The dermal or subcutaneous bone formation presents as stony hard nodules. The osteomata appear as irregular, hardened small nodules that are well circumscribed and generally of the same color as the skin.

HP:0025028.name: Abnormal enteric nervous system morphology
HP:0025028.definition: A structural anomaly of nerves of the enteric nervous system.

HP:0025030.name: Enteric neuronal degeneration
HP:0025030.definition: Deterioration of enteric neurons with impairment of enteric neuronal structure. Typical neuropathological findings include qualitative (e.g., neuronal swelling, intranuclear inclusions, axonal degeneration) and quantitative (e.g., reduction in the number of neurons) abnormalities of the enteric neurons.

HP:0025032.name: Abnormality of digestive system physiology
HP:0025032.definition: A functional anomaly of the digestive system.

HP:0025033.name: Abnormal digestive system morphology
HP:0025033.definition: A structural anomaly of the digestive system.

HP:0025034.name: Abnormal morphology of erythroid progenitor cell
HP:0025034.definition: Abnormal form of the progenitor cells committed to the erythroid lineage.

HP:0025035.name: Abnormal proerythroblast morphology
HP:0025035.definition: Anomalous form of the proerythroblast, i.e., the immature, nucleated erythrocyte occupying the stage of erythropoeisis that follows formation of erythroid progenitor cells. This cell is CD71-positive, has both a nucleus and a nucleolus, and lacks hematopoeitic lineage markers.

HP:0025037.name: Hypothalamic gliosis
HP:0025037.definition: Focal proliferation of glial cells in the hypothalamus.

HP:0025038.name: Intratesticular abscess
HP:0025038.definition: A collection of pus within a testicle. Ultrasonographic features include shaggy, irregular walls, intratesticular location, low-level internal echoes, and occasionally, hypervascular margins.

HP:0025039.name: Basal ganglia edema
HP:0025039.definition: Swelling within the basal ganglia due to the accumulation of fluid.

HP:0025040.name: Thalamic edema
HP:0025040.definition: Swelling within the thalamus due to the accumulation of fluid.

HP:0025042.name: Abnormality of mesenteric lymph nodes
HP:0025042.definition: A morphological anomaly of lymph nodes in the mesenteric root or throughout the mesentery.

HP:0025043.name: Enlarged mesenteric lymph node
HP:0025043.definition: Increase in size of one or more mesenteric lymph nodes.

HP:0025044.name: Lung abscess
HP:0025044.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in lung parenchyma, which leads to a cavity, and after formation of bronchopulmonary fistula, can manifest as an air-fluid level inside the cavity.

HP:0025045.name: Abnormal brain lactate level by MRS
HP:0025045.definition: A deviation from normal of the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025046.name: Reduced brain lactate level by MRS
HP:0025046.definition: A decrease in the level of lactate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025047.name: Abnormal brain choline level by MRS
HP:0025047.definition: A deviation from normal in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025048.name: Reduced brain choline level by MRS
HP:0025048.definition: An decrease in the level of choline-containing compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025049.name: Abnormal brain creatine level by MRS

HP:0025050.name: Elevated brain creatine level by MRS
HP:0025050.definition: An increase in the level of creatine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025051.name: Reduced brain creatine level by MRS
HP:0025051.definition: A decrease in the level of creatine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025052.name: Abnormal brain N-acetyl aspartate level by MRS
HP:0025052.definition: A deviation from normal in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025053.name: Elevated brain N-acetyl aspartate level by MRS
HP:0025053.definition: An increase in the level of N-acetyl aspartate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025057.name: Abnormal olfactory lobe morphology
HP:0025057.definition: A structural anomaly of the olfactory lobe, the structure within the brain that receives neural input from the nasal cavity and thereby processes the sense of smell.

HP:0025058.name: Hypothalamic atrophy
HP:0025058.definition: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of hypothalamus tissue that was once present.

HP:0025059.name: Splenic abscess
HP:0025059.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the parenchyma of the spleen.

HP:0025060.name: Multifocal splenic abscess
HP:0025060.definition: Multiple abscess lesions in the spleen.

HP:0025062.name: Geophagia
HP:0025062.definition: The practice of eating earth or soil-like substrates such as clay or chalk.

HP:0025063.name: Scaphoid abdomen
HP:0025063.definition: The anterior abdominal wall is sunken and presents a concave rather than a convex contour.

HP:0025065.name: Abnormal mean corpuscular volume
HP:0025065.definition: A deviation from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells, usually taken to be 80 to 100 femtoliters.

HP:0025066.name: Decreased mean corpuscular volume
HP:0025066.definition: A reduction from normal of the mean corpuscular volume, or mean cell volume (MCV) of red blood cells (usually defined as an MCV below 80 femtoliters).

HP:0025068.name: Incomitant strabismus
HP:0025068.definition: Strabismus in which the angle of deviation differs depending upon the direction of gaze or according to which eye is fixing, associated with: (i) defective movement of the eye, (ii) asymmetrical accommodative effort.

HP:0025069.name: Concomitant strabismus
HP:0025069.definition: Strabismus in which the angle of deviation of the squiting eye remains the same in relation to the other eye, in all directions of gaze, and whichever eye is fixing.

HP:0025070.name: Abnormal U wave
HP:0025070.definition: An anomaly of the U wave of the electrocardiogram (EKG). The U wave is a small (0.5 mm) deflection immediately following the T wave, usually in the same direction as the T wave. It is best seen in leads V2 and V3.

HP:0025071.name: U wave inversion
HP:0025071.definition: Direction of the U wave opposite to the T wave (i.e., below baseline) in leads with upright T waves.

HP:0025072.name: Prominent U wave
HP:0025072.definition: Increased amplitude of the U wave, defined as an amplitude greater than 1-2mm or 25 percent of the height of the T wave.

HP:0025073.name: Exercise-induced U wave inversion
HP:0025073.definition: U wave inversion that is induced by exercise stress testing.

HP:0025074.name: Abnormal QRS complex
HP:0025074.definition: An anomaly of the complex formed by the Q, R, and S waves, which occur in rapid succession on the electrocardiogram.

HP:0025075.name: Increased QRS voltage
HP:0025075.definition: Elevation of the voltage (height) of the QRS complex. There are several criteria in use, but the most common is the Sokolov-Lyon criterion (S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 greater than 35 mm).

HP:0025076.name: Abnormal QRS voltage
HP:0025076.definition: Abnormal amplitude of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG).

HP:0025077.name: Decreased QRS voltage
HP:0025077.definition: Reduced amplitude (height) of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG), defined as amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the limb leads are less than 5 mm or amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the precordial leads less than 10 mm.

HP:0025078.name: Electrical alternans
HP:0025078.definition: The QRS complexes of the electrocardiogram alternate in height.

HP:0025079.name: Pancreatic abscess
HP:0025079.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the parenchyma of the pancreas.

HP:0025080.name: Orthokeratotic hyperkeratosis
HP:0025080.definition: A form of hyperkeratosis characterized by thickening of the cornified layer without retained nuclei.

HP:0025081.name: Darier's sign
HP:0025081.definition: A skin change elicited by briskly rubbing the skin lesion in urticaria pigmentosa (UP), whereby the area begins to itch and becomes raised and surrounded by erythema. Unlike other forms of dermatographism, Darier's sign refers to urtication that is limited to the UP involved areas and, as in this case, spares the skin unaffected by UP.

HP:0025082.name: Abnormal cutaneous elastic fiber morphology
HP:0025082.definition: Any structural anomaly of the elastic fibers of the skin. Elastic fibers are the essential extracellular matrix macromolecules comprising an elastin core surrounded by a mantle of fibrillin-rich microfibrils.

HP:0025083.name: Elevated dermal desmosine content
HP:0025083.definition: An increased amount of desmosine measure in the skin. Desmosine is a cross-linking amino acid formed from lysyl residues in elastin.

HP:0025084.name: Folliculitis
HP:0025084.definition: Inflammatory cells within the wall and ostia of the hair follicle, creating a follicular-based pustule.

HP:0025085.name: Bloody diarrhea
HP:0025085.definition: Passage of many stools containing blood.

HP:0025086.name: Bloody mucoid diarrhea
HP:0025086.definition: Passage of many stools containing blood and mucus.

HP:0025087.name: Delayed recoil upon stretching of skin
HP:0025087.definition: Area of skin requiring an increased amount of time to return to its original shape after being stretched.

HP:0025088.name: Onychomadesis
HP:0025088.definition: Complete shedding (separation) of the nail from the proximal matrix. Onychomadesis is the proximal separation of the nail plate from the nail matrix due to a temporary cessation of nail growth.

HP:0025089.name: Feculent vomiting
HP:0025089.definition: Vomiting of material that is of fecal origin.

HP:0025090.name: Abnormal large intestinal mucosa morphology
HP:0025090.definition: A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the large intestine.

HP:0025092.name: Epidermal acanthosis
HP:0025092.definition: Diffuse hypertrophy or thickening of the stratum spinosum of the epidermis (prickle cell layer of the skin).

HP:0025093.name: Peripapillary exudate
HP:0025093.definition: A retinal exudate in the area surrounding the optic nerve head.

HP:0025094.name: Disciform macular scar
HP:0025094.definition: A subretinal scar with a disc-like shape in the region of the macula.

HP:0025095.name: Sneeze
HP:0025095.definition: A sudden violent, spasmodic, audible expiration of breath through the nose and mouth.

HP:0025097.name: Eyelid myoclonus
HP:0025097.definition: Marked, involuntary jerking of the eyelids.

HP:0025098.name: Dysgenesis of the hypothalamus
HP:0025098.definition: Structural abnormality of the hypothalamus related to defective development.

HP:0025099.name: Dysgenesis of the thalamus
HP:0025099.definition: Structural abnormality of the thalamus related to defective development.

HP:0025100.name: Abnormal hippocampus morphology
HP:0025100.definition: Any structural anomaly of the hippocampus,

HP:0025101.name: Dysgenesis of the hippocampus
HP:0025101.definition: Structural abnormality of the hippocampus related to defective development.

HP:0025102.name: Dysgenesis of the basal ganglia
HP:0025102.definition: Structural abnormality of the basal ganglia related to defective development.

HP:0025103.name: Umbilicated nodule
HP:0025103.definition: A type of skin nodule that has a small depression that resembles a navel (i.e., is umbilicated).

HP:0025104.name: Capillary malformation
HP:0025104.definition: A capillary malformation is a flat, sharply defined vascular stain of the skin. It may cover a large surface area or it may be scattered and appear as little islands of color. In a capillary maformation, the predominant vessels are small, slow-flow vessels (i.e., arterioles and postcapillary venules).

HP:0011567.name: Sinus venosus atrial septal defect
HP:0011567.definition: An interatrial communication caused by a deficiency of the common wall between the superior vena cava (SVC) and the right-sided pulmonary veins. SVASD is commonly associated with anomalous pulmonary venous connection (APVC) of some or all of the pulmonary veins, which produces additional left-to-right shunting.

HP:0011568.name: Double orifice mitral valve
HP:0011568.definition: The left atrio-ventricular connection consists of two anatomically distinct orifices separated by accessory fibrous tissue.

HP:0011569.name: Cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet
HP:0011569.definition: Cleft in the anterior mitral valve leaflet not associated with an atrioventricular canal defect.

HP:0011571.name: Parachute mitral valve
HP:0011571.definition: Abnormality of the mitral valve apparatus, whereby chordae attach to a single papillary muscle or hypoplastic papillary muscles.

HP:0011572.name: Supramitral ring
HP:0011572.definition: A congenital stenotic mitral valvular anomaly with a ring of tissue above the mitral valve.

HP:0011573.name: Hypoplastic tricuspid valve
HP:0011573.definition: Congenital defect characterized by underdevelopment of the tricuspid valve.

HP:0011574.name: Imperforate atrioventricular valve
HP:0011574.definition: An atrioventricular valve that has failed to open (atretic).

HP:0011575.name: Imperforate tricuspid valve
HP:0011575.definition: A tricuspid valve that has failed to open.

HP:0011576.name: Intermediate atrioventricular canal defect
HP:0011576.definition: A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and inlet ventricular defect. There is one valve annulus and two valve orifices.

HP:0011577.name: Partial atrioventricular canal defect
HP:0011577.definition: A specific combination of heart defects including a primum atrial septal defect and cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet. There is not an inlet ventricular septal defect present. There are two valve annuluses and two valve orifices.

HP:0011578.name: Transitional atrioventricular canal defect
HP:0011578.definition: A specific combination of heart defects with a primum atrial septal defect, cleft anterior mitral valve leaflet, and an inlet ventricular septal defect. There are two valve annuli and two valve orifices.

HP:0011579.name: Unbalanced atrioventricular canal defect
HP:0011579.definition: Anatomic features of unbalanced atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD) include varying amounts of ventricular hypoplasia, as well as malalignment of the atrioventricular junction. In complete AVSD, the common AV valve can be situated either equally over the right and left ventricles (balanced) or unequally over the ventricles (unbalanced).

HP:0011580.name: Short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve
HP:0011580.definition: Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve.

HP:0011581.name: Double outlet left ventricle
HP:0011581.definition: A congenital defect of heart development characterized by origin of both pulmonary artery and aorta from the morphological left ventricle.

HP:0011582.name: Abdominal ectopia cordis
HP:0011582.definition: Displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and into the abdomen.

HP:0011583.name: Cervical ectopia cordis
HP:0011583.definition: A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region and without a defect of the sternum.

HP:0011584.name: Thoracocervical ectopia cordis
HP:0011584.definition: A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region with a defect of the superior portion of the sternum.

HP:0011585.name: Thoracic ectopia cordis
HP:0011585.definition: Congenital malformation of the thoracic wall with partial or total displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity. This feature is associated with sternal cleft or absence of the sternum.

HP:0011586.name: Thoracoabdominal ectopia cordis
HP:0011586.definition: Congenital malformation of the ventral wall with partial or total evisceration of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and displacement partially into the abdominal cavity.

HP:0011587.name: Abnormal branching pattern of the aortic arch
HP:0011587.definition: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.

HP:0011588.name: Cervical aortic arch
HP:0011588.definition: The aortic arch extends into the soft tissues of the neck before turning down into to become the descending aorta.

HP:0011589.name: Common origin of the right brachiocephalic artery and left common carotid artery
HP:0011589.definition: The left common carotid artery has a common origin with the innominate artery.

HP:0011590.name: Double aortic arch
HP:0011590.definition: A conenital abnormality of the aortic arch in which the two embryonic aortc arches form a vascular ring that surrounds the trachea or esophagus and then join to form the descending aorta. Double aortic arch can cause symptoms because of compression of the esophagus (dysphagia, cyanosis while eating) or trachea (stridor).

HP:0011591.name: Left aortic arch with cervical origin of the right subclavian artery

HP:0011592.name: Left aortic arch with isolated subclavian artery
HP:0011592.definition: The subclavian artery arises from ductus arteriosus. While the ductus arteriosus is patent its blood supply comes from the ductus, hence from the pulmonary artery. After it closes, the blood supply is retrogradely from the vertebral artery via the circle of Willis.

HP:0011593.name: Left aortic arch with retroesophageal diverticulum of Kommerell
HP:0011593.definition: A patent ductus arteriosus or ductal ligament completes the ring.

HP:0011594.name: Right aortic arch with retroesophageal diverticulum of Kommerell
HP:0011594.definition: Aortic arch crosses the right mainstem bronchus. The left carotid artery is the first branch, right carotid artery the second branch and right subclavian artery as the third branch.

HP:0011595.name: Left aortic arch with retroesophageal right subclavian artery
HP:0011595.definition: Aortic arch crosses the left mainstem bronchus. The first branch is the right carotid artery, the second branch is the left carotid artery, the third branch is the subclavian artery, the fourth branch is the right subclavian artery arising from the posteromedial aspect of the distal aortic arch and continuing posterior to the esophagus to the right hand side of the body.

HP:0011596.name: Left aortic arch with right descending aorta and right ductus arteriosus
HP:0011596.definition: The ring may be completed by the ductal ligament.

HP:0011597.name: Right aortic arch with left descending aorta and left ductus arteriosus

HP:0011598.name: Right aortic arch with retroesophageal left subclavian artery

HP:0011599.name: Mesocardia
HP:0011599.definition: Mesocardia is an abnormal location of the heart in which the heart is in a midline position and the longitudinal axis of the heart lies in the mid-sagittal plane.

HP:0011600.name: Abnormal direction of ventricular apex
HP:0011600.definition: Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex. Left sided is normal.

HP:0011601.name: Rightward direction of ventricular apex
HP:0011601.definition: Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex towards the right. Left sided is normal.

HP:0011602.name: Midline direction of ventricular apex
HP:0011602.definition: Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex in the midline. Left sided is normal.

HP:0011603.name: Congenital malformation of the great arteries
HP:0011603.definition: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the aorta and pulmonary arteries.

HP:0011604.name: Aortopulmonary window
HP:0011604.definition: A congenital anomaly with an abnormal connection between the aorta and the main pulmonary artery resulting in an aortopulmonary shunt.

HP:0011605.name: obsolete Congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries with ventricular septal defect

HP:0011606.name: obsolete Transposition of the great arteries with intact ventricular septum

HP:0011607.name: obsolete Transposition of the great arteries with ventricular septal defect

HP:0011608.name: Type II truncus arteriosus
HP:0011608.definition: Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) with each pulmonary artery arising separate from each other on the posterior or lateral aspect of the truncus.

HP:0011609.name: Type III truncus arteriosus
HP:0011609.definition: Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby one of the two pulmonary artery branched does not arise from the common pulmonary trunk, but instead from the ductus arteriosus or directly from the aorta.

HP:0011610.name: Type IV truncus arteriosus
HP:0011610.definition: Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby the aortic arch is hypoplastic or interrupted, and a large patent ductus arteriosus is present.

HP:0011611.name: Interrupted aortic arch
HP:0011611.definition: Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.

HP:0011612.name: Interrupted aortic arch type A
HP:0011612.definition: Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment at the level of the isthmus.

HP:0011613.name: Interrupted aortic arch type B
HP:0011613.definition: Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment between the left carotid and subclavian arteries.

HP:0011614.name: Interrupted aortic arch type C
HP:0011614.definition: Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment between the innominate and left carotid arteries.

HP:0011615.name: Abnormal pulmonary situs morphology
HP:0011615.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, which is defined by characteristics such as the number of lobes per lung and the relationship of the pulmonary arteries to their bronchi.

HP:0011616.name: Pulmonary situs inversus
HP:0011616.definition: Mirror image arrangement of the mainstem bronchi with the right pulmonary artery posterior to the right upper lobe bronchus and the left pulmonary artery anterior to the left upper lobe bronchus.

HP:0011617.name: Pulmonary situs ambiguus
HP:0011617.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which the morphology of both left and right lungs is the same.

HP:0011618.name: Pulmonary situs ambiguus with bilateral morphologic right lungs
HP:0011618.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a right lung.

HP:0011619.name: Pulmonary situs ambiguus with bilateral morphologic left lungs
HP:0011619.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a left lung.

HP:0011620.name: Abnormality of abdominal situs
HP:0011620.definition: An abnormality of the abdominal situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the abdomen and its organs.

HP:0011621.name: Gerbode ventricular septal defect
HP:0011621.definition: A type of ventricular septal defect communicating directly between the left ventricle and right atrium. This is anatomically possible because the normal tricuspid valve is more apically displaced than the mitral valve.

HP:0011622.name: Inlet ventricular septal defect
HP:0011622.definition: A ventricular septal defect that involves the inlet of the right ventricular septum immediately inferior to the AV valve apparatus.

HP:0011623.name: Muscular ventricular septal defect
HP:0011623.definition: The trabecular septum is the largest part of the interventricular septum. It extends from the membranous septum to the apex and superiorly to the infundibular septum. A defect in the trabecular septum is called muscular VSD if the defect is completely rimmed by muscle.

HP:0011624.name: Apical muscular ventricular septal defect
HP:0011624.definition: A muscular ventricular septal defect located at the apex of the heart.

HP:0011625.name: Multiple muscular ventricular septal defects
HP:0011625.definition: A type of muscular ventricular septal defect characterized by the presence of multiple small defects in the ventricular septum.

HP:0011626.name: Scimitar anomaly
HP:0011626.definition: Right pulmonary venous return to the inferior vena cava.

HP:0011627.name: Aorto-ventricular tunnel
HP:0011627.definition: Aorto-ventricular tunnel is a congenital, extracardiac channel which connects the ascending aorta above the sinotubular junction to the cavity of the left, or (less commonly) right ventricle.

HP:0011628.name: Congenital defect of the pericardium
HP:0011628.definition: A developmental defect of the pericardium with congenital onset.

HP:0011629.name: Total absence of the pericardium
HP:0011629.definition: No pericardium around the heart, occurring as a congenital defect, not the result of a surgical pericardectomy.

HP:0011630.name: Complete diaphragmatic absence of pericardium
HP:0011630.definition: No pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.

HP:0011631.name: Complete right sided absence of pericardium
HP:0011631.definition: No pericardium is present on the righthand side of the heart. It is a congenital absence of pericardium rather than the result of a pericardectomy.

HP:0011632.name: Partial right sided absence of pericardium
HP:0011632.definition: A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the righthand side of the heart.

HP:0011633.name: Complete left sided absence of pericardium
HP:0011633.definition: A congenital anomaly with complete lack of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.

HP:0011634.name: Partial left sided absence of pericardium
HP:0011634.definition: A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.

HP:0011635.name: Partial diaphragmatic absence of pericardium
HP:0011635.definition: Lack of a part of the pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.

HP:0011636.name: Abnormal coronary artery origin
HP:0011636.definition: Isolated abnormalities of the coronary artery origins. This may be in associated with other structural heart malformations but not the patterns of complex structural heart malformations which result in abnormal course of the coronary arteries.

HP:0011637.name: Anomalous origin of coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
HP:0011637.definition: A coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta.

HP:0011638.name: Anomalous origin of left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
HP:0011638.definition: Left main coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the left cusp of the aortic valve.

HP:0011639.name: Anomalous origin of right coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
HP:0011639.definition: Right coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the right cusp of the aortic valve.

HP:0011640.name: Single coronary artery origin
HP:0011640.definition: The presence of a single coronary artery ostium from which both coronary arteries arise.

HP:0011641.name: Coronary artery fistula
HP:0011641.definition: A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and a heart chamber or another blood vessel.

HP:0011642.name: Abnormal coronary sinus morphology
HP:0011642.definition: An abnormality of the coronary sinus, which is formed by the union of the great cardiac vein and the left marginal vein and terminates in the right atrium. The coronary sinus functions to o collect deoxygenated blood from the myocardium of the heart and drain it into the right atrium.

HP:0011643.name: Coronary sinus atrial septal defect
HP:0011643.definition: An atrial septal defect characterized by a deficiency in the tissue separating the coronary sinus from the left atrium (LA). This results in partial or complete unroofing of the coronary sinus leading to a predominantly left-to-right shunt through the coronary sinus (LA to coronary sinus to right atrium [RA]). The orifice of the ostium is frequently large because of the increased flow. From the RA side, the defect is located at the level of the coronary sinus ostium and may also include some deficiency in atrial tissue around the ostium. From the LA side, the size can be variable depending on the degree of unroofing of the coronary sinus.

HP:0011644.name: Coronary sinus diverticulum
HP:0011644.definition: A venous pouch within the left ventricular wall, with a neck opening into the coronary sinus.

HP:0011645.name: Dilatation of the sinus of Valsalva
HP:0011645.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation of one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.

HP:0011646.name: Juxtaductal coarctation of the aorta
HP:0011646.definition: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized at the insertion of the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the juxtaductal region of aortic arch.

HP:0011647.name: Postductal coarctation of the aorta
HP:0011647.definition: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized distal to the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the postductal region of aortic arch.

HP:0011648.name: Patent ductus arteriosus after birth at term
HP:0011648.definition: Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus in postnatal life when birth was at 37 completed weeks of gestation or greater.

HP:0011649.name: Patent ductus arteriosus after premature birth
HP:0011649.definition: Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus when birth was at less than 37 weeks completed gestation.

HP:0011650.name: Bilateral ductus arteriosus
HP:0011650.definition: The presence of both a left and a right ductus arteriosus.

HP:0011651.name: Double outlet right ventricle with doubly committed ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011651.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011652.name: Double outlet right ventricle with doubly committed ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011652.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011653.name: Double outlet right ventricle with non-committed ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011653.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a non-committed ventricular septal defect (VSD), which is a VSD that is anatomically related to, or close to, neither great vessel, being separated from both by considerable muscle, and also has a pulmonary stenosis; abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011654.name: Double outlet right ventricle with non-committed ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011654.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a non-committed ventricular septal defect (VSD), which is a VSD that is anatomically related to, or close to, neither great vessel, being separated from both by considerable muscle, but there is not accompanying pulmonary stenosis; the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011655.name: Double outlet right ventricle with subaortic ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011655.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011656.name: Double outlet right ventricle with subaortic ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011656.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011657.name: Double outlet right ventricle with subpulmonary ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011657.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011658.name: Double outlet right ventricle with subpulmonary ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011658.definition: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.

HP:0011659.name: Tetralogy of Fallot with absent pulmonary valve
HP:0011659.definition: Features of tetralogy of Fallot with either rudimentary ridges or the complete absence of pulmonic valve tissue.

HP:0011660.name: Anomalous origin of one pulmonary artery from ascending aorta
HP:0011660.definition: Anomalous origin of one pulmonary artery from the ascending aorta with the contralateral pulmonary artery arising from the right ventricle.

HP:0011661.name: Anomalous origin of left pulmonary artery from ascending aorta
HP:0011661.definition: The left pulmonary artery originates from the ascending aorta in the presence of a pulmonary valve and main pulmonary artery.

HP:0011662.name: Tricuspid atresia
HP:0011662.definition: Failure to develop of the tricuspid valve and thus lack of the normal connection between the right atrium and the right ventricle.

HP:0011663.name: Right ventricular cardiomyopathy
HP:0011663.definition: Right ventricular dysfunction (global or regional) with functional and morphological right ventricular abnormalities, with or without left ventricular disease.

HP:0011664.name: Left ventricular noncompaction cardiomyopathy
HP:0011664.definition: Left ventricular non-compaction (LVNC) is characterized by prominent left ventricular trabeculae and deep inter-trabecular recesses. The myocardial wall is often thickened with a thin, compacted epicardial layer and a thickened endocardial layer. In some patients, LVNC is associated with left ventricular dilatation and systolic dysfunction, which can be transient in neonates.

HP:0011665.name: Takotsubo cardiomyopathy
HP:0011665.definition: Transient left ventricular apical ballooning syndrome or takotsubo cardiomyopathy is characterized by transient regional systolic dysfunction involving the left ventricular apex and/or mid-ventricle in the absence of obstructive coronary disease on coronary angiography. Patients present with an abrupt onset of angina-like chest pain, and have diffuse T-wave inversion, sometimes preceded by ST-segment elevation, and mild cardiac enzyme elevation.

HP:0011666.name: Absent right superior vena cava
HP:0011666.definition: Absence of the right superior vena cava (RSVC). An absent RSVC is always associated with a persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC). During normal fetal development, the left-sided anterior venous cardinal system regresses, leaving the coronary sinus (CS) and the ligament of Marshall. Failure of the closure of the left anterior cardinal vein results in PLSVC. In general, PLSVC is associated with the right superior vena cava (RSVC) and drains into the RA via a dilated CS. When developmental arrest occurs at an earlier stage, the CS is absent and the PLSVC drains into the left atrium.

HP:0011667.name: Bilateral superior vena cava with bridging vein

HP:0011668.name: Bilateral superior vena cava with no bridging vein

HP:0011669.name: Left superior vena cava draining directly to the left atrium
HP:0011669.definition: A persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC) that drains into the left atrium instead of the right atrium via the coronary sinus, resulting in a right to left sided shunt.

HP:0011670.name: Left superior vena cava draining to coronary sinus
HP:0011670.definition: A persistent left superior vena cava (PLSVC) that drains into the right atrium via the coronary sinus. This is the case in 80-92% of cases of PLSVC and results in no hemodynamic consequence.

HP:0011671.name: Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation
HP:0011671.definition: Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation is the result of connection failure between the right subcardinal vein and the right vitelline vein. Consequently, venous blood from the caudal part of the body reaches the heart via the azygous vein and superior vena cava.

HP:0011672.name: Cardiac myxoma
HP:0011672.definition: A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) of the heart. Cardiac myxomas consist of stellate to plump, cytologically bland mesenchymal cells set in a myxoid stroma. Cardiac myxomas are of endocardial origin and general project from the endocardium into a cardiac chamber.

HP:0011673.name: Cardiac hemangioma
HP:0011673.definition: Abnormal proliferation of blood vessels within the cardiac cavities attached to the endocardium.

HP:0011674.name: Cardiac teratoma
HP:0011674.definition: A teratoma within the heart. Most commonly, these tumors are detected in the pericardial cavity attached to the pulmonary artery and aorta. The tumor size within the heart varies from 2 to 9 cm in diameter, and intrapericardial tumors as large as 15 cm have been reported. Intracardiac tumors arise from the atrial or ventricular wall as nodular masses protruding into the cardiac chambers. Cardiac and pericardial teratomas are easily detected in the fetus and neonate by two-dimensional echocardiography as heterogeneous and encapsulated cystic masses. Histologically, cardiac teratomas contain multiple immature elements including epithelium, neuroglial tissue, thyroid, pancreas, smooth and skeletal muscle, cartilage and bone.

HP:0011675.name: Arrhythmia
HP:0011675.definition: Any cardiac rhythm other than the normal sinus rhythm. Such a rhythm may be either of sinus or ectopic origin and either regular or irregular. An arrhythmia may be due to a disturbance in impulse formation or conduction or both.

HP:0011676.name: Tetralogy of Fallot with absent subarterial conus

HP:0011677.name: Tetralogy of Fallot with atrioventricular canal defect

HP:0011678.name: Tetralogy of Fallot with pulmonary atresia and major aortopulmonary collateral arteries
HP:0011678.definition: A type of tetralogy of Fallot with pulmonary atresia in which all pulmonary blood flow is derived from major aortopulmonary collateral arteries (MAPCA).

HP:0011679.name: Tetralogy of Fallot with pulmonary stenosis
HP:0011679.definition: The commonest form of tetralogy of Fallot characterized by pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy, without pulmonary atresia, absent pulmonary valve, atrioventricular canal defect or absent subarterial conus.

HP:0011681.name: Subarterial ventricular septal defect
HP:0011681.definition: A ventricular septal defect that lies beneath the semilunar valve(s) in the conal or outlet septum.

HP:0011682.name: Perimembranous ventricular septal defect
HP:0011682.definition: A ventricular septal defect that is confluent with and involves the membranous septum and is bordered by an atrioventricular valve, not including the type 3 VSDs.

HP:0011683.name: Restrictive ventricular septal defect
HP:0011683.definition: Any ventricular septal defect (VSD) that is small enough to restrict flow across it such that a pressure gradient exists between the two sides of the VSD.

HP:0011684.name: Non-restrictive ventricular septal defect
HP:0011684.definition: Any ventricular septal defect (VSD) that does not restrict flow across it sufficiently to generate a pressure gradient between the two sides of the VSD.

HP:0011685.name: Infra-aortic superior vena cava
HP:0011685.definition: The superior vena cava passes below the aortic arch.

HP:0011686.name: Abnormal coronary artery course
HP:0011686.definition: An abnormal path of a coronary artery.

HP:0011687.name: AV nodal tachycardia
HP:0011687.definition: A type of supraventricular tachycardia that originates in the atrioventricular node.

HP:0011688.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with an accessory connection mediated pathway
HP:0011688.definition: Supraventricular tachycardia in which an accessory pathway connecting the atria and ventricles, apart from the AV node, participates as a necessary part of a reentrant mechanism.

HP:0011689.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a concealed accessory connection
HP:0011689.definition: Supraventricular tachycardia with an accessory connection mediated pathway that is called concealed because it is not seen on the ECG during sinus rhythm.

HP:0011690.name: Permanent junctional reciprocating tachycardia
HP:0011690.definition: An incessant orthodromic tachycardia with anterograde conduction over the atrioventricular node and by retrograde conduction via an accessory pathway usually located in the posteroseptal region with slow and decremental conduction.

HP:0011691.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a concealed accessory pathway on the left free wall

HP:0011692.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a concealed accessory pathway on the right free wall

HP:0011693.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a concealed accessory pathway on the septum

HP:0011694.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a manifest accessory pathway

HP:0011695.name: Cerebellar hemorrhage
HP:0011695.definition: Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the cerebellum.

HP:0011696.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a manifest accessory pathway on the left free wall

HP:0011697.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a manifest accessory pathway on the right free wall

HP:0011698.name: Supraventricular tachycardia with a manifest accessory pathway on the septum

HP:0011700.name: Automatic atrial tachycardia
HP:0011700.definition: Chronic supraventricular tachycardia predominantly seen in childhood.

HP:0011701.name: Multifocal atrial tachycardia
HP:0011701.definition: Multifocal atrial tachycardia is a rare supraventricular arrhythmia in neonates and young infants that is characterized by multiple P waves with varying P wave morphology and is usually asymptomatic.

HP:0011702.name: Abnormal electrophysiology of sinoatrial node origin
HP:0011702.definition: An abnormality of the sinoatrial (SA) node in the right atrium. THe SA node acts as the pacemaker of the heart.

HP:0011703.name: Sinus tachycardia
HP:0011703.definition: Heart rate of greater than 100 beats per minute.

HP:0011704.name: Sick sinus syndrome
HP:0011704.definition: An abnormality involving the generation of the action potential by the sinus node and is characterized by an atrial rate inappropriate for physiological requirements. Manifestations include severe sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses or arrest, sinus node exit block, chronic atrial tachyarrhythmias, alternating periods of atrial bradyarrhythmias and tachyarrhythmias, and inappropriate responses of heart rate during exercise or stress.

HP:0011705.name: First degree atrioventricular block
HP:0011705.definition: Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.

HP:0011706.name: Second degree atrioventricular block
HP:0011706.definition: An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.

HP:0011707.name: Mobitz I atrioventricular block
HP:0011707.definition: Progressive PR interval prolongation with the subsequent occurrence of a single nonconducted P wave that results in a pause. The pause that follows the nonconducted impulse is less than fully compensatory (less than the sum of two normal sinus intervals).

HP:0011708.name: Mobitz II atrioventricular block
HP:0011708.definition: A type of second degree atrioventricular (AV) block characterized by sudden failure to conduct an impulse through the AV node without a preceding change in the PR interval.

HP:0011709.name: Atrioventricular dissociation
HP:0011709.definition: Atrioventricular (AV) dissociation is present if the atria and the ventricles are under the control of two separate pacemakers. AV dissociation can occur in the absence of a primary AV conduction disturbance.

HP:0011710.name: Bundle branch block
HP:0011710.definition: Block of conduction of electrical impulses along the Bundle of His or along one of its bundle branches.

HP:0011711.name: Left anterior fascicular block
HP:0011711.definition: Conduction block in the anterior division of the left bundle branch of the bundle of His.

HP:0011712.name: Complete right bundle branch block
HP:0011712.definition: A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.

HP:0011713.name: Left bundle branch block
HP:0011713.definition: A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.

HP:0011714.name: Libman-Sacks lesions
HP:0011714.definition: Libman-Sacks valvular lesions are sterile fibrofibrinous vegetations that favor the left-sided heart valves and usually form on the ventricular surface of the mitral valve.

HP:0011715.name: Trifascicular block
HP:0011715.definition: Abnormal conduction in all three divisions of the intraventricular conducting tissue.

HP:0011716.name: Junctional ectopic tachycardia
HP:0011716.definition: Junctional ectopic tachycardia (JET) is a unique type of supraventricular arrhythmia defined by narrow QRS complex and atrioventricular (AV) dissociation or retrograde atrial conduction in a 1:1 pattern.

HP:0011717.name: Atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia
HP:0011717.definition: Accessory pathway-related atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) involves an abnormal electrical conduction of the accessory pathway. The accessory pathway connecting impulses between the atrium and the ventricle can be seen at any site in the AV groove.

HP:0011718.name: Abnormality of the pulmonary veins
HP:0011718.definition: An abnormality of the pulmonary veins.

HP:0011719.name: Supracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
HP:0011719.definition: Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.

HP:0011720.name: Cardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
HP:0011720.definition: Type 2 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.

HP:0011721.name: Infracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
HP:0011721.definition: Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.

HP:0011722.name: Mixed total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
HP:0011722.definition: Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.

HP:0011723.name: Congenital malformation of the right heart
HP:0011723.definition: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the right heart identifiable at birth.

HP:0011724.name: Uhl's anomaly
HP:0011724.definition: Uhl anomaly of the right ventricle refers to the almost complete absence of right ventricular myocardium, normal tricuspid valve, and preserved septal and left ventricular myocardium.

HP:0011726.name: Persistent fetal circulation
HP:0011726.definition: Systemic desaturation of a liveborn baby resulting from persistent pulmonary hypertension with a patent ductus arteriosus and patent foramen ovale, such that the circulation in postnatal life follows the fetal course.

HP:0011728.name: Elbow clonus
HP:0011728.definition: Clonus at the elbow joint, i.e., an exaggerated phasic stretch reflex characterized by repetitive, rhythmic contractions at the elbow, generated by rapid passive stretch at the elbow joint.

HP:0011729.name: Abnormality of joint mobility
HP:0011729.definition: An abnormality in the range and ease of motion of joints across their normal range.

HP:0011730.name: Abnormal central sensory function
HP:0011730.definition: An abnormality of sensation related to CNS function. Assuming the primary sensory modalities are intact and the patient is alert and cooperative, the presence of an abnormality of sensory function may indicate a lesion of a parietal cortex, the thalamocortical projections to the parietal cortex, or the spinal cord.

HP:0011731.name: Abnormality of circulating cortisol level
HP:0011731.definition: An abnormality of the concentration of cortisol in the blood.

HP:0011732.name: Abnormal adrenal morphology
HP:0011732.definition: Any structural anomaly of the adrenal glands.

HP:0011733.name: Abnormality of adrenal physiology
HP:0011733.definition: A functional abnormality of the adrenal glands.

HP:0011734.name: Central adrenal insufficiency
HP:0011734.definition: A form of adrenal insufficiency related to a lack of ACTH, which leads to a decrease in the production of cortisol by the adrenal glands. Aldosterone production is not usually affected.

HP:0011735.name: Adrenocorticotropin deficient adrenal insufficiency
HP:0011735.definition: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in ACTH production.

HP:0011736.name: Primary hyperaldosteronism
HP:0011736.definition: A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by a defect within the adrenal gland.

HP:0011737.name: Corticotropin-releasing hormone deficient adrenal insufficiency
HP:0011737.definition: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in corticotropin-releasing hormone production.

HP:0011738.name: Corticotropin-releasing hormone receptor defect
HP:0011738.definition: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in the corticotropin-releasing hormone receptor.

HP:0011739.name: Dexamethasone-suppressible primary hyperaldosteronism
HP:0011739.definition: A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone can be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone.

HP:0011740.name: Glucocortocoid-insensitive primary hyperaldosteronism
HP:0011740.definition: A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone cannot be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone or similar glucocorticoids.

HP:0011741.name: Secondary hyperaldosteronism
HP:0011741.definition: A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by abnormally increased renin levels.

HP:0011742.name: Ectopic adrenal gland
HP:0011742.definition: Abnormal anatomical location of the adrenal gland.

HP:0011743.name: Adrenal gland agenesis
HP:0011743.definition: Absent development of the adrenal gland.

HP:0011744.name: Secondary hypercortisolism
HP:0011744.definition: Hypercortisolemia associated with a overproduction of ACTH (often from a tumor), leading secondarily to overproduction of cortisol.

HP:0011745.name: Non-secretory adrenocortical adenoma
HP:0011745.definition: An hormonally inactive adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that does not secrete excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.

HP:0011746.name: Secretory adrenocortical adenoma
HP:0011746.definition: An hormonally active adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that secretes excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.

HP:0011747.name: Abnormality of the anterior pituitary
HP:0011747.definition: An abnormality of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

HP:0011748.name: Adrenocorticotropic hormone deficiency
HP:0011748.definition: A reduced ability to secrete adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), a hormone that stimulates the adrenal cortex to secrete of glucocorticoids such as cortisol.

HP:0011749.name: Adrenocorticotropic hormone excess
HP:0011749.definition: Overproduction of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which generally leads secondarily to overproduction of cortisol by the adrenal cortex.

HP:0011750.name: Neoplasm of the anterior pituitary
HP:0011750.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

HP:0011751.name: Abnormal posterior pituitary morphogenesis
HP:0011751.definition: An abnormality of the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.

HP:0011752.name: Neoplasm of the posterior pituitary
HP:0011752.definition: The presence of a neoplasm (tumor) in the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.

HP:0011753.name: Posterior pituitary dysgenesis
HP:0011753.definition: Abnormal development of the neurohypophysis during embryonic growth and development.

HP:0011754.name: Pituicytoma
HP:0011754.definition: A solid, low grade, spindle cell, glial neoplasm of adults that originates in the neurohypophysis or infundibulum. Clinical signs and symptoms include visual disturbance, headache and features of hypopituitarism. Pituicytomas are well-circumscribed, solid masses that can measure up to several centimeters. Histologically, they show a compact architecture consisting of elongate, bipolar spindle cells arranged in interlacing fascicles or assuming a storiform pattern.

HP:0011755.name: Ectopic posterior pituitary
HP:0011755.definition: An abnormal anatomical location of the posterior lobe of the hypophysis, also known as the neurohypophysis. The posterior pituitary is normally present in the dorsal portion of the sella turcica, but when ectopic is usually near the median eminence. This defect is likely to be due to abnormal migration during embryogenesis.

HP:0011756.name: Posterior pituitary agenesis
HP:0011756.definition: Absence of the neurohypophysis owing to a developmental defect.

HP:0011759.name: Pituitary gonadotropic cell adenoma
HP:0011759.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces gonadotropins.

HP:0011760.name: Pituitary growth hormone cell adenoma
HP:0011760.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces growth hormone.

HP:0011761.name: Pituitary null cell adenoma
HP:0011761.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma that is of unknown cellular origin and that lacks immunocytochemical or fine structural markers. Null cell adenomas are not associated with hormone excess.

HP:0011762.name: Pituitary thyrotropic cell adenoma
HP:0011762.definition: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH).

HP:0011763.name: Pituitary carcinoma
HP:0011763.definition: A pituitary tumor with subarachnoid, brain, or systemic metastasis. The diagnosis of a pituitary carcinoma requires evidence of metastatic disease, either outside the central nervous system (CNS) or as separate noncontiguous foci within the CNS.

HP:0011764.name: Pituitary spindle cell oncocytoma
HP:0011764.definition: A spindled-to-epithelioid, oncocytic, nonendocrine neoplasm of the anterior hypophysis that manifests in adults and follows a benign clinical course. Pituitary spindle cell oncocytomas are firm, fibrous, and adherent to surrounding structures and are highly vascular.

HP:0011766.name: Abnormal parathyroid morphology
HP:0011766.definition: A structural abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0011767.name: Abnormality of the parathyroid physiology
HP:0011767.definition: A functional abnormality of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0011768.name: Parathyroid dysgenesis
HP:0011768.definition: Abnormal embryonic development of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0011769.name: Ectopic parathyroid
HP:0011769.definition: An abnormal anatomical location of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0011770.name: Tertiary hyperparathyroidism
HP:0011770.definition: A type of hyperparathyroidism that occurs following kidney transplantation, which is a treatment for secondary hyperparathyroidism. Although kidney transplantation leads to a normalization of serum calcium and parathyroid hormone in most patients. The state of persistent hypercalcemia and hyperparathyroidism is referred to as tertiary hyperparathyroidism.

HP:0011771.name: Autoimmune hypoparathyroidism
HP:0011771.definition: A type of hypoparathyroidism with circulating antiparathyroid or anti-calcium sensing receptor antibodies indicative of autoimmunity.

HP:0011772.name: Abnormal thyroid morphology
HP:0011772.definition: A structural abnormality of the thyroid gland.

HP:0011773.name: Uninodular goiter
HP:0011773.definition: Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to a singular nodule in the thyroid gland.

HP:0011780.name: Thyroid hemiagenesis
HP:0011780.definition: Absence of a lobe of the thyroid gland related to a failure of its embryologic development.

HP:0011781.name: Thyroid C cell hyperplasia
HP:0011781.definition: An abnormal growth of parafollicular (C-cells) cells.

HP:0011786.name: Thyrotoxicosis with toxic single thyroid nodule

HP:0011787.name: Central hypothyroidism
HP:0011787.definition: A type of hypothyroidism due to an insufficient stimulation of an otherwise normal thyroid gland. Central hypothyroidism is caused by either pituitary (secondary hypothyroidism) or hypothalamic (tertiary hypothyroidism) defects.

HP:0011788.name: Increased circulating free T3
