HP:0030074.definition: A usually benign neoplasm originating in the chemoreceptor tissue of the carotid body, glomus jugulare, glomus tympanicum, aortic bodies, or the female genital tract.

HP:0030075.name: Ductal carcinoma in situ
HP:0030075.definition: Presence of abnormal cells inside a milk duct, that is, non-invasive breast cancer. Ductal carcinoma in situ is considered to be a precursor lesion to invasive breast cancer.

HP:0030077.name: Bronchial neoplasm
HP:0030077.definition: A tumor originating in a bronchus.

HP:0030079.name: Cervix cancer
HP:0030079.definition: A tumor of the uterine cervix.

HP:0030080.name: Burkitt lymphoma
HP:0030080.definition: A form of undifferentiated malignant lymphoma commonly manifested as a large osteolytic lesion in the jaw or as an abdominal mass.

HP:0030081.name: Punctate periventricular T2 hyperintense foci
HP:0030081.definition: Multiple pointlike areas of high T2 signal observed upon magnetic resonance imaging of the periventricular cerebral white matter.

HP:0030082.name: Abnormal drinking behavior
HP:0030082.definition: Abnormal consumption of fluids with excessive or insufficient consumption of fluid or any other abnormal pattern of fluid consumption.

HP:0030083.name: Salt craving
HP:0030083.definition: Hypersalivation, also known as salt craving, refers to an excessive desire to consume salt (sodium chloride) or salty foods.

HP:0030084.name: Clinodactyly
HP:0030084.definition: An angulation of a digit at an interphalangeal joint in the plane of the palm (finger) or sole (toe).

HP:0030085.name: Abnormal CSF lactate concentration
HP:0030085.definition: Abnormal concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0030086.name: Reduced CSF lactate
HP:0030086.definition: Decreased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0030087.name: Abnormal circulating testosterone concentration
HP:0030087.definition: An anomalous concentration of testosterone in the blood.

HP:0030088.name: Increased serum testosterone level
HP:0030088.definition: An elevated circulating testosterone level in the blood.

HP:0030089.name: Abnormal muscle fiber protein expression
HP:0030089.definition: An anomalous amount of protein present in or on the surface of muscle fibers. This feature may be appreciate upon immunohistochemical investigation of muscle biopsy tissue.

HP:0030090.name: Abnormal muscle fiber merosin expression
HP:0030090.definition: An anomalous amount of merosin in muscle fibers. Merosin is a basement membrane-associated protein found in placenta, striated muscle, and peripheral nerve.

HP:0030091.name: Absent muscle fiber merosin
HP:0030091.definition: Lack of merosin protein in the muscle biopsy.

HP:0030092.name: Reduced muscle fiber merosin
HP:0030092.definition: A reduced amount of merosin in muscle fibers. This feature is usually assessed by immunohistochemical examination of muscle biopsy tissue.

HP:0030093.name: Abnormal muscle fiber laminin beta 1
HP:0030093.definition: A deviation from normal of the amount of laminin beta 1 in muscle fiber tissue. Laminin 2 is a major component of the basal lamina of skeletal muscle cells. It is a heterotrimer composed of 3 chains: merosin (laminin alpha 2 chain), beta 1, and gamma 1.

HP:0030094.name: Reduced muscle fiber laminin beta 1
HP:0030094.definition: A reduced amount of laminin beta 1 in muscle fiber tissue. Laminin 2 is a major component of the basal lamina of skeletal muscle cells. It is a heterotrimer composed of 3 chains: merosin (laminin alpha 2 chain), beta 1, and gamma 1.

HP:0030095.name: Reduced muscle collagen VI
HP:0030095.definition: A decreased amount of collagen VI in muscle tissue. Collagen VI is a primarily associated with the extracellular matrix of skeletal muscle.

HP:0030096.name: Abnormal muscle fiber dystrophin expression
HP:0030096.definition: A deviation from normal in the amount of dystrophin in muscle fiber tissue. Dystrophin is located at the muscle sarcolemma in a membrane-spanning protein complex that connects the cytoskeleton to the basal lamina.

HP:0030097.name: Absent muscle dystrophin expression
HP:0030097.definition: Lack of dystrophin in muscle tissue. Immunohistochemistry reveals absent dystrophin protein in the muscle biopsy.

HP:0030098.name: Reduced muscle dystrophin expression
HP:0030098.definition: A decreased amount of dystrophin in muscle fiber tissue.

HP:0030099.name: Reduced muscle fiber alpha dystroglycan
HP:0030099.definition: Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha dystroglycan protein in the muscle biopsy. Alpha-dystroglycan is a heavily glycosylated peripheral-membrane component of the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex (DAPC), which, in addition to laminin alpha2, binds perlecan and agrin in the extracellular matrix, whereas beta-dystroglycan, derived from the same gene, is a transmembrane protein that links to dystrophin intracellularly.

HP:0030100.name: Abnormal muscle fiber alpha sarcoglycan
HP:0030100.definition: Deviation from normal in the amount of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. The alpha, beta, gamma, and delta sarcoglycans are components of the dystrophin-complex. They are all N-glycosylated transmembrane proteins with a short intra-cellular domain, a single transmembrane region and a large extra-cellular domain containing a cluster of conserved cysteines.

HP:0030101.name: Absent muscle fiber alpha sarcoglycan
HP:0030101.definition: Lack of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. Immunohistochemistry reveals absent alpha sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.

HP:0030102.name: Reduced muscle fiber alpha sarcoglycan
HP:0030102.definition: A decreased amount of alpha sarcoglycan in muscle. Immunohistochemistry reveals reduced alpha sarcoglycan protein in the muscle biopsy.

HP:0001271.name: Polyneuropathy
HP:0001271.definition: A generalized disorder of peripheral nerves.

HP:0001272.name: Cerebellar atrophy
HP:0001272.definition: Cerebellar atrophy is defined as a cerebellum with initially normal structures, in a posterior fossa with normal size, which displays enlarged fissures (interfolial spaces) in comparison to the foliae secondary to loss of tissue. Cerebellar atrophy implies irreversible loss of tissue and result from an ongoing progressive disease until a final stage is reached or a single injury, e.g. an intoxication or infectious event.

HP:0001274.name: Agenesis of corpus callosum
HP:0001274.definition: Absence of the corpus callosum as a result of the failure of the corpus callosum to develop, which can be the result of a failure in any one of the multiple steps of callosal development including cellular proliferation and migration, axonal growth or glial patterning at the midline.

HP:0001276.name: Hypertonia
HP:0001276.definition: A condition in which there is increased muscle tone so that arms or legs, for example, are stiff and difficult to move.

HP:0001278.name: Orthostatic hypotension
HP:0001278.definition: A form of hypotension characterized by a sudden fall in blood pressure that occurs when a person assumes a standing position.

HP:0001279.name: Syncope
HP:0001279.definition: Syncope is a syndrome in which loss of consciousness is of relatively sudden onset, temporary (usually less than 1 to 2 minutes), self-terminating, and of usually rapid recovery. Syncope leads to a generalized weakness of muscles with loss of postural tone, inability to stand upright, and loss of consciousness. Once the patient is in a horizontal position, blood flow to the brain is no longer hindered by gravitation and consciousness is regained. Unconsciousness usually lasts for seconds to minutes. Headache and drowsiness (which usually follow seizures) do not follow a syncopal attack. Syncope results from a sudden impairment of brain metabolism usually due to a reduction in cerebral blood flow.

HP:0001281.name: Tetany
HP:0001281.definition: A condition characterized by intermittent involuntary contraction of muscles (spasms) related to hypocalcemia or occasionally magnesium deficiency.

HP:0001283.name: Bulbar palsy
HP:0001283.definition: Bulbar weakness (or bulbar palsy) refers to bilateral impairment of function of the lower cranial nerves IX, X, XI and XII, which occurs due to lower motor neuron lesion either at nuclear or fascicular level in the medulla or from bilateral lesions of the lower cranial nerves outside the brain-stem. Bulbar weakness is often associated with difficulty in chewing, weakness of the facial muscles, dysarthria, palatal weakness and regurgitation of fluids, dysphagia, and dysphonia.

HP:0001284.name: Areflexia
HP:0001284.definition: Absence of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction.

HP:0001285.name: Spastic tetraparesis
HP:0001285.definition: Spastic weakness affecting all four limbs.

HP:0001288.name: Gait disturbance
HP:0001288.definition: The term gait disturbance can refer to any disruption of the ability to walk.

HP:0001289.name: Confusion
HP:0001289.definition: Lack of clarity and coherence of thought, perception, understanding, or action.

HP:0001290.name: Generalized hypotonia
HP:0001290.definition: Generalized muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone).

HP:0001291.name: Abnormal cranial nerve morphology
HP:0001291.definition: Structural abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

HP:0001297.name: Stroke
HP:0001297.definition: Sudden impairment of blood flow to a part of the brain due to occlusion or rupture of an artery to the brain.

HP:0001298.name: Encephalopathy
HP:0001298.definition: Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state.

HP:0001300.name: Parkinsonism
HP:0001300.definition: Characteristic neurologic anomaly resulting from degeneration of dopamine-generating cells in the substantia nigra, a region of the midbrain, characterized clinically by shaking, rigidity, slowness of movement and difficulty with walking and gait.

HP:0001302.name: Pachygyria
HP:0001302.definition: Pachygyria is a malformation of cortical development with abnormally wide gyri with sulci 1,5-3 cm apart and abnormally thick cortex measuring more than 5 mm (radiological definition). See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.

HP:0001304.name: Torsion dystonia
HP:0001304.definition: Sustained involuntary muscle contractions that produce twisting and repetitive movements of the body.

HP:0001305.name: Dandy-Walker malformation
HP:0001305.definition: A congenital brain malformation typically characterized by incomplete formation of the cerebellar vermis, dilation of the fourth ventricle, and enlargement of the posterior fossa. In layman's terms, Dandy Walker malformation is a cyst in the cerebellum (typically symmetrical) that is involved with the fourth ventricle. This may interfere with the ability to drain cerebrospinal fluid from the brain, resulting in hydrocephalus. Dandy Walker cysts are formed during early embryonic development, while the brain forms. The cyst in the cerebellum typically has several blood vessels running through it connecting to the brain, thereby prohibiting surgical removal.

HP:0001308.name: Tongue fasciculations
HP:0001308.definition: Fasciculations or fibrillation affecting the tongue muscle.

HP:0001310.name: Dysmetria
HP:0001310.definition: A type of ataxia characterized by the inability to carry out movements with the correct range and motion across the plane of more than one joint related to incorrect estimation of the distances required for targeted movements.

HP:0001311.name: Abnormal nervous system electrophysiology
HP:0001311.definition: An abnormality of the function of the electrical signals with which nerve cells communicate with each other or with muscles as measured by electrophysiological investigations.

HP:0001312.name: Giant somatosensory evoked potentials
HP:0001312.definition: An abnormal enlargement (i.e. increase in measured voltage) of somatosensory evoked potentials.

HP:0001315.name: Reduced tendon reflexes
HP:0001315.definition: Diminution of tendon reflexes, which is an invariable sign of peripheral nerve disease.

HP:0001317.name: Abnormal cerebellum morphology
HP:0001317.definition: Any structural abnormality of the cerebellum.

HP:0001319.name: Neonatal hypotonia
HP:0001319.definition: Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period.

HP:0001320.name: Cerebellar vermis hypoplasia
HP:0001320.definition: Underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

HP:0001321.name: Cerebellar hypoplasia
HP:0001321.definition: Cerebellar hypoplasia is a descriptive term implying a cerebellum with a reduced volume, but a normal shape and is stable over time.

HP:0001325.name: Hypoglycemic coma
HP:0001325.definition: Coma induced by low blood sugar.

HP:0001326.name: EEG with irregular generalized spike and wave complexes
HP:0001326.definition: EEG shows spikes (<80 ms) and waves, which are recorded over the entire scalp and do not have a specific frequency.

HP:0001327.name: Photosensitive myoclonic seizure
HP:0001327.definition: Generalised myoclonic seizure provoked by flashing or flickering light.

HP:0001328.name: Specific learning disability
HP:0001328.definition: Impairment of certain skills such as reading or writing, coordination, self-control, or attention that interfere with the ability to learn. The impairment is not related to a global deficiency of intelligence.

HP:0001331.name: Absent septum pellucidum
HP:0001331.definition: Absence of the septum pellucidum (meaning translucent wall in Latin - SP), also known as the ventricle of Sylvius. The septum pellucidum is a thin, triangular double membrane separating the frontal horns of the right and left lateral ventricles of the brain. It extends between the anterior portion of the corpus callosum, and the body of the fornix and its width varies from 1.5 to 3.0 mm.

HP:0001332.name: Dystonia
HP:0001332.definition: An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk.

HP:0001334.name: Communicating hydrocephalus
HP:0001334.definition: A form of hydrocephalus in which there is no visible obstruction to the flow of the cerebrospinal fluid between the ventricles and subarachnoid space.

HP:0001335.name: Bimanual synkinesia
HP:0001335.definition: Involuntary movements of one hand that accompany and mirror intentional movements of the opposite hand.

HP:0001336.name: Myoclonus
HP:0001336.definition: Very brief, involuntary random muscular contractions occurring at rest, in response to sensory stimuli, or accompanying voluntary movements.

HP:0001337.name: Tremor
HP:0001337.definition: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement about a joint axis.

HP:0001338.name: Partial agenesis of the corpus callosum
HP:0001338.definition: A partial failure of the development of the corpus callosum.

HP:0001339.name: Lissencephaly
HP:0001339.definition: A spectrum of malformations of cortical development caused by insufficient neuronal migration that subsumes the terms agyria, pachygyria and subcortical band heterotopia. See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.

HP:0001340.name: Enhancement of the C-reflex
HP:0001340.definition: Increase in amplitude of a long-loop response upon somatosensory evoked potential testing, representing an electrically evoked myoclonic response.

HP:0001342.name: Cerebral hemorrhage
HP:0001342.definition: Hemorrhage into the parenchyma of the brain.

HP:0001343.name: Kernicterus
HP:0001343.definition: Damage to cerebral nuclei caused in infants by highly increased levels of unconjugated bilirubin. The basal ganglia and brainstem nuclei could be shown to have a yellow staining historically in infants who died of kernicterus, that is, kernicterus is strictly speaking a pathological diagnosis. The presence of kernicterus may be inferred in infants with characteristic acute or chronic bilirubin-induced neurological dysfunction.

HP:0001344.name: Absent speech
HP:0001344.definition: Complete lack of development of speech and language abilities.

HP:0001345.name: Psychotic mentation
HP:0001345.definition: A pattern of thinking and perceiving characterized by a loss of contact with reality, leading to significant changes in thoughts, perceptions, and behaviors.

HP:0001347.name: Hyperreflexia
HP:0001347.definition: Hyperreflexia is the presence of hyperactive stretch reflexes of the muscles.

HP:0001348.name: Brisk reflexes
HP:0001348.definition: Tendon reflexes that are noticeably more active than usual (conventionally denoted 3+ on clinical examination). Brisk reflexes may or may not indicate a neurological lesion. They are distinguished from hyperreflexia by the fact that hyerreflexia is characterized by hyperactive repeating (clonic) reflexes, which are considered to be always abnormal.

HP:0001349.name: Facial diplegia
HP:0001349.definition: Facial diplegia refers to bilateral facial palsy (bilateral facial palsy is much rarer than unilateral facial palsy).

HP:0001350.name: Slurred speech
HP:0001350.definition: Abnormal coordination of muscles involved in speech.

HP:0001351.name: Jerk-locked premyoclonus spikes
HP:0001351.definition: Jerk-locked averaging (JLA) is used to record the timing and distribution of brain activity preceding brisk involuntary movements such as those observed in patients with myoclonus. JLA is capable of revealing a premyoclonus spike in the absence of paroxysmal activity in the routine EEG.

HP:0001355.name: Megalencephaly
HP:0001355.definition: Diffuse enlargement of the entire cerebral hemispheres leading to macrocephaly (with or without overlying cortical dysplasia).

HP:0001357.name: Plagiocephaly
HP:0001357.definition: Asymmetric head shape, which is usually a combination of unilateral occipital flattening with ipsilateral frontal prominence, leading to rhomboid cranial shape.

HP:0001360.name: Holoprosencephaly
HP:0001360.definition: Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles.

HP:0001361.name: Nystagmus-induced head nodding
HP:0001361.definition: Head movements associated with nystagmus, that may represent an attempt to compensate for the involuntary eye movements and to improve vision.

HP:0001362.name: Calvarial skull defect
HP:0001362.definition: A localized defect in the bone of the skull resulting from abnormal embryological development. The defect is covered by normal skin. In some cases, skull x-rays have shown underlying lytic bone lesions which have closed before the age of one year.

HP:0001363.name: Craniosynostosis
HP:0001363.definition: Craniosynostosis refers to the premature closure of the cranial sutures. Primary craniosynostosis refers to the closure of one or more sutures due to abnormalities in skull development, and secondary craniosynostosis results from failure of brain growth.

HP:0001367.name: Abnormal joint morphology
HP:0001367.definition: An abnormal structure or form of the joints, i.e., one or more of the articulations where two bones join.

HP:0001370.name: Rheumatoid arthritis
HP:0001370.definition: Inflammatory changes in the synovial membranes and articular structures with widespread fibrinoid degeneration of the collagen fibers in mesenchymal tissues, as well as atrophy and rarefaction of bony structures.

HP:0001371.name: Flexion contracture
HP:0001371.definition: A flexion contracture is a bent (flexed) joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively. It is thus a chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in muscle, tendons, ligaments, or skin that prevents normal movement of joints.

HP:0001376.name: Limitation of joint mobility
HP:0001376.definition: A reduction in the freedom of movement of one or more joints.

HP:0001377.name: Limited elbow extension
HP:0001377.definition: Limited ability to straighten the arm at the elbow joint.

HP:0001382.name: Joint hypermobility
HP:0001382.definition: The capability that a joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes.

HP:0001384.name: Abnormal hip joint morphology
HP:0001384.definition: An abnormality of the hip joint.

HP:0001385.name: Hip dysplasia
HP:0001385.definition: The presence of developmental dysplasia of the hip.

HP:0001387.name: Joint stiffness
HP:0001387.definition: Joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in a joint or joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity. Joint stiffness typically subsides over time.

HP:0001394.name: Cirrhosis
HP:0001394.definition: A chronic disorder of the liver in which liver tissue becomes scarred and is partially replaced by regenerative nodules and fibrotic tissue resulting in loss of liver function.

HP:0001395.name: Hepatic fibrosis
HP:0001395.definition: The presence of excessive fibrous connective tissue in the liver. Fibrosis is a reparative or reactive process.

HP:0001396.name: Cholestasis
HP:0001396.definition: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.

HP:0001397.name: Hepatic steatosis
HP:0001397.definition: Steatosis is a term used to denote lipid accumulation within hepatocytes.

HP:0001400.name: obsolete Hepatic abscesses due to immunodeficiency

HP:0001402.name: Hepatocellular carcinoma
HP:0001402.definition: A kind of neoplasm of the liver that originates in hepatocytes and presents macroscopically as a soft and hemorrhagic tan mass in the liver.

HP:0001403.name: Macrovesicular hepatic steatosis
HP:0001403.definition: A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of large, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes.

HP:0001405.name: Periportal fibrosis
HP:0001405.definition: The presence of fibrosis affecting the interlobular stroma of liver.

HP:0001406.name: Intrahepatic cholestasis
HP:0001406.definition: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in the small bile ducts within the liver.

HP:0001408.name: Bile duct proliferation
HP:0001408.definition: Proliferative changes of the bile ducts.

HP:0001409.name: Portal hypertension
HP:0001409.definition: Increased pressure in the portal vein.

HP:0001410.name: Decreased liver function
HP:0001410.definition: Reduced ability of the liver to perform its functions.

HP:0001412.name: Enteroviral hepatitis
HP:0001412.definition: Inflammation of the liver due to infection with enterovirus.

HP:0001413.name: Micronodular cirrhosis
HP:0001413.definition: A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of small regenerative nodules.

HP:0001414.name: Microvesicular hepatic steatosis
HP:0001414.definition: A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of small, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes.

HP:0001417.name: X-linked inheritance
HP:0001417.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome.

HP:0001419.name: X-linked recessive inheritance
HP:0001419.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for recessive traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome. In the context of medical genetics, X-linked recessive disorders manifest in males (who have one copy of the X chromosome and are thus hemizygotes), but generally not in female heterozygotes who have one mutant and one normal allele.

HP:0001421.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the hand

HP:0001423.name: X-linked dominant inheritance
HP:0001423.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for dominant traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome. In the context of medical genetics, X-linked dominant disorders tend to manifest very severely in affected males. The severity of manifestation in females may depend on the degree of skewed X inactivation.

HP:0001426.name: Non-Mendelian inheritance
HP:0001426.definition: A mode of inheritance that depends on genetic determinants in more than one gene.

HP:0001427.name: Mitochondrial inheritance
HP:0001427.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the mitochondrial genome. Because the mitochondrial genome is essentially always maternally inherited, a mitochondrial condition can only be transmitted by females, although the condition can affect both sexes. The proportion of mutant mitochondria can vary (heteroplasmy).

HP:0001433.name: Hepatosplenomegaly
HP:0001433.definition: Simultaneous enlargement of the liver and spleen.

HP:0001435.name: Abnormality of the shoulder girdle musculature

HP:0001436.name: Abnormality of the foot musculature
HP:0001436.definition: An anomaly of the musculature of foot.

HP:0001437.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the lower limbs

HP:0001438.name: Abnormal abdomen morphology
HP:0001438.definition: A structural abnormality of the abdomen ('belly'), that is, the part of the body between the pelvis and the thorax.

HP:0001442.name: Typified by somatic mosaicism
HP:0001442.definition: Description of conditions in which affected individuals typically display somatic mosaicism, i.e., genetically distinct populations of somatic cells in a given organism caused by DNA mutations, epigenetic alterations of DNA, chromosomal abnormalities or the spontaneous reversion of inherited mutations. In many conditions typified by somatic mosaicism, constitutive mutation is lethal and cases are exclusively or predominantly mosaic.

HP:0001444.name: obsolete Autosomal dominant somatic cell mutation

HP:0001446.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the upper limbs

HP:0001450.name: Y-linked inheritance
HP:0001450.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the Y chromosome.

HP:0001452.name: obsolete Autosomal dominant contiguous gene syndrome

HP:0001457.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the upper arm

HP:0001459.name: 1-3 toe syndactyly
HP:0001459.definition: Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to three.

HP:0001460.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the skeletal musculature
HP:0001460.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature.

HP:0001464.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the shoulder musculature
HP:0001464.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the muscles of the shoulder.

HP:0001466.name: Contiguous gene syndrome
HP:0001466.definition: A syndrome caused by the effects of abnormality (typically a deletion or duplication) of 2 or more adjacent genes

HP:0001467.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the musculature of the upper limbs
HP:0001467.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature of the upper limbs.

HP:0001468.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the musculature of the upper arm
HP:0001468.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the muscles of the upper arm.

HP:0001469.name: Abnormal morphology of the pelvis musculature

HP:0001470.name: Sex-limited expression
HP:0001470.definition: Sex limitation is used to refer to a monogenic trait linked to an autosomal locus in which the phenotypic effects of allelic differences are expressed only in one sex.

HP:0001471.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the musculature of the pelvis

HP:0001474.name: Sclerotic scapulae
HP:0001474.definition: Increased density of the bony tissue of the scapula.

HP:0001475.name: Male-limited expression
HP:0001475.definition: Used to refer to a monogenic trait linked to an autosomal locus in which the phenotypic effects of allelic differences are expressed only in the male sex.

HP:0001476.name: Delayed closure of the anterior fontanelle
HP:0001476.definition: A delay in closure (ossification) of the anterior fontanelle, which generally undergoes closure around the 18th month of life.

HP:0001477.name: Compensatory chin elevation
HP:0001477.definition: A tendency to hold the chin elevated by about 20 to 30 degrees to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0001480.name: Freckling
HP:0001480.definition: The presence of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin.

HP:0001482.name: Subcutaneous nodule
HP:0001482.definition: Slightly elevated lesions on or in the skin with a diameter of over 5 mm.

HP:0001483.name: Eye poking
HP:0001483.definition: Repetitive pressing, poking, and/or rubbing in the eyes.

HP:0001489.name: Posterior vitreous detachment
HP:0001489.definition: Separation of the vitreous humor from the retina.

HP:0001491.name: Congenital fibrosis of extraocular muscles
HP:0001491.definition: Congenital non-progressive ophthalmoplegia with multiple extraocular muscle restrictions. Typically, there is ptosis and variable degrees of restriction of horizontal and vertical eye movements.

HP:0001492.name: Axenfeld anomaly
HP:0001492.definition: Axenfeld's anomaly is a bilateral disorder characterized by a prominent, anteriorly displaced Schwalbe's line (posterior embryotoxon) and peripheral iris strands which span the anterior chamber angle to attach to Schwalbe's line.

HP:0001493.name: Falciform retinal fold
HP:0001493.definition: An area of the retina that is buckled so that a sector-shaped sheet of retina lies in front of the normal retina. This feature is of congenital onset.

HP:0001498.name: Carpal bone hypoplasia
HP:0001498.definition: Underdevelopment of one or more carpal bones.

HP:0001500.name: Broad finger
HP:0001500.definition: Increased width of a non-thumb digit of the hand.

HP:0001508.name: Failure to thrive
HP:0001508.definition: Failure to thrive (FTT) refers to a child whose physical growth is substantially below the norm.

HP:0001510.name: Growth delay
HP:0001510.definition: A deficiency or slowing down of growth pre- and postnatally.

HP:0001511.name: Intrauterine growth retardation
HP:0001511.definition: An abnormal restriction of fetal growth with fetal weight below the tenth percentile for gestational age.

HP:0001513.name: Obesity
HP:0001513.definition: Accumulation of substantial excess body fat.

HP:0001518.name: Small for gestational age
HP:0001518.definition: Smaller than normal size according to sex and gestational age related norms, defined as a weight below the 10th percentile for the gestational age.

HP:0001519.name: Disproportionate tall stature
HP:0001519.definition: A tall and slim body build with increased arm span to height ratio (>1.05) and a reduced upper-to-lower segment ratio (<0.85), i.e., unusually long arms and legs. The extremities as well as the hands and feet are unusually slim.

HP:0001520.name: Large for gestational age
HP:0001520.definition: The term large for gestational age applies to babies whose birth weight lies above the 90th percentile for that gestational age.

HP:0001522.name: Death in infancy
HP:0001522.definition: Death within the first 24 months of life.

HP:0001528.name: Hemihypertrophy
HP:0001528.definition: Overgrowth of only one side of the body.

HP:0001530.name: Mild postnatal growth retardation
HP:0001530.definition: A mild degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between two and three standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms.

HP:0001533.name: Slender build
HP:0001533.definition: Asthenic habitus refers to a slender build with long limbs, an angular profile, and prominent muscles or bones.

HP:0001537.name: Umbilical hernia
HP:0001537.definition: Protrusion of abdominal contents through a defect in the abdominal wall musculature around the umbilicus. Skin and subcutaneous tissue overlie the defect.

HP:0001538.name: Protuberant abdomen
HP:0001538.definition: A thrusting or bulging out of the abdomen.

HP:0001539.name: Omphalocele
HP:0001539.definition: A midline anterior incomplete closure of the abdominal wall in which there is herniation of the abdominal viscera into the base of the abdominal cord.

HP:0001540.name: Diastasis recti
HP:0001540.definition: A separation of the rectus abdominis muscle into right and left halves (which are normally joined at the midline at the linea alba).

HP:0001541.name: Ascites
HP:0001541.definition: Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity (between the layers of the peritoneum that lines the abdomen).

HP:0001543.name: Gastroschisis
HP:0001543.definition: A type of congenital ventral incomplete closure of the abdominal wall in which the intestines and sometimes other organs extend freely into the amniotic fluid space through a small opening in the abdomen, usually to the right of the umbilicus.

HP:0001547.name: Abnormal rib cage morphology
HP:0001547.definition: A morphological anomaly of the rib cage.

HP:0001548.name: Overgrowth
HP:0001548.definition: Excessive postnatal growth which may comprise increased weight, increased length, and/or increased head circumference.

HP:0001551.name: Abnormal umbilicus morphology
HP:0001551.definition: An abnormality of the structure or appearance of the umbilicus.

HP:0001552.name: Barrel-shaped chest
HP:0001552.definition: A rounded, bulging chest that resembles the shape of a barrel. That is, there is an increased anteroposterior diameter and usually some degree of kyphosis.

HP:0001555.name: Asymmetry of the thorax
HP:0001555.definition: Lack of symmetry between the left and right halves of the thorax.

HP:0001558.name: Decreased fetal movement
HP:0001558.definition: An abnormal reduction in quantity or strength of fetal movements.

HP:0001560.name: Abnormality of the amniotic fluid
HP:0001560.definition: Abnormality of the amniotic fluid, which is the fluid contained in the amniotic sac surrounding the developing fetus.

HP:0001561.name: Polyhydramnios
HP:0001561.definition: The presence of excess amniotic fluid in the uterus during pregnancy.

HP:0001562.name: Oligohydramnios
HP:0001562.definition: Diminished amniotic fluid volume in pregnancy.

HP:0001563.name: Fetal polyuria
HP:0001563.definition: Abnormally increased production of urine by the fetus resulting in polyhydramnios.

HP:0001566.name: Widely-spaced maxillary central incisors
HP:0001566.definition: Increased distance between the maxillary central permanent incisor tooth.

HP:0001571.name: Multiple impacted teeth
HP:0001571.definition: The presence of multiple impacted teeth.

HP:0001572.name: Macrodontia
HP:0001572.definition: Increased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD above mean for age. Alternatively, an apparently increased maximum width of the tooth.

HP:0001574.name: Abnormality of the integument
HP:0001574.definition: An abnormality of the integument, which consists of the skin and the superficial fascia.

HP:0001579.name: Primary hypercortisolism
HP:0001579.definition: Hypercortisolemia associated with a primary defect of the adrenal gland leading to overproduction of cortisol.

HP:0001581.name: Recurrent skin infections
HP:0001581.definition: Infections of the skin that happen multiple times.

HP:0001582.name: Redundant skin
HP:0001582.definition: Loose and sagging skin often associated with loss of skin elasticity.

HP:0001583.name: Rotary nystagmus
HP:0001583.definition: A form of nystagmus in which the eyeball makes rotary motions around the axis.

HP:0001586.name: Vesicovaginal fistula
HP:0001586.definition: The presence of a fistula connecting the urinary bladder to the vagina.

HP:0001591.name: Bell-shaped thorax
HP:0001591.definition: The rib cage has the shape of a wide mouthed bell. That is, the superior portion of the rib cage is constricted, followed by a convex region, and the inferior portion of the rib cage expands again to have a large diameter.

HP:0001592.name: Selective tooth agenesis
HP:0001592.definition: Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar.

HP:0001593.name: Maxillary lateral incisor microdontia
HP:0001593.definition: Decreased size of the maxillary permanent incisor.

HP:0001596.name: Alopecia
HP:0001596.definition: A noncongenital process of hair loss, which may progress to partial or complete baldness.

HP:0001597.name: Abnormal nail morphology
HP:0001597.definition: Abnormal structure or appearance of the nail.

HP:0001598.name: Concave nail
HP:0001598.definition: The natural longitudinal (posterodistal) convex arch is not present or is inverted.

HP:0001601.name: Laryngomalacia
HP:0001601.definition: Laryngomalacia is a congenital abnormality of the laryngeal cartilage in which the cartilage is floppy and prolapses over the larynx during inspiration.

HP:0001602.name: Laryngeal stenosis
HP:0001602.definition: Stricture or narrowing of the larynx that may be associated with symptoms of respiratory difficulty depending on the degree of laryngeal narrowing.

HP:0001604.name: Vocal cord paresis
HP:0001604.definition: Decreased strength of the vocal folds.

HP:0001605.name: Vocal cord paralysis
HP:0001605.definition: A loss of the ability to move the vocal folds.

HP:0001606.name: obsolete Vocal cord paralysis (caused by tumor impingement)

HP:0001609.name: Hoarse voice
HP:0001609.definition: Hoarseness refers to a change in the pitch or quality of the voice, with the voice sounding weak, very breathy, scratchy, or husky.

HP:0001611.name: Hypernasal speech
HP:0001611.definition: A type of speech characterized by the presence of an abnormally increased nasal airflow during speech associated with structural abnormality of the nasal passages.

HP:0001613.name: obsolete Hoarse voice (caused by tumor impingement)

HP:0001618.name: Dysphonia
HP:0001618.definition: Difficulty in speaking due to a physical disorder of the mouth, tongue, throat, or vocal cords. Associated with a known physical or neurological cause.

HP:0001620.name: Abnormally high-pitched voice
HP:0001620.definition: A persistent (minutes to hours) abnormal increase in the pitch (frequency) of the voice for the context or social situation or significantly different from baseline of the individual.

HP:0001622.name: Premature birth
HP:0001622.definition: The birth of a baby of less than 37 weeks of gestational age.

HP:0001623.name: Breech presentation
HP:0001623.definition: A position of the fetus at delivery in which the fetus enters the birth canal with the buttocks or feet first.

HP:0001626.name: Abnormality of the cardiovascular system
HP:0001626.definition: Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system.

HP:0001627.name: Abnormal heart morphology
HP:0001627.definition: Any structural anomaly of the heart.

HP:0001629.name: Ventricular septal defect
HP:0001629.definition: A hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.

HP:0001631.name: Atrial septal defect
HP:0001631.definition: Atrial septal defect (ASD) is a congenital abnormality of the interatrial septum that enables blood flow between the left and right atria via the interatrial septum.

HP:0001633.name: Abnormal mitral valve morphology
HP:0001633.definition: Any structural anomaly of the mitral valve.

HP:0001634.name: Mitral valve prolapse
HP:0001634.definition: One or both of the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve bulges back into the left atrium upon contraction of the left ventricle.

HP:0001635.name: Congestive heart failure
HP:0001635.definition: The presence of an abnormality of cardiac function that is responsible for the failure of the heart to pump blood at a rate that is commensurate with the needs of the tissues or a state in which abnormally elevated filling pressures are required for the heart to do so. Heart failure is frequently related to a defect in myocardial contraction.

HP:0001636.name: Tetralogy of Fallot
HP:0001636.definition: A congenital cardiac malformation comprising pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy. The diagnosis of TOF is made if at least three of the four above mentioned features are present.

HP:0001637.name: Abnormal myocardium morphology
HP:0001637.definition: A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall.

HP:0001638.name: Cardiomyopathy
HP:0001638.definition: A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality.

HP:0001639.name: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
HP:0001639.definition: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is defined by the presence of increased ventricular wall thickness or mass in the absence of loading conditions (hypertension, valve disease) sufficient to cause the observed abnormality.

HP:0001640.name: Cardiomegaly
HP:0001640.definition: Increased size of the heart, clinically defined as an increased transverse diameter of the cardiac silhouette that is greater than or equal to 50% of the transverse diameter of the chest (increased cardiothoracic ratio) on a posterior-anterior projection of a chest radiograph or a computed tomography.

HP:0001641.name: Abnormal pulmonary valve morphology
HP:0001641.definition: Any structural abnormality of the pulmonary valve.

HP:0001642.name: Pulmonic stenosis
HP:0001642.definition: A narrowing of the right ventricular outflow tract that can occur at the pulmonary valve (valvular stenosis), below the pulmonary valve (infundibular stenosis), or above the pulmonary valve (supravalvar stenosis).

HP:0001643.name: Patent ductus arteriosus
HP:0001643.definition: In utero, the ductus arteriosus (DA) serves to divert ventricular output away from the lungs and toward the placenta by connecting the main pulmonary artery to the descending aorta. A patent ductus arteriosus (PDA) in the first 3 days of life is a physiologic shunt in healthy term and preterm newborn infants, and normally is substantially closed within about 24 hours after bith and completely closed after about three weeks. Failure of physiologcal closure is referred to a persistent or patent ductus arteriosus (PDA). Depending on the degree of left-to-right shunting, PDA can have clinical consequences.

HP:0030484.name: Supernormal dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram b-wave

HP:0030487.name: Abnormal P50/N95 ratio of pattern electroretinogram

HP:0030488.name: Abnormal central response of multifocal electroretinogram

HP:0030489.name: Abnormal paracentral response of multifocal electroretinogram

HP:0030491.name: Choriocapillaris atrophy
HP:0030491.definition: Atrophy of the capillary lamina of choroid.

HP:0030493.name: Abnormality of foveal pigmentation
HP:0030493.definition: An anomaly of the pigmentation in the fovea centralis.

HP:0030494.name: Macular microaneurysm/hemorrhage
HP:0030494.definition: Small, red dots in the superficial retinal layers (it is difficult to distinguish between small hemorrhages and microaneurysms).

HP:0030495.name: Abnormality morphology of the macular vasculature
HP:0030495.definition: Any structural anomaly of the blood vessels of the macula.

HP:0030496.name: Macular exudate
HP:0030496.definition: Yellow-white intraretinal deposits in the macula typically associated with damaged outer blood-retina barrier and exudation of serous fluid and lipids from the retinal microvasculature.

HP:0030497.name: Macular cotton wool spot
HP:0030497.definition: Fluffy white patch on the macula, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fiber layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.

HP:0030498.name: Macular thickening
HP:0030498.definition: Abnormal increase in retinal thickness in the macular area observed on fundoscopy or fundus imaging.

HP:0030499.name: Macular drusen
HP:0030499.definition: Drusen (singular, 'druse') are tiny yellow or white accumulations of extracellular material (lipofuscin) that build up in Bruch's membrane of the eye. This class refers to the presence of Drusen in the macula.

HP:0030502.name: Retinoschisis
HP:0030502.definition: Splitting of the neuroretinal layers of the retina.

HP:0030504.name: Grouped congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium

HP:0030505.name: Nummular pigmentation of the fundus
HP:0030505.definition: Clumped pigmentary changes of nummular appearance (i.e., thought to resemble the shape of a coin or multiple coins stuck together) at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0030510.name: Combined hamartoma of the retinal pigment epithelium and retina

HP:0030512.name: Difficulty adjusting to changes in luminance

HP:0030513.name: Difficulty adjusting from light to dark

HP:0030514.name: Difficulty adjusting from dark to light

HP:0030515.name: Moderately reduced visual acuity
HP:0030515.definition: Moderate reduction of the ability to see. On the 6m visual acuity scale, moderate reduction is defined as less than 6/18 but at least 6/60. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, moderate reduction is defined as less than 20/70 but at least 20/200. On the decimal visual acuity scale, moderate reduction is defined as less than 0.3 but at least 0.1.

HP:0030522.name: Mild constriction of peripheral visual field
HP:0030522.definition: A diminution of the peripheral visual field whereby at least 50 degrees of central field are preserved in all meridians.

HP:0030523.name: obsolete Peripheral visual field constriction with 40-50 degrees central field preserved

HP:0030524.name: obsolete Peripheral visual field constriction with 30-39 degrees central field preserved

HP:0030525.name: Moderate constriction of peripheral visual field
HP:0030525.definition: Peripheral visual field constriction with 20-49 degrees binocular visual field preserved.

HP:0030526.name: Severe constriction of peripheral visual field
HP:0030526.definition: Peripheral visual field constriction with 10-19 degrees central field preserved.

HP:0030527.name: Very severe constriction of peripheral visual field
HP:0030527.definition: Peripheral visual field constriction with <10 degrees central field preserved.

HP:0030529.name: Ring scotoma
HP:0030529.definition: An annular field defect centered on fixation.

HP:0030534.name: Abnormal best corrected visual acuity test

HP:0030551.name: Visual acuity light perception with projection

HP:0030552.name: Visual acuity light perception without projection

HP:0030588.name: Abnormal visual field test
HP:0030588.definition: Abnormal result of a test designed to test an individual's central and peripheral vision by determining the ability of the individual to perceive objects at differing locations of the visual field.

HP:0030599.name: Abnormal Esterman grid perimetry test
HP:0030599.definition: The Esterman grid test assays scores visual acuity. The grid consists of 100 units whose unequal size and distribution reflect the unequal functional value of different parts of the field-in effect a weighted or relative-value scale. Because each unit equals 1 percent, a simple count of units yields the functional score in percent.

HP:0030602.name: Abnormal fundus autofluorescence imaging
HP:0030602.definition: Fundus autofluorescence (FAF) is a non-invasive retinal imaging modality used in clinical practice to provide a density map of lipofuscin, the predominant ocular fluorophore, in the retinal pigment epithelium. Autofluorescent patterns result from the complex interaction of fluorophores such a lipofuscin, which release an autofluorescent signal, and elements such as melanin and rhodopsin, which absorb the excitation beam and attenuate autofluorescence. Other structures such as retinal vessels and the crystalline lens may also influence autofluorescence through blocking and interference.

HP:0030604.name: Abnormal fundus fluorescein angiography
HP:0030604.definition: An abnormality observed by retinal fluorescein angiography, which involves the intravenous injection of fluorescein dye followed by fluorescent imaging of the fundus immediately after injection and for up to ten minutes thereafter. It can be used to study various retinal abnormalities including especially anomalies of the choroidal and retinal circulation.

HP:0030609.name: Photoreceptor layer loss on macular OCT
HP:0030609.definition: Loss of the outer nuclear layer (photoreceptor layer) as assessed by ocular coherence tomography.

HP:0030610.name: Photoreceptor outer segment loss on macular OCT

HP:0030611.name: Retinal pigment epithelial loss on macular OCT

HP:0030612.name: Abnormal retinal morphology on macular OCT

HP:0030613.name: Abnormal foveal morphology on macular OCT

HP:0030614.name: Foveal photoreceptor layer loss on macular OCT

HP:0030615.name: Foveal photoreceptor outer segment loss on macular OCT

HP:0030616.name: Foveal retinal pigment epithelial loss on macular OCT

HP:0030620.name: Inner retinal layer loss on macular OCT

HP:0030621.name: Foveal inner retinal layer loss on macular OCT

HP:0030622.name: Abnormal foveal pit on macular OCT

HP:0030623.name: Intraretinal hyporeflective spaces on macular OCT

HP:0030624.name: Subretinal hyporeflective spaces on macular OCT

HP:0030626.name: Foveal intraretinal hyporeflective spaces on macular OCT

HP:0030627.name: Foveal hyporeflective spaces on macular OCT

HP:0030628.name: Foveal subretinal hyporeflective spaces on macular OCT

HP:0030631.name: Hyperautofluorescent macular lesion
HP:0030631.definition: Increased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

HP:0030632.name: Hypoautofluorescent macular lesion
HP:0030632.definition: Decreased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

HP:0030633.name: Perifoveal ring of hyperautofluorescence surrounded by normal autofluorescence

HP:0030634.name: Perifoveal ring of hyperautofluorescence surrounded by abnormal autofluorescence

HP:0030635.name: Retinal dystrophy with early macular involvement

HP:0030636.name: Occult macular dystrophy
HP:0030636.definition: Occult macular dystrophy is a, typically hereditary, abnormality of the macula associated with progressive foveal cone dysfunction and no apparent fundoscopic, full-field electroretinogram (ERG), or fluorescein angiogram abnormalities.

HP:0030637.name: Congenital stationary cone dysfunction
HP:0030637.definition: Retinal phenotype characterized by cone photoreceptor dysfunction and preserved rod system. The abnormality is typically stationary or very slowly progressive and findings may include reduced central vision, color vision abnormalities, nystagmus and photophobia.

HP:0030638.name: Congenital stationary night blindness with normal fundus

HP:0030639.name: Congenital stationary night blindness with abnormal fundus

HP:0030645.name: Central
HP:0030645.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is located close to the median plane or midline of the body or of the referenced structure.

HP:0030652.name: Vitreous haze
HP:0030652.definition: Vitreous haze is the obscuration of fundus details by vitreous cells and protein exudation.

HP:0030654.name: Umbilical cord cyst
HP:0030654.definition: Any cystic lesion associated with the umbilical cord.

HP:0030655.name: Umbilical cord knot
HP:0030655.definition: An entwining of a segment of umbilical cord, usually without obstructing fetal circulation and commonly result from fetal slippage through a loop of the cord.

HP:0030656.name: Umbilical vein varix
HP:0030656.definition: Focal dilation of the umbilical vein.

HP:0030657.name: Umbilical cord hematoma
HP:0030657.definition: Bleeding from the vessels of the cord with extravasation of blood into the Wharton jelly surrounding the umbilical cord vessels.

HP:0030658.name: Marginal umbilical cord insertion
HP:0030658.definition: Insertion of the umbilical cord within 2 cm from the placental edge.

HP:0030659.name: Velamentous cord insertion
HP:0030659.definition: Insertion of the umbilical cord into the chorio-amniotic membranes of the placenta.

HP:0030660.name: Furcate cord insertion
HP:0030660.definition: Branching of the umbilical cord before its insertion into the placenta.

HP:0030661.name: Vitreous snowballs
HP:0030661.definition: Yellow-white inflammatory aggregates in the vitreous that are found in the midvitreous and inferior periphery.

HP:0030662.name: Vitreous inflammatory cells
HP:0030662.definition: The presence of inflammatory cells such as lymphocytes and macrophages in the vitreous.

HP:0030663.name: Optically empty vitreous
HP:0030663.definition: Vestigial vitreous gel occupying the immediate retrolental space and minimal to no discernible gel in the central vitreous cavity, giving the appearance of an empty vitreous cavity.

HP:0030664.name: Beevor's sign
HP:0030664.definition: Weakness of the inferior portion of the rectus abdominal muscle, which is ascertained clinically as follows. When a patient sits up or raises the head from a recumbent position, the umbilicus is displaced toward the head. This is the result of paralysis of the inferior portion of the rectus abdominal muscle, so that the upper fibers predominate pulling upwards the umbilicus.

HP:0030665.name: Rubral tremor
HP:0030665.definition: Rubral tremor is characterized by a slow coarse tremor at rest that is exacerbated by postural adjustments and by guided voluntary movements.

HP:0030666.name: Retinal neovascularization
HP:0030666.definition: In wound repair, neovascularization (NV) involves the sprouting of new vessels from pre-existent vessels to repair or replace damaged vessels. In the retina, NV is a response to ischemia. The NV adheres to the inner surface of the retina and outer surface of the vitreous. NV are deficient in tight junctions and hence leak plasma into surrounding tissue including the vitreous. Plasma causes the vitreous gel to degenerate, contract, and eventually collapse which pulls on the retina. Since retinal NV is adherent to both retina and vitreous, as the vitreous contracts the NV may be sheared resulting in vitreous hemorrhage or the NV may remain intact and pull the retina with the vitreous resulting in retinal elevation referred to as traction retinal detachment.

HP:0030667.name: Peripheral retinal neovascularization
HP:0030667.definition: A type of retinal neovascularization that affects the periphery of the retina.

HP:0030668.name: Periorbital dermoid cyst
HP:0030668.definition: A cyst that is localized in the region of the orbit and exhibits an epithelial lining with a keratin-filled lumen. Hair follicles are one of the adnexal structures that are commonly found in walls of dermoid cysts.

HP:0030669.name: Abnormal ocular adnexa morphology
HP:0030669.definition: A structural anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

HP:0030670.name: Hamartoma of the orbital region
HP:0030670.definition: A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) which can originate from any tissue of the orbital region.

HP:0030671.name: Abnormal common tendinous ring morphology
HP:0030671.definition: Any anomaly of the ring of fibrous tissue that surrounds the optic nerve at its entrance at the apex of the orbit. The common tendinous ring, also known as the annulus of Zinn or annular tendon, is the origin for five of the seven extraocular muscles.

HP:0030672.name: Asteroid hyalosis
HP:0030672.definition: The presence of small, white vitreous opacities consisting of calcium phosphate and complex, layered lipid deposits.

HP:0030673.name: Erosive vitreoretinopathy
HP:0030673.definition: A form of vitreoretinopathy characterized by thinning (erosion) of the retinal pigment epithelium that permits increased visualization of the choroidal vessels.

HP:0030675.name: Contracture of proximal interphalangeal joints of 2nd-5th fingers
HP:0030675.definition: Chronic loss of joint motion of the proximal interphalangeal joint of the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 5th fingers due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

HP:0030676.name: Satyr ear
HP:0030676.definition: Sharp pointed superior portion of the ear, with variable overfolding of the helix.

HP:0030677.name: Mozart ear
HP:0030677.definition: A congenital auricular deformity, which is mainly characterized by a bulging appearance of the anterosuperior portion of the auricle, a convexly protruded cavum conchae, and a slit-like narrowing of the orifice of the external auditory meatus.

HP:0030679.name: Ash-leaf spot
HP:0030679.definition: A hypopigmented spot in the shape of a leaf from the mountain ash tree.

HP:0030680.name: Abnormal cardiovascular system morphology
HP:0030680.definition: Any structural anomaly of the heart and blood vessels.

HP:0030681.name: Abnormal morphology of myocardial trabeculae
HP:0030681.definition: Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the right and left ventricles of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).

HP:0030682.name: Left ventricular noncompaction
HP:0030682.definition: Left ventricular noncompaction (LVNC) is defined by 3 markers: prominent left ventricular (LV) trabeculae, deep intertrabecular recesses, and the thin compacted layer.

HP:0030683.name: Vaginitis
HP:0030683.definition: Inflammation of the vagina that can result from a spectrum of conditions that cause vaginal and sometimes vulvar symptoms, such as itching, burning, irritation, odor, and vaginal discharge.

HP:0030684.name: Abnormal adiponectin level
HP:0030684.definition: A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of adiponectin, a 30-kDa complement C1-related protein that is the most abundant secreted protein expressed in adipose tissue, and that plays a crucial role in the regulation of insulin sensitivity and glucose metabolism.

HP:0030685.name: Decreased adiponectin level
HP:0030685.definition: A reduced circulating concentration of adiponectin, a 30-kDa complement C1-related protein that is the most abundant secreted protein expressed in adipose tissue.

HP:0030686.name: Increased adiponectin level
HP:0030686.definition: An elevated circulating concentration of adiponectin, a 30-kDa complement C1-related protein that is the most abundant secreted protein expressed in adipose tissue.

HP:0030687.name: Abnormal glucagon level
HP:0030687.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of glucagon in the blood circulation.

HP:0030688.name: Increased glucagon level
HP:0030688.definition: An elevated concentration of glucagon in the blood circulation.

HP:0030689.name: Decreased glucagon level
HP:0030689.definition: A reduced concentration of glucagon in the blood circulation.

HP:0030690.name: Gingival cleft
HP:0030690.definition: A fissure in the gingiva (gums), i.e., the mucosal tissue that lies over the mandible and maxilla.

HP:0030691.name: Divergence nystagmus
HP:0030691.definition: A condition in which both eyes beat outward simultaneously.

HP:0030692.name: Brain neoplasm
HP:0030692.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from or metastasizes to the brain.

HP:0030693.name: Supratentorial neoplasm
HP:0030693.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that occurs within the intracranial cavity above the tentorium cerebelli.

HP:0030706.name: Ranula
HP:0030706.definition: A ranula is a mucocele that occurs in the floor of the mouth and usually involve the major salivary glands. Specifically, the ranula originates in the body of the sublingual gland, in the ducts of the sublingual gland, in the Wharton's duct of the submandibular gland or infrequently from the minor salivary glands at this location.

HP:0030707.name: Unilateral lung agenesis
HP:0030707.definition: Lack of development of one lung.

HP:0030708.name: Myeloschisis
HP:0030708.definition: The severe form of a neural tube defect where the open neural tube appears as a flattened, plate-like mass of nervous tissue with no overlying membrane.

HP:0030709.name: Myelocystocele
HP:0030709.definition: Myelocystocele is characterized by a large, ependyma-lined, cystic dilation of the caudal end of the central canal of the spinal cord; it projects dorsally through a lamina defect, with overlying varying amounts of lipomatous subcutaneous tissue. Myelocystoceles are associated with a tethered cord and meningocele, which communicates with the spinal subarachnoid space, but not with the central canal cyst.

HP:0030710.name: Lipomeningocele
HP:0030710.definition: A form of closed neural tube defect in which the spinal tissue lies within the spinal cord having a junction between the spinal cord and the lipoma. Intact skin covers the defect. Neurologic findings first appear during the second year of life.

HP:0030711.name: Hydrocolpos
HP:0030711.definition: Distention of the vagina caused by accumulation of fluid due to congenital vaginal obstruction.

HP:0030712.name: Uterine synechiae
HP:0030712.definition: Adhesions or scar tissue that form inside the cavity of the uterus.

HP:0030713.name: Vein of Galen aneurysmal malformation
HP:0030713.definition: Vein of Galen aneurysmal malformation is a choroidal type of arteriovenous malformation that develops between 6 and 11 weeks of gestation. It results from 1 or more arteriovenous fistulas shunting blood toward the prosencephalic vein of Markowski, the embryonic precursor of the vein of Galen. This abnormal shunt leads to progressive dilation of the vein and prevents its involution and subsequent development into the vein of Galen.

HP:0030714.name: Subchorionic thrombohematoma
HP:0030714.definition: A large maternal clot that separates the chorionic plate from the villous chorion.

HP:0030715.name: Bronchial atresia
HP:0030715.definition: A developmental anomaly characterized by focal obliteration of the proximal segment of a bronchus. The bronchial pattern is entirely normal distal to the site of stenosis.

HP:0030716.name: Acrania
HP:0030716.definition: Partial or complete absence of the flat bones of the cranial vault. The condition is frequently, though not always, associated with anencephaly.

HP:0030717.name: Meconium peritonitis
HP:0030717.definition: Peritonitis caused by intrauterine intestinal rupture and spillage of fetal meconium into the fetal peritoneal cavity. Intra-peritoneal meconium usually calcifies, sometimes within 24 hours. Ultrasound findings may include intraabdominal calcifications.

HP:0030718.name: Right atrial enlargement
HP:0030718.definition: Increase in size of the right atrium.

HP:0030719.name: Unguarded tricuspid valve
HP:0030719.definition: A form of agenesis of the tricuspid valve in which (although the normal orifice between the right atrium and right ventricle exists) there is no tricuspid valvular tissue.

HP:0030720.name: Subchorionic septal cyst
HP:0030720.definition: Cyst on the surface of the placenta consisting of amnion and chorion.

HP:0030722.name: Ectopic liver
HP:0030722.definition: Ectopic liver is a rare developmental anomaly in which liver tissue is situated outside the liver. Thus, ectopic liver refers to autonomous islands of normal liver parenchyma located outside the liver. The term ectopic liver is also used, to include liver appendices attached to the native liver by a thin stalk although being fully separated from the latter.

HP:0030723.name: Congenital megalourethra
HP:0030723.definition: Dilation and elongation of the penile urethra associated with absence or hypoplasia of the corpora spongiosa and cavernosa.

HP:0030724.name: Central nervous system cyst
HP:0030724.definition: A fluid-filled sac (cyst) located within the central nervous system.

HP:0030725.name: Neurenteric cyst
HP:0030725.definition: The neurenteric cyst is a rare lesion composed of heterotopic endodermal tissue. During the third week of human embryogenesis, the neurenteric canal unites the yolk sac and the amniotic cavity as it traverses the primitive notochordal plate. Persistence of the normally transient neurenteric canal prevents appropriate separation of endoderm and notochord. This results in a variable degree of communication between neural and enteric epithelium.

HP:0030726.name: Spinal neurenteric cyst
HP:0030726.definition: A neurenteric cyst located in the spine.

HP:0030727.name: Intracranial neurenteric cyst
HP:0030727.definition: A neurenteric cyst located within the skull.

HP:0030728.name: Meromelia
HP:0030728.definition: Partial absence of a free limb (excluding girdle). It can refer to the proximal, middle or distal segment of the upper or lower limb. The deficiency may be transverse or longitudinal. Thus, meromelia is a lack of a part, but not all, of one or more limbs with the presence of a hand or foot.

HP:0030729.name: Frontoethmoidal meningocele
HP:0030729.definition: A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull at the junction of the frontal and ethmoidal bones.

HP:0030730.name: Parietal meningocele
HP:0030730.definition: A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull in the parietal region.

HP:0030731.name: Carcinoma
HP:0030731.definition: A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas (NCI Thesaurus).

HP:0030732.name: Dysplastic tricuspid valve
HP:0030732.definition: A congenital malformation of the tricuspid valve characterized by leaflet deformation.

HP:0030733.name: Vesicoallantoic abdominal wall defect
HP:0030733.definition: An abdominal wall defected related to a developmental anomaly of the allantois, which is an embryonic structure that develops as a diverticulum off the yolk sac at about 16 days post fertilization. During further development, the allantois becomes incorporated into the body of the embryo, connecting the ventral aspect of the urogenital sinus (which will develop into the upper pole of the urinary bladder) to the external portion of the umbilicus. Upon further development, the lumen of the allantois becomes obliterated and forms a thick fibrous cord called the urachus, which connects the apex of the bladder to the umbilicus. In adults, the urachus is known as the median umbilical ligament. Failure of the allantoic cavity to obliterate can result of one of four conditions: 1) congenital patent urachus (a completely open connection between bladder and umbilicus); 2) vesicourachal diverticulum (a diverticulum off the bladder but not communicating with the umbilicus); umbilical cyst and sinus (not communicating with the bladder); and 4) alternating urachal sinus. An abdominal wall defect can be associated with a urachal cyst.

HP:0030735.name: Ureterovesical junction obstruction
HP:0030735.definition: Blockage at the level of the bladder and the ureter caused by stenosis of the ureteral valves or failure of a narrow juxtavesical ureteral segment to dilate due to segmented fibrosis or localized absence of muscle.

HP:0030736.name: Sacrococcygeal teratoma
HP:0030736.definition: A teratoma arising in the sacro-coccygeal region.

HP:0030737.name: Altman type I sacrococcygeal teratoma
HP:0030737.definition: A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly external and projects from the sacrococcygeal region and presents with distortion of the buttocks.

HP:0030738.name: Altman type II sacrococcygeal teratoma
HP:0030738.definition: A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly external but has a large intrapelvic component.

HP:0030739.name: Altman type III sacrococcygeal teratoma
HP:0030739.definition: A type of sacrococcygeal teratoma that is predominantly intrapelvic with a small external, buttock mass.

HP:0030740.name: Anomalous muscle bundle of the right ventricle
HP:0030740.definition: An accessory (not normally present) muscle bundle in the right ventricle which obstructs the right ventricular outflow tract.

HP:0030741.name: Mediastinal teratoma
HP:0030741.definition: A teratoma located within the mediastinum (the cavity between the pleural sacs that contains the heart and all of the thoracic viscera except the lungs).

HP:0030742.name: Glial remnants posterior to lens
HP:0030742.definition: This anomaly, also known as Mittendorf dot, is a benign, nonprogressive recognizable lesion that does not cause visual impairment. However, it can resemble a pathological congenital or acquired cataract lesion which may enlarge and cause visual impairment. The dot appears as a black speck that ranges in size from the dot made by a sharp pencil point to the size of a poppy seed. It is usually well defined, although occasionally there may be irregular, fine lines radiating outward from the dot.

HP:0030743.name: Glial remnants anterior to the optic disc
HP:0030743.definition: Persistence of a posterior remnant of the hyaloid artery located at the optic disc.

HP:0030744.name: Hyaloid vascular remnant and retrolental mass
HP:0030744.definition: A type of persistence of the hyaloid vascular system associated with a retrolental mass that may lead to fetal cataract.

HP:0030745.name: Dilatation of the ductus arteriosus
HP:0030745.definition: Ductus arteriosus aneurysm (DAA) is a saccular dilatation of the ductus arteriosus. DAA can be either congenital or acquired (e.g. as a complication of surgical closure of a patent ductus arteriosus). Although the majority of patients with congenital DAA are asymptomatic and have a benign course, severe complications, such as rupture or thromboembolism, can occur. DAA is likely to emerge in the third trimester from the aortic junction of the DA, extending towards its pulmonary end.

HP:0030746.name: Intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030746.definition: Bleeding into the ventricles of the brain.

HP:0030747.name: Preterm intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030747.definition: Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a premature infant.

HP:0030748.name: Grade I preterm intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030748.definition: Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that is restricted to subependymal region/germline matrix which is seen in the caudothalamic groove.

HP:0030749.name: Grade II preterm intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030749.definition: Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that has extension into normal-sized ventricles and typically fills less than 50% of the volume of the ventricle.

HP:0030750.name: Grade III preterm intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030750.definition: Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that has extension into dilated ventricles.

HP:0030751.name: Grade IV preterm intraventricular hemorrhage
HP:0030751.definition: Intraventricular hemorrhage that occurs in a preterm infant and that shows parenchymal extension.

HP:0030752.name: Dacryocystocele
HP:0030752.definition: A nasolacrimal duct obstruction presenting as a grey-blue cystic swelling just below the medial canthus. Believed to be a result of concomitant upper obstruction of the Rosenmuller valve and lower obstruction of the Hasner valve.

HP:0030753.name: Intrauterine fetal demise of one twin after midgestation
HP:0030753.definition: Loss of one twin occurring after midgestation (17 weeks gestation).

HP:0030754.name: Allantoic cyst
HP:0030754.definition: A swelling formed at the base of umbilicus associated with a patent urachus which results from an allantoic remnant. The urachus is a fibrous remnant of the allantois which communicates from the apex of the urinary bladder to the umbilicus. Failed obliteration of the urachus can lead to various abnormalities: urachal cyst, urachal diverticulum, sinus or patent urachus - the most common type. Allantoic cysts in infants with patent urachus can be formed due to the drainage of urine into the umbilical cord, or in uncommon situations, after leakage of hypo-osmotic urine into the Wharton's jelly.

HP:0030755.name: Craniofacial teratoma
HP:0030755.definition: A teratoma located in the craniofacial region.

HP:0030756.name: Erythrodontia
HP:0030756.definition: Reddish, brown opalescent discoloration of teeth in normal light.

HP:0030757.name: Tooth abscess
HP:0030757.definition: A pocket of pus located within a region of a tooth.

HP:0030758.name: Periapical tooth abscess
HP:0030758.definition: A tooth abscess that occurs at the tip of the root (apex) of a tooth.

HP:0030759.name: Adipocyte hypertrophy
HP:0030759.definition: An increase in mean adipocyte cell size. This feature can be measured by determining the average cell diameter of adipocytes microscopically using abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue obtained by biopsy.

HP:0030760.name: Renal fibrosis
HP:0030760.definition: Renal fibrosis is the consequence of an excessive accumulation of extracellular matrix that occurs in virtually every type of chronic kidney disease.

HP:0030762.name: Mesangiolysis
HP:0030762.definition: Partial or complete dissolution of the mesangial matrix, identified by reduced staining on a periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) or silver stain.

HP:0030763.name: Amniotic Sheet
HP:0030763.definition: A sheet like projection that can result from uterine synechiae that has been encompassed by the expanding chorion and amnion.

HP:0030764.name: Ochronosis
HP:0030764.definition: Brown or blue-gray discoloration of the skin that can present on the axillary and inguinal areas, face, palms or soles. In addition, blue-black discoloration can be apparent on skin overlying cartilage in which the pigment is deposited, such as the ears. This is a characteristic manifestation of alkaptonuria, which is an autosomal recessively inherited deficiency of homogentisic acid oxidase that results in accumulation of homogentisic acid in collagenous structures. The sclerae are also typically involved.

HP:0030765.name: Sleep terror
HP:0030765.definition: Episodes of intense fear, screaming, and flailing occur even though the affected individuals are still asleep.

HP:0030766.name: Ear pain
HP:0030766.definition: Pain in the ear can be a consequence of otologic disease (primary or otogenic otalgia), or can arise from pathologic processes and structures other than the ear (secondary or referred otalgia).

HP:0030767.name: Epignathus
HP:0030767.definition: Epignathus is a teratoma originating from the upper jaw, usually connected with the sphenoid bone or hard palate.

HP:0030769.name: Exencephaly
HP:0030769.definition: A malformation of the neural tube with a large amount of protruding brain tissue and absence of calvarium.

HP:0030770.name: Craniorachischisis
HP:0030770.definition: A neural tube defect in which both the brain and spinal cord remain open to varying degrees.

HP:0030771.name: Mallet finger
HP:0030771.definition: Mallet finger refers to a condition in which the end joint of a finger bends but will not straighten by itself. In this situation, the joint can be pushed straight but will not hold that position on its own.

HP:0030772.name: Proximal femoral focal deficiency
HP:0030772.definition: Proximal femoral focal deficiency is a deformity manifested by hypoplasia of a variable portion of the femur with shortening of the entire limb.

HP:0030773.name: Internuclear ophthalmoplegia
HP:0030773.definition: An abnormality of conjugate lateral gaze in which the affected eye shows impairment of adduction. The pathognomonic clinical sign of internuclear ophthalmoplegia is an impaired adduction while testing horizontal saccades on the side of the lesion in the ipsilateral medial longitudinal fascicule.

HP:0030774.name: Mitochondrial swelling
HP:0030774.definition: The mitochondrial matrix refers to the substance occupying the space enclosed by the inner membrane of a mitochondrion, which contains enzymes, DNA, granules, and inclusions of protein crystals, glycogen, and lipid. Mitochondrial swelling refers to an increase in size of the mitochondrial matrix. This phenomenon is thought to be related to a permeabilized inner membrane that originates a large swelling in the mitochondrial matrix. Mitochondrial swelling may distend the outer membrane until it ruptures.

HP:0030775.name: Modic type vertebral endplate changes
HP:0030775.definition: An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate according to a widely used classification published by Dr. Michael Modic.

HP:0030776.name: Modic type I vertebral endplate changes
HP:0030776.definition: An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a low signal on T1-weighted sequences and high signal on T2-weighted sequences. Modic type I changes are thought to represent bone marrow edema and inflammation.

HP:0030777.name: Modic type II vertebral endplate changes
HP:0030777.definition: An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a high signal on T1-weighted sequences and high- or isointense signal on T2 sequences. Modic type II signals are thought to indicate fatty replacement in the bone marrow.

HP:0030778.name: Modic type III vertebral endplate changes
HP:0030778.definition: An abnormal magnetic resonance tomography signal from a vertebral endplate with a low signal on T1 and T2-weighted sequences. Modic type III signals are thought to correspond to subchondral sclerosis seen on plain radiographs.

HP:0030779.name: Ethmocephaly
HP:0030779.definition: Ethmocephaly is the rarest form of holoprosencephaly, which occurs due to an incomplete cleavage of the forebrain. Clinically, the disease presents with a proboscis, hypotelorism, microphthalmos and malformed ears.

HP:0030780.name: Abnormality of the protein C anticoagulant pathway
HP:0030780.definition: An anomaly of the protein C anticoagulant pathway, which serves as a major system for controlling thrombosis, limiting inflammatory responses, and potentially decreasing endothelial cell apoptosis in response to inflammatory cytokines and ischemia. A natural anticoagulant system denoted the protein C pathway exerts its anticoagulant effect by regulating the activity of FVIIIa and FVa. The vitamin K-dependent protein C is the key component of the pathway. Activated protein C (APC) cleaves and inhibits coagulation cofactors FVIIIa and FVa, which result in downregulation of the activity of the coagulation system. The endothelial protein C receptor stimulates the T-TM-mediated activation of protein C on the endothelial cell surface. The two cofactors, protein S and the intact form of FV, enhance the anticoagulant activity of APC.

HP:0030781.name: Increased circulating free fatty acid level
HP:0030781.definition: A higher than normal levels of the fatty acids which can occur in plasma as a result of lipolysis in adipose tissue or when plasma triacyglycerols are taken into tissues.

HP:0030783.name: Increased circulating interleukin 6 concentration
HP:0030783.definition: The concentration of interleukin-6 in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0030784.name: Anomic aphasia
HP:0030784.definition: An inability to name people and objects that are correctly perceived. The individual is able to describe the object in question, but cannot provide the name.

HP:0030785.name: Mediastinal cystic lymphangioma
HP:0030785.definition: A lymphangioma (congenital malformation consisting of focal proliferations of well-differentiated lymphatic tissue in multi cystic or sponge like structures) located within the mediastinum, i.e., the central compartment of the thoracic cavity that is surrounded by loose connective tissue. Mediastinal lymphangioma is a slow growing mass with benign features, and accounts for 1% of all mediastinal tumors.

HP:0030787.name: Cerumen abnormality
