HP:0030787.definition: Any anomaly of the cerumen (ear wax), the yellowish waxy substance secreted in the ear canal.

HP:0030788.name: Impacted cerumen
HP:0030788.definition: Blockage of the external auditory canal by a buildup of earwax.

HP:0030790.name: Abnormal cerumen color
HP:0030790.definition: An anomalous earwax color. Earwax (cerumen) is usually light to dark brown or orange in color.

HP:0030791.name: Abnormal jaw morphology
HP:0030791.definition: A structural anomaly of the jaw, the bony structure of the mouth that consists of the mandible and the maxilla.

HP:0030792.name: Jaw neoplasm
HP:0030792.definition: A tumor originating in the jaw (mandible or maxilla).

HP:0030793.name: Jaw swelling
HP:0030793.definition: Abnormal enlargement in the upper jaw (maxilla) or in the lower jaw (mandible).

HP:0030794.name: Abnormal circulating C-peptide concentration
HP:0030794.definition: An anomalous circulating concentration of the connecting (C) peptide, which links the insulin A and B chains in proinsulin, providing thereby a means to promote their efficient folding and assembly in the endoplasmic reticulum during insulin biosynthesis. After cleavage of proinsulin, C-peptide is stored with insulin in the soluble phase of the secretory granules and is subsequently released in equimolar amounts with insulin, providing a useful independent indicator of insulin secretion.

HP:0030795.name: Reduced C-peptide level
HP:0030795.definition: A decreased concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with reduced insulin secretion.

HP:0030796.name: Increased C-peptide level
HP:0030796.definition: An elevated concentration of C-peptide in the circulation. Since C-peptide is secreted in equimolar amounts to insulin, this feature correlates with increased insulin secretion.

HP:0030797.name: Reduced volume of central subdivision of bed nucleus of stria terminalis
HP:0030797.definition: A diminished volume of the central part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis.

HP:0030798.name: Abnormality of the bed nucleus of stria terminalis
HP:0030798.definition: The stria terminalis is a slender, compact fiber bundle that connects the amygdala (amygdaloid body) with the hypothalamus and other basal forebrain regions. The bed nucleus of the stria terminalis is a limbic forebrain structure that receives heavy projections from, among other areas, the basolateral amygdala, and projects in turn to hypothalamic and brainstem target areas that mediate many of the autonomic and behavioral responses to aversive or threatening stimuli. This term refers to an anomaly of the bed nucleus.

HP:0030799.name: Scaphocephaly
HP:0030799.definition: Scaphocephaly is a subtype of dolichocephaly where the anterior and posterior aspects of the cranial vault are pointed (boat-shaped). Scaphocephaly is caused by a precocious fusion of sagittal suture without other associated synostosis.

HP:0030800.name: Abnormal visual accommodation
HP:0030800.definition: An anomaly in the process of visual accommodation, which is the process of adjustment of the eye to enable sharp vision of objects at different distances. Accommodation is mediated by contraction of the ciliary muscles, which alter the convexity of the lens and, consequently, its refractive power.

HP:0030801.name: Reduced visual accommodation
HP:0030801.definition: A decreased ability of the eye to adjust and thereby enable sharp vision of objects at different distances.

HP:0030802.name: Lower eyelid retraction
HP:0030802.definition: Inferior malposition of the lower eyelid margin without eyelid eversion.

HP:0030804.name: Trachyonychia
HP:0030804.definition: Excessive longitudinal ridging that gives the surface of the nail plate a rough appearance. It results from multiple foci of defective keratinization of the proximal nail matrix.

HP:0030805.name: Absent lunula
HP:0030805.definition: Lack of the lunula at the base of a nail. The lunula is the crescent-shaped whitish area of the bed of a fingernail or toenail.

HP:0030806.name: Fast-growing nails
HP:0030806.definition: Nails whose growth is quicker than normal.

HP:0030807.name: Abnormal nail growth
HP:0030807.definition: Nail whose growth pattern or speed deviates from normal.

HP:0030808.name: Ragged cuticle
HP:0030808.definition: The cuticle (properly known as the eponychium, or the medial nail fold or the proximal nail fold), is the thickened layer of skin surrounding fingernails and toenails. Its function is to protect the area between the nail and epidermis from exposure to bacteria. This term refers to the presence of and irregular edge or outline of the cuticle.

HP:0030809.name: Abnormal tongue morphology
HP:0030809.definition: Any structural anomaly of the tongue.

HP:0030810.name: Abnormal tongue physiology
HP:0030810.definition: Any functional anomaly of the tongue.

HP:0030811.name: Tongue pain
HP:0030811.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the tongue.

HP:0030812.name: Enlarged tonsils
HP:0030812.definition: Increase in size of the tonsils, small collections of lymphoid tissue facing into the aerodigestive tract on either side of the back part of the throat.

HP:0030814.name: Orange discolored tonsils
HP:0030814.definition: A phenomenon of orange colored oral tonsils. This feature is characteristic of Tangier disease and illustrated will by Figure 1 of PMID:19470903.

HP:0030815.name: Lipoma of the tongue
HP:0030815.definition: A lipoma localized to the tongue. May present as a nontender, soft, spherical mass of the tongue.

HP:0030816.name: Gingival recession
HP:0030816.definition: The loss of gum tissue. The result is that gum tissue is recessed and its position on the tooth is lowered, exposing the roots of the teeth.

HP:0030817.name: Beaked nails
HP:0030817.definition: Severe nail curvature, causing the tip of the nail to point downwards with respect to the axis of the finger. Beaked nails are caused by resorption of the distal digit.

HP:0030818.name: Central nail canal
HP:0030818.definition: The presence of a depressed line (canal) in the center of the nail.

HP:0030819.name: Ski jump nail
HP:0030819.definition: Nails that slope upward at the free edge.

HP:0030820.name: Hooded eyelid
HP:0030820.definition: Eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.

HP:0030821.name: Hooded lower eyelid
HP:0030821.definition: Lower eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.

HP:0030822.name: Hooded upper eyelid
HP:0030822.definition: Upper eyelid partly covered by skin when eyes are open.

HP:0030823.name: Scleral thickening
HP:0030823.definition: Increased dimension of the sclera in the anterior-posterior axis.

HP:0030824.name: Mizuo phenomenon
HP:0030824.definition: Change in the color of the fundus from red in the dark-adapted state to golden immediately or shortly after the onset of the light. The color of the fundus reflex in the light adapted state has also been described as golden-yellow, gray-white, and yellow-white. This reflex can appear either homogeneous or in streaks in the fundus. The retinal vessels appear to be protruding in contrast to the radiant background. Dark adaptation leads to disappearance of the unusual fundus coloration [Digital Journal of Ophthalmology 2008; Volume 14, Number 14].

HP:0030825.name: Absent foveal reflex
HP:0030825.definition: Lack of the foveal reflex, which normally occurs as a result of the reflection of light from the ophthalmoscope in the foveal pit upon examination. The foveal reflex is a bright pinpoint of light that is observed to move sideways or up and down in response to movement of the opthalmoscope.

HP:0030826.name: Eyelid fasciculation
HP:0030826.definition: Tiny, repetitive muscle contractions in the eyelids, causing the appearance of twitching.

HP:0030828.name: Wheezing
HP:0030828.definition: A high-pitched whistling sound associated with labored breathing.

HP:0030829.name: Abnormal breath sound
HP:0030829.definition: An anomalous (adventitious) sound produced by the breathing process.

HP:0030830.name: Crackles
HP:0030830.definition: Crackles are discontinuous, explosive, and nonmusical adventitious lung sounds normally heard in inspiration and sometimes during expiration. Crackles are usually classified as fine and coarse crackles based on their duration, loudness, pitch, timing in the respiratory cycle, and relationship to coughing and changing body position.

HP:0030831.name: Rhonchi
HP:0030831.definition: Abnormal breath sounds characterized by low-pitched, snoring or rattle-like sounds.

HP:0030832.name: Vitreous strands
HP:0030832.definition: Fiber- or rope-like opacities located within the vitreous humor.

HP:0030833.name: Neck pain
HP:0030833.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the neck.

HP:0030834.name: Shoulder pain
HP:0030834.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the shoulder.

HP:0030835.name: Elbow pain
HP:0030835.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the elbow.

HP:0030836.name: Wrist pain
HP:0030836.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the wrist.

HP:0030837.name: Finger pain
HP:0030837.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the finger.

HP:0030838.name: Hip pain
HP:0030838.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the hip.

HP:0030839.name: Knee pain
HP:0030839.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the knee.

HP:0030840.name: Ankle pain
HP:0030840.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the ankle.

HP:0030841.name: Toe pain
HP:0030841.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the toe.

HP:0030842.name: Choking episodes
HP:0030842.definition: Incidents in which a piece of food or other objects get stuck in the upper airway and provoke coughing, gagging, inability to talk, and difficulty breathing.

HP:0030843.name: Cardiac amyloidosis
HP:0030843.definition: Extracellular deposition in cardiac tissue of a proteinaceous material that, when stained with Congo red, demonstrates apple-green birefringence under polarized light and that has a distinct color when stained with sulfated Alcian blue. Viewed with electron microscopy, the amyloid deposits are seen to be composed of a beta-sheet fibrillar material. These nonbranching fibrils have a diameter of 7.5 to 10 nm and are the result of protein misfolding.

HP:0030844.name: Undetectable pattern electroretinogram
HP:0030844.definition: Absent response to a pattern electroretinogram (PERG).

HP:0030845.name: Heliotrope rash of eyelid
HP:0030845.definition: Heliotrope rash is a violaceous discoloration of the eyelids associated with periorbital edema.

HP:0030847.name: Abnormal jugular venous pressure
HP:0030847.definition: An anomaly of the jugular venous pressure. The internal jugular veins, being continuous with the superior vena cava, provide a visible measure of the degree to which the systemic venous reservoir is filled. The vertical height above the right atrium to which they are distended and above which they are in a collapsed state provides an imperfect reflection of the right atrial pressure.

HP:0030849.name: Hepatojugular reflux
HP:0030849.definition: The examiner applies firm but persistent pressure over the liver for 10 seconds while observing the mean jugular venous pressure. Normally there is either no rise or only a transient (i.e., 2 to 3 sec) rise in mean jugular venous pressure. A sustained increase in the mean venous pressure until abdominal compression is released is abnormal and indicates impaired right heart function. This abnormal response is called hepatojugular reflux.

HP:0030850.name: Abnormal pulse pressure
HP:0030850.definition: An anomaly of the pulse pressure, which is defined as the systolic pressured minus the diastolic pressure.

HP:0030851.name: Low pulse pressure
HP:0030851.definition: Reduced amplitude of the pulse pressure (systolic blood pressure minus diastolic blood pressure).

HP:0030852.name: High pulse pressure
HP:0030852.definition: Increased amplitude of the pulse pressure (systolic blood pressure minus diastolic blood pressure).

HP:0030853.name: Heterotaxy
HP:0030853.definition: An abnormality in which the internal thoraco-abdominal organs demonstrate abnormal arrangement across the left-right axis of the body.

HP:0030854.name: Scleral staphyloma
HP:0030854.definition: A staphyloma is a localized defect in the eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.

HP:0030855.name: Anterior staphyloma
HP:0030855.definition: A localized defect in the anterior eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.

HP:0030856.name: Posterior staphyloma
HP:0030856.definition: A localized defect in the posterior eye wall with protrusion of uveal tissue due to alterations in scleral thickness and structure.

HP:0030857.name: Eye movement-induced pain
HP:0030857.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eye that is worse in certain directions of gaze and during prolonged gaze holding.

HP:0030858.name: Addictive behavior
HP:0030858.definition: When an activity, substance, object, or behavior becomes a major focus of a person's life, excluding other activities, or has begun to harm the individual or others physically, mentally, or socially, it can be considered addictive behavior. A person can become addicted or compulsively engaged with anything.

HP:0030859.name: Anti-topoisomerase I antibody positivity
HP:0030859.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against topoisomerase I.

HP:0030860.name: Abnormal CSF amyloid concentration
HP:0030860.definition: Abnormal concentration of amyloid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0030861.name: Decreased CSF amyloid concentration
HP:0030861.definition: Reduced concentration of amyloid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0030862.name: Elevated CSF amyloid concentration
HP:0030862.definition: Increased concentration of amyloid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0030863.name: Nasal flaring
HP:0030863.definition: Widening of the nostrils upon inhalation as a manifestation of respiratory distress.

HP:0030864.name: Intercostal retractions
HP:0030864.definition: A pulling inward of the soft tissues between the ribs upon inhalation. This is a sign of increased use of the chest muscles for breathing and is a manifestation of respiratory distress.

HP:0030865.name: Large elbow
HP:0030865.definition: Abnormal increased size of the elbow joint.

HP:0030866.name: Large knee
HP:0030866.definition: Abnormally increased size of the knee joint.

HP:0030867.name: Vertical orbital dystopia
HP:0030867.definition: The orbits do not lie on the same horizontal plane, that is, one eye is lower than the other.

HP:0030868.name: Monorchism
HP:0030868.definition: Having only one testis in the scrotum.

HP:0030869.name: Anorchism
HP:0030869.definition: An abnormality of XY sexual development characterized by the absence of both testes at birth.

HP:0030870.name: Abnormality of spinal facet joint
HP:0030870.definition: An anomaly of the small joints located between and behind adjacent vertebrae.

HP:0030871.name: Facet joint arthrosis
HP:0030871.definition: Osteoarthritis of facet joints in the spine. Degeneration of cartilage in the facet joints results in bone rubbing on bone and reactive new bone formation visible on X-ray.

HP:0030872.name: Abnormal cardiac ventricular function
HP:0030872.definition: An abnormality of the cardiac ventricular function.

HP:0030873.name: Anti-centromere antibody positivity
HP:0030873.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the centromeres or centromere components.

HP:0030874.name: Oxygen desaturation on exertion
HP:0030874.definition: Oxygen saturation less than 95% on exertion or arterial partial pressure of oxygen falling by more than 1kPa.

HP:0030875.name: Abnormality of pulmonary circulation
HP:0030875.definition: A functional anomaly of that portion of the cardiosvascular system that carries deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs and returns oxygenated blood back to the heart.

HP:0030877.name: Reduced FEV1/FVC ratio
HP:0030877.definition: Abnormally low FEV1/FVC (FEV1 - forced expiratory volume in 1 second; FVC forced vital capacity).

HP:0030878.name: Abnormality on pulmonary function testing
HP:0030878.definition: Any anomaly measure by pulmonary function testing, which includes spirometry, measures of diffusing capacity, and plethysmography.

HP:0030879.name: Interlobular septal thickening
HP:0030879.definition: Presence of thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a CT scan.

HP:0030881.name: Shoulder impingement
HP:0030881.definition: Trapping and compression of the rotator cuff tendons during shoulder movements.

HP:0030882.name: Coronary artery aneurysm
HP:0030882.definition: Enlargement of the diameter (cross-section) of a coronary artery as defined by a focal dilation of a segment at least 1.5 times larger than the reference vessel.

HP:0030883.name: Femoroacetabular impingement
HP:0030883.definition: Femoroacetabular impingement (FAI) results from one or more bony abnormalities that lead to abnormal contact between the acetabulum and the femoral head or neck. The femoral abnormality is proposed to cause compression and shear stresses in the region between the labrum and cartilage, anterosuperiorly. These stresses cause a separation between the labrum and cartilage as the labrum is pushed outwards and the cartilage is pushed centrally. This eventually leads to articular degeneration and eventually global hip osteoarthritis.

HP:0030884.name: Gastrojejunal tube feeding in infancy
HP:0030884.definition: Feeding problem necessitating gastrojejunal tube feeding.

HP:0030885.name: Recurrent parasitic infections
HP:0030885.definition: Increased susceptibility to parasitic infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of parasitic infection.

HP:0030886.name: Abnormal T cell apoptosis
HP:0030886.definition: Abnormal apoptosis by peripheral blood T cells in an in vitro culture, compared to a healthy control sample. May be either spontaneous, induced by UV, X-ray, FasL or other agens. Commonly measured by surface expression of phosphatidyl serine labelled by Annexin V, but other methods such as staning of cleaved Caspases may be used by different laboratories.

HP:0030887.name: Increased T cell apoptosis
HP:0030887.definition: Abnormal increase of apoptosis by peripheral blood T cells in an in vitro culture, compared to a healthy control sample. May be either spontaneous, induced by UV, X-ray, FasL or other agens. Commonly measured by surface expression of phosphatidyl serine labelled by Annexin V, but other methods such as staning of cleaved Caspases may be used by different laboratories.

HP:0030888.name: C3 nephritic factor positivity
HP:0030888.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against C3 convertase (C3bBb).

HP:0030889.name: Congenital shortened small intestine
HP:0030889.definition: Substantially shortened length of the small intestine as a result of a developmental defect.

HP:0030890.name: Hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
HP:0030890.definition: A brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

HP:0030891.name: Periventricular white matter hyperintensities
HP:0030891.definition: Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

HP:0030892.name: Deep cerebral white matter hyperintensities
HP:0030892.definition: Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from locations distant from the ventricular system.

HP:0030893.name: Abnormal response to short acting pulmonary vasodilator
HP:0030893.definition: Pulmonary vasodilator testing is performed during right-heart catheterization and involves a short-acting vasoactive agent such as adenosine, epoprostenol, or inhaled nitric oxide. The current definition of a normal (positive) response is a drop in mean pulmonary artery pressure of at least 10 mm Hg (or 20 percent) to below 40 mm Hg.

HP:0030894.name: Insufficient response to short acting pulmonary vasodilator
HP:0030894.definition: No fall in mean pulmonary arterial pressure (mPAP) falls by at least 10 mmHg to an absolute value less than 40 mmHg without a degradation in cardiac output (CO) in response to a short-acting vasoactive agent such as adenosine, epoprostenol, or inhaled nitric oxide.

HP:0030895.name: Abnormal gastrointestinal motility
HP:0030895.definition: An anomaly of the muscular contractions that propel food though the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0030896.name: Abnormal gastrointestinal transit time
HP:0030896.definition: A deviation from the normal amount of time required for food to pass through the intestines.

HP:0030897.name: Decreased intestinal transit time
HP:0030897.definition: A reduction in the length of time required for food to pass through the intestines.

HP:0030898.name: Pruritis on abdomen
HP:0030898.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the abdomen.

HP:0030899.name: Pruritis on hand
HP:0030899.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the hand.

HP:0030900.name: Pruritus on foot
HP:0030900.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the foot.

HP:0030901.name: Pruritis on breast
HP:0030901.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the skin of the breast.

HP:0030902.name: Palmomental reflex
HP:0030902.definition: A type of primitive reflex characterized by an involuntary contraction of the mentalis muscle of the chin caused by stimulation of the thenar eminence of the palm.

HP:0030903.name: Grasp reflex
HP:0030903.definition: A type of primitive reflex that can be elicated when the hand of the examiner is gently inserted into the palm of the patient's hand. The palmar surface is stroked or simply touched. The flexor surfaces of the fingers may be stimulated also by the examiner's fingers. The stimulus should be in a distal direction. With a positive response, the patient grasps the examiner's hand with variable strength and continues to grasp as the examiner's hand is moved. Ability to release the grip voluntarily depends on the activity of the reflex; some patients can do so readily, while others can even be lifted off the bed, since the grasp has such power [NCBI Books:NBK395].

HP:0030904.name: Glabellar reflex
HP:0030904.definition: A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by repetitive tapping on the forehead. Normal subjects usually blink in response to the first several taps, but if blinking persists, the response is abnormal and considered to be a sign of frontal release. Persistent blinking is also known as Myerson's sign.

HP:0030905.name: Snout reflex
HP:0030905.definition: A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by tapping the upper lip lightly. The contraction of the muscles causes the mouth to resemble a snout.

HP:0030906.name: Suck reflex
HP:0030906.definition: A type of primitive reflex that is elicited by lightly touching or tapping on the lips with an object such as a tongue blade, reflex hammer, or the examiner's finger. At times the reflex is obtained merely by approaching the lips with an object. A positive suck reflex consists of sucking movements by the lips when they are stroked or touched.

HP:0030907.name: Thunderclap headache
HP:0030907.definition: Severe head pain with sudden onset, reaching its maximum intensity in less than one minute and lasting from one hour to ten days.

HP:0030908.name: Liver kidney microsome type 1 antibody positivity
HP:0030908.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against P450 2D6, a cytochrome P450 mono-oxygenase. Anti-LKM-1 antibodies are considered to be a diagnostic marker of autoimmune hepatitis type 2 (AIH2).

HP:0030909.name: Anti-liver cytosolic antigen type 1 antibody positivity
HP:0030909.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against a 60-kd peptide contained in the liver cytosolic fraction.

HP:0030911.name: Bifid clitoris
HP:0030911.definition: Two clitorides located side by side.

HP:0030913.name: Exaggerated rugosity of the labia majora
HP:0030913.definition: Marked rugae formation of the skin of the labia majora.

HP:0030914.name: Abnormal peristalsis
HP:0030914.definition: An anomaly of the wave-like muscle contractions of the digestive tract.

HP:0030915.name: Cerebellar edema
HP:0030915.definition: Swelling from fluid accumulation (serous fluid infiltration into the interstitial space) in the cerebellum.

HP:0030934.name: Oral erythroplakia
HP:0030934.definition: A velvety red but not ulcerated lesion of the oral mucosa. The texture may be roughened or normal, and the lesion is neither raised nor depressed.

HP:0030935.name: Abnormal intestinal smooth muscle morphology
HP:0030935.definition: A structural anomaly of the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue of the intestine.

HP:0030936.name: Abnormal layering of muscularis propria
HP:0030936.definition: Abnormal layering of the intestinal muscularis propria into three layers; (1) inner circular; (2) additional oblique; and (3) outer longitudinal layer.

HP:0030937.name: Fibrotic muscularis propria
HP:0030937.definition: The presence of excessive fibrous connective tissue in the muscularis propria of the intestine. Fibrosis is a reparative or reactive process.

HP:0030938.name: Enteric intraneuronal nuclear inclusion bodies
HP:0030938.definition: Aggregates of stainable substances (proteins) in the nuclei of enteric neurons.

HP:0030939.name: Palpebral thickening
HP:0030939.definition: An increased thickness of the eyelid not related to acute inflammation.

HP:0030946.name: Conjunctival papillae
HP:0030946.definition: Raised tissue masses located on the palpebral conjunctiva with a central vessel. Papillae are created by a focal infiltration of inflammatory cells.

HP:0030947.name: Conjunctival follicles
HP:0030947.definition: Small, dome-shaped nodules without a prominent central vessel located on the conjunctiva. The lymphoid follicles are located in the subendothelial region of the conjunctiva. They consist of a germinal center that contains immature, proliferating lymphocytes, as well as a corona that contains mature lymphocytes and plasma cells.

HP:0030948.name: Elevated gamma-glutamyltransferase level
HP:0030948.definition: Increased level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.

HP:0030949.name: Glomerular deposits
HP:0030949.definition: An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.

HP:0030950.name: Pulmonary venous hypertension
HP:0030950.definition: An abnormal increase in pressure in the pulmonary veins, usually as a result of left atrial hypertension.

HP:0030951.name: Skeletal muscle fibrosis
HP:0030951.definition: Excessive formation of fibrous bands of scar tissue in between muscle fibers.

HP:0030952.name: Birdshot retinochoroidopathy
HP:0030952.definition: Multiple cream-yellow colored hypopigmented lesions typically located at the level of the choroid or retinal pigment epithelium; ovoid, cream-colored with indistinct borders. They are between 50 and 1,500 micrometers in size with a characteristic nasal, radial distribution in the postequatorial fundus.

HP:0030953.name: Conjunctival hyperemia
HP:0030953.definition: Dilatation of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva leading to a red appearance of the sclera.

HP:0030955.name: Addictive alcohol use
HP:0030955.definition: An addictive behavior is defined as drinking excessive amounts of alcohol over a prolonged period of time, having difficulty in reducing the amount of alcohol consumed, strongly desiring alcohol, and experiencing withdrawal symptoms when not drinking alcohol.

HP:0030956.name: Abnormality of cardiovascular system electrophysiology
HP:0030956.definition: An anomaly of the electrical conduction physiology of the heart.

HP:0030957.name: Ventricular septal aneurysm
HP:0030957.definition: A bowing (bulging to one side) of the interventricular septum of more than 15 mm on either side in adults and 5 mm in children during normal cardiac motion.

HP:0030958.name: Membranous ventricular septal aneurysm
HP:0030958.definition: Bowing (bulging out) of the membranous part of the interventricular septum of more than 10-15 mm into the cavity of an adjacent ventricle (usually into the right ventricle).

HP:0030959.name: Muscular ventricular septal aneurysm
HP:0030959.definition: Bowing (bulging out) of the muscular part of the interventricular septum of more than 10-15 mm into the cavity of an adjacent ventricle (usually into the right ventricle).

HP:0030961.name: Microspherophakia
HP:0030961.definition: Microspherophakia is a rare congenital anomaly characterized by the abnormal spherical shape of the crystalline lens. It is characterized by an increased anteroposterior thickness of the lens associated with reduced equatorial diameter. The primary pathology lies in the development of zonules. The condition is often bilateral and is characterized by small, thick, and spherical lenses.

HP:0030962.name: Abnormal morphology of the great vessels
HP:0030962.definition: A structural anomaly affecting a blood vessel involved in the circulation of the heart, i.e., the superior or inferior vena cava, the pulmonary arteries, the pulmonary veins, and the aorta.

HP:0030965.name: Aortic stiffness
HP:0030965.definition: The elastic properties of the aorta allow the aorta to store half of the cardiac ejected blood volume per beat, whereby aortic recoil during diastole pushes the remaining stored volume forward into the peripheral circulation, a phenomenon known as the Windkessel function. Aortic stiffness occurs as the elastic fibers within the arterial wall become disrupted due to mechanical stress (with age or due to other factors). Aortic stiffness refers to a reduction in the elasticity of the aorta, which is associated with an elevated pulse pressure, increased wave reflection, and often hypertension.

HP:0030966.name: Abnormal pulmonary artery morphology
HP:0030966.definition: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary artery.

HP:0030967.name: Abnormal pulmonary artery physiology
HP:0030967.definition: An abnormality of the function of the pulmonary artery.

HP:0030968.name: Abnormal pulmonary vein morphology
HP:0030968.definition: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary veins.

HP:0030969.name: Abnormal pulmonary vein physiology
HP:0030969.definition: An abnormality of the function of the pulmonary veins.

HP:0030970.name: Abnormal vena cava physiology
HP:0030970.definition: An abnormality of the function of the veins that return deoxygenated blood from the body into the heart, i.e., the superior vena cava and the inferior vena cava.

HP:0030972.name: Abnormal systemic blood pressure
HP:0030972.definition: A chronic deviation from normal pressure in the systemic arterial system.

HP:0030973.name: Postexertional symptom exacerbation
HP:0030973.definition: Post-exertional symptom exacerbation (PESE), also referred to as post-exertional malaise (PEM), is defined as the worsening of symptoms that can follow minimal cognitive, physical, emotional, or social activity, or activity that could previously be tolerated. Symptoms typically worsen 12 to 72 hours after activity and can last for days or even weeks, sometimes leading to a relapse.

HP:0030974.name: Cryptozoospermia
HP:0030974.definition: A type of oligozoospermia in which spermatozoa can be detected in an ejaculate only after centrifugation and inspection of the pellet.

HP:0030975.name: Pontine tegmental cap
HP:0030975.definition: An abnormal curved or vaulted (capped) structure covering the middle third of the dorsal pontine tegmentum and projecting into the fourth ventricle.

HP:0030976.name: Abnormal factor VIII activity
HP:0030976.definition: A deviation from the normal activity of coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.

HP:0030977.name: Increased factor VIII activity
HP:0030977.definition: Increased activity of the coagulation factor VIII. Factor VIII (fVIII) is a cofactor in the intrinsic clotting cascade that is activated to fVIIIa in the presence of minute quantities of thrombin. fVIIIa acts as a receptor, for factors IXa and X.

HP:0030978.name: Decreased CSF/serum albumin ratio
HP:0030978.definition: A reduction below normal limits of the ratio of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) albumin concentration to serum albumin concentration.

HP:0030979.name: Dilatation of large choroidal vessels
HP:0030979.definition: Enlargement of the large blood vessels in the choroid.

HP:0030980.name: Reduced brain glutamine level by MRS
HP:0030980.definition: An decrease in the level of glutamine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0030981.name: Abnormal CSF/serum albumin ratio
HP:0030981.definition: A deviation from the normal range of the ratio of the albumin concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) to the concentration in serum (which may be defined as 3.2-9.0). This is an index of blood-brain barrier (BBB) integrity, adjusted for the serum albumin concentration, and an increased ratio is taken as a sign of a loss of integrity of the BBB with leakage of albumin into the CSF.

HP:0030983.name: Ovarian thecoma
HP:0030983.definition: A sex cord-stromal tumor of the ovary. Thecomas range from small tumors to large solid or solid-cystic masses of up to 15 cm. They are unilateral in over 90 percent of cases and are rarely malignant. Thecomas are stromal tumors made up of cells that resemble theca cells, lutein cells and fibroblasts. They are traditionally classified within the sex cord-stromal tumor category of ovarian tumor types.

HP:0030984.name: Abnormal serum bile acid concentration
HP:0030984.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of serum bile acid concentration.

HP:0030985.name: Decreased serum bile acid concentration
HP:0030985.definition: A reduction in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.

HP:0030986.name: Biliary epithelial hyperplasia
HP:0030986.definition: Hyperplasia of lining epithelia of the septal and large bile ducts manifesting as micropapillary projections or as a stratification of the epithelium with or without dilatation of the duct lumen.

HP:0030987.name: Suppurative cholangitis
HP:0030987.definition: Cholangitis characterized by the presence of numerous polymorphonuclear cells around and within the wall as well as within the lumen of the ducts. This may involve ducts of any size and is occasionally associated with abscess formation (cholangitic abscess).

HP:0030988.name: Granulomatous cholangitis
HP:0030988.definition: Cholangitis characterized by the accumulation of granulomas. Granulomas are aggregates of modified macrophages (epithelioid cells) and other inflammatory cells that accumulate after chronic exposure to antigens. The underlying trigger may be exposure to noxious agents that cannot be biochemically degraded or to immune dysfunction. The ultimate result is a release of a variety cytokines that stimulate mononuclear cells that fuse to form multinucleated giant cells with a surrounding rim of lymphocytes and fibroblasts.

HP:0030989.name: Lymphoid cholangitis
HP:0030989.definition: Cholangitis characterized by a close association between duct branches, usually interlobular bile ducts, and lymphocytic aggregates, which may show a follicular arrangement.

HP:0030990.name: Pleomorphic cholangitis
HP:0030990.definition: Cholangitis associated with mixed inflammatory infiltrates and the presence of fibrosis or sclerosis of the biliary tree.

HP:0030991.name: Sclerosing cholangitis
HP:0030991.definition: Cholangitis associated with evident ductal fibrosis that develops as a consequence of long-standing bile duct inflammatory, obstruction, or ischemic injury; it can be obliterative or nonobliterative.

HP:0030992.name: Abnormal pancreatic duct morphology
HP:0030992.definition: Any structural anomaly of the pancreatic duct, which is the tubular structure that collects exocrine pancreatic secretions and transports them to the duodenum.

HP:0030993.name: Duplication of pancreatic duct
HP:0030993.definition: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of two separate pancreatic ducts.

HP:0030994.name: Pancreas divisum
HP:0030994.definition: A congenital anomaly of the pancreas that results from failed fusion of the dorsal and ventral ducts during embyological development. Three variants have been described: type 1 or classical divisum in which there is total failure of fusion; type 2 in which dorsal drainage is dominant in the absence of the duct of Wirsung; and type 3 or incomplete divisum where a small communicating branch is present.

HP:0030996.name: Megaduodenum
HP:0030996.definition: Dilation and elongation of the duodenum with hypertrophy of all layers of the duodenum.

HP:0030997.name: Atretic vas deferens
HP:0030997.definition: Abnormal closure or blockage of the vas deferens.

HP:0030998.name: Cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhoea
HP:0030998.definition: Drainage of cerebrospinal fluid through the nose. This can occur when there is a fistula between the dura and the skull base and discharge of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the nose.

HP:0030999.name: Abnormal vestibular saccule morphology
HP:0030999.definition: Any structural anomaly of the saccule of the vestibule. The saccule is the otolith organ that senses motions in the sagittal plane (i.e., up-down movement).

HP:0031000.name: Vestibular saccular degeneration
HP:0031000.definition: Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the saccule of the vestibule.

HP:0031001.name: Minifascicle formation
HP:0031001.definition: A nerve fascicle or fasciculus is a small bundle of axons, enclosed by the perineurium. A minifascule refers to a group of thinly myelinated and unmyelinated axons surrounded by a delicate perineurium, and with a smaller diameter than a normal nerve fascicle.

HP:0031004.name: Hemiareflexia
HP:0031004.definition: Areflexia that is limited to one side of the body.

HP:0031006.name: Acroparesthesia
HP:0031006.definition: A type of paresthesia (tingling, pins-and-needles, burning or numbness or stiffness) that occurs in the hands and feet and particularly in the fingers and toes.

HP:0031007.name: Orofacial action-specific dystonia induced by speech

HP:0031008.name: Lingual dystonia
HP:0031008.definition: Involuntary protrusions, movements, spams and contortions of the tongue.

HP:0031009.name: Ainhum
HP:0031009.definition: Development of a fibrotic constriction ring involving the base of one or more toes, conditioning eversion and absorption of distal structures, possibly progressing to spontaneous amputation.

HP:0031010.name: Hyperphalangy of the 3rd finger
HP:0031010.definition: An accessory phalanx of the third (middle) finger that is arranged linearly with the other phalanges. Hyperphalangy results from an accessory ossification center at the metacarpophalangeal joint.

HP:0031011.name: Fatty streak
HP:0031011.definition: Yellow-colored streaks, patches, or spots on the intimal surface of arteries. Fatty streaks stain red with Sudan III or Sudan IV.

HP:0031012.name: Thin-cap fibroatheroma
HP:0031012.definition: Thin-cap fibroatheroma is characterized by a relatively large necrotic core with an overlying thin fibrous cap measuring less than 65 micrometers and typically containing numerous macrophages, and is considered to be the precursor lesion of plaque rupture which is the most common cause of coronary thrombosis.

HP:0031013.name: Ankylosis
HP:0031013.definition: A reduction of joint mobility resulting from changes involving the articular surfaces.

HP:0031014.name: Arteria lusoria
HP:0031014.definition: Usually, three large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the brachiocephalic trunk (divided into the right common carotid artery and the right subclavian artery), the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery. However, when aberrant right subclavian artery variant is present, the brachiocephalic trunk is absent and four large arteries arise from the arch of the aorta: the right common carotid artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery, and the final one with the most distal left sided origin, the right subclavian artery, also called the arteria lusoria.

HP:0031015.name: Intrahepatic portal vein sclerosis
HP:0031015.definition: Sclerosis of the intrahepatic portal veins of the liver and generally accompanied by non-cirrhotic portal hypertension, features of which may include splenomegaly and varices.

HP:0031016.name: Alternating radiolucent and radiodense metaphyseal lines
HP:0031016.definition: Areas of radio-opaque sclerotic bands alternating with those of normal lucency give rise to stripes akin to a zebra.

HP:0031017.name: Swiss cheese atrial septal defect
HP:0031017.definition: Multiple defects in the atrial septum.

HP:0031018.name: Eccrine syringofibroadenoma
HP:0031018.definition: Eccrine syringofibroadenoma (ESFA) is a benign adnexal tumor arising most often on the extremities of elderly individuals characterized by anastomosing cords of cuboidal epithelial cells surrounded by a fibrovascular stroma containing plasma cells and ductal structures. ESFA stains positively with epithelial membrane antigen (EMA) and carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA).

HP:0031019.name: Pyknotic bone marrow neutrophils
HP:0031019.definition: Nuclear lobes of neutrophils in the bone marrow are thickened and condensed, and individual lobes are connected by unusually long chromatin filaments.

HP:0031020.name: Bone marrow hypercellularity
HP:0031020.definition: A larger than normal amount or percentage of hematopoietic cells relative to marrow fat.

HP:0031021.name: Squamous Papilloma
HP:0031021.definition: A benign epithelial neoplasm characterized by a papillary growth pattern and a proliferation of neoplastic squamous cells without morphologic evidence of malignancy [NCI thesaurus].

HP:0031022.name: Oropharyngeal squamous papilloma
HP:0031022.definition: A benign exophytic neoplasm that arises from the oropharynx. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core covered by stratified squamous epithelium [NCI thesaurus].

HP:0031023.name: Multiple mucosal neuromas
HP:0031023.definition: Multiple painful, dome-shaped, translucent pink to skin-colored papules on oral mucosa. Histologically, the lesions may demonstrate dermal proliferation of well-demarcated nerve bundles associated with abundant mucin and surrounded by a distinct perineural sheath.

HP:0031024.name: Cylindroma
HP:0031024.definition: A benign skin adnexal tumor of eccrine differentiation.

HP:0031025.name: Gastric leiomyosarcoma
HP:0031025.definition: A malignant neoplasm of the stomach that grows submucosally in the gastric wall. Necrosis and hemorrhage may be visible radiologically. Histologically, spindle cells with abnormal mitotic activity may be visible.

HP:0031026.name: Snail-like ilia
HP:0031026.definition: The ilia is round and hypoplastic with a very flat acetabular roof and a very unusual medial projection of bone that is said to resemble the head of a snail. Figure 4 of PMID:3799723 illustrates this feature.

HP:0031027.name: Internal notch of the femoral head
HP:0031027.definition: A small V-shaped indentation on the internal aspect of the femoral head. This feature is well illustrated in Figure 5 of PMID:11694546.

HP:0031028.name: Lactescent serum
HP:0031028.definition: Serum sample with a grossly white (milk-like, i.e., lactescent) appearance. This feature is indicative of an extremely elevated serum triglyceride level.

HP:0031029.name: Elevated circulating carcinoembryonic antigen concentration
HP:0031029.definition: Concentration of the carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. CEA is a member of the immunoglobulin supergene family. The human CEA gene family is clustered on chromosome 19q and comprises 29 genes. CEA is highly expressed in embryonic tissue and in some cancers, and is a widely used tumor marker.

HP:0031030.name: Elevated carcinoma antigen 125 level
HP:0031030.definition: An increased blood concentration of carcinoma antigen 125 (CA-125). CA-125, also known as mucin 16, can exhibit increased blood levels in certain types of cancer.

HP:0031031.name: Abnormal retinol-binding protein level
HP:0031031.definition: A deviation from normal blood concentration of retinol-binding protein (RBP). The most commonly used indicator of vitamin A status is the serum retinol concentration (retinol is one of the several compounds known as vitamin A). The serum RBP concentration is used as a surrogate measure for serum retinol.

HP:0031032.name: Decreased retinol-binding protein level
HP:0031032.definition: A reduced blood concentration of retinol-binding protein. This finding predicts vitamin A deficiency with high sensitivity and specificity.

HP:0031033.name: Impaired urinary acidification
HP:0031033.definition: The kidney contributes towards acid-base homeostasis by excreting H+ ions and retaining bicarbonate. This process is known as acidification of the urine. The pH of urine ranges normally from 4.5 to 8. The inability to reduce the pH of the urine in a situation where it would be otherwise expected is known as an acidification defect.

HP:0031034.name: Abnormal insulin like growth factor binding protein acid labile subunit level
HP:0031034.definition: A deviation from the normal blood concentration of the insulin like growth factor binding protein acid labile subunit (IGFALS; Entrez Gene ID 3483). The acid-labile subunit (IGFALS) acts in the insulin-like growth (IGF) system by binding circulating IGF1 in a ternary complex with binding protein (IGFBP)-3 to prevent IGF1 from crossing the endothelial barrier.

HP:0031035.name: Chronic infection
HP:0031035.definition: Presence of a protracted or persistent infection by a pathogen potentially related to an underlying abnormality of the immune system that is not able to clear the infection.

HP:0031036.name: Reduced growth-hormone binding protein level
HP:0031036.definition: A decreased blood concentration of growth hormone binding protein.

HP:0031037.name: Reduced insulin-like factor 3 level
HP:0031037.definition: Blood concentration of insulin-like factor 3 (ILF3) is below normal limits.

HP:0031038.name: Spermatogenesis maturation arrest
HP:0031038.definition: Maturation arrest (MA) is defined as germ cells that fail to complete maturation. Uniform MA is characterized by spermatogenic arrest at the same stage of spermatogenesis throughout the seminiferous tubules. MA is subcategorized into early MA, in which only spermatogonia or spermatocytes are found, and late MA, in which spermatids are detected without spermatozoa.

HP:0031039.name: Spermatocyte maturation arrest
HP:0031039.definition: A type of spermatogenesis maturation arrest in which the block of developmental occurs in the spermatocyte stage. Testicular histology shows seminiferous tubules with Sertoli cells, spermatogonial cells and spermatocytes but no further differentiated cells like round spermatids.

HP:0031040.name: Round spermatid arrest
HP:0031040.definition: A failure of spermatogenesis to progress beyond the round spermatid stage. The round spermatid is the first haploid cells produced during spermatogenesis and normally further develop into mature spermatozoa. This abnormality can be visualized with testicular biopsy and is characterized seminiferous tubules with increased numbers of round spermatids with few or no mature spermatozoa.

HP:0031041.name: Obstruction of the superior vena cava
HP:0031041.definition: Blockage of blood flow through the superior vena cava (SVC). Because the venous drainage from the upper extremities, upper thorax and head is obstructed, SVC obstruction presents with symptoms related to engorgement of these areas. Both the degree of SVC compromise and the extent of collateral veins determine the varied clinical presentation, which can be as mild as slight facial and upper extremity edema or as dire as intracranial swelling, seizures, hemodynamic instability and tracheal obstruction.

HP:0031042.name: Strawberry tongue
HP:0031042.definition: Inflamed tongue with hyperplastic (enlarged) fungiform papillae that is said to resemble a strawberry or raspberry.

HP:0031043.name: Type A4 brachydactyly
HP:0031043.definition: A type of brachydactyly characterized by brachymesophalangy affecting mainly the 2nd and 5th digits.

HP:0031044.name: Type A5 brachydactyly
HP:0031044.definition: A type of brachydactyly characterized by absent middle phalanges of digits 2 to 5.

HP:0031045.name: Acral blistering
HP:0031045.definition: Bullae (defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls) of the skin with an acral distribution (affecting peripheral regions such as hands and feet).

HP:0031046.name: Absent soft palate
HP:0031046.definition: A developmental defect characterized by lack of a soft palate.

HP:0031047.name: Paraproteinemia
HP:0031047.definition: An abnormal immunoglobulin or part of an Ig (light chain) in the circulation. Paraproteins are typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0031048.name: Light-chain paraproteinemia
HP:0031048.definition: An abnormal immunoglobulin light chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0031049.name: Heavy-chain paraproteinemia
HP:0031049.definition: An abnormal immunoglobulin heavy chain in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0031050.name: Whole-immunoglobulin paraproteinemia
HP:0031050.definition: An abnormal immunoglobulin (heavy and light chain) in the circulation and typically produced by a clonal population of B-cell derived plasma cells.

HP:0031051.name: Tarsal sclerosis
HP:0031051.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more tarsal bones of the foot. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0031052.name: Elevated vascular endothelial growth factor level
HP:0031052.definition: Increased blood concentration of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF).

HP:0031053.name: Coarctation in the transverse aortic arch
HP:0031053.definition: Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized to the region of the transverse aortic arch.

HP:0031054.name: Long segment coarctation of the aorta
HP:0031054.definition: Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a long segment of the arch of the aorta.

HP:0031055.name: Abnormal branching pattern of left aortic arch
HP:0031055.definition: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries, whereby the aortic arch descends on the left as normal (as opposed to right aortic arch).

HP:0031056.name: Fusiform cerebral aneurysm
HP:0031056.definition: A localized circumferential (i.e., bulges on all sides) dilatation or ballooning of a cerebral artery.

HP:0031057.name: Skin fissure
HP:0031057.definition: A clearly-defined and roughly linear cleavage in the skin that usually extends to the dermis.

HP:0031058.name: Impairment of activities of daily living
HP:0031058.definition: Difficulty in performing one or more activities normally performed every day, such as eating, bathing, dressing, grooming, work, homemaking, and leisure.

HP:0031059.name: Impaired ability to bathe oneself
HP:0031059.definition: This term applies to an individual who requires help to bathe more than one part of the body, get in or out of the tub or shower, or who requires total bathing.

HP:0031060.name: Impaired ability to dress oneself
HP:0031060.definition: This applies to an individual who needs help with dressing or needs to be completely dressed.

HP:0031061.name: Impaired toileting ability
HP:0031061.definition: This term applies to an individual who requires help transferring to the toilet, cleaning self or who uses bedpan or commode.

HP:0031062.name: Impaired transferring ability
HP:0031062.definition: Applies to an individual who needs help in moving from bed to chair or requires a complete transfer.

HP:0031063.name: Impaired feeding ability
HP:0031063.definition: Applies to an individual who needs partial or total help with feeding or requires parenteral feeding.

HP:0031064.name: Impaired continence
HP:0031064.definition: Partial or total incontinence of bowel or bladder.

HP:0031067.name: Empty ovarian follicle
HP:0031067.definition: A failure to collect oocytes after an apparently normal controlled ovarian hyperstimulation cycle for in vitro fertilization.

HP:0031069.name: Abnormal femoral torsion
HP:0031069.definition: Femoral torsion, also known as femoral rotation or femoral version, refers to the twist between the proximal and distal parts of the femur on the transverse plane. Femoral anteversion averages between 30-40 degrees at birth, and between 8-14 degrees in adults. This term applies if the amount of femoral torsion deviates from this range.

HP:0031071.name: Abnormal endocrine morphology
HP:0031071.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of an organ ofthe endocrine system.

HP:0031072.name: Abnormal endocrine physiology
HP:0031072.definition: Any anomaly of the function of the endocrine system.

HP:0031073.name: Abnormal response to endocrine stimulation test
HP:0031073.definition: An anomalous response to a test that is designed to probe the function of the endocrine system.

HP:0031074.name: Abnormal response to ACTH stimulation test
HP:0031074.definition: An anomalous response to stimulation by administration of the adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH). ACTH stimulation normally stimulates the adrenal glands to release cortisol and adrenaline.

HP:0031075.name: Abnormal response to insulin tolerance test
HP:0031075.definition: An anomalous response to the insulin tolerance test (ITT), in which insulin is administered intravenously and blood glucose and potentially other compounds are measured at intervals. Insulin administration is intended to induce extreme hypoglycemia (bloodgluoce below 40 mg/dl), which in turn induces release of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and growth hormone (GH). ACTH induces the adrenal gland to release cortisol, which together with GH opposes the action of insulin on the blood glucose level.

HP:0031076.name: Impaired cortisol response to insulin stimulation test
HP:0031076.definition: Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the insulin tolerance test (ITT).

HP:0031077.name: Abnormal response to corticotropin releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0031077.definition: An anomalous response to the corticotropin releasing hormone (CRH) stimulation test. Normally,CRH is released by the hypothalamus to induce adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) release by the anterior pituitary. In the stimulation test, CRH is administered intravenously and ACTH and cortisol are measured at intervals.

HP:0031078.name: Impaired cortisol response to corticotropin releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0031078.definition: Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the corticotropin releasing hormone stimulation test.

HP:0031079.name: Impaired growth-hormone response to insulin stimulation test
HP:0031079.definition: Failure of growth hormone levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the insulin tolerance test (ITT).

HP:0031080.name: Abnormal response to glucagon stimulation test
HP:0031080.definition: An anomalous response to the glucagon stimulation test, which like the insulin tolerance test (ITT) stimulates the release of both adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and growth hormone (GH).

HP:0031081.name: Impaired cortisol response to glucagon stimulation test
HP:0031081.definition: Failure of cortisol levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the glucagon stimulation test.

HP:0031082.name: Impaired growth-hormone response to glucagon stimulation test
HP:0031082.definition: Failure of growth hormone levels to respond adequately (by increasing) to the glucagon stimulation test.

HP:0031083.name: Abnormal response to human chorionic gonadotrophin stimulation test
HP:0031083.definition: An anomalous response to intravenous stimulation by human chorionic gonadotrophin. Stimulation with hCG stimulates testicular Leydig cells to secrete androgens via the Leydig hormone receptors.

HP:0031084.name: Excessive insulin response to glucagon test
HP:0031084.definition: An abnormally high increase in insulin levels following a glucagon stimulation test.

HP:0031085.name: Decreased circulating prealbumin concentration
HP:0031085.definition: Concentration of prealbumin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. Prealbumin, also known as transthyretin, has a half-life in plasma of about 2 days, much shorter than that of albumin. Prealbumin is therefore more sensitive to changes in protein-energy status than albumin, and its concentration closely reflects recent dietary intake rather than overall nutritional status.

HP:0031086.name: Ectopic ovary
HP:0031086.definition: Undescended or ectopic ovaries are characterized by the attachment of the upper pole of the ovary to an area above the level of the common iliac vessels.

HP:0031087.name: Absent pubertal growth spurt
HP:0031087.definition: The abrupt and transient increase in the annual growth rate normally observed in adolescent individuals does not occur.

HP:0031089.name: Palatal edema
HP:0031089.definition: Swelling related to fluid accumulation within the palate.

HP:0031090.name: Finger dactylitis
HP:0031090.definition: Fingers appear swollen and plump owing to inflammation of the complete finger.

HP:0031091.name: Toe dactylitis
HP:0031091.definition: Toes appear swollen and plump owing to inflammation of the complete toe.

HP:0031092.name: Spindle-shaped finger
HP:0031092.definition: Swelling of the hand at the knuckles, that gives the fingers a spindle shape (i.e., a round stick with tapered end and a broader base).

HP:0031093.name: Abnormal breast morphology
HP:0031093.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the breast.

HP:0031094.name: Abnormal breast physiology
HP:0031094.definition: Any anomaly of the function of the breast.

HP:0031095.name: Abnormal humerus morphology
HP:0031095.definition: Any structural anomaly of the structure of the humerus (i.e., upper arm bone).

HP:0031096.name: Delayed vertebral ossification
HP:0031096.definition: A decrease in the amount of mineralized bone in one or more vertebrae compared with that expected for a given developmental age.

HP:0031097.name: Abnormal thyroid-stimulating hormone level
HP:0031097.definition: Any deviation from the normal amount of the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates the function of the thyroid gland.

HP:0031098.name: Decreased thyroid-stimulating hormone level
HP:0031098.definition: Reduced amount of the thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), which is produced by the anterior pituitary gland and stimulates the function of the thyroid gland.

HP:0031099.name: Abnormal circulating inhibin level
HP:0031099.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of inhibins, which are heterodimeric protein hormones secreted by granulosa cells of the ovary in females and Sertoli cells of the testis in males. Inhibins suppress the secretion of pituitary follicle-stimulating hormone.

HP:0031100.name: Decreased circulating inhibin B concentration
HP:0031100.definition: The concentration of inhibin B in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0031101.name: Abnormal circulating antimullerian hormone concentration
HP:0031101.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the antimullerian hormone, a peptide produced by the granulosa cells of follicles. Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH), also known as Mullerian inhibiting substance, is produced by the granulosa cells of small antral follicles of the ovary. AMH has an inhibiting role in the ovary, contributing to follicular arrest. AMH levels in women are low until the age of 8, rise rapidly until puberty and decline steadily from the age of 25 until menopause, when AMH production ceases.

HP:0031102.name: Increased circulating antimullerian hormone concentration
HP:0031102.definition: An elevation above the normal range of the antimullerian hormone in the circulation.

HP:0031103.name: Decreased circulating antimullerian hormone circulation
HP:0031103.definition: A reduction below the normal range of the antimullerian hormone in the circulation.

HP:0031104.name: Insulin receptor antibody positivity
HP:0031104.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the insulin receptor.

HP:0031105.name: Abnormal uterus morphology
HP:0031105.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the uterus

HP:0031106.name: T-shaped uterus
HP:0031106.definition: An abnormality of the uterus characterized by a normal uterine outline but with an abnormal T-shaped uterine cavity with narrowing cavity due to thickened lateral walls with a correlation 2/3 uterine corpus and 1/3 cervix. The abnormlaity is said to resemble the letter T in hysterosalpingographic imaging.

HP:0031107.name: Decreased fibular diameter
HP:0031107.definition: Reduced width of the cross sectional diameter of the fibula.

HP:0031108.name: Triceps weakness
HP:0031108.definition: A lack of strength in the triceps muscle, which normally is responsible for extending (straightening) the elbow and mediating certain shoulder movements.

HP:0031109.name: Agalactia
HP:0031109.definition: Failure of secretion of milk following childbirth associated with an inability to breastfeed an infant.

HP:0031110.name: Twin-to-twin transfusion
HP:0031110.definition: As a result of sharing a single placenta, the blood supplies of monochorionic twin fetuses can become connected, so that they share blood circulation: although each fetus uses its own portion of the placenta, the connecting blood vessels within the placenta allow blood to pass from one twin to the other.Depending on the number, type and direction of the interconnecting blood vessels (anastomoses), blood can be transferred disproportionately from one twin (the donor) to the other (the recipient). This state of transfusion causes the donor twin to have decreased blood volume, retarding the donor's development and growth. The blood volume of the recipient twin is increased, which can strain the fetus's heart and eventually lead to heart failure.

HP:0031111.name: Cutaneous hamartoma
HP:0031111.definition: A hamartoma (tissue malformation consisting of an abnormal mixture of constitutive components) originating in the skin.

HP:0031117.name: Purely bicuspid aortic valve
HP:0031117.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by two equal-sized cusps, with no raphe and only two commissures. There is a lateral arrangement of the free edge of the cusps. Note that this differs from some other forms of BAV in which there are three commissures and two of the three cusps are joined by a raphe forming two functional leaflets. This type of BAV often is associated with aortic stenosis.

HP:0031118.name: Single raphe bicuspid aortic valve
HP:0031118.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valvue (BAV) characterized by the presence of a single raphe that extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps, resulting in two leaflets of unequal size.

HP:0031119.name: Bicuspid aortic valve with right-left cusp fusion
HP:0031119.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by a single raphe between the right and left cusps (RL fusion pattern). This results in two leaflefts with an anterior-posterior leaflet orientation (also called the typical pattern). There is thus one completely developed noncoronary cusp, two completely developed commissures, and one raphe between the underdeveloped left and right coronary cusps extending to the corresponding malformed commissure.

HP:0031120.name: Bicuspid aortic valve with right-noncoronary cusp fusion
HP:0031120.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by a single raphe between the right and noncoronary cusps (RN fusion pattern). This results in two leaflets with right-left leaflet orientation (also called the atypical pattern). There is thus one completely developed left cusp, two completely developed commissures, and one raphe between the underdeveloped right and noncoronary coronary cusps extending to the corresponding malformed commissure.

HP:0031121.name: Bicuspid aortic valve with left-noncoronary cusp fusion
HP:0031121.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by a single raphe between the left and noncoronary cusps (LN fusion pattern). There is thus one completely developed right cusp, two completely developed commissures, and one raphe between the underdeveloped left and noncoronary coronary cusps extending to the corresponding malformed commissure.

HP:0031122.name: Two-raphe bicuspid aortic valve
HP:0031122.definition: A type of bicuspid aortic valvue (BAV) characterized by the presence of two raphes that each extend from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps. This type of BAV has developmental anlagen of three cusps, commissures, and sinuses, but two commissures are more or less malformed and obliterated, giving rise to a raphe, a fibrous ridge, which extends from the commissure to the free edge of the two underdeveloped, conjoint cusps. This type of BAV is typically associated with a high degree of aortic stenosis.

HP:0031123.name: Recurrent gastroenteritis
HP:0031123.definition: Increased susceptibility to gastroenteritis, an infectious inflammationof the stomach and small intestines manifested by signs and symptoms such as diarheas and abdominal pain, as manifested by recurrent episodes of gastroenteritis.

HP:0031124.name: Decreased platelet thromboxane A2 receptor
HP:0031124.definition: Decreased cell membrane concentration of thromboxane A2 receptor that is stimulated by thromboxane A2 (TBXA2).

HP:0031125.name: Decreased platelet alpha-2A-adrenergic receptor
HP:0031125.definition: Decreased cell membrane concentration of alpha-2A adrenergic receptor that is stimulated by epinephrine.

HP:0031126.name: Impaired clot retraction
HP:0031126.definition: Platelets contain contractile proteins (actin and myosin) that induce clot retraction. As the platelets contract, they pull on the surrounding fibrin strands, squeezing serum form the mass, compacting the clot and drawing the ruptured edges of the blood vessel more closely together. Clot retraction is directly proportional to the platelet count and inversely proportional to the fibrinogen concentration.

HP:0031127.name: Impaired convulxin-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0031127.definition: Abnormal response to convulxin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of convulxin.

HP:0031128.name: Impaired collagen-related peptide-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0031128.definition: Abnormal response to collagen-related peptide (CRP) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of CRP.

HP:0031129.name: Impaired phorbol myristate acetate-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0031129.definition: Abnormal response to phorbol myristate acetate (PMA) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of PMA.

HP:0031130.name: Impaired calcium ionophore-induced platelet aggregation
HP:0031130.definition: Abnormal response to calcium Ionophore (such as A23187) as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of the ionophore.

HP:0031131.name: Abnormal platelet phosphatidylserine exposure
HP:0031131.definition: An abnormality of phosphatidylserine (PS) on activated platelets. PS is normally located on the cytoplasmic face of the resting platelet membrane but appears on the plasma-oriented surface of discrete membrane vesicles that derive from activated platelets. Thrombin, the central molecule of coagulation, is produced from prothrombin by a complex (prothrombinase) between factor Xa and its protein cofactor (factor V(a)) that forms on platelet-derived membranes. This complex enhances the rate of activation of prothrombin to thrombin by roughly 150,000 fold relative to factor X(a) in solution. The negatively charged surface of PS-containing platelet-derived membranes is at least partly responsible for this rate enhancement.

HP:0031132.name: Impaired annexin V binding to platelet phosphatidylserine
HP:0031132.definition: Reduced binding of annexin V to platelet membrane, which is mediated by exposed phosphatidylserine. This can be measured by flow cytometry.

HP:0031133.name: Increased annexin V binding to platelet phosphatidylserine
HP:0031133.definition: Elevated binding of annexin V to platelet membrane, which is mediated by exposed phosphatidylserine. This can be measured by flow cytometry.

HP:0031134.name: Cor triatriatum sinister
HP:0031134.definition: A developmental anomaly of the heart characterized by the presence of three atria because the left atrium is divided by an abnormal septum.

HP:0031135.name: Triggered by physical trauma
HP:0031135.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a trauma (injury to tissue).

HP:0031136.name: Decreased acrosin in sperm head
HP:0031136.definition: A reduced amount of the enzyme acrosin in the sperm head acrosome. The acrosome is an organelle in the anterior half of the head of spermatozoa, and acrosin is a protease that contributes to the digestation of the zona pellucida in the fertilization process.

HP:0031137.name: Storage in hepatocytes
HP:0031137.definition: Hepatocytes (liver parenchymal cells) exhibit a bloated appearance because of expansion of the cytoplasm by accumulated material.

HP:0031138.name: Abnormal circulating B-type natriuretic peptide concentration
HP:0031138.definition: A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).

HP:0031139.name: Frog-leg posture
HP:0031139.definition: A type of rest posture in an infant that indicated a generalized reduction in muscle tone. The hips are flexed and the legs are abducted to an extent that causes the lateral thigh to rest upon the supporting surface. This posture is said to resemble the legs of a frog.

HP:0031140.name: Abnormal liver sonography
HP:0031140.definition: An abnormal appearance of the liver or any of its components on sonography (ultrasound).

HP:0031141.name: Increased hepatic echogenicity
HP:0031141.definition: Increased echogenicity of liver tissue on sonography, manifested as an increased amount of white on the screen of the sonography device.

HP:0031142.name: Abnormal hepatic echogenicity
HP:0031142.definition: Any deviation from the normal degree of echogenicity of the liver on sonography. Echogenicity refers to the ability of a tissue to reflect or transmit ultrasound waves in the context of surrounding tissues. Whenever there is an interface of structures with different echogenicities, a visible difference in contrast will be apparent on the screen. Based on echogenicity, a structure can be characterized as hyperechoic (white on the screen), hypoechoic (gray on the screen) and anechoic (black on the screen).

HP:0031143.name: Decreased hepatic echogenicity
HP:0031143.definition: Reduced echogenicity of liver tissue on sonography, manifested as an increased amount of black on the screen of the sonography device.

HP:0031144.name: Coarsened hepatic echotexture
HP:0031144.definition: The appearance of the liver in sonographic images is normally uniform. This term applies when there is an irregular or non-uniform appearance of the liver parenchyma in liver sonography.

HP:0031145.name: Starry sky appearance on hepatic sonography
HP:0031145.definition: An abnormal echotexture visible in liver ultrasound manifesting as a diffuse hyperechoic liver echotexture with multiple, small hypoechoic lesions. The appearance is said to resemble a starry sky (multiple white spots on a dark background).

HP:0031146.name: Impaired oral bolus formation
HP:0031146.definition: An abnormality of swallowing characterized by reduced tongue coordination to form bolus after chewing. Food material spreads over the oral cavity instead of being concentrated into a bolus that is easily swallowed.

HP:0009150.name: Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009150.definition: Abnormality of the proximal phalanx of the little (5th) finger.

HP:0009152.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 5th finger
HP:0009152.definition: Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the proximal, middle, and distal phalanges of the 5th finger.

HP:0009153.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009153.definition: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the fifth finger. This epiphysis is located on the proximal end of the phalanx.

HP:0009154.name: Triangular epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009154.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the little finger of the hand. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat.

HP:0009155.name: Cone-shaped epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009155.definition: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the little finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. This epiphysis is located at the proximal end of the phalanx and is normally nearly flat. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of the phalanx.

HP:0009157.name: Ivory epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009157.definition: Sclerosis of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the little finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

HP:0009158.name: Enlarged epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009158.definition: Abnormally large size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009159.name: Small epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009159.definition: Abnormally small size of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

HP:0009160.name: Absent epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009160.definition: Absence of the epiphysis located at the proximal end of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009161.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009161.definition: Absence or underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the middle phalanx of the little (5th) finger.

HP:0009162.name: Absent middle phalanx of 5th finger
HP:0009162.definition: Absence of the middle phalanx of the little (5th) finger.

HP:0009163.name: obsolete Abnormal form of the 5th finger

HP:0009164.name: Abnormal calcification of the carpal bones

HP:0009165.name: Stippling of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009165.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009166.name: Fragmentation of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009166.definition: Fragmented appearance of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009167.name: Irregular epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009167.definition: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009168.name: Bullet-shaped middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009168.definition: Bullet-shaped phalanx refers to a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction. This term is used if the middle phalanx of the 5th finger is affected.

HP:0009169.name: Broad middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009169.definition: Increased width of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009170.name: Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009170.definition: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009171.name: Triangular epiphyses of the metacarpals
HP:0009171.definition: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpals. These epiphyses are located at the distal end of the metacarpals.

HP:0009172.name: Abnormal 4th finger phalanx morphology
HP:0009172.definition: Abnormality of the phalanges of the 4th (ring) finger.

HP:0009173.name: Curved middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009173.definition: Curved appearance of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009174.name: Abnormality of the epiphyses of the 4th finger
HP:0009174.definition: Abnormality of one or all of the epiphyses of the proximal, middle, and distal phalanges of the 4th finger.

HP:0009175.name: Patchy sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger
HP:0009175.definition: Patchy increase in bone density of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger.

HP:0009177.name: Proximal/middle symphalangism of 5th finger
HP:0009177.definition: Fusion of the proximal and middle phalanges of the 5th finger.

HP:0009178.name: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of 5th finger
HP:0009178.definition: Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger with another bone.

HP:0009179.name: Deviation of the 5th finger
HP:0009179.definition: Displacement of the 5th finger from its normal position.

HP:0009180.name: Ulnar deviation of the 5th finger
HP:0009180.definition: Displacement of the 5th finger towards the ulnar side.
