HP:0032863.definition: Typical absence status epilepticus is a type of generalized non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma that is semiologically a prolonged typical absence seizure.

HP:0032864.name: Focal aware sensory seizure with auditory features
HP:0032864.definition: A type of focal sensory seizure with auditory features during which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

HP:0032865.name: Myoclonic absence status epilepticus
HP:0032865.definition: Myoclonic absence status epilepticus is a type of generalized non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma that is semiologically a prolonged myoclonic absence seizure. Myoclonic absence status epilepticus consists of proximal, predominantly upper extremity myoclonic jerks corresponding with 3 Hz spike-wave discharges in the EEG.

HP:0032866.name: Oculoclonic status epilepticus
HP:0032866.definition: A type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by repetitive and rapid saccades, in association with epileptic discharges.

HP:0032867.name: Refractory status epilepticus
HP:0032867.definition: Refractory status epilepticus is defined as status epilepticus continuing despite two appropriately selected and dosed antiepileptic drugs, including a benzodiazepine.

HP:0032868.name: Super-refractory status epilepticus
HP:0032868.definition: Super-refractory status epilepticus is defined as refractory status epilepticus continuing for 24 h or more following initiation of anesthetic medications, including cases in which seizure control is attained after induction of anesthetic drugs but recurs on weaning the patient off the anesthetic agent.

HP:0032869.name: Focal non-convulsive status epilepticus without impairment of consciousness
HP:0032869.definition: Focal non-convulsive status epilepticus without impairment of consciousness is a type of focal non-convulsive status epilepticus in which awareness remains intact.

HP:0032870.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with dyslexia/alexia
HP:0032870.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with dyslexia / alexia characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032871.name: Focal aware cognitive seizure with hallucination
HP:0032871.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with hallucination characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.

HP:0032872.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with illusion
HP:0032872.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with illusion characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032873.name: Focal aware sensory seizure with cephalic sensation
HP:0032873.definition: A seizure characterized by a sensation in the head such as light-headedness or headache.

HP:0032874.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with auditory agnosia
HP:0032874.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with auditory agnosia characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032875.name: obsolete Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with impaired responsiveness

HP:0032876.name: Focal aware cognitive seizure with conduction dysphasia/aphasia
HP:0032876.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with conduction dysphasia / aphasia characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.

HP:0032877.name: Focal aware sensory seizure with hot-cold sensations
HP:0032877.definition: A seizure characterized by sensations of feeling hot and then cold.

HP:0032878.name: Focal impaired awareness sensory seizure with cephalic sensation
HP:0032878.definition: A focal sensory seizure with cephalic sensation in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032879.name: Focal impaired awareness seizure with dissociation at onset
HP:0032879.definition: A focal cognitive epileptic seizure with dissociation at the onset of the seizure and with impairment of awareness at at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032880.name: Focal impaired awareness sensory seizure with auditory features
HP:0032880.definition: A focal sensory seizure with auditory features in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032881.name: obsolete Focal aware cognitive seizure with impaired responsiveness

HP:0032882.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with deja vu/jamais vu
HP:0032882.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with deja vu / jamais vu characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032883.name: Focal aware cognitive seizure with deja vu/jamais vu
HP:0032883.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with deja vu / jamais vu characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.

HP:0032884.name: Focal aware sensory seizure with somatosensory features
HP:0032884.definition: A seizure characterized by sensory phenomena including tingling, numbness, electric-shock like sensation, pain, sense of movement, or desire to move. Awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

HP:0032885.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with hallucination
HP:0032885.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with hallucination characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032886.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with expressive dysphasia/aphasia
HP:0032886.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with expressive dysphasia / aphasia characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032887.name: Generalized atonic seizure
HP:0032887.definition: Generalized atonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterized by a sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone without apparent preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting about 1-2 s, involving head, trunk, jaw, or limb musculature.

HP:0032888.name: Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with forced thinking
HP:0032888.definition: A focal cognitive seizure with forced thinking characterized by impairment of awareness at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032889.name: Focal aware sensory seizure with gustatory features
HP:0032889.definition: A seizure characterized by taste phenomena including acidic, bitter, salty, sweet, or metallic tastes.

HP:0032890.name: Focal impaired awareness sensory seizure with somatosensory features
HP:0032890.definition: A focal sensory seizure with somatosensory features in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032891.name: Focal aware motor seizure with version
HP:0032891.definition: A focal motor seizure with version characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.

HP:0032892.name: Infection-related seizure
HP:0032892.definition: Seizure associated with a presumed or proven infection (excluding infection of the central nervous system) or inflammatory state without an alternative precipitant such as metabolic derangement, and regardless of the presence or absence of a fever.

HP:0032893.name: Gastroenteritis-related afebrile seizure
HP:0032893.definition: Afebrile (less than 38.0 degrees Celcius), brief, and generalized seizures accompanying gastroenteritis without an alternative cause.

HP:0032894.name: Seizure precipitated by febrile infection
HP:0032894.definition: Any form of seizure occurring at the time of a fever (temperature at or above 38.0 degrees Celcius) without infection of the central nervous system, and without an alternative cause such as severe metabolic derangement, occurring at any age.

HP:0032895.name: Febrile seizure outside the age of 3 months to 6 years
HP:0032895.definition: Any type of seizure (most often a generalized tonic-clonic seizure) occurring with fever (at least 38.0 degrees Celsius) but in the absence of central nervous system infection, severe metabolic disturbance or other alternative precipitant in people beyond the typical arrange of 3 months-6 years with no prior history of afebrile seizure.

HP:0032896.name: Music-induced seizure
HP:0032896.definition: Seizure precipitated by listening to music or other complex sounds.

HP:0032897.name: Focal impaired awareness sensory seizure with gustatory features
HP:0032897.definition: A focal sensory seizure with gustatory features in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032898.name: Focal automatism seizure
HP:0032898.definition: A focal seizure characterized at onset by coordinated motor activity. This often resembles a voluntary movement and may consist of an inappropriate continuation of preictal motor activity.

HP:0032899.name: Focal orofacial automatism seizure
HP:0032899.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by orofacial automatisms at onset.

HP:0032900.name: Focal manual automatism seizure
HP:0032900.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by manual automatisms at onset.

HP:0032901.name: Focal pedal automatism seizure
HP:0032901.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by coordinated bilateral or unilateral movements of the feet or legs at onset. The movement is more reminiscent of normal movements in amplitude, and is less frenetic or rapid in comparison to the movements seen in focal hyperkinetic seizures involving the legs.

HP:0032902.name: Focal perseverative automatism seizure
HP:0032902.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by inappropriate continuation of pre-seizure movement or behavior at onset.

HP:0032903.name: Focal vocal automatism seizure
HP:0032903.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by the production of single or repetitive meaningless vocal sounds such as shrieks or grunts at onset.

HP:0032904.name: Focal verbal automatism seizure
HP:0032904.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by the production of single or repetitive words, phrases, or brief sentences at onset.

HP:0032905.name: Focal sexual automatism seizure
HP:0032905.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary sexual behavior at onset.

HP:0032906.name: Focal head nodding automatism seizure
HP:0032906.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary head nodding at onset.

HP:0032907.name: Focal undressing automatism seizure
HP:0032907.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary undressing at onset.

HP:0032908.name: Focal aware undressing automatism seizure
HP:0032908.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary undressing at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032909.name: Focal impaired awareness automatism seizure
HP:0032909.definition: A focal seizure with automatism in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

HP:0032910.name: Focal aware automatism seizure
HP:0032910.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032911.name: Focal aware orofacial automatism seizure
HP:0032911.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by orofacial automatisms at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032912.name: Focal aware manual automatism seizure
HP:0032912.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by manual automatisms at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032913.name: Focal aware pedal automatism seizure
HP:0032913.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by coordinated bilateral or unilateral movements of the feet or legs at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout. The movement is more reminiscent of normal movements in amplitude, and is less frenetic or rapid in comparison to the movements seen in focal hyperkinetic seizures involving the legs.

HP:0032914.name: Focal aware perseverative automatism seizure
HP:0032914.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by inappropriate continuation of pre-seizure movement or behavior at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032915.name: Focal aware vocal automatism seizure
HP:0032915.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by the production of single or repetitive meaningless vocal sounds such as shrieks or grunts at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032916.name: Focal aware verbal automatism seizure
HP:0032916.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by the production of single or repetitive words, phrases, or brief sentences at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032917.name: Focal aware sexual automatism seizure
HP:0032917.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary sexual behavior at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032918.name: Focal impaired awareness orofacial automatism seizure
HP:0032918.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by orofacial automatisms at onset.

HP:0032919.name: Focal aware head nodding automatism seizure
HP:0032919.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary head nodding at onset and during which awareness is fully retained throughout.

HP:0032920.name: Focal impaired awareness manual automatism seizure
HP:0032920.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by manual automatisms at onset.

HP:0032921.name: Focal impaired awareness pedal automatism seizure
HP:0032921.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by coordinated bilateral or unilateral movements of the feet or legs at onset. The movement is more reminiscent of normal movements in amplitude, and is less frenetic or rapid in comparison to the movements seen in focal hyperkinetic seizures involving the legs.

HP:0032922.name: Focal impaired awareness perseverative automatism seizure
HP:0032922.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by inappropriate continuation of pre-seizure movement or behavior at onset.

HP:0032923.name: Focal impaired awareness vocal automatism seizure
HP:0032923.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by the production of single or repetitive meaningless vocal sounds such as shrieks or grunts at onset.

HP:0032924.name: Focal impaired awareness verbal automatism seizure
HP:0032924.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by the production of single or repetitive words, phrases, or brief sentences at onset.

HP:0032925.name: Focal impaired awareness sexual automatism seizure
HP:0032925.definition: A type of focal automatism seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is characterized by involuntary sexual behavior at onset.

HP:0032926.name: Focal impaired awareness head nodding automatism seizure
HP:0032926.definition: A type of focal automatism in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is seizure characterized by involuntary head nodding at onset.

HP:0032927.name: Focal impaired awareness undressing automatism seizure
HP:0032927.definition: A type of focal automatism in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure and is seizure characterized by involuntary undressing at onset.

HP:0032928.name: Elevated CSF neurofilament light chain concentration
HP:0032928.definition: Neurofilament light chain (NfL) is a neuronal cytoplasmic protein highly expressed in large caliber myelinated axons. Its levels increase in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and blood proportionally to the degree of axonal damage in a variety of neurological disorders, including inflammatory, neurodegenerative, traumatic and cerebrovascular diseases.

HP:0032929.name: Abnormal chondrocyte morphology
HP:0032929.definition: Any abnormal structure of a chondrocyte, which is a polymorphic cell that forms cartilage.

HP:0032931.name: obsolete Focal impaired awareness cognitive seizure with impaired attention

HP:0032932.name: Increased circulating pancreatic triacylglycerol lipase level
HP:0032932.definition: An increased level of triacylglycerol lipase in the blood circulation (can be measured in serum or plasma).

HP:0032933.name: Airway hyperresponsiveness
HP:0032933.definition: An increased sensitivity of the airways to an inhaled constrictor agonist, a steeper slope of the dose-response curve, and a greater maximal response to the agonist.

HP:0025105.name: Nevus anemicus
HP:0025105.definition: A congenital skin lesion characterized by irregular hypopigmented macules that coalesce to form plaques and occur particularly on the chest. It is generally present at birth or develops in the first days of life. It is more common in females. Diagnosis is confirmed by applying gentle friction to the lesion and the surrounding skin and checking that the erythema produced in the healthy skin does not appear in the hypopigmented lesion. This pale macule becomes more conspicuous when the lesion and its surroundings are rubbed. The margin of the naevus is ill-defined and consists of an archipelago of small anemic spots.

HP:0025106.name: Nevus roseus
HP:0025106.definition: A variant of port-wine stain characterized by a pale red or even pink tone, in contrast to the darker hue of the port-wine stain. By analogy with the term port-wine stain, this variant rose-wine stain, or nevus roseus. Nevus roseus, however, cannot be definitely diagnosed until adulthood as port-wine stains are sometimes pink in children. While the natural history of port-wine stains includes hypertrophy, darkening, and nodularity, nevus roseus remains unchanged for life.

HP:0025107.name: Cutis marmorata telangiectatica congenita
HP:0025107.definition: A congenital vascular malformation that presents as localized or generalized erythematous-telangiectatic lesions with a reticular pattern; the lesions are almost always present at birth or develop in the first days of life. Cutis marmorata telangiectatica congenita (CMTC) appears as marble-like pattern (mottling) on the surface of the skin. In contrast to cutis marmorata, the marbling is more severe and always visible.

HP:0025108.name: Angioma serpentinum
HP:0025108.definition: Angioma serpiginosum consists of punctate, tightly packed telangiectatic lesions. Characteristic histopathological features are dilated and tortuous capillaries involving the uppermost part of the dermis.

HP:0025109.name: Reduced red cell pyruvate kinase level
HP:0025109.definition: Decrease in the level of pyruvate kinase (PK) within erythrocytes. PK catalyzes the reaction: ATP + pyruvate = ADP + phosphoenolpyruvate.

HP:0025110.name: Placoid macular lesion
HP:0025110.definition: Yellow/white, sharply delineated lesion, typically of inflammatory nature, involving the macula.

HP:0025113.name: Misophonia
HP:0025113.definition: Misophonia is characterized by strong physiological, emotional, and behavioral reactions to auditory, visual, and/or kinesthetic stimuli of different nature regardless of their physical characteristics. These misophonic responses include anger, general discomfort, disgust, anxiety, and avoidance and escape behaviors.

HP:0025114.name: Hypergranulosis
HP:0025114.definition: Hypergranulosis is an increased thickness of the stratum granulosum.

HP:0025115.name: Civatte bodies
HP:0025115.definition: Eosinophilic hyaline ovoid bodies which are often found in the subepidermal papillary regions or sometimes in the epidermis. Civatte bodies (CBs) are seen as rounded, homogenous, eosinophilic masses on routine H and E staining lying in the deeper parts of epidermis/epithelium and more frequently in dermis/connective tissue. They are known as CBs (in epithelium/epidermis), colloid bodies, or hyaline bodies (in connective tissue). They are 10-25 micrometers in diameter and situated mostly within or above the inflammatory cell infiltrate. In lichen planus, the number of necrotic keratinocytes may be so large that they are seen lying in clusters in the uppermost dermis. These bodies show a positive periodic acid Schiff reaction and are diastase resistant

HP:0025116.name: Fetal distress
HP:0025116.definition: An intrauterine state characterized by suboptimal values in the fetal heart rate, oxygenation of fetal blood, or other parameters indicative of compromise of the fetus. Signs of fetal distress include repetitive variable decelerations, fetal tachycardia or bradycardia, late decelerations, or low biophysical profile.

HP:0025117.name: Rete ridge flattening
HP:0025117.definition: Rete pegs (or ridges) are the epithelial extensions that project into the underlying connective tissue in both skin and mucous membranes. Rete ridge flattening refers to the loss of these projections so that the skin epithelium acquires a relatively flat appearance.

HP:0025118.name: Lip discoloration
HP:0025118.definition: Lightening or darkening of the lips from their usual coloring.

HP:0025119.name: Violet lip discoloration
HP:0025119.definition: An alteration of the color of the lip to take on a violet color. This term does not include cyanosis.

HP:0025122.name: Sawtooth acanthosis
HP:0025122.definition: A type of epidermal acanthosis characterized by a jagged (sawtooth) appearance of the rete ridges of the epidermis.

HP:0025123.name: White streaks/specks on enamel.
HP:0025123.definition: Areas of white discoloration visible on the surface of the teeth (enamel) in the form of streaks or specks.

HP:0025124.name: Fragile teeth
HP:0025124.definition: A tendency of teeth to fracture as manifested by a history of repeated fracture of the dental enamel without adequate trauma.

HP:0025125.name: White lesion of the oral mucosa
HP:0025125.definition: White lesions of the oral mucosa are generally caused by a condition that increases the thickness of the epithelium. This increases the distance to the vascular bed and thereby tends to change the usual reddish color of the oral mucosa to white. Common causes include hyperkeratosis (thickening of the keratin layer), acanthosis (thickening of the spinous cell layer), increased edema in the epithelium (leukoedema), and reduced vascularity of the underlying lamina propria. Additionally, fibrin caps or surface ulcerations and collapsed bullae can appear white.

HP:0025126.name: Oral hairy leukoplakia
HP:0025126.definition: A corrugated white lesion of the oral mucosa that usually occurs on the lateral or ventral surfaces of the tongue and may have a shaggy or frayed appearance.

HP:0025127.name: Actinic keratosis
HP:0025127.definition: A scaly, crusty lesion caused by damage from the ultraviolet radiation of the sun, with typical location on sun-exposed areas of the skin. Actinic keratosis lesions are often elevated, rough, and wartlike, and may be red, or occasionally tan, pink, or flesh-toned in color.

HP:0025128.name: Reduced intraabdominal adipose tissue
HP:0025128.definition: An abnormally reduced amount of adipose tissue in the abdominal cavity.

HP:0025129.name: Abnormal small intestinal mucosa morphology
HP:0025129.definition: A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the small intestine.

HP:0025130.name: Decreased small intestinal mucosa lactase level
HP:0025130.definition: Lactase is produced in the small intestine in humans, Lactase is a member of the beta-galactosidase family of enzymes, and hydrolyzes D-lactose to form D-galactose and D-glucose, which can be absorbed by the small intestine. There are many ways of assessing lactase activity. In one test, an endoscopic biopsy from the postbulbar duodenum is incubated with lactose on a test plate, and a color reaction develops within 20 min as a result of hydrolyzed lactose (a positive result) in patients with normolactasia, whereas no reaction (a negative result) develops in patients with severe hypolactasia. Other, less direct, tests include the hydrogen breath test, and blood tests following lactose challenges.

HP:0025131.name: Finger swelling
HP:0025131.definition: Enlargement of the soft tissues of one or more fingers.

HP:0025132.name: Abnormal circulating estrogen level
HP:0025132.definition: A deviation from normal concentration of the hormone estrogen in the blood circulation.

HP:0025133.name: Abnormal serum estradiol
HP:0025133.definition: A deviation from normal concentrations of estradiol in the circulation.

HP:0025134.name: Increased serum estradiol
HP:0025134.definition: An elevation above normal limits of the concentration of estradiol in the circulation.

HP:0025135.name: Abnormal serum estriol
HP:0025135.definition: A deviation from normal concentration of estriol in the circulation.

HP:0025136.name: Increased serum estriol
HP:0025136.definition: An elevation above normal limits of estriol concentration in the circulation.

HP:0025137.name: Decreased serum estriol
HP:0025137.definition: A reduction below normal limits of estriol in the circulation.

HP:0025138.name: Abnormal serum estrone
HP:0025138.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of circulating estrone.

HP:0025139.name: Increased serum estrone
HP:0025139.definition: An elevation above normal limits of the concentration of estrone in the circulation.

HP:0025140.name: Decreased serum estrone
HP:0025140.definition: A reduction below normal limits of the concentration of estrone in the circulation.

HP:0025141.name: Gingival calcification
HP:0025141.definition: Ectopic deposition of calcium salts found in the gingiva.

HP:0025142.name: Constitutional symptom
HP:0025142.definition: A symptom or manifestation indicating a systemic or general effect of a disease and that may affect the general well-being or status of an individual.

HP:0025143.name: Chills
HP:0025143.definition: A sudden sensation of feeling cold.

HP:0025144.name: Shivering
HP:0025144.definition: Involuntary contraction or twitching of the muscles.

HP:0025145.name: Rigors
HP:0025145.definition: Severe chills with violent shivering. A rigor is an episode of shaking or exaggerated shivering which can occur with a high fever.

HP:0025146.name: Foveal degeneration
HP:0025146.definition: Deterioration of the tissue of the fovea, i.e.,the region of sharpest vision within the macula of the retina.

HP:0025147.name: Beaten bronze macular sheen
HP:0025147.definition: A shiny appearance of the macula, which is often called a beaten bronze appearance.

HP:0025148.name: Dark choroid
HP:0025148.definition: A fluorescein angiographic finding of absence of the normal background fluorescence (a dark choroid).

HP:0025149.name: Atrophic muscularis propria
HP:0025149.definition: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of muscularois propria tissue that was once present. The atrophy may involve a marked vacuolar degeneration of myocytes, loss of muscle fibers and some cases a highly characteristic honeycomb fibrosis.

HP:0025151.name: Ganglioneuromatosis
HP:0025151.definition: Hyperplastic submucosal and myenteric plexus containing an increased number of ganglion cells, glial cells and nerve fibers.

HP:0025152.name: Poor visual behavior for age
HP:0025152.definition: Lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities suggesting a lack of visual responsiveness or decrease in visual capabilities in an infant or young child in which visual behavior fails to meet normal developmental milestones.

HP:0025153.name: Transient
HP:0025153.definition: Short-lived and not permanent. This term applies to a phenotypic abnormality that is temporary and of short duration.

HP:0025154.name: Portosystemic collateral veins
HP:0025154.definition: Presence of biliary veins that serve as a collateral channel to the systemic circulation

HP:0025155.name: Abnormal hepatobiliary system physiology
HP:0025155.definition: A functional anomaly of the hepatobiliary system

HP:0025156.name: Dependency on intravenous nutrition
HP:0025156.definition: Inability to be weaned from intravenous (parenteral) nutrition, as judged by the hydration status (urine output, blood urea nitrogen, creatinine, urine sodium concentration), ability to maintain weight, stool output, and serum electrolyte status.

HP:0025157.name: Increased urinary sedoheptulose
HP:0025157.definition: An increased concentration of sedoheptulose in the urine. Sedoheptulose is a monosaccharide with seven carbon atoms and a ketone functional group.

HP:0025158.name: Hyperautofluorescent retinal lesion
HP:0025158.definition: Increased amount of autofluorescence in the retina as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

HP:0025159.name: Hypoautofluorescent retinal lesion
HP:0025159.definition: Decreased amount of autofluorescence in the retina as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

HP:0025160.name: Abnormal temper tantrums
HP:0025160.definition: Temper tantrums are brief episodes of extreme, unpleasant, and sometimes aggressive behaviors in response to frustration or anger, which are a normal part of development in toddlers. Temper tantrums that occur more frequently in a given time and/or are more severe in symptomatology and/or longer in duration and/or inappropriate for the given age compared to a temper tantrum that naturally occurs as a part of the developmental process are classified as abnormal temper tantrums.

HP:0025161.name: Frequent temper tantrums
HP:0025161.definition: Temper tantrums that occur more frequently compared to the temper tantrums that are a part of the normal developmental process.

HP:0025162.name: Severe temper tantrums
HP:0025162.definition: Temper tantrums, which occur with more severe symptomatology compared to a temper tantrum that occurs as a part of normal developmental process.

HP:0025163.name: Abnormal optic chiasm morphology
HP:0025163.definition: A structural abnormality of the optic chiasm.The optic chiasm, located below the hypothalamus, is a partial crossing of the optic nerves.

HP:0025164.name: Increased number of elastic fibers in the dermis
HP:0025164.definition: An elevated number of elastic fibers, that is of bundles of proteins and glycoproteins in the extracellular matrix in the reticular dermis. Elastic fibers can stretch and recoil back to their original length. This feature can be appreciated on histology with hematoxylin and eosin or other staining methods.

HP:0025165.name: Clumping of elastic fibers in the dermis
HP:0025165.definition: Formation of clumps or aggregates that make up small protuberances from elastic fibers within the dermis (especially the reticular dermis).

HP:0025166.name: Thickened elastic fibers in the dermis
HP:0025166.definition: An increase of the diameter of elastic fibers in the dermis.

HP:0025167.name: Fragmented elastic fibers in the dermis
HP:0025167.definition: Elastic fibers in the dermis exhibit an increased number of breaks associated with disorganization of the structure of the elastic fibers.

HP:0025168.name: Left ventricular diastolic dysfunction
HP:0025168.definition: Abnormal function of the left ventricule during left ventricular relaxation and filling.

HP:0025169.name: Left ventricular systolic dysfunction
HP:0025169.definition: Abnormality of left ventricular contraction, often defined operationally as an ejection fraction of less than 40 percent.

HP:0025170.name: Neuronal/glioneuronal neoplasm of the central nervous system
HP:0025170.definition: A central nervous system neoplasm with neuronal and, less consistently, glial differentiation.

HP:0025171.name: Rosette-forming glioneuronal tumor
HP:0025171.definition: A tumor of the central nervous system that has components of both neurocytic and glial areas, whereby usually the glial component of the tumor predominates. Rossette-forming glioneuronal tumors (RGNT) have biphasic cytoarchitecture with two elements; neurocytic rosettes resembling Homer-Wright rosettes, and astrocytic component resembling a pilocytic astrocytoma. RGNTs are low-grade tumors that lack histopathological signs of malignancy.

HP:0025172.name: Smooth septal thickening on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025172.definition: Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with a smooth appearance of the interlobular septa.

HP:0025173.name: Nodular septal thickening on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025173.definition: Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with a nodular or beaded appearance of the interlobular septa.

HP:0025174.name: Irregular septal thickening on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025174.definition: Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with an irregular appearance of the interlobular septa. THis feature is often associated with distortion of lung architecture.

HP:0025175.name: Honeycomb lung
HP:0025175.definition: Honeycombing represents destroyed and fibrotic lung tissue containing numerous cystic airspaces with thick fibrous walls, representing the late stage of various lung diseases, with complete loss of acinar architecture. The cysts range in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters in diameter, have variable wall thickness, and are lined by metaplastic bronchiolar epithelium. On chest radiographs, honeycombing appears as closely approximated ring shadows, typically 3-10 mm in diameter with walls 1-3 mm in thickness, that resemble a honeycomb; the finding implies end-stage lung disease. On CT scans, the appearance is of clustered cystic air spaces, typically of comparable diameters on the order of 3-10 mm but occasionally as large as 2.5 cm. Honeycombing is usually subpleural and is characterized by well-defined walls. It is a CT feature of established pulmonary fibrosis. Because honeycombing is often considered specific for pulmonary fibrosis and is an important criterion in the diagnosis of usual interstitial pneumonia, the term should be used with care, as it may directly impact patient care.

HP:0025176.name: Intralobular interstitial thickening
HP:0025176.definition: A fine reticular pattern on high-resolution computed tomography, with the visible lines separated by a few millimeters. Regions of the lung with intralobular interstitial thickening characteristically show a fine lacelike or netlike appearance.

HP:0025177.name: Peribronchovascular interstitial thickening
HP:0025177.definition: Thickening of the peribronchovascular interstitium, a connective tissue sheath that surrounds the central bronchi and pulmonary arteries. The peribronchovascular interstitium extends from the level of the pulmonary hila into the peripheral lung. This feature may be ascertained on high-resolution computer tomography.

HP:0025178.name: Subpleural interstitial thickening
HP:0025178.definition: Increase in thickness of the subpleural interstitium.

HP:0025179.name: Ground-glass opacification
HP:0025179.definition: On chest radiographs, ground-glass opacity appears as an area of hazy increased lung opacity, usually extensive, within which margins of pulmonary vessels may be indistinct. On CT scans, it appears as hazy increased opacity of lung, with preservation of bronchial and vascular margins. It is caused by partial filling of airspaces, interstitial thickening (due to fluid, cells, and/or fibrosis), partial collapse of alveoli, increased capillary blood volume, or a combination of these, the common factor being the partial displacement of air. Ground-glass opacity is less opaque than consolidation, in which bronchovascular margins are obscured.

HP:0025180.name: Centrilobular ground-glass opacification on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025180.definition: A hazy area of increased attenuation in centrilobular areas of the lung with preserved bronchial and vascular markings seen on a computer tomography scan. Centrilobular refers to a location that is central within secondary pulmonary lobules.

HP:0025181.name: Abdominal aseptic abscess
HP:0025181.definition: An abscess-like lesion located within the abdomen. The lesions are localized in the spleen, liver, abdominal lymph nodes. The lesions represent visceral sterile collections of mature neutrophils that do not respond to antibiotics but regress quickly when treated with corticosteroids, but relapses occur frequently.

HP:0025182.name: Localized area of pendulous skin
HP:0025182.definition: A confined region of lax skin that hangs below the level of the surrounding skin. Histopatholigically, there is a loss of elastic fibers in the dermis of the affected region.

HP:0025186.name: Marcus Gunn jaw winking synkinesis
HP:0025186.definition: Unilateral ptosis with associated upper eyelid contraction and contraction of either the external or the internal pterygoid muscle. It is thought to occur because of congenital miswiring of a branch of the fifth cranial nerve into the branch of the third cranial nerve supplying the levator muscle. In Marcus Gunn jaw winking synkinesis, elevation and even retraction of the affected eyelid is triggered by chewing, suction, lateral mandible movement, smiling, sternocleidomastoid contraction, protruding tongue, Valsalva maneuver and even by breathing.

HP:0025188.name: Retinal vasculitis
HP:0025188.definition: Inflammation of retinal blood vessels as manifested by perivascular sheathing or cuffing, vascular leakage and/or occlusion.

HP:0025190.name: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with generalized onset
HP:0025190.definition: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure with generalized onset is a type of bilateral tonic-clonic seizure characterized by generalized onset; these seizures rapidly engage networks in both hemispheres at the start of the seizure.

HP:0025192.name: Subtentorial periventricular white matter hyperdensity
HP:0025192.definition: Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the fourth cerebral ventricle (which is located beneath the tentorium of the cerebellum).

HP:0025193.name: Posterolateral diaphragmatic hernia
HP:0025193.definition: A posterolateral defect in the diaphragm, commonly referred to as a Bochdalek hernia, which is often accompanied by herniation of the stomach, intestines, liver, and/or spleen into the chest cavity.

HP:0025194.name: Morgagni diaphragmatic hernia
HP:0025194.definition: An anterior retrosternal or parasternal hernia that can result in the herniation of liver or intestines into the chest cavity.

HP:0025195.name: Central diaphragmatic hernia
HP:0025195.definition: A congenital diaphragm defect involving the central tendinous (e.g., amuscular) portion of the diaphragm, whereby the entire rim of diaphragmatic musculature is present.

HP:0025196.name: Increased total iron binding capacity
HP:0025196.definition: An elevation in the total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added. A high TIBC corresponds to a high transferrin concentration. The latent (or free) iron binding capacity is the difference between the TIBC and the measured serum iron, corresponding to the transferrin not bound to iron, i.e., free iron binding capacity.

HP:0025197.name: Inclusion body fibromatosis
HP:0025197.definition: A benign tumor made up of mostly myofibroblasts that appears almost exclusively on the digits of the hands and feet, rarely involving the thumb or big toe. The lesion displays a proliferation of bland intradermal spindle cells arranged in whorls, fascicles, or a storiform pattern in a collagenous background of varying degrees. Also usually present are perpendicular tumor cell fascicles that extend to the epidermis. The small intracytoplasmic inclusions are said to appear similar to red blood cells. The inclusion bodies have been shown to be made up of densely packed vimentin and actin filaments. The tumor often causes a dome-shaped elevation of the overlying structures, forming a protuberant or polypoid nodule. The overlying epidermis can display a host of changes, including acanthosis, hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, rete ridge flattening, entrapment of adnexal structures, and, rarely, ulceration.

HP:0025198.name: Inflammatory cap polyp
HP:0025198.definition: A non-malignant sessile or pedunculated polyp in the colon and rectum that displays a cap of inflammatory granulation tissue with fibrinopurulent exudate that covers the polyp.

HP:0025200.name: Muscle fiber actin filament accumulation
HP:0025200.definition: Accumulation in muscle cells of filaments composed of actin.

HP:0025201.name: Abnormal circulating apolipoprotein concentration
HP:0025201.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration in blood of an apolipoprotein, i.e., of a protein that binds lipids to form lipoprotein and is thereby responsible for the transport of lipids in the blood and lymph circulation.

HP:0025202.name: Elevated circulating apolipoprotein A-IV concentration
HP:0025202.definition: An increased concentration in blood of apolipoprotein A-IV, a major component of HDL and chylomicrons that has a role in VLDL secretion and catabolism and is required for efficient activation of lipoprotein lipase by ApoC-II.

HP:0025203.name: Caput medusae
HP:0025203.definition: Distended and engorged umbilical veins which are seen radiating from the umbilicus across the abdomen to join systemic veins.

HP:0025204.name: Triggered by
HP:0025204.definition: A trigger is defined as an external factor that leads to the manifestation of a sign or symptom in a person with a susceptibility to developing that manifestation.

HP:0025205.name: Triggered by breast feeding
HP:0025205.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by breast feeding in an infant.

HP:0025206.name: Triggered by cold
HP:0025206.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to cold surroundings.

HP:0025207.name: Triggered by dehydration
HP:0025207.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by being dehydrated, i.e., by a deficit in total body water.

HP:0025208.name: Triggered by carbohydrate ingestion
HP:0025208.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking carbohydrates.

HP:0025209.name: Triggered by fructose ingestion
HP:0025209.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking fructose.

HP:0025210.name: Triggered by glucose ingestion
HP:0025210.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking glucose.

HP:0025211.name: Triggered by ethanol ingestion
HP:0025211.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by drinking or otherwise ingesting ethanol.

HP:0025212.name: Triggered by fasting
HP:0025212.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by abstaining from eating food (fasting).

HP:0025213.name: Triggered by galactose ingestion
HP:0025213.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking galactose. Galactose usually is ingested as lactose, which is composed of equimolar amounts of glucose and galactose.

HP:0025214.name: Triggered by heat
HP:0025214.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to heat.

HP:0025215.name: Triggered by febrile illness
HP:0025215.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by febrile illness.

HP:0025216.name: Triggered by heavy meal
HP:0025216.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating large quantities of food, for instance, by a heavy meal.

HP:0025217.name: Triggered by high-fat diet
HP:0025217.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating a diet high in lipids.

HP:0025218.name: Triggered by hyperventilation
HP:0025218.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by excessively rapid and deep breathing.

HP:0025219.name: Triggered by vaccination
HP:0025219.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a vaccination.

HP:0025220.name: Triggered by menstruation
HP:0025220.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by menstruation in a female.

HP:0025221.name: Triggered by pregnancy
HP:0025221.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by pregnancy in a female.

HP:0025222.name: Triggered by sleep deprivation
HP:0025222.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a lack of sufficient sleep.

HP:0025223.name: Triggered by smoking
HP:0025223.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by smoking.

HP:0025224.name: Triggered by sodium ingestion
HP:0025224.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking sodium.

HP:0025225.name: Triggered by sound
HP:0025225.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to sound or noise.

HP:0025226.name: Triggered by stress
HP:0025226.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a physical, mental, or emotional factor associated with bodily or mental tension.

HP:0025227.name: Triggered by excitement
HP:0025227.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a a state of excitement or by being startled.

HP:0025228.name: Triggered by sudden movement
HP:0025228.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a sudden movement.

HP:0025229.name: Triggered by vestibular stimulation
HP:0025229.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by vestibular stimulation, including head turning, cold calorics, postural changes, or rotating chair.

HP:0025231.name: Abnormal synovial bursa morphology
HP:0025231.definition: A structural anomaly of a synovial bursa, which is a synovium-lined, sac-like structure found throughout the body near bony prominences and between bones, muscles, tendons, and ligaments. The bursa itself is a synovial lining that represents a potential space insofar as it is collapsed upon itself until a resulting trigger causes the bursa to become irritated and fill with synovial fluid.

HP:0025233.name: Sleep paralysis
HP:0025233.definition: An inability to move the body at the onset of sleep or upon awakening from sleep, lasting for seconds to a few minutes.

HP:0025234.name: Parasomnia
HP:0025234.definition: An undesirable physical event or experience that occurs during the process of falling asleep, while asleep, or when waking up from sleep.

HP:0025235.name: NREM parasomnia
HP:0025235.definition: A parasomnia that occurs during non-rapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:0025236.name: Somnambulism
HP:0025236.definition: Ambulation or other complex motor behaviors may occur after getting out of bed in a sleep-like state. During sleepwalking episodes, the individual who is somnambulating appears confused or dazed, with their eyes usually open. They may mumble or give inappropriate answers to questions, and occasionally appear agitated.

HP:0025237.name: Confusional arousal
HP:0025237.definition: A nocturnal episode is characterized by disorientation, grogginess, and, at times, significant agitation upon awakening from slow-wave sleep or following forced awakenings.

HP:0025238.name: Foot pain
HP:0025238.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the foot.

HP:0025239.name: Subhyaloid hemorrhage
HP:0025239.definition: A localized detachment of the vitreous from the retina due to the accumulation of blood. When localized in the macular area, it results in sudden profound loss of vision. Subhyaloid premacular hemorrhage is typically characterized by a circumscribed, round or dumb-bell shaped, bright red mound of blood beneath the internal limiting membrane (ILM) or between the ILM and hyaloid face, in or near to the central macular area.

HP:0025240.name: Preretinal hemorrhage
HP:0025240.definition: An accumulation of blood between the neurosensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) arising from the choroidal or retinal circulation.

HP:0025241.name: Flame-shaped retinal hemorrhage
HP:0025241.definition: A type of retinal hemorrhage that is located within the nerve fiber layer (NFL) of the retina and that exhibits a characteristic flame shape which results from constraints by the structure of the NFL (axons of the ganglion cells).

HP:0025242.name: Dot-and-blot retinal hemorrhage
HP:0025242.definition: Accumulation of blood located in the retina's inner nuclear and outer plexiform layers, and having a dot-like or blot-like shape. THe shape results from intraretinal compression, restricting the hemorrhages within a specific location.

HP:0025243.name: Subretinal hemorrhage
HP:0025243.definition: Accumulation of blood located beneath the neurosensory retina in the space between the neurosensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0025244.name: Subretinal pigment epithelium hemorrhage
HP:0025244.definition: An accumulation of blood located between the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) and Bruch's membrane.

HP:0025245.name: Cutaneous cyst
HP:0025245.definition: A hollow mass located in the skin that is surrounded by an epithelium-lined wall and is well demarcated from the adjacent tissue. Cysts are often said to be sac-like and may contain serous liquid or semisolid material.

HP:0025246.name: Trichilemmal cyst
HP:0025246.definition: Nontender, round and firm, but slightly compressible, intradermal or subcutaneous cyst measuring 0.5-5 cm in diameter. Trichilemmal cysts are acquired rather than congenital, and tend to appear on the scalp rather than the face, and to be intradermal rather than subcutaneous.

HP:0025247.name: Dermoid cyst
HP:0025247.definition: A congenital subcutaneous cyst that arises from entrapment of skin along the lines of embryonic fusion. In contrast to epidermal cysts, dermoid cysts tend to contain various adnexal structures such as hair, sebaceous, eccrine or apocrine glands. Dermoid cysts are present at birth, and are indolent, firm, deep, subcutaneous nodules. They are often located on the head and neck, and rarely in the anogenital area. Dermoid cysts are slowly progressive and can grow to a size of 1 to 4 cm.

HP:0025248.name: Eruptive vellus hair cyst
HP:0025248.definition: A cutaneous cyst that is small (one or two millimeters in diameter) and painless, presenting as a follicular papule that usually is skin colored but may have a reddish or brownish tinge.

HP:0025249.name: Comedo
HP:0025249.definition: A clogged cutaneous sebaceous follicle, which is a cutaneous gland that secretes sebum (usually into a hair follicle).

HP:0025250.name: Closed comedo
HP:0025250.definition: A comedo in which the top of the pore is not stretched open and thus does not expose the clogged portion (which would appear black), hence the name whitehead.

HP:0025251.name: Open comedo
HP:0025251.definition: A comedo in which the part of the pore at the surface of the skin is stretched and open, exposing the contents of the comedo, which appear black.

HP:0025252.name: Geographic tongue
HP:0025252.definition: An anomaly of the tongue characterized by loss (atrophy) of filiform papillae of the tongue, leaving areas of erythema (redness), surrounded by a serpiginous, white, hyperkeratotic border. The name geographic tongue refers to an appearance that is said to be similar to a map.

HP:0025253.name: Claustrophobia
HP:0025253.definition: An abnormal fear of being in a closed or narrow space with no escape is called claustrophobia.

HP:0025254.name: Ameliorated by
HP:0025254.definition: An ameliorating factor is defined as an external factor that leads to a sign or symptom that is already present improving or becoming more bearable

HP:0025255.name: Ameliorated by pregnancy
HP:0025255.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by pregnancy in a female.

HP:0025256.name: Ameliorated by heat
HP:0025256.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by heat (including fever).

HP:0025257.name: Ameliorated by carbohydrate ingestion
HP:0025257.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by eating or drinking carbohydrates including glucose (sugar).

HP:0025258.name: Stiff neck
HP:0025258.definition: A sensation of tightness in the neck when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity. Neck stiffness often involves soreness and difficulty moving the neck, especially when trying to turn the head to the side.

HP:0025259.name: Stiff elbow
HP:0025259.definition: A sensation of tightness in the elbow joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025260.name: Stiff wrist
HP:0025260.definition: A sensation of tightness in the wrist joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025261.name: Stiff finger
HP:0025261.definition: A sensation of tightness in a finger joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025262.name: Stiff hip
HP:0025262.definition: A sensation of tightness in the hip joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025263.name: Stiff knee
HP:0025263.definition: A sensation of tightness in the knee joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025264.name: Stiff ankle
HP:0025264.definition: A sensation of tightness in the ankle joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025265.name: Stiff toe
HP:0025265.definition: A sensation of tightness in a toe joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.

HP:0025267.name: Snoring
HP:0025267.definition: Deep, noisy breathing during sleep, accompanied by hoarse or harsh sounds, is caused by the vibration of respiratory structures, especially the soft palate. This vibration results in sound due to obstructed air movement during breathing while sleeping.

HP:0025268.name: Stuttering
HP:0025268.definition: Disruptions in the production of speech sounds, with involuntary repetitions of words or parts of words, prolongations of speech sounds, or complete blockage of speech production for several seconds.

HP:0025269.name: Panic attack
HP:0025269.definition: A sudden episode of intense fear in a situation where there is no danger or apparent cause.

HP:0025270.name: Abnormal esophagus physiology
HP:0025270.definition: Any physiological abnormality of the esophagus.

HP:0025271.name: Esophageal spasms
HP:0025271.definition: Involuntary contractions of the esophagus that are irregular, uncoordinated, and painful.

HP:0025274.name: Ovarian dermoid cyst
HP:0025274.definition: An cystic ovarian teratoma composed of dermal and epidermal elements and containing tissue components including hair, teeth, bone, thyroid, and others.

HP:0025275.name: Lateral
HP:0025275.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is located farther from the median plane or midline of the body or of the referenced structure.

HP:0025276.name: Abnormality of skin adnexa physiology
HP:0025276.definition: Any functional anomaly of the skin adnexa (skin appendages), which are specialized skin structures located within the dermis and focally within the subcutaneous fatty tissue, comprising three histologically distinct structures: (1) the pilosebaceous unit (hair follicle and sebaceous glands); (2) the eccrine sweat glands; and (3) the apocrine glands.

HP:0025277.name: Gustatory sweating
HP:0025277.definition: Hyperhidrosis that occurs with gustatory stimulation (e.g., moisture on face from sweating that occurs after eating).

HP:0025278.name: Cold-induced sweating
HP:0025278.definition: Sweating provoked by cold temperature rather than by heat.

HP:0025280.name: Pain characteristic
HP:0025280.definition: A pain characteristic is defined as a subjective category or type of pain.

HP:0025281.name: Sharp
HP:0025281.definition: Applied to pain that is described as sharp, i.e., sudden and severe.

HP:0025282.name: Dull
HP:0025282.definition: Applied to pain that is dull, i.e., not severe but that continues over a long period of time.

HP:0025283.name: Tender
HP:0025283.definition: Applied to pain that is tender, i.e., elicited by touching the affected body part.

HP:0025284.name: Sleep-interrupting
HP:0025284.definition: Applied to pain that wakes the affecting individual from sleep.

HP:0025285.name: Aggravated by
HP:0025285.definition: An aggravating factor is defined as an external factor that leads to a sign or symptom that is already present getting worse or becoming more severe.

HP:0025286.name: Aggravated by activity
HP:0025286.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is aggravated by activity, exertion, or exercise.

HP:0025287.name: Axial
HP:0025287.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the central part of the body, in the head and trunk as distinguished from the limbs.

HP:0025289.name: Cervical lymphadenopathy
HP:0025289.definition: Enlarged lymph nodes in the neck.

HP:0025290.name: Upper-body predominance
HP:0025290.definition: Applies to an abnormality that affects the arms, trunk, head more than the legs.

HP:0025291.name: Lower-body predominance
HP:0025291.definition: Applies to an abnormality that affects the legs more than the arms, trunk, head.

HP:0025292.name: Acral
HP:0025292.definition: Applies to an abnormality that affects the distal portions of limbs (hand, foot) and head (ears, nose).

HP:0025293.name: Distributed along Blaschko lines
HP:0025293.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose localization corresponds to the lines of Blaschko, which correspond to the lineage of epithelia cells. Blaschko lines are normally invisible but may become apparent with certain skin diseases and then can be seen to be distributed in lines horizontal to the body.

HP:0025294.name: Dermatomal
HP:0025294.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose localization corresponds to the dermatomes, i.e., the nerve root distribution.

HP:0025295.name: Herpetiform
HP:0025295.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles that of the grouped umbilicated vesicles seen in herpes simplex and herpes zoster infections.

HP:0025296.name: Morbilliform
HP:0025296.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles that of measles, i.e., maculopapular lesions that are red and roughly 2 to 10 mm in diameter and may be partially confluent.

HP:0025297.name: Prolonged
HP:0025297.definition: Applied to an abnormality whose duration is extended over a longer period of time than is expected or usual (e.g., prolonged fever lasts longer than one usually sees with an infection).

HP:0025300.name: Malar rash
HP:0025300.definition: An erythematous (red), flat facial rash that affects the skin in the malar area (over the cheekbones) and extends over the bridge of the nose.

HP:0025301.name: Nocturnal
HP:0025301.definition: Applies to an abnormality that occurs in or is exacerbated during the night.

HP:0025302.name: Diurnal
HP:0025302.definition: Applies to a sign, symptom, or other abnormality that occurs in or is exacerbated in the day time.

HP:0025303.name: Episodic
HP:0025303.definition: Applied to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that occurs multiple times at usually irregular intervals. The occurrences are separated by an interval in which the sign, symptom, or manifestation is not present.

HP:0025304.name: Periodic
HP:0025304.definition: Applies to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that recurs with a fixed time interval, i.e., the symptom-free periods are always of the same length.

HP:0025305.name: Quotidian
HP:0025305.definition: Applies to a sign, symptom, or other manifestation that is episodic with a fixed time interval of one day (24 hours).

HP:0025306.name: Acute emergence over minutes
HP:0025306.definition: Acute appearance of disease manifestations in a period of minutes.

HP:0025307.name: Acute emergence over hours
HP:0025307.definition: Acute appearance of disease manifestations in a period of hours.

HP:0025308.name: Acute emergence over days
HP:0025308.definition: Acute appearance of disease manifestations in a period of days.

HP:0025309.name: Abnormal pupil shape
HP:0025309.definition: A deviation from the normal circular shape of the pupil

HP:0025310.name: Oval pupil
HP:0025310.definition: An abnormal pupil shape that is elliptical, i.e., egg-like.

HP:0025311.name: Anterior chamber cyst
HP:0025311.definition: A closed sac, having a distinct membrane and division compared to the nearby tissue located within the anterior chamber. The sac that may contain air, fluids, or semi-solid material.

HP:0025312.name: Esophoria
HP:0025312.definition: A form of strabismus with both eyes turned inward to a relatively mild degree, usually defined as less than 10 prism diopters.

HP:0025313.name: Exophoria
HP:0025313.definition: A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward to a milder degree than with exotropia.

HP:0025314.name: Choroidal nevus
HP:0025314.definition: A benign, flat or slightly elevated melanocytic lesions of the posterior uveawith clearly defined margins. Choroidal nevi tend they remain stable in size, and to display features such as overlying drusen as well as retinal pigment epithelial atrophy, hyperplasia or fibrous metaplasia.

HP:0025315.name: Exacerbated by head trauma
HP:0025315.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is worsened, aggravated, or exacerbated by head trauma.

HP:0025317.name: Cubitus varus
HP:0025317.definition: A deformity of the elbow in which there is a deviation of the forearm toward the midline of the body.

HP:0025318.name: Ovarian carcinoma
HP:0025318.definition: A malignant neoplasm originating from the surface ovarian epithelium.

HP:0025320.name: Leakage of dye on fundus fluorescein angiography
HP:0025320.definition: Leakage of fluorescein dye observed upon retinal fluorescein angiography. Areas of leakage can be appreciated as showing gradual enlargement with blurring of margins.

HP:0025321.name: Copper accumulation in liver
HP:0025321.definition: An anomalous build up of copper (Cu) in the liver.

HP:0025322.name: Venous occlusion
HP:0025322.definition: Blockage of venous return (flow of blood from the periphery back towards the right atrium) in a vein.

HP:0025324.name: Arterial occlusion
HP:0025324.definition: Blockage of blood flow through an artery.

HP:0025325.name: Sparse medial eyebrow
HP:0025325.definition: Decreased density/number and/or decreased diameter of medial eyebrow hairs.

HP:0025326.name: Retinal arterial occlusion
HP:0025326.definition: Blockage of the retinal artery, generally associated with interruption of blood flow and oxygen delivery to the retina.

HP:0025327.name: Decreased renal parenchymal thickness
HP:0025327.definition: Reduced dimension of the solid part of the kidney (parenchyma, the renal cortex and medulla) as measured from the collecting system (renal calyces and pelvis) to the border of the kidney. This measurement can be performed by measuring the thickness of the parenchyma in computed tomography scans.

HP:0025328.name: Antepartum hemorrhage
HP:0025328.definition: Significant maternal hemorrhage/bleed in the second half of pregnancy and prior to the birth of the baby.

HP:0025329.name: Anti-glutamic acid decarboxylase antibody positivity
HP:0025329.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against glutamic acid decarboxylase.

HP:0025330.name: Downgaze palsy
HP:0025330.definition: A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze below the horizontal meridian.

HP:0025331.name: Upgaze palsy
HP:0025331.definition: A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze above the horizontal meridian.

HP:0025332.name: Abnormality of foot cortical bone
HP:0025332.definition: An anomaly of the outer shell (cortex) of a foot bone.

HP:0025333.name: Cortical thinning of foot bones
HP:0025333.definition: A reduction in the thickness of the outer shell (cortex) of foot bones.

HP:0025334.name: Triggered by emotion
HP:0025334.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by a strong spontaneously arising mental state, reaction or feeling (emotion).

HP:0025335.name: Delayed ability to stand
HP:0025335.definition: A failure to achieve the ability to stand up at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children begin to walk alone at 11 to 15 months of age. On average, children can stand while holding on at the age of 9 to 10 months, can pull up to stand and walk with one hand being held at 12 months, and can stand alone and walk well at 18 months.

HP:0025336.name: Delayed ability to sit
HP:0025336.definition: A failure to achieve the ability to sit at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children sit with support at 6 months of age and sit steadily without support at 9 months of age.

HP:0025337.name: Red eye
HP:0025337.definition: A reddish appearance over the white part (sclera) of the eye ranging from a few enlarged blood vessels appearing as wiggly lines over the sclera to a bright red color completely covering to sclera.

HP:0025338.name: Circumlimbal hyperemia
HP:0025338.definition: A ring of redness at the limbus of the eye, the border between the cornea and the sclera.

HP:0025339.name: Superficial episcleral hyperemia
HP:0025339.definition: Prominence of blood vessels of the superficial episcleral tissues.

HP:0025340.name: Deep episcleral hyperemia
HP:0025340.definition: Prominence of blood vessels of the deep episcleral tissues.

HP:0025341.name: Corneal keratic precipitates
HP:0025341.definition: An inflammatory cellular deposit deposited on the corneal endothelium and visible as spots on the cornea.

HP:0025342.name: Central retinal artery occlusion
HP:0025342.definition: Blockage of the main artery in the retina. The typical presentation is one of profound monocular visual loss.

HP:0025343.name: Lupus anticoagulant
HP:0025343.definition: Presence of lupus anticoagulant (LA) autoantibodies. LA represent a heterogeneous group of autoantibodies, IgG, IgM, or a mixture of both classes, that interfere with standard phospholipid-based coagulant tests (this is only an in vitro phenomenon, LA do not cause reduction of coagulation in vivo). The antibodies are directed against plasma proteins which also bind to phospholipid surfaces.

HP:0025344.name: Interlobular bile duct destruction
HP:0025344.definition: Damage to and obliteration of intrahepatic bile ducts (bile ducts that transport bile between the Canals of Hering and the interlobar bile ducts).

HP:0025345.name: Abnormality of circulating beta-2-microglobulin level
HP:0025345.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

HP:0025346.name: Increased circulating beta-2-microglobulin level
HP:0025346.definition: Elevated concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

HP:0025347.name: Decreased circulating beta-2-microglobulin level
HP:0025347.definition: Reduced concentration of beta-2-microglobulin in the blood.

HP:0025348.name: Abnormal corneal limbus morphology
HP:0025348.definition: An anomaly of the margin of the cornea overlapped by the sclera.

HP:0025349.name: Limbal edema
HP:0025349.definition: Swelling of the margin of the cornea overlapped by the sclera.

HP:0025350.name: Giant conjunctival papillae
HP:0025350.definition: Conjunctival papillae with a diameter greater than 1 millimeter. They characteristically have flattened tops which sometimes demonstrate staining with fluorescein.

HP:0025351.name: Recurrent interdigital mycosis
HP:0025351.definition: A history of repeated fungal infections located between the fingers or toes, usually manifested by scaling, maceration, and itching. The toes are more commonly affected than the fingers.

HP:0025352.name: Typically de novo
HP:0025352.definition: Description of conditions that are exclusively or predominantly observed to display de novo variants. In some cases, this may be due to the limited reproductive fitness of affected individuals.

HP:0025353.name: Anti-multiple nuclear dots antibody positivity
HP:0025353.definition: A type of antinuclear antibody (ANA) positivity revealed by indirect immunofluorescence (IFL). The multiple nuclear dots (MND) pattern is immunomorphologically characterized by the staining of 3-20 dots of variable size distributed all over the cell nucleus, but sparing the nucleoli, and, in contrast to the anticentromere pattern, MND reactivity does not stain the chromosomes in mitotic cells.

HP:0025354.name: Abnormal cellular phenotype
HP:0025354.definition: An anomaly of cellular morphology or physiology.

HP:0025355.name: Retinal arterial macroaneurysms
HP:0025355.definition: Acquired focal dilatations of branches of the retinal artery, usually second-order retinal arterioles, that range in size from 100 to 200 micrometers in diameter. Macroaneurysms are generally located at the temporal retina and may be hemorrhagic or exudative.

HP:0025357.name: Erratic myoclonus
HP:0025357.definition: A type of myoclonus in which the myoclonias shift from body region to another in a random and asynchronous fashion. Erratic myoclonus can affect the face or limbs, are brief, single or repetitive, very frequent and nearly continuous.

HP:0025358.name: Uveal ectropion
HP:0025358.definition: Presence of iris pigment epithelium on the anterior surface of the iris.

HP:0025359.name: Polygonal renal calices
HP:0025359.definition: An abnormal polygonal shape of the calices of the kidney (which normally have a rounded or cup-shaped appearance).

HP:0025360.name: Polycalycosis
HP:0025360.definition: Increased number of calices of the kidney.

HP:0025361.name: Abnormal medullary pyramid morphology
HP:0025361.definition: A structural anomaly of the pyramid of the adult kidney, cone-shaped structures with a broad base adjacent to the renal cortex and the narrow apex that is termed papilla.

HP:0025362.name: Renal medullary pyramid hypoplasia
HP:0025362.definition: Undergrowth of the pyramid of the adult kidney, cone-shaped structures with a broad base adjacent to the renal cortex and the narrow apex that is termed papilla.

HP:0025363.name: Glomerular endocapillary hypercellularity
HP:0025363.definition: Hypercellularity due to increased number of cells within glomerular capillary lumina, causing narrowing of the lumina.

HP:0025364.name: Glomerular extracapillary hypercellularity
HP:0025364.definition: Hypercellularity (increased number of cells) in the renal glomerulus but external to the glomerular capillaries, i.e., in the Bowman space or more than one layer of parietal or visceral epithelial cells.

HP:0025367.name: Trichoepithelioma
HP:0025367.definition: A benign hair follicle tumor whose tumor cells form rudimentary hair follicles but not actual hair shafts. A trichoepithelioma is usually less than one centimeter, firm, round, and shihy with yellow, pink, brown, or bluish color. They may occur multiply, usually on the face, and may gradually increase in number with age.

HP:0025368.name: Abnormal growth plate morphology
HP:0025368.definition: A structural anomaly of the growth plates (epiphyseal plates), areas of cartilage located near the ends of long bones that are located between the metaphysis (widened part of the shaft of the bone) and the epiphysis (end of the bone) and in which growth occurs in the developing bone. After conclusion of bone growth, the growth plates ossify (harden into solid bone).

HP:0025369.name: Thick growth plates
HP:0025369.definition: Increased thickness (dimension along the axis of the bone) of the growth plate.

HP:0025370.name: Abnormal ossification of the sacrum
HP:0025370.definition: Abnormal bone tissue formation (ossification) affecting the sacrum.

HP:0025371.name: Delayed ossification of the sacrum
HP:0025371.definition: Formation of the sacrum bone tissue occurs later than age-adjusted norms.

HP:0025372.name: Loud snoring
HP:0025372.definition: Snoring at a particularly loud or abnormally high volume.

HP:0025373.name: Interictal EEG abnormality
HP:0025373.definition: Interictal refers to a period of time between epileptic seizures. Electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns are important in the differential diagnosis of epilepsy, and the EEG is almost always abnormal during a seizure. Some persons with seizures may show EEG abnormalities between seizures, while others do not. In some cases, multiple interictal EEGs must be recorded before an abnormality is observed. In most cases the electrographic pattern of seizure onset is completely different from the activity recorded during interictal discharge.

HP:0025374.name: Duplicated odontoid process
HP:0025374.definition: The presence of two distinct odontoid processes. The odontoid process, also known as the dens of the axis, is a protuberance of the C2 vertebral body around which the first vertebra rotates.

HP:0025375.name: Orthotopic os odontoideum
HP:0025375.definition: Os odontoideum is classified into two anatomic types (orthotopic and dystopic). Os odontoideum is defined as an ossicle that consists of smooth and separate caudal portions of the odontoid process.With dystopic os odontoideum, the ossicle is located near the basion or is fused with the clivus.

HP:0025376.name: Hyperglutaminuria
HP:0025376.definition: An increased concentration of glutamine in the urine.

HP:0025377.name: Triggered by exertion
HP:0025377.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exertion or physical exercise.

HP:0025379.name: Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibody positivity
HP:0025379.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against thyroid peroxidase.

HP:0025380.name: Increased circulating androstenedione concentration
HP:0025380.definition: Increased concentration of androstenedione in the blood circulation.

HP:0025381.name: Anti-pituitary antibody positivity
HP:0025381.definition: Circulating antipituitary antibodies (APA) are markers of autoimmune hypophysitis, which may cause deficient pituitary function.

HP:0025382.name: Hypodipsia
HP:0025382.definition: Reduced fluid intake (drinking) in a clinical situation where the plasma molarity or sodium concentration normally would induce greater fluid intake.

HP:0025383.name: Dorsocervical fat pad
HP:0025383.definition: An area of fat accumulation at the back of the neck in the form of a hump.

HP:0025384.name: Diet-resistant subcutaneous adipose tissue
HP:0025384.definition: Areas of subcutanous fat tissue that are resistant to (do not respond as expected to) diet, life-style alteration, or bariatric surgery.

HP:0025385.name: Diet-resistant subcutaneous adipose tissue below waist
HP:0025385.definition: Areas of subcutanous fat tissue below the waist that are resistant to (do not respond as expected to) diet, life-style alteration, or bariatric surgery.

HP:0025386.name: Bitemporal hollowing
HP:0025386.definition: Depression of profile in both temporal regions.

HP:0025387.name: Pill-rolling tremor
HP:0025387.definition: A type of resting tremor characterized by simultaneous rubbing movements of thumb and index fingers against each other.

HP:0025388.name: Thyroid nodule
HP:0025388.definition: A nodular lesion that develops in the thyroid gland. The term "thyroid nodule" refers to any abnormal growth that forms a lump in the thyroid gland.

HP:0025389.name: Pulmonary interstitial high-resolution computed tomography abnormality
HP:0025389.definition: High-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) can distinguish findings that characterize characterize interstitial lung diseases in a way not possible with other modalities.

HP:0025390.name: Reticular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025390.definition: On pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography, reticular pattern is characterized by innumerable interlacing shadows suggesting a mesh.

HP:0025391.name: Crazy paving pattern
HP:0025391.definition: The so-called crazy paving pattern appears as thickened interlobular septa and intralobular lines superimposed on a background of ground-glass opacity, resembling irregularly shaped paving stones. The crazy-paving pattern is often sharply demarcated from more normal lung and may have a geographic outline. It was originally reported in patients with alveolar proteinosis and is also encountered in other diffuse lung diseases that affect both the interstitial and airspace compartments, such as lipoid pneumonia.

HP:0025392.name: Nodular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025392.definition: A nodular pattern is characterized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography by the presence of numerous rounded opacities that range from 2 mm to 1 cm in diameter, with micronodules defined as smaller than 3 mm in diameter.

HP:0025393.name: Reticulonodular pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025393.definition: Co-occurrence of reticular and micronodular patterns on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

HP:0025394.name: Cystic pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025394.definition: On pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography, the cystic pattern is composed by well-defined, round and circumscribed air-containing parenchymal spaces with a well-defined wall and interface with normal lung. The wall of the cysts may be uniform or varied in thickness, but usually is thin (less than 2 mm) and occurs without associated emphysema.

HP:0025395.name: Combined cystic and ground-glass pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025395.definition: Co-occurrence of the cystic pattern and the ground-glass pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography,

HP:0025396.name: Decreased attenuation pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025396.definition: Areas of low density corresponding to parenchymal destruction and reduced perfusion, and attenuation of the pulmonary vasculature, as visualized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

HP:0025397.name: Mosaic attenuation pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025397.definition: A patchwork of intermingled areas of increased and decreased attenuation visualized on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography.

HP:0025398.name: Nodular-perilymphatic pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025398.definition: A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that has a perilymphatic distribution.

HP:0025399.name: Nodular-centrilobular with tree-in-bud pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025399.definition: A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that displays a tree-in-bud pattern, representing centrilobular branching structures that resemble a budding tree.

HP:0025400.name: Nodular-random pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0025400.definition: A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that has an apparently random pattern.

HP:0025401.name: Staring gaze
HP:0025401.definition: An abnormality in which the eyes are held permanently wide open.

HP:0025402.name: Square-wave jerks
