HP:0025402.definition: Square wave jerks are saccadic eye movements which, when recorded with open eyes are considered to be a pathological sign, caused by fixation instability, and pointing to a central neurological lesion.

HP:0025403.name: Stooped posture
HP:0025403.definition: A habitual positioning of the body with the head and upper back bent forward.

HP:0025404.name: Abnormal visual fixation
HP:0025404.definition: Any anomaly in the process of ocular fixation, which is the maintaining of the visual gaze on a single location.

HP:0025405.name: Visual fixation instability
HP:0025405.definition: A deficit in the ability to fixate eye movements in order to stabilize images on the retina

HP:0025406.name: Asthenia
HP:0025406.definition: A state characterized by a feeling of weakness and loss of strength leading to a generalized weakness of the body.

HP:0025407.name: Rectourethral fistula
HP:0025407.definition: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the urethra.

HP:0025408.name: Abnormal spleen morphology
HP:0025408.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the spleen.

HP:0025409.name: Abnormal spleen physiology
HP:0025409.definition: Any anomaly of the function of the spleen.

HP:0025410.name: Splenogonadal fusion
HP:0025410.definition: Joining of the spleen and a gonad during embryological development.

HP:0025413.name: Fossa navicularis urethral stricture
HP:0025413.definition: A type of urethral stricture affecting the fossa navicularis, which is the spongy part of the male urethra located at the glans penis.

HP:0025414.name: Pendulous urethral stricture
HP:0025414.definition: A type of urethral stricture affecting the pendulous urethra, which is straight and fixed to the corpora cavernosa.

HP:0025415.name: Bulbar urethral stricture
HP:0025415.definition: A type of urethral stricture affecting the bulbar urethra, which is the part of the urethra that traverses the root of the penis.

HP:0025416.name: Vaginal stricture
HP:0025416.definition: A narrowing of the vagina owing to scar formation.

HP:0025417.name: Patulous urethra
HP:0025417.definition: Urethra more open or expanded than normal.

HP:0025418.name: Renal cortical necrosis
HP:0025418.definition: Patchy or diffuse ischemic destruction of all the elements of renal cortex resulting from significantly diminished renal arterial perfusion. Coagulative necrosis may be present, involving all tubular segments and glomeruli. Nuclei may be pale and pyknotic, or may no longer be apparent. Thrombi may be present in vessels at the edge of the infarct.

HP:0025419.name: Pulmonary pneumatocele
HP:0025419.definition: A pneumatocele is a thin walled, gas-filled space in the lung. It is most frequently caused by acute pneumonia, trauma, or aspiration of hydrocarbon fluid and is usually transient. The mechanism is believed to be a combination of parenchymal necrosis and check-valve airway obstruction. A pneumatocele appears as an approximately round, thin-walled airspace in the lung.

HP:0025420.name: Diffuse alveolar hemorrhage
HP:0025420.definition: A type of of pulmonary hemorrhage that originates from the pulmonary microcirculation, including the alveolar capillaries, arterioles, and venules. It presents with hemoptysis, anemia, diffuse lung infiltration, and acute respiratory failure. The diagnosis is confirmed by the observation of the accumulation of red blood cells, fibrin, or hemosiderin-laden macrophage in the alveolar space on pathologic biopsy. Hemosiderin, a product of hemoglobin degradation, appears at least 48-72 hours after bleeding and is helpful in distinguishing diffuse alveolar hemorrhage from surgical trauma. Mild interstitial thickening, organizing pneumonia, or diffuse alveolar damage can also be seen.

HP:0025421.name: Pneumomediastinum
HP:0025421.definition: The presence of free air in the mediastinum.

HP:0025422.name: Pleural cyst
HP:0025422.definition: A closed sac-like structure originating from the pleura that contains a liquid, gaseous, or semisolid substance.

HP:0025423.name: Abnormal larynx morphology
HP:0025423.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the larynx.

HP:0025424.name: Abnormal larynx physiology
HP:0025424.definition: Any anomaly of the function of the larynx.

HP:0025425.name: Laryngospasm
HP:0025425.definition: A spasm (involuntary contraction) of the vocal cords that can make it difficult to speak or breathe.

HP:0025426.name: Abnormal bronchus morphology
HP:0025426.definition: Any structural anomaly of the bronchi, i.e., of the airways leading from the trachea to the lungs.

HP:0025427.name: Abnormal bronchus physiology
HP:0025427.definition: Any anomaly of the function of the bronchi.

HP:0025429.name: Abnormal cry
HP:0025429.definition: Any anomaly of the vocalizing of an infant's crying, i.e.,the typically loud voice production that is accompanied by tears and agitation.

HP:0025430.name: High-pitched cry
HP:0025430.definition: A type of crying in an abnormally high-pitched voice.

HP:0025431.name: Staccato cry
HP:0025431.definition: A type of cry that is abnormal because it is consists of unusually shortened and detached vocalizations.

HP:0025432.name: Acanthoma
HP:0025432.definition: A benign epithelial skin tumor manifesting as a slightly elevated circular plaque or nodule with a red, pink or brown color and a diameter up to 22 mm.

HP:0025433.name: Decreased lecithin cholesterol acyl transferase level
HP:0025433.definition: Reduced level of the enzyme lecithin cholesterol acyl transferase.

HP:0025434.name: Reduced circulating CH50 activity
HP:0025434.definition: A diminished activity of the classical complement pathway as measured by the assay for 50% haemolytic complement (CH50) activity of serum.

HP:0025435.name: Increased circulating lactate dehydrogenase concentration
HP:0025435.definition: An elevated level of the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase in the blood circulation.

HP:0025436.name: Elevated serum 11-deoxycortisol
HP:0025436.definition: Increased concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the circulation. 11-deoxycorticosterone, which is also known as simply deoxycorticosterone and 21-hydroxyprogesterone, is a steroid hormore that is produces in the adrenals and is a precursor to aldosterone.

HP:0025437.name: Macrozoospermia
HP:0025437.definition: Increased size of the head of sperm.

HP:0025439.name: Pharyngitis
HP:0025439.definition: Inflammation (due to infection or irritation) of the pharynx.

HP:0025440.name: Warm reactive autoantibody positivity
HP:0025440.definition: Warm reactive autoantibodies are RBC-directed immune responses that are maximally reactive at 37 degrees C.

HP:0025441.name: Achilles tendon calcification
HP:0025441.definition: Ectopic deposition of calcium salts in the Achilles tendon.

HP:0025443.name: Abnormal cardiac atrial physiology
HP:0025443.definition: An abnormality of the function of the cardiac atria.

HP:0025444.name: Reduced amygdala volume
HP:0025444.definition: A decrease in the volume (size) of the amygdyla.

HP:0025445.name: Abnormal papillary muscle morphology
HP:0025445.definition: Any structural anomaly of the papillary muscles of the left ventricle.

HP:0025446.name: Anomalous insertion of papillary muscle directly into anterior mitral leaflet
HP:0025446.definition: A congenital malformation in which one or both of the papillary muscles (posteromedial or anterolateral) insert directly (that is, without interpositioned chordae tendineae) into the anterior mitral leaflet.

HP:0025447.name: Displacement of the papillary muscles
HP:0025447.definition: Abnormal location of the insertion of a papillary muscle into the left ventricular wall.

HP:0025448.name: Anterior displacement of the papillary muscles
HP:0025448.definition: Abnormally anterior location of the papillary muscles of the left ventricle.

HP:0025449.name: Apically displaced anterolateral papillary muscle
HP:0025449.definition: Abnormal location of the insertion of the anterolateral papillary muscle near to the apex of the left ventricle. This feature may be appreciated by noting that this muscle is usually not seen in the apical level of the parasternal short-axis echocardiographic view,

HP:0025451.name: Testicular adrenal rest tumor
HP:0025451.definition: Testicular adrenal rest tumor (TART) is a abenign tumor of the testis. TART generally occurs multiply and bilaterally within the rete testis. Histologically, TART resemble adrenocortical tissue, which led to the name. The tumous are not encapsulated and consist of sheets or confluent cords of large polygonal cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm.

HP:0025452.name: Pyoderma gangrenosum
HP:0025452.definition: A deep skin ulcer with a well defined border, which is usually violet or blue. The ulcer edge is often undermined (worn and damaged) and the surrounding skin is erythematous and indurated. The ulcer often starts as a small papule or collection of papules, which break down to form small ulcers with a so called cat's paw appearance. These coalesce and the central area then undergoes necrosis to form a single ulcer.

HP:0025453.name: Delayed adrenarche
HP:0025453.definition: Occurrence of adrenarche at a later than normal age. Adrenarche normally occurs between six and eight years of age with increased adrenal androgen secretion; its exact biologic role is not well understood. It is accompanied by changes in pilosebaceous units, a transient growth spurt and the appearance of axillary and pubic hair in some children, but no sexual development.

HP:0025454.name: Abnormal CSF metabolite concentration
HP:0025454.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of concentration of a metabolite in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0025455.name: Decreased CSF 5-hydroxyindolacetic acid concentration
HP:0025455.definition: 5-HIAA (5-hydroxyindolacetic acid) concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0025456.name: Abnormal CSF protein concentration
HP:0025456.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of a protein concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0025457.name: Decreased CSF protein concentration
HP:0025457.definition: CSF total protein level is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0025458.name: Decreased CSF albumin concentration
HP:0025458.definition: CSF albumin level is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0025459.name: Increased CSF/serum albumin ratio
HP:0025459.definition: An increase above normal limits of the ratio of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) albumin concentration to serum albumin concentration.

HP:0025460.name: High myoinositol in brain by MRS
HP:0025460.definition: An elevated level of myoinositol in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0025463.name: Abnormality of redox activity
HP:0025463.definition: An abnormality of the processes that maintain the redox environment of a cell or compartment within a cell, that is, the balance between reduction and oxidation chemical reactions.

HP:0025464.name: Increased reactive oxygen species production
HP:0025464.definition: An accumulation of free radical groups in the body inadequately neutralized by antioxidants, which creates a potentially unstable and damaging cellular environment linked to tissue damage.

HP:0025465.name: Abnormal circulating beta globulin level
HP:0025465.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of beta globulin. The beta globulins are a group of globular (globe-shaped) proteins in blood.

HP:0025466.name: Beta 2-microglobulinuria
HP:0025466.definition: Increased level of beta 2-microglobulins in the urine.

HP:0025469.name: Anagen effluvium
HP:0025469.definition: An abnormal loss of anagen (growth phase) hairs.

HP:0025470.name: Telogen effluvium
HP:0025470.definition: A type of hair loss characterized by an abnormal increase in dormant, telogen stage hair follicles.

HP:0025471.name: Congenital panfollicular nevus
HP:0025471.definition: A hamartomatous proliferation containing malformed hair follicles in various stages of development. Panfolliculomas are well-circumscribed lesions demonstrating all stages of follicular differentiation.

HP:0025472.name: Recurrent plantar mycosis
HP:0025472.definition: A history of repeated fungal infections located on the sole of the foot, usually manifested by scaling, maceration, and itching.

HP:0025473.name: Hyperpigmented papule
HP:0025473.definition: A papule (circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point) that exhibits increased pigmentation (is darker) compared to the surrounding skin.

HP:0025474.name: Erythematous plaque
HP:0025474.definition: A plaque (a solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter) with a red or reddish color often associated with inflammation or irritation.

HP:0025475.name: Erythematous macule
HP:0025475.definition: A macule (flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin) with a red or reddish color often associated with inflammation or irritation.

HP:0025476.name: Testicular lipomatosis
HP:0025476.definition: Multiple foci of adipocytes within the testicular interstitium, usually presenting as multiple bilateral ill-defined hyperechoic intratesticular lesions of different sizes but generally with maximum diameter of 4 mm.

HP:0025477.name: Periarticular calcification
HP:0025477.definition: Calcified deposits in soft tissue structures outside a joint.

HP:0025478.name: Atrial standstill
HP:0025478.definition: Atrial standstill or silent atrium is a rare condition presenting with the absence of electrical and mechanical activity in the atria. It presents with the absence of P waves, bradycardia, and wide QRS complex in the electrocardiogram.

HP:0025479.name: Self-neglect
HP:0025479.definition: A pathological neglect of personal needs and well-being that includes attending to self-grooming, personal care and the attention to cleanliness of personal space.

HP:0025480.name: Lipomyelomeningocele
HP:0025480.definition: A type of spinal dysraphism presenting as a subcutaneous fatty mass, that is, a spinal defect associated with lipomatous tissue, and covered by skin. The most usual location for lipomyelomeningocele is at the gluteal cleft.

HP:0025481.name: Cervical hemivertebrae
HP:0025481.definition: Absence of one half of the vertebral body in the cervical spine.

HP:0025482.name: Positive perchlorate discharge test
HP:0025482.definition: An abnormal result of the perchlorate discharge test. In this test, first radioactive iodine is administered, sufficient time is allowed to pass so that the radioactive iodine is captured by the thyroid,and then, perchlorate is administered orally. The perchlorate displaces non-organified iodide from the thyroid. The perchlorate discharge test is considered positive (abnormal) if there is an abnormally rapid loss of radioactive iodine from the thyroid.

HP:0025483.name: Abnormal circulating thyroglobulin concentration
HP:0025483.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of thyroglobulin, a protein produced in the thyroid gland that acts as a precursor to thyrroid hormones.

HP:0025484.name: Increased circulating thyroglobulin concentration
HP:0025484.definition: An abnormal elevation of the concentration of thyroglobulin, a protein produced in the thyroid gland that acts as a precursor to thyrroid hormones.

HP:0025485.name: Vaginal adenosis
HP:0025485.definition: Vaginal adenosis is defined by the presence of metaplastic cervical or endometrial epithelium within the vaginal wall, thought to be derived from persistent Müllerian (synonymous with paramesonephric) epithelium islets in postembryonic life.

HP:0025486.name: Fused labia majora
HP:0025486.definition: The outer labia are sealed together.

HP:0025487.name: Abnormal bladder morphology
HP:0025487.definition: Any structural anomaly of the bladder.

HP:0025488.name: Detrusor sphincter dyssynergia
HP:0025488.definition: A urodynamic anomaly characterized by bladder outlet obstruction from detrusor muscle contraction with concomitant involuntary urethral sphincter activation.

HP:0025489.name: Bladder duplication
HP:0025489.definition: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of two bladders.

HP:0025490.name: Myocardial bridging
HP:0025490.definition: A congenital variant of a coronary artery in which a portion of an epicardial coronary artery (most frequently the middle segment of the left anterior descending artery) takes an intramuscular course.

HP:0025491.name: Venous stenosis
HP:0025491.definition: Narrowing of a vein due to intimal hyperplasia and fibrosis.

HP:0025492.name: Microcoria
HP:0025492.definition: A small pupil (typically diameter less than 2 mm) that dilates poorly or not at all in response to topically administered mydriatic drugs.

HP:0025493.name: Palmoplantar erythema
HP:0025493.definition: Redness of the skin of the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.

HP:0025494.name: Coated aorta
HP:0025494.definition: Regular circumferential periaortic fibrosis involving the whole aorta and leading to a coated aorta appearance on computed tomography scans

HP:0025495.name: Descending aorta hypoplasia
HP:0025495.definition: Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of the descending aorta.

HP:0025496.name: Abnormal coronary artery physiology
HP:0025496.definition: Any anomaly of the function of a coronary artery.

HP:0025497.name: Coronary artery spasm
HP:0025497.definition: A brief and sudden narrowing of a coronary artery.

HP:0025498.name: Aceruloplasminemia
HP:0025498.definition: Absence of ceruloplasmin in the blood.

HP:0025499.name: Class I obesity
HP:0025499.definition: Obesity with a body mass index of 30 to 34.9 kg per square meter.

HP:0025500.name: Class II obesity
HP:0025500.definition: Obesity with a body mass index of 35 to 39.9 kg per square meter.

HP:0025501.name: Class III obesity
HP:0025501.definition: Obesity with a body mass index of 40 kg per square meter or higher.

HP:0025502.name: Overweight
HP:0025502.definition: Increased body weight with a body mass index of 25-29.9 kg per square meter.

HP:0025503.name: Anomalous coronary artery arising from the opposite sinus
HP:0025503.definition: Origin of the right coronary artery (RCA) from the left sinus of Valsalva or of the left main (LM) or left anterior descending (LAD) coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva.

HP:0025505.name: Anomalous origin of the circumflex artery from the right sinus of Valsalva
HP:0025505.definition: The circumflex coronary artery originates from the right aortic sinus of Valsalva.

HP:0025506.name: Coronary artery sandwich anomaly
HP:0025506.definition: Origin of the right coronary artery (RCA) from the left sinus of Valsalva or of the left main (LM) or left anterior descending (LAD) coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva, with the additional feature that the artery passes between the two great arteries. This carries a risk of the artery being compressed by these two vessels,

HP:0025508.name: Gottron's papules
HP:0025508.definition: Violaceous papules overlying the dorsal and lateral aspects of the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:0025509.name: Piezogenic pedal papules
HP:0025509.definition: Flesh-colored or yellowish papules, 2 mm or larger, that are responses to internal mechanical pressure and weakness in the connective tissue in the dermis, appear commonly over the medial aspect of the heel, but in some cases on the wrists. They are thought to represent herniations of adipose tissue through the plantar fascia retinaculum.

HP:0025510.name: Nevus spilus
HP:0025510.definition: A tan, regularly bordered patch with darker macules within the lesion.

HP:0025511.name: Nevus sebaceus
HP:0025511.definition: A solitary yellow-orange slightly raised plaque typically on scalp or face. The plaque typically thickens and becomes more verrucous or pebbly during childhood.

HP:0025512.name: Skin-colored papule
HP:0025512.definition: A papule with the same color as the surrounding skin.

HP:0025514.name: Morning glory anomaly
HP:0025514.definition: An abnormality of the optic nerve in which the optic nerve is large and funneled and displays a conical excavation of the optic disc. The optic disc appears dysplastic.

HP:0025515.name: Delayed thelarche
HP:0025515.definition: Later than normal development of the breasts.

HP:0025516.name: Coronary-pulmonary artery fistula
HP:0025516.definition: A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and the pulmonary artery.

HP:0025518.name: Visual gaze preference
HP:0025518.definition: An abnormality of gaze that can be observed following an acute supranuclear cerebral lesion (e.g., stroke) that is characterized by an acute inability to direct gaze contralateral to the side of the lesion and is accompanied by a tendency for tonic deviation of the eyes toward the side of the lesion.

HP:0025519.name: Multiple biliary hamartomas
HP:0025519.definition: Multiple biliary hamartomas are a rare clinicopathologic entity, consisting of small (less than 1.5cm), usually multiple and nodular cystic lesions in the liver.

HP:0025520.name: Calcinosis cutis
HP:0025520.definition: Deposition of calcium in the skin.

HP:0025521.name: Increased body fat percentage
HP:0025521.definition: The percentage of fat as a part of total body weight above the norm, usually defined as 32% for females and 25% for males.

HP:0025522.name: Elongated chordae tendinae of the mitral valve
HP:0025522.definition: Abnormal increased in length of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve.

HP:0025523.name: Abnormal morphology of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve
HP:0025523.definition: A structural anomaly of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve, whose main function is to transmit the contraction and relaxation of the papillary muscles during the cardiac cycle, thus ensuring the closing of the leaflets of the mitral valve.

HP:0025524.name: Palmoplantar scaling skin
HP:0025524.definition: Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot.

HP:0025525.name: Scaling skin on fingertip
HP:0025525.definition: Loss of the outer layer of the epidermis in large, scale-like flakes localized to one or more fingertips.

HP:0025526.name: Psoriasiform lesion
HP:0025526.definition: A skin lesions that resembles the lesions observed in psoriasis, viz., an erythematous plaque covered by fine silvery scales. Psoriasiform lesions can be observed in psoriasis as well as in other conditions including allergic contact dermatitis, seborrhoeic dermatitis, Atopic dermatitis, pityriasis rubra, and lichen simplex chronicus.

HP:0025527.name: Serpiginous cutaneous lesion
HP:0025527.definition: A skin lesion with a snake- or serpent-like distribution.

HP:0025528.name: Annular cutaneous lesion
HP:0025528.definition: A lesion of the skin with a ring-like distribution.

HP:0025529.name: Hyperpigmented nodule
HP:0025529.definition: A nodule of the skin that exhibits an increased amount of pigmentation.

HP:0025530.name: Xanthomas of the palmar creases
HP:0025530.definition: The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin distributed in the creases of the palm of the hand. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin.

HP:0025531.name: Harlequin phenomenon
HP:0025531.definition: The Harlequin phenomenon consists of a sudden change in skin color, resulting in two different body colors, one on each half of the body.

HP:0025532.name: Positive pathergy test
HP:0025532.definition: With the pathergy test, a small, sterile needle is inserted into the skin of the forearm. The site of injectionis circuled and observed after one and two days. If a small red bump or pustule at the site of needle insertion occurs, the pathergy test is considered to have a positive (abnormal) result.

HP:0025534.name: Ocular melanocytosis
HP:0025534.definition: A congenital lesion of the sclera characterized by unilateral patchy but extensive slate-gray or bluish discoloration of the sclera . The conjunctiva are spared.

HP:0025535.name: Shawl sign
HP:0025535.definition: Erythematous, poikilodermatous macules distributed in a shawl pattern over the shoulders, arms and upper back.

HP:0025536.name: V-sign
HP:0025536.definition: Erythematous, poikilodermatous macules distributed in a V-shaped distribution over the anterior neck and chest.

HP:0025537.name: Plantar edema
HP:0025537.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on sole of the foot.

HP:0025538.name: Palmar edema
HP:0025538.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the palm of the hand.

HP:0025539.name: Abnormal B cell subset distribution
HP:0025539.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of any B cell subpopulation, measured as percentage of total CD19+ or CD20+ B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0025540.name: Abnormal T cell subset distribution
HP:0025540.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of any T cell subpopulation, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0025541.name: obsolete Decreased activity of complement receptor

HP:0025546.name: Abnormal mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration
HP:0025546.definition: A deviation from the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell). A reduced mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) may indicate a hypochromic anemia, but the MCH may be normal if both the total hemoglobin and the red blood cell count are reduced.

HP:0025547.name: Decreased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration
HP:0025547.definition: A reduction from the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell). A reduced mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) may indicate a hypochromic anemia, but the MCH may be normal if both the total hemoglobin and the red blood cell count are reduced.

HP:0025548.name: Increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration
HP:0025548.definition: An elevation over the normal range of the average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell (27 to 31 picograms/cell).

HP:0025549.name: Eccentric visual fixation
HP:0025549.definition: A uniocular condition in which there is fixation of an object by a point other than the fovea. This point adopts the principal visual direction. The degree of the eccentric fixation is defined by its distance from the fovea in degrees.

HP:0025550.name: Elevated circulating ribitol concentration
HP:0025550.definition: The concentration of ribitol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0025551.name: Optic nerve misrouting
HP:0025551.definition: Abnormal decussation of the visual pathways, typically identified using visual evoked potentials (VEP) (asymmetrical distribution of the VEP over the posterior scalp).

HP:0025552.name: Periorbital purpura
HP:0025552.definition: Multiple red/purple spots on the skin that surrounds the eyes that do not blanch (whiten) upon pressure. Purpura is caused by subcutaneous bleeding.

HP:0025553.name: Periorbital ecchymosis with tarsal plate sparing
HP:0025553.definition: Subcutaneous bleeding with a diameter greater than 1 cm (ecchymosis). The bleeding does not extend into the tarsal plate (the comparatively thick, elongated plates of dense connective tissue within the eyelid) due to an anatomic structure called the orbital septum, which limits extravasation of blood beyond the tarsal plate.

HP:0025554.name: Yellow nodule
HP:0025554.definition: A type of skin nodule (a lesions that is greater than either 10mm in both width and depth, and most frequently centered in the dermis or subcutaneous fat) with a yellowish coloration (that reflects a high lipid content of the lesion).

HP:0025555.name: Periungual teleangiectasia
HP:0025555.definition: Telangiectasia (small dilated blood vessels) located near to the fingernails or toenails.

HP:0025558.name: Lamellar cataract with riders
HP:0025558.definition: Lamellar cataracts with associated linear lens opacities radially extending towards the periphery of the lens.

HP:0025559.name: Coronary cataract
HP:0025559.definition: A type of cataract characterized by club-shaped and dot opacities distributed radially in the deep cortex. These lens opacities surround the nucleus in an appearance that is though to resemble a crown.

HP:0025560.name: Anterior chamber cells
HP:0025560.definition: Tiny deposits corresponding to cells floating in the anterior chamber of the eye. This appearance is typically associated with intraocular inflammation leading to breakdown of the blood-aqueous barrier and resulting in an increase in the number of cells and in the aqueous humor. Grading (SUN Working Group) is performed by estimating the number of cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025561.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 1+
HP:0025561.definition: Anterior chamber cells with 6-15 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025562.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 0.5+
HP:0025562.definition: Anterior chamber cells with 1-5 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025563.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 0
HP:0025563.definition: Anterior chamber cells with less than one cell in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025564.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 2+
HP:0025564.definition: Anterior chamber cells with 16-25 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025565.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 3+
HP:0025565.definition: Anterior chamber cells with 26-50 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025566.name: Anterior chamber cells grade 4+
HP:0025566.definition: Anterior chamber cells with more than 50 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

HP:0025567.name: Central serous chorioretinopathy
HP:0025567.definition: An anomaly of the retina with serous detachment of the neurosensory retina secondary to one or more focal lesions of the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), and associated with blurred vision, usually in one eye only and perceived typically by the patient as a dark spot in the center of the visual field with associated micropsia and metamorphopsia. Normal vision often recurs spontaneously within a few months.

HP:0025568.name: Abnormal morphology of the choroidal vasculature

HP:0025569.name: Polypoidal choroidal vasculopathy
HP:0025569.definition: The presence of aneurysmal polypoidal lesions in the choroidal vasculature. The aneurysmal dilatations, also known as polyps, may be found at subfoveal, juxtafoveal, extrafoveal, peripapillary or even peripheral regions. These polypoidal dilatations may be visible as reddish-orange subretinal nodules during ophthalmoscopic examination. The polypoidal lesions are best detected on indocyanine green angiography (ICGA) and might be associated with a branching vascular network (BVN) of neovascularization.

HP:0025570.name: Choroidal vascular hyperpermeability
HP:0025570.definition: Increased tendency of choiroidal blood vessels to allow fluids to leak characterized by multifocal choroidal hyperfluorescence on indocyanine green angiography (ICGA).

HP:0025571.name: Christmas tree cataract
HP:0025571.definition: A type of cataract that shows a spectacular display of multiple colors that glitters with the change of incident light like an illuminated Christmas tree.

HP:0025572.name: Punctal stenosis
HP:0025572.definition: Punctal stenosis is a condition in which the external opening of the lacrimal canaliculus is narrowed or occluded.

HP:0025573.name: Mild myopia
HP:0025573.definition: A mild form of myopia with up to -3.00 diopters.

HP:0025574.name: Macular hemorrhage
HP:0025574.definition: Bleeding occurring within the macula lutea of the retina.

HP:0025575.name: Abnormal superior vena cava morphology
HP:0025575.definition: Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the upper portion of the body and delivering it to the right ventricle of the heart.

HP:0025576.name: Abnormal inferior vena cava morphology
HP:0025576.definition: Any structural anomaly of the principal vein draining blood from the lower portion of the body.

HP:0025578.name: Aortic valve prolapse
HP:0025578.definition: Aortic valve prolapse can be diagnosed when either or both of the right or non-coronary aortic valve cusps (seen in the cross sectional echocardiographic long axis view) show backward bowing towards the left ventricle beyond a line joining the points of attachment of the aortic valve leaflets to the annulus.

HP:0025579.name: Abnormal left atrium morphology
HP:0025579.definition: Any structural abnormality of the left atrium.

HP:0025580.name: Abnormal right atrium morphology
HP:0025580.definition: Any structural abnormality of the right atrium.

HP:0025582.name: Submacular hemorrhage
HP:0025582.definition: Bleeding between the neurosensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) arising from the choroidal or retinal circulation.

HP:0025583.name: Tapetal-like fundal reflex
HP:0025583.definition: Golden, scintillating, particulate reflection noted on fundus examination (typically in the macula and sparing the fovea). The term tapetal is used to describe this 'metallic' sheen appearance as it is thought to be similar to the 'tapetal' reflex seen in the eyes of certain animals.

HP:0025584.name: Hypotropia
HP:0025584.definition: A form of manifest strabismus (heterotropia) in which one eye is deviated downwards when both eyes are open.

HP:0025585.name: Hyperphoria
HP:0025585.definition: Tendency for the visual axis of one eye to be higher than that of the other.

HP:0025586.name: Hypertropia
HP:0025586.definition: A type of strabismus characterized by permanent upward deviation of the visual axis of one eye.

HP:0025587.name: Hyperdeviation
HP:0025587.definition: A type of strabismus in which the visual axis of one eye is higher than that of the other.

HP:0025588.name: Hypodeviation
HP:0025588.definition: A type of strabismus in which the visual axis of one eye is lower than that of the other.

HP:0025589.name: Cyclodeviation
HP:0025589.definition: Cyclodeviation is defined as the rotation of an eyeball along the anteroposterior axis and cyclotropia as a misalignment of cyclodeviation between the two eyes.

HP:0025590.name: Abnormal extraocular muscle physiology
HP:0025590.definition: A functional anomaly of the muscles of the eye.

HP:0025591.name: Abnormal superior oblique muscle physiology
HP:0025591.definition: A functional anomaly of the superior oblique muscle, a fusiform muscle that originates in the upper, medial side of the orbit. The superior oblique muscle abducts, depresses and internally rotates the eye, and is the only extraocular muscle innervated by the fourth cranial nerve.

HP:0025592.name: Superior oblique muscle weakness
HP:0025592.definition: Decreased strength of the superior oblique muscle.

HP:0025593.name: Superior oblique muscle restriction
HP:0025593.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the superior oblique muscle.

HP:0025594.name: Superior oblique muscle overaction
HP:0025594.definition: An ocular motility abnormality characterized by an overacting superior oblique muscle resulting to vertical incomitance of the eyes in lateral gaze. On examination, this is commonly seen as a downshoot of the adducting eye occurring when gaze is directed into the field of action of the inferior oblique muscle, producing a greater downward excursion of the adducted eye than of the abducted eye.

HP:0025595.name: Superior oblique muscle underaction
HP:0025595.definition: Reduced ocular movement of the superior oblique muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0025596.name: Abnormal inferior oblique muscle physiology
HP:0025596.definition: A functional anomaly of the inferior oblique muscle, an extraocular muscle that has its origin on the maxillary bone just posterior to the inferior medial orbital rim and lateral to the nasolacrimal canal and that is innervated by the inferior branch of the oculomotor nerve.

HP:0025597.name: Inferior oblique muscle restriction
HP:0025597.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the inferior oblique muscle.

HP:0025598.name: Inferior oblique muscle weakness
HP:0025598.definition: Decreased strength of the inferior oblique muscle.

HP:0025599.name: Inferior oblique muscle overaction
HP:0025599.definition: A common ocular motility disorder characterized by vertical incomitance of the eyes in lateral gaze. In primary inferior oblique muscle overaction, an upshoot of the adducting eye occurs when gaze is directed into the field of action of the inferior oblique muscle, producing a greater upward excursion of the adducted eye than of the abducted eye.

HP:0025600.name: Abnormal inferior rectus muscle physiology
HP:0025600.definition: A functional anomaly of the inferior rectus muscle, which is innervated by the inferior division of oculomotor nerve and functions in the depression, adduction, and lateral rotation (extortion) of the eye.

HP:0025601.name: Inferior rectus muscle weakness
HP:0025601.definition: Decreased strength of the inferior rectus muscle.

HP:0025602.name: Inferior rectus muscle restriction
HP:0025602.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the inferior rectus muscle.

HP:0025603.name: Abnormal superior rectus muscle physiology
HP:0025603.definition: A functional anomaly of the superior rectus muscle, an extraocular muscle that is innervated by the superior division of the oculomotor nerve, and whose primary function is the elevation of the globe.

HP:0025604.name: Orbital schwannoma
HP:0025604.definition: A schwannoma (benign, usually encapsulated slow growing tumor composed of Schwann cells) located in the orbit.

HP:0025605.name: Lid lag on downgaze
HP:0025605.definition: Delayed descent of the upper eyelid on downgaze. Also described by some authors as von Graefe sign.

HP:0025606.name: Abnormal medial rectus muscle physiology
HP:0025606.definition: A functional anomaly of the medial rectus muscle, an extraocular muscle that is innervated by the inferior division of the oculomotor nerve and whose sole action is the adduction of the eyeball.

HP:0025607.name: Upper eyelid entropion
HP:0025607.definition: An inward turning (inversion) of the margin of the upper eyelid.

HP:0025608.name: Cicatricial ectropion
HP:0025608.definition: An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin (i.e., ectropion) caused by shortening or contraction of the anterior or middle lamellae related to scarring.

HP:0025609.name: Anterior blepharitis
HP:0025609.definition: A type of blepharitis that affects the eyelid skin, base of the eyelashes, and the eyelash follicles.

HP:0025610.name: Posterior blepharitis
HP:0025610.definition: A type of blepharitis that affects the meibomian glands and meibomian gland orifices. This abnormality can be associated with a spectrum of appearances ranging from meibomian seborrhoea (foaming meibomian gland secretions) and meibomianitis (inflamed meibomian glands), to chalazia.

HP:0025611.name: Epicanthus superciliaris
HP:0025611.definition: A type of epicanthus in which more extensive epicanthal folds with their origins in the eyebrow cover, pass in front of and lateral to the medial canthus (middle corner of the eye).

HP:0025612.name: Corneal astigmatism
HP:0025612.definition: A type of refractive error related abnormal curvatures on the anterior or posterior surface of the cornea.

HP:0025613.name: Focal emotional seizure
HP:0025613.definition: Seizures presenting with an emotion or the appearance of having an emotion as an early prominent feature, such as fear, spontaneous joy or euphoria, laughing (gelastic), or crying, (dacrystic). These emotional seizures may occur with or without objective clinical signs of a seizure evident to the observer.

HP:0025615.name: Abscess
HP:0025615.definition: An abscess is a localized collection of purulent material surrounded by inflammation and granulation.

HP:0025616.name: Sterile abscess
HP:0025616.definition: An abscess not caused by infection with pyogenic bacteria. Operationally, a sterile abscess is inferred if investigations of an abscess fail to reveal evidence of pathogenic organisms.

HP:0025617.name: Abnormal plasma cell count
HP:0025617.definition: An abnormal number of plasma cells in the blood circulation. Plasma cells are the the effector cells dedicated to the production of a high amount of antibodies.

HP:0025618.name: Reduced plasma cell count
HP:0025618.definition: An abnormally low number of plasma cells in the blood circulation. Plasma cells are the the effector cells dedicated to the production of a high amount of antibodies.

HP:0025619.name: Elevated plasma cell count
HP:0025619.definition: An abnormally high number of plasma cells in the blood circulation. Plasma cells are the the effector cells dedicated to the production of a high amount of antibodies.

HP:0025620.name: Abnormal CD4+ central memory T cell proportion
HP:0025620.definition: An abnormal proportion of central memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These are memory cells that are located in the secondary lymphoid organs. These cells have the phenotype of CCR7-positive, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0025621.name: obsolete Increased proportion of CD4+ central memory cells

HP:0025622.name: obsolete Decreased proportion of CD4+ central memory cells

HP:0025623.name: Abnormal CD4+ effector memory T cell proportion
HP:0025623.definition: An abnormal proportion of effector memory CD4+ T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These are memory cells that are short-lived cells that migrate to the site of an infection and attempt to eliminate the pathogen. These cells have the phenotype CD3-positive, CD4-positive, CD62L-negative, CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0025624.name: Decreased CD4+ effector memory T cell proportion
HP:0025624.definition: An abnormally decreased proportion of effector memory CD4+ T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These are memory cells that are short-lived cells that migrate to the site of an infection and attempt to eliminate the pathogen. These cells have the phenotype CD3-positive, CD4-positive, CD62L-negative, CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0025625.name: Increased CD4+ effector memory T cell proportion
HP:0025625.definition: An abnormally increased proportion of effector memory CD4+ T cells. These are memory cells that are short-lived cells that migrate to the site of an infection and attempt to eliminate the pathogen. These cells may have a CD3/CD4/CD62L-/CD45RA phenotype.

HP:0025626.name: Increased circulating oleate level
HP:0025626.definition: An abnormally high concentration of oleic acid (oleate) in the blood circulation.

HP:0025627.name: Increased circulating octadecanoate level
HP:0025627.definition: An abnormally high concentration of octadecanoate in the blood circulation. Octadecanoate is a fatty acid anion 18:0 that is the conjugate base of octadecanoic acid (stearic acid).

HP:0025628.name: Increased circulating myristoleate level
HP:0025628.definition: An abnormally high concentration of myristoleate in the blood circulation.

HP:0025629.name: Anti-myelin-associated glycoprotein antibody positivity
HP:0025629.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against myelin-associated glycoprotein (MAG).

HP:0025630.name: Argininosuccinic aciduria
HP:0025630.definition: Increased amount of argininosuccinate in the urine.

HP:0025631.name: Alpha-aminobutyric aciduria
HP:0025631.definition: Increased amount of alpha-aminobutyric acid in the urine.

HP:0025632.name: obsolete Reduced reactive oxygen species production in neutrophils

HP:0025633.name: Abnormal ureter morphology
HP:0025633.definition: A structural abnormality of the ureter. The ureter is the duct by which urine passes from the kidney to the bladder.

HP:0025634.name: Abnormal ureter physiology
HP:0025634.definition: A functional abnormality of the ureter. The ureter is the duct by which urine passes from the kidney to the bladder.

HP:0025635.name: Ureteral polyp
HP:0025635.definition: A growth protruding from the mucous membrane of the ureter. Ureteral polyps can be attached to the ureter by a broad base or a thin stalk.

HP:0025636.name: Endometritis
HP:0025636.definition: Inflammation of the inner lining of the uterus (endometrium).

HP:0025637.name: Vasospasm
HP:0025637.definition: Narrowing of an artery due to constriction of the blood vessels.

HP:0025638.name: Elevated urinary N-butyrylglycine
HP:0025638.definition: An increased level of N-butyrylglycine in the urine.

HP:0025639.name: Increased urinary zinc level
HP:0025639.definition: An abnormally elevated amount of zinc in the urine, typically as assessed by a 24 hour urine collection.

HP:0025640.name: Abnormal urinary mineral level
HP:0025640.definition: An abnormal concentration or amount of a mineral in the urine. Medically relevant minerals include calcium, phosphorus, potassium, sodium, chloride, magnesium, iron, zinc, iodine, chromium, copper, fluoride, molybdenum, manganese, and selenium.

HP:0025641.name: Elevated circulating glycolate concentration
HP:0025641.definition: The concentration of glycolate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0025643.name: Tarlov cyst
HP:0025643.definition: A cerebrospinal fluid-filled nerve root cyst most often localized in the sacral spine.

HP:0025644.name: Fixation-off epileptiform discharges
HP:0025644.definition: Fixation off sensitivity (FOS) is characterized by posterior or generalized epileptiform discharges that consistently occur with conditions that eliminate central vision, such as closed eyes, complete darkness, modified Ganzfeld stimulation (using a large white surface without visual cues), and Frenzel lenses. The FOS electroencephalogram (EEG) pattern usually consists of spikes/polyspikes and waves localized in occipital regions (bilateral or unilateral) or generalized discharges. It is usually inhibited by fixation of gaze, observing patterns, or intermittent photic stimulation (e.g., flashing light or patterns used as stimuli during the recording of the EEG).

HP:0025646.name: Bilateral polymicrogyria
HP:0025646.definition: Polymicrogyria that affects all or some of both cerebral hemispheres.

HP:0025647.name: Steroid-sensitive nephrotic syndrome
HP:0025647.definition: A type of nephrotic syndrome in which complete remission (albumin urine dipstick negative/trace or proteinuria <4mg/m2/d or urinary protein to creatinine ratio <200mg/g (<20 mg/mmol) for 3 consecutive days) is achieved within initial 4 weeks of corticosteroid therapy.

HP:0025648.name: Steroid-sensitive nephrotic syndrome with infrequent relapses
HP:0025648.definition: A type of steroid-sensitive nephrotic syndrome in which relapses occur at a frequency of one relapse (albumin urine dipstick at least 3+ or proteinuria over 40 mg/m2/d or urinary protein to creatinine ratio at least 2000 mg/g for 3 consecutive days) within 6 months of initial response, or one to three relapses in any 12-month period.

HP:0025649.name: Steroid-sensitive nephrotic syndrome with frequent relapses
HP:0025649.definition: A type of steroid-sensitive nephrotic syndrome in which relapses occur at a frequency of two or more relapses (albumin urine dipstick at least 3+ or proteinuria over 40 mg/m2/d or urinary protein to creatinine ratio at least 2000 mg/g for 3 consecutive days) within 6 months of initial response or four or more relapses in any 12-month period.

HP:0025650.name: Steroid-dependent nephrotic syndrome
HP:0025650.definition: A type of nephrotic syndrome in which two consecutive relapses (albumin urine dipstick at least 3+ or proteinuria greater than 40 mg/m2/d or urinary protein to creatinine ratio at least 2000 mg/g for 3 consecutive days) occur during corticosteroid therapy, or within 14 days of ceasing therapy.

HP:0025652.name: Abnormal placental adhesion into the uterine wall
HP:0025652.definition: Abnormal placental adhesion is characterized by an anomalous adherence of the placenta to the uterine wall. Based on the degree of adhesion, placental invasion can be classified into accreta, increta, or percreta.

HP:0025653.name: Placenta percreta
HP:0025653.definition: Placenta percreta is a rare form of morbidly adherent placenta with penetration through the myometrium reaching serosa and even adjacent pelvic organs.

HP:0025654.name: Placenta accreta
HP:0025654.definition: Abnormally firm adherence of the placenta to the uterine wall.

HP:0025655.name: Placenta increta
HP:0025655.definition: Abnormal placental pentration into but not beyond the uterine wall.

HP:0025656.name: Prenatal double bubble sign
HP:0025656.definition: Sonographic detection of a double bubble sign in the upper abdomen is strongly indicative of duodenal obstruction. One bubble represents fetal stomach, and the other is attributed to a dilated proximal part of the duodenum; continuity between both bubbles is required for the sign.

HP:0025658.name: obsolete Abnormal umbilical artery Doppler pattern in pregnancy

HP:0025659.name: Decreased circulating creatine kinase concentration
HP:0025659.definition: A reduction in the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase (CK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood.

HP:0025660.name: Chiari type II malformation
HP:0025660.definition: A type of Chiari malformation that consists of brainstem herniation and a towering cerebellum in addition to the herniated cerebellar tonsils and vermis due to an open distal spinal dysraphism/myelomeningocele.

HP:0025661.name: Chiari type III malformation
HP:0025661.definition: A type of Chiari malformation that involves herniation of the hindbrain (cerebellum with or without the brainstem) into a low occipital or high cervical meningoencephalocele.

HP:0025662.name: Abnormal fetal skeletal morphology
HP:0025662.definition: An anomalous structural finding of the fetal skeleton. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other terms from the skeletal hierarchy can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

HP:0025663.name: Reduced fetal femur/foot length ratio
HP:0025663.definition: This ratio relates the length of the fetal femur to that of the fetal foot. The ratio is approximately 1 throughout the age range of 14 to 40 weeks of gestation. A substantial reduction in the raio can help differentiate fetuses that have dysplastic limb reduction from those whose limbs are short because of constitutional factors or IUGR. It can reduce the problem of an unknown gestational age and help to distinguish between fetal skeletal dysplasia and intrauterine growth retardation caused by other factors.

HP:0025664.name: Moderate to late preterm birth
HP:0025664.definition: Birth at 32 to 36 completed weeks of gestation.

HP:0025665.name: Extremely preterm birth
HP:0025665.definition: Birth before 28 completed weeks of gestation (up to and including 27 weeks and 6 days of gestation).

HP:0025666.name: Very preterm birth
HP:0025666.definition: Birth before 32 completed weeks of gestation (28 up to but not including 32 weeks).

HP:0025667.name: Fetal neck anomaly
HP:0025667.definition: A structural anomaly in the fetal neck region. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

HP:0025668.name: Abnormal neck morphology
HP:0025668.definition: Any structural anomaly of the neck region.

HP:0025669.name: Abnormal neck physiology
HP:0025669.definition: Any functional anomaly of the neck region.

HP:0025670.name: Syntelencephaly
HP:0025670.definition: Syntelencephaly is a rare malformation that consists of an abnormal midline connection of the cerebral hemispheres in the posterior frontal and parietal regions, with interhemispheric separation of the basal forebrain, anterior frontal lobes, and occipital regions.

HP:0025671.name: Fetal pericardial effusion
HP:0025671.definition: An abnormal accumulation of fluid in which the heart is partially or completely surrounded by fluid that is seen in all views and the thickness of the fluid as observed by prenatal ultrasound is above age-dependent norms.

HP:0025672.name: Fetal skin edema
HP:0025672.definition: A separation of skin in one or more regions of the body or even along the entire length of body wall (to a degree greater than gestational-age related norms) related to pathologically increased fluid accumulation in the subcutaneous tissue.

HP:0025673.name: Loculated ascites
HP:0025673.definition: A type of ascites (peritoneal fluid collection) that is divided into loculi (compartments) by septa (fibrous walls). Ascites fluid can become loculated when confined by adhesions, malignancy or infection.

HP:0025674.name: Meconium pseudocyst
HP:0025674.definition: A meconium-containing cyst in the peritoneal space . Meconium pseudocysts form in the presence of meconium peritonitis, which is defined as a sterile peritonitis caused by escape of meconium from the intestinal tract into the general peritoneal cavity during the fetal or perinatal period. When the extruded meconium becomes walled off, it can form a rim-calcified mass representing the meconium pseudocyst.

HP:0025675.name: Premature closure of the ductus arteriosus
HP:0025675.definition: A prenatal partial or complete closure of the ductus arteriosus (i.e., prior to delivery).

HP:0025676.name: Fetal pleural effusion
HP:0025676.definition: Fetal pleural effusion is the accumulation of excess fluid in the layers of tissue (pleura) lining the lungs and wall of the chest. It may be primary, also termed hydrothorax, occurring as an isolated finding or it may be secondary, most commonly resulting from non-immune hydrops.

HP:0025677.name: Fetal chylothorax
HP:0025677.definition: The presence of chyle (a type of lipid-rich lymph) in the pleural space (the space surrounding the lung) as observed in a fetus.

HP:0025678.name: Fetal hydrothorax
HP:0025678.definition: Accumulation of lymphatic fluid in the pleural space. This finding is usually observed by prenatal sonography. Once neonatal feeding is established and the lymphatic fluid contains chyle, transformation to chylothorax may be observed.

HP:0025679.name: Diskitis
HP:0025679.definition: Inflammation of an intervertebral disk or disk space.

HP:0025680.name: Compound muscle action potential amplitude facilitation
HP:0025680.definition: Compound muscle action potential amplitude (CMAP) facilitation denotes an increase in tendon reflexes, strength, or CMAP amplitude after 10 seconds of maximal voluntary contraction.

HP:0025681.name: Distal clavicular thinning
HP:0025681.definition: Abnormally reduced diameter (cross section) of the clavicles that is limited to the distal region.

HP:0025682.name: Crouch gait
HP:0025682.definition: A gait disturbance that is characterized by excessive ankle dorsiflexion, knee and hip flexion during the stance phase.

HP:0025683.name: Abnormal amyloid beta 42 peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025683.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of amyloid beta 42 peptide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). Amyloid beta is a peptide of 36-43 amino acids that is processed from the Amyloid precursor protein. ABeta42, which is 42 amino acids in length, is the longer form.

HP:0025684.name: Decreased amyloid beta 42 peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025684.definition: A reduction from the normal concentration of amyloid beta 42 peptide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0025685.name: Increased amyloid beta 42 peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025685.definition: An elevation above the normal concentration of amyloid beta 42 peptide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0025686.name: Abnormal amyloid beta 40 peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025686.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of amyloid beta 42 peptide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). Amyloid beta is a peptide of 36-43 amino acids that is processed from the Amyloid precursor protein. ABeta40, which is 40 amino acids in length, is the shorter form.

HP:0025687.name: Increased amyloid beta 40 peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025687.definition: An elevation above the normal concentration of amyloid beta 40 peptide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0025688.name: Abnormal amyloid beta peptide CSF concentration
HP:0025688.definition: Any anomaly in the concentration of a cleaved APP amyloid beta protein fragment in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0025689.name: Extra-abdominal umbilical vein varix
HP:0025689.definition: Focal dilatation of the extra-abdominal portion of the umbilical vein. An extra-abdominal umbilical varix is difficult to diagnose prenatally as it can appear like a cyst on ultrasound prior to birth.

HP:0025690.name: Fetal intra-abdominal umbilical vein varix
HP:0025690.definition: Fetal intra-abdominal umbilical vein varix (FIUVV) is defined by the focal dilatation of the fetal umbilical vein between its entry in the abdomen and its ending in the portal system. The dilatation can be defined using one of the following criteria: a portion of intra-abdominal umbilical vein that is at least 50% wider than the non-dilated portion; a dilatation of 9 mm or more, or a dilatation greater than 2 SD above the mean value for gestational age.

HP:0025691.name: Impaired fasting glucose
HP:0025691.definition: Impaired fasting glucose (IFG) is indicated by a fasting plasma glucose above normal but below the diabetic range. Levels between 110 mg/dl (6.1 mmol/l) to 125 mg/dl (6.9 mmol/l) are diagnostic of IFG.

HP:0025692.name: Atelencephaly
HP:0025692.definition: A defect of development of the brain characterized by absence of the telencephalon (embryonic structure from which the mature cerebrum develops).

HP:0025693.name: Pituitary macroadenoma
HP:0025693.definition: A pituitary gland adenoma that is larger than 10mm.

HP:0025694.name: Pituitary microadenoma
HP:0025694.definition: A pituitary adenoma that is less than 10 mm in diameter.

HP:0025695.name: Mucus plug
HP:0025695.definition: Mucus that is abnormally thick in consistency (ie, inspissated) and plugs the airway is known as a mucus plug. Mucus plugs consist of mucins and cells and can partially or completely obstruct one or more airways and cause serious consequences, including atelectasis and recurrent infection.

HP:0025696.name: Airway casts
HP:0025696.definition: A replicate of airways from accumulated and condensed mucous and cellular material. These semisolid occlusions take the shape of the airway within they are formed, leading to obstruction of the tracheobronchial tree with consecutive respiratory insufficiency. Based on their principal composition, one can differentiate fibrin casts and mucin casts. Plastic bronchitis is the name of the condition characterized by the formation of airway casts.

HP:0025697.name: Fibrin casts
HP:0025697.definition: A type of airway casts that consist of plasma components and inflammatory cells.

HP:0025698.name: Mucin casts
HP:0025698.definition: A type of airway casts that consist of impacted mucus.

HP:0025699.name: Perisylvian FDG hypermetabolism
HP:0025699.definition: 18F-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography and computed tomography (FDG-PET/CT) evaluates the glucose metabolism of the brain. FDG uptake is interpreted to represent glycolysis. This term therefore represents an abnormally increased FDG uptake (increased glucose metabolism) in the region of the brain that surrounds the Sylvian fissure.

HP:0025700.name: Anhydramnios
HP:0025700.definition: A complete or near-complete lack of amniotic fluid surrounding a fetus. This finding can be observed sonographically in the third trimesters if the deepest pocket of amniotic fluid is less than or equal to 2 cm.

HP:0025701.name: Distended jugular lymphatic sacs
HP:0025701.definition: The jugular lymphatic sacs (JLS) are a physiological and temporary part of fetal lymphatic development. They are formed from small buds of lymphatic endothelial cells arising from the internal jugular veins. By 14 weeks gestation they have developed into lymphatic nodes which drain into the systemic circulation. Visibility of JLS on ultrasound past 14 weeks of gestation implies distension and this may be associated with raised nuchal translucency.

HP:0033035.name: Abnormal Schwann cell morphology
HP:0033035.definition: Abnormality of schwann cells, glial cells that ensheath axons of neurons in the peripheral nervous system and are necessary for their maintenance and function.

HP:0033036.name: Decreased nasal nitric oxide
HP:0033036.definition: Reduced level of nasal nitric oxide (nNO). Current American Thoracic Society/European Respiratory Society (ATS/ERS) guidelines for nNO measurements recommend air aspiration via a nasal probe while the subject exhales through the mouth against resistance in order to maintain velum closure.

HP:0033038.name: Anti-RNA-polymerase-III-autoantibody positivity
HP:0033038.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to RNA-polymerase III.

HP:0033039.name: Increased circulating precipitin level
HP:0033039.definition: The presence of high titers of antigen-precipitating IgG in the serum.

HP:0033040.name: Anti-Sm antibody positivity
HP:0033040.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to seven proteins that consist of a core of small nuclear ribonucleoprotein (snRNP) particles.

HP:0033041.name: Cytokine storm
HP:0033041.definition: Excessive or uncontrolled release of proinflammatory cytokines.

HP:0033042.name: Abnormal chorion morphology
HP:0033042.definition: Any structural anomaly of the fetal part of the placenta, which is known as the chorion.

HP:0033043.name: Edematous chorionic villi
HP:0033043.definition: Swelling of the chorionic villi owing to fluid accumulation.

HP:0033044.name: Motor regression
HP:0033044.definition: Loss of previously achieved motor skills, as manifested by loss of developmental motor milestones.

HP:0033045.name: Bipedal edema
HP:0033045.definition: A palpable swelling in both feet and ankles caused by an increase in interstitial fluid volume (excess fluid).

HP:0033046.name: Michaelis-Gutmann bodies
HP:0033046.definition: Basophilic intracytoplasmic inclusions in macrophages. The inclusions have a small, round laminated appearance. Electron microscopy of Michaelis-Gutmann bodies exhibits partially digested bacteria.

HP:0033047.name: Body ache
HP:0033047.definition: Body ache is a complaint that is often used to denote vague symptoms of mild fatigue, lethargy, or dull aches. We will define it here to mean a dull and poorly localizable pain that is described by the affected individual to affect multiple joints or body parts or even the entire body.

HP:0033048.name: Substantia nigra hypointensity on susceptibility-weighted imaging
HP:0033048.definition: Hypointence (dark) appearance of the substantia nigra inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).

HP:0033049.name: Globus pallidus hypointensity on susceptibility-weighted imaging
HP:0033049.definition: Hypointence (dark) appearance of the globus pallidus inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).

HP:0033050.name: Pharyngalgia
HP:0033050.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the throat.

HP:0033051.name: Impaired executive functioning
HP:0033051.definition: A disturbance of executive functioning, which is broadly defined as the set of abilities that allow for the planning, executing, monitoring, and self-correcting of goal-directed behavior while inhibiting task-irrelevant behavior. At least some degree of executive skill is needed to complete most cognitive tasks, and deficits in executive abilities are central to many clinical conditions, including fronto-temporal dementia.

HP:0033052.name: Non-epileptic seizure
HP:0033052.definition: Psychogenic non-epileptic seizures (PNES) are not abnormal perceptions or abnormal beliefs/judgments, nor are they epileptic attacks. They are behaviors that simulate epileptic attacks, not fully consciously.

HP:0033053.name: Pseudoseizure
HP:0033053.definition: Sudden, involuntary seizure-like attacks that, unlike epileptic seizures, are not related to electrographic ictal discharges.

HP:0033054.name: Myoclonic tremor
HP:0033054.definition: A tremor-like cortical myoclonus. The tremulous movements are in fact small, high-frequency myoclonic jerks, induced by posture or action. They can be mild, but can also be more incapacitating. When present in the lower limbs, these may lead to gait disorders and even drop attacks. These tremor-like movements during action can be mistaken for essential tremor or epileptic seizures.

HP:0033055.name: Impaired ability to plan
HP:0033055.definition: Impaired ability to anticipate future events, implement instructions or goals, and develop appropriate steps ahead of time in order to carry out a task or activity.

HP:0033056.name: Impaired ability to organize
HP:0033056.definition: Impaired ability to bring order to information, actions, or materials to achieve a goal or to follow an established organized routine.

HP:0033057.name: Decreased circulating terminal complement component concentration
HP:0033057.definition: Concentration below the lower limit of normal of one or more components of the the terminal membrane attack complex (MAC) portion of complement, which represents the lytic, pore-forming part of the system. The MAC comprises seven components: C5b, C6, C7, C8 (a heterotrimer composed of C8alpha, C8beta and C8gamma) and multiple copies of C9.

HP:0033058.name: Decreased circulating complement C7 concentration
HP:0033058.definition: Concentration of the complement component C7 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0033059.name: Decreased circulating complement C6 concentration
HP:0033059.definition: Concentration of the complement component C6 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0033060.name: Decreased circulating complement C5 concentration
HP:0033060.definition: Concentration of the complement component C5 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0033061.name: Increased factor IX activity
HP:0033061.definition: Elevated activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.

HP:0033062.name: Abnormal factor IX activity
HP:0033062.definition: Abnormal activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.

HP:0033063.name: Shortened sleep phase
HP:0033063.definition: A tendency to sleep fewer hours than usual while feeling well-rested.

HP:0033064.name: Renal interstitial globotriaosylceramide inclusions
HP:0033064.definition: Accumulation of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) in kidney tissues, which can be quantified as the number of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) inclusions/kidney interstitial capillary (KIC).

HP:0033065.name: Mild albuminuria
HP:0033065.definition: The presence of mildly increased concentrations of albumin in the urine, defined as an albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR) less than 30 mg/gm (less than 3.4 mg/mmol).

HP:0033066.name: Severe albuminuria
HP:0033066.definition: The presence of severely increased concentrations of albumin in the urine, defined as an albumin-creatinine ratio greater than 300 mg/gm (greater than 34 mg/mmol).

HP:0033068.name: Medication crystalluria
HP:0033068.definition: A variety of drugs may occasionally cause transient crystalluria, in isolation or in conjunction with other urinary abnormalities. Overdose, dehydration, or hypoalbuminaemia, which increases the unbound drug which is ultrafiltrated by the glomerulus, are the factors usually favoring the precipitation of crystals within the tubular lumina. In some cases, medication-induced crystalluria has a distinct phenotypic appearance. For instance, Sulphadiazine crystals appear as strongly birefringent 'shocks of wheat' or 'shells' with an amber color. Acyclovir crystals are birefringent and needle-shaped, and when present in abundance give to urine a silky and opalescent macroscopic appearance.

HP:0033069.name: Renal interstitial IgG4+ plasma cell infiltration
HP:0033069.definition: An increased number of IgG4+ plasma cells in the interstitial space of the kidney.

HP:0033070.name: Impaired self monitoring
HP:0033070.definition: Impaired ability to track awareness of the effect that one's behavior has on others and how it compares with standards or expectations for behavior.

HP:0033071.name: Impaired task monitoring
HP:0033071.definition: Impaired ability to keep track of one's problem-solving success or failure, and to identify and correct mistakes during performance of a goal.

HP:0033072.name: Abnormal macroscopic urine appearance
HP:0033072.definition: Anomalous physical appearance (color, cloudiness, clarity) or odor of urine.

HP:0033073.name: Urate tophus
HP:0033073.definition: Intradermal urate crystal deposits appeared as small, superficial, pustule-like, whitish lesions. The lesions may be the focus of inflammatory episodes with increasing pain, swelling, and erythema of the intradermal tophi.

HP:0033074.name: Steroid-responsive anemia
HP:0033074.definition: Amelioration of anemia upon treatment with a steroid medication.

HP:0033075.name: Inappropriately normal thyroid-stimulating hormone level
HP:0033075.definition: A normal or elevated serum thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) level in the face of an elevation in circulating FT4 and/or FT3.

HP:0033076.name: Abnormal circulating free T4 concentration
HP:0033076.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of free thyroxine (T4) in the blood circulation. Circulating T4 is almost entirely bound to specific transport proteins such as thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG) but it is the unbound (free) fraction that is able to enter tissues and exert effects.

HP:0033077.name: Increased circulating free T4 concentration
HP:0033077.definition: An elevated concentration of free thyroxine (fT4) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033078.name: Decreased circulating free T4 concentration
HP:0033078.definition: A reduced concentration of free thyroxine (fT4) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033079.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thyroid gland
HP:0033079.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the thyroid gland.

HP:0033080.name: Abnormal TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0033080.definition: Thyrotrophin-releasing hormone (TRH) is a hypothalamic tripeptide synthesized by, stored within, and released from the hypothalamus. It stimulates the synthesis and release of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) from the anterior pituitary gland. Following administration of exogenous TRH, a transient increase in serum TSH is expected. This term refers to an abnormal response in the TRH stimulation test.

HP:0033081.name: Absent TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0033081.definition: Failure to increase serum TSH levels in response to a TRH stimulation test.

HP:0033082.name: Reduced TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0033082.definition: A lower than normal TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test.

HP:0033083.name: Increased circulating farnesol concentration
HP:0033083.definition: An elevated level of farnesol in the blood circulation.

HP:0033084.name: Abnormal antral follicle count
HP:0033084.definition: Any deviation from a count of antral follicles that is normal for age. Antral follicles appear as small fluid-filled sacs that contain an immature egg. Antral follicle count can be measured (usually on day 2-5 of the menstrual cycle) by transvaginal ultrasound. The number of antral follicles may reflect ovarian reserve.

HP:0033085.name: Reduced antral follicle count
HP:0033085.definition: A count of antral follicles that is lower than normal for age.

HP:0033086.name: Increased antral follicle count
HP:0033086.definition: A count of antral follicles that is higher than normal for age.

HP:0033087.name: Quotidian fever
HP:0033087.definition: Fever that occurs at daily intervals.

HP:0033088.name: Valinuria
HP:0033088.definition: Urine valine level above the normal range.

HP:0033089.name: Branched-chain aminoaciduria
HP:0033089.definition: An increased level of a branched chain family amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033090.name: Increased aromatic amino acid level in urine
HP:0033090.definition: An elevated level of an aromatic amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033091.name: Tyrosinuria
HP:0033091.definition: An abnormally increased level of tyrosine in the urine.

HP:0033092.name: Increased urine succinate level
HP:0033092.definition: The concentration of succinate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033093.name: Increased glutamine family amino acid level in urine
HP:0033093.definition: An elevated level of an glutamine family amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033094.name: Increased urine glutamate level
HP:0033094.definition: An increased concentration of glutamate in the urine.

HP:0033095.name: Increased sulfur amino acid level in urine
HP:0033095.definition: An elevated level of a sulfur-containing amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033096.name: Increased aspartate family amino acid level in urine
HP:0033096.definition: An elevated level of an aspartate family amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033097.name: Increased urine proteinogenic amino acid derivative level
HP:0033097.definition: An elevated urine level of a compound that is derived from an amino acid.

HP:0033098.name: Increased urinary non-proteinogenic amino acid level
HP:0033098.definition: An increased level in the urine of an alpha-amino acid which is not a member of the group of 23 proteinogenic amino acids.

HP:0033099.name: Increased serine family amino acid in urine
HP:0033099.definition: An increased level of a serine family amino acid in the urine.

HP:0033100.name: Increased proteinogenic amino acid level in urine
HP:0033100.definition: An elevated level of a proteinogenic amino acid in the urine. These are the 23 alpha-amino acids that are precursors to proteins, and are incorporated into proteins during translation. The group includes the 20 amino acids encoded by the nuclear genes of eukaryotes together with selenocysteine, pyrrolysine, and N-formylmethionine.

HP:0033101.name: Elevated urine aconitic acid level
HP:0033101.definition: An abnormally increased level of aconitic acid in the urine.

HP:0033102.name: Monkey wrench femoral neck
HP:0033102.definition: The femoral neck region shows medial metaphyseal beaking and a significant enlargement of the lesser trochanter (with some enlargement also of the greater trochanter), producing a monkey wrench (Swedish key) configuration of the proximal femur. A monkey wrench refers to a type of adjustable wrench with one fixed and one adjustable jaw at right angles to a straight handle.

HP:0033103.name: Elevated circulating CHI3L1 level
HP:0033103.definition: Increased concentration of chitinase 3-like 1 (CHI3L1) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033104.name: Inappropriate absence of fever
HP:0033104.definition: Failure to develop fever in the presence of an infection that normally would be expected to elicit a febrile response.

HP:0033105.name: Interhypothalamic adhesion
HP:0033105.definition: An abnormal parenchymal band connecting the medial margins of the left and right hypothalami across the third ventricle.

HP:0033106.name: Elevated circulating D-dimer concentration
HP:0033106.definition: An increased concentration of D-dimers, a marker of fibrin degradation, in the blood circulation.

HP:0033107.name: Abnormal circulating proteinogenic amino acid concentration
HP:0033107.definition: An elevated level of a proteinogenic amino acid in the blood circulation. These are the 23 alpha-amino acids that are precursors to proteins, and are incorporated into proteins during translation. The group includes the 20 amino acids encoded by the nuclear genes of eukaryotes together with selenocysteine, pyrrolysine, and N-formylmethionine.

HP:0033108.name: Abnormal circulating proteinogenic amino acid derivative concentration
HP:0033108.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a compound that is derived from an amino acid.

HP:0033109.name: Abnormal circulating non-proteinogenic amino acid concentration
HP:0033109.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of an alpha-amino acid which is not a member of the group of 23 proteinogenic amino acids.

HP:0033110.name: Elevated circulating alpha-aminobutyric acid concentration
HP:0033110.definition: An abnormally increased level of alpa-aminobutyric acid in the blood circulation. Alpha-aminobutyric acid alpha-amino acid that is butyric acid bearing a single amino substituent located at position 2.

HP:0033111.name: 3-hydroxyisovaleric aciduria
HP:0033111.definition: Concentration of 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid in the urine above the normal range.

HP:0033112.name: Elevated circulating apolipoprotein C-III concentration
HP:0033112.definition: An increased concentration in blood of apolipoprotein C-III, a protein component of triglyceride (TG)-rich lipoproteins (TRLs) including very low density lipoproteins (VLDL), high density lipoproteins (HDL) and chylomicrons.

HP:0033113.name: Gallop rhythm
HP:0033113.definition: In the normal heart cycle, two heart sounds can be heard by auscultation per cycle: S1 and S2. A gallop rhythm refers to the presence of three or four heart sounds per cardiac cycle, which is said to resemble the gallop of a horse.

HP:0033114.name: Quadruple gallop rhythm
HP:0033114.definition: A type of gallop rhythm in which both the third and the fourth sounds are present.

HP:0033115.name: Elevated circulating tenascin-C level
HP:0033115.definition: Abnormally increased concentration of tenascin-C in the blood circulation.

HP:0033116.name: Duodenal gastric metaplasia
HP:0033116.definition: Foci of gastric-type mucus-secreting cells interspersed between duodenal enterocytes. These foci of gastric epithelial cells contain Periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive neutral mucin and lack a brush border.

HP:0033117.name: Duodenitis
HP:0033117.definition: Inflammation of the lining of the upper small intestine (duodenum).

HP:0033118.name: Abnormal right ventricular function
