HP:0033118.definition: Anomalous physiology (function) of the right ventricle.

HP:0033119.name: Elevated right ventricular systolic pressure
HP:0033119.definition: Elevation of right ventricular systolic pressure (RVSP) above normal limits. In adults, RVSP is normally 20-30 mmHg.

HP:0033120.name: Nummular eczema
HP:0033120.definition: A type of eczema characterized by pruritic coin-shaped patches on the skin. Nummular eczema most commonly occurs on the extremities, particularly the legs, but may occur anywhere on the trunk, hands, or feet

HP:0033121.name: Barking cough
HP:0033121.definition: A cough with a characteristic sound that has been compared to a seal's bark.

HP:0033122.name: Absent P wave
HP:0033122.definition: The P wave that normally precedes each QRS complex by a fixed PR interval of 120 to 200 milliseconds is not present.

HP:0033123.name: Elevated circulating osteopontin level
HP:0033123.definition: Abnormally increased level of osteopontin in the blood circulation

HP:0033124.name: Increased serum sorbitol concentration
HP:0033124.definition: An increased level of sorbitol in the blood circulation.

HP:0033125.name: Follicular lymphoma
HP:0033125.definition: An indolent B cell lymphoproliferative disorder of transformed follicular center B cells. Follicular lymphoma is characterized by diffuse lymphadenopathy, bone marrow involvement, splenomegaly and less commonly other extranodal sites of involvement.

HP:0033126.name: Cutaneous necrosis
HP:0033126.definition: Skin and subcutaneous tissue necrosis (tissue death). Clinically, cutaneous necrosis may present as a painful and extremely tender black eschar (dead tissue found in a full-thickness wound) surrounded by dusky grey-red colored skin.

HP:0033127.name: Abnormality of the musculoskeletal system
HP:0033127.definition: An anomaly of the musculoskeletal system, which consists of the bones of the skeleton, muscles, cartilage, tendons, ligaments, joints, and other connective tissue. The musculoskeletal system supports the weight of the body, maintains body position and produces movements of the body or of parts of the body.

HP:0033128.name: Delayed ability to crawl
HP:0033128.definition: A failure to achieve the ability to crawl at an appropriate developmental stage. Normal infant motor development is marked by a series of postural milestones including learning to crawl on hands and knees between the ages of 6 and 10 months.

HP:0033129.name: Abnormal shoulder physiology
HP:0033129.definition: Anopmalous function of the shoulder. The shoulder is a ball-and-socket joint that is made up of humerus, scapula and clavicle, which are connected by the sternoclavicular joint (SC), the acromioclavicular joint (AC), the glenohumeral joint (GH), and the scapulothoracic joint (ST). The GH, AC and SC joints link the upper extremity to the axial skeleton at the thorax and enable movement at the shoulder joint: flexion, extension, and rotation of the arm.

HP:0033130.name: Abnormal renal echogenicity
HP:0033130.definition: Anomalous echogenicity of the kidney on ultrasound examination.

HP:0033131.name: Renal medullary hyperechogenicity
HP:0033131.definition: Increased echogenecity of the medullary region of the kidney.

HP:0033132.name: Renal cortical hyperechogenicity
HP:0033132.definition: Increased echogenecity of the kidney cortex.

HP:0033134.name: Abdominal adhesions
HP:0033134.definition: Fibrous bands (i.e., bands of scar-like tissue) that span two or more intra-abdominal organs and/or the inner abdominal wall (i.e. peritoneal membrane).

HP:0033135.name: Hepatic infarction
HP:0033135.definition: Hepatic infarction is defined as areas of coagulative necrosis from hepatocyte cell death caused by local ischemia. Liver infarctions appear as hypoechoic nonvascular regions on conventional and Doppler sonography.

HP:0033136.name: Lymph node abscess
HP:0033136.definition: An inflamed lymph node that is filled with pus.

HP:0033137.name: Abnormal pulmonary alveolar system morphology
HP:0033137.definition: A structural abnormality of the pulmonary acinus, alveolar parenchyma, or alveoli.

HP:0033138.name: Right atrial thrombus
HP:0033138.definition: A thrombus (i.e., a blood clot formed in situ within the vascular system) located in the right atrium of the heart.

HP:0033139.name: Elevated circulating uracil concentration
HP:0033139.definition: Concentration of uracil in the blood circulation is above the normal range.

HP:0033140.name: Blake's pouch cyst
HP:0033140.definition: The presence of an upwardly displaced normal cerebellar vermis, normal appearance of the fastigium, tentorium and size of the cisterna magna.

HP:0033141.name: Severe SARS-CoV-2 infection
HP:0033141.definition: Unusually severe clinical course of SARS-CoV-2 infection, manifested clinically by features such as dyspnea and hypoxia with diffuse bilateral ground-glass opacities of the lungs on computed tomographic scan with progressive respiratory insufficiency necessitating oxygen supplementation or mechanical ventilation.

HP:0033142.name: Long nasal bridge
HP:0033142.definition: Increased superior-inferior length of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose.

HP:0033143.name: Jejunitis
HP:0033143.definition: Inflammation of the lining of the middle section of the small intestine.

HP:0033144.name: Abnormal circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
HP:0033144.definition: Any deviation of the concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood from the normal range.

HP:0033145.name: Increased circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
HP:0033145.definition: Elevated concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood circulation.

HP:0033146.name: Elevated circulating methylsuccinic acid concentration
HP:0033146.definition: Increased concentration of methylsuccinic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0033147.name: Abnormal circulating short-chain fatty-acid concentration
HP:0033147.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a short-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0033148.name: Increased circulating isovaleric acid concentration
HP:0033148.definition: Increased concentration of isovaleric acid, a C5, branched-chain saturated fatty acid, in the blood concentration.

HP:0033149.name: Intrahepatic bile duct dilatation
HP:0033149.definition: Increased diameter (caliber) of intrahepatic bile ducts (bile ducts that transport bile between the Canals of Hering and the interlobar bile ducts).

HP:0033150.name: Anorectal abscess
HP:0033150.definition: An abscess located at the junction of the anal canal and the rectum.

HP:0033151.name: Abnormal pharynx morphology
HP:0033151.definition: A structural anomaly of the pharynx.

HP:0033152.name: Abnormal pharynx physiology
HP:0033152.definition: A functional anomaly of the pharynx.

HP:0033153.name: Elevated circulating dodecenoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033153.definition: An abnormally increased circulation of dodecenoylcarnitine, C12:1, in the blood circulation.

HP:0033154.name: Elevated circulating deoxypyridinoline concentration
HP:0033154.definition: An increased concentration of lysyl-pyridinoline (deoxypyridinoline) cross-links in the blood circulation.

HP:0033155.name: Elevated circulating L-alloisoleucine concentration
HP:0033155.definition: Abnormally increased concentration of L-alloisoleucine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033156.name: Elevated urine L-alloisoleucine level
HP:0033156.definition: Abnormally increased level of L-alloisoleucine in the urine.

HP:0033157.name: Elevated circulating 3-methylhistidine concentration
HP:0033157.definition: Abnormal increase of the concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033158.name: Reduced respiratory ciliary beating frequency
HP:0033158.definition: An abnormal reduction in the number of beats per unit time of the respiratory cilia.

HP:0033159.name: Reduced urinary inosine level
HP:0033159.definition: The amount of inosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal. Inosine is a purine nucleoside in which hypoxanthine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.

HP:0033160.name: Decreased urinary guanosine level
HP:0033160.definition: The amount of guanosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal. Guanosine is a purine nucleoside in which guanine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.

HP:0033161.name: Abnormal urinary purine level
HP:0033161.definition: Any deviation from the normal amount of a purine compound in the urine. Purines are aromatic heterocyclic compounds containing a purine moiety, which is formed a pyrimidine-ring ring fused to an imidazole ring. Two of the four deoxyribonucleotides (deoxyadenosine and deoxyguanosine) and two of the four ribonucleotides (adenosine, or AMP, and guanosine, or GMP) are purines.

HP:0033162.name: Abnormal urinary pyrimidine level
HP:0033162.definition: Any deviation from the normal amount of a pyrimidine compound in the urine. Pyrimidines and pyrimidine derivatives are compounds containing a pyrimidne ring, which is a six-member aromatic heterocycle which consists of two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 3) and four carbon atoms. The nucleotides cytosine, thymine and uracil are pyrimidines.

HP:0033163.name: Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth
HP:0033163.definition: An increased number and/or abnormal type of bacteria in the small bowel. Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth has been defined as the presence of greater than one hundred thousand bacteria (i.e. colony-forming units, CFU) per mL of proximal jejunal aspiration. The normal value is ten thousand or few CFU/ml.

HP:0033164.name: Focal active colitis
HP:0033164.definition: Focal active colitis (FAC) is characterized by focal crypt damage caused by neutrophils. FAC is characterized by an inflammatory infiltrate consisting of intraepithelial neutrophils and/or neutrophils invading the lumen of the criptae, with no other microscopic alteration of the colonic mucosa and, in particular, without the presence of signs of chronic inflammation.

HP:0033165.name: Necrotizing enterocolitis
HP:0033165.definition: Inflammation of the intestine leading to bacterial invasion causing cellular damage and death which causes necrosis of the colon and intestine.

HP:0033166.name: Recurrent viral upper respiratory tract infections
HP:0033166.definition: An increased susceptibility to viral upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent viral upper respiratory tract infections (otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).

HP:0033167.name: Neutrophilic urticarial dermatosis
HP:0033167.definition: A neutrophilic interstitial, perivascular and/or perieccrine infiltrate with leukocytoclasia. Notably, leukocytoclastic vasculitis is not present.

HP:0033168.name: Reduced mevalonate kinase activity
HP:0033168.definition: Abnormally reduced activity of mevalonate kinase, which is a key enzyme in the mevalonate biosynthetic pathway that leads to the synthesis of both cholesterol and nonsterol isoprenoids.

HP:0033169.name: Reduced total lung capacity
HP:0033169.definition: Abnormally reduced volume of air in the lungs upon the maximum effort of inspiration.

HP:0033170.name: Abnormal skinfold thickness measurement
HP:0033170.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of a skinfold thickness, which quantifies the amount of subcutaneous fat when the skin is pinched by specialized calipers.

HP:0033171.name: Abnormal triceps skinfold thickness
HP:0033171.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the thickness of the triceps skinfold, which quantifies the amount of subcutaneous fat when the skin is pinched by specialized calipers.

HP:0033172.name: Increased triceps skinfold thickness
HP:0033172.definition: Increased thickness of the triceps skinfold, which is measured halfway down the back of the upper arm is increased.

HP:0033173.name: Milky appearance of bronchoalveolar lavage fluid
HP:0033173.definition: Return of lavage fluid with a milky appearance due to the accumulation of a mixture of pulmonary surfactant, which is a lipoprotein complex, in the alveolar space.

HP:0033174.name: Bloody bronchoalveolar lavage fluid
HP:0033174.definition: Return of lavage fluid characteristically has a bloody appearance in pulmonary alveolar hemorrhage. This is due to admixture of blood, which typically increases with each consecutive lavage portion. Microscopically erythrocytes can be seen. After 24 to 48 h macrophages contain phagocytosed erythrocytes, indicating previous bleeding.

HP:0033175.name: Elevated circulating 5-oxoproline concentration
HP:0033175.definition: Concentration of L-pyroglutamic acid in the blood is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033176.name: Submandibular lymph node enlargement
HP:0033176.definition: Increased size of the lymph nodes that are located beneath the mandible (lower jaw).

HP:0033177.name: Elevated circulating suberic acid concentration
HP:0033177.definition: An increased concentration of suberic acid in the blood circulation. Suberic acid is an alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,6-dicarboxy derivative of hexane.

HP:0033178.name: Increased circulating interleukin 8 concentration
HP:0033178.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-8 in the circulation.

HP:0033179.name: Elevated circulating aconitic acid concentration
HP:0033179.definition: Concentration of aconitic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033180.name: Torsion of appendix of testis
HP:0033180.definition: The appendix testis or hydatid of Morgagni, is a vestigial remnant of the Müllerian duct located on the superior pole of the testicle between the testis and epididymis. Although this appendage has no vital function, it is present in 50% of males. Torsion of twisting of this vestigial remnant can be incredibly painful, but usually requires no medical intervention.

HP:0033181.name: Spinal epidural abscess
HP:0033181.definition: Spinal epidural abscess (SEA) is caused by a suppurative infection in the epidural space. The mass effect of the abscess can compress and reduce blood flow to the spinal cord, conus medullaris, or cauda equina.

HP:0033182.name: Increased circulating cathepsin D level
HP:0033182.definition: An increase in concentration of cathepsin D in the blood circulation.

HP:0033183.name: Bilobed right lung
HP:0033183.definition: A developmental defect of pulmonary lobation characterized by the presence of only two lobes of the right lung.

HP:0033185.name: Triggered by EBV infection
HP:0033185.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by infection by the Epstein-Barr virus.

HP:0033186.name: Misalignment of the pulmonary veins
HP:0033186.definition: The term is commonly used to describe a putative abnormal location of pulmonary vein branches adjacent to pulmonary arteries within the same adventitial sheath. However, evidence has been provided that the vessels in question are not pulmonary veins, however represent dilated bronchial veins.

HP:0033187.name: Hyperimidodipeptiduria
HP:0033187.definition: Elevated levels of proline-containing dipeptides in urine.

HP:0033188.name: Cystic acne
HP:0033188.definition: A severe type of acne characterized by the formation of cysts enclosing a mixture of keratin and sebum.

HP:0033189.name: Radiculomegaly
HP:0033189.definition: Tooth root length more than 2 SD above mean, or subjectively apparently increased tooth root length.

HP:0033190.name: Hypertrichotic hyperpigmented patch
HP:0033190.definition: A large nonpalpable spot of the skin over 1 cm in dimension with increased pigmentation and increased hair growth.

HP:0033191.name: Increased circulating selenium concentration
HP:0033191.definition: An increased concentration of selenium in the blood circulation.

HP:0033192.name: Decreased circulating selenium concentration
HP:0033192.definition: An abnormally reduced concentration of selenium in the blood circulation.

HP:0033193.name: Ballooning hepatocyte degeneration
HP:0033193.definition: Swelling of the hepatocyte, rounding of its contour, and alteration of the cytoplasm, which takes on a reticulated, rarefied, or flocculant quality. The cytoplasm of the ballooned hepatocytes often contains clumps of eosinophilic ropey material known as Mallory-Denk bodies (MDBs) or Mallory hyaline, which is composed of hyperphosphorylated misfolded intermediate filaments, ubiquitin, and ubiquitin-binding protein P62.

HP:0033194.name: Perioral erythema
HP:0033194.definition: Erythema (Redness of the skin caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin) localized to the region surrounding the mouth.

HP:0033195.name: Perianal erythema
HP:0033195.definition: Erythema (Redness of the skin caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin) localized to the region surrounding the anus.

HP:0033196.name: Portal inflammation
HP:0033196.definition: Infiltration of portal fields by inflammatory cells.

HP:0033197.name: Hepatic lobular inflammation
HP:0033197.definition: Infiltration of inflammatory cells in lobules of the liver. A focus of lobular inflammation can be defined as two or more inflammatory cells (neutrophils, lymphocytes and other mononuclear cells, eosinophils and microgranulomas) within the lobule present within the sinusoids or surrounding injured hepatocytes (ballooned or apoptotic hepatocytes).

HP:0033198.name: Triggered by viral infection
HP:0033198.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by infection by a virus.

HP:0033199.name: Increased circulating interleukin 10 concentration
HP:0033199.definition: An elevation of the concentration of interleukin 10 in the blood circulation.

HP:0033200.name: Triceps hyporeflexia
HP:0033200.definition: Reduced intensity of the triceps tendon reflex.

HP:0033201.name: Biceps hyporeflexia
HP:0033201.definition: Reduced intensity of the biceps tendon reflex.

HP:0033202.name: Brachioradialis hyporeflexia
HP:0033202.definition: Reduced intensity of the brachioradialis tendon reflex.

HP:0033203.name: Brachioradialis hyperreflexia
HP:0033203.definition: Increased intensity of the brachioradialis reflex.

HP:0033204.name: Triceps hyperreflexia
HP:0033204.definition: Increased intensity of the triceps reflex.

HP:0033205.name: Biceps hyperreflexia
HP:0033205.definition: Increased intensity of the biceps reflex.

HP:0033206.name: Hyperactive Achilles reflex
HP:0033206.definition: Increased intensity of the Achilles reflex.

HP:0033207.name: Increased CD21low B cell proportion
HP:0033207.definition: Increased proportion relative to B-lymphocytes of a subset of B lymphocytes characterized by dim/low levels of CD21, i.e., CD21-/low, in flow cytometry, and additionally enriched in autoreactive clones as determined for instance by clonse showing rheumatoid factor (anti-IgG) reactivity and antibodies recognizing cytoplasmic and to a lesser extent nuclear structures.

HP:0033208.name: Alveolar capillary dysplasia
HP:0033208.definition: A developmental defect of the alveolar airspace during cananicular lung development characterized by a decreased number of pulmonary capillaries located away from the alveolar epithelium, thickened alveolar septae, media hypertrophy of small pulmonary arteries and muscularization of distal arterioles, and in some cases lymphangiectasis.

HP:0033209.name: Acinar dysplasia
HP:0033209.definition: Arrest of lung development in the pseudoglandular stage (weeks 8 to 16 of human gestation) resulting in small sized lungs, predominantly composed of bronchial and bronchiolar structures embedded in abundant loose mesenchyme that is poorly vascularized. Acinar structures are essentially absent, with no significant formation of saccules and no alveoli.

HP:0033210.name: Congenital alveolar dysplasia
HP:0033210.definition: Arrest of lung development in the cananicular stage (weeks 18 to 26 of human gestation) resulting in simplified acinar spaces, frequently with abundant intervening mesenchyme and no alveoli. In later arrest growth stages early saccular formations may be seen. May resemble the lobular maldevelopment often seen in alveolar capillary dysplasia/misaligment of the pulmonary veins without vein misalignment or marked hypertensive changes of the pulmonary arteries.

HP:0033211.name: Decreased total iron binding capacity
HP:0033211.definition: A reduction in the total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added. The latent (or free) iron binding capacity is the difference between the TIBC and the measured serum iron, corresponding to the transferrin not bound to iron, i.e., free iron binding capacity.

HP:0033212.name: Abnormal total iron binding capacity
HP:0033212.definition: Any deviation from the normal total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added.

HP:0033213.name: Elevated urine suberic acid level
HP:0033213.definition: The concentration of suberic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033214.name: Recurrent viral pneumonia
HP:0033214.definition: Increased susceptibility to viral pneumonia, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral pneumonias.

HP:0033215.name: Obliterative abnormality of the renal glomerulus

HP:0033216.name: Glomerular hyalinosis
HP:0033216.definition: Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus. Distribution can include vascular pole, perihilar, tip or neither tip, perihilar or vascular.

HP:0033217.name: Perihilar glomerular hyalinosis
HP:0033217.definition: Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at the vascular pole/perihilum.

HP:0033218.name: Glomerular hyalinosis at the tubular pole
HP:0033218.definition: Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at the tip/tubular pole.

HP:0033219.name: Glomerular hyalinosis away from the vascular and tubular poles
HP:0033219.definition: Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at neither tip nor perihilar/vascular poles. Both the vascular and the tubular pole are present in the glomerular cross section.

HP:0033220.name: 2-ethylhydracylic aciduria
HP:0033220.definition: An increased concentration of 2-ethylhydracylic acid in the urine.

HP:0033221.name: Increased CD4:CD8 ratio
HP:0033221.definition: An abnormal elevation of the relative proportion of CD4+ to CD8+ T cells.

HP:0033222.name: Inverted CD4:CD8 ratio
HP:0033222.definition: CD4:CD8 ratio less than 1, measured either as proportion of total CD3+ T cells, or in absolute numbers per microliter. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population. Normally there are relatively more CD4+ than CD8+ T cells.

HP:0033223.name: Abnormal glomerular parietal epithelial cell morphology
HP:0033223.definition: Any structural abnormality of the parietal epithelial cells that line the inside of Bowman's capsule and form an inconspicuous sheet of flat epithelial cells in continuity with the proximal tubular epithelial cells at the urinary pole and with the podocytes at the vascular pole.

HP:0033224.name: Glomerular parietal epithelial cell hyperplasia
HP:0033224.definition: Increased number of parietal epithelial cells lining Bowman's capsule. Hyperplasia leads to the cells being present in 2 or more layers, often with crowding and multilayering.

HP:0033225.name: Glomerular parietal epithelial cell hypertrophy
HP:0033225.definition: An abnormality of the glomerular parietal epithelial cells characterized by (1) Increased parietal epithelial cell size, with or without cytoplasmic protein droplets; or (2) enlarged nuclei with prominent nucleoli. Both features can be present

HP:0033226.name: Bowman capsular hyaline drops
HP:0033226.definition: An insudative accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material protruding from Bowman's capsule into the urinary space. Although not always evident by light microscopy, this material is located between Bowman's capsule and the parietal epithelial cells, in some cases associated with newly formed matrix material.

HP:0033227.name: Glomerular synechial adhesion
HP:0033227.definition: An area of basement membrane continuity between the glomerular tuft and Bowman's capsule, without intervening crescent and not adjacent to an area of segmental sclerosis.

HP:0033228.name: Triceps areflexia
HP:0033228.definition: Inability to elicit triceps tendon reflex.

HP:0033229.name: Brachioradialis areflexia
HP:0033229.definition: Inability to elicit brachioradialis tendon reflex.

HP:0011170.name: Generalized myoclonic-atonic seizure
HP:0011170.definition: A generalized myoclonic-atonic seizure is a type of generalized motor seizure characterized by a myoclonic jerk followed by an atonic motor component.

HP:0011171.name: Simple febrile seizure
HP:0011171.definition: A short generalized seizure, of a duration of <15 min, not recurring within 24 h, occurring during a febrile episode not caused by an acute disease of the nervous system intracranial infection or severe metabolic disturbance.

HP:0011172.name: Complex febrile seizure
HP:0011172.definition: A febrile seizure that has any of the following features: focal semiology (or associated with post-ictal neurologic abnormalities beyond drowsiness, such as a Todd's paresis), prolonged seizure beyond 15 minutes, or recurring (occurring more than once) in a 24 hour period.

HP:0011173.name: Focal behavior arrest seizure
HP:0011173.definition: A type of focal non-motor seizure characterized by an arrest or pause of activities, freezing, or immobilization as the predominant semiological feature throughout the seizure.

HP:0011174.name: Focal hyperkinetic seizure
HP:0011174.definition: A focal seizure characterized at onset by predominantly proximal limb or axial muscles producing irregular sequential ballistic movements, such as pedaling, pelvic thrusting, thrashing, rocking movements.

HP:0011175.name: Focal motor seizure with version
HP:0011175.definition: A type of focal motor seizure characterized by sustained, forced conjugate ocular, cephalic, and/or truncal rotation or lateral deviation from the midline as the initial semiological manifestation.

HP:0011176.name: EEG with constitutional variants
HP:0011176.definition: An EEG with constitutional variants contains waves that are rare or unusual but not generally pathologic.

HP:0011179.name: Beta-EEG
HP:0011179.definition: EEG dominated by diffuse beta-waves (>13 Hz).

HP:0011180.name: Partial beta-EEG
HP:0011180.definition: EEG dominated by diffuse beta waves (>13 Hz) with occipitally localized alpha waves (8-13 Hz).

HP:0011181.name: Low voltage EEG
HP:0011181.definition: EEG with an amplitude less than 30 microvolts without observable occipital alpha rhythm (8-13 Hz).

HP:0011182.name: Interictal epileptiform activity
HP:0011182.definition: Epileptiform activity refers to distinctive EEG waves or complexes distinguished from background activity found in in a proportion of human subjects with epilepsy, but which can also be found in subjects without seizures. Interictal epileptiform activity refers to such activity that occurs in the absence of a clinical or subclinical seizure.

HP:0011183.name: EEG with hyperventilation-induced focal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011183.definition: Focal epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0011184.name: EEG with hyperventilation-induced generalized epileptiform discharges
HP:0011184.definition: Generalized epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0011185.name: EEG with focal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011185.definition: EEG discharges recorded in particular areas of a localized (focal) abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

HP:0011186.name: Focal epileptiform discharges with limited propagation to contralateral hemisphere
HP:0011186.definition: Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to contralateral hemisphere but without secondary generalization.

HP:0011187.name: Focal EEG discharges with propagation to ipsilateral hemisphere
HP:0011187.definition: Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to the hemisphere on the same side of the brain.

HP:0011188.name: Focal EEG discharges with secondary generalization
HP:0011188.definition: Focal EEG discharges that secondarily spread to both hemispheres and can then be recorded over the entire scalp.

HP:0011189.name: Bilateral multifocal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011189.definition: Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in both hemispheres.

HP:0011190.name: Uni- and bilateral multifocal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011190.definition: Epileptiform discharges identified at multiple locations temporarily in both hemispheres and temporarily in one hemisphere.

HP:0011191.name: Unilateral multifocal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011191.definition: Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in one hemisphere.

HP:0011192.name: Polymorphic focal epileptiform discharges
HP:0011192.definition: Focal epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.

HP:0011193.name: EEG with focal spikes
HP:0011193.definition: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.

HP:0011194.name: EEG with series of focal spikes
HP:0011194.definition: Focal spikes occurring for several seconds.

HP:0011195.name: EEG with focal sharp slow waves
HP:0011195.definition: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011196.name: EEG with focal sharp waves
HP:0011196.definition: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011197.name: EEG with focal spike waves
HP:0011197.definition: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011198.name: EEG with generalized epileptiform discharges
HP:0011198.definition: EEG discharges recorded on the entire scalp typically seen in persons with epilepsy.

HP:0011199.name: EEG with generalized sharp slow waves
HP:0011199.definition: EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011200.name: EEG with generalized polymorphic epileptiform discharges
HP:0011200.definition: Generalized epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.

HP:0011204.name: EEG with continuous slow activity
HP:0011204.definition: EEG showing diffuse slowing without interruption.

HP:0011205.name: EEG with intermittent slow activity
HP:0011205.definition: Non-continuous diffuse slowing of electroencephalographic patterns.

HP:0011206.name: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 1
HP:0011206.definition: Slowing at frequencies between 7.5 and 8.5 Hz.

HP:0011207.name: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 2
HP:0011207.definition: Generalized slowing of EEG activity at frequencies between 4-7 Hz.

HP:0011208.name: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 3
HP:0011208.definition: Generalized slowing of EEG activity at frequencies between 0.5-3 Hz.

HP:0011209.name: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 4

HP:0011210.name: EEG with occipital slowing
HP:0011210.definition: Slowing in occipital areas of the scalp EEG.

HP:0011211.name: EEG with photoparoxysmal response grade I
HP:0011211.definition: Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital regions during photic stimulation.

HP:0011212.name: EEG with photoparoxysmal response grade II
HP:0011212.definition: Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital and central regions during photic stimulation.

HP:0011213.name: EEG with photoparoxysmal response grade III
HP:0011213.definition: Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital, central, temporal and parietal regions during photic stimulation.

HP:0011214.name: EEG with photoparoxysmal response grade IV
HP:0011214.definition: Occurrence of generalized epileptiform discharges during photic stimulation.

HP:0011218.name: Abnormal shape of the frontal region
HP:0011218.definition: An abnormal shape of the frontal part of the head.

HP:0011219.name: Short face
HP:0011219.definition: Facial height (length) is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or an apparent decrease in the height (length) of the face (subjective).

HP:0011220.name: Prominent forehead
HP:0011220.definition: Forward prominence of the entire forehead, due to protrusion of the frontal bone.

HP:0011221.name: Vertical forehead creases
HP:0011221.definition: Vertical soft tissue creases in the midline of the forehead, often extending from the hairline to the brow, and seen with facial expression or when the face is at rest.

HP:0011222.name: Depressed glabella
HP:0011222.definition: Posterior positioning of the glabella, i.e., of the midline forehead between the supraorbital ridges.

HP:0011223.name: Metopic depression
HP:0011223.definition: Linear vertical groove in the midline of the forehead, extending from hairline to glabella.

HP:0011225.name: Epiblepharon
HP:0011225.definition: Redundant eyelid skin pressing the eyelashes against the cornea and/or conjunctiva.

HP:0011226.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the eyelid
HP:0011226.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the eyelid.

HP:0011227.name: Elevated circulating C-reactive protein concentration
HP:0011227.definition: An abnormal elevation of the C-reactive protein level in the blood circulation.

HP:0011228.name: Horizontal eyebrow
HP:0011228.definition: An eyebrow that extends straight across the brow, without curve.

HP:0011229.name: Broad eyebrow
HP:0011229.definition: Regional increase in the width (height) of the eyebrow.

HP:0011230.name: Laterally extended eyebrow
HP:0011230.definition: An eyebrow that extends laterally beyond the orbital rim rather than turning gently downward at that location.

HP:0011231.name: Prominent eyelashes
HP:0011231.definition: Eyelashes that draw the attention of the viewer due to increased density and/or length and/or curl without meeting the criteria of trichomegaly.

HP:0011232.name: Infra-orbital fold
HP:0011232.definition: Elevated ridge(s) of skin starting well below the medial aspect of the lower lid that curves gradually upward toward and/or across the nasal bridge.

HP:0011233.name: Antihelical shelf
HP:0011233.definition: Antihelix protrusion directed more anteriorly than laterally, forming a shelf overlying the posterior concha.

HP:0011234.name: Absent antihelix
HP:0011234.definition: No discernible ridge between concha and triangular fossa and helix.

HP:0011235.name: Additional crus of antihelix
HP:0011235.definition: Supernumerary ridge or crus of the ear arising from the antihelix.

HP:0011236.name: Angulated antihelix
HP:0011236.definition: Antihelical ridge that forms an acute angle between the antitragus and its bifurcation (stem) instead of a gently curving arc.

HP:0011237.name: Broad inferior crus of antihelix
HP:0011237.definition: Increased width of the inferred cross-section of the inferior crus.

HP:0011238.name: Prominent inferior crus of antihelix
HP:0011238.definition: Increased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.

HP:0011239.name: Underdeveloped inferior crus of antihelix
HP:0011239.definition: Decreased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.

HP:0011240.name: Prominent stem of antihelix
HP:0011240.definition: Increased protrusion of the antihelical ridge, proximal to its bifurcation, relative to the prominence of the helix.

HP:0011241.name: Serpiginous stem of antihelix
HP:0011241.definition: Posterior curving of the antihelix from its origin at the antitragus, traveling initially almost perpendicular to the descending helix and obscuring some of the concha.

HP:0011242.name: Underdeveloped stem of antihelix
HP:0011242.definition: Decreased protrusion of the antihelical ridge, proximal to its bifurcation, relative to the prominence of a normal helix.

HP:0011243.name: Abnormality of inferior crus of antihelix
HP:0011243.definition: An abnormality of the inferior crus of the antihelix is the lower cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.

HP:0011244.name: Abnormality of stem of antihelix
HP:0011244.definition: An abnormality of the stem of the antihelix, which is the part below the bifurcation of the antihelix into the inferior and superior crura.

HP:0011245.name: Abnormality of superior crus of antihelix
HP:0011245.definition: An abnormality of the superior crus of the antihelix is the upper cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.

HP:0011246.name: Underdeveloped superior crus of antihelix
HP:0011246.definition: Decreased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.

HP:0011247.name: Prominent superior crus of antihelix
HP:0011247.definition: Increased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.

HP:0011248.name: Everted antitragus
HP:0011248.definition: Positioning of the antitragus at an angle perpendicular to the plane of the ear (oriented away from the plane of the ear).

HP:0011249.name: Absent antitragus
HP:0011249.definition: Absence of the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

HP:0011250.name: Bifid antitragus
HP:0011250.definition: Double rather than single peak of the antitragus.

HP:0011251.name: Underdeveloped antitragus
HP:0011251.definition: Reduction in the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.

HP:0011252.name: Cryptotia
HP:0011252.definition: Invagination of the superior part of the auricle under a fold of temporal skin.

HP:0011253.name: Type I cryptotia
HP:0011253.definition: A type of cryptotia associated with reduction in size of the antihelix and superior crus.

HP:0011254.name: Type II cryptotia
HP:0011254.definition: A type of cryptotia associated with reduction in size of the antihelix and inferior crus that are affected.

HP:0011255.name: Absent crus of helix
HP:0011255.definition: Continuum between the tragus and ascending helix, without any evidence of a posterior extension (crus) towards the concha.

HP:0011256.name: Crus of helix connected to antihelix
HP:0011256.definition: Extension of the ridge of the crus helix across the ear and connection of the crus to the antihelix.

HP:0011257.name: Serpiginous crus of helix
HP:0011257.definition: Curving course of the crus of the helix, approaching or joining the antitragus.

HP:0011258.name: Tragal bridge of crus of helix
HP:0011258.definition: The anterior origin of the crus encompasses the superior margin of the tragus, the crus overrides the upper portion of the conchal cavum and ends at the antihelix.

HP:0011259.name: Expanded terminal portion of crus of helix
HP:0011259.definition: Widening, rather than tapering, of the crus at its posterior border near the antihelix.

HP:0011260.name: Darwin notch of helix
HP:0011260.definition: Small defect of the helical fold that lies at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.

HP:0011261.name: Darwin tubercle of helix
HP:0011261.definition: Small expansion of the helical fold at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.

HP:0011262.name: Crimped helix
HP:0011262.definition: Linear, circumferential indentation in the convexity of the outer surface of the helix.

HP:0011263.name: Forward facing earlobe
HP:0011263.definition: Positioning of the anterior surface of the ear lobe in a more coronal plane than the remainder of the ear.

HP:0011264.name: Discontinuous ascending root of helix
HP:0011264.definition: Interruption between the ascending helix and the crus helix, allowing the ascending helix to be attached directly to the mastoid.

HP:0011265.name: Cleft earlobe
HP:0011265.definition: Discontinuity in the convexity of the inferior margin of the lobe.

HP:0011266.name: Microtia, first degree
HP:0011266.definition: Presence of all the normal ear components and the median longitudinal length more than two standard deviations below the mean.

HP:0011267.name: Microtia, third degree
HP:0011267.definition: Presence of some auricular structures, but none of these structures conform to recognized ear components.

HP:0011268.name: Absent tragus
HP:0011268.definition: Lack of convexity or prominence of the contour of the ridge between the bottom of the incisura and the confluence of the ascending helix and crus helix.

HP:0011269.name: Bifid tragus
HP:0011269.definition: Increased height of the tragal ridge with a shallow indentation at the apex, giving the appearance of a double peak.

HP:0011270.name: Duplicated tragus
HP:0011270.definition: A complete or partial duplication of the tragus; expected to lie anterior to the normal tragus.

HP:0011271.name: Prominent tragus
HP:0011271.definition: Increase posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.

HP:0011272.name: Underdeveloped tragus
HP:0011272.definition: Decreased posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.

HP:0011273.name: Anisocytosis
HP:0011273.definition: Abnormally increased variability in the size of erythrocytes.

HP:0011274.name: Recurrent mycobacterial infections
HP:0011274.definition: Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.

HP:0011275.name: Recurrent mycobacterium avium complex infections
HP:0011275.definition: Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial avium complex infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.

HP:0011277.name: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology

HP:0011278.name: Intrapulmonary lobar sequestration
HP:0011278.definition: A type of pulmonary sequestration that occurs within the visceral pleura of normal lung tissue, usually without communication with the tracheobronchial tree.

HP:0011279.name: Abnormality of urine bicarbonate level
HP:0011279.definition: An abnormal amount of hydrogencarbonate in the urine.

HP:0011280.name: Abnormality of urine calcium concentration
HP:0011280.definition: An abnormality of calcium concentration in the urine.

HP:0011281.name: Abnormality of urine catecholamine level
HP:0011281.definition: An abnormal amount of urinary catecholamine concentration.

HP:0011282.name: Abnormal hindbrain morphology
HP:0011282.definition: An abnormality of the hindbrain, also known as the rhombencephalon.

HP:0011283.name: Abnormal metencephalon morphology
HP:0011283.definition: An abnormality of the metencephalon. The metencephalon is the part of the hindbrain that consists of the pons and the cerebellum.

HP:0011284.name: Short-segment aganglionic megacolon
HP:0011284.definition: A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment does not extend beyond the upper sigmoid.

HP:0011285.name: Long-segment aganglionic megacolon
HP:0011285.definition: A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment extends proximal to the sigmoid.

HP:0011286.name: Total colonic aganglionosis
HP:0011286.definition: A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment comprises the entire colon.

HP:0011287.name: EEG with occipital sharp slow waves
HP:0011287.definition: EEG with sharp slow waves in the occipital region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011288.name: EEG with parietal sharp slow waves
HP:0011288.definition: EEG with sharp slow waves in the parietal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011289.name: EEG with temporal sharp slow waves
HP:0011289.definition: EEG with sharp slow waves in the temporal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011290.name: EEG with frontal sharp slow waves
HP:0011290.definition: EEG with sharp slow waves in the frontal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011291.name: EEG with central sharp slow waves
HP:0011291.definition: EEG with sharp slow waves in the central region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

HP:0011292.name: EEG with occipital sharp waves
HP:0011292.definition: EEG with sharp waves in the occipital region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011293.name: EEG with central sharp waves
HP:0011293.definition: EEG with sharp waves in the central region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011294.name: EEG with frontal sharp waves
HP:0011294.definition: EEG with sharp waves in the frontal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011295.name: EEG with parietal sharp waves
HP:0011295.definition: EEG with sharp waves in the parietal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011296.name: EEG with temporal sharp waves
HP:0011296.definition: EEG with sharp waves in the temporal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

HP:0011297.name: Abnormal digit morphology
HP:0011297.definition: A morphological abnormality of a digit, i.e., of a finger or toe.

HP:0011298.name: Prominent digit pad
HP:0011298.definition: A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips or toe tips.

HP:0011299.name: Partial absence of finger
HP:0011299.definition: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a finger.

HP:0011300.name: Broad fingertip
HP:0011300.definition: Increased width of the distal segment of a finger.

HP:0011301.name: Absent foot
HP:0011301.definition: The total absence of the foot, with no bony elements distal to the tibia or fibula.

HP:0011302.name: Long palm
HP:0011302.definition: For children from birth to 16 years of age the length of the palm is more than the 97th centile; or, the length of the palm appears relatively long compared to the finger length or the limb length.

HP:0011303.name: Convex contour of sole
HP:0011303.definition: The contour of the foot in lateral profile has a convex shape.

HP:0011304.name: Broad thumb
HP:0011304.definition: Increased thumb width without increased dorso-ventral dimension.

HP:0011305.name: Partial absence of toe
HP:0011305.definition: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a toe or hallux.

HP:0011307.name: Splayed toes
HP:0011307.definition: Divergence of digits along the anteroposterior axis (in the plane of the sole).

HP:0011308.name: Slender toe
HP:0011308.definition: Toes that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.

HP:0011309.name: Tapered toe
HP:0011309.definition: The gradual reduction in girth of the toe from proximal to distal.

HP:0011310.name: Bridged palmar crease
HP:0011310.definition: A crease that connects the proximal and distal transverse palmar creases.

HP:0011311.name: Sydney crease
HP:0011311.definition: Extension of the proximal transverse crease (five finger crease) to the ulnar edge of the palm.

HP:0011312.name: Fused nails
HP:0011312.definition: A nail plate that has a longitudinal separation with partially separated nails, each with a separate lateral radius of curvature.

HP:0011314.name: Abnormal long bone morphology
HP:0011314.definition: An abnormality of size or shape of the long bones.

HP:0011315.name: Unicoronal synostosis
HP:0011315.definition: Synostosis affecting only one of the coronal sutures.

HP:0011316.name: Left unicoronal synostosis
HP:0011316.definition: Synostosis affecting only the left coronal suture.

HP:0011317.name: Right unicoronal synostosis
HP:0011317.definition: Unicoronal synostosis affecting only the right coronal suture.

HP:0011318.name: Bicoronal synostosis
HP:0011318.definition: Synostosis affecting the right and the left coronal suture.

HP:0011319.name: Bilambdoid synostosis
HP:0011319.definition: Premature synostosis of both lambdoid sutures.

HP:0011320.name: Unilambdoid synostosis
HP:0011320.definition: Premature synostosis of only one lambdoid suture.

HP:0011321.name: Left unilambdoid synostosis
HP:0011321.definition: Premature synostosis of only the left lambdoid suture.

HP:0011322.name: Right unilambdoid synostosis
HP:0011322.definition: Premature synostosis of only the right lambdoid suture.

HP:0011323.name: Cleft of chin
HP:0011323.definition: Incomplete fusion of the chin, resulting from a developmental defect and manifesting as a midline cleft or fissure of the chin.

HP:0011324.name: Multiple suture craniosynostosis
HP:0011324.definition: Craniosynostosis involving at least 2 cranial sutures, where the exact pattern of sutures fused has not been precisely specified.

HP:0011326.name: Anterior plagiocephaly
HP:0011326.definition: Asymmetry of the anterior part of the skull.

HP:0011327.name: Posterior plagiocephaly
HP:0011327.definition: Asymmetry of the posterior part of the skull.

HP:0011329.name: Abnormality of cranial sutures
HP:0011329.definition: Any anomaly of a cranial suture, that is one of the six membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.

HP:0011330.name: Metopic synostosis
HP:0011330.definition: Premature fusion of the metopic suture.

HP:0011331.name: Hemifacial atrophy
HP:0011331.definition: Unilateral atrophy of facial tissues, including muscles, bones and skin.

HP:0011332.name: Hemifacial hypoplasia
HP:0011332.definition: Unilateral underdevelopment of the facial tissues, including muscles and bones.

HP:0011333.name: Asymmetric crying face
HP:0011333.definition: Asymmetry observed in the face of a neonate or infant whose face appears symmetric at rest and asymmetric during crying as the mouth is pulled downward on one side while not moving on the other side.

HP:0011335.name: Frontal hirsutism
HP:0011335.definition: Excessive amount of hair growth on forehead.

HP:0011336.name: Bitemporal forceps marks
HP:0011336.definition: Bilateral temporal scarlike defects, which are said to resemble forceps marks.

HP:0033650.name: Pulmonary parenchymal band
HP:0033650.definition: A parenchymal band is a linear opacity, usually 1-3 mm thick and up to 5 cm long that usually extends to the visceral pleura (which is often thickened and may be retracted at the site of contact). It reflects pleuroparenchymal fibrosis and is usually associated with distortion of the lung architecture. Parenchymal bands are most frequently encountered in individuals who have been exposed to asbestos.

HP:0033651.name: Pulmonary mycetoma
HP:0033651.definition: A mycetoma is a discrete mass of intertwined hyphae, usually of an Aspergillus species, matted together by mucus, fibrin, and cellular debris colonizing a cavity, usually from prior fibrocavitary disease (eg, tuberculosis or sarcoidosis). A mycetoma may move to a dependent location when the patient changes position and may show an air crescent sign. CT scans may show a spongelike pattern and foci of calcification in the mycetoma.

HP:0033652.name: Broncholith
HP:0033652.definition: A broncholith, a calcified peribronchial lymph node that erodes into an adjacent bronchus, is most often the consequence of Histoplasma or tuberculous infection. The imaging appearance is of a small calcific focus in or immediately adjacent to an airway, most frequently the right middle lobe bronchus. Broncholiths are readily identified on CT scans. Distal obstructive changes may include atelectasis, mucoid impaction, and bronchiectasis

HP:0033653.name: Bronchocele
HP:0033653.definition: A bronchocele is bronchial dilatation due to retained secretions (mucoid impaction) usually caused by proximal obstruction, either congenital (eg, bronchial atresia) or acquired (eg, obstructing cancer). A bronchocele is a tubular or branching Y-or V-shaped structure that may resemble a gloved finger. The CT attenuation of the mucus is generally that of soft tissue but may be modified by its composition (eg, high-attenuation material in allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis). In the case of bronchial atresia, the surrounding lung may be of decreased attenuation because of reduced ventilation and, thus, perfusion.

HP:0033654.name: Beaded septum sign
HP:0033654.definition: Irregular and nodular thickening of interlobular septa reminiscent of a row of beads.

HP:0033655.name: Pulmonary cavity
HP:0033655.definition: A gas-filled space, seen as lucency or low-attenuation area, within a nodule, mass or area of parenchymal consolidations. It has a clearly defined wall over 4 mm thick.

HP:0033656.name: Juxtaphrenic peak
HP:0033656.definition: A juxtaphrenic peak is a small triangular opacity based at the apex of the dome of a hemidiaphragm, associated with upper lobe volume loss of any cause (eg, postirradiation fibrosis or upper lobectomy). It is most readily appreciated on a frontal chest radiograph. The peak is caused by upward retraction of the inferior accessory fissure or an intrapulmonary septum associated with the pulmonary ligament.

HP:0033657.name: Linear atelectasis
HP:0033657.definition: Linear atelectasis is a focal area of subsegmental atelectasis with a linear configuration, almost always extending to the pleura. It is commonly horizontal but sometimes oblique or vertical. The thickness of the atelectasis may range from a few millimeters to more than 1 cm.

HP:0033658.name: Rounded atelectasis
HP:0033658.definition: Rounded atelectasis is rounded collapsed lung associated with invaginated fibrotic pleura and thickened and fibrotic interlobular septa. Most frequently, it is the consequence of an asbestos-induced exudative pleural effusion with resultant pleural scarring, but it may occur with any cause of pleural fibrosis. On chest radiographs, rounded atelectasis appears as a mass abutting a pleural surface, usually in the posterior part of a lower lobe. Distorted vessels have a curvilinear disposition as they converge on the mass (the comet tail sign). The degree of lobar retraction depends on the volume of atelectatic lung. It is almost invariably associated with other signs of pleural fibrosis (eg, blunting of costophrenic angle). CT is more sensitive for the detection and display of the characteristic features of rounded atelectasis. An additional sign is homogeneous uptake of contrast medium in the atelectatic lung.

HP:0033660.name: Hand paresthesia
HP:0033660.definition: Tingling (often referred to as a pins and needles feeling) and numbness in the hand.

HP:0033661.name: Air crescent
HP:0033661.definition: An air crescent is a collection of air in a crescentic shape that separates the wall of a cavity from an inner mass. The air crescent sign is often considered characteristic of either Aspergillus colonization of preexisting cavities or retraction of infarcted lung in angioinvasive aspergillosis. However, the air crescent sign has also been reported in other conditions, including tuberculosis, Wegener granulomatosis, intracavitary hemorrhage, and lung cancer.

HP:0033662.name: Air bronchogram
HP:0033662.definition: An air bronchogram is a pattern of air-filled (low-attenuation) bronchi on a background of opaque (high-attenuation) airless lung. The sign implies (a) patency of proximal airways and (b) evacuation of alveolar air by means of absorption (atelectasis) or replacement (eg, pneumonia) or a combination of these processes. In rare cases, the displacement of air is the result of marked interstitial expansion (eg, lymphoma).

HP:0033663.name: Air trapping
HP:0033663.definition: Air trapping is retention of air in the lung distal to an obstruction (usually partial). Air trapping is seen on end-expiration CT scans as parenchymal areas with less than normal increase in attenuation and lack of volume reduction. Comparison between inspiratory and expiratory CT scans can be helpful when air trapping is subtle or diffuse.

HP:0033664.name: Ganglioglioma
HP:0033664.definition: Gangliogliomas are rare tumors of the central nervous system. The are WHO grade I and considered low grade. They are well differentiated neuroepithelial tumors consisting of both dysplastic neuronal and neoplastic glial cells.

HP:0033665.name: Diminished health-related quality of life
HP:0033665.definition: A reduction in an individual's subjective assessment of his or her sense of well-being and ability to perform social roles.

HP:0033666.name: Diminished physical functioning
HP:0033666.definition: A reduction in the ability to perform activities of daily living as compared to previous abilities because of functional deficits due to illness. The 36-item Short Form (SF-36) health survey questionnaire is one of many methods used to measure patients' perceptions of diminished physical functioning.

HP:0033667.name: Diminished mental health
HP:0033667.definition: A reduction in the subjective feeling of mental well being.

HP:0033668.name: Abnormal amygdala morphology
HP:0033668.definition: A structural anomaly of the amygdala.

HP:0033669.name: Enlarged amygdala
HP:0033669.definition: A increase in the volume (size) of the amygdyla.

HP:0033670.name: Organizing pneumonia
HP:0033670.definition: Organizing pneumonia manifests as a histologic pattern characterized by loose plugs of connective tissue in the airspaces and distal airways. Interstitial inflammation and fibrosis are minimal or absent. Cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, or COP, is a distinctive clinical disorder among the idiopathic interstitial pneumonias, but the histologic pattern of organizing pneumonia is encountered in many different situations, including pulmonary infection, hypersensitivity pneumonitis, and collagen vascular diseases. Airspace consolidation is the cardinal feature of organizing pneumonia on chest radiographs and CT scans. In COP, the distribution is typically subpleural and basal and sometimes bronchocentric. Other manifestations of organizing pneumonia include groundglass opacity, tree-in-bud pattern, and nodular opacities.

HP:0033671.name: Pulmonary oligemia
HP:0033671.definition: Oligemia is a reduction in pulmonary blood volume. Most frequently, this reduction is regional, but occasionally it is generalized. Regional oligemia is usually associated with reduced blood flow in the oligemic area. Oligemia appears as a regional or widespread decrease in the size and number of identifiable pulmonary vessels, which is indicative of less than normal blood flow.

HP:0033672.name: Positive carpal Tinel sign
HP:0033672.definition: The Tinel test is performed by lightly tapping (percussing) over the median nerve. It is positive (abnormal) if the patient experiences pain and paresthesias (tingling, numbness) along the distribution of the median nerve.

HP:0033673.name: Positive Phalen test
HP:0033673.definition: The Phalen maneuver is performed by having the patient hold both wrists in complete and forced flexion (pushing the dorsal surfaces of both hands together) for 30-60 seconds. This can increase the pressure in the carpal tunnel. The test is positive (abnormal) if the patient experiences characteristic symptoms of carpal tunnel syndrome (pain and paresthesias along the distribution of the median nerve, i.e., thumb, index finger, and middle finger).

HP:0033674.name: Pulmonary blood flow redistribution
HP:0033674.definition: Pulmonary blood flow redistribution refers to any departure from the normal distribution of blood flow in the lungs that is caused by an increase in pulmonary vascular resistance elsewhere in the pulmonary vascular bed. Pulmonary blood flow redistribution is indicated by a decrease in the size and/or number of visible pulmonary vessels in one or more lung regions, with a corresponding increase in number and/or size of pulmonary vessels in other parts of the lung.

HP:0033675.name: Frailty
HP:0033675.definition: A clinically recognizable state of increased vulnerability resulting from a decline in reserve and function across multiple physiologic systems such that the ability to cope with everyday or acute stressors is compromised.

HP:0033676.name: Posttraumatic stress symptom
HP:0033676.definition: A behavioral or psychological symptom that typically occurs following exposure to one or more traumatic events is posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD). Symptoms of PTSD include intrusive recollections, such as re-experiencing the trauma through flashbacks, memories, or nightmares. Additionally, individuals may experience avoidant and numbing symptoms, which can include diminished emotions and avoidance of situations that serve as reminders of the traumatic event. Hyperarousal is another symptom, characterized by increased irritability, exaggerated startle reactions, and difficulties with sleeping or concentrating.

HP:0033677.name: Acute respiratory distress syndrome
HP:0033677.definition: Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) is defined as an acute disorder that starts within seven days of the inciting event and is characterized by bilateral lung infiltrates and severe progressive hypoxemia in the absence of any evidence of cardiogenic pulmonary edema. ARDS is defined by the patient's oxygen in arterial blood (PaO2) to the fraction of the oxygen in the inspired air (FiO2). These patients have a PaO2/FiO2 ratio of less than 300.

HP:0033678.name: Acute coronary syndrome
HP:0033678.definition: The term acute coronary syndrome (ACS) refers to any group of clinical symptoms compatible with acute myocardial ischemia and includes unstable angina (UA), non-ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI), and ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI).

HP:0033679.name: Abnormal red nucleus morphology
HP:0033679.definition: Any structural anomaly of the red nucleus, a part of the midbrain involved in control of movement.

HP:0033680.name: Pilocytic astrocytoma
HP:0033680.definition: The most common form of astrocytoma (WHO Grade I) in childhood. These typically have MAPK signaling pathway abnormalities.

HP:0033681.name: Oligodendroglioma
HP:0033681.definition: Oligodendroglioma is a type of diffusely infiltrating glioma and constitutes approximately 5% of primary intracranial tumors. They often involve the cortical gray matter and are most commonly seen in the frontal lobes. OGs are generally low grade WHO grade II neoplasms that are slow-growing tumors and have a favorable treatment response when compared to other gliomas. Grade III anaplastic OG is a more malignant form of the tumor which portends a less favorable prognosis and may occur de novo or as degeneration from the lower grade OG.

HP:0033682.name: Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma
HP:0033682.definition: Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytomas (PXA) are rare low-grade astrocytomas (WHO Grade II) typically found in the temporal lobe and classically presenting with epilepsy. PXA is an astrocytic neoplasm that most often presents in children or young adults but can also occur in adults. The diagnosis of anaplastic PXA is made based upon tumor histopathologic characteristics and requires increased proliferative activity (mitotic index at least 5 mitoses/10 HPF), which is associated with worse overall survival. In general, anaplastic PXAs acquire features of a more aggressive astrocytic neoplasm that can include increased proliferation, necrosis, microvascular proliferation, loss of pericellular reticulin, and increased infiltrative growth.

HP:0033683.name: Jaw hyperreflexia
HP:0033683.definition: Increased intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in jaw.

HP:0033684.name: Abnormal muscle fiber-type distribution
HP:0033684.definition: Ay deviation from the normal distribution of fiber types in skeletal muscle. The skeletal muscle groups of the mammalian body are made up of bundles of muscle fibers. These fibers can be assigned to different Types, with characteristic movement rates, response to neural inputs, and metabolic styles. Skeletal muscle fibers are broadly classified as slow-twitch (type 1) and fast-twitch (type 2). Multiple fiber types are generally intermingled within a single muscle group, and different muscle groups have varying proportions of fiber types

HP:0033685.name: Fiber type grouping
HP:0033685.definition: An abnormal distribution of muscle fiber types in muscle tissue. Human skeletal muscle contains at least two fiber types recognizable by histochemical techniques. In transverse sections of normal skeletal muscle, type 1 and type 2 fibers are distributed in a random fashion. Grouping of fibers of the same type can be seen in certain peripheral neuropathies, thought to be due to reinnervation of denervated muscle fibers by sprouting axons. With grouping, motor units enlarge. The fibers of a motor unit, which are normally scattered, come to lie adjacent to one another. Histochemical examination shows groups of muscle fibers of the same histochemical type.

HP:0033686.name: Mitochondrial hypertrophy
HP:0033686.definition: Enlargement of mitochondria. Mitochondrial hypertrophy is not discernible by light microscopy. By electron microscopy (EM), hypertrophic mitochondria have normal cristae and normal matrix density. In contrast, swollen mitochondria display swollen cristae and irregular matrix densities in EM.

HP:0033687.name: Short term memory impairment
HP:0033687.definition: A deficit in the retention of pieces of information (memory chunks) for a relatively short time (usually up to 30 seconds).

HP:0033688.name: Long term memory impairment
HP:0033688.definition: A deficit in the ability to retrieve information from long-term memory, which can be defined as a seemingly unlimited capacity to store memories can last years and relate to the performance of actions or skills (i.e., procedural memories, knowing how) and memories of facts, rules, concepts, and events (i.e., declarative memories, knowing that).

HP:0033689.name: Anterograde memory impairment
HP:0033689.definition: The impaired ability to establish new long-term memories.

HP:0033690.name: Retrograde memory impairment
HP:0033690.definition: Inability to retrieve information from the long-term memory that was acquired before the onset of amnesia.

HP:0033691.name: Procedural memory loss
HP:0033691.definition: A reduction in the ability to retrieve information about how to perform activities, such as how to ride a bike or drive a car, how to perform activities of daily living, or how to play a musical instrument.

HP:0033692.name: Declarative memory loss
HP:0033692.definition: Impaired ability to remember facts and events.

HP:0033693.name: Phantosmia
HP:0033693.definition: Perception of an odor in the absence of any stimuli in the surrounding environment that could emit the odor.

HP:0033694.name: Tactile hallucination
HP:0033694.definition: Perception of touch without a tactile stimulus.

HP:0033695.name: Occupational disability
HP:0033695.definition: This is a general term that denotes a reduced ability to perform the work that one performed prior to an illness, and may be related to pain, cognitive dysfunction, fatigue or other physical disabilities.

HP:0033696.name: Pseudo-chilblain
HP:0033696.definition: Acral areas of erythema with vesicles or pustules. The lesions resemble chilblains and have purpuric areas, affecting hands and feet.

HP:0033697.name: Vesicular eruption
HP:0033697.definition: A type of acute-onset skin rash characterized by multiple vesicles, which are circumscribed, fluid-containing, epidermal elevation generally considered less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point. The fluid contained in a vesicle may be clear, serous, or hemorrhagic.

HP:0033698.name: Monomorphic vesicular eruption
HP:0033698.definition: A type of vesicular eruption in which the vesicles are at same stages.

HP:0033699.name: Polymorphic vesicular eruption
HP:0033699.definition: A type of vesicular eruption in which the vesicles are at different stages.

HP:0033700.name: Papulovesicular eruption
HP:0033700.definition: An acute onset rash characterized by by multiple vesicles, which are circumscribed, fluid-containing, epidermal elevations with a diameter less than 10mm at the widest point, and by multiple papules, which are circumscribed, solid epidermal elevations with no visible fluid with a diameter less than 10mm at the widest point.

HP:0033701.name: Cortical sclerosis of the iliac wing
HP:0033701.definition: Increased density related to increased bone mass in the outermost layer (edge) of the iliac wing.

HP:0033702.name: Subpleural curvilinear line
HP:0033702.definition: This finding is a thin curvilinear opacity, 1-3 mm in thickness, lying less than 1 cm from and parallel to the pleural surface. It corresponds to atelectasis of normal lung if seen in the dependent posteroinferior portion of lung of a patient in the supine position and is subsequently shown to disappear on CT sections acquired with the patient prone. It may also be encountered in patients with pulmonary edema or fibrosis (other signs are usually present).

HP:0033703.name: Dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumor
HP:0033703.definition: Dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumor (DNT) is a benign glioneuronal neoplasm that most commonly occurs in children and young adults and may present with medically intractable, chronic seizures. Lesions vary in size from 10 to 25 mm, although occasionally larger tumors of up to 70 mm have been reported. Grossly, tumors appear as well-defined, solitary nodular masses or poorly demarcated lesions. On the cut section, most tumors are cortically located and may extend into the underlying subcortical white matter in larger tumors. Multi-nodular appearance or cystic changes are commonly found

HP:0033704.name: Elevated urinary homogentisic acid
HP:0033704.definition: An increased amount of homogentisic acid in the urine.

HP:0033705.name: Tearfulness
HP:0033705.definition: A feeling of sadness characterized by episodes of crying that can occur suddenly and are not easily controlled in social situations.

HP:0033706.name: Progressive massive fibrosis
HP:0033706.definition: This condition is caused by slow-growing conglomeration of dust particles and collagen deposition in individuals (mostly coal workers) heavily exposed to inorganic dust. Progressive massive fibrosis manifests as masslike lesions, usually bilateral and in the upper lobes. Background nodular opacities reflect accompanying pneumoconiosis, with or without emphysematous destruction adjacent to the massive fibrosis. Lesions similar to progressive massive fibrosis sometimes occur in other conditions, such as sarcoidosis and talcosis.

HP:0033707.name: Perioral hyperkeratosis
HP:0033707.definition: Increased thickness of the stratum corneum (the outer layer of the skin) in the skin surrounding the mouth.

HP:0033709.name: Increased sputum production
HP:0033709.definition: An increase in the amount of airway mucus. This feature may be characterized by frequent or excessive throat clearing (exhalation through tightly constricted laryngopharyngeal tissues accompanied by vibration of the palatoglossal arch and the vocal folds serving to clear mucus from the airway).

HP:0033710.name: Rest dyspnea
HP:0033710.definition: A perception of shortness of breath that occurs independently of exertion.

HP:0033711.name: Pulmonary interstitial thickening
HP:0033711.definition: Pathological thickening of the pulmonary interstitium visualized radiographically and divided into interlobular and intralobular septal thickening.

HP:0033712.name: Repeated implantation failure
HP:0033712.definition: Repeated implantation failure refers to a situation in which embryos of good quality fail to implant following several in vitro fertilization (IVF) treatment cycles.

HP:0033713.name: Anti-signal recognition particle antibody positivity
HP:0033713.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against anti-signal recognition particle.

HP:0033714.name: Multiple meningiomas
HP:0033714.definition: The occurrence of multiple distinct meningiomas in the same individual.

HP:0033715.name: Hippocampal sclerosis
HP:0033715.definition: Hippocampal sclerosis is a neuropathologic finding characterized by neuronal loss and gliosis in the CA-1 and subiculum of the hippocampus.

HP:0033716.name: EEG with frontal epileptiform discharges
HP:0033716.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the frontal region.

HP:0033717.name: EEG with temporal epileptiform discharges
HP:0033717.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the temporal region.

HP:0033718.name: EEG with central epileptiform discharges
HP:0033718.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the central region.

HP:0033719.name: EEG with parietal epileptiform discharges
HP:0033719.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the parietal region.

HP:0033720.name: EEG with occipital epileptiform discharges
HP:0033720.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the occipital region.

HP:0032934.name: Spontaneous cerebrospinal fluid leak
HP:0032934.definition: A spontaneous cerebrospinal fluid leak (SCSFL) is a spontaneous and unexplained leak of the cerebrospinal fluid from the dura surrounding either the brain (cranial leak) or spine (spinal leak).

HP:0032935.name: Posterior crocodile shagreen of the cornea
HP:0032935.definition: Grayish, polygonal pattern of opacities with intervening clear zones across the central cornea that resembles crocodile skin.

HP:0032936.name: Intrusion symptom
HP:0032936.definition: Unintentional re-experiencing of a traumatic event involves symptoms that typically include sensory impressions and emotional responses stemming from the trauma. These symptoms seem to lack a sense of time perspective and context.

HP:0032937.name: Recurrent, involuntary, and intrusive distressing memories
HP:0032937.definition: After experiencing psychological trauma, individuals may repeatedly encounter sensory-perceptual impressions of the event that intrude into their consciousness involuntarily. These intrusive memories often manifest as visual images (such as mental pictures), but can also involve sounds, smells, tastes, and physical sensations. They are accompanied by a variety of negative emotions linked to the most intense moments of the traumatic memory.

HP:0032938.name: Recurrent trauma-related distressing dreams
HP:0032938.definition: Recurrent distressing dreams occur when the content and/or emotional impact of the dream is connected to a traumatic event or events.

HP:0032939.name: Physiological reactivity to cues
HP:0032939.definition: Marked physiological reactions to internal or external cues that symbolize or resemble an aspect of the traumatic event(s).

HP:0032940.name: Dissociation
HP:0032940.definition: Disruption or detachment of certain aspects of one's normal psychological functioning typically involves a disconnection or separation from thoughts, feelings, sensations, memories, or one's sense of identity or reality.

HP:0032941.name: Intense psychological distress to cues
HP:0032941.definition: Intense or prolonged psychological distress occurs when individuals are exposed to internal or external cues that symbolize or resemble an aspect of the traumatic event or events.

HP:0032942.name: Avoidance of stimuli associated with traumatic event
HP:0032942.definition: Avoidance of or efforts to avoid distressing memories, thoughts, or feelings about or closely associated with the traumatic event(s). Avoidance of or efforts to avoid external reminders (people, places, conversations, activities, objects, situations) that arouse distressing memories, thoughts, or feelings about or closely associated with the traumatic event(s).

HP:0032943.name: Abnormal urine pH
HP:0032943.definition: A deviation of urine pH from the normal range of 4.5 to 7.8.

HP:0032945.name: Renal interstitial inflammation
HP:0032945.definition: Histopathological findings of inflammation of the renal interstitium potentially involving fibrotic as well as non-fibrotic areas, composed of lymphocytes, monocytes, plasma cells.

HP:0032946.name: Renal cortical interstitial inflammation
HP:0032946.definition: Histopathological findings of inflammation of the renal interstitium involving fibrotic as well as non-fibrotic renal cortex, composed of lymphocytes, monocytes, plasma cells.

HP:0032947.name: Renal medullary interstitial inflammation
HP:0032947.definition: Histopathological findings of inflammation of the interstitium of the renal medulla, composed of lymphocytes, monocytes, plasma cells.

HP:0032948.name: Renal interstitial fibrosis
HP:0032948.definition: The accumulation of collagen and related extracellular matrix (ECM) molecules in the interstitium of the kidney. The interstitium is expanded by the presence of collagen that stain blue on trichrome. Tubules are not back to back, but rather separated by fibrosis and can be atrophic.

HP:0032949.name: Renal interstitial calcium phosphate deposits
HP:0032949.definition: The presence of interstitial aggregates of purple finely granular/laminated calcium- and phosphate deposits.

HP:0032950.name: Abnormal renal tubular lumen morphology
HP:0032950.definition: Abnormal structure or form of the lumen (opening) of kidney tubules.

HP:0032951.name: Renal tubular viral cytopathic changes
HP:0032951.definition: Viral cytopathic changes consist of smudgy basophilic intranuclear inclusions with enlarged nuclei of infected cells. Distal tubules are more commonly involved than proximal tubules. There is associated acute tubular injury, often with frank tubular necrosis and destruction, with acute interstitial nephritis, often with a pleomorphic infiltrate composed of lymphocytes, histiocytes, plasma cells, and variable numbers of neutrophils, with interstitial edema and hemorrhage. Tubular destruction may be associated with necrotizing interstitial granulomas. Severe granulomatous tubulointerstitial nephritis appears to be characteristic of adenoviral infection and is quite rare in other viral infections. Focal wedge-shaped necrosis may occur in renal parenchyma. Immunostaining for adenovirus shows strong nuclear and cytoplasmic staining in infected cells.

HP:0032952.name: Usual-type tubular atrophy
HP:0032952.definition: A type of renal tubular atrophy in which the tubules show thick tubular basement membranes lined by small cuboidal or flat cells. Generally accompanied by fibrosis.

HP:0032953.name: Renal tubular cytomegalovirus inclusions
HP:0032953.definition: Characteristic intranuclear glassy-appearing basophilic inclusions with surrounding halo (owl's eye-type inclusion) and marked increase in the size of the cell (cytomegaly), particularly in tubular epithelial cells and in endothelial cells.
