Often accompanied by cytopathic changes including patchy interstitial pleomorphic infiltrate with lymphocytes, plasma cells, and macrophages.

HP:0032954.name: Renal tubular adenovirus inclusions
HP:0032954.definition: Viral cytopathic changes consist of smudgy basophilic intranuclear inclusions with enlarged nuclei of infected cells. The inclusions stain positive for adenovirus (e.g., Figure 3 of PMID:29273157). Distal tubules are more commonly involved than proximal tubules. Occasionally glomerular visceral and parietal epithelial cells can be infected. There is associated acute tubular injury, often with frank tubular necrosis and destruction, with acute interstitial nephritis, often with a pleomorphic infiltrate composed of lymphocytes, histiocytes, plasma cells, and variable numbers of neutrophils, with interstitial edema and hemorrhage.

HP:0032955.name: Renal tubular polyoma virus inclusions
HP:0032955.definition: Renal tubular nuclear inclusions have a ground-glass appearance with irregular central clearing, or a coarse, vesicular appearance. Distal tubules are involved more often than proximal tubules. There may be only medullary involvement in early stages, and parietal epithelial cells may be involved in later stages of the infection. Infected epithelial cell nuclei stain with antibody to the large T antigen of the SV40 virus, which serves as a surrogate marker of human polyomavirus infection.

HP:0032956.name: Renal tubular herpes simplex virus inclusions
HP:0032956.definition: Renal tubular nuclear inclusions that stain positive for herpes simplex virus (HSV). HSV is typically associated with multinucleated giant cells with nuclear inclusions and may cause hemorrhagic interstitial nephritis.

HP:0032957.name: Dysmorphic hematuria
HP:0032957.definition: The presence of dysmorphic urinary erythrocytes. This feature can be observed by phase-contrastmicroscopy, differential interference microscopy, and bright-field microscopy. The acanthocyte or G1 cell, which is a doughnut-shaped cell with one or more blebs, is reported to constitute a special form of dysmorphic erythro-cyte (D cell) specific for glomerular hematuria.

HP:0032958.name: Urinary oval fat bodies
HP:0032958.definition: The presence in the urine of desquamated tubular epithelial cells or macrophages filled with lipid droplets.

HP:0032959.name: Intratubular calcium oxalate casts
HP:0032959.definition: Birefringent calcium- and oxalate-containing casts located within the tubuli of the kidney.

HP:0032960.name: Intratubular calcium phosphate casts
HP:0032960.definition: Purple and finely granular/laminated calcium- and phosphate-containing casts located within the tubuli of the kidney.

HP:0032961.name: Magnesium ammonium phosphate crystalluria
HP:0032961.definition: Magnesium ammonium phosphate crystals in the urine.

HP:0032962.name: Tubular microcystic change
HP:0032962.definition: Dilated renal tubules (over twice the diameter of a normal proximal tubule) containing eosinophilic amorphous material. This feature is generally accompanied by scalloping of the cast profile. The epithelium lining the microcyst is generally flattened and does not reveal brush border.

HP:0032963.name: Complex renal cyst
HP:0032963.definition: A renal cyst characterized by epithelium lined space (squamous/columnar) with septations.

HP:0032964.name: Uric acid crystalluria
HP:0032964.definition: The presence of uric acid crystals in the urine.

HP:0032965.name: Interstitial emphysema
HP:0032965.definition: Interstitial emphysema is characterized by air dissecting within the interstitium of the lung, typically in the peribronchovascular sheaths, interlobular septa, and visceral pleura. It is most commonly seen in neonates receiving mechanical ventilation. It is rarely recognized radiographically in adults and is infrequently seen on CT scans. It appears as perivascular lucent or low attenuating halos and small cysts.

HP:0032966.name: Centrilobular emphysema
HP:0032966.definition: A type of emphysema characterized by destroyed centrilobular alveolar walls and enlargement of respiratory bronchioles and associated alveoli. This is the commonest form of emphysema in cigarette smokers. CT findings are centrilobular areas of decreased attenuation, usually without visible walls, of nonuniform distribution and predominantly located in upper lung zones.

HP:0032967.name: Panacinar emphysema
HP:0032967.definition: Panacinar emphysema involves all portions of the acinus and secondary pulmonary lobule more or less uniformly. It predominates in the lower lobes and is the form of emphysema associated with1-antitrypsin deficiency. CT scans show a generalized decrease of the lung parenchyma with a decrease in the caliber of blood vessels in the affected lung. Severe panacinar emphysema may coexist and merge with severe centrilobular emphysema. The appearance of feature less decreased attenuation may be indistinguishable from severe constrictive obliterative bronchiolitis.

HP:0032968.name: Expiratory air trapping
HP:0032968.definition: Abnormal retention of gas within a lung or part of a lung, as a result of airway obstruction of abnormalities in lung compliance. In the classic presentation, the lung will appear normal at inspiration, but on exhalation, the diseased portions of the lung which have lost connective tissue recoil will remain lucent while the healthy portions of the lung will become more dense due to atelectasis. This helps distinguish it from mosaic attenuation due to patchy fibrosis, as occurs with nonspecific interstitial pneumonia, and in early usual interstitial pneumonitis (the hallmark imaging diagnosis of interstitial lung disease) in which there is no change with inspiration and expiration.

HP:0032969.name: Traction bronchiectasis
HP:0032969.definition: Distortion of the bronchial airways due to mechanical traction on the bronchi resulting from fibrosis of the surrounding lung parenchyma. CT findings represent irregular bronchial dilatation caused by surrounding retractile pulmonary fibrosis. Dilated airways are usually identifiable as such but may be seen as cysts.

HP:0032971.name: Computed tomographic halo sign
HP:0032971.definition: CT finding of ground-glass opacity surrounding a nodule or mass. It was first described as a sign of hemorrhage around foci of invasive aspergillosis. The halo sign is nonspecific and may also be caused by hemorrhage associated with other types of nodules or by local pulmonary infiltration by neoplasm.

HP:0032972.name: Nodular-centrilobular without tree-in-bud pattern on pulmonary HRCT
HP:0032972.definition: A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography which are anatomically located centrally within secondary pulmonary lobules. Centrilobular nodules may be dense (i.e., solid) and of homogeneous opacity or ground-glass opacity, and may range from a few millimeters to about 1 cm in size. Because of the similar size of secondary lobules, centrilobular nodules often appear to be evenly spaced. Centrilobular nodules are usually separated from the pleural surfaces, fissures, and interlobular septa by a distance of at least several millimeters. They may appear patchy or diffuse in different diseases.

HP:0032973.name: Abnormal bronchoalveolar lavage fluid morphology
HP:0032973.definition: Abnormal type or counts of nucleated immune cells and acellular components in bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) fluid. BAL us performed with a fiberoptic bronchoscope in the wedged position within a selected bronchopulmonary segment. BAL is commonly used to inform the differential diagnosis of interstitial lung disease or to monitor therapeutic interventions.

HP:0032974.name: Abnormal cellular composition of bronchoalveolar fluid
HP:0032974.definition: Deviation from the commonly in healthy people observe cellular distribution. Normal ranges are macrophages over 80%, lymphocytes less than 15%, neutrophils less than 3%, eosinophils less than 0.5%, mast cells less than 0.5%.

HP:0032975.name: Abnormal bronchoalveolar fluid protein level
HP:0032975.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of protein in the bronchoalveolar fluid.

HP:0032976.name: Elevated bronchoalveolar lavage fluid lymphocyte proportion
HP:0032976.definition: Usually, Lymphoycytes make up less than 15% of all cells found in the bronchoalveloar lavage fluid. This elevated cell proportion can be induced by virus or drugs, or is associated with specific diseases.

HP:0032977.name: Elevated bronchoalveolar lavage fluid neutrophil proportion
HP:0032977.definition: Usually, Neutrophils make up less than 3% of all cells found in the broncho-alveloar lavage fluid. In children, standard value of neutrophils is higher depending on their age (children under the age of 5 show a maximum value of 10%). This elevated cell proportion is a sign for acute and chronic infections (HP:0012387, HP:0006538) and can be associated to specific diseases.

HP:0032978.name: Lipid-laden macrophages in bronchoalveolar fluid
HP:0032978.definition: Accumulation of lipids in alveolar macrophages with droplet-shaped fat inclusions.

HP:0032979.name: Hemosiderin-laden macrophages in bronchoalveolar fluid
HP:0032979.definition: Hemosiderin-laden macrophages (HLM) in bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) fluid were originally known as adiagnostic biomarker of alveolar hemorrhage, but have also been observed in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) with histopathological pattern of usual interstitial pneumonia (UIP).

HP:0032980.name: Absent bronchoalveolar surfactant-protein C
HP:0032980.definition: Significantly decreased level or failed detection of surfactant protein C in broncho-alveolar lavage fluid. Comment: Pulmonary surfactant is a highly surface-active mixture of proteins and lipids that is synthesized and secreted onto the alveoli by type II epithelial cells. The protein part of surfactant constitutes of four types of surfactant proteins (SP), SP-A, SP-B, SP-C and SP-D. SP-A and SP-D are hydrophilic proteins that regulate surfactant metabolism and have immunologic functions, whereas SP-B and SP-C are hydrophobic molecules, which play a direct role in the organization of the surfactant structure in the interphase and in the stabilization of the lipid layers during the respiratory cycle. Lack of SP-C may result of surfactant metabolism dysfunction and is also observed in patients with other diffuse parenchymal lung diseases, pathogenetically related to the alveolar surfactant region.

HP:0032981.name: Absent bronchoalveolar dimeric surfactant-protein B
HP:0032981.definition: Significantly decreased level or failed detection of surfactant protein B in broncho-alveolar lavage fluid.

HP:0032983.name: Atoll sign
HP:0032983.definition: CT finding of central ground-glass opacity surrounded by denser consolidation of crescentic shape (forming more than three-fourths of a circle) or complete ring of at least 2 mm in thickness. A rare sign, it was initially reported to be specific for cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, but was subsequently described in patients with paracoccidioidomycosis.

HP:0032984.name: Abnormal alveolar macrophage morphology
HP:0032984.definition: Alveolar macrophages usually make up the majority of cells in the bronchoalveolar space (over 80%). The may contain intracellular material depending on underlying diseases or due to exposition to inhaled particles.

HP:0032985.name: Dust particle inclusion in alveolar macrophages
HP:0032985.definition: Accumulation of inhaled, nondigestable particles in macrophages.

HP:0032986.name: Smoker-inclusions in alveolar macrophages
HP:0032986.definition: In otherwise healthy smokers, characteristic so called smoker-inclusion can be found within the macrophages in the bronchoalveolar fluid. These blue/ black/ round/ oval cytoplasmic inclusions consist of pigmented lipid deposits.

HP:0032987.name: Elevated bronchoalveolar lavage fluid eosinophil proportion
HP:0032987.definition: Usually, eosinophils make up less than 0.5% of all cells found in the broncho-alveloar lavage fluid. But in eosinophilic lung disease, the eosinophil cell proportion typically represents more than 25%. Comment: An elevated level of eosinophil cells are also a result of infections, or an allergic reaction or can be drug-induced.

HP:0032988.name: Persistent head lag
HP:0032988.definition: The Premie-Neuro and the Dubowitz Neurological Examination score head lag in the same manner. Scoring for both is as follows: 0 = head drops and stays back, 1 = tries to lift head but drops it back, 2 = able to lift head slightly, 3 = lifts head in line with body, and 4 = head in front of body. This term applies if head lag persists beyond an expected age at a level of 0 or 1. Persistent head lag beyond age 4 mo has been linked to poor outcomes.

HP:0032989.name: Delayed ability to roll over
HP:0032989.definition: Delayed achievement of the ability to roll front to back and back to front.

HP:0032990.name: Localized pulmonary hemorrhage
HP:0032990.definition: Circumscribed pulmonary hemorrhage originating from a single bleeding site in the lungs. This can be due to infections, tumorigenesis, foreign bodies, or vascular abnormalities. Patient often feel the site of bleeding, contrast CT scan or angiography may localize the bleeder.

HP:0032991.name: Abnormal pulmonary fissure morphology
HP:0032991.definition: An abnormal form or number of the pulmonary fissures.

HP:0032992.name: Abnormal pulmonary fissure architecture
HP:0032992.definition: An abnormal form or location of a pulmonary fissure.

HP:0032993.name: Abnormal pulmonary fissure count
HP:0032993.definition: A deviation from the normal number of pulmonary fissures.

HP:0032994.name: Supernumerary pulmonary fissure
HP:0032994.definition: Presence of a lung fissure that does not exist normally. Supernumerary fissures include the superior accessory fissure, the medial basal fissure, the left horizontal fissure, and the azygos fissure form supernumerary lobes.

HP:0032995.name: Decreased pulmonary fissure count
HP:0032995.definition: Lack of one or more of the normal pulmonary fissures.

HP:0032996.name: Abnormal cystatin C level
HP:0032996.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of cystatin C in serum or plasma.

HP:0032997.name: Decreased circulating cystatin C concentration
HP:0032997.definition: The concentration of cystatin C in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0032998.name: Increased cystatin C level
HP:0032998.definition: A elevated concentration of cystatin C in the blood circulation.

HP:0032999.name: Increased fecal porphyrin
HP:0032999.definition: Abnormally high concentration of fecal porphyrins in feces.

HP:0033000.name: Subglottic laryngitis
HP:0033000.definition: Narrowing of the larynx, commonly occurring during viral respiratory tract infections, in particular in children, leads to symptoms such as hoarseness, a barking cough, stridor, and sometimes dyspnea and respiratory failure.

HP:0033001.name: Laryngeal papilloma
HP:0033001.definition: A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on the larynx.

HP:0033002.name: Bronchial papilloma
HP:0033002.definition: A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on a bronchus.

HP:0033003.name: Tracheal papilloma
HP:0033003.definition: A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on the trachea.

HP:0033004.name: Palmar warts
HP:0033004.definition: Multiple verrucous lesions on the skin of the palm. These lesions are raised, have a thickened and rough surface, and may display prominent black dots (thrombosed capillaries). Palmar warts are caused by human papillomavirus (HPV).

HP:0033005.name: Plantar warts
HP:0033005.definition: Multiple verrucous lesions on the skin of the sole of the foot. These lesions are raised, have a thickened and rough surface, and may display prominent black dots (thrombosed capillaries). Palmar warts are caused by caused by human papillomavirus (HPV).

HP:0033006.name: Diffuse alveolar damage
HP:0033006.definition: Diffuse alveolar damage (DAD) describes a common histologic injury pattern of the lung. The early stages are characterized by epithelial cell necrosis and sloughing, fibrous exsudate, edema, and hyaline membranes made of surfactant and proteins, filling the alveoli. This results in impaired gas exchange. In later stages, type II cells and myofibroblasts proliferate within the interstitium and airspaces. The corresponding clinical entity is acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). DAD may result from pulmonary drug toxicity, occurs in immunosuppressed, severe viral infections, acute interstial pneumonitis, and crack cocaine inhalation.

HP:0033007.name: Architectural distortion of the lung
HP:0033007.definition: Architectural distortion is characterized by abnormal displacement of bronchi, vessels, fissures, or septa caused by diffuse or localized lung disease, particularly interstitial fibrosis. This is visible in lung biopsy and CT scans in a distorted appearance and is usually associated with pulmonary fibrosis and accompanied by volume loss.

HP:0033008.name: Increased Z-disc width
HP:0033008.definition: Abnormally increased width of the Z-disk of the sarcomere, resulting from splitting or opening of the Z-disc (c.f., Figure 2 of PMID:28732005).

HP:0033009.name: Increased fecal coproporphyrin 1
HP:0033009.definition: Abnormally high concentration of coproporphyrin 1 in feces.

HP:0033010.name: Increased fecal coproporphyrin 3
HP:0033010.definition: Abnormally high concentration of coproporphyrin 3 in feces

HP:0033011.name: Platystencephaly
HP:0033011.definition: Extreme width of the skull in the occipital region, with anterior narrowing and prognathism.

HP:0033012.name: Abnormal salivary metabolite concentration
HP:0033012.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a metabolite in saliva.

HP:0033013.name: Abnormal salivary cortisol level
HP:0033013.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of cortisol in saliva.

HP:0033014.name: Decreased salivary cortisol level
HP:0033014.definition: Abnormally reduced concentration of cortisol in saliva.

HP:0033015.name: Increased salivary cortisol level
HP:0033015.definition: Abnormally elevated concentration of cortisol in saliva.

HP:0033016.name: Chronic decreased circulating IgD
HP:0033016.definition: A lasting reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood.

HP:0033017.name: Transient decreased circulating IgD
HP:0033017.definition: A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033018.name: Chronic absent circulating IgD
HP:0033018.definition: A lasting absence of immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood, whereby at most trace quantities of IgD can be measured.

HP:0033019.name: Male reproductive system neoplasm
HP:0033019.definition: A neoplasm that affects the male reproductive system.

HP:0033020.name: Female reproductive system neoplasm
HP:0033020.definition: A neoplasm that affects the female reproductive system.

HP:0033021.name: Transient decreased circulating IgE concentration
HP:0033021.definition: A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood.

HP:0033022.name: Chronic decreased circulating IgE concentration
HP:0033022.definition: A lasting reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood.

HP:0033023.name: Chronic absent circulating IgE
HP:0033023.definition: A lasting absence of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood circulation, whereby at most trace quantities of IgE can be measured.

HP:0033024.name: Transient decreased circulating IgA
HP:0033024.definition: A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin A (IgA) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033025.name: Chronic absent circulating total IgG
HP:0033025.definition: A lasting absence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood, whereby at most trace quantities of IgG can be measured.

HP:0033026.name: White oral mucosal macule
HP:0033026.definition: A small circumscribed whitish change in the color of the oral mucosa that is neither elevated nor depressed.

HP:0033027.name: Retinal peau d'orange
HP:0033027.definition: A pebbly orange appearance of the fundus that is said to resemble the skin of an orange.

HP:0033028.name: Anti-U1 ribonucleoprotein antibody positivity
HP:0033028.definition: The presence autoantibodies in the serum that react to proteins (70 Kd, A, C) that are associated with U1 RNA and form U1snRNP.

HP:0033030.name: Anti-glomerular basement membrane-antibody positivity
HP:0033030.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to the glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033031.name: Hyperpyrexia
HP:0033031.definition: An extreme elevation of core body temperature above normal defined as a rectal temperature of 41.1 degrees Celsius (106 degrees Fahrenheit).

HP:0033032.name: Triggered by an abusive adult
HP:0033032.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is induced by an abusive adult (usually a parent).

HP:0033033.name: Anti-MDA5 antibody positivity
HP:0033033.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to Anti-MDA5 (Anti-melanoma differentiation-associated proteine 5).

HP:0033034.name: Anti-citrullinated protein antibody positivity
HP:0033034.definition: The presence autoantibodies in the serum that react do different citrullinated antigens, including filaggrin, fibrinogen, vimentin and collagen.

HP:0034267.name: Pelvic pain
HP:0034267.definition: Pain perceived in the area of the pelvis, the lower part of the abdomen located between the hip bones.

HP:0034269.name: Abnormal vaginal discharge
HP:0034269.definition: Anomalous amount, odor, or consistency of the fluid or mucus that comes from the vagina

HP:0034270.name: Serrated incisors
HP:0034270.definition: Incisor teeth with irregular edges said to resemble a saw.

HP:0034271.name: Copper beaten skull
HP:0034271.definition: Diffuse prominent gyral impressions on the inner table of skull vault said to resemble beaten copper.

HP:0034272.name: Perifoveal hypoautofluorescence
HP:0034272.definition: Decreased amount of autofluorescence (emission of fluorescent light from ocular structures in the absence of sodium fluorescein) in the retina in the region surrounding the fovea.

HP:0034273.name: Premature sagging cheeks
HP:0034273.definition: Drooping or sinking of tissues of the cheeks more than would be expected at a given age. Sagging can occur due to a relative excess of skin and/or lack of elastic recoil as well as fat accumulation.

HP:0034274.name: Gastrointestinal ulcer
HP:0034274.definition: A deep defect in the esophageal, gastric, duodenal or intestinal wall involving the entire mucosal thickness and penetrating through the muscularis mucosae.

HP:0034275.name: Verrucous epidermal nevus
HP:0034275.definition: A type of epidermal nevus (which represent Blaschkoid hamartomas of the skin that result from mosaic post-zygotic mutations) that appears as skin-colored-to-brown, sharply demarcated, papillomatous papules that coalesce into plaques. The majority of these nevi are either present at birth or occur within the first year of life.

HP:0034276.name: Elevated circulating thymidine concentration
HP:0034276.definition: Concentration of thymidine in the blood circulation above the normal range.

HP:0034277.name: Elevated circulating deoxyuridine concentration
HP:0034277.definition: Concentration of 2-deoxyuridine in the blood circulation is above the normal range.

HP:0034278.name: Multinucleated erythroblast
HP:0034278.definition: Erythroblasts with multiple nuclei. Erythroblasts are nucleated precrusor cells of erythrocytes that are localized to the bone marrow. Normally, erythroblasts have a single nucleus. The abnormal finding of erythrocytes with two or more nuclei may be related to defects in cytokinesis.

HP:0034279.name: 2,8-dihydroxyadenine crystalluria
HP:0034279.definition: The presence of 2,8-dihydroxyadenine crystals in the urine. The crystals appear as round, yellow-brown crystals.

HP:0034280.name: Target cells
HP:0034280.definition: Target cells (codocytes) have a centrally located disk of hemoglobin surrounded by an area of pallor with an outer rim of hemoglobin adjacent to the cell membrane giving the cell the appearance of a target.

HP:0034281.name: Phalangeal cone-shaped epiphyses
HP:0034281.definition: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the phalanges of the hands or feet. Cone-shaped epiphyses (also known as coned epiphyses) are epiphyses that invaginate into cupped metaphyses. That is, the epiphysis has a cone-shaped distal extension resulting from increased growth of the central portion of the epiphysis relative to its periphery.

HP:0034282.name: Subcutaneous ossification
HP:0034282.definition: Formation of abnormal, extraskeletal bony tissue in the soft tissue beneath the skin. Subcutaneous ossifications may be observed by radiography or by palpation.

HP:0034283.name: Increased fecal protoporphyrin concentration
HP:0034283.definition: Abnormally high concentration of protoporphyrin (derivative of porphyrin with propionic acid groups) in feces.

HP:0034284.name: Recurrent gingivitis
HP:0034284.definition: Repeated occurrences of inflammatory condition of the gums (gingival tissue), most commonly caused by bacterial infection.

HP:0034285.name: Enteroviral encephalitis
HP:0034285.definition: Inflammation of the brain related to infection by an enterovirus.

HP:0034287.name: Afibrinogenemia
HP:0034287.definition: Lack of detectable fibrinogen in the blood circulation.

HP:0034288.name: Elevated circulating reverse T3 concentration
HP:0034288.definition: Abnormally increased concentration of reverse T3 (3,3',5'-triiodothyronine or rT3) in the blood circulation.

HP:0034289.name: Elevated circulating rT3/T3 ratio
HP:0034289.definition: An abnormally increased ratio of the concentrations of reverse T3 to T3 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034290.name: Elevated circulating tiglylglycine concentration
HP:0034290.definition: Concentration of tiglylglycine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0034291.name: Elevated circulating creatine concentration
HP:0034291.definition: An elevation above the normal range of creatine in the blood circulation.

HP:0034292.name: Reduced circulating creatine concentration
HP:0034292.definition: An reduction below the normal range of creatine in the blood circulation.

HP:0034293.name: Temporal lobe calcification
HP:0034293.definition: The presence of calcium deposition within the temporal lobe of the brain.

HP:0034294.name: Ductal bile plugs
HP:0034294.definition: Bile thrombi that form an obstruction (plug) in a dilated bile duct.

HP:0034295.name: Reduced cerebral white matter volume
HP:0034295.definition: An abnormally low volume of the white matter of the brain.

HP:0034297.name: Elevated circulating tetracosanoic acid concentration
HP:0034297.definition: Elevated concentration of tetracosanoic acid (a C24 straight-chain saturated fatty acid) in the blood circulation.

HP:0034298.name: Elevated circulating hexacosanoic acid concentration
HP:0034298.definition: Elevated concentration of hexacosanoic acid (a C26 straight-chain saturated fatty acid) in the blood circulation.

HP:0034299.name: Sertoli cell-only phenotype
HP:0034299.definition: A histological phenotype observed on testicular biopsy in which only Sertoli cells line the seminiferous tubules of the testis.

HP:0034300.name: Decreased acid sphingomyelinase activity
HP:0034300.definition: Reduced activity of the enzyme acid sphingomyelinase activity in the blood circulation.

HP:0034301.name: Congenital pouch colon
HP:0034301.definition: A malformation of the colon in which a pouch-like dilatation of a varying degree of shortened colon is associated with an anorectal malformation. The pouch usually terminates in a fistulous communication with the genitourinary tract.

HP:0034302.name: Megalopapilla
HP:0034302.definition: A congenitally anomalous enlarged optic disc (surface area greater than 2.50 square millimeters). It is considered to be a normal variant without physiological defects.

HP:0034303.name: Notched T wave
HP:0034303.definition: A bifid T-wave with a notch duration between the 2 peaks at least 0.04 sec and an amplitude at least 0.05 mV.

HP:0034304.name: Epsilon wave
HP:0034304.definition: An electric signal of depolarization observed between the end of the QRS complex and the beginning of the T wave.

HP:0034305.name: 2:1 atrioventricular block
HP:0034305.definition: A type of second-degree atrioventricular block in which every other P wave is not conducted through the AV node such that only every other P wave is followed by a QRS complex.

HP:0034306.name: Ventricular bigeminy
HP:0034306.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a normal QRS followed by a premature ventricular contraction; a rhythmic pairing of normal and atypical beats originating in the ventricles in a 1-1 ratio such that an ectopic ventricular beat follows each regular heartbeat.

HP:0034307.name: Elevated left ventricular end-diastolic diameter
HP:0034307.definition: The LV end-diastolic internal diameter was measured from two-dimensional (2D) images in the parasternal long-axis view, timed with mitral valve closure at the level of the mitral valve chordae.

HP:0034308.name: Prolonged P wave
HP:0034308.definition: Abnormal increased in the duration of the P wave, which is a marker of delayed inter-atrial conduction.

HP:0034309.name: Multiflagellar spermatozoa
HP:0034309.definition: Spermatozoa with multiple flagella attached to the sperm head.

HP:0034310.name: Post-vaccination yellow fever
HP:0034310.definition: Infection with the yellow fever virus of the live-attenuated vaccine.

HP:0034311.name: Hypoplastic optic chiasm
HP:0034311.definition: Developmental defect characterized by undergrowth of the optic chiasm.

HP:0034312.name: Nocturnal hypoxemia
HP:0034312.definition: Abnormally reduced oxyhemoglobin saturation during sleep (nocturnal). Different thresholds are used in the literature, including more than 10 percent of total sleep time below a SpO2 of 90 percent.

HP:0034313.name: Hyperdynamic left ventricular ejection fraction
HP:0034313.definition: An abnormally increased ejection fraction of the left ventricle, usually defined as a left ventricular ejection fraction greater than 70 percent.

HP:0034314.name: Abnormal left ventricular ejection fraction
HP:0034314.definition: Any abnormality of the left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF), which is the fraction of chamber volume ejected in systole (stroke volume) in relation to the volume of the blood in the ventricle at the end of diastole (end-diastolic volume). Stroke volume (SV) is calculated as the difference between end-diastolic volume (EDV) and end-systolic volume (ESV). LVEF is calculated as [SV/EDV] in percent.

HP:0034315.name: Chronic cough
HP:0034315.definition: A persistent cough, defined as a cough lasting longer than eight weeks in adults or longer than four weeks in children.

HP:0034316.name: Thinning of the substantia nigra pars compacta
HP:0034316.definition: Reduced volume of pars compacta of the substantia nigra.

HP:0034318.name: Unusual virus reactivation
HP:0034318.definition: Reactivation is the mechanism whereby a latent virus that has infected a host cell switches to a lytic stage, undergoing productive viral replication and allowing the virus to spread. This term refers to reactivation regarded as unusual because of frequency, intensity, location, or nature of the virus, in the sense that the reactivation would not be observed in an immunocompetent host.

HP:0034319.name: CNS vasculitis with reactivation of varicella-zoster virus
HP:0034319.definition: A vasculopathy in the central nervous system (CNS) following reactivation of varicella-zoster virus due to a productive viral infection of both large and small cerebral arteries.

HP:0034320.name: Muscle fiber intracytoplasmic reducing inclusion bodies
HP:0034320.definition: Intracytoplasmic inclusions in myofibers that reduce nitro-blue tetrazolium (NBT) and thus stain strongly with the menadione-NBT stain.

HP:0034321.name: Elevated circulating guanidinoacetic acid concentration
HP:0034321.definition: Concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0034322.name: Reduced tissue galactocerebrosidase activity
HP:0034322.definition: Concentration or activity of galactocerebrosidase (EC 3.2.1.46) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:0034323.name: Reduced circulating growth hormone concentration
HP:0034323.definition: Concentration of growth hormone in the blood circulation below normal limits.

HP:0034324.name: Brachiocephalic artery aneurysm
HP:0034324.definition: An abnormal widening (dilatation) of the brachiocephalic artery

HP:0034325.name: Common carotid artery aneurysm
HP:0034325.definition: An abnormal widening (dilatation) of the common carotid artery.

HP:0034326.name: Adenomyosis
HP:0034326.definition: Inappropriate (ectopic) endometrial tissue proliferation within the uterine myometrium, often presenting clinically with painful menses and heavy menstrual bleeding.

HP:0034327.name: Posterior corneal stroma punctiform multicolored opacities
HP:0034327.definition: Thin, punctiform elements of various colors in the posterior stroma of the cornea, immediately anterior to Descemet membrane. The elements are visible to direct and indirect illumination.

HP:0034328.name: Fibro-obliterative bile-duct lesion
HP:0034328.definition: A condition in which the lumen of a bile duct has been filled by fibrous scar material, in effect replacing the bile duct with a fibrous scar.

HP:0034329.name: Dysplastic megalencephaly
HP:0034329.definition: A congenital brain malformation characterized by marked overgrowth and dysplasia affecting one or both cerebral hemispheres, and, in some cases, subcortical brain regions as well. The presence of dysplasia in dysplastic megalencephaly distinguishes it from other forms of generalized megalencephaly.

HP:0034330.name: Regional right ventricular hypokinesis
HP:0034330.definition: Decreased range of right ventricular motion in a portion of the right ventricle of the heart.

HP:0034331.name: McConnell sign
HP:0034331.definition: Severe hypokinesia of the mid-free wall of the right ventricle of the heart with a normal contraction of the apical segment of the right ventricle.

HP:0034332.name: Cognitive regression
HP:0034332.definition: Loss of cognitive developmental skills, as manifested by loss of developmental cognitive milestones.

HP:0034333.name: Increased circulating hypoxanthine concentration
HP:0034333.definition: Elevated concentration of hypoxanthine in the blood circulation.

HP:0034335.name: Inheritance qualifier
HP:0034335.definition: The terms in this hierarchy can be used to specify the context in which inheritance of a disease is typically observed.

HP:0034336.name: Splenic infarction
HP:0034336.definition: Ischemia and necrosis of part or all of the spleen resulting from compromise of blood supply resulting from arterial or venous occlusion.

HP:0034337.name: Claw hand deformity
HP:0034337.definition: An abnormality of the hand characterized by metacarpophalangeal (MCP) hyperextension and proximal interphalangeal (PIP) and distal interphalangeal (DIP) flexion. The position of the affected hand is said to resemble a claw.

HP:0034338.name: Imprinted
HP:0034338.definition: Requires that the abnormal allele be paternal or maternal in origin, depending on the disease-gene relationship. Imprinting refers to a normal developmental process in which either the paternal or maternal allele is inactivated, depending on the specific locus, thus leading to expression from only one copy of the gene. Disease typically manifests when a deleterious variant is inherited from a parent whose copy of the gene would normally be expressed, but not when a deleterious variant is inherited from a parent whose copy of the gene would normally be inactivated.

HP:0034339.name: Pseudoautosomal inheritance
HP:0034339.definition: A pattern of inheritance observed for alleles in the X-Y identical regions is referred to as pseudoautosomal inheritance, because it resembles the pattern seen for alleles located on autosomes.

HP:0034340.name: Pseudoautosomal dominant inheritance
HP:0034340.definition: A type of pseudoautosomal inheritance that is dominant and in which heterozygous males and females both manifest a disease phenotype.

HP:0034341.name: Pseudoautosomal recessive inheritance
HP:0034341.definition: A type of pseudoautosomal inheritance that is recessive and in which biallelic males and females both manifest a disease phenotype.

HP:0034342.name: Trapezius muscle aplasia
HP:0034342.definition: A developmental defect characterized by lack of formation of the trapezius muscle, which is broad superficial muscle that extends from the posterior neck to the posterior part of the trunk (thorax).

HP:0034343.name: Requires heterozygosity
HP:0034343.definition: A rarely encountered phenomenon in which condition is most severe in the heterozygous state. Such disorders are rare and currently all are X-linked. Most X-linked recessive conditions manifest if hemizygous in males, or biallelic in females, though may have a mild phenotype in the heterozygous state in females.

HP:0034344.name: Female-limited expression
HP:0034344.definition: Used to refer to a monogenic trait linked to an autosomal locus in which the phenotypic effects of allelic differences are expressed only in the female sex.

HP:0034345.name: Mendelian inheritance
HP:0034345.definition: A mode of inheritance of diseases whose pathophysiology can be traced back to deleterious variants in a single gene. The inheritance patterns of these single-gene (monogenic) diseases are often referred to as Mendelian in honor of Gregor Mendel.

HP:0034346.name: Nesidioblastosis
HP:0034346.definition: An abnormality of pancreatic beta cells characterized by a proliferation of abnormal beta cells throughout the entire pancreas, with enlarged islet size and number (hypertrophic islets), increased periductular islets, enlarged beta-cell nuclei and abundant clear cytoplasm. Occasionally beta cells with pleomorphic nuclei, ductuloinsular complexes, and neoformation of islets from ducts are observed.

HP:0034347.name: Greater auricular nerve thickening
HP:0034347.definition: Increase in thickness of the great auricular nerve, a cutaneous nerve of the head. It originates from the cervical plexus, with branches of spinal nerves C2 and C3. Thickening may lead to the nerve being palpable or even visible in this region.

HP:0034348.name: Subpulmonary stenosis
HP:0034348.definition: A cardiovascular malformation associated with narrowing of the outflow tract of the right ventricle immediately below the pulmonary valve.

HP:0034349.name: Supravalvar pulmonary stenosis
HP:0034349.definition: A cardiovascular malformation associated with narrowing at the level of the pulmonary sinotubular junction above the pulmonic valve.

HP:0034350.name: Valvular pulmonary stenosis
HP:0034350.definition: A cardiovascular malformation associated with narrowing of the outflow tract of the right ventricle immediately at the level of the pulmonary valve.

HP:0034351.name: Neuromyotonia
HP:0034351.definition: Peripheral nerve hyperexcitability manifesting as spontaneous discharges originating from motor axons or their terminals, lead to overactivity of muscles, typically manifesting as twitches, cramps and stiffness.

HP:0034352.name: Bile duct polyp
HP:0034352.definition: An elevated growth from the the mucosa of the bile duct.

HP:0034353.name: Appendicular spasticity
HP:0034353.definition: A type of spasticity that affects one or more limbs (arms or legs).

HP:0034354.name: Trichoschisis
HP:0034354.definition: Transverse fractures through the hair shafts (trichoschisis). Trichoschisis is characterized by a sharp transverse fracture of the hair shaft.

HP:0034355.name: White cerebellum sign
HP:0034355.definition: On computed tomography of the brain,the white (or dense) cerebellum sign is seen when the cerebellum appears dense with respect to the cerebral parenchyma. The increase in attenuation of cerebellum is in fact a relative hyperdensity caused by decreased attenutation of the brain. It represents anoxic-ischemic cerebral injury, and has a very poor prognosis.

HP:0034356.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of low molecular weight protein
HP:0034356.definition: Increased loss of low-molecular weight proteins by the kidneys, measured in terms of the fractional excretion (FE). The FE of low-molecular-weight proteins such as beta2-microglobulin can be measured in terms of plasma and urine concentrations, since urinary low-molecular-weight protein concentrations can vary with water reabsorption.

HP:0034357.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of glucose
HP:0034357.definition: Increased fractional excretion (FE) of glucose in the urine. The FE of glucose is the percentage of the glucose filtered by the kidney which is excreted in the urine. It is measured in terms of plasma and urine glucose, rather than by the interpretation of urinary glucose concentration alone, as urinary glucose concentrations can vary with water reabsorption.

HP:0034358.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of sodium
HP:0034358.definition: Increased fractional excretion (FE) of sodium in the urine. The FE of sodium is the percentage of the sodium filtered by the kidney which is excreted in the urine. It is measured in terms of plasma and urine sodium, rather than by the interpretation of urinary glucose concentration alone, as urinary glucose concentrations can vary with water reabsorption.

HP:0034359.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of phosphate
HP:0034359.definition: Increased fractional excretion (FE) of glucose in the phosphate. The FE of glucose is the percentage of the phosphate filtered by the kidney which is excreted in the urine. It is measured in terms of plasma and urine phosphate, rather than by the interpretation of urinary phosphate concentration alone, as urinary glucose concentrations can vary with water reabsorption.

HP:0034360.name: Action myoclonus
HP:0034360.definition: A type of myoclonus (arrhythmic muscular jerking) that is induced by voluntary movement. It is made worse by attempts at precise or coordinated movement (intention myoclonus) and may also be provoked by certain sensory stimuli.

HP:0034361.name: Redundant umbilical skin
HP:0034361.definition: Greater than normal amount of skin surrounding the umbilicus (belly button) with protrusion of the umbilicus above the plane of the abdomen.

HP:0034362.name: Dull foveal reflex
HP:0034362.definition: Reduced brightness of the foveal reflex, which normally is a bright pinpoint of light that is observed to move sideways or up and down in response to movement of the opthalmoscope.

HP:0034363.name: Corneal pterygium
HP:0034363.definition: Corneal pterygium is an ocular surface disease characterized mainly by a wing-shaped growth of limbal and conjunctival tissue over the adjacent cornea.

HP:0034364.name: Fibrofatty replacement of right ventricular myocardium
HP:0034364.definition: Replacement of the myocardium of the right ventricular free wall by fat and fibrous tissue.

HP:0034365.name: Elevated circulating alpha-aminoadipic semialdehyde concentration
HP:0034365.definition: Increased concentration of alpha-aminoadipic semialdehyde in the blood circulation.

HP:0034366.name: Fracture blister
HP:0034366.definition: Fracture blister is a type of blister that forms following acute bone fractures, typically near the ankle, wrist elbow or foot, where skin adheres tightly to bone with little subcutaneous fat cushioning. The blister that results resembles that of a second degree burn.

HP:0034367.name: Decreased circulating beta-mannosidase activity
HP:0034367.definition: Activity of the enzyme beta-mannosidase below the lower limit of normal. Beta-mannosidase is a lysosomal enzyme that catabolizes oligosaccharides.

HP:0034368.name: Urolithiasis
HP:0034368.definition: Renal stones are formed within the kidneys, and this is called nephrolithiasis. Urolithiasis is a condition that occurs when these stones exit the renal pelvis and move into the remainder of the urinary collecting system, which includes the ureters, bladder, and urethra.

HP:0034369.name: Decreased level of coenzyme Q10 in skeletal muscle
HP:0034369.definition: Reduced amount of coenzyme Q10,a naturally occurring quinone, in skeletal muscle tissue.

HP:0034371.name: Reduced circulating prekallikrein concentration
HP:0034371.definition: Reduced concentration of prekallikrein (PK; also known as Fletcher factor) in the blood circulation. PK is the precursor of plasma kallikrein, a serine protease that activates kinins. PK is cleaved to produce kallikrein by activated Factor XII.

HP:0034373.name: External tibial torsion
HP:0034373.definition: External twisting of the tibia resulting in the toes of each foot pointing outward (outtoeing) .

HP:0034374.name: Trident acetabulum
HP:0034374.definition: Abnormal appearance of the acetabulum characterized by spurs at the medial and lateral acetabular margin and in the center of the acetabulum, giving rise to shape resembling a three-pronged spear sadi to resemble a trident.

HP:0034375.name: Spherophakia
HP:0034375.definition: Spherophakia is a rare congenital condition that presents with weak zonules around a more spherical crystalline lens with an increased anteroposterior thickness of the lens, and highly myopic eye. The lens zonules are developmentally hypoplastic and abnormally weak and due to non-attachment of the posterior zonules to the equatorial zone of the lens, the lens changes its normal shape to spherical.

HP:0034376.name: Atrioventricular valve regurgitation
HP:0034376.definition: Regurgitation of a heart valve that controls blood flow from a an atrium to a ventricle, including mitral, tricuspid, or, rarely, single atrioventicular valve.

HP:0034377.name: Single atrioventricular valve regurgitation
HP:0034377.definition: Regurgitation of the single atrioventricular valve regurgitation (AVVR) in the context of a congenital heart defect with a single ventricle. Roughly three quarters of patients following Fontan procedure display AVVR.

HP:0034378.name: Urethrovesical occlusion
HP:0034378.definition: Blockage of the flow of urine from the bladder into the urethra.

HP:0034379.name: obsolete Vascular granular osmiophilic material deposition
HP:0034379.definition: Accumulation of granular osmiophilic material in blood vessel walls. Osmiophilic material becomes black upon staining with osmium tetroxide.

HP:0034380.name: Juvenile type testicular granulosa cell tumor
HP:0034380.definition: Juvenile granulosa cell tumor of the testis of neonates and infants is an uncommon lesion frequently associated with abnormal sex chromosome and ambiguous genitalia.

HP:0034381.name: Central nervous system axonal spheroid
HP:0034381.definition: Axonal spheroids are bubble-like biological features that form on most degenerating axons. During neurodegeneration, bubble-like swellings form along the length of the axon, a primary and early effect of dynamic axonal deformation. These varicosities, spheroids, or swellings have been described as beads on a string and branches bearing fruit, and they frequently appear on degenerating axons. The focal swellings on degenerating axons, axonal spheroids, are often filled with cellular debris such as organelles, pathological proteins, and disorganized cytoskeletal elements.

HP:0034382.name: Disease remission
HP:0034382.definition: A decrease in or disappearance of signs and symptoms typically associated with a disease course.

HP:0034383.name: Elevated circulating biliverdin concentration
HP:0034383.definition: Increased concentration of biliverdin, a green tetrapyrrolic bile pigment, in the blood circulation.

HP:0034384.name: Elevated circulating insulin:C-peptide ratio
HP:0034384.definition: Increased ratio of insulin to C-peptide in the blood circulation.

HP:0034385.name: Abnormal left ventricular endsystolic diameter
HP:0034385.definition: A deviation from the normal range of the left ventricular endsystolic diameter.

HP:0034386.name: Reduced left ventricular endsystolic diameter
HP:0034386.definition: A lower than normal left ventricular endsystolic diameter.

HP:0034388.name: Hilar lymph node enlargement
HP:0034388.definition: Hilar lymphadenopathy is swelling or enlargement of lymph nodes localized in hila, wedge-shaped anatomical structures containing pulmonary vessels, major bronchi, nerves and lymph nodes. Hilar lymph nodes are not visible on chest X-ray if they are not enlarged. Hilar lymph node enlargement can be caused by benign and malignant conditions and can be symmetrical (bilateral) or asymmetrical (unilateral).

HP:0034389.name: Pulmonary vein varix
HP:0034389.definition: Pulmonary vein varix (PVV), refers to a localized dilatation of a pulmonary vein. PVV is a rare condition and can be congenital or acquired. PVV typically occur at the confluence of the veins adjacent to the left atrium. PVVs are sometimes classified into three morphological types: saccular, tortuous and confluent.

HP:0034390.name: Decreased CSF glycine concentration
HP:0034390.definition: Abnormally decreased levels of glycine in cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0034391.name: Elbow contracture
HP:0034391.definition: A limitation in the passive range of motion of the elbow resulting from loss of elasticity in the periarticular tissues owing to structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules or skin.

HP:0034392.name: Joint contracture
HP:0034392.definition: A limitation in the passive range of motion of a joint resulting from loss of elasticity in the periarticular tissues owing to structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules or skin. A contracture prevents movement of the associated body part.

HP:0034393.name: Elbow extension contracture
HP:0034393.definition: An elbow contracture that limits the ability of the elbow joint to flex (flexion of the the elbow joint refers to bending the elbow joint to bring the hand closer to the shoulder), meaning that the elbow is fixed in an extended (straight) position.

HP:0034394.name: Forearm supination contracture
HP:0034394.definition: A contracture that limits the ability of the forearm to stabilize the hand in pronation (pronation refers to a rotation of the forearm that causes the palm and forearm to face downwards), meaning that the palm is fixed in a upward orientation. Restriction of supination/pronation can occur at the elbow (radial-humeral joint), at the wrist (radial-ulnar joint), and anywhere in between.

HP:0034395.name: Forearm pronation contracture
HP:0034395.definition: A contracture that limits the ability of the forearm to stabilize the hand in supiation (supination refers to a rotation of the forearm that causes the palm and forearm to face upwards), meaning that the palm is fixed in a downward orientation. Restriction of supination/pronation can occur at the elbow (radial-humeral joint), at the wrist (radial-ulnar joint), and anywhere in between.

HP:0034396.name: Hippocampal malrotation
HP:0034396.definition: Hippocampal malrotation, also termed incomplete inversion of the hippocampus or hippocampal malformation, is an increasingly recognized neuroimaging finding of undetermined clinical significance. It is characterized by features including (i) Round or pyramidal shape instead of ovoid shape; (ii) Medial position of the hippocampus on the hippocampal sulcus; (iii) The collateral sulcus is excessively deep or verticalized; (iv) Fimbria located medial to the hippocampus; (v) Small or displaced fornix; (vi) Enlarged temporal horn and empty choroid fissure; (vii) Thickened subiculum; (viii) Reduced upper horizontal portion of the parahippocampal gyrus.

HP:0034397.name: Claw toe deformity
HP:0034397.definition: Claw toes are characterized by hyperextension at the metatarsal-phalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints.

HP:0034398.name: Toe deformity
HP:0034398.definition: Abnormal positioning of toe phalanges. Deformities of the lesser toes often occur gradually, though they can be brought on by trauma. The main adult sagittal plane deformities consist of claw toes, hammer toes and mallet toes. Axial plane deformities include crossover toes.

HP:0034399.name: Prolonged central motor conduction time
HP:0034399.definition: Increased duration of the central motor conduction time (CMCT). The CMCT estimates the conduction time of corticospinal fibers between motor cortex and spinal (or bulbar) motoneurons. It includes the times for excitation of cortical cells, conduction via the corticobulbar-corticospinal tract and excitation of the motoneuron sufficient to reach its firing threshold. CMCT is calculated by subtracting the peripheral conduction time from the MEP latency recorded after cortical stimulation.

HP:0034400.name: Circumferential skin creases on extremities
HP:0034400.definition: Ringed creases of the skin of the extremities related to folding of excess skin.

HP:0034401.name: Atypical teratoid/rhabdoid tumor
HP:0034401.definition: An aggressive malignant embryonal neoplasm arising from the central nervous system. It is composed of cells with a large eccentric nucleus, prominent nucleolus, and abundant cytoplasm. Mutations of the SMARCB1 gene or very rarely SMARCA4 (BRG1) gene are present. The vast majority of cases occur in childhood. Symptoms include lethargy, vomiting, cranial nerve palsy, headache, and hemiplegia.

HP:0034402.name: Rhabdoid tumor of the kidney
HP:0034402.definition: A highly aggressive, extremely rare neoplasm of the kidney that is usually seen in children. The term rhabdoid is used because the tumor cells resemble rhabdomyoblasts but lack myogenic markers, and pathologic diagnosis requires familiarity with these microscopic features plus awareness that adult onset is possible. It can be associated with abnormalities of chromosome 22. It is characterized by the presence of cells with a large eccentric nucleus, prominent nucleolus, and abundant cytoplasm.

HP:0034403.name: Subcutaneous panniculitis-like T-cell lymphoma
HP:0034403.definition: A form of T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma in which cytotoxic CD8+ T cells infiltrate adipose tissue forming subcutaneous nodules.

HP:0034404.name: Fungal hyphae in sputum
HP:0034404.definition: Presence of hyphae (long, branching, filamentous structures produced by fungi) in sputum.

HP:0034405.name: Enlarged tectum
HP:0034405.definition: Increasaed size of the tectum, which is the region of the midbrain posterior to the cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius. The midbrain is the most superior portion of the brainstem.

HP:0034407.name: Reduced circulating 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase concentration
HP:0034407.definition: Decreased concentration of 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase in th blood circulation.

HP:0034408.name: Solitary angiokeratoma
HP:0034408.definition: A dark, keratotic papule about 2-10 mm in diameter, usually occurring on the lower extremeities. Usually the lesions begin as bright, soft, and nonkeratotic paules which grow larger and change to a firm, blue to black and keratotic stage.

HP:0034409.name: Fordyce angiokeratoma
HP:0034409.definition: A type of angiokeratoma that most commonly occurs on the scrotum of patients who are 40 years old or older. The typical single lesion is a dark red to blue dome-shaped papule 2-4 mm in diameter with a very discrete keratotic surface. Typically, they are multiple and arranged in a line parallel to the raphe mediana of the scrotum. They also occur on the vulva and less commnly on the penis.

HP:0034410.name: Angiokeratoma circumscriptum naeviforme
HP:0034410.definition: A type of angiokeratoma that typically presents in childhood as a large, mostly linear and unilateral hyperkeratotic plaque which is composed of confluent keratotic papules. The size ranges from a few centimeters up to a major part of the body surface. Initially the lesions present as multiple reddish macules, clinically similar to a nevus flammeus. Within several years they develop into acanthokeratotic papules that agrregate into plaques which may have a hyperkeratotic surface.

HP:0034411.name: Angiokeratoma of Mibelli
HP:0034411.definition: A type of angiokeratoma that typically presents in women on the dorsa of fingers and toes and multiple dark red papules with a slightly verrucous surface, each measuring about 3-5 mm in diameter.

HP:0034412.name: Laryngeal mass
HP:0034412.definition: A lump in the region of the larynx. A mass is any lump in the body that can be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes or an immune reaction. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup. Laryngeal masses can be visualized by multiple methods include computed tomography.

HP:0034413.name: Palate mass
HP:0034413.definition: A lump in the region of the palate. A mass is any lump in the body that can be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes or an immune reaction. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.

HP:0034414.name: Thick oral frenulum
HP:0034414.definition: Increased thickness of an oral frenulum, flaps of mucous membrane that extend from the midline gingiva to the upper or lower lip.

HP:0034415.name: Tooth avulsion
HP:0034415.definition: A type of dental trauma characterized by total dislocation of the tooth from its socket.

HP:0034416.name: Torn oral frenulum
HP:0034416.definition: Laceration or tear of an oral frenulum, flaps of mucous membrane that extend from the midline gingiva to the upper or lower lip.

HP:0034417.name: Intraoral laceration
HP:0034417.definition: A wound of the mucosa within the oral cavity covering lips, tongue, palate, gingiva, pharynx, or retropharynx.

HP:0034418.name: Erythematous oral mucosa
HP:0034418.definition: An erythematous lesion of the oral mucosa may result from a variety of tissue alterations, including inflammation, erythrocyte extravasation, and atrophy or reduced keratinization of the surface epithelium.

HP:0034419.name: Mitral chordae tendinae rupture
HP:0034419.definition: Breakage of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve. This can lead to loss of tension of one of the mitral valve leaflets and mitral regurgitation.

HP:0034420.name: History of cardiovascular procedure
HP:0034420.definition: Indicates that a cardiovascular procedure such as stenting, bypass, catherization was performed on a patient.

HP:0034421.name: Ejection click
HP:0034421.definition: A high-pitched sound that occurs at the moment of maximal opening of the aortic or pulmonary valves. They are heard just after the first heart sound. The sounds occur in the presence of a dilated aorta or pulmonary artery or in the presence of a bicuspid or flexible stenotic aortic or pulmonary valve. Ejection clicks may also be called ejection sounds.

HP:0034422.name: Cryofibrinogenemia
HP:0034422.definition: Cryofibrinogen is an abnormal protein that forms precipitate only in plasma. consisting of fibrinogen, fibronectin, alpha1-antitrypsin and alpha2-macroglobulin.

HP:0034423.name: triggered by allergens
HP:0034423.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to allergens.

HP:0034424.name: Clicking tinnitus
HP:0034424.definition: A type of tinnitus that presents as clicks, resembling the noise made by the snapping together of 2 fingers.

HP:0034425.name: Reduced hair sulfur content
HP:0034425.definition: Abnormally low amount of sulfur in hair.

HP:0034427.name: Purulent eye discharge
HP:0034427.definition: Secretion of pus-like (purulent) material from the eye, which may caused the eyelids to be matted together.

HP:0034429.name: Bacteria in cerebrospinal fluid
HP:0034429.definition: Presence of bacteria in the cerebrospinal fluid, as manifested by visual inspection or bacterial culture results.

HP:0034431.name: Joint crepitus
HP:0034431.definition: A popping, clicking or crackling sound that accompaniees movement of a joint.

HP:0034432.name: Intertriginous distribution
HP:0034432.definition: Applies to the localization of a skin lesion involving any area of the body where two opposing skin surfaces can touch and rub or chaff.

HP:0034433.name: Distributed along skin tension lines
HP:0034433.definition: Applies to the localization of a skin lesion that correspond to skin tension lines, which are linear clefts in the skin that indicate the direction of orientation of the underlying collagen fibers. Skin tension lines are also known as Langer's lines or lines of cleavage.

HP:0034434.name: Abnormal communication
HP:0034434.definition: Presence of any form of communication (e.g., verbal or non-verbal) that does not align with cultural expectations or developmental level.

HP:0034435.name: Abnormal eye contact
HP:0034435.definition: Any abnormality of eye contact behavior. We define eye contact as a form of nonverbal communication between two individuals who are facing each other in which an individual directs the eyes towards the eyes or face of the other individual. Eye contact occurs frequently and voluntarily during face-to-face verbal communication. The duration and frequency of eye contact that is interpreted to be appropriate may follow social and situational norms.

HP:0034436.name: Gaze avoidance
HP:0034436.definition: A deliberate avoidance of eye contact.

HP:0034437.name: Excessive eye contact
HP:0034437.definition: Tendency to maintain sustained eye contact for an inappropriately long period of time.

HP:0034439.name: Instep location
HP:0034439.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the arched middle portion of the foot in front of the ankle joint (i.e., instep).

HP:0034440.name: Ameliorated by ultraviolet light exposure
HP:0034440.definition: Applies to a skin lesion that is improved or made more bearable by exposure to ultraviolet light (sunshine or phototherapy).

HP:0034441.name: Decreased circulating aspartic acid concentration
HP:0034441.definition: An reduced concentration of aspartic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0034442.name: Abnormal circulating erythropoietin concentration
HP:0034442.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of erythropoietin in the blood circulation. Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the peritubular cells of the kidney that stimulates red blood cell production.

HP:0034443.name: Reduced circulating erythropoietin concentration
HP:0034443.definition: Decreased concentration of erythropoietin in the blood circulation. Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the peritubular cells of the kidney that stimulates red blood cell production.

HP:0034444.name: Abnormal gamma-glutamyltransferase level
HP:0034444.definition: Any deviation from the normal level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.

HP:0034445.name: Reduced gamma-glutamyltransferase level
HP:0034445.definition: Decreased level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.

HP:0034446.name: Elevated circulating histamine concentration
HP:0034446.definition: Increased concentration of histamine in the blood circulation.

HP:0034447.name: Increased circulating interleukin 18 concentration
HP:0034447.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-18 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034448.name: Abnormal phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
HP:0034448.definition: Any deviation from the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.

HP:0034449.name: Increased phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
HP:0034449.definition: An elevation above the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.

HP:0034450.name: Decreased phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
HP:0034450.definition: A reduction below the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.

HP:0034451.name: Rectovesical fistula
HP:0034451.definition: An aberrant, pathological communication between the rectum and the bladder.

HP:0034452.name: Rectoureteral fistula
HP:0034452.definition: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the ureter.

HP:0034454.name: Arachnoid granulation
HP:0034454.definition: Arachnoid granulations (AGs) are tufts of arachnoid membrane invaginated into the dural sinuses through which cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) enters the venous system. The lesions are primarily located in the parasagittal region along the superior sagittal sinus, which is occasionally seen at the transverse sinus. Normally dural venous sinus AGs typically range from 2 to 8 mm in size, but may grow enough to expand the dural sinuses, and even the inner table, diploic space and outer table of the skull.

HP:0034455.name: Increased CSF taurine concentration
HP:0034455.definition: Increased concentration of taurine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0034456.name: Elevated circulating glutathione concentration
HP:0034456.definition: An abnormally increased level of glutathione in the blood circulation.

HP:0034457.name: Hawkinsinuria
HP:0034457.definition: The concentration of hawkinsin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0034458.name: Elevated urinary phenylpyruvic acid level
HP:0034458.definition: An abnormally increased amount of phenylpyruvic acid in the urine.

HP:0034459.name: Ameliorated by lumbar puncture
HP:0034459.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by lumbar puncture.

HP:0034460.name: Increased CSF uracil concentration
HP:0034460.definition: An increased level of uracil in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0034461.name: Elevated urine kynurenine level
HP:0034461.definition: An abnormally increased amount of kynurenine in the urine.

HP:0034462.name: Increased CSF L-alloisoleucine concentration
HP:0034462.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of L-alloisoleucine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0034463.name: Hydroxylysinemia
HP:0034463.definition: An increased concentration of hydroxylysine in the blood circulation. Hydroxylysine arises from a post-translational hydroxy modification of lysine and is unique to collagen and proteins containing collagen-like sequences. Elevated concentrations of hydroxylysine may indicate increased bone turnover.

HP:0034464.name: Homocitrullinuria
HP:0034464.definition: An increased amount of L-homocitrulline in the urine. L-homocitrulline is an L-lysine derivative that is L-lysine having a carbamoyl group at the N(6)-position. It is found in individuals with urea cycle disorders.

HP:0034465.name: 2-hydroxyadipic aciduria
HP:0034465.definition: The concentration of 2-hydroxyadipic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0034466.name: Homoargininuria
HP:0034466.definition: An increased amount of homoarginine in the urine. Homoarginine is a nonproteinogenic alpha amino acid.

HP:0034467.name: Increased urinary cysteine level
HP:0034467.definition: An increased concentration of cysteine in the urine.

HP:0034468.name: Gastric xanthoma
HP:0034468.definition: Gastric xanthomas (also known as xanthelasmas) are are plaque-like red lesions defined by the presence of histiocytic containing lipids.

HP:0034469.name: Decreased stool elastase level
HP:0034469.definition: Reduced amount of pancreatic elastase in the stool. This feature may be observed with pancreatic insufficiency.

HP:0034470.name: Elevated stool chloride content
HP:0034470.definition: Elevated amount of chloride in the stool.

HP:0034471.name: Increased fecal coproporphyrin III:coproporphyrin I ratio
HP:0034471.definition: Abnormal relative increase in the amount of fecal coproporphyrin III as compared to coproporphyrin I in the feces.

HP:0034472.name: Increased fecal harderoporphyrin
HP:0034472.definition: Abnormally high concentration of harderoporphyrin in feces.

HP:0034473.name: Increased fecal heptacarboxylporphyrin
HP:0034473.definition: Abnormally high concentration of heptacarboxylporphyrin in feces.

HP:0034474.name: Increased fecal pentacarboxylporphyrin
HP:0034474.definition: Abnormally high concentration of pentacarboxylporphyrin in feces.

HP:0034475.name: Increased fecal isocoproporphyrin
HP:0034475.definition: Abnormally high concentration of isocoproporphyrin in feces.

HP:0034476.name: Positive fecal Clostridium botulinum test
HP:0034476.definition: Identification of Clostridium botulinum toxin in the feces.

HP:0034477.name: Perihepatic adhesions
HP:0034477.definition: Abnormal union of the membranous surfaces of the liver capsule and the parietal peritoneum due to inflammation or injury. Adhesions may be visualized by laparoscopy and may have a violin string appearance.

HP:0034478.name: Dilated vas deferens
HP:0034478.definition: Abnormal increase in diameter (expansion) of the vas deferens.

HP:0034479.name: Enlarged epididymis
HP:0034479.definition: Abnormal increase in the size of the epididymis.

HP:0034481.name: Atypical gestures
HP:0034481.definition: Spontaneous production of communicative gestures that are perceived as odd or mechanical, or are poorly integrated with other means of communication. This may include inaccurate mimicry of typical gestures.

HP:0034483.name: Bone marrow vacuolated lymphocytes
HP:0034483.definition: The presence of lymphocytes with multilple vacuoles (a membrane-bound cell organelle) in the bone marrow.

HP:0034484.name: Spinal cord calcifications
HP:0034484.definition: The presence of calcium deposition in the spinal cord.

HP:0034485.name: Neuroepithelial cyst
HP:0034485.definition: A benign epithelial-lined cystic lesion that can occur anywhere in the neuraxis. Neuroepithelial cysts are ependymal or epithelial lined fluid collections of unknown etiology within the central nervous system parenchyma with no obvious ventricular or subarachnoid connection. Most cysts are asymptomatic, however, some present with seizures, mass effect, or rarely with movement disorders. On imaging, they present as CSF-like parenchymal cysts with smooth, rounded borders and minimal or no surrounding signal intensity abnormality.

HP:0034486.name: Reduced circulating interleukin 7 concentration
HP:0034486.definition: A diminished concentration of interleukin-7 in the circulation.

HP:0034487.name: Increased circulating interleukin 12 concentration
HP:0034487.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-12 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034488.name: Increased circulating interleukin 13 concentration
HP:0034488.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-13 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034489.name: Increased circulating interleukin 2 concentration
HP:0034489.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-2 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034490.name: Increased circulating interleukin 4 concentration
HP:0034490.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-4 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034491.name: Increased circulating interleukin 5 concentration
HP:0034491.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-5 in the blood circulation.

HP:0034492.name: Salpingitis
HP:0034492.definition: An inflammation of the fallopian tube.

HP:0034493.name: Tubo-ovarian abscess
HP:0034493.definition: A tubo-ovarian abscess (TOA) is a complex infectious mass of the adnexa that forms as a sequela of pelvic inflammatory disease.

HP:0034494.name: Opacified paranasal sinuses
HP:0034494.definition: White appearance (radio-opaqueness) of a paranasal sinus on radiography.

HP:0034495.name: Elevated brain glutamine level by MRS
HP:0034495.definition: An increased in the level of glutamine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0034496.name: Abnormal brain glutamine level by MRS
HP:0034496.definition: A deviation from normal in the level of glutamine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0034497.name: Increased urinary hexanoic acid level
HP:0034497.definition: The concentration of hexanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0034498.name: Hepatic focal nodular hyperplasia
HP:0034498.definition: Hepatic focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) is a benign hepatic tumor. FNH develops within hepatic parenchymal tissue that is otherwise histologically normal. Macroscopically, the tumor is characterized by the presence of depressed, grayish-white scar, which is generally (but not always) located at the center of the lesion, with fibrous septa radiating outward, toward the periphery of the tumor. This stellate scar is found in only 50% of all FNH nodules, but its presence is regarded as pathognomonic. The lesion itself is usually lighter in color than the tissue that surrounds it, and it sometimes has a yellowish hue. FNH nodules are generally not capsulated; their margins are well defined, and they are sometimes lobulated.

HP:0034499.name: Increased bone marrow iron
HP:0034499.definition: An increased amount of iron in the bone marrow.

HP:0034500.name: Glenoid fracture
HP:0034500.definition: A fracture of the glenoid fossa, a relatively shallow dish is located on the lateral scapula and is the socket portion of the shoulder joint that meets to articulate the humeral head.

HP:0034501.name: Widened mediastinum
HP:0034501.definition: Abnormal increase in the width of the mediastinum, often defined as being greater than 6 to 8 cm.

HP:0034502.name: Narrow mediastinum
HP:0034502.definition: Abnormal decrease in the width of the mediastinum.

HP:0034503.name: Ovarian torsion
HP:0034503.definition: Ovarian torsion is a twisting of the ligaments that support the adnexa, cutting off the blood flow to the ovary.

HP:0034504.name: Septate gallbladder
HP:0034504.definition: Septate gallbladder is characterized by the presence of a septum that divides the gallbladder in two chambers. When the septum dividing the gallbladder lies longitudinally it is called bilobed gallbladder and when there is a transverse septum separating the fundus from the rest of the gallbladder it is called an hour-glass gallbladder.

HP:0034505.name: Gallbladder wall thickening
HP:0034505.definition: Abnormal increased in the thickness of the wall of the gallbladder.

HP:0034506.name: Gallbladder enlargement
HP:0034506.definition: Abnormal increased in the thickness of the size of the gallbladder.

HP:0034507.name: Gallbladder mass
HP:0034507.definition: An abnormal lesion or swelling seen on gallbladder imaging.

HP:0034508.name: Fingerprint bodies
HP:0034508.definition: Fingerprint bodies are inclusion bodies located at the periphery of the muscle fibers underneath the sarcolemma (subsarcolemmal), consisting of non-membrane-bound packed lamellae arranged in concentric patterns resembling fingerprints.

HP:0034509.name: Spheroid bodies
HP:0034509.definition: An accumulation of myofilamentous material within individual muscle fibers, forming usually round but occasionally elongated bodies ranging from 2 to 15 pm in size. The so-called spheroid bodies stain green with the modified trichrome preparation and are mainly present in the periphery of type 1 muscle fibers, where they may occupy large sectors sharply demarcated from the remainder of the cross-sectioned muscle fiber.

HP:0034510.name: Abnormal muscle tissue enzyme activity or level
HP:0034510.definition: Any deviation from the normal activity or histological staining of an enzyme in muscle tissue, usually measured in a muscle biopsy specimen.

HP:0034511.name: Reduced muscle aconitase activity
HP:0034511.definition: Diminished activity of the enzyne aconitase in muscle tissue.

HP:0034512.name: Transitional-cell carcinoma of the ureter
HP:0034512.definition: A cancer of the ureter that most often arises in the distal third of the ureter and is often diagnosed during the sixth and seventh decades of life. The most common presentation is gross hematuria or flank pain.

HP:0034513.name: Increased circulating Interferon-alpha concentration
HP:0034513.definition: An elevation in the concentration of interferon alpha measured in the blood circulation.

HP:0034514.name: Liver hamartoma
HP:0034514.definition: A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the liver.

HP:0034515.name: Ameloblastoma
HP:0034515.definition: Ameloblastoma is a benign odontogenic tumor generally present in the jaw bone. The tumor originates from the residual epithelium of the tooth germ, epithelium of odontogenic cysts stratified squamous epithelium and epithelium of the enamel organ.

HP:0034516.name: Ameliorated by ketogenic diet
HP:0034516.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by following a ketogenic diet.

HP:0034517.name: Pretibial hyperpigmentation
HP:0034517.definition: Darkening of the area of skin that overlies the shin.

HP:0034519.name: Muscle fiber fuchsinophilic inclusion bodies
HP:0034519.definition: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that react positively with acid fuchsin.

HP:0034520.name: Esophageal myenteric plexus degeneration
HP:0034520.definition: Deterioration of the cells of the myenteric plexus (also known as the Auerbach plexus) located between the layers of the muscular propria of the esophagus.

HP:0034521.name: Periorificial hyperkeratosis
HP:0034521.definition: Scaling and overgrowth of horny tissue of the skin surrounding body orifices (including peri-auricular, peri-oral, peri-anal areas.

HP:0034522.name: Eosinophilic lymph node infiltration
HP:0034522.definition: Presence of an elevated number of eosinophils in a lymph node (usually as demonstrated by lymph node biopsy).

HP:0034523.name: Blood parasite
HP:0034523.definition: Detection of a parasitic organism in the blood stream. Blood parasites include malaria plasmodia, microfilaria species, trypanosomes (the causative agents of African sleeping sickness and South American Changas disease) and the causative agents of schistosomiasis of the bladder and the intestine.

HP:0034524.name: Bloodstream trypomastigotes
HP:0034524.definition: Presence of trypomastigote parasites in the blood stream. This finding can be demonstrated by the identification of trypomastigote parasites on peripheral blood smear.

HP:0034525.name: Adamantinoma
HP:0034525.definition: A primary low-grade, malignant bone tumor that is predominantly located in the mid-portion of the tibia. Histologically, classic adamantinoma is a biphasic tumor characterized by epithelial and osteofibrous components that may be intermingled with each other in various proportions and differentiating patterns.

HP:0034526.name: Abnormal enzyme activity in muscle tissue
HP:0034526.definition: Deviation from the normal activity of an enzyme in muscle tissue.

HP:0034527.name: Reduced muscle phosphoglycerate kinase activity
