The primary pathology is the decreased rate and other qualities of thinking (e.g. naming of objects) are intact, just slowed. This may be associated with slowed speech, but may be internal and masked by speech that is limited to brief (yes or no) answers.

HP:0031844.name: Euphoria
HP:0031844.definition: Euphoria is an overwhelming and all-encompassing feeling of intense inner sense of joy, happiness, excitement, or elation that is far beyond and blatantly abnormal for what would typically be anticipated in the context or social circumstance. It is experienced as an unusual pleasurable feeling often with an inspirational sense of profound insight.

HP:0031845.name: Abnormal libido
HP:0031845.definition: Any deviation from the normal sexual drive or desire for sexual activity.

HP:0031846.name: Femur fracture
HP:0031846.definition: A break or crush injury of the thigh bone (femur).

HP:0031847.name: Difficulty walking backward
HP:0031847.definition: Reduced ability to walk (ambulate) in a backwards direction.

HP:0031848.name: Cock-walk gait
HP:0031848.definition: An abnormality of gait that can be observed in individuals with dystonic posture in which the individual walks with an extended trunk and flexed arms, while strutting on the toes without the heels touching the floor.

HP:0031849.name: Sleep-wake inversion
HP:0031849.definition: A reversal of sleeping habits, with a tendency to sleep during the day and be awake at night.

HP:0031850.name: Abnormal hematocrit
HP:0031850.definition: Any deviation from the normal ratio of the volume of red blood cells to the total volume of blood.

HP:0031851.name: Reduced hematocrit
HP:0031851.definition: A reduction below the normal ratio of the volume of red blood cells to the total volume of blood.

HP:0031853.name: Isomerism
HP:0031853.definition: Isomerism in the context of the congenitally malformed heart is defined as a situation where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are, in morphologic terms, symmetrical mirror images of each other.

HP:0031854.name: Left Isomerism
HP:0031854.definition: A type of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal left-sided structures.

HP:0031855.name: Right isomerism
HP:0031855.definition: A type of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal right-sided structures.

HP:0031856.name: Hobby horse gait
HP:0031856.definition: An abnormal gait characterized by toe walking, stiff legs, and skipping. The gait pattern has some resemblance to cock-walk gait, but affected individuals are able to improve their dystonic gait by walking backward.

HP:0031857.name: Ineffective esophageal peristalsis
HP:0031857.definition: Reduced or inadequate esophageal peristalsis, with resultant slow passage of contents through the esophagus.

HP:0031858.name: Esophageal furrows
HP:0031858.definition: Longitudinal grooves in the surface of the esophagus arranged in a longitudinal fashion (from top to bottom of the esophagus).

HP:0031860.name: Abnormal heart rate variability
HP:0031860.definition: Any abnormality in the variability of the time interval between successive heartbeats.

HP:0031861.name: Decreased heart rate variability
HP:0031861.definition: Reduced variation of beat-to-beat intervals of the heart that occurs in conjunction with the respiratory cycle.

HP:0031862.name: Increased heart rate variability
HP:0031862.definition: Increased variation of beat-to-beat intervals of the heart that occurs in conjunction with the respiratory cycle.

HP:0031863.name: Bloodstream infectious agent
HP:0031863.definition: The presence of an infectious agent in the blood circulation.

HP:0031864.name: Bacteremia
HP:0031864.definition: Presence of viable bacteria in the blood.

HP:0031865.name: Abnormal liver physiology
HP:0031865.definition: Any functional anomaly of the liver.

HP:0031866.name: Clasp-knife sign
HP:0031866.definition: Clasp-knife phenomenon refers to increased muscle tone while bending or stretching a limb, whereby there is a sudden relaxation (decrease in resistance) as the muscle continues to be stretched. This phenomenon has been likened to opening a clasp knife.

HP:0031867.name: Neck hypertonia
HP:0031867.definition: Increased passive stiffness or tightness of the neck musculature.

HP:0031868.name: Optic ataxia
HP:0031868.definition: Difficulty reaching visually guided goals in peripheral vision, with the deficit, leaves voluntary eye movements largely unaffected.

HP:0031869.name: Recurrent joint dislocation
HP:0031869.definition: Dislocation of a given joint repeated times.

HP:0031870.name: Phosphohydroxylysinuria
HP:0031870.definition: An elevated concentration of phosphohydroxylysine in the urine.

HP:0031871.name: Abnormal Langerhans cell morphology
HP:0031871.definition: Any functional anomaly of Langerhans cells, which are dendritic cells in the epidermis and some other locations. Langerhans cells play roles in immune surveillance and homeostasis.

HP:0031872.name: Absent Birbeck granules in Langerhans cells
HP:0031872.definition: Birbeck granules (BG) are cytoplasmic organelles that are only found in Langerhans cells (LC). The function of BG is still not completely understood, although most studies point toward an active role in receptor-mediated endocytosis and participation in the antigen-processing/presenting function of LC. This feature refers to the absence of BG in LC, a feature that can be documented by means of electron microscopy.

HP:0031873.name: Early chronotype
HP:0031873.definition: A tendency towards rising very early in the morning and going to bed early in the evening.

HP:0031874.name: Late chronotype
HP:0031874.definition: A tendency towards waking up very late in the morning and staying up late at night.

HP:0031875.name: Abnormal circulating hepcidin concentration
HP:0031875.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation.

HP:0031876.name: Decreased circulating hepcidin concentration
HP:0031876.definition: Concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0031877.name: Elevated circulating hepcidin concentration
HP:0031877.definition: Concentration of hepcidin in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0031878.name: Acromicria
HP:0031878.definition: Small hands and feet in proportion to the rest of the body.

HP:0031879.name: Abnormal eyelid physiology
HP:0031879.definition: Any functional abnormality of the eyelid.

HP:0031880.name: Eyelid laxity
HP:0031880.definition: Abnormally lax eyelid associated with tissue relaxation; it can be demonstrated by the eyelid distraction test and/or the eyelid snap test.

HP:0031881.name: Decreased tear drainage
HP:0031881.definition: A form of watery eye associated with obstruction of the nasolacrimal system. This may arise at the level of the punctum, the canaliculi, the sac or the nasolacrimal duct.

HP:0031882.name: Agyria
HP:0031882.definition: A congenital abnormality of the cerebral hemisphere characterized by lack of gyrations (convolutions) of the cerebral cortex. Agyria is defined as cortical regions lacking gyration with sulci great than 3 cm apart and cerebral cortex thicker than 5 mm.

HP:0031883.name: Increased proinsulin:insulin ratio
HP:0031883.definition: An elevated concentration of proinsulin (the prohormone precursor to insulin) to mature insulin in the circulation.

HP:0031884.name: Abnormal CSF glucose concentration
HP:0031884.definition: A deviation from normal concentration of glucose content in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0031885.name: Hyperglycorrhachia
HP:0031885.definition: Abnormally high glucose concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0031886.name: Abnormal LDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0031886.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood circulation.

HP:0031887.name: Abnormal chylomicron concentration
HP:0031887.definition: Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of chylomicrons.

HP:0031888.name: Abnormal HDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0031888.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL) in the blood.

HP:0031889.name: Abnormal VLDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0031889.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0031890.name: Increased urine urobilinogen
HP:0031890.definition: An elevated concentration of urobilinogen in the urine.

HP:0031891.name: Decreased total eosinophil count
HP:0031891.definition: Abnormal decrease of absolute number of eosinophils in the blood, per microlitre, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0031898.name: Rouleaux formation
HP:0031898.definition: Increased amount of stacking of erythrocytes into long chains. Rouleaux (singular: rouleau) is derived from a French word that can refer to a stack of coins put into a cylindircal paper roll. Rouleaux formation is observed with increased serum proteins, particularly fibrinogen and globulins, and represents the cause of increased erythrocte sedimentation rate because rouleaux sediment more readily than isolated red blood cells.

HP:0031899.name: Abnormal coagulation factor V activity
HP:0031899.definition: Any deviation from the activity of coagulation factor V.

HP:0031901.name: Elevated total serum tryptase
HP:0031901.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of total tryptase (alpha and beta tryptase) in the blood circulation.

HP:0031902.name: obsolete Decreased serum mast cell beta-tryptase concentration

HP:0031903.name: Abnormal circulating selenium concentration
HP:0031903.definition: Any deviation from the normal circulating concentration of selenium.

HP:0031904.name: Abnormal total hemolytic complement activity
HP:0031904.definition: Any deviation from the normal total hemolytic complement activity in the circulation.

HP:0031905.name: Increased total hemolytic complement activity
HP:0031905.definition: An abnormally elevated total hemolytic complement activity in the circulation.

HP:0031906.name: obsolete Decreased total hemolytic complement activity

HP:0031907.name: Anti-mitochondrial M2 antibody positivity
HP:0031907.definition: The presence of M2 anti-mitochondrial antibody (immunoglobulins) in the serum.

HP:0031908.name: Micrographia
HP:0031908.definition: Abnormally small-sized handwriting is formally defined as an impairment of fine motor skills, which mainly manifests as a progressive or stable reduction in amplitude during a writing task.

HP:0031909.name: Unicornuate uterus
HP:0031909.definition: A uterus that has a single horn, with a banana-like shape that may or may not have a secondary rudimentary uterine horn.

HP:0031910.name: Abnormal cranial nerve physiology
HP:0031910.definition: A functional abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

HP:0031912.name: Trigeminal anesthesia
HP:0031912.definition: Decreased or absent sensation in the distribution of the trigeminal nerve, which provides tactile, proprioceptive, and nociceptive sensation in the area of the face and mouth.

HP:0031913.name: Rhombencephalosynapsis
HP:0031913.definition: Rhombencephalosynapsis is a rare brain malformation defined by midline fusion of the cerebellar hemispheres with partial or complete loss of the intervening vermis.

HP:0031914.name: Fluctuating
HP:0031914.definition: Varying irregularly over time in severity, amount, or amplitude.

HP:0031915.name: Stable
HP:0031915.definition: This modifier can be applied to a phenotypic feature that does not vary in severity or amount over time.

HP:0031917.name: Digital ulcer
HP:0031917.definition: An open sore on the surface of the skin of a finger or toe.

HP:0031918.name: Ovarian sex cord-stromal tumor
HP:0031918.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of granulosa cells, Sertoli cells, Leydig cells, theca cells, and fibroblasts.

HP:0031919.name: Juvenile type ovarian granulosa cell tumor
HP:0031919.definition: Juvenile granulosa cell ovarian tumor (JGCOT) is a rare sex cord stromal tumor, occurring most frequently in premenarchal girls or young women. In contrast to adult granulosa cell tumor, JGCOT has a high mitotic index and more aggressive tumor growth. Microscopically it is seen as diffuse and regularly distributed neoplastic cells with a wide cytoplasm and pleomorphic hyperchromatic nucleus. Follicle formation, in various sizes and shapes, is important in JGCOT. Call-Exner bodies are infrequently seen in JGCOT in contrast to the adult type.

HP:0031920.name: Malignant ovarian granulosa cell tumor
HP:0031920.definition: An aggressive granulosa cell tumor that arises from the ovary.

HP:0031922.name: Renal artery duplication
HP:0031922.definition: The renal arteries carry blood from the aorta to the kidney; normally one renal artery is present on each side of the body. Renal artery duplication refers to the presence of two rather than one renal artery on a given side of the body.

HP:0031923.name: Hematocolpos
HP:0031923.definition: Accumulation of blood in the vagina usually due to vaginal obstruction.

HP:0031924.name: Rope sign
HP:0031924.definition: The presence of linear erythematous palpable cords, often on the lateral trunk.

HP:0031925.name: Rosette
HP:0031925.definition: A halo or spoke-wheel arrangement of cells surrounding a central core or hub. The central hub may consist of an empty-appearing lumen or a space filled with cytoplasmic processes. The cytoplasm of each of the cells in the rosette is often wedge-shaped with the apex directed toward the central core; the nuclei of the cells participating in the rosette are peripherally positioned and form a ring or halo around the hub.

HP:0031926.name: Homer Wright rosette
HP:0031926.definition: A type of rosette in which the central lumen or hub is filled with fiber-like processes.

HP:0031927.name: Flexner-Wintersteiner rosette
HP:0031927.definition: The tumor cells that form the Flexner-Wintersteiner rosette circumscribe a central lumen that contains small cytoplasmic extensions of the encircling cells; however, unlike the center of the Homer Wright rosette, the central lumen does not contain the fiber-rich neuropil.

HP:0031928.name: True ependymal rosette
HP:0031928.definition: A type of rosette in which a halo of cells surrounds an empty lumen.

HP:0031929.name: Perivascular pseudorosette
HP:0031929.definition: A type of rosette in which a spoke-wheel arrangement of cells with tapered cellular processes radiates around a wall of a centrally placed vessel.

HP:0031930.name: Neurocytic rosette
HP:0031930.definition: A type of rosette that is similar to the Homer Wright rosette, but the central fiber-rich neuropil island is larger and more irregular.

HP:0031931.name: Ocular flutter
HP:0031931.definition: Ocular flutter is an abnormal eye movement consisting of repetitive, irregular, involuntary bursts of horizontal saccades without an intersaccadic interval. It is generally superimposed on normal oculomotor behavior and its occurrence may be favored by various events, such as blinks, the triggering of normal saccades or optokinetic stimulation.

HP:0031932.name: Aorto-left ventricular tunnel
HP:0031932.definition: Aorto-left ventricular tunnel (ALVT) is a congenital extracardiac channel connecting the ascending aorta above the sino-tubular junction to either left or right ventricular cavity.

HP:0031933.name: Aorto-right ventricular tunnel
HP:0031933.definition: The presence of an extracardiac channel that connects the ascending aorta above the sinotubular junction to the cavity of the right ventricle.

HP:0031934.name: Abnormal descending aorta morphology
HP:0031934.definition: A structural abnormality of the part of the aorta that begins at the aortic arch and then descends through the chest and abdomen.

HP:0031935.name: Ascending aorta hypoplasia
HP:0031935.definition: Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of or the entire ascending aorta.

HP:0031936.name: Delayed ability to walk
HP:0031936.definition: A failure to achieve the ability to walk at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children learn to walk in a series of stages, and learn to walk short distances independently between 12 and 15 months.

HP:0031937.name: Tachylalia
HP:0031937.definition: Speech that is abnormally fast as compared to the perceived cultural norm.

HP:0031938.name: Abnormal conus terminalis morphology
HP:0031938.definition: Any structural anomaly of the conus terminalis, which is the distal bulbous part of the spinal cord at the location where the spinal cord tapers and ends (usually between the L1 and L2 lumbar vertebrae).

HP:0031941.name: Abnormal portal venous system morphology
HP:0031941.definition: Any structural anomaly of the portal venous system, which comprises all of the veins draining the abdominal part of the digestive tract, including the lower esophagus but excluding the lower anal canal. The portal vein conveys blood from viscera and ramifies like an artery at the liver, ending at the sinusoids. Tributaries of the portal vein, which make up the portal venous system, are the splenic, superior mesenteric, left gastric, right gastric, paraumbilical, and cystic veins.

HP:0031942.name: Congenital absence of portal vein
HP:0031942.definition: Anomaly where the intestinal and the splenic venous drainage bypass the liver and drain into systemic veins through other possible venous shunts.

HP:0031943.name: Akathisia
HP:0031943.definition: A state of motor restlessness, usually in the lower extremities, that is often but not always accompanied by a subjective sense of inner restlessness, an urge to move, and anxiety or dysphoria.

HP:0031944.name: Pleural thickening
HP:0031944.definition: An increase in the thickness of the pleura, generally related to scarring of the pleural tissue.

HP:0031945.name: Elevated circulating N,N-dimethylglycine concentration
HP:0031945.definition: An increased concentration of N,N-dimethylglycine in the circulation.

HP:0031946.name: Elevated urinary N,N-dimethylglycine level
HP:0031946.definition: An increased concentration of N,N-dimethylglycine in the urine.

HP:0031947.name: Tongue tremor
HP:0031947.definition: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the tongue.

HP:0031948.name: Snowball lesion of corpus callosum
HP:0031948.definition: Centrally located corpus callosum hyperintensities said to resemble snowballs upon magnetic resonance imaging (with T2 or Sagittal fluid attenuated inversion recovery [FLAIR] sequences). The central location in the callosum makes them pathognomonic for Susac syndrome.

HP:0031949.name: Recurrent bacterial upper respiratory tract infections
HP:0031949.definition: An increased susceptibility to bacterial upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent bacterial upper respiratory tract infections (running ears - otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).

HP:0031950.name: Usual interstitial pneumonia
HP:0031950.definition: Temporal and spatial heterogeneity in lungs based on presence of fibrosis and honeycombing.

HP:0031951.name: Nocturnal seizures
HP:0031951.definition: Seizures that occur while the affected individual is sleeping.

HP:0031952.name: Neurogenic claudication
HP:0031952.definition: Lumbar spinal stenoses may induce symptoms following an individually typical latency on standing or when walking due to swelling of the cauda equina, which leads to compression. This is referred to as neurogenic claudication. The symptoms of lumbar spinal stenosis can be explained by an increase in lumbar lordosis and spinal canal stenosis in an upright position compared to the sitting position or if spondylolisthesis is present by a shift of the vertebrae while standing and walking. Following an individually characteristic distance, walking becomes associated with deep muscular pain and with neurological deficits, such as sensory deficits and paresis in the lower limbs, which resolve within minutes when the affected person sits or lies down. Activities performed in a flexed posture, such as cycling often cause less problems than walking. For the same reason, walking uphill may be tolerated better than walking downhill. Clinical neurological examination at rest may be entirely normal but there is usually pain on hyperextension of the lumbar spine.

HP:0031953.name: Cautious gait
HP:0031953.definition: Cautious gait refers to an excessive degree of age-related changes in walking and fear of falling. The walking difficulties seem out of proportion when considering the patient's actual sensory or motor deficits. The gait appears slow, with a wider base than normal, reduced arm swing bilaterally and a slightly stooped posture. This type of gait change often occurs after the first time a patient has fallen.

HP:0031954.name: Dystonic gait
HP:0031954.definition: Dystonic gait disorders frequently appear bizarre, particularly because activity increases dystonic tonus and posture. The abnormal posture of the foot in dystonic gait typically involves inversion, plantar flexion and tonic extension of the big toe. In many patients complex types of walking, such as walking backwards and running are paradoxically less impaired than walking forward and may seem completely unaffected. Sensory tricks, for instance, if the affected individual rests a hand on his or her neck, may improve or even normalize dystonic gait in some patients.

HP:0031955.name: Antalgic gait
HP:0031955.definition: To avoid pain weight is put on the affected leg for as short a time as possible, resulting in a limp. The patients appear to be walking as if there were a thorn in the sole of the foot. To reduce the load on the affected leg the patients lift and lower their foot in a fixed ankle position.

HP:0031956.name: Elevated circulating aspartate aminotransferase concentration
HP:0031956.definition: The concentration of aspartate aminotransferase (AST) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0031957.name: Spastic hemiparetic gait
HP:0031957.definition: Spastic hemiparesis is characterized by a dominance of the tonus in the upper limb flexor muscles: the arm is held in an adducted posture and is bent and rotated inwards, the forearm is pronated and the hand and the fingers are flexed. The leg is slightly bent at the hip, the knee cannot be extended fully at the end of the stance phase and the foot is inverted and in a plantar flexed position. Gait is slow, with a wide base and asymmetrical with a shortened weight-bearing phase on the paretic side. During the swing phase, the paretic leg performs a lateral movement (circumduction) which is characteristic of this gait disorder, also termed Wernicke-Mann gait. Spastic gait problems typically worsen on attempts to walk faster.

HP:0031958.name: Spastic paraparetic gait
HP:0031958.definition: A type of spastic gait in which the legs are usually slightly bent at the hip and in an adducted position. The knees are extended or slightly bent and the feet are in a plantar flexion position. This posture requires circumduction of the legs during walking. The gait may appear stiff (spastic gait disorder) or stiff as well as insecure (spastic ataxic gait disorder). In spastic paraparetic gait, each leg appears to be dragged forward. If the muscle tone in the adductors is marked, the resulting gait disorder is referred to as scissor gait.

HP:0031959.name: Leg dystonia
HP:0031959.definition: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the legs.

HP:0031960.name: Arm dystonia
HP:0031960.definition: A type of dystonia (abnormally increased muscular tone causing fixed abnormal postures) that affects muscles of the arms.

HP:0031961.name: Abnormal serum anion gap
HP:0031961.definition: Any deviation from the normal value of the serum anion gap, which is calculated from the electrolytes measured in the chemical laboratory, is defined as the sum of serum chloride and bicarbonate concentrations subtracted from the serum sodium concentration.

HP:0031962.name: Elevated serum anion gap
HP:0031962.definition: An abnormally high value of the serum anion gap (the sum of serum chloride and bicarbonate concentrations subtracted from the serum sodium concentration).

HP:0031963.name: Decreased serum anion gap
HP:0031963.definition: An abnormally low value of the serum anion gap (the sum of serum chloride and bicarbonate concentrations subtracted from the serum sodium concentration).

HP:0031964.name: Elevated circulating alanine aminotransferase concentration
HP:0031964.definition: An abnormally high concentration in the circulation of alanine aminotransferase (ALT).

HP:0031965.name: Increased RBC distribution width
HP:0031965.definition: Red blood cell distribution width (RDW) is a simple parameter of the standard full blood count and a measure of heterogeneity in the size of circulating erythrocytes. It is provided by automated hematology analyzers and it reflects the range of the red cell size. It is calculated by dividing the standard deviation of erythrocyte volume by the mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and multiplied by 100 to convert to a percentage.

HP:0031967.name: Cloudy urine
HP:0031967.definition: The appearance of the urine having visible material in suspension, i.e., appearing cloudy.

HP:0031969.name: Reduced blood urea nitrogen
HP:0031969.definition: An abnormally low concentration of urea nitrogen in the blood.

HP:0031970.name: Abnormal blood urea nitrogen concentration
HP:0031970.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of urea nitrogen in the blood.

HP:0031971.name: Subaortic ventricular septal bulge
HP:0031971.definition: A localized hypertrophy of the subaortic segment of the ventricular septum has been frequently described in elderly persons, and variously termed subaortic ventricular septal bulge (VSB), sigmoid-shaped septum, localized or discrete upper septal hypertrophy.

HP:0031972.name: Presyncope
HP:0031972.definition: Presyncope is a state of lightheadedness, muscular weakness, blurred vision, and feeling faint. Presyncope is most often cardiovascular in cause.

HP:0031973.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio
HP:0031973.definition: An abnormal increase in the ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk.

HP:0031974.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio - 0.6
HP:0031974.definition: Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk is 0.6 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

HP:0031975.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio - 0.7
HP:0031975.definition: Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk is 0.7 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

HP:0031976.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio - 0.8
HP:0031976.definition: Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk is 0.8 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

HP:0031977.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio - 0.9
HP:0031977.definition: Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk is 0.9 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

HP:0031978.name: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio - 1.0
HP:0031978.definition: Ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk is 1.0 (The normal cup-to-disc ratio is 0.3).

HP:0031979.name: Abnormal urine carbohydrate level
HP:0031979.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carbohydrate in the urine.

HP:0031980.name: Abnormal urine carboxylic acid level
HP:0031980.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carboxylic acid in the urine.

HP:0031981.name: Elevated urine glycolate
HP:0031981.definition: An increased concentration of glycolate in the urine.

HP:0031982.name: Abnormal putamen morphology
HP:0031982.definition: Any structural anomaly of the putamen, a brain nucleus which together with the caudate nucleus and fundus striati makes up the striatum.

HP:0031983.name: Abnormal pulmonary thoracic imaging finding
HP:0031983.definition: This term groups terms representing abnormal findings derived from chest X-ray investigation of the lung. In general, lung abnormalities can manifest as opacities (areas of increased density) or as regions with decreased density.

HP:0031984.name: Esophageal food impaction
HP:0031984.definition: A piece of food that has gotten stuck in the esophagus and prevents further swallowing.

HP:0031985.name: Esophageal exudate
HP:0031985.definition: An exudate is a mass of fluid and cells that has seeped out of blood vessels or an organ, usually related to inflammation. In the esophagus, exudates usually present as whitish plagues on the surface of the esophageal mucosa.

HP:0031986.name: Polyminimyoclonus
HP:0031986.definition: Minipolymyoclonus or polyminimyoclonus is a hyperkinetic movement disorder phenomenology characterized by intermittent, low-amplitude, arrhythmic movements of the hands, commonly of several fingers, with amplitudes just sufficient to produce visible and palpable movements of the joints. It is mostly noticed while the individual is maintaining a posture (commonly outstretched hands) or during action (especially the initial phase of movement).

HP:0031987.name: Diminished ability to concentrate
HP:0031987.definition: The inability to focus or concentrate on a specific task, activity, or object. The subject may find themselves unable to grasp or understand written text and re-reads frequently without understanding. Familiar tasks or activities are severely compromised due to the lack of ability to concentrate. Thinking through multi-step problems is typically very difficult or impossible, leading to avoidance of such activities.

HP:0031989.name: Perioral spasm
HP:0031989.definition: A sudden involuntary contraction of the musculature surrounding the mouth.

HP:0031990.name: Chvostek sign
HP:0031990.definition: A contraction of ipsilateral facial muscles subsequent to percussion over the facial nerve.

HP:0031991.name: Increased urinary excretion of galactosyl hydroxylysine
HP:0031991.definition: An increased concentration of beta-1-galactosyl-O-hydroxylysine (Gal-Hyl) in the urine. This is a biochemical marker of bone resorption.

HP:0031992.name: Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
HP:0031992.definition: Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (AHCM) is diastolic dysfunction due to abnormal stiffness of the left ventricle during diastole, with resultant impaired ventricular filling. In AHCM thickened apical segments produce a crowded, spade-shaped, small apical cavity.

HP:0031993.name: Hoffmann sign
HP:0031993.definition: A Hoffmann test is performed by flicking the fingernail of the long finger, from dorsal to volar, on each hand while the hand was supported by the examiner's hand. The test was done with the neck in the neutral position and then with the neck maximally forward flexed. Any flexion of the ipsilateral thumb and/or index finger was interpreted as a positive test.

HP:0031994.name: Bronchial breath sound
HP:0031994.definition: Bronchial breath sounds contain much higher frequency components than normal breath sounds due to alteration of the low pass filtering function of the alveoli, as occurs in consolidation. It is loud, hollow, and high pitch. Expiratory phase is longer than inspiratory phase with the inspiratory-expiratory ratio (I:E) changing from normal 3:1 to 1:2. There is distinct pause between inspiration and expiration due to absent alveolar phase. It is associated with whispering pectoriloquy.

HP:0031995.name: Squawks
HP:0031995.definition: Squawks are short inspiratory wheezes of less than 200 ms duration and are also known as squeaks. Acoustic analysis shows the fundamental frequency varying between 200 and 300 Hz. Squawks usually occur in late inspiration and are often preceded by late inspiratory crackles.

HP:0031996.name: Inspiratory crackles
HP:0031996.definition: Crackles that are heard during the inspiratory phase.

HP:0031997.name: Early inspiratory crackles
HP:0031997.definition: Crackles that appear at the beginning of inspiration and end before mid-inspiration.

HP:0031998.name: Late inspiratory crackles
HP:0031998.definition: Crackles that appear any time after the beginning of inspiration and last till the end of inspiration.

HP:0032000.name: Pleural rub
HP:0032000.definition: An abnormal breath sound that is nonmusical, short and explosive. It is grating, rubbing, creaky, or leathery in character and present in both phases of respiration. Typically the expiratory component mirrors the inspiratory component. It occurs due to inflamed pleural surface rubbing each other during breathing. Clinically, it is important to differentiate it from crackles

HP:0032001.name: Pink urine
HP:0032001.definition: An abnormal pink color of urine.

HP:0032002.name: Orange urine
HP:0032002.definition: An abnormal orange color of urine.

HP:0032003.name: Green urine
HP:0032003.definition: An abnormal green color of urine.

HP:0032004.name: Pruritus vulvae
HP:0032004.definition: A sensation of itching in the vulvar region.

HP:0032005.name: Hemidystonia
HP:0032005.definition: Hemidystonia refers to dystonia which involves the ipsilateral face, arm, and leg.

HP:0032006.name: Lip tremor
HP:0032006.definition: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the lip.

HP:0032007.name: Maceration
HP:0032007.definition: A softening and breaking down of skin resulting from prolonged exposure to moisture. Macerated skin becomes soft and wrinkly and takes on a whitish hue.

HP:0032008.name: Pulmonary fat embolism
HP:0032008.definition: The release of fat globules into the venous circulation, thereby blocking blood circulation to the lung.

HP:0032009.name: Infantile constant exotropia
HP:0032009.definition: Constant exotropia occurring before 6 months of age.; often associated with a large angle of deviation and ocular/CNS abnormalities.

HP:0032010.name: Basic constant exotropia
HP:0032010.definition: Constant exotropia for near and distance, presenting after 6 months of age.

HP:0032011.name: Heterophoria
HP:0032011.definition: Heterophorias are latent deviations that are controlled by fusion. In certain circumstances (specific visual tasks, fatigue, illness, etc.), fusion can no longer be maintained and decompensation occurs.

HP:0032012.name: Heterotropia
HP:0032012.definition: Manifest deviation of the visual axes not controlled by fusion.

HP:0032013.name: Hypermetric horizontal saccades
HP:0032013.definition: Overshoot of horizontal (sideways) saccadic eye movements.

HP:0032014.name: Dysmetric vertical saccades
HP:0032014.definition: Inaccurate saccades (rapid movement of the eye between fixation points) in the vertical direction.

HP:0032015.name: Dysmetric horizontal saccades
HP:0032015.definition: Inaccurate saccades (rapid movement of the eye between fixation points) in the horizontal direction.

HP:0032016.name: Abnormal sputum
HP:0032016.definition: Abnormal appearance of material expectorated (coughed up) from the respiratory system and that is composed of mucus but may contain other substances such as pus, blood, microorganisms, and fibrin.

HP:0032017.name: Sputum eosinophilia
HP:0032017.definition: An increased proportion of eosinophils in sputum in the differentiated cell count.

HP:0032018.name: Multiple mononeuropathy
HP:0032018.definition: A type of peripheral neuropathy that happens when there is damage to two or more different nerve areas characterized by peripheral neuropathy of both the motor and sensory nerves of at least two different nerve trunks. Different nerves are affected either simultaneously or sequentially.

HP:0032020.name: Eosinophilic bladder infiltration
HP:0032020.definition: Transmural inflammation of the bladder predominantly with eosinophils, associated with fibrosis with or without muscle necrosis.

HP:0032021.name: Eosinophilic liver infiltration
HP:0032021.definition: Cellular infiltration of the liver parenchyma with a preponderance of eosinophils.

HP:0032022.name: Eosinophilic dermal infiltration
HP:0032022.definition: Presence of abnormally increased amounts of intraepidermal inflammatory cells with a predominance of eosinophils.

HP:0032023.name: Eosinophilic gallbladder infiltration
HP:0032023.definition: Cellular infiltrate confirmed by a cellular infiltrate comprised of mainly eosinophils in the gallbladder wall on histological examination.

HP:0032024.name: Ileal ulcer
HP:0032024.definition: An erosion of the mucous membrane in a portion of the ileum.

HP:0032025.name: Reduced circulating alpha-1-antitrypsin concentration
HP:0032025.definition: A reduced concentration or activity of circulating alpha-1 antitrypsin, which is a 52-kDa glycoprotein mainly synthesized and secreted by hepatocytes into the bloodstream. Alpha-1 antitrypsin is a serine-proteinase inhibitor that it is crucial in maintaining protease-antiprotease homeostasis in the lungs.

HP:0032026.name: Anetoderma
HP:0032026.definition: Circumscribed area of flaccid skin due to the loss of elastic tissue in the dermis.

HP:0032027.name: Retinal dots
HP:0032027.definition: Yellow, white or grayish lesions in the retina that are well-defined/distinct, individual and mostly uniform in size.

HP:0032028.name: Macular dots
HP:0032028.definition: Yellow, white or grayish lesions in the macula that are well-defined/distinct, individual and mostly uniform in size.

HP:0032029.name: Floppy eyelid
HP:0032029.definition: Excessive eyelid tissue laxity, typically affecting both upper eyelids and associated with spontanteous tarsal eversion during sleep. It is more common in the obese, it may be associated with obstructive sleep apnea and it may result in corneal exposure or chronic papillary conjunctivitis.

HP:0032030.name: Lateral canthal tendon laxity
HP:0032030.definition: Laxity of the tendon stabilizing the lateral aspect of the tarsal plate to the zygomatic bone. This can result in rounded appearance of the lateral canthus. Also, when the eyelid is pulled medially, more than 2 mm movement of the canthal angle may be observed.

HP:0032031.name: Medial canthal tendon laxity
HP:0032031.definition: Laxity of the tendon stabilizing the medial aspect of the tarsal plate to the anterior and posterior lacrimal crests. This may lead to more than 2mm movement of the punctum when the eyelid is pulled laterally.

HP:0032032.name: Horizontal eyelid laxity
HP:0032032.definition: Abnormally lax eyelid associated with tissue relaxation, predominantly in the horizontal plane. It can be demonstrated by the horizontal eyelid distraction test (e.g. by pulling the eyelid medially and laterally). Medial and/or lateral canthal tendon laxity are often present.

HP:0032033.name: Vertical eyelid laxity
HP:0032033.definition: Abnormally lax eyelid associated with tissue relaxation, predominantly in the vertical plane. It can be demonstrated by vertical lid pull. Loosening of vertical stabilizing structures (e.g. lower lid retractors) or tarsal atrophy are often present.

HP:0032034.name: Upper eyelid laxity
HP:0032034.definition: Abnormally lax upper eyelid associated with tissue relaxation.

HP:0032035.name: Lower eyelid laxity
HP:0032035.definition: Abnormally lax lower eyelid associated with tissue relaxation.

HP:0032036.name: Reduced contrast sensitivity
HP:0032036.definition: An abnormality in perception of contrast. Spatial contrast is a physical dimension referring to the light-dark transition of a border or an edge in an image that delineates the existence of a pattern or an object. Contrast sensitivity refers to a measure of how much contrast a person requires to see a target. Contrast-sensitivity measurements differ from acuity measurements; acuity is a measure of the spatial-resolving ability of the visual system under conditions of very high contrast, whereas contrast sensitivity is a measure of the threshold contrast for seeing a target.

HP:0032037.name: Mildly reduced visual acuity
HP:0032037.definition: Mild reduction of the ability to see. On the 6m visual acuity scale, mild reduction is defined as less than 6/12 but at least 6/18. On the 20ft visual acuity scale, mild reduction is defined as less than 20/40 but at least 20/70. On the decimal visual acuity scale, mild reduction is defined as less than 0.5 but at least 0.3.

HP:0032039.name: Abnormality of the ocular adnexa
HP:0032039.definition: An anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

HP:0032040.name: Abnormal ocular adnexa physiology
HP:0032040.definition: A functional anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

HP:0032041.name: Vocal cord polyp
HP:0032041.definition: A small growth on a vocal cord that may appear as pedunculated or sessile and have varying size, shape, and color.

HP:0032044.name: Decreased vigilance
HP:0032044.definition: A decrease in the ability to maintain sustained attention is characterized by reduced alertness.

HP:0032045.name: Hypoplastic carotid canal
HP:0032045.definition: Underdevelopment of the carotid canal, which normally is a circular aperture in the temporal bone of the skull through which the internal carotid artery and the carotid plexus of nerves traverse.

HP:0032046.name: Focal cortical dysplasia
HP:0032046.definition: A type of malformation of cortical development that primarily affects areas of neocortex. It can be identified on conventional magnetic resonance imaging as focal cortical thickening, abnormal gyration, and blurring between gray and white matter, often associated with clusters of heterotopic neurons.

HP:0032047.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type I
HP:0032047.definition: A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by abnormal cortical layering.

HP:0032048.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type Ia
HP:0032048.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal radial cortical lamination.

HP:0032049.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type Ib
HP:0032049.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal tangential cortical lamination.

HP:0032050.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type Ic
HP:0032050.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal radial and tangential cortical lamination.

HP:0032051.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type II
HP:0032051.definition: A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by disrupted cortical lamination and specific cytological abnormalities.

HP:0032052.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIa
HP:0032052.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type II that is characterized by dysmorphic neurons, which present with a significantly enlarged cell body and nucleus, malorientation, abnormally distributed intracellular Nissl substance and cytoplasmic accumulation of neurofilament proteins.

HP:0032053.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIb
HP:0032053.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type II that is characterized by dysmorphic neurons (significantly enlarged with accumulation of neurofilament proteins) and balloon cells.

HP:0032054.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type III
HP:0032054.definition: A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by cortical lamination abnormalities associated with a principal lesion, usually adjacent to or affecting the same cortical area/lobe.

HP:0032055.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIIa
HP:0032055.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by alterations in architectural organization (cortical dyslamination) or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons outside Layer 5) in patients with hippocampal sclerosis (also known as Ammon's horn sclerosis).

HP:0032056.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIIb
HP:0032056.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by altered architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia without six-layered structure) and/or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons) of the neocortex, which occur adjacent to glial or glioneuronal tumor.

HP:0032057.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIIc
HP:0032057.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by alterations in architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia) or cytoarchitectural composition of the neocortex (hypertrophic neurons), which occur adjacent to vascular malformations (cavernomas, arteriovenous malformations, leptomeningeal vascular malformations, telangiectasias, meningioangiomatosis).

HP:0032058.name: Focal cortical dysplasia type IIId
HP:0032058.definition: A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by altered architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia without six-layered structure) or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons) of the neocortex, which occur adjacent to other lesions acquired during early life (not included into FCD Type IIIa-c). These lesions comprise a large spectrum including traumatic brain injury, glial scarring after prenatal or perinatal ischemic injury or bleeding, and inflammatory or infectious diseases, i.e. Rasmussen encephalitis, limbic encephalitis, bacterial or viral infections.

HP:0032059.name: Mild malformation of cortical development
HP:0032059.definition: A malformation of cortical development characterized by mild abnormalities of the cortex: excessive heterotopic neurons in Layer 1 or microscopic neuronal clusters or excess of single neurons of normal morphology in deep white matter.

HP:0032060.name: Epithelioid hemangioma
HP:0032060.definition: A benign neoplasm that includes blood vessel proliferation and a dense eosinophilic inflammatory infiltrate, manifesting as flesh/plum-colored pruritic nodules and papules, most commonly affecting the ear and the periauricular area.

HP:0032061.name: Severely increased total eosinophil count
HP:0032061.definition: Severe increase in circulating eosinophils, usually characterized as more than 1500 eosinophils per microlitre.

HP:0032062.name: Mallory-Weiss tear
HP:0032062.definition: Vomiting-induced mucosal laceration at the esophago-gastric junction.

HP:0032063.name: Ankle joint effusion
HP:0032063.definition: Abnormal accumulation of fluid in or around the ankle joint.

HP:0032064.name: Gastrointestinal eosinophilia
HP:0032064.definition: Eosinophilic infiltration of one or more gastrointestinal organs. Gastrointestinal eosinophilia is a broad term for abnormal eosinophil accumulation in the GI tract, involving many different disease identities. These diseases include primary eosinophil associated gastrointestinal diseases, gastrointestinal eosinophilia in HES and all gastrointestinal eosinophilic states associated with known causes. Each of these diseases has its unique features but there is no absolute boundary between them.

HP:0032065.name: Abnormal serum bicarbonate concentration
HP:0032065.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.

HP:0032066.name: Decreased serum bicarbonate concentration
HP:0032066.definition: An abnormal reduction of the concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.

HP:0032067.name: Elevated serum bicarbonate concentration
HP:0032067.definition: An abnormal increase in the concentration of bicarbonate, HCO3[-], in the circulation.

HP:0032068.name: Increased urinary mucus
HP:0032068.definition: An increased amount of urinary mucus. A small amount of mucus is produced by mucous membrane epithelial cells of the urinary tract. An increased amount of mucus can be detected upon urinalysis or other assays and may indicate conditions such as urinary tract infection, urinary tract reconstruction involving the use of bowel segments, or contamination of the urine sample prior to urinalysis.

HP:0032069.name: Anti-thyroglobulin antibody positivity
HP:0032069.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react to thyroglobulin.

HP:0032070.name: Leptomeningeal enhancement
HP:0032070.definition: Contrast material enhancement of the pia mater or enhancement that extends into the subarachnoid spaces of the sulci and cisterns is leptomeningeal enhancement. Leptomeningeal enhancement is usually associated with meningitis, which may be bacterial, viral, or fungal. The primary mechanism of this enhancement is breakdown of the blood-brain barrier without angiogenesis.

HP:0032071.name: Eosinophilic pneumonia
HP:0032071.definition: The presence of eosinophils in lung tissue, generally as detected by tissue biopsy, with or without blood eosinophilia.

HP:0032072.name: Popliteal synovial cyst
HP:0032072.definition: A fluid-filled mass that is a distention of a preexisting bursa in the popliteal fossa, most commonly the gastrocnemio-semimembranosus bursa. This bursa is unique in that it communicates with the knee joint, unlike other periarticular bursae, via an opening in the joint capsule posterior to the medial femoral condyle.

HP:0032073.name: Aplasia of the fallopian tube
HP:0032073.definition: Aplasia, that is failure to develop, of the fallopian tube.

HP:0032075.name: Splenopancreatic fusion
HP:0032075.definition: Fusion of the pancreatic tail and spleen.

HP:0032077.name: Male urethral meatus stenosis
HP:0032077.definition: An abnormal narrowing of the urethral opening (meatus) of the penis.

HP:0032078.name: Angel-shaped phalanx
HP:0032078.definition: A phalangeal malformation that is termed angel-shaped phalanx (ASP), because of its resemblance to the angels used for decoration of Christmas trees. The various components of an angel-shaped phalanx are: diaphyseal cuff (wings), surrounding a meta-diaphyseal core (body), which may appear empty or structured with a cone-shaped epiphysis (skirt) and pseudoepiphysis (head).

HP:0032079.name: Medial degeneration
HP:0032079.definition: Medial degeneration of the aorta is to be used as an overarching term for any aortic surgical specimens that demonstrate one or more of the specific histopathologies mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation, elastic fiber fragmentation and/or loss, elastic fiber thinning, elastic fiber disorganization, smooth muscle cell nuclei loss, laminar medial collapse, smooth muscle cell disorganization, medial fibrosis. Grading of medial degeneration is based on the average overall severity of specific histopathologies as described, considering the worst area(s) sampled from multiple slides and aorta sections.

HP:0032081.name: Intralamellar mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation
HP:0032081.definition: A type of mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation in which the increase in mucoid extracellular matrix does not significantly alter the arrangement of the lamellar units.

HP:0032082.name: Translamellar mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation
HP:0032082.definition: A type of mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation in which the increase in mucoid extracellular matrix alters the arrangement of the lamellar units to varying degrees.

HP:0032083.name: Aortic elastic fiber fragmentation
HP:0032083.definition: Loss and/or fragmentation of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta creating increasingly extended translamellar spaces, with absence of elastic fibers, and increased gaps in elastic fiber lamellae as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.

HP:0032084.name: Aortic elastic fiber thinning
HP:0032084.definition: A thinning out of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta that creates widening of intralamellar spaces, as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.

HP:0032085.name: Aortic elastic fiber disorganization
HP:0032085.definition: Nonparallel arrangement/disarray of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.

HP:0032086.name: Aortic smooth muscle cell nuclei loss
HP:0032086.definition: A region of the aortic media in which smooth muscle cell nuclei, involving multiple lamellae, are not clearly identifiable on an hematoxylin and eosin stain.

HP:0032087.name: Aortic laminar medial collapse
HP:0032087.definition: Architecturally, a compaction of aortic medial elastic fibers that creates thinning of the lamellar unit secondary to a band-like smooth muscle cell loss identified using a stain for elastic fibers.

HP:0032088.name: Aortic smooth muscle cell disorganization
HP:0032088.definition: Nonparallel arrangement/disarray of smooth muscle cells of the aortic media creating focal/multifocal disarray or sometimes nodular aggregates of smooth muscle cells.

HP:0032089.name: Aortic medial fibrosis
HP:0032089.definition: An increase in collagen fibers creating areas of substitutive fibrosis or a widening of intralamellar spaces in the media of the aorta. This can be seen in conjunction with a loss to varying degrees of parallel arrangement of the elastic lamellae (or lamellar units).

HP:0032090.name: Intralamellar aortic medial fibrosis
HP:0032090.definition: A type of aortic medial fibrosis in which the increase in collagen does not significantly alter the arrangement of the lamellar units.

HP:0032091.name: Translamellar aortic medial fibrosis
HP:0032091.definition: A type of aortic medial fibrosis in which the increase in collagen is more scar-like, altering the arrangement of the lamellar units.

HP:0032092.name: Left ventricular outflow tract obstruction
HP:0032092.definition: Left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) obstruction can occur at the valvular, subvalvular, or supravalvular level. In general, there is an obstruction to forward flow which increases afterload, and if untreated, can result in hypertrophy, dilatation, and eventual failure of the left ventricle.

HP:0032094.name: Increased circulating surfactant protein level
HP:0032094.definition: An increased concentration of a surfactant protein in the blood circulation. Pulmonary surfactant is a highly surface-active mixture of proteins and lipids that is synthesized and secreted onto the alveoli by type II epithelial cells. The protein part of surfactant constitutes of four types of surfactant proteins (SP), SP-A, SP-B, SP-C and SP-D. SP-A and SP-D are hydrophilic proteins that regulate surfactant metabolism and have immunologic functions. These two proteins are detectable in the bloodstream and an elevated level may reflect idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.

HP:0032096.name: Abnormal manganese concentration
HP:0032096.definition: A deviation from the normal range of manganese in the blood circulation.

HP:0032097.name: Hypermanganesemia
HP:0032097.definition: An elevation above the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.

HP:0032098.name: Hypomanganesemia
HP:0032098.definition: A reduction below the normal concentration of manganese in the blood.

HP:0032099.name: Perioral radial furrowing
HP:0032099.definition: The presence of radial grooves in the skin surrounding the mouth (see Figure 4 of PMID:27833976).

HP:0032100.name: Abnormal doll's eye reflex
HP:0032100.definition: The doll's eye reflex (also known as oculocephalic reflex) is a test of brain function that is performed in comatose patients by elevating the head roughly 30 degrees and rapidly rotating the head from side to side with the eyes kept open. A normal response is for the eyes to move in the opposite direction. If the eyes do not move in the opposite direction this may indicate severe brain damage.

HP:0032101.name: Unusual infection
HP:0032101.definition: A type of infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection. There are five general subtypes. (i) Opportunistic infection, meaning infection by a pathogen that is not normally able to cause infection in a healthy host (e.g., pneumonia by Pneumocystis jirovecii or CMV); (ii) Unusual location (focus) of an infection (e.g., an aspergillus brain abscess); (iii) a protracted course or lack of adequate response to treatment (e.g., chronic rhinosinusitis); (iv) Unusual severity or intensity of an infection; and (v) unusual recurrence of infections.

HP:0032102.name: Wilson sign
HP:0032102.definition: Wilson sign is defined as the elicitation of pain by internally rotating the patient's tibia during knee extension between 90 degrees and 30 degrees of flexion and then relieving that pain by externally rotating the tibia.

HP:0032104.name: Saccadic oscillation
HP:0032104.definition: An involuntary abnormality of fixation in which there is an abnormal saccade away from fixation followed by an immediate corrective saccade.

HP:0032105.name: Macrosaccadic oscillations
HP:0032105.definition: A type of saccadic oscillations with brief periods of fixation between saccades (intersaccadic interval approximately 200 msec). Macrosaccadic oscillations (up to 40 degrees) straddle the intended fixation position and show a crescendo-decrescendo pattern.

HP:0032106.name: Conjunctival icterus
HP:0032106.definition: Conjunctival icterus is a condition where there is yellowing of the whites of the eyes. This is most commonly seen in patients who have liver disease.

HP:0032107.name: Limbal stem cell deficiency
HP:0032107.definition: A condition characterized by a loss or deficiency of the stem cells in the limbus that are vital for re-population of the corneal epithelium and to the barrier function of the limbus.

HP:0032108.name: Mildly reduced contrast sensitivity
HP:0032108.definition: A mild reduction in the ability to perceive visual contrast characterized by 0.20-0.59 log unit contrast sensitivity loss.

HP:0032109.name: Moderately reduced contrast sensitivity
HP:0032109.definition: A moderate reduction in the ability to perceive visual contrast characterized by 0.60-0.99 log unit contrast sensitivity loss.

HP:0032110.name: Severely reduced contrast sensitivity
HP:0032110.definition: A severe reduction in the ability to perceive visual contrast characterized by 1.00 log unit or more contrast sensitivity loss.

HP:0032111.name: Abnormal Vistech contrast sensitivity test
HP:0032111.definition: An abnormality in perception of contrast as measured by the Vistech wall chart sine wave grating test.

HP:0032112.name: Abnormal Pelli Robson contrast sensitivity chart test
HP:0032112.definition: An abnormality in perception of contrast as measured by the Pelli-Robson contrast sensitivity chart, which is a large wall-mounted chart, with letters of a fixed size (comprising spatial frequencies appropriate for estimating peak contrast sensitivity) that decrease in contrast.

HP:0032113.name: Semidominant inheritance
HP:0032113.definition: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on chromosomes in which a trait can manifest in a monoallelic (e.g. heterozygotes) and biallelic (e.g. homozygotes, compound heterozygotes) state, with similar or differing phenotype severity present dependent on the number of alleles affected.

HP:0032114.name: Saccadic intrusion
HP:0032114.definition: An involuntary abnormality of fixation in which there is an abnormal saccade away from fixation followed by a delayed corrective saccade.

HP:0032116.name: Macrosquare-wave jerks
HP:0032116.definition: Horizontal 10-40 degree excursions from fixation and back again.

HP:0032118.name: Retinitis
HP:0032118.definition: Inflammation of the retina of the eye.

HP:0032120.name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system physiology
HP:0032120.definition: Any functional abnormality of the part of the nervous system that consists of the nerves and ganglia outside of the brain and spinal cord.

HP:0032121.name: Froment sign
HP:0032121.definition: An abnormal result of a physical examination of the the hand that tests for palsy of the ulnar nerve. This nerve innervates the adductor pollicis and interossei muscles and thereby enables adduction of the thumb and extension of the interphalangeal joint. An abnormal result consists in reduced functionality and muscular weakness in the pinch grip between the thumb and index finger of the affected hand as the patient attempts to pinch a piece of paper that the examiner tries to pull away. The flexor pollicis longus muscle tries to compensate for the weakness by flexing the tip of the thumb at the interphalangeal joint.

HP:0032122.name: Very low visual acuity
HP:0032122.definition: A reduction in visual acuity with best corrected visual acuity between 1.40 (20/500) and 1.89 logMAR (up to roughly 20/1590).

HP:0032123.name: Ultra-low vision
HP:0032123.definition: Best corrected visual acuity worse than 1.90 logMAR (roughly 20/1590).

HP:0032124.name: Abnormal unswitched memory B cell proportion
HP:0032124.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the unswitched memory B cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD27+IgM+, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032125.name: Increased unswitched memory B cell proportion
HP:0032125.definition: Abnormal increase of the unswitched memory B cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD27+IgM+, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032126.name: Decreased unswitched memory B cell proportion
HP:0032126.definition: Abnormal reduction of the unswitched memory B cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD27+IgM+, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032127.name: Abnormal plasmablast proportion
HP:0032127.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of plasmablasts, commonly characterized as CD27+CD38hi and sometimes additionally as IgMlowCD24-, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032128.name: Increased proportion of plasmablasts
HP:0032128.definition: Abnormal increase of plasmablasts, commonly characterized as CD27+CD38hi and sometimes additionally as IgMlowCD24-, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032129.name: Decreased proportion of plasmablasts
HP:0032129.definition: Abnormal decrease of plasmablasts, commonly characterized as CD27+CD38hi and sometimes additionally as IgMlowCD24-, measured as percentage of total B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032130.name: Mycobacterium abscessus abscessus infection
HP:0032130.definition: Mycobacterium abscessus complex comprises a group of rapidly growing, multidrug-resistant, nontuberculous mycobacteria that are responsible for a wide spectrum of skin and soft tissue diseases, central nervous system infections, bacteremia, and ocular and other infections.

HP:0032131.name: Cervical dysplasia
HP:0032131.definition: Cervical dysplasia is the precursor to cervical cancer. It is caused by the persistent infection of the human papillomavirus (HPV) into the cervical tissue. Affected cells develop morphologic features with immature basaloid- type squamous cells and mitotic figures in the upper half of the cervical epithelium.

HP:0032132.name: Decreased circulating total IgG concentration
HP:0032132.definition: A reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.

HP:0032133.name: Transient decreased circulating total IgG
HP:0032133.definition: A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.

HP:0032134.name: Chronic decreased circulating total IgG
HP:0032134.definition: A lasting reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.

HP:0032135.name: Decreased circulating IgG subclass concentration
HP:0032135.definition: A reduction below the normal concentration of a subclass of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood.

HP:0032136.name: Decreased circulating IgG1 concentration
HP:0032136.definition: A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG1 subclass in the blood circulation.

HP:0032137.name: Decreased circulating IgG3 concentration
HP:0032137.definition: A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG3 subclass in the blood circulation.

HP:0032138.name: Decreased circulating IgG4 concentration
HP:0032138.definition: A reduction in immunoglobulin levels of the IgG4 subclass in the blood circulation.

HP:0032139.name: Reduced isohemagglutinin level
HP:0032139.definition: Level of isohemagglutinin reduced below expected concentration. An isohemagglutinin refers to the naturally occurring antibodies in the ABO blood group system (i.e., anti-A in a group B person, anti-B in a group A person, and anti-A, anti-B, and anti-A,B in a group O person).

HP:0032140.name: Decreased specific antibody response to vaccination
HP:0032140.definition: A reduced ability to synthesize postvaccination antibodies against toxoids and polysaccharides in vaccines, as measured by antibody titer determination following vaccination.

HP:0032141.name: Precordial pain
HP:0032141.definition: A type of chest pain that arises in the or under the left breast and often described as throbbing, stabbing, or burning, and lasting hours or longer. The pain may arise with or after effort, and may spread to the left arm or left side of the neck.

HP:0032142.name: Fetor hepaticus
HP:0032142.definition: Fetor hepaticus is the characteristic breath of patients with severe parenchymal liver disease, which has been said to resemble the odor of a mixture of rotten eggs and garlic.

HP:0032143.name: Burning mouth
HP:0032143.definition: An intense sensation of burning, scalding, or tingling feeling of the tongue or other regions of the oral mucosa.

HP:0032144.name: Coffee ground vomitus
HP:0032144.definition: Vomit that has the appearance of coffee grounds, which occurs due to the presence of coagulated blood in the vomit.

HP:0032145.name: Sural nerve atrophy
HP:0032145.definition: Wasting of the sural nerve, a sensory nerve in the calf region of the leg.

HP:0032146.name: HbC hemoglobin
HP:0032146.definition: Presence of an abnormal type of hemoglobin characterized by the substitution of a glutamic acid residue at position 7 following the initial methionine residue by a lysine (6GAG>6AAG). The presence of HbC can be determined by hemoglobin electrophoresis.

HP:0032147.name: Erythromelalgia
HP:0032147.definition: Recurrent episodes of redness, burning pain, and warmth of the extremities following exposure to heat or exercise with symptoms predominantly involving the feet.

HP:0032148.name: Episodic pain
HP:0032148.definition: Intermittent pain, i.e., pain that occurs occasionally and at irregular intervals.

HP:0032149.name: Breakthrough pain
HP:0032149.definition: A episode of severe pain that breaks through (i.e., temporarily exacerbates) a period of persistent pain.

HP:0032150.name: Paroxysmal rectal pain
HP:0032150.definition: Excruciating burning pain in the rectal area that may be triggered by defecation.

HP:0032151.name: Episodic eosinophilia
HP:0032151.definition: Recurrent episodes of marked eosinophilia that resolve spontaneously.

HP:0032152.name: Keratosis pilaris
HP:0032152.definition: An anomaly of the hair follicles of the skin that typically presents as small, rough, brown folliculocentric papules distributed over characteristic areas of the skin, particularly the outer-upper arms and thighs.

HP:0100029.name: Lingual thyroid
HP:0100029.definition: An aberrant thyroid gland or Ectopic thyroid located at the base of the tongue, just posterior to the foramen cecum as a result of a failure of the thyroid to descend.

HP:0100030.name: Accessory ectopic thyroid tissue
HP:0100030.definition: Accessory ectopic thyroid tissue arising from remnants of the thyroglossal duct anywhere along the path of the thyroglossal duct tract.

HP:0100031.name: Neoplasm of the thyroid gland
HP:0100031.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the thyroid gland.

HP:0100033.name: Tics
HP:0100033.definition: Repeated, individually recognizable, intermittent movements or movement fragments that are almost always briefly suppressible and are usually associated with awareness of an urge to perform the movement.

HP:0100034.name: Motor tics
HP:0100034.definition: Movement-based tics affecting discrete muscle groups.

HP:0100035.name: Phonic tics
HP:0100035.definition: Tics are defined as movements or sounds that resemble physiological motor behaviors, but are typically inopportune to social context and appear sudden, repetitive, and often exaggerated. Tic vocalizations commonly termed vocal or phonic tics may include any possible sound (eg, sniffing, coughing, throat clearing, whistling, or grunting), word, or sentence and are most commonly encountered within the spectrum of primary tic disorders, as Tourette syndrome.

HP:0100036.name: Pseudo-fractures
HP:0100036.definition: A band of bone material of decreased density forming alongside the surface of the cortical bone with thickening of the periosteum. Callus formation in the affected area is common and gives the appearance of a false fracture.

HP:0100037.name: Abnormality of the scalp hair
HP:0100037.definition: An abnormality of the hair of head.

HP:0100038.name: Slow-growing scalp hair
HP:0100038.definition: Scalp hair whose growth is slower than normal.

HP:0100039.name: Thickened cortex of bones
HP:0100039.definition: An Abnormality of cortical bone leading to an abnormal thickness of the cortex of affected bones.

HP:0100040.name: Broad 2nd toe
HP:0100040.definition: A broad appearance of the second toe.

HP:0100041.name: Broad 3rd toe
HP:0100041.definition: A broad appearance of the third toe.

HP:0100042.name: Broad 4th toe
HP:0100042.definition: A broad appearance of the fourth toe.

HP:0100043.name: Broad 5th toe
HP:0100043.definition: A broad appearance of the fifth toe.

HP:0100048.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 2nd toe

HP:0100050.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 2nd toe
HP:0100050.definition: Epiphyses of the 2nd toe are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0100053.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 2nd toe
HP:0100053.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 2nd toe.

HP:0100059.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 3rd toe

HP:0100061.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 3rd toe
HP:0100061.definition: Epiphyses of the 3rd toe are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0100064.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 3rd toe
HP:0100064.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 3rd toe.

HP:0100070.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 4th toe

HP:0100072.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 4th toe
HP:0100072.definition: Epiphyses of the 4th toe are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0100075.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 4th toe
HP:0100075.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 4th toe.

HP:0100081.name: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 5th toe

HP:0100083.name: Ivory epiphyses of the 5th toe
HP:0100083.definition: Epiphyses of the 5th toe are hard and dense like ivory. Such an epiphysis has a uniformly dense appearance on radiographs.

HP:0100086.name: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 5th toe
HP:0100086.definition: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 5th toe.

HP:0100088.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0100089.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0100090.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0100091.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe

HP:0100092.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe

HP:0100093.name: Abnormality of the epiphysis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe
