HP:0100235.name: Synostosis involving bones of the toes

HP:0100238.name: Synostosis involving bones of the upper limbs
HP:0100238.definition: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the upper limbs.

HP:0100240.name: Synostosis of joints
HP:0100240.definition: The abnormal fusion of neighboring bones across a joint.

HP:0100241.name: Ectopic respiratory mucosa
HP:0100241.definition: Ectopic respiratory epithelium presenting as a superficial lesion in the skin usually localized unilateral in the skin of the forearm and associated with ipsilateral hand malformations.

HP:0100242.name: Sarcoma
HP:0100242.definition: A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells. Bone and soft tissue sarcomas are the main types of sarcoma. Sarcoma is usually highly malignant.

HP:0100243.name: Leiomyosarcoma
HP:0100243.definition: A smooth muscle connective tissue tumor, which is rare type of cancer that is a malignant neoplasm of smooth muscle. When such a neoplasm is benign, it is called a leiomyoma.

HP:0100244.name: Fibrosarcoma
HP:0100244.definition: A fibroblastic sarcoma is a malignant tumor derived from fibrous connective tissue and characterized by immature proliferating fibroblasts or undifferentiated anaplastic spindle cells.

HP:0100245.name: Gastrointestinal desmoid tumor
HP:0100245.definition: Benign, slow-growing tumors without any metastatic potential. Despite their benign nature, they can damage nearby structures causing organ dysfunction. Histologically they resemble low-grade fibrosarcomas, but they are very locally aggressive and tend to recur even after complete resection. There is a tendency for recurrence in the setting of prior surgery and the most common localisation of these tumors is intraabdominal from smooth muscle cells of the instestine.

HP:0100246.name: Osteoma
HP:0100246.definition: Osteomas are bony growths found most commonly on the skull and mandible; however, they may occur in any bone of the body. Osteomas do not usually cause clinical problems and do not become malignant.

HP:0100247.name: Recurrent singultus
HP:0100247.definition: A contraction of the diaphragm that repeats several times per minute. In humans, the abrupt rush of air into the lungs causes the epiglottis to close, creating a hic sound. Also known as synchronous diaphragmatic flutter (SDF), or singultus, from the Latin singult, the act of catching one's breath while sobbing. The hiccup is an involuntary action involving a reflex arc.

HP:0100248.name: Hemiballismus
HP:0100248.definition: Hemiballismus is a rare movement disorder that is caused primarily by damage to various areas in the basal ganglia. Hemiballismus is usually characterized by involuntary flinging motions of the extremities. The movements are often violent and have wide amplitudes of motion. They are continuous and random and can involve proximal and/or distal muscles on one side of the body, while some cases even include the facial muscles. The more a patient is active, the more the movements increase. With relaxation comes a decrease in movements.

HP:0100249.name: Calcification of muscles
HP:0100249.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in muscle tissue.

HP:0100251.name: Multiple central nervous system lipomas
HP:0100251.definition: The presence of multiple lipomas located in the central nervous system.

HP:0100253.name: Abnormality of the medullary cavity of the long bones
HP:0100253.definition: An abnormality of the medullary cavity (medulla, innermost part), which is the central cavity of bone shafts where red bone marrow and/or yellow bone marrow (adipose tissue) is stored.

HP:0100254.name: Stenosis of the medullary cavity of the long bones

HP:0100255.name: Metaphyseal dysplasia
HP:0100255.definition: The presence of dysplastic regions in metaphyseal regions.

HP:0100256.name: Senile plaques
HP:0100256.definition: Senile plaques are extracellular deposits of amyloid in the gray matter of the brain.

HP:0100257.name: Ectrodactyly
HP:0100257.definition: A condition in which middle parts of the hands and/or feet (digits and meta-carpals and -tarsals) are missing giving a cleft appearance. The severity is very variable ranging from slightly hypoplastic 3rd toe/fingers over absent 2nd or 3rd toes/fingers as far as oligo- or monodactyl hands and/or feet.

HP:0100258.name: Preaxial polydactyly
HP:0100258.definition: A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the thumb or great toe.

HP:0100259.name: Postaxial polydactyly
HP:0100259.definition: A form of polydactyly in which the extra digit or digits are localized on the side of the fifth finger or fifth toe.

HP:0100260.name: Mesoaxial polydactyly
HP:0100260.definition: The presence of a supernumerary finger or toe (not a thumb or hallux) involving the third or fourth metacarpal/tarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.

HP:0100261.name: Abnormal tendon morphology
HP:0100261.definition: An abnormality of the structure or form of the tendons, also often called sinews.

HP:0100266.name: Synostosis of carpals/tarsals
HP:0100266.definition: The carpus consists of the scaphoid, lunate, triquetal, pisiform, captitate, hamate, trapezoid, and trapezium bones. The tarsus consists of the talus, calcaneus, cuboid, cuneiform, and navicular bones. This term applies if there is any fusion among the bones of the carpus or tarsus.

HP:0100267.name: Lip pit
HP:0100267.definition: A depression located on a lip.

HP:0100268.name: Upper lip pit
HP:0100268.definition: Depression located on the vermilion of the upper lip, usually paramedian.

HP:0100269.name: Paramedian lip pit
HP:0100269.definition: Depression located paramedially on the vermilion of a lip.

HP:0100270.name: Abnormality of dorsoventral patterning of the limbs
HP:0100270.definition: An abnormality resulting from a defect or disruption of dorsoventral patterning that normally happens during early development of the limbs. A disruption of the normal development of the dorsoventral axis may lead to a variable spectrum of different phenotypic abnormalities that may affect the nails and or palmar and dorsal side of the hands and/or feet, ultimately changing the normal dorsoventral appearance of the affected limbs.

HP:0100271.name: Hyponasal speech
HP:0100271.definition: Hyponasal speech is when there is an abnormally reduced nasal airflow during speech often in a setting of nasal obstruction or congestion.

HP:0100272.name: Branchial sinus
HP:0100272.definition: A congenital branchial sinus is a remnant of the embryonic branchial arches and their intervening clefts and pouches that has failed to regress completely. Sinuses typically have their external orifice inferior to the ramus of the mandible. They may traverse the parotid gland, and run in close vicinity to the facial nerve in the external auditory canal.

HP:0100274.name: Gustatory lacrimation
HP:0100274.definition: Gustatory lacrimation results from an aberrant innervation of fibers from the seventh cranial nerve to the pterygopalatine ganglion which are destined originally for the submandibular ganglion. This aberrant innervation leads to uncontrollable tearing while eating or in anticipation of a meal.

HP:0100275.name: Diffuse cerebellar atrophy
HP:0100275.definition: Diffuse unlocalised atrophy affecting the cerebellum.

HP:0100276.name: Skin pit
HP:0100276.definition: A small, skin-lined tract that leads from the surface to deep within the tissues.

HP:0100277.name: Periauricular skin pits
HP:0100277.definition: Benign congenital lesions of the periauricular soft tissue consisting of a blind-ending narrow tube or pit.

HP:0100279.name: Ulcerative colitis
HP:0100279.definition: A chronic inflammatory bowel disease that includes characteristic ulcers, or open sores, in the colon. The main symptom of active disease is usually constant diarrhea mixed with blood, of gradual onset and intermittent periods of exacerbated symptoms contrasting with periods that are relatively symptom-free. In contrast to Crohn's disease this special form of colitis begins in the distal parts of the rectum, spreads continually upwards and affects only mucose and submucose tissue of the colon.

HP:0100280.name: Crohn's disease
HP:0100280.definition: A chronic granulomatous inflammatory disease of the intestines that may affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, causing a wide variety of symptoms. It primarily causes abdominal pain, diarrhea which may be bloody, vomiting, or weight loss, but may also cause complications outside of the gastrointestinal tract such as skin rashes, arthritis, inflammation of the eye, tiredness, and lack of concentration. Crohn's disease is thought to be an autoimmune disease, in which the body's immune system attacks the gastrointestinal tract, causing inflammation.

HP:0100281.name: Chronic colitis
HP:0100281.definition: A chronic inflammatory disease of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum).

HP:0100282.name: Acute colitis
HP:0100282.definition: An acute and self-limited inflammatory disease of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum).

HP:0100283.name: EMG: continuous motor unit activity at rest
HP:0100283.definition: Continuous electromyographic activity of motor units at rest, i.e., without voluntary movement of the muscles.

HP:0100284.name: EMG: myotonic discharges
HP:0100284.definition: High frequency discharges in electromyography (EMG) that vary in amplitude and frequency, waxing and waning continuously with firing frequencies ranging from 150/second down to 20/second and producing a sound that has been referred to as a dive bomber sound.

HP:0100285.name: EMG: impaired neuromuscular transmission
HP:0100285.definition: An electromyographic finding associated with erratic or absent neuromuscular transmission with erratic, moment-to-moment changes in the shape of the motor unit potential (MUP).

HP:0100287.name: EMG: slow motor conduction
HP:0100287.definition: The presence of reduced conduction velocity of motor nerves on electromyography.

HP:0100288.name: EMG: myokymic discharges
HP:0100288.definition: The presence of spontaneous bursts of rapidly firing potentials that recur at regular intervals of 2-10 per second and are unaffected by voluntary effort. This is an electromyographic (EMG) finding.

HP:0100289.name: Abnormality of pattern reversal visual evoked potentials

HP:0100290.name: Abnormality of peripheral somatosensory evoked potentials

HP:0100291.name: Delayed somatosensory central conduction time
HP:0100291.definition: An abnormal increase (delay) in the somatosensory central conduction time (CCT), which can be measured from the peak of N13 to the peak of N20 (peak CCT) or from the onset of N11 to the onset of N20 (onset CCT).

HP:0100292.name: Amyloidosis of peripheral nerves
HP:0100292.definition: The presence of amyloid deposition in the nerves of the peripheral nervous system.

HP:0100293.name: Hypertrophied muscle fibers
HP:0100293.definition: The presence of an increased amount of muscle fibers with an increased diameter. This feature can be ascertained by microscopic examination of a muscle biopsy sample. Together with fiber size variation and atrophied muscle fibers, and hypertrophied muscle fibers are commonly found in myopathies.

HP:0100297.name: Increased endomysial connective tissue
HP:0100297.definition: An increased volume of the endomysium, which is a connective tissue sheath that surrounds each muscle fiber. Together, bundles of muscle fibers form a fasciculus, surrounded by another layer of connective tissue called the perimysium.

HP:0100301.name: Muscle fiber tubular inclusions
HP:0100301.definition: Unusual regions of densely packed membranous tubules known as tubular aggregates which present as membranous inclusions, derived from membranes of sarcoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria, containing miscellaneous proteins with a variety of enzymatic activities.

HP:0100303.name: Muscle fiber cytoplasmatic inclusion bodies
HP:0100303.definition: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.

HP:0100304.name: Muscle fiber intranuclear inclusion bodies
HP:0100304.definition: The presence of inclusion bodies within the nucleus of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.

HP:0100305.name: Ring fibers
HP:0100305.definition: Ring fibers are formed by a bundle of peripheral myofibrils which are circumferentially oriented such that they encircle the internal portion of the sarcoplasm which is normal in structure and orientation.

HP:0100306.name: Muscle fiber hyaline bodies
HP:0100306.definition: Subsarcolemmal, eosinophilic glass-like regions in the cytoplasm of muscle fibers. Hyaline bodies show significant reactivity to myofibrillar ATPase after acid pre-incubation and with immunohistochemistry, show intense reactivity with only slow myosin heavy chain. Electron microscopy of the affected areas show a lack of myofibrils and a uniform, finely granular matrix, sometimes suggesting a filamentous nature, containing few scattered nuclei and mitochondria.

HP:0100308.name: Cerebral cortical hemiatrophy
HP:0100308.definition: Atrophy of one side of the brain, characterized by findings including thinning of the cerebral cortex, reduced volume of the cerebral white matter with abnormal myelination, and enlargement of the ispilateral fourth ventricle.

HP:0100309.name: Subdural hemorrhage
HP:0100309.definition: Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the arachnoid mater.

HP:0100310.name: Epidural hemorrhage
HP:0100310.definition: Hemorrhage occurring between the dura mater and the skull.

HP:0100311.name: Cerebral ventricular adhesions
HP:0100311.definition: Bands of scar-like tissue that have formed within a cerebral ventricle.

HP:0100312.name: Cerebral germinoma
HP:0100312.definition: The presence of a germ cell tumor of the cerebrum.

HP:0100313.name: Cerebral granulomatosis
HP:0100313.definition: Cerebral inflammation involving a granulomatous response, i.e., a non-specific inflammatory response involving granulomas, defined as a compact organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes including epithelioid and giant cells.

HP:0100314.name: Cerebral inclusion bodies
HP:0100314.definition: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within cells of the brain.

HP:0100316.name: Hirano bodies
HP:0100316.definition: Intracellular aggregates of actin and actin-associated proteins within nerve cells.

HP:0100317.name: Argyrophilic inclusion bodies
HP:0100317.definition: Presence of abundant argyrophilic grains and coiled bodies on microscopic examination of brain tissue.

HP:0100318.name: Lafora bodies
HP:0100318.definition: An intraneuronal inclusion body composed of acid mucopolysaccharides.

HP:0100319.name: Cerebral hyaline bodies
HP:0100319.definition: Cerebral eosinophilic, discrete, intracytoplasmatic inclusions of unknown significance.

HP:0100320.name: Rosenthal fibers
HP:0100320.definition: Thick, elongated, worm-like or corkscrew eosinophilic bundle that are found on H&E staining of the brain in the presence of long standing gliosis, occasional tumors, and some metabolic disorders.

HP:0100321.name: Abnormal dentate nucleus morphology
HP:0100321.definition: An abnormality of the dentate nucleus.

HP:0100323.name: Juvenile aseptic necrosis
HP:0100323.definition: Juvenile aseptic necrosis comprises a group of orthopedic diseases characterized by interruption of the blood supply of a bone, followed by localized bony necrosis most often of the epiphyses of bones of children or teenagers.

HP:0100324.name: Scleroderma
HP:0100324.definition: A chronic autoimmune phenomenon characterized by fibrosis (or hardening) and vascular alterations of the skin.

HP:0100326.name: Immunologic hypersensitivity
HP:0100326.definition: Immunological states where the immune system produces harmful responses upon reexposure to sensitizing antigens.

HP:0100327.name: Cow milk allergy
HP:0100327.definition: Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against cow milk protein.

HP:0100328.name: Carpometacarpal synostosis
HP:0100328.definition: Fusion involving carpal and metacarpal bones.

HP:0100333.name: Unilateral cleft lip
HP:0100333.definition: A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on one side only.

HP:0100335.name: Non-midline cleft of the upper lip
HP:0100335.definition: Clefting (gap or groove) of the upper lip affecting the lateral portions of the upper lip rather than the midline/median region.

HP:0100336.name: Bilateral cleft lip
HP:0100336.definition: A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on the left and right sides.

HP:0100337.name: Bilateral cleft palate
HP:0100337.definition: Nonmidline cleft palate on the left and right sides.

HP:0100495.definition: The presence of an increased number of mast cells and CD34+ mast cell precursors in the body.

HP:0100501.definition: An increased susceptibility to bronchiolitis as manifested by a history of recurrent bronchiolitis.

HP:0100508.name: Abnormality of vitamin metabolism
HP:0100508.definition: An anomaly in the metabolism of a vitamin.

HP:0100510.definition: The concentration of vitamin C in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0100512.name: Decreased circulating vitamin D concentration
HP:0100512.definition: The concentration of vitamin D in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0100513.name: Decreased circulating vitamin E concentration
HP:0100513.definition: A reduced concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation. Vitamin E is a lipophilic vitamin that is also known as alpha-tocopherol.

HP:0100514.name: Abnormal circulating vitamin E concentration
HP:0100514.definition: Concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation outside of normal limits.

HP:0100516.name: Neoplasm of the ureter
HP:0100516.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the ureter.

HP:0100517.name: Neoplasm of the urethra
HP:0100517.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the urethra.

HP:0100519.name: Anuria
HP:0100519.definition: Absence of urine, clinically classified as below 50ml/day.

HP:0100520.name: Oliguria
HP:0100520.definition: Low output of urine, clinically classified as an output below 300-500ml/day.

HP:0100521.name: Neoplasm of the thymus
HP:0100521.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the thymus.

HP:0100522.name: Thymoma
HP:0100522.definition: A tumor originating from the epithelial cells of the thymus.

HP:0100523.name: Liver abscess
HP:0100523.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the liver.

HP:0100524.name: Limb duplication
HP:0100524.definition: Congenital duplication of all or part of a limb.

HP:0100525.name: Urachus fistula
HP:0100525.definition: Persistence of the urachal canal with drainage of urine from the bladder through the persistent allantois canal to the umbilicus.

HP:0100528.name: Pleuropulmonary blastoma
HP:0100528.definition: A rare cancer originating in the lung or pleural cavity that occurs most often in infants and young children but also has been reported in adults. Pleuropulmonary blastoma is regarded as malignant.

HP:0100529.name: Abnormal blood phosphate concentration
HP:0100529.definition: An abnormality of phosphate homeostasis or concentration in the body.

HP:0100530.name: Abnormal circulating calcium-phosphate regulating hormone concentration
HP:0100530.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a hormone that is involved in the regulation of phosphate and calcium.

HP:0100531.name: Wind-swept deformity of the knees
HP:0100531.definition: The appearance of abnormal valgus deformity in one knee in association with varus deformity in the other.

HP:0100533.name: Inflammatory abnormality of the eye
HP:0100533.definition: Inflammation of the eye, parts of the eye or the periorbital region.

HP:0100534.name: Episcleritis
HP:0100534.definition: Inflammation of the episclera, a thin layer of tissue covering the white part (sclera) of the eye.

HP:0100537.name: Fasciitis
HP:0100537.definition: Inflammation of fascia, the tissue under the skin and over the muscle.

HP:0100538.name: Abnormality of the supraorbital ridges
HP:0100538.definition: An anomaly of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.

HP:0100539.name: Periorbital edema
HP:0100539.definition: Edema affecting the region situated around the orbit of the eye.

HP:0100540.name: Palpebral edema
HP:0100540.definition: Edema in the region of the eyelids.

HP:0100541.name: Femoral hernia
HP:0100541.definition: A hernia which occurs just below the inguinal ligament, where abdominal contents pass through a naturally occurring weakness called the femoral canal.

HP:0100542.name: Abnormal localization of kidney
HP:0100542.definition: An abnormal site of the kidney.

HP:0100543.name: Cognitive impairment
HP:0100543.definition: Abnormal cognition is characterized by deficits in thinking, reasoning, or remembering.

HP:0100544.name: Neoplasm of the heart
HP:0100544.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the heart.

HP:0100545.name: Arterial stenosis
HP:0100545.definition: Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of an artery.

HP:0100547.name: Abnormal forebrain morphology
HP:0100547.definition: An abnormality of the forebrain, which has as its parts the telencephalon, diencephalon, lateral ventricles and third ventricle.

HP:0100548.name: Exstrophy
HP:0100548.definition: Eversion of a hollow organ and exposure, inside out, and protruded through the abdominal wall.

HP:0100555.name: Asymmetric growth
HP:0100555.definition: A growth pattern that displays an abnormal difference between the left and the right side.

HP:0100556.name: Hemiatrophy
HP:0100556.definition: Undergrowth of the limbs that affects only one side.

HP:0100557.name: Hemiatrophy of lower limb
HP:0100557.definition: Unilateral atrophy (reduction in size) of a leg.

HP:0100558.name: Hemiatrophy of upper limb
HP:0100558.definition: Unilateral atrophy (reduction in size) of an arm.

HP:0100559.name: Lower limb asymmetry
HP:0100559.definition: A difference in length or diameter between the left and right leg.

HP:0100560.name: Upper limb asymmetry
HP:0100560.definition: Difference in length or size between the right and left arm.

HP:0100563.name: Diastomatomyelia
HP:0100563.definition: Coexistence of two hemicords, at variable levels, causing splaying of the posterior vertebral elements. Results in neurological deficits in lower limb or perineum.

HP:0100564.name: Triplomyelia
HP:0100564.definition: Triplication of the spinal cord - extremely rare.

HP:0100565.name: Hydromyelia
HP:0100565.definition: Dilation of central canal from incomplete fusion of the posterior columns or persistence of the primitive large canal of the embryo.

HP:0100566.name: Amyelia
HP:0100566.definition: Congenital absence of the spinal cord.

HP:0100568.name: Neoplasm of the endocrine system
HP:0100568.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the endocrine system.

HP:0100569.name: Abnormally ossified vertebrae
HP:0100569.definition: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of one or more vertebrae.

HP:0100570.name: Carcinoid tumor
HP:0100570.definition: A tumor formed from the endocrine (argentaffin) cells of the mucosal lining of a variety of organs including the stomach and intestine. These cells are from neuroectodermal origin.

HP:0100571.name: Cardiac diverticulum
HP:0100571.definition: A cardiac diverticulum is a rare congenital malformation which is either fibrous or muscular.

HP:0100572.name: Fibrous cardiac diverticulum
HP:0100572.definition: A fibrous cardiac diverticulum refers to an aneurysm and usually appears as an isolated congenital anomaly.

HP:0100574.name: Biliary tract neoplasm
HP:0100574.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the biliary system.

HP:0100575.name: Neoplasm of the gallbladder
HP:0100575.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the gallbladder.

HP:0100576.name: Amaurosis fugax
HP:0100576.definition: A transient visual disturbance that is typically caused by a circulatory, ocular or neurological underlying condition.

HP:0100579.name: Mucosal telangiectasiae
HP:0100579.definition: Telangiectasia of the mucosa, the mucous membranes which are involved in absorption and secretion that line cavities that are exposed to the external environment and internal organs.

HP:0100580.name: Barrett esophagus
HP:0100580.definition: An abnormal change (metaplasia) in the cells of the inferior portion of the esophagus. The normal squamous epithelium lining of the esophagus is replaced by metaplastic columnar epithelium. Columnar epithelium refers to a cell type that is typically found in more distal parts of the gastrointestinal system.

HP:0100581.name: Dilatation of renal calices
HP:0100581.definition: An abnormal enlargement of the renal calices, the system of ducts of the kidney that collect urine.

HP:0100582.name: Nasal polyposis
HP:0100582.definition: Polypoidal masses arising mainly from the mucous membranes of the nose and paranasal sinuses. They are freely movable and nontender overgrowths of the mucosa that frequently accompany allergic rhinitis.

HP:0100583.name: Corneal perforation
HP:0100583.definition: A rupture of the cornea through which a portion of the iris protrudes.

HP:0100584.name: Endocarditis
HP:0100584.definition: An inflammation of the endocardium, the inner layer of the heart, which usually involves the heart valves.

HP:0100585.name: Telangiectasia of the skin
HP:0100585.definition: Presence of small, permanently dilated blood vessels near the surface of the skin, visible as small focal red lesions.

HP:0100586.name: Sterile pyuria
HP:0100586.definition: Patients who routinely have greater than 20 leukocytes per microliter, but have abacterial urine, are said to have sterile pyuria.

HP:0100587.name: Abnormal preputium morphology
HP:0100587.definition: An abnormality of the retractable fold of skin that covers the tip of the penis.

HP:0100588.name: Paraphimosis
HP:0100588.definition: The foreskin becomes trapped behind the glans penis, and cannot be pulled back to its normal flaccid position covering the glans penis.

HP:0100589.name: Urogenital fistula
HP:0100589.definition: The presence of a fistula affecting the genitourinary system.

HP:0100590.name: Rectal fistula
HP:0100590.definition: The presence of a fistula affecting the rectum.

HP:0100592.name: Peritoneal abscess
HP:0100592.definition: The presence of an abscess of the peritoneum.

HP:0100593.name: Calcification of cartilage
HP:0100593.definition: The presence of calcium deposition in cartilage.

HP:0100594.name: Esophageal web
HP:0100594.definition: Thin (2-3mm) membranes of normal esophageal tissue consisting of mucosa and submucosa that can be congenital or acquired. Congenital webs commonly appear in the middle and inferior third of the esophagus, and they are more likely to be circumferential with a central or eccentric orifice. Acquired webs are much more common than congenital webs and typically appear in the cervical area (postcricoid). Clinical symptoms of this condition are selective (solid more than liquids) dysphagia, thoracic pain, nasopharyngeal reflux, aspiration, perforation and food impaction (the last two are very rare).

HP:0100595.name: Camptocormia
HP:0100595.definition: An abnormal forward-flexed posture e.g. forward flexion of the spine, which is noticeable when standing or walking but disappears when lying down. It is becoming an increasingly recognized feature of Parkinson's disease and dystonic disorders.

HP:0100596.name: Absent nares
HP:0100596.definition: The nostrils (the paired channels of the nose) are not present.

HP:0100599.name: Bifid penis
HP:0100599.definition: Two penile structures, separated from the tip to the base of the shaft.

HP:0100600.name: Penoscrotal transposition
HP:0100600.definition: A partial or complete positional exchange between the penis and the scrotum, with positioning of the scrotum superior to the penis.

HP:0100601.name: Eclampsia
HP:0100601.definition: An acute and life-threatening complication of pregnancy, which is characterized by the appearance of tonic-clonic seizures, usually in a patient who had developed pre-eclampsia. Eclampsia includes seizures and coma that happen during pregnancy but are not due to preexisting or organic brain disorders.

HP:0100602.name: Preeclampsia
HP:0100602.definition: Pregnancy-induced hypertension in association with significant amounts of protein in the urine.

HP:0100603.name: Toxemia of pregnancy
HP:0100603.definition: Pregnancy-induced toxic reactions of the mother that can be as harmless as slight Maternal hypertension or as life threatening as Eclampsia.

HP:0100604.name: Neoplasm of the lip
HP:0100604.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the lip.

HP:0100606.name: Neoplasm of the respiratory system
HP:0100606.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the respiratory system.

HP:0100607.name: Dysmenorrhea
HP:0100607.definition: Pain during menstruation that interferes with daily activities.

HP:0100610.name: Maternal hyperphenylalaninemia
HP:0100610.definition: A medical history of exposure during the fetal period to hyperphenylalaninemia because the mother had phenylketonuria with inadequate control during pregnancy.

HP:0100611.name: Multiple glomerular cysts
HP:0100611.definition: The presence of many cysts in the glomerulus of the kidney related to dilatation of the Bowman's capsule.

HP:0100612.name: Odontogenic neoplasm
HP:0100612.definition: Neoplasm involving odontogenic cells, an odontogenic tumor.

HP:0100613.name: Death in early adulthood
HP:0100613.definition: Death between the age of 16 and 40 years.

HP:0100614.name: Myositis
HP:0100614.definition: A general term for inflammation of the muscles without respect to the underlying cause.

HP:0100615.name: Ovarian neoplasm
HP:0100615.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the ovary.

HP:0100616.name: Testicular teratoma
HP:0100616.definition: The presence of a teratoma of the testis.

HP:0100617.name: Testicular seminoma
HP:0100617.definition: The presence of a seminoma, an undifferentiated germ cell tumor of the testis.

HP:0100618.name: Leydig cell neoplasia
HP:0100618.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Leydig cell.

HP:0100619.name: Sertoli cell neoplasm
HP:0100619.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the testis with origin in a Sertoli cell.

HP:0100620.name: Germinoma
HP:0100620.definition: A type of undifferentiated germ cell tumor that may be benign or malignant.

HP:0100621.name: Dysgerminoma
HP:0100621.definition: The presence of a dysgerminoma, i.e., an undifferentiated germ cell tumor of the ovary.

HP:0100623.name: Abnormal corpus cavernosum morphology
HP:0100623.definition: A structural anomaly of the corpus cavernosum, the erectile tissue of the penis.

HP:0100627.name: Displacement of the urethral meatus
HP:0100627.definition: A displacement of the external urethral orifice from its normal position (in males normally placed at the tip of glans penis, in females normally placed about 2.5 cm behind the glans clitoridis and immediately in front of that of the vagina).

HP:0100628.name: Esophageal diverticulum
HP:0100628.definition: The presence of a diverticulum of the esophagus.

HP:0100629.name: Midline facial cleft
HP:0100629.definition: A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the midline of the face.

HP:0100631.name: Neoplasm of the adrenal gland
HP:0100631.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adrenal gland.

HP:0100632.name: Pulmonary sequestration
HP:0100632.definition: The presence of a piece lung tissue which is not attached to the pulmonary blood supply and does not communicate with the other lung tissue (not connected to the standard bronchial airways and not performing a function in respiration).

HP:0100634.name: Neuroendocrine neoplasm
HP:0100634.definition: A tumor that originates from a neuroendocrine cell.

HP:0100635.name: Carotid paraganglioma
HP:0100635.definition: A paraganglioma (a neuroendocrine neoplasm) originating in a carotid artery.

HP:0100636.name: Pulmonary paraglioma
HP:0100636.definition: A rare paranglioma of the lung, tumors that arise from extra-adrenal chromaffin cells.

HP:0100638.name: Neoplasm of the pharynx
HP:0100638.definition: A neoplasm originating in the pharynx.

HP:0100639.name: Erectile dysfunction
HP:0100639.definition: A multidimensional but common male sexual dysfunction that involves an alteration in any of the components of the erectile response, including organic, relational and psychological.

HP:0100640.name: Laryngeal cyst
HP:0100640.definition: Presence of a cyst (sac-like structure) located in the larynx.

HP:0100641.name: Neoplasm of the adrenal cortex
HP:0100641.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the adrenal cortex.

HP:0100642.name: Neoplasm of the adrenal medulla
HP:0100642.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the adrenal medulla.

HP:0100643.name: Abnormality of nail color
HP:0100643.definition: An anomaly of the color of the nail.

HP:0100644.name: Melanonychia
HP:0100644.definition: Dark discoloration of a fingernail or toenail (brown, black, bluish and reddish).

HP:0100645.name: Cystocele
HP:0100645.definition: Anterior vaginal wall prolapse with bulging of the bladder into the vagina.

HP:0100647.name: Graves disease
HP:0100647.definition: An autoimmune disease where the thyroid is overactive, producing an excessive amount of thyroid hormones (a serious metabolic imbalance known as hyperthyroidism and thyrotoxicosis). This is caused by autoantibodies to the TSH-receptor (TSHR-Ab) that activate that TSH-receptor (TSHR), thereby stimulating thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion, and thyroid growth (causing a diffusely enlarged goiter). The resulting state of hyperthyroidism can cause a dramatic constellation of neuropsychological and physical signs and symptoms, which can severely compromise the patients.

HP:0100648.name: Neoplasm of the tongue
HP:0100648.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the tongue.

HP:0100649.name: Neoplasm of the oral cavity
HP:0100649.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the oral cavity.

HP:0100650.name: Vaginal neoplasm
HP:0100650.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the vagina.

HP:0100651.name: Type I diabetes mellitus
HP:0100651.definition: A chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin. Type I diabetes mellitus is manifested by the sudden onset of severe hyperglycemia with rapid progression to diabetic ketoacidosis unless treated with insulin.

HP:0100654.name: Retrobulbar optic neuritis
HP:0100654.definition: Optic neuritis that occurs in the section of the optic nerve located behind the eyeball.

HP:0100656.name: Thoracoabdominal wall defect
HP:0100656.definition: Failure of the chest and abdominal wall to close, which is likely caused by the failure of the ventral wall to close during week 4 of development.

HP:0100657.name: Thoracoabdominal eventration
HP:0100657.definition: Congenital protrusion of the abdominal or thoracic viscera, usually with a defect of the sternum and ribs as well as of the abdominal walls.

HP:0100658.name: Cellulitis
HP:0100658.definition: A bacterial infection and inflammation of the skin und subcutaneous tissues.

HP:0100659.name: Abnormal cerebral vascular morphology
HP:0100659.definition: An anomaly of the cerebral blood vessels.

HP:0100660.name: Dyskinesia
HP:0100660.definition: A movement disorder which consists of effects including diminished voluntary movements and the presence of involuntary movements.

HP:0100661.name: Trigeminal neuralgia
HP:0100661.definition: A neuropathic disorder characterized by episodes of intense pain in the face, originating from the trigeminal nerve. One, two, or all three branches of the nerve may be affected.

HP:0100663.name: Synotia
HP:0100663.definition: A congenital malformation characterized by the union or approximation of the ears in front of the neck, often accompanied by the absence or defective development of the lower jaw.

HP:0100665.name: Angioedema
HP:0100665.definition: Rapid swelling (edema) of the dermis, subcutaneous tissue, mucosa and submucosal tissues of the skin of the face, normally around the mouth, and the mucosa of the mouth and/or throat, as well as the tongue during a period of minutes to several hours. The swelling can also occur elsewhere, typically in the hands. Angioedema is similar to urticaria, but the swelling is subcutaneous rather than on the epidermis.

HP:0100668.name: Intestinal duplication
HP:0100668.definition: A developmental disorder in which there is a duplication the entire intestine or of a portion of the intestine.

HP:0100669.name: Abnormal pigmentation of the oral mucosa
HP:0100669.definition: An abnormality of the pigmentation of the mucosa of the mouth.

HP:0100670.name: Coarse metaphyseal trabecularization
HP:0100670.definition: Coarse appearance of the components of the network of osseous tissue that makes up the cancellous structure of a bone, i.e., thickening of the (usually fine) white lines that are produced by trabeculae in radiograms.

HP:0100671.name: Abnormal trabecular bone morphology
HP:0100671.definition: Abnormal structure or form of trabecular bone.

HP:0100672.name: Vaginal hernia
HP:0100672.definition: The presence of a hernia of the vagina.

HP:0100673.name: Vaginal hydrocele
HP:0100673.definition: A type of hydrocele testis in which the processus vaginalis remains patent only around the testes, and, as fluid accumulates, it renders the testes impalpable.

HP:0100677.name: Vulval varicose vein
HP:0100677.definition: Varicosity of veins in the vulval region.

HP:0100678.name: Premature skin wrinkling
HP:0100678.definition: The presence of an increased degree of wrinkling (irregular folds and indentations) of the skin as compared with age-related norms.

HP:0100681.name: Esophageal duplication
HP:0100681.definition: A developmental disorder in which there is a duplication of a portion of the muscle and submucosa of the esophagus without epithelial duplication.

HP:0100682.name: Tracheal atresia
HP:0100682.definition: A congenital absence or considerable underdevelopment of the trachea such that communication between the larynx proximally and the alveoli of the lungs distally is lacking.

HP:0100684.name: Salivary gland neoplasm
HP:0100684.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a salivary gland.

HP:0100685.name: Abnormal Sharpey fiber morphology
HP:0100685.definition: An abnormality of Sharpey's fibers (bone fibers, or perforating fibers), which are a matrix of connective tissue consisting of bundles of strong collagenous fibers connecting periosteum to bone.

HP:0100687.name: Polyotia
HP:0100687.definition: The presence of an extra auricle on one or both sides of the head.

HP:0100689.name: Decreased corneal thickness
HP:0100689.definition: A decreased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.

HP:0100691.name: Abnormality of the curvature of the cornea

HP:0100692.name: Increased corneal curvature
HP:0100692.definition: An increase in the degree of curvature of the cornea compared to normal.

HP:0100693.name: Iridodonesis
HP:0100693.definition: Tremulousness of the iris on movement of the eye, occurring in subluxation of the lens.

HP:0100694.name: Tibial torsion
HP:0100694.definition: Twisted position of the tibia (shin bone) associated with pathological rotation of the leg.

HP:0100695.name: Lipedema
HP:0100695.definition: Excess deposit and expansion of adipose tissue in an unusual pattern which cannot be lost through diet and exercise .

HP:0100697.name: Neurofibrosarcoma
HP:0100697.definition: A form of malignant cancer of the connective tissue surrounding nerves. Given its origin and behavior, it is classified as a sarcoma.

HP:0100698.name: Subcutaneous neurofibroma
HP:0100698.definition: A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the subcutis (subcutaneous region).

HP:0100699.name: Scarring
HP:0100699.definition: A scar refers to a lesion in which wound, burn, or sore has not healed completely and fibrous connective tissue has developed.

HP:0100700.name: Abnormal arachnoid mater morphology
HP:0100700.definition: An abnormality of the Arachnoid mater.

HP:0100701.name: Abnormal pia mater
HP:0100701.definition: An abnormality of the pia mater.

HP:0100702.name: Arachnoid cyst
HP:0100702.definition: An extra-parenchymal and intra-arachnoidal collection of fluid with a composition similar to that of cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0100703.name: Tongue thrusting
HP:0100703.definition: Pressing forward of the tongue in the mouth, a retained motoric habit from infantile swallowing patterns

HP:0100704.name: Cerebral visual impairment
HP:0100704.definition: A form of loss of vision caused by damage to the visual cortex rather than a defect in the eye.

HP:0100705.name: Abnormal glial cell morphology
HP:0100705.definition: An abnormality of the glia cell.

HP:0100706.name: Abnormal oligodendroglia morphology
HP:0100706.definition: One of the three types of glia cells that, with the nerve cells, compose the central nervous system and are characterized by sheetlike processes that wrap around individual axons to form the myelin sheath of nerve fibers.

HP:0100708.name: Abnormal microglia morphology
HP:0100708.definition: An abnormality of the microglial cells. They are also known as brain-resident macrophages or Hortega cells.

HP:0100710.name: Impulsivity
HP:0100710.definition: Acting on the spur of the moment or on a momentary basis without consideration of outcomes; having difficulty establishing or following plans; experiencing a sense of urgency and engaging in behavior that is uninhibited, cannot be inhibited, and is uncontrolled. The possibility of repression is inconceivable.

HP:0100711.name: Abnormal thoracic spine morphology
HP:0100711.definition: An abnormality of the thoracic vertebral column.

HP:0100712.name: Abnormal lumbar spine morphology
HP:0100712.definition: Any structural abnormality of the lumbar vertebral column.

HP:0100717.name: Abnormal cementum morphology
HP:0100717.definition: Any structural anomaly of the cementum, which is the mineralized connective tissue covering the dental root. The cementum allows anchoring of the fibers of the periodontal ligament. Cementum is secreted by cementoblasts, which may be, later on, embedded in the cementum. Cementum can be acellular (along the two third coronal portion of the root) and cellular (in the apical and interradicular part of the root).

HP:0100719.name: Lens coloboma
HP:0100719.definition: A sectoral indentation of the crystalline lens, usually due to zonular weakness or absence.

HP:0100721.name: Mediastinal lymphadenopathy
HP:0100721.definition: Swelling of lymph nodes within the mediastinum, the central compartment of the thoracic cavities that contains the heart and the great vessels, the esophagus, and trachea and other structures including lymph nodes.

HP:0100724.name: Hypercoagulability
HP:0100724.definition: An abnormality of coagulation associated with an increased risk of thrombosis.

HP:0100725.name: Lichenification
HP:0100725.definition: Thickening and hardening of the epidermis seen with exaggeration of normal skin lines.

HP:0100726.name: Kaposi's sarcoma
HP:0100726.definition: A systemic disease which can present with cutaneous lesions with or without internal involvement. Tumors are caused by Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV8), also known as Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV).

HP:0100727.name: Histiocytosis
HP:0100727.definition: An excessive number of histiocytes (tissue macrophages).

HP:0100730.name: Bronchogenic cyst
HP:0100730.definition: A rare congenital cystic lesion of the lungs in the mediastinum.

HP:0100731.name: Transverse facial cleft
HP:0100731.definition: A horizontal cleft of the face, varying from slight widening of the mouth, to a cleft extending to the ear.

HP:0100733.name: Neoplasm of the parathyroid gland
HP:0100733.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the parathyroid gland.

HP:0100734.name: Abnormal vertebral epiphysis morphology
HP:0100734.definition: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or more vertebrae.

HP:0100736.name: Abnormal soft palate morphology
HP:0100736.definition: An abnormality of the soft palate.

HP:0100738.name: Abnormal eating behavior
HP:0100738.definition: Abnormal eating habits involve excessive or insufficient consumption of food, or any other abnormal pattern of food consumption.

HP:0100739.name: Bulimia
HP:0100739.definition: A form of anomalous eating behavior characterized by binge eating is followed by self-induced vomiting or other compensatory behavior intended to prevent weight gain (purging, fasting or exercising or a combination of these).

HP:0100742.name: Vascular neoplasm
HP:0100742.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm (tumor) originating in the vascular system.

HP:0100745.name: Abnormality of the humeroulnar joint
HP:0100745.definition: An anomaly of the joint between the trochlear notch of ulna and the trochlea of humerus, which is part of the elbow joint.

HP:0100746.name: Macrodactyly of finger
HP:0100746.definition: A type of Macrodactyly affecting one or several fingers.

HP:0100747.name: Macrodactyly of toe
HP:0100747.definition: A type of Macrodactyly affecting one or several toes.

HP:0100749.name: Chest pain
HP:0100749.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the chest.

HP:0100750.name: Atelectasis
HP:0100750.definition: Collapse of part of a lung associated with absence of inflation (air) of that part.

HP:0100751.name: Esophageal neoplasm
HP:0100751.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the esophagus.

HP:0100752.name: Abnormal liver lobulation
HP:0100752.definition: Formation of abnormal lobules (small masses of tissue) in the liver.

HP:0100753.name: Schizophrenia
HP:0100753.definition: A mental disorder characterized by a disintegration of thought processes and emotional responsiveness. It most commonly manifests as auditory hallucinations, paranoid or bizarre delusions, or disorganized speech and thinking. It is accompanied by significant social or occupational dysfunction. The onset of symptoms typically occurs in young adulthood, with a global lifetime prevalence of about 1%. This term is not a helpful parent term to describe abnormal experiences.

HP:0100754.name: Mania
HP:0100754.definition: A state of abnormally elevated or irritable mood, arousal, and/or energy levels.

HP:0100757.name: Pancreatoblastoma
HP:0100757.definition: A rare pediatric carcinoma of the pancreas.

HP:0100758.name: Gangrene
HP:0100758.definition: A serious and potentially life-threatening condition that arises when a considerable mass of body tissue dies (necrosis).

HP:0100759.name: Clubbing of fingers
HP:0100759.definition: Terminal broadening of the fingers (distal phalanges of the fingers).

HP:0100760.name: Clubbing of toes
HP:0100760.definition: Terminal broadening of the toes (distal phalanges of the toes).

HP:0100763.name: Abnormality of the lymphatic system
HP:0100763.definition: An anomaly of the lymphatic system, a network of lymphatic vessels that carry a clear fluid called lymph unidirectionally towards either the right lymphatic duct or the thoracic duct, which in turn drain into the right and left subclavian veins respectively.

HP:0100764.name: Lymphangioma
HP:0100764.definition: Lymphangiomas are rare congenital malformations consisting of focal proliferations of well-differentiated lymphatic tissue in multi cystic or sponge like structures. Lymphangioma is usually asymptomatic due to its soft consistency but compression of adjacent structures can be seen due to the mass effect of a large tumor.

HP:0100766.name: Abnormal lymphatic vessel morphology
HP:0100766.definition: A structural anomaly of the vessel that contains or conveys lymph fluid.

HP:0100767.name: Abnormal placenta morphology
HP:0100767.definition: An abnormality of the placenta, the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall to enable nutrient uptake, waste elimination, and gas exchange.

HP:0100768.name: Choriocarcinoma
HP:0100768.definition: A malignant, trophoblastic and aggressive cancer, usually of the placenta. It is characterized by early hematogenous spread to the lungs and belongs to the far end of the spectrum of gestational trophoblastic disease (GTD), a subset of germ cell tumors.

HP:0100770.name: Hyperperistalsis
HP:0100770.definition: Excessively active peristalsis (wave of contraction of the tubular organs of the gastrointestinal tract) marked by excessive rapidity of the passage of food through the stomach and intestine.

HP:0100771.name: Hypoperistalsis
HP:0100771.definition: Reduced or inadequate peristalsis, with resultant slow passage of contents through the digestive tract.

HP:0100774.name: Hyperostosis
HP:0100774.definition: Excessive growth or abnormal thickening of bone tissue.

HP:0100775.name: Dural ectasia
HP:0100775.definition: A widening or ballooning of the dural sac surrounding the spinal cord usually at the lumbosacral level.

HP:0100776.name: Recurrent pharyngitis
HP:0100776.definition: An increased susceptibility to pharyngitis as manifested by a history of recurrent pharyngitis.

HP:0100777.name: Exostoses
HP:0100777.definition: An exostosis is a benign growth the projects outward from the bone surface. It is capped by cartilage, and arises from a bone that develops from cartilage.

HP:0100778.name: Cryoglobulinemia
HP:0100778.definition: Increased level of cryoglobulins in the blood. Cryoglobulins are abnormal immunoglobulins, especially IGG or IGM, that precipitate spontaneously when serum is cooled below 37 degrees Celsius.

HP:0100779.name: Urogenital sinus anomaly
HP:0100779.definition: A rare birth defect in women where the urethra and vagina both open into a common channel.

HP:0100780.name: Conjunctival hamartoma
HP:0100780.definition: A hamartoma (disordered proliferation of mature tissues) of the conjunctiva.

HP:0100781.name: Abnormal sacroiliac joint morphology
HP:0100781.definition: An anomaly of the sacroiliac joint, which connects the base of the spine (sacrum) to the ilium (a hip bone).

HP:0100783.name: Breast aplasia
HP:0100783.definition: Failure to develop and congenital absence of the breast.

HP:0100785.name: Insomnia
HP:0100785.definition: Persistent difficulty initiating or maintaining sleep.

HP:0100786.name: Hypersomnia
HP:0100786.definition: Excessive sleepiness or feeling of sleepiness, or difficulty staying awake despite having had adequate sleep, which persists over several days.

HP:0100788.name: Fused lips
HP:0100788.definition: Lack of separation of the upper and lower lips.

HP:0100789.name: Torus palatinus
HP:0100789.definition: A bony protrusion present on the midline of the hard palate.

HP:0100792.name: Acantholysis
HP:0100792.definition: The loss of intercellular connections, such as desmosomes, resulting in loss of cohesion between keratinocytes.

HP:0100795.name: Abnormally straight spine
HP:0100795.definition: The absence of the normal curvature of the vertebral column.

HP:0100797.name: Toenail dysplasia
HP:0100797.definition: An abnormality of the development of the toenails.

HP:0100798.name: Fingernail dysplasia
HP:0100798.definition: An abnormality of the development of the fingernails.

HP:0100799.name: Neoplasm of the middle ear
HP:0100799.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the middle ear.

HP:0100800.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the pancreas
HP:0100800.definition: A congenital underdevelopment (aplasia or hypoplasia) of the pancreas.

HP:0100802.name: Malposition of the stomach
HP:0100802.definition: Abnormal anatomical location of the stomach. This feature may be due to intestinal malrotation.

HP:0100803.name: Abnormal periungual morphology
HP:0100803.definition: An abnormality of the region around the nails of the fingers or toes.

HP:0100804.name: Ungual fibroma
HP:0100804.definition: Flesh-colored papule in or around the nail bed. Ungual fibromas may be periungual (arising under the proximal nail fold) or subungual (originating under the nail plate).

HP:0100807.name: Long fingers
HP:0100807.definition: The middle finger is more than 2 SD above the mean for newborns 27 to 41 weeks EGA or above the 97th centile for children from birth to 16 years of age AND the five digits retain their normal length proportions relative to each other (i.e., it is not the case that the middle finger is the only lengthened digit), or, Fingers that appear disproportionately long compared to the palm of the hand.

HP:0100808.name: Gastric diverticulum
HP:0100808.definition: An outpouching of the gastric wall.

HP:0100809.name: Scalp tenderness
HP:0100809.definition: Pain or discomfort of the scalp elicited by palpation.

HP:0100811.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the colon
HP:0100811.definition: Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the colon.

HP:0100812.name: Halitosis
HP:0100812.definition: Noticeably unpleasant odors exhaled in breathing.

HP:0100813.name: Testicular torsion
HP:0100813.definition: Testicular torsion is when the spermatic cord to a testicle twists, cutting off the blood supply. The most common symptom is acute testicular pain.

HP:0100814.name: Blue nevus
HP:0100814.definition: A solitary, bluish, smooth surfaced macule, papule or plaque that is generally round or oval in shape. The histopathology of blue nevi varies by subtype, but general characteristics include a vertical wedge or bulbous shaped proliferation of spindle cells, dendritic melanocytes, and melanophages into a sclerotic dermis or subcutis.

HP:0100817.name: Renovascular hypertension
HP:0100817.definition: The presence of hypertension related to stenosis of the renal artery.

HP:0100818.name: Long thorax
HP:0100818.definition: Increased inferior to superior extent of the thorax.

HP:0100819.name: Intestinal fistula
HP:0100819.definition: An abnormal connection between the gut and another hollow organ, such as the bladder, urethra, vagina, or other regions of the gastrointestinal tract.

HP:0100820.name: Glomerulopathy
HP:0100820.definition: Inflammatory or noninflammatory diseases affecting the glomeruli of the nephron.

HP:0100821.name: Urethrocele
HP:0100821.definition: The prolapse of the female urethra into the vagina.

HP:0100822.name: Rectocele
HP:0100822.definition: A Rectocele results from a tear in the rectovaginal septum (which is normally a tough, fibrous, sheet-like divider between the rectum and vagina). Rectal tissue bulges through this tear and into the vagina as a hernia. There are two main causes of this tear: childbirth, and hysterectomy.

HP:0100826.name: Neoplasm of the nail
HP:0100826.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the nail.

HP:0100827.name: Increased total lymphocyte count
HP:0100827.definition: Increase in the number or proportion of lymphocytes in the blood.

HP:0100828.name: Increased total T cell count
HP:0100828.definition: The absolute number of T cells per volume is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0100829.name: Galactorrhea
HP:0100829.definition: Spontaneous flow of milk from the breast, unassociated with childbirth or nursing.

HP:0100831.name: Abnormality of vitamin K metabolism
HP:0100831.definition: Vitamin K is a fat-soluble vitamin with a role in promoting the coagulation cascade.

HP:0100832.name: Vitreous floaters
HP:0100832.definition: Deposits of various size, shape, consistency, refractive index, and motility within the eye's vitreous humor, which is normally transparent.

HP:0100833.name: Neoplasm of the small intestine
HP:0100833.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the small intestine.

HP:0100834.name: Neoplasm of the large intestine
HP:0100834.definition: The presence of a neoplasm of the large intestine.

HP:0100835.name: Benign neoplasm of the central nervous system

HP:0100836.name: Malignant neoplasm of the central nervous system
HP:0100836.definition: A tumor that originates in the pineal gland, has moderate cellularity and tends to form rosette patterns.

HP:0100837.name: Atrophodermia vermiculata
HP:0100837.definition: Symmetrical vermiform facial atrophy that affects mainly the forehead, the chin, the ear lobes and helices. Atrophodermia vermiculata is characterized by erythema and follicular plugs on the cheeks, developing into painless reticular impressions.

HP:0100838.name: Recurrent cutaneous abscess formation
HP:0100838.definition: An increased susceptibility to cutaneous abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent cutaneous abscesses.

HP:0100839.name: Hepatic agenesis
HP:0100839.definition: Absence of the liver owing to a failure of the liver to develop.

HP:0100840.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the eyebrow
HP:0100840.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the eyebrow.

HP:0100841.name: Microgastria
HP:0100841.definition: A developmental anomaly with a small tubular or saccular midline stomach.

HP:0100842.name: Septo-optic dysplasia
HP:0100842.definition: Underdevelopment of the optic nerve and absence of the septum pellucidum.

HP:0100845.name: Anaphylactic shock
HP:0100845.definition: An acute hypersensitivity reaction due to exposure to a previously encountered antigen.

HP:0100847.name: Palmoplantar pustulosis
HP:0100847.definition: A chronic, relapsing, pustular eruption that is localized to the palms and soles.

HP:0100848.name: Neoplasm of the male external genitalia
HP:0100848.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the male external genitalia.

HP:0100849.name: Neoplasm of the scrotum
HP:0100849.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the scrotum.

HP:0100850.name: Neoplasm of the penis
HP:0100850.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the penis.

HP:0100851.name: Abnormal emotional state
HP:0100851.definition: Emotions are complex psychological states that involve three distinct components: a subjective experience, a physiological response, and a behavioral or expressive response. In an abnormal emotional state, an affected individual shows altered intensity, frequency, or duration of emotional experiences.

HP:0100852.name: Abnormal fear-induced behavior
HP:0100852.definition: An abnormal fear-induced behavior includes observable actions. This behavior is characterized by abnormal responses to fear or abnormal fear levels. Examples of such behavior include avoiding fear-inducing situations.

HP:0100853.name: Hypoplastic areola
HP:0100853.definition: Underdevelopment of the areola, the circular area of pigmented skin surrounding the nipple.

HP:0100856.name: Poorly ossified vertebrae
HP:0100856.definition: Decreased ossification of the vertebral bodies.

HP:0100858.name: Dilatation of celiac artery
HP:0100858.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the celiac artery.

HP:0100859.name: Dilatation of superior mesenteric artery
HP:0100859.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the superior mesenteric artery .

HP:0100860.name: Dilatation of Inferior mesenteric artery
HP:0100860.definition: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery .

HP:0100861.name: Sclerotic vertebral body
HP:0100861.definition: Increase in bone density of the vertebral body.

HP:0100864.name: Short femoral neck
HP:0100864.definition: An abnormally short femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft).

HP:0100865.name: Broad ischia
HP:0100865.definition: Increased width of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

HP:0100867.name: Duodenal stenosis
HP:0100867.definition: The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the duodenum.

HP:0100869.name: Palmar telangiectasia
HP:0100869.definition: The presence of telangiectases on the skin of palm of hand.

HP:0100870.name: Plantar telangiectasia
HP:0100870.definition: Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located on the skin of sole of foot.

HP:0100871.name: Abnormal palm morphology
HP:0100871.definition: An abnormality of the palm, that is, of the front of the hand.

HP:0100872.name: Abnormality of the plantar skin of foot
HP:0100872.definition: An abnormality of the plantar part of foot, that is of the soles of the feet.

HP:0100874.name: Thick hair
HP:0100874.definition: Increased density of hairs, i.e., and elevated number of hairs per unit area.

HP:0100875.name: Hemimacroglossia
HP:0100875.definition: Increased length and width of one half of the tongue.

HP:0100876.name: Infra-orbital crease
HP:0100876.definition: Skin crease extending from below the inner canthus laterally along the malar process of the maxilla and zygoma.

HP:0100877.name: Renal diverticulum
HP:0100877.definition: Cystic, urine-containing intrarenal cavities lined with transitional cell epithelium that communicate through a narrow channel with the collecting system.

HP:0100880.name: Nephrogenic rest
HP:0100880.definition: Abnormally persistent clusters of embryonal cells, representing microscopic malformations (dysplasias) of the developing kidney.

HP:0100881.name: Congenital mesoblastic nephroma
HP:0100881.definition: Congenital mesoblastic nephroma is a type of kidney tumor that is usually found before birth by ultrasound or within the first 3 months of life. It contains fibroblastic cells (connective tissue cells), and may spread to the other kidney or to nearby tissue.

HP:0100882.name: Fibrous hamartoma
HP:0100882.definition: A rare, benign soft tissue tumor that typically occurs within the first two years of life.

HP:0100883.name: Chorangioma
HP:0100883.definition: Hamartoma-like growth in the placenta consisting of blood vessels.

HP:0100884.name: Compensatory scoliosis
HP:0100884.definition: A scoliosis which is the results of a difference in leg length (which might be due to hemihypertrophy or hemihypotrophy of a leg) and the resulting tilting of the pelvis. If untreated this will lead to the development of scoliosis over time.

HP:0100885.name: Lateral venous anomaly
HP:0100885.definition: Persistence of the embryonic dorsal or sciatic vein system that normally should have involuted around the tenth to twelfth week of intrauterine life.

HP:0100886.name: Abnormality of globe location
HP:0100886.definition: An abnormality in the placement of the ocular globe (eyeball).

HP:0100887.name: Abnormality of globe size
HP:0100887.definition: An abnormality in the size of the ocular globe (eyeball).

HP:0100889.name: Abnormal ductus choledochus morphology
HP:0100889.definition: An abnormality of the Common bile duct, a tube-like anatomic structure in the human gastrointestinal tract, formed by the union of the Common hepatic duct and the Cystic duct from the gall bladder.

HP:0100891.name: Bifid xiphoid process
HP:0100891.definition: A cleft of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

HP:0100892.name: Abnormality of the xiphoid process
HP:0100892.definition: An abnormality of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

HP:0100893.name: Prominent xiphoid process
HP:0100893.definition: Increased prominence of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

HP:0100894.name: Broad xiphoid process
HP:0100894.definition: Increased side-to-side width of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

HP:0100896.name: Rectal polyposis
HP:0100896.definition: The presence of multiple rectal hyperplastic/adenomatous polyps.

HP:0100898.name: Connective tissue nevi
HP:0100898.definition: Connective tissue nevi are hamartomas in which one or several components of the dermis is altered.

HP:0100899.name: Sclerosis of finger phalanx
HP:0100899.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100900.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0100901.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0100902.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger

HP:0100903.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger

HP:0100904.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0100905.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0100906.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger

HP:0100907.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger

HP:0100908.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger

HP:0100909.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger

HP:0100910.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger

HP:0100911.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger

HP:0100912.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0100912.definition: An elevation of bone density in the distal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0100913.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
HP:0100913.definition: An elevation of bone density in the proximal phalanx of the thumb.

HP:0100915.name: Sclerosis of distal finger phalanx
HP:0100915.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more distal phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100916.name: Sclerosis of middle finger phalanx
HP:0100916.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more middle phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100917.name: Sclerosis of proximal finger phalanx
HP:0100917.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more proximal phalanges of the fingers. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100918.name: Sclerosis of 2nd finger phalanx
HP:0100918.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the second finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100919.name: Sclerosis of 3rd finger phalanx
HP:0100919.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the third finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100920.name: Sclerosis of 4th finger phalanx
HP:0100920.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fourth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100921.name: Sclerosis of 5th finger phalanx
HP:0100921.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fifth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100923.name: Clavicular sclerosis
HP:0100923.definition: An increase in bone density within the clavicle.

HP:0100924.name: Sclerosis of toe phalanx
HP:0100924.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100925.name: Sclerosis of foot bone
HP:0100925.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more foot bones. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100926.name: Sclerosis of 2nd toe phalanx
HP:0100926.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the second toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100927.name: Sclerosis of 3rd toe phalanx
HP:0100927.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100928.name: Sclerosis of 4th toe phalanx
HP:0100928.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fourth toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100929.name: Sclerosis of 5th toe phalanx
HP:0100929.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fifth toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100930.name: Sclerosis of hallux phalanx
HP:0100930.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the big toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100931.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
HP:0100931.definition: An elevation in bone density in the proximal phalanx of the second toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100932.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe
HP:0100932.definition: An elevation in bone density in the proximal phalanx of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100933.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0100934.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0100935.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0100936.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe
HP:0100936.definition: An elevation in bone density in the middle phalanx of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100937.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0100938.name: Sclerosis of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0100939.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe

HP:0100940.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe
HP:0100940.definition: An elevation in bone density in the distal phalanx of the third toe. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100941.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 4th toe

HP:0100942.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe

HP:0100943.name: Sclerosis of the proximal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0100944.name: Sclerosis of the distal phalanx of the hallux

HP:0100946.name: Sclerosis of proximal toe phalanx
HP:0100946.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more proximal phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100947.name: Sclerosis of middle toe phalanx
HP:0100947.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more middle phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100948.name: Sclerosis of distal toe phalanx
HP:0100948.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more distal phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:0100952.name: Enlarged sylvian cistern
HP:0100952.definition: An increase in size of the subarachnoid space associated with the lateral cerebral sulcus (Sylvian fissure).

HP:0100957.name: Abnormal renal medulla morphology
HP:0100957.definition: Any structural abnormality of the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0100958.name: Narrow foramen obturatorium
HP:0100958.definition: Decreased width of the foramen obturatorium. The foramen obturatorium (also known as the obturator foramen) is a hole located between the ischium and pubis bones of the pelvis.

HP:0100959.name: Dense metaphyseal bands
HP:0100959.definition: Dense radiopaque bands of bone which are thicker than the adjacent diaphyseal cortex and may form at the metaphysis of growing bones. They appear on radiographs as bone that is more radiopaque that the adjacent diaphyseal cortex.

HP:0100960.name: Lateral ventricular asymmetry
HP:0100960.definition: Abnormal difference in size between the left and right lateral cerebral ventricles.

HP:0100961.name: Enlarged hippocampus
HP:0100961.definition: Increase in size of the hippocampus.

HP:0100962.name: Excessive shyness
HP:0100962.definition: Atypically high degree of awkwardness or apprehension experienced when approaching or being approached by others.

HP:0100963.name: Hyperesthesia
HP:0100963.definition: Increased sensitivity to stimulation, excluding the special senses, which may refer to various modes of cutaneous sensibility including touch and thermal sensation without pain, as well as to pain.

HP:0200000.name: Dysharmonic skeletal maturation
HP:0200000.definition: Different levels of maturation of different bones.

HP:0200001.name: Dysharmonic accelerated bone age
HP:0200001.definition: A type of dysharmonic skeletal maturation in which there is an acceleration in skeletal maturation whose degree differs markedly in different bones.

HP:0200005.name: Abnormal shape of the palpebral fissure
HP:0200005.definition: The presence of an abnormal shape of the palpebral fissure.

HP:0200007.name: Abnormal size of the palpebral fissures
HP:0200007.definition: An abnormal size of the palpebral fissures for example unusually long or short palpebral fissures.

HP:0200008.name: Intestinal polyposis
HP:0200008.definition: The presence of multiple polyps in the intestine.

HP:0200013.name: Neoplasm of fatty tissue
HP:0200013.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of adipose tissue.

HP:0200016.name: Acrokeratosis
HP:0200016.definition: Overgrowth of the stratum corneum characterized by flesh-coloured or slightly pigmented smooth or warty papules on the upper surface of hands and feet.

HP:0031150.name: Vitreomacular adhesion
HP:0031150.definition: Perifoveal vitreous separation with remaining vitreomacular attachment and unperturbed foveal morphologic features. It is an OCT finding that is almost always the result of normal vitreous aging, which may lead to pathologic conditions.

HP:0031151.name: Vitreomacular traction
HP:0031151.definition: Vitreomacular traction is characterized by anomalous posterior vitreous detachment accompanied by anatomic distortion of the fovea, which may include pseudocysts, macular schisis, cystoid macular edema, and subretinal fluid. Vitreomacular traction can be subclassified by the diameter of vitreous attachment to the macular surface as measured by OCT, with attachment of 1500 micrometers or less defined as focal and attachment of more than 1500 micrometers as broad.

HP:0031152.name: Full-thickness macular hole
HP:0031152.definition: Full-thickness macular hole (FTMH) is defined as a foveal lesion with interruption of all retinal layers from the internal limiting membrane to the retinal pigment epithelium. Full-thickness macular hole is primary if caused by vitreous traction or secondary if directly the result of pathologic characteristics other than vitreomacular traction. Full-thickness macular hole is subclassified by size of the hole as determined by OCT and the presence or absence of vitreomacular traction.

HP:0031153.name: Membranous vitreous appearance
HP:0031153.definition: Vitreous humor of the eye displaying consisting of a vestigial gel in the retrolental space bounded by a convoluted membrane.

HP:0031154.name: Beaded vitreous appearance
HP:0031154.definition: Vitreous humor of the eye displaying beaded bundles of irregular diameters.

HP:0031155.name: Increased Arden ratio of electrooculogram
HP:0031155.definition: An abnormal increase in the Arden ratio, which is the ratio between the light peak and the dark trough of the smoothed (physiologic) EOG record.

HP:0031156.name: Decreased platelet glycoprotein Ib
HP:0031156.definition: Decreased platelet cell membrane concentration of glycoprotein Ib.

HP:0031157.name: Carotid cavernous fistula
HP:0031157.definition: An abnormal connection between a carotid artery and the cavernous sinus.

HP:0031158.name: Widened atrophic scar
HP:0031158.definition: An atrophic scar (fibrous connective tissue resulting from incomplete healing of a wound) that has stretched (gotten wider), a manifestation of tissue fragility.

HP:0031159.name: Thinning of Descemet membrane
HP:0031159.definition: A reduction in the thickness of Descemet's membrane.

HP:0031160.name: Myelokathexis
HP:0031160.definition: Impaired egress of mature neutrophils from bone marrow causing neutropenia.

HP:0031161.name: Reduced brain glutamate level by MRS
HP:0031161.definition: An decrease in the level of glutamate (Glu) in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0031162.name: Impaired oropharyngeal swallow response
HP:0031162.definition: Delay or absence of the swallow response, reflexes triggered by the contact the food bolus makes with the anterior faucial pillars.

HP:0031163.name: Low femoral bone density
HP:0031163.definition: Reduced bone mineral density of the femur.

HP:0031164.name: Growth arrest lines
HP:0031164.definition: Growth arrest lines are alternating transverse rings of sclerosis at the metaphysis of a long bone.

HP:0031165.name: Multifocal seizures
HP:0031165.definition: Seizures that start from several different areas of the brain (i.e., with multiple ictal onset locations).

HP:0031166.name: Eyelid myokymia
HP:0031166.definition: Involuntary, fine, continuous, undulating contractions of the eyelid.

HP:0031167.name: Triggered by ingestion of potassium-rich food
HP:0031167.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating or drinking foods rich in potassium.

HP:0031169.name: Postterm pregnancy
HP:0031169.definition: A pregnancy that extends to 42 weeks of gestation or beyond.

HP:0031170.name: Female fetal virilization
HP:0031170.definition: Fetal masculinization of female external genitalia.

HP:0031171.name: Femoral spur
HP:0031171.definition: A bony projection (spur, osteophyte) originating from the femur, often in the medial femoral neck.

HP:0031172.name: Sectoral retinitis pigmentosa
HP:0031172.definition: A variant of retinitis pigmentosa in which there is a regional distribution of the retinal degeneration.

HP:0031173.name: Tibial spur
HP:0031173.definition: A bony projection (spur, osteophyte) originating from the tibia.

HP:0031174.name: Double-layered patella
HP:0031174.definition: An anomaly of the patella characterized by two layers visible on lateral knee X-ray such that one layer is in front of the other in the sagittal orientation (See Figure 2A and 3B of PMID:12966518). This finding persists into adulthood.

HP:0031175.name: Absent cervical vertebra
HP:0031175.definition: A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies of the cervical spine.

HP:0031176.name: Absent thoracic vertebra
HP:0031176.definition: A developmental defect characterized by agenesis of one or more vertebral bodies of the thoracic spine.

HP:0031177.name: Finger flexor weakness
HP:0031177.definition: Reduced ability to flex (bend) the fingers. This can manifest as incomplete closure of the hand due to weakness in finger flexion.

HP:0031178.name: Fixed head retroflexion
HP:0031178.definition: Head is bent in the posterior direction in a permanent fashion.

HP:0031179.name: Nuchal rigidity
HP:0031179.definition: Resistance of the extensor muscles of the neck to being bent forwards (i.e., impaired neck flexion) as a result of muscle spasm of the extensor muscles of the neck. Nuchal rigidity is not a fixed rigidity. Nuchal rigidity has been used as a bedside test for meningism, although its sensitivity for this purpose has been debated.

HP:0031180.name: Erythema migrans
HP:0031180.definition: An expanding erythematous (red) skin lesion, usually round or oval, by definition at least 5 cm in size (in largest diameter).

HP:0031181.name: Necrolytic migratory erythema
HP:0031181.definition: Acral or periorificial lesions that evolve in recurrent crops, with an annular and migratory distribution.

HP:0031185.name: Increased circulating NT-proBNP concentration
