HP:0031185.definition: An elevated level of circulating N-terminal part of the prohormone of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP).

HP:0031186.name: Abnormal circulating deoxycorticosterone level
HP:0031186.definition: An abnormality of the concentration of deoxycorticosterone in the blood. Deoxycorticosterone comprises 11-deoxycorticosterone and 21-deoxycorticosterone.

HP:0031187.name: Abnormal circulating pregnenolone concentration
HP:0031187.definition: An abnormality of the concentration of pregnenolone in the blood.

HP:0031188.name: Genital edema
HP:0031188.definition: A buildup of fluid that causes swelling in the soft tissues of the genital area.

HP:0031189.name: Wrist drop
HP:0031189.definition: A condition in which the affected individual cannot extend the wrist, which hangs flaccidly.

HP:0031190.name: Superficial dermal perivascular inflammatory infiltrate
HP:0031190.definition: Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the superficial part of the dermis.

HP:0031191.name: Deep dermal perivascular inflammatory infiltrate
HP:0031191.definition: Numerous lymphocytes surrounding blood vessels in the deep part of the dermis.

HP:0031192.name: Abnormal morphology of left ventricular trabeculae
HP:0031192.definition: Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the left ventricle of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).

HP:0031193.name: Abnormal morphology of right ventricular trabeculae
HP:0031193.definition: Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the right ventricle of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).

HP:0031194.name: Increased density of left ventricular trabeculae
HP:0031194.definition: An increased density (number and tightness) of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the left ventricles of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).

HP:0031195.name: Apical hypertrabeculation of the left ventricle
HP:0031195.definition: An increased number and density of the trabeculae in the apex (tip) of the left ventricle.

HP:0031196.name: Thin myocardium compact layer
HP:0031196.definition: Reduced thickness of the outer, dense layer of the myocardium.

HP:0031197.name: Cellular urinary casts
HP:0031197.definition: A type of urinary cast composed of cells incorporated in a protein matrix. The cells can be those found in the urinary sediment (erythrocytes, leuklocytes, renal tubular epithelial cells).

HP:0031198.name: Renal tubular epithelial cell casts
HP:0031198.definition: A type of cellular urinary cast composed of renal tubular epithelial cells.

HP:0031199.name: Acellular urinary casts
HP:0031199.definition: A type of urinary cast composed of a proteinaceous matrix without a substantial number of cells.

HP:0031200.name: Hyaline casts
HP:0031200.definition: A type of acellular urinary cast that are composed only of Tamm-Horsfall glycoprotein, a fact which explains their low refractive index. Hyaline casts may display a spectrum of morphologies, which includes fluffy, compact, convoluted or wrinkled casts. Hyaline casts have a smooth texture and usually have parallel sides with clear margins and blunted ends.

HP:0031201.name: Granular casts
HP:0031201.definition: A type of acelluar casts that have a surface composed of granules, which can vary in size. The granules can be rather heterogeneous, ranging from fine (finely granular cast) up to coarse (coarsely granular cast), dark, clear, and pigmented.

HP:0031202.name: Waxy casts
HP:0031202.definition: A type of acellular urinary casts that display a melted wax (waxy) appearance, which gives them a high refractive index. They are frequently dark, with blunt extremities, indented and cracked edges and a large size, which is often several times that of other types of casts.

HP:0031203.name: Fatty casts
HP:0031203.definition: A type of acellular urinary casts that contain lipid droplets, oval fat bodies or cholesterol crystals, and are often associated with the free forms of these elements. Their identification may require the use of polarized light microscopy, under which fatty particles embedded into the cast matrix appear as Maltese crosses.

HP:0031204.name: Bacterial cell casts
HP:0031204.definition: A type of urinary cast that contain bacteria. Bacterial casts can be difficult to identify and can be distinguished from other types of casts using phase contrast microscopy. Bacterial casts are diagnostic of acute pyelonephritis or intrinsic renal infection.

HP:0031205.name: Reduced lysosomal acid lipase activity
HP:0031205.definition: Reduction in the activity of lysosomal acid lipase (LAL) in the blood. Lysosomal lipase activity is measured. LAL hydrolyzes cholesteryl esters derived from cell internalization of plasma lipoproteins.

HP:0031206.name: Striatal T2 hyperintensity
HP:0031206.definition: Abnormally bright T2 signal from the striatum on brain magnetic resonance imaging.

HP:0031207.name: Hepatic hemangioma
HP:0031207.definition: A congenital vascular malformation in the liver composed of masses of blood vessels that are atypical or irregular in arrangement and size.

HP:0031208.name: Increased pituitary glycoprotein hormone alpha subunit level
HP:0031208.definition: An increased concentration of circulating alpha polypeptide of glycoprotein hormones (NCBI Gene 1081). This alpha subunit is common to luteinizing hormone (LH) , follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) , thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) and human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), which are glycoprotein hormones composed of an identical alpha subunit together with a beta subunit that confers biological specificity. The alpha subunit is used as a marker for tumors that produce these hormones.

HP:0031209.name: Decreased circulating lipoprotein lipase concentration
HP:0031209.definition: Reduction in the level of lipoprotein lipase in the blood.

HP:0031210.name: Abnormal circulating hyaluronic acid concentration
HP:0031210.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of hyaluronic acid in the blood.

HP:0031211.name: Elevated cholesterol ester level
HP:0031211.definition: An elevated concentration of circulating cholesterol esters, which are fatty acid esters of cholesterol and make up about two-thirds of total plasma cholesterol.

HP:0031213.name: Elevated circulating 17-hydroxyprogesterone concentration
HP:0031213.definition: An increased level of 17-hydroxyprogesterone in the blood. 17-hydroxyprogesterone is an intermediate steroid in the adrenal biosynthetic pathway from cholesterol to cortisol and is the substrate for steroid 21-hydroxylase.

HP:0031215.name: Decreased circulating dehydroepiandrosterone-sulfate concentration
HP:0031215.definition: A reduced concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone-sulfate in the blood.

HP:0031216.name: Increased circulating progesterone
HP:0031216.definition: An elevated concentration of progesterone in the blood.

HP:0031217.name: Hot flashes
HP:0031217.definition: Sudden feelings of warmth that are generally most pronounced over the face, neck and chest.

HP:0031218.name: Inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion
HP:0031218.definition: A state of increased circulating antidiuretic hormone despite hyponatremia and hypo-osmolality with normal or increased plasma volume.

HP:0031219.name: Reduced radioactive iodine uptake
HP:0031219.definition: A decreased amount of uptake on the radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) test, which utilizes a radioisotope of iodine to measure how much iodine the thyroid gland absorbs from the blood. The radioactive marker is measured 4-6 hours and in some cases also 24 hours after administration of the radioactive marker.

HP:0031220.name: Increased radioactive iodine uptake
HP:0031220.definition: An elevated amount of uptake on the radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) test, which utilizes a radioisotope of iodine to measure how much iodine the thyroid gland absorbs from the blood. The radioactive marker is measured 4-6 hours and in some cases also 24 hours after administration of the radioactive marker.

HP:0031221.name: Abnormal radioactive iodine uptake test result
HP:0031221.definition: Any deviation from normal in the amount of uptake on the radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) test, which utilizes a radioisotope of iodine to measure how much iodine the thyroid gland absorbs from the blood. The radioactive marker is measured 4-6 hours and in some cases also 24 hours after administration of the radioactive marker.

HP:0031222.name: Increased circulating thyroxine-binding globulin level
HP:0031222.definition: An elevated concentration of thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG) in the blood.

HP:0031223.name: Focal pancreatic islet hyperplasia
HP:0031223.definition: Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans that affects only certain regions of the pancreas and not others.

HP:0031224.name: Diffuse pancreatic islet hyperplasia
HP:0031224.definition: Hyperplasia of the islets of Langerhans with a generalized distribution.

HP:0031225.name: Intrapulmonary shunt
HP:0031225.definition: Blood flow through a region of the lung in which little or no ventilation takes place, resulting in reduced oxygenation of the blood leaving the lungs.

HP:0031226.name: Perinephric fluid collection
HP:0031226.definition: An accumulation of fluid in one or more of the perinephric spaces, which consist of the subcapsular, perirenal, anterior and posterior pararenal spaces. This abnormality can be demonstrated by cross-sectional imaging, particularly computed tomography.

HP:0031227.name: Nasopharyngeal teratoma
HP:0031227.definition: A teratoma arising in the nasopharyngeal region.

HP:0031228.name: Abnormal incisura morphology
HP:0031228.definition: An abnormal shape of the incisura, defined as the narrowed downward continuation of the conchal space bounded anteriorly by the borders of the tragus, posteriorly by the antitragus, and along its lower lateral margins and inferior boundary by the connection between the first two. The upper boundary is a somewhat arbitrary line crossing from the apices of the antitragus and the tragus.

HP:0031229.name: Increased incisura length
HP:0031229.definition: The length of the incisura from the upper to lower border is greater than that observed in the average population.

HP:0031230.name: Decreased incisura length
HP:0031230.definition: The length of the incisura from the upper to lower border is less than that observed in the average population.

HP:0031231.name: Narrow incisura width
HP:0031231.definition: Width of the incisura from the anterior to posterior border less than that observed in the average population.

HP:0031232.name: Increased incisura width
HP:0031232.definition: Breadth of the incisura from the anterior to posterior border greater than that observed in the average population.

HP:0031233.name: Horizontal inferior border of scapula
HP:0031233.definition: A morphological abnormality of the scapula in which there is a flat (horizontal) inferior edge of the scapula. The entire scapula is said to resemble a square, leading to the designation sqaring of the scapula (in Figure 1 of PMID:24706940 the scapulae have a roughly rectangular shape).

HP:0031234.name: Neutrophilic infiltration of the skin
HP:0031234.definition: A predominantly neutrophilic infiltrate of the dermis and or epidermis (i.e., a large number of neutrophils inferred to have migrated into the skin).

HP:0031235.name: Predominantly epidermal neutrophilic infiltrate
HP:0031235.definition: Collection of neutrophils in the epidermis.

HP:0031236.name: Predominantly dermal neutrophilic infiltrate
HP:0031236.definition: Collection of neutrophils in the dermis.

HP:0031237.name: Internally nucleated skeletal muscle fibers
HP:0031237.definition: An abnormally increased proportion of nuclei of sarcomeres with an internal localization. Individual muscle fibers are syncytia, formed by embryonic fusion of many myoblasts or later, myosatellite cells. Each muscle fiber contains many nuclei, peripherally positioned immediately adjacent to the sarcolemmal membrane. In healthy muscle only 3-5% of fibers contain nuclei that are located internally, within the cell, but many disease processes lead to internal nuclei.

HP:0031238.name: Necklace skeletal muscle fibers
HP:0031238.definition: A histological alteration of muscle fibers that resembles a necklace (necklace fibers). A substantial proportion of fibers (4-20% in PMID:19084976) show internalized nuclei aligned in a basophilic ring (necklace) at 3 micrometers beneath the sarcolemma. Ultrastructurally, such necklaces consist of myofibrils of smaller diameter, in oblique orientation, surrounded by mitochondria, sarcoplasmic reticulum and glycogen granules.

HP:0031239.name: Extrafoveal choroidal neovascularization
HP:0031239.definition: A type of choroidal neovascularization in which the nearest edge of the area of neovascularization is located 200 to 1500 micrometers from the center of the fovea.

HP:0031240.name: Juxtafoveal choroidal neovascularization
HP:0031240.definition: A type of choroidal neovascularization in which the nearest edge of the area of neovascularization is located 1 to 199 micrometers from the center of the fovea.

HP:0031241.name: Subfoveal choroidal neovascularization
HP:0031241.definition: A type of choroidal neovascularization in which the area of neovascularization overlaps with the center of the fovea.

HP:0031242.name: Decreased circulating chylomicron concentration
HP:0031242.definition: Reduced plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.

HP:0031243.name: Decreased VLDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0031243.definition: A reduction in the amount of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

HP:0031244.name: Swollen lip
HP:0031244.definition: Enlargement of the lip typically due to fluid buildup or inflammation.

HP:0031245.name: Productive cough
HP:0031245.definition: A cough that produces phlegm or mucus.

HP:0031246.name: Nonproductive cough
HP:0031246.definition: A cough that does not produce phlegm or mucus.

HP:0031247.name: Whooping cough
HP:0031247.definition: A type of cough characterized by a burst of numerous and rapid coughs followed by a long inhaling effort that is accompanied by a high-pitched whooping sound produced by the inhalation of air.

HP:0031248.name: Palmar pruritus
HP:0031248.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching over the palm(s) of the hand.

HP:0031249.name: Parageusia
HP:0031249.definition: A distortion of the sense of taste, often characterized by the sensation of a metallic taste.

HP:0031250.name: Lip fissure
HP:0031250.definition: A severe crack in a lip. A lip fissure may be painful, may bleed and often is a recurring manifestation.

HP:0031251.name: Abnormal subclavian artery morphology
HP:0031251.definition: Any anomaly of a subclavian artery.

HP:0031252.name: Dilated left subclavian artery
HP:0031252.definition: Abnormally increased caliber of the left subclavian artery.

HP:0031253.name: Anomalous origin of left subclavian artery
HP:0031253.definition: Origin of the left subclavian artery from an anomalous anatomical location.

HP:0031254.name: Thalamic arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031254.definition: An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the thalamus.

HP:0031255.name: Hypothalamic arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031255.definition: An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the hypothalamus.

HP:0031256.name: Optic nerve arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031256.definition: An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the optic nerve.

HP:0031257.name: Arteriovenous malformation of the maxilla
HP:0031257.definition: An arteriovenous malformation is a disruption of the normal vascular pattern in which arteries or arterioles connect directly to the venous collection system, bypassing any capillary bed. This term refers to an arteriovenous malformation located in the maxilla.

HP:0031258.name: Delirium
HP:0031258.definition: A state of sudden and severe confusion.

HP:0031259.name: Oophoritis
HP:0031259.definition: An inflammation of the ovary or ovaries.

HP:0031260.name: Triangular tibia
HP:0031260.definition: A short, dysplastic tibia with a triangular shape. Instead of the normal shaft configuration of the tibia, the tibia forms a triangle with the longest side corresponding to the proximal-distal dimension, and the apex of the triangle directed laterally.

HP:0031261.name: Bladder polyp
HP:0031261.definition: An abnormal growth that projects from the mucous membrane of the urinary bladder.

HP:0031263.name: Abnormal renal corpuscle morphology
HP:0031263.definition: Any anomalous structure of the renal corpuscle, which is the initial component of the nephron that filters blood. The renal corpuscle consists of a knot of capillaries (glomerulus) that is surrounded by a double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.

HP:0031264.name: Abnormal Bowman capsule morphology
HP:0031264.definition: A structural anomaly of the double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.

HP:0031265.name: Abnormal glomerular visceral epithelial cell morphology
HP:0031265.definition: Any structural anomaly of the podocyte, which is a highly specialized cell of the Bowman capsule and which forms multiple interdigitating foot processes. Podocytes are interconnected by slit diaphragms and cover the exterior basement membrane surface of the glomerular capillary.

HP:0031266.name: Podocyte foot process effacement
HP:0031266.definition: An anomaly of podocyte morphology characterized by the loss of the interdigitating foot process pattern (generally called foot process effacement; FPE). The term FPE designates the loss of the usual interdigitating pattern of foot processes of neighboring podocytes, leading to relatively broad expanses of podocyte processes covering the glomerular basement membrane (GBM). It is widely viewed as a pathological derangement that is associated with leakage of macromolecules such as albumin through the glomerular filtration barrier.

HP:0031267.name: Abnormal CD69 upregulation upon TCR activation
HP:0031267.definition: Any abnormality in the upregulation of CD69 on T cells after activation via the T cell receptor (TCR). Upregulation of CD69 is one of the earliest and most sensitive measures of antigen recognition in the periphery, and transient expression of CD69 is associated with positive selection in the thymus.

HP:0031268.name: Decreased CD69 upregulation upon TCR activation
HP:0031268.definition: Reduced or impaired upregulation of CD69 on T cells after activation via the T cell receptor (TCR).

HP:0031269.name: Abnormal CD25 upregulation upon TCR activation
HP:0031269.definition: Any abnormality in the upregulation of CD25 on T cells after activation via the T cell receptor (TCR). CD25 is the alpha chain of the IL2 receptor. Ligation of the T cell antigen receptor leads to the induction of CD25 expression.

HP:0031270.name: Decreased CD25 upregulation upon TCR activation
HP:0031270.definition: Decreased or impaired upregulation of CD25 on T cells after activation via the T cell receptor (TCR).

HP:0031271.name: Absent ankle pulse
HP:0031271.definition: The pulsation of the posterior tibial artery behind the internal malleolus, or of the dorsalis pedis artery, cannot be detected on physical examination.

HP:0031272.name: Pulmonary arterial atherosclerosis
HP:0031272.definition: Accumulation of lipids and inflammatory cells along the inner walls of the pulmonary artery.

HP:0031273.name: Shock
HP:0031273.definition: The state in which profound and widespread reduction of effective tissue perfusion leads first to reversible, and then if prolonged, to irreversible cellular injury.

HP:0031274.name: Hypovolemic shock
HP:0031274.definition: A state of shock characterized by decreased circulating blood volume in relation to total vascular capacity. This type of shock is characterized by a reduction of diastolic filling pressures.

HP:0031275.name: Distributive shock
HP:0031275.definition: A hyperdynamic process resulting from excessive vasodilatation. Impaired blood flow causes inadequate tissue perfusion, which can lead to end-organ damage

HP:0031276.name: Obstructive shock
HP:0031276.definition: A type of shock characterized by inadequate cardiac preload due to obstructed venous return (e.g. pericardial tamponade, tension pneumothorax, abdominal compartment) or obstruction of arterial blood flow (e.g. pulmonary embolism).

HP:0031278.name: Abnormal thoracic duct morphology
HP:0031278.definition: Any structural anomaly of the thoracic duct.

HP:0031279.name: Abnormal response to gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0031279.definition: An abnormal response to the gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) stimulation test. This test typically involves intravenous administration of GnRH followed by repeated blood sampling at various time points to measure the levels of luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).

HP:0031280.name: Increased LH response to gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation test
HP:0031280.definition: An abnormally high amount of luteinizing hormone (LH) is released upon gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation test.

HP:0031282.name: Malalignment of the great toenail
HP:0031282.definition: A lateral deviation of the nail plate of the great toe along the longitudinal axis due to the lateral rotation of the nail matrix. The nail plate grows out in ridges.

HP:0031283.name: Tufted hairs
HP:0031283.definition: The presence of tufts of 8-15 hairs that appear to emerge from a single follicular orifice.

HP:0031284.name: Flushing
HP:0031284.definition: Recurrent episodes of redness of the skin together with a sensation of warmth or burning of the affected areas of skin.

HP:0031285.name: Abnormal perifollicular morphology
HP:0031285.definition: Any structural anomaly in the areas surrounding the hair follicles.

HP:0031287.name: Seborrheic keratosis
HP:0031287.definition: A raised growth on the skin of older individuals. The lesion usually is initially light tan and may darken to dark brown or nearly black. The consistent feature of seborrheic keratoses is their waxy, pasted-on or stuck-on look.

HP:0031288.name: Cobblestone-like hyperkeratosis
HP:0031288.definition: The presence of verrucous, cobblestone-like papules and nodules in a region of skin that is said to have an appearance like that of cobblestones.

HP:0031290.name: Tuberous xanthoma
HP:0031290.definition: A type of xanthoma characterized by a nodular form. Tuberous xanthomas are firm subcutaneous nodules,whereby the overlying skin can have red or red-yellow color changes.

HP:0031291.name: Ichthyosis follicularis
HP:0031291.definition: Ichthyosis follicularis is characterized by widespread non inflammatory thorn-like follicular projections. Dyskeratotic papules are most pronounced over the extensor extremities and scalp and are symmetrically distributed.

HP:0031292.name: Cutaneous abscess
HP:0031292.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the skin.

HP:0031293.name: Digital pitting scar
HP:0031293.definition: Pinhole-sized concave depressions with hyperkeratosis in the skin of a finger or toe.

HP:0031295.name: Left atrial enlargement
HP:0031295.definition: Increase in size of the left atrium.

HP:0031296.name: Atrial septal hypertrophy
HP:0031296.definition: An abnormal increase in the thickness of the atrial septum.

HP:0031297.name: Unroofed coronary sinus
HP:0031297.definition: Unroofed coronary sinus (CS) is a rare congenital cardiac anomaly in which there is partial (either focal or fenestrated) or complete absence of the roof of the CS, which results in a communication between the CS and the LA. Unroofed CS is the rarest type of atrial septal defect. It is often associated with persistent left superior vena cava (LSVC) and other forms of complex congenital heart disease, usually heterotaxia syndromes. The morphological types have been classified into 4 groups: Type I, completely unroofed with persistent LSVC; type II, completely unroofed without persistent LSVC; type III, partially unroofed mid portion; and type IV, partially unroofed terminal portion.

HP:0031298.name: Coronary sinus enlargement
HP:0031298.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the coronary sinus.

HP:0031299.name: Elevated left atrial pressure
HP:0031299.definition: An abnormal increase in magnitude of the pressure in the left atrium.

HP:0031300.name: Abnormal circulating properdin level
HP:0031300.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of properdin in the blood.

HP:0031301.name: Peripheral arterial calcification
HP:0031301.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall.

HP:0031302.name: Lower extremity peripheral arterial calcification
HP:0031302.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the leg.

HP:0031303.name: Femoral arterial calcification
HP:0031303.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the femoral artery.

HP:0031304.name: Iliac arterial calcification
HP:0031304.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the iliac artery.

HP:0031305.name: Tibial arterial calcification
HP:0031305.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall of the tibial artery.

HP:0031306.name: Intracranial arterial calcification
HP:0031306.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in an artery that is located within the skull (intracranial).

HP:0031307.name: Internal carotid artery calcification
HP:0031307.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the internal carotid artery.

HP:0031308.name: Vertebral artery calcification
HP:0031308.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the vertebral artery.

HP:0031309.name: Cerebral artery calcification
HP:0031309.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in a cerebral artery.

HP:0031310.name: Basilar artery calcification
HP:0031310.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the basilar artery.

HP:0031311.name: Middle cerebral artery calcification
HP:0031311.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the middle cerebral artery.

HP:0031313.name: Abdominal aortic calcification
HP:0031313.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in abdominal aorta.

HP:0031314.name: Carotid artery calcification
HP:0031314.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in a carotid artery.

HP:0031315.name: External carotid artery calcification
HP:0031315.definition: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in the external carotid artery.

HP:0031316.name: Abnormal ventricular myocardium morphology
HP:0031316.definition: A structural anomaly of the muscle layer of the heart wall of a cardiac ventricle.

HP:0031317.name: Fatty replacement of ventricular myocardial tissue
HP:0031317.definition: Presence of an increased amount of fat tissue within a cardiac ventricle with corresponding reduction of muscle tissue.

HP:0031318.name: Myofiber disarray
HP:0031318.definition: A nonparallel arrangement of cardiac myocytes.

HP:0031319.name: Cardiomyocyte hypertrophy
HP:0031319.definition: An increase in cell size, enhanced protein synthesis, and heightened organization of the sarcomere within cardiac myocytes.

HP:0031320.name: Cardiomyocyte mitochondrial proliferation
HP:0031320.definition: An abnormal increase in the number of mitochondria per cardiac myocyte.

HP:0031321.name: Myocardial immune cell infiltration
HP:0031321.definition: An increase in the number of immune cells in myocardial tissue (which can be assumed to have migrated into the myocardium).

HP:0031322.name: Myocardial lymphocytic infiltration
HP:0031322.definition: An increase in the number of lymphocytes in myocardial tissue.

HP:0031323.name: Myocardial eosinophilic infiltration
HP:0031323.definition: An increase in the number of eosinophils in myocardial tissue.

HP:0031324.name: Myocardial multinucleated giant cells
HP:0031324.definition: The presence of extremely large cells with multiple nuclei. The so-called giant cells are thought to be of macrophage origin.

HP:0031325.name: Myocardial granulomatous infiltrates
HP:0031325.definition: The presence of multiple granulomata (small nodular inflammatory lesions containing grouped mononuclear phagocytes) in the myocardium.

HP:0031326.name: Monoclonal light chain cardiac amyloidosis
HP:0031326.definition: A type of cardiac amyloidosis related to deposition of an immunoglobulin light chain. The current gold standard of amyloid typing is to determine the precursor protein using laser microdissection mass spectrometry.

HP:0031327.name: Transthyretin cardiac amyloidosis
HP:0031327.definition: A type of cardiac amyloidosis related to deposition of transthyretin (TTR), which is identified by immunohistochemical staining.

HP:0031328.name: Perivascular cardiac fibrosis
HP:0031328.definition: A type of myocardial fibrosis characterized by excessive diffuse collagen accumulation concentrated in perivascular spaces.

HP:0031329.name: Interstitial cardiac fibrosis
HP:0031329.definition: A type of myocardial fibrosis characterized by excessive diffuse collagen accumulation concentrated in interstitial spaces.

HP:0031330.name: Perivascular myocardial immune cell infiltration
HP:0031330.definition: An increase in the number of immune cells in myocardial tissue concentrated in the spaces surrounding blood vessels.

HP:0031331.name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte morphology
HP:0031331.definition: Any structural anomaly of cardiomyocytes, which are terminally differentiated muscle cells in the heart that are interconnected end to end by gap junctions, which allows coordinated contraction of heart tissue.

HP:0031332.name: Cardiomyocyte degeneration
HP:0031332.definition: Deterioration of cardiomyocyte characterized by abnormal features such as loss of myofilaments, occurrence of cellular sequestration, decreased mitochondrial sizes and cellular debris.

HP:0031333.name: Myocardial sarcomeric disarray
HP:0031333.definition: A disruption of the structure of the sarcomeres of cardiomyocytes. The sarcomere is the repeating unit between two Z lines comprised largely of myosin and actin that mediates contractility, and normally sarcomeres are aligned with the long axis of cells, with the Z bands being in register throughout the length of the cardiac myocytes.

HP:0031334.name: Cardiomyocyte inclusion bodies
HP:0031334.definition: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within cardiomyocytes.

HP:0031335.name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte mitochondrial morphology
HP:0031335.definition: An anomaly of the structure of mitochondria within cardiomyocytes.

HP:0031336.name: Intranuclear cardiomyocyte mitochondria
HP:0031336.definition: Abnormal localization of mitochondria within the nuclei of cardiomyocytes.

HP:0031337.name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte connexin43 staining
HP:0031337.definition: Anomalous staining of Connexin43 in cardiomyocytes. Connexin43 (Cx43) is the primary gap junction protein in the working myocardium. Cx43 exhibits increased localization at the lateral membranes of cardiomyocytes in a variety of heart diseases.

HP:0031338.name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte plakoglobin staining
HP:0031338.definition: Anomalous staining of plakoglobin in cardiomyocytes. Plakoglobin is a component of desmosomes in cardiomyocytes.

HP:0031339.name: Abnormal cardiomyocyte dystrophin staining
HP:0031339.definition: Anomalous staining of dystrophin in cardiomyocytes.

HP:0031340.name: Abnormal lysosomal morphology
HP:0031340.definition: A structural anomaly of lysosomes, membrane-enclosed organelles that contain an array of enzymes capable of catabolizing proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, and lipids.

HP:0031341.name: Gastric arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031341.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the stomach.

HP:0031342.name: Duodenal arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031342.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the duodenum.

HP:0031343.name: Jejunal arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031343.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the jejunum.

HP:0031344.name: Pelvic arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031344.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the pelvis.

HP:0031345.name: Colonic arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031345.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the colon.

HP:0031346.name: Rectal arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031346.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the rectum.

HP:0031347.name: Uterine arteriovenous malformation
HP:0031347.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in the uterus.

HP:0031348.name: Dextrotransposition of the great arteries
HP:0031348.definition: A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the right of the pulmonary artery. This is the most common kind of TGA.

HP:0031349.name: Levotransposition of the great arteries
HP:0031349.definition: A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the left of the pulmonary artery.

HP:0031350.name: Cardiac sarcoma
HP:0031350.definition: A malignant soft tissue neoplasm that arises from the heart.

HP:0031351.name: Calcified amorphous tumor of the heart
HP:0031351.definition: A non-neoplastic cardiac tumor characterized by calcification and eosinophilic amorphous material in the background of dense collagenous fibrous tissue.

HP:0031352.name: Chest tightness
HP:0031352.definition: An unpleasant sensation of tightness or pressure in the chest.

HP:0031353.name: Otitis media with effusion
HP:0031353.definition: Otitis media characterized by thick or sticky fluid behind the tympanic membrane.

HP:0031354.name: Sleep onset insomnia
HP:0031354.definition: Difficulty initiating sleep, that is, increased sleep onset latency, refers to the condition where it takes 30 minutes or more to fall asleep.

HP:0031355.name: Maintenance insomnia
HP:0031355.definition: Individuals affected by abnormal difficulty in staying asleep tend to wake up at night and struggle to return to sleep. This condition typically involves spending more than 30 minutes awake during the night.

HP:0031356.name: Terminal insomnia
HP:0031356.definition: A type of insomnia characterized by waking up too early in the morning is known as early morning awakening. The termination of sleep must occur at least 30 minutes before the desired time.

HP:0031357.name: Glomeruloid hemangioma
HP:0031357.definition: A histologically distinctive, cutaneous, benign vascular tumor that is characterized by a solitary or multiple blue-red papules and histologically resembles renal glomeruli.

HP:0031358.name: Vegetative state
HP:0031358.definition: The absence of wakefulness and consciousness, but in contrast to a coma, there is involuntary opening of the eyes and movements such as teeth grinding, yawning, or thrashing of the extremities.

HP:0031359.name: Cutaneous sclerotic plaque
HP:0031359.definition: A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter that is characterized by hardening (sclerosis) of the affected skin area (related to collagen thickening).

HP:0031360.name: Yellow skin plaque
HP:0031360.definition: A solid, raised, plateau-like (flat-topped) lesion greater than 1 cm in diameter and that has a yellow color.

HP:0031361.name: Zebra bodies
HP:0031361.definition: Intralysosomal, osmiophilic, lamellated and sometimes concentric cytoplasmic inclusions comprised of broad transversely-stacked myelinoid membranes and said to resemble a zebra in electron microscopic images.

HP:0031363.name: Palpable purpura
HP:0031363.definition: A type of purpura in which the lesions are raised (and can therefore be appreciated upon palpation).

HP:0031364.name: Ecchymosis
HP:0031364.definition: A purpuric lesion that is larger than 1 cm in diameter.

HP:0031365.name: Macular purpura
HP:0031365.definition: Purpura that is flat (non-palpable, not raised).

HP:0031366.name: Palate neoplasm
HP:0031366.definition: A neoplasm that affects the hard palate, soft palate, or uvula.

HP:0031367.name: Metaphyseal striations
HP:0031367.definition: Longitudinal densities on radiographs located in a metaphysis (the narrow region of a long bone between the epiphysis and the diaphysis).

HP:0031368.name: Intestinal perforation
HP:0031368.definition: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the intestine.

HP:0031369.name: Colon perforation
HP:0031369.definition: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the colon.

HP:0031370.name: Small intestinal perforation
HP:0031370.definition: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the small intestine.

HP:0031371.name: Rectal perforation
HP:0031371.definition: A hole (perforation) in the wall of the rectum.

HP:0031372.name: Cold paresis
HP:0031372.definition: Increased muscle weakness upon exposure to cold temperatures.

HP:0031373.name: Stiff tongue
HP:0031373.definition: Increased rigidity and reduced mobility of the tongue.

HP:0031374.name: Ankle weakness
HP:0031374.definition: Reduced strength of the muscles that lift or otherwise move the foot at the ankle.

HP:0031375.name: Refractory
HP:0031375.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is difficult to treat or cure.

HP:0031377.name: Abnormal cell proliferation
HP:0031377.definition: Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of cells, which may result in the expansion of a cell population.

HP:0031378.name: Abnormal lymphocyte proliferation
HP:0031378.definition: Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of lymphocytes, which results in the expansion of a cell population.

HP:0031379.name: Abnormal T cell proliferation
HP:0031379.definition: Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of T cells, which results in the expansion of a cell population.

HP:0031380.name: Abnormal B cell proliferation
HP:0031380.definition: Any abnormality in the multiplication or reproduction of B cells, which results in the expansion of a cell population.

HP:0031381.name: Decreased mitogen-induced T-cell proliferation
HP:0031381.definition: Abnormal decrease of T cell proliferation in response to mitogenic stimuli. This is commonly measured through intracellular expression of Ki67, decreasing surface expression of carboxyfluorescein diacetate (CFSE), or 3H-thymidine incorporation. Length of incubation, specific stimulus and strength of stimulation may vary between laboratories.

HP:0031382.name: Decreased anti-CD3/28-induced T-cell proliferation
HP:0031382.definition: Abnormal decrease of T cell proliferation in response to anti-CD3/28 stimulation. This is commonly measured through intracellular expression of Ki67, decreasing surface expression of carboxyfluorescein diacetate (CFSE), or 3H-thymidine incorporation. Length of incubation and strength of stimulation may vary between laboratories.

HP:0031383.name: Abnormal lymphocyte surface marker expression
HP:0031383.definition: Abnormal amount of a protein that is normally present on the cell surface of lymphocytes.

HP:0031384.name: Reduced T cell CD40 expression
HP:0031384.definition: A deficiency in the expression of the CD40 ligand on the surface of activated T-lymphocytes.

HP:0031385.name: Megakaryocyte nucleus hypolobulation
HP:0031385.definition: The presence of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow whose nuclei are less lobulated than expected for the size of the nucleus.

HP:0031386.name: Increased micromegakaryocyte count
HP:0031386.definition: The presence of abnormally high numbers of micromegakaryocytes in the bone marrow. Micromegakaryocytes are mononuclear diploid cells, with a nucleus similar in size to that of a myeloblast or promyelocyte with the cell being less than 30 micrometers in diameter.

HP:0031387.name: Increased multinucleated megakaryocyte count
HP:0031387.definition: The presence of abnormally high numbers of multinucleated megakaryocytes in the bone marrow.

HP:0031388.name: Megakaryocyte nucleus hyperlobulation
HP:0031388.definition: The presence of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow whose nuclei are more lobulated than expected for the size of the nucleus.

HP:0031389.name: Abnormal MHC II cell surface expression
HP:0031389.definition: A deviation from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.

HP:0031390.name: Reduced MHC II cell surface expression
HP:0031390.definition: Expression of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules at the cell surface is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0031391.name: Elevated MHC II cell surface expression
HP:0031391.definition: An increase above the normal level of major histocompatibility complex class II molecules expressed at the cell surface.

HP:0031392.name: Abnormal CD4+ T cell subset proportion
HP:0031392.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of helper CD3+CD4+ T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0031393.name: Abnormal CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0031393.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of cytotoxic CD3+CD8+ T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0031394.name: Abnormal CD4:CD8 ratio
HP:0031394.definition: Any abnormality in the relative amount of CD4+ and CD8+ T lymphocytes.

HP:0031396.name: Abnormal naive T cell proportion
HP:0031396.definition: Any abnormality in the proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

HP:0031397.name: Decreased proportion of naive T cells
HP:0031397.definition: An abnormally decreased proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

HP:0031398.name: Increased proportion of naive T cells
HP:0031398.definition: An abnormally increased proportion of naive T cells relative to the total number of T cells.

HP:0031399.name: Abnormal double-negative T cell proportion
HP:0031399.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of double-negative (DN) CD3+CD4-CD8- T cells, measured either as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, or as absolute number per microliter of blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0031401.name: Decreased double-negative T cell proportion
HP:0031401.definition: Abnormal decrease of double negative (DN) CD3+CD4-CD8- T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0031402.name: Reduced antigen-specific T cell proliferation
HP:0031402.definition: Impaired proliferation and expansion of a T cell population following activation by an antigenic stimulus.

HP:0031403.name: Impaired pathogen-specific CD8 cytoxicity
HP:0031403.definition: Impaired response of CD8 T cells to pathogens. CD8 T cells direct the killing of a target cell through the release of granules containing cytotoxic mediators or through the engagement of death receptors.

HP:0031404.name: Impaired antigen-specific response
HP:0031404.definition: An impaired immune response mediated by cells expressing specific receptors for antigen produced through a somatic diversification process, and allowing for an enhanced secondary response to subsequent exposures to the same antigen (immunological memory).

HP:0031405.name: Poroma
HP:0031405.definition: A benign, well circumscribed sweat gland neoplasm with eccrine or apocrine differentiation. It usually presents as a solitary, dome-shaped papule, nodule, or plaque on acral sites. It is characterized by a proliferation of uniform basaloid cells in the dermis and it is associated with the presence of focal ductal and cystic structures [NCIT:C27273].

HP:0031406.name: Abnormal cytokine signaling
HP:0031406.definition: Any abnormality in the series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

HP:0031407.name: Impaired cytokine signaling
HP:0031407.definition: A defect or impairment in the series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

HP:0031408.name: Increased proportion of CD25+ mast cells
HP:0031408.definition: An increased proportion of mast cells are positive for the cell surface marker CD25 (also called interleukin-2 receptor alpha chain).

HP:0031410.name: Abnormal distribution of CD56 bright/dim natural killer cells
HP:0031410.definition: An abnormal distribution in the number of CD56 bright NK cells, as measured by flow cytometry. CD56, an adhesion molecule mediating homotypic adhesion, is used as a functional marker for NK cells.

HP:0031411.name: Abnormal chromosome morphology
HP:0031411.definition: Any structural anomaly of a chromosome, which is a thread like molecule consisting of DNA and proteins (chromatin) that contains DNA sequences for genes and other genetic elements in linear order.

HP:0031413.name: Short telomere length
HP:0031413.definition: An abnormal reduction in telomere length. Telomeres are non-coding, repetitive sequences of DNA at the ends of the chromosomes of eukaryotic cells which become shorter as cells divide, and when telomere attrition reaches its limit, cell proliferation arrest, senescence, and apoptosis can occur.

HP:0031414.name: High serum calcifediol
HP:0031414.definition: An increased concentration of calcifediol in the blood. Calcifediol is also known as 25-hydroxycholecalciferol or 25-Hydroxyvitamin D3.

HP:0031415.name: High serum calcitriol
HP:0031415.definition: An increased concentration of calcitriol in the blood. Calcitriol is also known as 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.

HP:0031416.name: Abnormal nasal mucus secretion
HP:0031416.definition: Any deviation from the normal quantity of secretion of nasal mucus, a thick viscous liquid produced by the mucous membranes of the nose.

HP:0031417.name: Rhinorrhea
HP:0031417.definition: Increased discharge of mucus from the nose.

HP:0031418.name: Increased body mass index
HP:0031418.definition: Abnormally increased weight-to-height squared ratio, calculated by dividing the individual's weight in kilograms by the square of the individual's height in meters and used as an indicator of overweight compared to averages.

HP:0031419.name: Reduced sex -hormone binding protein level
HP:0031419.definition: A decreased concentration of sex-hormone binding protein in the circulation.

HP:0031420.name: Small yellow foveal lesion with surrounding gray zone
HP:0031420.definition: A lesion that is observed following light damage to the macula. Damage to the retinal by exposure to intense visible light, usually the sun. Intense light exposure such as staring at the sun causes fine structural anomalies in the outer segments of the photoreceptors and the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) cells of the macula. Symptoms usually develop within 1 to 4 h after exposure and include decreased vision, metamorphopsia, micropsia, and central or paracentral scotomas. Fundus examination typically shows a small yellow spot with a surrounding gray zone in the foveolar or parafoveolar area. Spontaneous evolution leads to the improvement of visual acuity.

HP:0031421.name: Small superior frontal cortex
HP:0031421.definition: Reduced size of the superior frontal portion of the cerebral cortex.

HP:0031422.name: Abnormal cerebellar cortex morphology
HP:0031422.definition: Any structural anomaly of the cortex of the cerebellum.

HP:0031423.name: Small cerebellar cortex
HP:0031423.definition: Reduced size of the cerebellar cortex.

HP:0031424.name: Abnormal circulating beta-C-terminal telopeptide concentration
HP:0031424.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation, a marker of the rate of bone turnover.

HP:0031425.name: Increased circulating beta-C-terminal telopeptide concentration
HP:0031425.definition: A abnormal elevation above the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation.

HP:0031426.name: Decreased circulating beta-C-terminal telopeptide concentration
HP:0031426.definition: A reduction from the normal concentration of beta-C-terminal telopeptide of type I collagen in the blood circulation.

HP:0031427.name: Abnormal circulating osteocalcin level
HP:0031427.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of osteocalcin in the blood circulation.

HP:0031428.name: Increased circulating osteocalcin level
HP:0031428.definition: An elevated level of osteocalcin in the blood.

HP:0031429.name: Decreased circulating osteocalcin level
HP:0031429.definition: A reduced level of osteocalcin in the blood.

HP:0031430.name: Oligoclonal T cell expansion
HP:0031430.definition: The presence of a population of T cells with a restricted T cell receptor (TCR) repertoire derived from a limited number of TCR clones.

HP:0031431.name: Persistent repetition of sounds
HP:0031431.definition: Repetition of sounds with no meaning.

HP:0031432.name: Restricted or repetitive behaviors or interests
HP:0031432.definition: A broad range of compulsive behaviors are repeated, including simple motor stereotypies and tics, as well as more complex repetitive movements or compulsions.

HP:0031433.name: Alexithymia
HP:0031433.definition: Alexithymia is characterized by an impaired ability to be aware of, explicitly identify, and describe one's feelings.

HP:0031434.name: Abnormal prosody
HP:0031434.definition: Prosody refers to the patterns of rhythm, stress, and intonation in spoken language. Abnormal prosody refers to abnormalities in the patterns of rhythm, stress, or intonation of speech or vocalization that can be heard by the observer. In general, this refers to overt and clear deviations in patterns from culturally accepted norms but many also include differences noted in comparison to the usual patterns of the individual (a quiet person suddenly becomes loud or vice versa).

HP:0031435.name: Monotonic speech
HP:0031435.definition: A speech pattern characterized by a persistently abnormal lack of tone in the voice. Monotonic speech is typically ongoing, lasting throughout the day, but may have a diurnal variation in the pattern, i.e. slower at specific times of the day.

HP:0031436.name: Singsong Intonation
HP:0031436.definition: A speech pattern characterized by abnormal fluctuations in the pitch of the voice.

HP:0031437.name: Pregnancy exposure
HP:0031437.definition: Exposure of pregnant women to toxins from any source, such as environmental toxins or chemicals, that may potentially cause problems such as miscarriage, preterm delivery, low birth weight, and, in some cases, developmental delays in infants.

HP:0031438.name: Abnormal sex hormone-binding globulin level
HP:0031438.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration in the circulation of sex hormone-binding globulin, a circulating glycoprotein that transports testosterone and other steroids in the blood.

HP:0031439.name: Abnormal angiostatin level
HP:0031439.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration in the circulation of angiostatin, an endogenous angiogenesis inhibitor, which blocks the growth of new blood vessels.

HP:0031441.name: Abnormal tricuspid valve annulus morphology
HP:0031441.definition: Any structural anomaly of the annulus of the tricuspid valve. The annulus is a ring composed of fibrous and myocardial tissue and is the structure onto which the cusps of the valve attach.

HP:0031442.name: Abnormal tricuspid chordae tendinae morphology
HP:0031442.definition: Any structural anomaly of the chordae tendinae of the tricuspid valve. The chordae tendineae connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve.

HP:0031443.name: Abnormal tricuspid valve leaflet morphology
HP:0031443.definition: Any structural anomaly of the leaflets (also known as cusps) of the tricuspid valve.

HP:0031444.name: Dilatation of the tricuspid annulus
HP:0031444.definition: An increase in the diameter of the ring (annulus) of the tricuspid valve.

HP:0031445.name: Oral mucosa nodule
HP:0031445.definition: A palpable, solid lesion greater than 5mm in diameter that is located in the mucosa of the mouth.

HP:0031446.name: Erosion of oral mucosa
HP:0031446.definition: Loss of the superficial layer of the oral mucosa usually resulting in a shallow or crusted lesion.

HP:0031447.name: Penile freckling
HP:0031447.definition: Multiple pigmented macules located on the skin of the penis.

HP:0031448.name: Herpetiform vesicles
HP:0031448.definition: Multiple vesicles distributed in multiple distinct groups consisting of multiple adjacent vesicles.

HP:0031449.name: Perineal hemangioma
HP:0031449.definition: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, located in the perineal region, i.e., the region between the anus and the genitals.

HP:0031450.name: Polycyclic
HP:0031450.definition: A distribution of skin lesions resembling multiple merged circles. For instance, this can be seen with multiple urticarial wheals as the individual, circular wheals resolve and merge.

HP:0031451.name: Lower extremity subcutanous fat hypertrophy
HP:0031451.definition: An abnormal increase in the amount of subcutaneous fat in the legs.

HP:0031452.name: Lichenoid skin lesion
HP:0031452.definition: Multiple skin lesions resembling those characteristic of the disease lichen planus. These lesions are violaceous (reddish-purple), shiny, isolated, flat-topped papules and plaques.

HP:0031453.name: Oral lichenoid lesion
HP:0031453.definition: Multiple lesions of the oral mucosa resembling those characteristic of the disease lichen planus. These are symmetric reticular lesions that resemble a white, lacelike network, as well as by papules, plaques, erythematous lesions, and erosions.

HP:0031454.name: Apocrine hidrocystoma
HP:0031454.definition: A cystic lesions that forms a benign tumor of an apocrine sweat gland.

HP:0031455.name: Presacral ganglioneuroma
HP:0031455.definition: A gangioleneuroma originating from sympathetic ganglion cells in the abdomen.

HP:0031456.name: Ectopic pregnancy
HP:0031456.definition: A pregnancy in which the fertilized egg inserts in a location outside of the main cavity of the uterus (usually in the Fallopian tube).

HP:0031457.name: Pulmonary opacity
HP:0031457.definition: Opacity refers to any area that preferentially attenuates the x-ray beam and therefore appears more opaque than the surrounding area. It is a nonspecific term that does not indicate the size or pathologic nature of the abnormality.

HP:0031458.name: Adenoiditis
HP:0031458.definition: An inflammation of the adenoid tissue.

HP:0031459.name: Soft tissue neoplasm
HP:0031459.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) that arises from the soft tissue. The most common types are lipomatous (fatty), vascular, smooth muscle, fibrous, and fibrohistiocytic neoplasms.

HP:0031460.name: Benign muscle neoplasm
HP:0031460.definition: A benign mesenchymal neoplasm arising from smooth, skeletal, or cardiac muscle tissue [NCIT:C4882].

HP:0031461.name: Intramuscular Myxoma
HP:0031461.definition: A benign tumor that is usually solitary, painless, palpable mass that is firm in consistency and slightly movable and often fluctuant. It can occur in any location, but tends to involve the muscles of the thighs, buttocks, and shoulders. On microscopic examination, there is abundant mucoid material and relative hypo cellularity and loose reticulin fibers. Vascular structures are sparse. The cells have a stellate shape with small hyper chromatic pyknotic nuclei and scanty cytoplasm. Some myxomas may show focal areas of hyper cellularity. However absence of nuclear atypia, mitotic figures or necrosis helps to rule out malignancy.

HP:0031462.name: Musculotendinous retraction
HP:0031462.definition: Abnormal reduction in length of a tendon which tends to pull (retract) the attached muscle tissue with shortening of the muscle fibers often accompanied by atrophy and fatty degeneration of the affected muscle tissue.

HP:0031463.name: Esophageal squamous papilloma
HP:0031463.definition: A rare benign epithelial tumor that is usually asymptomatic but can present with pyrosis and epigastric discomfort with or without dysphagia. Histopathologically, esophageal squamous papilloma has fingerlike projections lined with acanthotic stratified squamous epithelium with conservation of normal cellular with or without cellular atypia.

HP:0031464.name: Genital blistering
HP:0031464.definition: The presence of one or more bullae on the skin of the genital region, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls.

HP:0031465.name: Abnormal vasa vasorum morphology
HP:0031465.definition: A structural anomaly of vasa vasorum, which are defined as small blood vessels that supply or drain the walls of larger arteries and veins, delivering nutrients and oxygen as well as removing systemic waste products.

HP:0031466.name: Impairment in personality functioning
HP:0031466.definition: A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.

HP:0031467.name: Abnormal negative emotional state
HP:0031467.definition: An aversive emotional state characterized by negative emotional experiences, preoccupations, or internal states that are often related to negative perceptions of the self, the world, or the future.

HP:0031468.name: Separation insecurity
HP:0031468.definition: Fears of rejection by and/or separation from significant others are associated with fears of excessive dependency and complete loss of autonomy.

HP:0031469.name: Low self-esteem
HP:0031469.definition: Persistent, excessively negative, and critical thoughts of one's personal abilities, attributes, or any feature related to the self and self-attitude. The affected individual believes they are a lesser being compared to others in their social peer group.

HP:0031472.name: Risky behavior
HP:0031472.definition: Engaging in dangerous, risky, and potentially self-damaging activities, without considering the consequences, and include physical, health-related, and financial behaviors. It involves a disregard for one's limitations and a denial of personal danger. While consequences may not occur, the risks are high (e.g. driving too fast, unprotected casual sex, or risky investments).

HP:0031473.name: Anger
HP:0031473.definition: Persistent or frequent inner feelings of anger, irritability, or resentment that may be in response to an action or statement by others that is perceived to be a slight or challenge to the person regardless of the nature. Anger may also occur or arise spontaneously in the absence of any provocation and can be directed to another person or social entity.

HP:0031474.name: Pulmonary chondroma
HP:0031474.definition: A benign cartilaginous tumors of the lung.

HP:0031475.name: Status epilepticus without prominent motor symptoms
HP:0031475.definition: There is inconclusive evidence to precisely define the duration of the seizure; however, based on current evidence an operational threshold of 10 minutes is appropriate as beyond this a seizure is likely to be more prolonged. The individual may or may not be aware or in coma.

HP:0031476.name: Abnormal buccal mucosa cell morphology
HP:0031476.definition: Any structural anomaly of the cells of the mucosa of the oral cavity in the region of the cheek (buccal mucosa cells).

HP:0031478.name: Abnormal mitral valve annulus morphology
HP:0031478.definition: Any structural anomaly of the annulus of the mitral valve. The annulus is a ring composed of fibrous and myocardial tissue and is the structure onto which the cusps of the valve attach.

HP:0031479.name: Dilatation of the mitral annulus
HP:0031479.definition: An increase in the diameter of the ring (annulus) of the mitral valve.

HP:0031480.name: Abnormal mitral valve leaflet morphology
HP:0031480.definition: Any structural anomaly of the leaflets (also known as cusps) of the mitral valve.

HP:0031481.name: Abnormal mitral valve physiology
HP:0031481.definition: Any functional anomaly of the mitral valve.

HP:0031482.name: Abnormal regional left ventricular contraction
HP:0031482.definition: A wall motion abnormality observed upon left ventricular contraction that affects a specific region of the left ventricle.

HP:0031483.name: Reduced contraction of the left ventricular apex
HP:0031483.definition: Reduced wall motion (contraction) of the apex of the left ventricle. This manifestation can be observed on echocardiography.

HP:0031484.name: Cold-induced hemolysis
HP:0031484.definition: A form of hemolytic anemia that can be triggered by cold temperatures.

HP:0031485.name: Subperiosteal bone formation
HP:0031485.definition: The formation of new bone along the cortex and underneath the periosteum of a bone.

HP:0031486.name: Vascular malformation of the lip
HP:0031486.definition: An anomaly of blood vessels located in the lip.

HP:0031487.name: Capillary malformation of the lip
HP:0031487.definition: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is characterized by ectatic papillary dermal capillaries and postcapillary venules in the upper reticular dermis.

HP:0031488.name: Arteriovenous malformation of the lip
HP:0031488.definition: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is characterized by direct blood shunting from an artery to a vein due to the absence of a capillary bed. The artery and vein can be directly connected by a fistula or indirectly connected by an abnormal vessel channel termed a nidus.

HP:0031489.name: Venous malformation of the lip
HP:0031489.definition: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is related to abnormal vascular morphogenesis.

HP:0031490.name: Hemangioma of the lip
HP:0031490.definition: A vascular malformation located in the lip that is related to vascular endothelial cell hyperplasia.

HP:0031491.name: Continuous spike and waves during slow sleep
HP:0031491.definition: Diffuse, bilateral and recently also unilateral or focal localization spike-wave occurring in slow sleep or non-rapid eye movement sleep.

HP:0031492.name: Epithelial neoplasm
HP:0031492.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from and is composed of epithelial cells. This category include adenomas, papillomas, and carcinomas [NCIT:C3709].

HP:0031493.name: Glandular cell neoplasm
HP:0031493.definition: A tumor that arises from a gland cell.

HP:0031494.name: Ovarian mucinous tumor
HP:0031494.definition: Ovarian mucinous neoplasms consist of borderline tumors (tumors of low malignant potential, or LMP tumors), intraepithelial (non-invasive) carcinoma, and invasive carcinoma.

HP:0031496.name: Mucinous cystic neoplasm of the pancreas
HP:0031496.definition: Mucin-producing and septated cyst-forming epithelial neoplasia of the pancreas with a distinctive ovarian-type stroma.

HP:0031497.name: Mucinous colorectal carcinoma
HP:0031497.definition: A subtype of colorectal carcinoma with mucin lakes.

HP:0030448.name: Soft tissue sarcoma
HP:0030448.definition: A type of sarcoma (A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells) that develops from soft tissues like fat, muscle, nerves, fibrous tissues, blood vessels, or deep skin tissues.

HP:0030449.name: Therapeutic abortion
HP:0030449.definition: Delivery by means of therapeutic termination of pregnancy. Therapeutic abortion may be done to end a pregnancy if the mother's life is in danger or if the baby has abnormalities involving the major organ systems and is not expected to survive after birth or by choice.

HP:0030450.name: Neoplasm of the autonomic nervous system
HP:0030450.definition: A tumor that arises from an element of the autonomic nervous system.

HP:0030451.name: Mesenteric cyst
HP:0030451.definition: A closed fluid filled sac originating from the mesentary.

HP:0030452.name: Chylolymphatic mesenteric cyst
HP:0030452.definition: A type of mesenteric cyst that is lined with a thin endothelium or mesothelium and filled with chylous and lymphatic fluid.

HP:0030454.name: Abnormal electrooculogram
HP:0030454.definition: The clinical electro-oculogram (EOG) is an electrophysiological test of function of the outer retina and retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) in which changes in electrical potential across the RPE are recorded during successive periods of dark and light adaptation.

HP:0030455.name: Abnormality of pattern visual evoked potentials

HP:0030456.name: Abnormality of pattern onset/offset visual evoked potentials

HP:0030457.name: Abnormal amplitude of pattern onset/offset visual evoked potentials

HP:0030458.name: Abnormal timing of pattern onset/offset visual evoked potentials

HP:0030460.name: Abnormal timing of pattern reversal visual evoked potentials

HP:0030461.name: Abnormal timing of flash visual evoked potentials

HP:0030462.name: Abnormal amplitude of flash visual evoked potentials

HP:0030463.name: Asymmetrical distribution of flash visual evoked potentials

HP:0030464.name: Asymmetrical distribution of pattern reversal visual evoked potentials

HP:0030465.name: Undetectable light-adapted electroretinogram
HP:0030465.definition: No detectable response to the light-adapted 3.0 ERG (single-flash cone response). This type of ERG measures responses of the cone system; a-waves arise from cone photoreceptors and cone off-bipolar cells; the b-wave comes from On- and Off-cone bipolar cells.

HP:0030467.name: Abnormal pattern electroretinogram
HP:0030467.definition: An anomalous response to a pattern electroretinogram (PERG), a particular kind of ERG obtained in response to contrast modulation of patterned visual stimuli at constant mean luminance-typically contrast-reversing gratings or checkerboards-whose characteristics are fundamentally different from those of the traditional ERG in response to diffuse flashes of light.

HP:0030475.name: Abnormal timing of dark-adapted dim flash electroretinogram

HP:0030476.name: Abnormal amplitude of dark-adapted dim flash electroretinogram

HP:0030477.name: Abnormal timing of dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram

HP:0030478.name: Abnormal amplitude of dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram

HP:0030479.name: Abnormal amplitude of light-adapted flicker electroretinogram

HP:0030480.name: Abnormal timing of light-adapted flicker electroretinogram

HP:0030481.name: Abnormal amplitude of light-adapted single flash electroretinogram

HP:0030482.name: Abnormal timing of light-adapted single flash electroretinogram

HP:0030483.name: Reduced amplitude of dark-adapted bright flash electroretinogram a-wave
HP:0030483.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amplitude of the a-wave.

HP:0410181.name: Increased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in dried blood spot
HP:0410181.definition: An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.

HP:0410182.name: Decreased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in dried blood spot
HP:0410182.definition: A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.

HP:0410183.name: Abnormal glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in leukocytes
HP:0410183.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.

HP:0410184.name: Abnormal glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in red blood cells
HP:0410184.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.

HP:0410185.name: Abnormal glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in tissue
HP:0410185.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.

HP:0410186.name: Increased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in tissue
HP:0410186.definition: An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.

HP:0410187.name: Decreased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in tissue
HP:0410187.definition: A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in tissue.

HP:0410188.name: Decreased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in red blood cells
HP:0410188.definition: A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.

HP:0410189.name: Increased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in red blood cells
HP:0410189.definition: An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in red blood cells.

HP:0410190.name: Decreased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in leukocytes
HP:0410190.definition: A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.

HP:0410191.name: Increased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in leukocytes
HP:0410191.definition: An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in leukocytes.

HP:0410192.name: obsolete Abnormal uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level

HP:0410193.name: Abnormal circulating UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410193.definition: An abnormality in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in plasma. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410194.name: Increased circulating UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410194.definition: An increase in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in plasma. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410195.name: Decreased circulating UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410195.definition: A decrease in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in plasma. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410196.name: Abnormal erythrocyte UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410196.definition: An abnormality in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in red blood cells. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410197.name: Increased erythrocyte UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410197.definition: An increase in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in red blood cells. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410198.name: Decreased erythrocyte UDP glucose-4-epimerase concentration
HP:0410198.definition: A decrease in uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase level in red blood cells. Uridine diphosphate glucose-4-epimerase catalyzes the reaction: UDP-glucose = UDP-galactose.

HP:0410199.name: Increased CSF urate concentration
HP:0410199.definition: Increased concentration of urate in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0410200.name: Positive meconium barbiturate test
HP:0410200.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in meconium.

HP:0410201.name: Positive hair barbiturate test
HP:0410201.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in the hair.

HP:0410202.name: Positive stool barbiturate test
HP:0410202.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in the stool.

HP:0410203.name: Positive gastric fluid barbiturate test
HP:0410203.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as phenobarbital in the gastric fluid.

HP:0410204.name: Increased intestinal transit time
HP:0410204.definition: An increase in the length of time required for food to pass through the intestines.

HP:0410205.name: Abnormal circulating nicotinurate concentration
HP:0410205.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of nicotinurate in the blood.

HP:0410206.name: Increased circulating nicotinurate level
HP:0410206.definition: An increased amount of nicotinurate in the blood.

HP:0410207.name: Positive methadone plasma/serum test
HP:0410207.definition: Detection of methadone or its metabolite 2-ethylidene-1,5-dimethyl-3,3- diphenylpyrrolidine (EDDP) in plasma or serum.

HP:0410208.name: Positive plasma/serum cotinine test
HP:0410208.definition: Detection of cotinine, an alkaloid found in tobacco and the predominant metabolite of nicotine, in plasma or serum.

HP:0410209.name: Folate deficiency in CSF
HP:0410209.definition: A reduced concentration of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9 in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0410210.name: Abnormal cord blood measurement
HP:0410210.definition: An abnormality in any umbilical cord measurement performed after birth, such as the blood gas level.

HP:0410211.name: Abnormal blood gas level in cord blood

HP:0410212.name: Hyperoxemia in cord blood
HP:0410212.definition: An abnormally high level of blood oxygen in the cord blood.

HP:0410213.name: Hypoxemia in cord blood
HP:0410213.definition: An abnormally low level of blood oxygen in the cord blood.

HP:0410214.name: Hypercapnia in cord blood
HP:0410214.definition: Abnormally elevated blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level in the cord blood.

HP:0410215.name: Hypocapnia in cord blood
HP:0410215.definition: Abnormally decreased blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level in the cord blood.

HP:0410216.name: Abnormal blood 5-methyltetrahydrofolate level
HP:0410216.definition: An abnormal concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate in the blood.

HP:0410217.name: Reduced blood 5-methyltetrahydrofolate level
HP:0410217.definition: A decreased concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate in the blood.

HP:0410218.name: Hypoplasia of maxilla relative to mandible
HP:0410218.definition: Abnormally small dimension of the maxilla (upper jaw) relative to the mandible (lower jaw).

HP:0410219.name: Hypoplasia of mandible relative to maxilla
HP:0410219.definition: Abnormally small dimension of the mandible (lower jaw) relative to the maxilla (upper jaw).

HP:0410220.name: Increased anti-dairy protein IgE antibody level
HP:0410220.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against dairy proteins, including casein, alpha-lactalbumin, beta-lactoglobulin or bovine serum albumin contained in cow, sheep or goat milk and milk products.

HP:0410221.name: Increased anti-animal protein IgE antibody level
HP:0410221.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against animal proteins, such as albumins that are present in animal hair, dander, shed skin, saliva and urine.

HP:0410222.name: Increased anti-seafood IgE antibody level
HP:0410222.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against seafood, including fish, shrimp, lobster, crab, squid and abalone.

HP:0410223.name: Increased anti-dust mite IgE antibody level
HP:0410223.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against dust mites, such as house dust mites.

HP:0410224.name: Increased anti-bacteria IgE antibody level
HP:0410224.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against bacteria.

HP:0410225.name: Increased anti-drug IgE antibody level
HP:0410225.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against a drug or class of drugs, such as antibiotics.

HP:0410226.name: Increased anti-feather IgE antibody level
HP:0410226.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against feathers, which could be indicative of an allergy against feathers themselves, or mite allergens present in feathers.

HP:0410227.name: Increased anti-food allergen IgE antibody level
HP:0410227.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against proteins found in foods, such as milk, egg, soy, wheat, peanut, treenut, fish, and shellfish.

HP:0410228.name: Increased anti-plant based food allergen IgE antibody level
HP:0410228.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against a plant based food allergen, including vegetables and fruits.

HP:0410229.name: Increased anti-gluten IgE antibody level
HP:0410229.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye.

HP:0410230.name: Increased anti-nut food product IgE antibody level
HP:0410230.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against nut food products such as peanuts or tree nuts, such as hazelnuts, walnuts, cashews, and almonds.

HP:0410231.name: Increased anti-egg IgE antibody level
HP:0410231.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against eggs, including egg whites, egg yolks, and egg proteins such as ovoalbumin and ovomucoid.

HP:0410232.name: Increased anti-fungi IgE antibody level
HP:0410232.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against fungus, such as molds like zygomycota, ascomycota and deuteromycota.

HP:0410233.name: Increased anti-meat allergen IgE antibody level
HP:0410233.definition: Increased level of IgE antibody against meat, such as mammalian meat, including beef or pork, or poultry, like duck or chicken.

HP:0410234.name: Increased anti-parasite IgE antibody level
