HP:0200036.definition: Morphologically similar to a papule, but greater than either 10mm in both width and depth, and most frequently centered in the dermis or subcutaneous fat.

HP:0200037.name: Skin vesicle
HP:0200037.definition: A circumscribed, fluid-containing, epidermal elevation generally considered less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point.

HP:0200039.name: Pustule
HP:0200039.definition: A small elevation of the skin containing cloudy or purulent material usually consisting of necrotic inflammatory cells.

HP:0200040.name: Epidermoid cyst
HP:0200040.definition: Nontender, round and firm, but slightly compressible, intradermal or subcutaneous cyst measuring 0.5-5 cm in diameter. Epidermal cysts are intradermal or subcutaneous tumors, grow slowly and occur on the face, neck, back and scrotum. They usually appear at or around puberty, and as a rule an affected individual has one solitary or a few cysts.

HP:0200041.name: Skin erosion
HP:0200041.definition: A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting incomplete loss of the epidermis, a lesion that is moist, circumscribed, and usually depressed.

HP:0200042.name: Skin ulcer
HP:0200042.definition: A discontinuity of the skin exhibiting complete loss of the epidermis and often portions of the dermis and even subcutaneous fat.

HP:0200043.name: Verrucae
HP:0200043.definition: Warts, benign growths on the skin or mucous membranes that cause cosmetic problems as well as pain and discomfort. Warts most often occur on the hands, feet, and genital areas.

HP:0200044.name: Porokeratosis
HP:0200044.definition: A clonal disorder of keratinization with one or multiple atrophic patches surrounded by a clinically and histologically distinctive hyperkeratotic ridgelike border called the cornoid lamella.

HP:0200046.name: Cat cry
HP:0200046.definition: The presence of a characteristic high-pitched cry that sounds similar to the meowing of a kitten.

HP:0200047.name: Chondritis of pinna
HP:0200047.definition: Inflammation of the cartilage of the external ear.

HP:0200049.name: Upper limb hypertonia
HP:0200049.definition: Increased muscle tone observed in the arms of the affected person.

HP:0200053.name: Hemihypotrophy of lower limb
HP:0200053.definition: Shortening of a leg affecting only one side.

HP:0200057.name: Marcus Gunn pupil
HP:0200057.definition: An aberrant pupillary response characterized by (i) Constriction of pupils of both eyes when the light stimulus is applied to the normal eye, and (ii) Dilatation of pupils of both eyes when the light stimulus is rapidly transferred from the normal eye (after brief light exposure to the normal eye) to the affected eye.

HP:0200063.name: Colorectal polyposis
HP:0200063.definition: Multiple abnormal growths that arise from the lining of the large intestine (colon or rectum) and protrude into the intestinal lumen.

HP:0200064.name: Asymmetry of iris pigmentation
HP:0200064.definition: Asymmetry between the two irides or asymmetry between different parts of one iris.

HP:0200067.name: Recurrent spontaneous abortion
HP:0200067.definition: Repeated episodes of abortion (Expulsion of the product of fertilization before completing the term of gestation) without deliberate interference.

HP:0200071.name: Peripheral vitreoretinal degeneration
HP:0200071.definition: A type of vitreoretinal degeneration with manifestations that are concentrated at the periphery of the retina.

HP:0200072.name: Episodic quadriplegia
HP:0200072.definition: Intermittent episodes of paralysis of all four limbs.

HP:0200073.name: Respiratory insufficiency due to defective ciliary clearance

HP:0200084.name: Giant cell hepatitis
HP:0200084.definition: Chronic hepatitis characterized by parenchymal inflammation with formation of large multinucleated hepatocytes in response to a variety of insults to the liver.

HP:0200096.name: Triangular-shaped open mouth
HP:0200096.definition: A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth, in which the upper lip is tented in a way that the opened mouth has the appearance of a triangle.

HP:0200104.name: Absent fifth fingernail
HP:0200104.definition: Absence of nail of little finger.

HP:0200114.name: Metabolic alkalosis
HP:0200114.definition: Metabolic alkalosis is defined as a disease state where the pH is elevated to greater than 7.45 secondary to some metabolic process.

HP:0200117.name: Recurrent upper and lower respiratory tract infections
HP:0200117.definition: Increased susceptibility to upper and lower respiratory tract infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of upper and lower respiratory tract infections.

HP:0200119.name: Acute hepatitis
HP:0200119.definition: Acute hepatic injury resulting from inflammation typically accompanied by increased serum alanine transaminase activity. Etiologies include viral hepatitis, drugs, toxins, and autoimmune disorders.

HP:0200120.name: Chronic active hepatitis
HP:0200120.definition: Chronic hepatitis associated with recurrent clinical exacerbations, extrahepatic manifestations, and progression to cirrhosis.

HP:0200123.name: Chronic hepatitis
HP:0200123.definition: Hepatitis that lasts for more than six months.

HP:0200124.name: Chronic hepatitis due to cryptosporidium infection
HP:0200124.definition: Chronic hepatitis associated with infection by cryptosporidia, as demonstrated (for example) by immunohistochemistry of liver tissue.

HP:0200127.name: Atrial cardiomyopathy
HP:0200127.definition: Any complex of structural, architectural, contractile or electrophysiological changes affecting the atria with the potential to produce clinically relevant manifestations.

HP:0200128.name: Biventricular hypertrophy
HP:0200128.definition: Thickening of the heart walls in both ventricles.

HP:0200134.name: Epileptic encephalopathy
HP:0200134.definition: A condition in which epileptiform abnormalities are believed to contribute to the progressive disturbance in cerebral function. Epileptic encephalaopathy is characterized by (1) electrographic EEG paroxysmal activity that is often aggressive, (2) seizures that are usually multiform and intractable, (3) cognitive, behavioral and neurological deficits that may be relentless, and (4) sometimes early death.

HP:0200146.name: Mucoid extracellular matrix accumulation
HP:0200146.definition: An increase of medial mucoid extracellular matrix creating translamellar and/or intralamellar expansions including extracellular pools as noted on an H&E stain and/or a stain to highlight extracellular matrix material (Movat's pentachrome, Alcian blue, etc.).

HP:0200147.name: Neuronal loss in basal ganglia
HP:0200147.definition: A reduction in the number of nerve cells in the basal ganglia.

HP:0200148.name: Abnormal liver function tests during pregnancy

HP:0200149.name: CSF lymphocytic pleiocytosis
HP:0200149.definition: An increased lymphocyte count in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0200150.name: Increased serum bile acid concentration during pregnancy

HP:0200151.name: Cutaneous mastocytosis
HP:0200151.definition: Multifocal dense infiltrates of mast cells in cutaneous tissue.

HP:0200158.name: Agenesis of permanent mandibular lateral incisor

HP:0200159.name: Agenesis of primary mandibular lateral incisor

HP:0400000.name: Tall chin
HP:0400000.definition: Increased vertical distance from the vermillion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin.

HP:0400001.name: Chin with vertical crease
HP:0400001.definition: Vertical crease fold situated below the vermilion border of the lower lip and above the fatty pad of the chin with the face at rest.

HP:0400002.name: Extra concha fold
HP:0400002.definition: Folds or ridges within the concha that are distinct from the crus helix.

HP:0400003.name: Focal absence of the external ear
HP:0400003.definition: Absence of a localized portion of the ear that cannot be described by a more precise term (e.g., absent ear lobe).

HP:0400004.name: Long ear
HP:0400004.definition: Median longitudinal ear length greater than two SD above the mean determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear.

HP:0400005.name: Short ear
HP:0400005.definition: Median longitudinal ear length less than two SD above the mean determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear.

HP:0400007.name: Polymenorrhea
HP:0400007.definition: Frequent menses; menstrual cycles lasting less than 21 days.

HP:0400008.name: Menometrorrhagia
HP:0400008.definition: Prolonged/excessive menses and bleeding at irregular intervals.

HP:0410006.name: Abnormality of ophthalmic artery
HP:0410006.definition: Abnormality of the first branch of the internal carotid artery.

HP:0410008.name: Abnormality of the peripheral nervous system
HP:0410008.definition: Any abnormality of the part of the nervous system that consists of the nerves and ganglia outside of the brain and spinal cord.

HP:0410009.name: Abnormality of the somatic nervous system
HP:0410009.definition: Any abnormality of the part of the peripheral nervous system associated with sensation and skeletal muscle voluntary control of body movements.

HP:0410010.name: Abnormality of somatic nerve plexus
HP:0410010.definition: Any abnormality of the somatic nerve plexus.

HP:0410011.name: Abnormality of masticatory muscle
HP:0410011.definition: Any abnormality of the masticatory muscle.

HP:0410012.name: Abnormal mouth floor morphology
HP:0410012.definition: Any abnormality of the mouth floor.

HP:0410013.name: Abnormality of the submandibular region
HP:0410013.definition: Any abnormality of the submandibular region, the region between the mandible and the hyoid bone contains the submandibular and sublingual glands, suprahyoid muscles, submandibular ganglion, and lingual artery.

HP:0410014.name: Abnormal ganglion morphology
HP:0410014.definition: An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the autonomic nervous system.

HP:0410015.name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system ganglion morphology
HP:0410015.definition: An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the peripheral autonomic nervous system.

HP:0410016.name: Abnormal cranial ganglion morphology
HP:0410016.definition: An abnormality of nerve cell cluster or a group of nerve cell bodies located in the autonomic nervous system of the cranium.

HP:0410017.name: Otitis externa
HP:0410017.definition: Inflammation or infection of the external auditory canal (EAC), the auricle, or both.

HP:0410018.name: Recurrent ear infections
HP:0410018.definition: Increased susceptibility to ear infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of ear infections.

HP:0410019.name: Epigastric pain
HP:0410019.definition: Pain that is localized to the region of the upper abdomen immediately below the ribs.

HP:0410020.name: Fish odor
HP:0410020.definition: Body odor characterized by an offensive body odor and the smell of rotting fish due to the excessive excretion of trimethylamine (TMA) in the urine, sweat, and breath of affected individuals.

HP:0410022.name: Vaginal fish odor
HP:0410022.definition: A fish odor in the vaginal area, that is characteristic of bacterial vaginosis (BV), and is due to trimethylamine (TMA).

HP:0410023.name: Abnormal distribution of cell junction proteins in buccal mucosal cells
HP:0410023.definition: An anomalous amount or location of cell junction proteins such as plakoglobin or Cx43.

HP:0410027.name: Alveolar bone loss around teeth
HP:0410027.definition: A decrease in the amount of alveolar bone around the root of a tooth.

HP:0410028.name: Recurrent oral herpes
HP:0410028.definition: Recurrent episodes of oral herpes, typically characterized by blisters or ulcers on the gums, lips and/or tongue caused by herpes virus.

HP:0410030.name: Cleft lip
HP:0410030.definition: A gap in the lip or lips.

HP:0410031.name: Submucous cleft of soft and hard palate
HP:0410031.definition: Soft and hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the soft and hard palate that are covered by the lining (ie mucous membrane) of the roof of the mouth.

HP:0410033.name: Unilateral alveolar cleft of maxilla
HP:0410033.definition: One sided alveolar cleft of the maxilla.

HP:0410034.name: Bilateral alveolar cleft of maxilla
HP:0410034.definition: Nonmidline alveolar cleft of the maxilla.

HP:0410035.name: Abnormal T cell activation
HP:0410035.definition: Any abnormality in the activation of T cells, i.e. the change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

HP:0410042.name: Abnormal liver morphology
HP:0410042.definition: Any structural anomaly of the bile-secreting organ that is important for detoxification, for fat, carbohydrate, and protein metabolism, and for glycogen storage.

HP:0410043.name: Abnormal neural tube morphology
HP:0410043.definition: Any structural anomaly of the hollow epithelial tube found on the dorsal side of the vertebrate embryo that develops into the central nervous system (i.e. brain and spinal cord).

HP:0410050.name: Decreased level of 1,5 anhydroglucitol in serum
HP:0410050.definition: A decrease in the level of 1,5 anhydroglucitol in the serum. 1,5-Anhydrosorbitol is a validated marker of short-term glycemic control. This substance is derived mainly from food, is well absorbed in the intestine, and is distributed to all organs and tissues.

HP:0410051.name: Increased level of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric acid in urine
HP:0410051.definition: The concentration of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410052.name: Increased level of allantoin in serum
HP:0410052.definition: An increase in the level of allantoin in the serum.

HP:0410053.name: Elevated circulating gamma-aminobutyric acid concentration
HP:0410053.definition: An increase in the level of Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) in the blood circulation.

HP:0410054.name: Decreased circulating GABA concentration
HP:0410054.definition: A decrease in the level of GABA in the serum.

HP:0410055.name: Decreased level of erythritol in urine
HP:0410055.definition: A decrease in the level of erythritol in the urine.

HP:0410056.name: Decreased CSF erythritol concentration
HP:0410056.definition: Concentration of erythritol in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0410057.name: Increased level of D-threitol in plasma
HP:0410057.definition: An increase in the level of D-threitol in the plasma.

HP:0410058.name: Increased CSF D-threitol concentration
HP:0410058.definition: The concentration of D-threitol in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410059.name: Increased level of D-threitol in urine
HP:0410059.definition: An increase in the level of D-threitol in the urine.

HP:0410060.name: Decreased level of D-mannose in urine
HP:0410060.definition: A decrease in the level of D-mannose in the urine.

HP:0410061.name: Increased level of galactitol in plasma
HP:0410061.definition: An increase in the level of galactitol in the plasma.

HP:0410062.name: Increased level of galactitol in urine
HP:0410062.definition: An increase in the level of galactitol in the urine.

HP:0410063.name: Increased level of galactonate in red blood cells
HP:0410063.definition: An increase in the level of galactonate in the red blood cells.

HP:0410064.name: Increased level of galactitol in red blood cells
HP:0410064.definition: An increase in the level of galactitol in the red blood cells.

HP:0410065.name: Increased level of hippuric acid in blood
HP:0410065.definition: An increase in the level of hippuric acid in the blood.

HP:0410066.name: Increased level of hippuric acid in urine
HP:0410066.definition: An increase in the level of hippuric acid in the urine.

HP:0410067.name: Increased level of L-fucose in urine
HP:0410067.definition: An increase in the level of L-fucose in the urine.

HP:0410068.name: obsolete Increased level of L-glutamic acid in blood

HP:0410069.name: Increased level of propylene glycol in blood
HP:0410069.definition: An increase in the level of propylene glycol in the blood.

HP:0410070.name: Increased level of ribitol in urine
HP:0410070.definition: An increase in the level of ribitol in the urine. Ribotol is a crystalline pentose alcohol (C5H12O5) and is a metabolic end product formed by the reduction of ribose.

HP:0410071.name: Increased CSF ribitol concentration
HP:0410071.definition: The concentration of ribitol in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410072.name: Increased level of ribose in urine
HP:0410072.definition: An increase in the level of ribose in the urine.

HP:0410073.name: Increased CSF ribose concentration
HP:0410073.definition: The concentration of ribose in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410074.name: Increased level of xylitol in urine
HP:0410074.definition: An increase in the level of xylitol in the urine.

HP:0410075.name: Increased CSF xylitol concentration
HP:0410075.definition: The concentration of xylitol in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410132.name: Increased level of L-pyroglutamic acid in urine
HP:0410132.definition: An increase in the level of L-pyroglutamic acid in the urine.

HP:0410133.name: Chronic idiopathic urticaria
HP:0410133.definition: Urticaria characterized by spontaneously recurring hives for 6 weeks or longer.

HP:0410134.name: Physical urticaria
HP:0410134.definition: Urticaria caused by physical agents, such as heat, cold, light, friction.

HP:0410135.name: Cold urticaria
HP:0410135.definition: Urticaria may be caused by cold temperatures.

HP:0410136.name: Aquagenic urticaria
HP:0410136.definition: A form of physical urticaria, in which contact with water, regardless of its temperature and source, evokes pruritic follicular wheals on the skin.

HP:0410137.name: Solar urticaria
HP:0410137.definition: Urticaria in response to exposure to ultraviolet-A (UVA), ultraviolet-B (UVB), visible and rarely infrared light.

HP:0410138.name: Vibratory urticaria
HP:0410138.definition: Urticaria in response to dermal vibration, with coincident degranulation of mast cells and increased histamine levels in serum.

HP:0410144.name: Abnormal circulating biotinidase concentration
HP:0410144.definition: An abnormality in the biotinidase level, an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.

HP:0410145.name: Decreased circulating biotinidase concentration
HP:0410145.definition: Concentration of biotinidase in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. Biotidinase is an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.

HP:0410146.name: Elevated circulating biotinidase concentration
HP:0410146.definition: Concentration of biotinidase in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Biotidinase is an enzyme that releases biotin from biocytin, the product of biotin-dependent carboxylases degradation.

HP:0410147.name: Eosinophilic infiltration in the stomach mucosa
HP:0410147.definition: Infiltration of eosinophils in the stomach mucosa, that is diagnosed by an upper endoscopy and microscopy that shows more than 20 eosinophils per high-power field in association with peripheral eosinophilia and the absence of secondary cause of eosinophilia.

HP:0410148.name: Idiopathic anaphylaxis
HP:0410148.definition: A rare form of anaphylaxis for which triggers cannot be identified despite a detailed history and careful diagnostic assessment.

HP:0410149.name: Drug-induced anaphylaxis
HP:0410149.definition: A form of anaphylaxis that is triggered by intake of drugs or medications.

HP:0410151.name: Eosinophilic infiltration of the esophagus
HP:0410151.definition: Infiltration of numerous eosinophils (usually greater than 15 per high power field) into the squamous epithelium of the esophagus, and layering of eosinophils on the surface layer of the esophagus.

HP:0410152.name: Eosinophilic microabscess formation in the esophagus
HP:0410152.definition: The formation of small localized collection of eosinophiles (an eosinophilic microabscess) in the esophagus. Usually clusters of greater than or equal to 4 eosinophils are seen, that appear as exudates or white spots or white plaques.

HP:0410153.name: Increased level of methylsuccinic acid in urine
HP:0410153.definition: The concentration of methylsuccinic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0410154.name: Increased level of myristic acid in serum
HP:0410154.definition: An increase in the level of myristic acid in the serum.

HP:0410156.name: Increased level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in urine
HP:0410156.definition: An increase in the level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in the urine.

HP:0410157.name: Increased level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in fibroblasts
HP:0410157.definition: An increase in the level of N-acetylneuraminic acid in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:0410166.name: Defective interstrand cross-link repair
HP:0410166.definition: A defect in the of the process of interstrand cross-link repair: removal of a DNA interstrand crosslink (a covalent attachment of DNA bases on opposite strands of the DNA) and restoration of the DNA. DNA interstrand crosslinks occur when both strands of duplex DNA are covalently tethered together (e.g. by an exogenous or endogenous agent), thus preventing the strand unwinding necessary for essential DNA functions such as transcription and replication.

HP:0410167.name: Abnormal morphology of the chest musculature
HP:0410167.definition: Any abnormality of the chest muscles.

HP:0410168.name: Abnormality of the back musculature
HP:0410168.definition: Any abnormality of the back muscles.

HP:0410169.name: Abnormal morphology of the shoulder musculature
HP:0410169.definition: Any abnormality of the shoulder muscles.

HP:0410170.name: Hippocampal atrophy
HP:0410170.definition: Partial or complete wasting (loss) of hippocampus tissue that was once present.

HP:0410171.name: Increased cotinine level
HP:0410171.definition: Increased concentration of cotinine in urine.

HP:0410172.name: Blood xenobiotic
HP:0410172.definition: The presence of a xenobiotic in blood.

HP:0410173.name: Increased circulating troponin I concentration
HP:0410173.definition: An increased concentration of tropnin I in the blood, which is a cardiac regulatory protein that controls the calcium mediated interaction between actin and myosin. Raised cardiac troponin concentrations are now accepted as the standard biochemical marker for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction.

HP:0410174.name: Increased circulating troponin T concentration
HP:0410174.definition: An increased concentration of tropnin T in the blood, which is a cardiac regulatory protein that controls the calcium mediated interaction between actin and myosin. Raised cardiac troponin concentrations are now accepted as the standard biochemical marker for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction.

HP:0410175.name: Hyperketonemia
HP:0410175.definition: An increase in the level of ketone bodies (acetoacetic acid, beta-hydroxybutyric acid, and acetone) in the blood.

HP:0410176.name: Abnormal circulating glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase concentration
HP:0410176.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase.

HP:0410177.name: Abnormal glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in blood
HP:0410177.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in the blood.

HP:0410178.name: Increased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in blood
HP:0410178.definition: An increase in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in the blood.

HP:0410179.name: Decreased glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in blood
HP:0410179.definition: A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in the blood.

HP:0410180.name: Abnormal glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level in dried blood spot
HP:0410180.definition: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in a dried blood spot.

HP:6000071.name: Heterotopic dermal ossification
HP:6000071.definition: Formation of abnormal, extraskeletal bony tissue in the dermis (i.e., the layer of skin that lies beneath the epidermis and above the subcutaneous layer).

HP:6000072.name: Thinning of outer muscular layer of small bowel
HP:6000072.definition: The depth of the outer muscular layer of the small bowel is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000073.name: Renal lymphangiectasia
HP:6000073.definition: A developmental anomaly of renal lymphatics that results from a failure of the lymphatics to make communication with the rest of the lymph trunks. The abnormal lymphatics thus dilate and form cystic spaces at the renal sinus and in the perinephric space.

HP:6000074.name: Pharyngeal myxoma
HP:6000074.definition: A myxoma (benign, locally infiltrative neoplasms arising from mesenchymal origin) localized to the pharynx.

HP:6000076.name: Renal vasculitis
HP:6000076.definition: Vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessels) in the kidney. Renal vasculitis can be observed with numerous disorders and presents clinically as rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN) which is characterized by acute kidney injury (AKI), haematuria and proteinuria. Histological examination of the kidney reveals severe inflammation in the form of crescent formation, glomerular necrosis and vasculitis of small and medium sized vessels within the kidney.

HP:6000077.name: Pancreatic islet beta cell iron deposition
HP:6000077.definition: Accumulation of abnormally high amounts of iron in beta cells of the pancreas.

HP:6000078.name: Nasal hamartoma
HP:6000078.definition: A hamartoma (tissue malformation consisting of an abnormal mixture of constitutive components) originating in the nose.

HP:6000079.name: Metachromatic intraneuronal lipid deposits
HP:6000079.definition: A type of metachromasia localized to a peripheral nerve. Metachromasia may be defined as the staining of tissue or tissue components such that the color of the tissue-bound dye complex differs significantly from the color of the original dye complex to give a marked contrast in color. For instance in metachromatic leukodystrophy, bloated Schwann cells, containing granularmetachromatic storage material May display a characteristic yellow green dichroism under crossed polarised light.

HP:6000080.name: Reduced phosphoserine phosphatase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000080.definition: Activity of phosphoserine phosphatase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000081.name: Reduced alpha-aminoadipic semialdehyde synthase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000081.definition: Activity of alpha-aminoadipic semialdehyde synthase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000082.name: Reduced hepatic beta-ureidopropionase activity
HP:6000082.definition: Activity of beta-ureidopropionase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000083.name: Reduced hepatic dihydropyrimidinase activity
HP:6000083.definition: Activity of dihydropyrimidinase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000084.name: Sunken fontanelle
HP:6000084.definition: Fontanelle that is more deeply set than normal. Fontanelles are normally relatively firm and curve only slightly inward. A sunken fontanelle can be a sign of dehydration or marasmus.

HP:6000085.name: Angulation of penis
HP:6000085.definition: Formation of an angle (tilt) along the shaft of the penis.

HP:6000086.name: History of urethral procedure or catheterization
HP:6000086.definition: A past medical history of a procedure or catheterization involving the urethra.

HP:6000087.name: Penile swelling
HP:6000087.definition: Abormal enlargement of the penis owing to accumulation of fluid.

HP:6000088.name: Reduced muscle alpha-1,4-glucosidase activity
HP:6000088.definition: Activity of the enzyme alpha-1,4-glucosidase activity in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000089.name: Brown tumor
HP:6000089.definition: A brown tumor is a bone lesion that results from bony resorption by excess osteoclastic activity, and replacement by fibrous tissue and giant cells. Brown tumor is an uncommon pathognomonic sign of hyperparathyroidism.

HP:6000090.name: Dermal flame figures
HP:6000090.definition: Flame-figures are composed of a central part consisting of collagen fibers and eosinophilic granules, surrounded by a histiocytic and eosinophilic infiltrate. Subsequently, eosinophils tend to disappear and are replaced by phagocytic granulomas, consisting of histiocytes and sometimes giant cells, around the flame figures.

HP:6000091.name: Postpartum exacerbation
HP:6000091.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is present during pregnancy and becomes worse following birth.

HP:6000093.name: Propylthiouracil exposure
HP:6000093.definition: History of having been treated with propylthiouracil.

HP:6000094.name: History of outdoor activities
HP:6000094.definition: History of spending a substantial amount of time outdoors with occupation or hobbies related to the outdoors, including hunting, gardening, farming, agriculture, horticulture, miners, working in wet fields.

HP:6000095.name: Draining sinus tract in skin
HP:6000095.definition: A sinus tract is an abnormal channel that originates from the skin or a mucous surface to a deep-seated focus of suppuration.

HP:6000096.name: Corneal transplant history
HP:6000096.definition: Past medical history of surgical replacement of the cornea with corneal tissue from a donor.

HP:6000097.name: Spontaneous lens capsule rupture
HP:6000097.definition: Breakage of the capsule of the lens. This is most often observed as a complication of lens surgery, but this term refers to lens capsule rupture not related to surgery or major trauma.

HP:6000098.name: Contact lens wearer
HP:6000098.definition: A past medical history of wearing contact lenses.

HP:6000099.name: Airway mucosal thickening
HP:6000099.definition: Increase in thickness of the mucosa of the airways above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000100.name: Hyperpolarized transepithelial nasal potential difference
HP:6000100.definition: Increased (more negative) voltage across the nasal epithelium.

HP:6000101.name: Corneopalpebral synechiae
HP:6000101.definition: An adhesion between the conjunctiva of the eyelid and the cornea.

HP:6000102.name: Breast intraductal papilloma
HP:6000102.definition: Intraductal papilloma is a benign tumor found within breast ducts. The abnormal proliferation of ductal epithelial cells causes growth. A solitary intraductal papilloma is usually found centrally posterior to the nipple affecting the central duct. Multiple intraductal papillomas are located peripherally, found in any breast quadrant affecting the peripheral ducts.

HP:6000103.name: Precipitous labor
HP:6000103.definition: Precipitous labor is extremely rapid labor and delivery, usually defined as expulsion of the fetus within less than 3 hours of commencement of regular contractions.

HP:6000104.name: Twin pregnancy
HP:6000104.definition: Maternal history of a pregnancy with two fetuses in the uterus.

HP:6000105.name: Vaginal mass
HP:6000105.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the vagina. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000106.name: Costovertebral angle tenderness
HP:6000106.definition: Pain that is elicited by palpation of the region inside of the costovertebral angle, which is formed by the 12th rib and the spine.

HP:6000107.name: Cervical motion tenderness
HP:6000107.definition: Pain that is elicited by moving the uterine cervix. This finding can be ascertained by pelvic exam. Cervical motion tenderness is a gynecological exam finding that could be indicative of peritoneal infection.

HP:6000108.name: Abnormal urethral discharge
HP:6000108.definition: Fluid that originates from the urethra that is not urine, pre-ejaculate or semen.

HP:6000109.name: Supernumerary finger flexion crease
HP:6000109.definition: The presence of an extra digital crease in and individual with normal joint anatomy.

HP:6000110.name: Large joint predominance
HP:6000110.definition: Refers to a phenotypic abnormality that mainly affect large joints.

HP:6000111.name: Monoarticular
HP:6000111.definition: Refers to a phenotypic abnormality that affects a single joint.

HP:6000112.name: Hockey-stick palmar crease
HP:6000112.definition: An abnormality of the upper palmar crease whereby the crease widens and ends between the second and third fingers and is said to resemble a hockey stick.

HP:6000113.name: Elevated urinary succinyladenosine level
HP:6000113.definition: The amount of succinyladenosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000114.name: Elevated urinary 5-hydroxymethyluracil level
HP:6000114.definition: The amount of 5-hydroxymethyluracil in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000115.name: Decreased urine creatinine level
HP:6000115.definition: The amount of creatinine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000116.name: Elevated urinary deoxyuridine level
HP:6000116.definition: The amount of deoxyuridine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000118.name: Elevated urinary dihydrouracil level
HP:6000118.definition: The amount of dihydrouracil in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000119.name: Elevated urinary dihydrothymine level
HP:6000119.definition: The amount of dihydrothymine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000120.name: Elevated urinary sulfatide level
HP:6000120.definition: The amount of sulfatides in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Sulfatides are derived from GalCer via esterification of a sulfate group to 3-hydroxyl of the galactose moiety.

HP:6000121.name: Elevated urinary xanthurenic acid level
HP:6000121.definition: The amount of xanthurenic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000122.name: Increased urinary N-acetylglucosamine-rich oligosaccharide level
HP:6000122.definition: Presence of N-acetylglucosamine-rich oligosaccharides in the urine.

HP:6000123.name: Elevated urinary 2'-deoxyadenosine level
HP:6000123.definition: The amount of 2'-deoxyadenosine (dAdo) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000124.name: Positive 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine urine test
HP:6000124.definition: Positive (abnormal) result of the 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine urine test, which indicates the presence of alpha-ketoacids in the urine.

HP:6000125.name: Elevated urinary dolichol level
HP:6000125.definition: The amount of dolichol in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000126.name: Decreased urinary bile acid level
HP:6000126.definition: The amount of bile acids in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000127.name: Elevated urinary creatine/creatinine ratio
HP:6000127.definition: The ratio of creatine to creatinine concentration in the urine is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000128.name: Elevated urinary thymidine level
HP:6000128.definition: The amount of thymidine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000129.name: Elevated urinary glutarylglycine level
HP:6000129.definition: The amount of glutarylglycine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000130.name: Elevated urinary indican level
HP:6000130.definition: Detection of indican in the urine. Urinary indican concentration may be elevated in small bowel bacterial overgrowth. Indican is produced by bacterial deconjugation of dietary tryptophan to indole which is absorbed at all levels of the intestine, but principally from the small bowel.

HP:6000131.name: Dacrolith
HP:6000131.definition: Dacryolith is a concretion (accumulation of sediment) within the nasolacrimal system.

HP:6000132.name: Reduced erythrocyte gamma-glutamyl cysteine synthetase activity
HP:6000132.definition: Activity of gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase (EC 6.3.2.2) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000133.name: Decreased erythrocyte nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide-cytochrome b5 reductase activity
HP:6000133.definition: The activity of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH)-cytochrome b5 reductase in erythrocytes (red blood cells) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000134.name: Reduced alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000134.definition: Activity of alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR; EC 5.1.99.4) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000135.name: Low semen volume
HP:6000135.definition: Volume of semen in ejaculate below the lower limit of normal. This finding can be ascertained by semen analysis. Comment: Sperm are produced within the testis, in the process of spermatogenesis, then travel through the male reproductive tract (the seminiferous tubules, epididymis, vas deferens, prostate and urethra). As the sperm travel, seminal fluid is added from the seminal vesicles, prostate, testis and epididymis and periurethral glands. The function of the ejaculate is to transport sperm into the female genital tract and to provide a suitable environment for sperm survival during this transit.

HP:6000136.name: Elbow localization
HP:6000136.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the elbow.

HP:6000137.name: Enlarged lunula
HP:6000137.definition: Abnormal enlargement of the visible portion of the distal nail matrix that extends beyond the proximal nail fold, which is referred to as the lunula.

HP:6000138.name: Heel localization
HP:6000138.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the heel.

HP:6000139.name: Splinter hemorrhages
HP:6000139.definition: Thin, red to reddish-brown lines of blood (hemorrhages) under the nails. Splinter hemorrhages run vertically under the nails.

HP:6000140.name: Lateral thrust
HP:6000140.definition: Lateral thrust (LT) refers to an abnormal knee joint motion in the early stance phase where the knee joint center moves laterally. Also known as varus thrust, LR is defined as the dynamic worsening or abrupt onset of varus (bow-leg) alignment as the limb accepts weight (stance phase), with a return to less varus and more neutral alignment during lift-off and the non-weight-bearing (swing) phase of gait, varus thrust is a potent mechanical risk factor for medial knee osteoarthritis progression.

HP:6000141.name: Cerebral contusion
HP:6000141.definition: A contusion is a region of injured tissue in which blood capillaries have been ruptured without laceration (bruise). Brain contusions are bruises of the cortical surface that damage the surface from the outside inward, producing disruption of tissue and vessels. The term cerebral contusion describes the pathology of focal necrosis and hemorrhage, typically observed in older children, involving particularly cerebral cortex and subcortical white matter. Such lesions are usually found in coup and contrecoup, as well as inferior orbital, frontal, and temporal locations. Cerebral contusions cause permanent damage to tissues of the cerebrum. The etiology of cerebral contusion is trauma to the head.

HP:6000142.name: Fecolith
HP:6000142.definition: A mass of accumulated hardened fecal matter.

HP:6000143.name: Appendicitis
HP:6000143.definition: Appendicitis is an inflammation of the vermiform appendix, which is a hollow organ located at the tip of the cecum, usually in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen.

HP:6000144.name: Left ventricular aneurysm
HP:6000144.definition: A severely scarred portion of infarcted ventricular myocardium that does not contract normally but instead bulges outward while the rest of the ventricle contracts during systole.

HP:6000145.name: Boot-shaped cardiac silhouette
HP:6000145.definition: An abnormal form of the heart seen upon chest radiography in which the heart displays an upturned apex and slight concave pulmonary artery segment. This configuration is said to resemble a boot.

HP:6000146.name: Hydrosalpinx
HP:6000146.definition: Hydrosalpinx is a distension or dilatation of the fallopian tube in the presence of a distal tubal occlusion.

HP:6000147.name: Elevated methylhex-dienedioic level by MRS
HP:6000147.definition: An increase in the level of 3-methylhex-2,4-dienedioic acid or 3-methylhex-3,4-dienedioic acid in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:6000148.name: Perihepatic enhancement
HP:6000148.definition: Increased signal (contrast enhancement) surrounding the liver observed on computer tomography or magnetic resonance imaging following administration of contrast agents.

HP:6000149.name: Reduced in vitro contracture test threshold
HP:6000149.definition: The in vitro contracture test determines the sensitivity of freshly obtained skeletal muscle specimens to caffeine or halothane applied to a bathing solution. Muscles from persons susceptible to malignant hyperthermia have lower contracture thresholds for these agents than do normal muscle.

HP:6000150.name: Reduced F-wave amplitude
HP:6000150.definition: Reduced strength (amplitude) of the F-wave, which is an electrophysiological artifact produced by antidromic activation of motoneurons following distal electrical stimulation of motor nerve fibers.

HP:6000151.name: Enlarged peroxisomes
HP:6000151.definition: Abnormal increase in size of peroxisomes.

HP:6000152.name: Adrenocortical hyperplasia
HP:6000152.definition: A non-malignant growth, or enlargement, of the adrenal glands, specifically the cortex, although the cortex cannot be definitively identified by conventional imaging. Adrenal cortical hyperplasia is defined radiologically as a non-malignant growth, or enlargement, of the adrenal glands.

HP:6000153.name: Lymphocytic infiltration of the parotid gland
HP:6000153.definition: Accumulation of lymphocytes in the parotid gland. This feature is generally defined as a count of lymphocytes per area that is above normal limits on histopathological examination.

HP:6000154.name: Bone marrow granuloma
HP:6000154.definition: A granuloma (a focal aggregate of immune cells that forms in response to a persistent inflammatory stimulus) localiyed to the bone marrow. A granuloma characteristically demonstrates the compact organization of mature macrophages, which may or may not be associated with other inflammatory cell types.

HP:6000155.name: Neuronal intranuclear inclusion bodies
HP:6000155.definition: The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neurons.

HP:6000157.name: Decreased pancreatic acinar cell density
HP:6000157.definition: Number (count) of pancreatic acinar cells reduced below normal. This feature can be ascertained by pancreas biopsy.

HP:6000158.name: Unesterified cholesterol accumulation in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000158.definition: An abnormal result of the filipin test. This test is based on the reaction of unesterified cholesterol with fluorescent antibiotic filipin giving a strongly fluorescent, stable cholesterol-filipin complex suitable for in situ detection. An abnormal test result is present if there is a perinuclear accumulation of staining in lysosomal storage organelles (LSOs).

HP:6000160.name: Splenic lipid-laden macrophage infiltration
HP:6000160.definition: Accumulation of foamy cells (lipid-laden macrophages) in the parenchyma of the spleen.

HP:6000161.name: Reduced hepatic N-acetylglutamate synthase activity
HP:6000161.definition: Concentration or activity of N-acetylglutamate synthase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000162.name: Excessive licorice consumption
HP:6000162.definition: Ingestion of large amounts of licorice.

HP:6000163.name: Shoulder localization
HP:6000163.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the shoulder.

HP:6000164.name: Pregnancy conceived despite intrauterine device
HP:6000164.definition: Intrauterine devices (IUDs) are used for contraception. Rarely pregnancy occurs despite the presence of an IUD. Such pregnancies are associated with an increased risk of spontaneous abortion and preterm delivery due to infection, and a higher risk of maternal septic complications.

HP:6000165.name: Maternal folate deficiency
HP:6000165.definition: The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of folate deficiency during the corresponding pregnancy.

HP:6000166.name: Maternal zinc deficiency
HP:6000166.definition: The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of abnormally low zinc levels during the corresponding pregnancy.

HP:6000167.name: Use of intrauterine device
HP:6000167.definition: Intrauterine devices (IUD) are commonly used for contraception. IUD complications are rare, but include perforation, pelvic infection, expulsion, missing strings, and difficult IUD removal.

HP:6000168.name: History of recent central venous catheter
HP:6000168.definition: A past medical history of a recent central venous catheter (CVC). A CVC is an indwelling device inserted into a large, central vein (most commonly the internal jugular, subclavian, or femoral) and advanced until the terminal lumen resides within the inferior vena cava, superior vena cava, or right atrium. CVCs can be a necessary producre for critically ill patients with indications such as total parenteral nutrition administration, dialysis, plasmapheresis, medication administration, and hemodynamic monitoring, and to facilitate further complex interventions such as transvenous pacemaker placement. Complications include arrhythmia, central vein stenosis, and sepsis.

HP:6000169.name: History of total parenteral nutrition dependence
HP:6000169.definition: A past medical history of a recent depence on total parenteral nutrition (TPN), which refers to intravenously administered nutrition being the only source of nutrition the patient is receiving.

HP:6000170.name: Pain alleviated by testicle elevation
HP:6000170.definition: This refers to testicular pain that is lessened or made more bearable by elevation of the testicle.

HP:6000171.name: Abdominal wall mass
HP:6000171.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the abdominal wall (the skin, fascia, and muscle encases the abdominal cavity and viscera). The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000172.name: Tympanic membrane bulging
HP:6000172.definition: The tympanic membrane protrudes (swells outwards). This feature may be observed with otoscopy.

HP:6000173.name: Ear pain exacerbated by manipulating tragus or pinna
HP:6000173.definition: Applies to pain of the ear that is worsened, aggravated, or exacerbated by touching or moving the tragus or pinna.

HP:6000174.name: Lateral neck mass
HP:6000174.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the side of the neck. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000175.name: Occipital location
HP:6000175.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the occiput (back part of the head).

HP:6000176.name: Anterior neck swelling
HP:6000176.definition: Abormal enlargement of the front part of the neck owing to accumulation of fluid.

HP:6000177.name: Uvular swelling
HP:6000177.definition: Abnormal enlargement of the uvula related to an abnormal accumulation of fluid.

HP:6000178.name: obsolete Purulent drainage from Stensen duct

HP:6000179.name: History of gastric bypass surgery
HP:6000179.definition: History of having received gastric bypass surgery. This is a procedure that reduces the functional volume of the stomach and is used to treat morbid obesity.

HP:6000180.name: Triggered by volatile organic compounds
HP:6000180.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to volatile organic compounds (VOCs), which comprise various organic chemicals which are released as gases from different liquids or solids.

HP:0031498.name: Mucinous gastric carcinoma
HP:0031498.definition: A poorly differentiated type of gastric carcinoma with a substantial amount of extracellular mucus (over 50% of tumor volume) within the tumor.

HP:0031499.name: Appendiceal mucinous neoplasm
HP:0031499.definition: An epithelial neoplasm originating in the appendix and often associated with cystic dilation of the appendix due to accumulation of gelatinous material, morphologically referred to as mucoceles.

HP:0031500.name: Abdominal mass
HP:0031500.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the abdomen.

HP:0031501.name: Pelvic mass
HP:0031501.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the pelvic region.

HP:0031502.name: Trophoblastic tumor
HP:0031502.definition: A gestational or non-gestational neoplasm composed of neoplastic trophoblastic cells [NCIT:C3422].

HP:0031503.name: Night gasping
HP:0031503.definition: Waking up at night gasping for breath.

HP:0031504.name: Foamy urine
HP:0031504.definition: Urine has an increased amount of frothy fine bubbles.

HP:0031505.name: Abnormal circulating T4 concentration
HP:0031505.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).

HP:0031506.name: Increased circulating T4 concentration
HP:0031506.definition: An elevation above the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).

HP:0031507.name: Decreased circulating T4 concentration
HP:0031507.definition: A reduction below the normal concentration of thyroxine in the blood. Thyroxine (also known as T4) is the main hormone secreted by the thyroid gland into the blood. It can be converted into the active form triiodothyronine (also known as T3).

HP:0031508.name: Abnormal circulating thyroid hormone concentration
HP:0031508.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the hormones produced by the thyroid gland.

HP:0031509.name: Dry nipple
HP:0031509.definition: Abnormally dry skin in the area of the nipple of the breast.

HP:0031510.name: Linear earlobe crease
HP:0031510.definition: A transverse linear fissure (crease) in the lobule of the ear.

HP:0031511.name: Diagonal earlobe crease
HP:0031511.definition: Diagonal earlobe creases run from the lower pole of the external meatus, diagonally backwards to the edge of the lobe at approximately 45 degrees.

HP:0031513.name: Luse bodies
HP:0031513.definition: Fusiform collagen fibers with abnormally long spacing (exceeding 100 nm) between electron-dense bands.

HP:0031514.name: Increased proportion of exhausted T cells
HP:0031514.definition: An abnormally elevated proportion of exhausted T cells (Tex) among circulating T cells. T cell exhaustion is a distinct differentiation state that can be distinguished from naive, effector, and memory T cells. Compared to effector (TE) and memory (TMEM) T cells, exhausted T cells (TEX) display impaired effector functions (e.g., rapid production of effector cytokines, cytotoxicity). TEX have limited proliferative potential, especially compared to some subsets of TMEM and naive T cells.

HP:0031515.name: Abnormal meiosis
HP:0031515.definition: Any anomaly of meiosis, a type of cell division that reduces the number of chromosomes in the parent cell by half and produces four gamete cells.

HP:0031516.name: Oocyte arrest at metaphase I
HP:0031516.definition: Failure of oocytes to proceed through the stages of meiosis with stoppage at the first metaphase stage.

HP:0031517.name: Verruciform xanthoma
HP:0031517.definition: A papillary or cauliflower-like growth characterized by the presence of foamy histiocytes within the elongated dermal papillae forms.

HP:0031518.name: Absent posterior alpha rhythm
HP:0031518.definition: Lack of normal alpha rhythm in the EEG. Alpha rhythm has been defined as a rhythm at 8-13 Hz occurring during wakefulness over the posterior regions of the head, generally with higher voltage over the occipital areas. Amplitude is variable but is mostly below 50 microvolt in adults. It is best seen with eyes closed and under conditions of physical relaxation and relative mental inactivity. It is blocked or attenuated by attention, especially visual and mental effort. One should here note the difference between the terms alpha rhythm and alpha activity: Alpha activity refers to activity in the range of 8-13 Hz and alpha rhythm is the activity of 8-13 Hz with specific characteristics as defined above.

HP:0031519.name: Cauliflower deformity of dermal collagen fibrils
HP:0031519.definition: An anomaly of collagen fibers of the skin that is said to resemble a cauliflower and can be appreciated by electron microscopy.

HP:0031520.name: Groin pain
HP:0031520.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the groin region.

HP:0031521.name: Vaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma
HP:0031521.definition: A type of adenocarcinoma originating in the vagina and characterized by large cells with moderate to abundant clear cytoplasm.

HP:0031522.name: Cervical clear cell adenocarcinoma
HP:0031522.definition: A type of adenocarcinoma originating in the cervix and characterized by large cells with moderate to abundant clear cytoplasm.

HP:0031523.name: Salivary gland oncocytoma
HP:0031523.definition: A benign epithelial neoplasm composed of layers of oncocytes (small round nucleus, micro-granular, eosinophilic cytoplasm with numerous tightly-packed mitochondria)

HP:0031524.name: Ampulla of Vater carcinoma
HP:0031524.definition: A carcinoma originating in the ampulla of Vater (also known as the hepatopancreatic duct), which is formed by the union of the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct.

HP:0031525.name: Keratoacanthoma
HP:0031525.definition: Keratoacanthoma (KA) is a common benign epithelial tumor that originates from the pilosebaceous glands. In most cases, it is characterized by rapid evolution, followed by spontaneous resolution over 4 to 6 months. KA usually presents as a solitary flesh-coloured nodule with a central keratin plug on the sun-exposed skin of elderly individuals.

HP:0031526.name: Subretinal fluid
HP:0031526.definition: Edema/fluid accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane.

HP:0031527.name: Retinal edema
HP:0031527.definition: Accumulation of fluid within the layers of the retina not limited to the macular region.

HP:0031528.name: Subretinal deposits
HP:0031528.definition: Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0031529.name: Focal subretinal deposits
HP:0031529.definition: Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium and that have a focal distribution.

HP:0031530.name: Multifocal subretinal deposits
HP:0031530.definition: Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium and that are distributed with multiple foci.

HP:0031531.name: Sub-RPE deposits
HP:0031531.definition: Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane.

HP:0031532.name: Focal sub-RPE deposits
HP:0031532.definition: Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane and that are distributed in a single focus.

HP:0031533.name: Multifocal sub-RPE deposits
HP:0031533.definition: Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane and that are distributed in multiple foci.

HP:0031534.name: Passive dorsiflexion of the 5th finger more than 90 degrees
HP:0031534.definition: An abnormally increased ability to bend (dorsiflex) one's fifth finger. To assess this feature, the examiner requests to proband to extend the elbows,to bend the wrist back so that it forms a ninety degree angle to the forearm, and to extend the fingers. Then, the proband is requested to bend the fifth finger back as far as is possible without discomfort. If the angle of the fifth finger exceeds 90 degrees, this is considered to be abnormal.

HP:0031535.name: Increased theta frequency activity in EEG
HP:0031535.definition: Increased frequency of theta wave activity in the electroencephalogram. Theta waves have a frequency of 3.5-7.5 Hertz, and are present in very small amounts in healthy waking adult EEGs. Theta activity is normal in small very amounts in the healthy waking adult EEG in a symmetrical distribution.

HP:0031536.name: Separate origin of the left anterior descending and left circumflex artery
HP:0031536.definition: Anomalous coronary origin whereby the left anterior descending (LAD) and the left circumflex artery (LCX) arise separately. Normally, these arteries arise from a common stem, the left main coronary artery (LMCA).

HP:0031537.name: Anomalous origin of the left circumflex artery from the right coronary artery
HP:0031537.definition: An abnormal origin of the left circumflex artery (LCX) from the right coronary artery. Normally, the left anterior descending (LAD) and the LCX arise from a common stem, the left main coronary artery (LMCA).

HP:0031538.name: Abnormal dermoepidermal junction morphology
HP:0031538.definition: Any anomaly of the structure of the acellular zone that is between the dermis and the epidermis and which functions to bind the epidermis to the dermis and to serve as a selective barrier allowing the control of molecular and cellular exchanges between the two compartments.

HP:0031539.name: Linear IgA deposits along the epidermal basement membrane zone
HP:0031539.definition: Presence of IgA antibodies in the dermoepidermal junction that are distributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.

HP:0031540.name: Linear IgG deposits along the epidermal basement membrane zone
HP:0031540.definition: Presence of IgG antibodies in the dermoepidermal junction that are distributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.

HP:0031541.name: Linear C3 deposits along the epidermal basement membrane zone
HP:0031541.definition: Presence of complement C3 in the dermoepidermal junction that are distributed in a linear pattern. This feature can be appreciated by immunofluorescence microscopy.

HP:0031542.name: Myelin-like whorls in vacuolated fibers
HP:0031542.definition: Muscle fibers contain one or more vacuoles (membrane-bound cavity) associated with collections of membranes arranged in a whorl-like (spiral or circular) manner.

HP:0031544.name: Elevated circulating palmitoleylcarnitine concentration
HP:0031544.definition: An elevated level of propionylcarnitine in the circulation. Propionylcarnitine is present in high abundance in the urine of patients with Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (MUT) deficiency.

HP:0031545.name: Abnormally low T cell receptor excision circle level
HP:0031545.definition: Reduced level of T cell receptor excision circle (TRECs) as measured by the TREC assay. Late in maturation, 70% of thymocytes that will ultimately express alpha/beta-T cell receptors form a circular DNA TREC from the excised TCRdelta gene that lies within the TCRalpha genetic locus. The circles are stable but do not increase following cell division and, therefore, become diluted as T cells proliferate. A quantitative polymerase chain reaction (PCR) reaction across the joint of the circular DNA provides the TREC copy number, a marker of newly-formed, antigenically-naïve thymic emigrant T cells.

HP:0031546.name: Cardiac conduction abnormality
HP:0031546.definition: Any anomaly of the progression of electrical impulses through the heart.

HP:0031547.name: Abnormal QT interval
HP:0031547.definition: Any anomaly of the time interval between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).

HP:0031548.name: Follicular infundibulum tumor
HP:0031548.definition: A cutaneous adnexal neoplasm with variable clinical presentation. It tends to be located in the head and neck and the presentation is papulonodular, scaly, asymptomatic, measuring up to 1-2cm, simulating a basal cell carcinoma.

HP:0031549.name: Lymphocytoma cutis
HP:0031549.definition: Lymphocytoma cutis, or Spiegler-Fendt sarcoid, is classed as one of the pseudolymphomas, referring to inflammatory disorders in which the accumulation of lymphocytes on the skin resemble, clinically and histopathologically, cutaneous lymphomas. Careful clinical evaluation, histopathological and immunohistochemical exams may be needed to make the correct diagnosis.

HP:0031550.name: Abnormal flow cytometry test result
HP:0031550.definition: Any abnormal result of flow cytometry, a method that suspends cells in a stream of fluid and passes them through an electronic detection apparatus in order to assess cell count or measure biomarkers or surface molecules.

HP:0031551.name: Reduced cell surface marker level
HP:0031551.definition: Reduced level of a protein that is normally present on the cell surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031552.name: Reduced fibroblast surface marker level
HP:0031552.definition: Reduced level of a protein that is normally present on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031553.name: Reduced granulocyte surface marker level
HP:0031553.definition: Reduced level of a protein that is normally present on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031554.name: Reduced granulocyte CD55 level
HP:0031554.definition: Reduced level of CD55 on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031555.name: Reduced granulocyte CD59 level
HP:0031555.definition: Reduced level of CD59 on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031556.name: Reduced granulocyte CD16 level
HP:0031556.definition: Reduced level of CD16 on the granulocyte surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031557.name: Reduced fibroblast CD55 level
HP:0031557.definition: Reduced level of CD55 on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031558.name: Reduced fibroblast CD59 level
HP:0031558.definition: Reduced level of CD59 on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031559.name: Reduced fibroblast CD16 level
HP:0031559.definition: Reduced level of CD16 on the fibroblast surface as assessed by flow cytometry.

HP:0031560.name: Coronary cameral fistula
HP:0031560.definition: An abnormal communication between coronary artery and a cardiac chamber.

HP:0031561.name: Coronary cameral fistula to right ventricle
HP:0031561.definition: An abnormal communication between the terminus of a coronary artery, bypassing the myocardial capillary bed and entering the right ventricle.

HP:0031562.name: Balanced double aortic arch
HP:0031562.definition: A type of double aortic arch in which the two branches are of equal size. In most cases of double aortic arch, the right aortic arch is larger and located higher than the left aortic arch.

HP:0031563.name: Coronary arteriovenous fistula
HP:0031563.definition: An abnormal communication between the terminus of a coronary artery, bypassing the myocardial capillary bed and entering any segment of the systemic or pulmonary circulation.

HP:0031564.name: Bronchial isomerism
HP:0031564.definition: An anomalous mirror-imaged arrangement of some bronchial structures. Right isomerism is defined as a subset of heterotaxy where some paired structures on opposite sides of the left-right axis of the body are symmetrical mirror images of each other, and have the morphology of the normal right-sided structures (vice versa for left isomerism).

HP:0031565.name: Abdominal situs ambiguus
HP:0031565.definition: An abnormality in which the abdominal organs are positioned in such a way with respect to each other and the left-right axis as to be not clearly lateralised and thus have neither the usual, or normal (situs solitus), nor the mirror-imaged (situs inversus) arrangements.

HP:0031566.name: Abnormal pulmonary valve cusp morphology
HP:0031566.definition: Any structural anomaly of the pulmonary valve leaflets.

HP:0031567.name: Abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
HP:0031567.definition: Any structural anomaly of the aortic valve leaflets.

HP:0031568.name: Thickened aortic valve cusp
HP:0031568.definition: An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the aortic valve.

HP:0031569.name: Absent aortic valve cusps
HP:0031569.definition: A developmental defect characterized by the lack of aortic valve cusps (leaflets). There may be remnants of the aortic valve in form of a nonobstructive fibrous ridge or rudimentary leaflets or sinuses of Valsalva.

HP:0031570.name: Tessier number 0 facial cleft
HP:0031570.definition: A Number 0 Tessier cleft is a true median cleft lip with a broad columella and bifid nasal tip. The alveolar cleft is between the central incisors. The nasal septum may be thickened, duplicated, or absent. The nasal bridge is usually broad with associated orbital hypertelorism. The midline soft tissue anomaly may range from a mild broadening of the philtrum or there may be a true median cleft lip. The columella and nasal tip are typically bifid and broadened with a midline depression. The alae nasi are intact but laterally displaced. The nose appears shortened in the vertical dimension.

HP:0031571.name: Paramedian facial cleft
HP:0031571.definition: A type of facial cleft located near to but not directly on the midline of the face.

HP:0031572.name: Tessier number 1 facial cleft
HP:0031572.definition: As seen in a typical cleft lip, a cleft of the lip is found in the region of the cupid's bow. The nostril is cleft through the alar dome and extends above onto the nasal dorsum. It passes medial to a normal, but dys- topic, medial canthus. There is an alveolar cleft between the central and lateral incisors that extends above through the pyriform margin lateral to the anterior nasal spine; the nasal septum is not involved. The bony cleft extends through the nasal bone or between the junction of the nasal bone and frontal process of the maxilla. Above the cleft lip, the clefting of the alar dome is associated with deviation to the opposite side of the shortened and broadened columella and nasal tip. Extension of the soft tissue cleft onto the nasal dorsum can be manifest as a series of vertical soft tissue furrows and ridges. Vertical inner canthal dysto- pia and severe telecanthus mark the superior aspect of the Number 1 facial cleft. A cranial soft tissue extension characterized by a tongue-like projection of the frontal hairline delineates the number 13 cleft. Skeletal clefting of the maxilla may extend posteriorly to form a complete cleft of the hard and soft palate. The maxilla is hypoplastic in all three dimensions. There is a keel-shaped alveolus and anterior open bite. Normal septation is preserved between the nasal cavity and the hypoplastic maxillary antrum on the affected side. Distortion of the nasal skeleton produces gross flattening of the nasal dorsum. There is asymmetry of the pterygoid plates, of the greater and lesser wings of the sphenoid, and of the floor of the anterior cranial fossa. The distortion of the cranial base may result in a mild plagiocephaly.

HP:0031573.name: Tessier number 2 facial cleft
HP:0031573.definition: As is typically seen in isolated cleft cases, a cleft of the lip is present. There is hypoplasia, but not true notching of the ala nasi with flattening of the lateral part of the nose. The nasal root is broadened, with lateral displacement of the inner canthus. The palpebral fissure and lacrimal drainage system are not disturbed. The alveolar cleft is through the lateral incisor area and extends to the pyriform aperture. There is normal septation between the nasal cavity and maxillary sinus. Notching at the junction between the nasal bone is present, as is a broad, flat frontal process of the maxilla. Transverse ethmoid enlargement produces orbital hypertelorism. Above the cleft of the lip and palate is a true broad cleft of the nostril that is medial to the intact, but laterally displaced, tail of the alar cartilage. A shallow soft tissue groove extends superiorly to the asymmetrically widened nasal root. The lacrimal system, palpebral fissures, and eyebrows remain intact. The alveolar cleft extends posteriorly as a complete unilateral cleft of the hard and soft palate. The nasal septum is intact but deviated to the opposite side. The nasal cavity remains separated from the normally pneumatized, although hypoplastic, maxilla on the cleft side. Above the nasomaxillary notching, the ethmoid sinus is less well developed, and there is no pneumatization of the frontal sinus on this side. Anterior rotation of the greater and lesser wings of the sphenoid occurs on the cleft side in relation to the narrower orbit and smaller ethmoid sinus. There is mild asymmetry of the anterior cranial fossa, which is narrower on the cleft side. The cranium is brachycephalic with marked occipital flattening.

HP:0031574.name: Orbital cleft
HP:0031574.definition: A facial cleft characterized by involvement of the orbit.

HP:0031575.name: Tessier number 3 facial cleft
HP:0031575.definition: As in the Number 1 and Number 2 clefts, this cleft extends through the lip in the region of the typical cleft lip; however, it does not extend through the base. The cleft continues superiorly to involve the inner canthus and lower eyelid medial to the inferior lacrimal punctum, thereby disrupting the nasolacrimal system. Microphthalmia may be present. The alveolar cleft is between the lateral incisor and the canine. Absent septation between the nasal cavity and maxillary antrum, together with the distortion of the frontal process of the maxilla and lacrimal fossa, produces direct communication between the orbit, maxillary sinus, and nose. There is hypoplasia of the soft tissue margins of the cleft in the vertical dimension. This produces extreme soft tissue deficiency between the alar base and the cleft of the medial aspect of the lower eyelid. The inferior lacrimal punctum is evident at the lateral margin of the lower eyelid cleft. The lacrimal drainage system ends as an opening directly onto the cheek without communication into the nasal cavity. The globe is normal in size, but it is displaced inferiorly and laterally. The nasal septum shows the characteristic distortion seen in typical cleft lip and palate. There is absence of septation between the nasal cavity on the cleft side and the maxilla. The maxilla is hypoplastic in three dimensions, with a marked reduction in pneumatization. Superior extension of the skeletal clefting into the medial portion of the orbital floor and into the inferior orbital rim in the region of the frontal process of the maxilla allows direct communication between the orbit above and the nasomaxillary region below. There is mild narrowing of the ethmoid sinus and of the body of the sphenoid on the cleft side. The pterygoid process appears anatomically normal, but less displaced from the midline compared with that of the noncleft side. Both the orbit and the floor of the anterior cranial fossa are inferiorly displaced.

HP:0031576.name: Tessier number 4 facial cleft
HP:0031576.definition: The cleft lip is midway between the philtral ridge and the commissure of the mouth. The cleft is lateral to the normally shaped and placed nasal ala and passes onto the cheek. The cleft extends through the lower eyelid lateral to the punctum. The lacrimal system and inner canthus are normal. Microphthalmia may be present. The alveolar cleft passes between the lateral incisor and canine, as in the Number 3 cleft. The cleft passes around the pyriform aperture and continues through the portion of the maxillary sinus medial to the infraorbital foramen. The cleft terminates at the medial end of the inferior orbital rim. There is severe vertical soft tissue deficiency in a Number 4 cleft, with the medial margins of the cleft lip extending directly into the medially placed cleft of the lower eyelid. Within the medial segment of the right-sided cleft lip, muscle elements are apparently absent. Muscle bunching is noted in the ipsilateral lateral lip segment, as is seen in a typical unilateral cleft lip. The anatomically normal nasal ala is superiorly displaced in association with a severe deficiency in the overall nasal length. Marked dystopia of the right globe results in its inferior displacement into the medially deficient orbital floor and inferior rim. Both globes are otherwise normal. The complete palatal cleft passes through the maxilla medial to the infraorbital foramen and extends to the medial portion of the inferior orbital rim without evidence of an intact maxillary sinus. Bony septation persists medially, thereby separating the nasal cavity from the orbit, maxillary sinus, and mouth, which are contiguous. Marked midfacial hypoplasia is present. The cleft is manifest as asymmetry of the body of the sphenoid; it is smaller on the right, with asymmetric placement of the pterygoid plates relative to the midline. The orbital floor cleft has no communication with the inferior orbital fissure. The cleft does not extend to the skull base, but there is marked facial asymmetry associated with plagiocephaly.

HP:0031577.name: Tessier number 5 facial cleft
HP:0031577.definition: The cleft of the lip is just medial to the oral commissure and extends across the cheek as a furrow. It ends as a cleft at the junction of the middle and lateral third of the lower eyelid. Microphthalmia is frequently present. The alveolar cleft is through the premolar region and extends superiorly through the orbit at the inferolateral part of the rim and floor. There is a vertical soft tissue deficiency between the lateral portion of the lip and the lower eyelid cleft. The left side of the nose shows vertical shortening, and the left alar base is displaced superiorly. Facial asymmetry secondary to the skeletal abnormality is reflected by a vertical orbital dystopia. However, bothglobes are normal, and there is no abnormality of the upper eyelids, eyebrow, forehead, or frontal hairline. The skeletal clefts vary, ranging from a narrow skeletal furrow that traverses the anterior maxillary wall as on the rightto a broad cleft of the maxilla lateral to the infraorbital foramen and maxillary sinus. This latter cleft enters the inferolateral orbital rim and floor without posterior communication with the inferior orbital fissure on the left side. Medial collapse of the lateral maxillary segments is present bilaterally, with reduction in the transverse dimensions of the maxillary arch. Manifestations of the skeletal disturbance in the sphenoid include a shortening and thickening of the lateral orbital walls in the region of the greater wing and mild asymmetric placement of the pterygoid plates relative to the midline. The right-sided pterygoid plates are smaller and closer to the midline. There is minimal asymmetry of the cranial base and calvarium.

HP:0031578.name: Tessier number 6 facial cleft
HP:0031578.definition: A facial cleft extending from the zygomatic arch to the eye. This zygomaticomaxillary cleft is similar to that typically found in Treacher Collins syndrome. The overlying tissue shows a vertical sclerodermic furrow radiating from the labial commissure or the angle of the mandible across the cheek to a coloboma of the lower eyelid between the middle and lateral one-third. Microphthalmia is not observed. The skeletal cleft is between the maxilla and zygoma; it passes through the inferolateral orbital rim to enter the inferior orbital fissure. No alveolar cleft is present. The zygomatic arch is intact. The soft tissue furrow, which is more apparent on the right, radiates from the oral commissure toward the lateral two-thirds of the lower eyelid. The antimongoloid obliquity of the palpebral fissures is associated with laterally placed lower eyelid clefts and some ectropion. A left-sided anophthalmia is accompanied by adjacent soft tissue hypoplasia and is reflected in a short palpebral fissure, enophthalmos, and minor ptosis of the eyebrow. No abnormality is present in the alveolar arch except for some tilting of the occlusal plane secondary to hypoplasia of the left side of the maxilla. There is a vertical bony groove in the region of the zygomaticomaxillary suture that ends in the inferolateral portion of a small bony orbit. More laterally, the remainder of the zygomatic body and arch is normal in both shape and dimension. The lateral orbital floor is downslanting but intact, and it lacks direct communication with the temporal or infratemporal fossae. The hypoplasia of the left side of the maxilla and orbit is associated with a reduction in the transverse and anteroposterior dimensions of the anterior cranial fossa; mild asymmetry of the middle cranial fossa and calvarium is present. No significant asymmetry of size, shape, or position is present in the sphenoid.

HP:0031579.name: Tessier number 7 facial cleft
HP:0031579.definition: The temporozygomatic Number 7 cleft is found in both Treacher Collins syndrome and hemifacial microsomia. Soft tissue manifestations include macrostomia, malformations of the external and middle ear, temporalis muscle, variable involvement of the seventh cranial nerve (in hemifacial microsomia), and abnormalities of the preauricular hair in Treacher Collins syndrome. The skeletal cleft is through the pterygomaxillary junction, and vertical maxillary hypoplasia is present. In addition, abnormality of the mandibular ramus, coronoid, and condyle and absence of the zygomatic arch are typically present. A soft tissue furrow extends from the macrostomia laterally and superiorly across the cheek toward the preauricular hairline. The lower eyelids are intact. The anatomy of the external ear is normal, and there are no preauricular tags. Bony clefting is through the pterygomaxillary junction with hypoplasia of the alveolar process in the molar region, thereby producing a posterior open bite. The maxilla is hypoplastic, although the maxillary sinuses are symmetrically pneumatized. The hypoplastic zygomatic body arches upward, but then it takes a downward course and is severely malformed and displaced. The zygoma is continuous posteriorly with an apparently normal zygomatic process of the temporal bone. The mandibular condyle and coronoid process are hypoplastic and asymmetric. There is no antegonial notching of the mandible. Marked cranial base asymmetry, with tilting and asymmetric positioning of the temporomandibular articulations, is present. The anatomy of the sphenoid is abnormal, especially on the right where there is no recognizable medial or lateral pterygoid plate.

HP:0031580.name: Tessier number 8 facial cleft
