HP:0031580.definition: The frontozygomatic or Number 8 cleft is found in both Treacher Collins syndrome and the Goldenhar variant of hemifacial microsomia. Skeletal defects are more prominent in Treacher Collins syndrome, whereas the soft tissue clefting is more typical in cases of ''Goldenhar syndrome''. Soft tissue clefting presents as a dermatocele, a true lateral eyelid coloboma with absence of the outer canthus, and anomalies of the globe itself, especially epibulbar cysts in patients with Goldenhar syndrome. The frontozygomatic bony cleft produces absence of the lateral orbital rim; this border now is formed by the hypoplastic greater wing of the sphenoid. The absence of bony support for the outer canthus produces lateral canthal dystopia and the characteristic antimongoloid slant of the palpebral fissures. Secondary to the bony deficiency in the lateral orbital wall and floor, there is soft tissue continuity between the orbit, temporal fossa, and infratemporal region. Preauricular hairline indicators delineate the Number 8 cleft as the first of the northbound clefts. Complete absence of the bony lateral orbital wall and rim constitute the skeletal element of the Number 8 cleft. The lateral border of the orbit is formed by the greater wing of the sphenoid from which small spicules of bone, which represent the rudimentary zygoma, may be found in Treacher Collins syndrome. The symmetry of the facial anomalies is reflected in the apparently normal symmetric anterior and middle cranial fossae.

HP:0031581.name: Tessier number 9 facial cleft
HP:0031581.definition: This is an upper lateral orbital cleft. The soft tissue deformity is in the lateral one-third of the upper eyelid, and the bony cleft is through the superolateral orbital angle. Microphthalmia is present. The superolateral bony deficiency of the orbits allows a lateral displacement of the globes. The lateral one-third of the upper eyelid and the outer canthus are distorted, thus preventing apposition to the globe. The upper eyelid does not have a true cleft. A soft tissue furrow radiates superiorly and posterisphenoid is symmetric and normal. Mild cranial base asymmetry is reflected in the pterygoid plates. The left pair is more laterally displaced from the midline. Skull vault plagiocephaly is evident with an apparent reduction in the anteroposterior dimension of the anterior cranial fossa.

HP:0031582.name: Tessier number 10 facial cleft
HP:0031582.definition: In a Number 10 Tessier cleft there is an upper central orbital cleft with a cleft of the middle one-third of the upper eyelid, which often results in total ablepharia. The eyebrow is disrupted, being virtually absent medially, whereas the lateral portion angles upward toward the frontal hairline. There may be ocular anomalies, including colobomata of the iris. The skeletal cleft is through the midportion of the supraorbital rim, the adjacent frontal bone, and the orbital roof lateral to the supraorbital nerve. A frontal encephalocele frequently occupies the frontal bony cleft. The palpebral fissure is grossly elongated with an amblyopic eye displaced inferiorly and laterally. There is also a divergent squint of the right eye. The eyebrow is deficient medially and becomes thinned out laterally , where it is contiguous with a broad downward and forward projection of the frontotemporal hairline (this may be seen in both the Number 9 and 10 clefts.) A broad frontal encephalocele bulges forward from the middle one-third of the right forehead, supraorbital ridge, and orbital roof. The bony cleft, through which the frontal encephalocele presents, involves the anterior half of the orbital roof, the supraorbital rim, and two-thirds of the vertical height of the frontal bone lateral to the supraorbital nerve. The bony orbit is inferiorly displaced and widened with the lateral orbital wall shortened and laterally deviated. Similar distortion of the anterior cranial fossa is evident, being broader and more flattened on the affected side. The calvarium above the level of the cleft and the cranial base below is symmetric.

HP:0031583.name: Tessier number 11 facial cleft
HP:0031583.definition: An upper medial orbital cleft produces a cleft of the medial one-third of the upper eyelid that extends through the eyebrow into the frontal hairline. The skeletal element of the cleft in the region of the frontal process of the maxilla may either pass lateral to the ethmoid, through the supraorbital rim, or it may pass through the ethmoidal labyrinth to produce orbital hypertelorism. This cleft usually accompanies the Number 3 cleft. The soft tissue features include a cleft of the medial portion of the upper eyelid, an irregularity in hair orientation at the medial end of the eyebrow, and a long tongue-like projection of the frontal hairline onto the forehead. There is a mild flattening of the frontal process of the maxilla and extensive pneumatization of both the ethmoidal and frontal sinuses, both of which are more prominent on the cleft side. No bony clefting of the supraorbital rim or frontal bone is evident. The cranial base and sphenoid architecture, including the pterygoid processes, are symmetric and normal.

HP:0031584.name: Tessier number 12 facial cleft
HP:0031584.definition: There is a soft tissue cleft medial to the inner canthus with a cleft of the root of the eyebrow. The frontal process of the maxilla is flat and broadened, and the ethmoid labyrinth is increased in transverse dimension, thereby producing orbital hypertelorism. The cribriform plate is of normal width. The frontal sinus is enlarged. Even though the frontal bone is flattened, bony clefts with encephalocele have not been observed. There is a lateral displacement of the inner canthus with a mild thinning, aplasia, or irregularity of the medial end of the eyebrow. There are no eyelid clefts. The soft tissue contour of the forehead is normal, with only a short downward prolongation of the paramedian frontal hairline to mark the superior extent of the soft tissue cleft. Flattening of the frontal process of the maxilla, an increase in the transverse dimension of the ethmoid sinus, and a laterally convex bowing of the medial orbital wall produce orbital hypertelorism. Superiorly there is a minor flattening of the frontal bone medially, and the nasofrontal angle is somewhat obtuse. The extensive pneumatization of the sinuses on the cleft side extends backward through the frontal and ethmoid sinuses and into the sphenoid sinus. The anatomy of the sphenoid, including the pterygoid processes, is otherwise normal. The anterior and middle cranial fossae floors are both broadened on the cleft side with minor widening of the cribriform plate.

HP:0031585.name: Tessier number 13 facial cleft
HP:0031585.definition: There is a paramedian frontal encephalocele and a soft tissue cleft that passes medial to an intact eyebrow. The frontal bone shows a paramedian bony cleft with an associated encephalocele. The olfactory groove, cribriform plate, and ethmoid sinus are all increased in transverse diameter, resulting in hypertelorism. The cleft extends medially to the undisturbed eyebrow to end in a short paramedian frontal widow's peak. The bony cleft begins in the region of the nasal bone and extends superiorly through the full height of the frontal bone. Posteriorly, the cleft extends through the cribriform plate and ethmoid sinus as far as the lesser wing and body of the sphenoid. The pterygoid processes are anatomically normal, but they are displaced laterally from the midline on the cleft side. There is orbital hypertelorism below and asymmetry of the floor of the anterior cranial fossa above.

HP:0031586.name: Tessier number 14 facial cleft
HP:0031586.definition: This midline cranial cleft usually occurs with a midline facial cleft that completes a median craniofacial dysraphia. A broad nasal root and bifid nose are associated with orbital hypertelorism and a median frontal encephalocele. The frontal bone abnormality varies from a minor flattening to a large midline defect. There is an increased distance between the olfactory grooves. The crista galli is widened, duplicated, or in some cases absent. Marked inferior prolapse of the enlarged ethmoid bone occurs with orbital hypertelorism. The severe orbital hypertelorism is associated with a broad flattening of the glabella and extreme lateral displacement of the inner canthi. The periorbita, including the eyelids and eyebrows, are otherwise normal. A long midline projection of the frontal hairline marks the superior extent of the soft tissue features of this midline cranial cleft. The median frontal defect delineates the region through which the frontal encephalocele herniates. The lateral segments of the frontal bone sweep upward from the region of the intact glabella and are flattened laterally. No pneumatization of the frontal sinus is evident. The crista galli and the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid are bifid. Just as the ethmoid, including the cribriform plate, is widened and caudally displaced, the sphenoid sinus is broadened and extensively, but symmetrically pneumatized. The lateral rotation of the greater and lesser wings of the sphenoid results in a relative shortening of the anteroposterior dimension of the middle cranial fossa. The floor of the anterior cranial fossa is upslanting from its medial aspect to its lateral aspect, with a harlequin appearance on the coronal scan.

HP:0031587.name: Tessier number 30 facial cleft
HP:0031587.definition: A lower midline facial cleft, also known as the median mandibular cleft. It is a rare anomaly, which may be limited to a defect in the soft tissue of the lower lip. However, in the more severe form, it may extend into the bony mandibular symphysis.

HP:0031588.name: Unhappy demeanor
HP:0031588.definition: A noticeably unhappy disposition is characterized by negative assumptions, self-defeating talk, fear of failure, and negative rumination about past events.

HP:0031589.name: Suicidal ideation
HP:0031589.definition: Frequent thoughts about or preoccupation with killing oneself.

HP:0031590.name: Asthenopia
HP:0031590.definition: Eye strain, i.e., a feeling of fatigue or discomfort of the eyes related to 'overuse' of the eyes in activities such as reading or working at the computer and often accompanied by lacrimation or headache.

HP:0031591.name: Enlarged Eustachian valve
HP:0031591.definition: An abnormally large Eustachian valve (postnatally). The Eustachian valve is also known as the valve of the inferior vena cava, and is an embryologic remnant of the valve of the inferior vena cava.

HP:0031592.name: Situs inversus with levocardia
HP:0031592.definition: Situs inversus of thoracic and abdominal viscera with the heart remaining normally situated on the left; usually associated with congenital cardiac abnormalities such as transposition of the great vessels and/or spleen defects including asplenia or polysplenia.

HP:0031593.name: Abnormal PR interval
HP:0031593.definition: An anomaly of the PR interval, which is the portion of the ECG from the onset of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex. A normal PR interval in adults is 0.12-0.2 seconds.

HP:0031594.name: PR segment depression
HP:0031594.definition: A reduction in voltage of the PR segment below baseline.

HP:0031595.name: Abnormal P wave
HP:0031595.definition: Any anomaly of the P wave of the EKG, which results from atrial depolarization. The P wave occurs when the sinoatrial node creates an action potential that depolarizes the atria.

HP:0031596.name: Abnormal PR segment
HP:0031596.definition: An anomaly of the PR segment, which begins at the endpoint of the P wave and ends at the onset of the QRS complex. The PR segment is normally flat and isoelectric.

HP:0031597.name: PR segment elevation
HP:0031597.definition: An increase in voltage of the PR segment above baseline.

HP:0031598.name: Notched P wave
HP:0031598.definition: V-shaped cut (notch) in the middle of the P wave.

HP:0031599.name: P mitrale
HP:0031599.definition: A broad (120 ms or longer in duration) and bifid P-wave in EKG lead II.

HP:0031600.name: P wave inversion
HP:0031600.definition: P wave below instead of above the baseline. P-wave inversion in the inferior leads may indicate a non-sinus origin of the P waves.

HP:0031601.name: P pulmonale
HP:0031601.definition: The presence of tall, peaked P waves in EKG lead II.

HP:0031602.name: Abnormal mucociliary clearance
HP:0031602.definition: An anomaly in the system of mucociliary transport, which functions to transport the mucous layer lining the respiratory epithelium by ciliary beating.

HP:0031603.name: Impaired nasal mucociliary clearance
HP:0031603.definition: An abnormally increased amount of time required to clear mucus (and substances contained in the mucus) from the nasal mucosa. The nasal mucociliary clearance (NMC) system functions to transport the mucous layer lining the nasal epithelium towards the naso pharynx by ciliary beating in a metachronous fashion at a frequency of 7-16 Hz. NMC depends upon two principal components: physicochemical qualities and quantities of mucus and the properties of cilia that propel it. NMC is considered to be representative of pulmonary clearance. normal NMC time is determined to be up to 20 minutes. Duration of 30 minutes is considered as the cutoff point that discriminates normal subjects from subjects with impaired NMC. NMC can be measured by determination of the transport time of markers that are placed on the nasal mucosa including saccharine, radioactive markers, and dyes.

HP:0031604.name: Agenesis of the carotid canal
HP:0031604.definition: A developmental defect characterized by the lack of formation of the carotid canal, which normally is a circular aperture in the temporal bone of the skull through which the internal carotid artery and the carotid plexus of nerves traverse.

HP:0031605.name: Abnormality of fundus pigmentation
HP:0031605.definition: Any anomaly of the pigmentation of the fundus, the posterior part of the eye including the retina and optic nerve.

HP:0031606.name: Retinal cotton wool spot
HP:0031606.definition: Fluffy white patch on the retina, representing localized areas of dense white swelling of the retinal nerve fiber layer. They often have a zigzag internal structure, a feathered edge but an otherwise well-delineated form and an approximately 1 mm dimension; they project slightly into the vitreous and sometimes deflect retinal vessels.

HP:0031607.name: Pelvic organ prolapse
HP:0031607.definition: Weakness in the supporting structures of the pelvic floor allowing the pelvic viscera to descend or one or more of the pelvic organs drop from their normal position.

HP:0031609.name: Geographic atrophy
HP:0031609.definition: Sharply demarcated area of partial or complete depigmentation of the fundus reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss. The margins of the de-pigmented area are usually scalloped and the large choroidal vessels are visible through the atrophic retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:0031611.name: Sub-inner limiting membrane hemorrhage
HP:0031611.definition: A type of intraretinal hemorrhage that is located in the superficial retina between the inner limiting membrane and the retinal nerve fiber layer.

HP:0031613.name: Inferior chorioretinal coloboma
HP:0031613.definition: Absence of a region of the retina, retinal pigment epithelium, and choroid at the lower part of the fundus.

HP:0031614.name: Inferior retinal coloboma
HP:0031614.definition: A notch or cleft of the lower part of the retina.

HP:0031615.name: Hypopyon
HP:0031615.definition: Presence of pus (appears as a white fluid) producing a fluid level in the inferior part of the anterior chamber.

HP:0031616.name: Anterior chamber flare
HP:0031616.definition: An abnormal appearance of the beam of light traveling through the anterior chamber of the eye in a slit lamp examination. The flare is produced by an increased concentration of proteins in the aqueous humor in the anterior chamber.

HP:0031619.name: Anterior chamber flare grade 2+
HP:0031619.definition: Moderate anterior chamber flare (iris and lens details clear).

HP:0031620.name: Anterior chamber flare grade 3+
HP:0031620.definition: Marked anterior chamber flare (iris and lens details hazy).

HP:0031622.name: Brown anomaly
HP:0031622.definition: An ocular motility defect where the affected eye(s) does not elevate in adduction but has full depression in adduction. It can be congenital or acquired from injury to or defect of the superior oblique tendon or trochlea and has a positive forced duction test result.

HP:0031623.name: Brow ptosis
HP:0031623.definition: Drooping of the upper eyebrow below the superior orbital rim.

HP:0031624.name: Moderate myopia
HP:0031624.definition: A moderate form of myopia with refractive error of between -3.00 and -6.00 diopters.

HP:0031625.name: Pseudoaneurysm
HP:0031625.definition: A contained rupture of an artery with a disruption in all 3 layers of the arterial wall.

HP:0031626.name: Coronary ostial atresia
HP:0031626.definition: Absence of the normal opening of a coronary ostium. There are normally two coronary ostia, which are site of origin of the main left or right main coronary artery and are located in the ascending aorta just above the aortic valve.

HP:0031627.name: Globus pallidus calcification
HP:0031627.definition: Pathological deposition of calcium salts in the globus pallidus.

HP:0031628.name: Aborted sudden cardiac death
HP:0031628.definition: Cardiac arrest that would have led to rapid and unexpected death had an intervention not taken place to prevent it.

HP:0031629.name: Impaired tandem gait
HP:0031629.definition: Reduced ability to walk in a straight line while placing the feet heel to toe.

HP:0031630.name: Abnormal subpleural morphology
HP:0031630.definition: Any structural anomaly located between the pleura and the chest wall.

HP:0031631.name: Subpleural honeycombing
HP:0031631.definition: So-called honeycombs (variably sized cysts in a background of densely scarred tissue) located in the subpleural space.

HP:0031632.name: Anomalous origin of the right subclavian artery from the descending aorta
HP:0031632.definition: Abnormal origin of the right subclavian artery from the descending aorta. The right subclavian artery normally arises from the brachiocephalic trunk, which divides into the right common carotid artery and right subclavian artery.

HP:0031633.name: Isolation of the left subclavian artery
HP:0031633.definition: The loss of continuity between the left subclavian artery and the aorta, with persistent connection to the homolateral pulmonary artery through the patent (PDA) or nonpatent ductus arteriosus.

HP:0031634.name: Anomalous origin of the left common carotid artery from the main pulmonary artery
HP:0031634.definition: The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the main pulmonary artery.

HP:0031635.name: Anomalous origin of the left common carotid artery from the brachiocephalic artery
HP:0031635.definition: The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the brachiocephalic artery.

HP:0031636.name: Anomalous origin of the right common carotid artery from the aorta
HP:0031636.definition: The right common carotid artery normally originates from the brachiocephalic artery. This term refers to an origin of this artery directly from the aorta.

HP:0031637.name: Right coronary artery ostial atresia
HP:0031637.definition: Absence of the normal opening of the coronary ostium from which the right main coronary artery originates.

HP:0031638.name: Anomalous origin of the left anterior descending artery from the pulmonary artery
HP:0031638.definition: The left anterior descending artery (LAD) branches off from the pulmonary artery.

HP:0031639.name: Absent left main coronary artery
HP:0031639.definition: The left main coronary artery (LMCA) is absent and the left anterior descending (LAD) and left circumflex (LCX) arteries arise from separate but adjacent ostia in the left sinus of Valsava.

HP:0031640.name: Abnormal radial artery morphology
HP:0031640.definition: Any structural anomaly of the radial artery.

HP:0031643.name: Fusiform ascending tubular aorta aneurysm
HP:0031643.definition: A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the ascending tubular aorta that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall.

HP:0031644.name: Fusiform abdominal aortic aneurysm
HP:0031644.definition: A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall

HP:0031645.name: Saccular abdominal aortic aneurysm
HP:0031645.definition: An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall.

HP:0031646.name: Fusiform aortic arch aneurysm
HP:0031646.definition: A concentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch that involves the full circumference of the vessel wall.

HP:0031647.name: Saccular aortic arch aneurysm
HP:0031647.definition: An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the aortic arch that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall.

HP:0031648.name: Penetrating aortic ulcer
HP:0031648.definition: A focal defect in the elastic lamina of the aortic wall that leads to localized medial disruption and potential rupture.

HP:0031649.name: Aortic rupture
HP:0031649.definition: Tearing of the aortic wall generally associated with profuse internal bleeding.

HP:0031650.name: Abnormal atrioventricular valve physiology
HP:0031650.definition: Any functional defect of the mitral or tricuspid valve.

HP:0031651.name: Abnormal tricuspid valve physiology
HP:0031651.definition: Any functional defect of the tricuspid valve.

HP:0031653.name: Abnormal heart valve physiology
HP:0031653.definition: Any functional abnormality of a cardiac valve.

HP:0031654.name: Abnormal pulmonary valve physiology
HP:0031654.definition: Any functional anomaly of the pumonary valve.

HP:0031655.name: Quadricuspid aortic valve
HP:0031655.definition: The presence of an aortic valve with four instead of the normal three cusps (flaps).

HP:0031656.name: Systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve
HP:0031656.definition: Systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve (SAM) is a paradoxical motion of the anterior, and occasionally posterior, mitral valve leaflet towards the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) during systole.

HP:0031657.name: Abnormal heart sound
HP:0031657.definition: Any abnormal noise generated by the beating heart.

HP:0031658.name: Third heart sound
HP:0031658.definition: The third heart sound (S3) is related to rapid filling in diastole. S3 can be a normal finding in children and adolescents but suggests heart failure in older patients.

HP:0031659.name: Fourth heart sound
HP:0031659.definition: The fourth heart sound (S4) is a low-pitched sound that occurs just before the first heart sound (S1) when the atria contract to force blood into the left ventricle, that is, coincident with late diastolic filling of the ventricle due to atrial contraction.

HP:0031660.name: Loud first heart sound
HP:0031660.definition: Abnormally increased volume of the first heart sound.

HP:0031661.name: Abnormal second heart sound
HP:0031661.definition: Any anomaly of the second heart sound (S2), which is produced by aortic (A2) and pulmonic (P2) valve closure. The A2-P2 interval normally increases with inspiration and narrows with expiration.

HP:0031662.name: Fixed splitting of the second heart sound
HP:0031662.definition: Lack of variation in the splitting between the two components of the second heart sound with respiration. Normally, the aortic valve closure (A2) is followed by the pulmonic valve closure (P2) but the A2-P2 interval increases with inspiration and decreases with expiration.

HP:0031663.name: Paradoxical splitting of the second heart sound
HP:0031663.definition: Normally, the aortic valve closure (A2) is followed by the pulmonic valve closure (P2) but the A2-P2 interval increases with inspiration and decreases with expiration. With paradoxical splitting, there is a delay in the closure of the aortic valve, so that A2 can follow P2; the individual components can be appreciated at the end of expiration and the interval narrows with inspiration (which is the opposite of the normal pattern).

HP:0031664.name: Systolic heart murmur
HP:0031664.definition: A heart murmur limited to systole, i.e., between the first and second heart sounds S1 and S2.

HP:0031665.name: Midsystolic murmur
HP:0031665.definition: A systolic murmur that begins after S1 and ends before S2, typically with a crescendo-decrescendo pattern.

HP:0031666.name: Late systolic murmur
HP:0031666.definition: A murmur that occurs in the latter phase of systole.

HP:0031667.name: Holosystolic murmur
HP:0031667.definition: A heart murmur that occurs during the entire systolic phase from S1 to S2.

HP:0031668.name: Diastolic heart murmur
HP:0031668.definition: A heart murmur that occurs during diastole, i.e., in the time between S2 and the subsequent S1.

HP:0031669.name: Middiastolic murmur
HP:0031669.definition: A murmur that occurs in the middle of the diastolic phase.

HP:0031670.name: Continuous heart murmur
HP:0031670.definition: A murmur that occurs in both systole and diastole.

HP:0031671.name: Typical atrial flutter
HP:0031671.definition: Typical atrial flutter is an organized atrial tachycardia. It can also be defined as a macroreentrant tachycardia confined to the right atrium. This arrhythmia has a 200-260 ms cycle length, although it may fluctuate depending on patient's previous treatment or ablation, congenital heart disease, etc. Ventricular rate response will be limited by the atrioventricular node conductions, usually presenting a 2:1 or 3:1 response, during atrial flutter. Typical (counter clockwise) flutter is associated with the common flutter pattern: a regular continuous undulation with dominant negative deflections in inferior leads II, III and aVF, often described also as a saw tooth pattern, and flat atrial deflections in leads I and aVL. Atrial deflections in V1 can be positive, biphasic or negative.

HP:0031672.name: Reverse typical atrial flutter
HP:0031672.definition: A type of atrial flutter associated with rounded or bimodal positive deflections in inferior leads II, III and aVF, and a very characteristic bimodal negative wave in the shape of a W is seen in lead V1.

HP:0031673.name: Orthodromic atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia
HP:0031673.definition: A type of atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) where the atrioventricular node is used for anterograde conduction and the accessory pathway for retrograde conduction.

HP:0031674.name: Antidromic atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia
HP:0031674.definition: A type of atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) where the accessory pathway is used for anterograde conduction and the atrioventricular node for retrograde conduction.

HP:0031675.name: Fascicular left ventricular tachycardia
HP:0031675.definition: A ventricular tachycardia (VT) characterized by right bundle branch block (RBBB) and left axis deviation (LAD) on electrocardiogram (ECG).

HP:0031676.name: Monomorphic ventricular tachycardia
HP:0031676.definition: A type of ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by uniform QRS complexes within each lead (i.e., each QRS is identical or nearly so).

HP:0031677.name: Polymorphic ventricular tachycardia
HP:0031677.definition: A type of ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by variable QRS complexes within each lead (i.e., QRS complexes may be different from beat to beat).

HP:0031678.name: Atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031678.definition: A lesion associated with atherosclerosis, a multifactorial and multipart progressive disease manifested by the focal development within the arterial wall of lesions, that ranges from the development of a fatty streak, plaque progression, and plaque disruption. Atherosclerotic lesions demonstrate consistent morphological characteristics, which indicate that each type may stabilize temporarily or permanently and that progression to the next type may require an additional stimulus.

HP:0031679.name: Type I atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031679.definition: Type I lesions represent the very initial changes and are recognized as an increase in the number of intimal macrophages and the appearance of macrophages filled with lipid droplets (foam cells).

HP:0031680.name: Type II atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031680.definition: Type II atherosclerotic lesions include the fatty streak lesion, the first grossly visible lesion, and are characterized by layers of macrophage foam cells and lipid droplets within intimal smooth muscle cells and minimal coarse-grained particles and heterogeneous droplets of extracellular lipid.

HP:0031681.name: Type III atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031681.definition: Type III (intermediate) atherosclerotic lesions are the morphological and chemical bridge between type II and advanced lesions. Type III lesions appear in some adaptive intimal thickenings (progression-prone locations) in young adults and are characterized by pools of extracellular lipid in addition to all the components of type II lesions.

HP:0031682.name: Type V atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031682.definition: Type V lesions are defined as lesions in which prominent new fibrous connective tissue has formed. When the new tissue is part of a lesion with a lipid core (type IV), this type of morphology may be referred to as fibroatheroma or type Va lesion. A type V lesion in which the lipid core and other parts of the lesion are calcified may be referred to as type Vb. A type V lesion in which a lipid core is absent and lipid in general is minimal may be referred to as type Vc. With these lesions, arteries are variously narrowed, generally more than with type IV. Importantly, as with type IV lesions, type V lesions may develop fissures, hematoma, and/or thrombus (type VI lesion), and for this reason too they are clinically relevant.

HP:0031683.name: Type VI atherosclerotic lesion
HP:0031683.definition: Type VI atherosclerotic lesions generally have the underlying morphology of type IV or V lesions, surface disruptions, hematoma, and thrombosis may be (although less often) superimposed on any other type of lesion and even on intima without an apparent lesion. Complicating features may arise because of individual differences in risk factors and tissue reactions. These may include differences in composition of the blood, the relative quantities and distributions in the components of the underlying lesion or intima, as well as modifications of shear and tensile forces to which the lesion or intima is exposed. Clinical imaging of lesions may be expected to contribute greatly to the understanding of type VI lesions and the associated clinical syndromes.

HP:0031684.name: Renal artery atherosclerosis
HP:0031684.definition: An atherosclerotic lesion located in the renal artery.

HP:0031685.name: Abnormal stool composition
HP:0031685.definition: Abnormal level of metabolite or other abnormal analyte result in a stool test.

HP:0031686.name: Increased stool alpha1-antitrypsin concentration
HP:0031686.definition: An abnormally elevated amount of alpha1-antitrypsin in the feces.

HP:0031687.name: Abnormally loud pulmonic component of the second heart sound

HP:0031688.name: Erythroid dysplasia
HP:0031688.definition: Dysplasia in the erythroid lineage, which presents with a variety of morphological changes in the bone marrow, including nuclear budding or irregular nuclear contour in erythroblasts.

HP:0031689.name: Megakaryocyte dysplasia
HP:0031689.definition: The presence of micro-megakaryocytes, hypo-lobed, or non-lobed nuclei in megakaryocytes of all sizes and multiple, widely-separated nuclei.

HP:0031690.name: Opportunistic infection
HP:0031690.definition: An infection that is caused by a pathogen that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such pathogens take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

HP:0031692.name: Severe cytomegalovirus infection
HP:0031692.definition: An unusually severe infection by cytomegalovirus.

HP:0031693.name: Severe Epstein Barr virus infection
HP:0031693.definition: An unusually severe Epstein Barr virus (EBV) infection.

HP:0031695.name: Severe parainfluenza infection
HP:0031695.definition: An unusually severe infection by a parainfluenza virus.

HP:0031696.name: Disseminated viral infection
HP:0031696.definition: A viral infection that fails to be contained by the immune system and spreads throughout the body.

HP:0031697.name: Disseminated infection with live vaccine virus
HP:0031697.definition: A dissemination viral infection caused by a live attenuated vaccine virus.

HP:0031698.name: obsolete Disseminated Bacillus Calmette-Guerin infection
HP:0031698.definition: Failure to contain thebacillus Calmette-Guerin (BCG) following vaccination leading to spread of BCG to many sites in the body. The tuberculosis vaccine BCG contains live attenuated Mycobacterium bovis.

HP:0031699.name: Disseminated cryptosporidium infection
HP:0031699.definition: Failure to contain infection by a protozoan of the genus Cryptosporidium, leading to spread to many parts of the body.

HP:0031700.name: Invasive parasitic infection
HP:0031700.definition: A parasitic infection whereby the parasite invades (migrates through) tissues of the infected host.

HP:0031701.name: Anterior chamber inflammatory cells
HP:0031701.definition: The presence of inflammatory cells in the aqueous humor of the anterior chamber of the eye.

HP:0031702.name: Anterior chamber red blood cells
HP:0031702.definition: The presence of erythrocyte in the aqueous humor of the anterior chamber of the eye.

HP:0031703.name: Abnormal ear morphology
HP:0031703.definition: Any structural anomaly of the ear.

HP:0031704.name: Abnormal ear physiology
HP:0031704.definition: Any functional anomaly of the ear.

HP:0031705.name: Compensatory head posture
HP:0031705.definition: A compensatory head posture occurs when the head is deviated out of the normal primary straight head position in order to compensate for an ocular problem.

HP:0031706.name: Compensatory chin depression
HP:0031706.definition: A tendency to hold the chin depressed (lowered) to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0031707.name: Compensatory face turn to the right
HP:0031707.definition: A tendency to turn the face to the right to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0031708.name: Compensatory face turn to the left
HP:0031708.definition: A tendency to turn the face to the left to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0031709.name: Compensatory head tilt to the right shoulder
HP:0031709.definition: A tendency to tilt the head towards the right shoulder to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0031710.name: Compensatory head tilt to the left shoulder
HP:0031710.definition: A tendency to tilt the head towards the left shoulder to compensate for a limitation of eye movement.

HP:0031711.name: Asymmetric abdominal aortic aneurysm
HP:0031711.definition: An abdominal aortic aneurysm that is not symmetric around its axis (not axisymmetric).

HP:0031713.name: Constant exotropia
HP:0031713.definition: A form of divergent strabismus (exotropia) in which the eye turns outward at all distances and at all times.

HP:0031714.name: Distance exotropia
HP:0031714.definition: A type of divergent strabismus (exotropia) in which an eye tends to turn outwards (i.e., the eye squints) mainly when looking at distant objects. The eyes tend to remain straight when they look at near objects. Distance exotropia may be constant or intermittent.

HP:0031715.name: Near exotropia
HP:0031715.definition: An intermittent exotropia where there is binocular single vision on distance fixation and exotropia at near (intermittent or constant).

HP:0031716.name: Cyclic exotropia
HP:0031716.definition: A type of exotropia (divergent strabismus) in which binocular single vision alternates with large angle exotropia in rhythmic cycle.

HP:0031717.name: Alternating exotropia
HP:0031717.definition: A type of exotropia in which either eye may be used for fixation.

HP:0031718.name: Consecutive exotropia
HP:0031718.definition: Exotropia in an individual who has previously had esotropia or esophoria.

HP:0031719.name: True distance exotropia
HP:0031719.definition: Exotropia (intermittent or constant) on distance fixation with binocular single vision on near fixation under all testing conditions. The accommodative convergence/accommodation (AC:A) ratio is within normal limits.

HP:0031720.name: Simulated distance exotropia
HP:0031720.definition: Exotropia (intermittent or constant) worse for distance fixation in which the near angle of deviation increases (or near exophoria becomes exotropia) with: (1) prolonged disruption of fusion and/or (2) elimination of accommodation.

HP:0031721.name: Sensory exotropia
HP:0031721.definition: A type of divergent strabismus (exotropia) that develops in a poorly seeing eye.

HP:0031722.name: Near esotropia
HP:0031722.definition: An intermittent esotropia where there is binocular single vision on distance fixation and esotropia at near even when the accommodation is relieved.

HP:0031723.name: Secondary esotropia
HP:0031723.definition: Convergent squint which follows loss or impairment of vision.

HP:0031724.name: Microtropia
HP:0031724.definition: A small angle heterotropia (usually of 10 diopters or less) in which a form of binocular single vision occurs.

HP:0031725.name: Hypophoria
HP:0031725.definition: A form of latent strabismus (heterophoria) in which, on dissociation, the occluded eye deviates downwards.

HP:0031726.name: Incyclotropia
HP:0031726.definition: A type of cyclotropia (torsion of one or both eye around the visual axis of the eyes) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated inward (medially) to each other.

HP:0031727.name: Excyclotropia
HP:0031727.definition: A type of cyclotropia (torsion of one or both eye around the visual axis of the eyes) in which the upper poles of the globes are rotated outward (laterally) to each other.

HP:0031728.name: Mild hypermetropia
HP:0031728.definition: A form of hypermetropia with not more than +2.00 diopters.

HP:0031729.name: Moderate hypermetropia
HP:0031729.definition: A form of hypermetropia with more than +2.00 diopters but not more than +5.00 diopters.

HP:0031730.name: Axial myopia
HP:0031730.definition: A form of myopia related to an axial length above the norm and too long for the refractive power of the whole optical system of the eye.

HP:0031731.name: Increased tear production
HP:0031731.definition: Increased lacrimation owing to overproduction of tears.

HP:0031732.name: Increased basal tear production
HP:0031732.definition: A form of watery eye associated with overproduction of tears due to an increased parasympathetic drive to the secretory component of the lacrimal system (lacrimal gland); this could be due to pro-secretory drug use (e.g. pilocarpine) or autonomic disturbance.

HP:0031733.name: Reflex tearing
HP:0031733.definition: A form of watery eye associated with overproduction of tears due to reflex tearing in response to a local irritant (e.g. trichiasis or foreign body), chronic ocular surface disease (e.g. blepharitis) or systemic disease (e.g. thyroid eye disease).

HP:0031734.name: Lacrimal pump failure
HP:0031734.definition: A form of watery eye associated with abnormal lid tone and/or lid position. The former is due to lid laxity (common involutional change in the elderly) or a weak orbicularis muscle (e.g. due to VII cranial nerve palsy). The latter is typically associated with ectropion causing punctal eversion.

HP:0031736.name: Involutional entropion
HP:0031736.definition: An abnormal inversion of the eyelid towards the globe resulting from inferior retractor muscle dysfunction with tissue laxity and, possibly, overriding of the preseptal orbicularis muscle over the pretarsal orbicularis muscle.

HP:0031737.name: Cicatricial entropion
HP:0031737.definition: Abnormal inversion (turning inward) of the eyelid towards the globe associated with scarring that vertically shortens the posterior lamella of the eyelid.

HP:0031738.name: Mechanical entropion
HP:0031738.definition: A type of entropion (abnormal inversion of the eyelid towards the globe) that is related to a mass effect of a lesion (e.g., a tumor) that pulls the eyelid margin away from the globe.

HP:0031739.name: Abnormal oblique muscle physiology
HP:0031739.definition: A functional anomaly of the inferior or superior oblique muscle.

HP:0031740.name: Abnormal horizontal rectus muscle physiology
HP:0031740.definition: A functional anomaly of the medial rectus muscle or lateral rectus muscle.

HP:0031741.name: Inferior oblique muscle underaction
HP:0031741.definition: Reduced ocular movement by the inferior oblique muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0031742.name: Inferior rectus muscle underaction
HP:0031742.definition: Reduced movement by the inferior rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0031743.name: Inferior rectus muscle overaction
HP:0031743.definition: Excessive action of the inferior rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.

HP:0031744.name: Superior rectus muscle weakness
HP:0031744.definition: Decreased strength of the superior rectus muscle.

HP:0031745.name: Superior rectus muscle overaction
HP:0031745.definition: Excessive action of the superior rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.

HP:0031746.name: Superior rectus muscle restriction
HP:0031746.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the superior rectus muscle.

HP:0031747.name: Superior rectus muscle underaction
HP:0031747.definition: Reduced movement of the superior rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0031748.name: Abnormal vertical rectus muscle physiology
HP:0031748.definition: A functional anomaly of the superior or inferior rectus muscle.

HP:0031749.name: Abnormal lateral rectus muscle physiology
HP:0031749.definition: A functional anomaly of the lateral rectus muscle.

HP:0031750.name: Lateral rectus muscle weakness
HP:0031750.definition: Decreased strength (ability to move) of the lateral rectus muscle.

HP:0031751.name: Lateral rectus muscle underaction
HP:0031751.definition: Reduced movement of the lateral rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0031752.name: Lateral rectus muscle overaction
HP:0031752.definition: Excessive action of the lateral rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.

HP:0031753.name: Medial rectus muscle weakness
HP:0031753.definition: Decreased strength of the medial rectus muscle.

HP:0031754.name: Medial rectus muscle overaction
HP:0031754.definition: Excessive action of the medial rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.

HP:0031755.name: Abnormal rectus muscle physiology
HP:0031755.definition: A functional anomaly of a vertical or horizontal rectus muscle.

HP:0031756.name: Medial rectus muscle underaction
HP:0031756.definition: Reduced movement of the medial rectus muscle which improves on testing ductions, typically associated with neurogenic palsy.

HP:0031757.name: Medial rectus muscle restriction
HP:0031757.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the medial rectus muscle.

HP:0031758.name: Lateral rectus muscle restriction
HP:0031758.definition: Mechanical limitation of the range of movement of the lateral rectus muscle.

HP:0031759.name: Basic constant esotropia
HP:0031759.definition: A form of convergent strabismus (esotropia) in which the deviation is present under all conditions (ie at all distances and at all times).

HP:0031760.name: Non-accomodative esotropia
HP:0031760.definition: A form of esotropia in which the angle of deviation is not affected by accommodative effort.

HP:0031761.name: Infantile constant esotropia
HP:0031761.definition: Constant esotropia occurring before 6 months of age. It is typically associated with a large angle of deviation, alternating fixation (therefore low risk of amblyopia) and poor potential for binocular single vision. Other features that might be present in individuals with infantile (constant) esotropia include latent nystagmus or manifest latent nystagmus, dissociated vertical divergence, cyclotropia, abnormal head posture, limited abduction.

HP:0031762.name: Distance esotropia
HP:0031762.definition: An intermittent esotropia where binocular single vision is present on near fixation and an esotropia on distance fixation. Often associated with myopia and aging.

HP:0031763.name: Cyclic esotropia
HP:0031763.definition: Convergent strabismus in which normal binocular single vision is alternating with large angle esotropia in rhythmic cycle.

HP:0031764.name: Fully accomodative esotropia
HP:0031764.definition: Esotropia in which normal binocular single vision is present for all distances when the hypermetropic refractive error is corrected. Esotropia is present for near and distance on accommodation without correction.

HP:0031765.name: Partially accomodative esotropia
HP:0031765.definition: A form of constant esotropia in which the angle of deviation is partially affected by accommodative effort. Typically there is esotropia at near and distance with hypermetropic correction and the angle of deviation increases without glasses.

HP:0031766.name: Convergence excess esotropia
HP:0031766.definition: An intermittent esotropia with binocular single vision present at distance fixation but esotropia on accommodation for near fixation. Usually associated with hypermetropia but patients can be emmetropic and rarely myopic. Associated with a high accommodative convergence/accommodation (AC/A) ratio.

HP:0031767.name: Consecutive esotropia
HP:0031767.definition: Esotropia in a patient who has previously had exotropia or exophoria; may be constant or intermittent and usually follows surgical overcorrection.

HP:0031768.name: Parafoveal fixation
HP:0031768.definition: Fixation of an object in the area adjacent to the fovea.

HP:6000686.name: Mucus in stool
HP:6000686.definition: Abnormally increased amount of mucus in the feces. Mucus is a slippery aqueous secretion produced by mucous membranes including those of the intestines.

HP:6000687.name: Elevated circulating CCL3 concentration
HP:6000687.definition: The concentration of C-C Motif Ligand 3 (CCL3) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000688.name: Elevated circulating CCL4 concentration
HP:6000688.definition: The concentration of C-C Motif Ligand 4 (CCL4) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000689.name: Elevated CSF 14-3-3 protein concentration
HP:6000689.definition: The concentration of 14-3-3 protein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000690.name: Elevated CSF dihydrobiopterin concentration
HP:6000690.definition: Concentration of dihydrobiopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000691.name: Left atrial fibrosis
HP:6000691.definition: Atrial fibrosis is an hallmark of atrial structural remodelling, characterized by the aberrant activation, proliferation and differentiation of fibroblasts, and subsequent excessive synthesis and irregular deposition of extracellular matrix proteins.

HP:6000692.name: Abnormal circulating atrial natriuretic peptide pro-hormone concentration
HP:6000692.definition: The concentration in the blood circulation of atrial natriuretic peptide pro-hormone or one of its processed fragments is outside of the range of normal.

HP:6000693.name: Reduced circulating NT-proANP concentration
HP:6000693.definition: The concentration of NT-proANP in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000694.name: Elevated circulating 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid concentration
HP:6000694.definition: The concentration of delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000695.name: Reduced tissue delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000695.definition: Concentration or activity of delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase (P5CDH; EC 1.5.1.12) below the lower limit of normal. P5CDH can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. P5CDH is a mitochondrial matrix NAD(+)-dependent dehydrogenase which catalyzes the second step of the proline degradation pathway, converting pyrroline-5-carboxylate to glutamate.

HP:6000696.name: Elevated circulating N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid concentration
HP:6000696.definition: The concentration of N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000697.name: Low tissue ferrochelatase activity
HP:6000697.definition: Concentration or activity of Ferrochelatase (FECH; EC 4.99.1.1) below the lower limit of normal. FECH enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. FECH is the terminal enzyme of the heme biosynthetic pathway, and catalyzes the insertion of iron into protoporphyrin to form heme.

HP:6000698.name: Elevated circulating heptacarboxylporphyrin concentration
HP:6000698.definition: The concentration of heptacarboxylporphyrin in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000699.name: Aggravated by menstruation
HP:6000699.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is more severe during mensutruation.

HP:6000700.name: Reduced breast milk zinc concentration
HP:6000700.definition: The concentration of zinc in breast milk is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000701.name: Elevated urinary bile acid level
HP:6000701.definition: The amount of bile acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000702.name: Elevated urinary glyoxylic acid level
HP:6000702.definition: The amount of glyoxylic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. The conjugate base of glyoxylic acid is known as glyoxylate.

HP:6000703.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid concentration
HP:6000703.definition: The concentration of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000704.name: Elevated circulating CXCL9 concentration
HP:6000704.definition: The concentration of chemokine (C-X-C motif) ligand 9 in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000705.name: Thickened fibular cortex
HP:6000705.definition: Abnormal increase in the thickness (distance between the inner and outer boundaries) of the outer layer (cortex) of the fibula.

HP:6000706.name: New medication added in recent weeks
HP:6000706.definition: Medical history of starting a new medication recently.

HP:6000708.name: Femoral osteosclerosis
HP:6000708.definition: An abnormal increase of bone mineral density of the femur. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:6000709.name: Absent Bell phenomenon
HP:6000709.definition: The Bell phenomenon is the reflex upward movement of the front of the eyeball when the eyelids close (or blink). It protects the eye by helping to keep the cornea moist. This term refers to a lack of this phenomenon, which can be observed with certain conditions such as congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles.

HP:6000710.name: Dalen Fuchs nodules
HP:6000710.definition: Nodules (yellow-white subretinal pigment epithelium lesions) that form between Bruch's membrane and the retinal pigment epithelium.

HP:6000711.name: Triggering by ocular trauma
HP:6000711.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by trauma to the eye.

HP:6000712.name: Gelatinous drop-like dystrophic cornea
HP:6000712.definition: Deposition of amyloid material in the subepithelial space of the cornea.

HP:6000713.name: Hepatic reticuloendothelial system cell iron deposition
HP:6000713.definition: Abnormal accumulation of iron in reticuloendothelial cells of the liver. This feature can be appreciated on liver biopsy by Perls iron stain for granular iron deposition, based on agreement that only discernible hemosiderin granules represent significant iron deposition.

HP:6000714.name: Reduced epidermal kindlin-1 expression
HP:6000714.definition: Lower than normal amount of kindlin-1 in the epidermis.

HP:6000715.name: Central giant cell lesion of the jaw
HP:6000715.definition: A benign proliferative and asymptomatic intraosseous lesion of the jaw formed by fibrous tissue that contains multiple focus of hemorrhage and an aggregation of multinucleated giant cells.

HP:6000716.name: Terminal hepatic lobular vascular occlusion
HP:6000716.definition: A type of Hepatic venous outflow obstruction characterized by fibrous concentric narrowing of zone 3 terminal hepatic venules, centrilobular hepatocyte necrosis, and sinusoidal congestion, accomapnied by necrosis of pericentral hepatocytes, and narrowing and eventual fibrosis of central veins.

HP:6000717.name: Axonal spheroids
HP:6000717.definition: During neurodegeneration, bubble-like swellings form along the length of the axon, a primary and early effect of dynamic axonal deformation. These varicosities, spheroids, or swellings have been described as beads on a string and branches bearing fruit, and they frequently appear on degenerating axons.

HP:6000718.name: Decreased liver bile salt export pump expression
HP:6000718.definition: Amount of bile salt export pump (BSEP, coded by the ABCB11 gene) in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000719.name: Reduced tissue type II iodothyronine deiodinase activity
HP:6000719.definition: Concentration or activity of type II iodothyronine deiodinase below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in tissues such as cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000720.name: Reduced tissue fatty aldehyde dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000720.definition: Activity of fatty aldehyde dehydrogenase (EC 1.2.1.3) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts and leukocytes.

HP:6000721.name: Decreased circulating pancreatic isoamylase activity
HP:6000721.definition: The activity of alpha-Amylase (1,4-alpha-D-glucan-4-glucanohydrolase E. C. 3.2.1.1, pancreatic isoamylase) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000722.name: Reduced tissue guanidinoacetate methyltransferase activity
HP:6000722.definition: Activity of the mitochondrial enzyme guanidinoacetate methyltransferase in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts.

HP:6000723.name: Reduced erythrocyte galactokinase activity
HP:6000723.definition: Activity or concentration of in the level of galactokinase (EC 2.7.1.6) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000724.name: Auspitz sign
HP:6000724.definition: The appearance of small bleeding points after successive layers of scale have been removed from the surface of psoriatic papules or plaques.

HP:6000725.name: Salty tasting skin
HP:6000725.definition: Skin tastes marked salty without an obvious explanation such as heat or exercise. This finding can be observed in infants with cystic fibrosis.

HP:6000726.name: Scalp nodule
HP:6000726.definition: A small firm lump located in the skin of the scalp that is greater than one cm in diameter.

HP:6000727.name: History of undercooked pork ingestion
HP:6000727.definition: A history of ingestion of undercooked pork. This is particularly relevant in areas with a high prevalence of cysticercosis.

HP:6000728.name: History of recent rodent exposure
HP:6000728.definition: A history of exposed to rodents (mice, rats, prarie dogs) within several weeks of the current presenting complaint.

HP:6000729.name: Positive CSF fungus test
HP:6000729.definition: Any kind of test for a fungal infectious agent in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) positive.

HP:6000730.name: Positive CSF human T-lymphotropic virus type I antibody positivity
HP:6000730.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of human T-lymphotropic virus type I.

HP:6000731.name: Positive chlamydia trachomatis urine nucleic acid test
HP:6000731.definition: Detection of Chlamydia trachomatis nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000732.name: Anti-streptococcus deoxyribonuclease-B antibody positivity
HP:6000732.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against streptococcal deoxyribonuclease-B (ADN-B). Almost all group A streptococci have this antigen and a strong elevation of the antibody is observed in patients with acute rheumatic fever, acute glomerulonephritis and other streptococcal infections.

HP:6000733.name: Positive streptococcus A rapid antigen detection test
HP:6000733.definition: Positive detection of a group A streptococcal antigen in a test perforned on a throat swab.

HP:6000734.name: Positive synovial mycobacterial culture
HP:6000734.definition: Growth of a mycobacteria in a culture derived from synovial fluid.

HP:6000735.name: Positive mycobacterial synovial nucleic acid test
HP:6000735.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of mycobacteria in the synovial fluid by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000736.name: Positive bloodstream babesia nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:6000736.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of genus Babesia (parasite) in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000737.name: Positive bloodstream influenza nucleic test
HP:6000737.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of an influenza virus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000738.name: Positive bloodstream parainfluenza virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000738.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of parainfluenza virus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000739.name: Positive bloodstream adenovirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000739.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of an adenovirus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000740.name: Anti-Francisella tularensis antibody positivity
HP:6000740.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Francisella tularensis.

HP:6000741.name: Positive bloodstream MERS coronavirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000741.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000742.name: Positive nasopharyngeal corynebacterium diphtheriae nucleic acid test
HP:6000742.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Corynebacterium diphtheriae in nasopharyngeal secretions by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000743.name: Pediculosis capitis
HP:6000743.definition: Visualization of at least one louse on visual inspection of the head hair. Use of a bright light, magnifying lens, or fine-toothed comb (lice comb) can aid in diagnosis.

HP:6000744.name: Premature glabellar skin wrinkling
HP:6000744.definition: The presence in the skin of the glabellar region of an increased degree of wrinkling (irregular folds and indentations) of the skin as compared with age-related norms.

HP:6000745.name: Flexural reticulate hyperpigmentation
HP:6000745.definition: Hyperpigmented macules with a reticulate (net-like) pattern involving the neck, axillae, groins, and other flexures like the inframammary folds in females. Histopathology shows orthokeratosis or hyperkeratosis, thinning of the suprapapillary epithelium, elongation of the rete ridges, hyperpigmentation of the basal layer, and follicular cysts. A perivascular lymphohistiocytic infiltrate can be observed in the papillary dermis.

HP:6000746.name: Elevated fractional excretion of urate
HP:6000746.definition: Abnormally increased proportion of filtered urate that is excreted in the urine as calculated using the concentrations of urate and creatinine in both blood and urine. Clinically this manifests as uric acid wasting.

HP:6000747.name: Abnormal urinary creatine level
HP:6000747.definition: The amount of creatine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.

HP:6000748.name: Decreased urinary creatine level
HP:6000748.definition: The amount of creatine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000749.name: Elevated circulating type I procollagen aminoterminal propeptide concentration
HP:6000749.definition: The concentration of type I procollagen aminoterminal propeptide in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. The aminoterminal propeptide of type I procollagen (PINP) in serum is a sensitive indicator of the synthesis of type I collagen.

HP:6000750.name: Decreased tissue S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase activity
HP:6000750.definition: Concentration or activity of S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase (EC 3.3.1.1) below the lower limit of normal. FECH enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including erythrocytes and liver.

HP:6000751.name: Decreased urinary dopamine level
HP:6000751.definition: The concentration of dopamine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000752.name: Elevated erythrocyte AICA-ribotide concentration
HP:6000752.definition: Concentration of 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxamide (AICA-riboside) in red blood cells is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000753.name: Elevated circulating monomethyl sterol concentration
HP:6000753.definition: Concentration of monomethylsterols (such as 4alpha-monomethylsterol) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000754.name: Elevated circulating dimethyl sterol concentration
HP:6000754.definition: The concentration of dimethylsterols in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000755.name: Elevated circulating C-terminal fibroblast growth factor 23 concentration
HP:6000755.definition: The concentration of the C-terminal portion of fibroblast growth factor 23 in the blood circulation is outside of the limits of normal.

HP:6000756.name: Elevated urinary 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid level
HP:6000756.definition: The amount of 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5-HIAA) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000757.name: Elevated circulating thiosulfate concentration
HP:6000757.definition: The concentration of thiosulfate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000758.name: Elevated circulating interleukin 1 receptor antagonist concentration
HP:6000758.definition: The concentration of interleukin 1 receptor antagonist (IL-1RA) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000759.name: Positive CSF West Nile virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000759.definition: Detection of West Nile virus nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000760.name: Positive CSF herpes simplex virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000760.definition: Detection of herpes simplex virus (HSV) nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000761.name: Positive CSF cryptococcal antigen test
HP:6000761.definition: A test result demonstrating the presence of a cryptococal antigen in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000762.name: Positive rubella CSF culture
HP:6000762.definition: Growth of rubella virus in a culture derived from cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000763.name: Positive CSF treponema pallidum nucleic acid test
HP:6000763.definition: Detection of Treponema pallidum (syphillis) nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000764.name: Decreased CSF tetrahydrobiopterin level
HP:6000764.definition: Concentration of tetrahydrobiopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000765.name: Decreased CSF N-acetyl-aspartyl-glutamate concentration
HP:6000765.definition: The concentration of N-acetyl-aspartyl-glutamate (NAAG) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000766.name: Positive CSF Tropheryma whipplei bacteria microscopy
HP:6000766.definition: Demonstration of Tropheryma whipplei bacteria in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) my microscopic analysis.

HP:6000767.name: CSF treponemal antibody positivity
HP:6000767.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of treponema pallidum (syphilis).

HP:6000768.name: Echophenomenon
HP:6000768.definition: A stimulus triggered repetition of an action (echopraxia) or sound (echolalia) performed without the explicit awareness of an individual.

HP:6000769.name: Paracentral hyper-autofluorecence
HP:6000769.definition: Increased autofluorescence in areas adjacent to the central macula (but not including the very center).

HP:6000770.name: Fixed fetal extremities
HP:6000770.definition: A condition in which the limbs of a fetus are immobile or held in a rigid position. The limbs are consistently immobile and rigid. Fixed extremities can be observed during prenatal imaging (e.g., ultrasound).

HP:6000771.name: Abnormal peripapillary microvascular network
HP:6000771.definition: The density of the deep peripapillary microvascular network (i.e., the number of blood vessels) is below the lower limit of normal. This finding is observable by optical coherence tomography angiography.

HP:6000772.name: Auriculitis
HP:6000772.definition: Inflammation of the skin and soft tissues of the outer ear.

HP:6000773.name: Recent history of moisture in external ear canal
HP:6000773.definition: A recent history of being exposed to moisture in the external ear canal.

HP:6000774.name: History of recent trauma to external ear canal
HP:6000774.definition: Medical history of trauma to the external ear canal, including cotton-swab use, in recent weeks.

HP:6000775.name: Elevated urinary 4-tyramine level
HP:6000775.definition: The amount of 4-tyramine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000776.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxykynurenine concentration
HP:6000776.definition: The concentration of 3-hydroxykynurenine in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000778.name: Cone-shaped distal tibial epiphysis
HP:6000778.definition: The distal epiphysis (rounded portion of bone at the far end of the tibia distal to the growth plate) has an abnormal cone-shaped appearance, that is, the epiphysis has a globular form at the bottom, tapering to a point at the top.

HP:6000779.name: Osteoporotic femoral neck
HP:6000779.definition: Low bone mass localized in the neck of the femur. Osteoporosis is defined based on a T-score of -2.5 or lower (bone mineral density of 2.5 or more standard deviations below that of a normal young adult).

HP:6000781.name: Reduced tissue phosphomannomutase activity
HP:6000781.definition: Activity of the enzyme phosphomannomutase (EC 5.4.2.8) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes, fibroblasts, and liver.

HP:6000782.name: Reduced tissue phosphomannose isomerase activity
HP:6000782.definition: Activity of the mitochondrial enzyme phosphomannose isomerase (PMI; EC 5.3.1.8) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes, fibroblasts, and liver.

HP:6000783.name: Reduced tissue palmitoyl-protein thioesterase activity
HP:6000783.definition: Activity of the enzyme palmitoyl-protein thioesterase (PPT; EC 3.1.2.22) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts and leukocytes.

HP:6000784.name: Maternal household cat exposure
HP:6000784.definition: The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of regular exposure to one or more cats, e.g., in the household.

HP:6000785.name: Protein craving
HP:6000785.definition: Unusually strong preference for protein-rich foods.

HP:6000786.name: Absent superficial temporal artery pulse
HP:6000786.definition: The pulsation of the superficial temporal artery cannot be detected on physical examination.

HP:6000787.name: Basilar artery fenestration
HP:6000787.definition: A fenestration affecting the basilar artery. Basilar fenestration typically occurs at the lower end of the basilar artery just as the vertebral arteries join Fenestrations of intracranial arteries are segmental duplications of the lumen into two distinct endothelium-lined channels, which may or may not share their adventitial layer. They can range from a small focus of divided tissue to long-segment duplication. Fenestrations are the result of partial failure of fusion of paired primitive embryologic vessels or incomplete obliteration of different anastomosis in a primitive vascular network. The association of fenestrations with aneurysms has been suggested in many small case series, though the exact relationship is not well defined.

HP:6000788.name: Displacement of the extensor tendon in metacarpophalangeal joint
HP:6000788.definition: Dislocation of the extensor tendons from their central position on the metacarpal heads can be traumatic, congenital, spontaneous, or degenerative.

HP:6000789.name: Heloma
HP:6000789.definition: A corn, also known as a clavus, heloma, or focal intractable plantar hyperkeratosis, is a type of callosity. Corns are uncomfortable, thickened skin lesions that result from repeated mechanical trauma due to friction or pressure forces.

HP:6000790.name: Exacerbated by pronation
HP:6000790.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is aggravated by (or made more painful by) pronation. Pronation of the hand involves the rotation of the forearm and wrist so that the palm of the hand faces downwards or towards the back (posteriorly).

HP:6000791.name: Distortion of the anterior part of the interhemispheric fissure
HP:6000791.definition: Change in the normal shape (displacement, asymmetry) of the anterior part of the interhemispheric fissure. This finding can be identified prenatally by sonography or magnetic resonance imaging.

HP:6000792.name: Positive lacrimal tract actinomyces culture
HP:6000792.definition: Growth of Actinomyces israelii (anaerobic filamentous gram positive) culture of lacrimal discharge or concretions.

HP:6000793.name: Eschar
HP:6000793.definition: A type of wound characterized by dry, black, hard necrotic tissue.

HP:6000794.name: History of wearing tightly fitted clothing
HP:6000794.definition: History of wearing tight clothing such as compression shorts, sports bras, bike shorts, wet suits, spandex, veils, and tight hats.

HP:6000795.name: Anti-folate receptor antibody positivity
HP:6000795.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the folate receptor in the blood circulation.

HP:6000796.name: Positive bloodstream VDRL test
HP:6000796.definition: An abnormal (positive) result of the Venereal Disease Research Laboratory (VDRL) test performed in peripheral blood, suggesting past or present syphilis.

HP:6000797.name: Positive bloodstream rapid plasma reagin test
HP:6000797.definition: Positive result of the the rapid plasma reagin test (RPR test. This is a rapid diagnostic test that looks for non-specific antibodies in the blood of the patient that may indicate an infection by syphilis or related non-venereal treponematoses.

HP:6000798.name: Positive bloodstream HIV p24 antigen test
HP:6000798.definition: Demonstration of the p24 antigen of human immunodeficiency virus in the bloodstream.

HP:6000799.name: Positive Quantiferon tuberculosis test
HP:6000799.definition: A positive Quantiferon test result indicating Mycobacterium tuberculosis. The Quantiferon assay is designed to stimulate IFN-gamma release from CD4+ T cells in a single tuberculosis antigen tube using long peptides from three M. tuberculosis antigens.

HP:6000800.name: Tzanck smear with multinucleated giant cells
HP:6000800.definition: Tzanck smear demonstrates multinucleated giant cells, a sign that is suggestive for herpetic infections. Such smears are taken from skin lesions and display multinucleated cells with ground glass nuclei, nuclear moulding, and margination of nuclear chromatin typical of herpes simplex and varicella infection.

HP:6000801.name: Positive Mazzotti test
HP:6000801.definition: Locally applied 1.6 percent diethylcarbamazine citrate in Nivea lotion can be used as a diagnostic test for onchocerciasis. Papular reactions are considered as positive test results.

HP:6000802.name: Positive bloodstream Tropheryma whippelii nucleic acid test
HP:6000802.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Tropheryma whippelii in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000803.name: Elevated urinary 2,8-dihydroxyadenine level
HP:6000803.definition: The amount of 2,8-dihydroxyadenine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000804.name: Elevated urine fructose level
HP:6000804.definition: Amount of fructose in the urine above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000805.name: Elevated urinary uroporphyrin level
HP:6000805.definition: The amount of uroporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000806.name: Elevated urinary phosphohydroxylysine level
HP:6000806.definition: The amount of phosphohydroxylysine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000807.name: Cervical C6/C7 vertebrae fusion
HP:6000807.definition: Fusion of cervical vertebrae at C6 and C7, caused by a failure in the normal segmentation or division of the cervical vertebrae during the early weeks of fetal development, leading to a short neck with a low hairline at the back of the head, and restricted mobility of the upper spine.

HP:6000808.name: Periumbilical depression
HP:6000808.definition: The tissue that immediately surrounds the umbilicus is located below the normal plane of the abdomen.

HP:6000809.name: Thickened tibial cortex
HP:6000809.definition: Abnormally increased thicknes of the cortical layer of the tibia.

HP:6000810.name: Thickened femoral cortex
HP:6000810.definition: Abnormally increased thicknes of the cortical layer of the femur.

HP:6000811.name: Thickened cortex of the radius
HP:6000811.definition: Abnormally increased thickness of the cortical layer of the radius.

HP:6000812.name: Thickened cortex of the ulna
HP:6000812.definition: Abnormally increased thickness of the cortical layer of the ulna.

HP:6000813.name: Elevated circulating aspartate aminotransferase to alanine aminotransferase ratio
HP:6000813.definition: Aspartate aminotransferase to alanine aminotransferase ratio increased greater than 1.5.

HP:6000814.name: Temporomandibular joint dislocation
HP:6000814.definition: The lower jawbone (mandible) pulls away from the temporomandibular joints (TMJ). It is characterized by pain, clicking and functional restriction.

HP:6000815.name: Amyloid goiter
HP:6000815.definition: Amyloidosis is defined as the accumulation of amorphous, proteinaceous material in different parts of the body. Amyloid can be deposited in the thyroid gland in such quantities to cause a clinically apparent enlargement of the gland known as Amyloid goiter.

HP:6000817.name: Melorheostosis
HP:6000817.definition: Regions of sclerosing hyperostosis in the cortex of long bones, which might have a radiologic appearance of dripping candle wax.

HP:6000818.name: Transverse terminal limb defect
HP:6000818.definition: A congenital anomaly that appears as an amputation at different levels of the extremity. The limb is missing the terminal (distal) segment(s), with preservation of all the segment(s) proximal to the missing segment.

HP:6000819.name: Elevated circulating beta-glucuronidase activity
HP:6000819.definition: The activity of beta-glucuronidase (EC 3.2.1.31) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000820.name: Elevated osmolality gap
HP:6000820.definition: Plasma osmolality is determined mainly by Sodium, its counter ions, and uncharged species such as Glucose and Urea. Knowledge of the plasma concentration of these species allows calculation of the plasma osmolality quite accurately. If the difference between the measured osmolality (MO) and calculated osmolality (CO) is known as the osmolar gap (OG) is large (greater than 15) osmolar gap can help identify the presence in plasma of substances such as ethanol, methanol, isopropanol, ethylene glycol, propylene glycol..

HP:6000821.name: Elevated circulating bile alcohol concentration
HP:6000821.definition: The concentration of bile alcohols in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000822.name: Elevated CSF tetrahydrobiopterin level
HP:6000822.definition: Concentration of tetrahydrobiopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000823.name: Elevated CSF 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid concentration
HP:6000823.definition: The concentration of 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000824.name: Cerebrospinal fluid eosinophilia
HP:6000824.definition: Presence of at least 10% eosinophils in the total cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leukocyte count.

HP:6000825.name: Reduced C27 3beta-HSD activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000825.definition: Concentration or activity of 3beta-hydroxy-delta5-C27-steroid oxidoreductase (C27 3beta-HSD) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.

HP:6000826.name: Reduced procollagen-lysine,2-oxoglutarate 5-dioxygenase 1 activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000826.definition: Concentration or activity of procollagen-lysine,2-oxoglutarate 5-dioxygenase 1 (PLOD1; also known as Lysyl hydroxylase; EC 1.14.11.4) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. PLOD1 catalyzes the formation of hydroxylysine in collagens and other proteins with collagen-like amino acid sequences, by the hydroxylation of lysine residues in X-lys-gly sequences.

HP:6000827.name: Diminished tissue fumarylacetoacetate hydrolase activity
