HP:6000827.definition: Concentration or activity of fumarylacetoacetate hydrolase (FAH; EC 3.7.1.2) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000828.name: Reduced tissue peptidase D activity
HP:6000828.definition: Concentration or activity of Peptidase D (EC 3.4.13.9; also known as prolidase, imidodipeptidase, proline dipeptidase, and aminoacyl-L-proline hydrolase) below the lower limit of normal. The activity of this enzyme can be measured in erythrocytes, leukocytes, or fibroblasts.

HP:6000829.name: Reduced tissue glycine cleavage enzyme activity
HP:6000829.definition: Concentration or activity of the glycine cleavage enzyme below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000830.name: Diminished alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000830.definition: Concentration or activity of the alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase complex as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. This enzyme is a multienzyme complex consisting of 3 protein subunits, oxoglutarate dehydrogenase, also known as alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase or E1k (EC 1.2.4.2.), dihydrolipoyl succinyltransferase (DLST, or E2k; 126063), and dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase (DLD, or E3; 238331). The complex catalyzes a key reaction in the Krebs tricarboxylic acid cycle.

HP:6000831.name: Increased circulating dihydroxycholestanoic acid concentration
HP:6000831.definition: The concentration of dihydroxycholestanoic acid (DHCA) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000832.name: Reduced tissue phosphorylase kinase activity
HP:6000832.definition: Concentration or activity of phosphorylase kinase below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000833.name: Hyperkalemia while symptomatic
HP:6000833.definition: Increased concentration of potassium in the blood circulation specifically measured during a disease flareup, attack, or exacerbation.

HP:6000834.name: Elevated urinary gamma-glutamylcysteine level
HP:6000834.definition: The amount of gamma-glutamylcysteine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000835.name: Positive CSF mycobacterial culture
HP:6000835.definition: Growth of mycobacteria in a culture derived from cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000836.name: Positive respiratory tract nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:6000836.definition: Positive (abnormal) result of a sputum or pharyngeal sample test such as polymerase chain reaction that is targeted against a nucleic acid sequence specific for a pathogen.

HP:6000837.name: Positive respiratory tract SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000837.definition: Detection of SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus nucleic acid in the sputum or pharyngeal sample by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000838.name: Positive fecal cryptosporidium antigen test
HP:6000838.definition: Cryptosporidium antigen present in stool. Tests include direct fluorescent-antibody (DFA), which detects intact organisms, and enzyme immunoassays (EIAs), which detect soluble stool antigens.

HP:6000839.name: Horizontal position of testicle
HP:6000839.definition: The Bell Clapper deformity is one of the causes for the testicular torsion. In this condition, testis lacks a normal attachment to tunica vaginalis and hangs freely, causing it to sit horizontally rather than vertically in the scrotum.

HP:6000840.name: Localized soft-tissue swelling on extremity
HP:6000840.definition: Abnormal enlargement (swelling) that is restricted to a specific part of a limb.

HP:6000841.name: Abnormal scleral thickness
HP:6000841.definition: Any deviation from the normal height of the sclera, the white part of the eye that forms the tough, fibrous outer layer of the exterior of the eyeball.

HP:6000842.name: Multiple eyelid beaded papules
HP:6000842.definition: Multiple beaded papules along the eyelid margins and inner canthus.

HP:6000843.name: Nonexudative conjunctivitis
HP:6000843.definition: A type of conjunctivitis that is not characterized by appreciable exudate, i.e., fluid, cells, or other substances that have escaped from blood vessels and have been deposited around the eyelids.

HP:6000844.name: Nematode in retina
HP:6000844.definition: Demonstration of a nematode (roundworm) in the retina, generally by an imaging procedure such as fundoscopy.

HP:6000845.name: Vascular compression of the eighth cranial nerve
HP:6000845.definition: A condition in which blood vessels adjacent to the eighth cranial nerve (vestibulocochlear nerve) such as the anterior inferior cerebellar artery abnormally contact or compress the vestibulocochlear nerve as it exits the brainstem or travels within the cerebellopontine angle.

HP:6000846.name: Beaded bile ducts
HP:6000846.definition: Multifocal intra- and extra-hepatic bile duct strictures alternating with normal caliber or slightly dilated segments, resembling beads on a string.

HP:6000847.name: Cardiac mass
HP:6000847.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized in the heart. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000848.name: Superior olive hypertrophy
HP:6000848.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the superior olive, also known as the superior olivary complex. The superior olive is a collection of brainstem nuclei that is located in pons, functions in multiple aspects of hearing and is an important component of the ascending and descending auditory pathways of the auditory system.

HP:6000849.name: Spinal extradural arachnoid cyst
HP:6000849.definition: Spinal extradural arachnoid cyst is a cyst in the spinal canal that protrudes into the epidural space from a defect in the dura mater.

HP:6000850.name: Temporal cortex localization
HP:6000850.definition: Localization to or predominance in the temporal cortex of the brain.

HP:6000851.name: Basilar meningeal enhancement
HP:6000851.definition: Abnormal enhancement of CT or MIR contrast medium in the basilar meninges, that is, those located in the basal cisterns or spaces at the base of the brain, due to increased permeability of blood vessels in these areas.

HP:6000852.name: Megacolon
HP:6000852.definition: Persistent and substantial increase in diameter diameter and length of the colon.

HP:6000853.name: Thyroid cyst
HP:6000853.definition: A fluid-filled sac or cavity that develops due to fluid accumulation within the thyroid tissue.

HP:6000854.name: Decreased circulating sulfate concentration
HP:6000854.definition: The concentration of sulfate in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000855.name: Cold intolerance
HP:6000855.definition: The inability to maintain a comfortable body temperature in a cold environment or cold temperatures.

HP:6000856.name: Head and neck distribution
HP:6000856.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the head and neck region.

HP:6000857.name: Symmetric distribution
HP:6000857.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is highly similar on the left and right sides of the body.

HP:6000858.name: Muscle extensor surface location
HP:6000858.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in extensor surface of an extremity.

HP:6000859.name: Dermal foam cells
HP:6000859.definition: Presence of lipid-laden macrophages (foam cells) in the inner layer of the skin (dermis).

HP:6000860.name: Diminished tissue very long-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000860.definition: Diminished activity of Very long-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (VLCAD), an enzyme that catalyzes the initial step of mitochondrial beta-oxidation of long-chain fatty acids with a chain length of 14 to 20 carbons. VLCAD activity can be measured with biochemical testing using cultured fibroblasts or lymphocytes.

HP:6000861.name: Diminished tissue glycogen branching enzyme activity
HP:6000861.definition: Activity of glycogen branching enzyme in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts.

HP:6000862.name: Parotid adenoma
HP:6000862.definition: A benign tumor of the parotid salivary gland.

HP:6000863.name: Elevated serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG)
HP:6000863.definition: An elevation of the serum ascites albumin gradient (SAAG), which is based on the difference between the albumin level of serum and of ascitic fluid, may be used to assess the extent of ascites. The SAAG is thought to reflect the colloid osmotic pressure gradient and the degree of portal hypertension. It has been shown that SAAG is a better discriminator of portal hypertension than ascites. A SAAG of 1.1 gm/dL or higher is considered as high, indicating the presence of portal hypertension, while SAAG less than 1.1 gm/dL is low, indicating the absence of portal hypertension.

HP:6000864.name: Transverse smile
HP:6000864.definition: Inability to raise the corners of the mouth during the act of smiling due to facial muscle weakness. The act of smiling is accompanied by a horizontal movement of the mouth.

HP:6000865.name: Hyperphalangy of the 4th finger
HP:6000865.definition: An accessory phalanx of the fourth (ring) finger that is arranged linearly with the other phalanges. Hyperphalangy results from an accessory ossification center at the metacarpophalangeal joint.

HP:6000866.name: Delayed distal femoral epiphyseal ossification
HP:6000866.definition: Developmental delay of ossification of the distal epiphysis of the femur.

HP:6000867.name: Delayed tibial epiphyseal ossification
HP:6000867.definition: Developmental delay of ossification of an epiphysis of the tibia.

HP:6000868.name: Toe hyperphalangy
HP:6000868.definition: Hyperphalangy is a digit morphology in which increased numbers of phalanges are arranged linearly within a toe. That is, there is an accessory phalanx that is arranged linearly with the other phalanges.

HP:6000869.name: Sclerotic ilium
HP:6000869.definition: An elevation in bone density in the ilium. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

HP:6000870.name: Metaphyseal chevron deformity
HP:6000870.definition: The chevron sign refers to an inverted V-shape metaphyses. It is most commonly seen in the distal femur and tends to disappear with age.

HP:6000871.name: Popcorn calcification
HP:6000871.definition: Popcorn calcifications are areas of amorphous calcifications often with rings and arcs that resemble popped corn kernels in the metaphysis and epiphysis around the growth plate.

HP:6000872.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the calvaria
HP:6000872.definition: A developmental defect characterized by absence or underdevelopment of the calvaria.

HP:6000873.name: Bowdler spurs
HP:6000873.definition: Transverse long bone midshaft spurs or osteochondral projections typically occuring in the fibulae and less commonly in the forearms.

HP:6000874.name: Delayed ossification of the clavicle
HP:6000874.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of the clavicle.

HP:6000875.name: Wide sacroiliac joint
HP:6000875.definition: Distance between the sacrum and the ilium bones of the pelvis at the sacroiliac joint is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000876.name: Anti-Glutamate Receptor delta2 antibody positivity
HP:6000876.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against glutamate receptor delta2.

HP:6000877.name: Anti-dachshund family transcription factor 1 antibody positivity
HP:6000877.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against dachshund-homolog 1 (DACH1) autoantigen.

HP:6000878.name: Anti-potassium channel tetramerization domain containing 16 antibody positivity
HP:6000878.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against potassium channel tetramerization domain containing 16 (KCTD16).

HP:6000879.name: Anti-regulator of G protein signaling 8 antibody positivity
HP:6000879.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against regulator of G-protein signaling 8 (RGS8).

HP:6000880.name: Anti-neurochondrin antibody positivity
HP:6000880.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against neurochondrin .

HP:6000881.name: Anti-DCC netrin 1 receptor antibody positivity
HP:6000881.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against Netrin-1 receptors DCC (deleted in colorectal carcinoma).

HP:6000882.name: Anti-recoverin antibody positivity
HP:6000882.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against recoverin. Recoverins are calcium-binding proteins primarily expressed in retinal rod photoreceptors and primarily involved in phototransduction.

HP:6000883.name: Recent history of sedation by propofol infusion
HP:6000883.definition: A history of exposure to anesthesia by propofanol infusion recently before the presenting complaint.

HP:6000884.name: Enlarged humeral head
HP:6000884.definition: Size (volume) of the head of the humerus above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000885.name: Enlarged radial head
HP:6000885.definition: Size (volume) of the head of the radius above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000886.name: Enlarged distal tibial epiphysis
HP:6000886.definition: Size (volume) of the distal epiphysis of the tiba above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000887.name: Elevated blood bismuth concentration
HP:6000887.definition: The concentration of bismuth in the blood is above the upper limit of a guidance value for total blood bismuth concentrations that implies possible injurious effects.

HP:6000888.name: Elevated urine bismuth level
HP:6000888.definition: Detection of a level of bismuth in the urine high enough to raise the suspicion of bismuth toxicity, usually greater than 20microgram per deciliter.

HP:6000889.name: Distal radioulnar joint dislocation
HP:6000889.definition: Distal radioulnar joint dislocation is more commonly displaced dorsally (i.e. the distal ulna is dorsally dislocated with respect to the distal radius), but can be volarly displaced.

HP:6000890.name: Proximal radioulnar joint dislocation
HP:6000890.definition: he proximal radioulnar translocation means that both the radius and ulna are dislocated from the humerus.

HP:6000891.name: Absent toe phalanx flexion crease
HP:6000891.definition: Absence of one or more interphalangeal creases of a toe (i.e., of the transverse lines in the skin between the phalanges of the toes).

HP:6000892.name: White matter globoid cells
HP:6000892.definition: Multinucleated phagocytes in the cerebral white matter, typically are 10-15 micrometers in diameter, that contain fatty filamentous inclusions that stain positive for periodic acid-Schiff (PAS), which may be phagocytized myelin, as these cells are often found in proximity to sites where demyelination is prominent. Globoid cells have been to thought to originate from CNS resident microglia and/or infiltrating peripheral macrophages.

HP:6000893.name: Gaucher cells
HP:6000893.definition: Glucosylceramide forms fibrillar aggregates that accumulate in macrophages and result in the cell cytoplasm presenting a characteristic crumpled tissue paper appearance. These cells, known as Gaucher cells, infiltrate various organs (e.g., bone marrow, spleen, and liver) and are responsible for the major signs of Gaucher disease.

HP:6000894.name: Breast adenoma
HP:6000894.definition: A benign, well circumscribed neoplasm that arises from the breast.

HP:6000895.name: Breast apocrine adenoma
HP:6000895.definition: A type of breast adenoma composed of benign apocrine cells.

HP:6000896.name: Fibrocystic breast lesion
HP:6000896.definition: A type of benign cyst or cysts in breast tissue that are typically mobile within the glandular breast tissue, chest wall, and skin and are rubber-like in texture. The main histological features are an extracellular matrix of collagen, peri canalicular patterns of stromal cells with the presence of florid epithelial hyperplasia.

HP:6000897.name: Pancreatic VIPoma
HP:6000897.definition: A type of neuroendocrine tumor that originates in the pancreas and secretes excessive amounts of vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP).

HP:6000898.name: Gastric carcinoid tumor
HP:6000898.definition: Originating from enterochromaffin-like cells, gastric carcinoid tumors are rare tumors that develop within the gastric mucosa. They can present as an isolated lesion or there can be multiple lesions. The tumor can invade locally into deeper structures of the gastrointestinal tract wall. Solitary gastric carcinoids have a greater chance for the development of malignancy and metastasis as compared to multiple gastric carcinoids due to hypergastrinemia.

HP:6000899.name: Positive skin scabies test
HP:6000899.definition: Identification of scabies by means of an examination of the skin such as microscopic identification of scabies mites, eggs, or feces from obtained scales by skin scraping.

HP:6000900.name: Positive mumps virus PCR test in the blood circulation
HP:6000900.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of the mumps virus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000901.name: Positive bloodstream tuberculosis-induced T-cell-based interferon-gamma release assay
HP:6000901.definition: Detection of Mycobacterium tuberculosis in the bloodstream by means of detection of interferon-gamma secreted by T cells in response to specific antigens from Mycobacterium tuberculosis, commonly 6kD early secretory antigenic target-6 and 10kD culture filtrate protein-10.

HP:6000902.name: Positive blood Neisseria gonorrhoeae culture
HP:6000902.definition: Growth of Neisseria gonorrhoeae in a culture derived from circulating blood.

HP:6000903.name: Anti-mumps antibody positivity
HP:6000903.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Mumps virus.

HP:6000904.name: Positive Vibrio cholerae stool culture
HP:6000904.definition: Growth of Vibrio cholerae in a culture derived from a feces sample.

HP:6000905.name: Positive cutaneous varicella zoster virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000905.definition: Detection of mucocutaneous varicella zoster virus nucleic acid in the skin by a method such as polymerase chain reaction. The sample is usually obtained by swab from skin or mucous membranes.

HP:6000906.name: Positive bloodstream cryptococcus culture
HP:6000906.definition: Growth of Cryptococcus in a culture derived from a blood sample.

HP:6000907.name: Positive bloodstream Borrelia miyamotoi nucleic acid test
HP:6000907.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Borrelia miyamotoi in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000908.name: Positive bloodstream Coxsackievirus nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:6000908.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Coxsackievirus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000909.name: Positive stool Cryptosporidium antigen test
HP:6000909.definition: Fecal analysis for Cryptosporidium antigen is abnormal. Tests include direct fluorescent-antibody (DFA), which detects intact organisms, and enzyme immunoassays (EIAs), which detect soluble stool antigens.

HP:6000910.name: Diminished tissue alpha-L-iduronidase activity
HP:6000910.definition: Concentration or activity of alpha-L-iduronidase (IDUA; EC 3.2.1.76) below the lower limit of normal. FECH enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including cultured fibroblasts and leukocytes.

HP:6000911.name: Reduced tissue neuraminidase activity
HP:6000911.definition: Activity of neuraminidase (EC 3.2.1.18)in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts. Neuraminidase is also known as lysosomal sialidase.

HP:6000912.name: Nummular keratitis
HP:6000912.definition: Nummular keratitis consists of multiple scattered small round anterior corneal superficial stromal infiltrates.

HP:6000913.name: Swelling of inguinal region
HP:6000913.definition: Bulging in the area of the lower abdomen, just above the thigh and near the groin.

HP:6000914.name: Single lesion
HP:6000914.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are solitary and localized to a part of the skin, a tissue or an organ that differs from the surrounding healthy tissue.

HP:6000915.name: Dysorthography
HP:6000915.definition: A specific disorder of spelling. A score on a standardized spelling test is at least two standard errors of prediction below the level expected on the basis of the child's chronological age and general intelligence in the context of scores on reading accuracy and comprehension and on arithmetic that are within the normal range (within two standard deviations from the mean).

HP:6000916.name: Echogenic fetal colon
HP:6000916.definition: A type of echogenic fetal bowel in which the hyperechogenicity is strictly limited to the colon.

HP:6000917.name: Bone marrow edema
HP:6000917.definition: Accumulation of excess fluid in the bone marrow.

HP:6000918.name: Transverse terminal upper limb defect
HP:6000918.definition: A congenital anomaly that appears as an amputation at different levels of the arm, e.g. humerus, proximal forearm, wrist or finger. The limb is missing the terminal (distal) segment(s), with preservation of all the segment(s) proximal to the missing segment.

HP:6000919.name: Trousseau sign
HP:6000919.definition: After inflating a blood pressure cuff from 10 mm Hg to 20 mm Hg over the patient's systolic blood pressure, the Trousseau sign is considered positive if carpal spasm develops, with flexion of the thumb and adduction of the finger within 3 minutes. However, this can be painful, so the time should be noted, and the cuff should be deflated once the test is positive.

HP:6000920.name: Craniocervical junction constriction
HP:6000920.definition: Congenital or acquired abnormalities of the occipital bone, foramen magnum, or first two cervical vertebrae that decrease the space for the lower brain stem and cervical cord. These malformations can lead to cranial nerve compression, vertebral artery compression, and obstructive hydrocephalus.

HP:6000921.name: Fibular torsion
HP:6000921.definition: Excessively rotated (also called torsion) position of the fibula (calf bone). An increased external rotation of the fibula in the incisura tibiofibularis of more than 5 degrees may lead to an increased pressure and will negatively affect the cartilage.

HP:6000922.name: Abnormal finger phalanx ossification
HP:6000922.definition: Any abnormal process of ossification of the phalangeal bones, which normally are ossified from the body and proximal extremity. Ossification of the body commences during the eighth week of fetal development. Ossification of the proximal extremity commences in the bones between the third and fourth years.

HP:6000923.name: Positive bloodstream EBV monospot test
HP:6000923.definition: The monospot test is a latex agglutination test which utilizes equine erythrocytes as the primary substrate and tests for specific heterophile antibodies produced by the human immune system in response to EBV infection. When these specific antibodies are present in the patient's blood specimen, exposure to equine erythrocytes will lead to clumping of the sample, thus signaling a positive agglutination reaction.

HP:6000924.name: Positive CSF Toxoplasma gondii antibody positivity
HP:6000924.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of Toxoplasma gondii.

HP:6000925.name: Positive tuberculin skin test
HP:6000925.definition: A positive result of the tuberculin skin test suggesting previous expouse or infection with mycobacterium teberculosis. A standard dose of five tuberculin units (TU) (0.1ml) is injected intradermally (into the skin) and read 48 to 72 h later. A person who has been exposed to the bacteria is expected to mount an immune response in the skin containing the bacterial proteins. The volar aspect of the forearm is the preferred site of test. The basis of reading is the presence or absence of induration, which may be determined by inspection (from a side view against the light as well as by direct light) and by palpation. For standardization, the diameter of induration should be measured transversely to the long axis of the forearm and recorded in millimeters.

HP:6000926.name: Anti-Treponema pallidum antibody positivity
HP:6000926.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Treponema pallidum.

HP:6000927.name: Positive CSF Borrelia burgdorferi antibody positivity
HP:6000927.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of Borrelia burgdorferi.

HP:6000928.name: Positive CSF JC-virus antibody positivity
HP:6000928.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of JC-virus (also known as JC-polyomavirus and John Cunningham virus).

HP:6000929.name: Neutralizing anti-rabies virus antibody positivity
HP:6000929.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that act against the rabies virus function by blocking the binding of the glycoprotein to a receptor or preventing the membrane fusion process.

HP:6000930.name: Impaired hepatobiliary scintigraphy tracer uptake
HP:6000930.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of radioactive tracer uptake upon hepatobiliary scintigraphy.

HP:6000931.name: Calcified pulmonary nodule
HP:6000931.definition: A pulmonary nodule with calcium deposits. On radiography, these nodules appear dense.

HP:6000932.name: Postprandial exacerbation
HP:6000932.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is more severe following a meal.

HP:6000933.name: Koebner Phenomenon
HP:6000933.definition: The appearance of new skin lesions on previously unaffected skin secondary to trauma. This phenomenon is also termed the isomorphic (from Greek, equal shape) response, given the fact that the new lesions that appear are clinically and histologically identical to the patient's underlying cutaneous disease.

HP:6000934.name: Glenoid dysplasia
HP:6000934.definition: Glenoid dysplasia is a developmental anomaly of the scapula that is characterized by a bony deficiency of the posteroinferior glenoid and the adjacent scapular neck.

HP:6000935.name: Prolonged retraction of penile foreskin
HP:6000935.definition: A past medical history of recently having retracted the penile foreskin for a prolonged period of time. Paraphimosis commonly occurs iatrogenically, when the foreskin is retracted for cleaning, placement of a urinary catheter, a procedure such as a cystoscopy, or for penile examination. Failure to return the retracted foreskin over the glans promptly after the initial retraction can lead to paraphimosis.

HP:6000936.name: Thickened cortex of the clavicle
HP:6000936.definition: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the clavicle.

HP:6000937.name: Thickened cortex of the mandible
HP:6000937.definition: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the mandible.

HP:6000938.name: Thumb hypoplasia grade 1
HP:6000938.definition: Minor hypoplasia (developmental undergrowth) of the thumb, whereby all musculoskeletal and neurovascular components of the digit are present, just small in size (Blauth classification).

HP:6000939.name: Thumb hypoplasia grade 2
HP:6000939.definition: A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby all of the osseous structures are present (may be small), and there is metacarpophalangeal joint ulnar collateral ligament instability and thenar hypoplasia.

HP:6000940.name: Thumb hypoplasia grade 3A
HP:6000940.definition: A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies with the carpometacarpal (CMC) joint intact. Absence of active motion at the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.

HP:6000941.name: Thumb hypoplasia grade 3B
HP:6000941.definition: A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies characterized by basal metacarpal aplasia with deficient carpometacarpal (CMC) joint, and absence of metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.

HP:6000942.name: Thumb hypoplasia grade 4
HP:6000942.definition: A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb characterized by attachment to the hand only by the skin and digital neurovascular structures.

HP:6000943.name: Femoral osteopoikilosis
HP:6000943.definition: Multiple multiple, small, well-defined radiodense foci of cortical-like bone in the medullary space parallel to the trabeculae located in the femur. The loci correspond to condensations of the lamellar trabeculae on histology.

HP:6000944.name: Carotidynia
HP:6000944.definition: Pain or tenderness in the region of the carotid artery.

HP:6000945.name: Asymmetric blood pressure between arms
HP:6000945.definition: A substantial difference in blood pressure (e.g., 20 mmHg) between the right and left arms.

HP:6000946.name: Transverse terminal lower limb defect
HP:6000946.definition: A congenital anomaly that appears as an amputation at different levels of the leg, e.g. femur, foreleg, ankle or toe. The limb is missing the terminal (distal) segment(s), with preservation of all the segment(s) proximal to the missing segment.

HP:6000947.name: Hemimelia of lower leg
HP:6000947.definition: A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the lower leg (eg tibia and fibula), ankle and foot.

HP:6000948.name: Hemimelia of forearm
HP:6000948.definition: A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the forearm (eg ulna and radius), wrist and hand.

HP:6000949.name: Sodium glucose transport inhibitor exposure
HP:6000949.definition: History of having been treateed with a sodium glucose transport inhibitors such as dapagliflozin, empagliflozin, canagliflozin, sglt-i, SGLT2, bexagliflozin, ertugliflozin, sotagliflozin, jardiance, invokana, forxiga, brenzavvy, steglatro, inpefa.

HP:6000950.name: Breath-holding spell
HP:6000950.definition: A benign paroxysmal nonepileptic disorder occurring in healthy children 6 to 48 months of age. The episodes start with a provocation such as emotional upset or minor injury, and might progress to breath holding, cyanosis, and syncope.

HP:6000951.name: Flared proximal tibial metaphysis
HP:6000951.definition: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of the proximal tibia.

HP:6000952.name: Delayed toe phalanx ossification
HP:6000952.definition: Delayed maturation and calcification of any of the toe phalanges.

HP:6000953.name: Sorbitol ingestion
HP:6000953.definition: A history of ingestion of a relatively high amount of foods containing sorbitol.

HP:6000954.name: Positive peritoneal fluid bacterial culture
HP:6000954.definition: Growth of bacteria in a culture dervied from ascites fluid.

HP:6000955.name: Ocular cystine crystal deposition
HP:6000955.definition: Accumulation of cystine crsytals in the eye. Patients present with crystal accumulation affecting the cornea and conjunctiva, but crystals can also be deposited in the iris, ciliary body, choroid and retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), and lens capsule. Corneal crystal deposition starts in infancy in the anterior periphery of the cornea, and progresses centrally and posteriorly. The crystals, which have a fine, uniform needle-shaped structure, are diffusely distributed within the corneal tissues.

HP:6000956.name: Exuberant granulation tissue
HP:6000956.definition: A manifestation of abnormal wound healing in which there is formation of excessive granulation tissue, with the granulation tissue rising above the level of surrounding skin and creating a raised, reddish, moist, and bumpy surface.

HP:6000957.name: Oral mucosal papule
HP:6000957.definition: A small (less than 5 mm in diameter), elevated, circumscribed, solid, palpable mass located in thte mucosa of the oral cavity.

HP:6000958.name: Excessive piloerection
HP:6000958.definition: Abnormally increased degree of goose bump formation, that is, of involuntary formation of bumps on a person's skin at the base of body hairs.

HP:6000959.name: Scalp edema
HP:6000959.definition: A palpable swelling in the scalp caused by an increase in interstitial fluid volume (excess fluid).

HP:6000960.name: Serpiginous burrow
HP:6000960.definition: A slightly raised and often reddish serpentine or curvilinear path in the skin.

HP:6000961.name: Positive brain-tissue rabies nucleic acid test
HP:6000961.definition: Detection of rabies nucleic acid in brain tissue by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000962.name: Positive respiratory tract Bordetella pertussis nucleic acid test
HP:6000962.definition: Detection of Bordetella pertussis PCR nucleic acid in in nasopharyngeal secretions by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000963.name: Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli in wound tissue
HP:6000963.definition: Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli by microscopic examination of wound tissue. Acid fastness is a physical property that gives a bacterium the ability to resist decolorization by acids during staining procedures.

HP:6000964.name: Positive tissue encapsulated budding yeast test
HP:6000964.definition: Identification of encapsulated budding yeasts in smears of body fluids, secretions, exudates, or other specimens.

HP:6000965.name: Positive tissue coccidioidomycosis culture
HP:6000965.definition: Growth of coccidioidomycosis in a culture derived from skin or an organ.

HP:6000966.name: Diminished tissue dihydropteridine reductase activity
HP:6000966.definition: Concentration or activity of dihydropteridine reductase (EC 1.6.99.7) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and erythrocytes.

HP:6000967.name: Decreased circulating transcobalamin I concentration
HP:6000967.definition: Concentration of transcobalamin I in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000968.name: Diminished circulating cationic trypsinogen concentration
HP:6000968.definition: Concentration of cationic trypsinogen in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000969.name: Diminished circulating hyaluronidase activity
HP:6000969.definition: The activity or concentration of hyaluronidase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000970.name: Diminished sulfotransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000970.definition: Rate of proteoglycan sulfation (sulfotransferase activity) is below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000971.name: Elevated tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity
HP:6000971.definition: Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) above the upper limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.

HP:6000972.name: Abnormal tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity
HP:6000972.definition: Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) outside of the limits of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.

HP:6000973.name: Elevated circulating trihydroxycholestanoic acid concentration
HP:6000973.definition: The concentration of trihydroxycholestanoic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000974.name: Elevated circulating glyoxylic acid concentration
HP:6000974.definition: The concentration of glyoxylic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000975.name: Elevated CSF sepiapterin concentration
HP:6000975.definition: Concentration of sepiapterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000976.name: Intrahepatic inclusion bodies
HP:6000976.definition: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within hepatocytes.

HP:6000977.name: Muscle vacuoles
HP:6000977.definition: Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. The vacuoles are often associated with cytoplasmic and occasionally intranuclear eosinophilic inclusions.

HP:6000978.name: Nonrimmed muscle vacuoles
HP:6000978.definition: Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. On histological staining with hematoxylin and eosin, non-rimmed vacuoles lack the prominent dark border (rim) seen in rimmed vacuoles.

HP:6000979.name: Reduced hepatic glycogen phosphorylase activity
HP:6000979.definition: Activity or concentration of glycogen phosphorylase L in the liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000980.name: Bone marrow hemophagocytosis
HP:6000980.definition: Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the bone marrow.

HP:6000981.name: Splenic granulomatosis
HP:6000981.definition: Splenic inflammation involving a granulomatous response, i.e., a non-specific inflammatory response involving granulomas, defined as a compact organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes including epithelioid and giant cells.

HP:6000982.name: Immediate detumescence of penis at time of symptom onset
HP:6000982.definition: Loss of erection at the time point of pain or other symptom onset.

HP:6000983.name: History of aortic valve replacement
HP:6000983.definition: History of having received a surgical replacement of the aortic valve.

HP:6000984.name: Coved type ST segment elevation
HP:6000984.definition: An ST-segment elevation of at least 2 mm in at least one right precordial lead (V1 to V3), followed by an r'-wave and a concave or straight ST segment. The descending ST segment crosses the isoelectric line and is followed by a negative and symmetric T-wave.

HP:6000985.name: Saddle-back type ST segment elevation
HP:6000985.definition: An ST-segment elevation of at least 0.5 mm (generally at least 2 mm in V2) in at least one right precordial lead (V1 to V3), followed by a convex ST. The r'-wave may or may not overlap the J point, but it has a slow downward slope. The ST segment is followed by a positive T-wave in V2 and is of variable morphology in V1.

HP:6000986.name: Substantially elevated circulating ethanol concentration
HP:6000986.definition: A blood concentration of ethanol that is consistent with alcohol intoxication, generally assumed to be 0.0800 g/dL or higher.

HP:6000987.name: Tortuous appearance of the stomach
HP:6000987.definition: Abnormal twisting or winding of the stomach.

HP:6000988.name: Cochlear nerve aplasia
HP:6000988.definition: A developmental defect causing an absence of the cochlear nerve resulting in sensorineural hearing loss.

HP:6000989.name: Slit-like lateral ventricle
HP:6000989.definition: Abnormally small lateral ventricle with a slit-like appearance.

HP:6000990.name: Fetal methamphetamine exposure
HP:6000990.definition: A history of exposure during pregnancy (including during the period of conception) of the mother of a fetus or child to methamphetamine.

HP:6000991.name: Elevated circulating 4-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
HP:6000991.definition: Concentration of 4-hydroxybutyric acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000992.name: Elevated urinary 2,4-dihydroxybutyric acid level
HP:6000992.definition: The amount of 2,4-dihydroxybutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000993.name: Pupillary hypersensitivity to parasympathomimetic agents
HP:6000993.definition: A higher than normal tendency of parasympathomimetic agents to induce miosis.

HP:6000994.name: Lack of pupillary response to hydroxyamphetamine
HP:6000994.definition: 4-hydroxyamphetamine is used in eye drops to dilate the pupil, e.g.., to induce mydriasis for fundus examinations. This term refers to a lack of response of the pupil to topical application of 4-hydroxyamphetamine.

HP:6000995.name: Subcortical U fiber lesion
HP:6000995.definition: Abnormal morphology of subcortical U fibers, typically as assessed by abnromal intensity on magnetic resonance imaging of the brain.

HP:6000996.name: Intraspinal extradural lipoma
HP:6000996.definition: A lipoma (a benign encapsulated mass with lobulated mature adipose tissue enclosed by fibrous tissue) located within the spine but outside of the dura mater.

HP:6000997.name: Intranasal mass
HP:6000997.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the nasal cavity. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000998.name: Liver rupture
HP:6000998.definition: Subcapsular hepatic rupture is characterized by the development of a hematoma, often quite large, beneath the liver capsule. An interval of days or hours may elapse between the time of injury and the first appearance of symptoms. A history of injury may be entirely lacking, or may be so unremarkable that it is elicited only by diligent interrogation. The hematoma tends to increase in size.

HP:6000999.name: Elevated urinary mandelic acid
HP:6000999.definition: The amount of mandelic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001000.name: Elevated urine malic acid level
HP:6001000.definition: The amount of malic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001001.name: Elevated urine 3-hydroxysebacic acid level
HP:6001001.definition: The amount of 3-hydroxysebacic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001002.name: Elevated urinary vanillactic acid level
HP:6001002.definition: The amount of vanillactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001003.name: Elevated urine 4,5-dihydroxyhexanoic acid level
HP:6001003.definition: The amount of 4,5-dihydroxyhexanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001004.name: Elevated urine hydroxyphenyllactic acid level
HP:6001004.definition: The amount of hydroxyphenyllactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001005.name: Positive gastric CMV intranuclear inclusions
HP:6001005.definition: Demonstration of the presence of cytomegalovirus in the stomach by means of a method such as in-situ hybridization.

HP:6001006.name: Elevated urine dihydroxycholestanoic acid level
HP:6001006.definition: The amount of dihydroxycholestanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001007.name: Elevated urinary bile alcohol level
HP:6001007.definition: The amount of bile alcohol in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001008.name: Elevated urine glucose tetrasaccharide level
HP:6001008.definition: The amount of glucose tetrasaccharide in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001009.name: Increased urine 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate level
HP:6001009.definition: The amount of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001010.name: Inability to protrude lips
HP:6001010.definition: Lack of ability to purse or pucker the lips.

HP:6001011.name: Wet voice
HP:6001011.definition: Wet voice is a perceptual vocal quality that is gurgly or liquid sounding and is due to the voice being produced through moisture. It is commonly used as an indicator of penetration and/or aspiration in clinical swallowing assessments and bedside screening tests.

HP:6001012.name: Erythema marginatum
HP:6001012.definition: An erythematous (pink-red, depending on the skin color of the affected individual) macule that spreads peripherally and coalesces to form polycyclic or serpentine patches or plaques. Lesions occur in crops over days to weeks and are evanescent. The rate of migration is 2 to 12 mm over a period of a few hours. Erythema marginatum tends to affect the trunk more than the extremities and to not be accompanied by pruritus.

HP:6001013.name: Mechanic's hands
HP:6001013.definition: Mechanic's hands are fissured, erythematous, hyperkeratotic eruptions on the hands, resembling the type of occupational dermatosis said to resemble the hands of a manual laborer. The lesions are classically on the lateral edges of the fingers and thumbs, largely sparing the palmar, and dorsal aspects of the digits.

HP:6001014.name: Hiker's feet
HP:6001014.definition: Hyperkeratotic scaly fissured plaques on the fingers/palms or soles, generally more evident on the lateral aspect of index fingers.

HP:6001015.name: Anti-HLA-DQ antibody positivity
HP:6001015.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against a human leukocyte antigen (HLA-DQ). DQ is one of several antigens involved in antibody-mediated rejection of organ transplants.

HP:6001016.name: Inappropriate normal or low erythropoietin
HP:6001016.definition: Erythropoietin is produced and released into the blood by the kidneys in response to hypoxemia, and would normally be expected to increase with decreasing hemoglobin levels. This term applies if the increase fails to occur, as may be seen in conditions including chronic kidney disease.

HP:6001017.name: Rapid gastric emptying
HP:6001017.definition: A condition in which food moves through the stomach into the small intestine at an abnormally fast rate.

HP:6001018.name: Mediastinal lymph node calcification
HP:6001018.definition: Abnormal deposition of calcium in mediastinal lymph nodes.

HP:6001019.name: Eggshell calcification of lymph nodes
HP:6001019.definition: Eggshell calcification refers to fine calcification seen at the periphery of a mass and usually relates to lamellar lymph node calcification.

HP:6001020.name: Knee joint effusion
HP:6001020.definition: Abnormal accumulation of fluid within the knee joint or around the knee. Symptoms maye include, pain, swelling, and stiffness.

HP:6001021.name: Subcutaneous emphysema
HP:6001021.definition: Skin emphysema/Subcutaneous emphysema occurs when gas or air accumulates and seeps under the skin, where normally no gas should be present. While the presence of air in subcutaneous or mediastinal tissue is not dangerous in itself, prompt recognition of the underlying cause is essential.

HP:6001022.name: Elevated bone scintigraphy uptake
HP:6001022.definition: Bone scintigraph is performed with technetium 99m-labeled diphosphonates. The uptake of these radiopharmaceuticals depicts osteoblastic activity and regional blood flow to bone.

HP:6001023.name: Diminished long-chain-enoyl-CoA hydratase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6001023.definition: Concentration or activity of long-chain-enoyl-CoA hydratase (EC 4.2.1.74) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.

HP:6001024.name: Diminished acetyl-CoA C-acyltransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6001024.definition: Concentration or activity of acetyl-CoA C-acyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.16) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. This enzyme catalyzes the reaction acetyl-CoA + an acyl-CoA = a 3-oxoacyl-CoA + CoA. It is also known as 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase and beta-ketothiolase.

HP:0032153.name: Joint subluxation
HP:0032153.definition: A partial dislocation of a joint.

HP:0032154.name: Aphthous ulcer
HP:0032154.definition: Oral aphthous ulcers typically present as painful, sharply circumscribed fibrin-covered mucosal defects with a hyperemic border.

HP:0032155.name: Abdominal cramps
HP:0032155.definition: A type of abdominal pain characterized by a feeling of contractions and typically fluctuating in intensity.

HP:0032156.name: Skin detachment
HP:0032156.definition: Loss of sections of skin either spontaneously or after gentle handling.

HP:0032157.name: Recurrent genital herpes
HP:0032157.definition: Recurrent episodes of genital herpes, typically characterized by stages of erythema, papules, short-lived vesicles, painful ulcers, and crusts on the skin of the genitals and surrounding area, and that typically resolve over a period of 2 to 3 weeks.

HP:0032158.name: Unusual infection by anatomical site
HP:0032158.definition: An unusual infection classified by the affected body part.

HP:0032159.name: Fungal meningitis
HP:0032159.definition: An infection of the meninges caused by a fungus. Generally, only individuals with deficiencies of the immune system contract fungal meningitis.

HP:0032160.name: Cryptococcal meningitis
HP:0032160.definition: A type of fungal meningitis caused by an encapsulated yeast that belongs to the genus Cryptococcus. Cryptococcus neoformans and Cryptococcus gattii are responsible for the majority of cases of human cryptococcosis.

HP:0032161.name: Coccidioidal meningitis
HP:0032161.definition: A type of fungal meningitis caused by dissemination of coccidioides to basilar meninges.

HP:0032162.name: Unusual skin infection
HP:0032162.definition: A type of infection of the skin that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

HP:0032163.name: Molluscum contagiosum
HP:0032163.definition: Molluscum contagiosum is a cutaneous viral infection that is commonly observed in both healthy and immunocompromised children. The infection is caused by a member of the Poxviridae family, the molluscum contagiosum virus. Molluscum contagiosum presents as single or multiple small white or flesh-colored papules that typically have a central umbilication. The central umbilication may be difficult to observe in young children and, instead, may bear an appearance similar to an acneiform eruption. The lesions vary in size (from 1 mm to 1 cm in diameter) and are painless, although a subset of patients report pruritus in the area of infection. On average, 11-20 papules appear on the body during the course of infection and generally remains a self-limiting disease. However, in immunosuppressed patients, molluscum contagiosum can be a severe infection with hundreds of lesions developing on the body. Extensive eruption is indicative of an advanced immunodeficiency state.

HP:0032164.name: Increased blood folate concentration
HP:0032164.definition: An elevated circulating concentration of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9.

HP:0032165.name: Placental mesenchymal dysplasia
HP:0032165.definition: Placental mesenchymal dysplasia is a rare anomaly characterized by placentomegaly, dilatation of chorionic vessels and hydropic stem villi with cistern-like formation. It is often clinically mistaken for a partial hydatidiform mole but there is no trophoblastic proliferation. P57 immunohistochemical expression is discordant, showing a normal positive expression in the cytotrophoblastic cells, and loss of expression in the stromal cells.

HP:0032167.name: Clostridium difficile enteritis
HP:0032167.definition: An infection of the small intestine (enteritis) by clostridium difficile.

HP:0032168.name: Clostridium difficile colitis
HP:0032168.definition: An infection of the colon (colitis) by clostridium difficile.

HP:0032169.name: Severe infection
HP:0032169.definition: A type of infection that is regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection because of unusual severity or intensity of the infection.

HP:0032170.name: Severe varicella zoster infection
HP:0032170.definition: An unusually severe form of varicella zoster virus (VZV) infection. In the majority of the cases, especially in children, varicella is a very mild infection characterized by skin lesions, low grade fever and malaise. Severe infection is characterized by manifestations including VZV pneumonia, hepatitis, meningitis, and disseminated varicella.

HP:0032171.name: Bladder pain
HP:0032171.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the urinary bladder. Bladder pain may be more pronounced with a full bladder and relieved upon urination, but this is not always the case.

HP:0032172.name: Air crescent sign
HP:0032172.definition: A crescent of air surrounding a soft-tissue mass in a pulmonary cavity and can be seen in both plain X-ray and CT scan.

HP:0032173.name: Continuous diaphragm sign
HP:0032173.definition: This sign is seen in pneumomediastinum in which air accumulates between the lower border of the heart and the superior part of the diaphragm, which results in complete visualization of the diaphragm in chest X-ray, hence named continuous diaphragm sign.

HP:0032174.name: Tree-in-bud pattern
HP:0032174.definition: The tree-in-bud pattern represents centrilobular branching structures that resemble a budding tree. The pattern reflects a spectrum of endo- and peribronchiolar disorders, including mucoid impaction, inflammation, and/or fibrosis (See Figure 70 of PMID:18195376).

HP:0032175.name: Signet ring sign
HP:0032175.definition: This finding is composed of a ring-shaped opacity representing a dilated bronchus in cross section and a smaller adjacent opacity representing its pulmonary artery, with the combination resembling a signet (or pearl) ring. It is the basic sign of bronchiectasis in pulmonary computed tomography imaging.

HP:0032176.name: Apical pulmonary opacity
HP:0032176.definition: An apical cap is a caplike lesion at the lung apex, usually caused by intrapulmonary and pleural fibrosis pulling down extrapleural fat or possibly by chronic ischemia resulting in hyaline plaque formation on the visceral pleura. The prevalence increases with age. It can also be seen in hematoma resulting from aortic rupture or in other fluid collection associated with infection or tumor, either outside the parietal pleura or loculated within the pleural space.

HP:0032177.name: Parenchymal consolidation
HP:0032177.definition: Consolidation refers to an exudate or other product of disease that replaces alveolar air, rendering the lung solid (as in infective pneumonia).

HP:0032178.name: Flaky paint dermatosis
HP:0032178.definition: A dermatosis characterized by generalized shiny, enamel-like, hyperpigmented scales in an irregular pattern. The scales may peel or desquamate, rather like old, sun-baked blistered paint, often with areas of underlying hypopigmentation. This has led to the terms peeling paint or flaky paint dermatosis (See the Figure in PMID:24285001).

HP:0032179.name: Abnormal circulating globulin concentration
HP:0032179.definition: An abnormal concentration of globulins in the blood. Albumin makes up more than half of the total protein present in serum. The remaining blood proteins except albumin and fibrinogen (which is not in serum) are referred to as globulins. The globulin fraction includes hundreds of serum proteins including carrier proteins, enzymes, complement, and immunoglobulins. Most of these are synthesized in the liver, although the immunoglobulins are synthesized by plasma cells. Globulins are divided into four groups by electrophoresis. The four fractions are alpha1, alpha2, beta and gamma, depending on their migratory pattern between the anode and the cathode.

HP:0032180.name: Abnormal circulating metabolite concentration
HP:0032180.definition: An abnormal level of an analyte measured in the blood.

HP:0032181.name: Anomalous hepatic venous drainage into the left atrium
HP:0032181.definition: An abnormality of the hepatic veins, which normally drain de-oxygenated blood from the liver into the inferior vena cava, whereby the hepatic veins drain into the left atrium.

HP:0032182.name: Abnormal memory T cell proportion
HP:0032182.definition: An abnormal proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. Memory T cells have previously encountered and responded to their cognate antigen and upon a repeated encounter with the antigen can mount a faster and stronger response.

HP:0032183.name: Decreased memory T cell proportion
HP:0032183.definition: An abnormally reduced proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood.

HP:0032184.name: Increased memory T cell proportion
HP:0032184.definition: An abnormally elevated proportion of memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood.

HP:0032185.name: Disseminated molluscum contagiosum
HP:0032185.definition: The presence of molluscum contagiosum lesions across multiple areas of the body.

HP:0032186.name: Anal neoplasm
HP:0032186.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the anal canal or anal margin.

HP:0032187.name: Anal intraepithelial neoplasia
HP:0032187.definition: Anal intraepithelial neoplasia (AIN) is a premalignant lesion of the anal mucosa that is a precursor to anal cancer.

HP:0032188.name: Cellular hypersensitivity to mitomycin C
HP:0032188.definition: An increased cellular sensitivity to the DNA cross-linking agent, mitomycin C (MMC). In the presence of increased sensitivity, MMC causes increased cell death, chromosome breakage, and accumulation in the G2 phase of the cell cycle.

HP:0032189.name: Cellular hypersensitivity to diepoxybutane
HP:0032189.definition: An increased cellular sensitivity to the DNA cross-linking agent, diepoxybutane (DEB). In the presence of increased sensitivity, DEB causes cell death, chromosome breakage, and accumulation in the G2 phase of the cell cycle.

HP:0032190.name: Abnormal meniscus morphology
HP:0032190.definition: Abnormal structure of the meniscus of the knee, two crescent shape fibrocartilaginous pads that disperse the weight of the body and reduce friction of the knee joint during movement.

HP:0032191.name: Torn meniscus
HP:0032191.definition: A tear in the cartilaginous pad (meniscus) of the knee.

HP:0032192.name: Hydatidiform mole
HP:0032192.definition: Hydatidiform mole (HM) is an aberrant human pregnancy with absence of, or abnormal embryonic development, hydropic degeneration of chorionic villi, and excessive proliferation of the trophoblast.

HP:0032193.name: Decreased low-density lipoprotein particle size
HP:0032193.definition: An abnormal decrease in the average size of low-density lipoprotein particle size in the blood circulation.

HP:0032195.name: Abnormal S wave
HP:0032195.definition: Any anomaly of the S wave, which is the third component of the QRS wave complex. The S wave signifies the final depolarization of the ventricles at the base of the heart.

HP:0032196.name: Prominent S wave in lead I
HP:0032196.definition: Increased amplitude (0.1 mV or more) and/or duration (40 ms or more) of the S wave as measured in lead I of the electrocardiogram.

HP:0032197.name: Deep S wave in lead V5
HP:0032197.definition: Abnormal depth of the S wave in lead V5 of the electrocardiogram.

HP:0032198.name: Decreased prothrombin time
HP:0032198.definition: Abnormally short time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.

HP:0032199.name: Abnormal prothrombin time
HP:0032199.definition: Any deviation from the normal amount of time to coagulation in the prothrombin time test, which is a measure of the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. The results of the prothrombin time test are often expressed in terms of the International normalized ratio (INR), which is calculated as a ratio of the patient's prothrombin time (PT) to a control PT standardized for the potency of the thromboplastin reagent developed by the World Health Organization (WHO) using the formula: INR is equal to Patient PT divided by Control PT.

HP:0032200.name: Perivascular fibrosis
HP:0032200.definition: The presence of thick collagen bundles around blood vessels, often in an onion-skin type whorling pattern.

HP:0032201.name: Rotator cuff tear
HP:0032201.definition: The term rotator cuff describes the tendons connecting the infraspinatus, supraspinatus, teres minor, and subscapularis muscles to the humeral head.Traumatic tears of the rotator cuff tend to occur at the tendon-bone junction of the supraspinatus and greater tuberosity of the humerus whereas degenerative tears tend to be seen posteriorly at the junction of the supraspinatus and infraspinatu A rotator cuff tear is when one or more of these tendons tears or detaches from the humerus.

HP:0032202.name: Vulvar intraepithelial neoplasia
HP:0032202.definition: Vulvar intraepithelial neoplasia (VIN) is widely accepted as the precursor lesion of vulvar squamous cell carcinoma (VSCC). VSCC arises via either a human papilloma virus (HPV)-associated pathway, or more commonly, via a mechanism independent of HPV, often being linked to chronic inflammatory conditions such as lichen sclerosus (LS). Accordingly, two distinct subtypes of VIN are recognized: the HPV-associated high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion/usual VIN (HSIL/uVIN) and the non-HPV-associated differentiated VIN (dVIN). HSIL is clinically identified by its multifocal, warty appearance and on histology by conspicuous cytological and architectural atypia. Differentiated VIN, on the other hand, often produces ill-defined lesions, and on histology, notoriously mimics non-neoplastic epithelial disorders (NNED), particularly LS. As a result, dVIN is rarely identified in advance of a diagnosis of invasive malignancy, despite being the precursor lesion of the majority of VSCC.

HP:0032203.name: Lymphoid nodular hyperplasia
HP:0032203.definition: Lymphoid nodular hyperplasia (LNH) of the terminal ileum and colon has been considered a mucosal response to nonspecific stimuli, most often infections, and consequently has been regarded as a pathophysiologic phenomenon during infancy and childhood. LNH can be ascertained by colonoscopy, whereby a lymphoid nodule is defined as an extruding follicle with a diameter of not more than 2 mm, and LNH is defined as a cluster of not more than 10 of such extruding lymphoid nodules (see Figure 1 of PMID:17368236).

HP:0032204.name: Chronic active Epstein-Barr virus infection
HP:0032204.definition: Chronic active Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection is an uncommon outcome of EBV infection and may present as a waxing and waning or fulminant syndrome. Unlike acute infectious mononucleosis, wherein EBV establishes lifelong infection and survives by maintaining a delicate balance with the host as a latent infection, in chronic active EBV infection the host-virus balance is disturbed.

HP:0032205.name: Increased circulating galectin-3 level
HP:0032205.definition: An increased circulation of galectin-3 in the blood circulation.

HP:0032207.name: obsolete Abnormal cerebrospinal fluid metabolite concentration

HP:0032208.name: Increased urinary type 1 collagen N-terminal telopeptide level
HP:0032208.definition: An increased concentration of type 1 collagen N-terminal telopeptide (NTx) level in the urine. Generally the test is performed over a period of time, for instance, 10 cc of morning urine can be collected following 12 hours overnight fasting or for 24 hours.

HP:0032209.name: Abnormal circulating free T3 concentration
HP:0032209.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of free triiodothyronine (T3) in the blood circulation. A proportion of T3 is bound to plasma proteins in the blood, including mainly thyroxine binding globulin, transthyretin, and albumin. T3 that is not bound to a protein is referred to as free T3.

HP:0032210.name: Decreased circulating free T3
HP:0032210.definition: A reduced concentration of free 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the blood circulation.

HP:0032211.name: Increased urinary epithelial cell count
HP:0032211.definition: An increased number of epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.

HP:0032212.name: Increased urinary squamous epithelial cell count
HP:0032212.definition: An increased number of squamous epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.

HP:0032213.name: Increased urinary renal tubular epithelial cell count
HP:0032213.definition: An increased number of renal tubular epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.

HP:0032214.name: Increased urinary transitional epithelial cell count
HP:0032214.definition: An increased number of transitional epithelial cells per high-power field in urinanalysis.

HP:0032215.name: Disseminated cutaneous warts
HP:0032215.definition: Multiple skin warts located in multiple parts of the body, e.g., neck, trunks, and extremities.

HP:0032216.name: Lymphocytic infiltration of the colorectal mucosa
HP:0032216.definition: Abnormally increased intraepithelial lymphocyte count. This finding may be appreciated as large numbers of surface intraepithelial lymphocytes as seen (for instance) with hematoxylin and eosin staining of a colonic biopsy sample taken during colonoscopy.

HP:0032217.name: Indurated nodule
HP:0032217.definition: A skin nodule that is unusually hard (indurated).

HP:0032218.name: Decreased proportion of CD4-positive T cells
HP:0032218.definition: Abnormal decrease of helper CD3+CD4+ T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0032219.name: Increased proportion of CD4-positive T cells
HP:0032219.definition: Abnormal increase of helper CD3+CD4+ T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

HP:0032220.name: Interface hepatitis
HP:0032220.definition: Inflammation of the liver characterized by a mononuclear cell infiltrate whereby portal inflammatory cells extend through the limiting plate between the portal tract and liver parenchyma.

HP:0032221.name: Periportal emperipolesis
HP:0032221.definition: The engulfing of lymphocytes by hepatocytes, which typically occurs in the interface hepatitis area.

HP:0032222.name: Serrated intestinal polyps
HP:0032222.definition: The presence of multiple serrated polyps in the intestine. Unlike conventional adenomas, which are uniformly dysplastic, the vast majority of serrated lesions contain no dysplasia. The serrated class includes the hyperplastic polyps, which are not considered precancerous; sessile serrated polyps (also called sessile serrated adenomas); and traditional serrated adenomas. Sessile serrated polyps are larger on average and more often located in the proximal colon. Sessile serrated polyps have a more irregular surface, a pattern to the surface that has been called cloudlike, and indistinct edges compared with hyperplastic polyps. Sessile serrated polyps also have large open pits on the surface (type O pits) when viewed with magnification.

HP:0032223.name: Blood group
HP:0032223.definition: Any of the various types of human blood whose antigen characteristics determine compatibility in transfusion. While the ABO and Rhesus systems are the most well known, there are in total about 300 different blood type antigens distributed across 34 different blood type systems.

HP:0032224.name: ABO blood group
HP:0032224.definition: The ABO system consists of A and B antigens and antibodies against these antigens.

HP:0032225.name: Perifollicular fibroma
HP:0032225.definition: Perifollicular fibroma is a rare cutaneous hamartoma that shows differentiation in the connective tissue sheath of hair follicles. It can occur as a solitary papule or as multiple lesions. Histologically, the lesion consists of a concentric arrangement of cellular fibrous tissue around a normal hair follicle.

HP:0032226.name: Abnormal sebaceous gland morphology
HP:0032226.definition: Any structural anomaly of the sebaceous glands.

HP:0032227.name: Sebaceous hyperplasia
HP:0032227.definition: A common, benign skin condition involving hypertrophy of the sebaceous glands characterized by single or multiple lesions that manifest as yellow, soft, small papules with umbilication. The lesions are located commonly on the central face (specifically, the nose, cheeks and forehead) but may also occur elsewhere, including the chest, mouth, scrotum, foreskin, penile shaft, vulva, and areola.

HP:0032228.name: Trichodiscoma
HP:0032228.definition: A small benign fibrovascular tumor of the dermal part of the hair disk. Trichodiscoma is rather simple in appearance and consists of a dome-shaped fibrous tumor with a prominent vascular component that fills the papillary dermis under an atrophic epidermis. As in a normal hair disk, a hair follicle may be present at one edge of the papular lesion.

HP:0032229.name: Perinuclear antineutrophil antibody positivity
HP:0032229.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against proteins predominantly expressed in perinuclear region of neutrophils.

HP:0032230.name: Cytoplasmic antineutrophil antibody positivity
HP:0032230.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against proteins predominantly expressed in cytoplasmic granules of neutrophils.

HP:0032231.name: Hypochromia
HP:0032231.definition: A qualitative impression that red blood cells have less color than normal when examined under a microscope, usually related to a reduced amount of hemoglobin in the red blood cells.

HP:0032232.name: Increased circulating creatine kinase MB isoform
HP:0032232.definition: An increased concentration of the MB isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.

HP:0032233.name: Increased circulating creatine kinase BB isoform
HP:0032233.definition: An increased concentration of the BB isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.

HP:0032234.name: Increased circulating creatine kinase MM isoform
HP:0032234.definition: An increased concentration of the MM isoform of creatine kinase in the blood circulation.

HP:0032235.name: Anti-La/SS-B antibody positivity
HP:0032235.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against La/SSB autoantigens.

HP:0032236.name: Increased circulating immature neutrophil count
HP:0032236.definition: An abnormally increased number of immature neutrophils in the peripheral blood circulation.

HP:0032237.name: Increased circulating myelocyte count
HP:0032237.definition: The number of myelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Myelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 12-18 micrometers, a round or oval nucleus with no nucleoli, bluish-pink staining cytoplasm with primary and secondary granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 2:1.

HP:0032238.name: Increased circulating metamyelocyte count
HP:0032238.definition: The number of metamyelocytes in the peripheral blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Metamyelocytes are immature neutrophils with a size of 10-18 micrometers, an indented or kidney-shaped nucleus, pinkish-blue staining cytoplasm with secondary granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 1.5:1.

HP:0032239.name: Increased circulating band cell count
HP:0032239.definition: The number of band cells in the peripheral blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Band cells are immature neutrophils with a size of 10-18 micrometers, a horseshoe-shaped nucleus with no nucleoli, light-pink staining cytoplasm with many small secondary granules, and a nucleus:cytoplasm ratio of 1:2.

HP:0032240.name: Elevated circulating E selectin level
HP:0032240.definition: An increased concentration of E selectin in the blood circulation.

HP:0032241.name: Cervical neoplasm
HP:0032241.definition: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterine cervix.

HP:0032242.name: Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia
HP:0032242.definition: A precancerous condition characterized by dysplasia of the cervical epithelium. Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN) 1, 2 and 3 based on its relationship with the prognosis. CIN 1 is mild dysplasia, which is mostly observed because it disappears as part of its natural course. CIN 3 includes severe dysplasia and carcinoma in situ, and management involves treatment because it is highly likely to develop into invasive cancer.

HP:0032243.name: Abnormal tissue metabolite concentration
HP:0032243.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a metabolite in a tissue.

HP:0032244.name: Decreased serum thromboxane B2
HP:0032244.definition: A reduction in the concentration of thromboxane B2 in the blood circulation.

HP:0032245.name: Abnormal metabolism
HP:0032245.definition: An abnormality in the function of the chemical reactions related to processes including conversion of food to enter, synthesis of proteins, lipids, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates, or the elimination of waste products.

HP:0032247.name: Persistent CMV viremia
HP:0032247.definition: Lasting (uncontrolled) presence of cytomegalovirus in the blood circulation.

HP:0032248.name: Persistent viremia
HP:0032248.definition: Persistence of virus in the blood circulation longer than would be normal in an immunocompetent host.

HP:0032249.name: Coccidioidomycosis
HP:0032249.definition: Infection by a Coccidioides species fungus. These are dimorphic, soil-dwelling, fungi known to cause a broad spectrum of disease, ranging from a mild febrile illness to severe pulmonary manifestations or disseminated disease. The genus Coccidioides is comprised of two genetically distinct species: Coccidioides immitis and C. posadasii.

HP:0032250.name: Acinetobacter infection
HP:0032250.definition: An infection by Acinetobacter baumannii, a Gram-negative bacillus that is aerobic, pleomorphic and non-motile. An opportunistic pathogen, A. baumannii has a high incidence among immunocompromised individuals, particularly those who have experienced a prolonged (over 90 d) hospital stay.

HP:0032252.name: Granuloma
HP:0032252.definition: A compact, organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes, which may be but is not necessarily accompanied by accessory features such as necrosis.

HP:0032253.name: Eosinophilic granuloma
HP:0032253.definition: A type of granuloma characterized morphologically by the predominance of Langerhans cells with characteristic grooved, folded, indented nuclei in the appropriate milieu that includes variable numbers of eosinophils and histiocytes including multinucleated forms, often appearing similar to osteoclasts or touton like giant cells, neutrophils and small lymphocytes. The concentration of the eosinophilic infiltrate varies from scattered mature cells to sheet-like masses of cells. Occasionally, areas of bone necrosis may interrupt the cellular infiltrate. The foamy cells may also be amassed in clumps, which are of no clinical significance because these clumps represent phagocytosis of lipid debris.

HP:0032254.name: Increased circulating copper concentration
HP:0032254.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of copper in the blood circulation. This term refers to the total copper concentration.

HP:0032255.name: Opportunistic fungal infection
HP:0032255.definition: An infection that is caused by a fungus that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such fungi take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

HP:0032256.name: Histoplasmosis
HP:0032256.definition: Histoplasmosis is caused by the fungus Histoplasma capsulatum and is consider to be an opportunistic infection in immunosuppressed persons.

HP:0032257.name: Disseminated histoplasmosis
HP:0032257.definition: Histoplasmosis infection involving multiple sites of the body. Disseminated histoplasmosis can involve various organs, including reticuloendothelial organs, gastrointestinal tract, adrenal glands, central nervous system, endovascular structures, kidney, and skin. It typically presents with systemic symptoms like fever, generalized fatigue, night sweats, weight loss, and the symptoms related to the specific organ involved. Severe disseminated disease can manifest as septic shock, multi organ failure, and ARDS.

HP:0032258.name: Pulmonary histoplasmosis
HP:0032258.definition: Infection of the lungs with Histoplasma capsulatum. Symptoms may include fever, headache, weakness, chest pain and dry cough. When imaging is done, chest radiographs may show patchy pneumonia involving one or more lobes with adenopathy of the mediastinum or hilum.

HP:0032259.name: Chronic tinea infection
HP:0032259.definition: The term tinea means fungal infection, whereas dermatophyte refers to the fungal organisms that cause tinea. This term refers to a tinea infection that is chronic or recalcitrant to treatment and may be reflective of an immune defect.

HP:0032260.name: Opportunistic bacterial infection
HP:0032260.definition: An infection that is caused by a bacterium that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such bacteria take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

HP:0032261.name: Nontuberculous mycobacterial pulmonary infection
HP:0032261.definition: An infection of the lung caused by environmental mycobacteria. Such infections can occur in individuals with predisposing lung disease or immune disease.

HP:0032262.name: Pulmonary tuberculosis
HP:0032262.definition: A lung infection by Mycobacterium tuberculosis a slightly curved non-motile, aerobic, non-capsulated and non-spore forming strains of mycobacteria.

HP:0032263.name: Increased blood pressure
HP:0032263.definition: Abnormal increase in blood pressure. An individual measurement of increased blood pressure does not necessarily imply hypertension. In practical terms, multiple measurements are recommended to diagnose the presence of hypertension.

HP:0032264.name: Anti-NMDA receptor antibody positivity
HP:0032264.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against the NMDA (N-methyl-D-aspartate)-type glutamate receptor.

HP:0032265.name: CSF autoimmune antibody positivity
HP:0032265.definition: The presence of an antibody in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that is directed against the organism's own cells or tissues.

HP:0032266.name: CSF anti-NMDA receptor antibody positivity
HP:0032266.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against the NMDA (N-methyl-D-aspartate)-type glutamate receptor.

HP:0032267.name: Empty delta sign
HP:0032267.definition: This sign is created by a nonenhancing thrombus in the dural sinus surrounded by triangular enhancing dura as seen on cross-section. The sign, seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan images, suggests dural sinovenous thrombosis. It is best seen on wider window settings.
