It is a reliable sign of sinus thrombosis but is seen only in 25-30% of these cases.

HP:0032268.name: Dural tail sign
HP:0032268.definition: This sign represents thickening and enhancement of the dura mater in continuity with a mass, which on MR images, gives the appearance of a tail arising from the mass. The dural tail is thought to represent reactive change; however, it may also be due to tumor invasion. Three criteria need to be met for a positive dural tail sign: the tail should be seen on two successive images through the tumor, it should taper away from the tumor, and it must enhance more than the tumor.

HP:0032269.name: Lemon sign
HP:0032269.definition: The lemon sign refers to the shape of the fetal skull at ultrasonography (US) when the frontal bones lose their normal convex contour and appear flattened or inwardly scalloped. This gives the skull a shape that is said to resemble a lemon.. The sign is seen on transverse sonograms of the fetal cranium obtained at the level of the ventricles.

HP:0032270.name: Optic nerve tram-track sign
HP:0032270.definition: A tram-track sign is composed of two enhancing areas of tumor separated from each other by the negative defect of the optic nerve. It is seen on contrast-enhanced CT scan and MRI images, in optic nerve sheath meningioma. The sign helps distinguish between optic nerve sheath meningioma and optic glioma. Optic glioma arises from glial cells within the optic nerve and there is no clear separation between the nerve and the tumor; hence the tram-track sign is not seen in optic gliomas. Calcification may be seen in optic nerve sheath meningiomas in 20-50% of cases and hence the tram-track sign may be seen on nonenhanced CT scan images as a linear calcification around the nerve, but this is less common.

HP:0032271.name: Extrapulmonary tuberculosis
HP:0032271.definition: A type of tubercular infection located outside of the lung, which is the most common location of tuberculosis. There are two types of clinical manifestation of tuberculosis (TB) are pulmonary TB (PTB) and extrapulmonary TB (EPTB). The former is most common. EPTB refers to TB involving organs other than the lungs (e.g., pleura, lymph nodes, abdomen, genitourinary tract, skin, joints and bones, or meninges). A patient with both pulmonary and EPTB is classified as a case of PTB.

HP:0032272.name: obsolete Elevated urinary N-acetylaspartic acid level

HP:0032273.name: Increased circulating N-acetylaspartic acid concentration
HP:0032273.definition: Concentration of N-acetylaspartic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0032274.name: Increased CSF N-acetylaspartic acid concentration
HP:0032274.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of N-acetylaspartic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0032275.name: Recurrent shingles
HP:0032275.definition: Repeated episodes of a localized, painful cutaneous eruption related to reactivation of varicella zoster virus (VZV) and characterized by a characteristic rash in one or two adjacent dermatomes.

HP:0032276.name: Prominent subcalcaneal fat pad
HP:0032276.definition: Abnormally increased prominence of the fat pad underneath the heal. This feature can be appreciated in figure 1 of PMID:26769062.

HP:0032278.name: 2-hydroxyglutarate aciduria
HP:0032278.definition: The concentration of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0032281.name: Abnormal base excess
HP:0032281.definition: Deviation from the normal quantity of base excess, defined as the amount of strong acid (in millimoles per liter) that needs to be added in vitro to 1 liter of fully oxygenated whole blood to return a blood sample to standard conditions (pH of 7.40, Pco2 of 40 mm Hg, and temperature of 37 degrees C).

HP:0032282.name: Contact dermatitis
HP:0032282.definition: An inflammatory process in skin caused by an exogenous agent that directly or indirectly injure the skin. If the offending agent is identified and removed, the eruption will resolve. An unusual or patterned eruption may be a clue to the presence of a contact dermatitis. Patch testing may be helpful in the differential diagnosis.

HP:0032283.name: Disseminated nontuberculous mycobacterial infection
HP:0032283.definition: An infection with nontuberculous mycobacteria that affects multiple body sites. Such infections can occur in individuals with immune disease.

HP:0032284.name: Ultra-low vision with retained motion projection
HP:0032284.definition: Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to identify a moving object (typically hand motion at distance of 30 cm).

HP:0032285.name: Ultra-low vision with retained light projection
HP:0032285.definition: Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark. Also when light is projected in each of the four quadrants of the visual field, the individual is able to correctly identify the origin of the light stimulus.

HP:0032286.name: Ultra-low vision with retained light perception
HP:0032286.definition: Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark.

HP:0032287.name: Ultra-low vision with no light perception
HP:0032287.definition: Ultra-low vision with complete lack of light and form perception.

HP:0032288.name: Polyclonal elevation of circulating IgG
HP:0032288.definition: An increase in polyclonal immunoglobulins resulting from many different plasma cells. On serum electrophoresis, a polyclonal gammopathy is characterized by a broad diffuse band with one or more heavy chains and kappa and lambda light chains.

HP:0032289.name: Oligoclonal elevation of circulating IgG
HP:0032289.definition: An increase in circulating immunoglobulins characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032290.name: Monoclonal elevation of IgG
HP:0032290.definition: An increase in circulating immunoglobulins characterized by a single band in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032291.name: Monoclonal elevation of intact IgG
HP:0032291.definition: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has a normal structure with a light and heavy chain.

HP:0032292.name: Monoclonal elevation of IgG light chain
HP:0032292.definition: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a light chain but not a heavy chain.

HP:0032293.name: Monoclonal elevation of IgG heavy chain
HP:0032293.definition: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a heavy chain but not a light chain.

HP:0032294.name: Monoclonal elevation of IgG kappa chain
HP:0032294.definition: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a kappa light chain but not a heavy chain.

HP:0032295.name: Monoclonal elevation of IgG lambda chain
HP:0032295.definition: A type of monoclonal elevation of IgG in which the involved immunoglobulin has an abnormal structure with a lambda light chain but not a heavy chain.

HP:0032296.name: Increased circulating IgG subclass
HP:0032296.definition: An elevation of circulating IgG level predominantly related to an elevation of one of the four IgG subclasses.

HP:0032297.name: Increased circulating IgG3 level
HP:0032297.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG3 subtype in the blood circulation.

HP:0032298.name: Increased circulating IgG1 level
HP:0032298.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG1 subtype in the blood circulation.

HP:0032299.name: Increased circulating IgG2 level
HP:0032299.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG2 subtype in the blood circulation.

HP:0032300.name: Increased circulating IgG4 level
HP:0032300.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of the IgG4 subtype in the blood circulation.

HP:0032301.name: Genital warts
HP:0032301.definition: Warts affecting the skin in the genital area (penile shaft, scrotum, vagina, or labia majora). Warts can be small, beginning as a pinhead-size swelling that may become larger and take on a pedunculated appearance. Warts can spread and coalesce into large masses in the genital or anal area. Their color is variable but tends to be skin colored or darker, and they may occasionally bleed. Warts may cause itching, redness, or discomfort. An outbreak of genital warts may also cause psychological distress.

HP:0032302.name: Kappa Bence Jones proteinuria
HP:0032302.definition: The presence of free monoclonal kappa immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.

HP:0032303.name: Lambda Bence Jones proteinuria
HP:0032303.definition: The presence of free monoclonal lambda immunoglobulin light chains in the urine.

HP:0032304.name: Abnormal circulating mannose-binding protein concentration
HP:0032304.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of mannose-binding protein in the blood circulation.

HP:0032305.name: Decreased circulating mannose-binding protein concentration
HP:0032305.definition: Concentration of mannose-binding protein in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0032306.name: Increased circulating mannose-binding protein concentration
HP:0032306.definition: Concentration of mannose-binding protein in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0032308.name: Increased circulating procalcitonin concentration
HP:0032308.definition: An elevated concentration of procalcitonin in the blood circulation.

HP:0032309.name: Abnormal granulocyte count
HP:0032309.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of absolute number of granulocytes in the blood, per microliter, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0032310.name: Increased total granulocyte count
HP:0032310.definition: An increased count of granulocytes in the peripheral blood circulation.

HP:0032311.name: Increased circulating globulin level
HP:0032311.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of globulins in the blood.

HP:0032312.name: Decreased circulating globulin level
HP:0032312.definition: An abnormally reduced concentration of globulins in the blood.

HP:0032313.name: Frontotemporal hypertrichosis
HP:0032313.definition: Excessive, increased hair growth located in the region of the forehead and temple.

HP:0032314.name: Abnormal areolar morphology
HP:0032314.definition: An abnormal appearance or structure of the ring of pigmented skin that surrounds the nipple.

HP:0032315.name: Areolar fullness
HP:0032315.definition: The areola (ring of pigmented skin surrounding the nipple) is filled out so as to produce a rounded shape.

HP:0032316.name: Family history
HP:0032316.definition: Information about close relatives of an individual who is the proband of a study or who is being investigated with the goal of identifying a medical diagnosis. Usually, the family history includes information from three generations of relatives, including children, brothers and sisters, parents, aunts and uncles, nieces and nephews, grandparents, and cousins.

HP:0032317.name: Family history of cancer
HP:0032317.definition: A close blood relative had cancer.

HP:0032318.name: Family history of heart disease
HP:0032318.definition: A close blood relative had heart disease.

HP:0032319.name: Health status
HP:0032319.definition: Health status of a family member with respect to the disease being investigated in a proband.

HP:0032320.name: Affected
HP:0032320.definition: This term applies to a family member who is diagnosed with the same condition as the individual who is the primary focus of investigation (the proband).

HP:0032321.name: Unaffected
HP:0032321.definition: This term applies to a family member in whom the diagnosis that is the primary focus of investigation is excluded.

HP:0032322.name: Healthy
HP:0032322.definition: No history of any serious disease, including the disease being investigated in the proband.

HP:0032323.name: Periodic fever
HP:0032323.definition: Episodic fever that recurs at regular intervals.

HP:0032324.name: Non-periodic recurrent fever
HP:0032324.definition: Episodic fever that recurs at irregular intervals.

HP:0032325.name: Lacunar stroke
HP:0032325.definition: A stroke related to a small infarct (2-20 mm in diameter) in the deep cerebral white matter, basal ganglia, or pons, that is presumed to result from the occlusion of a single small perforating artery supplying the subcortical areas of the brain.

HP:0032326.name: Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus infection
HP:0032326.definition: Infection with staphylococcus aureus resistant to the antibiotic methicillin (MRSA). MRSA can infect any individual but is more common among hospitalized patients, and can also occur as an opportunistic infection.

HP:0032327.name: Interhemispheric cyst
HP:0032327.definition: Cystic collection (sac-like, fluid containing pocket of membranous tissue) located in the interhemispheric fissure, with or without communication with the ventricular system.

HP:0032328.name: Temporomandibular joint adhesion
HP:0032328.definition: Formation of one or more fibrous bands within the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) with resulting limitation of movement of the TMJ. Adhesions may be seen in degenerative processes that involve the TMJ.

HP:0032329.name: Increased urinary 11-deoxycortisol level
HP:0032329.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of 11-deoxycortisol in the urine.

HP:0032330.name: Increased urinary 11-deoxycorticosterone level
HP:0032330.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration or amount of 11-deoxycorticosterone in the urine.

HP:0032331.name: Increased urinary 11-deoxytetrahydrocorticosterone level
HP:0032331.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration or amount of 11-deoxytetrahydrocorticosterone the urine.

HP:0032332.name: Oligoclonal elevation of circulating IgM
HP:0032332.definition: An increase in circulating IgM characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase.

HP:0032333.name: Polyclonal elevation of circulating IgA
HP:0032333.definition: A heterogeneous increase in IgA mmunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.

HP:0032334.name: Oligoclonal elevation of circulating IgA
HP:0032334.definition: An increase in circulating IgA characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032335.name: Monoclonal elevation of circulating IgA
HP:0032335.definition: An increase in circulating IgA characterized by one predominant band in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032336.name: Increased circulating specific IgE antibody concentration

HP:0032337.name: Monoclonal elevated circulating IgE concentration
HP:0032337.definition: An increase in circulating IgE characterized by one predominant band in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032338.name: Oligoclonal elevated circulating IgE concentration
HP:0032338.definition: An increase in circulating IgE characterized by two or more bands in serum electrophoresis but not the broad diffuse band that characterizes a polyclonal increase in circulating immunoglobulins.

HP:0032339.name: Polyclonal elevated circulating IgE concentration
HP:0032339.definition: A heterogeneous increase in IgE mmunoglobulins characterized by a diffuse band on serum electrophoresis.

HP:0032341.name: Reduced forced vital capacity
HP:0032341.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal inspiration.

HP:0032342.name: Reduced forced expiratory volume in one second
HP:0032342.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can forcefully expel in one second.

HP:0032345.name: Elevated cancer Ag 19-9 level
HP:0032345.definition: An abnormal increased in the amount of the carbohydrate antigen 19-9, a recognizable sialo-ganglioside in the blood circulation.

HP:0032346.name: Cutaneous lichen amyloidosis
HP:0032346.definition: Lichen amyloidosis presents with multiple localized or rarely generalized, hyperpigmented grouped papules with a predilection for the shins, calves, ankles, and dorsa of the feet and thighs.

HP:0032347.name: Cutaneous macular amyloidosis
HP:0032347.definition: A type of cutaneous amyloidosis that is characterized by hyperpigmented patches with indefinite margins composed of grayish brown macules, often with a reticulated or rippled appearance.

HP:0032348.name: Cutaneous nodular amyloidosis
HP:0032348.definition: A type of cutaneous amyloidosis that is characterized clinically by waxy, purpuric plaques and nodules and histologically by amyloid deposits in the dermis and subcutaneous tissue.

HP:0032349.name: Serinuria
HP:0032349.definition: A increased concentration of serine in the urine.

HP:0032350.name: Sulfocysteinuria
HP:0032350.definition: A increased concentration of sulfocysteine in the urine.

HP:0032351.name: Phenylalaninuria
HP:0032351.definition: Increased level of phenylalanine in urine.

HP:0032352.name: Methioninuria
HP:0032352.definition: Level of methionine in urine above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0032353.name: Leucinuria
HP:0032353.definition: Increased level of leucine in urine.

HP:0032355.name: Decreased peak expiratory flow
HP:0032355.definition: A reduction in the maximum expiratory flow per minute, which can be used to measure how fast a subject can exhale as well as to judge the strength of the expiratory muscles and the condition of the large airways.

HP:0032356.name: Decreased pre-bronchodilator forced vital capacity
HP:0032356.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal insipiration, with the test being performed before the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

HP:0032357.name: Decreased post-bronchodilator forced vital capacity
HP:0032357.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can expel following maximal insipiration, with the test being performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

HP:0032358.name: Decreased post-bronchodilator forced expiratory volume in one second
HP:0032358.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of air a person can forcefully expel in one second, with the test being performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

HP:0032359.name: Decreased forced expiratory flow 25-75%
HP:0032359.definition: A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled.

HP:0032360.name: Decreased pre-bronchodilator forced expiratory flow 25-75%
HP:0032360.definition: A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled. Here, the test is performed before the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

HP:0032361.name: Decreased post-bronchodilator forced expiratory flow 25-75%
HP:0032361.definition: A reduction compared to the predicted value of the forced expiratory flow over the middle one-half of the FVC; the average flow from the point at which 25% of the FVC has been exhaled to the point at which 75% of the FVC has been exhaled. Here, the test is performed after the administration of a bronchodilating medication.

HP:0032362.name: Increased circulating corticosterone level
HP:0032362.definition: An abnormally elevated concentration of corticosterone in the blood.

HP:0032363.name: Decreased circulating corticosterone level
HP:0032363.definition: An abnormally reduced concentration of corticosterone in the blood.

HP:0032364.name: obsolete Abnormal CSF amino acid level

HP:0032365.name: Exacerbated by aspirin exposure
HP:0032365.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by ingestion of aspirin.

HP:0032366.name: Positive direct antiglobulin test
HP:0032366.definition: A positive result of the direct antiglobulin test (DAT), a method of demonstrating the presence of antibody or complement bound to red blood cell (RBC) membranes by the use of anti-human globulin to form a visible agglutination reaction.

HP:0032367.name: Abnormal growth hormone level
HP:0032367.definition: Any deviation from the normal level of growth hormone (GH) in the blood circulation. GH or somatotropin is a peptide hormone that stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and cell regeneration. Its secretion from the pituitary is regulated by the neurosecretory nuclei of the hypothalamus, which can release Growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH or somatocrinin) and Growth hormone-inhibiting hormone (GHIH or somatostatin) into the hypophyseal portal venous blood surrounding the pituitary. GH is secreted in a pulsatile manner, which is one of the reasons why an isolated measurement of its blood concentration is not meaningful.

HP:0032368.name: Acidemia
HP:0032368.definition: An abnormally low blood pH (usually defined as less than 7.35).

HP:0032369.name: Alkalemia
HP:0032369.definition: An abnormally high blood pH (usually defined as 7.41 or above).

HP:0032370.name: Blood group A
HP:0032370.definition: ABO phenotype A, corresponding to the genotype AO or AA.

HP:0032371.name: Isoleucinuria
HP:0032371.definition: An increased concentration of isoleucine in the urine.

HP:0032372.name: Increased peripheral blast count
HP:0032372.definition: An increased count in the peripheral blood of cells that are precursors to mature circulating blood cells such as neutrophiles, monocytes, lymphocutes, and erythrocytes. Blasts are not usually found in significant numbers in the peripheral blood circulation, but can be observed in hematopoietic neoplasms such as leukemia, severe infections, and as a result of certain medications.

HP:0032373.name: Duffy blood group
HP:0032373.definition: The Duffy blood group system is based on the presence of a glycoprotein termed Fy that is on the surface of erythrocytes and some other cells. There are two Duffy antigens named Fya and Fyb, and thus there are four Duffy phenotypes: a+b+, a+b-, a-b+,a-b-.

HP:0032374.name: Duffy Fya positivity
HP:0032374.definition: Presence of the Duffy Fya antigen.

HP:0032375.name: Duffy Fyb positivity
HP:0032375.definition: Presence of the Duffy Fyb antigen.

HP:0032376.name: Anti-beta 2 glycoprotein I antibody positivity
HP:0032376.definition: Presence of antibodies against beta 2 glycoprotein I in the circulation. Beta-2 glycoprotein I (beta2GPI) is the principal target of autoantibodies in the antiphospholipid syndrome (APS).

HP:0032377.name: Increased urinary orosomucoid
HP:0032377.definition: An increased concentration in the urine of alpha-1-acid glycoprotein (AGP), also known as orosomucoid (ORM). AGP is a 41-43-kDa glycoprotein with a pI of 2.8-3.8. AGP is an acute-phase protein that has many activities including, but not limited to, acting as an acute-phase reactant and disease marker, modulating immunity, binding and carrying drugs, maintaining the barrier function of capillary, and mediating the sphingolipid metabolism.

HP:0032378.name: Immediate-type hypersensitivity drug reaction
HP:0032378.definition: Hypersensitivity that is observed within 1 hr of exposures. A variety of adverse reactions can occur within minutes to hours of exposure to a drug. Some can be related to the pharmacological action of the drug (WHO Adverse Reaction Terminology type A for augmented) and usually have a low mortality. Others are not readily predictable based on the structure and pharmacological action of the drug and have a relatively high mortality risk (Type B for bizarre). The most serious form of immediate onset drug hypersensitivity reaction, anaphylaxis. Other reactions including itching, dizziness/light-headedness, nausea, chest discomfort but without any objective skin features, physical signs or physiological compromise. Skin only reactions include generalized erythema, urticaria or angioedema without any sentinel features (see below) of other organ involvement.

HP:0032379.name: Polymorphous light eruption
HP:0032379.definition: The cardinal symptom is severely pruritic skin lesions. Macular, papular, papulovesicular, urticarial, multiforme- and plaque-like variants are differentiated morphologically, hence the name polymorphous. Usually one morphology dominates in a single individual (monomorphous). The skin lesions develop a few hours to several days after sun exposure. Initially, patchy erythema develops, accompanied by pruritus. Distinct lesions then develop. The upper chest, upper arms, backs of the hands, thighs, and the sides of the face are the primary localizations. The skin lesions resolve spontaneously within several days of ceasing sun exposure and do not leave behind any traces.

HP:0032381.name: Hydroa vacciniforme
HP:0032381.definition: In response to the spring sun distinct inflamed reddened skin develops on the ears, nose, cheeks, fingers, backs of the hands, and the lower arms, on which blisters with serous or hemorrhagic content develop. These dry out with the formation of a blackish scab. After shedding of the scab, depressed, varioliform, often hypopigmented scars remain. In addition, hyper- and hypopigmentation are present together, resulting in a polymorphous skin presentation.

HP:0032382.name: Uniparental disomy
HP:0032382.definition: Inheritance of both homologues of a chromosome pair from the same parent.

HP:0032383.name: Uniparental heterodisomy
HP:0032383.definition: A type of uniparental disomy in which the two different chromosomes (or chromosome segments) of the same parent are transmitted.

HP:0032384.name: Uniparental isodisomy
HP:0032384.definition: A type of uniparental disomy in which the two identical chromosomes (or chromosome segments) of the same parent are transmitted.

HP:0032385.name: Abnormal circulating transferrin concentration
HP:0032385.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.

HP:0032386.name: Elevated circulating transferrin concentration
HP:0032386.definition: An abnormally increased concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.

HP:0032387.name: Reduced circulating transferrin concentration
HP:0032387.definition: An abnormally decreased concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.

HP:0032388.name: Periventricular nodular heterotopia
HP:0032388.definition: Nodules of heterotopia along the ventricular walls. There can be a single nodule or a large number of nodules, they can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, they can be small or large, single or multiple.

HP:0032389.name: Periventricular laminar heterotopia
HP:0032389.definition: A large mass of heterotopia in a laminar configuration along the ventricular walls. Usually bilateral.

HP:0032390.name: Periventricular ribbonlike heterotopia
HP:0032390.definition: Heterotopia that forms a continuous wavy line along the ventricular wall.

HP:0032391.name: Subcortical heterotopia
HP:0032391.definition: A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.

HP:0032392.name: Nodular subcortical heterotopia in peritrigonal regions
HP:0032392.definition: Solid nodular heterotopia situated in the region of the peritrigonal optic pathway posterior to the deep gray nuclei.

HP:0032393.name: Diffuse ribbon-like subcortical heterotopia
HP:0032393.definition: Subcortical heterotopia consisting of a bilateral and symmetric single continuous, undulating ribbon-like layer of gray matter located in the frontal, parietal and occipital lobes. It has no visible connection to the overlying cortex.

HP:0032394.name: Mesial parasagittal subcortical heterotopia
HP:0032394.definition: Subcortical heterotopia extending along the mesial aspect of the lateral ventricles, with direct connection to mesial polymicrogyria-like cortex at the anterior and posterior limits of the heterotopia.

HP:0032395.name: Curvilinear subcortical heterotopia
HP:0032395.definition: Large subcortical heterotopia of variable morphology with streaks and swirls. These always connect to the overlying cortex in at least one, but usually in multiple, locations. Spaces with the signal intensity of CSF are usually seen within the heterotopia.

HP:0032396.name: Transmantle columnar heterotopia
HP:0032396.definition: Linear heterotopia spanning from the cerebral mantle from the pia to the ependyma.

HP:0032397.name: Citrullinuria
HP:0032397.definition: The amount of citrulline in the urine, when normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0032398.name: Dysgyria
HP:0032398.definition: An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation.

HP:0032399.name: Dysgyria with normal cortical thickness
HP:0032399.definition: An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation but with a normal thickness of the cortex.

HP:0032400.name: Dysgyria with thickened cortex
HP:0032400.definition: An abnormal gyral pattern characterized by abnormalities of sulcal depth or orientation and a thickened cortex intermediate between pachygyria and polymicrogyria.

HP:0032401.name: Aspartic aciduria
HP:0032401.definition: A increased concentration of aspartic acid in the urine.

HP:0032403.name: Asparaginuria
HP:0032403.definition: An increased concentration of asparagine in the urine.

HP:0032404.name: Testicular mass
HP:0032404.definition: An abnormal bulge or lump in a testis. A testicular mass has a long differential diagnosis including testicular torsion, epididymitis, acute orchitis, strangulated hernia and testicular cancer.

HP:0032405.name: Increased urinary phosphoserine level
HP:0032405.definition: An increased level of phosphoserine in the urine.

HP:0032406.name: Unilateral perisylvian polymicrogyria
HP:0032406.definition: A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that largely affects one side of the brain.

HP:0032407.name: Bilateral perisylvian polymicrogyria
HP:0032407.definition: A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that affects both sides of the brain.

HP:0032408.name: Breast mass
HP:0032408.definition: A breast lump is any discrete mass in a breast noticed by the patient, significant other, or physician.

HP:0032409.name: Subcortical band heterotopia
HP:0032409.definition: A form of subcortical heterotopia with mislocalized gray matter within the white matter.It is defined as longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter. It is part of the lissencephaly spectrum.

HP:0032410.name: Bilateral generalized polymicrogyria
HP:0032410.definition: Symmetric generalized polymicrogyria with no obvious gradient or region of maximal severity; may have abnormal high signal in white matter.

HP:0032411.name: Posterior predominant subcortical band heterotopia
HP:0032411.definition: Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the occipital cortex.

HP:0032412.name: Anterior predominant subcortical band heterotopia
HP:0032412.definition: Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible in the frontal and temporal lobes.

HP:0032413.name: Diffuse subcortical band heterotopia
HP:0032413.definition: Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the whole brain.

HP:0032414.name: Hydroxylysinuria
HP:0032414.definition: The presence of an elevated amount of 5-hydroxylysine in the urine. This compound is a hydroxylated derivative of the amino acid lysine that is present in certain collagens.

HP:0032415.name: Parasagittal parieto-occipital polymicrogyria
HP:0032415.definition: Polymicrogyria in parasagittal and mesial aspects of parieto-occipital cortex.

HP:0033230.name: Biceps areflexia
HP:0033230.definition: Inability to elicit biceps tendon reflex.

HP:0033231.name: Abnormal glomerular mesangial cellularity
HP:0033231.definition: Abnormal number of its constituent cells of the mesangium of the glomerulus of the kidney.

HP:0033232.name: Abnormal glomerular mesangial matrix morphology
HP:0033232.definition: Any structural anomaly of the glomerular matrix. Mesangial cells generate and embed in their own extracellular matrix. The mesangial matrix is different in composition from the glomerular basement membrane. Its constituents are type IV collagen (but only the alpha1 and alpha2 chains); type V collagen; laminin A, B1, and B2; and considerable amounts of fibronectin, heparan sulfate and chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans, entactin, and nidogen. Furthermore, small amounts of the proteoglycans decorin and biglycan are found in the mesangial matrix.

HP:0033233.name: Paramesangial deposits
HP:0033233.definition: Mesangial immune deposit located adjacent to the paramesangial glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033234.name: Mesangial hyaline deposition
HP:0033234.definition: Extracellular mesangial accumulation of moderately electron-dense, generally homogenous, amorphous-appearing extracellular material.

HP:0033236.name: Cognitive fatigue
HP:0033236.definition: A failure to sustain attention that requires self-motivation to optimize performance.

HP:0033237.name: Visceral epithelial cell detachment
HP:0033237.definition: Detachment of visceral epithelial cells (podocytes) from underlying glomerular basement membrane with intervening new loose basement membrane material (pale on Hematoxylin and eosin, periodic acid-Shiff, trichrome, or silver stain) forming a so-called 'halo'.

HP:0033238.name: Podocyte microvillous transformation
HP:0033238.definition: Cytoplasmic projections into the urinary space from the luminal side of the podocyte.

HP:0033239.name: Visceral epithelial cell capping
HP:0033239.definition: Layer of hypertrophied visceral epithelial cells overlying a sclerosed segment of the tuft of the glomerulus.

HP:0033240.name: Elevated RV/TLC ratio
HP:0033240.definition: An increase in the ratio of residual volume (RV) to total lung capacity (TLC) on pulmonary function testing. RV is the amount of air remaining aftermaximal expiration and TLC is the total amount of air in theungs at full inspiration. These volumes cannot be determined by spirometry, but can be measured by inert gas dilution, nitrogen washout, and (3) body plethysmography. An elevated RV/TLC can be interpreted as a sign of air trapping and hyperinflation.

HP:0033241.name: Polyalveolar lobe
HP:0033241.definition: An elevation of the total count of alveoli as determined by microscopic point-counting of randomly taken lung sections, not secondary to abnormalities in number, size and structure of the airways. In polyaveolar lobe, the number of alveoli is generally increased three to fivefold.

HP:0033242.name: Horseshoe lung
HP:0033242.definition: A horseshoe lung is an uncommon congenital abnormality caused by the partial fusion of the bases of both lungs behind the pericardial sac.

HP:0033243.name: Pulmonary necrosis
HP:0033243.definition: Cellular death affecting one or more parts of the lung. Necrosis is caused by diverse external and internal factors which result in the unregulated digestion of cell components.

HP:0033244.name: Glycogen accumulation in pulmonary interstitial cells
HP:0033244.definition: Accumulation of immature interstitial cells containing abundant cytoplasmic glycogen defined by periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) positive cells.

HP:0033245.name: Abnormal alveolar type II pneumocyte morphology
HP:0033245.definition: Any structural abnormality of alveolar type 2 (ATII) cells.

HP:0033246.name: Type II pneumocyte hypertrophy
HP:0033246.definition: Increase in size of type II pneumocytes, characterized by qualitative morphologic alterations, including cuboidal shapes, increased nucleocytoplasmic ratio, enlarged nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and various alterations in their nuclear chromatin.

HP:0033247.name: Pulmonary amyloidosis
HP:0033247.definition: Extracellular deposition in lung tissue of a proteinaceous material that, when stained with Congo red, demonstrates apple-green birefringence under polarized light and that has a distinct color when stained with sulfated Alcian blue. Viewed with electron microscopy, the amyloid deposits are seen to be composed of a beta-sheet fibrillar material. These nonbranching fibrils have a diameter of 7.5 to 10 nm and are the result of protein misfolding.

HP:0033248.name: Multiple pulmonary interstitial hyalinized nodules
HP:0033248.definition: Fibrosing nodules, consisting of either unilateral or bilateral central whorled deposits of lamellar collagen hyalin.

HP:0033249.name: Focal substantia nigra T2 hyperintensity
HP:0033249.definition: Hyperintense lesion in the substantia nigra on magnetic resonance T2 imaging.

HP:0033250.name: Nailfold capillary tortuosity
HP:0033250.definition: An increased number of turns of the blood vessels of the nailfold with a charactereistic winded or twisted appearance of the blood vessels.

HP:0033251.name: Elevated residual volume
HP:0033251.definition: Increase in the amount of air remaining in a person's lungs after full exhalation.

HP:0033252.name: Palmar hyperlinearity
HP:0033252.definition: Exaggerated skin markings (dermatoglyphics) on the palms of the hand.

HP:0033253.name: Reduced circulating interferon gamma concentration
HP:0033253.definition: A reduction in the concentration of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.

HP:0033254.name: Anorectal stricture
HP:0033254.definition: Narrowing of the anorectum associated with inflammation or scar tissue.

HP:0033255.name: Congenital lobar overinflation
HP:0033255.definition: A congenital malformation characterized by an overdistended segment of lung, affecting an party of a lobe or the entire one. It results in progressive overinflation of one or more lobes.

HP:0033257.name: Delayed ability to walk with support
HP:0033257.definition: A failure to achieve the ability to walk with support (cruise) at an appropriate developmental stage.

HP:0033258.name: Sudden unexpected death in epilepsy
HP:0033258.definition: Sudden unexpected death in epilepsy (SUDEP) is a sudden, unexpected, witnessed or unwitnessed, non-traumatic and non-drowning death, occurring in benign circumstances, in an individual with epilepsy, with or without evidence for a seizure and excluding documented status epilepticus, in which postmortem examination has not revealed a cause of death.

HP:0033259.name: Non-motor seizure
HP:0033259.definition: A seizure with clinical manifestation but without motor signs (other than possible behavior arrest) as its initial clinical manifestation. The electrographic onset may be generalized, focal, or unknown.

HP:0033260.name: Livedo racemosa
HP:0033260.definition: Livedo racemosa describes a reddish-blue mottling of the skin in an irregular, reticular pattern. It differs from the more common livedo reticularis by its shape. Livedo racemosa consists of broken circular segments resulting in a seemingly larger pattern, as opposed to the fine, regular, complete network of livedo reticularis. Livedo racemosa results from permanent impairment of peripheral blood flow and, unlike livedo reticularis, it persists on warming.

HP:0033261.name: Renal artery aneurysm
HP:0033261.definition: Increase in diameter of a segment of the renal artery that can be defined as a focal, isolated dilatation of all three layers of the arterial wall over 1.5 times the diameter of the disease-free proximal adjacent arterial segment.

HP:0033262.name: Transphyseal fracture of the distal humerus
HP:0033262.definition: A fracture through the distal humeral physis that separates the entire distal humeral epiphysis from the metaphysis.

HP:0033263.name: Absent platelet dense granules
HP:0033263.definition: Lack of platelet dense granules, a type of platelet organelles.

HP:0033264.name: Enlarged platelet dense granules
HP:0033264.definition: Increased size of platelet dense granules.

HP:0033265.name: Podocyte myelin figures
HP:0033265.definition: Lamellated intracytoplasmic lipid inclusions within podocytes.

HP:0033266.name: Glomerular pseudocrescent
HP:0033266.definition: Visceral epithelial cell hyperplasia with resulting cellular crowding of the the urinary space. In contrast with true crescents, these proliferations lack inflammatory cells and fibrin. The cells are typically plump (not spindle-shaped) and often vacuolated, and Bowman's capsule is usually intact.

HP:0033267.name: Abnormal glomerular capillary lumen morphology
HP:0033267.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space of the capillary of the renal glomerulus.

HP:0033268.name: Deflation of the glomerular tuft
HP:0033268.definition: Wrinkling and folding of the capillaries without epithelial cell (podocyte) hyperplasia (formerly called ischemic type of collapse) involving o 80% of the glomerular tuft. The wrinkling is generally made by small regular folds of the glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033269.name: Glomerular capillary collapse
HP:0033269.definition: Collapse is generally accompanied by other descriptors such as hypertrophy and hyperplasia of overlying glomerular epithelial cells, halo, protein droplets in podocytes and glomerular parietal epithelial cells (PECs).

HP:0033270.name: Glomerular capillary congestion
HP:0033270.definition: Global distention of glomerular capillaries with intraluminal intact red blood cells.

HP:0033271.name: Glomerular capillary microaneurysm
HP:0033271.definition: Glomerular capillary dilatation due to loosening/detachment of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) from its anchoring points, usually in the context of mesangiolysis or nodular glomerulosclerosis.

HP:0033272.name: Abnormal glomerular endothelial cell morphology
HP:0033272.definition: An abnormal structure of the glomerular endothelial cells, which are highly specialized cells with fenestrae and a charged luminal glycocalyx layer that contribute to the filtration barrier.

HP:0033273.name: Loss of glomerular endothelial cell fenestration
HP:0033273.definition: Loss of round to oval discontinuities normally present in the glomerular capillary endothelial cell cytoplasm.

HP:0033274.name: Glomerular endotheliosis
HP:0033274.definition: Enlargement of glomerular endothelial cells by cytoplasmic swelling with resulting partial or complete occlusion of the lumen.

HP:0033275.name: Glomerular endothelial tubuloreticular inclusion
HP:0033275.definition: Inter-anastomosing tubular structures located within cisternae of endoplasmic reticulum, most often within endothelial cells and associated with exposure to interferon.

HP:0033277.name: Glomerular fibrinoid necrosis
HP:0033277.definition: Fibrin associated with glomerular basement membrane disruption and/or lysis of the mesangial matrix; this lesion does not require the presence of karyorrhexis.

HP:0033278.name: Reduced CD95-induced lymphocyte apoptosis
HP:0033278.definition: Reduced amount of programmed cell death in peripheral blood lymphocytes following exposure to CD95 (APO-1/Fas), which is a member of the death receptor family, a subfamily of the TNF-R superfamily. Crosslinking of CD95 with its natural ligand CD95L (CD178) or with agonistic antibodies such as anti-APO-1 induces apoptosis in sensitive cells.

HP:0033279.name: Enterocutaneous fistula
HP:0033279.definition: An abnormal connection (fistula) between the intra-abdominal intestinal tract and the skin.

HP:0033280.name: Paratracheal lymphadenopathy
HP:0033280.definition: Enlargement of lymph nodes surrounding the trachea.

HP:0033281.name: Circulating nucleated red blood cells
HP:0033281.definition: The presence of nucleated red blood cells in the peripheral blood circulation.

HP:0033282.name: Abnormal glomerular basement membrane morphology
HP:0033282.definition: Any abnormal sttructure of the glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033283.name: Segmentally thickened glomerular basement membrane
HP:0033283.definition: Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting a segmental and increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by EM. Thickening is measured from endothelial to visceral epithelial plasma membrane and mainly attributable to an increase in thickness of the lamina densa, generally to an overall thickness more than 2 standard deviations greater than that of the normal mean GBM thickness for health age- and sex matched individuals.

HP:0033284.name: Diffusely thickened glomerular basement membrane
HP:0033284.definition: Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by EM. Thickening is measured from endothelial to visceral epithelial plasma membrane and mainly attributable to an increase in thickness of the lamina densa, generally to an overall thickness more than 2 standard deviations greater than that of the normal mean GBM thickness for health age- and sex matched individuals.

HP:0033285.name: Thickened glomerular basement membranes with no electron dense deposits
HP:0033285.definition: Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by electron microscopy.

HP:0033286.name: Thickened glomerular basement membranes with electron dense deposits

HP:0033287.name: Glomerular basement membrane lucencies
HP:0033287.definition: Lucent zones within the glomerular basement membranes. May reflect remote/resolved deposits.

HP:0033289.name: Glomerular basement membrane wrinkling
HP:0033289.definition: Irregular folding of the glomerular basement membrane with an intact lamina densa.

HP:0033290.name: Glomerular subendothelial widening
HP:0033290.definition: Expansion of the space between the glomerular endothelium and lamina densa by electron-lucent material.

HP:0033291.name: Glomerular karyhorrhectic debris
HP:0033291.definition: Apoptotic, pyknotic, and fragmented nuclei within the glomerulus.

HP:0033292.name: Glomerular fibrin thrombus
HP:0033292.definition: An aggregate of coagulated blood containing fibrin, with or without entrapped cellular elements, within a glomerular capillary lumen.

HP:0033293.name: Glomerular hyaline pseudothrombus
HP:0033293.definition: Intracapillary amorphous, eosinophilic material consisting of immune deposits.

HP:0033294.name: Glomerular lipoprotein thrombus
HP:0033294.definition: Intracapillary silver-positive material that is finely vacuolated and laminated, and stains with oil red O on frozen sections.

HP:0033295.name: Mesangial Immune complex deposition
HP:0033295.definition: Extracellular meangial accumulation of finely granular material corresponding to immunoglobulin and/or complement by immunofluorescence/immunohistochemistry; most typically electron-dense although this may decrease with resorption of the deposit.

HP:0033296.name: Binucleated visceral epithelial cells
HP:0033296.definition: Visceral epithelial cells with 2 nuclei. Can be observed on light or ultrastructral microscopy.

HP:0033297.name: Multinucleated visceral epithelial cells
HP:0033297.definition: Visceral epithelial cells with more than two nuclei. Can be observed on light or ultrastructral microscopy.

HP:0033298.name: Abnormal circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
HP:0033298.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration in blood of factor H-related protein 1 (FHR-1)

HP:0033299.name: Reduced circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
HP:0033299.definition: Decreased level of circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration in the blood circulation.

HP:0033300.name: Increased circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
HP:0033300.definition: Elevated level of circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration in the blood circulation.

HP:0033301.name: Elevated circulating 1-methylhistidine concentration
HP:0033301.definition: An abnormally increased level of 1-methylhistidine in the blood circulation. 1-methylhistidine is a derivative of L-histidine.

HP:0033302.name: Elevated circulating 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid concentration
HP:0033302.definition: The concentration of 4-Hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033303.name: Elevated urinary monocarboxylic acid level
HP:0033303.definition: Abnormally increased amount of a monocarboxylic acid in the urine. Monocarboxylic acids are molecules with one COOH functional group.

HP:0033305.name: Abnormal circulating fetuin A concentration
HP:0033305.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of fetuin A in the blood circulation.

HP:0033306.name: Decreased circulating fetuin A concentration
HP:0033306.definition: A reduction below normal of fetuin A in the blood circulation.

HP:0033307.name: Increased circulating fetuin A concentration
HP:0033307.definition: An elevation above normal of fetuin A in the blood circulation.

HP:0033309.name: Ileoileal intussusception
HP:0033309.definition: A type of intussusception of the small intestine in which one part of the ileum invaginates (telescopes) into another part of the ileum.

HP:0033310.name: Osmotic diarrhea
HP:0033310.definition: Osmotic diarrhea results from the presence of osmotically active, poorly absorbed solutes in the bowel lumen that inhibit normal water and electrolyte absorption.

HP:0033311.name: Abdominal aortic dissection
HP:0033311.definition: A tear in the intimal layer of the abdominal aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers.

HP:0033312.name: Abnormal Bowman space morphology
HP:0033312.definition: Structural anomaly located in Bowman's space, which represents the beginning of the urinary space and is contiguous with the proximal convoluted tubule of the nephron.

HP:0033313.name: Urinary space collagenization
HP:0033313.definition: Acellular collagenous matrix within Bowman's space, not associated with extracapillary hypercellularity or necrosis, associated with sclerosis or deflation of the tuft.

HP:0033314.name: Visceral epithelial cell hyperplasia
HP:0033314.definition: Increased number of visceral epithelial cells (2 or more layers), often with crowding and multilayering, but without continuity with the parietal epithelium.

HP:0033315.name: Visceral epithelial hyaline droplets
HP:0033315.definition: Round to ovoid, Periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, fuchsinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions within visceral epithelial cells.

HP:0033316.name: Glomerular crescent formation
HP:0033316.definition: Glomerular crescent refers hyperplastic lesions involving 10% or more of the circumference of Bowman's capsule. Crescents can be composed of a variable mixture of epithelial/leukocyte hypercellularity, fibrous matrix, and fibrin.

HP:0033317.name: Cellular crescent
HP:0033317.definition: A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary hypercellularity of greater than two cell layers and involving more than 10% of the capsular circumference, composed of greater than 75% cells with or without fibrin, and less than 25% fibrous matrix.

HP:0033318.name: Fibrocellular crescent
HP:0033318.definition: A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary hypercellularity of more than 2 cell layers and involving over 10% of the capsular circumference, composed of 25% to 75% cells with or without fibrin, and the remainder fibrous matrix.

HP:0033319.name: Fibrous crescent
HP:0033319.definition: A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary fibrosis composed of greater than 75% matrix and of less than 25% cells with or without fibrin, usually associated with disruption of Bowman's capsule and involving over 10% of the capsular circumference.

HP:0033320.name: Mesangial cell loss
HP:0033320.definition: Loss of mesangial cells segmentally or globally.

HP:0033321.name: Glomerular obsolescence
HP:0033321.definition: Globally sclerotic glomeruli are that are small and without hyalinosis and may appear with collapse of the tuft with collagenization of the urinary space. Bowman's capsule is completely or partially absent and there is no periglomerular fibrosis and glomerular size is decreased by more than 50% compared to all other glomeruli in the same biopsy. Obsolescent glomeruli may appear to be receding into the interstitium.

HP:0033322.name: Glomerular capillary wall duplication without cellular interposition
HP:0033322.definition: Double contouring of the original glomerular basement membrane (GBM)/additional layer(s) of overlying basement membrane matrix, with or without endocapillary hypercellularity and no evidence of interposed migrated cells (mesangial, endothelial, monocytes) between the layers of original GBM and de novo GBM.

HP:0033323.name: Glomerular capillary wall duplication with cellular interposition
HP:0033323.definition: Double contouring of the original glomerular basement membrane (GBM)/additional layer(s) of overlying basement membrane matrix with interposed migrated cells (mesangial, endothelial, monocytes) between the layers of original GBM and de novo GBM.

HP:0033324.name: Elevated circulating homovanillic acid concentration
HP:0033324.definition: The concentration of homovanillic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033325.name: Elevated circulating sebacic acid concentration
HP:0033325.definition: Increased concentration of sebacic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0033326.name: Elevated circulating hydroxyphenlyllactic acid concentration
HP:0033326.definition: An increased concentration of 4-hydroxyphenlyllactic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0033327.name: Nail psoriasis
HP:0033327.definition: Psoriatic nail abnormality characterized by the presence of neutrophils in the nail bed epithelium, hyperkeratosis with parakeratosis, presence of exudates on the corneal epithelium, focal hypogranulosis and psoriasiform hyperplasia of the nail bed.

HP:0033328.name: Type II pneumocyte hyperplasia
HP:0033328.definition: Increase in the number of type II pneumocytes.

HP:0033329.name: Abnormal postural reflex
HP:0033329.definition: Anomaly of the physiological response to maintain the body's posture when movement and position is altered.

HP:0033330.name: Impaired neck-righting reflex
HP:0033330.definition: Abnormal neck-righting response, which is said to be a physiological response when a child is placed flat on his or her back and the head is turned 90 degrees to the right or the left. With a normal neck-righting response, there follows a reflected torsion of the vertebral column in the same direction as the induced rotation of the neck. That is, the whole body follows the direction in which the head was turned. The response is present from birth to the age of five years.

HP:0033331.name: Acute phase response
HP:0033331.definition: Presence of one or more manifestations of the acute phase response. Acute phase proteins (APP) are blood proteins primarily synthesized by hepatocytes as part of the acute phase response (APR). The APR is part of the early-defense or innate immune system, which is triggered by different stimuli including trauma, infection, stress, neoplasia, and inflammation. The APR results in a complex systemic reaction with the goal of reestablishing homeostasis and promoting healing.

HP:0033332.name: Elevated circulating amyloid A concentration
HP:0033332.definition: The concentration of serum amyloid A in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033333.name: Jaw contracture
HP:0033333.definition: Limitation of motion of the jaw due to structural changes in a muscle such as the massseter responsible for jaw movement.

HP:0033334.name: Abnormal embryonic development
HP:0033334.definition: An anomaly in the development of the embryo, that is, of the early developmental stage of development that follows the fertilization of an egg by sperm.

HP:0033335.name: Abnormal preimplantation embryonic development
HP:0033335.definition: An anomaly in the development of the embryo in a stage prior to implantation.

HP:0033336.name: Zygotic cleavage failure
HP:0033336.definition: Failure of a fertilized oocyte to undergo the first round of cell division.

HP:0033337.name: Abnormal gametogenesis
HP:0033337.definition: An anomaly in the process by a a haploid cell is formed from a diploid cells through meiosis. In males, diploid spermatogonia produce two haploid cells (secondary spermatocytes) in meiosis I and four haploid spermatids in meiosis II. In females, primordial germ cells under meiosis II before birth to form primary oocytes. Once puberty cell begins, these cells form secondary oocytes through meiosis II.

HP:0033339.name: Increased circulating inosine concentration
HP:0033339.definition: An increased concentration of inosine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033340.name: Increased circulating guanosine concentration
HP:0033340.definition: Increased concentration of guanosine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033341.name: Elevated circulating sitosterol concentration
HP:0033341.definition: An increased concentration of beta-sitosterol in the blood circulation.

HP:0033342.name: Anti-aquaporin 4 antibody positivity
HP:0033342.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against aquaporin-4.

HP:0033343.name: Mucoid diarrhea
HP:0033343.definition: Passage of an increased number of stools containing mucus, a thick fluid substance secreted by mucous membranes.

HP:0033344.name: Pleural cobblestoning
HP:0033344.definition: A pleural cobblestone appearance characterized by irregular bumps surrounded by depressed lines in open lung biopsy. Caused by underlying scarring causing retraction of the interlobular septa where they insert on the pleura.

HP:0033345.name: Neuralgia
HP:0033345.definition: Pain (An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience) along the course of a nerve.

HP:0033346.name: Psychic epileptic aura
HP:0033346.definition: Aura with affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual phenomena including illusory or composite hallucinatory events.

HP:0033347.name: Cognitive epileptic aura
HP:0033347.definition: A purely subjective manifestation of an epileptic seizure pertaining to altered cognition.

HP:0033348.name: Epileptic aura
HP:0033348.definition: An epileptic aura is a purely subjective clinical manifestation of an epileptic seizure. If an epileptic aura is not followed by loss of awareness or propagation to a bilateral tonic-clonic seizure then it is a type of focal aware non-motor seizure.

HP:0033349.name: Seizure cluster
HP:0033349.definition: A fourfold or greater increase of usual seizure frequency within a 3-day period, where the patient demonstrates full recovery between seizure events within the cluster. The seizure cluster should be recognizable by the primary clinician, carer or patient.

HP:0033350.name: Elevated forced expiratory volume in one second
HP:0033350.definition: An increase in the amount of air a person can forcefully expel in one second, compared to some standard or previous measure of same subject.

HP:0033351.name: Candida esophagitis
HP:0033351.definition: Candida infections of the esophagus are considered opportunistic infections and are seen most commonly in immunosuppressed patients, the most common symptoms being dysphagia, odynophagia, and retrosternal pain.

HP:0033352.name: Pulmonary hypertensive crisis
HP:0033352.definition: Pulmonary hypertensive crisis involves sudden and potentially lethal increases in PAP and PVR that cause acute rise in right atrial and right ventricular end-diastolic pressure accompanied by low cardiac output.

HP:0033353.name: Abnormal blood vessel morphology
HP:0033353.definition: Any structural anomaly of a blood vessel (artery, arteriole, capillary, venule, or vein).

HP:0033354.name: Abnormal urine metabolite level
HP:0033354.definition: Any deviation from the normal amount of a metabolite in urine.

HP:0033355.name: Increased urine deoxypyridinoline level
HP:0033355.definition: An increased level of deoxypyridinoline in the urine. Deoxypyridinoline is a crosslink product of collagen molecules found in bone and excreted in urine during bone degradation, has been described as a marker of bone turnover.

HP:0033356.name: Elevated circulating o-phosphoserine concentration
HP:0033356.definition: An abnormally increased level of o-phosphoserine in the blood circulation. o-phosphoserine is a derivative of serine.

HP:0033357.name: Limited head rotation
HP:0033357.definition: Reduced range of motion turning the head side to side.

HP:0033358.name: Abnormal urine osmolality
HP:0033358.definition: A deviation from the normal range of concentration of particles in urine.

HP:0033359.name: Hyperosthenuria
HP:0033359.definition: An abnormally high urinary specific gravity, i.e., increased concentration of solutes in the urine.

HP:0033360.name: Impaired ability to shift attention
HP:0033360.definition: A behavioral abnormality whereby a person is unable to move freely from one situation, activity or aspect of aa problem to another as circumstances demand. Key aspects of shifting include the ability to make transitions, problem solve flexibly, switch or alternate attention, and change focus from one mind-set or topic to another. Mild deficits in the ability to shift compromise the efficiency of problem solving, whereas more severe difficulties are reflected in perseverative behaviors. Sometimes this is described as being rigid or inflexible.

HP:0033361.name: Nasal ulcer
HP:0033361.definition: An open sore of the nasal mucosa.

HP:0033362.name: Recurrent coughing spasms
HP:0033362.definition: Repeated occurrence of episodes of coughing, with each episode consisting of at least five minutes of continuous coughing.

HP:0033363.name: Hyaline membranes
HP:0033363.definition: Hyaline membranes are homogeneous eosinophilic material composed of cellular debris, plasma proteins, and surfactant plastered against alveolar ducts and alveolar walls. The hyaline membranes are deposited along the walls of the alveoli, where gas exchange typically occurs, thereby making gas exchange difficult.

HP:0033364.name: Lipoid pneumonia
HP:0033364.definition: A specific form of lung inflammation that results from accumulation of lipids in the alveoli. Lipoid pneumonia can be either exogenous or endogenous in cause based on the source of the lipid.

HP:0033365.name: Endogenous lipoid pneumonia
HP:0033365.definition: A type of lipoid pneumonia in which the source of the lipids is the body itself. When an airway is obstructed, it is often the case that distal to the obstruction, lipid-laden macrophages and giant cells fill the lumen of the disconnected airspace.

HP:0033366.name: Exogenous lipoid pneumonia
HP:0033366.definition: A type of lipoid pneumonia in which the source of the lipids is external to the body.

HP:0033367.name: Orthodeoxia
HP:0033367.definition: Low level of blood oxygen induced by changing from a recumbent to an upright position.

HP:0033368.name: Platypnea
HP:0033368.definition: A type of dyspnea that occurs when the affected person changes from a recumbent to an upright position.

HP:0033369.name: Cavitating leukodystrophy
HP:0033369.definition: A type of leukodystrophy characterized by multiple small cavitations typically in the periventricular and deep cerebral white matter. The cavitations are visible as a central cavity with cerebrospinal fluid-like signal intensity.

HP:0033370.name: Bronchial telangiectasia
HP:0033370.definition: Telangiectasias (small dilated blood vessels located near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes) located in the trachoebronchial system.

HP:0033371.name: Bronchocentric granulomatosis
HP:0033371.definition: Granulomatous inflammation that surrounds the bronchi and bronchioles, replacing bronchial walls and mucosa. In bronchocentric granulomatosis, the lumen of the airway contains necrotic debris, and palisaded histiocytes surround the lumen.

HP:0033372.name: Abnormal KCO
HP:0033372.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of KCO. The KCO is a measurement of the rate constant for alveolar uptake of CO during breath-holding in the single breath measurement of DLCO at full inflation. The DLCO is derived as the product of the KCO and the single breath alveolar volume (VA) divided by PB-PH2O.

HP:0033373.name: Increased KCO
HP:0033373.definition: Increased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (CO) rate constant (efficiency index).

HP:0033374.name: Decreased KCO
HP:0033374.definition: Decreased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (CO) rate constant (efficiency index).

HP:0033375.name: Anthracosis
HP:0033375.definition: Anthracosis is the deposition of black carbon pigment. It is commonly seen in perihilar lymph nodes as well as within lung parenchyma. There can be prominent storiforming (i.e., spiral patterning) of histiocytes, to such an extent as to mimic a neoplastic lesion histologically. Anthracosis is a common finding in smokers and polluted city dwellers.

HP:0033376.name: Alveolar septal thickening
HP:0033376.definition: Increased width of the alveolar septum, which is the structure that separates neighboring alveoli. This finding can be appreciated on histology.

HP:0033377.name: Increased airway neuroendocrine cells
HP:0033377.definition: Presence of increased numbers of bombesin-immuno-positive neuroendocrine cells (NECs) within distal airways. There are no formal criteria for an increase (which is also dependent on the sensitivity of the staining method), findings of neuroendocrine cells in at least 70% of bronchioles by lung biopsy and at least 10% NECs in an individual airway are consistent with the diagnosis of Neuroendocrine cell hyperplasia of infancy in the appropriate clinical setting. Increases are also seen in other clinical settings. Neuroendocrine neoplasms of the lung encompass NE tumors (NETs), which split into typical and atypical carcinoids, and NE carcinomas (NECs).

HP:0033378.name: Increased airway neuroepithelial bodies
HP:0033378.definition: Presence of increased numbers of bombesin-immuno-positive neuroendocrine cell cluster (neuroepithelial bodies) in the alveolar ducts.

HP:0033379.name: Bilateral superior vena cava
HP:0033379.definition: The presence of a left and a right superior vena cava.

HP:0033380.name: Nasal chondritis
HP:0033380.definition: Inflammation of the cartilage of the nose.

HP:0033381.name: Elevated circulating stearoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033381.definition: Abnormally increased concentration of O-stearoylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033382.name: Elevated circulating palmitoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033382.definition: Abnormally increased concentration of palmitoylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033383.name: Decreased compound muscle action potential amplitude
HP:0033383.definition: Reduced level of the compound muscle action potential (CMAP), which is recorded following electrical stimulation of a nerve from surface electrodes overlying a muscle supplied by that nerve.

HP:0033384.name: Elevated urinary collagen degradation products
HP:0033384.definition: Increased level in the urine of a metabolite that results from collagen degradation, e.g., a fragment of a collagen produced by a collagenase or serine protease.

HP:0033385.name: Elevated urine pyridinoline level
HP:0033385.definition: An increased amount of pyridinoline in the urine.

HP:0033386.name: Abnormal circulating collagen degradation product concentration
HP:0033386.definition: Abnormal concentration in the blood circulation of a metabolite that results from collagen degradation, e.g., a fragment of a collagen produced by a collagenase or serine protease.

HP:0033387.name: Elevated circulating pyridinoline concentration
HP:0033387.definition: An increased concentration of hydroxylysyl-pyridinoline (pyridinoline) in the blood circulation.

HP:0033388.name: Abnormal bronchial artery morphology
HP:0033388.definition: Any structural abnormality of a bronchial artery.

HP:0033389.name: Bronchopulmonary anastomosis
HP:0033389.definition: Abnormal arterial anastomosis (connection) between bronchial and pulmonary arteries.

HP:0033390.name: Bronchial artery dilatation
HP:0033390.definition: Increased caliber of a bronchial artery, which can be defined as a bronchial artery diameter that exceeds 2 mm.

HP:0033391.name: Bronchial artery hypertrophy
HP:0033391.definition: Increase in the volume of bronchial artery wall due to the enlargement of its component cells.

HP:0033392.name: Perivascular pre-capillary pulmonary artery inflammation
HP:0033392.definition: Inflammatory cell infiltration surrounding precapillary pulmonary arteries (arterioles; 20-70 micrometer).

HP:0033393.name: Irregularly shaped sperm tail
HP:0033393.definition: Irregular or changing caliber (diameter) along the tail of the sperm.

HP:0033394.name: Anti-carbonic anhydrase II antibody positivity
HP:0033394.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against carbonic anhydrase II.

HP:0033395.name: Antilactoferrin antibody positivity
HP:0033395.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against lactoferrin.

HP:0033396.name: Glomerular extracapillary fibrin
HP:0033396.definition: Presence of ropey, eosinophilic material (brght red on Trichrome staining) consistent with extracapillary fibrin outside of capillary lumina.

HP:0033397.name: Bowman-space proteinaceous debris
HP:0033397.definition: The presence of eosinophilic Periodic Acid Schiff (PAS)-positive cell free, protein-derived material occupying Bowman's space.

HP:0033398.name: Pleural plaque
HP:0033398.definition: Deposits of hyalinized collagen fibers in the parietal pleura (preferentially pleura adjacent to ribs, particularly the sixth through ninth ribs).

HP:0033399.name: Persistent fever
HP:0033399.definition: Fever that persists longer than expected for an acute infectious disease. No precise threshold exists, and the clinical interpretation of fever is context-dependent, but as a rule of thumb, this term refers to fever that persists longer than 2-3 weeks.

HP:0033400.name: Acute abdomen
HP:0033400.definition: A sudden onset of abdominal pain with associated nausea or vomiting. The acute abdomen may be caused by an infection, inflammation, vascular occlusion, or obstruction.

HP:0033401.name: Tissue ischemia
HP:0033401.definition: Ischemia is defined as a restriction of arterial blood supply to a tissue associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolis requirements of the tissue. Depending on the involved tissues, clinical manifestations may include pain, pallor, lack of pulse, coldness, paresthesia, and paralysis. Additional associated manifestations include hemodynamic parameters (reduced blood pressure distal to the site of restricted arterial supply) and angiographic evidence of arterial occclusion.

HP:0033402.name: Digital ischemia
HP:0033402.definition: Restriction of arterial blood supply to a digit (finger or toe) associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the digit. Clinical manifestations may include pain, pallor, lack of pulse, coldness, paresthesia, and paralysis.

HP:0033403.name: Testicular ischemia
HP:0033403.definition: Restriction of arterial blood supply to a testis associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the tissue. Clinical manifestations may include pain and swelling of the affected testis.

HP:0033404.name: Intestinal ischemia
HP:0033404.definition: Restriction of arterial blood supply to the intestine associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the tissue. Acute intestinal ischemia can involve the small or large intestine, and usually presents with sudden severe non-specific abdominal pain.

HP:0033405.name: Abnormal circulating organic amino compound concentration
HP:0033405.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of an organic amino compound, defined as a compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by organyl groups.

HP:0033406.name: Elevated circulating phosphoethanolamine concentration
HP:0033406.definition: An increased concentration of o-phosphoethanolamine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033407.name: Elevated urine acetoacetic acid level
HP:0033407.definition: Elevated amount of acetoacetic acid in the urine.

HP:0033408.name: Elevated circulating acetoacetic acid concentration
HP:0033408.definition: An increased level of acetoacetic acid in the blood circulation. Acetoacetic acid is one of the predominant ketone bodies.

HP:0033409.name: Elevated urinary 2-hydroxybutyric acid
HP:0033409.definition: An increased amount of 2-hydroxybutyric acid in the urine.

HP:0033410.name: Elevated circulating cartilage oligomeric matrix protein concentration
HP:0033410.definition: An increased blood concentration of cartilage oligomeric matrix protein (COMP).

HP:0033411.name: Lower extremity akinesia
HP:0033411.definition: Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily in the lower extremities.

HP:0033412.name: Upper extremity akinesia
HP:0033412.definition: Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily in the upper extremities.

HP:0033413.name: Upper extremity hypokinesia
HP:0033413.definition: Abnormally diminished movement of the upper extremities. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.

HP:0033414.name: Lower extremity hypokinesia
HP:0033414.definition: Abnormally diminished movement of the lower extremities. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.

HP:0033415.name: Cardiac tamponade
HP:0033415.definition: The accumulation of pericardial fluid with subsequent compression of all cardiac chambers which prevents cardiac filling.

HP:0033416.name: Hip adductor weakness
HP:0033416.definition: Reduced ability to bring the leg toward the midline of the body.

HP:0033417.name: Elevated circulating hydroxybutyric acid concentration
HP:0033417.definition: An increased concentration in the blood circulation of a hydroxybutyric acid, that is, of a compound comprising a butyric acid core carrying at least one hydroxy substituent.

HP:0033418.name: Elevated circulating 2-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
HP:0033418.definition: Elevation of the 2-hydroxybutyric acid concentration in the blood above the normal range.

HP:0033419.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
HP:0033419.definition: Elevation of the 3-hydroxybutyric acid concentration in the blood above the normal range.

HP:0033420.name: Pulmonary arterial plexiform lesion
HP:0033420.definition: Focal proliferation of pulmonary artery endothelial cells, leading to the formation of complex capillary-like channels.

HP:0033421.name: Pulmonary artery intimal thickening
HP:0033421.definition: Increased thickness of the intimal layer of the pulmonary artery. Throughout the pulmonary arterial tree, the thin intima consists of a non-fenestrated monolayer of endothelial cells lining the vessel lumen, as well as a sub-endothelial interstitium that extends to the internal elastic lamina. Intimal thickness in human lung ranges from 1-16% of total wall thickness. Pulmonary artery intimal thickening can be defined as a relative intima thickness to the thickness of the vessel wall of over 10%.

HP:0033422.name: Pulmonary artery adventitial fibrosis
HP:0033422.definition: Increased amount of collagen, proteoglycans, and other extracellular matrix proteins resulting in scarring and thickening in the adventia of the pulmonary arterial tree.

HP:0033423.name: Pulmonary arterial hypertension with positive acute response to NO challenge
HP:0033423.definition: A form of pulmonary arterial hypertension in which there is a reduction of mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP) at least 10 mmHg to reach an absolute value of mPAP not more than 40 mmHg with an increased or unchanged cardiac output (CO) in response to inhaled nitric oxide at 10-20 ppm.

HP:0033424.name: Pulmonary arterial hypertension with lack of acute response to NO challenge
HP:0033424.definition: A form of pulmonary arterial hypertension with lack of adequate hemodynamic response to NO challenge (adequate response is defined as a reduction of mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP) of at least 10 mmHg to reach an absolute value of mPAP 40 mmHg or less with an increased or unchanged cardiac output (CO) in response to inhaled nitric oxide at 10-20 ppm).

HP:0033425.name: Periungual erythema
HP:0033425.definition: Erythema (redness of the skin caused by hyperemia in superficial capillaries) in the region surrounding a fingernail or toe nail.

HP:0033426.name: Pulmonary air embolism
HP:0033426.definition: Venous air embolism is a consequence of air being introduced into the venous circulation, and subsequently to the right heart, and pulmonary circulation. When small amounts of air reach pulmonary circulation they can be removed by gas diffusion across the arteriolar wall into the alveoli, amounts of gas exceeding 50 ml can cause pulmonary outflow tract obstruction with or without concomitant arterial embolisation.

HP:0033427.name: Pulmonary capillary angioectasia
HP:0033427.definition: Focal accumulation of dilated pulmonary capillaries.

HP:0033428.name: Systemic autoinflammation
HP:0033428.definition: Dysregulation of the innate immune system characterized by systemic pathobiology, i.e., with symptoms that can affect the entire body.

HP:0033429.name: Neuroinflammation
HP:0033429.definition: Activation of the brain's innate immune system in response to an inflammatory challenge and is characterized by a host of cellular and molecular changes within the brain.

HP:0033430.name: Non-infectious meningitis
HP:0033430.definition: Inflammation of the layers of tissue that cover the brain and spinal cord (meninges) and of the fluid-filled space between the meninges (subarachnoid space) when it is caused by disorders that are not infections or by drugs or vaccines.

HP:0033431.name: Cytomegalovirus colitis
HP:0033431.definition: A form of cytomegalovirus infection characterized by infection and inflammation of the colon.

HP:0033433.name: Ileocecal ulcer
HP:0033433.definition: An erosion of the mucous membrane in the region connecting the ileum and cecum.
