HP:0033434.name: Nasal septum perforation
HP:0033434.definition: A full-thickness defect of the nasal septum.

HP:0033435.name: Abnormal circulating keto acid concentration
HP:0033435.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of a keto acid in the blood circulation. Keto acids or ketoacids are organic compounds that contain a carboxylic acid group and a ketone group.

HP:0033436.name: Elevated circulating 3-methyl-2-oxovaleric acid concentration
HP:0033436.definition: The concentration of 3-methyl-2-oxovaleric acidin the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033437.name: Elevated circulating 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid concentration
HP:0033437.definition: The concentration of 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033438.name: Elevated circulating myoglobin concentration
HP:0033438.definition: An increased blood concentration of myoglobin.

HP:0033439.name: Elevated circulating decenoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033439.definition: Concentration of decenoylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033440.name: Elevated circulating octenoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033440.definition: Concentration of octenoylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033441.name: Elevated circulating hexanoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033441.definition: Concentration of hexanoylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033442.name: Elevated circulating glutarylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033442.definition: Concentration of glutarylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033443.name: Elevated circulating propionylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033443.definition: Increased concentration of propionylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033444.name: Elevated circulating dodecanoylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033444.definition: Concentration of dodecanoylcarnitine (C12:0) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033445.name: Reduced circulating acylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033445.definition: An abnormally reduced concentration in the blood circulation of acylcarnitine, which is produced by reversible esterification of the 3-hydroxyl group of carnitine.

HP:0033446.name: Elevated circulating butyrylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033446.definition: Concentration of O-butyrylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033447.name: Elevated circulating isovalerylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033447.definition: Concentration of O-isovalerylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033448.name: Increased mid-arm muscle circumference
HP:0033448.definition: Elevation of the midupper arm circumference midway between the acromion and olecranon processes of the ulna with the use of a steel or fiberglass tape. This measure is a proxy for the muscle mass of the upper arm and can be used as a part of the assessment of nutritional status in children.

HP:0033449.name: Decreased mid-arm muscle circumference
HP:0033449.definition: Reduction of the midupper arm circumference midway between the acromion and olecranon processes of the ulna with the use of a steel or fiberglass tape. This measure is a proxy for the muscle mass of the upper arm and can be used as a part of the assessment of nutritional status in children.

HP:0033450.name: Abnormal circulating prealbumin concentration
HP:0033450.definition: Any deviation from normal concentration of albumin in the blood circulation.

HP:0033451.name: Increased circulating prealbumin concentration
HP:0033451.definition: An elevation above the normal concentration of prealbumin in the blood circulation.

HP:0033453.name: Limited neck extension
HP:0033453.definition: Reduced ability to move the head back towards the ceiling so that one is looking upwards.

HP:0033454.name: Tube feeding
HP:0033454.definition: Feeding problem necessitating food and nutrient delivery via a tube.

HP:0033455.name: obsolete Elevated urinary dicarboxylic acid level

HP:0033456.name: Elevated urine keto acid level
HP:0033456.definition: Increased amount of a keta acid in the urine.

HP:0033457.name: Elevated urine 3-methyl-2-oxovaleric acid level
HP:0033457.definition: Increased amount of 3-methyl-2-oxovaleric acid in the urine.

HP:0033458.name: Elevated urine 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid level
HP:0033458.definition: Increased amount of 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid in the urine.

HP:0033459.name: Decreased circulating apolipoprotein concentration
HP:0033459.definition: Reduced concentration in the blood circulation of a lipid-transport protein (apoliprotein).

HP:0033460.name: Increased circulating apolipoprotein circulation
HP:0033460.definition: Elevated concentration in the blood circulation of a lipid-transport protein (apoliprotein).

HP:0033461.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxylinoleylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033461.definition: Increased concentration of 3-hydroxylinoleylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033462.name: Elevated circulating oleylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033462.definition: Increased concentration of oleylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033464.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxypalmitoleylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033464.definition: Concentration of 3-hydroxypalmitoleylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033466.name: Weak grip
HP:0033466.definition: Reduced grip strength. Gripping is the motion by which the hand tightly grasps an object or other hand.

HP:0033467.name: Low 10-minute APGAR score
HP:0033467.definition: A normal APGAR score can be coded as 'not Low 10-minute APGAR score'.

HP:0033475.name: Limited shoulder abduction
HP:0033475.definition: Decreased ability to move the arm away from the midline of the body.

HP:0033476.name: Extractable nuclear antigen positivity
HP:0033476.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against extractable nuclear components that are referred to as extractable because they can be extracted from cell nuclei with saline solution.

HP:0033477.name: Abnormal circulating lipoprotein lipase concentration
HP:0033477.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of lipoprotein lipase in the blood circulation.

HP:0033478.name: Increased circulating lipoprotein lipase concentration
HP:0033478.definition: Increased concentration of lipoprotein lipase in the blood circulation.

HP:0033480.name: Hypobilirubinemia
HP:0033480.definition: Concentration of bilirubin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0033481.name: Limited lateral neck flexion
HP:0033481.definition: Reduced range of motion resulting in decreased ability to move the ear toward the top of the shoulder.

HP:0033482.name: Limited shoulder flexion
HP:0033482.definition: A reduced ability to flex the shoulder. Shoulder flexion is the motion that moves the arms from a resting position by the side of the body to a position above the head.

HP:0033483.name: Podocyte infolding
HP:0033483.definition: Folding of cytoplasmic processes of podocytes into the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) with thickening of the lamina densa and microspheres and/or microtubular structures within the GBM.

HP:0033484.name: Elevated circulating linoleylcarnitine concentration
HP:0033484.definition: Increased concentration of linoleylcarnitine in the blood circulation.

HP:0033485.name: Glomerular basement membrane disruption
HP:0033485.definition: A point of rupture in the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) where the discontinuous portions of GBM are still identifiable with a basement membrane stain such as Periodic acid Schiff (PAS) or silver.

HP:0033486.name: Abnormal glomerular basement membrane texture
HP:0033486.definition: Anomalous appearance or structure of the surface of the glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033487.name: Glomerular basement membranes powdery deposit
HP:0033487.definition: Punctate electron-dense material typically in a band-like distribution along the lamina rara interna and within tubular basement membranes within the subendothelial aspect of the glomerular basement membrane.

HP:0033488.name: Glomerular endocapillary leukocyte hypercellularity
HP:0033488.definition: Increased number of leukocytes internal to the glomerular basement membrane (GBM), but not limited to within glomerular capillaries.

HP:0033489.name: Glomerular endocapillary neutrophil hypercellularity
HP:0033489.definition: Increased number of neutrophils internal to the glomerular basement membrane (GBM), but not limited to within glomerular capillaries.

HP:0033490.name: Glomerular endocapillary foam-cell hypercellularity
HP:0033490.definition: Presence of lipid-filled cells, often a macrophage, with a vacuolated appearance in the glomerulus often occupying the endocapillary space.

HP:0033491.name: Global mesangial sclerosis
HP:0033491.definition: A generalized global (over 80%) increase of mesangial matrix that is present throughout the mesangial stalk (with or without associated mesangial hypercellularity).

HP:0033492.name: Podocyte cytoskeletal condensation
HP:0033492.definition: Reorganization of podocyte cytoskeletal proteins at the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) aspect of the cell, with associated cytoplasmic electron density at the GBM aspect of the podocyte.

HP:0033493.name: Mesangial matrix expansion
HP:0033493.definition: Increased mesangial extracellular material with interspace width of over 2 mesangial cell nuclei, in one or more peripheral mesangial areas.

HP:0033494.name: Glomerular basement membrane amyloid spicule
HP:0033494.definition: Amyloid spicules are projections of typically silver-positive material from the outer aspect of the glomerular capillary wall, perpendicular to the glomerular basement membrane (GBM), most often caused by amyloidosis with the latter confirmed by additional stains.

HP:0033495.name: Segmental glomerulosclerosis
HP:0033495.definition: Segmental solidification of the glomerular tuft by increased extracellular matrix, causing glomerular capillary obliteration and can include hyalinosis, foam cells, hypertrophy of overlying glomerular epithelial cells, podocyte depletion, halo and adhesion of the tuft to the Bowman capsule.

HP:0033496.name: Perihilar segmental glomerulosclerosis
HP:0033496.definition: Segmental solidification of the glomerular tuft by increased extracellular matrix, causing glomerular capillary obliteration is present at the vascular pole, involving less than 50% of the tuft. It can be accompanied by other descriptors such as hyalinosis, foam cells, hypertrophy of overlying glomerular epithelial cells, podocyte depletion, halo and adhesion of the tuft to the Bowman's capsule.

HP:0033497.name: Tip variant segmental glomerulosclerosis
HP:0033497.definition: Segmental solidification of the glomerular tuft characterized by an adhesion at the tip of the glomerular tuft abutting the proximal tubular taek-off can be accompanied by increased extracellular matrix, causing glomerular capillary obliteration at the glomerular tip. Features including hyalinosis, foam cells, hypertrophy of overlying glomerular epithelial cells can also be observed.

HP:0033498.name: Segmental glomerulosclerosis away from the vascular and tubular poles
HP:0033498.definition: Segmental solidification of the glomerular tuft characterized by increased extracellular matrix, causing glomerular capillary obliteration at neither the tubular or vascular poles. Features including hyalinosis, foam cells, hypertrophy of overlying glomerular epithelial cells can also be observed.

HP:0033499.name: Glomerular basement membrane electron dense deposits
HP:0033499.definition: Electron-dense deposits in the lamina densa with a ribbon or a sausage structure.

HP:0033500.name: Subendothelial glomerular basement membrane electron dense deposits
HP:0033500.definition: Electron dense deposits in the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) subendothelial space associated with a prominent GBM reflecting an increase in thickness. This feature can be associated with GBM remodeling along the endothelial aspect.

HP:0033501.name: Subepithelial glomerular basement membrane electron dense deposits
HP:0033501.definition: Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting a diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with exogenous material deposited between the outer (epithelial) aspect of the GBM and the visceral epithelial cell, with varying degrees of incorporation into the GBM.

HP:0033502.name: Abnormal esterified to free carnitine ratio
HP:0033502.definition: Any deviation from the normal ratio of acylcarnitine (i.e., esterified carnitine) to free carnitine.

HP:0033503.name: Elevated CSF fumarate concentration
HP:0033503.definition: An increased concentration of fumarate, an intermediate in the citric acid cycle, in the cebrebrospinal fluid.

HP:0033504.name: Elevated circulating fumarate concentration
HP:0033504.definition: An increased concentration of fumarate, an intermediate in the citric acid cycle, in the blood circulation.

HP:0033505.name: Livedo reticularis
HP:0033505.definition: Livedo reticularis is characterized by the presence of a bluish purple, mottled or netlike pattern in unbroken circles on the skin. Exposure to cold environments usually intensifies the vascular pattern. Presumably, the condition results from slow or stagnant blood flow, vessel-wall pathology, and decreased oxygen tension.

HP:0033506.name: Increased esterified to free carnitine ratio
HP:0033506.definition: An elevated ratio of acylcarnitine (i.e., esterified carnitine) to free carnitine.

HP:0033507.name: Decreased esterified to free carnitine ratio
HP:0033507.definition: A reduced ratio of acylcarnitine (i.e., esterified carnitine) to free carnitine.

HP:0033508.name: EBV meningitis
HP:0033508.definition: Inflammation of the meninges related to infection by Epstein-Barr virus.

HP:0033509.name: EBV encephalitis
HP:0033509.definition: Inflammation of the brain related to infection by Epstein-Barr virus.

HP:0033510.name: Cutaneous horn
HP:0033510.definition: A cutaneous horn is a keratinized non-malignant protrusion on the surface of the skin. Diagnosis is established by biopsy of the horn and biopsy of the horn and the underlying skin.

HP:0033511.name: Addictive substance use
HP:0033511.definition: Chronic compulsive drug seeking and continued use despite harmful consequences.

HP:0033512.name: Addictive stimulant use
HP:0033512.definition: Addiction to a stimulant drug is defined as a drug that typically increases alertness, attention, and energy while also elevating blood pressure, heart rate, and breathing.

HP:0033514.name: Addictive amphetamine use
HP:0033514.definition: Addiction to amphetamine or dextroamphetamine is a serious concern.

HP:0033520.name: Paradoxical embolism
HP:0033520.definition: Paradoxical embolism describes the passage of a venous or right-sided cardiac thrombus into the arterial or systemic circulation.

HP:0033521.name: Nasal dryness
HP:0033521.definition: A lack of humidification of the nasal mucosa.

HP:0033522.name: Cerebral cavernous malformation
HP:0033522.definition: A cerebral cavernous malformation (also known as cavernoma, cavernous angioma, cavernous hemangioma) is a collection of structurally abnormal slow-flow capillaries predominantly in the central nervous system. These are multiple mulberry-like distended caverns of dilated thin-walled capillaries without the normal intervening brain parenchymal architecture. Often, individual cavernomas are surrounded by hemosiderin representing remote oozing due to the abnormal capillaries.

HP:0033523.name: Abnormal sperm principal piece morphology
HP:0033523.definition: A structural anomaly of the part of the sperm flagellum that is distal to the sperm midpiece and mitochondrial sheath and which leads into the end piece.

HP:0033524.name: Abnormal sperm axoneme morphology
HP:0033524.definition: Abnormal structure of the sperm axonemal structure which consists of a ring of nine microtubular doublets and a central pair of microtubules, giving the classical 9+2 microtubular arrangement. The axoneme contains a central pair of microtubules (C1 and C2) that are connected by a bridge-like structure forming the central pair complex (CPC). Each of the nine outer doublets is composed of type A and B microtubules and connected by radial spokes to the CPC.

HP:0033525.name: Absent sperm axoneme central pair complex
HP:0033525.definition: Absence of the central pair of microtubules in the sperm axoneme, thereby forming a 9+0 pattern instead of the normal 9+2 pattern.

HP:0033526.name: Limited ankle dorsiflexion
HP:0033526.definition: Reduced ability to move the foot up toward the shin.

HP:0033527.name: Decreased gonadotropin-stimulated testosterone-to-androstenedione ratio
HP:0033527.definition: A reduced amount of testosterone relative in androstenedione in the blood circulation following administration of hCG (Human Chorionic Gonadotropin).

HP:0033528.name: Abnormal cardiac output
HP:0033528.definition: A deviation from normal Cardiac output, which is defined as the amount of blood pumped by the heart minute and is the mechanism whereby blood flows around the body, especially providing blood flow to the brain and other vital organs.

HP:0033529.name: Abnormal cardiac index
HP:0033529.definition: Any deviation from the normal value of the cardiac index, defined as cardiac output divided by body surface area.

HP:0033530.name: Increased cardiac index
HP:0033530.definition: An elevated cardiac index, defined as cardiac output divided by body surface area.

HP:0033531.name: Decreased cardiac index
HP:0033531.definition: A reduced cardiac index, defined as cardiac output divided by body surface area.

HP:0033532.name: Decreased cardiac output
HP:0033532.definition: A decreased volume of blood pumped by the left and right ventricle, per unit time. Cardiac output (CO) is the product of the heart rate (HR), i.e. the number of heartbeats per minute (bpm), and the stroke volume (SV), which is the volume of blood pumped from the ventricle per beat.

HP:0033533.name: Increased cardiac output
HP:0033533.definition: An increased volume of blood pumped by the left and right ventricle, per unit time. Cardiac output (CO) is the product of the heart rate (HR), i.e. the number of heartbeats per minute (bpm), and the stroke volume (SV), which is the volume of blood pumped from the ventricle per beat.

HP:0033534.name: Increased circulating brain natriuretic peptide concentration
HP:0033534.definition: An increased concentration of brain natriuretic peptide in the blood circulation.

HP:0033535.name: Reduced platelet dense granules
HP:0033535.definition: Decreased number of platelet dense granules, a type of platelet organelle.

HP:0033536.name: Reduced platelet alpha granules
HP:0033536.definition: A reduced number of platelet alpha granules.

HP:0033537.name: Mosaic pulmonary attenuation pattern
HP:0033537.definition: Mosaic attenuation refers to heterogeneous areas of differing pulmonary attenuation on CT imaging.

HP:0033538.name: Aortic annulus calcification
HP:0033538.definition: Pathological deposition of calcium salts in the aortic annulus, a fibrous ring-like structure found at the insertion point of the basal attachments of the aortic valve leaflets within the left ventricular outflow tract.

HP:0033539.name: Bilateral apical pulmonary fibrosis
HP:0033539.definition: A reticular pattern of linear or lineonodular densities in apical portions of both the right and left lungs seen initially on high-resolution computed tomography and in case of progression also on standard chest x-ray.

HP:0033540.name: Reversible airflow obstruction
HP:0033540.definition: Airflow obstruction with a significant response to a bronchodilator defined as an increase in FEV1 and/or FVC by 12 percent or more and by at least 200 mL.

HP:0033541.name: Irreversible airflow obstruction
HP:0033541.definition: Airflow obstruction without significant response to a bronchodilator defined as an increase in FEV1 and/or FVC by 12 percent or more and by at least 200 mL.

HP:0033542.name: Bronchial wall thickening
HP:0033542.definition: Radiological appearance of increased density around the walls of a bronchus or large bronchiole. This feature is thought to be related to edema involving the bronchial wall as well as the peribronchial interstitial space. If the cross section of a bronchus is captured in a radiograph or computed tomography image, it is said to have the appearance of a donut because of the central lucency representing the airway of the bronchus surrounded by a circular region of increased density.

HP:0033543.name: Addictive nicotine use
HP:0033543.definition: Nicotine addiction can be defined as a chronic, compulsive craving for nicotine and continued usage despite harmful consequences.

HP:0033544.name: Mesangial fibril deposition
HP:0033544.definition: Extracellular mesangial accumulation of slender proteinaceous fibers.

HP:0033545.name: Mesangial fibrillary deposits
HP:0033545.definition: Extracellular mesangial aggregates composed of randomly arranged, straight, non-branching fibrils that are thicker than amyloid fibrils (average diameter about 20 nm) and are often admixed with smudgy, electron-dense material.

HP:0033546.name: Mesangial microfibril deposition
HP:0033546.definition: Unbranched noncollagenous microfibrils within the mesangial matrix, composed of proteins not present within the glomerular basement membrane (GBM), most notably fibrillin-1, that attach to mesangial cells and GBM structural proteins.

HP:0033547.name: Mesangial immunotactoid deposits
HP:0033547.definition: Extracellular mesangial aggregates composed of non-branching fibrils, focally parallel over 30 nM in diameter. The term immunotactoid refers to highly organized immune depositions appearing as rod-like microtubular structures in ultrastructural examination.

HP:0033548.name: Mesangial amyloid deposition
HP:0033548.definition: Extracellular mesangial aggregates composed of fine, randomly oriented, non-branching fibrils 8-12 nm in diameter, often forming a cottony mass.

HP:0033549.name: Nodular mesangiosclerosis
HP:0033549.definition: Lobular, round to oval mesangial lesions with an acellular hyaline/matrix core surrounded by compressed mesangial nuclei.

HP:0033550.name: Necrotizing pulmonary granulomatosis
HP:0033550.definition: A granuloma that is associated with necrotic changes. Caseation necrosis is defined as a region in granulomas with eosinophilic, granular and cheese-like cellular debris with necrosis. The word caseous itself means pertaining or related to cheese, and comes from the Latin word caseus, meaning cheese.

HP:0033551.name: Non-necrotizing pulmonary granulomatosis
HP:0033551.definition: A granuloma located in the lung that is not associated with necrotic changes.

HP:0033552.name: Chronic villitis
HP:0033552.definition: Villitis of unknown etiology (synonymous with villitis of unknown etiology) is a histologic diagnosis and, although it may have a variable distribution, evidence indicates that 3 parenchymal blocks will identify 62% of villitis, reaching an asymptote of 6 and 7 blocks identifying 85% of villitis. Villitis of unknown etiology by definition excludes those cases where an etiology is identified, such as viral or acute infections, and thus is preferred to the term nonspecific chronic villitis. It is usually lymphohistiocytic: although the presence of rare plasma cells does not exclude the diagnosis, thorough evaluation for an infectious etiology, such as cytomegalovirus, is required in a predominantly plasma cell villitis.

HP:0033553.name: Septic embolism
HP:0033553.definition: Embolization of intravascular thrombus containing microorganisms into the distant tissues via arterial system.

HP:0033554.name: Anti-Mi2 antibody positivity
HP:0033554.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against the Mi-2 antigen.

HP:0033555.name: Anti-Ro/SS-A antibody positivity
HP:0033555.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against Ro/SSA autoantigens.

HP:0033556.name: Anti-nucleoporin 62 antibody positivity
HP:0033556.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against nucleoporin 62.

HP:0033557.name: Anti-proteinase 3 antibody positivity
HP:0033557.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against proteinase 3. Proteinase 3 (PR3) antigen is a 29-kD serine protease that exists as a protein triplet in human neutrophils

HP:0033558.name: Anti-histone antibody positivity
HP:0033558.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone antigens.

HP:0033559.name: Anti-myeloperoxidase antibody positivity
HP:0033559.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against myeloperoxidase.

HP:0033560.name: Anti-PM-Scl antibody positivity
HP:0033560.definition: Anti-PM-Scl antibodies target components of RNA-processing exosome complex in the nucleolus. There are ten proteins in this complex and antibodies to eight of them are found at varying frequencies; PM/Scl-100, PM/Scl-75, hRrp4, hRrp42, hRrp46, hCs14, hRrp41, and hRrp40.

HP:0033561.name: Anti-bactericidal/permeability-increasing protein antibody positivity
HP:0033561.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against bactericidal/permeability-increasing protein (BPI). BPI is an endotoxin-binding host protein with important antibacterial effects against Gram-negative bacteria, such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa. BPI is a 55 kDalton protein that is most abundant in the azurophilic granules of neutrophils. BPI also acts as a target antigen for antineutrophil cytoplasmic autoantibodies.

HP:0033562.name: Anti-glycoprotein-210 antibody positivity
HP:0033562.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against glycoprotein-210.

HP:0033563.name: Anti-tissue transglutaminase antibody positivity
HP:0033563.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against tissue transglutaminase.

HP:0033564.name: Stasis dermatitis
HP:0033564.definition: Stasis dermatitis commonly occurs in older age. It is caused by venous hypertension resulting from retrograde flow due to incompetent venous valves, valve destruction, or obstruction of the venous system. Further tissue changes arise from an inflammatory process mediated by metalloproteinases, which are up-regulated by ferric ion from extravasated red blood cells. Stasis dermatitis presents initially as poorly demarcated erythematous plaques of the lower legs bilaterally, classically involving the medial malleolus.

HP:0033565.name: Anti-epidermal transglutaminase antibody positivity
HP:0033565.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against epidermal transglutaminase.

HP:0033566.name: Abnormal ventricular axis
HP:0033566.definition: Any deviation from the normal direction of the ventricular axis. The left ventricle makes up most of the heart muscle under normal circumstances and therefore generates the most electrical force visible on the EKG. The normal ventricular axis is directed downward and slightly towards the left. The ventricular axis can be determined by analyzing the QRS complex, which represents ventricular depolarization.

HP:0033567.name: Right axis deviation
HP:0033567.definition: A kind of abnormal ventricular axis in the EKG whereby the QRS axis falls between +90 degrees and 180 degrees, or beyond +100 degrees if the adult range is used.

HP:0033568.name: Left axis deviation
HP:0033568.definition: A kind of abnormal ventricular axis in the EKG whereby the QRS axis falls between -30 degrees and -90 degrees.

HP:0033569.name: Extreme axis deviation
HP:0033569.definition: A kind of abnormal ventricular axis in the EKG whereby the QRS axis fall sbetween -90 degrees and 180 degrees. In this case, the ventricular vector is directed upward and to the right.

HP:0033570.name: Indeterminate ventricular axis
HP:0033570.definition: A kind of abnormal ventricular axis in the EKG whereby the QRS complex is isoelectric or equiphasic in all leads with no dominant QRS deflection.

HP:0033571.name: Peripheral lung neovascularity
HP:0033571.definition: The presence of small, tortuous, micronodular, serpiginous intrapulmonary vessels often in the subpleural lung or in proximity to centrilobular arterioles, coursing in directions inconsistent with known arteriolar anatomy.

HP:0033572.name: Anti-H1 antibody positivity
HP:0033572.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone H1.

HP:0033573.name: Anti-H4 antibody positivity
HP:0033573.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone H4.

HP:0033574.name: Anti-H3 antibody positivity
HP:0033574.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone H3.

HP:0033575.name: Anti-H2A antibody positivity
HP:0033575.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone H2A.

HP:0033576.name: Anti-H2B antibody positivity
HP:0033576.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against histone H2B.

HP:0033577.name: In situ pulmonary artery thrombosis
HP:0033577.definition: Localized thrombosis in pulmonary arteries frequently found in patients with idiopathic and hereditary pulmonary arterial hypertension and pulmonary arterial hypertension associated with congenital heart disease.

HP:0033578.name: Pre-capillary pulmonary hypertension
HP:0033578.definition: Pre-capillary pulmonary hypertension is a haemodynamic condition characterized by elevated mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP over 20 mmHg) and pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR 3 Wood units or more) accompanied by normal pulmonary artery wedge pressure (PAWP not more than 15 mmHg).

HP:0033579.name: Decreased growth hormone responses to growth hormone-releasing hormone challenge
HP:0033579.definition: Insufficient growth hormone secretion following administration of growth hormone-releasing hormone.

HP:0033580.name: Compound motor action potential abnormality
HP:0033580.definition: An abnormal finding in a compound motor action potential measurement in EMG. Nerve conduction studies involve the application of a depolarising square wave electrical pulses to the skin over a peripheral nerve producing: (1) a propagated nerve action potential (NAP) recorded at a distant point over the same nerve: and (2) a compound muscle action potential (CMAP) arising from the activation of muscle fibers in a target muscle supplied by the nerve. In both cases these may be recorded with surface or needle electrodes. The CMAP is a summated voltage response from the individual muscle fiber action potentials. The shortest latency of the CMAP is the time from stimulus artifact to onset of the response and is a biphasic response with an initial upward deflection followed by a smaller downward deflection. The CMAP amplitude is measured from baseline to negative peak (the neurophysiological convention is that negative voltage is demonstrated by an upward deflection) and measured in millivolts (mV).

HP:0033581.name: Absent peripheral lymph nodes in presence of infection
HP:0033581.definition: The absence of any palpable lymph nodes in the presence of symptoms suggesting infection in that drainage area should raise suspicion for immunodeficiency diseases.

HP:0033582.name: Pulmonary interstitial lymphocyte infiltration
HP:0033582.definition: Abnormal accumulation of lymphocytes in the interstitium of the lung.

HP:0033583.name: Follicular bronchiolitis
HP:0033583.definition: Follicular bronchiolitis is a polyclonal hyperplasia of bronchiolar associated lymphoid tissue characterized by the is characterized by the development of lymphoid follicles with germinal centers in walls of the small airways.

HP:0033584.name: Nonspecific interstitial pneumonia
HP:0033584.definition: Temporally uniform (all lesions are in the same stage of evolution) pattern of diffuse inflammatory interstitial process, mostly symmetric over the entire lung, involving mainly the alveolar septa.

HP:0033585.name: Fibrotic non-specific interstitial pneumonia
HP:0033585.definition: A type of non-specific interstitial pneumonia in which interstitial thickening is due to uniform dense or loose fibrosis and mild chronic inflammation.

HP:0033586.name: Cellular non-specific interstitial pneumonia
HP:0033586.definition: A type of non-specific interstitial pneumonia in which interstitial thickening is mainly due to infiltration of inflammatory cells and type II pneumocyte hyperplasia.

HP:0033587.name: Vulvar abscess
HP:0033587.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the vulvar region.

HP:0033588.name: Labial adhesion
HP:0033588.definition: Synechia vulvae (adhesions of the labia minora) are characterized by a complete or partial fusion of the labia minora in the midline.

HP:0033589.name: Flatulence
HP:0033589.definition: Passage of excessive amounts of gas and the feeling of abdominal fullness and bloating.

HP:0033590.name: Inguinal abscess
HP:0033590.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the groin (inguinal region).

HP:0033591.name: Staghorn calculus
HP:0033591.definition: Large branching stones that fill part of all of the renal pelvis and renal calyces and they can be complete or partial depending on the level of occupancy of the collecting system.

HP:0033592.name: Anti-H3-H4 antibody positivity
HP:0033592.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against the H3-H4 histone dimer.

HP:0033593.name: Anti-H2A-H2B antibody positivity
HP:0033593.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against the H2A-H2B histone dimer.

HP:0033594.name: Elevated urinary 7-biopterin level
HP:0033594.definition: An abnormally increased amount of 7-biopterin in the urine.

HP:0033595.name: Elevated circulating globotriaosylceramide concentration
HP:0033595.definition: Increased concentration of globotriaosylceramide (Gb3) in the blood circulation. Globotriaosylceramide, also named ceramidetrihexoside, is the primary lipid storage in Fabry disease.

HP:0033596.name: Elevated urinary 3-methylcrotonylglycine level
HP:0033596.definition: An abnormally increased amount of 3-methylcrotonylglycine in the urine.

HP:0033597.name: Decreased mucosal sucrase-isomaltase activity
HP:0033597.definition: Reduced activity of the linked disaccharidase, sucrase-isomaltase, which is a glycoprotein localized to the brush border membrane of small intestinal villi.

HP:0033598.name: Fibrillar glomerular subepithelial deposits
HP:0033598.definition: Fibrillar deposits located between the outer (epithelial) aspect of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) and the visceral epithelial cell, with varying degrees of incorporation into the GBM. This feature is associated with a prominent GBM reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033599.name: Glomerular amyloid subepithelial deposits
HP:0033599.definition: A type of fibrillar glomerular subepithelial deposit characterized by extracellular aggregates composed of fine, randomly oriented, non-branching fibrils 8-12 nm in diameter, often forming a cottony mass. This feature is associated with a prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033600.name: Fibrillary glomerular subepithelial deposits
HP:0033600.definition: A type of fibrillar glomerular subepithelial deposit characterized by extracellular aggregates of randomly arranged, straight, non-branching fibrils that are thicker than amyloid fibrils (average diameter about 20 nm) and are often admixed with smudgy, electron-dense material. This feature is associated with a prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033601.name: Glomerular subepithelial immune-complex deposits
HP:0033601.definition: A type of glomerular subepithelial deposit characterized by finely granular material deposited between the outer (epithelial) aspect of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) and the visceral epithelial cell, with varying degrees of incorporation into the GBM and corresponding to immunoglobulin and/or complement by immunofluorescence/immunohistochemistry. This feature is associated with a prominent GBM reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033602.name: Glomerular hyaline subepithelial deposits
HP:0033602.definition: A type of glomerular subepithelial deposit characterized by a moderately electron-dense, generally homogenous, amorphous-appearing extracellular material located between the outer (epithelial) aspect of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) and the visceral epithelial cell, with varying degrees of incorporation into the GBM. This feature is associated with a prominent GBM reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033603.name: Glomerular subepithelial deposits
HP:0033603.definition: Deposits located between the outer (epithelial) aspect of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) and the visceral epithelial cell, with varying degrees of incorporation into the GBM. This feature may be associated with a prominent GBM reflecting an diffuse and relatively uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate).

HP:0033604.name: Glomerular capillary wire loop deposits
HP:0033604.definition: Glomerulus showing markedly and irregularly thickened capillary walls with massive fuchsinophilic subendothelial deposits, resulting in narrowing of capillary lumina. This feature is said to resemble a wire loop.

HP:0033605.name: Pustular rash
HP:0033605.definition: A rash composed of pustular lesions. A pustule is defined as a vesicle or bulla containing purulent material. It varies in size and may occur at different levels within the epidermis: subcorneal, intraepidermal, or basement membrane zones. The pustules may or may not be sterile and are normally filled with neutrophils.

HP:0033606.name: Bone marrow maturation arrest
HP:0033606.definition: Interruption of the procecss of diffferentiation of hematopoietic cells in the bone marrow, manifested by an increased proportion of immature cells in the bone marrow.

HP:0033607.name: Bone marrow arrest at the promyelocytic stage
HP:0033607.definition: A type of bone marrow maturation arrest characterized by accumulation of neutrophil precursor cells in the bone marrow.

HP:0033608.name: Pulmonary nodule
HP:0033608.definition: Focal rounded or ovoid opacity, not more than 3 cm in diameter. Pulmonary nodules are typically observed by chest radiography or computer tomography imaging.

HP:0033609.name: Solid pulmonary nodule
HP:0033609.definition: A type of pulmonary nodule whose density obscures the underlying parenchyma and thus has a "solid" appearance.

HP:0033610.name: Subsolid pulmonary nodule
HP:0033610.definition: Pulmonary subsolid nodules (SSNs) refer to pulmonary nodules with pure ground-glass nodules and part-solid ground-glass nodules. A ground-glass nodule (GGN) is the morphologic description of a pulmonary nodule category on thin-section chest computed tomography (CT). During the past decade, the natural history, management strategy and long-term prognosis in the case of GGNs have attracted attention.

HP:0033611.name: Part-solid pulmonary nodule
HP:0033611.definition: Part-solid pulmonary nodules are nodules that present with both ground-glass and solid components in which the underlying lung architecture cannot be visualized.

HP:0033612.name: Pure ground-glass pulmonary nodule
HP:0033612.definition: Pure ground-glass pulmonary nodules (GGNs) are defined as focal nodular areas of increased lung attenuation through which lung parenchymal structures, such as the pulmonary vessels or bronchial structures, can be observed.

HP:0033613.name: Perifissural pulmonary nodule
HP:0033613.definition: Solid, homogenous nodules characterized by a smooth margin and oval, rounded, lentiform or triangular shape. They are typically located within 15 mm from the issue or the pleura. Perifissural nodules may be further differentiated into typical (have contact with interlobar septum) and atypical (do not have contact with interlobar septum). They likely represent intrapulmonary lymphnodes.

HP:0033614.name: Tracheal bronchus
HP:0033614.definition: Aberrant or accessory bronchus supplying the upper lobe originating from the lateral wall of the trachea. The tracheal bronchus is more commonly right-sided, has a variable length and may be blind-ended. Two common types of tracheal bronchus are: supernumerary and displaced.

HP:0033615.name: Displaced tracheal bronchus
HP:0033615.definition: Accessory bronchus originating from trachea replacing one of the segmental branches of the anatomically normal upper lobe bronchus.

HP:0033616.name: Accessory cardiac bronchus
HP:0033616.definition: Accessory bronchus originating from the medial wall of the right or left ban bronchus or bronchus intermedius. A cardiac bronchus is usually blind-ended.

HP:0033617.name: Supernumerary tracheal bronchus
HP:0033617.definition: Accessory bronchus which exits the trachea in addition to an anatomically normal branching upper lobe bronchus.

HP:0033618.name: Displaced lobar tracheal bronchus
HP:0033618.definition: Accessory entire right upper lobe bronchial system originating from the trachea with absent anatomically normal upper lobe bronchus.

HP:0033619.name: Typical perifissural nodule
HP:0033619.definition: A perifissural nodule that has contact with the interlobar septum (and is therefore considered typical).

HP:0033620.name: Atypical perifissural nodule
HP:0033620.definition: A perifissural nodule that does not have contact with the interlobar septum (and is therefore considered atypical).

HP:0033621.name: Bronchial diverticula
HP:0033621.definition: Bronchial diverticula are blind-ended outpouchings arising from the bronchial tree. They are commonly pulsion diverticula acquired related to chronic cough. Subcarinal air cyst is thought to represent a small main bronchial diverticulum.

HP:0033622.name: Migratory erythematous plaque
HP:0033622.definition: A migratory, centrifugal, erythematous, tender, non-purpuric, and well-demarcated plaque. This feature may be observed in TNF receptor-associated periodic syndrome, in which it often occurs together with migratory myalgia in muscles located underneath the affected areas of skin.

HP:0033623.name: Birth history
HP:0033623.definition: Information about the delivery and health status at birth typically elicited as a part of the past medical history.

HP:0033624.name: History of congenital CMV infection
HP:0033624.definition: A congenital cytomegalovirus (CMV) infection of the newborn can follow either a primary or recurrent maternal infection. Jaundice, petechiae, and hepatosplenomegaly are the most frequently noted clinical triad in symptomatic infants. Affected infants may develop permanent disabilities such as hearing loss, vision loss, motor and cognitive deficits.

HP:0033625.name: Emotional insecurity
HP:0033625.definition: A feeling of general unease or nervousness that may be triggered by a sense of vulnerability or instability, which is perceived as threatening.

HP:0033626.name: Increased non-HDL cholesterol concentration
HP:0033626.definition: Increase above normal levels of non-HDL cholesterol in the blood. Non-HDL cholesterol is total cholesterol minus high-density lipoprotein HDL-cholesterol (high-density lipoprotein-cholesterol).

HP:0033627.name: Increased urine harderoporphyrin level
HP:0033627.definition: Concentration of harderoporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0033628.name: Bowel irritability
HP:0033628.definition: Intermittent abdominal pain with diarrhea and/or constipation.

HP:0033629.name: IgG4 autoimmune antibody positivity
HP:0033629.definition: The presence of an antibody of subclass IgG4 in the blood circulation that is directed against the organism's own cells or tissues.

HP:0033630.name: Brain fog
HP:0033630.definition: Brain fog is a type of transient cognitive dysfunction that comprises a constellation of symptoms that impair intellectual functioning to a level that interferes with daily activities, commonly including forgetfulness, mental slowness, difficulty thinking or focusing, a perceived slowing of mental processing speed, inability to find the right words, a sensation that the mind went blank or is "cloudy". Brain fog tends to recur and may be triggered by factors such as physical fatigue, lack of sleep, and prolonged standing or may appear to occur spontaneously.

HP:0033631.name: Spondylitis
HP:0033631.definition: Inflammation of the vertebrae (vertebral bodies) or spine.

HP:0033632.name: Abnormal alveolar volume
HP:0033632.definition: Alveolar volume (VA) is a volume accessible during 10-second breath-hold, measured during a single breath maneuver. VA is calculated by knowing the fractional concentration of the tracer gas (eg helium) and the volume of the gas inhaled. VA = Vi*(Fi tracer/Fa tracer). In this equation, Vi = inspired volume of tracer gas, Fi tracer= inspired fraction of tracer gas, Fa tracer = alveolar (exhaled) fraction of tracer gas.

HP:0033633.name: Decreased alveolar volume
HP:0033633.definition: An abnormal reduction in alveolar volume.

HP:0033634.name: Increased alveolar volume
HP:0033634.definition: An abnormal elevation in alveolar volume.

HP:0033635.name: Post-capillary pulmonary hypertension
HP:0033635.definition: Post-capillary pulmonary hypertension is a hemodynamic condition characterized by elevated mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP greater than 20 mmHg) and pulmonary artery wedge pressure (PAWP greater than 15 mmHg) and pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR less than 3 Wood units).

HP:0033636.name: Combined pre- and post-capillary pulmonary hypertension
HP:0033636.definition: Combined pre- and post-capillary pulmonary hypertension is a haemodynamic condition characterized by elevated mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP over 20 mmHg) and pulmonary artery wedge pressure (PAWP over 15 mmHg) and pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR at least 3 Wodd units).

HP:0033637.name: Anti-endomysial antibody positivity
HP:0033637.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against endomysial tissue transglutaminase 2 (tTG2).

HP:0033638.name: Intralobular septal thickening
HP:0033638.definition: Intralobular septal thickening is a computed tomography finding of increased width of the walls (septa) within a pulmonary lobule. Secondary pulmonary lobules represent a cluster of up to 30 acini 9 supplied by a common distal pulmonary artery and bronchiole. These clustered acini are bounded by interstitial fibrous septa (interlobular septa) which outline an irregular polyhedron of varying size between 1 and 2.5 cm. Interlobular septal thickening is seen on chest radiographs as thin linear opacities at right angles to and in contact with the lateral pleural surfaces near the lung bases. In contrast, intralobular septal thickening are visible as fine linear opacities in a lobule when the intralobular interstitial tissue is abnormally thickened. When numerous, they may appear as a fine reticular pattern.

HP:0033639.name: Septic pulmonary embolism
HP:0033639.definition: Embolization of intravascular thrombus containing microorganisms into the pulmonary parenchyma via arterial system. Septic pulmonary embolism (PE) can be associated with multiple additional clinical manifestations such as fever, tachypnea, and hemoptysis. This HPO term refers to the finding of the septic embolus in the lung, which can be inferred from radiological findings. Typical radiographic features of septic PE include patchy air space lesions simulating non-specific bronchopneumonia; multiple ill defined round or wedge shaped densities of varying sizes from approximately 0.5 to 3.5 cm located peripherally; lesions abutting the pleura and located at the end of vessels (feeding vessel sign) seen on chest CT scans. Other pulmonary features suggesting septic PE include bilateral, occasional unilateral, rapid progression of cavities or abscess formations.

HP:0033640.name: Acetabular erosions
HP:0033640.definition: Erosion (loss of substance) of the acetabular subchondral cortical bone. The acetabulum is the concave surface that meets with the head of the femur, forming the hip joint.

HP:0033641.name: Aortic valve leaflet calcification
HP:0033641.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in the leaflets (cusps) of the aortic valve.

HP:0033642.name: Mitral valve leaflet calcification
HP:0033642.definition: Deposition of calcium salts in the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve.

HP:0033643.name: Increased circulating very long-chain fatty acid concentration
HP:0033643.definition: Increased concentration of very long-chain fatty acids in the blood circulation. Very long-chain fatty acids are fatty acids (FAs) with a chain-length of 22 or more carbons.

HP:0033644.name: Elevated circulating erythropoietin concentration
HP:0033644.definition: Increased concentration of erythropoietin in the blood circulation. Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the peritubular cells of the kidney that stimulates red blood cell production.

HP:0033645.name: Midline brainstem cleft
HP:0033645.definition: A developmental defect characterized by an abnormal cleft (V-shaped indentation of the stalklike part of the brain consisting of the medulla oblongata, the midbrain, and the pons.

HP:0410373.name: Abnormal naive CD4-positive T cell proportion
HP:0410373.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the naive CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA+, CD45RO-, or CD27+, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These cells are sometimes also characterized as CD62L+ and CCR7+.

HP:0410374.name: Abnormal naive CD8 T cell proportion
HP:0410374.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the naive CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA+, CD45RO-, or CD27+, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These cells are sometimes also characterized as CD62L+ and CCR7+.

HP:0410375.name: Increased naive CD4-positive T cell proportion

HP:0410376.name: Increased proportion of naive CD8 T cells
HP:0410376.definition: Abnormal increase of the naive CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA+, CD45RO-, or CD27+, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These cells are sometimes also characterized as CD62L+ and CCR7+.

HP:0410377.name: Decreased naive CD8 T cell proportion
HP:0410377.definition: Abnormal decrease of the naive CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA+, CD45RO-, or CD27+, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These cells are sometimes also characterized as CD62L+ and CCR7+.

HP:0410378.name: Decreased naive CD4-positive T cell proportion
HP:0410378.definition: The proportion of naive CD4 T cells relative to the total number of T cells is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0410379.name: Abnormal CD4+ memory T cell proportion
HP:0410379.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the memory CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0410380.name: Abnormal CD8+ memory T cell proportion
HP:0410380.definition: Abnormal increase or decrease of the memory CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0410381.name: obsolete Abnormal proportion of central memory CD4-positive T cells

HP:0410382.name: obsolete Abnormal proportion of effector memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells

HP:0410383.name: Abnormal effector memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410383.definition: An abnormal proportion of effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype of CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410384.name: Abnormal central memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410384.definition: An abnormal proportion of central memory CD8-positive memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-positive, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410385.name: Decreased CD8+ memory T cell proportion
HP:0410385.definition: Decreased proportion of CD8-positive memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. A CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell with memory phenotype is CD45RO and CD127-positive. This cell type is also described as being CD25-negative, CD44-high, and CD122-high.

HP:0410386.name: Decreased proportion of CD4-positive memory T cells
HP:0410386.definition: Decresaed proportion of CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype of CD45RO-positive and CD127-positive. This cell type is also described as being CD25-negative, CD44-high, and CD122-high.

HP:0410387.name: obsolete Decreased proportion of effector memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells

HP:0410388.name: Decreased proportion of central memory CD4-positive T cells
HP:0410388.definition: A reduced proportion of central memory CD4-positive memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype of CCR7-positive, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410389.name: Decreased central memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410389.definition: A reduced proportion of CD8-positive central memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410390.name: Decreased effector memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410390.definition: A reduced proportion of CD8-positive effector memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410391.name: Increased CD4+ memory T cell proportion
HP:0410391.definition: Abnormal increase of the memory CD4+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD4+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0410392.name: Increased CD8+ memory T cell proportion
HP:0410392.definition: Abnormal increase of the memory CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

HP:0410393.name: Increased proportion of central memory CD4-positive T cells
HP:0410393.definition: An abnormally elevated proportion of central memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype of CCR7-positive, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410394.name: Increased proportion of effector memory CD4-positive T cells
HP:0410394.definition: An abnormally elevated proportion of effector memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410395.name: Increased effector memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410395.definition: An increased proportion of effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-negative, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410396.name: Increased central memory CD8+ T cell proportion
HP:0410396.definition: An increased proportion of central memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CCR7-positive, CD127-positive, CD45RA-negative, CD45RO-positive, and CD25-negative.

HP:0410397.name: Bronchiolectasis
HP:0410397.definition: Saccular dilatation of the terminal bronchioles.

HP:0410399.name: Positive blood lead test
HP:0410399.definition: Detection of lead in the blood.

HP:0410400.name: Absent sebaceous glands
HP:0410400.definition: Absence of the sebaceous gland, the holocrine gland that secretes sebum into the hair follicles, or in hairless areas into ducts.

HP:0410401.name: Worse in evening
HP:0410401.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is exacerbated in the evening as compared to the day.

HP:0430000.name: Abnormal frontal bone morphology
HP:0430000.definition: An abnormality of the frontal bone.

HP:0430002.name: Abnormal lacrimal bone morphology
HP:0430002.definition: An abnormality of the lacrimal bone.

HP:0430003.name: Abnormal palatine bone morphology
HP:0430003.definition: An abnormality of the palatine bone.

HP:0430005.name: Abnormal ethmoid bone morphology
HP:0430005.definition: An abnormality of the ethmoid bone

HP:0430006.name: Ectopic cilia of eyelid
HP:0430006.definition: An eyelash that emerges from the underside (conjunctiva) of the upper or lower eyelid.

HP:0430007.name: Symblepharon
HP:0430007.definition: A partial or complete adhesion of the palpebral conjunctiva of the eyelid to the bulbar conjunctiva of the eyeball.

HP:0430008.name: Accessory eyelid
HP:0430008.definition: The presence of more than the normal number of eyelids.

HP:0430010.name: Microblepharia
HP:0430010.definition: Abnormal shortness of the vertical dimensions of the eyelids.

HP:0430011.name: Defect of palpebral conjunctiva
HP:0430011.definition: An abnormality of the palpebral conjunctiva.

HP:0430012.name: Incomplete ossification of palatine bone
HP:0430012.definition: Failure to complete ossification (maturation and calcification) of the palatine bone.

HP:0430013.name: Absent palatine bone ossification
HP:0430013.definition: Lack of formation of the palatine bone.

HP:0430014.name: Abnormality of musculature of soft palate
HP:0430014.definition: An abnormality of one or more of the five muscles of the soft palate.

HP:0430015.name: Abnormal morphology of musculature of pharynx
HP:0430015.definition: An abnormality of any of the muscles of the pharynx.

HP:0430016.name: Abnormality of tensor veli palatini muscle
HP:0430016.definition: An abnormality of the tensor veli palatini muscle

HP:0430017.name: Abnormality of uvular muscle
HP:0430017.definition: An abnormality of the uvular muscle

HP:0430018.name: Abnormality of nasal musculature
HP:0430018.definition: An abnormality of the muscles of the structure of the nose.

HP:0430019.name: Abnormality of muscle of facial expression
HP:0430019.definition: An abnormality of any of the muscles of facial expression, which are innervated by the seventh (VII) cranial nerve and control facial expression.

HP:0430020.name: Abnormality of levator labii superioris alaeque nasi muscle
HP:0430020.definition: An abnormality of the levator labii superioris alaeque nasi muscle.

HP:0430021.name: Abnormal common carotid artery morphology
HP:0430021.definition: An abnormality of the common carotid arteries, which provide the arterial supply to the head and neck and give rise to the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.

HP:0430022.name: Abnormality of the sphenoid sinus
HP:0430022.definition: An abnormality of the sphenoid sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The sphenoid sinus is located within the sphenoid bone.

HP:0430023.name: Abnormality of the maxillary sinus
HP:0430023.definition: An abnormality of the maxillary sinus, one of the mucosa-lined, normally air-filled paranasal sinuses of the bones of the skull. The maxillary sinus is located within the skeleton of the midface, lateral to the nasal cavity.

HP:0430024.name: Abnormality of external jugular vein
HP:0430024.definition: An abnormality of an external jugular vein of the neck.

HP:0430025.name: Bilateral facial palsy
HP:0430025.definition: Two-sided or bilateral weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure.

HP:0430026.name: obsolete Abnormality of the shape of the midface

HP:0430028.name: Hyperplasia of the maxilla
HP:0430028.definition: Abnormally increased dimension of the maxilla, especially relative to the mandible, resulting in a malocclusion or malalignment between the upper and lower teeth or in anterior positioning of the nasal base, increased convexity of the face, increased nasolabial angle, or increased width (transverse dimension of the maxilla.

HP:0430029.name: Hyperplasia of the premaxilla
HP:0430029.definition: An abnormality of the premaxilla (the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla) causing it to appear relatively large in size compared to the other parts of the maxilla or other facial structures.

HP:0430030.name: Positive infectious agent test
HP:0430030.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in a specimen positive.

HP:0430031.name: Aqueous humor viral DNA positivity
HP:0430031.definition: The presence of viral DNA (e.g., cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex virus, or varicella zoster virus) in the aqueous humor of the eye.

HP:0430032.name: Electronic cigarette exposure history
HP:0430032.definition: History of use of electronic cigarettes (vaping).

HP:0430033.name: Gottron sign
HP:0430033.definition: Erythematous macules or patches over extensor surfaces of elbows, knuckles, knees, and ankles.

HP:0430034.name: Hypertension resistant to conventional therapy
HP:0430034.definition: Resistant hypertension is defined as above-goal elevated blood pressure in a patient despite the concurrent use of 3 antihypertensive drug classes, commonly including a long-acting calcium channel blocker, a blocker of the renin-angiotensin system (angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker), and a diuretic.

HP:0430035.name: Tibiofibular interosseous membrane calcification
HP:0430035.definition: Deposition of excess calcium in the interosseous membrane of the leg, which extends between the interosseous crests of the tibia and fibula and separates the anterior and posterior muscles of the lower leg.

HP:0430036.name: Supracondylar elbow fracture
HP:0430036.definition: A type of elbow fracture that involves the distal humerus just above the elbow.

HP:0430043.name: Thoracic lordosis
HP:0430043.definition: Thoracic lordosis refers to an abnormal curvature of the thoracic spine in which the thoracic spine displays lordosis (inward curve) instead of the normal kyphosis (outward curve).

HP:0430044.name: Radiation into left arm
HP:0430044.definition: Refers to pain or discomfort that is perceived to travel from the chest into the left arm.

HP:0430045.name: Radiation into right arm
HP:0430045.definition: Refers to pain or discomfort that is perceived to travel from the chest into the right arm.

HP:0430046.name: Small joint hypermobilty
HP:0430046.definition:
The capability that a small joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Small joints include metacarpophalangeal joints, proximal interphalangeal joints, 
second to fifth metatarsophalangeal joints, and wrists.

HP:0430047.name: Large joint hypermobilty
HP:0430047.definition: The capability that a large joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Large joints include shoulders, elbows, hips, knees, and ankles.

HP:0430048.name: Intracranial calcification
HP:0430048.definition: Intracranial calcifications refer to calcifications within the brain parenchyma or vasculature. The five major components of the brain comprise the cerebrum, cerebellum, brain stem, pituitary gland, and hypothalamus.

HP:0430050.name: Anti-thyroid antibody positivity
HP:0430050.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against one or more components on the thyroid.

HP:0430051.name: Bloodstream pathogen-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430051.definition: Positive serology for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining serum for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

HP:0430052.name: Anti-SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus antibody positivity
HP:0430052.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus type 2 (SARS-CoV-2).

HP:0430053.name: Anti-West Nile virus antibody positivity
HP:0430053.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the West Nile virus.

HP:0430054.name: Anti-microfilaria antibody positivity
HP:0430054.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a microfilaria (parasite).

HP:0430055.name: Anti-trypanosoma cruzi antibody positivity
HP:0430055.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of trypanosoma cruzi.

HP:0430056.name: Anti-chikungunya virus antibody positivity
HP:0430056.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chikungunya virus.

HP:0430057.name: Anti-chlamydia psittaci antibody positivity
HP:0430057.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chlamydia psittaci.

HP:0430058.name: Anti-herpes simplex antibody positivity
HP:0430058.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of herpes simplex.

HP:0430059.name: Bloodstream virus-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430059.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a virus.

HP:0430060.name: Bloodstream parasite-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430060.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a parasite.

HP:0430061.name: Bloodstream antibacterial antibody positivity
HP:0430061.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a bacterium.

HP:0430062.name: Anti-Japanese encephalitis virus-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430062.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Japanese encephalitis virus.

HP:0430063.name: Anti-chlamydia trachomatis-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430063.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chlamydia trachomatis.

HP:0430064.name: Anti-Epstein-Barr virus-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430064.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Epstein Barr virus (EBV).

HP:0430065.name: Anti-babesia-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430065.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a parasite of the genus Babesia (parasite).

HP:0430066.name: Anti-Zikavirus-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430066.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Zika virus.

HP:0430067.name: Positive bloodstream nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:0430067.definition: Positive (abnormal) result of a test such as polymerase chain reaction that is targeted against a nucleic acid sequence specific for a pathogen.

HP:0430068.name: Positive microfilaria PCR test in the blood circulation
HP:0430068.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of a microfilarial parasite in the blood circulation.

HP:0430069.name: Positive JC-virus PCR test in the blood circulation
HP:0430069.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of the JC-virus (JC-Polyomavirus, John Cunningham virus) in the blood circulation.

HP:0430070.name: Placenta previa
HP:0430070.definition: Implantation of the placenta over or near the internal os of the cervix.

HP:0430071.name: Abnormal circulating organic compound concentration
HP:0430071.definition: Any deviation of the concentration of an orrganic compound from the normal range. An organic compound is defined as any compound that contains a carbon atom.

HP:0430072.name: Abnormal circulating beta-carotene concentration
HP:0430072.definition: Any deviation of the concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation from the normal range.

HP:0430073.name: Decreased circulating beta-carotene concentration
HP:0430073.definition: The concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0430074.name: Increased circulating beta-carotene concentration
HP:0430074.definition: The concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430075.name: Mammary blocked duct
HP:0430075.definition: Blocked mammary ducts represent an area of localized milk stasis, typically associated with breast engorgement and resulting in a localized tender breast lump or area of blushed color; the breast may feel hot; and there may be a white, painful bleb on the end of the nipple.

HP:0430076.name: Bloodstream antifungal antibody positivity
HP:0430076.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a fungus.

HP:0430077.name: Anti-coccidioidal antibody positivity
HP:0430077.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a fungus of the Coccidioides genus.

HP:0430078.name: Anti-cryptococcal antibody positivity
HP:0430078.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a fungus of the Cryptoccous genus.

HP:0430079.name: Anti-mycoplasma antibody positivity
HP:0430079.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a mycoplasmal component.

HP:0430080.name: Anti-rickettsial antibody positivity
HP:0430080.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a rickettsial bacterium. Rickettsiae are gram-negative bacteria with an obligate intracellular life cycle circulating between mammalian hosts and hematophagous arthropod vectors

HP:0430081.name: Anti-Bartonella henselae antibody positivity
HP:0430081.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Bartonella.

HP:0430082.name: Anti-Dengue virus antibody positivity
HP:0430082.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Dengue virus.

HP:0430083.name: Anti-arbovirus antibody positivity
HP:0430083.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of an Arbovirus.

HP:0430084.name: Anti-lymphocytic choriomeningitis antibody positivity
HP:0430084.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus (LCMV).

HP:0430085.name: Anti-varicella-zoster antibody positivity
HP:0430085.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Varicella-zoster virus.

HP:0430086.name: Anti-rubella antibody positivity
HP:0430086.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of rubella virus.

HP:0430087.name: Anti-cytomegalovirus antibody positivity
HP:0430087.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of cytomegalovirus (CMV).

HP:0430088.name: Anti-measles antibody positivity
HP:0430088.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of measles virus.

HP:0430089.name: Anti-schistosoma antibody positivity
HP:0430089.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a parasite of the genus Schistosomiasis is a parasitic disease historically known as bilharzia caused by the trematode of the genus Schistosoma. Schistosomiasis is a parasitic disease historically known as bilharzia caused by the trematode of the genus Schistosoma.

HP:0430090.name: Anti-Powassan virus antibody positivity
HP:0430090.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a Powassan virus (POW), which is an arbovirus within the family of Flaviviruses primarily found in the Northeastern United States, Canada, and Russia. It is a zoonotic infection transmitted to humans by several tick species and is the only member of the tick-borne flaviviruses endemic to North America.

HP:0430091.name: Marker expression
HP:0430091.definition: Detection of a marker such as a protein by immunohistochemistry or related investigation techniques. The presence or absence of such markers can be used to identify cell types on the basis of a profile of expressed markers. These terms do not imply abnormality and can be used for any cell type or organ.

HP:0430092.name: BCL2 expression
HP:0430092.definition: Detection of the presence of BCL2 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-BCL2 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430093.name: BCL6 expression
HP:0430093.definition: Detection of the presence of BCL6 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-BCL6 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430094.name: CD5 expression
HP:0430094.definition: Detection of the presence of CD5 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD5 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430095.name: CD10 expression
HP:0430095.definition: Detection of the presence of CD10 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD10 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430096.name: CD23 expression
HP:0430096.definition: Detection of the presence of CD23 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD23 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430097.name: CD38 expression
HP:0430097.definition: Detection of the presence of CD38 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD38 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430098.name: CD45 expression
HP:0430098.definition: Detection of the presence of CD45 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD45 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430099.name: Cyclin D1 expression
HP:0430099.definition: Detection of the presence of cyclin D1 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-cyclin D1 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430100.name: FMC7 expression
HP:0430100.definition: Detection of the presence of FMC7 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-FMC7 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430101.name: CD19 expression
HP:0430101.definition: Detection of the presence of CD19 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD19 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430102.name: CD20 expression
HP:0430102.definition: Detection of the presence of CD20 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD20 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).

HP:0430103.name: Past surgical history
HP:0430103.definition: information about the patient's previous surgical treatments that might be relevant to the presenting illness or to provide optimal clinical management.

HP:0430104.name: Abnormal superficial temporal artery morphology
HP:0430104.definition: Any structural abnormality of a superficial temporal artery, originating from the external carotid artery and passing over the zygomatic process. The superficial temporal artery is located on the superficial parts of the forehead and sides of the head and face.

HP:0430105.name: Skip lesions on temporal artery biopsy
HP:0430105.definition: Patchy inflammation of the superficial temporal artery, forming isolated foci of arteritis.

HP:0430106.name: Abnormal brain-evoked potentials
HP:0430106.definition: Any anomaly of brain-evoked potentials, defined as potentials generated by exteroceptive stimuli reflect synchronized activity by neuronal and axonal groups in the central nervous system (CNS) resulting from the arrival of nerve impulses after stimulation of a peripheral nerve or its receptors. Depending on the type of stimulus, evoked potentials are categorized as visual (VEP), auditory (AEP), or somatosensory (SSEP). Motor evoked potentials (MEP) occur when the brain's motor area is stimulated. They result from the activation of a sufficient number of motor units.

HP:0430107.name: Sputum infectious agent
HP:0430107.definition: The presence of an infectious agent in the sputum, as characterized by sputum culture or other investigation.

HP:0430108.name: Positive Mycobacterium avium sputum culture
HP:0430108.definition: Growth of mycobacterium avium in a sputum culture.

HP:0430109.name: Positive bloodstream infectious agent antigen test
HP:0430109.definition: A test result demonstrating the presence of an antigen (marker such as a protein against which an antibody reacts) specific to an infectious agent.

HP:0430110.name: Positive bloodstream Cysticercosis antigen test
HP:0430110.definition: Demonstration of an antigen specific to Cysticercosis in the bloodstream.

HP:0430111.name: Klazomania
HP:0430111.definition: Involuntary attacks of compulsive paroxysmal shouting. The shouting behaviors may be extremely loud and not related to the ongoing mental state of the affected individual. Shouting episodes may occur in bouts and last for several hours.

HP:0430112.name: Coprolalia
HP:0430112.definition: Coprolalia denotes the involuntary utterance of obscenities. Intent is an important classifier in coprolalic behaviors, and unfortunately it remains unclear how to objectively distinguish coprolalia from common swearing.

HP:0430113.name: Continuous involuntary vocalizations
HP:0430113.definition: Continuous groaning, moaning, grunting, and shrieking.

HP:0430114.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the uterine cervix
