HP:0430114.definition: Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the uterine cervix.

HP:0430116.name: Primary peritoneal serous papillary adenocarcinoma
HP:0430116.definition: A serous papillary adenocarcinoma that arises from the lining of the peritoneum

HP:0430117.name: Positive skin infectious agent test
HP:0430117.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in skin positive.

HP:0430118.name: Positive skin fungus test
HP:0430118.definition: A test for fungus, e.g., fungal hyphae, in a skin specimen (usually a skin scraping), demonstrates the presence of fungi. Most commonly, a skin scraping is obtained using a small scalpel blade, the specimen is placed on a clean glass slide, a drop of potassium hydroxide (KOH) is added, and the specimen is examined microscopically for fungal structures such as hyphae or yeast.

HP:0430119.name: Nasal secretion eosinophilia
HP:0430119.definition: Count of eosinophils in nasal secretions (for instance, nasal discharge) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430120.name: Nasal secretion neutrophilia
HP:0430120.definition: Count of neutrophils in nasal secretions (for instance, nasal discharge) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430121.name: Seminal vesicle agenesis
HP:0430121.definition: A developmental defect characterized by congenital absence of the seminal vesicle.

HP:0430122.name: Head impulse test has corrective saccade
HP:0430122.definition: In a patient with nystagmus, The examiner briskly rotates the head of the patient while having the patient fixate on a target. A corrective saccade indicates the patient's eye will move in one direction and quickly return back to neutral position.

HP:0430123.name: Positive CSF infectious agent test
HP:0430123.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) positive.

HP:0430124.name: Positive CSF toxoplasma gondii nucleic acid test
HP:0430124.definition: Detection of Toxoplasma gondii nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:0430125.name: Elevated circulating plasminogen activator inhibitor 1 activity
HP:0430125.definition: The activity or concentration of plasminogen activator inhibitor-1 in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430126.name: Abnormal circulating plasminogen activator inhibitor 1 activity
HP:0430126.definition: The activity or concentration of plasminogen activator inhibitor-1 in the blood circulation is outside of the limits of the normal range.

HP:0430127.name: Brain localization
HP:0430127.definition: The pattern by which a phenotype is localized to or predominant in a part of the brain.

HP:0430128.name: Frontal cortical localization
HP:0430128.definition: Localization to or predominance in the frontal cortex of the brain.

HP:0430129.name: Posterior fossa localization
HP:0430129.definition: Localization to or predominance in the parts of the brain within the posterior fossa.

HP:0430130.name: Subcortical localization
HP:0430130.definition: Localization to or predominance in the subcortical region of the brain.

HP:0430131.name: Parietal cortex localization
HP:0430131.definition: Localization to or predominance in the parietal cortex of the brain.

HP:0430132.name: Occipital cortex localization
HP:0430132.definition: Localization to or predominance in the occipital cortex of the brain.

HP:0430133.name: Tobacco use history
HP:0430133.definition: History of use of tobacco products such as cigarettes.

HP:0430134.name: Bartholin cyst
HP:0430134.definition: A fluid-filled sac near the vaginal opening. A Bartholin cyst is usually unilateral, asymptomatic blockage of the Bartholin gland, which may lead to a painless swelling.

HP:0430135.name: Abnormal circulating hepatic transaminase concentration
HP:0430135.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of alanine aminotransferase or aspartate aminotransferase.

HP:0430136.name: Reduced circulating aspartate aminotransferase concentration
HP:0430136.definition: The concentration of aspartate aminotransferase (AST) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0430137.name: Elevated urine succinic acid level
HP:0430137.definition: The concentration of succinic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430138.name: Positive CSF varicella zoster virus nucleic acid test
HP:0430138.definition: Detection of Varicella zoster virus nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:0430139.name: CSF pathogen-specific antibody positivity
HP:0430139.definition: Positive serology in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining CSF for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

HP:0430140.name: Positive CSF nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:0430140.definition: Positive (abnormal) result of a cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) test such as polymerase chain reaction that is targeted against a nucleic acid sequence specific for a pathogen.

HP:0430141.name: CSF varicella zoster antibody positivity
HP:0430141.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of varicella zoster virus.

HP:0430142.name: Reduced circulating interleukin 6 concentration
HP:0430142.definition: The concentration of interleukin-6 in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:0430143.name: Elevated circulating C12 acylcarnitine concentration
HP:0430143.definition: Concentration of C12 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C12 acylcarnitines have a twelve-carbon acyl chain.

HP:0430144.name: Frontalis muscle overactivity
HP:0430144.definition: Increased activity of the frontalis muscle, causing a characteristic staring and astonished facial expression.

HP:0430145.name: Nasal dermoid cyst
HP:0430145.definition: An ectodermal inclusion cyst containing skin and skin appendages; sebaceous glands, hair follicles, and occasionally sweat glands.

HP:0430146.name: Elevated circulating complement C3 concentration
HP:0430146.definition: Concentration of the complement component C3 in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0430147.name: Abnormal circulating inhibin B concentration
HP:0430147.definition: The concentration of inhibin B in the blood circulation is outside the limits of normal.

HP:0430148.name: Abnormal circulating lipoprotein(a) concentration
HP:0430148.definition: The concentration of lipoprotein(a) in the blood circulation is outside the limits of normal.

HP:0430150.name: Positive blood infectious agent test
HP:0430150.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the blood circulation positive.

HP:0430151.name: Positive respiratory tract infectious agent test
HP:0430151.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the respiratory tract positive.

HP:0500001.name: Body odor
HP:0500001.definition: A perceived unpleasant smell given off by the body.

HP:0500005.name: Anal pain
HP:0500005.definition: Pain in and around the anus or rectum (perianal region).

HP:0500007.name: Iris flocculi
HP:0500007.definition: Multiple cysts along the pupillary margin that appear as spherical or tear-drop-shaped pigmented lesions or wrinkled masses emerging from the pupillary border of the iris.

HP:0500008.name: Cornea verticillata
HP:0500008.definition: Golden brown or gray deposits with a clockwise, whorl-like distribution in the inferior interpalpebal portion of the cornea.

HP:0500009.name: Dysplastic gangliocytoma of the cerebellum
HP:0500009.definition: It is a rare, slowly growing tumor of the cerebellum, a gangliocytoma sometimes considered to be a hamartoma, characterized by diffuse hypertrophy of the granular layer of the cerebellum.

HP:0500011.name: Moon facies
HP:0500011.definition: A rounded, puffy face with fat deposits in the temporal fossa and cheeks, a double chin.

HP:0500012.name: Abnormal gonadotropin-releasing hormone concentration
HP:0500012.definition: A deviation from the normal circulating concentration of the normal gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH). Intermittent GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus acts upon its receptor in the anterior pituitary to regulate the production and release of the gonadotropins, follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).

HP:0500013.name: Lack of gonadotropin-releasing hormone pulsatility
HP:0500013.definition: Secretion of gonadotropin-releasing hormone that does not occur in a pulsatile fashion.

HP:0500015.name: Abnormal cardiac test
HP:0500015.definition: Abnormal test result of cardiovascular physiology.

HP:0500016.name: Abnormal cardiac MRI
HP:0500016.definition: Abnormal results of a MRI for the heart.

HP:0500017.name: Abnormal cardiac catheterization
HP:0500017.definition: Abnormal results from the diagnostic tests resulting from cardiac catheterization.

HP:0500018.name: Abnormal cardiac exercise stress test
HP:0500018.definition: Abnormal results of exercise on heart function.

HP:0500019.name: Abnormal resting energy expenditure from metabolic cart test
HP:0500019.definition: Resting energy expenditure (REE) can be measured with indirect calorimetry using a metabolic cart, which is used to measure the oxygen consumption (VO2) and carbon dioxide production (VCO2).

HP:0500020.name: Abnormal cardiac biomarker test
HP:0500020.definition: Abnormal blood test results measuring creatine kinase (CK), CK-MB, troponin (TROPI), myoglobin, and/or cardiac enzymes.

HP:0500021.name: Reduced brain gamma-aminobutyric acid level by MRS
HP:0500021.definition: An decreased level of gamma-aminobutyric acid in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:0500022.name: Abnormal circulating dehydroepiandrosterone concentration
HP:0500022.definition: A deviation from the normal concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone in the circulation.

HP:0500024.name: Aplasia of the musculature of the pelvis
HP:0500024.definition: Absence of the musculature of the pelvis.

HP:0500026.name: Hypoplasia of the musculature of the pelvis
HP:0500026.definition: Underdevelopment of the musculature of the pelvis.

HP:0500028.name: Cotton wool plaques
HP:0500028.definition: Deposition of large, diffuse cotton wool amyloid plaques (CWPs) lacking a dense core and associated neuritic changes.

HP:0500030.name: Abnormal hepatic glycogen storage
HP:0500030.definition: Change in normal glycogen storage content.

HP:0500031.name: Sclerosis of the carpal bones
HP:0500031.definition: An elevation in bone density in one or more carpal bones of the hand.

HP:0500032.name: Abnormal neuron branching
HP:0500032.definition: Abnormality of the structure and branching of the dendrites of a neuron.

HP:0500033.name: Abnormal natural killer subset distribution
HP:0500033.definition: Any abnormality in the proportion natural killer subsets relative to the total number of natural killer cells.

HP:0500035.name: Nasolacrimal sac granuloma
HP:0500035.definition: A mass of granulation tissue in response to chronic dacryocystitis as polypoid formations or they follow accidental injury, from probing and as a reaction to retained foreign bodies in the sac.

HP:0500036.name: Nasolacrimal sac papilloma
HP:0500036.definition: Benign tumor of the nasolacrimal sac.

HP:0500037.name: Nasolacrimal sac epithelial papillary carcinoma
HP:0500037.definition: The malignant epithelial neoplasm with papillary growths in the nasolacrimal sac.

HP:0500039.name: Conjunctival cicatrization
HP:0500039.definition: An abnormality of the conjuctiva and ocular surface caused by conjunctival inflammation and associated with scarring.

HP:0500040.name: Dermolipoma of the conjunctiva
HP:0500040.definition: A benign tumor composed of adipose tissue and dense connective tissue usually located near the temporal fornix.

HP:0500041.name: Myopic astigmatism
HP:0500041.definition: A condition where one or both of the two principal meridians focus in the front of the retina when the eye is at rest.

HP:0500042.name: Latent hypermetropia
HP:0500042.definition: A term to describe when farsightedness is masked when the accommodative muscles are used to increase the focusing power of the eye.

HP:0500043.name: Eyelid retraction
HP:0500043.definition: With the eyes in primary position, the sclera is visible above the superior corneal limbus.

HP:0500044.name: Upper eyelid retraction
HP:0500044.definition: An elevation of the eyelid above the normal level in the primary position.

HP:0500045.name: Collier's sign
HP:0500045.definition: A unilateral or bilateral eyelid retraction due to midbrain lesions.

HP:0500046.name: Seborrhoeic blepharitis
HP:0500046.definition: Inflammation of the eyelid due to overactivity of the sebaceous gland.

HP:0500047.name: Nasolacrimal sac lymphoma
HP:0500047.definition: A type of lymphoma that involves the nasolacrimal sac.

HP:0500048.name: Delayed canalization of nasolacrimal duct
HP:0500048.definition: A very common condition in which the extreme end of the nasolacrimal duct underneath the inferior turbinate fails to complete its canalization in the newborn period.

HP:0500049.name: Retinopathy of prematurity
HP:0500049.definition: An avascular or abnormally vascularized retina that occurs in premature infants and can lead to blindness.

HP:0500050.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 1
HP:0500050.definition: The retinal vessels stop and then a linear flat white line is present that usually runs the circumference of the vascular retina.

HP:0500051.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 2
HP:0500051.definition: The accumulating neovascularization thickens and manifests as a linear bump. The neovascularization remains along the surface of the retina and does not extend off the retina into the cortical vitreous.

HP:0500052.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 3
HP:0500052.definition: The neovascularization accumulates at the edge of the vascularized retina and extends into the vitreous (also called extra retinal fibrosis proliferation). In cases of Zone 2 and Zone 3, this may be sausage shaped. In more posterior Zone 1 disease, the stage 3 can appear as a direct extension of the normal retinal vessels but extending tangentially over the avascular retina.

HP:0500053.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 4
HP:0500053.definition: Scar tissue that forms a continuous sheet coming up from the edge of the vascularized retina. This scar tissue can grow toward the vitreous base/posterior lens capsule resulting in traction, distortion, and even detachment.

HP:0500054.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 4a
HP:0500054.definition: A detachment that involves the peripheral retina that does not extend into the macula.

HP:0500055.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 4b
HP:0500055.definition: A detachment that involves the peripheral retina that involves the macula itself. The detachment usually starts in the temporal periphery although can also involve the nasal retina as well.

HP:0500056.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 5
HP:0500056.definition: Funnel detachment from the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.

HP:0500057.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 5a
HP:0500057.definition: An open funnel detachment of the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.

HP:0500058.name: Retinopathy of prematurity stage 5b
HP:0500058.definition: A closed funnel detachment of the retina with generally traction in all four quadrants.

HP:0500059.name: Retinopathy of prematurity zone I
HP:0500059.definition: Retinopathy which extends from the center of the optic disc to twice the distance from the center of the optic disc to the center of the macula.

HP:0500060.name: Retinopathy of prematurity zone II
HP:0500060.definition: Retinopathy which extends centrifugally from the edge of zone I to the nasal ora serrata.

HP:0500061.name: Retinopathy of prematurity zone III
HP:0500061.definition: Retinopathy which is a residual crescent of retina anterior to zone II.

HP:0500062.name: Retinopathy of prematurity plus
HP:0500062.definition: Venous dilatation and arteriolar tortuosity of the posterior retinal vessels and may later increase in severity to include iris vascular engorgement, poor pupillary dilatation (rigid pupil), and vitreous haze. This definition has been further refined in the later clinical trials in which the diagnosis of plus disease could be made if sufficient vascular dilatation and tortuosity are present in at least 2 quadrants of the eye.

HP:0500063.name: Retinopathy of prematurity pre-plus
HP:0500063.definition: As vascular abnormalities of the posterior pole that are insufficient for the diagnosis of plus disease but that demonstrate more arterial tortuosity and more venous dilatation than normal.

HP:0500064.name: Retinopathy of prematurity threshold
HP:0500064.definition: A retinopathy with a 50% likelihood of progressing to retinal detachment. Threshold disease is considered to be present when stage 3 retinopathy of prematurity (ROP) is present in either zone I or zone II, with at least 5 continuous or 8 total clock hours of disease, and the presence of plus disease.

HP:0500065.name: Retinopathy of prematurity prethreshold
HP:0500065.definition: High risk patients who were in Zone 1 (no Plus or stage 3) or Zone 2 with Plus or stage 3 but not both.

HP:0500066.name: Latent myopia
HP:0500066.definition: The difference between total and manifest myopia.

HP:0500069.name: Paralytic ectropion
HP:0500069.definition: A type of ectropion associated with orbicularis muscle weakness caused by cranial nerve VII palsy.

HP:0500070.name: Conjunctival dermolipoma
HP:0500070.definition: A conjuctival lesion composed of adipose tissue and dense connective tissue. Such choristomas of dermal elements are normally found at the outer canthus, and have a gelatinous appearance. Classically, there is an indistinct posterior border (with the lesion frequently extending into the orbit) and a well-demarcated anterior border several millimeters posterior to the limbus.

HP:0500072.name: Absolute eccentric fixation
HP:0500072.definition: Eccentric fixation in which the angle of eccentricity equals the objective angle of deviation.

HP:0500073.name: Abnormal ocular alignment
HP:0500073.definition: Any deviation from the normal ocular alignment.

HP:0500074.name: Dissociated vertical deviation
HP:0500074.definition: An incomitant tendency for an occluded eye to elevate and extort which resolves on uncovering.

HP:0500075.name: Dissociated horizontal deviation
HP:0500075.definition: A change in horizontal ocular alignment, unrelated to accommodation, that is brought about solely by a change in the balance of visual input from the two eyes.

HP:0500076.name: Alternating hypertropia
HP:0500076.definition: A type of vertical tropia in which, when one eye is fixing, the other eye is deviated upwards.

HP:0500077.name: Alternating hyperphoria
HP:0500077.definition: A type of vertical phoria in which, in dissociation, the occluded eye deviates upwards.

HP:0500078.name: Alternating hypotropia
HP:0500078.definition: A type of vertical tropia in which, when one eye is fixing, the other eye is deviated downwards.

HP:0500079.name: Alternating hypophoria
HP:0500079.definition: A type of vertical phoria in which, in dissociation, the occluded eye deviates downwards.

HP:0500081.name: Pseudophakia
HP:0500081.definition: The term pseudophakia refers to having an artificial lens implanted after the natural eye lens has been removed. During cataract surgery the natural cloudy lens is replaced by an pseudophakia intraocular lens (IOL).

HP:0500086.name: Optic nerve gray crescent
HP:0500086.definition: Having a characteristic appearance of a slate gray area of pigmentation within the disk margins that commonly appears along the inferotemporal or temporal neuroretinal rim areas.

HP:0500087.name: Peripapillary atrophy
HP:0500087.definition: Thinning in the layers of the retina and retinal pigment epithelium around the optic nerve.

HP:0500088.name: Foveal depigmentation
HP:0500088.definition: Loss of pigment in the fovea centralis.

HP:0500089.name: Optic nerve sheath meningioma
HP:0500089.definition: A benign tumor of meningothelial cells of the meninges that usually occurs in middle age. It is typically unilateral and there is an association with neurofibromatosis type 2.

HP:0500090.name: Periocular capillary hemangioma
HP:0500090.definition: A capillary hemangioma surrounding the eyeball but within the orbit.

HP:0500091.name: Lymphangioma of the orbit
HP:0500091.definition: A hamartoma of lymph vessels that usually presents in childhood. It tends to increase in size with head-down posture and with the Valsalva maneuver. Superficial lesions are visible as transilluminable cystic spaces of the lid or conjunctiva that may also contain blood. Deep lesions may cause gradual proptosis or present acutely with orbital pain and reduced vision due to hemorrhage.

HP:0500092.name: Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma
HP:0500092.definition: A mesenchymal tumor that is considered to be the commonest primary orbital malignancy in children. Histologically, it may be differentiated into embryonal, alveolar, and pleomorphic types. It is usually intraconal or within the superior orbit.

HP:0500093.name: Food allergy
HP:0500093.definition: Primary food allergies primarily occur as a result (most likely) of gastrointestinal sensitization to predominantly stable food allergens (glycoproteins). A secondary food allergy develops after primary sensitization to airborne allergens (e. g., pollen allergens) with subsequent reactions (due to cross-reactivity) to structurally related often labile allergens in (plant) foods.

HP:0500094.name: Latex allergy
HP:0500094.definition: Latex allergy is an IgE-mediated immediate hypersensitivity response to natural rubber latex (NRL) protein with a variety of clinical signs ranging from contact urticaria, angioedema, asthma, and anaphylaxis.

HP:0500095.name: Food-induced anaphylaxis
HP:0500095.definition: Food-induced anaphylaxis is a severe, potentially fatal, systemic allergic reaction that occurs suddenly after contact with an allergy-causing food.

HP:0500096.name: Venom-induced anaphylaxis
HP:0500096.definition: A form of anaphylaxis that is triggered by exposure to venom.

HP:0500098.name: Meconium xenobiotic
HP:0500098.definition: Presence of a xenobiotic in meconium.

HP:0500100.name: Plasma/serum xenobiotic
HP:0500100.definition: Presence of a xenobiotic in plasma and/or serum.

HP:0500101.name: Gastric fluid xenobiotic
HP:0500101.definition: Presence of a xenobiotic in gastric fluid.

HP:0500104.name: Decreased diastolic blood pressure
HP:0500104.definition: Abnormal decrease in diastolic blood pressure.

HP:0500105.name: Decreased systolic blood pressure
HP:0500105.definition: Abnormal decrease in systolic blood pressure.

HP:0500106.name: Isolated systolic hypertension
HP:0500106.definition: Elevated systolic blood pressure without an elevated blood pressure.

HP:0500107.name: Isolated diastolic hypotension
HP:0500107.definition: A decrease in diastolic blood pressure (<60 mmHg) without a decrease in systolic blood pressure (> or = to 100 mmHg).

HP:0500108.name: Positive urine cocaine test
HP:0500108.definition: Detection of cocaine or its major metabolite, benzoylecgonine, in urine.

HP:0500109.name: Positive urine barbiturate test
HP:0500109.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as Phenobarbital in urine.

HP:0500110.name: Positive urine cannabinoid test
HP:0500110.definition: Detection of delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) or other cannabinoid metabolites in urine.

HP:0500111.name: Positive urine benzodiazepines test
HP:0500111.definition: Detection of benzodiazepine metabolites, primarily nordiazepam, oxazepam, and temazepam, in urine.

HP:0500112.name: Positive urine amphetamine test
HP:0500112.definition: Detection of amphetamine or its metabolites in urine.

HP:0500113.name: Positive urine opioid test
HP:0500113.definition: Detection of opioids or opioid metabolites in urine.

HP:0500114.name: Abnormal stool urobilinogen concentration
HP:0500114.definition: Abnormal concentration of urobilinogen present in the stool.

HP:0500115.name: Increased stool urobilinogen concentration
HP:0500115.definition: An increased amount of urobilinogen present in the stool.

HP:0500116.name: Positive blood barbiturate test
HP:0500116.definition: Detection of barbiturate metabolites such as Phenobarbital in blood.

HP:0500117.name: Abnormal CSF urate concentration
HP:0500117.definition: Abnormal concentration of urate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:0500132.name: Hypovalinemia
HP:0500132.definition: A decreased amount of valine in the blood.

HP:0500133.name: Hypotyrosinemia
HP:0500133.definition: An decreased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.

HP:0500134.name: Hypertryptophanemia
HP:0500134.definition: An increased amount of tryptophan in the blood.

HP:0500135.name: Hypotryptophanemia
HP:0500135.definition: A decreased amount of tryptophan in the blood.

HP:0500136.name: Hypothreoninemia
HP:0500136.definition: A decreased amount of threonine in the blood.

HP:0500138.name: Hyperserinemia
HP:0500138.definition: An increased amount of serine in the blood.

HP:0500139.name: Hypoprolinemia
HP:0500139.definition: A decreased amount of proline in the blood.

HP:0500140.name: Decreased circulating hydroxyproline concentration
HP:0500140.definition: A decreased amount of hydroxyproline in the blood.

HP:0500141.name: Hypophenylalaninemia
HP:0500141.definition: A decreased amount of phenylalanine in the blood.

HP:0500142.name: Hypolysinemia
HP:0500142.definition: A decreased amount of lysine in the blood.

HP:0500143.name: Hypoleucinemia
HP:0500143.definition: Decreased amount of leucine in the blood.

HP:0500144.name: Hypoisoleucinemia
HP:0500144.definition: A decreased amount of isoleucine in the blood.

HP:0500145.name: Hypohistidinemia
HP:0500145.definition: A decreased amount of histidine in the blood.

HP:0500147.name: Hypoglutaminemia
HP:0500147.definition: Decreased amount of glutamine in the blood.

HP:0500148.name: Abnormal circulating glutamate concentration
HP:0500148.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamate in the blood circulation.

HP:0500149.name: Hyperglutamatemia
HP:0500149.definition: Concentration of glutamate in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:0500150.name: Hypoglutamatemia
HP:0500150.definition: A decreased amount of glutamate in the blood.

HP:0500151.name: Hypercystinemia
HP:0500151.definition: An increased amount of cystine in the blood.

HP:0500152.name: Hypocystinemia
HP:0500152.definition: A decreased amount of cystine in the blood.

HP:0500153.name: Hyperargininemia
HP:0500153.definition: An increased amount of arginine levels in the blood.

HP:0500154.name: Hypoalaninemia
HP:0500154.definition: A decreased amount of alanine in the blood.

HP:0500155.name: Abnormal circulating asparagine concentration
HP:0500155.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of asparagine in the blood circulation.

HP:0500156.name: Hyperasparaginemia
HP:0500156.definition: An increased amount of asparagine in the blood.

HP:0500157.name: Hypoasparaginemia
HP:0500157.definition: A decreased amount of asparagine in the blood.

HP:0500158.name: Abnormal circulating aspartic acid concentration
HP:0500158.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of aspartate in the blood circulation.

HP:0500159.name: Increased circulating aspartic acid concentration
HP:0500159.definition: An increased concentration of aspartic acid in the blood circulation.

HP:0500160.name: Abnormal circulating carnosine concentration
HP:0500160.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of carnosine in the blood circulation.

HP:0500161.name: Increased circulating carnosine concentration
HP:0500161.definition: Concentration of carnosine in the blood circulation above normal limits.

HP:0500162.name: Decreased circulating carnosine concentration
HP:0500162.definition: A decreased amount of carnosine in blood.

HP:0500163.name: Hypoornithinemia
HP:0500163.definition: An abnormal decrease in ornithine in the blood.

HP:0500164.name: Abnormal blood carbon dioxide level
HP:0500164.definition: An abnormality of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the arterial blood.

HP:0500165.name: Abnormal blood oxygen level
HP:0500165.definition: An abnormality of the partial pressure of oxygen in the arterial blood.

HP:0500166.name: Abnormal circulating gastrin concentration
HP:0500166.definition: An abnormal concentration of gastrin in the blood.

HP:0500167.name: Hypergastrinemia
HP:0500167.definition: An elevated amount of gastrin in the blood.

HP:0500170.name: Abnormal concentration of acylcarnitine in the urine
HP:0500170.definition: An abnormal amount of acylcarnitine in the urine.

HP:0500173.name: Reflex asystolic syncope
HP:0500173.definition: A loss of consciousness followed by stiffening and brief clonic movements affecting some or all limbs, often misinterpreted as an epileptic seizure.

HP:0500180.name: Abnormal circulating amino sulfonic acid concentration

HP:0500181.name: Hypertaurinemia
HP:0500181.definition: An increased amount of taurine in the blood.

HP:0500182.name: Hypotaurinemia
HP:0500182.definition: A decreased amount of taurine in the blood.

HP:0500183.name: Abnormal CSF carboxylic acid concentration
HP:0500183.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a carboxylic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500184.name: Abnormal CSF amino acid concentration
HP:0500184.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500185.name: Abnormal CSF branched chain amino acid concentration
HP:0500185.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of branched-chain amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500186.name: Abnormal CSF valine concentration
HP:0500186.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500187.name: Increased CSF valine concentration
HP:0500187.definition: Any increased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500188.name: Decreased CSF valine concentration
HP:0500188.definition: Any decreased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500189.name: Abnormal CSF leucine concentration
HP:0500189.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of leucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500190.name: Decreased CSF leucine concentration
HP:0500190.definition: Abnormally decreased levels of leucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500191.name: Increased CSF leucine concentration
HP:0500191.definition: Abnormally increased levels of leucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500192.name: Abnormal CSF isoleucine concentration
HP:0500192.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of isoleucine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500193.name: Increased CSF isoleucine concentration
HP:0500193.definition: Abnormally increased levels of isoleucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500194.name: Decreased CSF isoleucine concentration
HP:0500194.definition: Abnormally decreased levels of isoleucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:0500195.name: Abnormal CSF glutamine family amino acid concentration
HP:0500195.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamine-family amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.

HP:6001025.name: Pathological inclusion body
HP:6001025.definition: Pathological inclusion bodies are are composed of glycogen, proteins, nucleic acids, lipids, hemosiderin, and calcium, that accumulate as metabolic by-products, catabolic products of macromolecular complexes, or in the context of cell injury.

HP:6001026.name: Reduced epidermal collagen IV alpha 5 chain staining
HP:6001026.definition: Diminished or absent collagen alpha5(IV) chain staining pattern in the epidermal basement membrane.

HP:6001027.name: Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 3 chain staining
HP:6001027.definition: Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 3 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.

HP:6001028.name: Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 4 chain staining
HP:6001028.definition: Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 4 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.

HP:6001029.name: Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 5 chain staining
HP:6001029.definition: Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 5 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.

HP:6001031.name: Cystine nephrolithiasis
HP:6001031.definition: Deposition of cystine crystals in kidney tissue. Cystine crystals display a pathognomic hexagonal shape.

HP:6001032.name: Hepatic cystine accumulation
HP:6001032.definition: Accumulation of cystine in the liver.

HP:6001033.name: Bone marrow cystine accumulation
HP:6001033.definition: The presence of cystine crystals in bone marrow cells as demonstrated in a fresh bone marrow aspiration sample.

HP:6001034.name: Desmoid tumor
HP:6001034.definition: Desmoid tumors are rare, locally aggressive, fibroblastic soft-tissue tumors that are characterized by infiltrative growth and tendency to recur. Desmoid tumors do not metastasize but can arise in any part of the body: extra-abdominal (appear in the head and neck, chest, extremities), and abdominal wall or intra-abdominal (originating in tissue that connects abdominal organs).

HP:6001035.name: Tubular jejunal duplication
HP:6001035.definition: A segment of the jejunum that runs parallel to the normal jejunum and communicates with the jejunal lumen at one or both ends.

HP:6001036.name: Left ventricular rupture
HP:6001036.definition: A full thickness tear or breakage of the myocardium of the left ventricle.

HP:6001037.name: Punctate pontine perivascular enhancement
HP:6001037.definition: Multiple punctate (speckled, patchy spot-like) and/or curvilinear areas of gadolinium enhancement distributed around blood vessels in the pons.

HP:6001038.name: Intestinal worm
HP:6001038.definition: Presence of one or more adult worms in the intestine as demonstrated by sonography or passage of a worm in the stool. On sonography, worms may appear as linear, echogenic structures within the intestines.

HP:6001039.name: Scrotal worm
HP:6001039.definition: Demonstration of one or more worms in the scrotum. This finding can be appreciated by sonography, where echogenic, linear structures could be seen moving within the scrotum.

HP:6001040.name: Small intestinal adenoma
HP:6001040.definition: A small bowel tumor with adenomatous epithelium.

HP:6001041.name: Maternal retinal mottling
HP:6001041.definition: Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium in the mother of the index patient. Retinal mottling may indicate a mosaic X-linked inactivation state in the mother.

HP:6001042.name: Twisted gallbladder pedicle
HP:6001042.definition: A stretched conical-shaped structure found at the gallbladder neck with several linear echoes converging towards its tip. This finding is demonstrated by sonography and can indicate gallbladder volvulus.

HP:6001043.name: Cholecyst-enteric fistula
HP:6001043.definition: Fistula between the gallbladder and the intestine.

HP:6001044.name: Dyschronometria
HP:6001044.definition: Impaired ability to accurately measure or estimate time intervals.

HP:6001045.name: History of recent intermittent breastfeeding
HP:6001045.definition: History of recently intermittent breastfeeding an infant (i.e., on and off).

HP:6001046.name: Breast cyst
HP:6001046.definition: A benign, fluid-filled sac in the breast.

HP:6001047.name: Circumscribed
HP:6001047.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are well-defined and localized to a specific area.

HP:6001048.name: Lobulated
HP:6001048.definition: Applies to an abnormality that displays multiple indentations and/or elevations producing an irregular surface contour.

HP:6001049.name: Spiculated
HP:6001049.definition: Applies to an abnormality with irregular, radiating, or spiky edges.

HP:6001050.name: Whorled
HP:6001050.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles series of a concentric circles or spirals.

HP:6001051.name: Delta brush pattern on EEG
HP:6001051.definition: Delta brushes are transient patterns characterised by a slow delta wave with superimposed fast activity.

HP:6001052.name: Tibiotalar synostosis
HP:6001052.definition: Fusion of the junction between the distal tibia, fibula and the talus.

HP:6001053.name: Vertebra plana
HP:6001053.definition: he term given when a vertebral body has lost almost its entire height anteriorly and posteriorly, representing a very advanced compression fracture.

HP:6001054.name: Intoeing
HP:6001054.definition: An abnormal gait caused by a rotational variation anywhere in the lower extremity that causes the foot to point inward, instead of pointing straight ahead or outward, when walking or running.

HP:6001055.name: Palpable thrill on extremity
HP:6001055.definition: A vibration felt upon palpation of a blood vessel over an extremity.

HP:6001056.name: Out-toeing
HP:6001056.definition: The feet turn excessively outward when walking, caused by a rotational variation in the leg.

HP:6001057.name: Ankle dislocation
HP:6001057.definition: An abnormal separation between the talo-tibial joint.

HP:6001058.name: Anti-neuronal intermediate filament antibody positivity
HP:6001058.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against neuronal intermediate filament.

HP:6001059.name: Anti-DREBRIN antibody positivity
HP:6001059.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against dendritic spine scaffolding protein Drebrin.

HP:6001060.name: Anti-lipoprotein lipase autoantibody positivity
HP:6001060.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against anti-lipoprotein lipase.

HP:6001061.name: Anti-apolipoprotein CII autoantibody positivity
HP:6001061.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against apoCII.

HP:6001062.name: Eosinophilic neuronal inclusion bodies
HP:6001062.definition: The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neurons that stain with eosin, a red or pink dye.

HP:6001063.name: Sweaty foot-like odor
HP:6001063.definition: A characteristic smell said to resemble the odor of dirty socks.

HP:6001064.name: Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibody positivity
HP:6001064.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against acetylcholine receptor.

HP:6001065.name: Hair shaft lesion
HP:6001065.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is located on hair shafts.

HP:6001066.name: Prolonged use of tightly fitting footwear
HP:6001066.definition: History of use of tightly fitting shoes for a long period of time.

HP:6001067.name: Triggered by high protein intake
HP:6001067.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about ingestion of high quantities of protein.

HP:6001068.name: Thickened tricuspid valve cusp
HP:6001068.definition: An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the tricuspid valve.

HP:6001069.name: Displaced anterior fontanelle
HP:6001069.definition: Abnormal shifting of the anterior fontanelle fropm its normal central position.

HP:6001070.name: Subdural hygroma
HP:6001070.definition: Accumulation of cerebral spinal fluid in the subdural space.

HP:6001071.name: Incus ankylosis
HP:6001071.definition: Incus ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the incus, which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles).

HP:6001072.name: Excessive diet restriction
HP:6001072.definition: A tendency to reject a variety of foods and/or to eat a restricted range of foods.

HP:6001073.name: Left ventricular apical dyskinesis
HP:6001073.definition: Dyskinesis is used to describe ventricular muscle segments that bulge outside the left ventricular cavity during systole, as opposed to contracting inwards with the rest of the segments.

HP:6001074.name: Longitudinal erythronychia
HP:6001074.definition: A longitudinal red band extending from the proximal nail fold or lunula to the distal nail plate.

HP:6001075.name: Exacerbated by exposure to sunlight
HP:6001075.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by exposure to sunlight.

HP:6001076.name: Exacerbated by heat
HP:6001076.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by exposure to heat (high ambient temperatures).

HP:6001077.name: Exacerbated by excessive sweating
HP:6001077.definition: Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by excessive sweating.

HP:6001078.name: Malignant pleural effusion
HP:6001078.definition: The accumulation of a significant amount of exudate in the pleural space, accompanied by the presence of malignant cells or tumour tissue.

HP:6001079.name: Inappropriately low urine osmolality following challenge
HP:6001079.definition: In diabetes insipidus, affected individuals produce large quantities of dilute urine. In nephrogenic DI, the kidneys do not respond to vasopressin. In a water deprivation test or with administration of exogenous vasopressin, the osmolaltiy of the urine does not increase as normally.

HP:6001080.name: Reduced urine tetrahydrocortisol plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone ratio
HP:6001080.definition: Abnormally low ratio of tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone (THE).

HP:6001081.name: Elevated urinary 2,4-dihydroxyglutarate level
HP:6001081.definition: The amount of 2,4-dihydroxyglutarate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001082.name: Abnormal urine D-xylose test
HP:6001082.definition: An abnormal result of the xylose absorption test that is used to assess the ability of the intestines to absorb D-xylose. D-xylose is a five-carbon monosaccharide found in some plants. The patient drinks a solution containing a specific amount of D-xylose and the concentration of xylose is measured in the blood circulation and then in the urine. A low amount of D-xylose indicates reduced small intestinal absorbtion.

HP:6001083.name: Cerebral hemisphere mass lesion
HP:6001083.definition: An abnormal growth or accumulation of tissue in a hemisphere of the cerebrum. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.

HP:6001084.name: T2-hyperintense putaminal rim
HP:6001084.definition: Increased signal on T2 magnetic resonance imaging characterized by a linear region of high signal surrounding the lateral aspect of the putamen at 1.5 Tesla.

HP:6001085.name: Posterior fossa mass lesion
HP:6001085.definition: An abnormal growth or accumulation of tissue in the posterior fossa, affecting the cerebellum or fourth ventricle. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.

HP:6001086.name: Irregular RR interval
HP:6001086.definition: Abnormal increased variability in the timing between consecutive R-waves on an electrocardiogram.

HP:6001087.name: Irregular P-P interval
HP:6001087.definition: Abnormally increased variability in the timing between consecutive P-waves on an electrocardiogram.

HP:6001088.name: Fungal hair infection
HP:6001088.definition: Demonstration of fungi growing on hair by a method such as microscopy of hairs mounted on slides with 10% potassium hydroxide.

HP:6001089.name: Long hairstyle
HP:6001089.definition: A past medical history of having long, full hair.

HP:6001090.name: Conjunctival subepithelial fibrosis
HP:6001090.definition: fine white linear scars under intact conjunctival epithelium. This scarring appears in areas of previous conjunctival ulceration or pseudomembrane formation, weeks to months after the insult is healed.

HP:6001091.name: Conjunctival fornix foreshortening
HP:6001091.definition: Abnormal reduction in depth of the fornix of the conjunctiva. The fornix is the area where the conjunctiva folds back upon itself, thereby creating a recessed space.

HP:6001092.name: Strong ultraviolet light exposure
HP:6001092.definition: History of exposure to ultraviolet light, such as may be encountered with outdoor activities, living near equator, radiation.

HP:6001093.name: Exposure to vaginal douching
HP:6001093.definition: A history of intravaginal cleansing with a liquid solution for personal hygiene or aesthetic reasons.

HP:6001094.name: Exposure to oily lotions or creams
HP:6001094.definition: A history of applying oily lotions or creams to the skin.

HP:6001095.name: Elevated circulating pristanic acid concentration following branched-chain fatty acid ingestion
HP:6001095.definition: Concentration of pristanic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. This finding can be observed in Zellweger syndrome. Note that branched-chain fatty acid accumulation depends on dietary intake of phytanic acid, which is minimal in formula- and breast-fed infants. Thus, phytanic and pristanic acid levels are normal in a neonate with Zellweger spectrum disorder.

HP:6001096.name: Decreased CD4+ T cell ZAP-70 protein expression
HP:6001096.definition: Reduction in the level of ZAP-70 protein CD4-positive T cells.

HP:6001097.name: Dorsal flexion contracture of the ankle
HP:6001097.definition: A type of contracture in which the dorsal flexion muscles of the ankle are contracted.

HP:6001098.name: Metaphyseal undermodelling
HP:6001098.definition: Lack of the normal diaphyseal constriction (thinning of long bones toward the midshaft area) giving the submetaphyseal areas an abnormally wide appearance.

HP:6001099.name: Iliac vein compression
HP:6001099.definition: Compression of the common iliac vein against the spine by the contralateral common iliac artery.

HP:6001100.name: Positive serum amyloid P scintigraphy
HP:6001100.definition: Detection of abnormal amyloid deposits in the body by 123I-labeled serum amyloid P component (SAP) scintigraphy.

HP:6001101.name: crossed brainstem sign
HP:6001101.definition: Motor and/or sensory cranial nerve findings ipsilateral to the lesion, and at the same time motor and/or sensory findings on the contralateral side of the body.

HP:6001102.name: Inability to puff cheeks
HP:6001102.definition: Reduced ability to inflate the cheeks by blowing air into them while keeping the lips closed.

HP:6001103.name: Entoptic phenomenon
HP:6001103.definition: Visual sensations caused by changes within the eye itself, rather than by the normal light stimulation process. Entoptic phenomena are classified in the syndrome as floaters, blue field entoptic phenomenon, photopsia and self-light of the eye.

HP:6001104.name: Abnormal vestibulo-spinal reflex
HP:6001104.definition: An abnormality of the vestibulospinal (VS) reflexes, which contribute to the control of postural orientation. In this task, they continuously collaborate with reflexes elicited by stimulation of visual and somatosensory receptors. Labyrinthine receptors are sensitive to modifications (i) of the head position with respect to the earth vertical or (ii) of the angular/linear velocity of head motion in space. This information can be used to monitor deviations from the maintained body position.

HP:6001105.name: Positive probe-to-bone test
HP:6001105.definition: An abnormal result of the probe-to-bone (PTB) test. The PTB test is performed by inserting a sterile, metal surgical probe into the ulcer and is positive if a hard, gritty surface is felt inside. For large wounds, this may require gentle exploration of the wound with the probe.

HP:6001106.name: Exposure to repetitive hand impact
HP:6001106.definition: A history of exposure to repetitive impact on palm or hand, such as working with a jackhammer.

HP:6001107.name: Fractured scaphoid bone
HP:6001107.definition: A partial or complete breakage of the scaphoid bone.

HP:6001108.name: Local anesthetic ineffectiveness
HP:6001108.definition: Resistance to the effects of local anaesthesia, with delayed onset or failure of local anesthetics to incude numbness or relieve pain.

HP:6001109.name: Palmoplantar location
HP:6001109.definition: Applied to lesions whose distribution is confined or restricted to the palms of the hands and soles of the feet.

HP:6001110.name: Oral mucosa plaque
HP:6001110.definition: A raised, flat-topped lesion with a diameter of one centimeter or more that is located in the mucosa of the mouth.

HP:6001111.name: Positive saliva rabies nucleic acid test
HP:6001111.definition: Detection of rabies nucleic acid in saliva by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6001112.name: Elevated tissue arylsulfatase A activity
HP:6001112.definition: Activity of arylsulfatase A (EC 3.1.6.8) above the upper limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts and leukocytes or in the blood circulation.

HP:6001113.name: Elevated circulating methysterol concentration
HP:6001113.definition: The concentration of a methysterol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001114.name: Elevated urinary adipic acid
HP:6001114.definition: The amount of adipic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Adipic acid is an alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,4-dicarboxy derivative of butane.

HP:6001115.name: EEG with temporal slowing
HP:6001115.definition: Slow-wave activity observed in the temporal area of the scalp electro-encephalogram (EEG).

HP:6001116.name: History of high-pressure injection injury of the hand
HP:6001116.definition: Medical history of the hand having come into contact with the nozzle of a high-pressure injecting system such as a paint gun or air compressor.

HP:6001117.name: Hypertrophic ulnar styloid process
HP:6001117.definition: Excessively long styloid process of the ulna.

HP:6001118.name: History of recent peripheral venous catheter
HP:6001118.definition: A history of placement of a peripehral venous catheter in the hours, days, or weeks before the current presenting complaint.

HP:6001119.name: Purulent drainage from skin
HP:6001119.definition: Exudation of a thick, opaque fluid from a wound or skin lesion, typically as a result of infection and draining pus, i.e., dead white blood cells, bacteria, and tissue debris.

HP:6001120.name: Occupational history of putting fingers in other people's mouths
HP:6001120.definition: A history of exposure of fingers by putting them in other peoples' mouths occupationally, e.g., as a dentist or physician.

HP:6001121.name: Single-finger involvement
HP:6001121.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are limited to or predominantly affect a single finger.

HP:6001122.name: Multiple-finger involvement
HP:6001122.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance affect more than one finger.

HP:6001123.name: Pain disproportionate to abnormality on physical exam
HP:6001123.definition: Exquisite tenderness in a specific region, beyond what one would surmise from examination.

HP:6001124.name: Sphenoid wing dysplasia
HP:6001124.definition: Hypoplasia or aplasia of the greater or lesser wing of the sphenoid bone, typically resulting in widening of the superior orbital fissure, elevation of the [lesser sphenoid wing, and ipsilateral orbital enlargement.

HP:6001125.name: Skin laceration
HP:6001125.definition: An injury in which skin and underlying tissues are cut or torn.

HP:6001126.name: Metacarpal fracture
HP:6001126.definition: A partial or complete breakage of a metacarpal bone.

HP:6001127.name: Pain at the base of the thumb
HP:6001127.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort localized to the base of the thumb, over thenar eminence or thumb metacarpal.

HP:6001128.name: History of recent participation in athletics
HP:6001128.definition: Medical history of participation in sports (football, basketball, soccer, skiing) in the hours, days, or weeks prior to the current presenting complaint.

HP:6001129.name: Remote trauma history
HP:6001129.definition: History of trauma months to years ago, including but not limited to fracture or other orthopedic injury at the symptomatic area.

HP:6001130.name: Distal radioulnar joint arthritis
HP:6001130.definition: An inflammatory condition of the joint that connects the far ends of the radius and the ulna, known as the distal radioulnar joint (DRUJ). DRUJ arthritis may be characterized by widening of the DRUJ interval, volar/dorsal displacement of the distal ulna, radiographic evidence of osteoarthritis at the DRUJ joint including osteophytes, subchondral cysts, subchrondal sclerosis, and joint space narrowing.

HP:6001131.name: Radial head fracture
HP:6001131.definition: Fracture of the proximal end of the radius involving the radial head.

HP:6001132.name: Elbow lateral collateral ligament tear
HP:6001132.definition: An injury to the lateral collateral ligament (LCL) of the elbow. The LCL is a complex capsuloligamentous structure critical in stabilizing the ulnohumeral and radiocapitellar articulations. LCL injury can result in elbow instability, allowing the proximal radius and ulna to externally rotate away from the humerus as a supination stress is applied to the forearm.

HP:6001133.name: Elbow medial collateral ligament tear
HP:6001133.definition: An injury to the medial collateral ligament (MCL) of the elbow.

HP:6001134.name: Coronoid fracture
HP:6001134.definition: Fracture of the coronoid process on the proximal ulna.

HP:6001135.name: History of spinal cord injury
HP:6001135.definition: A medical history of hving had a spinal cord injury prior to the presenting complaint.

HP:6001136.name: Femoral nerve distribution
HP:6001136.definition: Paresthesias in anterior/medial aspect of the thigh (anterior and medial cutaneous nerves of the thigh) and/or medial aspect of the lower leg and foot (saphenous distribution). May be accompanied by weakness in the quadriceps.

HP:6001138.name: Digoxin exposure
HP:6001138.definition: History of having been treateed with digoxin.

HP:6001139.name: Upper arm pain
HP:6001139.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the upper arm.

HP:6001140.name: Capitellum fracture
HP:6001140.definition: A partial or complete breakage of the capitulum of the humerus, which is a smooth, rounded eminence on the lateral portion of the distal articular surface of the humerus.

HP:6001141.name: Anterior shoulder pain
HP:6001141.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the anterior (front) part of the shoulder.

HP:6001142.name: Pain at the anterior aspect of the elbow
HP:6001142.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the front part of the elbow front part of the elbow, that is, on the ventral side of the arm where the arm bends.

HP:6001143.name: Posterior fat pad sign of the elbow
HP:6001143.definition: Lateral elbow x-ray showing lucent crescent of fat that indicates a joint effusion in the elbow .

HP:6001144.name: Pain at the anterior aspect of the knee
HP:6001144.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the front part of the knee, that is, the side of the knee where the patella is located.

HP:6001145.name: Pain at the posterior aspect of the knee
HP:6001145.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the back part of the knee, that is, opposite to the side of the knee where the patella is located.

HP:6001146.name: Biceps tendonitis
HP:6001146.definition: Biceps tendinitis is inflammation of the tendon around the long head of the biceps muscle.

HP:6001147.name: Increased peripheral nerve cross sectional area
HP:6001147.definition: Ultrasonography showing increased cross sectional area (CSA) of a peripheral nerve as it travels through a potential site of compression.

HP:6001148.name: Pain exacerbated by passive flexion at joint
HP:6001148.definition: Pain in extremity that worsens with joint is passively flexed.

HP:6001149.name: Positive hook test at the elbow
HP:6001149.definition: With forearm fully supinated and elbow flexed to 90 degrees, examiner hooks a finger a bit around the distal biceps tendon at the anterior aspect of the elbow. Test is positive when there is lack of appreciable cord like structure to hook around.

HP:6001150.name: Positive Speed's test
HP:6001150.definition: Manual downward pressure on the arm with the shoulders flexed forward to 90 degrees, elbows fully extended, and palm facing up recreates pain in the anterior shoulder region; named after Dr. Speed.

HP:6001151.name: Triangular lunate bone
HP:6001151.definition: A disruption of the greater and lesser arcs of the lunate bone, with the lunate having a triangular silhouette, know as the piece of pie sign. Often caused by falling on an outstretched hand, patients will have tenderness to palpation over the dorsum of the wrist and may have sensory deficits in the median nerve distribution.

HP:6001152.name: Pain exacerbated by wrist deviation
HP:6001152.definition: Pain worsens with wrist ulnar or radial deviation.

HP:6001153.name: Pain on the lateral aspect of the foot
HP:6001153.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the side of the foot nearest to the little (fifth) toe.

HP:6001154.name: Pain at the medial aspect of the knee
HP:6001154.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the inner side of knee, that is, the region of the knee that faces the other knee.

HP:6001155.name: Pain at the lateral aspect of the knee
HP:6001155.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the outer side of knee, that is, the region of the knee that faces away from the other knee.

HP:6001157.name: Occupational exposure to frequent kneeling
HP:6001157.definition: A history of exposure to frequent squatting/kneeling and/or heavy lifting.

HP:6001158.name: Trochanteric pain
HP:6001158.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the structures around the greater trochanter (the bony prominence on the outer part of the femur).

HP:6001159.name: Pulsatile mass in extremity
HP:6001159.definition: A noticeable lump or swelling in the arm or leg that you can feel with you fingers and this lump is beating or pulsating, similar to the feeling of a heartbeat.

HP:6001160.name: Abnormal R wave
HP:6001160.definition: Any anomaly of the R wave of the EKG, which is the first upward deflection after the P wave. The R wave reflects early ventricular depolarisation.

HP:6001161.name: Poor R-wave progression
HP:6001161.definition: Absence of the normal increase in size of the R wave in the precordial leads when advancing from lead V1 to V6 of the electrocardiogram.

HP:6001162.name: Prominent V1-V2 R wave
HP:6001162.definition: The R wave in leads V1-V2 is normally considerably smaller in amplitude than the S wave in the same leads. Prominent R wave in these leads implies the R wave is larger than the S-wave, which may indicate cardiovascular pathology. This term includes Tall R wave in lead V1, which is defined by a R/S ratio greater than 1.

HP:6001163.name: Finger mass
HP:6001163.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to a finger.

HP:6001164.name: Foot mass
HP:6001164.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to a foot.

HP:6001165.name: Abnormal retinal vein morphology
HP:6001165.definition: A condition characterized by structural abnormalities of the retinal veins, including tortuosity, dilation, narrowing, or irregularities in branching patterns. These changes may be associated with systemic or ocular diseases such as retinal vein occlusion, diabetic retinopathy, or hypertensive retinopathy.

HP:6001166.name: Spongiosis
HP:6001166.definition: Spongiosis refers to the increased intercellular edema in the epidermis resulting in the pulling away of the keratinocytes from their surrounding desmosomes. Histologically, the spongiotic tissue reaction pattern involves the accumulation of fluid in the intercellular spaces of the epidermis, making the desmosomes junctions more easy to appreciate. Parakeratosis forms above the areas of spongiosis. The foci of spongiosis can be microscopic to grossly identifiable clinically with vesicles or bullae.

HP:6001167.name: Discoid adrenal gland
HP:6001167.definition: A congenital finding where the adrenal gland does not form it's typical triangular, Y or V shape and is instead discoid, straight or elongated in shape. It is often found incidentally on renal ultrasound and is associated with renal agenesis and other renal congenital anomalies.

HP:6001168.name: Abnormal optic disc vasculature morphology
HP:6001168.definition: A structural abnormality in the blood vessels of the optic disc, including bleeding, tortuosity, dilation, shunting, or other unusual branching patterns.

HP:6001169.name: Supraclavicular nerve distribution
HP:6001169.definition: Localization of symptoms such as numbness or paresthesias on the skin over the upper chest, specifically above the clavicle and over the lateral aspect of the neck, corresponding to the distribution of the supraclavicular nerve.

HP:6001170.name: Limited shoulder internal rotation
HP:6001170.definition: Difficulty rotating the lower part of the arm towards the body (tested with the elbow flexed and the elbow held next to the side of the body or shoulder 90 degrees abducted to the side) secondary to pain, weakness, or mechanical block.

HP:6001171.name: Superior displacement of the humeral head
HP:6001171.definition: An anterior posterior (AP) shoulder radiograph shows distance between the the proximal aspect of the humeral head and inferior aspect of the acromion of less than 7 mm.

HP:6001172.name: Increased compartment pressure
HP:6001172.definition: intracompartmental pressure (ICP) over 30 mmHg. Acute compartment syndrome occurs when there is increased pressure within a closed osteofascial compartment, resulting in impaired local circulation. Acute compartment syndrome is considered a surgical emergency since, without proper treatment, it can lead to ischemia and eventually necrosis. Generally, acute compartment syndrome is considered a clinical diagnosis. However, ICP over 30 mmHg can be used as a threshold to aid in diagnosis.

HP:6001173.name: Pain at the lateral aspect of the elbow
HP:6001173.definition: Pain localized to the radial aspect of the elbow.

HP:6001174.name: Pain at the posterior aspect of the elbow
HP:6001174.definition: Pain localized to the posterior aspect of the elbow.

HP:6001175.name: Pain at the medial aspect of the elbow
HP:6001175.definition: Pain localized to the medial aspect of the elbow.

HP:6001176.name: Radial nerve distribution
HP:6001176.definition: Applies to the localization of findings corresponding to the distribution of the radial nevrve, such as (i)paresthesias on the dorsoradial aspect of the hand and wrist, including the dorsal thumb, index finger and middle finger and (ii) Weakness in elbow extension, wrist extension, finger extension, thumb extension and/or supination of the forearm.

HP:6001177.name: Omovertebral bone
HP:6001177.definition: An osseous connection between the superomedial border of the right scapula and C5-C6 spinous processes.

HP:6001178.name: Clavicular edema
HP:6001178.definition: Swelling on the chest between the neck and the shoulder, above the clavicel (collar bone).

HP:6001179.name: Positive CSF anti-measles antibody test
HP:6001179.definition: The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of measles virus.

HP:6001180.name: Vogt striae
HP:6001180.definition: Vertical lines in the posterior stroma of the cornea, aligned with Descemet membrane. These lines temporarily disappear with pressure applied to the cornea. Vogt striae are a hallmark feature of keratoconus but have also been observed in healthy eyes. Rare cases of horizontal striae have been reported.

HP:6001181.name: Choroid thickening
HP:6001181.definition: A condition characterized by an abnormal increase in the thickness of the choroid, which may be associated with various ocular or systemic conditions. Choroid thickening can be measured using imaging techniques such as optical coherence tomography (OCT).

HP:6001182.name: Corneal epithelial edema
HP:6001182.definition: A condition characterized by accumulation of fluid within the corneal epithelium, leading to swelling, blurred vision, and discomfort. It is often associated with increased intraocular pressure, endothelial dysfunction, or contact lens overuse. Clinical features may include a hazy cornea and microcystic changes visible on slit-lamp examination.

HP:6001183.name: Retinal shunt vessels
HP:6001183.definition: bnormal blood vessels in the retina that form as a response to vascular occlusion, serving as bypass channels to redirect blood flow around obstructed or damaged retinal vessels. Retinal shunt vessels are often associated with conditions like retinal vein occlusion or diabetic retinopathy and may appear as tortuous or dilated vessels on fundoscopic examination.

HP:6001184.name: Filamentary keratitis
HP:6001184.definition: A condition characterized by the formation of filaments composed of degenerated epithelial cells and mucus attached to the corneal surface. It is associated with symptoms such as pain, foreign body sensation, photophobia, and tearing. Filamentary keratitis is often linked to underlying conditions such as dry eye disease, post-surgical ocular surface disorders, or systemic diseases like Sjoegren syndrome.

HP:6001185.name: Elevated circulating glucosylsphingosine concentration
HP:6001185.definition: Concentration of D-glucosylsphingosine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001186.name: Optic disc hemorrhage
HP:6001186.definition: A condition characterized by bleeding at or near the optic disc, visible as a flame-shaped or splinter hemorrhage on fundoscopic examination.

HP:6001187.name: Reduced circulating progranulin concentration
HP:6001187.definition: The concentration of progranulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6001188.name: Preauricular lymphadenopathy
HP:6001188.definition: Enlargement of one or more lymph nodes located in front of the ear.

HP:6001189.name: Onychoheterotopia
HP:6001189.definition: Growth of nail tissue outside the ungual plate, generally in the finger.

HP:6001190.name: Abnormal MHC surface expression
HP:6001190.definition: A deviation from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules expressed at the cell surface. The cell-mediated adaptive immune response is regulated by the MHC, which is called human leukocyte antigen (HLA) in humans. HLA molecules are cell surface glycoproteins whose primary function is to present endogenous and exogenous antigens to T lymphocytes for recognition and response. The HLA molecules that present antigen to T lymphocytes are divided into two main classes: HLA class I and HLA class II molecules.

HP:6001191.name: Forward displacement of posterior cervical dura mater on neck flexion
HP:6001191.definition: Flexion MRI (imaging with neutral and flexed about 30-40 degrees neck position) reveals an anterior shift of the cervical dural sac from the lamina in the region of C4 to C7.

HP:6001192.name: Corneal dellen
HP:6001192.definition: A localized area of corneal thinning typically occurring adjacent to an elevated lesion, such as a conjunctival scar, pterygium, or poorly fitting contact lens. Corneal dellen result from tear film instability and localized dehydration. Without timely treatment, they may progress to epithelial defects or corneal ulceration.

HP:6001193.name: Conjunctival xerosis
HP:6001193.definition: A condition characterized by dryness of the conjunctiva, often associated with keratinization of the conjunctival epithelium. Conjunctival xerosis is commonly linked to vitamin A deficiency, severe dry eye disease, or systemic conditions such as Sjogren syndrome. Clinical features may include a dull, rough conjunctival surface and reduced mucosal secretions.

HP:6001194.name: Limited shoulder external rotation
HP:6001194.definition: Difficulty rotating the lower part of the arm away from the body (tested with the elbow flexed and the elbow held next to the side of the body) secondary to pain, weakness, or mechanical block.

HP:6001195.name: Occupational exposure to frequent hand trauma
HP:6001195.definition: A history of exposure to repeated hand trauma as observed with occupations in which use of hands is frequent such as construction, food preparation and serving related occupations, and transportation and material moving occupations.

HP:6001196.name: Inability to fully extend finger at metacarpophalangeal joint
HP:6001196.definition: An inability to fully extend the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint of a finger (extension of an MCP joint straightens the finger).

HP:6001198.name: Scapholunate interval widening
HP:6001198.definition: Widening of the space between the scaphoid and lunate on x-ray; scapholunate dissociation.

HP:6001199.name: FInger pulp localization
HP:6001199.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution is limited to or predominantly affects the fleshy mass on the volar (palmar) aspect of the digit, distal to the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint (known as the pulp of the finger).

HP:6001200.name: Ulnar wrist pain
HP:6001200.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the ulnar side of the wrist.

HP:6001201.name: Lunotriquetral interval widening
HP:6001201.definition: Radiographic widening of the space between the lunate and triquetrum bones.

HP:6001202.name: Ulnar translocation of the carpus
HP:6001202.definition: Anteroposterior wrist radiograph showing ulnar translocation of the carpus from the distal radius with widening of the radial styloid-scaphoid space.

HP:6001203.name: Snapping sensation at time of injury
HP:6001203.definition: A popping or snapping sensation (noise or feeling) at the time of an injury.

HP:6001204.name: Pagetoid spread
HP:6001204.definition: Pagetoid spread connotes the spread of single neoplastic cells, and small nests of them above the basal layer in a variety of melanocytic and nonmelanocytic neoplasms similar to the pattern seen in Paget's and in extramammary Paget disease.

HP:6001206.name: Scapholunate ligament tear
HP:6001206.definition: A breakage (partial or complete tear) of the scapholunate ligament. The most common cause is physical trauma to the wrist such as a fall onto an outstretched hand. Tear of the scapholunate ligament may lead to carpal instability.

HP:6001207.name: Lunotriquetral ligament tear
HP:6001207.definition: A breakage (partial or complete tear) of the lunotriquetral ligament. The most common cause is physical trauma to the wrist such as a fall onto an outstretched hand. Rupture or tear of the the lunotriquetral ligament may lead to carpal instability.

HP:6001208.name: Pisotriquetral arthritis
HP:6001208.definition: Arthritis at the pisotriquetral joint. Radiographic evidence of arthritis at the pisotriquetral joint includes joint space narrowing, osteophytes, subchondral cysts, and/or subchondral sclerosis.

HP:6001209.name: Volar intercalated segment instability
HP:6001209.definition: A type of carpal instability characterized by volar tilt of the lunate bone.

HP:6001210.name: Inaccurate finger pulse oximetry oxygen saturation measurement
HP:6001210.definition: Any substantial discrepancy between the measurement of oxygen saturation with finger probe pulse oximetry as compared to an arterial blood gas, which is considered the gold standard.

HP:6001211.name: Finger pulse oximetry lower than arterial blood gas analysis measurement of oxygen saturation
HP:6001211.definition: Inaccurately reduced oxygen saturation as measured by finger or toe pulse oximetry compared to oxygen saturation as measured by venous or arterial blood gas analysis.

HP:6001212.name: Finger pulse oximetry higher than arterial blood gas analysis measurement of oxygen saturation
HP:6001212.definition: Inaccurately elevated oxygen saturation as measured by finger or toe pulse oximetry compared to oxygen saturation as measured by venous or arterial blood gas analysis.

HP:6001213.name: History of thumb sucking past the age of four years
HP:6001213.definition: Thumb sucking is a behavior that ceases spontaneously in most children between 2 and 4 years of age. If thumb sucking continues, negative consequences can occur, such as a deformity of the nail or paronychia. This term refers to a history of habitual thumb sucking past the age of 4 years of life.

HP:6001214.name: Cutaneous granulomatosis
HP:6001214.definition: Skin inflammatory reaction triggered by a wide variety of stimuli, including infections, foreign bodies, malignancy, metabolites, and chemicals. From a pathogenic point of view, they are divided into non-infectious and infectious granulomas. From a clinical point of view, it is useful to divide cutaneous granulomatosis into localized and more disseminated forms, although this distinction can be sometimes artificial.

HP:6001215.name: Ureteric stricture
HP:6001215.definition: Obstruction of urine flow through one or both ureters caused by issues such as injury, infection, tumours and surgery.

HP:6001216.name: Arteriovenous crossing sign
HP:6001216.definition: A retinal vascular abnormality characterized by indentation or compression of a retinal vein at an arteriovenous crossing, leading to changes in venous caliber. AV crossing signs are commonly associated with hypertensive retinopathy and may contribute to retinal vein occlusion. They are indicative of vascular remodeling due to chronic hypertension or other systemic vascular diseases.

HP:6001217.name: Haab striae
HP:6001217.definition: Curvilinear or circumferential breaks in Descemet membrane, typically associated with congenital glaucoma. Haab striae result from elevated intraocular pressure during corneal development, leading to the formation of horizontal or arcuate lines that may be visible on slit-lamp examination. They can contribute to corneal astigmatism and visual impairment.

HP:6001218.name: Positive Legionella sputum culture
HP:6001218.definition: Growth of Legionella bacteria in a sputum culture.

HP:6001219.name: Positive Streptococcus pneumoniae sputum culture
HP:6001219.definition: Streptococcus pneumoniae growth in sputum culture.

HP:6001220.name: Positive Blastomyces dermatitidis sputum fungal stain
HP:6001220.definition: Demonstration of Blastomyces dermatitidis by microscopic examination of a stained sputum specimen.

HP:6001221.name: Posterior shoulder pain
HP:6001221.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the posterior (back) part of the shoulder.

HP:6001222.name: Superior shoulder pain
HP:6001222.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the superior or proximal aspect of the shoulder over the acromion, distal clavicle, and/or acromioclavicular (AC) joint.

HP:6001223.name: Lateral shoulder pain
HP:6001223.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the localized aspect (on the side) of the shoulder.

HP:6001224.name: Shoulder instability
HP:6001224.definition: Subjective or objective feeling of clunking/clicking in the shoulder with movement, shoulder 'giving way', or sensation of shoulder dislocating.

HP:6001225.name: Shoulder labrum tear
HP:6001225.definition: A injury with a team (rip, split, or disruption) to the labrum, which is the ring of cartilage that surrounds the socket of the shoulder joint (the glenoid).

HP:6001226.name: Positive modified dynamic labral shear test
HP:6001226.definition: Sensation of a pain with or without clicking or clunking sensation with the following test. Flex patients elbow to 90 degrees and abduct the arm 120 degrees while maximally externally rotating the arm, then examiner lowers the arm to 60 degrees of abduction. A positive test occurs with pain and/or a painful click along the posterior joint line between 120 degrees and 90 degrees of abduction.

HP:6001227.name: Positive O'Brien active compression test
HP:6001227.definition: Pain in shoulder reproduced when examiner applies downward pressure on the arm while patient resists pressure in the following position: elbow extended, shoulder forward flexed to 90 degrees and 10-15 degrees adducted with palm facing down. This can be compared to the same position but with the palm facing up which should be less painful.

HP:6001228.name: Positive shoulder apprehension test
HP:6001228.definition: The individual being investigated displays noticeable apprehension (unease) during a test for shoulder instability in which the individual is laying supine with shoulder abducted to 90 degrees, elbow flexed to 90 degrees, and an external rotation pressure with combined downward pressure is applied on the upper arm.

HP:6001229.name: Foamy tear film
HP:6001229.definition: A condition characterized by the presence of foam or bubbles within the tear film, often associated with meibomian gland dysfunction or ocular surface diseases.

HP:6001230.name: Salzmann corneal nodules
HP:6001230.definition: The formation of large, bluish, nodular lesions in the superficial corneal stroma, often associated with chronic keratitis or aging. These nodules may lead to visual impairment.

HP:6001231.name: Corneal stromal vascularisation
HP:6001231.definition: The abnormal growth of blood vessels into the corneal stroma, often associated with ocular herpes, chronic inflammation, infection, or hypoxia. This condition can lead to corneal scarring and vision impairment.

HP:6001232.name: Corneal iron line
HP:6001232.definition: Linear or arcuate deposition of iron within the corneal epithelium or stroma, typically associated with conditions such as keratoconus, corneal degeneration, or postsurgical corneal changes.

HP:6001233.name: Conjunctivochalasis
HP:6001233.definition: A condition characterized by redundant, loose conjunctival tissue, typically located between the globe and the lower eyelid, which may cause ocular discomfort, tear film instability, or epiphora.

HP:6001234.name: Conjunctival hyperpigmentation
HP:6001234.definition: Increased pigmentation of the conjunctiva, characterized by brown or black discoloration due to melanocytic proliferation or pigment deposition. It may be associated with benign conditions such as primary acquired melanosis or malignant transformation into conjunctival melanoma.
