HP:6001235.name: Anti-Saccharomyces cerevisiae antibodies
HP:6001235.definition: Antibodies against antigens presented by the cell wall of the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

HP:6001236.name: Elevated fraction exhaled nitric oxide
HP:6001236.definition: The fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) is elevated above the upper limit of normal. FeNO is an endogenous gaseous molecule which can be measured in the human breath test because of airway inflammation. It has been studied extensively as a marker of inflammation and has been incorporated into an algorithm for asthma management.

HP:6001237.name: Iris hyperemia
HP:6001237.definition: A condition characterized by increased blood flow and congestion of the iris vasculature, leading to a reddish discoloration of the iris. Iris hyperemia is commonly associated with anterior uveitis, angle-closure glaucoma, or ocular inflammation.

HP:6001238.name: Elevated circulating reticulated platelet count
HP:6001238.definition: The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6001239.name: Reduced circulating reticulated platelet count
HP:6001239.definition: The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6001240.name: Abnormal circulating reticulated platelet count
HP:6001240.definition: The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is outside the limits of normal.

HP:6001241.name: Flexed posturing of finger
HP:6001241.definition: A sign that can be observed in diseases such as Pyogenic or suppurative flexor tenosynovitis in which the affected finger is held in a flexed position. Often, there is pain on any attempt at passive finger extension. This finding is to be distinguished from a contracture of a finger joint in which the flexed positions is fixed.

HP:6001242.name: Positive synovial fluid alpha-defensin
HP:6001242.definition: Elevation of the the alpha-defensin concentration in synovial aspirate is above the upper limit of normal. The alpha-defensin test is a qualitative immunoassay optimized and validated for synovial fluid. The alpha-defensin protein is an antimicrobial peptide that is naturally released by neutrophils responding to a pathogen in the synovial fluid.

HP:6001243.name: Physeal fracture
HP:6001243.definition: Salter-Harris fractures (physeal fractures) refer to fractures through a growth plate (physis) and are, therefore, specifically applied to bone fractures in children.

HP:6001244.name: Salter I fracture
HP:6001244.definition: A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture line extends through the physis or within the growth plate. Type I fractures are due to the longitudinal force applied through the physis, which splits the epiphysis from the metaphysis.

HP:6001245.name: Salter II fracture
HP:6001245.definition: A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture extends through both the physis and metaphysis. These are most common and occur away from the joint space. When the small corner of the metaphysis is visible, this is known as a corner sign or Thurston-Holland fragment.

HP:6001246.name: Salter III fracture
HP:6001246.definition: A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture is intra-articular and extends from the physis into the epiphysis.

HP:6001247.name: Salter IV fracture
HP:6001247.definition: A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture is intra-articular and passes through the epiphysis, physis, and metaphysis.

HP:6001248.name: Salter V fracture
HP:6001248.definition: A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture that is due to a crush or compression injury of the growth plate. In type V, the force is transmitted through the epiphysis and physis, potentially disrupting the germinal matrix, hypertrophic region, and vascular supply.

HP:6001249.name: Nail bed laceration
HP:6001249.definition: A cut or injury to the soft tissue under the fingernail or toenail.

HP:6001250.name: History of distal radius fracture
HP:6001250.definition: Recent or remote history of distal radius fracture of the symptomatic arm.

HP:6001251.name: History of triangular fibrocartilage complex tear
HP:6001251.definition: Recent or remote history of a tear in the triangular fibrocartilage complex (TFCC). The TFCC is a load-bearing structure between the lunate, triquetrum, and ulnar head. The function of the TFCC is to act as a stabilizer for the ulnar aspect of the wrist. The TFCC is at risk for either acute or chronic degenerative injury.

HP:6001252.name: Reduced plantar creases
HP:6001252.definition: The creases (wrinkles) on the soles of the feet are less pronounced than normal, or absent.

HP:6001253.name: Skin burn
HP:6001253.definition: Damage to the skin and underlying tissues caused by an agents such as heat, chemicals, electricity, radiation, or friction, resulting in pain, redness, swelling, and sometimes blisters or charring.

HP:6001254.name: Elevanted carboxysterol concentration in cultured lymphoblasts
HP:6001254.definition: The concentration of carboxysterols in lymphoblastoid cells cultured in cholesterol-depleted medium is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6001255.name: Superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition
HP:6001255.definition: An anomaly that can be ascertained by iron-specific magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) sequences such as gradient-echo (GRE) and susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI). Superficial siderosis of the central nervous system is a chronic condition due to persistent or repeated long-term bleeding into the subarachnoid space, leading to subpial hemosiderin deposition. Hemosiderin deposition on MRI is seen as a T2 hypointensity and preferentially outlines the cerebellum and brainstem surface.

HP:6001256.name: Cortical superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition
HP:6001256.definition: A type of superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition that most commonly occurs due to iron deposits in the superficial cortical layers following bleeding from leptomeningeal vessels, most often from cerebral amyloid angiopathy in patients aged 55 or older.

HP:6001257.name: Infratentorial superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition
HP:6001257.definition: A type of superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition that involves the cerebellum and brainstem, most commonly the superior vermis, quadrigeminal plate, and basal cerebral surfaces. Cerebellar atrophy, particularly the superior vermis and anterior cerebellar hemispheres, can also be seen on a computed tomography scan of the head. The MRI of the spinal cord may reveal myelomalacia, syringomyelia, owl-eyes, or snake-eyes signs. The most common etiology for classic or primary infratentorial superficial siderosis is spinal dural defects, often dural tears.

HP:6001258.name: Pulmonary hyperplasia
HP:6001258.definition: Pulmonary Hyperplasia is an absolute increase in the number of alveoli, which are mildly enlarged. Pulmonary hyperplasia has been also referred to as polyalveolar lobe and type 3 cystic adenomatoid malformation.

HP:6001259.name: Positive protozoan parasite CSF wet mount test
HP:6001259.definition: Demonstration of protozoan parasites in a cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) specimen by microscopy.

HP:6001260.name: Gallbladder polyp
HP:6001260.definition: A gallbladder (GB) polyp is a growth that projects from the lining of the inside wall of the gallbladder into the lumen of the GB. GB polyps are a common incidental sonographic finding, the vast majority of which are benign.

HP:6001261.name: Gallbladder polyposis
HP:6001261.definition: Multiple polyps arising from the gallbladder mucosal wall.

HP:6001262.name: Biceps tendon rupture
HP:6001262.definition: Discontinuity of the biceps tendon as observed by ultrasound or magnetic resonance (MR) imaging.

HP:6001263.name: Medial epicondyle apophysitis
HP:6001263.definition: Medial epicondyle apophysitis (MEA), also known as little league elbow, is an overuse injury prevalent among adolescent athletes whose sport involves repetitive overhand throwing, racket use, or other overhead arm motions. The medial epicondyle is a bony protrusion on the medial elbow with its own ossification center, separate from the main distal humeral physis, known as an apophysis. Medial epicondyle apophysitis occurs due to excessive and repetitive valgus stress placed on the apophysis before its closure. Over time, the repetitive strain results in a traction-type injury and may cause pathologic widening and inflammation of the apophysis or even an avulsion fracture.

HP:6001264.name: Thumb carpometacarpal subluxation
HP:6001264.definition: A partial (subluxation) loss of alignment at the base of the thumb, where the first metacarpal bone meets the trapezium bone of the wrist. Thumb radiographs showing carpometacarpal (CMC) joint space widening and/or incongruity of the joint space between thumb metacarpal bone and the trapezium bone.

HP:6001265.name: Localized to the lower eyelid
HP:6001265.definition: A descriptor indicating that a condition, lesion, or abnormality is confined to the lower eyelid. This localization may be relevant for various ocular conditions, including infections, structural abnormalities, or dermatological diseases affecting the lower eyelid region.

HP:6001266.name: Localized to eyelid
HP:6001266.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in an eyelid.

HP:6001267.name: Halo vision
HP:6001267.definition: A visual phenomenon characterized by the perception of bright rings or halos surrounding light sources. Halo vision is often associated with optical irregularities such as corneal edema, cataracts, or intraocular lens complications. It may also occur in conditions affecting the tear film or due to the presence of glare from light scattering within the ocular media.

HP:6001268.name: Hematospermia
HP:6001268.definition: The presence of blood in the seminal fluid.

HP:6001269.name: Choledocholithiasis
HP:6001269.definition: Choledocholithiasis is the presence of stones within the common bile duct.

HP:6001270.name: Axillary nerve distribution
HP:6001270.definition: Paresthesias on the lateral aspect of the shoulder and upper arm. Weakness in shoulder abduction (deltoid) and shoulder external rotation (teres minor).

HP:6001271.name: Pelvic ring fracture
HP:6001271.definition: X-ray of the pelvis (AP, inlet, and outlet views) showing fracture of the pelvic ring, including iliac wing (ilium), superior or inferior pubic ramus, or ischium, and/or displacement of the pubic symphysis or sacroiliac joints.

HP:6001272.name: Scapulothoracic dissociation
HP:6001272.definition: An injury consisting of a laterally displaced scapula with separation of the ipsilateral acromioclavicular joint, disruption of the ipsilateral subclavian vessels and brachial plexus, and an intact overlying skin.

HP:6001273.name: Pain exacerbated by weight bearing
HP:6001273.definition: Refers to pain that is worse when the individual bears weight with the affected body part.

HP:6001274.name: Thumb sign
HP:6001274.definition: The distal phalanx of the adducted thumb extends beyond the ulnar border of the palm (The thumb protrudes from the clenched fist).

HP:6001275.name: Tibialis anterior tendon rupture
HP:6001275.definition: Partial or complete breakage (rupture) of the tibialis anterior tendon (TAT). The TAT is the principal dorsiflexor of the ankle joint and secondary invertor of the foot. It has important roles in the different stages of gait; in the swing phase, it concentrically dorsiflex the ankle for foot clearance and during plantarflexion of the ankle in the stance phase, it eccentrically contract to stabilize the ankle and prevent damage to the foot and ankle. Clinically, presentations in acute lacerations or direct trauma cases are straight forward, in chronic and atraumatic cases usually the symptoms at the time of TAT rupture are more subtle. Other manifestations include mild pain, localized mass, palpable gap, loss of strength, instability during gait, gait disturbances with forefoot dropping and stumbling and high stepping gait.

HP:6001276.name: Decreased circulating ADAMTS13 activity
HP:6001276.definition: Activity of the enzyme von Willebrand factor-cleaving protease (ADAMTS13) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6001277.name: Abnormal methacholine challenge test
HP:6001277.definition: An abnormal result of the methacholine challenge test, which is a bronchoprovocation technique used to evaluate airway hyperresponsiveness, particularly in patients with suspected asthma.

HP:0034881.name: Uterine mass
HP:0034881.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the uterus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:0033721.name: EEG with centrotemporal epileptiform discharges
HP:0033721.definition: Focal epileptiform EEG discharges recorded in the centrotemporal region.

HP:0033722.name: Autonomic epileptic aura
HP:0033722.definition: An autonomic epileptic aura is a purely subjective manifestation of an epileptic seizure pertaining to autonomic nervous system function. Autonomic auras include cardiorespiratory (e.g., palpitations and shortness of breath), gastrointestinal, genitourinary (genital sensations, urinary urge), and cutaneous (feeling of warmth or cold) sensations. Abdominal auras constitute the most common type of autonomic aura. These include sensations of nausea, pain, or indescribable discomfort in the abdominal or periumbilical area that can be static, rise to the chest and throat, or descend into the lower abdominal region.

HP:0033723.name: Abnormal cerebral venous sinus morphology
HP:0033723.definition: Abnormal structure of the venous sinuses that drain blood from the cerebral veins and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the arachnoid granulations to the internal jugular veins.

HP:0033724.name: Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis
HP:0033724.definition: An intracranial thrombosis of the venous sinuses. These typically present with headache, seizures or venous stroke secondary to raised cerebral venous pressure. Cerebral venous sinus thromboses usually affect larger areas of brain parenchyma than those affected by cerebral vein thromboses.

HP:0033725.name: Thin corpus callosum
HP:0033725.definition: An abnormally thin corpus callous, due to atrophy, hypoplasia or agenesis. This term is intended to be used in situations where it is not known if thinning of the corpus callosum (for instance, as visualized by magnetic resonance tomography) is due to abnormal development (e.g. a leukodystrophy) or atrophy following normal development (e.g. neurodegeneration).

HP:0033726.name: Lupus nephritis
HP:0033726.definition: Lupus nephritis is a type of glomerulonephritis that constitutes one of the most severe organ manifestations of systemic lupus erythematosus. Lupus nephritis is subclassified in six distinct classes, that represent different manifestations and severities of renal involvement and guide the therapeutic management.

HP:0033727.name: Diffuse lupus nephritis
HP:0033727.definition: A subclass of lupus nephritis with active or inactive diffuse, segmental or global endocapillary or extracapillary glomerulonephritis involving at least 50% of all glomeruli, typically with diffuse subendothelial immune deposits, with or without mesangial alterations.

HP:0033728.name: Mesangial proliferative lupus nephritis
HP:0033728.definition: A subclass of lupus nephritis with purely mesangial hypercellularity of any degree or mesangial matrix expansion by lightmicroscopy, with mesangial immune deposits. A few isolated subepithelial or subendothelial deposits may be visible by immunoflourescence or electron microscopy, but not by light microscopy.

HP:0033729.name: Minimal mesangial lupus nephritis
HP:0033729.definition: A subclass of lupus nephritis with normal glomeruli by light microscopy, but mesangial immune deposits by immunofluorescence.

HP:0033730.name: Membranous lupus nephritis
HP:0033730.definition: A lupus nephritis subclass with global or segmental subepithelial immune deposits or their morphological sequelae by light microscopy and by immunofluorescence or electron microscopy, with or without mesangial alterations. May occur in combination with class III or IV, in which case both classes are diagnosed. May show advanced sclerosis

HP:0033731.name: Focal lupus nephritis
HP:0033731.definition: A subclass of lupus nephritis with active or inactive focal, segmental or global endocapillary or extracapillary glomerulonephritis involving less than 50% of all glomeruli, typically with focal subendothelial immune deposits, with or without mesangial alterations

HP:0033732.name: Advanced sclerotic lupus nephritis
HP:0033732.definition: A subclass of lupus nephritis with at least 90% of glomeruli globally sclerosed without residual activity.

HP:0033733.name: Low-grade vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033733.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux without dilation of the renal calyces (Grade I-II).

HP:0033734.name: High-grade vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033734.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux with dilation of the renal calyces (Grade III - V).

HP:0033735.name: Grade I vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033735.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux into the ureter only.

HP:0033736.name: Grade II vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033736.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux into a non-dilated pyelocalyceal system.

HP:0033737.name: Grade III vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033737.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux with dilatation of the collecting system.

HP:0033738.name: Primary vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033738.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux due to abnormalities in ureterovesical junction, e.g. ectopic insertion of the ureter or short intravesical tunnel at the ureterovesical junction.

HP:0033739.name: Secondary vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033739.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux induced by increased bladder pressures in patients with voiding dysfunction e.g. in case of congenital posterior urethral valves or neurogenic bladder dysfunction.

HP:0033740.name: Grade V vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033740.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux with massive dilation of the collecting system and severe tortuosity of the ureter.

HP:0033741.name: Grade IV vesicoureteral reflux
HP:0033741.definition: Vesicoureteral reflux with more-extensive dilation with blunting of the calyces and tortuosity of the ureter.

HP:0033742.name: Intrarenal reflux
HP:0033742.definition: Severe vesicoureteral reflux reaching the kidney parenchyma.

HP:0033743.name: Macular agenesis
HP:0033743.definition: A congenital defect characterized by lack of development of the macula.

HP:0033744.name: Global cerebellar dysplasia
HP:0033744.definition: A type of cerebellar dysplasia that affects the entire cerebellum.

HP:0033745.name: Dysplasia of the superior cerebellar vermis
HP:0033745.definition: A type of cerebellar dysplasia that affects the upper part of the cerebellar vermis.

HP:0033746.name: Intrascapular pain
HP:0033746.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the area between the shoulder blades.

HP:0033747.name: Abnormal exteroceptive sensation
HP:0033747.definition: A type of somatic sensory dysfunction characterized by abnormality of superficial sensation that is mediated by receptors in skin and mucous membranes.

HP:0033749.name: Abnormal functional residual capacity
HP:0033749.definition: A deviation from normal values for the functional residual capacity, which is defined as the volume remaining in the lungs after a normal, passive exhalation.

HP:0033750.name: Reduced functional residual capacity
HP:0033750.definition: An abnormal reduction in the volume remaining in the lungs after a normal, passive exhalation.

HP:0033751.name: Elevated functional residual capacity
HP:0033751.definition: An abnormal increase in the volume remaining in the lungs after a normal, passive exhalation.

HP:0033752.name: Abnormal residual volume
HP:0033752.definition: Any deviation from normal values of the residual volume, which is defined as the volume of air left in the lungs at the end of maximal expiration (ie. the volume of air which you cannot voluntarily exhale from your lungs).

HP:0033753.name: Reduced residual volume
HP:0033753.definition: Abnormal decrease in the amount of air remaining in a person's lungs after full exhalation.

HP:0033754.name: Abnormal left ventricular end-diastolic volume
HP:0033754.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of end-diastolic volume of the left ventricle, which is the volume of blood in the left ventricle at the end of diastole (just before systole).

HP:0033755.name: Increased left ventricular end-diastolic volume
HP:0033755.definition: Abnormally high volume of blood in the left ventricle at the end of diastole (just before systole).

HP:0033756.name: Decreased left ventricular end-diastolic volume
HP:0033756.definition: Abnormally low volume of blood in the left ventricle at the end of diastole (just before systole).

HP:0033758.name: Labial abscess
HP:0033758.definition: A circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris in the labia.

HP:0033759.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of magnesium
HP:0033759.definition: Decreased renal tubular reabsorption of magnesium.

HP:0033760.name: Decreased maximal oxygen uptake
HP:0033760.definition: Maximum oxygen uptake (VO2max) is defined as the highest rate of oxygen uptake and utilization by the body during intense, maximal exercise, whereby further increases in work rate do not bring on additional rises in VO2 (i.e. plateau). VO2Max is typically measured with a treadmill and ergometer and the participant exercises with increasing levels of intensity. VO2Max is the point at which oxygen uptake no longer increases despite an increase in workload.

HP:0033761.name: Xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis
HP:0033761.definition: Xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis is a granulomatous inflammatory infiltrate composed of neutrophils, lymphocytes, plasma cells, xanthomatous histiocytes, and multinucleated giant cells.

HP:0033762.name: Middle cerebral artery stroke
HP:0033762.definition: Acute onset neurological deficits such as weakness, dizziness, numbness, issues with speech, or visual changes related to sudden impairment of blood flow to a part of the brain due to occlusion or rupture of the middle cerebral artery to the brain.

HP:0033763.name: Death in adulthood
HP:0033763.definition: Cessation of life at the age of 16 years or later.

HP:0033764.name: Death in middle age
HP:0033764.definition: Death between the age of 40 and 60 years.

HP:0033765.name: Death in late adulthood
HP:0033765.definition: Death at an age of at least 60 years.

HP:0033766.name: Polymelia
HP:0033766.definition: Polymelia is a congenital anomaly, which is defined as the presence of accessory limbs attached to various body regions and could be classified as cephalomelia (extra-limb attached to the head), notomelia (extra-limb attached to the back bone), thoracomelia (extra-limb attached to the thorax), and pyromelia (extra-limb attached to the pelvis).

HP:0033767.name: Abnormal single motor unit action potential
HP:0033767.definition: Abnormally high or low single motor unit action potential reading (-Pk Amps).

HP:0033768.name: Penile thrush
HP:0033768.definition: Overgrowth of candida albicans in the penis.

HP:0033769.name: Fundic gland polyposis
HP:0033769.definition: Multiple polyps in the acid-secreting mucosa of the gastric body and fundus. Fundic gland polyps (FGP) are usually 1 to 5 mm in size, though larger polyps have been found. FGPs are typically sessile, shiny, translucent, pale to pinkish in color (resembling the surrounding mucosa), and often exhibit tiny surface blood vessels. These polyps have characteristically been observed to chunk off or detach entirely at the base when removed with cold forceps, in contrast to other types of gastric polyps.

HP:0033770.name: Gastric adenocarcinoma
HP:0033770.definition: An adenocarcinoma arising from the stomach glandular epithelium. Gastric carcinoma often produces no specific symptoms when it is superficial and potentially surgically curable, although up to 50% of patients may have nonspecific gastrointestinal complaints such as dyspepsia.

HP:0033771.name: Pleuritic chest pain
HP:0033771.definition: Pleuritic chest pain is characterized by sudden and intense sharp, stabbing, or burning pain in the chest when inhaling and exhaling.

HP:0033772.name: Abnormal RV/TLC ratio
HP:0033772.definition: Any deviation from the normal ratio of residual volume (RV) to total lung capacity (TLC) on pulmonary function testing. RV is the amount of air remaining aftermaximal expiration and TLC is the total amount of air in theungs at full inspiration. These volumes cannot be determined by spirometry, but can be measured by inert gas dilution, nitrogen washout, and body plethysmography.

HP:0033773.name: Decreased RV/TLC ratio
HP:0033773.definition: An abnormally low ratio of residual volume (RV) to total lung capacity (TLC) on pulmonary function testing. RV is the amount of air remaining after maximal expiration and TLC is the total amount of air in the lungs at full inspiration. These volumes cannot be determined by spirometry, but can be measured by inert gas dilution, nitrogen washout, and body plethysmography.

HP:0033774.name: Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of uric acid
HP:0033774.definition: Decreased renal tubular reabsorption of uric acid.

HP:0033775.name: Pulmonary imaging sign
HP:0033775.definition: An abnormal pulmonary imaging finding defined by eponym or reference to signs, symbols, or naturalistic images.

HP:0033776.name: Enamel pearls
HP:0033776.definition: Small nodules of enamel on the root of a tooth.

HP:0033777.name: Supernumerary cusp
HP:0033777.definition: Additional cusps of a dental crown.

HP:0033778.name: Leung cusp
HP:0033778.definition: An additional cusp located in the middle of the occlusal surface.

HP:0033779.name: Barrel-shaped tooth
HP:0033779.definition: A tooth crown with convex mesial and distal surfaces.

HP:0033780.name: Bulbous tooth
HP:0033780.definition: A tooth crown with a marked cervical area constriction.

HP:0033781.name: Tapered tooth
HP:0033781.definition: A tooth with a crown that narrows from proximal toward the incisal edge. Tapering of teeth typically involves incisors.

HP:0033782.name: Semilunar tooth
HP:0033782.definition: An incisor with a half-moon shape incisal edge.

HP:0033783.name: Molar incisor malformation
HP:0033783.definition: Molar incisor malfomation (MIM) is composed of normal crown with marked cervical constriction, thin, narrow short roots which is a combination of signs that occurs in deciduous and permanent molars.

HP:0033784.name: Dentin dysplasia
HP:0033784.definition: This is a bundled term as dentin dysplasia is composed of short roots with pointed ends and taurodontism and intrapulpal calcifications.

HP:0033785.name: Enamel agenesis
HP:0033785.definition: Complete or almost complete absence of enamel.

HP:0033786.name: Hypomature enamel
HP:0033786.definition: Enamel with a white or brown discoloration without hypoplasia.

HP:0033787.name: Cementum hypoplasia
HP:0033787.definition: The decrease or absence of cementum. The cementum anchors the periodontal ligament attachment fiber between the tooth root and the alveolar bone. Its absence leads to early loss of teeth.

HP:0033788.name: Cementum overgrowth
HP:0033788.definition: Excess of cementum on the tooth root surface.

HP:0033789.name: Triggered by cheese ingestion
HP:0033789.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating cheese.

HP:0033790.name: Thistle tube shaped pulp
HP:0033790.definition: A thistle tube shape of the pulp chamber, meaning an enlarged coronal pulp chamber with narrow pulp canals giving a radiographic appearance of the shape of a thistle tube or a flame. It may occur isolated or associated with other dental anomalies and rare diseases such as dentinogenesis imperfecta, which should be assessed and coded separately. The diagnosis thistle tube shape pulp requires clinical and radiographic examinations.

HP:0033791.name: Tooth ankylosis
HP:0033791.definition: Fusion of a tooth with alveolar bone.

HP:0033792.name: Cross bite
HP:0033792.definition: Lingual occlusion of buccal cusps and/or incisal edge of maxillary teeth to the buccal cusps and/or incisal edge of mandibular teeth.

HP:0033793.name: Triggered by food ingestion
HP:0033793.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by eating a certain food.

HP:0033794.name: Acral overgrowth
HP:0033794.definition: Excessive growth of hands and feet (predominantly due to soft tissue swelling). Typical manifestations include shoe size increase, foot enlargement, glove tightness, and hand enlargement.

HP:0033796.name: Abnormal leukocyte physiology
HP:0033796.definition: A functional abnormality of a white blood cell.

HP:0033797.name: Leukocyte migration defect
HP:0033797.definition: Any abnormality of leukocyte motility in response to chemokines, which is required for the inflammatory response to infections, and for organ development, tissues homeostasis, and vascularization.

HP:0033799.name: Abnormal circulating sex hormone concentration
HP:0033799.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a sex hormone in the blood circulation

HP:0033800.name: Blistering by anatomical location
HP:0033800.definition: Blistering (presence of multiple fluid filled blisters) categorized according to the body site where they occur.

HP:0033801.name: Blistering by histological location
HP:0033801.definition: Blistering (presence of multiple fluid filled blisters) categorized according to the layer of the skin in which the blister originates. The skin is divided into three layers. The epidermis (outermost layer, which mainly consists of keratinocytes), the dermis, and a subcutaneous layer. The epidermis is divided into five layers: the basal lamina (innermost layer), the basal cell layer, the stratum spinosum, the stratum granulosum, and the stratum corneum (outermost layer). Cleavage in epidermolysis bullosa (EB) simplex occurs within the basal keratinocytes; in junctional EB, within the lamina lucida; and in dystrophic EB occurs in the sublamina densa, in the upper portion of the dermis (papillary dermis). In Kindler's EB, cleavage can occur in the basal keratinocytes, in the lamina lucida, or below the lamina densa.

HP:0033802.name: Intra-epidermal blistering
HP:0033802.definition: A type of blistering in which the lesions are located within the epidermis with loss of cell-cell adhesion of keratinocytes. In simplex EB, cleavage occurs in the basal layer, which is the innermost layer of the epidermis and consists of a single layer of basal germinative cells (mostly epidermal Keratinocytes) that proliferate and thereby produce new cells for other epidermal layers. As the cells move towards the upper layers of the epidermis they mature and eventually form cornified cells. The suprabasal cell layer lies directly above the basal layer and is composed of five to ten layers of cells.

HP:0033803.name: Sub-lamina densa cleavage
HP:0033803.definition: A type of blistering in which the cleavage plane of blisters is located below the lamina densa.

HP:0033804.name: Subepidermal blistering
HP:0033804.definition: A type of blistering in which the lesions are located beneath the epidermis.

HP:0033805.name: Non-necrotizing granuloma
HP:0033805.definition: A granuloma which is not associated with necrotic changes.

HP:0033806.name: Abnormal epidermis stratum granulosum morphology
HP:0033806.definition: An abnormal structure of the stratum granulosum, which is is a thin layer of cells in the epidermis lying above the stratum spinosum and below the stratum corneum.

HP:0033807.name: Absent keratohyalin granules
HP:0033807.definition: Lack of keratohyalin granules, which are normally present in the stratum granulosum of the epidermal layer of the skin.

HP:0033808.name: Spermatocele
HP:0033808.definition: A cystic structure arising from the epididymis, rete testis or efferent ductuli. These structures are filled with spermatozoa containing fluid that may be milky. These cysts are usually outside the tunica vaginalis and, as with hydrocele, transluminate easily.

HP:0033809.name: Increased circulating 17 hydroxypregnenolone concentration
HP:0033809.definition: Increased concentration of 17alpha-hydroxypregnenolone in the blood circulation. 17alpha-hydroxypregnenolone is a 21-carbon steroid that is converted from pregnenolone by steroid 17-alpha-hydroxylase, as an intermediate in the biosynthesis of gonadal steroid hormones and adrenal corticosteroids.

HP:0033810.name: Decreased circulating dihydrotestosterone concentration
HP:0033810.definition: A reduced concentration of dihydrotestosterone in the blood circulation.

HP:0033811.name: Abnormal circulating androstenedione concentration
HP:0033811.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of androstenedione in the blood circulation.

HP:0033812.name: Decreased circulating androstenedione concentration
HP:0033812.definition: Reduced concentration of androstenedione in the blood circulation.

HP:0033813.name: Perilobular
HP:0033813.definition: Situated or occurring around a lobe of an organ.

HP:0033814.name: Paraseptal
HP:0033814.definition: Characterized by predominant involvement of the distal alveoli and their ducts and sacs. It is characteristically bounded by any pleural surface and the interlobular septa.

HP:0033816.name: Centrilobular
HP:0033816.definition: Located in the center of the secondary pulmonary lobules, which are the functional units of the lungs.

HP:0033817.name: Miliary
HP:0033817.definition: Characterized by numerous small lesions said to resemble millet seed.

HP:0033818.name: Reticular
HP:0033818.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles a net or network-like structure.

HP:0033819.name: Perilymphatic
HP:0033819.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are located at or near lymphatic structures (node or vessel).

HP:0033820.name: Apical
HP:0033820.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are located at the apex of an organ. For instance, apical refers to the superior portion of the lung.

HP:0033821.name: Pulmonary mass
HP:0033821.definition: A mass in the lung seen on chest imaging is defined as an opacity greater than 3 cm in diameter (without regard to contour, border, or density characteristics).

HP:0033822.name: Mass on thoracic imaging
HP:0033822.definition: A mass is any pulmonary, pleural, or mediastinal lesion seen on chest radiographs as an opacity greater than 3 cm in diameter (without regard to contour, border, or density characteristics). Mass usually implies a solid or partly solid opacity. CT allows more exact evaluation of size, location, attenuation, and other features.

HP:0033823.name: Mediastinal mass
HP:0033823.definition: A mass in the mediastinum seen on chest imaging is defined as an opacity greater than 3 cm in diameter (without regard to contour, border, or density characteristics).

HP:0033824.name: Pleural mass
HP:0033824.definition: A mass in the pleura seen on chest imaging is defined as an opacity greater than 3 cm in diameter (without regard to contour, border, or density characteristics).

HP:0033825.name: Superior mediastinal mass
HP:0033825.definition: A type of mediastinal mass that is located above the thoracic plane (a horizontal line that runs from the manubriosternal joint (sternal angle or angle of Louis) to the inferior endplate of T4).

HP:0033826.name: Inferior mediastinal mass
HP:0033826.definition: A type of mediastinal mass that is located below the thoracic plane (a horizontal line that runs from the manubriosternal joint (sternal angle or angle of Louis) to the inferior endplate of T4).

HP:0033827.name: Anterior mediastinal mass
HP:0033827.definition: A type of inferior mediastinal mass that is located in front of the pericardium.

HP:0033828.name: Middle mediastinal mass
HP:0033828.definition: A type of inferior mediastinal mass that is located withinthe pericardium.

HP:0033829.name: Posterior mediastinal mass
HP:0033829.definition: A type of inferior mediastinal mass that is located behind the pericardium.

HP:0033830.name: Hyperdense pulmonary mass
HP:0033830.definition: A type of pulmonary mass with high attenuation.

HP:0033831.name: Cavitating pulmonary mass
HP:0033831.definition: Thick-walled abnormal gas-filled interstitial mass within a lung with a diameter greater than 30 mm.

HP:0033832.name: Livedo
HP:0033832.definition: A reddish-blue mottled condition of skin caused by inflammation of the cutaneous blood vessels.

HP:0033833.name: Elevated circulating soluble CD25 concentration
HP:0033833.definition: Increased concentration of the interleukin-2 receptor alpha-chain (CD25) in the blood circulation. CD25 is shed upon immune activation. Increased levels of soluble CD25, therefore, are an indication of an on-going immune response.

HP:0033834.name: Malaise
HP:0033834.definition: A feeling of general discomfort, weakness, or lack of health.

HP:0033835.name: Abnormal renal vascular morphology
HP:0033835.definition: Anomalous structure of a blood vessel in the kidney.

HP:0033836.name: Abnormal intrarenal artery morphology
HP:0033836.definition: An anomalous structure of an artery located in the kidney.

HP:0033837.name: Abnormal arcuate artery morphology
HP:0033837.definition: Anomalous structure of the arc-shaped arteries located at the border of the renal cortex and renal medulla.

HP:0033838.name: Dysphoria
HP:0033838.definition: A state of feeling very unhappy, uneasy, or dissatisfied.

HP:0033839.name: Testicular pain
HP:0033839.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to one or both testes.

HP:0033840.name: Postmenopausal bleeding
HP:0033840.definition: Uterine bleeding that occurs after at least one year of amenorrhea in a woman who is not receiving hormone therapy.

HP:0033841.name: Ocular pruritus
HP:0033841.definition: Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased sensation of itching in the region of the eye.

HP:0033842.name: Early satiety
HP:0033842.definition: The condition of being unable to eat a full meal because of a feeling of fullness (satiety), or or feeling very full after eating only a small amount of food.

HP:0033844.name: Racing thoughts
HP:0033844.definition: An inner sense (from the self) that thoughts are moving abnormally fast and in a manner that the individual typically feels that the rate is beyond their control, i.e. they feel unable to slow the rate of thoughts. Racing thoughts by themselves have a linear progression, following a line of thinking or logic, which distinguishes racing thoughts from flight of ideas. Racing thoughts may however, co-occur with or be independent from flight of ideas, they may be associated with pressured speech or be an internal perception of the rate of thinking. The core element being the rate of the thoughts themselves.

HP:0033845.name: Sense of impending doom
HP:0033845.definition: A feeling that something life-threatening or tragic is about to occur.

HP:0033846.name: Spinal hypomyelination
HP:0033846.definition: Reduced amount of myelin in the spinal cord resulting from defective myelinogenesis.

HP:0033847.name: Phantageusia
HP:0033847.definition: A form of altered taste sensation in which the affected person perceives a taste, usually an unpleasant one, in the absence of a corresponding stimulus in the environment.

HP:0033848.name: Receptive aphasia
HP:0033848.definition: A type of aphasia that is characterized by impaired language comprehension.

HP:0033849.name: Bilingual aphasia
HP:0033849.definition: The term bilingual aphasia is used to refer to aphasia in persons who speak two or more languages. When a multilingual speaker has aphasia following a stroke, the languages spoken premorbidly may show comparable or differential patterns of impairment. Differential patterns may manifest as greater impairment in one language compared to another, or as differences in the characteristics of aphasia. Clinical reports of bilingual aphasia show dissociations in the processing of the language learned first (L1) and and second (L2), with one language more impaired than the other. Other cases show a pattern of differential recovery where L2 is recovered only after L1. Another pattern is alternating antagonism; i.e., patients access one language in spontaneous speech and inhibit the other language for alternating periods. This term should be used for a type of aphasia in a person who speaks multiple languages in which the impairment is different for different languages.

HP:0033850.name: Coldness
HP:0033850.definition: Relative coldness of a body part to palpitation, often acccompanied by feelings of coldness.

HP:0033851.name: Oculomotor synkinesis
HP:0033851.definition: Elevation of the upper eyelid on attempted downward gaze or adduction, adduction of the eye on attempted upward or downward gaze, and constriction of the pupil on attempted adduction.

HP:0033852.name: Abnormal intrarenal vein morphology
HP:0033852.definition: Abnormal structure of a vein located inside the kidney parenchyma.

HP:0033853.name: Abnormal arcuate vein morphology
HP:0033853.definition: Any structural anomaly of the arcuate vein. The arcuate veins cross traverse along the corticomedullary junction (at the border of the kideny cortex and medulla).

HP:0033854.name: Abnormal interlobular vein morphology
HP:0033854.definition: Any structural anomaly of the interlobular veins of the kidney. An interlobular vein is surrounded by the renal cortex and located between renal lobules (consisting of the nephrons surrounding a single medullary ray and draining into a single collecting duct).

HP:0033855.name: Abnormal interlobular vein lumen morphology
HP:0033855.definition: Any structural anomaly located in the the inside space of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033856.name: Cholesterol emboli within interlobular vein lumen
HP:0033856.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of interlobular veins. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033857.name: Intraluminal thrombi within interlobular veins
HP:0033857.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding vascular lumen of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033858.name: Organized thrombi within interlobular vein lumen
HP:0033858.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033859.name: Abnormal peritubular capillary morphology
HP:0033859.definition: Anomalous structure of the capillaries that are derived from the efferent arteriole, forming a capillary network that surrounds the distal portions of the nephron tubule,

HP:0033860.name: Abnormal cortical peritubular capillary morphology
HP:0033860.definition: Anomalous structure of the peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0033861.name: Multilamellation of cortical peritubular capillary basement membranes
HP:0033861.definition: Duplicated basement membranes of the peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney and arranged in multiple concentric layers.

HP:0033862.name: Cortical peritubular capillaritis
HP:0033862.definition: Inflammation of the peritubular capillaries in the cortex of the kidney characterized by Inflammatory cells in over 10 percent of the interstitial capillaries in the cortex with at least some capillaries having three or more luminal cells.

HP:0033863.name: Abnormal cortical peritubular capillary lumen morphology
HP:0033863.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space of the peritubular capillary in the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0033864.name: Abnormal medullary peritubular capillary morphology
HP:0033864.definition: Anomalous structure of the peritubular capillaries located in the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0033865.name: Medullary peritubular capillaritis
HP:0033865.definition: Inflammation of the peritubular capillaries in the medulla of the kidney characterized by Inflammatory cells in over 10 percent of the interstitial capillaries in the cortex with at least some capillaries having three or more luminal cells.

HP:0033866.name: Medullary peritubular capillary erythrocyte congestion
HP:0033866.definition: Substantially increased numbers of red blood cells within capillaries surrounding tubules in the medulla of the kidney. This feature is assessed in histological images as the presence of numerous erythrocytes in a segment of the capillary such that the vessel appears to be congested (not open).

HP:0033867.name: Multilamellation of medullary peritubular capillary basement membranes
HP:0033867.definition: Duplicated basement membranes of the peritubular capillaries located in the medulla of the kidney and arranged in multiple concentric layers.

HP:0033868.name: Abnormal medullary peritubular capillary lumen morphology
HP:0033868.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space of the peritubular capillary in the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0033869.name: Medullary peritubular capillary lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033869.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of peritubular capillaries located in the medulla of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033870.name: Medullary peritubular capillary intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033870.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the peritubular capillaries located in the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0033871.name: Medullary peritubular capillary lumen organized thrombi
HP:0033871.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the peritubular capillaries of the medulla of the kidney.

HP:0033872.name: Cortical peritubular capillary lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033872.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033873.name: Cortical peritubular capillary intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033873.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0033874.name: Cortical peritubular capillary lumen organized thrombi
HP:0033874.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the peritubular capillaries of the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0033875.name: Abnormal arcuate vein lumen morphology
HP:0033875.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space (lumen) of the arcuate vein of the kidney.

HP:0033876.name: Arcuate vein lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033876.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of arcuate veins of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033877.name: Arcuate vein intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033877.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033878.name: Arcuate vein lumen organized thrombi
HP:0033878.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033879.name: Abnormal arcuate vein intima/media morphology
HP:0033879.definition: Any structural anomaly located in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033880.name: Arcuate vein intimal mucoid edema
HP:0033880.definition: Accumulation of edematous extracellular matrix in the inner layer (intima) of arcuate veins of the kidney. The material resembles mucus and appears pale blue on hematoxylin and eosin staining.

HP:0033881.name: Arcuate vein intimal/medial myxomatous degeneration
HP:0033881.definition: Accumulation of myxoid material (mucus-like material) within the inner or middle layer of the arcuate vein of the kidney.

HP:0033882.name: Arcuate vein intima/medial amyloidosis
HP:0033882.definition: Amorphous extracellular substance in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney. Amyloidosis stains Congo-red positive with typically an apple green birerfingence on polarization microscopy, and 8-12 nm fibrils on electron microscopy.

HP:0033883.name: Abnormal cortical radial artery morphology
HP:0033883.definition: Any structural anomaly of the radial arteries that branch off at right angles from the arcuate artery and carry blood toward the cortex of the kidney.

HP:0033884.name: Abnormal cortical radial artery lumen morphology
HP:0033884.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space of the cortical radial arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033885.name: Cortical radial artery lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033885.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of cortical radial arteries (interlobular arteries) of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033886.name: Abnormal arcuate artery intima/media morphology
HP:0033886.definition: Anomalous structure of the inner or middle layer of the arc-shaped arteries located at the border of the renal cortex and renal medulla.

HP:0033887.name: Cortical radial artery intimal/medial amyloidosis
HP:0033887.definition: Amorphous extracellular substance in the glomerular, interstitial or vascular compartments of the interlobular arteries of the kidney. Congo-red positive with typically an apple green birerfingence on polarization microscopy, and 8-12 nm fibrils on electron microscopy

HP:0033888.name: Abnormal cortical radial artery intima/media morphology
HP:0033888.definition: Any structural anomaly of the inner or middle layer of the cortical radial arteries (also known as interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033889.name: Abnormal renal arteriole morphology
HP:0033889.definition: Any structural anomaly of the glomerular arterioles. The interlobar arteries of the kidney branch into arcuate arteries, cortical radiate arteries, and then into afferent arterioles. After passing through the renal corpuscle, the capillaries form the efferent arteriole. The afferent and efferent arterioles are difficult to distinguish histologically and are thus both included in this term and its descendents.

HP:0033890.name: Abnormal renal arteriole lumen morphology
HP:0033890.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space (lumen) of renal arterioles.

HP:0033891.name: Renal arteriolar lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033891.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of arterioles of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033892.name: Abnormal renal arteriole intima/media morphology
HP:0033892.definition: Any structural anomaly located in the inner or middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033893.name: Renal arteriolar lumen organized thrombi
HP:0033893.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033894.name: Renal arteriolar intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033894.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033895.name: Abnormal renal arteriole endothelium morphology
HP:0033895.definition: Any structural anomaly of the lining (endothelium) of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033896.name: Abnormal arcuate artery lumen morphology
HP:0033896.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space (lumen) of the arcuate artery of the kidney.

HP:0033897.name: Arcuate artery lumen cholesterol emboli
HP:0033897.definition: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of arcuate arteries of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.

HP:0033898.name: Arcuate artery intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033898.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the arcuate arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033899.name: Arcuate artery lumen organized thrombi
HP:0033899.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels located within the lumen of the arcuate arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033900.name: Renal arteriole intima/media amyloidosis
HP:0033900.definition: Amorphous extracellular substance in the inner or middle layer of renal arterioles. Amyloidosis stains Congo-red positive with typically an apple green birerfingence on polarization microscopy, and 8-12 nm fibrils on electron microscopy.

HP:0033901.name: Abnormal arcuate artery endothelium morphology
HP:0033901.definition: Any structural anomaly of the lining (endothelium) of the arcuate arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033902.name: Arcuate artery endotheliosis
HP:0033902.definition: Enlargement of endothelial cells of the arcuate arteries of the kidney because of cytoplasmic swelling.

HP:0033903.name: Arcuate artery endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033903.definition: Proliferation of endothelial cells (increased number of cells) of the lining (endothelium) of the arcuate arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033904.name: Renal arteriole intima/media hyalinosis
HP:0033904.definition: Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material (hyalinosis) in the inner or middle layer of the renal arterioles. This feature may be accompanied by hypertrophy of the media and intima fibrosis.

HP:0033905.name: Arcuate artery intima/media arteriosclerosis
HP:0033905.definition: Thickening of the intima of the arcuate arteries of the kidney with fibrosis and/or duplication of the elastic lamina.

HP:0033906.name: Renal intimal/medial arteriolitis
HP:0033906.definition: Inflammation of an arteriole of the kidney, which may involve only the intma or can be transmural.

HP:0033907.name: Renal arteriole intima/media arteriolosclerosis
HP:0033907.definition: Thickening of the intima of renal arterioles with fibrosis and/or duplication of the elastic lamina.

HP:0033908.name: Renal arteriole medial atrophy
HP:0033908.definition: Atrophy (wasting, decreased thickness) of of the middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033909.name: Arcuate vein medial hypertrophy
HP:0033909.definition: Increased thickness of middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033910.name: Arcuate vein medial atrophy
HP:0033910.definition: Atrophy (wasting, decreased thickness) of the middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033911.name: Cortical radial artery medial hypertrophy
HP:0033911.definition: Increased thickness of the middle layer of the cortical radial arteries (also known as the interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033912.name: Cortical radial artery medial atrophy
HP:0033912.definition: Atrophy (wasting, decreased thickness) of the middle layer of the cortical radial arteries (also known as the interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033913.name: Cortical radial artery medial/intimal arteriitis
HP:0033913.definition: Inflammation of a the intima or the entire wall of cortical radial arteries (also known as the interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033914.name: Arcuate artery intima/media amyloidosis
HP:0033914.definition: Amorphous extracellular substance in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate arteries of the kidney. Congo-red positive with typically an apple green birerfingence on polarization microscopy, and 8-12 nm fibrils on electron microscopy.

HP:0033915.name: Arcuate artery intimal mucoid edema
HP:0033915.definition: Accumulation of edematous extracellular matrix in intima resembling mucus. This feature appears pale blue on hematoxylin and eosin staining.

HP:0033916.name: Medial/intimal arcuate venosclerosis
HP:0033916.definition: Thickening of the intima with fibrosis and/or duplication of the elastic lamina in arcuate veins.

HP:0033917.name: Arcuate intimal/medial venulitis
HP:0033917.definition: Inflammation of the inner or middle layer of arcuate venules. This feature may involve only the intima or it can be transmural.

HP:0033918.name: Renal arteriole medial hypertrophy
HP:0033918.definition: Increased thickness of middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033920.name: Renal arteriole intima/media storage material accumulation
HP:0033920.definition: Deposition of storage material other than amyloid (glycogen, glycosphingolipid in Fabry's disease, sphingomyelin in Nieman Pick disease, glucosylceramide in Gaucher's disease, gangliosides, mucopolysaccahrides, phytanic acid in Refsum disease) in the inner or middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033921.name: Renal arteriole endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033921.definition: Abnormal and excessive number of cells (hypercellularity) in the lining (endothelium) of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033922.name: Renal arteriole leukocytic endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033922.definition: A type of renal arteriole endoarterial hypercellularity due to increased number of white blood cells (leukocytes).

HP:0033923.name: Renal arteriole foam cell endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033923.definition: A type of renal arteriole leukocytic endoarterial hypercellularity due to the presence of lipid-filled cells, often a macrophage, with a vacuolated appearance in arteriolar lumen.

HP:0033924.name: Renal arteriole neutrophil endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033924.definition: A type of renal arteriole leukocytic endoarterial hypercellularity due to the presence of increased numbers of neutrophils within the arteriolar lumen.

HP:0033925.name: Renal arteriole lymphocyte endoarterial hypercellularity
HP:0033925.definition: A type of renal arteriole leukocytic endoarterial hypercellularity due to the presence of increased number of lymphocytes in the arteriolar lumen.

HP:0033926.name: Renal arteriole intimal/medial multilamellation
HP:0033926.definition: Myointimal hyperplasia arranged in multiple concentric layers in the inner or middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033927.name: Arcuate artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity
HP:0033927.definition: Arcuate artery endoarterial hypercellularity due to increased numbers of white blood cells (leukocytes).

HP:0033928.name: Arcuate artery endoarterial foam cell hypercellularity
HP:0033928.definition: A type of arcuate artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of lipid-filled cells, often a macrophage, with a vacuolated appearance in arteriolar lumen.

HP:0033929.name: Arcuate artery endoarterial neutrophil hypercellularity
HP:0033929.definition: A type of arcuate artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of increased numbers of neutrophils withinin the lumen of arcuate artery.

HP:0033930.name: Arcuate artery endoarterial lymphocyte hypercellularity
HP:0033930.definition: A type of arcuate artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of increased number of lymphocytes in the lumen of arcuate artery.

HP:0033931.name: Arcuate artery intima/media necrosis
HP:0033931.definition: Death of tissue in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate artery of the kidney.

HP:0033932.name: Arcuate artery intima/media coagulative necrosis
HP:0033932.definition: A type of arcuate artery intima/media necrosis in which the necrotic tissue retains the outlines of the dead (necrotic) structures.

HP:0033933.name: Arcuate artery intima/media liquefactive necrosis
HP:0033933.definition: A type of arcuate artery intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue breaks down such that cellular detail is no longer recognized.

HP:0033934.name: Arcuate vein intimal/medial storage material accumulation
HP:0033934.definition: Accumulation of material other than amyloid (glycogen, glycosphingolipid in Fabry's disease, sphingomyelin in Nieman Pick disease, glucosylceramide in Gaucher's disease, gangliosides, mucopolysaccahrides, phytanic acid in Refsum disease) in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033935.name: Cortical radial artery intima/media necrosis
HP:0033935.definition: Cell death (necrosis) in the inner or middle layer of the cortical radial arteries (also known as the interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033936.name: Cortical radial artery intima/media liquefactive necrosis
HP:0033936.definition: A type of cortical radial artery intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue breaks down such that cellular detail is no longer recognized.

HP:0033937.name: Cortical radial artery intima/media coagulative necrosis
HP:0033937.definition: A type of cortical radial artery intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue retains the outlines of the dead structures.

HP:0033938.name: Renal arteriole intima/media necrosis
HP:0033938.definition: Cell death (necrosis) in the inner or middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033939.name: Renal arteriole intima/media liquefactive necrosis
HP:0033939.definition: A type of renal arteriole intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue breaks down such that cellular detail is no longer recognized.

HP:0033940.name: Renal arteriole intima/media coagulative necrosis
HP:0033940.definition: A type of renal arteriole intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue retains the outlines of the dead structures.

HP:0033941.name: Granulomatous arteriolitis of the arteriolar intima/media
HP:0033941.definition: A type of renal intimal/medial arteriolitis characteriezed by circumscribed inflammatory lesions comprised primarily of macrophages present in inflamed arteries.

HP:0033942.name: Arcuate vein medial/intimal necrosis
HP:0033942.definition: Cell death (necrosis) of the inner or middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033943.name: Arcuate vein medial/intimal coagulative necrosis
HP:0033943.definition: A type of arcuate vein medial/intimal necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue retains the outlines of the dead structures.

HP:0033944.name: Arcuate vein medial/intimal liquefactive necrosis
HP:0033944.definition: A type of arcuate vein medial/intimal necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue breaks down such that cellular detail is no longer recognized.

HP:0033945.name: Arcuate intimal/medial granulomatous venulitis
HP:0033945.definition: A type of arcuate intimal/medial venulitis characterized by circumscribed inflammatory lesions comprised primarily of macrophages present in inflamed veins.

HP:0033946.name: Arcuate vein intima/media crystal accumulation
HP:0033946.definition: Deposition of crystals such as uric acid, oxalate, or cystine in the inner or middle layer of the arcuate veins of the kidney.

HP:0033947.name: Renal arteriole intima/media crystal accumulation
HP:0033947.definition: Deposition of crystals such as uric acid, oxalate, or cystine in the inner or middle layer of the arterioles of the kidney.

HP:0033948.name: Arcuate artery intima/media arteriitis
HP:0033948.definition: Inflammation of the inner or middle layer of the arcuate arteries of the kidney.

HP:0033949.name: Arcuate artery intima/media granulomatous arteriitis
HP:0033949.definition: A type of arcuate artery intima/media granulomatous arteriitis characterized by circumscribed inflammatory lesions comprised primarily of macrophages present in inflamed arteries.

HP:0033950.name: Cortical radial artery intraluminal thrombi
HP:0033950.definition: Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding vascular lumen within the interior space of cortical radial arteries (interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033951.name: Cortical radial artery intraluminal organized thrombi
HP:0033951.definition: Thrombi containing fibrous tissue and capillary-like vascular channels within the interior space of cortical radial arteries (interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033952.name: Abnormal cortical radial artery endothelium morphology
HP:0033952.definition: Abnormal structural characteristics of the lining (endothelium) of the cortical radial arteries (also known as interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033953.name: Cortical radial artery endotheliosis
HP:0033953.definition: Enlargement of endothelial cells of the cortical radial arteries (also known as the interlobular arteries) of the kidney because of cytoplasmic swelling.

HP:0033954.name: Cortical radial artery hypercellularity
HP:0033954.definition: Proliferation of endothelial cells (increased number of cells) of the lining (endothelium) of the cortical radial arteries (also known as interlobular arteries) of the kidney.

HP:0033955.name: Cortical radial artery leukocyte hypercellularity
HP:0033955.definition: A type of cortical radial artery endoarterial hypercellularity due to increased numbers of white blood cells (leukocytes).

HP:0033956.name: Cortical radial artery lymphocyte hypercellularity
HP:0033956.definition: A type of cortical radial artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of increased number of lymphocytes in the lumen of cortical radial arteries.

HP:0033957.name: Cortical radial artery neutrophil hypercellularity
HP:0033957.definition: A type of cortical radial artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of increased numbers of neutrophils in the lumen of cortical radial arteries.

HP:0033958.name: Cortical radial artery foam cell hypercellularity
HP:0033958.definition: A type of cortical radial artery endoarterial leukocyte hypercellularity due to the presence of lipid-filled cells, often macrophages, with a vacuolated appearance in the lumen of cortical radial artery (also known as the interlobular artery) of the kidney.

HP:0033959.name: Cortical radial artery intima/media arteriosclerosis
HP:0033959.definition: Thickening of the intima of the cortical radial artery (also known as the interlobular artery) of the kidney characterized by fibrosis and/or duplication of the elastic lamina.

HP:0033960.name: Cortical radial artery intimal mucoid edema
HP:0033960.definition: Accumulation of edematous extracellular matrix in the intima of the cortical radial artery (also known as the interlobular artery) of the kidney. This material resembles mucus and stains pale blue on hematoxylin and eosin staining.

HP:0033961.name: Cortical radial artery intima/media multilamellation
HP:0033961.definition: Myointimal hyperplasia of the inner and middle layer of the cortical radial artery (also known as the interlobular artery) of the kidney, arranged in multiple concentric layers.

HP:0033962.name: Cortical radial artery medial/intimal granulomatous arteriitis
HP:0033962.definition: A type of cortical radial artery medial/intimal arteriitis that is characterized by circumscribed inflammatory lesions comprised primarily of macrophages present in inflamed arteries.

HP:0033963.name: Abnormal interlobular vein intima/media morphology
HP:0033963.definition: Any structural anomaly of the inner or middle layer of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033964.name: Interlobular intima/media venosclerosis
HP:0033964.definition: Thickening of the intima with fibrosis and/or duplication of the elastic lamina in interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033965.name: Interlobular vein intimal mucoid edema
HP:0033965.definition: Accumulation of edematous extracellular matrix in the intima of the interlobular vein of the kidney. This material resembles mucus and stains pale blue on hematoxylin and eosin staining.

HP:0033966.name: Interlobular vein intima/media amyloidosis
HP:0033966.definition: Amorphous extracellular substance in the glomerular, interstitial or vascular compartments of the interlobular veins of the kidney. Congo-red positive with typically an apple green birerfingence on polarization microscopy, and 8-12 nm fibrils on electron microscopy

HP:0033967.name: Interlobular vein intima/media venulitis
HP:0033967.definition: Inflammation of the interlobular veins of the kidney which may affect only the intima or may be transmural.

HP:0033968.name: Interlobular vein intima/media granulomatous venulitis
HP:0033968.definition: A type of interlobular vein intima/media venulitis that is characterized by circumscribed inflammatory lesions comprised primarily of macrophages present in inflamed veins.

HP:0033969.name: Interlobular vein intima/media necrosis
HP:0033969.definition: Cell death (necrosis) in the inner or middle layer of the interlobular vein of the kidney.

HP:0033970.name: Interlobular vein intima/media liquefactive necrosis
HP:0033970.definition: A type of interlobular vein intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue breaks down such that cellular detail is no longer recognized.

HP:0033971.name: Interlobular vein intima/media coagulative necrosis
HP:0033971.definition: A type of interlobular vein intima/media necrosis in which the dead (necrotic) tissue retains the outlines of the dead structures.

HP:0033972.name: Interlobular vein medial atrophy
HP:0033972.definition: Atrophy (wasting, decreased thickness) of the medial layer pf the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033973.name: Interlobular vein medial hypertrophy
HP:0033973.definition: Increased thickness of middle layer of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

HP:0033974.name: Interlobular vein intima/media multilamellation
HP:0033974.definition: Myointimal hyperplasia of the inner and middle layer of the interlobular veins of the kidney, arranged in multiple concentric layers.

HP:0033975.name: Absent second fingernail
HP:0033975.definition: Absence of the fingernail of the index (second) finger.

HP:0033976.name: Volar fingernail
HP:0033976.definition: The presence of an extra nail on the palmar (volar, ventral) surface of the finger.

HP:0033977.name: Talar aplasia
HP:0033977.definition: Absent talus owing to a congenital defect.

HP:0033978.name: Reduced beta-hexosaminidase B activity
HP:0033978.definition: Diminished activity of the enzyme beta-hexosaminidase in the blood circulation.

HP:0033979.name: Excessive dynamic airway collapse
HP:0033979.definition: Excessive anterior displacement of the tracheal and/or bronchial membranous wall.

HP:0033980.name: Paroxysmal tonic upgaze
HP:0033980.definition: Recurrent episodes of sustained upward deviation of the eyes and incomplete downward saccades, and normal horizontal eye movements without impairment of consciousness.

HP:0033981.name: Vertebral artery tortuosity
HP:0033981.definition: Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of the vertebral arteries.

HP:0033982.name: Celiac artery dissection
HP:0033982.definition: A separation (dissection) of the layers of the celiac artery wall.

HP:0033983.name: Decreased circulating apolipoprotein C-II concentration
HP:0033983.definition: Reduced concentration of apolipoprotein C-II in the blood circulation.

HP:0033984.name: Increased urinary 8-oxo-7,8-dihydroguanosine level
HP:0033984.definition: An elevated amount of 8-oxo-7,8-dihydroguanosine in the urine.

HP:0033985.name: Elongated femoral neck
HP:0033985.definition: Increased length of the neck of the femur.

HP:0033986.name: Tortuous lymphatic vessels
HP:0033986.definition: The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of lymphatic vessels.

HP:0033987.name: Phosphaturic mesenchymal tumor
HP:0033987.definition: A rare, endocrine active tumor that causes severe renal phosphate wasting, which in turn can lead to critical osteomalacia. Phosphaturic mesenchymal tumors (PMTs) are typically small and mostly benign tumors producing fibroblast growth factor 23 (FGF-23). FGF-23 lowers the expression of sodium/phosphate cotransporters, which are the primary transport proteins responsible for phosphate reabsorption in the kidneys. The paraneoplastic overproduction of FGF-23 lowers reabsorption of phosphate and causes severe paraneoplastic renal phosphate wasting and hypophosphatemia. FGF-23 also affects vitamin D levels by lowering 25-hydroxyvitamin D 1-alpha-hydroxylase in the proximal renal tubules and by increasing the expression of vitamin D 24-hydroxylase, a mitochondrial enzyme responsible for inactivating vitamin D metabolites.

HP:0033988.name: Amygdala microinfarct
HP:0033988.definition: An infarct located in the almond-shaped body of basal nuclei anterior to the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle of the brain, within the temporal lobe that can only be observed microscopically.

HP:0033989.name: Hippocampal microinfarct
HP:0033989.definition: An infarct located in the structure of the cerebrum involved with memory storage and spatial navigation that can only be observed microscopically.

HP:0033990.name: Cartilaginous tracheobronchomalacia
HP:0033990.definition: Softening of the tracheal and/or bronchial cartilage resulting in segmental tracheal and/or bronchial weakness.

HP:0033991.name: Vasa previa
HP:0033991.definition: Vasa previa occurs when the membranes that contain the umbilical cord traverse the membranes overlying the internal os of the cervix. There is a high risk of fetal mortality if not identified perinatally.

HP:0033992.name: Chronotropic incompetence
HP:0033992.definition: Inability of the heart to increase its rate commensurate with increased activity or demand.

HP:0033993.name: Viral encephalitis
HP:0033993.definition: An inflammation of brain parenchyma due to infection with a virus. Viral encephalitis can occur as a rare complication of common infections (eg, herpes virus infections) or can occur as a characteristic presentation of rare viruses (eg, rabies virus infection). Encephalitis may be the only neurologic manifestation of infection, or may occur in association with meningitis, myelitis, radiculitis, or neuritis. Viral encephalitis is associated with neurological dysfunction.

HP:0033994.name: Dependency on parenteral nutrition
HP:0033994.definition: Inability to ingest sufficient quantities of nutrition by mouth or by tube-feeding with the corresponding requirement for intravenous administration of nutrition.

HP:0033995.name: Microvillus inclusions
HP:0033995.definition: The presence of vacuoles bearing centripetal microvilli in small gut villus enterocytes.

HP:0033996.name: Microvillar PAS-positive secretory granules
HP:0033996.definition: The presenceaccumulationof periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) granules in the subapical region of small intenstinal microvilli, appearing as different kinds of vesicular/tubular structures.

HP:0033997.name: Perinuclear cardiomyocyte vacuolization
HP:0033997.definition: Formation of vacuoles, i.e., membrane-bound organelles, in the portion of the cytoplasm near the nucleus within myocytes of the heart.

HP:0033998.name: Single-lobed right lung
HP:0033998.definition: A developmental defect of pulmonary lobation characterized by the presence of only one lobe of the right lung, which normally has three lobes.

HP:0033999.name: Bronchial hemorrhage
HP:0033999.definition: Bronchial hemorrhage is a focal bleeding located in the bronchial system. It can be diagnosed by tracheobronchoscopy.

HP:0034000.name: Tracheal hemorrhage
HP:0034000.definition: Tracheal hemorrhage is a focal bleeding within the trachea. It be diagnosed by tracheobronchoscopy.

HP:0034001.name: Anti-Complement factor H antibody positivity
HP:0034001.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against complement factor H.

HP:0034002.name: Anti-phospholipase A2 receptor antibody positivity
HP:0034002.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the phospholipase A2 receptor.

HP:0034003.name: Broad medial eyebrow
HP:0034003.definition: Regional increase in the width (height) of the middle portion of the eyebrow.

HP:0034004.name: Parosmia
HP:0034004.definition: Misperception of existing odor, that is, distorted or altered olfactory perception in the presence of known stimuli.

HP:0034005.name: Decreased dendritic spine number
HP:0034005.definition: An abnormal reduction in the amount of spines on a given dendrite.

HP:0034006.name: Decreased urinary lysyl-pyridinoline-hydroxylysyl-pyridinoline ratio
HP:0034006.definition: A decreased amount of the urinary cross-links lysyl-pyridinoline (LP, or deoxypyridinoline DPD) as compared to hydroxylysyl-pyridinoline (HP, or pyridinoline PYD). Both are established biochemical markers of osteoclastic bone resorption and collagen degradation.

HP:0034007.name: Posterior atrophy of corpus callosum
HP:0034007.definition: The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the posterior portion of the corpus callosum.

HP:0034009.name: Pelvic lipomatosis
HP:0034009.definition: Overgrowth of fat in the perivesical and perirectal area.

HP:0034010.name: Increased megakaryocyte colony forming unit count
HP:0034010.definition: Increased numbers of megakryocyte precursors (megakaryocyte colony forming units) in the bone marrow.

HP:0034011.name: Reduced progressive sperm motility
HP:0034011.definition: A reduced proportion of sperm that move in a straight line or large circles; alternatively, an increased proportion of sperm that move in tight circles or in some other non-linear fashion.

HP:0034012.name: Palmoplantar hypohidrosis
HP:0034012.definition: Decreased sweating on the palms and soles.

HP:0034013.name: Curvilinear pericallosal lipoma
HP:0034013.definition: A type of pericallosal lipoma that is thin and curves around the posterior end of the splenium of the corpus callosum.

HP:0034014.name: Tubulonodular pericallosal lipoma
HP:0034014.definition: A type of pericallosal lipoma with a rounded or lobular appearance and a diameter that is usually above 2 cm. They are anteriorly situated and are associated with extensive callosal and often fronto-facial anomalies. A tubulonodular pericallosal lipoma can extend into the choroid plexus or lateral ventricles.

HP:0034015.name: Cavitating pulmonary nodule
