HP:5000026.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against neurexin-3alpha.

HP:5000027.name: Anti-P/Q-type VGCC antibody positivity
HP:5000027.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against P/Q-type voltage-gated calcium channels (VGCCs).

HP:5000028.name: Anti-MAP1B antibody
HP:5000028.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against microtubule-associated protein 1B (MAP1B).

HP:5000029.name: Anti-PKCgamma antibody
HP:5000029.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against protein kinase Cgamma.

HP:5000030.name: Anti-Ri antibody
HP:5000030.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Ri, an antineuronal antibody.

HP:5000031.name: Anti-Septin-5 antibody
HP:5000031.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Septin-5.

HP:5000032.name: Anti-SEZ6L2 antibody
HP:5000032.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against seizure-related 6 homolog like 2 (SEZ6L2).

HP:5000033.name: Anti-SOX1 antibody
HP:5000033.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against SOX1. Anti-SOX1 antibodies, also known as antiglial nuclear antibody (AGNA), are specifically found in paraneoplastic neurological disorders. Since SOX1 is expressed in neuronal precursor cells in the developing central nervous system, it has been used as an early marker of neural stem cells.

HP:5000034.name: Anti-Tr/DNER antibody
HP:5000034.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Tr/DNER. Anti-Tr antibodies are directed against cerebellar Purkinje cells (termed anti-Tr or PCA-Tr). Anti-Tr autoantibodies are frequently associated with Hodgkin lymphoma (HL). Anti-Tr antibodies are defined by a specific staining pattern in cerebellar tissue that is characterized by punctate immunoreactivity in both the dendritic tree and soma of Purkinje cells but not in their axons. This characteristic pattern is indicative of the presence of anti-Tr antibodies. The Delta/Notch-like epidermal growth factor-related receptor (DNER) was identified as the target antigen of anti-Tr.

HP:5000035.name: Anti-TRIM46 antibody
HP:5000035.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the axon initial segment protein tripartite motif 46 (TRIM46).

HP:5000036.name: Anti-TRIM9/TRIM67 antibody
HP:5000036.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against TRIM9/TRIM67.

HP:5000037.name: Anti-Yo antibody positivity
HP:5000037.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Yo.

HP:5000038.name: Anti-titin antibody positivity
HP:5000038.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against titin.

HP:5000039.name: Anti-Zic4 antibody positivity
HP:5000039.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Zic family member 4 (ZIC4).

HP:5000042.name: Anti-Sj/ITPR1 antibody
HP:5000042.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Sj/inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate receptor.

HP:5000043.name: Anti-D2 R antibody
HP:5000043.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against dopamine-2 receptor.

HP:5000044.name: Anti-GluK2 antibody
HP:5000044.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against glutamate kainate receptor subunit 2 (GluK2).

HP:5000046.name: Anti-Lrp4 antibody positivity
HP:5000046.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against low-density lipoprotein receptor (Lrp4).

HP:5000047.name: Anti-ryanodine receptor antibody
HP:5000047.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against ryanodine receptor.

HP:5000048.name: Anti-Kv1.4 antibody
HP:5000048.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.4.

HP:5200001.name: Selective mutism
HP:5200001.definition: Voluntary failure to use spoken language (at whatever level attained) in selective social contexts over a period of time.

HP:5200002.name: Limited repertoire of facial expression
HP:5200002.definition: An abnormally limited range of facial expressions demonstrated by a lack of nuance of facial expression to match specific social situations or an inability to demonstrate a normal range of emotions with one's face.

HP:5200003.name: Excessive interest in others
HP:5200003.definition: A strong desire to interact and engage with others that is perceived to be inappropriate or excessive in the context of cultural norms.

HP:5200004.name: obsolete Reduced response to another's attempt to get direct attention

HP:5200005.name: Abnormal pitch
HP:5200005.definition: Persistently abnormally high or low-pitched vocalization or speech than is considered the norm for the context of social situation or significantly different from baseline of the individual.

HP:5200006.name: Disjointed sentences
HP:5200006.definition: Persistent abnormalities in the sentence structure in speech, phrases may not be logically connected to each other, gives the impression of rambling. This may be a characteristic feature of the individual or may be a change from the norm of the affected individual.

HP:5200007.name: Neologism
HP:5200007.definition: Consistent use of an invented word that is unique to an individual.

HP:5200008.name: Overly formal/pedantic language
HP:5200008.definition: Use of language that is overly formal, precise, detailed, or pedantic for the social context.

HP:5200009.name: Midline hand movements
HP:5200009.definition: Hand stereotypies within the medial plane of the body.

HP:5200010.name: Abnormal Intonation
HP:5200010.definition: Abnormal rise and fall of the voice in speech and vocalization for the context and cultural situation.

HP:5200011.name: Abnormal speech rate
HP:5200011.definition: Speech that is abnormally fast or slow as compared to the perceived cultural norm.

HP:5200012.name: Abnormal speech rhythm
HP:5200012.definition: Speech with persistent abnormal rhythm or pattern for the context and cultural situation. This may occur constantly throughout conversations with the person or may occur in periodic bursts lasting several minutes to hours.

HP:5200013.name: Ambiguous facial expression
HP:5200013.definition: Spontaneous production of communicative facial expressions that have poor quality or are perceived as odd or mechanical. This may include inaccurate mimicry of typical facial expressions. These expressions may be difficult to interpret for someone who is not familiar with the individual making the expression.

HP:5200014.name: Exaggerated facial expression
HP:5200014.definition: A tendency to make facial expressions that are exaggerated and a failure to make subtle facial expressions in a social context when a subtle expression is more appropriate.

HP:5200015.name: Muted facial expression
HP:5200015.definition: A tendency to produce facial expressions with decreased intensity or expressivity which appear muted or flat.

HP:5200016.name: Abnormal peer relationships
HP:5200016.definition: The state of having abnormal relationships with others. This does not describe specific aspects of one's social aptitudes but rather a state which may come about from these aptitudes, such as lacking peer relationships or lacking close friends.

HP:5200017.name: Stereotypic movements of face and head
HP:5200017.definition: Abnormal movements of face and head.

HP:5200018.name: Stereotypic upper-extremity movements
HP:5200018.definition: Abnormal movements of the upper extremities.

HP:5200019.name: Stereotypic whole-body movements
HP:5200019.definition: Abnormal movements of the whole body.

HP:5200020.name: Abnormal interest in others
HP:5200020.definition: A social interest in others that is abnormal given the social context. This can include an increased interest with another person or an abnormal lack of interest in other people.

HP:5200021.name: Reduced social insight
HP:5200021.definition: A lack of awareness of social rules in multiple social settings, which are simple or intuitive to others in the same social setting.

HP:5200022.name: Reduced awareness of convention
HP:5200022.definition: Reduced awareness of expected conventions, which are normal and expected for particular social settings or interactions.

HP:5200024.name: Abnormal relationship
HP:5200024.definition: The state of having abnormal relationships with others. This does not describe specific aspects of one's social aptitudes but rather a state which may come about from these aptitudes, such as lacking peer relationships, lacking close friends, or having a relational network that is abnormal given one's cultural context.

HP:5200026.name: Impaired social imitation
HP:5200026.definition: Reduced use of imitation of tasks or movements of others in play or learning.

HP:5200027.name: Infrequent social initiations
HP:5200027.definition: Social initiation refers to the ability to begin interactions with other people. This term refers to a reduction in the frequency with which an individual attempts to begin interactions. The term should only be used for individuals who are assessed to have sufficient intellectual and language skills to interact with others.

HP:5200028.name: Reduced responsiveness to social cues
HP:5200028.definition: A tendency to display responces to social cues that are interpreted (e.g., by family members, peers, or caregivers) as diminished compared to what would be expected based on the developmental stage and cultural context of an individual.

HP:5200029.name: Social disinhibition
HP:5200029.definition: A tendency to violate social norms because of a failure to resist temptations or urges in social settings.

HP:5200030.name: Diminished integration of verbal and non-verbal communicative behavior
HP:5200030.definition: A communicative abnormality where one's nonverbal and verbal communication are poorly integrated. This may occur when verbal and nonverbal communication are intact alone but are abnormal when used together, or an abnormality in the use of typically integrated communication such as the use of beat gestures during speech.

HP:5200032.name: obsolete Reduced immediate imitation of others

HP:5200035.name: Reduced cooperative imaginative play
HP:5200035.definition: Failure of a child to engage with peers games that involve creating imaginary scenarios or narratives, for instance, in which children pretend to be characters or act out adventurous scenarios.

HP:5200036.name: obsolete Reduced responsiveness to verbal cues

HP:5200037.name: Lack of expressed empathy
HP:5200037.definition: This term refers to the observation that an affected person tends not to provide situationally appropriate responses to other people in times when these people are in emotional need. For instance, failure to provide comfort to a person who is sad or crying.

HP:5200038.name: Bradylalia
HP:5200038.definition: Speech that is abnormally slow as compared to the perceived cultural norm.

HP:5200039.name: Excessively loud speech
HP:5200039.definition: Speech which is persistently abnormally and noticeably loud or high volume for the social and cultural context and is not due to a structural or muscular abnormality. Those around the person often consider them to be shouting.

HP:5200040.name: Excessively quiet speech
HP:5200040.definition: Speech which is persistently abnormally quiet, or of low in volume for the social and cultural context. This includes persistent and inappropriate whispering. It is not due to a medical or surgical condition that results in hoarseness, nor structural or muscular abnormality that results in low speech volume.

HP:5200043.name: Abnormal speech volume
HP:5200043.definition: Speech that is abnormally loud or quiet for the social and cultural context in which it is spoken. It is clinically noted by others, including family, friends, or clinical providers.

HP:5200044.name: Reduced attention regulation
HP:5200044.definition: An abnormality in one's ability to control their attention towards a specific subject or task can include difficulties in changing or maintaining attention.

HP:5200045.name: Reduced impulse control
HP:5200045.definition: Reduced ability to control, or a failure to resist a temptation, urge, or impulse.

HP:5200046.name: Sensory behavioral abnormality
HP:5200046.definition: Abnormal sensory behavior, including avoiding or seeking sensory input or difficulty modulating sensory stimuli.

HP:5200047.name: Idiosyncratic gesture
HP:5200047.definition: When one uses gestures that are unique to them and have no apparent meaning to others.

HP:5200049.name: Atypical sorting
HP:5200049.definition: Atypical focus on arranging, balancing, or positioning objects; may be atypical in focus or intensity.

HP:5200050.name: Excessive checking
HP:5200050.definition: Checking behavior that is excessive for the situational context.

HP:5200051.name: Excessive hand washing
HP:5200051.definition: Hand washing behavior that is excessive for the situational context.

HP:5200052.name: Resistance to trivial environmental changes
HP:5200052.definition: Distress in response to minor changes in one's environmental expectations.

HP:5200053.name: obsolete Reduced nonverbal responsiveness to verbal cues

HP:5200054.name: obsolete Reduced verbal responsiveness to verbal cues

HP:5200055.name: Reduced co-speech gestures
HP:5200055.definition: Reduced use of speech-integrated gestures such as the use of beat gestures.

HP:5200056.name: Limited head nodding or shaking
HP:5200056.definition: Absence or reduction in the use of head nodding to indicate agreement or head shaking to indicate disagreement.

HP:5200057.name: Limited pointing
HP:5200057.definition: Absence or reduction in the use of pointing to request or direct another's attention.

HP:5200058.name: Sensory hypersensitivity
HP:5200058.definition: A decreased tolerance to sensory stimuli that triggers emotional and/or physical distress.

HP:5200059.name: Sensory hyposensitivity unexplained by sensory deficit
HP:5200059.definition: Increased tolerance to sensory stimuli due to diminished sensory ability.

HP:5200060.name: Auditory hypersensitivity
HP:5200060.definition: Hyperresponsive to sound that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200061.name: Tactile hypersensitivity
HP:5200061.definition: A decreased tolerance to physical touch.

HP:5200062.name: Auditory sensory seeking
HP:5200062.definition: Pursuit of specific sounds or noises that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200063.name: Gustatory sensory seeking
HP:5200063.definition: Pursuit of a particular taste that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200064.name: Olfactory sensory seeking
HP:5200064.definition: Pursuit of specific scents, smells, or fragrances that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200065.name: Tactile sensory seeking
HP:5200065.definition: Pursuit of a specific texture that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200066.name: Vestibular sensory seeking
HP:5200066.definition: Pursuit of vestibular stimulation that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200067.name: Visual sensory seeking
HP:5200067.definition: Pursuit visual stimulation by looking at specific sights, images, and/or colors that is abnormal in intensity and/or frequency.

HP:5200068.name: Socially inappropriate questioning
HP:5200068.definition: A tendency to ask questions that are overly personal or otherwise inappropriate in the social situation in which they are asked.

HP:5200069.name: Spinning
HP:5200069.definition: An excessive frequency of spinning one's body.

HP:5200071.name: Delayed Echolalia
HP:5200071.definition: Repetition of borrowed words or phrases outside of the context in which they were originally heard. E.g., scripting from TV shows or movies.

HP:5200072.name: Immediate Echolalia
HP:5200072.definition: Immediate repetition of another person's speech.

HP:5200073.name: Excessive cleaning
HP:5200073.definition: Excessive cleaning of surfaces, living space, or environment that is excessive for the situational context.

HP:5200100.name: Facial expressions not directed to others

HP:5200102.name: Reduced social smiling
HP:5200102.definition: Reduced production of smiles during engagement with an interactive parent, caregiver, or peer.

HP:5200104.name: Abnormal play
HP:5200104.definition: An abnormality in a child's ability play.

HP:5200105.name: Reduced imaginative play skills
HP:5200105.definition: Reduced or lack of pretending in play (does not assign abstract properties to objects, use invisible objects, or use objects in nonliteral ways other than their intended purpose in play).

HP:5200108.name: Nonfunctional or atypical use of objects in play
HP:5200108.definition: Use of objects in atypical, unimaginitive ways other than for which they are intended (banging, throwing, shaking, sorting, lining up, spinning).

HP:5200110.name: Infrequent social engagement with peers
HP:5200110.definition: Social engagement refers to the interaction of an individual with others in a contextually appropriate manner. This term refers to a lower than typical number of attempts to engage peers in conversation, play, or other interactions.

HP:5200111.name: Avoidance of emotional intimacy
HP:5200111.definition: An atypically high tendency to avoid interpersonal exchanges characterizing by sharing of personal feelings, expressions of understanding, affirmation, and demonstrations of caring.

HP:5200113.name: Failure to offer information to initiate social interaction
HP:5200113.definition: An atypically low tendency to offer information as a means to initiate or sustain social interactions or direct another's attention.

HP:5200116.name: Difficulty understanding nonliteral meaning of conversation

HP:5200118.name: Difficulty recognizing another's emotions
HP:5200118.definition: A difficulty in being able to understand the emotions of other people. This can range from recognizing emotions from facial expressions to an inability to empathize with others when they describe their feelings

HP:5200120.name: Abnormal social emotional interactions
HP:5200120.definition: Social emotional interactions refer to the exchange of feelings during social interactions by means of a wide range of communicative behaviors including facial expressions, body language, and verbal communication. This term refers to an atypically low production of emotion social communication by an individual.

HP:5200121.name: Objectification of others
HP:5200121.definition: A tendency to interact with others as if they are objects with functional purpose rather than engaging in social/emotional interactions.

HP:5200124.name: Indifference to social norms
HP:5200124.definition: Failure to follow social norms (shared standards of acceptable behavior) even though one has awareness of these norms and the ability to follow them. This is characterized by an indifference to the consequences of breaking social norms.

HP:5200125.name: Aggression towards others
HP:5200125.definition: Aggression that is directed towards other individuals, as opposed to oneself.

HP:5200126.name: Aggression towards caregivers
HP:5200126.definition: Aggression that is directed towards caregivers.

HP:5200127.name: Aggression toward non-caregivers
HP:5200127.definition: Aggression that is directed towards non-caregivers.

HP:5200128.name: obsolete Deficit applying language skills across context

HP:5200129.name: Abnormal rituals
HP:5200129.definition: Insistence on rituals which are self-imposed on a person's environment including directing the behavior of those around them.

HP:5200131.name: obsolete Reduced use of language for social purposes

HP:5200134.name: Jumping
HP:5200134.definition: An excessive frequency of jumping in place.

HP:5200135.name: Delay in the acquisition of cooperative play skills
HP:5200135.definition: Failure to acquire the ability to play cooperatively, a type of play in whichchildren work together towards a common goal and in which a child displays interest both in the play and in the the other child or children involved in playing. This ability is observed in neurotypical children from the age of 3 to 6 years.

HP:5200136.name: Reduced social reciprocity with peers
HP:5200136.definition: Reduced back and forth interactions with others compared to what would be expected for the developmental level.

HP:5200137.name: obsolete Infrequent social engagement with peers

HP:5200200.name: Olfactory hallucination
HP:5200200.definition: Perception of smell without olfactory stimulus.

HP:5200201.name: Gustatory hallucination
HP:5200201.definition: Perception of taste without gustatory stimulus.

HP:5200202.name: Abnormal interpretation of external stimuli
HP:5200202.definition: Abnormal perception of reality is characterized by an abnormal or inaccurate experience of external stimuli.

HP:5200203.name: Proprioceptive hallucination
HP:5200203.definition: A type of hallucination that involves the perception of distorted or abnormal sensations related to one's body position or movement.

HP:5200204.name: Disturbed perception with a stimulus
HP:5200204.definition: A perceptual experience in which an individual's perception of sensory stimuli is altered or disrupted in some way, resulting in abnormal or distorted sensory perceptions despite the presence of actual external stimuli.

HP:5200205.name: Illusions
HP:5200205.definition: Perceptual experiences that involve misinterpretations or distortions of sensory stimuli.

HP:5200207.name: Inattentiveness illusion
HP:5200207.definition: Instances in which individuals fail to perceive or notice salient or significant stimuli in their visual field due to a lack of attention.

HP:5200208.name: Illusions due to affect
HP:5200208.definition: Perceptual distortions or misinterpretations of sensory information arise as a result of the individual's emotional or affective state.

HP:5200209.name: Pareidolia
HP:5200209.definition: Apophenia is a psychological phenomenon in which individuals perceive familiar patterns or meaningful images in random or ambiguous stimuli, such as clouds, shadows, or inanimate objects.

HP:5200210.name: Autoscopy
HP:5200210.definition: A phenomenon in which an individual perceives themselves from an external perspective, as if they are observing their own body or self from a location outside of their physical body.

HP:5200211.name: Subjective eidetic images
HP:5200211.definition: A mental phenomenon is when an individual can vividly visualize or recall visual information from memory with exceptional detail and accuracy. These images are experienced subjectively by the individual, meaning they are not physically present or visible to others.

HP:5200212.name: Amplification of social interactions
HP:5200212.definition: A increase in the tendency of a person to seek or maintain social connections or interactions with others compared to previous norms for an individual.

HP:5200213.name: Diminishment of emotional responsiveness
HP:5200213.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to display emotional responsiveness or empathy towards others during interpersonal interactions as compared to that person's previous norm.

HP:5200214.name: Somatic hallucination
HP:5200214.definition: A type of hallucination that involves the perception of sensory experiences related to the body or its internal organs, systems, or processes. It is a hallucinatory experience that primarily affects bodily sensations rather than external sensory perceptions.

HP:5200215.name: Visceral hallucination
HP:5200215.definition: A type of hallucination that involves the perception of internal bodily sensations or processes that do not actually exist.

HP:5200216.name: Abnormal perceptual state
HP:5200216.definition: Temporary alteration of the awareness of reality or self-perception.

HP:5200217.name: Depersonalization
HP:5200217.definition: A psychological experience or symptom characterized by a sense of detachment or estrangement from oneself or one's surroundings.

HP:5200218.name: Derealization
HP:5200218.definition: A subjective experience in which an individual feels a sense of detachment or estrangement from their surroundings, leading to a distorted perception of the external world. It is characterized by a feeling of unreality or unfamiliarity with one's environment, as if things are dreamlike, artificial, or lacking in significance.

HP:5200220.name: Decreased facial expression mirroring
HP:5200220.definition: Diminished mirroring or reflection of facial expressions in another person during social interactions.

HP:5200221.name: Diminishment of comfort with casual physical contact
HP:5200221.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to accept casual physical contact with others as compared to that person's previous norm.

HP:5200227.name: Thought blocking
HP:5200227.definition: The experience of sudden cessation of the thought/thinking process, the person often describes the mind going blank and there is frequently a period of silence that is accompanied by a perplexed state, not understanding what transpired. Some may describe the experience as an abrupt emptying of the mind or the belief that an external force removed their thoughts from their head.

HP:5200230.name: Maladaptive fear-related cognitions
HP:5200230.definition: Threat-based cognitive biases result in a skewed perception, experience, or processing of internal or external stimuli.

HP:5200231.name: Hypervigilance
HP:5200231.definition: A heightened alertness is characterized by a broad awareness and/or excessive scanning of environmental stimuli.

HP:5200232.name: Phobia
HP:5200232.definition: Extreme, irrational, and persistent fears of certain objects, situations, activities, or persons can impede functioning in day-to-day life.

HP:5200233.name: Anticipatory anxiety
HP:5200233.definition: A state characterized by future-oriented worry, accompanied by negative affect and autonomic arousal.

HP:5200234.name: Flight of ideas
HP:5200234.definition: Successive thoughts and speech are easily diverted by external stimuli or internal superficial associations. Unable to maintain a constant train of thought and lose themselves in side issues, losing the thread and are unable to recover it. Superficial connections appear to drive the subject matter.

HP:5200241.name: Recurrent maladaptive behavior
HP:5200241.definition: A repeating behavior that is either immediately unproductive or has negative long-term consequences. This includes harmful coping mechanisms such as addictive behavior and failure to control impulses and compulsions.

HP:5200242.name: Cognitive distortion
HP:5200242.definition: A cognitive distortion is a maladaptive, exaggerated, or irrational thought pattern.

HP:5200243.name: Abnormal change in social behavior
HP:5200243.definition: An alternation in the habits and emotional tendencies of an individual with a change in behavior that is typically noticed by family members or peers.

HP:5200261.name: Abnormal demeanor
HP:5200261.definition: An anomaly in demeanor, which refers to the outward behavior, manner, or conduct of a person. It encompasses how an individual presents themselves to others in terms of attitude, posture, and general comportment.

HP:5200263.name: Abnormally increased volition
HP:5200263.definition: An excessive increase in motivated and goal directed as well as non-goal directed behaviors that are usually accompanied by elevated energy and interest that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action. The increase is often disruptive and typically results in unfavorable consequences.

HP:5200265.name: Pressured speech
HP:5200265.definition: Speech pattern that is excessive and intense that often imparts a sense of urgency, the individual appears to be driven to communicate with many words that are spoken very quickly and may run into each other. The person is frequently difficult to interrupt and appears to not respond to social cues for the conversational partner(s) to take their turn in speaking.

HP:5200267.name: Leaden paralysis
HP:5200267.definition: The sensation of having heavy arms and legs, or feeling a heaviness in the limbs.

HP:5200270.name: Grandiosity
HP:5200270.definition: Persistently exaggerated feelings and thoughts of an inflated sense of self-importance, superiority, uniqueness, or invulnerability. The affected individual may project arrogance with a dismissive behavioral pattern towards others the individual deems inferior.

HP:5200271.name: Hopelessness
HP:5200271.definition: Persistent and excessive feelings of despair with an overwhelming lack of hope. While hopelessness is primarily a personal experience, the sense of hopelessness becomes pervasive and affects most aspects of the personal experience in relation to the world. For example the person may communicate a sense of hopelessness for family and friends (who themselves do not experience hopelessness), as well as the world in general.

HP:5200273.name: Abnormal sadness
HP:5200273.definition: Experience of intense or excessively negative feelings that may include profound unhappiness, feeling low, down, or sorrowful and are beyond cultural or societal norms. Commonly associated with a low self-attitude and grim outlook.

HP:5200276.name: Decreased need for sleep
HP:5200276.definition: There has been a noticeable decrease in the need for sleep, where individuals feel refreshed even with minimal or no sleep.

HP:5200283.name: Sleep-related breathing disorders
HP:5200283.definition: Conditions of abnormal and difficult respiration during sleep, including chronic snoring and sleep apnea.

HP:5200284.name: Bruxism during sleep
HP:5200284.definition: Bruxism is a condition in which you grind, gnash, or clench your teeth while asleep.

HP:5200287.name: Nightmare disorder
HP:5200287.definition: Nightmare disorder is defined by the repeated occurrence of nightmares that cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational or other important areas of functioning, which are not attributable to the physiological effects of a substance (e.g. drug abuse or medication) and which cannot be adequately explained by coexisting mental and medical disorders.

HP:5200288.name: Sleep-related eating disorder
HP:5200288.definition: Eating while asleep can be problematic, as it may involve potentially harmful behaviors like overeating or consuming raw meat.

HP:5200289.name: Microsleep
HP:5200289.definition: Sudden onset of extreme drowsiness or falling asleep during the day for a short period of time.

HP:5200290.name: Exploding head syndrome
HP:5200290.definition: Sleep disorder in which one hears a loud noise or explosive crashing sound in their head. The sound is not real or heard by anyone else. The episode typically happens suddenly, either when beginning to fall asleep or when waking up during the night.

HP:5200291.name: REM sleep behavior disorder
HP:5200291.definition: REM Sleep Behavior Disorder (RBD) is a chronic sleep condition characterized by dream enactment and loss of REM atonia.

HP:5200292.name: Non-restorative sleep
HP:5200292.definition: Perception of feeling unrefreshed after sleep.

HP:5200293.name: Disturbance during transitions between sleep and wake states
HP:5200293.definition: A group of parasomnias that occur during the transition from wakefulness to sleep or from one sleep stage to another. Rhythmic Movement Disorder, Sleep Starts, Sleep Talking, and Nocturnal Leg Cramps - these four disorders belong to Sleep-Wake Transition Disorders in the International Classification of Sleep Disorders.

HP:5200294.name: Sexsomnia
HP:5200294.definition: Unintentional sexual behavior during sleep, such as masturbation, initiation of sex, or making sexual noises, is known as sexsomnia. Sexsomnia predominantly occurs during NREM sleep.

HP:5200295.name: Periodic limb movements
HP:5200295.definition: Repetitive limb movements during sleep can affect the quality of your sleep.

HP:5200296.name: Abnormal hypnagogia
HP:5200296.definition: Abnormal transition of consciousness from wakefulness to sleep.

HP:5200297.name: Abnormal hypnopompia
HP:5200297.definition: Abnormal transition of consciousness from sleeping to wakefulness.

HP:5200298.name: Abnormal sleep architecture
HP:5200298.definition: Interruptions during the various stages of sleep.

HP:5200300.name: Abnormal movement during sleep
HP:5200300.definition: Periodic Limb Movement Disorder, also known as Sleep-Related Myoclonus Syndrome or Nocturnal Myoclonus Syndrome, refers to the periodic and stereotypic movements of the legs or upper limbs during sleep.

HP:5200304.name: Short N1 sleep
HP:5200304.definition: Decreased duration of phase N1 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200305.name: Paradoxical insomnia
HP:5200305.definition: Paradoxical insomnia is a condition in which individuals with a normal or near-normal sleep macrostructure tend to severely underestimate the quantity and quality of their sleep.

HP:5200307.name: Short N2 sleep
HP:5200307.definition: Decreased duration of phase N2 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200309.name: Short N3 sleep
HP:5200309.definition: Decreased duration of phase N3 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200310.name: Diminishment of social interactions
HP:5200310.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to seek or maintain social connections or interactions with others compared to previous norms for an individual.

HP:5200311.name: Amplification of interpersonal communication
HP:5200311.definition: An increase in the tendency of a person to share information or emotions compared to that person's previous norms.

HP:5200315.name: Amplification of relationship seeking
HP:5200315.definition: Increased frequency or duration in social outings and interactions as part of relationship-seeking or maintenance compared to the previous norms of an individual. May be considered to be overfamiliar and have a tendency to engage strangers in a presumptive manner.

HP:5200316.name: Diminishment of interpersonal communication
HP:5200316.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to share information or emotions compared to that person's previous norms.

HP:5200320.name: Diminishment of relationship seeking
HP:5200320.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to seek new interpersonal relationships or maintain existing relationships.

HP:5200321.name: Amplification of sexual behavior
HP:5200321.definition: An abnormal increase of libido (sexual desire), typically accompanied by a higher frequency of sexual activity compared to from a person's previous norm.

HP:5200322.name: Amplification of emotional expression
HP:5200322.definition: An increase in the tendency of a person to express emotions compared to that person's previous norm.

HP:5200323.name: Amplification of emotional responsiveness
HP:5200323.definition: An increase in the tendency of a person to display emotional responsiveness or emotional empathy towards others during interpersonal interactions as compared to that person's previous norm. May be considered to be overreactive or over-engaged with interpersonal situations that may take on a persistent preoccupation and would appear to be relatively unrelated to the person, and beyond the expression of normal empathy.

HP:5200325.name: Amplification of comfort with casual physical contact
HP:5200325.definition: An increase in the tendency of a person to be comfortable with physical contact with others compared to that person's previous norm. Often considered to be intrusive and encroaching on personal space of others less known to the person, frequently causing discomfort and may result in argument or altercation.

HP:5200327.name: Diminishment of sexual behavior
HP:5200327.definition: A reduction of libido (sexual desire), typically accompanied by a reduction in the frequency of sexual activity , and/or activity compared to the affected individual's previous state.

HP:5200328.name: Diminishment of emotional expression
HP:5200328.definition: A reduction in the tendency of a person to express emotions that is typically noticed as a change in behavior by family members or peers.

HP:5200329.name: Problematic alcohol consumption
HP:5200329.definition: Impaired ability to stop or control alcohol use despite adverse social, occupational, or health consequences.

HP:5200331.name: Addictive sedative use
HP:5200331.definition: Misuse and/or abuse of sedative drugs.

HP:5200332.name: Addictive non-substance behaviors
HP:5200332.definition: Uncontrolled use or problematic behaviors of dependency without the use of drugs or substances can be detrimental.

HP:5200333.name: Addictive spending behavior
HP:5200333.definition: An uncontrollable urge to shop and spend money can lead to distress or impairment.

HP:5200334.name: Addictive gambling behavior
HP:5200334.definition: The act of taking chances or engaging in behaviors without restraint, typically involving the wagering of something valuable, in pursuit of acquiring something of higher value.

HP:5200335.name: Addictive sex behavior
HP:5200335.definition: Inability to control or manage sexual urges, fantasies, or behaviors that impair one's ability to function.

HP:5200336.name: Addictive video game use
HP:5200336.definition: The inability to regulate persistent gaming behavior is characterized by a heightened prioritization of gaming activities over regular daily tasks and responsibilities.

HP:5200337.name: Compulsive stealing
HP:5200337.definition: Irresistible impulses to take easily affordable items.

HP:5200338.name: Excessive fire setting
HP:5200338.definition: The inability to control urges of deliberately setting fires for pleasure and gratification, without any criminal intent.

HP:5200339.name: Self-cutting
HP:5200339.definition: Deliberate harm to one's body, in the form of cutting that results in tissue damage, without a conscious intent to die.

HP:5200341.name: Addictive cannabis use
HP:5200341.definition: A persistent and compulsive need to use cannabis, despite negative consequences.

HP:5200342.name: Autophagia
HP:5200342.definition: The habitual action of inflicting pain upon oneself by biting and/or devouring portions of one's body.

HP:5200352.name: Hypnagogic sleep paralysis
HP:5200352.definition: Sleep paralysis that occurs when falling asleep.

HP:5200353.name: Hypnopompic sleep paralysis
HP:5200353.definition: Sleep paralysis that occurs when waking up from sleep.

HP:5200356.name: Sleep onset rapid eye movement period
HP:5200356.definition: Entering REM sleep immediately upon falling asleep.

HP:5200357.name: Prolonged N1 sleep
HP:5200357.definition: Increased duration of phase N1 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200358.name: Prolonged N2 sleep
HP:5200358.definition: Increased duration of phase N2 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200359.name: Prolonged N3 sleep
HP:5200359.definition: Increased duration of phase N3 of nonrapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.

HP:5200401.name: Abnormal judgment
HP:5200401.definition: Beliefs that deviate from what is considered rational or within the range of normal human judgment and belief formation.

HP:5200402.name: Overvalued idea
HP:5200402.definition: A solitary belief that may be held by others in the society that is maintained by the person to an abnormal and morbid degree and overtly drives behaviors that are considered unhealthy, intrusive, or illegal. This includes fads and cults that the person may adhere to and practice to a morbid degree. The content may vary and ranges from religion, health, romance, or politics.

HP:5200403.name: Time agnosia
HP:5200403.definition: The inability to perceive the passage of time is usually due to a disorder involving the temporal area of the brain.

HP:5200405.name: Olfactory agnosia
HP:5200405.definition: The inability to recognize certain smells or types of odors that you previously recognized.

HP:5200406.name: Tactile agnosia
HP:5200406.definition: The inability to recognize objects by touch is called tactile agnosia.

HP:5200407.name: Topographical agnosia
HP:5200407.definition: The inability to rely on visual cues to guide one's direction is due to the inability to recognize objects.

HP:5200409.name: Delusional memory
HP:5200409.definition: Delusional memory is a memory that is false or fantastically distorted, but held with firm and irrefutable conviction despite evidence to the contrary. It is often seen in psychiatric conditions such as delusional disorders, schizophrenia, and sometimes in severe mood disorders. These memories can be completely fabricated or have a basis in an actual event that has been grossly misinterpreted or altered by the individual's mind.

HP:5200410.name: Auditory agnosia
HP:5200410.definition: The condition is characterized by the inability to recognize spoken languages and/or nonverbal environmental sounds and music, despite having adequate hearing. However, spontaneous speech, reading, and writing abilities remain intact.

HP:5200411.name: Gustatory agnosia
HP:5200411.definition: People cannot identify tastes, even though they can experience them.

HP:5200412.name: Allesthesia
HP:5200412.definition: Referral of a sensory stimulus from one side of the body to the other.

HP:5200413.name: Autotopagnosia
HP:5200413.definition: The loss of the ability to localize, recognize, or identify specific parts of one's body.

HP:5200415.name: Persecutory delusion
HP:5200415.definition: False beliefs (or judgements) that are held with extraordinary conviction and subjective certainty that are impervious to other experiences or counterarguments and the content is generally considered impossible for the context and circumstance. Delusional beliefs may arise meaningfully from personal or social experiences, yet are impossible, held with conviction, and irrefutable; more commonly they may be psychologically irreducible, appearing with no logical or meaningful connection to the individual experience.

HP:5200416.name: Morbid jealousy
HP:5200416.definition: A disorder of delusional content wherein the affected individual believes they are a victim of their partner's infidelity. It is often based on delusional evidence of an erotic or romantic nature. There may be an affective (mood related) component or may be associated with substance use disorders. It may also occur on its own. There may be associated behaviors to monitor or gather evidence of the perceived infidelity.

HP:5200417.name: Grandiose delusion
HP:5200417.definition: Delusional beliefs of a fantastical, expansive, or supernatural quality related to power, ability, wealth, or station. They are often related to origin (aristocratic lineage, royal birth, being raised as a foster child), possessions (owning vast estates, castles, etc., which are withheld through intrigue), abilities (being great inventors, discoverers, artists, possessors of special wisdom, gifted with inspiration), and status (adviser to prominent diplomats, the true director of political destinies). Grandiose delusions may be related to affective states, substance use, or may occur independently.

HP:5200418.name: Folie à deux
HP:5200418.definition: Delusional beliefs are transmitted from one individual to another.

HP:5200419.name: Disorder of thought control
HP:5200419.definition: A false belief that another person, group of people, or external force controls one's general thoughts, feelings, impulses, or behaviors.

HP:5200420.name: Delusion of love
HP:5200420.definition: A delusional belief that the person is secretly loved by another individual who is often of recognized fame or authoratative significance. There is typically no overt evidence and the delusional belief may be driven by falsely perceived indicators. Often there is a blend of erotic delusions and morbid infatuation.

HP:5200421.name: Nihilistic delusion
HP:5200421.definition: A delusion that elements of the self, body, or world no longer exist. The person typically recognizes that the entity did in fact exist at one time, but has ceased to exist. The cause of which may be related to disease, decay, or may have been removed or taken by unknown forces.

HP:5200422.name: Cotard delusion
HP:5200422.definition: A false belief that you or your body parts are dead, dying, or do not exist.

HP:5200423.name: Abnormal experience of reality
HP:5200423.definition: Subjective phenomena or perceptions that deviate from what is considered correct or are outside the range of normal human experiences.

HP:5200424.name: Delusional perception
HP:5200424.definition: A true perception, to which a patient attributes a false and usually bizarre meaning or interpretation. It is often a revelatory experience that is sudden and is a profound realization of the delusional belief. It often occurs in the context of delusional mood or atmosphere wherein vague and mysterious hunches or concerns with nebulous meaning evolve into clear, delusional observations, and expresses delusions of reference.

HP:5200425.name: Hypochondriac delusion
HP:5200425.definition: Delusion quality to belief that one is suffering from an illness despite reassurances based on medical examination and testing. The person may (or not) express pain or discomfort that they attribute to the disease. They are frequently treatment seeking, but do not induce illness features (which is termed Munchhausen syndrome).

HP:5200426.name: Delusions of infestation
HP:5200426.definition: A persistent belief that a person is infested with living or non-living pathogens, such as parasites, insects, or bugs, when no such infestation is present.

HP:5200427.name: Delusional atmosphere
HP:5200427.definition: A persistent sense or a hunch that something is different in an imperceptible manner. Typically the perception is one of a sinister, portentous , uncanny, mysterious, or peculiar sense of foreboding in an indefinable way. There is an innate sense of inexplicable self-relevance to the person. There is often a feeling of anticipation, sometimes even excitement, that soon the mystery may be revealed and all the separate parts of their experience will fit together to reveal something immensely significant. The duration of this experience may vary, lasting from hours to days. It may be intermittent over an extended period of time (months to years).

HP:5200428.name: Delusional misidentification
HP:5200428.definition: A group of complex, monothematic delusional phenomena in which subjects hold a belief that the identity of a familiar person, object, location, or self has been altered or replaced. The majority of misidentifications are spouses or first degree relatives, i.e. someone well-known to the person.

HP:5200429.name: Religious delusion
HP:5200429.definition: Delusions with a religious content that are considered delusional in nature based on how the belief is held and the evidence offered to support it, which is generally considered impossible or fantastical in the cultural setting of the person. It differs from unusual beliefs that are held with tenacity or conviction and are typically associated with other phenomena consistent with mental illness.

HP:5200430.name: Abnormal psychotic pattern
HP:5200430.definition: Any abnormal pattern of psychotic experiences, where an individual has significant disturbances in their thoughts, perceptions, emotions, and behavior, resulting in a loss of touch with reality.

HP:5201000.name: Incomplete unilateral cleft lip
HP:5201000.definition: Unilateral cleft lip cleft that starts from the bottom of the upper lip but does not reach the nasal cavity.

HP:5201001.name: Complete unilateral cleft lip
HP:5201001.definition: Unilateral cleft lip cleft that starts from the bottom of the upper lip and reaches the nasal cavity.

HP:5201002.name: Microform unilateral cleft lip
HP:5201002.definition: Notch, groove, or scar of the upper lip without noticeable rupture of the lip. Microforms are sometimes associated with disruption of the continuity of the orbicularis oris muscle.

HP:5201003.name: Complete cleft hard palate
HP:5201003.definition: Cleft hard palate in which the cleft goes through the entire length of the hard palate, ie. from the incisor foramen to the anterior border of the soft palate.

HP:5201004.name: Incomplete cleft hard palate
HP:5201004.definition: Cleft hard palate in which the cleft does not go through the entire length of the hard palate, ie. the cleft does not go from the incisor foramen to the anterior border of the soft palate.

HP:5201005.name: Complete cleft soft palate
HP:5201005.definition: Cleft soft palate in which the cleft goes through the entire length of the soft palate, i.e. from the posterior border of the hard palate until the uvula.

HP:5201006.name: Incomplete cleft soft palate
HP:5201006.definition: Cleft soft palate in which the cleft does not go through the entire length of the soft palate, i.e. the cleft does not go from the posterior border of the hard palate until the uvula.

HP:5201007.name: Incomplete cleft maxillary alveolar ridge
HP:5201007.definition: Cleft maxillary alveolar ridge in which the cleft does not go through the entire length of the maxillary alveolar ridge.

HP:5201008.name: Complete cleft maxillary alveolar ridge
HP:5201008.definition: Cleft maxillary alveolar ridge in which the cleft goes through the entire length of the maxillary alveolar ridge.

HP:5201009.name: Complete cleft of the upper lip
HP:5201009.definition: Cleft of the upper lip that starts from the bottom of the upper lip and reaches the nasal cavity.

HP:5201010.name: Microform cleft of the upper lip
HP:5201010.definition: Notch, groove, or scar of the upper lip without noticeable rupture of the lip.

HP:5201011.name: Complete bilateral cleft lip
HP:5201011.definition: Bilateral cleft lip in which the cleft lip on both sides is complete, i.e. start from the bottom of the upper lip and reach the nasal cavity.

HP:5201012.name: Incomplete bilateral cleft lip
HP:5201012.definition: Bilateral cleft lip in which the cleft lip on both sides are incomplete (i.e. start from the bottom of the upper lip but do not reach the nasal cavity), or the cleft lip on one is incomplete and a microform on the other side.

HP:5201013.name: Microform bilateral cleft lip
HP:5201013.definition: Bilateral cleft lip in which the cleft lip on both sides are microform, i.e. a notch, groove, or scar without noticeable rupture of the lip.

HP:5201014.name: Asymmetric bilateral cleft lip
HP:5201014.definition: Bilateral cleft lip in which the cleft lip on one side is complete (i.e. starts from the bottom of the upper lip and reaches the nasal cavity), and the one on the other side is incomplete (i.e. starts from the bottom of the upper lip but does not reach the nasal cavity) or microform (i.e. a notch, groove, or scar without noticeable rupture of the lip).

HP:5201015.name: Craniofacial cleft
HP:5201015.definition: Congenital abnormality with cleft (gap or opening) in the craniofacial bones. Craniofacial cleft includes facial cleft, orofacial clef, and cleft of the jaw.

HP:5201016.name: Submucous cleft palate
HP:5201016.definition: A cleft of the muscular portion of the palate that is covered by mucous membrane.

HP:6000000.name: Left-right disorientation
HP:6000000.definition: A tendency to mix up left and right in one's own body space, typically elicited by asking a person to perform a two-stage command involving specified lateralized anatomy.

HP:6000001.name: Elevated circulating DNAJB9 protein concentration
HP:6000001.definition: Concentration of DnaJ homolog subfamily B member 9 (DNAJB9) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000002.name: Olecranon fracture
HP:6000002.definition: A partial or complete break in the olecranon,which is the proximal articular portion of the ulna and makes up part of the elbow.

HP:6000003.name: History of mastectomy
HP:6000003.definition: Past medical history of surgical breast removal.

HP:6000004.name: Lymphangiosarcoma
HP:6000004.definition: A malignant neoplasm arising from the endothelial cells of the lymphatic vessels.

HP:6000005.name: Exposure to inhaled lipids
HP:6000005.definition: Aspiration or inhalation of lipid-containing products.

HP:6000006.name: Holster sign
HP:6000006.definition: Symmetric poikiloderma of hips and lateral thighs below the greater trochanter.

HP:6000007.name: Salivary basal cell adenoma
HP:6000007.definition: A rare neoplasm consisting of a monomorphic population of basaloid epithelial cells, and it accounts for approximately 1-2% of all salivary gland tumors.

HP:6000008.name: Hemidiaphragm elevation
HP:6000008.definition: Elevated Hemidiaphragm is a condition where one portion of the diaphragm is higher than the other. Elevated hemidiaphragm occurs when one side of the diaphragm becomes weak from muscular disease or loss of innervation due to phrenic nerve injury.

HP:6000009.name: Cerebriform connective tissue nevus
HP:6000009.definition: The cerebriform connective tissue nevus (CCTN) is one of the most characteristic skin findings. It commonly occurs on the soles of the feet, and frequently causes problems because of pain, pruritus, infection, bleeding,exudation, odor, and walking impairment.

HP:6000010.name: Linear Hyperpigmentation along Blaschko's lines
HP:6000010.definition: Linear streaks and swirls of macular hyperpigmentation along the lines of Blaschko.

HP:6000011.name: Excessive guilt
HP:6000011.definition: Excessive guilt is an internal feeling that is intense and considered clinically to be beyond normal range, out of proportion for the act or offense; excessive guilt is typically based on an incorrect judgment of responsibility for an unfavorable outcome. Excessive guilt is typically pervasive and enduring, i.e. it is not fleeting or a temporary thought associated with a specific action.

HP:6000012.name: Mediastinal shift
HP:6000012.definition: A deviation of the mediastinum from its normal position in the midline of the thoracic cavity. The mediastinum is a compartment of the thoracic cavity that contains the heart and its blood vessels, the esophagus, trachea, thymus, as well as nerves and lymph nodes.

HP:6000013.name: Bendopnea
HP:6000013.definition: Dyspnea as a result of bending forward while not holding one's breath; dyspnea or shortness of breath onset within 30 seconds of bending forward.

HP:6000014.name: Pain worse when lying flat
HP:6000014.definition: Refers to pain that is worse when the affected individual lies down (flat).

HP:6000015.name: Tympanic membrane hypermobility
HP:6000015.definition: Abnormally increased ability to move of the tympanic membrane.

HP:6000016.name: Elevated circulating vitamin B12 concentration
HP:6000016.definition: Concentration of vitamin B12 in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000017.name: Elevated circulating soluble FASL concentration
HP:6000017.definition: The concentration of soluble FASL in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. The first apoptosis signal receptor (FAS) pathway regulates apoptosis and is critical for proper development and functioning of the immune system. FAS ligand (FASL) can bind to FAS receptors.

HP:6000018.name: Internal anal sphincter achalasia
HP:6000018.definition: A disorder of the internal anal sphincter (IAS) in which the IAS fails to relax that manifests clinically as intractable constipation.

HP:6000019.name: Anthracycline exposure
HP:6000019.definition: History of treatment with an anthracycline chemotherapy agent.

HP:6000020.name: Binge drinking
HP:6000020.definition: A pattern of episodic heavy alcohol use characterized by the consumption of a high number of drinks per occasion.

HP:6000021.name: Decreased circulating thrombopoietin concentration
HP:6000021.definition: Concentration of thrombopoietin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. Thrombopoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the liver and kidney that stimulates the production and differentiation of megakaryocytes.

HP:6000022.name: Collagenoma
HP:6000022.definition: A rare hamartomatous malformation characterized by the predominant proliferation of normal collagen fibers and normal, decreased, or increased elastic fibers. Collagenomas may be solitary or multiple, sporadic, acquired or inherited.

HP:6000023.name: Lack of sufficient daily physical activity
HP:6000023.definition: Physical activity levels less than those required for optimal health and prevention of premature death.

HP:6000024.name: Synesthesia
HP:6000024.definition: A phenomenon whereby stimulation of one sensory or cognitive pathway leads to automatic, involuntary experiences in a second sensory or cognitive pathway. For instance, people with synaesthesia may experience unusual colors, tastes, and other sensations when engaged in everyday activities like reading or listening to music.

HP:6000025.name: Dark cerumen
HP:6000025.definition: Abnormally dark color of cerumen (earwax), which is a waxy substance secreted in the ear canal that normally has a brown, orange, red, yellowish or gray.

HP:6000026.name: History of spicy food intake
HP:6000026.definition: A history of high intake of spciy foods with ingrediaents such as capsaicin, pepper, chili, ginger, garlic, onion, fenugreek, and turmeric.

HP:6000027.name: Oil-drop brown pigmentation of the corneal limbus
HP:6000027.definition: Brown pigment spots in the limbus (border between the cornea and the sclera).

HP:6000028.name: Hazardous alcohol use
HP:6000028.definition: Hazardous drinking is defined as a quantity or pattern of alcohol consumption that places individuals at risk for adverse health events. This could include alcohol use despite potentially hazardous or risky consequences, such as operating heavy machinery or drunk driving.

HP:6000029.name: Social anxiety
HP:6000029.definition: Excessive fear of embarrassment, humiliation, or rejection when exposed to possible negative evaluation by others when engaged in a public performance or social interaction.

HP:6000030.name: Placidity
HP:6000030.definition: Flat affect and reduced response to emotional stimuli. Fear and anger responses that are normally present are blunted.

HP:6000031.name: Phaeohyphomycosis
HP:6000031.definition: Phaeohyphomycosis refers to infections due to a large group of heterogenous organisms called dematiaceous or melanized fungi. These fungi are distinguished by the predominance of melanin in their cell walls, which likely acts as a virulence factor. Virtually, everyone is exposed to dematiaceous fungi through inhalation, as they are ubiquitous in the environment, although the development of infection is extremely uncommon.

HP:6000032.name: Autophony
HP:6000032.definition: Hearing one's own voice resonating loudly in the ear.

HP:6000033.name: High altitude exposure
HP:6000033.definition: A history of being at high altitude in situations such hiking, mountain climbing, travel to mountains, or air travel.

HP:6000034.name: History of recent hospitalization
HP:6000034.definition: A past medical history of recently being hospitalized.

HP:6000035.name: Palpitations terminated by Valsava maneuver
HP:6000035.definition: Cessation of palpitations can be induced by Valsava maneuver.

HP:6000036.name: Long telomere length
HP:6000036.definition: Abnormally long telomeres in somatic cells.

HP:6000037.name: Reduced circulating aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase activity
HP:6000037.definition: The activity of aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (also known as DOPA decarboxylase, tryptophan decarboxylase, and 5-hydroxytryptophan decarboxylase) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000038.name: Subclavian artery stenosis
HP:6000038.definition: Abnormal narrowing of the subclavian artery.

HP:6000040.name: Neuropathic pain
HP:6000040.definition: Neuropathic pain is triggered by lesions to the somatosensory nervous system that alter its structure and function so that pain occurs spontaneously and responses to noxious and innocuous stimuli are pathologically amplified.

HP:6000041.name: Repeated cold water exposure
HP:6000041.definition: A history of repeated exposure to cold water, as may result, for instance, from surfing, diving, kayaking, or swimming.

HP:6000042.name: Tinnitus exacerbated by swallowing
HP:6000042.definition: Tinnitus (sound heard by a subjhect when no corresponding external sound is present) that is made worse by swallowing.

HP:6000043.name: Rhythmic movements of the tympanic membrane
HP:6000043.definition: Regularly occurring motion of the tympanic membrane (eardrum), which is located between the inner and middle ear. This can be a manifestation of tensor tympani myoclonus, which can also be ascertained as sawtooth patterns on long-term tympanometry.

HP:6000044.name: Elongated temporal styloid process
HP:6000044.definition: The length of the temporal styloid process is above the upper limit of normal. The styloid process is a cylindrical, slender, needle-like projection of varying lengths averaging 2 to 3 cm. The styloid process projects from the inferior part of the petrous temporal bone and offers attachment to the stylohyoid ligament and the stylohyoid, stylopharyngeus, and styloglossus muscles.

HP:6000045.name: Ameliorated by nitroglycerin
HP:6000045.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with nitroglycerin.

HP:6000046.name: Pulsus paradoxus
HP:6000046.definition: Pulsus paradoxus refers to a systolic pressure drop greater than 10mmHg during inspiration.

HP:6000047.name: Chest pain triggered by palpation
HP:6000047.definition: Chest pain can be induced by palpation of the chest, which may be an indication of costochondritis.

HP:6000048.name: Chest pain described as pressure
HP:6000048.definition: Discomfort in the chest described as pressure, heaviness, or tightness.

HP:6000049.name: Chest pain described as ripping or tearing
HP:6000049.definition: Chest pain described as a tearing or ripping sensation.

HP:6000050.name: Ameliorated by flexion
HP:6000050.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by bending (flexing) a joint.

HP:6000051.name: Located on the chest
HP:6000051.definition: Applies to a finding that is situated or occurring around the thorax (chest).

HP:6000052.name: Localized to the penis
HP:6000052.definition: Applies to a finding that is situated or occurring in or on the penis.

HP:6000053.name: Snowstorm pattern of uterus on ultrasound
HP:6000053.definition: A sonographic snowstorm pattern of the uterus that results from the presence of a complex vesicular intrauterine mass containing many grape-like cysts.

HP:6000055.name: Exposure to aquatic animals
HP:6000055.definition: History of exposure to aquatic animals.

HP:6000056.name: Superficial blush-like subcutaneous fatty lesions
HP:6000056.definition: Multiple, oblong, fatty lesions in the superficial subcutaneous fatty tissue. They are mostly under 2 cm in long axis diameter. They demonstrate nodular (blush-like) increased fluid signal at unenhanced MRI and are markedly hyperechoic at ultrasound.

HP:6000057.name: Dermal multinucleated giant cells
HP:6000057.definition: Presence of giant cells in the dermis. Giant cells are formed by fusion of various cells such as macrophage, epithelioid cells, monocytes, etc., These are multi-nucleated, large in size, and generally present at the site of chronic inflammation and other granulomatous conditions.

HP:6000058.name: Exacerbation of eyelid lesion by crying
HP:6000058.definition: Applies to an eyelid lesion such as hemangiomas or varices that swells upon crying.

HP:6000059.name: Localized to upper eyelid
HP:6000059.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the upper eyelid.

HP:6000060.name: Aerophagia
HP:6000060.definition: Repetitive air swallowing and belching and that may result in abdominal distention.

HP:6000061.name: Vaginal passage of hydatidiform mole tissue
HP:6000061.definition: Passage from the vagina of hyatidiform tissue, appearing as clusters of vesicles (similar to small grapes) developed from the transformation of chorionic villi. This is a manifestation of a molar pregnancy (hyatidiform mole).

HP:6000062.name: Abnormal nipple discharge
HP:6000062.definition: Abnormal fluid that seeps out of the nipple of the breast. Nipple discharge is categozied as lactational, physiologic, or pathologic.

HP:6000063.name: Hepatolithiasis
HP:6000063.definition: The presence of gallstones within the intrahepatic bile ducts proximal to the right and left hepatic ducts.

HP:6000064.name: Excessive eructation
HP:6000064.definition: Abnormally frequent belching (expelling gas noisily from the stomach through the mouth).

HP:6000065.name: Esophageal fibrosis
HP:6000065.definition: Fibrosis located in the subepithelial portion of the esophagus. Fibrosisis is defined by the overgrowth, hardening, and/or scarring of various tissues and is attributed to excess deposition of extracellular matrix components including collagen.

HP:6000066.name: Triggered by extension of leg
HP:6000066.definition: This term refers to pain that is triggered by extending (straightening) the leg.

HP:6000067.name: Increased myocardial pyrophosphate uptake
HP:6000067.definition: Amount of pyrophosphate uptake by the myocardium as demonstrated by by technetium pyrophosphate (99mTc-PYP) scintigraphy above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000068.name: Ameliorated by nerve block
HP:6000068.definition: Refers to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by anesthetic block of a nerve.

HP:6000069.name: Brief tear break-up time
HP:6000069.definition: Tear film break up time (number of seconds that elapse between the last blink and the appearance of the first dry spot in the tear film) below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000070.name: Cutaneous granuloma
HP:6000070.definition: A granuloma localized to the skin, that is, a chronic inflammatory manifestation with localized aggregation of histiocytes with or without other inflammatory cells (such as plasma cells, eosinophils, or neutrophils), with or without necrosis, with or without vasculitis, with or without calcification, and with or without foreign bodies. Granulomas may be due to infection or chronic inflammatory disease or reactions to foreign material.

HP:0034242.name: Abnormal fetal genitourinary system morphology
HP:0034242.definition: An anomalous structural finding of the fetal genitourinary system. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

HP:0034243.name: Abnormal fetal pulmonary morphology
HP:0034243.definition: An anomalous structural finding of the fetal lungs. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

HP:0034244.name: Gastric pseudomass
HP:0034244.definition: At US examination from the second trimester onward, the fetal stomach appears as a uniformly anechoic, sharply circumscribed round structure in the left upper quadrant. However, debris is commonly visualized in the stomach, forming a pseudomass.

HP:0034246.name: Fetal scalp mass
HP:0034246.definition: An abnormal growth (lump) of tissue that projects from the fetal scalp.

HP:0034247.name: Fetal lower urinary tract obstruction
HP:0034247.definition: An obstruction in the ureter leading to bladder outlet obstruction. Special criteria are used for lower urinary tract obstruction (LUTO) in the fetus. Prenatal LUTO has classically been suspected on the basis of three ultrasonographic findings: megacystis, dilated posterior urethra (known as the keyhole sign) and hydronephrosis.

HP:0034248.name: Increased fetal lens echogenicity
HP:0034248.definition: Increased echogenicity (increased brightness in the gray-scale sonography image) of the lens of a fetus.

HP:0034249.name: Severe influenza infection
HP:0034249.definition: An unusually severe infection by an influenza virus.

HP:0034250.name: Fetal nuchal edema
HP:0034250.definition: Nuchal edema is considered present in a fetus at gestational week 14 or more if in the midsagittal plane of the neck, there is subcutaneous edema that produces a characteristic tremor on ballotment of the fetal head. This constitutes the severe end of the spectrum of increased nuchal fold thickness, which is defined as soft-tissue thickening of 6 mm or more, seen in the suboccipitobregmatic view of the fetal head. Nuchal edema may be confined to the neck or it may be generalized, as part of hydrops fetalis.

HP:0034251.name: Abnormal corneal reflex
HP:0034251.definition: An anomaly of the corneal reflex that normally induces involuntary blinking of the eyelids following contact of the cornea.

HP:0034252.name: Absent corneal reflex
HP:0034252.definition: Absence of the corneal blinking reflex, which normally induces involuntary blinking of the eyelids following contact of the cornea. The corneal blink reflex is caused by a loop between the trigeminal sensory nerves and the facial motor (VII) nerve innervation of the orbicularis oculi muscles.

HP:0034253.name: Eosinophil nuclear hypersegmentation
HP:0034253.definition: An excessive division of the lobes of the nucleus of eosinophils. Eosinophils with more than two nuclear lobes are commonly regarded as hypersegmented, because seventy to ninety percent of peripheral blood eosinophils have two nuclear lobes.

HP:0034254.name: Face of the giant panda sign
HP:0034254.definition: The face of the giant panda sign on T2-weighted MRI is characterized by preservation of normal signal intensity in the red nuclei and lateral portion of the pars reticulata of the substantia nigra, high signal in the tegmentum, and hypointensity of the superior colliculus. The findings are said to resemble the face of a giant panda.

HP:0034255.name: Colovesical fistula
HP:0034255.definition: An aberrant, pathological communication between the colon and the bladder.

HP:0034256.name: Absent dermoepidermal hemidesmosomes
HP:0034256.definition: Lack of demonstrable hemidesmosomes at the dermoepidermal junction. Hemidesmosomes are the specialized junctional complexes, that contribute to the attachment of epithelial cells to the underlying basement membrane in stratified and other complex epithelia, such as the skin.

HP:0034257.name: C4 nephritic factor positivity
HP:0034257.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that recognize C4b2a, the C3 convertase of the classical pathway of complement.

HP:0034258.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the midbrain
HP:0034258.definition: Absence or underdevelopment of the midbrain (mesencephalon).

HP:0034259.name: Hypoplasia of the midbrain
HP:0034259.definition: A developmental defect characterized by underdevelopment of the mesencephalon.

HP:0034260.name: Aplastic zygomatic arch
HP:0034260.definition: Developmental defect characterized by the absence of the zygomatic arch.

HP:0034261.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of facial bones
HP:0034261.definition: A developmental defect characterized by absence or underdevelopment of one or more facial bone.

HP:0034262.name: Absent lanugo
HP:0034262.definition: Lack of development of lanugo, the fine, soft, unpigmented hair on the body of a fetus or newborn baby.

HP:0034263.name: Abnormal vaginal bleeding
HP:0034263.definition: Abnormal vaginal bleeding occurs between menstrual periods, after sex, or after menopause. Menstrual periods that are heavier or last longer than usual or last more than seven days also are considered abnormal.

HP:0034264.name: Postcoital vaginal bleeding
HP:0034264.definition: Postcoital bleeding (PCB) consists of spotting or bleeding after sexual intercourse that is not related to a person's menstrual cycle.

HP:6000181.name: History of radiation therapy
HP:6000181.definition: A medical history of having undergone radiation therapy, which is a treatment that uses ionizing radiation for purposes such as the control the growth of malignant cells in cancer treatment.

HP:6000182.name: Absent otoacoustic emissions
HP:6000182.definition: Failure to record otoacoustic emissions (OAE), i.e., sounds generated from the cochlea in response to an acoustic stimulus and transmitted across the middle ear to the external ear canal.

HP:6000183.name: Thickened tympanic membrane
HP:6000183.definition: The tympanic membrane (eardrum, myringa) is a thin, semitransparent, oval membrane, approximately 1 cm in diameter, that separates the external acoustic meatus from the tympanic cavity. Thickening refers to an increase of the dimension across the membrane.

HP:6000184.name: Filum terminale lipoma
HP:6000184.definition: Filum terminale lipomas (FTLs) are a type of lumbosacral lipoma in which the fat is entirely within the filum terminale and separate from the conus medullaris.

HP:6000185.name: Low tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF/tetrahydrocortisone (THE) ratio
HP:6000185.definition: The relative concentration of tetrahydrocortisol plus 5-alpha-tetrahydrocortisol relative to that of tetrahydrocortisone is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000186.name: Anti-soluble liver antigen/liver pancreas antibody positivity
HP:6000186.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against soluble liver antigen.

HP:6000187.name: Anti-thrombospondin type I domain-containing 7A antibody positivity
HP:6000187.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against thrombospondin type I domain-containing 7A.

HP:6000188.name: Antisperm antibody positivity
HP:6000188.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against sperm antigens.

HP:6000189.name: Decreased circulating ficolin 3 concentration
HP:6000189.definition: Concentration of ficolin 3 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000190.name: Abnormal seminal vesicle morphology
HP:6000190.definition: A structural abnormality of the seminal vesicle. The seminal vesicles are a pair of glands that also include the prostate gland and the bulbourethral glands and are located in the pelvis superior to the rectum, inferior to the fundus of the bladder and posterior to the prostate. The seminal vesicles contribute around 70% of the fluid that will eventually become semen.

HP:6000191.name: Seminal vesicle cyst
HP:6000191.definition: A cyst (sac-like mass that may contain serous liquid or semisolid material) caused by distention of the seminal vesicle due to atresia of the ejaculatory duct.

HP:6000192.name: Silica dust exposure
HP:6000192.definition: History of exposure to respirable crystalline silica (SiO2).

HP:6000193.name: Anti-osteoprotegerin antibody positivity
HP:6000193.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against osteoprotegerin.

HP:6000194.name: History of adrenalectomy
HP:6000194.definition: A past medical history of having had a surgical procedure to remove the adrenal glands.

HP:6000195.name: Elevated mitochondrial citrate synthase activity
HP:6000195.definition: Activity of the enzyme mitochondrial citrate synthase (EC:2.3.3.1) in muscle tissue is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000196.name: Reduced muscle lactate dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000196.definition: Activity of the enzyme lactate dehdrogenase (LHD; 1.1.1.27) in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. LDH catalyzes the conversion of pyruvate to lactate and back, as it converts NAD+ to NADH and back.

HP:6000197.name: Reduced muscle phosphoglycerate mutase activity
HP:6000197.definition: Activity of the enzyme Phosphoglycerate mutase (PGM) in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. PGM is an enzyme that catalyzes step 8 of glycolysis (EC 5.4.2.11).

HP:6000198.name: Reduced muscle phosphorylase kinase activity
HP:6000198.definition: Activity of the enzyme muscle phosphorylase kinase (PhK) in muscle tissue below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000199.name: Reduced 3-beta-hydroxysteroid-delta-5-desaturase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000199.definition: Activity of 3-beta-hydroxysteroid-delta-5-desaturase, also known as Sterol C5-desaturase (EC 1.3.3.2), or SC5D below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000200.name: Reduced hepatic glucose-6-phosphatase activity
HP:6000200.definition: Activity of glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9) in the liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000201.name: Reduced hepatic glucose-6-phosphate translocase activity
HP:6000201.definition: Activity of glucose-6-phosphate translocase in liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000202.name: Cerebrospinal fluid erythrocytes
HP:6000202.definition: The presence of red blood cells (RBCs) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). The CSF normally does not contain RBCs (erythrocytes).

HP:6000203.name: Elevated CSF cholestanol concentration
HP:6000203.definition: The concentration of cholestanol in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal. Cholestanol is the 5-alpha-dihydro derivative of cholesterol.

HP:6000204.name: Elevated CSF apolipoprotein B concentration
HP:6000204.definition: The concentration of apolipoprotein B in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000205.name: Elevated CSF myelin basic protein concentration
HP:6000205.definition: The concentration of myelin basic protein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000206.name: Reduced CSF pyridoxal-5'-phosphate concentration
HP:6000206.definition: The concentration of pyridoxal-5'-phosphate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000207.name: Elevated CSF thymine concentration
HP:6000207.definition: The concentration of thymine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000208.name: Elevated CSF 5-hydroxymethyluracil concentration
HP:6000208.definition: The concentration of 5-hydroxymethyluracil in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000209.name: Elevated CSF N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid concentration
HP:6000209.definition: The concentration of N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000210.name: Elevated CSF N-carbamyl-beta-alanine concentration
HP:6000210.definition: The concentration of N-carbamyl-beta-alanine in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000211.name: Elevated CSF dihydrouracil concentration
HP:6000211.definition: The concentration of dihydrouracil in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000212.name: Elevated CSF dihydrothymine concentration
HP:6000212.definition: The concentration of dihydrothymine in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.
