HP:6000213.name: Elevated circulating Angiotensin-converting enzyme concentration
HP:6000213.definition: Concentration of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000214.name: Decreased 3-hydroxyisobutyrate dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000214.definition: The activity of 3-hydroxyisobutyrate dehydrogenase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000215.name: Reduced circulating 3-hydroxyisobutyryl-CoA hydrolase activity
HP:6000215.definition: The activity of 3-hydroxyisobutyryl-CoA hydrolase in the blood corculation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000216.name: Reduced HMG-CoA lyase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000216.definition: Activity of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl coenzyme A lyase (HMG CoA lyase) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000217.name: Reduced circulating acyl-CoA oxidase activity
HP:6000217.definition: The activity of acyl-CoA oxidase activity in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000218.name: Reduced circulating xanthine oxidase activity
HP:6000218.definition: Activity of the enzyme xanthine oxidase (EC 1.17.3.2) below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000219.name: Reduced methylmalonate semialdehyde dehydrogenase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000219.definition: The activity of methylmalonate semialdehyde dehydrogenase ( EC 1.2.1.27) in cultured fibroblasts is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000220.name: Pharyngeal mass
HP:6000220.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the pharynx (i.e., the throat, the space that connects the nose and mouth to the larynx and esophagus). The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000221.name: Positive stool occult blood test
HP:6000221.definition: The presence of hidden (occult) blood in the stool.

HP:6000222.name: Painful defecation
HP:6000222.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort that occurs when passing stool.

HP:6000223.name: Recent history of caustic substance ingestion
HP:6000223.definition: Medical history of a recent ingestion of a caustic substance, i.e., a highly acidic or alkaline chemicals that can cause severe burns to the mouth and digestive tract when swallowed.

HP:6000224.name: Delayed passage of meconium
HP:6000224.definition: Failure to pass meconium (the first stool following birth) in the first 48 hours of life.

HP:6000225.name: Single second heart sound
HP:6000225.definition: The second sound can remain single throughout the respiratory cycle due to either absence of one component or to synchronous occurrence of the two components. Since the pulmonary vascular impedance increases with age, many normal patients over age 50 have a single S2 or at most a narrow physiologic split on inspiration because P2 occurs early. A single second sound, however, is usually due to inability to auscultate a relatively soft pulmonic component. Such inability is rare in healthy infants, children, and young adults and is uncommon even in older persons under good auscultatory conditions using a rigid stethoscopic diaphragm.

HP:6000226.name: Elevated aortic transvalvular pressure gradient
HP:6000226.definition: The gradient (in this case, drop) in pressure across the aortic valve is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000227.name: Prosthetic heart valve
HP:6000227.definition: A past surgical history of the implanation of an artificial heart valve.

HP:6000228.name: Failure to increase oxygen saturation on hyperoxia test
HP:6000228.definition: Hyperoxia test is the initial method to distinguish critical congenital heart disease (CCHD) from pulmonary disease. The test consists in measuring an arterial blood gas at room air and 100% inspired oxygen after 10 minutes. Neonates with congenital heart disease are usually not able to increase PaO2 above 100 mm Hg during 100% oxygen administration. In patients with pulmonary disease, PaO2 generally increased greater than or equal to 100 mm Hg with 100% oxygen as ventilation-perfusion discrepancies are overcome. A positive result indicates the cardiac origin and further cardiac workup is indicated to rule out CCHD.

HP:6000229.name: High-set nipples
HP:6000229.definition: Placement of the nipples at a higher than normal location.

HP:6000230.name: Decreased muscle caveolin-3 level
HP:6000230.definition: The amount of calveolin-3 in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000231.name: Abnormal tissue enzyme concentration or activity
HP:6000231.definition: Concentration of an enyzme in a tissue is above or between the limit of normal. This term is intended to be used for enzymes that can be measured in multiple tissues other than blood.

HP:6000232.name: Splenic necrosis
HP:6000232.definition: Cell dealth (necrosis) located in the spleen.

HP:6000233.name: Carcinoid tumor of the pancreas
HP:6000233.definition: A carcinoid tumor of the pancreas (CTP) is a rare neuroendocrine tumor arising from the serotonin-secreting cells (enterochromaffin or Kultscitsky's cells).

HP:6000234.name: Elevated circulating dihydroxyphenylacetic acid concentration
HP:6000234.definition: The concentration of dihydroxyphenylacetic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000235.name: Inappropriately low concentration of acetoacetate
HP:6000235.definition: Lower than appropriate concentration of acetoacetate in states such as hypoglycemia in which the normal response would be to elevate acetoacetate.

HP:6000236.name: Inappropriately low concentration of beta-hydroxybutyrate
HP:6000236.definition: Lower than appropriate concentration of beta-hydroxybutyrate in states such as hypoglycemia in which the normal response would be to elevate acetoacetate.

HP:6000237.name: Elevated circulating 3-hydroxybutyryl-carnitine concentration
HP:6000237.definition: Concentration of 3-hydroxybutyryl-carnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000238.name: Elevated CSF 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxyamide concentration
HP:6000238.definition: The concentration of 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxyamide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000239.name: Elevated circulating tumor necrosis factor alpha concentration
HP:6000239.definition: The concentration of tumor necrosis factor alpha in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000240.name: Reduced circulating pyrimidine 5-prime-nucleotidase activity
HP:6000240.definition: The activity of concentration of pyrimidine 5-prime-nucleotidase (EC 3.1.3.5) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000241.name: Diminished prolactin response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation
HP:6000241.definition: The increase in prolactin concentration (PRL) following stimulation with thyrotropin (thyrdoid releasing hormone) as compared to baseline PRL concentration is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000242.name: Decreased circulating complement component 1s concentration
HP:6000242.definition: The concentration of complement component 1s (C1s) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000243.name: Reduced circulating cortisol-binding globulin concentration
HP:6000243.definition: The concentration of cortisol-binding globulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000244.name: Decreased circulating thyroglobulin concentration
HP:6000244.definition: The concentration of thyroglobulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000245.name: Elevated circulating granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor concentration
HP:6000245.definition: The concentration of granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000246.name: Elevated CSF D-2-hydroxyglutaric acid concentration
HP:6000246.definition: The concentration of D-2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000247.name: Esophageal mass
HP:6000247.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the esophagus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000248.name: Bursa fluid crystals
HP:6000248.definition: The presence of crystals (microscopic solids that form distinct lattices, with definable fixed angles, faces, walls) in the bursa fluid.

HP:6000249.name: Enlarged gastric folds
HP:6000249.definition: Giant gastric folds are recognized at endoscopy as an increase in the size of the gastric rugae and a lack of flattening.

HP:6000250.name: Gastric intraepithelial lymphocytosis
HP:6000250.definition: The count of lymphocytes located in the epithelial layer of the gastric mucosa is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000251.name: Small intestinal intraepithelial lymphocytosis
HP:6000251.definition: The count of lymphocytes located in the epithelial layer of the mucosa of the small intestine is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000252.name: Fetal lung hyperechogenicity
HP:6000252.definition: Increased response (echo) of lung tissue of a fetus observed on prenatal sonography. Increased echo response is conventially displayed as a higher degree of brightness.

HP:6000253.name: Necrotizing vasculitis
HP:6000253.definition: A histopathological finding characterized by inflammation of the arterial and/or capillary and/or venous blood vessels, leading to a change in the vascular wall as a whole.

HP:6000254.name: Abnormal proximal convoluted tubule morphology
HP:6000254.definition: Any structural anomaly of the proximal convoluted tubule, which is the first tubular component of the nephron and arises as a continuation of the Bowman space from the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle. The proximal convoluted tubule is located within the renal cortex.

HP:6000255.name: Demonstration of Leishmania in tissue
HP:6000255.definition: Presence of Leishmania, a parasitic protozoan, in a tissue specimen. Leishmania is responsible for leishmaniasis.

HP:6000256.name: Pneumocystis cysts in respiratory secretions
HP:6000256.definition: Demonstration of cysts of Pneumocystis (a genus of related fungal species) in respiratory secretions such as nasopharyngeal secretions or pleural fluid.

HP:6000257.name: Spinal cord granuloma
HP:6000257.definition: An aggregation of macrophages (forming in response to chronic inflammation) localized in or on the spinal cord.

HP:6000258.name: Impaired folate absorption
HP:6000258.definition: Reduced ability to absorb folate in the diet. This finding can be measured by a folic acid loading test in which blood concentration of folate is measured after oral administration of folic acid.

HP:6000259.name: Positive hydrogen breath test
HP:6000259.definition: Abnormally elevated quantiy of hydrogen measured by a hydrogen breath test (HBT). HBTs administer substrates such as glucose, lactulose, lactose and fructose and subsequently measure hydrogen exhaled in the breath using a gas chromatograph.

HP:6000260.name: History of recent plant thorn skin puncture
HP:6000260.definition: A history of a plant skin puncture preceding the current presenting condition by hours, days, or weeks.

HP:6000261.name: Absent circulating immunoglobulin kappa chain
HP:6000261.definition: Nondetectable kappa chain in the blood circulation.

HP:6000262.name: Pseudoglioma
HP:6000262.definition: A circumscribed whitish-yellow mass in the posterior chamber associated with retinal folds and sometimes retinal detachment and is said to resemble a retinal glioma.

HP:6000263.name: Papillary dermal edema
HP:6000263.definition: Swelling due to fluid acculuation of the papillary dermis.

HP:6000264.name: Fetal tachycardia
HP:6000264.definition: The number of beats per minute (bpm) of the fetal heart is above the upper limit of the normal for the gestational age. Fetal tachycardia is thus defined as a heart rate greater than 160-180 bpm.

HP:6000265.name: Elevated urinary 3-hydroxykynurenine level
HP:6000265.definition: The amount of 3-hydroxykynurenine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000266.name: 2-oxoadipic aciduria
HP:6000266.definition: The amount of 2-oxoadipic acid in the urine, normaliyed for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000267.name: Elevated circulating methionine sulfoxide concentration
HP:6000267.definition: The concentration of methionine sulfoxide in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000268.name: Elevated circulating pipecolic acid concentration
HP:6000268.definition: The concentration of pipecolic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000269.name: Elevated urinary pipecolic acid level
HP:6000269.definition: The amount of pipecolic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000270.name: Elevated CSF saccharopine concentration
HP:6000270.definition: Concentration of saccharopine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000271.name: Elevated circulating glycylproline concentration
HP:6000271.definition: Concentration in the bloodstream of glycylproline above the upper limit of normal. Glycylproline is a dipeptide composed of glycine and proline, and is an end product of collagen metabolism that is further cleaved by prolidase (EC 3.4.13.9).

HP:6000272.name: Elevated circulating octanoylcarnitine concentration
HP:6000272.definition: Concentration of octanoylcarnitine (C8:0) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000273.name: Elevated circulating decanoylcarnitine concentration
HP:6000273.definition: Concentration of decanoylcarnitine (C10:0) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000274.name: 2--hydroxyphenylacetic aciduria
HP:6000274.definition: Increased concentration of 2-hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the urine.

HP:6000275.name: 4-hydroxyphenyllactic aciduria
HP:6000275.definition: Amount of 4-hydroxyphenyllactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000277.name: Elevated CSF beta-alanine concentration
HP:6000277.definition: The concentration of beta-alanine present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000278.name: Elevated circulating 2-aminoadipic acid concentration
HP:6000278.definition: The concentration of 2-aminoadipic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000279.name: Elevated urinary N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine level
HP:6000279.definition: The amount of N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine present in urine, when adjusted for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000280.name: Elevated CSF cystathionine concentration
HP:6000280.definition: Concentration of cystathionine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000281.name: Elevated urinary gamma-glutamylphenylalanine level
HP:6000281.definition: The amount of gamma-glutamylphenylalanine in the urine, when normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000282.name: Elevated circulating aspartylglucosamine concentration
HP:6000282.definition: Concentration of aspartylglucosamine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000283.name: Elevated urinary saccharopine level
HP:6000283.definition: The amount of saccharopine in the urine, when normalized to urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000284.name: Tectal plate enlargement
HP:6000284.definition: Abnormal increase in size of the tectal plate (also known as the tectum or the quadrigeminal plate). The tectum is the dorsal portion of the midbrain (brainstem).

HP:6000285.name: Retroperitoneal mass
HP:6000285.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the retroperitoneal region. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000286.name: Focal T1 hyperintense brainstem lesion
HP:6000286.definition: A lighter than expected T1 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.

HP:6000287.name: Subchondral fracture
HP:6000287.definition: A type of fracture that occurs in the trabecular cancellous bone just beneath the subchondral bone plate without disruption of the articular surface.

HP:6000288.name: Deep neck abscess
HP:6000288.definition: An abscess (i.e., a circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris) localized in the area surrounded by the deep fascia of the neck including the pharynx, larynx, trachea, upper esophagus, thyroid, and parathyroid glands. Infections of pharyngeal, tonsillar, and laryngeal origin affect this space, which includes the parapharyngeal and retropharyngeal spaces.

HP:6000289.name: Epiglottic enlargement
HP:6000289.definition: Anlarged and edematous epiglottis. This sign can be observed on a lateral radiograph of the neck and it suggests a diagnosis of acute infectious epiglottitis.

HP:6000290.name: Prevertebral space enlargement
HP:6000290.definition: Increase in the anterior posterior dimension of the prevertebral space, which is located in the neck region between the anterior part of the cervical spine and the deep layer of the deep cervical fascia running between the transverse processes of the spine.

HP:6000291.name: Third cranial nerve thickening
HP:6000291.definition: Increase in diameter of the third cranial nerve (oculomotor nerve). This feature can be observed by magnetic resonance imaging and may be accompanied by contrast enhancement.

HP:6000292.name: Elevated tissue sphingomyelin concentration
HP:6000292.definition: Concentration of sphoingomyelin in tissues above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000293.name: History of recent iodated contrast medium administration
HP:6000293.definition: Medical history of recent iodinated or radioiodine contrast use.

HP:6000294.name: Difficulty passing nasogastric tube
HP:6000294.definition: Difficulty inserting a nasogastric tube (NGT), a flexible plastic tube that is placed through the nose and esophagus into the stomach and used to administer drugs or for feeding. There are certain circumstances that may make NGT insertion difficult. They are esophageal narrowing, comatose or intubated patients, and patients who have sustained severe facial or skull injuries.

HP:6000295.name: Persistent falcine venous sinus
HP:6000295.definition: A falcine sinus that does not involute but persists beyond birth is defined as a persistent falcine sinus. In the 20-mm embryo stage, the primitive falx cerebri contains the sagittal plexus, a meshwork of anastomotic venous channels from which the superior sagittal sinus and straight sinus are thought to develop. A persistent falcine sinus represents a persistent channel of the caudal anastomotic loops of the sagittal plexus.

HP:6000296.name: Penis uncircumcised
HP:6000296.definition: A medical history in a male of not having been circumcized.

HP:6000297.name: History of facial cosmetic use
HP:6000297.definition: A medical history of use of facial makeup.

HP:6000298.name: Snapping sensation at metacarpophalangeal joint
HP:6000298.definition: A feeling of clicking or snapping at the knuckle (metacarpophalangeal joint) upon extension of flexion of the finger.

HP:6000299.name: Forearm pain
HP:6000299.definition: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the forearm.

HP:6000300.name: Rotational fracture
HP:6000300.definition: A type of displaced fracture in which there has been a rotation of the distal fracture fragment in relation to the proximal portion.

HP:6000301.name: Localized over bony prominences
HP:6000301.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated on the skin in areas where bones are close to the surface (bony prominences).

HP:6000302.name: History of compressive footwear
HP:6000302.definition: A past medical history of wearing tight shoes, toe-box shoes, or high heel shoes.

HP:6000303.name: Decreased skin turgor
HP:6000303.definition: Reduced skin turgor means reduced elastic recoil of the skin to its normal contour after being pinched in a fold.

HP:6000304.name: Recent foraged mushroom consumption
HP:6000304.definition: Medical history of recently eating wild mushrooms.

HP:6000305.name: Proximal to distal progression
HP:6000305.definition: Refers to symptomatology that begins in the proximal limbs and subsequently affects the distal limbs.

HP:6000306.name: Autonomic-voluntary dissociation of facial movements
HP:6000306.definition: The selective paralysis of voluntary fascio-pharyngo-glosso-masticatory movements with preservation of reflexive and automatic functions is referred to as autonomic-voluntary dissociation, which is a distinctive feature of Anterior opercular syndrome (also known as Foix-Chavany-Marie syndrome).

HP:6000307.name: Jaw mass
HP:6000307.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the jaw. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000308.name: Excessive nocturnal light exposure
HP:6000308.definition: Exposure to continuous light at night, including night-shift work or a nocturnal lifestyle.

HP:6000309.name: Menstruating female between menarche and menopause
HP:6000309.definition: Past medical history of a woman who is menstruating, i.e., not premenstrual or post-menopause.

HP:6000310.name: Preterm premature rupture of membranes
HP:6000310.definition: PPROM (preterm premature rupture of membranes) occurs at less than 37 weeks of gestation. PPROM can happen spontaneously, during preterm labor, or following a procedure such as amniocentesis.

HP:6000311.name: History of abdominal surgery
HP:6000311.definition: A past medical history that indicates that the patient had a surgical procedure involving the abdomen.

HP:6000312.name: Thickened Descemet membrane
HP:6000312.definition: The thickness of the Descement membrane is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000313.name: Incomplete right bundle branch block
HP:6000313.definition: Right bundle branch block (RBBB) represents an abnormality in the intraventricular electrical conduction system of the human heart, generating enlarged QRS and modified vectors on the electrocardiogram (ECG). Incomplete RBBB (IRBBB) is defined by (i) QRS duration between 110 and 120 ms in adults; (ii) rsr, rsR, or rSR in leads V1 or V2. The R or r deflection is usually wider than the initial R wave. In a minority of patients, a wide and often notched R wave pattern may be seen in leads V1 and/or V2; (iii) S wave of greater duration than R wave or greater than 40 ms in leads I and V6 in adults; and (iv) Normal R peak time in leads V5 and V6 but greater than 50 ms in lead V1. The first 3 criteria should be present to make the diagnosis. When a pure dominant R wave with or without a notch is present in V1, criterion 4 should be satisfied.

HP:6000314.name: Perimenopausal onset
HP:6000314.definition: Onset of signs or symptoms of disease during the period of a woman's life shortly before the occurrence of the menopause.

HP:6000315.name: Postmenopausal onset
HP:6000315.definition: Onset of signs or symptoms of disease during the period of a woman's life after the occurrence of the menopause.

HP:6000316.name: Spastic monoplegia
HP:6000316.definition: Spastic weakness found in only one upper or lower extremity.

HP:6000317.name: Mosaic attenuation pattern in lung
HP:6000317.definition: Mosaic attenuation pattern in the lung is a term used to describe regions of differing pulmonary attenuation on CT imaging. It is a non-specific finding, although is associated with several conditions such as obstructive small airway disease, occlusive vascular disease (in which case is called mosaic perfusion pattern), pulmonary edema, and parenchymal diseases.

HP:6000318.name: Elevated aldosterone:renin ratio
HP:6000318.definition: The ratio of aldosterone concentration to renin concentration is above the upper limit of normal. If aldosterone is expressed in ng/dl and plasma renin activity is expressed as ng/ml/hr, then values above 20 with aldosterone level above 15 are considered indicative of primary aldosteronism.

HP:6000319.name: Meteorism
HP:6000319.definition: An increase in the gas content inside the bowel associated with distension of the abdomen and hydroaeric noises. The most common symptom of meteorism is a bloated sensation. It may be associated with abdominal discomfort. Some individuals may also complain of a distended stomach and excessive belching and/or passage of flatus.

HP:6000320.name: Failure to elevate ammonia on ischemic exercise
HP:6000320.definition: Normal subjects display an increase in the concentration of ammonia in the blood following an ischemic exercise test. This term refers to an increase in ammonia that is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000321.name: Labile Hypertension
HP:6000321.definition: Frequent fluctuations of blood pressure between normal and high levels, changing more dramatically than normal.

HP:6000322.name: Absent axon flare response after intradermal histamine injection
HP:6000322.definition: The axon reflex (also known as the flare response) is a response that is stimulated by peripheral nerves of the body that travels away from the nerve cell body and branches to stimulate target organs. In the human skin, there are three different phenomena mediated by axon reflex mechanism; flare, sweating and pilomotion. Stroking or intradermal injection of histamine or substance P into the human skin pro- duces widespread vasodilatation (flare) and plasma extravasation (wheal). This term refers to the failure of intradermal hista injection to elicit flare.

HP:6000323.name: Reduced sympathoneural responses to the cold pressor test
HP:6000323.definition: Response to the cold pressor test below the lower limit of normal. The cold pressor test is a simple and validated test in which the subject immerses one hand or foot into ice water for 1 to 3 minutes while blood pressure (BP) and heart rate are monitored. The cold stimulus activates afferent sensory pathways that, in turn, trigger a sympathetic response resulting in an increase in BP.

HP:6000324.name: Positive stool Giardia antigen test
HP:6000324.definition: Fecal analysis for Giardia antigen is abnormal. Tests include direct fluorescent-antibody (DFA), which detects intact organisms, and enzyme immunoassays (EIAs), which detect soluble stool antigens.

HP:6000325.name: Excessive blood loss during delivery
HP:6000325.definition: Loss of a substantial amount of blood during delivery (some definitions stipulate 1000 ml or more), typically associated with manifestations such as low blood pressure, a rapid heart rate, dizziness, light-headedness, fatigue, and weakness.

HP:6000326.name: Cardiac valve vegetations
HP:6000326.definition: Endocarditis infection occurs along the edges of the heart valves. Damage to the cardiac endothelium followed by platelet and fibrin deposition results in a sterile lesion known as nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis (NBTE) or vegetation. Microbes entering the bloodstream via routine or invasive procedures adhere to the vegetation and are engulfed in an outer meshwork of fibrin and platelets. Subsequent rapid microbial multiplication in a protected area of impaired host defense leads to vegetation growth and continuous bacteremia.

HP:6000327.name: Thoracic cage flatness
HP:6000327.definition: The anteroposterior dimension of the chest on the lateral radiograph is often relatively narrow compared with the chest width on the frontal radiograph.

HP:6000328.name: Absent zona pellucida
HP:6000328.definition: Lack of the oocyte extracellular matrix region (zona pellucida). This feature can be observed following follicular aspiration (retrieval of eggs for fertility treatments).

HP:6000329.name: Umbilical cord prolapse
HP:6000329.definition: The presence of the umbilical cord (UC) between the fetal presenting part and the cervix, regardless of the membrane status (intact or ruptured). Descent of the UC through the cervix is essential for diagnosing cord prolapse. It can be either overt (past the presenting part) or occult (alongside the presenting part).

HP:6000330.name: Increased ratio of deoxypyridinoline to pyridinoline cross-links in urine
HP:6000330.definition: The relative concentration of deoxypyridinoline (Dpyr) to that of pyridinoline (Pyr) cross-links in urine is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000331.name: Elevated urinary thymine level
HP:6000331.definition: The amount of thymine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000332.name: Elevated urinary indoleacetic acid level
HP:6000332.definition: The amount of indoleacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000333.name: Reduced hepatic phosphorylase kinase activity
HP:6000333.definition: Activity of phosphorylase kinase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal. Phosphorylase kinase (PhK) has a major regulatory role in the breakdown of glycogen. The enzyme PhK comprises four copies each of four subunits, encoded by PHKA1, PHKA2, PHKB, and PHKG.

HP:6000334.name: Reduced hepatic ornithine transcarbamylase activity
HP:6000334.definition: Activity or concentration of ornithine transcarbamylase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000335.name: Elevated urinary quinolinic acid level
HP:6000335.definition: The amount of quinolinic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Quinolinic acids is a pyridinedicarboxylic acid that is pyridine substituted by carboxy groups at positions 2 and 3. It is a metabolite of tryptophan.

HP:6000336.name: Rectal duplication
HP:6000336.definition: A developmental anomaly characterized by an additional rectum that is typically lined with intestinal mucosa with one or more cell types of the gastrointestinal tract overlying submucosa and smooth muscle layer.

HP:6000337.name: Thinned small intestinal mucosa
HP:6000337.definition: Abrnormal reduction in the height of the mucosa of the small intestine. The mucosa is arranged in regular circular folds (the circular valves of Kerckrin), the mucosal surface is covered with small projections called villi, which are slender, about 1.5-2 mm long projections of the mucosa into the lumen. In between the villi are the crypts. This term refers to a pathological thinning of these structures.

HP:6000338.name: Seminal vesicle hypoplasia
HP:6000338.definition: A congenital anomaly characterized by underdevelopment of one or both seminal vesicles, which are the two small glands that store and produce the majority of the fluid that makes up semen.

HP:6000339.name: Small fetal abdominal circumference
HP:6000339.definition: The distance around the abdomen of a fetus, generally as measured by prenatal sonography, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000340.name: Prenatal flattened diaphragm
HP:6000340.definition: The diaphragm normally projects up into the thoracic cavity. In the presence of malformations such as enlarged lungs, the diaphragm may appear abnormally flat or even everted (with the middle of the diaphragm projecting downwards into the abdominal cavity).

HP:6000341.name: Snowflake effect in amniotic cavity
HP:6000341.definition: Dense floating particles in amniotic fluid, said to resemble snowflakes. This finding can result from shedding of the epidermis in conditions such as Harlequin ichthyosis.

HP:6000342.name: Thickened mitral valve cusp
HP:6000342.definition: An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the mitral valve.

HP:6000343.name: Antiparietal cell antibody positivity
HP:6000343.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against parietal cell antigens.

HP:6000344.name: Anti-intrinsic factor antibody positivity
HP:6000344.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against intrinsic factor.

HP:6000345.name: Anti-human immunodeficiency virus antibody positivity
HP:6000345.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).

HP:6000346.name: Anti-polio virus antibody positivity
HP:6000346.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of poliovirus.

HP:6000347.name: Anti-NR2A antibody positivity
HP:6000347.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the N-Methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor NR2A subunit.

HP:6000348.name: Antistreptolysin O antibody positivity
HP:6000348.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against streptolysin O.

HP:6000349.name: Reduced tissue tissue AICAR transformylase activity
HP:6000349.definition: Concentration or activity of 5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide formyltransferase; EC 2.1.2.3) a in a tissue is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000350.name: Ameliorated by gastric acid-reducing therapy
HP:6000350.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with an agent that reduces gastric acidity such as proton pump inhibitors, histamine receptor blockers,omeprazole, esomeprazole, dexlansoprazole, pantoprazole, lansoprazole, famotidine, or ranitidine.

HP:6000351.name: Anti-coagulation factor antibody positivity
HP:6000351.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against a coagulation factor.

HP:6000353.name: Reduced tissue argininosuccinate synthetase activity
HP:6000353.definition: Concentration of argininosuccinate synthetase (EC 6.3.4.5) in body tissues is below the lower limit of normal. Clinically, argininosuccinate synthetase is measured in the liver or in cultered skin fibroblasts.

HP:6000354.name: Reduced aspartoacylase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000354.definition: Activity of aspartoacylase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts. Aspartoacylase (EC 3.5.1.15), also called aminoacylase-2, is an enzyme that hydrolyzes N-acetyl-L-aspartic acid (NAA) to aspartate and acetate.

HP:6000355.name: Reduced malonyl-CoA decarboxylase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000355.definition: Activity of malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.9) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000356.name: Reduced tissue medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity
HP:6000356.definition: Concentration or activity of medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (EC 1.3.8.7;MCAD) in tissues is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000357.name: Reduced cystathionine beta-synthase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000357.definition: Activity of cystathionine beta-synthase (EC 4.2.1.22) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000358.name: Reduced muscle glycogen phosphorylase activity
HP:6000358.definition: Activity of the enzyme glycogen phosphorylase in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. Glycogen phosphorylase (EC 2.4.1.1) is also known as amylophosphorylase, muscle phosphorylase a and b, polyphosphorylase, and myophosphorylase.

HP:6000359.name: Reduced muscle 6-phosphofructokinase activity
HP:6000359.definition: Activity of the enzyme 6-phosphofructokinase in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. 6-phosphofructokinase (EC 2.7.1.11) is also known as phosphofructokinase I and phosphohexokinase. The PFKM gene encodes the muscle isoform of phosphofructokinase. PFK catalyzes the irreversible conversion of fructose-6-phosphate to fructose-1,6-bisphosphate and is a key regulatory enzyme in glycolysis.

HP:6000360.name: Reduced tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity
HP:6000360.definition: Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.

HP:6000361.name: Reduced succinyl-CoA:3-oxoacid-CoA transferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000361.definition: Activity of succinyl-CoA:3-oxoacid-CoA transferase (SCOT, or OXCT1; EC 2.8.3.5) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000362.name: Blunted aldosterone response to aldosterone suppression test
HP:6000362.definition: A non-suppressible aldosterone excess, defined as an abnormal result of one of any four suppression tests. These tests use oral sodium loading, oral fludrocortisone, oral captopril, or saline infusion to suppress aldosterone secretion.

HP:6000363.name: Flank mass
HP:6000363.definition: An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the flank, which is the fleshy part of the side of the body between the ribs and the hip.

HP:6000364.name: Synovial cyst
HP:6000364.definition: A fluid-filled sac or pouch-like mass that is a distention of a preexisting bursa in a joint, tendon sheaths or bursae. Synovial cysts contain synovial fluid and are lined by synovial membrane.

HP:6000365.name: Brown pigmentation of the conjunctiva
HP:6000365.definition: Deposition of brown pigmentation in the conjunctiva.

HP:6000366.name: Gastrocnemius contracture
HP:6000366.definition: Limitation of simultaneous ankle dorsiflexion and knee extension during mid-stance of gait.

HP:6000367.name: Central thinning of the outer nuclear layer of the retina
HP:6000367.definition: Reduced thickness of the outer nuclear layer in the middle region of the retina. The outer nuclear layer (ONL) of the retina contains the nuclei of the cone and rod photoreceptors. Loss of the cellular machinery found in these nuclei causes irreparable loss of the photoreceptors and the capacity for visual function. This feature can be appreciated by directional optical coherence tomography.

HP:6000368.name: Sonographic renal salt and pepper pattern
HP:6000368.definition: Heterogeneous, increased parenchymal echogenicity. This imaging appearance is caused by multiple tiny cysts smaller than or just approaching the size necessary for detection, which disrupt the echo pattern without being clearly distinguishable, and appear as white grains on renal ultrasound, mainly in a subcapsular location.

HP:6000369.name: Ductus venosus agenesis with intrahepatic drainage
HP:6000369.definition: A form of ductus venosus agenesis in which the umbilical vein connects via the portal sinus to the portal venous system (PVS) without giving rise to the ductus venosus. In some cases an intrahepatic shunt from a portal to a hepatic vein can be detected prenatally. This variant has been reported to have a favorable prognosis.

HP:6000370.name: Ductus venosus agenesis with extrahepatic drainage and liver bypass
HP:6000370.definition: A form of ductus venosus agenesis in which umbilical vein does not connect to the portal venous system. The liver is bypassed and the umbilical vein drains into a systemic vein such as the inferior vena cava. This variant has been reported to have an unfavorable prognosis due to a presumed association with congestive heart failure and hydrops.

HP:6000371.name: Elevated circulating D-glyceric acid concentration
HP:6000371.definition: The concentration of D-gyceric acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000372.name: Elevated CSF D-glyceric acid concentration
HP:6000372.definition: The concentration of D-carboxylic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000373.name: Ameliorated by riboflavin
HP:6000373.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by ingestion of riboflavin (Vitamin B2).

HP:6000374.name: Increased circulating interleukin 1beta concentration
HP:6000374.definition: An increased concentration of interleukin-1beta in the blood circulation.

HP:6000375.name: Reduced neutrophil myeloperoxidase activity
HP:6000375.definition: Concentration or activity of myeloperoxidase (EC 1.11.1.7) as measured in neutrophils is below the limits of normal.

HP:6000376.name: Jugular foramen stenosis
HP:6000376.definition: Reduction in diameter of the jugular foramen, an opening in the base of the skull that is located behind the carotid canal and is formed by the temporal bone and the occipital bone. The inferior petrosal sinus, three cranial nerves, the sigmoid sinus, and meningeal arteries pass through the jugular foramen.

HP:6000377.name: Intramural intestinal gas
HP:6000377.definition: The presence of extraluminal gas within the bowel wall.

HP:6000378.name: Delayed scintigraphic gallbladder filling
HP:6000378.definition: Hepatobiliary scintigraphy is a nuclear imaging technique that permits evaluation of the liver and biliary system for acute and chronic cholecystitis, biliary atresia, biliary obstruction, and post-surgical biliary leak. With this investigation, a radiotracer is administered intravenously, bound to albumin, transported to the liver, and excreted into the biliary system. This term refers to a longer than normal time for the radiotracer to be visualized in the gallbladder. This finding may be a sign of chronic gallbladder disease or partial obstruction of the common bile duct.

HP:6000379.name: Pancreatic arteriovenous malformation
HP:6000379.definition: Pancreatic arteriovenous malformation is defined as an abnormal vascular net, developed from one or more feeding arteries and enlarged early draining veins, creating an arteriovenous shunting.

HP:6000380.name: Anti-perilipin-1 antibody positivity
HP:6000380.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against perilipin-1 (PLIN1).

HP:6000381.name: Splenic calcification
HP:6000381.definition: Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the spleen.

HP:6000382.name: Short esophagus
HP:6000382.definition: Abnormal reduction in the length of the esophagus.

HP:6000383.name: Gastric perforation
HP:6000383.definition: A full-thickness injury of the wall of the stomach.

HP:6000384.name: Gastric volvulus
HP:6000384.definition: A gastric volvulus occurs when the stomach rotates on itself at least 180 degrees along its transverse or longitudinal axis.

HP:6000385.name: Elevated circulating soluble CD163 concentration
HP:6000385.definition: The concentration of Soluble CD163 in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000386.name: Positive cold agglutinin test
HP:6000386.definition: Cold agglutinin are erythrocyte antibodies which possess the property of agglutinating red blood cells at temperatures of below 37 degrees C, this phenomenon is reversible after heating.

HP:6000387.name: Anti-D-L antibody positivity
HP:6000387.definition: The presence of Donath-Landsteiner (D-L) autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum.

HP:6000388.name: Anti-erythrocyte autoantibody positivity
HP:6000388.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against an antigen on the surface of erythrocytes (red-blood cells).

HP:6000389.name: Non-glucose reducing substance in urine
HP:6000389.definition: Abnormal result for this screening test for urinary reducing substances including glucose, fructose, galactose, lactose, pentose and maltose, as well as amino acids, cysteine, tyrosine, homogentisic acid, ketone bodies, ascorbic acid and many drugs. This term is applied if the urine stick test for glucose was negative (normal).

HP:6000390.name: Elevated urinary succinylaminoimidazole carboxamide riboside level
HP:6000390.definition: Presence of succinylaminoimidazole carboxamide riboside (SAICAr). SAICAr is a toxic intermediate metabolite of purine synthesis.

HP:6000391.name: Elevated urine hyaluronic acid level
HP:6000391.definition: Excessive amount of hyaluronic acid in urine.

HP:6000392.name: Elevated urinary methylmalonylcarnitine level
HP:6000392.definition: The amount of methylmalonylcarnitine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000393.name: Elevated urine trihydroxycholestanoic acid level
HP:6000393.definition: Presence of trihydroxycholestanoic acid in the urine. Trihydroxycholestanoic acid is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of cholic acid. Elevated plasma levels of trihydroxycholestanoic acid have been found in patients with Zellweger syndrome.

HP:6000394.name: Elevated CSF ammonia concentration
HP:6000394.definition: The concentration of amonia in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000395.name: Positive CSF VDRL test
HP:6000395.definition: An abnormal (positive) result of the Venereal Disease Research Laboratory (VDRL) test performed in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), suggesting past or present neurosyphilis.

HP:6000396.name: Elevated CSF guanidinoacetic acid concentration
HP:6000396.definition: The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000397.name: CSF oligoclonal immunoglobulin G bands
HP:6000397.definition: Oligoclonal immunoglobulin G (IgG) bands (OCBs) are a useful diagnostic tool to detect a central humoral response. In particular, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)-restricted OCBs represent a hallmark of multiple sclerosis (MS).

HP:6000398.name: Decreased CSF 3-methoxy-4-hydroxyphenylglycolaldehyde concentration
HP:6000398.definition: The concentration of 3-methoxy-4-hydroxyphenylglycolaldehyde in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000399.name: Elevated CSF alpha-crystallin B chain concentration
HP:6000399.definition: The concentration of alpha-crystallin B chain in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000400.name: Reduced CSF creatine concentration
HP:6000400.definition: The concentration of creatine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000401.name: Reduced circulating protein Z concentration
HP:6000401.definition: The concentration of protein Z in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000402.name: Elevated circulating 27-hydroxycholesterol concentration
HP:6000402.definition: The concentration of 27-hydroxycholesterol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000403.name: Elevated circulating lysophosphatidylcholine concentration
HP:6000403.definition: The concentration of lysophosphatidylcholines in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000404.name: Reduced circulating insulin-like growth factor 2 concentration
HP:6000404.definition: The concentration of insulin-like growth factor 2 (IGF2) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal. IGF2 is a peptide hormone regulating various cellular processes such as proliferation and apoptosis.

HP:6000405.name: Decreased circulating nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide concentration
HP:6000405.definition: The concentration of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000406.name: Diminished circulating reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) concentration
HP:6000406.definition: The concentration of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000407.name: Elevated circulating fibroblast growth factor 23 concentration
HP:6000407.definition: The concentration of fibroblast growth factor 23 in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000408.name: Reduced CSF asparagine concentration
HP:6000408.definition: The concentration of asparagine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000409.name: Pancreatic mass
HP:6000409.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the pancreas. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000410.name: Small intestine mass
HP:6000410.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the small intestine. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000411.name: Facial nerve compression
HP:6000411.definition: Impingement of another object such as a blood vessel upon the facial nerve, causing it to lose volume in the compressed region.

HP:6000412.name: Pulmonary perfusion defect
HP:6000412.definition: Lack of blood perfusion in a specific area of the lung. Pulmonary ventilation (V) and Perfusion (Q) scan, also known as lung V/Q scan, is a nuclear test that uses the perfusion scan to delineate the blood flow distribution and the ventilation scan to measure airflow distribution in the lungs.

HP:6000413.name: Ectopic ureteral orifice
HP:6000413.definition: Drainage of the ureter on one or both sides into an abnormal location. Normally the ureter drains via the internal ureteral orifice at the trigone of the urinary bladder. Ectopic ureteral orifice can be either intravesical (bladder neck) or, more often, extravesical. Ectopia in women is more frequently found in the urethra and the vaginal vestibule; much less frequently in vagina and in uterus. In men it is mostly found in the posterior urethra; in the male genital tract is very rare.

HP:6000414.name: Duplicate uterine cervix
HP:6000414.definition: A congenital developmental defect characterized by the presence of two cervices on the uterus.

HP:6000415.name: Intradural spinal lipoma
HP:6000415.definition: Intradural spinal lipoma (ISL) constitutes approximately 1% of all spinal tumors and is usually associated with lumbo-sacral spinal dysraphism. ISLs unassociated with spinal dysraphism are rare with only a few cases being reported in literature. They are seen in children and young adults and are situated on the posterior aspect of the spinal cord in the cervico-thoracic or thoracic regions. They represent intradural, subpial, juxtamedullary lesions.

HP:6000416.name: T2 hyperintense cerebellar lesion
HP:6000416.definition: A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the cerebellum. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the cerebellum.

HP:6000417.name: Inferior vena cava obstruction
HP:6000417.definition: Physical invasion or compression of the inferior vena cava by a pathological process or by thrombosis within the vein itself.

HP:6000418.name: Rheumatoid nodule
HP:6000418.definition: A well-demarcated, flesh colored, subcutaneous and usually freely movable lump or mass. Rheumatoid nodules can vary in size from small, pea sized lesions up to the size of a lemon and are most often round. The nodules usually are doughy or firm however and not tender. Typically rheumatoid nodules are distributed over areas of repeated trauma or pressure and occur adjacent to joints on extensor surfaces, such as the elbow, fingers and forearms.

HP:6000419.name: Elevated circulating proinsulin concentration
HP:6000419.definition: The concentration of proinsulin in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000420.name: Burning eye sensation
HP:6000420.definition: A feeling of stinging or irritation of the eyes.

HP:6000421.name: Collarettes
HP:6000421.definition: Buildup of waxy flesh-colored scales on the margin of the eyelid.

HP:6000422.name: Tympanic membrane bulla
HP:6000422.definition: Presence of blisters (bullae) on the tympanic membrane, often accompanied by fever, thickening, and erythematous appearance of the tympanic membrane, decreased or absent light reflex, and decreased mobility.

HP:6000423.name: Beard and mustache distribution
HP:6000423.definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are located at regions of the male face covered by a beard or mustache.

HP:6000424.name: Kerion
HP:6000424.definition: Kerion is an erythematous, boggy, tender, often sterile, weeping nodule or plaque with pustules and draining sinuses. Hair in these areas appears lusterless, brittle, and is easily plucked. Kerion can be solitary or multiple but is usually unilateral. Patients with inflammatory tinea barbae may have constitutional symptoms like fever and malaise. Kerion is a coalesced sterile pustule, but occasionally they can get superinfected with cutaneous bacteria and develop regional lymphadenopathy.

HP:6000425.name: Truncal location
HP:6000425.definition: Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the trunk of the body. The trunk is the main part of a person's body, not including the head, legs, or arms.

HP:6000426.name: Reduced Acyl-CoA:dihydroxyacetone phosphate acyltransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000426.definition: Activity of acyl-CoA:dihydroxyacetone phosphate acyltransferase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000427.name: Reduced alkyl-dihydroxyacetonephosphate synthase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000427.definition: Activity of alkyl-dihydroxyacetonephosphate (DHAP) synthase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000428.name: Glomerular fibronectin deposits
HP:6000428.definition: Accumulation of fibronectin in the glomerulus.

HP:6000429.name: Renal tubular karyomegaly
HP:6000429.definition: Marked enlargement of nuclei observed predominantly in the proximal convoluted tubule cells.

HP:6000430.name: Reduced tissue acetyl-CoA carboxylase activity
HP:6000430.definition: Activity of acetyl-CoA carboxylase in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including liver.

HP:6000431.name: Elevated urinary glycolic acid level
HP:6000431.definition: The amount of glycolic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000432.name: Elevated urine propionic acid level
HP:6000432.definition: The amount of propionic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000433.name: Elevated urinary butyric acid level
HP:6000433.definition: The amount of butyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000434.name: Elevated urinary isovaleric acid level
HP:6000434.definition: The amount of isovaleric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000435.name: Elevated circulating alpha-ketoglutarate concentration
HP:6000435.definition: The concentration of alpha-ketoglutarate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000436.name: Elevated circulating ghrelin concentration
HP:6000436.definition: The concentration of ghrelin in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Ghrelin is a 28-amino-acid peptide predominantly secreted in the stomach and stimulates appetite and growth hormone (GH) release.

HP:6000437.name: Reduced circulating stearoylcarnitine concentration
HP:6000437.definition: The concentration of stearoylcarnitine (C18:0) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000438.name: Reduced urinary iodine level
HP:6000438.definition: The amount of iodine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000439.name: Increased circulating interleukin 15 concentration
HP:6000439.definition: The concentration of interleukin 15 (IL-15) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000440.name: Reduced circulating squalene concentration
HP:6000440.definition: The concentration of squalene in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000441.name: Abnormal circulating interleukin 6 concentration
HP:6000441.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the concentration of interleukin 6 (IL-6) in the blood circulation.

HP:6000442.name: Abnormal circulating interleukin 12 concentration
HP:6000442.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the concentration of interleukin 12 in the blood circulation.

HP:6000443.name: Elevated blood mercury concentration
HP:6000443.definition: The concentration of mercury in the blood is above the upper limit of a guidance value for total blood mercury concentrations that implies possible injurious effects.

HP:6000444.name: Elevated blood cadmiun concentration
HP:6000444.definition: The concentration of cadmium in the blood is above the upper limit of a guidance value for total blood mercury concentrations that implies possible injurious effects.

HP:6000445.name: Elevated thallium concentration
HP:6000445.definition: The concentration of thallium in the blood is above the upper limit of a guidance value for total blood mercury concentrations that implies possible injurious effects.

HP:6000446.name: Abnormal circulating CC chemokine concentration
HP:6000446.definition: The concentration in the blood circulation of a member of the CC chemokine family is outside of normal limits.

HP:6000447.name: Decreased CSF asialotransferrin to transferrin ratio
HP:6000447.definition: The concentration of asialotransferrin relative to that of transferrin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000448.name: Anti-desmocollin antibody positivity
HP:6000448.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against desmocollin.

HP:6000449.name: Occupational exposure to raw nonsynthetic textiles
HP:6000449.definition: A history of exposure by inhalation of airborne particles generated during the processing of raw, nonsynthetic textiles, particularly cotton. Classically, exposure to cotton dust during the spinning and manufacturing process causes byssinosis. However, exposure to jute, flax, and hemp fibers has also been implicated in its development.

HP:6000450.name: Rokitansky-Aschoff gallbladder sinuses
HP:6000450.definition: Localized or diffuse epithelial proliferation with hypertrophy of the muscularis layer and invagination of the mucosa through the muscularis, forming intramural diverticula (i.e., small, bulging pouches in the wall of the gallbladder).

HP:6000451.name: Porcelain gallbladder
HP:6000451.definition: Porcelain gallbladder refers to the condition in which the inner gallbladder wall is encrusted with calcium. The wall becomes brittle, hard, and often takes on a bluish hue. It is usually found incidentally on plain abdominal x-rays or other imaging because most patients are asymptomatic.

HP:6000452.name: Gallbladder adhesions
HP:6000452.definition: Strands of scar tissue bands of scar tissue that form an abnormal connection between the gallbladder and another abdominal structure. Adhesions can form followiing gallbladder inflammation (cholecystitis).

HP:6000453.name: Bilioduodenal fistula
HP:6000453.definition: An abnormal connection between the gallbladder and the duodenum.

HP:6000454.name: Pneumobilia
HP:6000454.definition: Accumulation of gas in the biliary tree.

HP:6000455.name: Ectopic gallstone
HP:6000455.definition: A gallstone located outside of the gallbladder.

HP:6000456.name: Sleep drunkeness
HP:6000456.definition: Sleep drunkenness refers to the prolonged and pronounced difficulty with awakening from nocturnal sleep and daytime naps. This symptom should be distinguished from the milder and physiologic state of sleep inertia seen even in healthy controls .

HP:6000457.name: Mallory bodies
HP:6000457.definition: Cytoplasmic hyaline inclusions of hepatocytes that are predominantly filamentous ranging from a diameter of 3 to 24 nm vs. 10 nm of classical IF. Mallory-Denk bodies can be classified as type I (parallels filaments), II (randomly orient filaments), or III (granular and amorphous). Type II occurs in the periphery while type III occurs around the center. MDB occur in ballooned hepatocytes.

HP:6000458.name: Sulfur-containing abscess
HP:6000458.definition: An abscess containing tiny yellow clumps (sulfur granules), formed by infection with Actinomyces and generally associated with a granulomatous and suppurative infection.

HP:6000459.name: Retracted tympanic membrane
HP:6000459.definition: A condition in which part of the tympanic membrane is pull backed into the middle ear cavity (also called retraction pocket).

HP:6000460.name: Ectopic testis
HP:6000460.definition: Localization of the testis in an anatomic location other than the scrotum.

HP:6000461.name: Cerebral subcortical cyst
HP:6000461.definition: A fluid-filled sac (cyst) in the region below the cortex of the cerebrum. In magnetic resonance imaging, the fluid within the cyst has the same appearance as cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000462.name: Anti-ADAMTS13 antibody positivity
HP:6000462.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against A Disintegrin and Metalloprotease with ThromboSpondin type 1 repeats, member 13 (ADAMTS13).

HP:6000463.name: Habitual mouth breathing
HP:6000463.definition: A tendency to breathe through the mouth. Defined as over 25-30 percent of the air passing through the mouth instead of the nose, mouth breathing often occurs due to upper airway obstruction which reduces the nasal airflow and forces the air to enter completely or partially through oral cavity.

HP:6000464.name: Squared off shoulders
HP:6000464.definition: An appearance of the shoulders whereby the neck-trapezius angle (angle between the neck and the shoulder) and the angle formed by the shoulder and the arms hanging at the side of the body are both close to 90 degrees. This gives the should the appearance of the corner of a square.

HP:6000465.name: Elevated urine mesaconic acid level
HP:6000465.definition: The amount of mesaconic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000466.name: Elevated urine 3-methyladipic acid level
HP:6000466.definition: The amount of 3-methyladipic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000467.name: Elevated urine D-lactate level
HP:6000467.definition: The amount of D-lactate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. L-lactate is a familiar molecule to the human body and is also produced in large amounts in human tissues, depending on metabolic conditions. In contrast, D-lactate is produced only in minute quantities in human tissues, and is therefore not detectable in the bloodstream under normal physiological conditions.

HP:6000468.name: Elevated CSF alpha-ketoglutarate concentration
HP:6000468.definition: The concentration of alpha-ketoglutarate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000469.name: Elevated urine 2,3-dihydroxy-2-methylbutanoic acid level
HP:6000469.definition: The amount of 2,3-dihydroxy-2-methylbutanoic acidin the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000470.name: Fetal oral mass
HP:6000470.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized to the oral cavity of a fetus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined. This finding is generally first observed by prenatal sonography or magnetic resonance imaging.

HP:6000471.name: Dilated ejaculatory duct
HP:6000471.definition: Increase in diameter of the ejeculatory duct. The ejaculatory duct delivers sperm into the urethra, adding secretions from the prostate and is formed by the union of the vas deferens with the duct of the seminal vesicle.

HP:6000472.name: Decreased Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome protein concentration in hematopoietic cells
HP:6000472.definition: The concentration of Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome protein in hematopoietic cells is below the lower limit of normal. This feature is measured by flow cytometry or Western blotting.

HP:6000473.name: Decreased FOXP3-expressing T cell count
HP:6000473.definition: The number of T cells in peripheral blood that express FOXP3-expressing is below the lower limit of normal. This finding is determined by flow cytometry.

HP:6000474.name: Elevated circulating complement component concentration
HP:6000474.definition: Concentration of a complement component in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000475.name: Anti-beta fodrin antibody positivity
HP:6000475.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against a component of beta-fodrin.

HP:6000476.name: Elevated circulating tetradecenoylcarnitine concentration
HP:6000476.definition: The concentration of tetradecenoylcarnitine (C14:1) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000477.name: Elevated urine 2-trans,4-cis-decadienoylcarnitine level
HP:6000477.definition: The amount of 2-trans,4-cis-decadienoylcarnitine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000478.name: Elevated circulating 2-trans,4-cis-decadienoylcarnitine concentration
HP:6000478.definition: The concentration of 2-trans,4-cis-decadienoylcarnitine in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000479.name: Elevated urine N-acetyltyrosine level
HP:6000479.definition: The amount of N-acetyltyrosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000480.name: Elevated urine manganese level
HP:6000480.definition: The amount of manganese in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000481.name: Reduced urinary manganese level
HP:6000481.definition: The amount of manganese in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000482.name: Decreased circulating catecholamine concentration
HP:6000482.definition: Concentration of a catecholamine in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000483.name: Empty sella turcica
HP:6000483.definition: Empty sella or arachnoidocele has been defined as the herniation of the subarachnoid space within the sella turcica, associated with elongated pituitary stalk and flattening of the pituitary gland.

HP:6000484.name: Elevated brain guanidinoacetate level by MRS
HP:6000484.definition: An increase in the level of guanidinoacetate in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).

HP:6000485.name: Elevated circulating beta chorionic gonadotropin concentration
HP:6000485.definition: The concentration of beta chorionic gonadotropin in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000486.name: Elevated circulating CXCL10 concentration
HP:6000486.definition: The concentration of C-X-C motif chemokine 10 (CXCL10) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000487.name: Reduced circulating interleukin 12 concentration
HP:6000487.definition: The concentration of interleukin 12 (IL-12) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000488.name: Reduced circulating fibroblast growth factor 23 concentration
HP:6000488.definition: The concentration of fibroblast growth factor 23 in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000489.name: Abnormal circulating fibroblast growth factor 23 concentration
HP:6000489.definition: The concentration of fibroblast growth factor 23 in the blood circulation is outside of the limits of normal.

HP:6000490.name: Impaired heel-walking ability
HP:6000490.definition: Difficulty or reduced ability to walk on heels. Heel-walking can be tested as a part of the neurological examination. Foot dorsal extension weakness leads to difficulties in walking on heels.

HP:6000491.name: Anti-prothrombin antibody positivity
HP:6000491.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against prothrombin.

HP:6000492.name: Anti-factor V antibody positivity
HP:6000492.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against factor V.

HP:6000493.name: Anti-factor VII antibody positivity
HP:6000493.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against factor VII.

HP:6000494.name: Anti-factor VIII antibody positivity
HP:6000494.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against factor VIII.

HP:6000495.name: Anti-factor IX antibody positivity
HP:6000495.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against factor IX.

HP:6000496.name: Anti-factor X antibody positivity
HP:6000496.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against factor X.

HP:6000497.name: Anti-factor XI antibody positivity
HP:6000497.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against factor XI.

HP:6000498.name: Anti-factor XIII antibody positivity
HP:6000498.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against factor XIII.

HP:6000499.name: Anti-factor H antibody positivity
HP:6000499.definition: The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against factor H.

HP:6000500.name: Extremities cold to touch
HP:6000500.definition: Cool or cold arms or legs related to peripheral vasoconstriction, the narrowing of blood vessels resulting from the contraction of muscular walls in large arteries and the small arterioles of skin and most internal organs. Following exposure to low ambient temperatures, vasoconstriction decreases heat dissipation from skin surfaces, thus preventing life-threatening hypothermia.

HP:6000501.name: Ruffled acrosome
HP:6000501.definition: An irregular wavy appearance of sperm acrosomes.

HP:6000502.name: Elevated circulating calprotectin concentration
HP:6000502.definition: The concentration of calprotectin in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000503.name: 4-5 toe cutaneous syndactyly
HP:6000503.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the toes 4 and 5.

HP:6000504.name: Poly-hill sign
HP:6000504.definition: A typical physical examination in patients with muscular dystrophies and selective weakness and atrophy of the trapezius muscle and proximal deltoid muscle. The contour of the back shows unique hills and drops.

HP:6000505.name: 3-5 finger cutaneous syndactyly
HP:6000505.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the third to the fifth fingers that extends distally to at least the level of the proximal interphalangeal joints.

HP:6000506.name: Radioulnar subluxation
HP:6000506.definition: Partial dislocation of the radioulnar joint.

HP:6000507.name: Non-pitting edema
HP:6000507.definition: Non-pitting edema occurs when excess fluid builds up in the body causing swelling that does not indent when pressure is applied. It usually occurs in the limbs, and often results from underlying medical conditions affecting lymphatic system function.

HP:6000508.name: Anti-human ferritin peptide antibody positivity
HP:6000508.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the human ferritin peptide.

HP:6000509.name: Elevated CSF L-2-hydroxyglutaric acid concentration
HP:6000509.definition: The concentration of L-2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000510.name: Elevated erythrocyte inosine triphosphate concentration
HP:6000510.definition: Concentration of inosine triphosphate in red blood cells is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000511.name: Reduced erythrocyte inosine triphosphatase activity
HP:6000511.definition: Activity or concentration of inosine triphosphate pyrophosphohydrolase (EC 3.6.1.19) in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000512.name: Reduced circulating alpha-1,3-fucosyltransferase activity
HP:6000512.definition: Concentration or activity of alpha-1,3-fucosyltransferase is below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.

HP:6000513.name: Diminished neutrophil myeloperoxidase activity
HP:6000513.definition: Activity of the enzyme myeloperoxidase (EC 1.11.1.7) in neutrophils below the lower limit of normal. This feature can be measured by peroxidase cytochemistry or biochemical assays. Myeloperoxidase is a lysosomal hemoprotein located in the azurophilic granules of polymorphonuclear leukocytes and monocytes.

HP:6000514.name: Reduced erythrocyte uroporphyrinogen III cosynthase activity
HP:6000514.definition: Activity or concentration of in the level of uroporphyrinogen III (EC 4.2.1.75) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000515.name: Elevated 18-hydroxycorticosterone to aldosterone ratio
HP:6000515.definition: The relative concentration in the blood circulation of 18-hydroxycorticosterone compared to that of aldosterone is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000516.name: Elevated circulating 21-deoxycortisol concentration
HP:6000516.definition: The concentration of 21-deoxycortisol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000517.name: Elevated monolysocardiolipin/cardiolipin ratio
HP:6000517.definition: The concentration of monolysocardiolipin related to that of cardiolipin is above the upper limit of normal. This is a functional assay that can be performed from a blood spot to diagnose Barth syndrome (OMIM:302060).

HP:6000518.name: Low maternal vitamin B12 concentration
HP:6000518.definition: The concentration of vitamin B12 in the mother's blood during pregnancy is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000519.name: Elevated circulating inhibin A concentration
HP:6000519.definition: The concentration of inibin A in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000520.name: Increased circulating inhibin B concentration
HP:6000520.definition: The concentration of inhibin B in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000521.name: Elevated circulating lipoprotein(a) concentration
HP:6000521.definition: The concentration of lipoprotein(a) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Lipoprotein(a), also known as apolipoprotein(A), is encoded by LPA (HGNC:6667).

HP:6000522.name: Reduced circulating lipoprotein(a) concentration
HP:6000522.definition: The concentration of lipoprotein(a) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal. Lipoprotein(a), also known as apolipoprotein(A), is encoded by LPA (HGNC:6667).

HP:6000523.name: obsolete Increased urinary bile acid level
HP:6000523.definition: The amount of bile acids in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000524.name: Abnormal urinary bile acid level
HP:6000524.definition: The amount of bile acids in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.

HP:6000525.name: Reduced erythrocyte glutathione reductase activity
HP:6000525.definition: Activity of glutathione reductase (EC 1.6.4.2) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000526.name: Failure to elevate lactate upon ischemic exercise test
HP:6000526.definition: Failure to elevate lactate in blood washed out from ischemically exercised muscles as assayed by the forearm ischemic exercise test.

HP:6000527.name: Elevated circulating cholestanol concentration
HP:6000527.definition: The concentration of cholestanol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal. Cholestanol is the 5-alpha-dihydro derivative of cholesterol.

HP:6000528.name: Livestock exposure
HP:6000528.definition: A medical history of having been exposed to livestock (animals such as cattle and sheep which are kept on a farm ).

HP:6000529.name: Synchronous skin lesions
HP:6000529.definition: Applies to an abnormality of the skin in which multiple lesions occur at the same time.

HP:6000530.name: Serpentine skin location
HP:6000530.definition: Refers to a skin lseion that has a snake-like (serpentine) shape.

HP:6000531.name: Abnormal urinary organic compound level
HP:6000531.definition: The amount of an organic compound in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside the limits of normal. An organic compound is defined here as a chemical compound that contains a carbon-hydrogen or carbon-carbon bond, although some other definitions exist. Examples of organic compounds includes alkanes, alkenes, alkynes, aromatic compounds, alcohols, ketones, aldehydes, carboxylic acids, and esters.

HP:6000532.name: Elevated urinary histamine level
HP:6000532.definition: The amount of histamine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000533.name: Elevated urinary N-methylhistamine level
HP:6000533.definition: The amount of N-methylhistamine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000534.name: Elevated urinary ureidopropionic acid level
HP:6000534.definition: The amount of ureidopropionic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000535.name: Elevated urinary porphyrin level
HP:6000535.definition: The amount of a porphyrin compound in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Porphrins are natural pigments containing a fundamental skeleton of four pyrrole nuclei united through the alpha-positions by four methine groups to form a macrocyclic structure. Porpyrins giove rise to heme and combalamine.

HP:6000536.name: Elevated urinary coproporphyrin level
HP:6000536.definition: The amount of a coproporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000537.name: Ecrrine sweat gland predominance
HP:6000537.definition: Applies to an abnormality of the skin that is located in or surrounding eccrine sweat glands.

HP:6000538.name: Poorly demarcated skin lesion
HP:6000538.definition: Applies to an abnormality of the skin whose boundary to the surrounding normal skin is not clearly defined.

HP:6000539.name: History of recent cat bite
HP:6000539.definition: Medical history of a recent bite or scratch injury due to a cat.

HP:6000540.name: History of recent stay in area with inadequate sewage sanitation
HP:6000540.definition: A history of having been in an area with inadequate sewage sanitation in the recent past.

HP:6000541.name: Positive cutaneous herpes simplex virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000541.definition: Detection of cutaneous herpes simplex virus nucleic acid in the skin by a method such as polymerase chain reaction. The sample is usually obtained by cutaneous swabs from skin lesions.

HP:6000542.name: Positive CSF mycobacterium tuberculosis nucleic acid test
HP:6000542.definition: Detection of Mycobacterium tuberculosis nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000543.name: Positive mycobacterium CSF culture
HP:6000543.definition: Growth of mycobacterium in a culture derived from cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000544.name: Positive mycobacterium CSF microscopy
HP:6000544.definition: The demonstration of mycobacterium by microscopy of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000545.name: Positive treponema pallidum PCR test in the blood circulation
