HP:6000545.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of treponema pallidum in the blood circulation by a method such a polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000546.name: Positive human Immunodeficiency virus nucleic acid test in the blood circulation
HP:6000546.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of human immunodeficiency vrus (HIV) in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000547.name: Positive CSF enterovirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000547.definition: Detection of enteroviral nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000548.name: Positive CSF Borrelia burgdorferi nucleic acid test
HP:6000548.definition: Detection of Borrelia burgdorferi nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000549.name: Positive CSF arbovirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000549.definition: Detection of arbovus nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR..

HP:6000550.name: Positive Bartonella henselae nucleic acid test in the blood circulation
HP:6000550.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Bartonella henselae in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000551.name: Positive Dengue virus PCR test in the blood circulation
HP:6000551.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of the Dengue virus in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000552.name: Positive CSF JC-virus nucleic acid test
HP:6000552.definition: Detection of JC-virus nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

HP:6000553.name: Bloodstream Malaria parasite
HP:6000553.definition: Presence of malaria parasites in the peripheral blood.

HP:6000554.name: Positive bloodstream plasmodium falciparum nucleic acid pathogen test
HP:6000554.definition: Detection of nucleic acid of Plasmodium falciparum (a type of Malaria parasite) in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

HP:6000555.name: Decreased erythrocyte fructose-1,6-bisphosphate aldolase activity
HP:6000555.definition: Activity or concentration of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate aldolase (EC 4.1.2.13) in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000556.name: Reduced circulating dopamine beta-hydroxylase activity
HP:6000556.definition: Concentration of Dopamine beta-hydroxylase (DBH; EC 1.14.17.1) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. DBH catalyzes the oxidative hydroxylation of dopamine to norepinephrine.

HP:6000557.name: Reduced erythrocyte bisphosphoglycerate mutase activity
HP:6000557.definition: Activity or concentration of bisphosphoglycerate mutase (BPGM; EC 5.4.2.4;) in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. BPGM is a multifunctional enzyme specifically found in red blood cells that synthesizes 2,3-diphosphoglycerate through its synthase activity and degrades it through its phosphatase activity.

HP:6000558.name: Reduced erythrocyte adenylate kinase activity
HP:6000558.definition: Activity or concentration of in the level of adenylate kinase (EC 2.7.4.3) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal. Adenylate kinase is a ubiquitous monomeric enzyme that catalyzes the reversible conversion of MgATP plus AMP to MgADP plus ADP and contributes to homeostasis of the adenine nucleotide composition in the cell.

HP:6000559.name: Reduced erythrocyte hexokinase activity
HP:6000559.definition: Activity or concentration of hexokinase (EC 2.7.1.1) in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Arginase catalyzes the last step of the urea cycle.

HP:6000560.name: Decreased circulating carboxypeptidase N activity
HP:6000560.definition: Activity of the enzyme Carboxypeptidase N (arginine carboxypeptidase, EC 3.4.17.3) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000561.name: Elevated red cell pyruvate kinase activity
HP:6000561.definition: Activity or concentration of pyruvate kinase (EC 2.7.1.40) in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal. Pyruvate kinase (EC 2.7.1.40) is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyzes the transphosphorylation from phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) to ADP, yielding pyruvate and ATP.

HP:6000562.name: Reduced circulating adenosine deaminase-2 activity
HP:6000562.definition: Concentration of adenosine deaminase 2 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000563.name: Reduced sepiapterin reductase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000563.definition: Activity of sepiapterin reductase (7,8-dihydrobiopterin:NADP+ oxidoreductase; EC 1.1.1.153) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000564.name: Elevated circulating vasoactive intestinal peptide concentration
HP:6000564.definition: The concentration of vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000565.name: Elevated circulating cholesterol sulfate concentration
HP:6000565.definition: The concentration of cholesterol sulfate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000566.name: Elevated circulating lipoprotein X concentration
HP:6000566.definition: The concentration of lipoprotein X in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000567.name: Elevated circulating oxalate concentration
HP:6000567.definition: The concentration of oxalate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000568.name: Elevated blood ethylene glycol concentration
HP:6000568.definition: The concentration of ethylene glycol in the blood is above the upper limit of a guidance value for total concentrations that implies possible injurious effects.

HP:6000569.name: Midline notching of lower lip
HP:6000569.definition: Exaggerated indentation at the very middle (midline) of the lower lip.

HP:6000570.name: Reduced tissue thymidine phosphorylase activity
HP:6000570.definition: Activity of thymidine phosphorylase (EC 2.4.2.4) in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes.

HP:6000571.name: Reduced tissue tripeptidyl peptidase 1 activity
HP:6000571.definition: Activity of tripeptidyl peptidase 1 (TPP1;EC 3.4.14.9) in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. TTP1 activity can be measured in tissues including fibroblasts and leukocytes muscle.

HP:6000572.name: Reduced tissue arginine:glycine amidinotransferase activity
HP:6000572.definition: Activity of L-arginine:glycine amidinotransferase (GATM; EC 2.1.4.1) in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. GATM activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000573.name: Reduced tissue aspartylglucosaminidase activity
HP:6000573.definition: Activity of aspartylglucosaminidase (AGA; EC 3.5.1.26) in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. AGA activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000574.name: Reduced tissue carnitine-acylcarnitine translocase activity
HP:6000574.definition: Activity of carnitine-acylcarnitine translocase (CACT) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. CACT activity can be measured in multiple tissues.

HP:6000575.name: Reduced circulating 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase activity
HP:6000575.definition: The activity of 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000576.name: Reduced tissue mannosyl-oligosaccharide glucosidase activity
HP:6000576.definition: Activity of mannosyl-oligosaccharide glucosidase (MOGS) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. MOGS activity can be measured in multiple tissues including liver and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000577.name: Reduced tissue 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA hydratase activity
HP:6000577.definition: Activity of the mitochondrial enzyme 3-methylglutaconyl-CoA hydratase (EC 4.2.1.18) in tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts.

HP:6000578.name: Reduced tissue gamma-glutamyltransferase activity
HP:6000578.definition: Activity of gamma-glutamyltransferase in the tissues below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000579.name: Positive oropharangeal infectious agent test
HP:6000579.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the oropharynx positive. The oropharynx is defined as the middle part of the throat and includes the soft palate, the side and back walls of the throat, the tonsils, and the posterior one-third of the tongue.

HP:6000580.name: Positive oropharynx poliovirus nucleic acid test
HP:6000580.definition: Detection of poliovirus nucleic acid in the oropharynx by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

HP:6000581.name: Positive synonvial fluid infectious agent test
HP:6000581.definition: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the synovial fluid (i.e., in a joint) positive.

HP:6000582.name: Positive synonvial fluid culture
HP:6000582.definition: Growth of an infectious agent in a culture derived from synovial fluid.

HP:6000583.name: Positive synovial fluid gram stain
HP:6000583.definition: Demonstration of the presence of bacteria by gram staining of joint (synovial) fluid. The sample is generally obtained by arthrocentesis.

HP:6000584.name: Anti Parvovirus antibody positivity
HP:6000584.definition: The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of parvovirus.

HP:6000585.name: Brain parenchymal tuberculoma
HP:6000585.definition: Tuberculoma results from hematogenous spread of Mycobacterium tuberculosis (M. tb) from an extracranial source. Diagnosis is based on computed tomography (CT) scan and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) studies with a similar ring-enhancing lesion.

HP:6000586.name: Muscle arteriovenous malformation
HP:6000586.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in muscle tissue.

HP:6000587.name: Bone arteriovenous malformation
HP:6000587.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in a bone.

HP:6000588.name: Periosteal elevation
HP:6000588.definition: Lifting or separation of the periosteum from the outer surface of a bone. Periosteal elevation is usually seen in benign process, frequently in cranioencephalic traumas. There is an elevation of the periosteum after blood, like in cephalohematomas.

HP:6000589.name: Esophageal dilation
HP:6000589.definition: Widening (relatively uniform increase in diameter) of a segment of the esophagus.

HP:6000590.name: Spinal lipoma
HP:6000590.definition: A lipoma that is localized to the spine.

HP:6000591.name: Loose body in joint
HP:6000591.definition: Small fragments of articular cartilage that break off in a joint as a result of a injury, degeneration, or other processes.

HP:6000592.name: Paraspinal arteriovenous malformation
HP:6000592.definition: An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in adjacent to the spine, i.e., in a location that is normally occupied by muscles, ligaments, nerves, and other tissues that run alongside the spinal column.

HP:6000593.name: Supernumerary tarsal bone
HP:6000593.definition: The presence of an additional tarsal bone that is not one of the canonical tarsal bones (cuboid, medial, intermediate, and lateral cuneiform, navicular, talus, calcaneus).

HP:6000594.name: Maxillary cyst
HP:6000594.definition: A closed sac that has developed in the upper jaw bone (maxilla) and contains fluid or semi-solid material. Cystic lesions of the maxilla are benign entities with both odontogenic and non-odontogenic origins.

HP:6000595.name: Mandibular cyst
HP:6000595.definition: A closed sac that has developed in the lower jaw bone (mandibula) and contains fluid or semi-solid material.

HP:6000596.name: Sixth cranial nerve hypoplasia
HP:6000596.definition: Underdevelopment of the six cranial nerve (abducens nerve).

HP:6000597.name: Third cranial nerve hypoplasia
HP:6000597.definition: Underdevelopment of the third cranial nerve (oculomotor nerve).

HP:6000598.name: Elevated urinary succinylacetone level
HP:6000598.definition: Presence in the urine of succinylacetone, which is one of the toic block metabolites formed in tyrosinaemia type 1 because of a defect in the final enzyme of the pathway of the degradation of tyrosine, namely fumarylacetoacetase (FAH, EC 3.7.1.2).

HP:6000599.name: Elevated urinary 2-oxoisocaproic level
HP:6000599.definition: The amount of 2-oxoisocaproic in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000600.name: Elevated urinary 2-oxovaleric acid level
HP:6000600.definition: The amount of 2-oxovaleric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000601.name: Elevated urinary 2-hydroxyisocaproic acid level
HP:6000601.definition: The amount of 2-hydroxyisocaproic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000602.name: Elevated urinary isovalerylglycine level
HP:6000602.definition: The amount of isovalerylglycine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000603.name: Elevated urinary 2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyric acid level
HP:6000603.definition: The amount of 2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000604.name: Elevated urinary 3-hydroxypentanoic acid level
HP:6000604.definition: The amount of 3-hydroxypentanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000605.name: Elevated urinary 7-hydroxyoctanoic acid level
HP:6000605.definition: The amount of 7-hydroxyoctanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000606.name: Elevated urinary D-glyceric acid level
HP:6000606.definition: The amount of D-glyceric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000607.name: Elevated urinary 3-hydroxyisobutyric acid level
HP:6000607.definition: The amount of 3-hydroxyisobutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000608.name: Elevated urinary 3,4-Dihydroxybutyric acid level
HP:6000608.definition: The amount of 3,4-Dihydroxybutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000609.name: Elevated urinary 3-hydroxyadipic acid level
HP:6000609.definition: The amount of 3-hydroxyadipic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000610.name: Elevated erythrocyte galactose-1-phosphate concentration
HP:6000610.definition: Concentration of galactose-1-phosphate in red blood cells (erythrocytes) above the upper level of normal.

HP:6000611.name: Elevated circulating chitotriosidase activity
HP:6000611.definition: Increased activity or concentration of the enzyme chitotriosidase. Serum chitotriosidase is a biomarker that has shown high specificity and sensitivity in patients with sarcoidosis.

HP:6000612.name: Squamosal suture synostosis
HP:6000612.definition: Premature closure of the squamosal suture, which is one of the lateral minor skull sutures, separating the parietal and squamous temporal bones.

HP:6000613.name: Enlarged fetal lungs
HP:6000613.definition: The size (volume) of the lungs of a fetus above the upper limit of normal for the gestational age.

HP:6000614.name: Orbital inflammation
HP:6000614.definition: An inflammatory condition localized to the orbit, presenting capillary dilatation, leukocytic infiltration, redness, heat, and pain. CT or MIR Imaging demonstrates enlargement of the muscle belly of one (or more) extraocular muscles typically with the involvement of tendinous insertions. Inflammation can also be observed in surrounding tissues, including the orbital fat, lacrimal gland, and optic nerve sheath.

HP:6000615.name: Reduced Inositol polyphosphate 5-phosphatase OCRL-1 activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000615.definition: Concentration or activity of inositol polyphosphate 5-phosphatase OCRL-1 as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. This enzyme has phosphoinositide 5-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.36) activity.

HP:6000616.name: Reduced muscle glycogen debrancher enzyme activity
HP:6000616.definition: Activity of the gycogen debrancher enzyme (GDE) in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. GDE is a large monomeric protein with two catalytic activities: amylo-1,6-glucosidase (EC 3.2.1.33) and 4-alpha-glucanotransferase (EC 2.4.1.25).

HP:6000617.name: Reduced tissue UDP-glucuronyl-transferase activity
HP:6000617.definition: Concentration or activity of uridine diphosphate glucuronosyltransferase below the lower limit of normal. The activity of this enzyme can be measured in liver and rarely in other tissues.

HP:6000618.name: Temporal artery giant cells
HP:6000618.definition: The presence of giant cells in the temporal artery. This is a feature of giant cell arteritis. Giant cells are multinucleated cells formed by fusion of multiple macrophages and are typically located in the intima of the arterial wall. This feature is typically demonstrated by temporal artery biopsy but other arteries may also be affected.

HP:6000619.name: Reduced phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase activity in cultured fibroblasts
HP:6000619.definition: Activity of phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (EC 4.1.1.32) is below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

HP:6000620.name: Elevated urinary pyrroline hydroxycarboxylic acid level
HP:6000620.definition: The amount of pyrroline hydroxycarboxylic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000621.name: Elevated urinary N-tau-ribosylhistidine level
HP:6000621.definition: Presence of N tau-ribosylhistidine (His-R) in the urine. His-R is a histidine derivative found in the urine of histidinemic patients.

HP:6000622.name: Elevated urinary ureidoisobutyric acid level
HP:6000622.definition: The amount of ureidoisobutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Ureidoisobutyric acid is increased in the urine of patients with beta-ureidopropionase (EC 3.5.1.6) deficiency.

HP:6000623.name: Elevated urinary N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid level
HP:6000623.definition: The amount of N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000624.name: Nipple epidermal Paget cells
HP:6000624.definition: Malignant, intraepithelial adenocarcinoma cells of variable sizes usually large in size, present singly or in the form of small groups within the epidermis of the nipple. Cells may be ovoid, round, or signet-ring forms, usually mucin positive, and the cytoplasm may contain periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, diastase-resistant granules, indicating the presence of neutral mucopolysaccharides. The cells possess microscopic features of glandular cells with pale to clear vacuolated cytoplasm, and nuclei are usually high-grade with prominent nucleoli.

HP:6000625.name: Penile corporal blood gas ischemia
HP:6000625.definition: Partial pressure of oxygen (pO2) in cavernous blood of the penis is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000626.name: Recent temporal region trauma
HP:6000626.definition: A history of an injury to the temporal region of the skull that occurred recently (several hours, days, or weeks before the current presenting complaint).

HP:6000627.name: Rest limb pain
HP:6000627.definition: Rest pain is a continuous unrelenting pain due to ischemia of the lower leg, beginning with or being aggravated by elevation and being relieved by sitting with legs in a dependent position or by standing.

HP:6000628.name: Scalloped appearance of liver surface
HP:6000628.definition: A lesion associated with pseudomyxoma peritonei whosetypical CT appearance is scalloping of the surface of the liver and spleen caused by loculated accumulations of mucin, which distinguishes mucin from fluid ascites. The mucinous material is similar in density to water. There are also islands of higher attenuation due to scattered solid elements and calcification within mucinous material.

HP:6000629.name: Nipple thickening
HP:6000629.definition: Thickening of the skin around the nipple.

HP:6000630.name: Hypoechoic breast mass
HP:6000630.definition: A breast mass visualized by sonography that displays a lower than normal echo signal (and this that appears dark gray in the typical ultrasound image).

HP:6000631.name: Unilocular ovarian cyst
HP:6000631.definition: An ovarian cyst without septa and a solid component.

HP:6000632.name: Mesenteric torsion
HP:6000632.definition: Mesenteric torsion is a pathological rotation of the intestinal tract around the axis of the mesenteric root, resulting in rapid occlusion of the cranial mesenteric artery.

HP:6000633.name: High-pitched bowel sounds
HP:6000633.definition: Abnormal bowel sounds of an unually high frequency.

HP:6000634.name: Exacerbated by opiate medication
HP:6000634.definition: Applied to a sign orr symptom that is worsed by administration of opiate medications.

HP:6000635.name: Breast granuloma
HP:6000635.definition: Formation of a non-necrotizing granuloma in breat tissue typically in combination with a localized infiltrate of multi-nucleated giant cells, epithelioid histiocytes, lymphocytes, and plasma cells.

HP:6000636.name: Exposure to cosmetic fragrances
HP:6000636.definition: A history of exposure to fragrances found in cosmetic products.

HP:6000637.name: Sweating and flushing in the preauricular area in response to mastication
HP:6000637.definition: Sweating and flushing in the preauricular area in response to mastication or a salivary stimulus. Facial warmth, flushing, and sweating in the territory of the auriculotemporal nerve overlying the parotid gland, which may include the preauricular skin, the temporal skin, the scalp, and the temporomandibular joint region. Symptoms occur during meals, especially with spicy and sour foods. This feature is inferred to be a consequence of injury to the auriculotemporal nerve, a branch if the trigeminal nerve.

HP:6000638.name: Reduced hepatic glyoxylate reductase activity
HP:6000638.definition: Activity of glyoxylate reductase/hydroxypyruvate reductase (GRHPR; EC 1.1.1.79) in liver below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000639.name: PAS-positive lymphocyte vacuolization
HP:6000639.definition: Presence of lymphocytes with positive staining for periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) cytoplasmic vacuoles.

HP:6000640.name: Lipid-laden bone-marrow macrophages
HP:6000640.definition: Bone marrow with increased numbers of macrophages heavily laden with lipids.

HP:6000641.name: Bone marrow monocytosis
HP:6000641.definition: Increased count of monocytes in the bone marrow.

HP:6000642.name: Sunflower cataract
HP:6000642.definition: Sunflower cataract (SC) is a type of anterior subcapsular cataract almost only seen in Wilson disease, an autosomal-recessive condition with a defect in the metabolism of copper leading to accumulation of copper in the liver and basal ganglia. SC consists of a thin, centralized opacification that is located directly under the anterior capsule and encompasses between one-third and one-half of the anterior lens pole surface area. In all cases, the central opacification is surrounded by additional, secondary opacifications arranged in ray-like structures around it. This pattern is said to resemble a sunflower, with a large central disk surrounded by petals.

HP:6000643.name: Anti-lamin A antibody positivity
HP:6000643.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against lamin A.

HP:6000644.name: Anti-lamin C antibody positivity
HP:6000644.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against human lamin C.

HP:6000645.name: Anti-vinculin antibody positivity
HP:6000645.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against vinculin.

HP:6000646.name: Anti-annexin A5 antibody positivity
HP:6000646.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against annexin A5.

HP:6000647.name: Bulging fontanelle
HP:6000647.definition: An outward curving of a fontanelle, which occurs when fluid builds up in the brain or the brain swells, causing increased pressure inside the skull.

HP:6000648.name: 3-4 toe cutaneous syndactyly
HP:6000648.definition: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between the toes 3 and 4.

HP:6000649.name: Triangular nail
HP:6000649.definition: Nail so wide as long with a distal part presenting an acute angle.

HP:6000650.name: Distal tibiofibular synostosis
HP:6000650.definition: Fusion of the distal (i.e.., located away from the trunk) part of the tibia and fibula.

HP:6000651.name: Abnormal metacarpal ossification
HP:6000651.definition: Any abnormal process of ossification of the metacarpal bones, which normally are each ossified from two centers: one for the body, and one for the head (metacarpal II,III,IV, and V) and one for the body and one for the base (metacarpal I). At the eighth to ninth week of fetal life, ossification commences in the middle of the body. At the third year the distal extremities of the metacarpals of the fingers and the base of the metacarpal of the thumb begin to ossify; they unite with the bodies at about the twentieth year.

HP:6000652.name: Rib spur
HP:6000652.definition: A bony projection (spur, osteophyte) originating from a rib.

HP:6000653.name: Crescent-shaped iliac bone
HP:6000653.definition: Deficient mineralization of the iliac wings, giving a paraglider/crescent shape to the iliac bone.

HP:6000654.name: Abnormal ischium ossification
HP:6000654.definition: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of ischial bones.

HP:6000655.name: Femoral neck fracture
HP:6000655.definition: A partial or complete breakage of the neck of femur.

HP:6000656.name: Papillary dermis eosinophilic hyaline material
HP:6000656.definition: Accumulation of eosinophilic hyaline material observed around the papillary dermis and the blood vessels located in it. The papillary dermis is the uppermost layer of the dermis. It intertwines with the rete ridges of the epidermis and is composed of fine and loosely arranged collagen fibers.

HP:6000657.name: Pancreatic intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm
HP:6000657.definition: Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN) is an exocrine neoplasm of the pancreas consisting of epithelial cells growing within the pancreatic ducts (main pancreatic duct or its major branches) and producing mucin. IPMN is a mucin-producing pancreatic cystic tumor. IPMN contains epithelial cells that can create papillary projections.

HP:6000658.name: Medium vessel vasculitis
HP:6000658.definition: A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) that affects medium-sized blood vessels. By common usage, vasculitis predominantly refers to arterial disease. Medium-sized vasculitis is observed in diseases including polyarteritis nodosa, Kawasaki disease, and cutaneous polyarteritis nodosa.

HP:6000659.name: Elevated muscle fiber laminin alpha 5 expression
HP:6000659.definition: A decreased amount of laminin alpha-5 in muscle tissue. This feature can be shown by immunohistochemistry or Western blotting of muscle tissue. Laminin subunit alpha-5 is a protein encoded by the LAMA5 gene.

HP:6000660.name: Paravertebral mass
HP:6000660.definition: A swelling or enlargement localized next to the vertebral column. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.

HP:6000661.name: Phlebolith
HP:6000661.definition: A calcified structure that forms within a vein. The pathogenesis of phleboliths is thought to involve an organized thrombus produced when the peripheral blood flow slows. The thrombus calcifies, form- ing the core of the phlebolith. Then, the fibrinous com- ponent undergoes secondary calcification and becomes attached. Repetition of this process causes enlargement of the phlebolith.

HP:6000662.name: Bladder rupture
HP:6000662.definition: A perforation in the wall of the urinary bladder. Bladder rupture, a relatively rare condition, is most commonly due to abdominal or pelvic trauma but may be spontaneous or iatrogenic in association with surgical or endoscopic procedures. In most cases, patients with bladder rupture have gross hematuria. Other symptoms of bladder rupture include pelvic pain, lower abdominal pain, and difficulty voiding.

HP:6000663.name: Elevated myocardial iron load
HP:6000663.definition: Increased amount of iron in myocardial tissue.

HP:6000664.name: Right ventricular regional wall motion abnormality
HP:6000664.definition: The occurrence of abnormal or absent contractility of a region of the heart muscle of the right ventricule. Conventional assessment of RWMA is based on visual interpretation of endocardial excursion and myocardial thickening from the echocardiogram videos.

HP:6000665.name: Right ventricular regional akinesia
HP:6000665.definition: A region of the right ventricle exhibits absent contraction (akinesia) compared to the rest of the ventricle.

HP:6000666.name: Right ventricular regional dyskinesia
HP:6000666.definition: A region of the right ventricle exhibits abnormal contraction (dyskinesia) compared to the rest of the ventricle, leading to outward bulging or ballooning during contraction or inadequate inward movement.

HP:6000667.name: Right ventricular aneurysm
HP:6000667.definition: A localized, abnormal dilation or bulging of a portion of the right ventricular wall.

HP:6000668.name: Glomerular immune-complex deposition
HP:6000668.definition: Accumulation of immune deposits, containing immunoglobulins, complement, and other proteins, at various intraglomerular locations. This can lead to glomerulonephritis, with the type of injury that results being dependent on four factors: the mechanism of the deposit formation, the site of deposit formation, the composition of the deposits and the amount of the deposits.

HP:6000669.name: Glomerular PLA2R immune-complex deposition
HP:6000669.definition: Accumulation of immune deposits, containing auto-antibodies against the podocyte antigen M-type phospholipase A2 receptor (PLA2R) in intraglomerular locations.

HP:6000670.name: Elevated urinary L-glycerate level
HP:6000670.definition: The amount of L-glycerate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000671.name: Breast myxoma
HP:6000671.definition: A rare, benign mesenchymal tumor of the breast characterized histologically by stellate, round, and spindle-shaped cells with vesicular nuclei and scant cytoplasm that are scattered in the myxoid stroma.

HP:6000672.name: Ovarian cystadenoma
HP:6000672.definition: A common, benign ovarian tumor that carries a good prognosis. The two most frequent types of cystadenomas are serous and mucinous cystadenomas whereas endometrioid and clear cell cystadenomas are rare.

HP:6000673.name: Abnormal CSF N-acetylaspartic acid concentration
HP:6000673.definition: Any deviation from the normal concentration of N-acetylaspartic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

HP:6000674.name: Decreased CSF N-acetylaspartic acid concentration
HP:6000674.definition: Concentration of N-acetylaspartic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000675.name: Elevated urinary mevalonate lactone level
HP:6000675.definition: The amount of mevalonate lactone in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000676.name: Anti-von Willebrand factor antibody positivity
HP:6000676.definition: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to von Willebrand factor (VWF).

HP:6000677.name: Increased total natural killer cell count
HP:6000677.definition: The absolute count of natural killer cells in the blood, per microlitre, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000678.name: Myositis-specific autoantibody positivity
HP:6000678.definition: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that display a high degree of specificity for idiopathic inflammatory myopathy (myositis-specific autoantibodies (MSAs)). MSAs are clinically useful biomarkers to help the diagnosis of polymyositis/dermatomyositis (PM/DM). Many of these are also associated with a unique clinical subset of PM/DM, making them useful in predicting and monitoring certain clinical manifestations.

HP:6000679.name: Abnormal serum osmolality
HP:6000679.definition: Any deviation from the normal range of the serum osmolality, defined as the sum of the osmolalities of every single dissolved particle in the blood such as sodium and associated anions, potassium, glucose, and urea.

HP:6000680.name: Low serum osmolality
HP:6000680.definition: Serum osmolality, which is defined as the sum of the osmolalities of every single dissolved particle in the blood such as sodium and associated anions, potassium, glucose, and urea, is below the lower limit of normal.

HP:6000681.name: High serum osmolality
HP:6000681.definition: Serum osmolality, which is defined as the sum of the osmolalities of every single dissolved particle in the blood such as sodium and associated anions, potassium, glucose, and urea, is above the upper limit of normal.

HP:6000682.name: History of compressive dressings
HP:6000682.definition: A past medical history of having been treated with tight bandages, compression sleeve, tight casts or splints, immobilizers, or similar items such as overly tight clothes, watch bands, or handcuffs.

HP:6000683.name: Triggered by overhead motions
HP:6000683.definition: Applies to a sign or symptom that is induced by repeatedly performing overhead motions, such as painting a ceiling or working on objects located above the head, or some types of athletics.

HP:6000684.name: Radiating pain
HP:6000684.definition: Pain that is perceived to extend or spread out from one area of the body to another.

HP:6000685.name: Mitral opening snap
HP:6000685.definition: Opening snap is an additional sound heard in the diastole that is related to the opening of a stenotic but mobile mitral valve. It is described as an early diastolic, high-pitched sound, which is associated with opening of the mitral and/or tricuspid valve.
